<HEAD>I.<LB>Die nordenglische Legendensammlung<LB>des Ms. Harl. 4196 (und Ms. Cott. Tiber. E VII).</HEAD>
<DIV2 TYPE="prolog">

<PB REF="00000141.tif" N="[2]">
<HEAD>Incipit hic tractatus de legenda sanctorum.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Die Sammlung des Ms. Harl. 4196 besteht aus 2 Theilen: der erste Theil, bis fol. 165, sindet sich nur theilweise im Ms. Tib. E VII und hat in den gleichen Legen|den einen im Einzelnen vielfach abweichenden, umgebildeten Text; bei fol. 165 be|ginnt eine andere Hand und von hier ab stimmt Harl. buchst&auml;blich mit Tib. &uuml;berein.</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Here may men luke, who likes to lere,<MILESTONE N="133" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Of liues and dedis of saintes sere,</L>
<L>And in olde times how it bifell.</L>
<L>Als men in inglis tung mai tell.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Out of latyn &thorn;us er &thorn;ai draune,</L>
<L>Omong laud men forto be knaune.</L>
<L>And first es ordand forto shewe</L>
<L>&THORN;e solempne fest of Saint Andrew.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Diese einleitenden Verse der Sammlung finden sich im Ms. Tib. E VII nicht.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="1" TYPE="legend">
<HEAD>I. De s. Andrea apostolo historia<NOTE PLACE="foot">Diese, die Sammlung des Ms. Harl. 4196 beginnende Legende ist in dems. Ms. am Schlusse der Sammlung fol. 197b (hinter Katharina) nochmals wiederholt, zugleich mit Anastasia, fol. 199b, die bereits im ersten Theil des Ms., der Homiliensammlung, voranging, beide von derselben zweiten Hand, die von fol. 165 ab den letzten Theil der Sammlung geschrieben hat; ein am Rande von derselben Hand vermerktes Vacat bezeichnet indessen beide Legenden als dort nicht g&uuml;ltig. Dieser 2<SUP>te</SUP> Text des An|dreas umfasst nur die ersten 258 Verse (das Miraculum fehlt) und weicht im Einzel|nen vielfach ab (er ist k&uuml;rzer), stimmt dagegen buchst&auml;blich mit dem im Ms. Tiber. E VII fol. 277b hinten, nach Katharina, folgenden Texte dieseI Legende &uuml;berein, woraus eben dieser 2<SUP>te</SUP> Text des Ms. Harl., wie fast alle Legenden von fol. 165 ab, buchst&auml;blich entnommen ist. Leider ist Ms. Tib., die fr&uuml;here und bessere Hs., durch Feuer sehr besch&auml;digt, und von je 2 Columnen einer Seite nur eine (auf der Vorderseite die linke, auf der R&uuml;ckseite die rechte) ganz oder gr&ouml;sstentheils (bis auf die obersten 3&mdash;5 Verse) lesbar, von der andern meist nur Anf&auml;nge oder Schluss|w&ouml;rter einzelner Verse. Die Texte des Ms. Tib. haben durchaus den Vorzug; es ist nothwendig, die Lesarten desselben genau zu verzeichnen, wenn auch, bei der theil|weisen Zerst&ouml;rung dieser Hs., Ms. Harl. der Ausgabe zu Grunde zu legen ist.</NOTE>).<NOTE PLACE="foot">Hier folgen die Varianten des 2<SUP>ten</SUP> Textes des Ms. Harl. (=Tib.):</NOTE></HEAD>
<DIV3 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Saint Andrew, Cristis apostil dere,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Cristes appostell.</NOTE></L>
<L>Whils he went in &thorn;is werld here,<NOTE PLACE="foot">wond.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ful mekill folk in sere cuntre<NOTE PLACE="foot">ful mani men.</NOTE></L>
<L>To cristen trouth conuertid he.<NOTE PLACE="foot">faith st. trouth. conuerted.</NOTE></L>
<L>And at &thorn;e last so it byfell,<NOTE PLACE="foot">and fehlt. befell.</NOTE></L>
<L>In a cete whore he gun dwell:<NOTE PLACE="foot">(hier wird Tib. lesbar) als st. whore. gan dwel.</NOTE></L>
<L>A domesman in &thorn;at cete was,</L>
<L>And his name was cald Egeas,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&THORN;at named was &thorn;an Cosdroas (! sp&auml;ter v. 35 Egeas, Tib. Egeas).</NOTE></L>
<L>A man &thorn;at lifed in maumetry</L>
<L N="10">And in fals goddes, ful of enuy.<NOTE PLACE="foot">9&mdash;10) fehlen.</NOTE></L>
<L>He gederd togedir both bond &amp; fre,<NOTE PLACE="foot">And he gert call both.</NOTE></L>
<L>Riche and pouer of ilk cuntre,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Pouer and riche of &thorn;at c.</NOTE></L>
<L>And bad &thorn;ai suld mak sacrafise<NOTE PLACE="foot">And comand &thorn;am opon all wise</NOTE></L>
<L>Vnto his goddes of mekil prise;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Till his goddes at mak sacrafise.</NOTE></L>
<L N="15">And who so wold noght ofrand make,<NOTE PLACE="foot">wald noht.</NOTE></L>
<L>Grete uengeance wold he on &thorn;am take.<NOTE PLACE="foot">On &thorn;am he toke uengance and wrake.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000142.tif" N="4"></L>
<L>&THORN;e folk ful fast &thorn;an &thorn;eder soght</L>
<L>And to &thorn;o warlaus wirschip wroght.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">17&mdash;18) fehlen.</NOTE></L>
<L>And sone when saint Andrew herd tell</L>
<L N="20">Of &thorn;at foul fare how it bifell,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Of all &thorn;is fare.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;edir ful playnli gun he pas<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&thorn;eder he whent (T. went) with ful gude chere,</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;us he sayd vnto Egeas:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">And said to him on &thorn;is manere.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Sen &thorn;ou couaytes &thorn;at folk &thorn;e ken</L>
<L>Als domesman ouer al o&thorn;er men,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">all.</NOTE></L>
<L N="25">&THORN;an suld &thorn;ou knaw in dede &amp; steuyn</L>
<L>&THORN;i domesman: &thorn;at es god in heuyn,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">god fehlt.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at sal &thorn;e deme efter &thorn;i dede &mdash;</L>
<L>Him forto knaw now war it nede;</L>
<L>He es &thorn;i god and ouer all mighti,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">ouer fehlt. mighty (y h&auml;usiger im Auslaut).</NOTE></L>
<L N="30">And all o&thorn;er er fals maumetri;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">fals fehlt. maw|metry (T. mawmettri).</NOTE></L>
<L>Him forto honure euermore &thorn;e awe<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Him suld &thorn;ou honore als &thorn;e aw,</NOTE></L>
<L>And verraily for &thorn;i god him knawe,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">And uerrayly (T. verrayli) &thorn;ou suld him knaw.</NOTE></L>
<L>And draw &thorn;i hert fro deuils oway<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&thorn;am st. deuils.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at ledis to pine &thorn;at lastes ay".<NOTE PLACE="foot2">ledes. payn.</NOTE></L>
<L N="35">Egeas &thorn;an answerd ogayne:</L>
<L>"&THORN;ir wurdes, he sayd, er all in vayne,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">And said &thorn;ir wordes er.</NOTE></L>
<L>And no-thing suth &thorn;ou tels me till<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&thorn;at &thorn;ou here towches me untill.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at may I proue by propir skill:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&thorn;at proue I &thorn;e by proper skill.</NOTE></L>
<L>For, whils &yogh;owre god, &thorn;at &yogh;e on call,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">zowre, ze (von fol. 165 an schreibt Harl. z st. &yogh;).</NOTE></L>
<L N="40">Prechid &thorn;e pople in erth ouer-all<NOTE PLACE="foot2">preched (T. prechid) &thorn;is same in erth.</NOTE></L>
<L>And techid his men &thorn;at with him dweld</L>
<L>To preche &thorn;e same &thorn;at &thorn;ou here teld:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">41&mdash;2) fehlen.</NOTE></L>
<L>Omang &thorn;e Iews here tane was he</L>
<L>And nayled &amp; hanged high on a tre:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">and nayled fehlt. opon.</NOTE></L>
<L N="45">And had he bene god, als &thorn;ou says,</L>
<L>It had noght bene so, by no ways.</L>
<L>&THORN;arfore I say, &thorn;ir wurdes er vayne".<NOTE PLACE="foot2">I say fehlt. er all in.</NOTE></L>
<L>Saint Andrew &thorn;an answerd ogayne:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">saint fehlt.</NOTE></L>
<L>"And &thorn;ou kouth klerely knaw and se<NOTE PLACE="foot2">if st. and. cowth. said he st. and se.</NOTE></L>
<L N="50">&THORN;e vertu of &thorn;at ilk haly tre<NOTE PLACE="foot2">ilk fehlt.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at named es &thorn;e cros in land,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&thorn;e fehlt (steht in T.).</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;an wald &thorn;ou wit and vnderstand</L>
<L>How Jhesu Crist, my maystir fre,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&thorn;at st. how.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bi resonable caus of charite<NOTE PLACE="foot2">resonabill.</NOTE></L>
<L N="55">And for pete &thorn;at he had in mynde<NOTE PLACE="foot2">for fehlt. minde.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of &thorn;e grete mescheuys of man-kynde<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Vnto &thorn;e mescheues. kinde.</NOTE></L>
<L>Payn of &thorn;e cros he putted him till,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">umgesetzt.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">put.</NOTE></L>
<L>Noght maugre his, bot with his will".<NOTE PLACE="foot2">umgesetzt.</NOTE></L>
<L>Egeas &thorn;an vnto &thorn;is thing</L>
<L N="60">Answerd als in grete hething,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">with st. in. heting.</NOTE></L>
<L>He sayd: "how may &thorn;ou say &thorn;ir sawes,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">And sayd. &thorn;ow. &thorn;is saw.</NOTE></L>
<L>Sen &thorn;at &thorn;i-self &thorn;e suth wele knawes?<NOTE PLACE="foot2">wele fehlt. kan knaw.</NOTE></L>
<L>At &thorn;e first time bitrayd was he,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">he (!) at &thorn;e first bitrayed was he.</NOTE></L>
<L>And thurgh ane of his awin men&yogh;e,<NOTE PLACE="foot1">And ist zu tilgen.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">and fehlt.</NOTE></L>
<L N="65">And sethin takin with iews kene</L>
<L>And bunden and led furth &thorn;am bitwene</L>
<L>To Cayfas hall &thorn;e graythest gate,</L>
<L>And fro &thorn;e&thorn;in vnto Sir Pilate;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">65&mdash;8: &thorn;at ful preue with him had bene, &amp; se&thorn;in taken with iews kene (= 65) And led a spot of euyl gate (!) Vntill &thorn;ai come to sir Pilate.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ore was he demid on cros to hang,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">And demid &thorn;are on.</NOTE></L>
<L N="70">Als &thorn;e iews ordand &thorn;am omang.</L>
<L>Maugre his &thorn;ai gun him spill &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">mawgre. gan.</NOTE></L>
<L>How proues &thorn;ou &thorn;an, it was his will?"</L>
<L>Saynt Andrew says: "his will it was:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">said.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at may I proue wele, or I pas:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&thorn;at proue I &thorn;e wele.</NOTE></L>
<L N="75">Of his men&yogh;e mi-self was one<NOTE PLACE="foot2">ane.</NOTE></L>
<L>In &thorn;e same time when he was tone;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">In &thorn;at ilk t. . tane.</NOTE></L>
<L>And bifor &thorn;e time he was bitrayd,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">And or tyme &thorn;at he.</NOTE></L>
<L>Vnto vs all samyn &thorn;us he sayd:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">vntill.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000143.tif" N="5"></L>
<L>How he s&ubreve;ld for mans syns be sold<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at st. how. sin. salde.</NOTE></L>
<L N="80">And suffer paynes ful monyfolde<NOTE PLACE="foot">manifalde.</NOTE></L>
<L>And dy on &thorn;e cros, right als &thorn;ou tels,<NOTE PLACE="foot">right fehlt. telles.</NOTE></L>
<L>For hele of mans sauls, &amp; for n(o)ght els,<NOTE PLACE="foot">man sawl. for fehlt.</NOTE></L>
<L>And on &thorn;e thrid day ful right vprise &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">third (T. thrid). ful fehlt.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ir wurdes he tolde vs on &thorn;is wise.<NOTE PLACE="foot">wordes said he on.</NOTE></L>
<L N="85">&THORN;arfore I tell &thorn;e in &thorn;is stede</L>
<L>&THORN;at with his will he sufferd dede".<NOTE PLACE="foot">85&mdash;6) fehlen.</NOTE></L>
<L>Egeas &thorn;an thoght grete dispite,<NOTE PLACE="foot">despite.</NOTE></L>
<L>And to saint Andrew said he tite:<NOTE PLACE="foot">&amp; unto him &thorn;us said.</NOTE></L>
<L>"&THORN;ou haues lerid of a symple skole,</L>
<L N="90">&THORN;i preching proues &thorn;i-self a fole:</L>
<L>For &mdash; whethir it war his will or none &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou grauntes &thorn;at he on cros was done<NOTE PLACE="foot">89&mdash;92) fehlen.</NOTE></L>
<L>And hangid he was, als I said are.</L>
<L>And &thorn;arfore leue &thorn;at lurdans lare<NOTE PLACE="foot">93&mdash;94) Bot if &thorn;ou leue &thorn;at lurdans lare, &thorn;at hanged was als I said are.</NOTE></L>
<L N="95">And vnto my goddes offrand make,<NOTE PLACE="foot">ofrand.</NOTE></L>
<L>Or els I sall for &thorn;i god sake<NOTE PLACE="foot">I sall alsone for.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ger hang &thorn;e right on swilk a tre</L>
<L>Als &thorn;ou sais suld so honorde be &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">honord.</NOTE></L>
<L>For fouler dede may no-man haue;</L>
<L N="100">&THORN;arfore on &thorn;e I vouche it saue".<NOTE PLACE="foot">99&mdash;100) fehlen.</NOTE></L>
<L>Saint Andrew &thorn;an with-outen ire</L>
<L>Said: "sertis, &thorn;at es my moste desire,<NOTE PLACE="foot">sertes.</NOTE></L>
<L>I wold be wurthi for his sake<NOTE PLACE="foot">wald. worthi.</NOTE></L>
<L>Opon a cros my dede to take;<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e st. a. mi ded.</NOTE></L>
<L N="105">&THORN;arto euer sal I redi be,<NOTE PLACE="foot">And &thorn;arto. euer fehlt.</NOTE></L>
<L>For any payn &thorn;ou may do me".<NOTE PLACE="foot">paynes,</NOTE></L>
<L>Egeas &thorn;an with grete enuy<NOTE PLACE="foot">full of (T. off) enuy.</NOTE></L>
<L>Sent efter al his turmentry<NOTE PLACE="foot">al fehlt.</NOTE></L>
<L>And bad &thorn;am smertly &thorn;am omang<NOTE PLACE="foot">&amp; bad &thorn;ai suld sone &thorn;am o.</NOTE></L>
<L N="110">Ordan a cros, him forto hang,<NOTE PLACE="foot">ordaine.</NOTE></L>
<L>And fest &thorn;arto both hend and fete,<NOTE PLACE="foot">bath.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at none of &thorn;am with o&thorn;er mete;<NOTE PLACE="foot">&amp; &thorn;at none suld with.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Festes him with none nayles, I rede,</L>
<L>To ger him hastili be so dede,<NOTE PLACE="foot">so fehlt. ded.</NOTE></L>
<L N="115">Bot bindes him to with rapes strang,<NOTE PLACE="foot">bandes st. rapes.</NOTE></L>
<L>So &thorn;at he may be pyned lang!"</L>
<L>To do his biding, war &thorn;ai bayne:<NOTE PLACE="foot">prest st. bayne.</NOTE></L>
<L>A cros &thorn;ai made with al &thorn;aire maine,<NOTE PLACE="foot">fehlen.</NOTE></L>
<L>And handes on him &thorn;an fast &thorn;ai fest &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">and fehlt. ful sone st. &thorn;an fast.</NOTE></L>
<L N="120">To do him payne &thorn;ai war ful prest &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">fehlen.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ai led him thurgh &thorn;at cete<NOTE PLACE="foot">&amp; st. &thorn;ai.</NOTE></L>
<L>To &thorn;e stede whore (he) suld hanget be.<NOTE PLACE="foot">till st. to. whare he. hanged.</NOTE></L>
<L>And al &thorn;e folk &thorn;at dweld &thorn;are obout,<NOTE PLACE="foot">And all &thorn;e folk &thorn;an &thorn;are obout.</NOTE></L>
<L>Gedird togyder in ful grete rout<NOTE PLACE="foot">gederd togeder. ful fehlt. rowt.</NOTE></L>
<L N="125">And al &thorn;us said &thorn;ai &thorn;am omang:</L>
<L>"Allas, &thorn;is wirking es al wrang.<NOTE PLACE="foot">all.</NOTE></L>
<L>What has &thorn;is rightwis man done ill,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &yogh;e on &thorn;is wise will him spill?</L>
<L>&THORN;is nobill man &thorn;at neuer did mis,<NOTE PLACE="foot">nobil (T. nobill).</NOTE></L>
<L N="130">Ful sakles suffers he all &thorn;is,</L>
<L>Ful sakles bese done on rode<NOTE PLACE="foot">bese he.</NOTE></L>
<L>And sakles sall men spill his blode;<NOTE PLACE="foot">sall be spilt.</NOTE></L>
<L>For he has euer bene blith &amp; glad</L>
<L>To mend al men &thorn;at mister had".<NOTE PLACE="foot">133&mdash;4) fehlen.</NOTE></L>
<L N="135">Saint Andrew &thorn;an &thorn;e puple praid<NOTE PLACE="foot">pople.</NOTE></L>
<L>And al &thorn;us vnto &thorn;am he sayd:<NOTE PLACE="foot">all (T. al).</NOTE></L>
<L>"Wendis ogayn, all I &yogh;ow pray,<NOTE PLACE="foot">wen|des.</NOTE></L>
<L>And lettes me noght of ioy &thorn;is day:<NOTE PLACE="foot">lettes noght my ioy.</NOTE></L>
<L>Desturbes noght now mi passioun!<NOTE PLACE="foot">now fehlt. passioune.</NOTE></L>
<L N="140">For vnto blis it makes me boun".<NOTE PLACE="foot">boune.</NOTE></L>
<L>And sone when saint Andrew bihelde</L>
<L>&THORN;e cros bifor him in &thorn;e felde,<NOTE PLACE="foot">on st. in.</NOTE></L>
<L>Vnto god made he his prayere,</L>
<L>And vnto &thorn;e cros on &thorn;is manere<NOTE PLACE="foot">to st. vnto.</NOTE></L>
<L N="145">He cried and sayd with ful high voice:<NOTE PLACE="foot">On hegh he said with full hegh uoyce.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000144.tif" N="6"></L>
<L>"Hayl be &thorn;ou, haly and blisced croyce!<NOTE PLACE="foot">blissed &amp; haly.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at haloud es and euer glorifide<NOTE PLACE="foot">halowd. euer fehlt.</NOTE></L>
<L>With Cristes membris on ilk a side,<NOTE PLACE="foot">membres.</NOTE></L>
<L>And honourd es &thorn;ou with his banes<NOTE PLACE="foot">And blissed es &thorn;ou with.</NOTE></L>
<L N="150">Wele better &thorn;an with precius stanes.<NOTE PLACE="foot">And honord als with (!).</NOTE></L>
<L>With ioyful hert I cum to &thorn;e,<NOTE PLACE="foot">ioyfull.</NOTE></L>
<L>So &thorn;at &thorn;ou gladli resayue me,</L>
<L>Disciple of him with-outen pere,<NOTE PLACE="foot">desiple.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at hanged on &thorn;e, mi mayster dere.</L>
<L N="155">Now es &thorn;ou redi, me on to hang,</L>
<L>&THORN;at I in hert haue couayt lang;<NOTE PLACE="foot">co|uait, 158 couayt.</NOTE></L>
<L>I haue &thorn;e lufde with hert and will<NOTE PLACE="foot">lufed.</NOTE></L>
<L>And couayted euer to cum &thorn;e till".<NOTE PLACE="foot">euer fehlt. forto.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bifor &thorn;e cros &thorn;an knelid (he) doune<NOTE PLACE="foot">knelid he.</NOTE></L>
<L N="160">And &thorn;us he made his orisoune:<NOTE PLACE="foot">ori|sowne.</NOTE></L>
<L>"A, nobil cros of grete bounte,<NOTE PLACE="foot">nobill. gret.</NOTE></L>
<L>Fro erthli men resayue now me<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ou st. now.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &yogh;elde me to my maister gude,<NOTE PLACE="foot">zeld.</NOTE></L>
<L>So &thorn;at he may with mild mode</L>
<L N="165">By &thorn;e resayue me, &thorn;at he wroght,<NOTE PLACE="foot">thurgh st. by.</NOTE></L>
<L>Als he thurgh &thorn;e fro bale me boght.<NOTE PLACE="foot">on st. thurgh.</NOTE></L>
<L>No better bede I haue to byd".</L>
<L>His ouermast clothes &thorn;an of he did,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e turmentours he gun &thorn;am bede</L>
<L N="170">And bad &thorn;ai suld do furth &thorn;aire dede.<NOTE PLACE="foot">167&mdash;170) fehlen.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e turmentours, when &thorn;is was sayde,<NOTE PLACE="foot">said.</NOTE></L>
<L>Toke his bodi with bitter brayde,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Unto sant Andrew bremely braid.</NOTE></L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e cros &thorn;ai gun it bend<NOTE PLACE="foot">And up on &thorn;e. gun fehlt. him.</NOTE></L>
<L>And festid ful fast bothe fete &amp; hend,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&amp; band &thorn;arto both.</NOTE></L>
<L N="175">And all his bodi ful fast &thorn;ai band,<NOTE PLACE="foot">ful fehlt.</NOTE></L>
<L>Als Egeas had &thorn;am comand;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Als it was to &thorn;am cumand,</NOTE></L>
<L>When he was bunden so on brede,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Unto &thorn;e cros ilk lim (ms. him) on brede.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ai lete him hing and home &thorn;ai &yogh;ede.<NOTE PLACE="foot">When &thorn;is was done, away &thorn;ai zede.</NOTE></L>
<L>Folk gederd ful fast him obout<NOTE PLACE="foot">Bot many folk come him o.</NOTE></L>
<L N="180">Of al &thorn;at cuntre &iacute;n grete rout.<NOTE PLACE="foot">all.</NOTE></L>
<L>He held his eghen vp vnto heuin<NOTE PLACE="foot">he lifted. up till &thorn;e heuyn.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;us he sayd with ioyful steuin:</L>
<L>"I se mi lord god and al-weldand,<MILESTONE N="134" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="foot">and fehlt. all.</NOTE></L>
<L>And in his sight now here I stand".<NOTE PLACE="foot">in fehlt.</NOTE></L>
<L N="185">Opon &thorn;e cros &thorn;ore quik he hang<NOTE PLACE="foot">Quilk (!) on &thorn;e cros &thorn;are so he hang.</NOTE></L>
<L>Two days, prechand &thorn;e puple omang;<NOTE PLACE="foot">tow (st. two) daies precheand.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at was ful lang, swilk payn to fele,<NOTE PLACE="foot">slike pain.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bot with Crist was he confort wele.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Bot Crist him confort wonder wele.</NOTE></L>
<L>Twenti thousand folk war &thorn;ore,</L>
<L N="190">To here him preche, with hertes sore.<NOTE PLACE="foot">189&mdash;190) fehlen.</NOTE></L>
<L>When &thorn;e first day till end was went,</L>
<L>Al &thorn;at puple by one assent<NOTE PLACE="foot">All &thorn;e folk. ane.</NOTE></L>
<L>Til Egeas hows fast &thorn;ai ryn<NOTE PLACE="foot">Vntill. fast &thorn;ai fehlt. gan rin.</NOTE></L>
<L>And said: al quik &thorn;ai suld him brin,<NOTE PLACE="foot">And said &thorn;ai suld all quik.</NOTE></L>
<L N="195">Bot if he tite gert tak him doune<NOTE PLACE="foot">doun.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at hanged was ogayns resoune:<NOTE PLACE="foot">resoun.</NOTE></L>
<L>"He es a rightwis man, &thorn;ai say,</L>
<L>And wele has done both night and day;<NOTE PLACE="foot">&amp; wele doand.</NOTE></L>
<L>A gude techer euer has he bene,<NOTE PLACE="foot">And gude t. ay has bene.</NOTE></L>
<L N="200">And more suthfast was neuer sene:<NOTE PLACE="foot">And so swthfast.</NOTE></L>
<L>And swilk a man, sir, for sertayne</L>
<L>Suld noght suffer so hard payne.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Aw noght to suffer swilk payne.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;arfore, bot he be tane doun sone,</L>
<L>In euil tyme &thorn;at dede was done".<NOTE PLACE="foot">Illa haile (!) euer was it done.</NOTE></L>
<L N="205">Egeas dred &thorn;e puple wrake</L>
<L>And doun he hight him forto take,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&amp; doun he said he suld him take.</NOTE></L>
<L>And furth he went with &thorn;am in hi,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ai hasted &thorn;am. hy.</NOTE></L>
<L>Both he and al hys turmentri;<NOTE PLACE="foot">both fehlt. all his.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e folk thrang efter al on a thrum.<NOTE PLACE="foot">&amp; o&thorn;er pople all and sum.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000145.tif" N="7"></L>
<L N="210">And when saint Andrew saw &thorn;am cum,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;aire cumyng he was noght paid,</L>
<L>And vnto Egeas &thorn;us he sayd:<NOTE PLACE="foot">And till.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Wharto cums &thorn;ou vnto me &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">cumes (Ms. cum es).</NOTE></L>
<L>Bot &thorn;ou wald trow in Jhesu fre<NOTE PLACE="foot">If &thorn;ow will.</NOTE></L>
<L N="215">And leue &thorn;i maumetes more &amp; les<NOTE PLACE="foot">mawmettes.</NOTE></L>
<L>And pray to Jhesu of forgifnes?<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;an of god gettes &thorn;ou f.</NOTE></L>
<L>If &thorn;ou will noght on &thorn;is wise do,<NOTE PLACE="foot">And if. sogat st. on &thorn;is wise.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ryn fast, or vengeance cum &thorn;e to!<NOTE PLACE="foot">rin, fast fehlt. uengance.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ou gettes no force ne no fuysoune<NOTE PLACE="foot">For &thorn;ou. no fehlt vor fuisowne.</NOTE></L>
<L N="220">To negh my bodi ne tak it doune;<NOTE PLACE="foot">at st. ne. doun.</NOTE></L>
<L>Mi lord will len to me &thorn;at lane</L>
<L>&THORN;at quik sall I noght doun be tane".<NOTE PLACE="foot">he&thorn;in st. doun.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;an turmenturs with egir mode<NOTE PLACE="foot">turmentoures. eger.</NOTE></L>
<L>Went to him, als &thorn;ai war wode,</L>
<L N="225">&THORN;ai rugget at him with ful grete bir;<NOTE PLACE="foot">And rugged. byr.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bot no-thing might &thorn;ai of (him) stir:<NOTE PLACE="foot">of him.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;aire armes and handes sone in hi,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Bot armes.</NOTE></L>
<L>Als &thorn;ai war herdes, wex &thorn;ai dri;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Right als herdes.</NOTE></L>
<L>Als &thorn;ai kest vp &thorn;aire armes him till,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&amp; als. vp fehlt.</NOTE></L>
<L N="230">Als dry stykkes &thorn;an stode &thorn;ai still.<NOTE PLACE="foot">dri stikkes. &thorn;ai stode so still.</NOTE></L>
<L>Saint Andrew &thorn;an made his prayere,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Androw.</NOTE></L>
<L>To mighty god on &thorn;is manere<NOTE PLACE="foot">Vnto god.</NOTE></L>
<L>He said: "lord, if it be &thorn;i will,<NOTE PLACE="foot">And said.</NOTE></L>
<L>In &thorn;is stede lat me hing still,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at I st. lat me.</NOTE></L>
<L N="235">&THORN;at none haue power me to fell</L>
<L>Doun of &thorn;is cros &thorn;at I on dwell,<NOTE PLACE="foot">doun fehlt. fro st. of.</NOTE></L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;at tyme &thorn;i-self vouche saue<NOTE PLACE="foot">Untill time &thorn;at. vowche.</NOTE></L>
<L>To &thorn;e blis of heuin me forto haue;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Vnto &thorn;i blis me.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bot lat me hing still, als I do,<NOTE PLACE="foot">bot fehlt. here als.</NOTE></L>
<L N="240">Til-tyme &thorn;ou tak mi saul &thorn;e to!"<NOTE PLACE="foot">Untill. tyme fehlt. my gaste.</NOTE></L>
<L>When &thorn;is was said, &thorn;ar come a light<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;are.</NOTE></L>
<L>Doun fro &thorn;e heuyn with bemis bright<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e fehlt.</NOTE></L>
<L>And vmbilappid his bodi about.<NOTE PLACE="foot">(T. vmbilapped). obout.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e folk &thorn;arfore had mekil dout,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;arfore &thorn;e folk. mekill.</NOTE></L>
<L N="245">&THORN;ai might noght luke for mekil light</L>
<L>Vnto his bodi: so was it bright.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Vntill.</NOTE></L>
<L>And als &thorn;e light was al&thorn;ir-maste,<NOTE PLACE="foot">all&thorn;er.</NOTE></L>
<L>To god in heuyn he gaf &thorn;e gaste.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Vnto. in heuyn fehlt.</NOTE></L>
<L>Egeas was ful dredand &thorn;an</L>
<L N="250">And for ferde fast home he ran.</L>
<L>Bot in &thorn;e way, or he come hame,</L>
<L>He sufferd ded with mykel schame:</L>
<L>So sudan sorous war to him sent:</L>
<L>Als wurthi was, to wo he went.<NOTE PLACE="foot">249&mdash;254) fehlen.</NOTE></L>
<L N="255">Saint Andrew saul with angell steuyn</L>
<L>And with &thorn;at light was lifted to heuyn,<NOTE PLACE="foot">255&mdash;6) And with &thorn;at light &amp; an|gell steuyn His (saule) was tane to blis of heuyn. Darauf folgen als Schlussverse: Vntill &thorn;at ilk blis bring us he, &thorn;at boght us dere opon &thorn;e tre, Thurgh bisekeing and prayere Of saint Andrew &thorn;e appostel dere. &mdash;</NOTE></L>
<L>Whore he lendes in ay lastand blis.</L>
<L>Al-weldand god &thorn;eder us wis!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="260">Egeas had a wurthli wife,</L>
<L>&THORN;at lufed saint Andrew in his life;</L>
<L>For him scho ordand a monument</L>
<L>And berid his bodi with trew entent.</L>
<L>And of his graue, als men might se,</L>
<L N="265">Sprang vp oyle ful fayre plente,</L>
<L>&THORN;at medcyn was to more and les</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;eder soght for sere sekenes.</L>
<L>And by &thorn;at oyl, als says &thorn;e buke,</L>
<L>Al &thorn;at cuntre ensaumple toke:</L>
<L N="270">For, when it sprang on sides sere,</L>
<L>&THORN;an hopid &thorn;ai forto haue gude &yogh;ere</L>
<L>Of corn and fruyt and o&thorn;er thing;</L>
<L>And, when &thorn;ai saw it skarsli spring,</L>
<L>&THORN;an hopid &thorn;ai to haue skant of corn</L>
<L N="275">And of fruyt. als I sayd biforn,</L>
<L>Who so saynt Andrew lufes in lede,</L>
<L>He may noght mis forto haue mede;</L>
<L>For fro al harmes he haldes &thorn;am hale,</L>
<L>Als men may here tell by a tale.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="section"><PB REF="00000146.tif" N="8">
<HEAD>Quomodo s. Andreas vicit diabolum.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A nobil bisschop, als we rede,</L>
<L N="280">In halines his life gun lede.</L>
<L>He lufed saint Andrew al his life</L>
<L>And euer he vsid &thorn;is reson rife:</L>
<L>In al &thorn;e dedis &thorn;at he su(l)d do,</L>
<L>&THORN;us said he, when he went &thorn;arto:</L>
<L N="285">"&THORN;is werk here I bigyn to schew</L>
<L>In &thorn;e name of god and saint Andrew".</L>
<L>&THORN;us vsid he euir in all hys dede:</L>
<L>So hopid he his werk suld wele spede &mdash;</L>
<L>In saint Andrew he had swilk trist;</L>
<L N="290">And of &thorn;at merk no-thing he myst.</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;an &thorn;e fende, oure enmy,</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;at bisschop had grete enuy;</L>
<L>For he to god hys hert had sett,</L>
<L>He did his force &thorn;at life lett:</L>
<L N="295">He assayd him with moni a syn.</L>
<L>Bot on none wise he might him wyn.</L>
<L>Til al &thorn;e last he wroght a wile</L>
<L>With lusty luf hym to bigyle.</L>
<L>To ger hym fall in foul lichery,</L>
<L N="300">He schop hym to be like a fayre lady,</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e bisschops palays hastid he</L>
<L>And said &thorn;at he wold schriuen be.</L>
<L>&THORN;e bisschoppes men&yogh;e gun him tell</L>
<L>How &thorn;ore was cumen a damysell,</L>
<L N="305">&THORN;e fairest &thorn;at &thorn;ai bifore had sene,</L>
<L>And said scho wold be schreuen clene.</L>
<L>When &thorn;e bisschop &thorn;is tale had herd,</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;o men &thorn;us he answerd:</L>
<L>"Gose, ledes hir to mi penitancere!</L>
<L N="310">For of me has he playn powere".</L>
<L>Bot when &thorn;e ladi herd &thorn;is tale,</L>
<L>Scho sayd: "for suth, I neuer sale</L>
<L>Reherce how &thorn;at I am gylty</L>
<L>Bot to &thorn;e bisschoppes awyn body;</L>
<L N="315">I haue in hert swilk priuete:</L>
<L>I will none wit bot god and he".</L>
<L>&THORN;us when &thorn;e bisschop wist hir will,</L>
<L>He bad scho suld be broght him till.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai broght hir furth &thorn;an him bifore.</L>
<L N="320">And ful mekely, when scho com &thorn;ore,</L>
<L>Doun scho knelid bifor his kne</L>
<L>And sayd: "lord, haue mercy on me</L>
<L>And here my tales all vntil ende!"</L>
<L>He wist noght &thorn;at it was &thorn;e fende,</L>
<L N="325">"Tel on, he sayd, my doghter dere,</L>
<L>&THORN;i hert all halely vnto me now here!</L>
<L>I sall &thorn;e here euer-ilka thing</L>
<L>And counsayl &thorn;e efter my cunyng".</L>
<L>"Sir, scho sayd, all-if &yogh;e now se</L>
<L N="330">I am pouer and in pilgrym degre,</L>
<L>Cumen I am of kyng and quene</L>
<L>And in grete bewtes haue I bene</L>
<L>And fosterd furth full tendirly &mdash;</L>
<L>Of tender eld als &yogh;it am I.</L>
<L N="335">Bot neuer-&thorn;e-lese in all mi &yogh;owth</L>
<L>Ay wirschip Crist ful wele I kouth.</L>
<L>And when I past out of barnhede,</L>
<L>&THORN;e king, my fader, gun me bede</L>
<L>&THORN;at a riche prince suld me wed.</L>
<L N="340">And &thorn;an I was full sore adred</L>
<L>&THORN;at my lord Crist suld be euyl payd,</L>
<L>And vnto my fader &thorn;us I sayd:</L>
<L>&THORN;at erthli husband wald I none,</L>
<L>For vnto Crist I had me tone,</L>
<L N="345">'Vnto him haue I hertly hight</L>
<L>To kepe me clene both day &amp; night;</L>
<L>&THORN;arfore none o&thorn;er may I take,</L>
<L>For his lufe sal I neuer forsake'".</L>
<L>When mi fader herd me so say,</L>
<L N="350">Ful wroth he went fro me oway,</L>
<L>He said I suld wirk at his will</L>
<L>Or els be puted vnto paynes ill.</L>
<L>&THORN;an in my hert I toke &thorn;is thoght:</L>
<L>&THORN;at leuyr me war in bale be broght,</L>
<L N="355">In wildernes al-way to wake,</L>
<L>&THORN;an Crist, my spous, forto forsake.</L>
<L>Oway I went &thorn;an so priuely,</L>
<L>&THORN;at no-man wist bot god and I.</L>
<L>Sethin, haly fader, suth it es,</L>
<L N="360">I haue herd of youre halines,</L>
<L>How &yogh;e er blith, and euir has bene,</L>
<L>To confort &thorn;am &thorn;at kepis &thorn;am clene.</L>
<L>&THORN;arfore I thoght: and I might wyn</L>
<L>Vnder &yogh;oure ward and wun &thorn;arin,</L>
<L N="365">&THORN;an suld I liff in rest and ese,</L>
<L>With gude prayers my god to plese,</L>
<L>And so forsake &thorn;is werldely liue</L>
<L>And lere condicions contemplatiue".</L>
<L>When &thorn;e bisschop herd &thorn;ir wordes wise,
<PB REF="00000147.tif" N="9"></L>
<L N="370">Ful gretely gun he him auyse;</L>
<L>First he meruayled in his minde</L>
<L>How scho was cumen of gentil kinde,</L>
<L>And how scho was of tender eld,</L>
<L>Had so clere wit, at will to welde,<MILESTONE N="135" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="375">And &thorn;at scho was namore adred</L>
<L>In vnkuth stede forto be sted.</L>
<L>Ful mekely &thorn;an vnto hir he said:</L>
<L>"Mi doghter dere, be noght affrayd!</L>
<L>&THORN;e spous &thorn;at &thorn;ou has tane &thorn;e to,</L>
<L N="380">Will gif &thorn;e grace ay wele to do;</L>
<L>Fro erthli folis he will &thorn;e fend</L>
<L>And gif &thorn;e blis with-outen end.</L>
<L>And I, als a seruand of his.</L>
<L>Grauntes me to wirk als &thorn;ou will wis!</L>
<L N="385">Here sall be no-thing &thorn;e to greue &mdash;</L>
<L>Lend, whils &thorn;e list &mdash; I gif &thorn;e leue.</L>
<L>And this day sall &thorn;ou with me ete,</L>
<L>More of &thorn;is mater forto trete."</L>
<L>&THORN;e fende answerd and (said): "sir, nay,</L>
<L N="390">Bid me noght ett with &thorn;e &thorn;is day,</L>
<L>Lat me ett els whore so &thorn;ou will, &mdash;</L>
<L>For drede of sum suspecion of ill</L>
<L>With sum might (haue) so bisene,<NOTE PLACE="foot">der Vers ist verderbt; haue ist zu erg&auml;nzen?</NOTE></L>
<L>Wold haue suspecion vs bitwene &mdash;</L>
<L N="395">And &thorn;at war litel force for me,</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;e halines, fader, of yowre pouste".</L>
<L>&THORN;an said &thorn;e bisschop: "caus es &thorn;at none.</L>
<L>We sal noght be bi us-self allone,</L>
<L>&THORN;ar sall be o&thorn;er inowe at none".</L>
<L N="400">&THORN;an sayd sho: "sir, &yogh;owre will be done".</L>
<L>&THORN;an wesch &thorn;ai sone and went to mete.</L>
<L>Bifor him-self was made hir sete.</L>
<L>&THORN;e bisschop ay hertly hir bihelde &mdash;</L>
<L>Him thoght hir faire als floure in felde;</L>
<L N="405">So swete him thoght both cheke &amp; chin,</L>
<L>&THORN;at lust wounded his hert within.</L>
<L>&THORN;e fende defigurd him fayre &thorn;arfore,</L>
<L>To wound his hert ay more &amp; more.</L>
<L>So hertly he byheld hir face,</L>
<L N="410">&THORN;at he thoght: when he might (haue) space</L>
<L>To haue &thorn;at woman at his will,</L>
<L>&THORN;e wretchid werk he wold fulfill.</L>
<L>Bot saint Andrew, his faithful frend,</L>
<L>Saw he was ouer-sett with &thorn;e fend.</L>
<L N="415">He putted him in a palmer state,</L>
<L>And come vnto &thorn;e bisschop &yogh;ate,</L>
<L>And on &thorn;e &yogh;ate fast knokkid he</L>
<L>And asked almus par charite,</L>
<L>And of &thorn;e bisschop gun he craue</L>
<L N="420">&THORN;at day in &thorn;e hall his mete to haue.</L>
<L>Sanctus Andreas erat peregrinus.</L>
<L>&THORN;e porter told &thorn;e lord in his sete</L>
<L>How swilk a palmer askid him mete,</L>
<L>And askid if he suld him in lat.</L>
<L>&THORN;e lady answerd vnto &thorn;at,</L>
<L N="425">Scho sayd: "sir, if it be &yogh;oure will,</L>
<L>I rede we proue him by sum skill.</L>
<L>Palmers walkes both fer and nere,</L>
<L>Sum questioun we will enquere;</L>
<L>And if he answer wele vnto all,</L>
<L N="430">&THORN;an es he wurthi to ette in hall".</L>
<L>&THORN;e bisschop answerd &thorn;us &thorn;arto:</L>
<L>"Damysell, &thorn;at can &yogh;e best do.</L>
<L>Says, what &yogh;e will, to him in hy!"</L>
<L>Scho sayd: "Igraunt, sir; graunt mercy!"</L>
<L N="435">&THORN;e porter, bad scho, suld be boune</L>
<L>And ask of &thorn;e palmer &thorn;is resoune:</L>
<L>Of all &thorn;is werld in litel space</L>
<L>Whore god has scheud most might &amp; grace?</L>
<L>&THORN;e porter with &thorn;is message went</L>
<L N="440">And said &thorn;e palmer how he was sent</L>
<L>&THORN;is questioun forto enquere.</L>
<L>And he answerd on &thorn;is manere:</L>
<L>"Sir, sen &thorn;is werld was first bygun,</L>
<L>A mans face was neuer &yogh;it fun</L>
<L N="445">Like to a-nother in al making.</L>
<L>&THORN;arfore I say in so litill thing</L>
<L>Has god noght schewd slike might &amp; grace</L>
<L>Als he has schewd in a mans face.</L>
<L>&THORN;e space es litil forto discryue,</L>
<L N="450">And &thorn;orein er &thorn;e wittes fyue</L>
<L>&THORN;at rewles all a mans lifing here.</L>
<L>Go, tell &thorn;i lord on &thorn;is manere!"</L>
<L>&THORN;e porter went &amp; tald &thorn;us all.</L>
<L>&THORN;an al &thorn;e folk within &thorn;at hall</L>
<L N="455">Sayd &thorn;at &thorn;e palme(r) answerd ful wele;</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;e deuyll likid yt no dele.</L>
<L>&THORN;e bisschop sayd: "lo, dere damysell,</L>
<L>Will &yogh;e oght els vnto him tell?"</L>
<L>Scho sayd: "syr, &yogh;a; and &yogh;e vouche saue,
<PB REF="00000148.tif" N="10"></L>
<L N="460">A harder question now sal he haue</L>
<L>And more maystry, if &thorn;at I may:</L>
<L>So sall we best his wit assay.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. euyn.</NOTE></L>
<L>Go, bid hym here vnto vs (n)euyn</L>
<L>Whore &thorn;e erth es hegher &thorn;an &thorn;e heuyn?"</L>
<L N="465">&THORN;e porter went and told &thorn;is tale.</L>
<L>&THORN;e palmer answerd with wurdes hale:</L>
<L>"Go, say &thorn;i lord he suld haue mynde</L>
<L>How Crist in erth he toke mans kynd.</L>
<L>He lightid in a mayden mylde,</L>
<L N="470">And fleschly was scho neuer filde;</L>
<L>Of hyr bodi he wold be born,</L>
<L>And of erth was scho made biforn.</L>
<L>Se&thorn;in Crist vp vnto heuyn ascend</L>
<L>With mans kinde, als wele es kend:</L>
<L N="475">Mans kinde so made of erth &amp; clay</L>
<L>In Cristes auwen person wuns al-way.</L>
<L>In his persoun so may we neuyn</L>
<L>&THORN;e erth es hegher &thorn;an any heuyn</L>
<L>Go, say &thorn;i lord &thorn;us in &thorn;is manere!"</L>
<L N="480">&THORN;e porter went with ful gude chere,</L>
<L>He rehercyd vnto &yogh;ong and olde</L>
<L>Euyn als &thorn;e palmer had him tolde.</L>
<L>And al &thorn;ai said, als &thorn;ai gun fit,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e palmer was parfite in wit</L>
<L N="485">And &thorn;at he was wurthi to prais.</L>
<L>&THORN;an &thorn;e woman to &thorn;e porter says:</L>
<L>"&THORN;e thrid thing sal &thorn;ou bid him do;</L>
<L>And if he answer wele &thorn;arto,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou sall haue leue to bring him ner</L>
<L N="490">And noman sall oppose him fer.</L>
<L>Aske him: how fer &thorn;e space es set</L>
<L>Fro heuyn to erth, by mesure mett?</L>
<L>And if he now &thorn;e maystri gete,</L>
<L>&THORN;an baldly bring him in to mete!"</L>
<L N="495">&THORN;e porter went and told ilk dele,</L>
<L>And sayd: "syr, if &thorn;ou now say wele,</L>
<L>&THORN;i mete for &thorn;is sal &thorn;ou haue</L>
<L>And no-man sall more of &thorn;e craue</L>
<L>No-thing, bot tel &thorn;am &thorn;is resoun,</L>
<L N="500">&THORN;e space fro heuyn till erth here doun".</L>
<L>&THORN;e palmer said: "&thorn;is sall be kend</L>
<L>Of &thorn;am self &thorn;at &thorn;e heder send:</L>
<L>It es a deuil &thorn;at sittes byfore</L>
<L>In wedis als it a woman wore;</L>
<L N="505">Go, tell vnto him hardily</L>
<L>He knawes &thorn;e space better &thorn;an I,</L>
<L>For he fel doun fro heuyn to hell &mdash;</L>
<L>And doun fro heuyn &yogh;it neuer I fell;</L>
<L>&THORN;e space fro heuyn wele may he ges,</L>
<L N="510">For he has mett how mekil it es.</L>
<L>Go, sai him &thorn;us with sembland sad!"</L>
<L>&THORN;an was &thorn;e porter wunder rad;</L>
<L>Bot neuer-&thorn;e-les &yogh;it went he in</L>
<L>And told &thorn;is tale to more &amp; myn.</L>
<L N="515">Al war awunderd &thorn;at it herd.</L>
<L>And when &thorn;e fende saw how it ferd,</L>
<L>He made grete noys omang &thorn;am all</L>
<L>And bare oway half of &thorn;e hall.</L>
<L>&THORN;an had &thorn;e bisschop mekill wo</L>
<L N="520">And sorow, for he assentyd so</L>
<L>With foul syn his saul to schende</L>
<L>Thurgh fals fanding so of &thorn;e fende</L>
<L>Efter &thorn;e palmer ful sone he sent;</L>
<L>Bot noman wist whore he was went.</L>
<L N="525">&THORN;e bisschop was &thorn;an ful wo for&thorn;i,</L>
<L>And sune he gert samyn his clergi,</L>
<L>He chargid al folk to fast and pray</L>
<L>And do penaunce both night &amp; day,</L>
<L>&THORN;at god his grace to sum wold send:</L>
<L N="530">So &thorn;at &thorn;e palmer might be kend</L>
<L>&THORN;at to &thorn;e deuyl had done swilk gref</L>
<L>And helpid out of &thorn;at mischef.</L>
<L>On &thorn;e night in vision warnid he was</L>
<L>How saint Andrew him helpid has.</L>
<L N="535">&THORN;an loued he god with wurdes hend</L>
<L>And thankid saint Andrew, his frende.</L>
<L>And on &thorn;e morn he told &thorn;is thing</L>
<L>Al opynli vnto olde and &yogh;ing.</L>
<L>Saynt Andrew wirschiped he euermore</L>
<L N="540">More derely &thorn;an euer he did bifore,</L>
<L>And lifed and endid in goddes seruise.</L>
<L>God graunt vs to wirk on swilk wise!
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="2" TYPE="legend"><PB REF="00000149.tif" N="11">
<HEAD>2. Hic incipit historia de s. Nicholao episcopo.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Die Leg. von Nicholaus steht im Ms. Tib. hinten nach Andreas, fol. 278 b, mit im Einzelnen oft abweichendem Text. Folgen die Varianten:</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Saint Nicholas, &thorn;e nobil clerk,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at st. &thorn;e.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at witti was in goddes werk,</L>
<L>In his barnhede by resons rife</L>
<L>Bygan he to lede haly life.<NOTE PLACE="foot">3&mdash;4) In his barnhed he bigan Forto be an hali man.</NOTE></L>
<L N="5">&THORN;at was wele witnest by his dede:</L>
<L>For in his stori may men rede<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;us we st. may men.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at of none o&thorn;er find we swilk:</L>
<L>For, whils he souked his moder milk,<NOTE PLACE="foot">sowked.</NOTE></L>
<L>Noght-withstanding &thorn;at he was &yogh;ing,<NOTE PLACE="foot">noghtwithstandand.</NOTE></L>
<L N="10">He chastyd his flesch with fasting,<NOTE PLACE="foot">chastist. fless.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e ferth fery and &thorn;e sext alway</L>
<L>Souked bot ones on al &thorn;e day &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><P>11&mdash;12) For two dayes in euerilk a woke Bot anes on &thorn;e day milk he toke. Hier schliesst fol. 278 und es fehlt im Ms. ein fol.</P><P>Das folg. Blatt im Ms. Tib., dessen erste Verse ganz zerst&ouml;rt sind, ist nur theilweise zu entziffern, selbst in der ersten Columne; lesbar sind die Versenden von 229&mdash;249, der gr&ouml;sste Theil der Verse von 250&mdash;270; dann beginnt die 2<SUP>te</SUP> Columne, von der nur Versanf&auml;nge deutlich sind. Von V. 12&mdash;229 z&auml;hlte Ms. Tib. 16 Verse weniger.</P></NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at es wedynsday and frydai ilka wuke &mdash;</L>
<L>In his barnhed &mdash; &thorn;us tels &thorn;e boke.</L>
<L N="15">Cumen he was of kinred gude</L>
<L>And gendred of ful gentill blode;</L>
<L>Bot more gentill war his maners,</L>
<L>Als his lessons vnto vs lers &mdash;</L>
<L>For so with fasting in his &yogh;owth</L>
<L N="20">Ful his flessch ful wele he couth.</L>
<L>In &yogh;outh to halines &thorn;us gun he helde.</L>
<L>And when (he) wex more furth in elde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he kouth speke &amp; graythly gang:</L>
<L>&THORN;an he refuysed al werkis wrang;</L>
<L N="25">He forsoke cumpany of schrews</L>
<L>And gaf him al vnto gude thews.</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e scoles he went ful tentyuely,</L>
<L>Till he had clere knawing in clergy.</L>
<L>Sethen haunted he fast to hali kirk,</L>
<L N="30">With will, goddes werk alway to wirk.</L>
<L>Sethin was he chosen, whils he was &yogh;ing,</L>
<L>Thurgh &thorn;e haly gastes ordaynyng</L>
<L>To be bisschop of &thorn;at same cete</L>
<L>Whilk in &thorn;at tyme was namyd Myrre.</L>
<L N="35">For, when &thorn;aire bisschop &thorn;ore was ded,</L>
<L>Sere bisschopes come vnto stede,</L>
<L>&THORN;ore forto chese &thorn;am an abyll man,</L>
<L>Als custum in &thorn;at cuntre was &thorn;an.</L>
<L>When &thorn;ai gederd ilkone in-fere,</L>
<L N="40">Vnto god made &thorn;ai &thorn;aire prayere</L>
<L>&THORN;at he suld send &thorn;am grace, forto haue</L>
<L>Swilk a man als he vouched saue,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at &thorn;ai suld by sum signe se</L>
<L>Whom he wold chese to &thorn;at degre.</L>
<L N="45">And so als &thorn;ai woke on &thorn;e night,</L>
<L>A voyce was sent fro heuyn right</L>
<L>Vnto a bisschop of grete pryse</L>
<L>And sayd vnto him on &thorn;is wise:</L>
<L>"&thorn;e first man &thorn;at &thorn;ou metes to morn</L>
<L N="50">In kirk-&yogh;erd euyn &thorn;e byforn,</L>
<L>To &yogh;oure bisschop sal &yogh;e chese &thorn;at same,</L>
<L>And Nicholas sal be his name".</L>
<L>Sune on &thorn;e morn, when it was day,</L>
<L>Furth of &thorn;e kirk he toke &thorn;e way</L>
<L N="55">And lukid furth into &thorn;e strete</L>
<L>Efter &thorn;e man &thorn;at he suld mete.</L>
<L>So sese he cum a ful fayre childe,</L>
<L>He haylsid him with wurdes milde:</L>
<L>"&THORN;i right name, gude sun, tel &thorn;o(u) me!"</L>
<L N="60">"Mi name es Nicholas, sir, sayd he,</L>
<L>&YOGH;owre seruand, and (I) might oght mend".</L>
<L>&THORN;an &thorn;e bisschop halsyd him with his hend &mdash;</L>
<L>For als sone als he herd his name,</L>
<L>&THORN;an wist he wele, &thorn;at was &thorn;e same</L>
<L N="65">&THORN;at god had chosen to &thorn;at degre</L>
<L>&THORN;aire bisschop in &thorn;at stede to be;</L>
<L>&THORN;at it was he, ful wele he wist,</L>
<L>He toke hym vp in armes &amp; kyst,</L>
<L>Into &thorn;e mynster so he hym bare
<PB REF="00000150.tif" N="12"></L>
<L N="70">Whore o&thorn;er bisschoppes bidand ware.</L>
<L>He sayd to &thorn;am with wurdes balde</L>
<L>How &thorn;e haly gaste to him had talde</L>
<L>And how &thorn;at night warned was he</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;is barn suld &thorn;aire bisschop be.</L>
<L N="75">&THORN;us was he made bisschop in barnhed. &mdash;</L>
<L>And &yogh;it in mynde of &thorn;att ilk dede</L>
<L>Men vses in diuers cuntres sere</L>
<L>To chese barn-bisschops ilka &yogh;ere. &mdash;</L>
<L>Ful wele (he) rewlid his bisschop-rike &mdash;</L>
<L N="80">Bifor his tyme had none bene slike.</L>
<L>Euer of &thorn;e pouer he had pete,</L>
<L>And al &thorn;at nede had helpyd he.</L>
<L>And left hym was ful grete riches</L>
<L>Efter his fader and moder disses.</L>
<L N="85">He prayd god euer him forto send</L>
<L>His grace, &thorn;at gude wele forto spend,</L>
<L>Noght for no ruse of erthli thing,</L>
<L>Bot allone vnto goddes louyng;</L>
<L>And night and day he had in mynde</L>
<L N="90">&THORN;ir wurdes, &thorn;at we &thorn;us writen finde,</L>
<L>Whilk Crist says in his godspell</L>
<L>And er in latyn &thorn;us to tell:</L>
<L>Nisi quis renunciauerit omnia que possi|det, non potest meus esse discipulus:</L>
<L>Bot if a man forsake, he says,</L>
<L>Welth of &thorn;is werldly gude alway</L>
<L N="95">And lif in luf and charite,</L>
<L>Els my disciple may he noght be.</L>
<L>&THORN;arfore &thorn;is gudman Nicholas</L>
<L>Vnto god euir prayand was</L>
<L>&THORN;at he suld send him hert &amp; will</L>
<L N="100">&THORN;e gudes &thorn;at he had gifen him till,</L>
<L>Forto spend &thorn;am leli and right</L>
<L>With-outen louyng of mans sight.</L>
<L>And in &thorn;at same maner he did,</L>
<L>His almus fro mans sight he hid:</L>
<L N="105">Als wele was schewd by maidens thre</L>
<L>&THORN;at thurgh him come till gude degre.</L>
<L>&THORN;aire fader was mighty man sumtyme,</L>
<L>And pouert sethin fell vnto him,</L>
<L>&THORN;at n(o)ght he had to find him fode</L>
<L N="110">Ne his thre doghters, milde of mode.</L>
<L>And in dole so on a day</L>
<L>Vnto his doghters gun he say:</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;am bihoued bordell bigin</L>
<L>And lede &thorn;aire life in lust of syn,</L>
<L N="115">To find him &amp; &thorn;am mete and drink &mdash;</L>
<L>For o&thorn;er-wise kouth &thorn;ai noght swink.</L>
<L>Saint Nicholas herd tell of &thorn;is:</L>
<L>How &thorn;ir maydens suld do omis</L>
<L>Forto find &thorn;aire fader fode,</L>
<L N="120">&amp; all for defaut of erthly gude.</L>
<L>To &thorn;at mans hows he toke &thorn;e gate</L>
<L>Preuely by night, &thorn;at no-man wate,</L>
<L>A bag with gold with him he toke;</L>
<L>And whore &thorn;ir maydins wepeand woke</L>
<L N="125">And kepid &thorn;aire fader with grete care,</L>
<L>All &thorn;at gold he putted in &thorn;are<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. &amp; all.</NOTE></L>
<L>Euyn biside &thorn;a(i)re fader bedd,</L>
<L>And preuely oway he fledd.</L>
<L>&THORN;aire fader, when he fand &thorn;is thing,</L>
<L N="130">Vnto god made he grete louyng;</L>
<L>And on &thorn;e morn sune ordand he</L>
<L>To mary one of &thorn;e maydens thre;</L>
<L>&THORN;e eldist first was helpid to hame.</L>
<L>And for &thorn;e secund he did &thorn;e same,</L>
<L N="135">And &thorn;e thrid tyme he broght al-so</L>
<L>Als mikel als till &thorn;e o&thorn;er two.</L>
<L>And out of care so couerd he</L>
<L>&THORN;e fader and maydins thre.</L>
<L>And al &thorn;at he herd in swilk case,</L>
<L N="140">Ful hertly helpyd &thorn;am he hase &mdash;</L>
<L>And all he did euer so priuely,</L>
<L>&THORN;at none wist bot god almighty. &mdash;</L>
<L>Other vertus ful mony and sere</L>
<L>War wroght by him in &thorn;is werld here.</L>
<L N="145">And in &thorn;is tyme sum will we tell.</L>
<L>Oft-sithes, opon &thorn;e see bifell</L>
<L>&THORN;at mony men fro perils sere</L>
<L>War helpid thurgh his prayere.</L>
<L>With stormes ones men had swilk str(i)fe</L>
<L N="150">&THORN;at &thorn;ai trowed titter dede &thorn;an life.</L>
