<L>And sone efter so it bifell:</L>
<L>Theues had ordand &thorn;am &thorn;arfore</L>
<L>And stale oway all his tresore,</L>
<L N="425">His iewels toke &thorn;ai euer - ilkone,</L>
<L>And left &thorn;e image &thorn;ore allone.</L>
<L>&THORN;e iew come home &thorn;at o&thorn;er day</L>
<L>And fand al robbid on euyl aray</L>
<L>To &thorn;e image he went with bitter brayd</L>
<L N="430">And on &thorn;is wise &thorn;arto he sayd;</L>
<L>"Nicholas, say, left I noght &thorn;e</L>
<L>To kepe my gudes saueli to me,</L>
<L>Als man, I leuid for trew and lele?</L>
<L>Whi haues &thorn;ou sufferd theues it stele?</L>
<L N="435">&THORN;ou haues done to me vntreuly:<NOTE PLACE="foot">s in haues ist von and. Hand zugesetzt.</NOTE></L>
<L>I sal be vengid on &thorn;e for&thorn;i,</L>
<L>It sal be boght with bitter payne,</L>
<L>Bot if &thorn;ou get my gude ogayne".</L>
<L>He bet &thorn;e image, when he was greuid,</L>
<L N="440">Trowand so to be releuyd,</L>
<L>Of his gudes to haue restoring.</L>
<L>And so bifell a ferly thing:</L>
<L>Als &thorn;e theuis in certayn tyde</L>
<L>Partid &thorn;aire pelf bi a wud side,</L>
<L N="445">Saynt Nicholas to &thorn;am aperd</L>
<L>Als he had bene bet with a &yogh;erd,</L>
<L>And vnto &thorn;am al &thorn;us he said:</L>
<L>"For &yogh;ow am I &thorn;us euyll arayd,</L>
<L>For &yogh;e haue wr(o)ght &thorn;e werkis wrang</L>
<L N="450">Wharfore I suffer paynes strang.</L>
<L>And bot &yogh;e wil wightly bere ogayne</L>
<L>&THORN;e gudes &thorn;at &yogh;e haue tane with trayne,</L>
<L>Goddes vengeance sal on &yogh;ow be tone</L>
<L>And hangid sal &yogh;e be euerilkone".</L>
<L N="455">&THORN;an war &thorn;ai ferde and answerd &thorn;us:</L>
<L>"What ertow &thorn;at sais so till us?"</L>
<L>He said &thorn;an: "&yogh;e sall wele vnterstand:</L>
<L>I am Nicholas, Jhesu Crist seruand,</L>
<L>Vnto wham &thorn;e iew bitoke his gude.</L>
<L N="460">&THORN;us haues he bet me, sen &yogh;e &yogh;ode".</L>
<L>For &thorn;ir wurdes war &thorn;e theuis so rad,</L>
<L>&THORN;at al &thorn;e gudes ogayn &thorn;ai had.</L>
<L>And vnto &thorn;e iew &thorn;ai told &thorn;aire thoght,</L>
<L>And he told &thorn;am how he had wroght</L>
<L N="465">With &thorn;e image, and all &thorn;e case.</L>
<L>And al &thorn;ai loued saynt Nicholas.</L>
<L>&THORN;e theues bicome gude cristin men,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e iew was cristend &thorn;en,</L>
<L>And al &thorn;ai endid in goddes seruyse &mdash;</L>
<L N="470">God graunt us to end on swilk wise!
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="3" TYPE="legend"><PB REF="00000155.tif" N="17">
<HEAD>3. De s. Lucia virgine historia<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Lucia fehlt im Ms. Tib., da auf Nicolas sofort Thomas folgt; sie geh&ouml;rt nicht zur Sammlung des Ms. Tib.</NOTE>).</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Saynt Lucy, &thorn;e maiden clene &amp; gude,</L>
<L>Was getyn and born of gentil blude;</L>
<L>Hir fader was a man mekill of might,</L>
<L>And Eutycia hyr moder hyght.</L>
<L N="5">Foure &yogh;ere ful grete sekenes scho had:</L>
<L>In flux of blode so was scho stad;</L>
<L>To sere sides oft - sithes scho send</L>
<L>And fand no medcyn hir might mend.</L>
<L>Hir doghter Lucy &thorn;an herd wele tell</L>
<L N="10">Of saint Aga&yogh; how it byfell,</L>
<L>How grete vertues war for hir wr(o)ght.</L>
<L>And with hir moder &thorn;eder scho soght.</L>
<L>When &thorn;ai come to saynt Aga&yogh; graue,</L>
<L>For help ful hertly gun &thorn;ai craue.</L>
<L N="15">So on a day als &thorn;ai herd mes</L>
<L>Whore in a godspell wryten es</L>
<L>How oure lord Crist a woman helid</L>
<L>Of sw(i)lk sekenes als scho with deld:</L>
<L>Saynt Lucy said: "moder, takes hede</L>
<L N="20">And trewly trous &thorn;is &thorn;at &thorn;ai rede;</L>
<L>And &thorn;at saint Agace of god mai haue</L>
<L>What thing so scho will efter craue.</L>
<L>And trewly if &yogh;e trow &thorn;is tale</L>
<L>And touche hir toumb, &yogh;e sal be hale".</L>
<L N="25">Hyr moder sayd: "I trow right wele</L>
<L>&THORN;at it be suth euer - ilkadele".</L>
<L>So in &thorn;aire praiers als &thorn;ai dwell,</L>
<L>Saint Lucy &thorn;ore on sleping fell.</L>
<L>Hir thoght sune &thorn;at scho saw in sight</L>
<L N="30">Saynt Aga&yogh;e omang angels bright,</L>
<L>In schineand wede scho was arayd,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ir wurdes vnto hir scho said:</L>
<L>"Mi sister Luci, mak gude chere,</L>
<L>For vnto god ertou ful dere.</L>
<L N="35">Why askes (&thorn;ou) swilk thing of me<NOTE PLACE="foot1">im Ms. fehlt &thorn;ou.</NOTE></L>
<L>Whilk &thorn;ou has in &thorn;ine awin pouste:</L>
<L>&THORN;at I suld mak &thorn;i moder hale?</L>
<L>&THORN;i hertly trouth now saue hir sale".<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Ms. throuth st. trouth.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;an wakind scho and was wele payd</L>
<L N="40">And to hir moder al &thorn;us scho sayd:</L>
<L>"God has &thorn;e helyd thurgh his pouste.</L>
<L>And for his sake byseke I &thorn;e</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;are be neuer - more to me bed</L>
<L>Erthly man me forto wed" &mdash;</L>
<L N="45">For bifore - tyme had &thorn;ai ordand</L>
<L>&THORN;at scho suld sone haue ane husband.</L>
<L>&THORN;an vnto Crist hir hert was tone,</L>
<L>&THORN;at husband bot him wald scho none;</L>
<L>Fro erthly luf hir hert scho cast.</L>
<L N="50">And to hir moder praid scho fast</L>
<L>&THORN;at all &thorn;e gudes &thorn;at to hir ffell</L>
<L>Suld be departid pouer men omell.</L>
<L>"Doghter, scho sayd, when I am dede,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou sal haue power in my stede</L>
<L N="55">&THORN;i gudes to gif at &thorn;ine awin will".</L>
<L>&THORN;an answerd Lucy &thorn;us hir vntill:</L>
<L>"Moder, scho said, &thorn;are he(l)pis noght<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Ms. hepis.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bot &thorn;at es gifen with (&thorn;y) thoght.<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Ms. withy.</NOTE></L>
<L>When &thorn;ou sall dy, &thorn;an giff &thorn;ou wald</L>
<L N="60">Thing &thorn;at &thorn;ou mai no langer hald;</L>
<L>At gif to &thorn;an ertow full fre,<NOTE PLACE="foot1">to st. it?</NOTE></L>
<L>For &thorn;ou may noght bere it with &thorn;e.</L>
<L>Here in &thorn;i liue do almus-dede!</L>
<L>In heuyn &thorn;an sall &thorn;ou haue &thorn;i mede".</L>
<L N="65">With al swilk wurdes went &thorn;ai home.</L>
<L>And hastily, when &thorn;ai &thorn;are come,</L>
<L>Lucy euerilka day with - drogh</L>
<L>Hir gudes and gaf pouer men Inogh</L>
<L>Of all thinges &thorn;at scho might cum by,</L>
<L N="70">Noght in appert, but ful priuely.</L>
<L>He &thorn;at suld haue wed hir, vnderstode</L>
<L>How &thorn;at scho gaf oway hir gude</L>
<L>And how scho hight to kepe hir clene.</L>
<L>And &thorn;arefore was he wonder tene,</L>
<L N="75">He made playnt to &thorn;e prince Paschasius</L>
<L>&THORN;at was &thorn;e grettest vnder Augustus,</L>
<L>Al - how his spous was turned &thorn;an</L>
<L>And wold bycum cristen woman.
<PB REF="00000156.tif" N="18"></L>
<L>Paschasius &thorn;an cum(an)ded &thorn;ore</L>
<L N="80">To bring &thorn;e mayden furth him bifore,</L>
<L>And in grete hast he hir cumand</L>
<L>Vnto his goddes to mak ofrand.</L>
<L>Saynt Lucy &thorn;an vnto him gun say:</L>
<L>"Ofrand &thorn;at vnto god suld pay</L>
<L N="85">&THORN;at es: pouer folk forto releue</L>
<L>And to visite &thorn;am in &thorn;aire mescheue.</L>
<L>Now haue I noght, &thorn;am with to belde,</L>
<L>Myne awin bodi to god I &yogh;elde".</L>
<L>&THORN;an answerd &thorn;e prince Paschasius:</L>
<L N="90">"Why answers &thorn;ou vnto me &thorn;us?</L>
<L>&THORN;ou suld do more reuerence to me,</L>
<L>For of al princes I haue pouste</L>
<L>And forto gif &thorn;e ioy or payne".</L>
<L>&THORN;an Lucy answerd &thorn;us ogayne:</L>
<L N="95">"Sen &thorn;ou &thorn;e lawes has forto &yogh;eme,</L>
<L>Do &thorn;ou als best will to &thorn;e seme!</L>
<L>&THORN;e laufe of Crist I think to kepe</L>
<L>And him allone I will wirschipe.</L>
<L>Sen &thorn;ou of &thorn;i right wil noght tyne,</L>
<L N="100">Do &thorn;ou &thorn;i prophet &mdash; I wil do myne".<NOTE PLACE="foot">prophet = profit.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;an answerd he to hir in haste:</L>
<L>"&THORN;i gudes vnwisely haues &thorn;ou waste</L>
<L>With filers of fleschely foly!"</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;is &thorn;an answerd Lucy:</L>
<L N="105">"Mi gudes I haue noght spend in vayn,</L>
<L>Bot for god, whore &thorn;ai most mai gayn;</L>
<L>And fleschli filers none I knaw".</L>
<L>&THORN;an answerd he vnto &thorn;at saw:</L>
<L>"Whilk haldes &thorn;ou fleschli filers now?"</L>
<L N="110">Scho answerd and said: "swilk als &thorn;ou;</L>
<L>For bodi and sawl both wald &thorn;ou schende</L>
<L>In sin and seruis of &thorn;e fende,</L>
<L>For lust and liking es &thorn;e leuyr</L>
<L>&THORN;an life of heuyn &thorn;at lastes euir".</L>
<L N="115">He said: "&thorn;ou wil turn &thorn;ine entent</L>
<L>Fro-tyme we put &thorn;e to turment;</L>
<L>&THORN;an hope I &thorn;ou will hald &thorn;i pese".</L>
<L>Scho said: "goddes wurd sal neuer fefe".</L>
<L>He said: "ertow god &thorn;an almyghty?"</L>
<L N="120">Scho sayd: "hys hand-mayden am I.</L>
<L>For, whils he welk in &thorn;is werld here,</L>
<L>He said to his appostels in-fere:<MILESTONE N="139" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>When &yogh;e er broght for luf of me</L>
<L>Bifor kinges &amp; princes of &thorn;is cuntre,</L>
<L N="125">Haue &yogh;e no thoght what &yogh;e sal say,</L>
<L>For I sall gif &yogh;ow wordes alway &mdash;</L>
<L>Dum steteritis ante reges &amp; presides &mdash;</L>
<L>He said: &thorn;e hali gaste sall speke in &yogh;ow.</L>
<L>And right so wirkes he with me now".</L>
<L>In ful grete ire &thorn;an answerd he:</L>
<L N="130">"&THORN;an es &thorn;at ilk haly gaste in &thorn;e?"</L>
<L>Scho said: "who kepis &thorn;am clene &amp; chaste,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai er &thorn;e hous of &thorn;e hali gaste".</L>
<L>He said: "&thorn;at sall we smertly se,</L>
<L>For in comune bordell sal &thorn;ou be</L>
<L N="135">And &thorn;ore be fyled with men of myne &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;i haly gaste so sal &thorn;ou tyne".</L>
<L>Scho sayd: "my flesche sall neuer be schent</L>
<L>Bot if my saul vnto syn assent;</L>
<L>If &thorn;ou me driue to wikked dede,</L>
<L N="140">To me it sall be dubble mede.</L>
<L>Mi bodi sal be redi with will al-way</L>
<L>To all &thorn;e paynes &thorn;ou can puruay.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou deuyll son, do furth &thorn;i will!</L>
<L>I couayt &thorn;at &thorn;ou it fulfill".</L>
<L N="145">&THORN;an was Paschasius wunder wrathe,</L>
<L>He sware hir ded with many ane athe.</L>
<L>He prayd al &thorn;at to hym war nere</L>
<L>Te venge him on &thorn;at fendes fere;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. te st. to.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Out of &thorn;e toun tite &yogh;e hir take</L>
<L N="150">To al turmentes &thorn;at men mai make,</L>
<L>&THORN;at scho be dede &thorn;is day or none!</L>
<L>And tel me &thorn;an how &yogh;e haue done".</L>
<L>Sone all assembled at his saw</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;e toune hir forto draw.</L>
<L N="155">Bot swilk strenkith god sent to hir:</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;at stede might none hir stir.</L>
<L>Paschasius fast comanded &thorn;en:</L>
<L>A thousand or mo of his men</L>
<L>Suld bynd &thorn;e mayden hend and fete</L>
<L N="160">And by strenkith draw hir in &thorn;e strete.</L>
<L>Bot by all craftes &thorn;ai couth controue</L>
<L>&THORN;ai might no-thing &thorn;e maiden moue.</L>
<L>A thousand oxen &thorn;an cumanded he</L>
<L>Suld vnto &thorn;at mayden bunden be</L>
<L N="165">And men and oxen draw al at-anes,</L>
<L>To brest in-sunder both flesch &amp; banes.
<PB REF="00000157.tif" N="19"></L>
<L>And als he cumand, sune &thorn;ai wroght;</L>
<L>Bot all &thorn;aire werk auayled noght.</L>
<L>&THORN;an raisid he deuyls, hir to assayl;</L>
<L N="170">Bot ilkone tynt &thorn;ai &thorn;aire trauail:</L>
<L>For in hir stede ay stode scho still.</L>
<L>&THORN;e prince &thorn;an cried with voice ful schill:</L>
<L>"What deuils might es made in hir</L>
<L>&THORN;at nouther men ne bestes mai stir?"</L>
<L N="175">Scho sayd: "&thorn;are es no might in me</L>
<L>Bot anely of my lordes pouste.</L>
<L>If &thorn;ou wold bring furth ten thousand,</L>
<L>Still in &thorn;is stede &yogh;it sall I stand".</L>
<L>Paschasyus &thorn;an was wude for wo</L>
<L N="180">And cumand swith &thorn;at men suld go,</L>
<L>To mak grete fire in &thorn;at same stede</L>
<L>And bryn hir &thorn;ore vnto &thorn;e ded;</L>
<L>Pik and rosyn he bad in cast</L>
<L>And oyle, to ger &thorn;e fire brin fast.</L>
<L N="185">&THORN;an fast &thorn;ai ordand ful grete fire,</L>
<L>Al obout hir brinand schire.</L>
<L>&THORN;e mayden stode ful still omyd</L>
<L>And vnto hir no dere it did.</L>
<L>Scho was euer meri &amp; milde of mode</L>
<L N="190">And &thorn;us scho sayd &thorn;ore als scho stode:</L>
<L>"Mi lord god has giffen me &thorn;is grace</L>
<L>In life to haue &thorn;us lang a space,</L>
<L>&THORN;at o&thorn;er may my turmentes se</L>
<L>And trow in him thurgh minde of me</L>
<L N="195">And erthly dole noght forto drede,</L>
<L>Bot haue gude hope of heuynli mede".</L>
<L>Paschasius &thorn;an for wo was wude.</L>
<L>And one of his men wightly &yogh;ode</L>
<L>To venge his lord of &thorn;is lang note:</L>
<L N="200">A swerd he schot thurgh-out hir throte.</L>
<L>Hir wurdes &thorn;arfore ne war noght layd:</L>
<L>"I tell here vnto &yogh;ow all, scho sayd,</L>
<L>&THORN;at thurgh &thorn;is werk &thorn;at &yogh;e here wyrk</L>
<L>Cumes pese and rest vnto hali kirk.</L>
<L N="205">And vnto all &thorn;is wordes I say:</L>
<L>Maximiane, he es dede &thorn;is day,</L>
<L>&THORN;at Emperoure was of grete renoune,</L>
<L>And Dioclicyane, he es done downe:</L>
<L>And so sall now fendes power sese</L>
<L N="210">And haly kirk now sall so encrese.</L>
<L>And right als Aga&yogh;, my sister fre,</L>
<L>&YOGH;emes Atenes, &thorn;at riche cete,</L>
<L>Right so sal I &thorn;is cete kepe</L>
<L>And &yogh;eme it vnto goddes wirschepe".</L>
<L N="215">&YOGH;it in &thorn;at stede so stode scho still</L>
<L>And spak wise wurdes thurgh goddes will:</L>
<L>Vnto prestes come with gude entent</L>
<L>And broght vnto hir sacrament,</L>
<L>Of Cristes blist bodi forto taste.</L>
<L N="220">&THORN;an sone vnto god scho gaf &thorn;e gaste.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai byried hir bodi &thorn;are sone onone,</L>
<L>Whore sethin was made a kirk of stone.</L>
<L>Ful moni vertuse &thorn;or war done</L>
<L>To men &thorn;at askyd hir any bone.</L>
<L N="225">&THORN;an Cesar &thorn;e Emperoure herd tell</L>
<L>Of al &thorn;is fare how it bifell,</L>
<L>And how Paschasius had ordand</L>
<L>To waste and destroy all &thorn;at land.</L>
<L>Ful mighti men for him he sent,</L>
<L N="230">And at his will wightli &thorn;ai went.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai broght him bunden vnto Rome,</L>
<L>And hastily he had hys dome</L>
<L>&THORN;at men suld sone strik of his heuid &mdash;</L>
<L>On swilk manere his lordschip leuid.</L>
<L N="235">Saint Lucy in heuyn has hir mede &mdash;</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;at life oure lord vs lede!</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="4" TYPE="legend">
<HEAD>4. De s. Thoma apostolo historia.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Saint Thomas, &thorn;e apostill trew</L>
<L>&THORN;at welk in werld here with Jhesu,</L>
<L>Named he was Thomas of Ynde,</L>
<L>For in &thorn;ose partys was he pynde.<NOTE PLACE="foot">In Ms. Tib. bildet diese Legende das Ende der Sammlung fol. 279b Col. 2; der Text weicht in Einzelheiten vielfach ab. Die 4 ersten Verse sind nicht sichtbar, 5 u. 7 theilweise; der Rest der Columne ist meist deutlich.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000158.tif" N="20"></L>
<L N="5">Bot als men redis in his story,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Bot als we. .</NOTE></L>
<L>He was precheand in land of Cesari.<NOTE PLACE="foot">(he) was prechand in. .</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ore Jhesu Crist gun to him apere<NOTE PLACE="foot">. .come oure lord of (heuyn),</NOTE></L>
<L>And spak vnto him on &thorn;is manere:<NOTE PLACE="foot">And said to him &thorn;us in his steuyn.</NOTE></L>
<L>"&thorn;e king of Ynde, Gundoforus.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Inde.</NOTE></L>
<L N="10">Vnto men he has sent message &thorn;us.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Vnto me has.</NOTE></L>
<L>One Abbanes, his owin steward,<NOTE PLACE="foot">One fehlt. Abbanes &thorn;e king steward.</NOTE></L>
<L>Has soght fro the&thorn;in al hiderward<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e&thorn;in all.</NOTE></L>
<L>A cunand wright, wele forto make<NOTE PLACE="foot">A kunand wright &thorn;at wele. .</NOTE></L>
<L>A faire palas for &thorn;e kinges sake.<NOTE PLACE="foot">faire fehlt.</NOTE></L>
<L N="15">Cum furth &mdash; for &thorn;eder I will &thorn;e send &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;arfore &thorn;eder I will &thorn;e send.</NOTE></L>
<L>And wirk &thorn;ou als I haue &thorn;e kend!"<NOTE PLACE="foot">Die Reimworte sind nicht sichtbar.</NOTE></L>
<L>Saynt Thomas answerd him till<NOTE PLACE="foot">Die Reimworte sind nicht sichtbar.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;an answerd Thomas him. .</NOTE></L>
<L>And said: "lord, if it be &thorn;i will,</L>
<L>Send me to folk of ilk a kynde,<NOTE PLACE="foot">kinde.</NOTE></L>
<L N="20">Outaken vnto folk of Ynde &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Out taken. &thorn;e folk.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;are wold I noght cum bi no way".<NOTE PLACE="foot">wald.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;an oure lord gun to him say:<NOTE PLACE="foot">till him gan. .</NOTE></L>
<L>"Wend with him baldly to &thorn;at kith!<NOTE PLACE="foot">Wend with him als I cumand,</NOTE></L>
<L>For I sal al-way wend &thorn;e with,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Mi self sall alway with &thorn;e stand,</NOTE></L>
