<L>Thurgh &thorn;e appostell bodi he it brayd<NOTE PLACE="foot2">. .&thorn;e appostell right he ran.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;ir ilk wurdes &thorn;arwith he sayd:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">. .wurdes said he &thorn;an.</NOTE></L>
<L>"I sall venge &thorn;e wranges euerylkone<NOTE PLACE="foot2">. .wranges euerilkane</NOTE></L>
<L N="250">&THORN;at my god in &thorn;is tyme has tone"<NOTE PLACE="foot2">. .my god. .ow here has tane. Darauf folgt ein Verspaar mehr: . .to &thorn;e grounde, . . .terd in &thorn;at stounde.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;an all &thorn;e folk &thorn;at trowed in Crist</L>
<L>And of hym war bifore baptist,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">251&mdash;2 = Harl.</NOTE></L>
<L>Efter &thorn;at bisschop ful fast &thorn;ai ran;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">ful fehlt. fast &thorn;ai soght</NOTE></L>
<L>For he so murthird &thorn;at haly man,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">(&thorn;)at him so vnto ded had broght,</NOTE></L>
<L N="255">Al quik &thorn;ai said he suld be brinde.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">And said he suld all quik be brind.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000162.tif" N="24"></L>
<L>And o&thorn;er folk &thorn;at left byhind</L>
<L>Toke &thorn;e body &thorn;at so was dede,<NOTE PLACE="foot">. .&thorn;at was ded.</NOTE></L>
<L>And beryd it in ful hali stede.<NOTE PLACE="foot">(ber)ied. ful fehlt. Die Schlussverse wie in Harl., aber 264: (Thurgh prai)er of his moder amen. Darunter steht, zur Be|zeichnung des Endes der Sammlung, noch ein gr&ouml;sseres Amen. Der Rest der Seite ist leer. Die R&uuml;ckseite ist beschrieben, aber ganz unleserlich; einzelne Worte (wie Gold mirr and ensens offird &thorn;ai) lassen vermuthen, dass von den h. 3 K&ouml;nigen die Rede; das Gedicht ist unvollendet. Das in Harl., wie in Tib., untergesetzte gr&ouml;ssere Amen beweist, dass hier urspr&uuml;nglich das Ende der Sammlung war, welche also mit dem Ende des Jahres schloss.</NOTE></L>
<L>His sawle went vnto blis ful clere</L>
<L N="260">And wuns &thorn;ore with his mayster dere,</L>
<L>&THORN;at es Jhesu, oure sauyore &mdash;</L>
<L>Vnto whom be louyng and honoure!</L>
<L>And vnto his kingdom he us ken</L>
<L>Thurgh prayers of saint Thomas! Amen.<NOTE PLACE="end">Die nachfolgenden 4 Legenden: Anastasia, Stephan, Johannes Evang., und Thomas von Canterbury, stehen in Ms. Harl. 4196 unter den Homilien im ersten Theile dieses Ms. und fehlen, bis auf Anastasia, welche am Ende mit Andreas w&ouml;rtlich nochmals wiederholt ist fol. 198b, im Legendentheile. Ms. Tib. ent|h&auml;lt dieselben nicht<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Dass sie in Tib. am Ende, hinter Thomas, noch folgten, ist nicht wahrscheinlich, da die H&auml;lfte des letzt vorhandenen Blattes, fol. 281 a, leer geblieben ist.</NOTE>. Anastasia schliesst sich an das Evang.: Pastores loqueban|tur, Stephan an: In principio erat verbum, darauf solgen unmittelbar Johannes und Thomas von Canterbury. Dann folgt die Homilie aus Innocentes, welche sich mit ganz demselben Text in Ms. Tib. unter den Evangelien, fol. 115b, findet. Ich lasse diese 4 Legenden hier folgen, weil sie sich nach dem Datum hier an|schliessen.</NOTE></L>
<TRAILER>A M E N.
</TRAILER>

</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="5" TYPE="legend"><PB REF="00000163.tif" N="[25]">
<HEAD>5. De sancta Anastasia.<NOTE PLACE="foot1">[The footnotes contain] Variantes des 2. Textes fol. 198b:</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Saint Anastase was born in Rome<MILESTONE N="15" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And of &thorn;e best kinred scho come.</L>
<L>Hir fader and moder, als clerkes knawe,<NOTE PLACE="foot1">clers.</NOTE></L>
<L>Lifd efter &thorn;e payens lawe.</L>
<L N="5">&THORN;e mayden, when scho come to elde,<NOTE PLACE="foot1">neu od. uen? st. come.</NOTE></L>
<L>In Cristes lawe sauore scho felde.<NOTE PLACE="foot1">sawore.</NOTE></L>
<L>Saint Grisogon, &thorn;at nobill man,<NOTE PLACE="foot1">nobil.</NOTE></L>
<L>In &thorn;at cete was wonand &thorn;an:<NOTE PLACE="foot1">cyte. wonan.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e lawe of Crist he kend hir wele;<NOTE PLACE="foot1">law.</NOTE></L>
<L N="10">And efter him did scho ilkadele,<NOTE PLACE="foot1">dyd.</NOTE></L>
<L>Scho lerid of him euer als hir list,</L>
<L>So preuely, &thorn;at none it wist.</L>
<L>Hir frendes ware myghty men of mode,<NOTE PLACE="foot1">war.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ai marid hir with mekyl gude<NOTE PLACE="foot1">mekill.</NOTE></L>
<L N="15">Vnto a man, hight Pupillus.</L>
<L>And sone, when scho was marid &thorn;us,<NOTE PLACE="foot1">schone st. sone.</NOTE></L>
<L>Scho sayd &thorn;at scho had sekenes sere,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at scho myght noght negh him nere;<NOTE PLACE="foot1">neght.</NOTE></L>
<L>Scho feyned hir to be so bysted</L>
<L N="20">&THORN;at scho might cum to no mans bed.</L>
<L>Bot preuely both day and night</L>
<L>To visit pouer men, was scho lyght,</L>
<L>In &thorn;aire mischef &thorn;am to mend,</L>
<L>And namely &thorn;at scho cristend kend;</L>
<L N="25">For of gudes had scho grete plente,<NOTE PLACE="foot1">audes st. gudes.</NOTE></L>
<L>Scho helpid &thorn;am with hert ful fre.</L>
<L>Till at &thorn;e last scho was ascride:<NOTE PLACE="foot1">tyl</NOTE></L>
<L>Hir husband preuely aspide</L>
<L>How &thorn;at scho went both euyn &amp; morn</L>
<L N="30">And none hir folowd ne went byforn</L>
<L>Bot one mayden, &thorn;at with hir &yogh;ede,<NOTE PLACE="foot1">zede.</NOTE></L>
<L>And both war cled in symple wede &mdash;</L>
<L>And in maner of cristen men &mdash;</L>
<L>By-caus none o&thorn;er suld &thorn;am ken.</L>
<L N="35">So mendid scho al &thorn;at mister hade,<NOTE PLACE="foot1">all. had.</NOTE></L>
<L>In pouert or in presoun stade.<NOTE PLACE="foot1">presount.</NOTE></L>
<L>And when hir husband vnde(r)stode</L>
<L>&THORN;at scho so gaf oway his gude,</L>
<L>He sayd scho suld do so namore,</L>
<L N="40">And all &thorn;us ordand he &thorn;arfore:<NOTE PLACE="foot1">al.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000164.tif" N="26"></L>
<L>He sperd hir in a hous of stone</L>
<L>And mete he bad scho suld haue none<NOTE PLACE="foot2">haf.</NOTE>&mdash;</L>
<L>To ded he thoght hir forto pyne,</L>
<L>Leuer &thorn;an so his gude to tyne.</L>
<L N="45">In &thorn;at preson so was scho sted,</L>
<L>And preuely with hir frendes fed.</L>
<L>To Grisogon letters scho sent</L>
<L>And told to him al hir entent,</L>
<L>How scho was presond in &thorn;at plase,</L>
<L N="50">And asked his counseyl in &thorn;at case.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">counseyld &thorn;at case!</NOTE></L>
<L>He sent hir cumfort gude ogayn<NOTE PLACE="foot2">cumfert.</NOTE></L>
<L>And sayd scho suld pas all hir payn;</L>
<L>In stabill trowth he bad hir dwell.</L>
<L>And efterward so it byfell:</L>
<L N="55">Hir husband was in sekenes kast</L>
<L>And languyst and dyed at &thorn;e last.</L>
<L>And so when he oway was gone,</L>
<L>Was Anastase fro preson tone</L>
<L>And to hir hows ogayn scho wendes &mdash;</L>
<L N="60">Full mekill mirth made al hir frendes.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">all.</NOTE></L>
<L>Scho wund &thorn;an in wydow degre.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">wydwo.</NOTE></L>
<L>And seruandes had scho sisters thre:</L>
<L>Of Cristes law scho gun &thorn;am lere;</L>
<L>Ful faire &thorn;ai wer and mild of chere.</L>
<L N="65">Ful faire woman was Anastase,</L>
<L>And faire seruandes with hir scho has,</L>
<L>Cristend war &thorn;ai euerilkone<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&thorn;a.</NOTE></L>
<L>And gaf &thorn;aire luf to god allone.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">gaff.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;are wund a prince of grete powste,</L>
<L N="70">Bot hathin man &thorn;at tyme was he:</L>
<L>To &thorn;ir wymen he gun him bede</L>
<L>In foly delyte for &thorn;aire fayrehede.<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Ms. foly (sp&auml;terer Text fole).</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">fole.</NOTE></L>
<L>With wurdes faire for &thorn;am he sent</L>
<L>To turn &thorn;am vnto euyll entent;</L>
<L N="75">He told vnto &thorn;am all his thoght,</L>
<L>Bot sone he wist &thorn;ai wold him noght.</L>
<L>He soght his foly to fulfill</L>
<L>With graunte or els ogayns &thorn;aire will:</L>
<L>In a hows he sperd &thorn;am sone<NOTE PLACE="foot2">spere.</NOTE></L>
<L N="80">Whare he wend al his wille haue done.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">whore. wil.</NOTE></L>
<L>In &thorn;at hows was to kepe vessell:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">uessell.</NOTE></L>
<L>Caldrons, als vnto &thorn;e k(e) chin fell,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">kytchyn.</NOTE></L>
<L>Pottes and pannes, &amp; o&thorn;er slyke<NOTE PLACE="foot2">ouer st. o&thorn;er.</NOTE></L>
<L>Als ketils, crassetes, to kechin like.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">kychin luke.</NOTE></L>
<L N="85">&THORN;e prynce, &thorn;at brinned in lusty lufe,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">luffe.</NOTE></L>
<L>Opon a day his poynt wold proue:</L>
<L>In to &thorn;o wemen he went &thorn;at tyde<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&thorn;e st. &thorn;o.</NOTE></L>
<L>And bad his men suld him habide.</L>
<L>When he come in, his mynde he mist,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">mind.</NOTE></L>
<L N="90">&THORN;e pottes and caldrons fast he kyst:</L>
<L>Hym thoght &thorn;ai war fayre damysels,</L>
<L>He halsed &amp; kissed &thorn;am &mdash; &amp; noght els;</L>
<L>His maystris with &thorn;am gun he mak,</L>
<L>Til his face &amp; clething was kole blak.<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Ms. chething,</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">lyke st. kole.</NOTE></L>
<L N="95">&THORN;e maydens stode ay and byhelde &mdash;</L>
<L>Of his fowl fare no-thing &thorn;ai felde;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">fowll.</NOTE></L>
<L>And his sight was so fro him sperd</L>
<L>&THORN;at he wist noght how foul he ferd.</L>
<L>When he had fulfild his foule entent,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">fild st. fulfild.</NOTE></L>
<L N="100">So foule defigurd furth he went.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">foul defigure.</NOTE></L>
<L>His men &thorn;an demyd him more &amp; les</L>
<L>Chaunged in-to a deuils lyknes;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">unto.</NOTE></L>
<L>Sum spit opon him for despite,</L>
<L>And sum ful smertly gun him smyte,</L>
<L N="105">Sum o&thorn;er, &thorn;at durst noght do so.</L>
<L>Left him allone and fled him fro.</L>
<L>He had meruail what it might mene;</L>
<L>To &thorn;e Emperoure went he in tene</L>
<L>&THORN;ore forto pleyn him of &thorn;is dede.</L>
<L N="110">Bot o&thorn;er men euer als he &yogh;ede</L>
<L>Bet him both with wandes &amp; staues<NOTE PLACE="foot2">both fehlt</NOTE></L>
<L>And cried ful loud: "lo how he raues!"</L>
<L>&THORN;e Emperours men, when he come &thorn;ore,</L>
<L>Lusshed opon him both les and more<NOTE PLACE="foot2">both fehlt</NOTE></L>
<L N="115">And filthes in his face &thorn;ai kest &mdash;</L>
<L>So ran he furth withouten rest.<MILESTONE N="16" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Grete meruaill in his hert had he &mdash;</L>
<L>Opon him-self he couth noght se;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">of of st. opon.</NOTE></L>
<L>Him thoght him-self and albydene</L>
<L N="120">War cled in clething fa(i)re and clene,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">fayre.</NOTE></L>
<L>And meruayl thoght him &thorn;at his men<NOTE PLACE="foot2">muayl.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ne his kinred kouth noght him ken
<PB REF="00000165.tif" N="27"></L>
<L>Ne &thorn;at &thorn;ai mened him &thorn;an namore</L>
<L>&THORN;at to honure him war fain bifore.</L>
<L N="125">Till at &thorn;e last &thorn;an had he sight</L>
<L>How he was farn and fouly dight,<NOTE PLACE="foot">farin.</NOTE></L>
<L>And how he had wroght with vessels</L>
<L>He wend haue done with damysels.</L>
<L>&THORN;an to &thorn;e Emperoure made he playnte</L>
<L N="130">How &thorn;e wemen war slegh and qua(i)nte:<NOTE PLACE="foot">quaynte.</NOTE></L>
<L>With wicche-craft his eghen &thorn;ai hid<NOTE PLACE="foot">witche.</NOTE></L>
<L>And made him do so als he did;</L>
<L>He sayd &thorn;ai trowed on Cristes lawe<NOTE PLACE="foot">in st. on.</NOTE></L>
<L>And o&thorn;er god &thorn;ai wold none knawe.</L>
<L N="135">&THORN;e Emperoure &thorn;an greuid was<NOTE PLACE="foot">greued.</NOTE></L>
<L>And gert send efter Anastas,</L>
<L>At &thorn;e barr bifor him forto be.<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e fehlt.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ai broght hir &amp; hir maydens thre.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Emperoure at &thorn;e princes prayer</L>
<L N="140">Gert nakkin &thorn;am al foure in fere<NOTE PLACE="foot">nakkyn,</NOTE></L>
<L>And said: &thorn;ai suld be scornid &thorn;ore</L>
<L>Als &thorn;ai skorned &thorn;e prince bifore &mdash;</L>
<L>And noght allone &thorn;arfore did he,</L>
<L>Bot for him-self naked wold &thorn;am se.<NOTE PLACE="foot">he self. nakid.</NOTE></L>
<L N="145">Bot god ordand so &thorn;aire clething<NOTE PLACE="foot">se st. so.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at noman might it of &thorn;am bring,</L>
<L>For nonekyns craft &thorn;at &thorn;ai do can.<NOTE PLACE="foot">nonekyng (!).</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e Emperoure had meruayl &thorn;an,</L>
<L>&THORN;e prince forferlid fel on slepe.</L>
<L N="150">And Anastase was giffen to kepe</L>
<L>Vnto a knight of grete honure,</L>
<L>&THORN;at was next to &thorn;e Emperoure,</L>
<L>On &thorn;is couenand: &thorn;at, if he may<NOTE PLACE="foot">coueand.</NOTE></L>
<L>Turn hir hert fro Cristes lay</L>
<L N="155">And by &thorn;aire law to lede hir life,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;are st. &thorn;aire.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at he suld wed hir to his wife.</L>
<L>Of &thorn;is couenand &thorn;e knight was glad,</L>
<L>For grete reches he wist scho had.</L>
<L>Into his chaumber he hir broght<NOTE PLACE="foot">Unto.</NOTE></L>
<L N="160">And wend with hir his will haf wroght;<NOTE PLACE="foot">wil.</NOTE></L>
<L>In his armes he has hir tone:<NOTE PLACE="foot">done st. tone.</NOTE></L>
<L>And blynd he was als any stone.</L>
<L>&THORN;an of his doing had he drede<NOTE PLACE="foot">ding st. doing.</NOTE></L>
<L>And to his goddes he gert him lede:</L>
<L N="165">Vnto his goddes he told his tale</L>
<L>And askyd yf &thorn;ai migh(t) make him hale.<NOTE PLACE="foot">mak.</NOTE></L>
<L>His goddes said: "&thorn;is harm &thorn;ou has,</L>
<L>For &thorn;ou trispast to Anastas.</L>
<L>Of &thorn;i sekenes &thorn;ou sal noght mend</L>
<L N="170">Bot wun with vs with-outen end".</L>
<L>His menze led him home ogayne</L>
<L>And sune he dyed with sorow &amp; payne.</L>
<L>And sone, when &thorn;at he so ded was,</L>
<L>&THORN;e Emperoure &thorn;an ordand has<NOTE PLACE="foot">ordan.</NOTE></L>
<L N="175">Saint Anastase to a-nother knight,</L>
<L>To kepe hir sauely day and night,</L>
<L>And said &thorn;at &thorn;ai suld ordain sone</L>
<L>To deme what suld of hir be done.<NOTE PLACE="foot">wat.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;is knight had herd oft-tymes tell<NOTE PLACE="foot">her st herd.</NOTE></L>
<L N="180">Of grete reches &thorn;at to hir fell;<NOTE PLACE="foot">riches.</NOTE></L>
<L>His hert was set on couatyse,</L>
<L>And to hir spak he on &thorn;is wise:</L>
<L>"Anastas, als &thorn;ou may se,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou ert putted into my powste,<NOTE PLACE="foot">unto. pouste.</NOTE></L>
<L N="185">Als me list forto spare or spill.</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;ou sal fare wele, if &thorn;ou will.<NOTE PLACE="foot">sall far.</NOTE></L>
<L>If &thorn;ou will be cristen woman,</L>
<L>&THORN;e bus do als Crist counseiles &thorn;an,</L>
<L>Els es &thorn;i purpose noght to prays.</L>
<L N="190">For on &thorn;is wise, &thorn;ou wote, he says:</L>
</LG>
<Q>Qui non renunciauerit omnibus que possidet et. c. &mdash;</Q>
<LG>
<L>Vnto my law who sum sall take,</L>
<L>His werldly gudes him bus forsake,</L>
<L>My seruand els he may noght be &mdash;</L>
<L>And &thorn;arfore &thorn;us I cownsail &thorn;e:</L>
<L N="195">Gif al &thorn;i gudes into my hand</L>
<L>And wend &thorn;i way I &thorn;e warand.</L>
<L>And verraly may &thorn;ou say &thorn;an<NOTE PLACE="foot">werraly.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou ert werray cristen woman".<NOTE PLACE="foot">uerraly.</NOTE></L>
<L>Saint Anastase answerd him to<NOTE PLACE="foot">answer.</NOTE></L>
<L N="200">And said: "my lord Crist biddes noght so,</L>
<L>To riche men forto gif my gude &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Do st. to.</NOTE></L>
<L>Onmis &thorn;o wurdes &thorn;ou vnderstode &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">emis. &thorn;e st. &thorn;o.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000166.tif" N="28"></L>
<L>He biddes me gif vnto &thorn;e pore</L>
<L>And find &thorn;am fode &thorn;at febilly fore.<NOTE PLACE="foot1">felully.</NOTE></L>
<L N="205">I wote &thorn;ou has reches plente;</L>
<L>&THORN;an, if I gaf my gude to &thorn;e,</L>
<L>I did ogayns goddes cumandment,</L>
<L>And &thorn;arto sall I neuer assent".</L>
<L>In strang preson &thorn;an was scho sted</L>
<L N="210">And mete and drink both hir forbed.</L>
<L>Bot fro heuyn had scho finding &thorn;ore</L>
<L>Two monethes and sumdele more.</L>
<L>&THORN;an al hir gudes scho gert gif fast<NOTE PLACE="foot1">all.</NOTE></L>
<L>To pouer and lame, whils &thorn;ai wold last.</L>
<L N="215">Ful mony maidens and mony a wife<NOTE PLACE="foot1">many, dann mony.</NOTE></L>
<L>Thurgh hir war turned to cristen life.</L>
<L>When a moneth and more was spend,</L>
<L>&THORN;an was scho demid forto be brend.</L>
<L>Hir body was bun to a stake</L>
<L N="220">And sufferd ded for goddes sake,<NOTE PLACE="foot1">suffere.</NOTE></L>
<L>And many mo of hir assent</L>
<L>War ded &thorn;ore with diuers turment.</L>
<L>Cristen men berid hir body</L>
<L>With wirschip, als it was wurthy.</L>
<L N="225">Hir sawl was hent to heuyn for ay&mdash;</L>
<L>God wis vs forto wend &thorn;at way!</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="6" TYPE="legend">
<HEAD>6. De sancto Stephano prothomartire<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Auf Anastasia folgt die Ueberschrift: Incipit hic secunda particula euangelii: Ostensio diui|nit(at)is in Christo. In die natali domini euang. sec. Johannem: In principio erat verbum. Der Text ist eine Uebersetzung des 1. Cap. Joh, in c. 120 V. Hieran schliesst sich Stephan an, welcher, wie aus den einleit. Versen dieser Leg. hervorgeht, nebst Iohannes und Innocentes offenbar einen integrirenden Theil der Homilien bildete.</NOTE>.</HEAD>
<DIV3 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Saynt Steuyn his passion has puplist<MILESTONE N="17" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Next folowand efter &thorn;e birth of Crist,</L>
<L>Als haly kirk it has ordand.</L>
<L>Bot we sal noght so vnderstand</L>
<L N="5">&THORN;at saynt Steuyn died when Crist was born,</L>
<L>Als sum laude men haue said biforn&mdash;</L>
<L>For he died, als with clerkes es kend,</L>
<L>Efter &thorn;e tyme &thorn;at Crist to heuyn assend;</L>
<L>Bot in &thorn;is tyme er festes thre</L>
<L N="10">Ordand for more solempnite,</L>
<L>And for al men suld make more mirth</L>
<L>And more honure to Cristes birth.</L>
<L>And in &thorn;ir thre festes, als &thorn;ai cum,</L>
<L>Er thre maners of martyrdom,</L>
<L N="15">And al marters &thorn;at euer was</L>
<L>By one of &thorn;o thre hethin gun pas:</L>
<L>&THORN;e first marterdom es of all &thorn;o</L>
<L>&THORN;at passes by wil and werk also,</L>
<L>&THORN;e secund marterdom to merk</L>
<L N="20">&THORN;at passes by will &amp; noght by werk,</L>
<L>&THORN;e thrid marterdom &thorn;ai fulfill</L>
<L>&THORN;at passes by werk &amp; noght by will.</L>
<L>&THORN;e first fulfild saynt Steuyn allone,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e secund fulfild saynt John,</L>
<L N="25">And &thorn;e thrid fulfild haly Innocentes&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;us may men tell who to &thorn;am tentes.</L>
<L>Saynt Steuyn with will &amp; his awin rede</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e Jewes was staned to dede,</L>
<L>Saynt Iohn &thorn;e Ewangelist sertayne</L>
<L N="30">Died wilfully with-owten payne,</L>
<L>&THORN;e Innocentes tholed angers ill</L>
<L>And greuance grete ogaynis &thorn;aire will.</L>
<L>&THORN;us er &thorn;ir marterdoms all thre</L>
<L>In Cristes birth ordand to be.</L>
<L N="35">Bot first of saynt Steuyn sal we tell</L>
<L>And of his fare how it byfell.&mdash;</L>
<L>When Jhesus Crist to heuyn was went</L>
<L>And &thorn;e haly gast to erth was sent,</L>
<L>Whilk gaf &thorn;e appostels wit to teche</L>
<L N="40">And will &thorn;e wordes of god to preche:</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;am come al lele and trew</L>
<L>&THORN;at war disciples of Jhesu.</L>
<L>And for &thorn;e nowmber wex so grete,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai ordand men to dight &thorn;aire mete,
<PB REF="00000167.tif" N="29"></L>
<L N="45">Swilk als &thorn;ai knew war grath &amp; gude</L>
<L>To ordayn for &thorn;aire erthly fode&mdash;</L>
<L>So &thorn;at &thorn;e apostels suld noght tent,</L>
<L>Bot preche &amp; teche Cristes cumandment;</L>
<L>Seuyn dekyns &thorn;ai ordand &thorn;en,</L>
<L N="50">Whilk &thorn;ai wist war haly men,</L>
<L>For &thorn;am to mak puruyance</L>
<L>And ordayn for ilk erthly chaunce.</L>
<L>Of wilk seuyn saynt Steuyn was one</L>
<L>And first of &thorn;am all chosen &amp; tone,</L>
<L N="55">Als a souerayne, to ouer-se,</L>
<L>And o&thorn;er vnder him forto be.</L>
<L>Saynt Steuyn, &thorn;at wald swilk trauayl tast,</L>
<L>Was fulfild of &thorn;e haly gast</L>
<L>And of god had he strenkith &amp; might</L>
<L N="60">To schow grete meruails in mens sight,</L>
<L>And of his meruailes of(t) men mened.</L>
<L>Wharfore &thorn;e iews oft-tymes war tened</L>
<L>And oft &thorn;ai ordant &thorn;am omell</L>
<L>By quayntys how &thorn;ai might him quell.</L>
<L N="65">First &thorn;ai kest to bring him downe</L>
<L>Thurgh dome of grete disputysowne;</L>
<L>And if &thorn;ai might noght by &thorn;at thing,</L>
<L>&THORN;an wold &thorn;ai by fals witnesing;</L>
<L>And if &thorn;aire werk war &thorn;an in vayne,</L>
<L N="70">&THORN;an wold &thorn;ai put him to grete payne&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;us thoght &thorn;ai by one of &thorn;ir thre</L>
<L>&THORN;at he suld sune ouercummen be.</L>
<L>First of &thorn;aire sinagoges vp rase</L>
<L>Maysters, &thorn;at grete manace mase;</L>
<L N="75">Of whilk sum war cald Libertynes,</L>
<L>And sum of &thorn;e cete hight Cirenynes,</L>
<L>Of Alexandre ful grete clergy,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. cleray.</NOTE></L>
<L>And of Cilyce, and of Assy.</L>
<L>&THORN;e nobillest of &thorn;ir nacions fyue</L>
<L N="80">Stirt vp, with saint Steuyn to stryue,</L>
<L>To faynde how &thorn;ai might ger him fall.</L>
<L>Bot he answerd to &thorn;am all,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at might had &thorn;ai none zit</L>
<L>Ne strenkth forto gaynstand his wit,</L>
<L N="85">Bot al &thorn;aire domes he made ful dym&mdash;</L>
<L>So was &thorn;e haly gaste in him.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai saw &thorn;at &thorn;is awayled noght:</L>
<L>&THORN;an two fals witnes furth &thorn;ai broght,</L>
<L>Whilk acused him of sinnes sere</L>
<L N="90">And specially on foure manere:</L>
<L>&THORN;ai said he suld a sklaunder rays</L>
<L>Of god &thorn;at grettest es to prays,</L>
<L>And of Moyses, and of &thorn;aire law,</L>
<L>And of &thorn;aire temple, to whilk &thorn;am aw</L>
<L N="95">To do honure, als has bene vsed.</L>
<L>Of al &thorn;ir foure he him excused.</L>
<L>For when &thorn;ai war in counsayl set</L>
<L>And saint Steuyn was bifor &thorn;am fett,</L>
<L>&THORN;am thoght his face was schinand schene</L>
<L N="100">Als it had of ane angel bene,</L>
<L>And al his chere &thorn;am thoght was &thorn;an</L>
<L>More like ane angell &thorn;an a man;</L>
<L>He answerd &thorn;ore to more and les</L>
<L>And so ouercome &thorn;e two fals witnes.</L>
<L N="105">&THORN;e Iews saw al &thorn;is noght avayle:</L>
<L>And put to him &thorn;e thrid batayle.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai thret him fast forto be slayne,</L>
<L>To ger him fayle for drede of payne.</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;arogayn to &thorn;am he kend</L>
<L N="110">On thre maners &thorn;aire mys to mend</L>
<L>And forto sese of swilk reproue:</L>
<L>For schame, for drede, &amp; als for lufe.</L>
<L>"First, he sayd, &yogh;e suld haue shame</L>
<L>On me to put swilk wrangwys blame.</L>
<L N="115">Bot yowre vnkyndnes euer &yogh;e knewe</L>
<L>To &thorn;am &thorn;at to yow war ful trewe;</L>
<L>Sere prophetes told to &yogh;ow byforn</L>
<L>How Crist suld here in erth be born:</L>
<L>&YOGH;owre faders slogh &thorn;am for &thorn;aire dede;</L>
<L N="120">And vnto me &yogh;e shew swilk mede,</L>
<L>For I &thorn;e trowth tell &yogh;ow vnto&mdash;</L>
<L>&YOGH;e suld haue shame so forto do".</L>
<L>&THORN;e iewes when &thorn;ai &thorn;ir wurdes herd,</L>
<L>With mekel felnes &thorn;an &thorn;ai ferd</L>
<L N="125">And in &thorn;aire hertes ill war &thorn;ai meuyd;</L>
<L>&THORN;ai gnaistid &thorn;aire teth &mdash; so war &thorn;ai greuyd,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai grynned on him als on a hownde.</L>
<L>And ful still stode he in &thorn;at stownde.</L>
<L>And for he saw &thorn;ai tuke no hede,</L>
<L N="130">He put to &thorn;am &thorn;is poynt of drede</L>
<L>And sayd: &thorn;at he saw Jhesu stand<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. Jh&cmacr;, sonst=Jhesus.</NOTE></L>
<L>Redy him to help with hert and hand&mdash;</L>
<L>For he hopid so &thorn;ai suld be flayd
<PB REF="00000168.tif" N="30"></L>
<L>And namore vnto him haue sayd;</L>
<L N="135">Bot for al &thorn;is &thorn;ai wald noght lett,</L>
<L>Ful sad assautes to him &thorn;ai sett.</L>
<L>And when he was so, als god wild,</L>
<L>With &thorn;e gude haly gaste fulfild,</L>
<L>He byheld vp vnto &thorn;e heuyn</L>
<L N="140">And al &thorn;us sayd he in his steuyn:</L>
<L>Ecce video celos apertos:</L>
<L>"Lo, he sayd, I se ful right</L>
<L>&THORN;e heuyn es opyn vnto my sight,</L>
<L>And mans sun I se wele stand</L>
<L>Byside &thorn;e fader of heuyn right hand".</L>
<L N="145">&THORN;e Iews war ferd &thorn;an of &thorn;is fare,</L>
<L>Bot werr &thorn;ai wex &thorn;an &thorn;ai war are,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai ditted &thorn;aire eris, for &thorn;ai suld noght</L>
<L>Here &thorn;ir wurdes &thorn;at &thorn;us war wroght.</L>
<L>And al despite &thorn;ai couth asspy</L>
<L N="150">Did &thorn;ai, forto ger him dy,</L>
<L>And al assentid &thorn;at he suld be</L>
<L>Led with-owten &thorn;at cete</L>
<L>And &thorn;are he suld be staned to dede &mdash;</L>
<L>Herto al haly gaf &thorn;ai rede.<MILESTONE N="18" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="155">So, said &thorn;ai, &thorn;ai suld be excusid:</L>
<L>For by &thorn;e lawe &thorn;an was it vffid</L>
<L>&THORN;at, who so sklaunderd &thorn;e god-hede,</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;e town men suld him lede</L>
<L>And stane him to ded hastily.</L>
<L N="160">&THORN;us did &thorn;ai with saint Steuyn forthi.</L>
<L>&THORN;e two fals witnes &thorn;an war &thorn;ore</L>
<L>&THORN;at acused him falsly byfore,</L>
<L>Al redy forto do &thorn;at dede.</L>
<L>Bot or &thorn;ai to &thorn;aire trauail &yogh;ode,</L>
<L N="165">&THORN;aire ouermast clothes of &thorn;ai kest &mdash;</L>
<L>For so &thorn;ai hopid to stir &thorn;am best;</L>
<L>And for &thorn;aire clothes suld noght be filde,</L>
<L>At kepe &thorn;ai toke &thorn;am to a childe</L>
<L>Whilk in his &yogh;owth was namyd Sawl</L>
<L N="170">And efterward he was saynt Pawle &mdash;</L>
<L>He kepid &thorn;aire clothes, als clerkes rede,</L>
<L>Ay whyls &thorn;ai did &thorn;at wikked dede;</L>
<L>Wharfore sum sais he was assent</L>
<L>With &thorn;am to fulfil &thorn;at turment.</L>
<L N="175">Bot when saynt Steuyn saw by &thorn;aire dede</L>
<L>&THORN;ai wold noght let for shame ne drede,</L>
<L>With faire wordes &thorn; a <I>m</I> wold h <I>e</I> proue<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. &thorn;ai wold him st. &thorn;am wold he.</NOTE></L>
<L>To mend &thorn;aire wikked life by lufe;</L>
<L>And &thorn;at was fore he for &thorn;am prayd.</L>
<L N="180">For when &thorn;ai staned him, &thorn;us he sayd:</L>
<L>"Jhesus, my lord and mayster fre,</L>
<L>Resayue my saul now vnto &thorn;e!"</L>
<L>Sethin on his knese he knelid downe</L>
<L>And sayd for &thorn;am &thorn;is orisowne:</L>
<L N="185">"Lord, forgif &thorn;am &thorn;at &thorn;is wroght!</L>
<L>For what &thorn;ai wirk ne wate &thorn;ai noght".</L>
<L>Lo, how grete luf to &thorn;am he schewd</L>
<L>&THORN;at to him had bene euer shrewed &mdash;</L>
<L>Kneland for &thorn;am to god he prayd</L>
<L N="190">And standand for him-self he sayd;</L>
<L>Takand ensaumple of Jhesu</L>
<L>&THORN;at prayed his fader for ilka Iew</L>
<L>&THORN;at him pursued and did to dede.</L>
<L>&THORN;an died saynt Steuyn in &thorn;at same stede.</L>
<L N="195">Saynt Gamalyell and Nichodeme</L>
<L>With wirship, &thorn;at &thorn;arto wald seme,</L>
<L>Berid &thorn;e body in honest place,</L>
<L>Whare god has shewed sethin ful grete grace.</L>
<L>His sawl was tane to heuyn blis &mdash;</L>
<L N="200">&THORN;at way to wend Jhesu vs wys!</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="section">
<HEAD>Inuencio corporis sancti Stephani.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Saynt Steuen was staned &amp; grauen was he</L>
<L>Byside Jerusalem, &thorn;e riche cete,</L>
<L>Als saynt Gamaliel and Nichodeme</L>
<L>In &thorn;at tyme &thorn;ar-to toke &yogh;eme &mdash;</L>
<L N="205">For &thorn;ai war disciples of Crist</L>
<L>And on his name byfore baptist;</L>
<L>&THORN;arfore Gamaliell wouched saue</L>
<L>To lay &thorn;at body in his awyn graue.</L>
<L>Bot efterward thurgh goddes grace</L>
<L N="210">It was translate till o&thorn;ir place &mdash;</L>
<L>And of &thorn;at ilk translacioun</L>
<L>Es named "saynt Steuyn inuencioun":</L>
<L>&THORN;at es &thorn;e finding of his body &mdash;</L>
<L>With wirship, als it was worthy.</L>
<L N="215">Gamaliell liffed lang efter &thorn;an</L>
<L>And Nichodem also, &thorn;at nobil man;</L>
<L>And Saul, &thorn;at &thorn;e ftaners clothes held,
<PB REF="00000169.tif" N="31"></L>
<L>In cumpany &thorn;an with &thorn;am dweld,</L>
<L>Als a child halden in awe,</L>
<L N="220">And of &thorn;am lered he goddes lawe.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. ho st. he.</NOTE></L>
<L>And sethin, when &thorn;ai both war ded,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai war berid in &thorn;at same sted</L>
<L>Whore &thorn;ai had layd sayn Steuyn body &mdash;</L>
<L>For wele &thorn;ai loffed to lig him by.</L>
<L N="225">Lang efter &mdash; who so likes to lere,</L>
<L>How &thorn;ai war translate, may men here &mdash;</L>
<L>Biside Jerusalem wund ane,</L>
<L>A nobill prest, hight Lucyane;</L>
<L>Ful haly man and gude was he,</L>
<L N="230">&THORN;arfore god shewed him preuete.</L>
<L>It fel on a friday at night</L>
<L>Half slepand saw he selkuth sight:</L>
<L>A faire old man stode him byfore,</L>
<L>Of stature had he sene none more,</L>
<L N="235">With longe berd, and light of chere,</L>
<L>His klothing was al whyt &amp; clere,</L>
<L>It was enbrouded many folde</L>
<L>With crosses &amp; with ringes of golde,</L>
<L>His shose war wroght withouten wems,</L>
<L N="240">With gold bordures obout &thorn;e hems;</L>
<L>Of gold also he bare a wand.</L>
<L>&THORN;ar-with he touched &thorn;e prestes hand:</L>
<L>"Rise vp, he sayd, and redy &thorn;e</L>
<L>To wend fro my felows &amp; me</L>
<L N="245">&THORN;at ligges &thorn;ore in swilk a stede</L>
<L>And so lang es sen we war dede;</L>
<L>Wend vnto Iohn, &thorn;e pape of Rome,</L>
<L>And say him: it es goddes dome</L>
<L>Oure bodis to be in honest place,</L>
<L N="250">Whare god for vs will shew his grace:</L>
<L>For when &thorn;e world sal be desesed,</L>
<L>By oure prayers he will be plesed,</L>
<L>And men &thorn;at sal be in mischeue</L>
<L>For oure sake sal haue releue".</L>
<L N="255">&THORN;e preste was for &thorn;is fare affrayd</L>
<L>And softly &thorn;us to him he sayd:</L>
<L>"Lord, he sayd, what man ertow</L>
<L>&THORN;at tels &thorn;ir tales vnto me now?"</L>
<L>He sayd: "I am Gamaliell,</L>
<L N="260">Of wham &thorn;ou herd oft-tymes tell.</L>
<L>I norishd &thorn;e appostell Paule,</L>
<L>&THORN;at byfore tyme was namid Saul,</L>
<L>I lered him of goddes lay.</L>
<L>And also, sir, &thorn;ou has herd say</L>
<L N="265">How &thorn;at Iews ogayns resown</L>
<L>Staned saynt Steuen withoute toun;</L>
<L>His body left &thorn;ai in &thorn;e felde,</L>
<L>Wild bestes at &thorn;aire will to welde.</L>
<L>I berid it, &thorn;ou wote wele whare,</L>
<L N="270">And my body es berid right &thorn;are,</L>
<L>And Nichodeme, my cosyn trew,</L>
<L>&THORN;at on &thorn;e night spak with Jhesu &mdash;</L>
<L>Of Peter &amp; Iohn he was baptist</L>
<L>And lely lerd &thorn;e lawe of Crist.</L>
<L N="275">Saynt Steuen &amp; I ligges euyn mete,</L>
<L>And he ligges at saynt Steuen fete;</L>
<L>And by him sal &thorn;e body be fun</L>
<L>Of Abyas, &thorn;at was my sun</L>
<L>And with my-self he toke baptym</L>
<L N="280">And clene vnto Crist kepid he him</L>
<L>And his laws was him lefe to lere &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;us sal &thorn;ou find vs foure in-fere.</L>
<L>And my wife &amp; myne o&thorn;er fun,</L>
<L>&THORN;at Cristes law wald neuer cun,</L>
<L N="285">In o&thorn;er place &thorn;ai grauen ware</L>
<L>And &thorn;aire graues er both voyd &amp; bare.</L>
<L>&THORN;us saltow find, als I &thorn;e say".</L>
<L>When &thorn;is was said, he was oway.</L>
<L>&THORN;an &thorn;is gude preste Luciane</L>
<L N="290">Wakend &amp; was will of wane.</L>
<L>He prayd to god &thorn;at he wit moght</L>
<L>Whethir &thorn;ir saws war suth or noght;</L>
<L>And if he suld wirk on swilk wise,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he myght haue &thorn;is warnig thrise.</L>
<L N="295">It fell efter on &thorn;at day seuyn-night</L>
<L>Of al &thorn;is same &thorn;an had he sight;</L>
<L>&THORN;e old man askid him whi</L>
<L>&THORN;at he forgat him so lyghtly,</L>
<L>And whi he tentid no better to</L>
<L N="300">His herand for him forto do?</L>
<L>&THORN;an Lucian answerd, als him thoght,</L>
<L>And said: "sir, I forgat it noght.</L>
<L>Bot vnto god &thorn;us-gat I prayd:</L>
<L>If he war of &thorn;is message payd</L>
<L N="305">And if it war in goddes name,</L>
<L>&THORN;at I suld thre tymes se &thorn;at same;</L>
<L>And if it war by goddes will,
<PB REF="00000170.tif" N="32"></L>
<L>I wold be fayn it to fulfill".</L>
<L>&THORN;an answerd &thorn;us Gamaliell:</L>
<L N="310">"For &thorn;ou trowes noght &thorn;at I &thorn;e tell,</L>
<L>I sal &thorn;e shew by proces playne</L>
<L>Als &thorn;ou sall find &thorn;e suth sertayne".</L>
<L>Foure panyers shewd he in &thorn;at stede,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e first of gold ful of roses rede,</L>
<L N="315">And o&thorn;er two of gold ful clere</L>
<L>Full of whit roses both in-fere,</L>
<L>&THORN;e ferth of siluer burnist bright</L>
<L>And ful of fafron semyd it right.</L>
<L>"&THORN;us sal &thorn;ou find wele on &thorn;is wise</L>
<L N="320">&THORN;e graues whare oure foure bodis lies:</L>
<L>Whore &thorn;ou sal fynd swilk roses rede,</L>
<L>&THORN;at es saynt Steuyn, &thorn;at first was dede;</L>
<L>By two with whit roses, tak &thorn;ou &yogh;eme,</L>
<L>My graue and my cosins Nichodeme;</L>
<L N="325">And by &thorn;e ferth full of safron</L>
<L>&THORN;e graue of Abyas, my sun,</L>
<L>&THORN;at al his life in clennes last</L>
<L>And clene out of &thorn;is werld past.</L>
<L>&THORN;us sal &thorn;ou find, als I &thorn;e say".</L>
<L N="330">When &thorn;is was sayd, he was oway.</L>
<L>Lucian to &thorn;is tale gude tent toke,</L>
<L>Bot &yogh;et habade he al &thorn;at woke</L>
<L>By-caus he wald thryse se &thorn;at sight.</L>
<L>And fel &thorn;at same day seuyn-night:</L>
<L N="335">Gamaliell gun to him appere</L>
<L>And rebuted him on ruid manere</L>
<L>And blamed him ful bitterly &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at Lucian was abayst &thorn;ar-by.</L>
<L>And on &thorn;e morn with trew entent</L>
<L N="340">Vnto Jerusalem he went</L>
<L>To Iohn, &thorn;at &thorn;an was bisshop &thorn;are,</L>
<L>And told him al &thorn;is ferly fare</L>
<L>And how &thorn;at it was goddes will</L>
<L>&THORN;at saynt Steuyn suld noght lig &thorn;ore still,</L>
<L N="345">And of &thorn;e rose he told tokinnyg<MILESTONE N="19" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And als of all &thorn;at o&thorn;er thing.</L>
<L>When &thorn;e bisshop wist al what he ment,</L>
<L>Efter o&thorn;er bisshopes sone he sent</L>
<L>And o&thorn;er maysters of clergy,</L>
<L N="350">To do &thorn;at dede more solemply.</L>
<L>And in &thorn;at place &thorn;ai all apperd</L>
<L>Whore Lucian, &thorn;e preste, &thorn;am lerd.</L>
<L>And als &thorn;ai in &thorn;e ground &thorn;ore groue,</L>
<L>&THORN;e erth it-self bygan to moue;</L>
<L N="355">Omang &thorn;am come so nobill smell,</L>
<L>&THORN;at grete ioy was &thorn;ore forto dwell.</L>
<L>Of Jerusalem and of &thorn;at cuntre</L>
<L>Come mekill folk, &thorn;at sight to se,</L>
<L>And mony seke &amp; sare fast &thorn;eder soght.</L>
<L N="360">And many miracles was &thorn;are wroght:</L>
<L>For thurgh &thorn;o sayntes war helid &thorn;en</L>
<L>Of seke and sore sexty and ten.</L>
<L>In saynt Steuyn graue rede roses war laid,</L>
<L>Als Lucian byfore had &thorn;am said.</L>
<L N="365">&THORN;ai toke vp &thorn;e relikes bydene</L>
<L>And layd &thorn;am in cases ful clene.</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e cete &thorn;ai &thorn;am bare,</L>
<L>With wirship als &thorn;ai worthi ware,</L>
<L>And &thorn;are &thorn;ai did &thorn;am for hald</L>
<L N="370">In a kirk, &thorn;at was Syon cald,</L>
<L>Whare saynt Steuyn had bene bifore &mdash;</L>
<L>For lyfand was he dekyn &thorn;ore.</L>
<L>In whilk place was grete vertu shewd</L>
<L>And grete belde both to lerid and lawd:</L>
<L N="375">For &thorn;eder men soght fro sydes sere.</L>
<L>And sethin byfell on &thorn;is manere:</L>
<L>Ane Alexander, of grete honowre,</L>
<L>Of Jerusalem was senatowre;</L>
<L>He lufid saynt Steuyn with hert &amp; thoght</L>
<L N="380">For grete werkys &thorn;at he saw &thorn;ore wroght:</L>
<L>And in &thorn;at same place gert he make<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. meke in make corr.</NOTE></L>
<L>A fayre chapell for saynt Steuyn sake;</L>
<L>A reall towmb he made al-so</L>
<L>And &thorn;orein set he kistes two:</L>
<L N="385">In &thorn;at one to rest ful really</L>
<L>&THORN;e relikes of saynt Steuyn body,</L>
<L>And in &thorn;at o&thorn;er ordand he</L>
<L>His owyn body suld berid be.</L>
<L>And so it was, when he was dede,</L>
<L N="390">And seuyn &yogh;eres restid he in &thorn;at stede.</L>
<L>&THORN;an fell auenture so &thorn;at his wife,</L>
<L>&THORN;at efter him was left on life,</L>
<L>Wold wende whore scho was born &amp; bred</L>
<L>In o&thorn;er cuntre to hir kynred,</L>
<L N="395">And counsayl gat &thorn;at scho suld craue</L>
<L>Hir husband cors with hir to haue.</L>
<L>For &thorn;at poynt fast scho puruayd
<PB REF="00000171.tif" N="33"></L>
<L>And to &thorn;e bischop fast scho prayd</L>
<L>To haue &thorn;e body of hir husband</L>
<L N="400">With hir home to hir owyn land,</L>
<L>For hertly luf, scho had him till.</L>
<L>&THORN;e bisshopp grauntted to do hir will;</L>
<L>"Bot, dame, within &thorn;e towmb, he sayd,</L>
<L>Two kistes of siluer se I grayd;</L>
<L N="405">And whethir of &thorn;am &thorn;i husband be,</L>
<L>&THORN;at wote noght I &mdash; &thorn;i-self byse!"</L>
<L>"A, sir, scho sayd, wele I record</L>
<L>Whilk es saynt Steuyn &amp; whilk my lord".</L>
<L>And so thurgh hap, als says &thorn;e boke,</L>
<L N="410">&THORN;e relikes of saynt Steuen scho toke,</L>
<L>&THORN;ethin gert scho bere &thorn;am albydene</L>
<L>And wend &THORN;at it hir lord had bene.</L>
<L>Scho festid &thorn;am forto lede ouer se</L>
<L>To Costantyne, hir owyn cuntre.</L>
<L N="415">&THORN;e mariners &thorn;are ship ordand.</L>
<L>And als &thorn;ai went with &thorn;am fro land,</L>
<L>Ful mekyll mirth come &thorn;am omell</L>
<L>Of angell sang and nobill smell.</L>
<L>Bot when &thorn;ai come in-middes &thorn;e flode,</L>
<L N="420">&THORN;an deuils cried als &thorn;ai war wode,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai raysed &thorn;e wynd with weders wik</L>
<L>And made &thorn;e ayre with mist ful thik,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai cried ful loud and sayd: "allas!</L>
<L>Steuyn, oure enmy, now here furth pas.</L>
<L N="425">Vnto vs dose he grete dispite,</L>
<L>Now sal we fand it forto quite".</L>
<L>&THORN;e mariners &thorn;an wend haue dyed</L>
<L>And on saynt Steuen ful fast &thorn;ai cried.</L>
<L>And sune to &thorn;am he gun apere:</L>
<L N="430">"Dredes &yogh;ow noght, for I am here!"</L>
<L>&THORN;an al &thorn;e tempest ful sone sest,</L>
<L>So of &thorn;aire wo &thorn;ai war relest.</L>
<L>Bot deuils set vp a sori sown</L>
<L>And sayd: "sen we may noght &thorn;am drown,</L>
<L N="435">Bot brin &thorn;am sone we sall noght tary,</L>
<L>Both &thorn;e ship and Steuen, oure aduersary".</L>
<L>&THORN;ai kest vp fire ligh als &thorn;e leuyn.</L>
<L>Bot angels sone war sent fro heuyn</L>
<L>And al &thorn;o deuils, if &thorn;ai war wode,</L>
<L N="440">War drownd in depnes of &thorn;e flode.</L>
<L>&THORN;e mariners furth sayled syne</L>
<L>And sauely come vnto Costantyne.</L>
<L>Vnto a kirk, &thorn;at &thorn;an was &thorn;are,</L>
<L>&THORN;e body of saynt Steuen &thorn;ai bare,</L>
<L N="445">With mekill mirth &amp; solempne sang.</L>
<L>And &thorn;ore &thorn;o relikes restid lang. &mdash;</L>
<L>Now may men lere with-outen let</L>
<L>How saynt Steuen &amp; saynt Lourance met</L>
<L>&THORN;aire bodis samen efter &thorn;aire dede,</L>
<L N="450">And &yogh;it &thorn;ai rest in &thorn;at same stede.</L>
<L>Theodolus, Emperoure of Rome,</L>
<L>To Costantyne &thorn;at tyme he come</L>
<L>For thing &thorn;at fell to his empire,</L>
<L>And also for he had grete desyre</L>
<L N="455">Of saynt Steuen vertus forto here.</L>
<L>And for he had a doghter dere</L>
<L>&THORN;at trauaild was with fendes fele,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ore he hopid scho suld haue hele:</L>
<L>To Rome he sent so als he thoght,</L>
<L N="460">And bad scho suld be &thorn;eder broght,</L>
<L>To be touched with &thorn;o relikes gude.</L>
<L>And when &thorn;e fende &thorn;is vnderstode,</L>
<L>&THORN;eder to pas he was noght payd,</L>
<L>He cried within hir and &thorn;us sayd:</L>
<L N="465">"Out of &thorn;is woman I will noght pas,</L>
<L>Or tyme &thorn;at Steuen, &thorn;at staned was,</L>
<L>Be broght to Rome, and his body</L>
<L>Be dight with saynt Lowrance for to ly,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at his body lig &thorn;ore still &mdash;</L>
<L N="470">For so es &thorn;e appostels will".</L>
<L>And sone when &thorn;ir wordes bald</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e Emperoure war tald,</L>
<L>He gedird togeder &thorn;e clergy</L>
<L>Of Costantyne, &amp; prayd specially</L>
<L N="475">For his sake &thorn;at &thorn;ai wald vouche saue</L>
<L>Saynt Steuen body &thorn;at he might haue,</L>
<L>With reuerence forto rest in Rome,</L>
<L>And saynt Lourence to Costantyne at come &mdash;</L>
<L>His body hight he &thorn;ai suld haue</L>
<L N="480">In stede of saynt Steuen forto graue.</L>
<L>On &thorn;at couenand &thorn;ai graunted tyte.</L>
<L>And &thorn;an &thorn;e Emperoure gert write</L>
<L>And sent letters &thorn;e pope vnto,</L>
<L>To aske his leue &thorn;is dede to do.</L>
<L N="485">&THORN;e pope &thorn;an, &thorn;at hight Pelagy,</L>
<L>By counsail of al his clergy</L>
<L>Graunted &thorn;e Emperours entent,</L>
<L>And cardinals &thorn;arfore he sent,</L>
<L>For saynt Steuen suld by &thorn;aire presens</L>
<L N="490">Be broght to Rome with grete reuerence.
<PB REF="00000172.tif" N="34"></L>
<L>And so he was sone efter syne.</L>
<L>And Grekes come fro Costantyne</L>
<L>Saynt Lourence body &thorn;eder to bringe.</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;ore bifell ful ferly thinge:</L>
<L N="495">&THORN;ai come to Rome with grete renowne</L>
<L>And to a kirk &thorn;ai made &thorn;am bowne,</L>
<L>Namid of saynt Peter ad uincula;</L>
<L>And &thorn;e Emperoure doghter, Eudosya,</L>
<L>Foloud ful fast with mony a frende,</L>
<L N="500">Forto be deliuerd of &thorn;e fende.</L>
<L>Bot when &thorn;ai to &thorn;e kirk war cumen,</L>
<L>&THORN;e berers semid nerehand bynomen;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. bynomen.</NOTE></L>
<L>In-to &thorn;e kirk &thorn;ai might noght wyn.</L>
<L>&THORN;an &thorn;e fend, &thorn;at was &thorn;e woman in,</L>
<L N="505">Cried and said: "&yogh;e wirk in vayne.</L>
<L>I told byfore my-self sertayne</L>
<L>&THORN;at he wold by saynt Lourence ly,</L>
<L>By-caus he lufes his cumpany".</L>
<L>&THORN;an turned &thorn;ai furth with gude entent</L>
<L N="510">And to saynt Lourence graue &thorn;ai went.</L>
<L>&THORN;e mayden touched, when &thorn;ai come &thorn;are,</L>
<L>&THORN;e kist whore saynt Steuen relikes ware:<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. kirk st. kist.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e fend with mekill care and cri</L>
<L>Went out, and scho was hale in hy.</L>
<L N="515">&THORN;an al &thorn;e peple in &thorn;at place</L>
<L>Louid god ful fast for his grete grace.</L>
<L>&THORN;e stone obouen &thorn;ai put oway</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e toumb whorin saynt Lourence lay:</L>
<L>&THORN;e body remude, als god vouche saue,</L>
<L N="520">And left to saint Steuen half &thorn;e graue &mdash;</L>
<L>In takining &thorn;at he was wele payd</L>
<L>His brother suld be by him layd.</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;an &thorn;e Grekes layd on &thorn;aire hand</L>
<L>Him forto haue by &thorn;aire couenand</L>
<L N="525">In stede of saynt Steuen euermore,</L>
<L>Als &thorn;aire forward was made bifore.</L>
<L>To tak him vp, none wald &thorn;am let;</L>
<L>Bot al &thorn;at &thorn;aire hend on him set</L>
<L>And al &thorn;at for &thorn;at same war sent,</L>
<L N="530">Out of &thorn;aire wit wightly &thorn;ai went;</L>
<L>And nothing might relese &thorn;aire payne,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e bodis war laid samyn ogayne:</L>
<L>&THORN;an war &thorn;ai helid, als &thorn;e buke says,</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;ai died al within ten days.</L>
<L N="535">When &thorn;ir relikes war samyn layd,</L>
<L>A voyce was herd fro heuyn, &thorn;at sayd:</L>
<L>"A grete reuerence to Rome bitides,<MILESTONE N="20" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;at in a close haldes and hides</L>
<L>&THORN;e bodis of two sayntes sere</L>
<L N="540">&THORN;at er ful blissed both in-fere</L>
<L>And ful grete bifore god in heuyn".</L>
<L>Al had grete ioy &thorn;at herd &thorn;is steuyn.</L>
<L>&THORN;an al &thorn;e pople home &thorn;ai &yogh;ode,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ore rested &thorn;e relikes gude.</L>
<L N="545">Whore mekell grace sethin has bene sheud<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. sethim.</NOTE></L>
<L>And grete releue to lered and lewd.</L>
<L>For &thorn;ore to blind es gyfen &thorn;e sight,<NOTE PLACE="foot">es st. was.</NOTE></L>
<L>And vnto crokid &thorn;aire lims ful right,</L>
<L>&THORN;e ded war raised in diuers place</L>
<L N="550">Thurght &thorn;e relikes and goddes grace,</L>
<L>&THORN;e dom might speke, &thorn;e defe might here;</L>
<L>And als al o&thorn;er seknes sere</L>
<L>Wharfore men wold for comfort craue,</L>
<L>&THORN;aire hele ful haftly might &thorn;ai haue.</L>
<L N="555">Of many meruailes might men tell</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ore in diuers tymes byfell.</L>
<L>Whilk er noght set here in &thorn;is boke,</L>
<L>Bot in &thorn;aire legend, who likes to loke,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Beachte den Gegensatz von legend u. lesson 560.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ore may men se &thorn;am set al sere.</L>
<L N="560">And by &thorn;is lesson may men lere</L>
<L>To wirk wele in &thorn;is werld al-way</L>
<L>And cum to &thorn;e life &thorn;at lastes ay.</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;at life &thorn;at lord vs lede</L>
<L>&THORN;at sufferd ded for oure misdede! Amen.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="7" TYPE="legend"><PB REF="00000173.tif" N="35">
<HEAD>7. De sancto Johanne euangelista.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Saynt John, appostel &amp; euangelist,</L>
<L>Was cosyn vnto Jhesu Crist,</L>
<L>Born of &thorn;e thrid of Maries thre,</L>
<L>And his fader hight &YOGH;ebede.</L>
<L N="5">&THORN;is &YOGH;ebede has suns two:</L>
<L>Elder James, saynt John also.</L>
<L>&THORN;aire fader &amp; &thorn;ai ferd on &thorn;e flode</L>
<L>And with fisshing &thorn;ai gat &thorn;aire fode.</L>
<L>Sethin may men rede how Crist &thorn;am cald</L>
<L N="10">And made &thorn;am to wirk als he wald.</L>
<L>Vnto him war &thorn;ai both ful dere,</L>
<L>By-caus &thorn;ai war his cosins nere.</L>
<L>He lufed saynt John ouer al bydene,</L>
<L>For he was mild and mayden clene.</L>
<L N="15">And how he lufed him, may men lere,</L>
<L>When Cristes passion drogh him nere:</L>
<L>&THORN;an slepid saynt John in Cristes kne</L>
<L>And saw of heuyn sere preuete &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at preuelage to him was tone</L>
<L N="20">By-fore his felows euerilkone.</L>
<L>Also, when Crist suld suffer dede,</L>
<L>&THORN;an set he saynt John in his stede</L>
<L>Vntill his moder to tak &yogh;eme;</L>
<L>For so he said it wold wele seme</L>
<L N="25">A mayden, &thorn;at lifd in chastite,</L>
<L>Suld keper of a mayden be &mdash;</L>
<L>Byfor o&thorn;er had he swilk wirshepe,</L>
<L>And &thorn;arto toke he ful gude kepe.</L>
<L>Bot efterward so it byfell:</L>
<L N="30">When Crist had rysen &amp; herid hell</L>
<L>And steghed to heuyn, whore mirth es mast,</L>
<L>And sent to erth his haly gaste</L>
<L>Opon his men &amp; gaf &thorn;am might</L>
<L>To preche his word by day and night:</L>
<L N="35">&THORN;an war &thorn;e appostels parted wide</L>
<L>To sere cuntres and on sere syde.</L>
<L>Saynt Jon &thorn;an gun his iorne hald</L>
<L>Vnto a cuntre, was Asy cald.</L>
<L>&THORN;e word of Crist &thorn;ore preched he</L>
<L N="40">And turned pople ful grete plente,</L>
<L>In Cristes law forto be lele,</L>
<L>And founded kirkes ful ferly fele.</L>
<L>&THORN;e word of him welk al &thorn;e land</L>
<L>And folk ful fast fell to his hand.</L>
<L N="45">Till at &thorn;e last &thorn;e Emperoure,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ore was lord of grete honure,</L>
<L>Herd tel al how saynt Jon had went.</L>
<L>And efter him sone has he sent,</L>
<L>Opon his goddes he bad him trow.</L>
<L N="50">And for he wold noght to him bow,</L>
<L>He gert ordan a tun of bras,</L>
<L>Ful of oyle welland it was,</L>
<L>He gert saynt John &thorn;arin be done &mdash;</L>
<L>For so he hopid be venged sone.</L>
<L N="55">&THORN;e stede &thorn;at it was ordand in</L>
<L>Was named &thorn;an "&thorn;e port latyn".</L>
<L>Al-if &thorn;e oyle war welland warme,</L>
<L>&THORN;e appostell had &thorn;arof no harme;</L>
<L>For he was clene of flesly syn,</L>
<L N="60">No&thorn;er oyle ne fire his flesh might brin,</L>
<L>Bot furth he went with-outen skathe.</L>
<L>&THORN;an was &thorn;e Emperoure wonder wrathe.</L>
<L>&THORN;e appostell preched ay more and more,</L>
<L>&THORN;e Emperoure ordand &thorn;arfore &mdash;</L>
<L N="65">To exile him &thorn;an thoght him best,</L>
<L>For els he hopid to haue no rest:</L>
<L>He sent him furth with mony a knight</L>
<L>Vnto ane ile, &thorn;at Patmos hight,</L>
<L>And so he ordand him to close,</L>
<L N="70">He suld noght pas out of Patmose.</L>
<L>So lifd he &thorn;ore in ermit state</L>
<L>And in &thorn;at tyme a buke he wrate</L>
<L>Of heuynly sightes, &thorn;at he gun se</L>
<L>Whils &thorn;at he slepid in Cristes kne;</L>
<L N="75">&THORN;at buke "Apocolips" es cald &mdash;</L>
<L>So was it wretyn, als god wald.</L>
<L>Byfell in &thorn;at same &yogh;ere sertayne.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Emperoure was in batayl slayne,</L>
<L>And efter &thorn;e dede of &thorn;e Emperoure</L>
<L N="80">Was lord souerayn &thorn;e senatoure.</L>
<L>Dedes &thorn;at &thorn;e Emperoure gert do,</L>
<L>War nothing lykand him vnto;</L>
<L>To him &amp; his counsayl it semid</L>
<L>&THORN;at saynt Jon was with wrang flemid,</L>
<L N="85">And sone &thorn;ai toke &thorn;aire purpos playn
<PB REF="00000174.tif" N="36"></L>
<L>&THORN;at saynt Jon sold be broght ogayn.</L>
<L>And so ogayn he was gert cum</L>
<L>With grete honoure to Ephesum,</L>
<L>&THORN;at was a cete of grete wirshepe.</L>
<L N="90">Ful mekill folk went him to kepe:</L>
<L>"Blisced mot he be, al say &thorn;ai &thorn;us,</L>
<L>&THORN;at in goddes name cumes vntil vs!"</L>
<L>&THORN;us witht grete mirth &thorn;ai gun him mete.</L>
<L>And euyn ogayns &thorn;am in &thorn;e strete</L>
<L N="95">&THORN;ai met men makand symple chere,</L>
<L>And omang &thorn;am &thorn;ai bare a bere</L>
<L>With a body, &thorn;at to ded was dight,</L>
<L>Of a widoy &thorn;at Drusyan hight.</L>
<L>Scho had bene a ful worthly wyue</L>
<L N="100">And lufed saynt Jon wele al hir lyue.</L>
<L>Sune when hir kinred saw saynt Jon,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai knew him wele and cried ilkone:</L>
<L>"A, saynt Johne, we bere now here</L>
<L>Drusyan &thorn;at was &thorn;e ful dere,</L>
<L N="105">&THORN;at euer was bown in wurd &amp; will</L>
<L>&THORN;i bidinges baynly to fulfill;</L>
<L>And scho couayted ouer alkyn thing</L>
<L>For to here of &thorn;i home-cumyng:</L>
<L>For in hir prayers night &amp; day</L>
<L N="110">&THORN;ir wordes on &thorn;is wise wald scho say:</L>
<L>Lord, wher I sall euermore se</L>
<L>My lordes appostell cum to me? &mdash;</L>
<L>Now ertw cumen: &amp; so es dyght</L>
<L>&THORN;at scho may neuer of &thorn;e haue sight".</L>
<L N="115">When saynt John saw &thorn;is simple chere,</L>
<L>He bad &thorn;ai suld sett down &thorn;e bere,</L>
<L>"And leses &thorn;e body al-so!" he sayd.</L>
<L>And &thorn;an on &thorn;is maner he prayd:</L>
<L>"My lord Jhesu, god most of might,</L>
<L N="120">Drusyan, my frend, he rais &thorn;e right!</L>
<L>I bid &thorn;e rise, &amp; wend furth home</L>
<L>And dight my mete ogayns my come".</L>
<L>&THORN;an rase scho vp both hale &amp; fere,</L>
<L>Right als scho fro slepe raysed were,</L>
<L N="125">And, als he cumand, home scho wendes.</L>
<L>Ful mekill mirth made al hir frendes</L>
<L>And loued god &thorn;at hir had raysed,</L>
<L>And all &thorn;e peple &thorn;e appostell praysed.</L>
<L>Sune efter &thorn;an &thorn;us byfell:</L>
<L N="130">&THORN;ore in &thorn;at same cete gun dwell</L>
<L>A philisopher, &thorn;at Craton hight,</L>
<L>A grete klerk &amp; man mekil of might;</L>
<L>Perfite he was in payines lawe,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. paymes.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ful mony assented vnto his sawe.</L>
<L N="135">Disciples had he many also,</L>
<L>And omang &thorn;am war brether two,</L>
<L>To wham grete rentes in mony a stede</L>
<L>Was fallen efter &thorn;aire fader dede.</L>
<L>&THORN;is Craton gaf &thorn;am to counsaile</L>
<L N="140">And sayd: "&thorn;is werld will fayntly faile;</L>
<L>Deles noght &thorn;ar-with &mdash; &thorn;an do &yogh;e wele,</L>
<L>Gose sell yowre rent euer-ilka dele!"</L>
<L>And als he bad, &thorn;ai did in hy.</L>
<L>&THORN;an precius stones he gert &thorn;am by.</L>
<L N="145">When &thorn;ai had boght ful grete plente,</L>
<L>&THORN;e folk &thorn;an samyn sembled he,</L>
<L>For he wold lere &thorn;am on &thorn;at wise</L>
<L>&THORN;e werldes welth forto despise.</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;o childer &thorn;an gun he speke:<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. gum.).</NOTE></L>
<L N="150">"&THORN;ir stones in-sunder sal &yogh;e breke,</L>
<L>&THORN;at men may se &amp; ensawmple take</L>
<L>&THORN;is worldes welth how &yogh;e forsake".</L>
<L>&THORN;e childer war rewlid efter his rede,</L>
<L>Byfor &thorn;e pople in &thorn;at stede</L>
<L N="155">&THORN;ai brak &thorn;e stones &thorn;at &thorn;ai had boght,</L>
<L>Als men &thorn;at of no riches roght &mdash;</L>
<L>Stones &thorn;at bifore war mekill of prise</L>
<L>War nothing wurth, brokin on &thorn;at wise.</L>
<L>Herfore &thorn;e pople &thorn;am praysed fast.</L>
<L N="160">So fell: saynt John furth by &thorn;am past.</L>
<L>Of &thorn;at werk was he nothing payd</L>
<L>And vnto Craton &thorn;us he sayd:</L>
<L>"Who so wold &thorn;is werld despise,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai suld noght wirk opon &thorn;is wise.</L>
<L N="165">&THORN;at almus es noght wurth, we ken,<MILESTONE N="21" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;at es done for louyng of men.</L>
<L>In sight of men &yogh;e do &thorn;is dede,</L>
<L>&THORN;arfore of god &yogh;e get no mede;</L>
<L>Of men it makes &yogh;ow haf a name,</L>
<L N="170">Bot of god es it more to blame.</L>
<L>Who so will right &thorn;e werld for-sake,</L>
<L>Of Crist he sall ensawmple take:</L>
<L>He sais &thorn;us: &thorn;ou sal sel &thorn;i gude</L>
<L>And gif to find pouer men &thorn;aire fode,</L>
<L N="175">&THORN;an of &thorn;i gift will god be payd".
<PB REF="00000175.tif" N="37"></L>
<L>To &thorn;is Craton answerd and sayd:</L>
<L>"If verray god &thorn;i maister be</L>
<L>And techis &thorn;us als &thorn;ou tels to me.</L>
<L>And will pouer men herof haue dale:</L>
<L N="180">Lat se, tak &thorn;ou &thorn;ir peces smale</L>
<L>And mak &thorn;am precius stones ogayne!</L>
<L>So &thorn;is &thorn;at I haue wrogh(t) in vayne,</L>
<L>By-caus men suld &thorn;ar-to tak kepe,</L>
<L>Do &thorn;ou it vnto goddes wirshepe!"</L>
<L N="185">Saynt John &thorn;an gedird &thorn;o peces smale</L>
<L>And thurght his prayer made &thorn;am hale</L>
<L>In precius stones, sum les, sum more,</L>
<L>Als faire als euer &thorn;ai war byfore.</L>
<L>&THORN;an Craton and &thorn;e childer two,</L>
<L N="190">And men &amp; wemen mony one mo,</L>
<L>Turned to Crist and toke baptym</L>
<L>Of saynt John, and furth folowed him.</L>
<L>&THORN;e childer sold &thorn;aire stones &thorn;en</L>
<L>And gaf &thorn;e prise vnto pouer men;</L>
<L N="195">&THORN;e pople &thorn;an praysed &thorn;am more</L>
<L>&THORN;an for &thorn;e dede &thorn;ai did byfore.</L>
<L>Furth with saynt John &thorn;ai went alway.</L>
<L>Till efterward opon a day</L>
<L>&THORN;ai se whore men &amp; wemen standes</L>
<L N="200">&THORN;at byfore had bene &thorn;aire seruandes,</L>
<L>Ful faire of face &amp; nobilly fed</L>
<L>And in ful precius clething cled &mdash;</L>
<L>And &thorn;am-self was in symple wede<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. symeple.</NOTE></L>
<L>And pouerly, als &thorn;e apostell, &yogh;ede:</L>
<L N="205">&THORN;an in &thorn;aire hertes &thorn;ai gun repent</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ai had sold all &thorn;aire rent</L>
<L>And broght &thorn;am self to begger state.</L>
<L>&THORN;aire chere bygan forto abate</L>
<L>And dreri wex &thorn;ai in &thorn;aire mode.</L>
<L N="210">And sone, when saynt John vnderstode</L>
<L>&THORN;at of &thorn;aire werk &thorn;ai war noght payd,</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;o childer &thorn;us he sayd:</L>
<L>"Gose to &thorn;e wod &amp; get &yogh;ow wandes</L>
<L>And bring &thorn;am home bunden in bandes!</L>
<L N="215">And gose to grauell biside &thorn;e se</L>
<L>And many stones bringes vnto me!</L>
<L>So sall &yogh;e be cumforted right sone".</L>
<L>And als he cumand, so haue &thorn;ai done.</L>
<L>Sone when &thorn;ai war broght him byfore,</L>
<L N="220">In o&thorn;er kind he turned &thorn;am &thorn;ore:</L>
<L>&THORN;e wandes to gold gude for &thorn;e nones,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e grauell to precius stones;</L>
<L>He toke &thorn;am to &thorn;e childer two</L>
<L>And bad &thorn;am vnto goldsmithes go</L>
<L N="225">And vnto Jewelers, &thorn;at knew</L>
<L>To luke if &thorn;ai war gude &amp; trew.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai went seuyn dais &amp; come ogayne</L>
<L>And sayd: "sir, al men says sertayne</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ir wandes er gold ful clene,</L>
<L N="230">And better stones haf &thorn;ai noght sene".</L>
<L>&THORN;an sayd saint John: "no lenger &yogh;e stand</L>
<L>Bot gose and byes ogayne youre land</L>
<L>And rent, &thorn;at &yogh;e byfore haf solde,</L>
<L>Ou&thorn;er &thorn;e same or duble folde!</L>
<L N="235">So sal &yogh;e sone haue vp &yogh;owre cost &mdash;</L>
<L>And blis of heuyn &yogh;e both haue lost.</L>
<L>A while &yogh;e sall be faire als floures,</L>
<L>Bot for euer &yogh;e sall cast colurs;</L>
<L>A while in riches sall &yogh;e lend,</L>
<L N="240">And be beggers with - outen end".</L>
<L>&THORN;an saynt John gun a sarmon make</L>
<L>How men suld werldes welth forsake,</L>
<L>&THORN;at es to say: noght sett &thorn;arby</L>
<L>Bot to goddes seruis soueraynly.</L>
<L N="245">&THORN;at shews he by ensaumples sere,</L>
<L>And sex resons he rekin here<NOTE PLACE="foot">rekin st. rekins.</NOTE></L>
<L>No cristen men suld couayt it.</L>
<L>&THORN;e first he preues by haly wryt:</L>
<L>How &thorn;e riche man sat in his hall</L>
<L N="250">Cled in purpure and in pall,</L>
<L>And had what he wald efter think,</L>
<L>Both daynte metes &amp; delicius drink,</L>
<L>And al men fayn him forto plese;</L>
<L>And &thorn;e Lacer, &thorn;at died in disese,</L>
<L N="255">Was lifted to heuyn &amp; with god lufde,</L>
<L>When &thorn;e riche man in hell was reproued &mdash;</L>
<L>Noght onely for his erthly fode,</L>
<L>Bot for he gaf noght of his gude</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e pouer &thorn;at had more nede; &mdash;</L>
<L N="260">Herto he bad men suld tak hede.</L>
<L>&THORN;e secund: he sayd men suld haue mynde</L>
<L>How &thorn;ai er pouer of &thorn;aire owyn kynde:</L>
<L>Nakid born and all vncled</L>
<L>And with grete bale broght furth &amp; bred,</L>
<L N="265">And se&thorn;in &thorn;e life &thorn;at &thorn;ai here lede
<PB REF="00000176.tif" N="38"></L>
<L>Es night &amp; day in dole and drede.</L>
<L>If werldes riches be to &thorn;am send,</L>
<L>To goddes louyng &thorn;ai suld it spend,</L>
<L>For als nakid sal &thorn;ai wend oway</L>
<L N="270">Als &thorn;ai come furth on &thorn;e first day;</L>
<L>If &thorn;ai gif gudes to goddes louyng,</L>
<L>To blis in heuyn it will &thorn;am bring;</L>
<L>And in euil vse if &thorn;ai it spend,</L>
<L>It wynnes &thorn;am wo with-outen end.</L>
<L N="275">&THORN;e thrid: who will &thorn;e werld forsake,</L>
<L>He sayd, &thorn;ai suld ensaumple take</L>
<L>At &thorn;e sun &amp; mone and sternes bright,</L>
<L>&THORN;at dose &thorn;aire deueyre day and night,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai send &thorn;aire light to ilka place,</L>
<L N="280">To mend al men &thorn;at mister hase;</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;am-self &thorn;ai hald noght fre</L>
<L>Bot castes al furth in comunalte.</L>
<L>So suld we comun oure erthly gude,</L>
<L>&THORN;at none fail for defaut of fode;</L>
<L N="285">Vnto oure - self we suld noght spare</L>
<L>And suffer o&thorn;er men mys - fare.</L>
<L>&THORN;e ferth caus may be cald vnhapp,</L>
<L>&THORN;at so a mans hert may vmlapp:</L>
<L>He dredes his gude sal fro him fall,</L>
<L N="290">So &thorn;at he dar noght part with all.</L>
<L>&THORN;e buke says seruand he es</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e fend &amp; to riches;</L>
<L>He serues to &thorn;e fend fully,</L>
<L>For he serues vnto mawmetry</L>
<L N="295">When his hert &amp; will er ordand euyn</L>
<L>More to his gudes &thorn;an to god of heuyn;</L>
<L>For &thorn;an, als witnes haly writ,</L>
<L>His gude him &yogh;emes, &amp; he noght it.</L>
<L>&THORN;e fift: men suld refuys riches</L>
<L N="300">For grete charges and for bysines</L>
<L>And grete trauayl by many ways</L>
<L>&THORN;at fallis &thorn;arto both nightes &amp; days.</L>
<L>For werldly gudes who so will gete,</L>
<L>Ful oft - tymes bus haue trauayl grete.</L>
<L N="305">When it es getyn, &thorn;an has he drede,</L>
<L>To spend it vnto his moste spede;</L>
<L>With mekill drede he will it kepe,</L>
<L>To make haue werldly wirshepe.</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;e werst es, when he has wo</L>
<L N="310">And sorowe when he sal part &thorn;arfro:</L>
<L>Him think it es to him so dere,</L>
<L>He wold ay &thorn;at &thorn;ai samyn were;</L>
<L>To part &thorn;arfro he has grete payne &mdash;</L>
<L>And o&thorn;er frendes &thorn;ar - fore er fayne.</L>
<L N="315">&THORN;ir thre maners men may reherce</L>
<L>Als es contend here in two uerse:</L>
<L>Diues diuicias non congregat absque dolore,</L>
<L>Non tenet absque metu, non deserit absque dolore.</L>
<L>&THORN;e sext teches both old and ying</L>
<L>To refuys riches for ruseing,</L>
<L>For riches bringes in rosing so</L>
<L N="320">&THORN;at it ledes to ay - lastand wo.</L>
<L>Duble desese it dose to sum:</L>
<L>In &thorn;is life, &amp; in life to cum;</L>
<L>In &thorn;is life gers it him haue rose,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he takes no hede how he dose,</L>
<L N="325">In hert it makes so hawtayne</L>
<L>&THORN;at nou&thorn;er he sese to ioy ne payne;</L>
<L>With rosing so &thorn;e werld him glose</L>
<L>&THORN;at lastand life it gers him lose;</L>
<L>&THORN;us duble harm to a man it wins.</L>
<L N="330">And duble gude fro him it twins:</L>
<L>&THORN;at es grace &thorn;at he here suld haue,</L>
<L>To sese of syn, and his sawle saue;</L>
<L>It reues him will wele forto wirk</L>
<L>Owther vnto god or haly kirk,</L>
<L N="335">And so he loses ay-lastand sele,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he suld wyn, if he did wele. &mdash;</L>
<L>Whils saynt John prechid on &thorn;is wise</L>
<L>And wissed men &thorn;e werld to despise,</L>
<L>So was &thorn;ore broght furth him biforn</L>
<L N="340">A body &thorn;at was to beriyng born;</L>
<L>His frendes for him ful fast gun grete</L>
<L>And fell byfore &thorn;e appostell fete.</L>
<L>&THORN;e moder him prayd to rays hir sun,</L>
<L>Als he with Drusyane are had done:</L>
<L N="345">"Gude sir, do to my sun &thorn;at same</L>
<L>Thurgh might of &thorn;i god &amp; his name!"</L>
<L>On &thorn;is wise all &thorn;e pople prayd.</L>
<L>And when saynt John herd how &thorn;ai sayd</L>
<L>And how sad trowth in &thorn;am was sett,</L>
<L N="350">He knelid to grownd, &amp; for Joy gret.</L>
<L>And by he had made his prayere,</L>
<L>&THORN;e childe rase vp both hale &amp; fere.</L>
<L>Al loue &thorn;ai god &thorn;an in &thorn;at stede.</L>
<L>And saynt John bad him &thorn;at was dede<MILESTONE N="22" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="355">&THORN;at he sul tell &thorn;o brether two
<PB REF="00000177.tif" N="39"></L>
<L>&THORN;at first graunted with him to go</L>
<L>And now wold by &thorn;aire rent ogayne,</L>
<L>Whethir &thorn;ai suld haue Joy or payne.</L>
<L>&THORN;an &thorn;is child bygan to tell</L>
<L N="360">Of paradys &amp; of paynes of hell,</L>
<L>Whilk was to loue &amp; whilk to lak.</L>
<L>And &thorn;an to &thorn;o brether he spak:</L>
<L>"Allas, he sayd, wricches vnwise!</L>
<L>&YOGH;e haue made ful euil marchandise!</L>
<L N="365">I saw yowre angels wepeand sore</L>
<L>And deuils laghand ful fast &thorn;arfore.</L>
<L>I saw a palais of grete cost</L>
<L>&THORN;at &yogh;e haue for &yogh;owre foly lost;</L>
<L>With al riches it es arrayd,</L>
<L N="370">perfitely paynted and purtrayd;</L>
<L>&THORN;ore es delites of mete &amp; drink,</L>
<L>More &thorn;an men may efter think:</L>
<L>&THORN;ar es no tung in erth may tell</L>
<L>What Joy &thorn;ai haue &thorn;at &thorn;ore sal dwell,</L>
<L N="375">And &thorn;at sal last withouten end &mdash;</L>
<L>Ful wele es &thorn;am sall &thorn;eder wend!"</L>
<L>And &thorn;an he told &thorn;am &thorn;ore ogayne</L>
<L>How &thorn;ai had serued sertayne payne.</L>
<L>And sum paynes gun he &thorn;am rehers</L>
<L N="380">Als es contend here in two vers:</L>
<L>Vermes &amp; tenebre, flagellum, frigus &amp; ignis,</L>
<L>Demonum aspectus, scelerum confusio, luctus &mdash;</L>
<L>Wurms mony, with mirknes, cold,</L>
<L>Beteing ful felly, with fire hate,</L>
<L>Deuils sight in dirknes of syn</L>
<L>And shame, wepeing with wonges wate.</L>
<L N="385">When al &thorn;ir tales war told &thorn;am to,</L>
<L>&THORN;an both he and &thorn;e brether two</L>
<L>Fel doun to &thorn;e apostell fete</L>
<L>And for &thorn;aire syn sore gun &thorn;ai grete;</L>
<L>&THORN;e brether sayd &thorn;ai wold for-sake</L>
<L N="390">Al erthly gudes and to him take,</L>
<L>&THORN;e werldes riches &thorn;ai wold despise.</L>
<L>&THORN;an said he to &thorn;am on &thorn;is wise:</L>
<L>"&THORN;ir thritty dais I bid &yogh;e be</L>
<L>In prayers &amp; in penaunce fre,</L>
<L N="395">And prays to god for his grete might</L>
<L>To turn &thorn;is gold &amp; &thorn;ir besandes bright</L>
<L>In-to &thorn;aire kind to cum ogayne:</L>
<L>&THORN;an sal &yogh;e haue &yogh;oure purpose playne".</L>
<L>By thritty days war cumen all clene,</L>
<L N="400">&THORN;e gold was wurthed to wandes grene,</L>
<L>And to grauell &thorn;e precius stones.</L>
<L>&THORN;an wist saynt John wele for &thorn;e nones</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;am was graunted grace ogayne</L>
<L>&THORN;at so byfore had seruid payne.</L>
<L N="405">So was it shewd efter ful sone:</L>
<L>For grete uertuis by &thorn;am war done.</L>
<L>&THORN;an saynt John and his cumpany</L>
<L>In Effesom and in Assy</L>
<L>Techid &thorn;e folk &amp; told &thorn;am how</L>
<L N="410">&THORN;at &thorn;ai to Crist suld turn &amp; trow</L>
<L>And stabilly &thorn;an how &thorn;ai suld stand.</L>
<L>And &thorn;an &thorn;e maysters of &thorn;at land,</L>
<L>&THORN;at of &thorn;aire lawes couth dudge &amp; deme<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. dudge = judge; d scheint durch die Alliter. gefordert.</NOTE></L>
<L>And had &thorn;aire fals goddes forto &yogh;eme,</L>
<L N="415">To saynt John had &thorn;ai grete despite.</L>
<L>And &thorn;arfore gert &thorn;ai tak him tyte</L>
<L>And broght byfor &thorn;aire god Dyane:</L>
<L>"Do wirship him!" &thorn;ai cried ilkone.</L>
<L>&THORN;an saynt John to &thorn;o maysters spak</L>
<L N="420">And sayd: "I will &thorn;is couenand mak:</L>
<L>If &yogh;e may ger &yogh;owre god Dyane</L>
<L>Cast down a kirk of tre and stane</L>
<L>&THORN;at ordand es in &thorn;e name of Criste,</L>
<L>&THORN;an will I be to him obliste;</L>
<L N="425">And if he may none swilk dedes do</L>
<L>And I here speke so him vnto</L>
<L>In Cristes name forto ger fall</L>
<L>His temple &amp; him - self with all,</L>
<L>To Crist &yogh;e sall turn &yogh;owre entent".</L>
<L N="430">Vnto &thorn;is saw &thorn;ai all assent.</L>
<L>&THORN;e appostel prayd &thorn;an in &thorn;at stounde:</L>
<L>And sone he gert all go to grounde,</L>
<L>Als wax &thorn;at meltes ogayns &thorn;e fire.</L>
<L>&THORN;an was &thorn;e bisshop ful of ire,</L>
<L N="435">And grete power &thorn;an sembled he,</L>
<L>With cristen folk to feght or fle.</L>
<L>&THORN;an saynt John thoght, it was noght gude</L>
<L>To be caus of spillyng of blude,
<PB REF="00000178.tif" N="40"></L>
<L>If it myght any better be;</L>
<L N="440">&THORN;an to &thorn;e bisshop &thorn;us sayd he:</L>
<L>"Sir, lat all &thorn;is strif be still</L>
<L>And I sall wirk what so &thorn;ou will".</L>
<L>&THORN;an thoght &thorn;e bisshop with sum wile</L>
<L>Or with sum gaud him to bygile,</L>
<L N="445">And &thorn;us he sayd: "if &thorn;ou so think,</L>
<L>Venom will I &thorn;at &thorn;ou drink:</L>
<L>And if &thorn;ou haue no harm &thorn;arby,</L>
<L>&THORN;an semys it &thorn;i god es mighty.</L>
<L>And if &thorn;ou will I on him trow,</L>
<L N="450">Do so als I haf sayd &thorn;e now!"</L>
<L>So trowed he to ouercum him wele.</L>
<L>&THORN;e appostell sayd: "I graunt ilk dele".</L>
<L>&THORN;an sayd &thorn;e bisshop, him forto flay:</L>
<L>"O&thorn;er men sall &thorn;i drink assay:</L>
<L N="455">And if &thorn;ai dy bifor &thorn;i sight,</L>
<L>&THORN;an may &thorn;ou be avised right</L>
<L>Whe&thorn;ir &thorn;ou will lif or so be shent".</L>
<L>&THORN;e appostell sayd: "sir, I assent".</L>
<L>&THORN;an gert he bring furth in &thorn;at stede</L>
<L N="460">Two men &thorn;at war dampned to be dede:</L>
<L>&THORN;ai drank and so &thorn;ai war poysound,</L>
<L>&THORN;at down &thorn;ai fell ded on &thorn;e ground.</L>
<L>And &thorn;an &thorn;e appostell tok &thorn;e same</L>
<L>And blisced it in Cristes name;</L>
<L N="465">He drank it of euer-ilka dele</L>
<L>And no harm &thorn;ar-of gun he fele.</L>
<L>Al &thorn;e folk loued god &thorn;ar-fore.</L>
<L>Bot &yogh;it &thorn;e bisshop sayd to him more:</L>
<L>"I se &thorn;i god es mekill of mede,</L>
<L N="470">Bot &yogh;it sum - dele I dwell in drede.</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou might now &thorn;ir ded men rays,</L>
<L>&THORN;an think me &thorn;i god war to prays,</L>
<L>&THORN;an wold I turn and trow him to</L>
<L>And namo maystris bid &thorn;e do</L>
<L N="475">Ne miyn to (!) &thorn;e none o&thorn;ir note".<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. miyn, oder nuyn?</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e appostell &thorn;an did of his cote</L>
<L>And toke it &thorn;ore &thorn;e bisshop to.</L>
<L>And he askyd him whi he did so:</L>
<L>"Trous &thorn;ou, he sayd, to ger me dote,</L>
<L N="480">To trow in &thorn;i god for &thorn;i cote?</L>
<L>Gif it to &thorn;am &thorn;ar - of has nede!</L>
<L>Or tell me whi &thorn;ou dose &thorn;is dede!"</L>
<L>He sayd: "sir, for to mak &thorn;e stabill</L>
<L>And lat &thorn;e fele it es no fabill.</L>
<L N="485">Go lay it on &yogh;on ded bodise</L>
<L>And speke vnto &thorn;am of &thorn;is wise:</L>
<L>Cristes appostell sent me hider</L>
<L>In his name to rays yow both to-geder".</L>
<L>&THORN;e bisshop toke &thorn;e cote and &yogh;ode &mdash;</L>
<L N="490">Ful mekill folk obout &thorn;am stode;</L>
<L>He sayd als &thorn;e appostell him gert:</L>
<L>And vp &thorn;ai rase in ful gude quert.</L>
<L>&THORN;e bisshop &thorn;an &amp; al his clerkes</L>
<L>Praysed &thorn;e appostell and his werkis,</L>
<L N="495">And all &thorn;e pople turned to Crist,</L>
<L>And of &thorn;e appostell &thorn;ai war baptist;</L>
<L>And of &thorn;aire fals laws so &thorn;ai sest</L>
<L>And cristen law ful fast encrest.</L>
<L>&THORN;e bisshop gert mak kirkes of stone</L>
<L N="500">In &thorn;e honure of god and saynt John,</L>
<L>And almus-dedes on dyuers wise,</L>
<L>And endid so in goddes seruise. &mdash;</L>
<L>When saynt John was in &thorn;is werld here</L>
<L>Of eld nerehand a hundreth &yogh;ere,</L>
<L N="505">&THORN;an, als he went opon a day,</L>
<L>A brid was gifen him in &thorn;e way.</L>
<L>And als he playd &thorn;ar-with &thorn;at tyde,</L>
<L>&YOGH;ong childer &yogh;ode shoteand byside.</L>
<L>One of &thorn;am to his felows says:</L>
<L N="510">"Se, &yogh;on olde man with a brid plays</L>
<L>Als &yogh;ong childer er wont to do."</L>
<L>&THORN;an saynt John cald &thorn;at child him to,</L>
<L>For wele he wist all his entent.</L>
<L>And &thorn;e child sune his bow vnbent</L>
<L N="515">And to &thorn;e appostell he him puruayd.</L>
<L>And &thorn;an saynt John vnto him sayd:</L>
<L>"Sune, whi lettes &thorn;ou down &thorn;i string?"</L>
<L>And &thorn;e child said: "sir, for &thorn;is thing:</L>
<L>To ger my bow be more of mayn</L>
<L N="520">And bigger, when it es bent ogayn:</L>
<L>&THORN;e stiffer strake &thorn;an sall it strike".</L>
<L>And saynt John sayd: "so es it like</L>
<L>With men &thorn;at vses deuociowne</L>
<L>And will to goddes biddinges be bowne.</L>
<L N="525">Sum tyme of solace haue &thorn;ai nede,</L>
<L>Els sall &thorn;ai be dull in &thorn;aire dede;
<PB REF="00000179.tif" N="41"></L>
<L>And efter solace er &thorn;ai more abill</L>
<L>To stody, more stalwurth &amp; stabill". &mdash;</L>
<L>Of saynt John may men find also:</L>
<L N="530">On of his clerkis was went him fro;</L>
<L>He vsed to thift and robry</L>
<L>And gat to him grete cumpany,</L>
<L>And by a mountayne syide &thorn;ai dweld</L>
<L>And als &thorn;aire mayster &thorn;is &thorn;ai held;</L>
<L N="535">&THORN;ai robbed men &thorn;ore many one.</L>
<L>&THORN;e appostell wist noght wheder he was gone.</L>
<L>Bot at &thorn;e last when he herd tell</L>
<L>Of &thorn;at mountayn whore &thorn;ai gun dwell,</L>
<L>A hors he bad suld redid be;</L>
<L N="540">For olde and al vnwelde was he,</L>
<L>He was noght vsed ful oft to ride,</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;an he wold no langer byde,</L>
<L>He rade vp to &thorn;at hill on hight.</L>
<L>And when his clerk of him had sight,<MILESTONE N="23" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="545">He fled for shame and wald haf past.</L>
<L>And saynt John strake his hors ful fast</L>
<L>And efter him he cald and cried,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at o&thorn;er fast fro him hyed:</L>
<L>"Dere sun, habyde &amp; speke with me!</L>
<L N="550">Whi suld &thorn;ou fro &thorn;i fader fle?</L>
<L>&THORN;ou wist neuer none &thorn;at wirship wan</L>
<L>To fle an old vnarmyd man.</L>
<L>Dere sun, habide and drede &thorn;e noght!</L>
<L>And als &thorn;ou will, so sal be wroght.</L>
<L N="555">Vnto god for &thorn;e sal I pray</L>
<L>And my life for &thorn;e will I lay.</L>
<L>God has me sent &thorn;e forto seke".</L>
<L>When &thorn;e child herd &thorn;o wurdes meke,</L>
<L>He fel vnto &thorn;e appostel fete</L>
<L N="560">And for his sin sore gun he grete.</L>
<L>&THORN;e appostel kneled &amp; kissed his hand,</L>
<L>Als him &thorn;at he repentand fand.</L>
<L>&THORN;us he &amp; his felows in-fere</L>
<L>Conuerted to Crist with hertes clere.</L>
<L N="565">Saint John his clerk &thorn;us helpid has,</L>
<L>And se&thorn;in a gude bisshop he was</L>
<L>And lifed and dyed in goddes seruise &mdash;</L>
<L>God graunt vs to wirk on swilk wise. &mdash;</L>
<L>Isyder tels vs: when saynt John</L>
<L N="570">Was old a hundreth &yogh;ere al bot one &mdash;</L>
<L>And fel fro Cristes passion euyn</L>
<L>To rekyn sexty &yogh;eres and seuyn &mdash;</L>
<L>Crist and o&thorn;er appostels ilkone</L>
<L>Aperd and sayd &thorn;us to saynt John:</L>
<L N="575">"Cum vnto me, my wele-lufd frende!</L>
<L>For it es tyme now &thorn;at &thorn;ou wend</L>
<L>Fro &thorn;is werld, &thorn;at sune befe seste,</L>
<L>And with &thorn;i brether be at my feste.</L>
<L>For &thorn;ou in flesh has done no mys,</L>
<L N="580">&THORN;i sawl sal be with me in blis".</L>
<L>Saynt John &thorn;an made him bown to gang;</L>
<L>Crist sayd: "abyde &yogh;it, bot noght lang!</L>
<L>On sunday next, now warn I &thorn;e,</L>
<L>At my fest &thorn;an sal &thorn;ou be".</L>
<L N="585">Saynt John on &thorn;at same sunday &thorn;an</L>
<L>Ordans him in al &thorn;at he can;</L>
<L>In &thorn;at same kyrk he held him &thorn;ore</L>
<L>&THORN;at in his name was founded byfore.</L>
<L>And al &thorn;e peple of &thorn;at cete</L>
<L N="590">Cum vnto &thorn;e kirk &thorn;an cumand he.</L>
<L>He prechid &thorn;am of goddes law,</L>
<L>Fro &thorn;e first cok bigan to craw</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e sext houre of &thorn;e day,</L>
<L>And &thorn;us he warned &thorn;am al-way</L>
<L N="595">And bad, &thorn;at &thorn;(a)i sold euer-more be<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. &thorn;i st. &thorn;ai.</NOTE></L>
<L>In perfite luf and charite</L>
<L>And ilkon do to o&thorn;er ryght so</L>
<L>Als &thorn;ai wold wer done &thorn;am vnto,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at &thorn;ai suld be euer-more abill</L>
<L N="600">In &thorn;aire faith forto be stabill</L>
<L>And hald &thorn;at &thorn;ai hete in bapteme</L>
<L>And Cristes bidinges al-so to &yogh;eme.</L>
<L>When &thorn;is was done, he did a mes</L>
<L>And resayued Crist, als custum es,</L>
<L N="605">And of his brether howseld he</L>
<L>And o&thorn;er &thorn;at wold howseld be.</L>
<L>When tyme come nere &thorn;at he suld wende,</L>
<L>&THORN;an euyn at &thorn;e high-awter ende</L>
<L>A graue foure-cornerd gert he wirk</L>
<L N="610">And kest &thorn;e erth without &thorn;e kirk;</L>
<L>And euyn reuist right als he was,</L>
<L>Into &thorn;at graue so gun he pas.
<PB REF="00000180.tif" N="42"></L>
<L>To god he held vp both his hend</L>
<L>And sayd: "my lord, sen &thorn;ou has send</L>
<L N="615">To call me, to &thorn;i fest at cum</L>
<L>With my brether all and sum,</L>
<L>Knawand on what wyse &thorn;at I</L>
<L>Haue &yogh;ernid to &thorn;e euer soueraynly:</L>
<L>Now cum I at &thorn;i cumandment,</L>
<L N="620">Loueand &thorn;i grace with gude entent".</L>
<L>His brether &thorn;an he blissed &thorn;ore,</L>
<L>And so of him &thorn;ai saw namore.</L>
<L>Als he was clene fro syn sertayne,</L>
<L>So went his sowl with-outen payne;</L>
<L N="625">And als he was here mayden milde,</L>
<L>So was his fleff fro filth vnfilde.</L>
<L>&THORN;an swilk a light come in &thorn;at place</L>
<L>And held wele half an houre of space,</L>
<L>&THORN;at noman might luke whore he lay.</L>
<L N="630">And when &thorn;e light was went oway,</L>
<L>&THORN;an fand &thorn;ai al ful, whore he stode,</L>
<L>Of manna, &thorn;at es angell fode.</L>
<L>And &yogh;it es sene at &thorn;at same graue</L>
<L>How al has hele &thorn;at help will craue:</L>
<L N="635">For thurght &thorn;e mightes of saynt John</L>
<L>Miracles es done &thorn;ore manyone. &mdash;</L>
<L>And als men may find in a stede,</L>
<L>Mony hundreth &yogh;eres efter he was dede</L>
<L>Saynt Edward was of I(n)gland kyng;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. Igland.</NOTE></L>
<L N="640">And who so askid him ani thing</L>
<L>For saynt Jhones luf, &thorn;e euangelist,</L>
<L>Of almys-dede neuermore &thorn;ai mist.</L>
<L>And so bifell opon a day:</L>
<L>He met a palme(r) in &thorn;e way,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. palme.</NOTE></L>
<L N="645">&THORN;at for saynt Jhon made his prayere,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e kinges awmoner was noght nere.</L>
<L>And for he had none o&thorn;er thing,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e palmer gaf he his gold ring.</L>
<L>And efter &thorn;at tyme wele two &yogh;ere</L>
<L N="650">&THORN;an bifel on &thorn;is manere:</L>
<L>A knight trauayld by&yogh;onde &thorn;e se</L>
<L>And in-to Ingland boun was he;</L>
<L>A palmer met him on a day,</L>
<L>&THORN;at vnto him &thorn;ir wurdes gun say:</L>
<L N="655">"Sir, bere &yogh;owre king &thorn;is ring with &thorn;e</L>
<L>And say to him &thorn;ir wordes fro me:</L>
<L>&THORN;e man to wham &thorn;ou gaf &thorn;i ring,</L>
<L>&THORN;at for saynt Jhones luf asked sum thing,</L>
<L>He sendes &thorn;e here &thorn;i ring ogayne".</L>
<L N="660">&THORN;an may men se by proces playne</L>
<L>&THORN;at saynt Jhon was in pilgrim wede</L>
<L>And proued &thorn;e king of almus-dede. &mdash;</L>
<L>God graunt vs so oure gudes to gif,</L>
<L>&THORN;at we in lastand life may lif! Amen.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="8" TYPE="legend">
<HEAD>8. De sco Thoma episc. Cantuariensi.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>Die ganze Legende ist ausradirt, doch sind die Spuren der Buchstaben sichtbar geblieben. Nach V. 70 fehlt leider I fol., welches absichtlich ausgerissen scheint.</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Of marters if we suld (haue) mynde,<NOTE PLACE="foot">haue fehlt im Ms.</NOTE><MILESTONE N="23b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;an sal we carp, if we be kinde,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e gude marter saynt Thomas</L>
<L>&THORN;at here in Ingland wunand was.</L>
<L N="5">Born he was of gentill blode,</L>
<L>And euermore meke &amp; myld of mode</L>
<L>And merciful to more and les,</L>
<L>Als al his wirking beres witnes.</L>
<L>Ful cunand was he in clergy,</L>
<L N="10">And grete ofice he had for-&thorn;i:</L>
<L>First with lordes of sere degre,</L>
<L>And in &thorn;e kinges hows sethin was he</L>
<L>To ofice and to reuerence raysed,</L>
<L>And with al pople was he praysed.
<PB REF="00000181.tif" N="43"></L>
<L N="15">Till at &thorn;e last he saw &thorn;ai wroght</L>
<L>And made lawes &thorn;at him liked noght,</L>
<L>Contrary to ryghtes of haly kirk.</L>
<L>And when he saw &thorn;ai so wold wirk,</L>
<L>He left &thorn;aire mirth, if it war mery,</L>
<L N="20">And went to &thorn;e court of Canterbery.</L>
<L>&THORN;e archebisshop &thorn;an him with-held,</L>
<L>And als ane archedekyn &thorn;ore he dweld.</L>
<L>He was so milde and so honeste,</L>
<L>&THORN;at all men luffed him, most &amp; leste.</L>
<L N="25">Till at &thorn;e last &thorn;e king puruayd,</L>
<L>And also &thorn;e archebisshop prayd,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he suld vndertake &thorn;is thing</L>
<L>For to be chaunceller with &thorn;e king;</L>
<L>For &thorn;an &thorn;e archebisshop trowed wele</L>
<L N="30">&THORN;at he suld fordo ilka dele</L>
<L>&THORN;at men byfore had euill ment.</L>
<L>And he toke it to &thorn;at entent.</L>
<L>And so wisely his werk was proued:</L>
<L>&THORN;e king and al &thorn;e lordes him lufed.</L>
<L N="35">And so bifell it in &thorn;at tyde</L>
<L>&THORN;e archebisshop of Canterbiry dyde,</L>
<L>Whilk archebisshop hight Theobald.</L>
<L>And &thorn;an bityd &thorn;us, als god wald:</L>
<L>&THORN;e king &thorn;an by &thorn;e clergy rede</L>
<L N="40">Ordand saynt Thomas in his stede.</L>
<L>Bot saynt Thomas arly and late</L>
<L>Groched to gouerne so grete a state.</L>
<L>Till at &thorn;e last thurght grete praere</L>
<L>He oblist him &thorn;at charge to bere.</L>
<L N="45">And hastily he chaunged &thorn;an</L>
<L>Al his maners, als a new man,</L>
<L>Al erthly solace he forsoke</L>
<L>And preuely him vnto penaunce toke;</L>
<L>In fastinge was he ful perfite</L>
<L N="50">And left al dayntes of delite,</L>
<L>In stede of fyn cloth clene &amp; faire</L>
<L>Next his flesh he werd &thorn;e hayre.</L>
<L>Ful riche pelure he werd outward,</L>
<L>And within was &thorn;e haire ful hard.</L>
<L N="55">And so his halynes he hid,</L>
<L>&THORN;at noman wist what dedes he did,</L>
<L>Ne none was lerid of his lifing</L>
<L>Bot god, &thorn;at sese al erthly thing,</L>
<L>And his moder blissed Mary,</L>
<L N="60">To wham he prayed euer specially.</L>
<L>With al men was he mery &amp; glad,</L>
<L>Right als he &thorn;at no penance had,</L>
<L>And euer arrayd with realte</L>
<L>And ful fayre, als fell to his degre.</L>
<L N="65">He was ay redy in word &amp; dede</L>
<L>To help all &thorn;at of help had nede;</L>
<L>And ilk day, kneleand on his kne,</L>
<L>Threttene pore mens fete wesh he</L>
<L>And for &thorn;at day gert gif &thorn;am fode</L>
<L N="70">And ilkone fowre penys, when &thorn;ai &yogh;ode.</L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
</LG>
<P>(Hier fehlt ein Blatt im Ms.)</P>
<LG>
<L>Office of ded was none done &thorn;ore,<MILESTONE N="24" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>In signe &thorn;at he sul lif euer-more,</L>
<L>Bot swilk als for gude marters fell,</L>
<L>In signe &thorn;at he suld with &thorn;am dwell.</L>
<L N="265">&THORN;is miracle opinly was shewd</L>
<L>In grete louing to lerd and lewd;</L>
<L>For with god was he mekill in prise,</L>
<L>To wham angels did swilk seruise</L>
<L>And fro oure sauioure so war sent</L>
<L N="270">For to honure his enterment.</L>
<L>Many o&thorn;er miracles god ordand</L>
<L>For to be shewd for his seruand.</L>
<L>Any of &thorn;at water who so might wyn</L>
<L>&THORN;at his body was wasshen in</L>
<L N="275">Or els his clothes, more or les,</L>
<L>It might &thorn;am saue of al sekenes.</L>
<L>And so bifell it on a day:</L>
<L>A lad, &thorn;at lift his lord bitray,</L>
<L>Water of a well furth broght he has</L>
<L N="280">And sayd it was water of saynt Thomas;</L>
<L>In a boyft was it gudely grayd.</L>
<L>And &thorn;an his lord &thorn;us to him sayd:</L>
<L>"If &thorn;ou be trew in alkin thing,</L>
<L>Water of saynt Thomas may &thorn;ou bring;</L>
<L N="285">And if &thorn;ou be fals vnto me,</L>
<L>&THORN;i boist of water void sal be".</L>
<L>&THORN;e seruand knew him-self gylty</L>
<L>And graunted his trispas sone in hy.</L>
<L>&THORN;e boist &thorn;ai oppind &thorn;am bitwene:</L>
<L N="290">A(nd) no water &thorn;arin was sene.</L>
<L>So was &thorn;e seruand funden fals</L>
<L>Both of thift and of lesing als. &mdash;</L>
<L>A man, &thorn;at luffed saynt Thomas wele,</L>
<L>Grete sekenes in his flesh gun fele;</L>
<L N="295">He soght unto saynt Thomas graue:
<PB REF="00000182.tif" N="44"></L>
<L>And of his sekenes sone was he saue.</L>
<L>When he was hale, hamward he went</L>
<L>And &thorn;us he thoght in his entent:</L>
<L>"here bodyly l haue releue,</L>
<L N="300">&THORN;at in auenture my sawl may greue".</L>
<L>And &thorn;at poynt wald he proue ful fayne:</L>
<L>In &thorn;is entent he turned ogayne</L>
<L>And prayd saynt Thomas specially:</L>
<L>If it war for sawl-hele soueraynly,</L>
<L N="305">He nold haue hele, als he had &thorn;ore,</L>
<L>Or els be als he was byfore.</L>
<L>And sone, als he &thorn;us prayed has,</L>
<L>He wex als seke als euer he was.</L>
<L>&THORN;us may men lere by lessons lele</L>
<L N="310">Men suld pray noght bot for saul-hele,</L>
<L>&THORN;at es forto haue endles blis &mdash;</L>
<L>So forto wirk Jhesu vs wys!</L>
<TRAILER>Amen.
</TRAILER>

</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="9" TYPE="legend"><PB REF="00000183.tif" N="[45]">
<HEAD>9. In festo purificacionis beate Marie. Euangelium sec. Lucam: Postquam impleti sunt dies purgacionis Marie e. c.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>Auf Thomas folgt im Ms. Harl unmittelbar In festo Purificacionis beate Marie in 552 Versen, zusammengesetzt 1) aus der im Evangelientheil des Ms. Tib. fol. 113 enthaltenen Homilie auf die Reinigung Marias nach dem Gesetze Moises, nebst Exposicio presentacionis Christi und Confessio Simeonis, in 292 Versen; im ersten Theil des Ms. Harl. fehlt diese Homilie; Harl. und Tib., im Allgemeinen &uuml;berein|stimmend, weichen im Einzelnen vielfach ab. Dieser Texi stimmt nicht mit dem von Small: English metrical homilies edirten Texte des Ms. Edinb. Royal Coll. of Phys., des &auml;ltesten Homilienmanuskripts, &uuml;berein. 2) aus den Miraculis de itinere, nebst einer Einleitung &uuml;ber die 3 Namen des Festes, 293&mdash;552; dieser Theil findet sich nicht im Ms. Tib., ist aber identisch (wenn auch im Einzelnen frei umgebildet) mit dem Texte jenes Ms. Edinb.; aus dem im Einzelnen vielfach abweichenden Ms. Vernon sind diese beiden Miracula edirt mit den "Evangeliengeschichten des Ms. Vernon" in Herrigs Archiv 1875. &mdash; Das Ganze ist ein bezeichnendes Beispiel f&uuml;r das Verfahren des Sammlers der Legenden des Ms. Harl.</P><P>Ich lasse dieses Stuck. wie Nr. 12 und 15. hier ungedruckt, weil sie urspr&uuml;nglich der Homiliensammlung angeh&ouml;ren.</P></HEADNOTE>
<P> </P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="10" TYPE="legend">
<HEAD>10. De s. Agatha historia<NOTE PLACE="foot">Diese Leg. fehlt im Ms. Tib.</NOTE>.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Sant Agace, &thorn;e mayden gude,<MILESTONE N="143b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Was getin &amp; born of gentil blude.</L>
<L>Scho was ful faire of hide and hew,</L>
<L>In trowth of Crist stedfast and trew;</L>
<L N="5">Als hir life schewis, whils scho wa(s) &yogh;ing</L>
<L>Scho honurde god ouer alkins thing.</L>
<L>So fell: &thorn;are was a domesman,</L>
<L>&THORN;e whilk was named Quincian,</L>
<L>In Ce&yogh;ile whore &thorn;is mayden dwelde,</L>
<L N="10">And al with mawmetes he him melde;</L>
<L>He was lothly and litcherous<MILESTONE N="144" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And of ryches ful couaytous.</L>
<L>When he herd of &thorn;is mayden meke,</L>
<L>He cumand &thorn;at men suld her seke</L>
<L N="15">And bring hir, forto wirk his will,</L>
<L>His litchery forto fulfill.</L>
<L>Bot first he sayd &thorn;at scho suld bow</L>
<L>Opon his mawmettes forto trow.</L>
<L>And when scho was bifor him broght,</L>
<L N="20">On none wise might he turn hir thoght</L>
<L>Ne ger hir go fro goddes seruyse.</L>
<L>And &thorn;an he ordand on &thorn;is wise:</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e bordell he her sent.</L>
<L>Nyen of his doghters with hir went,</L>
<L N="25">Wilk gaf &thorn;am all to ill lifing,</L>
<L>To ger hir assent to &thorn;at same thing.</L>
<L>And thritty days &thorn;ai did &thorn;aire might</L>
<L>Besily both day and nyght,</L>
<L>Sum tyme with hard, sum tyme with nesch,
<PB REF="00000184.tif" N="46"></L>
<L N="30">To mak hir to defoul hir flesch;</L>
<L>And so &thorn;ai wald hir saul haue slayne.</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;us scho sayd to &thorn;am ogayne:</L>
<L>"My hert es sett fast opon a stone,</L>
<L>&THORN;at es Jhesu, my lord allone;</L>
<L N="35">In him &thorn;e grounde es made so trewe,</L>
<L>&THORN;at noman may it &thorn;e&thorn;in remewe.</L>
<L>&YOGH;oure wurdes to me er all in vayne,</L>
<L>&YOGH;oure hetinges waste als wind in rayne:</L>
<L>All-if &thorn;ai blaw obout me fast,</L>
<L N="40">My hert &thorn;ai may noght ouercast".</L>
<L>Oft-si&thorn;es &thorn;us to &thorn;am scho sayd,</L>
<L>And night and day to god scho prayd</L>
<L>To mak hir wurthi forto cum</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e grete ioy of martirdom.</L>
<L N="45">When &thorn;e kepers of &thorn;at bordell</L>
<L>Herd hir alswilk tales tell,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at &thorn;ai might noght turne hir mode:</L>
<L>&THORN;an to Sir Quincian &thorn;ai &yogh;ode,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai said: "sir, we might better stir</L>
<L N="50">A milne-stone &thorn;an we may hir;</L>
<L>Hard iren might we better melt</L>
<L>&THORN;an hir hert &thorn;at we with haue delt.</L>
<L>In cristen trouth es scho so stabyll,</L>
<L>&THORN;at all oure fare scho haldes bot fabill".</L>
<L N="55">Sir Quincian &thorn;an with-outen more</L>
<L>Bad bring &thorn;e mayden him bifore.</L>
<L>He assaid hir by sere resounes</L>
<L>Of kinred and of condiciounes.</L>
<L>Saynt Agace said with milde mode</L>
<L N="60">&THORN;at scho was born of gentyl blode,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at scho was a seruand trew</L>
<L>Vnto hir lord, mighty Jhesu.</L>
<L>"&THORN;an se I wele" said sir Quincian,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou ert now no fre woman;</L>
<L N="65">A fre woman, &thorn;ou vnderstand,</L>
<L>Vnto none o&thorn;er suld be seruand:</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou grauntes forto do seruise".</L>
<L>Saint Agace answerd on &thorn;is wise:</L>
<L>"&THORN;e moste gentrise, in werld mai be,</L>
<L N="70">Es forto serue to Jhesu fre".</L>
<L>Sir Quincian said: "sen &thorn;ou wil so,</L>
<L>Do chese bilyue one of &thorn;ir two:</L>
<L>Mak ofrand to oure god of might,</L>
<L>Or diuers dole to &thorn;e be dight".</L>
<L N="75">Saint Agace answerd &thorn;us ogayne:</L>
<L>"I haue no drede of erthly payne.</L>
<L>&THORN;i maumettes er bot fendes blake,</L>
<L>&THORN;aire sacrifice I wil euir forsake.</L>
<L>Swilk als &thorn;i goddes er, sal &thorn;ou be".</L>
<L N="80">In ful grete ire &thorn;an answerd he:</L>
<L>"&THORN;ir bitter wurdes &thorn;ou sal aby!</L>
<L>&THORN;ai er goddes, and so es noght I".</L>
<L>&THORN;an said saint Agace &thorn;us in hy:</L>
<L>"&THORN;i wurdes proues wele &thorn;i foul foly,</L>
<L N="85">When &thorn;ou wil noght &thorn;i life be slike</L>
<L>Als &thorn;ai &thorn;at &thorn;ou sais er goddes like;</L>
<L>How will &thorn;ou by &thorn;aire lawes lif</L>
<L>And will noght &thorn;i life to &thorn;am gif?</L>
<L>If &thorn;ou &thorn;aire felischip will fle,</L>
<L N="90">&THORN;an assentes &thorn;ou vnto me."</L>
<L>&THORN;an with &thorn;ir wurdes he wex nere wude</L>
<L>And sayd: "bot &thorn;ou tite turne &thorn;i mode</L>
<L>To wirschip oure goddes in &thorn;is stede,</L>
<L>With diuers doles &thorn;ou sal be ded.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. doles doles.</NOTE></L>
<L N="95">And &thorn;arfore smertly &thorn;e auyse!"</L>
<L>Saint Agace answerd in &thorn;is wise:</L>
<L>"&THORN;ou may noght let me forto lif.</L>
<L>For, to wilde bestes if &thorn;ou me gif,</L>
<L>Hastily &thorn;ai sal be made tame,</L>
<L N="100">When &thorn;ai here me neuin Cristes name;</L>
<L>And with fire if &thorn;ou vmbraste,</L>
<L>With dew of heuin it sal be waste.</L>
<L>To diuers paynes if &thorn;ou me deme,</L>
<L>&THORN;e haly gaste euer sal me &yogh;eme,</L>
<L N="105">And vnto me he will tak hede.</L>
<L>&THORN;arfore &thorn;i dome no-thing I drede".</L>
<L>He cumand &thorn;an, scho suld be kast</L>
<L>In prisoun and &thorn;ore feterd fast.</L>
<L>&THORN;edir scho went with hert ful glad</L>
<L N="110">And euir to heuyn hir hert scho had.</L>
<L>Quincian cumand on &thorn;e morn,</L>
<L>Scho suld be broght furth him biforn.</L>
<L>He bad, scho suld forsake Jhesu</L>
<L>And trow his goddes &thorn;at war trew.</L>
<L N="115">Bot scho diffied &thorn;am al bidene.</L>
<L>And &thorn;an he cumand in grete tene</L>
<L>To hing hir on &thorn;e pillory,</L>
<L>And bad &thorn;ai suld bete hir body</L>
<L>And ger hir so hir goddes forsake
<PB REF="00000185.tif" N="47"></L>
<L N="120">And ofrand to his maumetis make.</L>
<L>Saint Agace answerd &thorn;us alstyte:</L>
<L>"In &thorn;ir paynes haue I swilk delite</L>
<L>Als if a man war in fer land</L>
<L>And of his frendes herd gude ti&thorn;and,</L>
<L N="125">Or als a man of &thorn;am wold be</L>
<L>&THORN;at he had &yogh;ernid lang to se.</L>
<L>For right als corn here es noght sene</L>
<L>Done in gerner or it be clene</L>
<L>And al filthis clensid &thorn;ar-fro,</L>
<L N="130">My saul bus be clensid right so</L>
<L>With diuers paynes of marterdom</L>
<L>Or it to blis of paradis cum".</L>
<L>&THORN;an cumand he tite him biforn</L>
<L>&THORN;at both hir pappes suld be of schorn:</L>
<L N="135">So wend he wele hir sone to schende.</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;us answerd &thorn;e mayden hende:</L>
<L>"Cursed terand, whore es &thorn;i mynde?</L>
<L>&THORN;ou cumandes now ogayns &thorn;i kinde;</L>
<L>To schere my pappes, &thorn;e suld noght like,</L>
<L N="140">For of &thorn;i moder &thorn;ou souked slike.</L>
<L>Mi bodili pappes if &thorn;ou of schere,</L>
<L>Within my saul ful hale pappes ere:</L>
<L>&THORN;o pappes &thorn;ou may noght fro me riue,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai haue norist my wittes fiue</L>
<L N="145">And sustend me sen my barnhede</L>
<L>To serue to god in wurd and dede".</L>
<L>&THORN;an was &thorn;e terand wunder wo.</L>
<L>And when hir pappes war raced hir fro,</L>
<L>To prison demid he hir ogayne</L>
<L N="150">And cumand &thorn;e kepers on grete payne</L>
<L>&THORN;at no wight suld vnto hir wend</L>
<L>With nonekins medcin hir to mend,</L>
<L>Ne gif hir noght bot water and brede:</L>
<L>"So sall scho sone be pyned to dede".</L>
<L N="155">Bot to wham scho had hyr tone,</L>
<L>He wald noght leue hyr so allone.</L>
<L>Obout midnyght als scho was stedd,</L>
<L>When al hir kepers war to bedd,</L>
<L>Ane old man and a litel childe</L>
<L N="160">Come vnto &thorn;at mayden milde;</L>
<L>&THORN;e childe broght a lantern with light,</L>
<L>&THORN;e olde medcins in boystes bright.</L>
<L>&THORN;e olde man doun bifor hir kneld</L>
<L>And profird him to be hir belde,</L>
<L N="165">And &thorn;us he said hir forto plese:</L>
<L>"All-if &thorn;e domesman do &thorn;e dissese</L>
<L>To pyne &thorn;e &thorn;us with paynes sore,</L>
<L>&THORN;ine answers turmentes him wele more;</L>
<L>I was byside and saw ilkdele.</L>
<L N="170">And if &thorn;ou will, I wote right wele</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou mai be helid of &thorn;i payn</L>
<L>And haue &thorn;i pappes restored ogayn".</L>
<L>Saint Agace &thorn;an wele trowed and wend</L>
<L>&THORN;at he for syn war &thorn;eder send;</L>
<L N="175">&THORN;arfore in hert scho was affraid</L>
<L>And al &thorn;us vnto him scho sayd:</L>
<L>"I toke neuer medcyn bodily</L>
<L>Forto do hele to my body.</L>
<L>And schame war to tyne vs bitwene</L>
<L N="180">&THORN;at I so lang haue kepid clene:</L>
<L>Mi maidenhed euer haue I hight</L>
<L>To my luf Jhesu, moste of might".</L>
<L>"Drede &thorn;e noght, doghter! said he &thorn;an,</L>
<L>For sertes I am a cristen man.</L>
<L N="185">Be noght asschamid to speke with me!</L>
<L>For I am cumen to confort &thorn;e".</L>
<L>"Nai, sertis, scho said, I am right balde</L>
<L>And noght afferd; for &thorn;ou ert alde,</L>
<L>And I am woundid so wikkedli:</L>
<L N="190">Men lathes to luke on my body.</L>
<L>Bot I loue god with hert and hend</L>
<L>&THORN;at sucure has to me send".</L>
<L>&THORN;an vnto hir al &thorn;us said he:</L>
<L>"Why will &thorn;ou noght be helid of me,</L>
<L N="195">Sen I may relese al &thorn;i payne"?</L>
<L>And &thorn;an answerd scho &thorn;us ogayne:</L>
<L>"I haue Jhesu, my lord and king,</L>
<L>&THORN;at with his wurd mai hele al thing:</L>
<L>He may me hele wele, if he will,</L>
<L N="200">For al defautes he may fulfill".</L>
<L>&THORN;an &thorn;e olde man on hir smilde</L>
<L>And sayd &thorn;us vnto &thorn;at maiden milde:</L>
<L>"I am Peter &thorn;at with Jhesu went,<MILESTONE N="145" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And &thorn;us vnto &thorn;e he has me sent.</L>
<L N="205">Luke trewly &thorn;at &thorn;ou trow &thorn;is tale,</L>
<L>And in his name &thorn;ou sal be hale".</L>
<L>Scho said: "sir, all &thorn;i tales I trow".</L>
<L>&THORN;an was he went, scho wist noght how.</L>
<L>Hir pappes war on hir brest ogayne;</L>
<L N="210">Scho thankid god and was ful fayne.</L>
<L>&THORN;e kepers, when &thorn;ai saw &thorn;at sight,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai war all so ferd for &thorn;at light:
<PB REF="00000186.tif" N="48"></L>
<L>Ilkone &thorn;ai fled and durst noght bide</L>
<L>And left &thorn;e dores all opyn wide.</L>
<L N="215">A seruand said saint Agace vntill:</L>
<L>"Wend furth now, woman, whore &thorn;ou will!</L>
<L>For dores and &yogh;ates es opin sett</L>
<L>And here es none &thorn;e forto let".</L>
<L>Saint Agace said: "nai, god forbede</L>
<L N="220">&THORN;at I suld fle and lose mi mede!</L>
<L>It sall noght cum in myne entent</L>
<L>To ger my kepers so be schent".</L>
<L>When foure days war fully gone,</L>
<L>&THORN;an was scho broght to bar allone.</L>
<L N="225">&THORN;e domesman bad hir mercy craue,</L>
<L>Or more sorow &yogh;it suld scho haue</L>
<L>And suffer ded with diuers payne.</L>
<L>Scho sayd: "&thorn;i wurdes er al in vaine</L>
<L>And foule foly, &thorn;at es noght faire:</L>
<L N="230">&THORN;ai file &thorn;e erth and als &thorn;e ayre.</L>
<L>Wretche, scho said, with-outen witt,</L>
<L>How wold &thorn;ou &thorn;at I wirschipd &yogh;it</L>
<L>&THORN;i maumetes made of tre and stone</L>
<L>And leue Jhesu, my lord allone,</L>
<L N="235">&THORN;at helid my woundes whore I satt?"</L>
<L>And &thorn;an said he: "what es he &thorn;at?"</L>
<L>Scho said: "my lord, god sun in heuyn".</L>
<L>And &thorn;an sayd he: "how dar &thorn;ou neuyn</L>
<L>His name &thorn;at mai mak &thorn;e more stryf?"</L>
<L N="240">Scho sayd: "euir, whils me lastes life,</L>
<L>I schall let for none erthly schame</L>
<L>Nyght and day forto neuyn his name".</L>
<L>Quyncian sayd: "sune sall we se</L>
<L>Whe&thorn;ir es more mayster, I or he".</L>
<L N="245">He bad, &thorn;ai suld tak scharp schelles</L>
<L>And brinand coles and no-thin(g) ells,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. thin.</NOTE></L>
<L>And lay &thorn;aron hir body all bare.</L>
<L>Bot sone when thir thinges ordand ware,</L>
<L>Swilk ane erthdin bigan to be,</L>
<L N="250">So &thorn;at grete partyse of &thorn;at cete</L>
<L>War kasten doun, both halles and boures;</L>
<L>And two of &thorn;e chefe counsaloures</L>
<L>Of Quinciane war fallen to dede.</L>
<L>And all &thorn;e folk ful will of rede</L>
<L N="255">&THORN;ai cried to him and &thorn;us &thorn;ai tell</L>
<L>&THORN;at all &thorn;is vengeance &thorn;at &thorn;ore fell</L>
<L>And all torfers &thorn;at &thorn;ore bityd</L>
<L>Was for &thorn;e euyl dedis &thorn;at he did</L>
<L>To saynt Agace, &thorn;e mayden milde.</L>
<L N="260">And &thorn;an he held him all bigilde,</L>
<L>For grete erthdin &thorn;at fel &thorn;at tyde</L>
<L>And for &thorn;e folk &thorn;at ful fast cride;</L>
<L>He wist neuer what was best to do,</L>
<L>Bot prison he bad &thorn;am put hir to.</L>
<L N="265">So when scho was in prison done,</L>
<L>&THORN;us vnto god scho made hir bone:</L>
<L>"My lord Jhesu, als &thorn;ou me wroght</L>
<L>And fro barnhed &thorn;us has me broght</L>
<L>And kepid my body clene of syn</L>
<L N="270">And left none erthly luf &thorn;arein</L>
<L>And in my paynes more &amp; les</L>
<L>Sendes me &thorn;e vertu of mekenes:</L>
<L>Lord, &thorn;ou haue mercy on me</L>
<L>And sune resayue mi saul to &thorn;e!"</L>
<L N="275">Hir prayer herd oure lord Jhesu</L>
<L>And toke to him his seruand trew:</L>
<L>For sune when scho hir speche had spend,</L>
<L>To heuyn scho held ut heuid and hend<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. ut st. up.</NOTE></L>
<L>And in &thorn;at stede scho gaf &thorn;e gaste</L>
<L N="280">Vnto hir lorde &thorn;at scho lufde maste.</L>
<L>&THORN;an cristen folk tok hir body</L>
<L>And wroght &thorn;arwit ful wirschiply:</L>
<L>&THORN;ai groue it in a graue of stone</L>
<L>With bawm and vnementes gude wone.</L>
<L N="285">Whore efter was grete vertu schewd</L>
<L>And grete releue to lerd and lewde.</L>
<L>For who so wold &thorn;ore sucure craue,</L>
<L>Of sere sekenes sune war &thorn;ai saue;</L>
<L>And who askid hir any bone,</L>
<L N="290">With sekir hope &thorn;ai had it sone &mdash;</L>
<L>Als es wele proued and apertly</L>
<L>In &thorn;e legend of Saynt Lucy.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="11" TYPE="legend"><PB REF="00000187.tif" N="49">
<HEAD>11. De festo sci Petri apostoli quod dicitur in Cathedra.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Saint Peter, Cristes apostil dere,</L>
<L>In &thorn;is werld had grete powere.</L>
<L>&THORN;is fest he has and o&thorn;er twa,</L>
<L>And &thorn;is es cald &thorn;us: In Cathedra.</L>
<L N="5">It leres vs with-outen lett</L>
<L>How he was first in chayer set</L>
<L>In Antioche, and sethin in Rome,</L>
<L>Als chefe curate of Cristendome.</L>
<L>Bot first he went in diuers land,</L>
<L N="10">&THORN;e sede of goddes wurd sawand;</L>
<L>Of haly kirk he set &thorn;e ground,</L>
<L>Als god him-self first had it found:</L>
<L>For god to him &thorn;ir wurdes said,</L>
<L>Als it es in &thorn;e godspell grayd:</L>
<L>Dico tibi quia tu es petrus &amp; super</L>
<L>hanc petram edificabo ecclesiam meam:</L>
<L N="15">"Peter, he sayd, &thorn;ou es &thorn;at stone</L>
<L>&THORN;at I sal big my kirk opon".</L>
<L>And al &thorn;is to fulfill in dede,</L>
<L>To Antioche prechand he &yogh;ede.</L>
<L>Sune when &thorn;e folk might vnderstand</L>
<L N="20">&THORN;at Peter was to &thorn;am cumand,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai went with grete processioune</L>
<L>And kest pouder opon &thorn;air croune,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai did penaunce with all &thorn;aire mayne,</L>
<L>And barfote went &thorn;ai him ogayne.</L>
<L N="25">&THORN;&agrave;i loued god fast for his cumyng,</L>
<L>And sum men loued him for &thorn;is thing:</L>
<L>For he had Simon Magus feld</L>
<L>&THORN;at lang bifore had with &thorn;am dweld.</L>
<L>And many &thorn;at war seke and sore</L>
<L N="30">And with &thorn;at maumet hurt bifore,</L>
<L>Come &thorn;edir and vnto Peter knelde</L>
<L>And prayd him forto be &thorn;are belde</L>
<L>And warisch &thorn;am out of &thorn;aire wo.</L>
<L>With-outen noumber come &thorn;ar so.</L>
<L N="35">Saint Peter &thorn;an saw wele inogh</L>
<L>How all cuntres vnto him drogh.</L>
<L>&THORN;an vnto god hertly he prayd</L>
<L>And in his praiers &thorn;us he sayd:</L>
<L>"High fader in heuyn, loued mot &thorn;ou be</L>
<L N="40">&THORN;at of &thorn;i grace grauntes to me</L>
<L>Forto fulfill all &thorn;at &thorn;ou hight</L>
<L>To oure maister Jhesu, mekil of might:</L>
<L>So &thorn;at ilk creature may knaw</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou es lord of high and law".</L>
<L N="45">&THORN;us praid he vnto god, and gret.</L>
<L>An(d) sethin on heght vp he him sett,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at all &thorn;e puple might him se,</L>
<L>And vnto &thorn;am all &thorn;us said he:</L>
<L>"Bihaldes, he said, and sese me now</L>
<L N="50">Ane erthly man als ane of &yogh;ow,</L>
<L>And &thorn;arfore trows noght more ne les</L>
<L>&THORN;at I may saue &yogh;ow of no sekenes!</L>
<L>Bot trous &thorn;at he may &yogh;ow amend</L>
<L>&THORN;at doun fro heuyn to erth descend:</L>
<L N="55">For in him es al &thorn;e hele anely</L>
<L>Both of man saul and of body.</L>
<L>And in him if &yogh;e trewly trow,</L>
<L>Thurgh his help hele hete I &yogh;ow".</L>
<L>&THORN;ai cried and graunted both &yogh;ung and alde</L>
<L N="60">Him verray god &thorn;at he of talde,</L>
<L>And &thorn;arto held &thorn;ai handes on hight.</L>
<L>And so &thorn;ore come a sodain light</L>
<L>Thurgh grace of god omang &thorn;am all:</L>
<L>So war &thorn;ai helid grete and small;</L>
<L N="65">Al &thorn;at war blind sune had &thorn;ai sight,</L>
<L>And croked and lame rase vp ful right.</L>
<L>Byfor saynt Peter fete &thorn;ai fell,</L>
<L>Ful mekil mirth was &thorn;am omell.</L>
<L>In seuyn days, when &thorn;is was puplist,</L>
<L N="70">Mo &thorn;an ten thowsand war baptist;</L>
<L>&THORN;ai forsoke al &thorn;aire maumetry</L>
<L>And trowed in Jhesu Crist mercy.</L>
<L>So als he to &thorn;e pople prechid</L>
<L>And laus of Crist vnto &thorn;am techid,</L>
<L N="75">A proud prince, &thorn;at hight Trophilus,</L>
<L>Sent efter Peter and said him &thorn;us:</L>
<L>"How dar &thorn;ou, felow, for drede &amp; awe</L>
<L>Turn my folk ogayns my lawe?"</L>
<L>Saynt Peter sayd: "I dar avow,</L>
<L N="80">Al &thorn;at I tell aw &thorn;e to trow".</L>
<L>&THORN;e prince bad &thorn;an &thorn;at he suld sune
<PB REF="00000188.tif" N="50"></L>
<L>Into a depe dongeon be dune,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at no man for luf ne drede</L>
<L>Suld mete ne drink vnto him bede.</L>
<L N="85">His men did sone als he cumand,</L>
<L>Saint Peter in prisoun &thorn;ai band.</L>
<L>And &thorn;ore he sat all out of sight,</L>
<L>Till he had lost mekyll of his might.</L>
<L>&THORN;an vnto god &thorn;us gun he pray:</L>
<L N="90">"My lord Jhesu, &thorn;at helpis me ay</L>
<L>And all &thorn;at for &thorn;e suffers any grefe,</L>
<L>Haue mynde on me in &thorn;is mischefe!</L>
<L>For now I faile for faut of fude".</L>
<L>And sune he had herting ful gude:</L>
<L N="95">Oure lord Jhesu to him aperd</L>
<L>And gude releue to him he lerid:</L>
<L>"Peter, he sayd, why trowes &thorn;ou</L>
<L>&THORN;at I haue &thorn;e forsaken now?</L>
<L>Trist in my help! &thorn;ou sall it haue,<MILESTONE N="146" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="100">Sune sall he cum &thorn;at sall &thorn;e saue".</L>
<L>When &thorn;is was said, he herd namore.</L>
<L>&THORN;us ful wele was he cumfort &thorn;ore.</L>
<L>And on &thorn;e morn so it byfell:</L>
<L>Saynt Paul, his brother, sone herd tell</L>
<L N="105">How saynt Peter in prisoun was.</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e prince sone gun he pas,</L>
<L>He sayd he couth of alkins werk</L>
<L>&THORN;at fell to laud man or to clerk,</L>
<L>In tre and stone he couth wirk wele</L>
<L N="110">And graue in iren and als in stele,</L>
<L>And alkins werk wele couth he wirk</L>
<L>&THORN;at fell to castell or to kirk &mdash;</L>
<L>And all &thorn;is sayd he for &thorn;is thing:</L>
<L>His brother out of bale to bring.</L>
<L N="115">When &thorn;e prince herd him &thorn;usgat tell,</L>
<L>He prayd him in his court to dwell.</L>
<L>In &thorn;e princis court he dwellid &thorn;an.</L>
<L>And into &thorn;e prisoun sune he wan</L>
<L>Whore Peter lay in poynt of dede.</L>
<L N="120">And when Paul saw him in &thorn;at stede,</L>
<L>He wepid for him fast als he stode,</L>
<L>And sethin he sayd with dreri mode:</L>
<L>"A, Petir, my brothir, comfort &thorn;e</L>
<L>And opyn &thorn;i mouth &amp; speke with me!"</L>
<L N="125">Saint Petir herd and wele him knew</L>
<L>&THORN;at it was Paul, his brothir trew;</L>
<L>He lukid on him, and gret alway,</L>
<L>Bot no wurde might he to him say.</L>
<L>&THORN;an Poul by strenth opind his mouth,</L>
<L N="130">And comfort him all &thorn;at he couth:</L>
<L>God sent vnto &thorn;am mete &amp; drink,</L>
<L>Swilk als &thorn;aire hertes wald efter think.</L>
<L>Saint Peter gat sum might ogaine,</L>
<L>And aythir of othir was ful fayne;</L>
<L N="135">Of greteing might &thorn;ai noght be still,</L>
<L>Til &thorn;ai had both wepid &thorn;aire fill.</L>
<L>Saint Poul of &thorn;e kepers gat slike grace,</L>
<L>&THORN;at al night dweld he in &thorn;at place.</L>
<L>And when it drogh nere to &thorn;e day,</L>
<L N="140">Ful preuely he passed oway.</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e prince with faire quaintise</L>
<L>He come and counsayld on &thorn;is wise:</L>
<L>"Sir, &thorn;ou es prince &thorn;at reulis al right,</L>
<L>And no-thing may gaynstand &thorn;i might;</L>
<L N="145">Bot one thing, syr, als thinkes me</L>
<L>Es mikell ogayns &thorn;ine honeste:</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou wil so in prison hald</L>
<L>A pouer man, &thorn;at es Peter cald;</L>
<L>Pyned he es vnto &thorn;e last end,</L>
<L N="150">And &thorn;at may noght to &thorn;e amend</L>
<L>All-if he in his mightes faile.</L>
<L>His wurdes might moni men auail,</L>
<L>And his life might do mekill gude:</L>
<L>For &thorn;us men has sayd, whore he &yogh;ode,</L>
<L N="155">&THORN;at he has helid both man &amp; wife</L>
<L>And raysed ded men vnto life.</L>
<L>Sir, swilk a man suld noght be slayne".</L>
<L>And &thorn;an answerd &THORN;e prince ogayne:</L>
<L>"Al &thorn;ir wurdes &thorn;at &thorn;ou tels to me</L>
<L N="160">Er fabill and faynt. &thorn;at proue I &thorn;e.</L>
<L>If he myght rays ded men of graue,</L>
<L>Why will he noght him-seluyn saue</L>
<L>Out of prisoun and out of payne?"</L>
<L>&THORN;an answerd Poul vnto him ogayne:</L>
<L N="165">"Sir, he said, he wirkes now here</L>
<L>By ensaumple of Crist, his maister dere.</L>
<L>We wote wele, Crist rase vp ful right,</L>
<L>When he was ded, by his owin might;</L>
<L>And neuer-&thorn;e-les &yogh;it wold he noght</L>
<L N="170">Cum doune, when he on cros was broght.</L>
<L>For &thorn;is skill Peter, ane of twelue,</L>
<L>Will noght assay to saue him-selue,</L>
<L>Bot redy es he for hys sake</L>
<L>Paynes and turmentes forto take".</L>
<L N="175">&THORN;an sayd &thorn;e prince: "sen he lufs so
<PB REF="00000189.tif" N="51"></L>
<L>To suffer paynes, he sall haue mo.</L>
<L>Bot neuer-&thorn;e-les sune sal we se</L>
<L>If &thorn;is be trew &thorn;ou tels to me.</L>
<L>I had a sun &thorn;at was me dere,</L>
<L N="180">And sethin he dyed, es fourtene &yogh;ere:</L>
<L>If he ogayn may ger him life,</L>
<L>&THORN;an all my grefe I wil forgife</L>
<L>And relese him, with pardon playne".</L>
<L>&THORN;an said Poul &thorn;us to him ogaine:</L>
<L N="185">"Thurgh grace of god &thorn;is sal be done".</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e prisoun &thorn;an went he sone,</L>
<L>He told to Peter how he had hight</L>
<L>&THORN;e prince sun forto rayse up right</L>
<L>&THORN;at had bene ded ful fourtene &yogh;ere.</L>
<L N="190">&THORN;an Peter said: "Paul, brother dere,</L>
<L>A grete thing has &thorn;ou vndertane.</L>
<L>Bot to god grete thing es it nane &mdash;</L>
<L>We wote, his might es mekill more".</L>
<L>&THORN;an was Peter tone fro prison &thorn;ore.</L>
<L N="195">Onto graue &thorn;ai went ilkone,</L>
<L>He bad &thorn;am stir oway &thorn;e stone</L>
<L>And remu al &thorn;e erth oway.</L>
<L>And als he cumand, so did &thorn;ai.</L>
<L>To god &thorn;an made he his prayere:</L>
<L N="200">And he &thorn;at was ded fourtene &yogh;ere</L>
<L>Thurgh grace of god &thorn;an was raysed.</L>
<L>&THORN;e prince and al &thorn;e puple him praysd.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai turned to Crist and baptym toke</L>
<L>And war sauid, als sais &thorn;e boke.</L>
<L N="205">&THORN;e prince &thorn;an kest him wele to wirk:</L>
<L>Of his castell he made a kirk</L>
<L>With grete riches ful really</L>
<L>In honure of god almighty;</L>
<L>And in &thorn;at kirk &thorn;an he ordand</L>
<L N="210">A riche chayer on heght to stand,</L>
<L>And Peter &thorn;aire bisschop forto be</L>
<L>And to sit so, &thorn;at al men might se.</L>
<L>&THORN;us haly kirk &thorn;ore was bigun,</L>
<L>And &thorn;is fest &thorn;arof founded and fun</L>
<L N="215">How saint Peter gat to grete degre</L>
<L>In Antioche, &thorn;e riche cete.</L>
<L>Seuyn winters was (he) bisschop &thorn;ore</L>
<L>And made Cristes law ay more &amp; more;</L>
<L>Prestes and dekins ordand he,</L>
<L N="220">To serue vnto god in sere degre.</L>
<L>&THORN;an was fulfild &thorn;e prophecy</L>
<L>&THORN;at spekis of (him) &thorn;us appertly:</L>
</LG>
<Q>Exaltent eum in ecclesia plebis: &amp; in cathedra seniorum laudent eum &mdash;</Q>
<LG>
<L>"&THORN;ai sall enhigh him in &thorn;e kirk</L>
<L>Whore &thorn;e pople sall goddes wirschip wirk,</L>
<L N="225">And in &thorn;e chayer of olde men</L>
<L>Sal all him loue &thorn;at him sal ken".</L>
<L>When seuin winters war past till end,</L>
<L>&THORN;an god slike grace vnto him send,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he was chosen pape of Rome</L>
<L N="230">And chef curate of Cristendome &mdash;</L>
<L>For god gaff him his power playne</L>
<L>&THORN;at, wham he lesid of syn sertayne</L>
<L>In &thorn;is erth thurgh his pouste,</L>
<L>In heuyn &thorn;an lesid suld &thorn;ai be,</L>
<L N="235">And wham he band here bi his steuyn</L>
<L>&THORN;ai suld be bunden fro blis of heuyn.</L>
<L>&THORN;us was he pape thurgh goddes powere</L>
<L>Fully fyue and twenty &yogh;ere,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ore he dyed and went to blis&mdash;</L>
<L N="240">&THORN;at way to wende oure lord us wis!</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="12" TYPE="legend">
<HEAD>12. In festo Annunciacionis beate Marie.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>Auch dieses St&uuml;ck, wie No. 9, besteht aus 1) dem Evangelium des Tages (-97) nebst Expositio (-168) und 2) einem Miraculum (-306). Der erste Theil sindet sich bereits im Evangelientheil dess. Ms. fol. 6, und des Ms. Tib. fol. 103, mit dems. Text vom Aue Maria an (der Anfang ist frei nach Ashm. 42); das Miraculum fehlt in Tib. und dem ersten Theil des Ms. Harl. Das Ganze ist eine etwas freiere Umbildung ders. Homilie in der n&ouml;rdl. Evangeliensammlung (Ms. Ashm. 42 u. a.). Das Mirac. ist aus Ms. Vernon abgedruckt in den "Evangeliengeschichten des Ms. Vernon" in Herrig's Archiv, No. 4, u. d. T. de milite depauperato diligente matrem domini.</P></HEADNOTE>
<P> </P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="13" TYPE="legend">

<PB REF="00000190.tif" N="52">
<HEAD>13. In festo sanctorum apostolorum Philippi &amp; Jacobi.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>Mit dieser Legende beginnt die der Homiliensammlung angeh&auml;ngte Legendenreihe des Ms. Tib., fol. 244 b, ohne weitere Einleitung und, wie es scheint, ohne beson|deren Titel oder Absatz; sie schliesst sich unmittelbar den auf der Vorderseite been|deten Homilien an. Die erste Columne ist nur theilweise lesbar. Der Text weicht, wie bei den fr&uuml;heren Legenden, in Einzelheiten ab. &mdash; Als Varianten sind lesbar:</P></HEADNOTE>
<DIV3 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Saint Philip &amp; Jacob day<MILESTONE N="148" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="foot">Jacobes.</NOTE></L>
<L>Es first in &thorn;e moneth of May:</L>
<L>In &thorn;at day &thorn;ai both in a stede</L>
<L>For Cristes sake war done to dede,</L>
<L N="5">When twenty &yogh;ere to end war went</L>
<L>Fro-tyme &thorn;at Crist to heuyn was hent,</L>
<L>Als men may in &thorn;aire storis tell.</L>
<L>&THORN;an on &thorn;is maner it bifell:</L>
<L>Saint Philip prechid of god almighty</L>
<L N="10">In a land &thorn;at was named Sithy;<NOTE PLACE="foot">2&mdash;10) sind ganz zerst&ouml;rt.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot">lesbar Sythi.</NOTE></L>
<L>He prechid &thorn;e might of god verray</L>
<L>To folk &thorn;at lifd on deuils lay.<NOTE PLACE="foot">11&mdash;12) umgesetzt.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot">lifed.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;o lawles folk his lare fo(r)soke,<NOTE PLACE="foot">lesbar ist: . . folk his . . forsuke.</NOTE></L>
<L>And sune omang &thorn;am &thorn;ai him toke,<NOTE PLACE="foot">sone.</NOTE></L>
<L N="15">Vnto &thorn;aire maumet &thorn;ai him led.<NOTE PLACE="foot">(An)d to.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;an was &thorn;at deuil ful sore adred<NOTE PLACE="foot">sare.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at he suld sune &thorn;ore be distruyed:</L>
<L>&THORN;arfore al &thorn;at he might he noyed.<NOTE PLACE="foot">17)-18) fehlen.</NOTE></L>
<L>By deuils might &thorn;an, als men knew,<NOTE PLACE="foot">(&thorn;an) &thorn;at mawmet als men knew.</NOTE></L>
<L N="20">Blastes out of his mouth he blew,</L>
<L>&THORN;at war so euyl and vn-honeste:<NOTE PLACE="foot">lesbar (hon)este.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ai destryd oft both man and beste.<NOTE PLACE="foot">oft (destr)yd.</NOTE></L>
<L>And with blast of hys mouth allone<NOTE PLACE="foot">allane.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e prince sun of &thorn;e land was slone,<NOTE PLACE="foot">slane.</NOTE></L>
<L N="25">And two grete maysters of &thorn;e law<NOTE PLACE="foot">25 ff.) nur einzelne Worte sind lesbar, meist=Harl.</NOTE></L>
<L>With his blast war broght of daw,</L>
<L>And all &thorn;e folk &thorn;at itt come nere</L>
<L>War mesels made and all vnfere.</L>
<L>Grete sorow was sene on ilka side<NOTE PLACE="foot">(M)ekell wa . .</NOTE></L>
<L N="30">For care &thorn;at come to &thorn;am &thorn;at tide;</L>
<L>On ilka side was sorows sere;<NOTE PLACE="foot">(And)ilkane had &thorn;are sorows sere.</NOTE></L>
<L>Sum war &thorn;ai ded, and sum ful nere.</L>
<L>Saint Philip, when he saw &thorn;at sight,</L>
<L>How dolefully &thorn;e folk war dight,</L>
<L N="35">In his hert he had grete pete,</L>
<L>And vnto &thorn;am all &thorn;us said he:</L>
<L>"And &yogh;e will trow als I &yogh;ow lere,</L>
<L>Sune &yogh;e sall be hale and fere</L>
<L>Of euyls &thorn;at &yogh;e er in stad".</L>
<L N="40">&THORN;ai graunted all with hertis glad,</L>
<L>What he wold deme al wold &thorn;ai do.</L>
<L>&THORN;an on &thorn;is wise he said &thorn;am to:</L>
<L>"Trowes in Crist and mercy cry,</L>
<L>And dinges downe al &thorn;is maumetry!</L>
<L N="45">And rays &yogh;e sall &thorn;an bi my rede</L>
<L>&THORN;e cros of Crist in &thorn;at same stede".</L>
<L>Saynt Philip &thorn;an thurgh goddes grace</L>
<L>Byfor al &thorn;e puple in &thorn;at place</L>
<L>A foul deuyl he gert out gang</L>
<L N="50">&THORN;at &thorn;am had &thorn;ore disceayued lang &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">33&mdash;50) lesbar sind nur die Reimw&ouml;rter mawmettri 44, rede 45, same stede 46, goddes grace 47, (&thorn;a)m omang 49, gang 50. Die 2. Columne 51&mdash;98 ist deutlich lesbar.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ful vgly was he on to se.<NOTE PLACE="foot">&THORN;at vgly was on forto se.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;an &thorn;e puple grete plente</L>
<L>Drogh doun &thorn;aire temple, more &amp; myn,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Drogh to ground both more and min</NOTE></L>
<L>All &thorn;at &thorn;aire mawmet are stode in,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&THORN;at &thorn;aire mawmet are stode in.</NOTE></L>
<L N="55">And in &thorn;at stede &thorn;ai raysid a rude<NOTE PLACE="foot">And &thorn;are &thorn;ai raised vp a rode.</NOTE></L>
<L>And cald on Crist with mayn &amp; mode.</L>
<L>So when &thorn;e cros was raysed &thorn;are<NOTE PLACE="foot">And when.</NOTE></L>
<L>And ordand, als &thorn;ai wald it ware,</L>
<L>And &thorn;aire maumet broght to grounde:</L>
<L N="60">&THORN;an war &thorn;e folk sune hale &amp; sounde,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&THORN;e folk ful sone wex hale and sound.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000191.tif" N="53"></L>
<L>And many &thorn;at to ded war dight<NOTE PLACE="foot2">And &thorn;e men &thorn;at war ded right.</NOTE></L>
<L>War raysid ogayn thurgh godes might.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">ogaine.</NOTE></L>
<L>Al war &thorn;ai warist and wele ferd,</L>
<L>All folk war fayn &thorn;at hereof herd.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">63&mdash;64) &THORN;an all &thorn;e folk &thorn;at hereof herd With mekill ioy in hert &thorn;ai ferd.</NOTE></L>
<L N="65">Ful grete puple fro sere cuntre<NOTE PLACE="foot2">And mani folk in &thorn;at cuntre</NOTE></L>
<L>Com &thorn;ore, &thorn;at selkuth sight to se.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Come &thorn;at selkuth forto se.</NOTE></L>
<L>And all &thorn;ai trowed in Jhesu Criste<NOTE PLACE="foot2">al. to st. in.</NOTE></L>
<L>And in his name &thorn;ai war baptist;</L>
<L>&THORN;e cros &thorn;ai honurd in &thorn;at stede<NOTE PLACE="foot2">And honord &thorn;e cros.</NOTE></L>
<L N="70">For him &thorn;at &thorn;aron sufferd dede.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">ded.</NOTE></L>
<L>Lely &thorn;ai lifed to &thorn;aire liues end</L>
<L>And lufed Crist als sayn Philip kend.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">71&mdash;72) And lifed till &thorn;aire liues end Wele als saint Mathew (!) &thorn;am kend.</NOTE></L>
<L>And when he had &thorn;ir dedis done,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">dedes.</NOTE></L>
<L>He wist he suld mak ending sone.</L>
<L N="75">And &thorn;arfore smertly ordand he<NOTE PLACE="foot2">74&mdash;75) To god he sent his sawl ful sone; Bot or he died &thorn;an ordand he.</NOTE></L>
<L>Prestis and dekins forto be,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">prestes.</NOTE></L>
<L>And mony kirkes he gert up rays,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">many. he gan vp rayse.</NOTE></L>
<L>For&thorn;i &thorn;at &thorn;e folk suld Jhesu prays.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">So &thorn;at. prayse.</NOTE></L>
<L>Opon a day, ogayns his dede,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">And on a. ded.</NOTE></L>
<L N="80">He gert cum samyn into a stede<NOTE PLACE="foot2">in a.</NOTE></L>
<L>Prestis and dekins &thorn;a he had puruaid,<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Ms. &thorn;a st. &thorn;at.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">Prestes and dekins of sere degre.</NOTE></L>
<L>And vnto &thorn;am al &thorn;us he sayd:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Vnto &thorn;am &thorn;an al &thorn;us said he.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Seuyn dais has god grauntid me<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&thorn;ir seuyn daies. granted.</NOTE></L>
<L>Here in &thorn;is erthly life to be,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">here fehlt. lif.</NOTE></L>
<L N="85">And when seuyn days er went to end,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">til end.</NOTE></L>
<L>Til endles blis &thorn;an sal I wend.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">To endles welt(h). sall.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;arfore, when I am went fro &yogh;ow,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">fra.</NOTE></L>
<L>Als I haue told luke &thorn;at &yogh;e trow,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">tald.</NOTE></L>
<L>In &thorn;e law of Crist luke &thorn;at &yogh;e last,</L>
<L N="90">And in his trouth bese euer stedfast".<NOTE PLACE="foot2">89&mdash;90) In trowth luke &thorn;at &yogh;e be stedfast And in &thorn;e laus of Crist lely last.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;an lifed he efter &thorn;at seuyn dais,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&thorn;at fehlt.</NOTE></L>
<L>Techeand &thorn;e folk goddes wurd always.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&thorn;e folk fehlt. word.</NOTE></L>
<L>And sethin, als he bifore had sayd<NOTE PLACE="foot2">se&thorn;in.</NOTE></L>
<L>And als god of heuyn had puruayd,</L>
<L N="95">Omang his men&yogh;e leste and maste<NOTE PLACE="foot2">lest.</NOTE></L>
<L>To god in heuyn he gaf &thorn;e gaste.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Vnto god he &yogh;ald his gaste.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e blis of heuyn he past vnto &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">And heuyn blis he.</NOTE></L>
<L>God graunt vs all grace so to do!<NOTE PLACE="foot2">grante. all fehlt. so forto.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="section">
<HEAD>Vlterius de sco Jacobo.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Jacob beginnt fol. 245.</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Saint Jacob, als clerkis mai kun,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&thorn;ir clerkes.</NOTE></L>
<L N="100">He was our ladi sister sun<NOTE PLACE="foot2">he fehlt. oure.</NOTE></L>
<L>And cosyn he was to Jhesu Crist,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">cosin. he fehlt.</NOTE></L>
<L>Als men mai lere who so list.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">wha will it list.</NOTE></L>
<L>Saint Anne, oure ladis moder dere,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">ladi.</NOTE></L>
<L>Had thre husbandes in &thorn;is life here,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">lif.</NOTE></L>
<L N="105">And Joachim &thorn;e first was he,</L>
<L>Sethin Cleophas, &thorn;an Salome;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Solome.</NOTE></L>
<L>And scho had with ilkone of &thorn;o<NOTE PLACE="foot2">ilkane.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ane mayden-child and namo &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">a st. ane.</NOTE></L>
<L>Fayrer maydins might none be,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">maydens.</NOTE></L>
<L N="110">And Mari war &thorn;ai namd all thre.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">named al.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e eldist may, lufly of lym,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">(e)ldest.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at doghter was vnto Joachim,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">of st. vnto.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ful haly life alway scho led<NOTE PLACE="foot2">lif.</NOTE></L>
<L>And sethin to Josep was scho wed,<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Ms. &thorn;e = &thorn;at?</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">sethin fehlt. vnto Joseph.</NOTE></L>
<L N="115">And in hir, als all clerkis knew,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">of st. in. &thorn;ir st. all. clerkes.</NOTE></L>
<L>Lykid oure lord to light, Jhesu.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">L(i)ked oure dere lord Jhesu, darauf folgende 2 Verse: Fless and blude here forto take (And) so be born for mans sake.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e midelest mayden of &thorn;e thre,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Mari st. mayden.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e doghter was vnto Cleophe,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&THORN;at (H. &thorn;e). of st. vnto. Cleofe.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000192.tif" N="54"></L>
<L>Was wedded vnto &YOGH;ebedeus,<MILESTONE N="149" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="foot2">with st. vnto. Sebedeus.</NOTE></L>
<L N="120">&THORN;at was a fisscher &mdash; men findes &thorn;us &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">a fehlt.</NOTE></L>
<L>And with him had scho childer two &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">him fehlt. twa</NOTE></L>
<L>Ful blisced childer both war &thorn;o:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">barnes st. childer. bath. &thorn;a.</NOTE></L>
<L>More Jams and John &thorn;e euangelist,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">James.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at ful dere was with Jhesu Crist.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&thorn;at derrest was.</NOTE></L>
<L N="125">&THORN;e &yogh;ongest mayden of &thorn;o thre<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&thorn;e &yogh;ungest was wed of &thorn;am thre</NOTE></L>
<L>Was wedded vnto a man, Salome,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Vntill a man &thorn;at hight Alphe(!).</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;e les Jams hir sun was &thorn;an<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&thorn;e fehlt.</NOTE></L>
<L>And Josep, &thorn;at was namid rightwisman,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">And als Joseph &thorn;e right|wisman.</NOTE></L>
<L>Simund and Jude &thorn;an efter nere &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Simond.</NOTE></L>
<L N="130">Brethir war al &thorn;ir foure in-fere.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">bre&thorn;er. al fehlt.</NOTE></L>
<L>Al &thorn;ir sex suns, we may se &thorn;us,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Al fehlt. &yogh;e st. we.</NOTE></L>
<L>War all cosins to oure lord Jhesus,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">War cosins all vnto Jhesus.</NOTE></L>
<L>And apostils war &thorn;ai euerilkone,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">appostels. euer fehlt. ilkane.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bot rightwis Josep &mdash; he was none. &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">All bot Joseph, he was nane.</NOTE></L>
<L N="135">Namore hereof reherce we right,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Namore of &thorn;am now tell we right.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bot of les James, &thorn;at Jacob hight,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;is Jacob als I bigan<NOTE PLACE="foot2">And of him als I are bigan.</NOTE></L>
<L>Will I declare now, als I can.</L>
<L>Efter time &thorn;at Criste sufferd ded,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">time fehlt. Crist had sufferd.</NOTE></L>
<L N="140">Saint Jacob prechid in mony stede.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">preched. mani a.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;e folk thoght, whore so he come,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">whare.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at he was man of grete wisdome.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&thorn;at fehlt. He suld be man.</NOTE></L>
<L>Fro sere sides &thorn;ai soght him tyll,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">On st. fro. come st. soght.</NOTE></L>
<L>Sum for gude and sum for ill.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Hier beginnt die 2. Col., bis 170 ziemlich lesbar.</NOTE></L>
<L N="145">&THORN;is Jacob was cald Cristes brother &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">And sum men (cald him) Cristes bro&thorn;er.</NOTE></L>
<L>So was &thorn;at one ay like &thorn;at o&thorn;er.</L>
<L>He was (&thorn;e) first &thorn;at in werld bygan<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&thorn;e first. ouar st. in werld.</NOTE></L>
<L>Last enoyntyng to cristenman;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Enoynting last of.</NOTE></L>
<L>When paynes of ded to him war sent,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">When ded panes sere has him h(ent),</NOTE></L>
<L N="150">&THORN;an he bigan &thorn;at haly sacrament.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">First he . . (&thorn;)at sacrament.</NOTE></L>
<L>Grete penance he vsid ay whore he dweld,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Grete penance vsed he w . . .</NOTE></L>
<L>And euir in prayers he him held.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">And euer praiers and in (?). .</NOTE></L>
<L>So stabilly to god gun he pray<NOTE PLACE="foot2">And vnto god so. .</NOTE></L>
<L>Kneleand both by nyght and day,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">bath. Die Vers|schl&uuml;sse sind bis 159 nicht sichtbar.</NOTE></L>
<L N="155">&THORN;at on his knese war waxen biles</L>
<L>Als es on kamels, like to kyles &mdash;</L>
<L>For of prayers wald he neuir sese,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">praier.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e folk of syns forto relese.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">sins.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e scribes and phariseus bath</L>
<L N="160">Wayted him alway with scath,</L>
<L>And, for he prechid ogains &thorn;aire laws,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai derid him both in dedis and saws.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">159&mdash;162) &THORN;e scribes and &thorn;e pharisews, &THORN;at euer with Cristes men war schrews, Reuiled him of(t) in &thorn;aire (s)awes, For he preched ogains &thorn;aire laws.</NOTE></L>
<L>And on a time &thorn;ai haue him tone</L>
<L>Vntill ane high pynacle of stone<NOTE PLACE="foot2">163&mdash;4) &THORN;ai toke him on a tyme ilkane And on a high pinacle of stane</NOTE></L>
<L N="165">Whareon &thorn;aire temple was puruayd,<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Ms. whareon st. that on.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">&thorn;at on.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ore sett &thorn;ai him and &thorn;us &thorn;ai sayd:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&thorn;ore fehlt. set. &thorn;us gat said.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Of al men right wisest es &thorn;ou,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&THORN;e right wisest of men ertow.</NOTE></L>
<L>To wham vs awe ilkone to bow.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">aw.</NOTE></L>
<L>Sen al &thorn;e folk both olde and &yogh;ing<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Sen al &thorn;e folk als. . wele wist</NOTE></L>
<L N="170">In errure dwell for Cristes cuming<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Erres efter (cuming of Crist). Von 170&mdash;194 sind nur die Versanf&auml;nge erhalten:</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at crossed was &thorn;e iewes omell &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">=H.</NOTE></L>
<L>All sere tales of him men tell:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Sere sawes of hi(m) . .</NOTE></L>
<L>Sum sais he was prophet by steuyn,</L>
<L>Sum sais he was god sun of heuyn &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Ms. gog. st. god.</NOTE></L>
<L N="175">ssen &thorn;ou of men es wisest now,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">And . .</NOTE></L>
<L>Tell vs of him what we sal trow<NOTE PLACE="foot2">What. . Dann folgt: &thorn;an an (swerd). ., And said. ., &THORN;at made. . (der Text ist hier um ein Verspaar k&uuml;r|zer)</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000193.tif" N="55"></L>
<L>And by what name we sall him knaw!"</L>
<L>&THORN;an answerd Jacob to &thorn;aire saw</L>
<L>And said: "he es oure Sauyoure,</L>
<L N="180">To wham all folk suld do honoure;</L>
<L>He made &thorn;is werld both more &amp; myn,</L>
<L>And al men may he saue of syn.<NOTE PLACE="foot">And all &THORN;i(r) . .</NOTE></L>
<L>On rude he dyed for oure misdede,<NOTE PLACE="foot">On rode he . .</NOTE></L>
<L>Fro syn to saue all Adam sede;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Of sin to saw(e) . .</NOTE></L>
<L N="185">His handwerk out fro hell he hent<NOTE PLACE="foot">His handwerk . .</NOTE></L>
<L>And rase fro ded and to heuin went.<NOTE PLACE="foot">And rase fr(a d)ed . .</NOTE></L>
<L>In dome sall he sit, als we rede,<NOTE PLACE="foot">And in dome sall he . .</NOTE></L>
<L>And deme ilk man efter his dede:<NOTE PLACE="foot">And deme ilk man efter . .</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;an sall &thorn;ai by with sorou and site<NOTE PLACE="foot">&THORN;an sall &thorn;ai wit of s(orou) . .</NOTE></L>
<L N="190">&THORN;at dose to him or his despite".<NOTE PLACE="foot">&THORN;at dose till him and . .</NOTE></L>
<L>So als he prechid in &thorn;at place,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&THORN;us als he preched . .</NOTE></L>
<L>Ful many louid god of his grace<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ful many loued god . .</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;ir wurdes &thorn;ai said &thorn;arwith:<NOTE PLACE="foot">And &thorn;ir wordes . .</NOTE></L>
<L>"He saue us, &thorn;e sun of Dauid!"<NOTE PLACE="foot">He saue vs &thorn;e sun. . Bei 195 beginnt die R&uuml;ckseite; von der 1. Columne ist nur der obere Theil und meist nur die Versenden erhalten.</NOTE></L>
<L N="195">&THORN;an &thorn;e scribes and &thorn;e phariseus<NOTE PLACE="foot">. . and pharisews</NOTE></L>
<L>Thoght no-thing gude of &thorn;ir thews.<NOTE PLACE="foot">. . no thing gude of &thorn;aire thewes.</NOTE></L>
<L>For he prechid &thorn;aire lawes to lett,<NOTE PLACE="foot">. . will was him &thorn;are to sett(?)</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;arfore on hill &thorn;ai him sett,<NOTE PLACE="foot">. . he suld lett.</NOTE></L>
<L>Forto be casten doune with tene,</L>
<L N="200">And &thorn;us &thorn;ai cried all &thorn;am bitwene:</L>
<L>"Wend we up to him in &thorn;is stounde</L>
<L>And cast him doun to &thorn;e depe grounde</L>
<L>And breke him sunder ilka lym,<NOTE PLACE="foot">199&mdash;203) ganz zerst&ouml;rt.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at o&thorn;er may be war by him:<NOTE PLACE="foot">. . (m)ay be warned by him.</NOTE></L>
<L N="205">&THORN;an sal none be so hardy more<NOTE PLACE="foot">. . mare.</NOTE></L>
<L>To swilk sawes als he said ore,<NOTE PLACE="foot">. . als he did (?) are.</NOTE></L>
<L>And so sall all &thorn;e folk forward now<NOTE PLACE="foot">all &thorn;e folk fra now.</NOTE></L>
<L>Turne &thorn;am and noght on him trow".</L>
<L>And &thorn;arwith kest &thorn;ai up a cry</L>
<L N="210">"&THORN;is rightwis man raues, weterly".</L>
<L>&THORN;aire cry &thorn;an made &thorn;e folk affrayd.<NOTE PLACE="foot">208&mdash;211) =H.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;us vnto him &thorn;an &thorn;ai sayd:<NOTE PLACE="foot">se&thorn;in st. &thorn;us u. so(?) st. &thorn;an.</NOTE></L>
<L>"We prayd &thorn;e &thorn;at &thorn;ou suld for oure sake<NOTE PLACE="foot">. . praied &thorn;e for oure sake (&thorn;at &thorn;ou suld fehlt)</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e fals trowth fro oure puple take,<NOTE PLACE="foot">(&thorn;e) fals trowth fra o(ure) folk to take.</NOTE></L>
<L N="215">And &thorn;ou encreses it more and more<NOTE PLACE="foot">(An)d &thorn;ou encreses it mare and mare,</NOTE></L>
<L>And makes wer &thorn;an it was bifore:<NOTE PLACE="foot">(An)d mase &thorn;am wer &thorn;an &thorn;ai war are.</NOTE></L>
<L>And of &thorn;at werk er we noght paid".<NOTE PLACE="foot">(&thorn;ar)fore with &thorn;e (er we) noght paid.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;an answerd James to &thorn;am &amp; said:<NOTE PLACE="foot">. . and to &thorn;am said.</NOTE></L>
<L>"&THORN;e rightwis trouth here haue I kend</L>
<L N="220">And all fals errure I defend:<NOTE PLACE="foot">. . defend.</NOTE></L>
<L>For &thorn;at thing &yogh;e call rightwisnes,<NOTE PLACE="foot">. . right|wisnes. Von hier ab bis zur 2. Col. (V. 243 ff.) ist nichts erhalten.</NOTE></L>
<L>Falshed and eresy it proued es.</L>
<L>For rightwis trouth to trow es none</L>
<L>Bot in my lord Jhesu allone;</L>
<L N="225">He es souerayne and sauyoure &mdash;</L>
<L>Al o&thorn;ir trouth es fals erroure".</L>
<L>Ful many folk &thorn;at herd &thorn;is saw</L>
<L>Turned &thorn;am vnto Cristes law</L>
<L>And loued god hertly &thorn;am bitwene.</L>
<L N="230">&THORN;an had &thorn;e maysters mekil tene.</L>
<L>Vpon &thorn;e hill went &thorn;ai all,</L>
<L>And to ground &thorn;ai gert him fall,</L>
<L>And on him kest &thorn;ai ful grete stones,</L>
<L>So forto brek him bak and bones.</L>
<L N="235">Opon his knese mekly he knelid</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e heuin vp he bihelde,</L>
<L>Vnto god with gude hert he prayd</L>
<L>And in his prayers &thorn;us he sayd:</L>
<L>"Lord, do mercy &thorn;ir men vnto,</L>
<L N="240">For-wy &thorn;ai wate noght what &thorn;ai do".</L>
<L>So als &thorn;o lurdans al at ones</L>
<L>Dang on his heuyd with heuy stones:
<PB REF="00000194.tif" N="56"></L>
<L>A prest, &thorn;at said &thorn;am &thorn;aire seruise,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Die Schlussverse sind deutlich.</NOTE></L>
<L>Herd how he prayd for his enmise.<NOTE PLACE="foot">praied.</NOTE></L>
<L N="245">To &thorn;am he said with wurdes meke:</L>
<L>"Spares &thorn;is man, I &yogh;ow byseke,</L>
<L>Sethin &thorn;at he prays for &yogh;ow so<NOTE PLACE="foot">Sen. praies. &yogh;ou.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at dose all &thorn;is harm him vnto.<NOTE PLACE="foot">all fehlt. harmis.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;is rightwis man prayes for &yogh;ow all,</L>
<L N="250">And &yogh;e lat stones &thorn;us on him fall!"<NOTE PLACE="foot">stanes so.</NOTE></L>
<L>Byside &thorn;an stode a pharisew,</L>
<L>Omang &thorn;am all a mekill schrew;</L>
<L>Him liked noght &thorn;e wurdes &thorn;am omang<NOTE PLACE="foot">Him tened &thorn;at wordes was &thorn;am omang.</NOTE></L>
<L>And tenid at &thorn;e apostel lifd so lang.<NOTE PLACE="foot">And for &thorn;e appostel lifed.</NOTE></L>
<L N="255">A walker perk byside him stode,</L>
<L>&THORN;arto he went als he war wode,<NOTE PLACE="foot">ran st. went.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e apostil on &thorn;e heuid he strake,<NOTE PLACE="foot">stake.</NOTE></L>
<L>A martyr so he gun him make;<NOTE PLACE="foot">marter. gan.</NOTE></L>
<L>For with &thorn;at perk his heuid he brak,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e perke.</NOTE></L>
<L N="260">So &thorn;at his hernis opon it stak.<NOTE PLACE="foot">so fehlt. hernes gan out schak.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;an &thorn;e folk went ful gude spede,</L>
<L>Him forto tak &thorn;at did &thorn;at dede</L>
<L>And forto schend him, if &thorn;ai may;<NOTE PLACE="foot">sla st. schend.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bot with fals help he wan oway.</L>
<L N="265">And &thorn;an &thorn;ai toke &thorn;at blisced body<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e st. &thorn;at.</NOTE></L>
<L>And enterid it ful wirschiply.<NOTE PLACE="foot">And groue it &thorn;are ful.</NOTE></L>
<L>And at &thorn;aire might &thorn;aire mis &thorn;ai mend<NOTE PLACE="foot">with st. at. &thorn;ai fehlt. amend.</NOTE></L>
<L>And trowed in Crist als he had kend;<NOTE PLACE="foot">267&mdash;8 umgesetzt.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ai war cristend and come to blis &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">And cristend war.</NOTE></L>
<L N="270">So forto wirk Jhesu vs wis.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="14" TYPE="legend">
<HEAD>14. De Inuencione s. crucis</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>Diese Legende ist, nebst der Exaltacio Crucis, bereits edirt von Morris in den "Legends of the holy Rood" f&uuml;r die Early Engl. Text Soc., London 1871, p. 87 ss., jedoch ohne Benutzung des Ms. Tib.</P><P>Im Ms. Tib. stehen die ersten 20 (18) Verse auf fol. 245 b Col. 2., der Rest auf fol. 230 und 232, welche nebst fol. 231 und 233 (so in unrichtiger Folge) beim bin|den unter die Homilien gerathen sind. &mdash; Varianten des Ms. Tib.:</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Men aw to honure euer omang<NOTE PLACE="foot">honour.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e cros &thorn;at al our hele on hang;<NOTE PLACE="foot">oure.</NOTE></L>
<L>And how &thorn;at haly tre was fun,</L>
<L>Was &thorn;is feste ordand and bigun.<NOTE PLACE="foot">3&mdash;4) fehlen.</NOTE></L>
<L N="5">&THORN;at tre vs aw forto do honoure</L>
<L>&THORN;at bare oure lord and oure sauioure. &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">5&mdash;6) &thorn;at bare Jhesus oure sauyowre, Vnto wham be euer honowre.</NOTE></L>
<L>Whils Constantyne, &thorn;e nobil king,</L>
<L>Lifd here in erth in grete liking,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lifed here in erthly likeing.</NOTE></L>
<L>Trew he was in dede and saw</L>
<L N="10">And lely lifed he in his law;</L>
<L>In Rome he regnid als Emperoure<NOTE PLACE="foot">regned.</NOTE></L>
<L>And gouerned it with grete honoure.</L>
<L>So in his tyme, trewly to tell,</L>
<L>All on &thorn;is maner it bifell:<NOTE PLACE="foot">All fehlt.</NOTE></L>
<L N="15">&THORN;e Grekis and &thorn;e folk of barbary<NOTE PLACE="foot">beide &thorn;e fehlen.</NOTE></L>
<L>Gederd ful grete cumpany</L>
<L>Forto gif batail ogaynes Rome<NOTE PLACE="foot">To.</NOTE></L>
<L>And so by strenkit it to ouercum.<NOTE PLACE="foot">with st. by.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000195.tif" N="57"></L>
<L>And when king Constantine herd tell</L>
<L N="20">Off al &thorn;is fare how it byfell,</L>
<L>In his hert he had grete drede &mdash;</L>
<L>For ful grete power gun &thorn;ai lede.<NOTE PLACE="foot">21 ff. Die erste Col. des fol. 230, bis V. 68, ist fast ganz leserlich.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">gan.</NOTE></L>
<L>He ordand him grete cumpany</L>
<L>Of men of armes and archery,</L>
<L N="25">His land with fighting to defend</L>
<L>And to hald it fro his enmis hend.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">to fehlt. fra.</NOTE></L>
<L>And als he lay opon a night,</L>
<L>Bifore &thorn;at day &thorn;at &thorn;ai suld fight:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Bifor &thorn;e day.</NOTE></L>
<L>Him thoght he lukid to heuyn on high:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">luked.</NOTE></L>
<L N="30">And in &thorn;e aire him thoght he sigh<NOTE PLACE="foot2">segh.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e same cros, &thorn;at Crist was on done,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">same fehlt. Crist here was.</NOTE></L>
<L>And a voice sayd &thorn;us to him sone:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&thorn;us fehlt. vnto.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Ordayne &thorn;ine armes on &thorn;is-kin wise:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">kin fehlt.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;an sal &thorn;ou ouercum &thorn;ine enmise;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&thorn;at st. &thorn;an. saltow.</NOTE></L>
<L N="35">And in &thorn;is figure fully &thorn;ou trayst:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">in fehlt. luke st. fully.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;an thar &thorn;e no-thing be abaist.</L>
<L>Mak &thorn;is in &thorn;ine armes for&thorn;i:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">For if &thorn;ou traist in &thorn;is anely.</NOTE></L>
