<L>He cals us now, to blis at cum".</L>
<L>Bot saint Peter out of prison went,</L>
<L N="530">And techid &thorn;e folk with gude entent.</L>
<L>And on &thorn;at same night ordand he</L>
<L>Allone to wend fro &thorn;at riche cete.</L>
<L>And when he come without &thorn;e &yogh;ate,</L>
<L>He saw Jhesus cum &thorn;ore in &thorn;e gate.</L>
<L N="535">&THORN;an knelid he doun and was wele payd</L>
<L>And vnto him &thorn;ir wurdes he sayd:</L>
<L>Domine, quo vadis?</L>
<L>&THORN;at es in Inglis &thorn;us forto say:</L>
<L>"Lord, whider es now &thorn;i way?"</L>
<L>"I cum to Rome, &thorn;an &thorn;us said he,</L>
<L N="540">Ano&thorn;ir tym crossed forto be".</L>
<L>&THORN;an bi &thorn;ir wurdes saint Peter wist<NOTE PLACE="foot">wordes.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at it was &thorn;e will of Crist</L>
<L>&THORN;at he suld noght fle, bot be boun<NOTE PLACE="foot">&THORN;at him self suld mak him boun,</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ore forto suffer his passioun.<NOTE PLACE="foot">&THORN;at tyme to suffer passioun</NOTE></L>
<L N="545">&THORN;an Jhesus might he namore se,</L>
<L>Vnto Rome &thorn;an ogain went he.<NOTE PLACE="foot">545&mdash;6) &THORN;arfore no ferrer gan he frain, Bot to &thorn;e toune turned ogaine.</NOTE></L>
<L>And with &thorn;e Emperoure was he sone<NOTE PLACE="foot">tane st. sone.</NOTE></L>
<L>Demyd vnto ded to be done</L>
<L>On a cros, als his mayster was,</L>
<L N="550">For his law &thorn;at he mayntend has.<NOTE PLACE="foot">548&mdash;50) And demed sone forto be slane, &thorn;ai demid him all with a voyce Forto be hanged opon a croce, Als &thorn;ai wist his mayster was, Of wham he preched whare he gan pas (Harl. k&uuml;rzer).</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ai led him furth ful grete plente<NOTE PLACE="foot">furth of &thorn;e cete.</NOTE></L>
<L>To &thorn;e stede whore he suld hanged be.<NOTE PLACE="foot">whare. Darauf folgt: And sune when he &thorn;e cros might se, A ioyful man in hert was he.</NOTE></L>
<L>To &thorn;e cros ful gladly gun he gang<NOTE PLACE="foot">&THORN;arto ful gladly gan he ga.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000210.tif" N="72"></L>
<L>And prayd &thorn;o men &thorn;at suld him hang,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e. sla st. hang.</NOTE></L>
<L N="555">And mekly &thorn;is bone he &thorn;am ass:<NOTE PLACE="foot">&THORN;is bone hertly of &thorn;am he ass.</NOTE></L>
<L>Noght to be hanged als Jhesus was:<NOTE PLACE="foot">hin|ged.</NOTE></L>
<L>"For, he said, I am noght wurthy<NOTE PLACE="foot">vnworthy.</NOTE></L>
<L>So als my lord dyed forto dy.<NOTE PLACE="foot">so fehlt. Auf 558 folgt noch: &THORN;arfore when &yogh;e haue made al boun, I pray &yogh;ow turn my heued doun.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;arfore my fete vpward &yogh;e trus,<NOTE PLACE="foot">And mi fete.</NOTE></L>
<L N="560">Contrary vnto my lord Jhesus!"<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e contrari of.</NOTE></L>
<L>His will &thorn;ai graunted with-outen let:<NOTE PLACE="foot">&THORN;ai granted his will.</NOTE></L>
<L>His heuyd vnto &thorn;e erth &thorn;ai sett<NOTE PLACE="foot">set.</NOTE></L>
<L>And his fete vpward &thorn;ai thring;<NOTE PLACE="foot">sling.</NOTE></L>
<L>So went &thorn;ai home and lete him hing.<NOTE PLACE="foot">And went &thorn;am hame.</NOTE></L>
<L N="565">&THORN;us when &thorn;e quellers war went home,</L>
<L>Ful mekill folk obout him come.<NOTE PLACE="foot">565&mdash;6) &thorn;us when he on &thorn;e cros was done, Ful mekil folk come &thorn;eder sone.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ful sare &thorn;ai wepid for his sake<NOTE PLACE="foot">weped.</NOTE></L>
<L>And weryed &thorn;am &thorn;at did him wrake.<NOTE PLACE="foot">werid.</NOTE></L>
<L>Saint Peter cumfort &thorn;am and said:<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;an Peter comfort. sad.</NOTE></L>
<L N="570">"Wepis noght, bot bese wele payd!<NOTE PLACE="foot">Wepes.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bifor &yogh;oure sight I sall wend euyn<NOTE PLACE="foot">Bifor &yogh;ow sall I wend ful euyn.</NOTE></L>
<L>To ordayn &yogh;ow a place in heuyn.<NOTE PLACE="foot">stede.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;is es &thorn;e tre of life to tell,<NOTE PLACE="foot">lif.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at destroys &thorn;e endles ded of hell.<NOTE PLACE="foot">stroyes.</NOTE></L>
<L N="575">I pray &thorn;e, Jhesu, my lord so fre:<NOTE PLACE="foot">&THORN;arfore I pray &thorn;e Jhesu fre.</NOTE></L>
<L>Als &thorn;ou has ordand &thorn;is vnto me,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ou &thorn;is ordand.</NOTE></L>
<L>Lighten &thorn;ir folk and gif &thorn;am grace<NOTE PLACE="foot">men st. folk.</NOTE></L>
<L>To se &thorn;i vertu in &thorn;is place".</L>
<L>And &thorn;us when he had prayd right,<NOTE PLACE="foot">prayed.</NOTE></L>
<L N="580">God opind &thorn;aire eghen to gastly sight.</L>
<L>&THORN;an saw &thorn;ai all obout him wend<NOTE PLACE="foot">stand st. wend.</NOTE></L>
<L>Angels with corons in &thorn;aire hend<NOTE PLACE="foot">corones in &thorn;aire hand.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of floures, &thorn;at war faire to sight,<NOTE PLACE="foot">hier beg. fol. 247.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot">. . .of flowres (sch)ene,</NOTE></L>
<L>Lilys and roses of colure bright.<NOTE PLACE="foot">(Of) lilies and of rose(s) bi(dene).</NOTE></L>
<L N="585">And on &thorn;e cros end saw &thorn;ai stand</L>
<L>Crist with a buke in his hand;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Saint. . and a boke in his hand.</NOTE></L>
<L>Vnto saint Peter &thorn;e buke he layd:<NOTE PLACE="foot">And cr(ist) &thorn;e boke vntill him laid.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;arin was writen al &thorn;at he sayd.<NOTE PLACE="foot">wreten.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;an ful grete ioy in hert had &thorn;ai,<NOTE PLACE="foot">gret.</NOTE></L>
<L N="590">And sune &thorn;at sight vanist oway.<NOTE PLACE="foot">so &thorn;is.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;an thoght &thorn;ai all &thorn;ai wald be fayn<NOTE PLACE="foot">&THORN;ai thoght all &thorn;at &thorn;ai. faine.</NOTE></L>
<L>For Cristes sake to suffer payn.<NOTE PLACE="foot">luf st. sake. payne.</NOTE></L>
<L>Saint Peter persayued in &thorn;at place<NOTE PLACE="foot">When st. Saint.</NOTE></L>
<L>How god had scheud to &thorn;am his grace:<NOTE PLACE="foot">schewed.</NOTE></L>
<L N="595">Louyng he made to god of heuyn<NOTE PLACE="foot">loueing.</NOTE></L>
<L>And said &thorn;ir wurdes with mild steuyn:<NOTE PLACE="foot">And &thorn;ir wordes said he in his st.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Lord, I &yogh;eld now here into &thorn;i hend<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;elde. now here fehlt.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e schepe &thorn;at &thorn;ou to me bykend:</L>
<L>&THORN;ou tak &thorn;am now into &thorn;i fald<NOTE PLACE="foot">geder st. tak. now fehlt.</NOTE></L>
<L N="600">And &yogh;eme &thorn;am &thorn;at for &thorn;ine er talde&mdash;</L>
<L>For &thorn;ou ordans for alkins thing.<NOTE PLACE="foot">For &thorn;ou fulfilles. for fehlt.</NOTE></L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e, lord, be ay loueing!"</L>
<L>Amen, &thorn;an sayd both &yogh;ung &amp; alde.<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ai st. both.</NOTE></L>
<L>And so to god his gast he &yogh;alde<NOTE PLACE="foot">his gaste to god.</NOTE></L>
<L N="605">And went to blis &thorn;at neuir sal blin&mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">to heuyn withowten blin.</NOTE></L>
<L>God graunt us grace &thorn;eder to wyn!<NOTE PLACE="foot">grante. Hier|auf folgen noch folg. 12 Verse: More of saint Peter might men tell, Of sere ferlis &thorn;at to him fell. Bot &thorn;are er o&thorn;er festes sere Ordand of him in &thorn;e &yogh;ere, Whare men may o&thorn;er thinges rede. And &thorn;arfore now it es no nede, To tell more how his wirking was. Bot to saint Paul now will I pas, For &thorn;ai war ded both on a day, So &thorn;at I may efter say, How &thorn;ai war beried both in fere And schewed mightes mani and sere.</NOTE>
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="section"><PB REF="00000211.tif" N="73">
<HEAD>De passione sancti Pauli apo|stoli historia.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>S. Paul. Die ersten Verse lauten: Saint Paul efter his conuersioune Bicome Cristes nobil champiowne, And traueld als a nobil knight, Prechand &thorn;e puple day and night. And at &thorn;e last he come to Rome, Als Crist had ordand him to come, Saint Peter &thorn;are forto socoure Ogaines Nero &thorn;e Emperoure. And when he come in &thorn;at cete&mdash; hier beginnt die zuerst fast ganz zers&ouml;rte 2. Col.; lesbar ist And im 2. Verse der Col. Der 3. Vers beginnt: To h(ere) = 612 in Harl.</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Saint Paul efter saint Peter ded</L>
<L>Dwellid stil in &thorn;e same stede</L>
<L>Whore Nero gert prison &thorn;am two</L>
<L N="610">And whore saint Peter past him fro.</L>
<L>Ful mekil folk vnto him come,</L>
<L>To here him carp of cristendome.</L>
<L>And als he sat so on a tyme</L>
<L>Techeand &thorn;e folk &thorn;at come to him:</L>
<L N="615">&THORN;e buteller &thorn;at was with &thorn;e Emperoure<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e bottel(er). .</NOTE></L>
<L>Herd speke of saint Paul grete honoure,</L>
<L>And pryuely furth gun he pas<NOTE PLACE="foot">preuely. Die folgenden Anf&auml;nge sind abweichend: Vnto &thorn;e . ., &thorn;e halynes of . ., And goddes . . (Tib. hat ein Verspaar mehr), Bot in &thorn;e hows . . 619, For many folk &thorn;are . . 620.</NOTE></L>
<L>Forto wit how his wurd was;</L>
<L>Bot for &thorn;e folk he might noght win</L>
<L N="620">Vnto &thorn;e place whor he was in:</L>
<L>To a window on heght he wan,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Till a high window he . .,</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ore forto here &thorn;e haly man.<NOTE PLACE="foot">So forto here &thorn;at haly . ., dann folgt: &thorn;are held he him al (stille), And so when he had. ., Vnto himself he. ., In &thorn;at window he . .,</NOTE></L>
<L>Lang lerid he &thorn;ore at his awin list,</L>
<L>And sethin he slepid, or euer he wist.</L>
<L N="625">Down he fell vnto &thorn;e grounde<MILESTONE N="156" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="foot">And doun he draf vnto . .,</NOTE></L>
<L>And lay ded still &thorn;ore in &thorn;at stounde.<NOTE PLACE="foot">And lay &thorn;are still. . (Harl. k&uuml;rzer).</NOTE></L>
<L>When Nero herd &thorn;ir tithinges tell</L>
<L>On what maner his butler fell,<NOTE PLACE="foot">manere.</NOTE></L>
<L>He fore als he war wude for wo,<NOTE PLACE="foot">wode.</NOTE></L>
<L N="630">For he had lost his seruand so.<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at st. for.</NOTE></L>
<L>Saint Paul, als he sat, wist ful wele</L>
<L>What was done euerilka dele,</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e puple &thorn;us said he:</L>
<L>"Wendes furth, for &yogh;e sal se<NOTE PLACE="foot">627&mdash;634 = Harl.</NOTE></L>
<L N="635">&THORN;e butteler of &thorn;e Emperoure</L>
<L>Es fallen doun out of &yogh;on toure</L>
<L>And on &thorn;e ground &thorn;ore ded es he;</L>
<L>Bot wendis and bringes him vnto me!"</L>
<L>&THORN;ai meruaild how he wist it so,</L>
<L N="640">Sen no-man told it him vnto.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai broght &thorn;e body vnto him nere.</L>
<L>&THORN;an said saint Paul to &thorn;am in-fere:</L>
<L>"In stedfast trouth luke &thorn;at &yogh;e be</L>
<L>And prayes all vnto god with me</L>
<L N="645">&THORN;at he his grace vnto vs giff,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at &thorn;is man mai rise &amp; lif!"<NOTE PLACE="foot">635&mdash;646) Statt dieser 12 V. hatte Tib. 18 V., wovon nur sichtbar die Anf&auml;nge: A ser(uand). ., Es (636), Sp. ., weiter unten Pa(trok?). ., And. ., &THORN;an al &thorn;e folk. ., How Paul. ., &THORN;at &thorn;is man. ., And noman. ., Saint Paul &thorn;an. ., Vntill al &thorn;at folk. . .</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot">643&mdash;6=Harl.: In stedfast luke &thorn;at. ., And praies all. ., &THORN;at he his grace. ., So &thorn;at &thorn;is man. . Dann folgt die Ueber|schrift: De resuscitacione s. .</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e folk &thorn;an knelid and to god prayd.</L>
<L>And saint Paule to &thorn;e cors sayd:<NOTE PLACE="foot">647 ff. Die 1. Col. der R&uuml;ckseite ist bis auf einige Reimw&ouml;rter ganz zerst&ouml;rt, sie reicht bis 682, der Text in Tib. hatte also 10 Verse mehr als in Harl.; nach 666 stand lat. Ueberschrift (sichtbar ist . . ficum). Bis 656 hatte Tib. 8 V. mehr; dieser ganze Passus ist zerst&ouml;rt, bis auf die Reimw&ouml;rter mare, &thorn;en.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Patrok, I bid, &thorn;ou rise up sone</L>
<L N="650">And say what god has for &thorn;e done".</L>
<L>With &thorn;at voice &thorn;e man vp lepe</L>
<L>Als he had bene flaide fro his slepe.</L>
<L>&THORN;an al &thorn;e puple in &thorn;at place</L>
<L>Loued god of his gude grace</L>
<L N="655">And praysed saint Paul for &thorn;at dede.</L>
<L>&THORN;an Patrok to &thorn;e palays &yogh;ede</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e Emperoure told he sone</L>
<L>Of &thorn;is dede and who had it done.<NOTE PLACE="foot">657&mdash;8) . . sone, . . was done, = Harl. Dann folgt ein Verspaar mit den Schlussw&ouml;rtern: . . was raysed, . . pople was praysed (vgl 653&mdash;5). Darauf die Vers|schl&uuml;sse wit, itt, be soght, him broght, (stal)worth men and wight, bifor his sight, him se, said he, (tr)aytoure=659&mdash;667. Unten ist nur noch sichtbar: wonder tene 678, ful tite 679, smyte 680.-683&mdash;718 2. Col., leserlich bis auf die ersten 6 Verse. Die Rede 680&mdash;6 z&auml;hlte in Tib. 11 Verse, davon 8 in der 2. Col.; die Anf&auml;nge des 5. u. 6. V. der Col. lauten: And &thorn;at . ., May noght . ., der 7. u. 8. Vers: And &thorn;at sal now be sene alsone, When he sal to ded be done (die Reime wie 685&mdash;6 Harl.).</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000212.tif" N="74"></L>
<L>&THORN;an Nero was wude, out of wit,</L>
<L N="660">For &thorn;ai said saint Paul had done it;</L>
<L>Bilyue he bad he suld be soght</L>
<L>And bunden and bifor him broght.</L>
<L>Furth went stalwurth men and wight</L>
<L>And broght saint Paul bifor his sight.</L>
<L N="665">And als sone als he might him se,</L>
<L>&THORN;ir wurdes vnto his men said he:</L>
<L>"Takes vnto yhow &thorn;at traytoure</L>
<L>And heuydes him als a fals faytoure!</L>
<L>With falshed turnes he, als we fynde,</L>
<L N="670">Days and &yogh;eres out of &thorn;aire kinde,</L>
<L>He slaes and says he rayses ogayne.</L>
<L>&THORN;arfore bilyue &thorn;at he be slayne!"</L>
<L>Saint Paul &thorn;an answerd him vnto:</L>
<L>"I dout no dere &thorn;at &thorn;ou mai do.</L>
<L N="675">For fro &thorn;i payn sune sal I wende</L>
<L>And wun in blis with-outen ende</L>
<L>With Jhesu, my lord of all bydene".</L>
<L>&THORN;an was &thorn;e emperoure wunder tene</L>
<L>And to his men he sayd ful tyte:</L>
<L N="680">"His heuyd I byd byliue of smyte,</L>
<L>And lat him wightly wend his ways</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;at life &thorn;at he so pra(i)ses!</L>
<L>Bot he sall wit his lord and he</L>
<L>Has no might to mayster me;</L>
<L N="685">Bot I sal maister him alsone,</L>
<L>For tyte he sal to ded be done".</L>
<L>Saint Paul &thorn;an said to him &thorn;is saw:<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;an said saint Paul to him &thorn;is saw.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Sir, for &thorn;ou sal wit and knaw<NOTE PLACE="foot">sall.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at I in endles blis sal be,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at I sal lif with heuyn-king &mdash; And be in blis withouten ending, And &thorn;at &thorn;ou sal ouercumen be (diese 2 V. fehlen in H.).</NOTE></L>
<L N="690">I say &thorn;e, sir, &thorn;ou sal me se</L>
<L>In &thorn;i palays to &thorn;e apere<NOTE PLACE="foot">690&mdash;1 = Harl.</NOTE></L>
<L>Efter time my heuid be tane of here,<NOTE PLACE="foot">time fehlt.</NOTE></L>
<L>sso forto schew to man and wife</L>
<L>&THORN;at Jhesus es lord of lastand life<NOTE PLACE="foot">693&mdash;4) Daf&uuml;r liest Tib.: Forto schew &thorn;e verrayly, &thorn;at my lord god almighty Es maister of ded and lord of life And may medcyn both man and wife.</NOTE></L>
<L N="695">And ouercumen sal neuer be,</L>
<L>Bot ouercumer of al es he</L>
<L>And lastand lord with-outen ende".<NOTE PLACE="foot">695&mdash;7 = H.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot">king st. lord.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;an was &thorn;e Emperoure wunder tende<NOTE PLACE="foot">At &thorn;ir wordes was &thorn;e Emperoure tende.</NOTE></L>
<L>And namore wald he speke him tyll,</L>
<L N="700">Bot bad bilyue &thorn;ai suld him spill.<NOTE PLACE="foot">699&mdash;700 = H.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ai led him furth fro &thorn;at cete<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;an went &thorn;ai furth fra &thorn;e cete.</NOTE></L>
<L>To &thorn;e hill whore he suld hedid be.<NOTE PLACE="foot">a st. &thorn;e. whare. sul.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ful mekill folk &thorn;an with him &yogh;ode,<NOTE PLACE="foot">And st. ful.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at murning made with dreri mode.<NOTE PLACE="foot">murnig.</NOTE></L>
<L N="705">And als &thorn;ai come vnto &thorn;e &yogh;ate,</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;e toun to tak &thorn;e gate,</L>
<L>With a woman &thorn;ore he mett<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;are. met.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at lufed him wele &amp; for him gret:</L>
<L>Plantilla was &thorn;e womans name.</L>
<L N="710">Vnto hir said saint Paul: "gude dame,<NOTE PLACE="foot">And to hir.</NOTE></L>
<L>Len me &thorn;i corchef in &thorn;is tyde,</L>
<L>My face &amp; mine eghen forto hide,<NOTE PLACE="foot">with to hid.</NOTE></L>
<L>So &thorn;at I se noght my paine!<NOTE PLACE="foot">dede st. paine. Darauf folgt: And bide me still here in &thorn;is stede, For als sone als I am slayn, &THORN;i corchef sall I bring ogaine (714), And also dame for &thorn;i gude dede Ful wele sal I quit &thorn;i mede (715). &THORN;e woman &thorn;an with hert glad Lent him hir corchef als he bad.</NOTE></L>
<L>And sone I sal bring it ogayne,</L>
<L N="715">And ful wele sal be quit &thorn;i mede".</L>
<L>Sune als he bad, scho did in dede.</L>
<L>&THORN;an al &thorn;e folk &thorn;at went biforn<NOTE PLACE="foot">And st. &thorn;an.</NOTE></L>
<L>For &thorn;at dede drafe hir to scorne,<NOTE PLACE="foot">717&mdash;8 wie H.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot">drafe. Hierauf beginnt fol. 248: die ersten 2 V. fehlen in H., der Reim scheint scathe, . . sal so los &thorn;i cla&thorn;e (?).</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000213.tif" N="75"></L>
<L>&THORN;ai said: "luke what &thorn;i corchef cost,<NOTE PLACE="foot">couerchef.</NOTE></L>
<L N="720">And euyn als mekil has &thorn;ou lost".<NOTE PLACE="foot">hastou.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot">Nach 720 folgt weiter: And al &thorn;is werld sal neuer. . (Ma)re tell (?) of him and al his kyn.</NOTE></L>
<L>Saint Paul sayd to hir &thorn;am omell:<NOTE PLACE="foot">&THORN;an said Paul to to hir &thorn;am omell.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Woman, trow what I &thorn;e tell!</L>
<L>Bide here still, til I cum to &thorn;e:<NOTE PLACE="foot">Bide me till.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;i corchef sal I bring with me,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e st. &thorn;i.</NOTE></L>
<L N="725">My blude &thorn;ou sal se &thorn;aron sched".</L>
<L>&THORN;an als a thefe furth &thorn;ai him led<NOTE PLACE="foot">725&mdash;6) And &thorn;arof to bere witnes gude, &THORN;ou sall se &thorn;e singne of my blode. Lange in &thorn;at stede &thorn;ai wald noght sted (!), Als a thefe furth &thorn;ai him led (H. k&uuml;rzer).</NOTE></L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e place whore he suld dy.<NOTE PLACE="foot">hill st. place. whare. Die folg. Verse lauten: And &thorn;are he set him doun in hy Opon his knese and made loueing Vnto god of alkin thing; And &thorn;an he blissed &thorn;am al to-geder, &THORN;at for his sake war comen &thorn;eder; &THORN;e woman corchefe &thorn;an he toke And band his eien, als sais &thorn;e boke, He held his hend vnto &thorn;e heuyn And streked furth his nec ful euyn. &THORN;e manqueller &thorn;an to him weuyd And with grete strenkit strake of his heuyd.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;ore he thankid god specialli</L>
<L>Of al kindnes &thorn;at he him kyd;</L>
<L N="730">With &thorn;e corchef &thorn;an his eghen he hid.</L>
<L>And so when he of praying leuyd,</L>
<L>&THORN;e manqu(e)ller strake of his heuyd.</L>
<L>And &thorn;e heuid when it lay on ground,<NOTE PLACE="foot">And &thorn;e heuyd when it lay on ground,</NOTE></L>
<L>Neuind Jhesu thrise in &thorn;at stound.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Nemned Jhesus many a stounde.</NOTE></L>
<L N="735">To tak &thorn;e corchef wele &thorn;ai trow:</L>
<L>It was oway, &thorn;ai wist noght how.<NOTE PLACE="foot">735&mdash;6) And sum of &thorn;am &thorn;arto gan ga, &THORN;e corchef &thorn;arfra to haue tane; Bot als &thorn;ai doun till it gan bow, It was oway &thorn;ai wist noght how (H. hat nur 1 Verspaar).</NOTE></L>
<L>And of his hals &thorn;ore in &thorn;at stede<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;are.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ran white milk wit blude rede.<NOTE PLACE="foot">with.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ful mekil light come &thorn;am omell</L>
<L N="740">And neuer &thorn;ai felid so nobil smell.<NOTE PLACE="foot">739&mdash;40) And &thorn;are was &thorn;an ful nobill smell, And more light &thorn;an mans tong mai tell.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;arbi his frendes wist ilkone<NOTE PLACE="foot">And &thorn;arby wist &thorn;ai euerilkane.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at his gaste vnto heuin was gane,<NOTE PLACE="foot">vnto god was tane.</NOTE></L>
<L>And god &thorn;ai louid with al &thorn;aire mayn.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Emperoures men &thorn;an wendes ogain.<NOTE PLACE="foot">743&mdash;4) And god &thorn;ai loued with hert and handes, &THORN;at so ordains for his seruandes. &THORN;e Empe|roures men &thorn;an turned ogain Vnto &thorn;e cete-ward certayne (H. k&uuml;rzer).</NOTE></L>
<L N="745">&THORN;e woman met &thorn;ai, als &thorn;ai went,</L>
<L>&THORN;at to saint Paul &thorn;e corchef lent.<NOTE PLACE="foot">cor|chefe.</NOTE></L>
<L>Vnto hir said &thorn;ai in scornyng:<NOTE PLACE="foot">And to.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Plantilla, &thorn;ou mun haue &thorn;i thing</L>
<L>Outher to morn or neuermore &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">748 ff.) Plantilla &thorn;ou mun haue &thorn;i thing, &THORN;at &thorn;ou lent till &thorn;e prechore are, Ou&thorn;er to morn or neuermare. Die 2 ersten Verse der 2. Col. sind zerst&ouml;rt; lesbar ist in beiden der Anfang &thorn;i, der Reim scheint grete.</NOTE></L>
<L N="750">&THORN;i heuyd may haue grete cald &thorn;er|fore".</L>
<L>&THORN;an answerd scho to &thorn;am ogayn:<NOTE PLACE="foot">&THORN;an answerd scho and said . .</NOTE></L>
<L>"I haue my corchef, sirs, sertayne!<NOTE PLACE="foot">751 ff. nur die Anf&auml;nge sind lesbar.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot">I haue mi corchef sirs ser(tayne).</NOTE></L>
<L>He broght it me faland fro heuyn</L>
<L>And on &thorn;is wise I herd his steuyn:<NOTE PLACE="foot">Statt 753&mdash;4 hat Tib. 6 Verse: And &thorn;arof (wonder?). ., It es wet with. ., Vnto. ., Cumand. ., Ful mekill he . ., And vnto me al (&thorn;us he) said.</NOTE></L>
<L N="755">&THORN;at &thorn;ou in erth has done to me<NOTE PLACE="foot">In erth &thorn;at &thorn;u has. .,</NOTE></L>
<L>In heuyn sal it &yogh;olden be".<NOTE PLACE="foot">In heuin sal it &yogh;olden (be). Darauf folgt: And for &thorn;ai suld &thorn;e. ., Furth scho gun &thorn;e. .</NOTE></L>
<L>Scho schewid &thorn;e couerchef blodi &thorn;ore.<NOTE PLACE="foot">And schewd. . . .,</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;arof &thorn;ai all awunderd wore,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&THORN;arof &thorn;ai all awondred (ware),</NOTE></L>
<L>And al &thorn;at went to do &thorn;at dede</L>
<L N="760">Had in &thorn;aire hertes mekill drede.<NOTE PLACE="foot">759&mdash;60) And in &thorn;aire hertes. .drede, For &thorn;ai had done swilk (a) de(de).</NOTE></L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e Emperoure &thorn;ai tell<NOTE PLACE="foot">And to &thorn;e Emperour. .,</NOTE></L>
<L>Of all &thorn;ir ferlis als &thorn;ai fell.<NOTE PLACE="foot">All &thorn;ir ferlis als &thorn;ai. . .</NOTE></L>
<L>And when he heris al how it was,<NOTE PLACE="foot">And when he heris . .,</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000214.tif" N="76"></L>
<L>Grete drede &thorn;an in his hert he has;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Grete sorow in his . .</NOTE></L>
<L N="765">Ful sone vnto him gert he call<NOTE PLACE="foot">And sone vnto . .</NOTE></L>
<L>His counsail &amp; his knightes all,<NOTE PLACE="foot">His counsayl and his knightes. .,</NOTE></L>
<L>Forto ordayn ogain &thorn;e morn<NOTE PLACE="foot">Forto assay opon &thorn;e. .</NOTE></L>
<L>What counsail might be &thorn;arforn.<NOTE PLACE="foot">What counsail w. . . Dann Ueber|schrift: Aparuit Paulus . .</NOTE></L>
<L>Opon &thorn;e morn within &thorn;e bayle<NOTE PLACE="foot">On &thorn;e . .</NOTE></L>
<L N="770">When &thorn;ai war gederd to counsayle</L>
<L>In preue place whore none &thorn;am herd,</L>
<L>And al &thorn;e &yogh;ates vnto &thorn;am sperd:</L>
<L>Saint Paul come in omang &thorn;am &thorn;an</L>
<L>And said: "se now, &thorn;ou wikked man,<NOTE PLACE="foot">770&mdash;4) ganz zerst&ouml;rt.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot">And said. .</NOTE></L>
<L N="775">I am Paul &thorn;at told &thorn;e bifore<NOTE PLACE="foot">I am Paul &thorn;at. . 776&mdash;84 Anf&auml;nge wie in H.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at my life suld last euermore;<NOTE PLACE="foot">lif.</NOTE></L>
<L>Al-if &thorn;ou slogh me here with paine,</L>
<L>With my lord Crist I lif ogayne.</L>
<L>And, wretche, vnto &thorn;e sal bitide</L>
<L N="780">Sorous sere on ilka side<NOTE PLACE="foot">sorows.</NOTE></L>
<L>And sethin &thorn;ou sal far with &thorn;e fende</L>
<L>And wun in wo with-o(u)ten ende &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">won. wa.</NOTE></L>
<L>So gret vnto god es &thorn;i gilt,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Grete.</NOTE></L>
<L>For sakles blude &thorn;at &thorn;ou has spilt".</L>
<L N="785">&THORN;an was he sone oway &thorn;am fro.<NOTE PLACE="foot">When &thorn;is was said . .,</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;e Emperoure was ful wo.<NOTE PLACE="foot">He went oway &thorn;ai. ., dann folgt. noch ein Verspaar mit wa als letztem Reimwort. Auf der R&uuml;ckseite ist die 1. Col. mit dem Schluss von Paul und den 17 ersten Versen von Jacobus bis auf wenige Spuren zerst&ouml;rt. Die lesbaren W&ouml;rter stimmen mit H. &uuml;berein, so: war ded 791, taken 793, had forsaken 794, ber(id) preuely 796, herd &thorn;e Grekes (say) 797, berid . . 798, stollen &thorn;am still 799, will 800, trembild . . obout 801, durst noght ga for dout 802, out of Rome 803, cristendome 804, vnto &thorn;e toune 807, &thorn;are 809, ware 810.</NOTE></L>
<L>In mynde he wex all mad for dout</L>
<L>And &thorn;e fende made him wude al out,</L>
<L>He turment him als wurthi was,</L>
<L N="790">And so he went vnto Sathanas.</L>
<L>Saint Peter and Paul a dai war dede</L>
<L>And both war berid in one stede:</L>
<L>Ane Marcill, &thorn;at right trouth had takin</L>
<L>And Simon Magus first forsaken,</L>
<L N="795">He gat vnto him o&thorn;er cumpany</L>
<L>And beryed &thorn;am ful preuely.</L>
<L>Sethin efter herd &thorn;e Grekes say</L>
<L>Whore &thorn;aire two bodis beried lay:</L>
<L>Oway &thorn;ai wald haue stollen &thorn;am still.</L>
<L N="800">Bot &thorn;an, als it was goddes will,</L>
<L>&THORN;e erth so tremblid &thorn;am obout:</L>
<L>&THORN;ai darid and durst noght do for dout.</L>
<L>Sethin come &thorn;ore fele folk out of Rome</L>
<L>&THORN;at of &thorn;am had tane cristendome;</L>
<L N="805">&THORN;aire graues &thorn;ai opind both at ones</L>
<L>And tuke vp all &thorn;aire blisced bones,<NOTE PLACE="foot">V. 805&mdash;6 fehlten in Tib.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ai bare &thorn;am al into &thorn;e toune</L>
<L>With ful faire processioune,</L>
<L>A place &thorn;ai ordand for &thorn;am &thorn;ore</L>
<L N="810">With wirschip, als &thorn;ai wurthi wore.</L>
<L>&THORN;us Peter and Paul tok passioune</L>
<L>Efter oure lord Cristes ascensioune</L>
<L>Thretty &yogh;eres and &thorn;arto seuyn,</L>
<L>And went both to &thorn;e blis of heuyn,</L>
<L N="815">Whore &thorn;ai sall lif euer in lyking&mdash;</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;at blis Jhesu us bring! amen.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="appendix"><PB REF="00000215.tif" N="77">
<HEAD>Anhang: Sermo in festo apostolorum Petri et Pauli, aus Ms. Ashm. 42, fol. 281b.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>Ein &auml;lterer, k&uuml;rzerer, vielfach abweichender Text der Leg. von Peter und Paul findet sich in der Evangeliensammlung des Ms. Ashm. 42, fol. 281b, hinten angeh&auml;ngt.</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ir werldes princes hase seruise</L>
<L>Of &thorn;aire seruaundes on all wise,</L>
<L>And twa pryncis of hali kirk</L>
<L>Was als &thorn;is daie of pyne full yrk:</L>
<L N="5">&THORN;ir twa Petir and Paule ware</L>
<L>&THORN;at tholid als &thorn;is daie paines sare:</L>
<L>Bothe ware &thorn;ai slayne for goddes sake.</L>
<L>For&thorn;i of &thorn;aim feste burd vs make</L>
<L>And wirschipe &thorn;aim in worde &amp; dede</L>
<L N="10">And of &thorn;aire passioune singe and rede.</L>
<L>&THORN;e feste of vs ask &thorn;ai to daie,</L>
<L>Forthi es gode som thinge to saie</L>
<L>Off &thorn;aire life &amp; &thorn;aire endinge,</L>
<L>And &thorn;areto ask &thorn;aim helpinge.</L>
<L N="15">In boke of &thorn;aim writen we finde</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ai come of &thorn;e Jewes kynde,</L>
<L>Bot sainte Petir was &thorn;e elder</L>
<L>&amp; was bot a pure fihssere.</L>
<L>Of him will i first schawe,</L>
<L N="20">And sithen of Paule, his felawe. &mdash;</L>
<L>Sainte Petir had names thre:</L>
<L>For first Symon callid was he,</L>
<L>&THORN;at bemenes "bousome" in ynglihffe:</L>
<L>For so bowsome was he iwisse</L>
<L N="25">&THORN;at he lefft schippe and his fihssinge</L>
<L>And folowid Criste wi&thorn; a callinge</L>
<L>&amp; fullfillid all Cristis biddingef</L>
<L>And was bowsome in all thinges &mdash;</L>
<L>Forthi he was Symon right callde,</L>
<L N="30">For he did all &thorn;at Criste wallde.</L>
<L>His o&thorn;er name gaue him Jesus,</L>
<L>Als &thorn;e gospell telles vs:</L>
<L>&THORN;at was Petir: &thorn;at es to saie</L>
<L>"Knawinge" on ynglihffe "of god verraie".</L>
<L N="35">Oure gospell spekes of right knawinge</L>
<L>&THORN;at Petir had of Criste, oure kinge:</L>
<L>Som men wend Criste had bene Elye,</L>
<L>And som &thorn;e prophete Jeremie,</L>
<L>And som men Jone &thorn;e baptiste;</L>
<L N="40">Bot Petir knewe him wele for Criste:</L>
<L>"Criste, goddes sonne, he saide, ertowe"&mdash;</L>
<L>And als he saide we awe to trowe.</L>
<L>His thrid name was Bariona;</L>
<L>&THORN;e resone whi &thorn;at he hight swa,</L>
<L N="45">Es &thorn;is &thorn;at to vndirstandinge is</L>
<L>"A doufe sonne" in propir ynglihffe:</L>
<L>For doufe sonne was Petir iwisse,</L>
<L>For meke he was als &thorn;e doufe is;</L>
<L N="50">&THORN;e doufe mase dule in stede of sange:</L>
<L>And so did Petir, &thorn;at sorowid lange</L>
<L>To haue of Criste sight effter &thorn;e time</L>
<L>&THORN;at he sawe Jesu stye fra hime;</L>
<L>For aie he grette when he herd neuene</L>
<L N="55">Of Jesu passioune, &thorn;at es in heuene;</L>
<L>And when he herd neuene Jesu Criste,</L>
<L>He saide to men: if &thorn;at &thorn;ai wiste</L>
<L>How sweteli Jesu to vs spak,</L>
<L>"Grete dole for him wald &yogh;e make.</L>
<L N="60">"Oure allir, he saide, was Jesus,</L>
<L>And aie spake he so faire to vs,</L>
<L>&THORN;at gretinge maie i no&yogh;t forbere</L>
<L>When Jesu ringis in myne ere."&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;is es againe prelates &amp; maistirs</L>
<L N="65">&THORN;at &thorn;aire vndirmen so felli faistirs</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; chid&iacute;nge and wi&thorn; schamefull sawe,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ai er faine fra &thorn;aime to drawe;</L>
<L>Dar &thorn;ai na worde speke &thorn;aim againe</L>
<L>Ne to &thorn;aire biddinge be vnbaine;</L>
<L N="70">If ani againe &thorn;aire will o&yogh;t schawe,</L>
<L>His resoune es no&yogh;t worthe a hawe,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; threte es he made so faine</L>
<L>&THORN;at he hase saide to call againe.</L>
<L>Hetheli glowminge &amp; wordes grete,</L>
<L N="75">Doute to tyne maistrie for threte,</L>
<L>Mase vndirmen to be full still</L>
<L>And saie no&yogh;t againe &thorn;aire will &mdash;</L>
<L>For, wha so duse, als wele he maie</L>
<L>Take his staffe &amp; wende his waie!</L>
<L N="80">Swilk prelates leues Petir lare,</L>
<L>&THORN;at saide to &thorn;aim wi&thorn; swete sware:</L>
<L>"Beese no&yogh;t lordes of lerid men,</L>
<L>Bot gude ensaumpil &yogh;e &thorn;aim ken</L>
<L>How &thorn;aim awe to folow &yogh;owe</L>
<L N="85">In mekenes &amp; in sawle prowe;</L>
<L>For gude ensaumpil gaue Jesus:</L>
<L>So mekeli spak he to vs". &mdash;</L>
<L>Now haue i twa resones talde</L>
<L>Whi sainte Petir "doufe sonne" es calde.</L>
<L N="90">His first name es callid Symone,</L>
<L>&THORN;e to&thorn;er Petir, wi&thorn; resoune,</L>
<L>And "doufe sonne" was the thrid &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;ir thre names in kirk er kid. &mdash;</L>
<L>So mikil lufid sainte Petir Kriste,</L>
<L N="95">Als Austine saise, &thorn;at, if he had wiste</L>
<L>&THORN;at Judas suld haue done Criste tresoune,</L>
<L>He had slaine him als feloune;
<PB REF="00000216.tif" N="78"></L>
<L>Forthi wald Criste his name no&yogh;t saie</L>
<L>Bot saide: "one of &yogh;ow sall me betraie",</L>
<L>For, had he Judas name neuende,</L>
<L N="100">Att &thorn;e mawnde had Criste bene heuende;<NOTE PLACE="foot">heuende = avenged.</NOTE></L>
<L>And herebi maie we all se</L>
<L>&THORN;at mikil lufe to Criste had he.</L>
<L>And forthi gaue Jesu him might</L>
<L>To binde &amp; louse man of plight.</L>
<L N="105">He was so hali, &thorn;at he &yogh;ede</L>
<L>Apon &thorn;e se, als we rede.</L>
<L>He tornid on &thorn;e wittesondaie</L>
<L>Thre &thorn;ousand men to cristen laie.</L>
<L>He baptisid sir Cornelie,</L>
<L N="110">&THORN;at hethen was &amp; man mi&yogh;tie.</L>
<L>He raisid fra dede to life Tabite,</L>
<L>And men of sekenes made hale &amp; qwite&mdash;</L>
<L>For &thorn;e schadowe of his bodie</L>
<L>Gaue &thorn;e seke &thorn;aire hele in hye.</L>
<L N="115">Herode helde him in his presoune,</L>
<L>Foule ffettrid als feloune;</L>
<L>Bot Criste sent him his aungel bri&yogh;t</L>
<L>And lowsid him apon a night,</L>
<L>Oute of presoune Petir he lete</L>
<L N="120">And ledde into &thorn;e hye strete.</L>
<L>In pouerte all his life he ledde,</L>
<L>In mantil &amp; kirtill was he cledde.&mdash;</L>
<L>In &thorn;at tyme &thorn;us it befell:</L>
<L>A fals man began to spell</L>
<L N="125">In Rome &amp; in &thorn;e contre bie</L>
<L>And gert men fall in heresie:</L>
<L>Symon Magus was he callde;</L>
<L>He saide he might do what he walde,</L>
<L>For goddes sonne, he saide, he wase</L>
<L N="130">And fra dede to lyue he rase;</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; whicchecrafft men he betraiste</L>
<L>&amp; gert men wene &thorn;at he was Criste,</L>
<L>And ferlies did he full fele</L>
<L>&amp; mani men gert of him mele.</L>
<L N="135">Petir prechid him againe</L>
<L>&amp; sayde: fro him men suld &thorn;aime sayne,</L>
<L>For so full he was of &thorn;e fende</L>
<L>&THORN;at mani saules made he to schende;</L>
<L>Petir bad men &thorn;ai suld him no&yogh;t trowe,</L>
<L N="140">F(or i)t was no&yogh;t &thorn;aire saules prowe;</L>
<L>He praied god he suld &thorn;aim schelde</L>
<L>&amp; hald &thorn;aim fro &thorn;e deuels belde.</L>
<L>"Trowes no&yogh;t, he saide, on his fals sawe:</L>
<L>It es againe all cristen lawe;</L>
<L N="145">He will to hell &yogh;ou all drawe,</L>
<L>Als i &yogh;ou mai wi&thorn; resoune schawe".</L>
<L>&THORN;us prechid Petir againe his lare</L>
<L>And forbade all his fals fare,</L>
<L>And gert men se wi&thorn; resoune hende</L>
<L N="150">&THORN;at he was fullfillid of &thorn;e fende.</L>
<L>Symon was wrathe, als &thorn;e boke saise,</L>
<L>And rusid him &thorn;an &thorn;at he might raise</L>
<L>Dede men to lyue, to gange &amp; speke.</L>
<L>&THORN;an died a man &thorn;at had bene seke:</L>
<L N="155">And &thorn;e corse was bro&yogh;t in plase swithe</L>
<L>To ger Petir or Symon kythe</L>
<L>&THORN;air crafft, &amp; whilk of &thorn;aim &thorn;an</L>
<L>Might raise to life &thorn;at dede man;</L>
<L>And who so failid of &thorn;at dede,</L>
<L N="160">He suld be slaine for his mede.</L>
<L>&THORN;is conand grauntid all &thorn;at ware</L>
<L>wi&thorn; Petir and wi&thorn; Symounde &thorn;are.</L>
<L>And to &thorn;at corse come firste Symoune</L>
<L>&amp; made fast his coniurisoune:</L>
<L N="165">and wi&thorn; crafft of &thorn;e euile gaste</L>
<L>&THORN;e dede mannes heued sterid in haste.</L>
<L>&THORN;an wald &thorn;e folk haue slaine Peter swithe.</L>
<L>And Petir bad &thorn;aim listen &amp; lithe</L>
<L>&amp; saide: "late Symon hethen wende,</L>
<L N="170">&amp; &thorn;an sall &yogh;e se &thorn;at &thorn;e fende</L>
<L>Stires &thorn;e heuede of &yogh;one dede mane;</L>
<L>For life in him forsothe es nane."</L>
<L>&THORN;an gert &thorn;ai Symone gange awaie:</L>
<L>And still als stane &thorn;e bodi laie &mdash;</L>
<L N="175">&THORN;an tho&yogh;t Symon mikil schame.</L>
<L>And Petir spake in Cristes name</L>
<L>&amp; saide: "dede man, i comaunde &thorn;e</L>
<L>In Cristis name &thorn;at died on tre</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou rise vppe hale and sounde</L>
<L N="180">And tell vs what man es Symounde!"</L>
<L>&THORN;e dede man rase &amp; talde bedene<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. calde.</NOTE></L>
<L>What he of heuene &amp; hell had sene,</L>
<L>And saide: "forsothe, i &yogh;ow tell</L>
<L>&THORN;at Symounde tillis &yogh;ou all to hell.</L>
<L N="185">Trowes him no&yogh;t, for full es he</L>
<L>Of Sathanas, in whase pouste</L>
<L>He duse &thorn;ir ferlies &thorn;at &yogh;e se &mdash;</L>
<L>For god his dede hase schewid me."</L>
<L>&THORN;an wald &thorn;e folk haue Symounde slaine.</L>
<L N="190">Bot Petir fast was &thorn;are agayne</L>
<L>And saide: "if we do Cristis will,</L>
<L>we sall do gude agaynes ylle:</L>
<L>For so bad Criste him-self vs do</L>
<L>When he prechid vs vnto.</L>
<L N="195">Forthi do we Symounde na skathe,</L>
<L>Bot late him ga wi&thorn;-outen lathe!</L>
<L>For sorowe &amp; schame he hase ynoghe:</L>
<L>Forthi i praie he haue na woghe."</L>
<L>Bot here-wi&thorn;-all lefft no&yogh;t Symoune</L>
<L N="200">To do againe Petir tresoune,</L>
<L>Bot &yogh;ode &amp; tyed a band-dogge strange</L>
<L>&THORN;are Petire was wonte to come &amp; gange,</L>
<L>And saide: "now sall we all se</L>
<L>If Petir dare come to louse &thorn;e."</L>
<L N="205">When Petir herd saie what he had done,</L>
<L>To &thorn;at band-dogge he come full sone</L>
<L>And lousid him: &amp; on Symounde</L>
<L>So frek was &thorn;at vncely hounde,
<PB REF="00000217.tif" N="79"></L>
<L>&THORN;at he him filchid felli &thorn;are,</L>
<L N="210">And him had wiried, if Petir ne ware.</L>
<L>Petir bad &thorn;e hounde &thorn;at he suld leeue:</L>
<L>And he lefft and his taile gon weue.</L>
<L>&THORN;an fled Symounde of Rome for doute</L>
<L>And &thorn;at twelfemonethe was he oute&mdash;</L>
<L N="215">For so mikil schame him tho&yogh;t</L>
<L>&THORN;at come in Rome mi&yogh;t he no&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;an effter sone he come</L>
<L>Till sir Nero, emperoure of Rome,</L>
<L>And saide &thorn;at he had tane grete scathe</L>
<L N="220">Off Petir &amp; of Paule bathe:</L>
<L>"Of &thorn;aim, he saide, &thorn;ou venge me,</L>
<L>Als &thorn;ou will &thorn;at i saue &thorn;e!</L>
<L>And if &thorn;ou trow no&yogh;t mi mi&yogh;t,</L>
<L>I sall it schew in all mennes sight."</L>
<L N="225">Als he &thorn;us before him stode,</L>
<L>In sere liknes he chaungid his mode:</L>
<L>Now semid him &yogh;onge, &amp; now alde,</L>
<L>And schewid liknes manifalde;</L>
<L>He &thorn;aim begilid als a Juggeloure,</L>
<L N="230">And saide &thorn;an to &thorn;e emperoure:</L>
<L>"Sir Emperoure, i pray the,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou ger smyte of &thorn;e heued of me:</L>
<L>And i sall rise qwik &thorn;e thrid daie.</L>
<L>Wha maie &thorn;an agaynes me saie</L>
<L N="235">&THORN;at i ne am god all-mightie,</L>
<L>To do in erde what euer will i?"</L>
<L>&THORN;an bad Nero it suld be done.</L>
<L>And he toke a wedir sone</L>
<L>And made it him-seluene like</L>
<L N="240">Be &thorn;e deueles crafft &thorn;at him gon swike&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;is he did be enchauntemente,</L>
<L>&THORN;at made his saule to be schente.</L>
<L>&THORN;an Nero gert his heuede of strike:</L>
<L>For &thorn;e wedir schepe was him like,</L>
<L N="245">&THORN;is Symounde gaue &thorn;e qwellare mede</L>
<L>And gert him do in mirk his dede.</L>
<L>For, when &thorn;e heuede was smiten awaie,</L>
<L>A tope-heued on &thorn;e erde laie.</L>
<L>And Symon twa daies him hidde</L>
<L N="250">And come to Nero on &thorn;e thridde.</L>
<L>&amp; Nero wende he qwikkind ware,</L>
<L>And &thorn;erfore held him mikil in are</L>
<L>&amp; saide &thorn;at he was all-mighti</L>
<L>God of heuene witirlie.</L>
<L N="255">Bot Petir &amp; Paule saide &thorn;at he was</L>
<L>&THORN;e foule fende Sathanase.</L>
<L>&THORN;an Symon on Petir &amp; Paule lied</L>
<L>And to Nero &thorn;aim falsli wried</L>
<L>And saide: &thorn;ai ware aboute to stroie</L>
<L N="260">&THORN;e kingrike, &amp; &thorn;e kinge to noye.</L>
<L>And Nero gert &thorn;aim bothe somounde,</L>
<L>To defende againe Symounde.</L>
<L>&THORN;an come &thorn;ai all before Nero,</L>
<L>To dispuite to and fro.</L>
<L N="265">Petir proued be gude resoune</L>
<L>&THORN;at Symounde was full of tresoune.</L>
<L>For "Symounde", he saide, "if &thorn;ou can rede</L>
<L>What i think to do in dede,</L>
<L>&THORN;an mai all men bathe here &amp; se</L>
<L N="270">If &thorn;ou god of heuene be.</L>
<L>For god knawes all men tho&yogh;t</L>
<L>And fro god maie be hidde no&yogh;t;</L>
<L>And if &thorn;ou goddes sonne be,</L>
<L>late it be sene &amp; saie &thorn;ou me</L>
<L N="275">What i think! &amp; &thorn;an may all</L>
<L>On &thorn;e trowe &amp; on &thorn;e call.</L>
<L>And if &thorn;ou may no&yogh;t mi tho&yogh;t schewe,</L>
<L>&THORN;an all mai se &thorn;ou ert a schrewe</L>
<L>&THORN;at takes on &thorn;e Cristis name;</L>
<L N="280">&THORN;an duse &thorn;ou god mikil schame,</L>
<L>For &thorn;ou ert aboute all men to schende</L>
<L>And ger &thorn;aire saules ga to &thorn;e fende."</L>
<L>When Petir had saide &thorn;is &amp; mare,</L>
<L>Symoun answerd &amp; saide &thorn;are:</L>
<L N="285">"I ask dome, sir emperoure,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou me wreke of &thorn;is traytoure!</L>
<L>Si&thorn;en &thorn;ou wate wele &thorn;at i vprase</L>
<L>Fra dede to liue, als mi will wase,</L>
<L>Me think grete ferli now of &thorn;e</L>
<L N="290">&THORN;at &thorn;ou lates him speke againes me."</L>
<L>Nero answerd &amp; saide: "Symon,</L>
<L>Me think &thorn;at Petir saise resone.</L>
<L>If &thorn;ou be goddes sonne, latte se,</L>
<L>And what he thinkes tell &thorn;ou me!"</L>
<L N="295">Symon saide: "late se, haue done!</L>
<L>What euer he thinkis, i sall saie sone."</L>
<L>And Petir said Nero what he tho&yogh;t,</L>
<L>All priueli, &thorn;at he herd no&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&amp; saide: "Emperoure, &yogh;e ger me haue</L>
<L N="300">All priuelie a barli laue!"</L>
<L>&THORN;is brede was bro&yogh;t all priuelie,</L>
<L>And Petir halowid it in hye.</L>
<L>&THORN;an Petir bad Symon saie sone</L>
<L>What &thorn;at he had saide &amp; done:</L>
<L N="305">Symond answerde, &amp; was full wa,</L>
<L>And saide: "myne aungelles, here &yogh;e ga</L>
<L>&amp; venge me tite apon mi fa!</L>
<L>I comaunde &yogh;ou &thorn;at &yogh;e him sla."</L>
<L>And sone come &thorn;are forthe dogges blak</L>
<L N="310">&amp; on Petir gon &thorn;ai snak.</L>
<L>And Petir &thorn;e hali brede &thorn;aim bedde:</L>
<L>And fra Petir fast &thorn;ai fledde.</L>
<L>&THORN;an saide Petir to &thorn;e emperoure:</L>
<L>"&THORN;ou sees, Symon es bot a traytoure:</L>
<L N="315">Of honde kynde er his aungelles;</L>
<L>&THORN;us wi&thorn; falshede his tales he tellis."</L>
<L>&THORN;an was Symounde at Petir tene</L>
<L>And saide: "Nero, nou sall be sene</L>
<L>What i am, when &thorn;ou sees me flie</L>
<L N="320">In-till heuene als god mightie;</L>
<L>&amp; sithen &thorn;e &amp; o&thorn;ir ma</L>
<L>To heuene &thorn;an sall i ger &yogh;ow ga,</L>
<L>&THORN;arein to dwell euermore wi&thorn; me &mdash;
<PB REF="00000218.tif" N="80"></L>
<L>For i will here na langer be.</L>
<L N="325">And if &thorn;ow will &thorn;is maistrie se,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou ger do make a toure of tre,</L>
<L>&THORN;at i maie stand in all men sight,</L>
<L>&THORN;are all mai se me take mi flight".</L>
<L>A hye toure was &thorn;are made swithe.</L>
<L N="330">And Symond gon his maistrie kythe:</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; fendes crafft vppe he flawe</L>
<L>Into &thorn;e lifft, &thorn;at all men sawe.</L>
<L>And Nero saide to Petir &thorn;an:</L>
<L>"Now maie &thorn;ou se, &thorn;ou fals man,</L>
<L N="335">&THORN;at goddes sonne of heuene es Symounde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at flyande maie to heuene founde".</L>
<L>&THORN;an saide Petir: "late him flie!"</L>
<L>And when Symoun was right hye,</L>
<L>&THORN;an saide Petir: "I comaunde &yogh;owe,</L>
<L N="340">&YOGH;e fendes, &thorn;at beres Symounde nowe,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &yogh;e late him doune fall</L>
<L>In &thorn;is plase ymange vs all!"</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;at he fell &amp; brast in-sondere,</L>
<L>And his saule went to hell wi&thorn; thondir,</L>
<L N="345">&THORN;are to dwell for euermare</L>
<L>For his falshede &thorn;at he did &thorn;are.</L>
<L>And &thorn;an Nero was full wrathe</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; Petir &amp; wi&thorn; Paule bathe</L>
<L>For his dede, &amp; demede sone</L>
<L N="350">&THORN;at &thorn;ai to dede bathe suld be done,</L>
<L>Petir to be on rode weuede</L>
<L>And Paule smitene of his heuede.</L>
<L>Bot when Petir come to &thorn;e rode</L>
<L>And sawe &thorn;at it vpwarde stode,</L>
<L N="355">He saide: "i am no&yogh;t worthi to be</L>
<L>Done on rode als Criste was for me;</L>
<L>Bot torne &thorn;e rode vppe so doune,</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e erde &yogh;e torne mi croune</L>
<L>And vpward mi fete &yogh;e feste!</L>
<L N="360">For &thorn;us will i on rode reste,</L>
<L>Aye to mi saule mi lorde fange,</L>
<L>For whase lufe on rode i hange".</L>
<L>Till his biddinge was bernes boune:</L>
<L>&amp; Petir heuede hangid &thorn;ai doune</L>
<L N="365">&amp; vpward his fete &thorn;ai fest,</L>
<L>And bro&yogh;t his saule to heuenes rest.</L>
<L>&THORN;us died Petir on &thorn;e rude.</L>
<L>And Paule (for) Criste schedde his blude.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>How it of Paule passioune fell,</L>
<L N="370">If &yogh;e listen, i will &yogh;ou tell.</L>
<L>Vnto Nero saide sainte Paule:</L>
<L>"&THORN;ou hase, sir, in bodi a saule,</L>
<L>And thi bodi sall rote in molde,</L>
<L>Be &thorn;ou to it neuer so holde;</L>
<L N="375">And on domisdaie sall tow rise</L>
<L>And come before &thorn;e hie iustise,</L>
<L>To &yogh;elde acounte (of) &thorn;at &thorn;ou duse here,</L>
<L>Of ylle and gude &thorn;at &thorn;ou hase done fere".</L>
<L>&THORN;an was Nero wondir wrathe</L>
<L N="380">&amp; saide: "now sall i proue &mdash; if &thorn;e be lathe &mdash;</L>
<L>If &thorn;ou maie rise effter &thorn;i dede".</L>
<L>And bad men lede him to &thorn;e stede</L>
<L>&THORN;are he suld slaine be.</L>
<L>And to Nero &thorn;an saide he:</L>
<L N="385">"Effter mi dede &thorn;ou sall me se</L>
<L>Stande, als i do now, before the,</L>
<L>To ger &thorn;e witte &thorn;at i sall aie</L>
<L>Lyue wi&thorn; Criste in ioye &amp; plaie".</L>
<L>When &thorn;is was saide, to dede he wente.</L>
<L N="390">And cristen men full mikil him mente.</L>
<L>&amp; als he &yogh;ode, a wife him mette</L>
<L>&THORN;at him wele knewe &amp; for him grette.</L>
<L>He bad hir lene him hir couerchefe,</L>
<L>Before his eyene forto wefe,</L>
<L N="395">"And i, he saide, sall &yogh;elde it &thorn;e,</L>
<L>When mi heuede es smiten of me".</L>
<L>Hir couerchefe to him scho gafe.</L>
<L>And foles hir to hethinge drafe</L>
<L>And saide: "whi giues &thorn;ou swilk a clathe?</L>
<L N="400">It to tyne &thorn;e suld think lathe".</L>
<L>Scho made na forse of &thorn;aire sawes,</L>
<L>Bot grette sare for Paule hard thrawes.</L>
<L>When Paule come &thorn;are whare he suld dye,</L>
<L>He made his praiere wi&thorn; tere of ye.</L>
<L N="405">And when he had made his praiere,</L>
<L>Off smate his heuede &thorn;e manqwellere.</L>
<L>&THORN;e heuede stert fra &thorn;e bodie</L>
<L>And saide "Jesue" apertelie,</L>
<L>Fyue hondrethe sithis, als saise &thorn;e boke,</L>
<L N="410">He neuend Jesu, wha will it loke.</L>
<L>First come milk oute of his throte</L>
<L>And sithen blude a mikil gote.</L>
<L>&THORN;an lemes light and swete smell</L>
<L>Was felid and sene, &thorn;are he doune fell.</L>
<L N="415">And als &thorn;is qwellare hamward wente,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ilk wife he mette &thorn;at Paule lente</L>
<L>&THORN;at faire couerchefe of hir heuid,</L>
<L>&amp; scho askid him whare he Paule leuede.</L>
<L>"He ligges, he saide, slaine in&yogh;one plase,</L>
<L N="420">And &thorn;i couerchefe on his face".</L>
<L>&THORN;an forthe &thorn;e clothe blodi scho drewe</L>
<L>And schewid it him &thorn;at sainte Paule slewe,</L>
<L>Scho saide: "ri&yogh;t now was Paule here</L>
<L>And gaue me &thorn;is wi&thorn; mylde chere;</L>
<L N="425">And Petir wi&thorn; him als sawe I,</L>
<L>In bright clethinge stode him bie".</L>
<L>&THORN;e emperoure Nero sone herd &thorn;is</L>
<L>And of &thorn;at was vnglad iwisse;</L>
<L>He callid his frendes all him to</L>
<L N="430">And asked what him ware best to do.</L>
<L>And als he &thorn;us in counsell sate,</L>
<L>Paule come him to in atte sperid &yogh;ate,</L>
<L>And to Nero &thorn;us spak he</L>
<L>And saide: "emperoure, now maye &thorn;ou se</L>
<L N="435">&THORN;at i sall liue wi&thorn;-outene ende.</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou to pyne to hell sall wende
<PB REF="00000219.tif" N="81"></L>
<L>For cristen men &thorn;at &thorn;ou geres sla"</L>
<L>And oute of his sight he went full thra.</L>
<L>&THORN;e emperoure Nero afraiede satte.</L>
<L N="440">&THORN;an oute of presoune he gert late</L>
<L>All cristen men &thorn;at he helde &thorn;are;</L>
<L>Bot he ne wald trowe on cristen lare &mdash;</L>
<L>He was so rotid in his synne</L>
<L>&THORN;at hele of life wald he no&yogh;t wynne:</L>
<L N="445">Had he na grace to do penaunce.</L>
<L>Forthi on him fell foule mischaunce &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at oure-lange ware now to tell;</L>
<L>Bot schorteli, he es in hell.</L>
<L>Him-self was his awne bane;</L>
<L N="450">Forthi he es wi&thorn; foule Sathane.</L>
<L>And Petir &amp; Paul, &thorn;at he sloghe,</L>
<L>Er bathe now in blisse ynoghe.</L>
<L>To &thorn;at ilk blisse he vs bringe</L>
<L>&THORN;at for oure lufe on rode walde hinge!</L>
<TRAILER>W. amen. S.</TRAILER>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="17" TYPE="legend">
<HEAD>17. De sca Maria Magdalena historia.</HEAD>
<DIV3 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Of Mari Maudelayn mai men take<MILESTONE N="157" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="foot">Magdalena und Christina fehlen im Ms. Tib.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ensaumple, sins forto forsake.</L>
<L>Scho had a sister, hight Martha;</L>
<L>Full nobil wemen war &thorn;ai twa;</L>
<L N="5">Both war lufed with our lord Jhesus.</L>
<L>A bro&thorn;er &thorn;ai had, hight La&yogh;arus,</L>
<L>Wham Crist raysed when he was ded,</L>
<L>Als es red in ane o&thorn;er stede.</L>
<L>Born &thorn;ai war of gentyll blode</L>
<L N="10">And riche &thorn;ai war of werldly gude.</L>
<L>And als it es in storise redd,</L>
<L>&THORN;is Mari Maudelayne was wedd</L>
<L>Vnto saynt John &thorn;e Ewangeliste.</L>
<L>He left his wife &amp; went with Criste</L>
<L N="15">At &thorn;e grete fest of Architrycline,</L>
<L>Whore Crist turned water vnto wyne.</L>
<L>Sum clerkes wil &thorn;is purpose halde:</L>
<L>By-cause hir spous was fro hir calde,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai say &thorn;at was enchesun why</L>
<L N="20">Scho assentid to syn with hir body,</L>
<L>And efterwarde for &thorn;at same skill</L>
<L>God granted gretter grace hyr till.</L>
<L>Fro scho had takin hir vnto syn,</L>
<L>&THORN;ar might no-man mak hir to blyn;</L>
<L N="25">Til scho was broght in swilk defame,</L>
<L>&THORN;at in &thorn;at tyme &thorn;ai turned hir name:</L>
<L>Mari &thorn;e synner, sum cald hir &thorn;an,</L>
<L>And sum: Mari &thorn;e wikked woman.</L>
<L>Til al &thorn;e last god vouched saue</L>
<L N="30">&THORN;at scho suld his forgifnes haue:</L>
<L>He sent his grace hir hert with-in</L>
<L>Forto haue sorow for hir syn.</L>
<L>In Simondes hous when scho herd tell</L>
<L>&THORN;at Crist suld vnto soper dwell,</L>
<L N="35">Scho thoght on what wise scho might wyn</L>
<L>To get forgifnes for hir syn &mdash;</L>
<L>For wele scho trowed with-outyn trayne</L>
<L>&THORN;at in hym was all power playne.</L>
<L>In &thorn;at cuntre, als clerkis wate,</L>
<L N="40">&THORN;an was &thorn;e sun so wunder hate,</L>
<L>&THORN;at, who-so wore walkand &thorn;arin,</L>
<L>All &thorn;at war bare euyll wold it brin;</L>
<L>Wharfore &thorn;e riche men of &thorn;at land</L>
<L>Had gude vnement &thorn;arfore ordand</L>
<L N="45">Forto enoynt &thorn;aire face and fete,</L>
<L>So forto saue &thorn;am fro &thorn;at hete.</L>
<L>And for scho hopid so Crist to plese,</L>
<L>Vnement broght scho, him to ese.</L>
<L>Scho wald noght wande, if it war dere,</L>
<L N="50">Bot helt it out with hertly chere</L>
<L>Both on his heuid and on his fete,</L>
<L>And wesch &thorn;am with hir teris wete,</L>
<L>And sethin scho dried &thorn;am with hir hare,</L>
<L>And for hir sins scho wepyd sare.</L>
<L N="55">Crist knew hir menyng more and les:</L>
<L>&THORN;arfore he grauntid hir forgifnes.</L>
<L>And in his lufe so he hir knyt,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;arfro wald scho neuer flit.
<PB REF="00000220.tif" N="82"></L>
<L>Scho wold noght leue him in no stede,</L>
<L N="60">Bot foloud him right vnto &thorn;e ded.</L>
<L>And sethin vnto his graue scho soght</L>
<L>And ful gude vnementes with hir broght,</L>
<L>Fro wurmes hys body forto saue,</L>
<L>And for it suld noght rote in graue.</L>
<L N="65">&THORN;arfore kindenes to hir he kyd</L>
<L>More &thorn;an he vnto o&thorn;er did:</L>
<L>For, when he rase, als we er lerde,</L>
<L>Vnto hir first he &thorn;an aperde,</L>
<L>To mak hir in hir trouth be stabill,</L>
<L N="70">To trow it fast with-outen fabill;</L>
<L>And &thorn;an he made hir messangere</L>
<L>Vnto al his appostels dere,</L>
<L>And bad hir tell to lerd and leude</L>
<L>His rising &mdash; &thorn;us kindnes he scheude.</L>
<L N="75">&THORN;an with &thorn;e apostels furth scho dweld,</L>
<L>And euer in halyne(s)scho hir held;</L>
<L>Scho lifd in ful grete deuocioune.</L>
<L>And sethin, efter Cristes ascensioune</L>
<L>When scho had lifde so fourtene &yogh;ere,</L>
<L N="80">&THORN;an bifell on &thorn;is manere.</L>
<L>A nobil preste hight Maximyne,</L>
<L>&THORN;at in faith of Cr(i)st was ful fyne;</L>
<L>He was one of &thorn;e sexty and two</L>
<L>&THORN;at war wunt with Crist to go.</L>
<L N="85">Saint Peter made him cumandment</L>
<L>To Mary Maudelayne for to tent</L>
<L>And to Lazare, hir brother, alswa</L>
<L>And vnto hyr sister Martha,</L>
<L>With o&thorn;er mo of &thorn;aire men&yogh;e,</L>
<L N="90">And bad he suld &thorn;aire &yogh;emer be.</L>
<L>&THORN;an was saint Peter made pape of Rome</L>
<L>And chefe curate of cristendome,</L>
<L>And o&thorn;er apostels in sere land</L>
<L>Of Cristes passioune went prechand.</L>
<L N="95">Mari Maudelayne with hir men&yogh;e</L>
<L>Dwellid &thorn;an in &thorn;e land of Jude.</L>
<L>Ful mani folk &thorn;ore gun scho draw</L>
<L>Forto lif by Cristes lawe.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Jeus &thorn;an had ful grete enuy</L>
<L N="100">To hir and to all hir cumpany,</L>
<L>And oft &thorn;ai cumpast &thorn;am omang</L>
<L>&THORN;am to destroy with sorow strang.</L>
<L>And so &thorn;ai ordand at &thorn;e last</L>
<L>Ane olde schip withouten mast,</L>
<L N="105">Withouten are, anker or ani gude</L>
<L>&THORN;at suld fend ogayns &thorn;e flode:</L>
<L>And &thorn;orein did &thorn;ai euerilkone</L>
<L>&THORN;at vnto Cristes trouth had tone,</L>
<L>And put &thorn;am furth &thorn;an to &thorn;e se,</L>
<L N="110">So for &thorn;ai suld sune perist be,</L>
<L>Both with &thorn;e felnes of &thorn;e flode</L>
<L>And also for defaut of fode.</L>
<L>Bot Crist, for wham &thorn;ai war exilde,</L>
<L>Wold noght lat &thorn;am be bigilde:</L>
<L N="115">Al-if &thorn;am wanted mast &amp; sayle,</L>
<L>He sent &thorn;am sone gude gouernaile.</L>
<L>So &thorn;at &thorn;ai rafe up in ane Ile,</L>
<L>A high cuntre, &thorn;at hight Marcyle.</L>
<L>&THORN;at land knew noght of Cristes lare,</L>
<L N="120">&THORN;arfore &thorn;ai war noght welkum &thorn;are.</L>
<L>Bot sone, when &thorn;ai war wun to land,</L>
<L>Omong &thorn;e folk &thorn;ai went prechand,</L>
<L>Of Cristes faith fast &thorn;ai declarid;</L>
<L>Bot no-man toke to &thorn;am reward.</L>
<L N="125">With daunger gat &thorn;ai drink &amp; mete,</L>
<L>Bot herbering &thorn;ai might none gete.</L>
<L>So was &thorn;are standand on a wall</L>
<L>A maumet &thorn;at &thorn;o men on call,</L>
<L>Als for &thorn;aire god to him &thorn;ai soght;</L>
<L N="130">And ouer him was a pentice wroght,</L>
<L>To couer hym fro weders wete,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at was made to &thorn;e midftrete.</L>
<L>&THORN;ore herberd Mary and hir men&yogh;e</L>
<L>For best socure &thorn;at &thorn;ai kouth se.</L>
<L N="135">Bot when scho saw sune on &thorn;e morn</L>
<L>How folk come &thorn;at maumet biforn</L>
<L>And soght to him fro sydes sere</L>
<L>Als to &thorn;aire god of grete powere</L>
<L>And to him made &thorn;ai sacrifise:</L>
<L N="140">&THORN;an was scho ful wroth on hir wise,</L>
<L>Furth scho stode with face ful playne</L>
<L>And said, &thorn;aire werkes war all in uayne;</L>
<L>With stabill tung to &thorn;am scho spak</L>
<L>And &thorn;aire law fast gun scho lak;</L>
<L N="145">Of Crist scho prechid al opinly,</L>
<L>And said &thorn;aire werk was maumetry.</L>
<L>Hir wurdes war so wisely wroght,</L>
<L>&THORN;at al &thorn;e folk grete ferly thoght;</L>
<L>&THORN;ai had ferly of hir fairehede</L>
<L N="150">And how scho durst do swilk a dede.</L>
<L>Bot hir wurdes war so swete to here,</L>
<L>&THORN;at many men held hir dedis dere &mdash;
<PB REF="00000221.tif" N="83"></L>
<L>Bot no wunder if &thorn;e wurde war swete</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e mouth &thorn;at kist Cristes fete!</L>
<L N="155">Hir wurdes &thorn;arfore war of swilk grace,</L>
<L>&THORN;at mekil pople in &thorn;at same place</L>
<L>Vnto hir tales swilk tent &thorn;an toke</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;aire fals sacrifise &thorn;ai forsoke;</L>
<L>Sum lerid ful fast of Cristes lay.</L>
<L N="160">And so bifell it opon ane day:</L>
<L>A mighti prince of &thorn;at cuntre</L>
<L>Soiorned in &thorn;at same cete;</L>
<L>He and his wife war &thorn;edir soght</L>
<L>And to &thorn;at maumet ofrand broght,</L>
<L N="165">For werldes welth &thorn;ai hade gude wane</L>
<L>Bot childe bitwix &thorn;am had &thorn;ai nane;</L>
<L>&THORN;at maumet soght &thorn;ai, for &thorn;ai wend</L>
<L>&THORN;at he childe suld to &thorn;am send &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;ai honord him to &thorn;at entent.</L>
<L N="170">And when Mari wist what &thorn;ai ment,</L>
<L>Ful opinly scho &thorn;am reproued,</L>
<L>And diuers maters &thorn;ore scho moued</L>
<L>&THORN;at in &thorn;at maumet might was none</L>
<L>Ne comfort, bot in Crist allone;</L>
<L N="175">&THORN;is proued scho wele by proces playne,</L>
<L>And so scho gert &thorn;am turn ogayne.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. and st. &thorn;at? l. so to ger?</NOTE></L>
<L>And on &thorn;e night next folowand</L>
<L>&THORN;e prince and his wife lay slepand:</L>
<L>&THORN;an &thorn;e Maudelayn, to amend &thorn;aire life,</L>
<L N="180">Aperd vnto &thorn;e princes wife</L>
<L>And bad scho suld hir erand say</L>
<L>Vnto hir lord &thorn;at by hir lay:</L>
<L>Sen werldes welth was to him sent,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he suld better tak entent</L>
<L N="185">To goddes folk, &thorn;at &thorn;are peryst</L>
<L>Herberles for hunger and thrist,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. for herberles st. herberles for.</NOTE></L>
<L>And bid him &thorn;aire mischef amend</L>
<L>For gods sake &thorn;at him al send.</L>
<L>&THORN;e ladi wakkend &amp; wele scho thoght</L>
<L N="190">On &thorn;is tale. bot scho tolde it noght</L>
<L>Vnto hir lord, als had bene right.<MILESTONE N="158" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;arfore on &thorn;at o&thorn;er night</L>
<L>&THORN;e Maudelayn vnto hir aperd</L>
<L>And &thorn;at same lesson eft hir lerd:</L>
<L N="195">Scho comand hir with wurdes fell</L>
<L>Vnto hir lord &thorn;at scho suld tell</L>
<L>Goddes men&yogh;e forto releue,</L>
<L>Or els, scho said, it suld hir greue.</L>
<L>When al &thorn;ir tales war told hir till,</L>
<L N="200">Scho wakkend, &amp; &yogh;it held hir still;</L>
<L>To hir it was ful grete affray,</L>
<L>Bot to hir lord scho durst noght say.</L>
<L>&THORN;arfore &thorn;e Maudlain was noght fayn;</L>
<L>On &thorn;e thrid night scho come ogayn:</L>
<L N="205">&THORN;an scho aperd vnto &thorn;am bathe</L>
<L>And spak to &thorn;am with wurdes wrathe &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;e hous was all fulfild of light:</L>
<L>To &thorn;am &thorn;at was a selkuth sight;</L>
<L>In &thorn;aire slepe war &thorn;ai ful affraid.</L>
<L N="210">And to &thorn;e prince al &thorn;us scho sayd:</L>
<L>"Slepis &thorn;ou, terand ful of ire?</L>
<L>A, lym of Satenas, &thorn;i sire!</L>
<L>Call &thorn;ou vp &thorn;at nedder kinlyng</L>
<L>&THORN;at I bad suld mi message bring:</L>
<L N="215">&THORN;at es &thorn;i wife &thorn;at by &thorn;e lise,</L>
<L>To wham I cumand on &thorn;is wise:</L>
<L>On mi bihalue at tell to &thorn;e</L>
<L>Ofe goddes pople to haue pete.</L>
<L>&YOGH;e welter here with wombes grete,</L>
<L N="220">And &thorn;ai haue now&thorn;er drink ne mete;</L>
<L>&YOGH;e lig in forures mani follde,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ai perisch with windes colde;</L>
<L>Ful mekil beld es &yogh;ow obout,</L>
<L>And goddes folk lat &yogh;e lig &thorn;erout;</L>
<L N="225">In silk and sendell here &yogh;e slape &mdash;</L>
<L>I say &yogh;e sall noght so eschape,</L>
<L>Bot ful dere sal &yogh;e both aby</L>
<L>Bot-if &yogh;e help goddes folk in hy</L>
<L>For his sake &thorn;at &yogh;ow al has sent."</L>
<L N="230">When &thorn;is was said, oway scho went.</L>
<L>&THORN;e ladi wakkend &amp; wepid sore:</L>
<L>For so ferd was scho neuer byfore.</L>
<L>&THORN;e prince wakind &amp; was euil flayd.</L>
<L>And sune &thorn;e ladi vnto him said:</L>
<L N="235">"Sir, saw &yogh;e noght &thorn;is selkuth sight</L>
<L>&THORN;at me has noyed in &thorn;is night?"</L>
<L>"&YOGH;is, sertes, he sais, I saw it wele;</L>
<L>&THORN;arfore ful grete ferdnes I fele.</L>
<L>So selkuth sight haue I noght sene &mdash;</L>
<L N="240">I meruail what it may bymene."</L>
<L>Scho said: "sir, &thorn;us has me bitid</L>
<L>Two nightes, and &thorn;is es &thorn;e thrid.
<PB REF="00000222.tif" N="84"></L>
<L>&YOGH;one woman &thorn;at ligges in &thorn;e way</L>
<L>And kens &thorn;e folk of Cristes lay,</L>
<L N="245">Vnto vs both scho has declarde</L>
<L>&THORN;at we to hir suld tak rewarde</L>
<L>And (mend) hir men&yogh;e fro mischefe,<NOTE PLACE="foot">mend fehlt im Ms.</NOTE></L>
<L>Or els it will turn vs to grefe.</L>
<L>And better es, we to hir bowe</L>
<L N="250">And to hir teching &thorn;at we trowe,</L>
<L>&THORN;an ger hir god be with us wrath;</L>
<L>For &thorn;an we mai noght skape fro skath."</L>
<L>&THORN;e prince said: "so sall be done"</L>
<L>And on &thorn;e morn he hasted sone</L>
<L N="255">To pray Mari and hir men&yogh;e</L>
<L>At his hous herberd forto be.</L>
<L>And at his will with him &thorn;ai &yogh;ede.</L>
<L>Ful faire he ordand &thorn;am to fede</L>
<L>With al dayntes &thorn;at he might gete.</L>
<L N="260">And euyn als &thorn;ai sat at &thorn;e mete,</L>
<L>Mari was carpand euer of Crist</L>
<L>And diuers maters scho poplist:</L>
<L>"None o&thorn;er lord es to a-low,</L>
<L>Ne o&thorn;er trowth es none to trow",</L>
<L N="265">And o&thorn;er goddes withouten him</L>
<L>Demyd scho al for deuils dym.</L>
<L>&THORN;e prince hir sufferd in hir saw,</L>
<L>Noght all for lufe, bot als for aw.</L>
<L>Fel on a day: so als scho prechid</L>
<L N="270">And Cristes trouth vnto &thorn;am techid,</L>
<L>&THORN;e prince lete &thorn;an als he wold lere,</L>
<L>And askid Mari on &thorn;is manere:</L>
<L>"Troues &thorn;ou, he sais, &thorn;ou may defend</L>
<L>&THORN;is cristen trouth &thorn;at &thorn;ou has kend,</L>
<L N="275">And mayntene it in al manere?"</L>
<L>&THORN;an answerd scho with stabil chere:</L>
<L>"I am redi with hert and hend</L>
<L>&THORN;e faith of Crist forto defend.</L>
<L>My mayster, Peter, &thorn;e pape of Rome,</L>
<L N="280">Has biden me do efter his dome;</L>
<L>He wil wele mayntene al mi dede.</L>
<L>And &thorn;arfore, sir, it es no nede</L>
<L>So straitly of me to enquere</L>
<L>To defend &thorn;e law &thorn;at I &yogh;ow lere.</L>
<L N="285">I haue herting of heuynli mede,</L>
<L>&THORN;at no doute haue I in mi dede."</L>
<L>&THORN;an &thorn;is prince and his gude lady</L>
<L>On &thorn;is manere said to Mary:</L>
<L>"If al be trew &thorn;at &thorn;ou here techis,</L>
<L N="290">And &thorn;i god of wham &thorn;ou prechis</L>
<L>War of swilk might &amp; swilk powere</L>
<L>Als &thorn;ou has told vnto vs here;</L>
<L>And &thorn;an &thorn;at &thorn;ou wold of him craue</L>
<L>And help &thorn;at we a child might haue:</L>
<L N="295">&THORN;an wold we to &thorn;i sawes assent</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e turn al our entent."</L>
<L>Mari was of &thorn;ir wurdes fayne</L>
<L>And &thorn;us scho said to &thorn;am ogayne:</L>
<L>"Mi god mai do what so him list&mdash;</L>
<L N="300">&THORN;ar may no might in him be mist.</L>
<L>Vnto him sall I pray for &yogh;ow;</L>
<L>And if &yogh;e trewly in him trow,</L>
<L>&THORN;an dar I hete &thorn;at &yogh;e sal haue</L>
<L>A child, or els what &yogh;e wil craue,</L>
<L N="305">&THORN;at may seme vnto &yogh;oure saul hele."</L>
<L>&THORN;an leuyd &thorn;ai wele &thorn;at scho was lele.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai welkumd hire &thorn;an, als was wurthi,</L>
<L>Both hir and al hir cumpani;</L>
<L>Ful haly folk &thorn;e prince &thorn;am held,</L>
<L N="310">And in grete daynte &thorn;ore &thorn;ai dweld.</L>
<L>&THORN;an Mari, als scho first had sayd,</L>
<L>Vnto god for &thorn;e gude lady praid;</L>
<L>So did Martha and Maximyne</L>
<L>And al hir folk with hertes fine,</L>
<L N="315">Of hir bone to be hir bylde.</L>
<L>And als god wold, scho wex with childe</L>
<L>And grete scho was by way of kinde.</L>
<L>&THORN;an had &thorn;e prince grete mirth in mynde.</L>
<L>And purpos plainly taken he has</L>
<L N="320">&THORN;at he wold vnto saint Peter pas</L>
<L>And of hym al haly wit he wold</L>
<L>If tales war trew &thorn;at Mari tolde,</L>
<L>And do he wold efter his dome:</L>
<L>Sen he was heuid of cristendome.</L>
<L N="325">Bot when &thorn;e lady &thorn;us herd tell</L>
<L>&THORN;at hir lord wald no langer dwell</L>
<L>Bot wend he wold sune ouer &thorn;e se,</L>
<L>Scho said: "lord, I wil wend with &thorn;e;</L>
<L>For no-mans speking wil I spare,</L>
<L N="330">Bot als &thorn;ou fars, lord, lat me fare!"</L>
<L>&THORN;an said &thorn;e prince to hir ogayne:</L>
<L>"Wife, &thorn;ir wurdes er al in vayne.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou mai noght wend so wele als I;</L>
<L>I sall &thorn;e say encheson why:</L>
<L N="335">&THORN;ou wote how &thorn;ou es grete with childe,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e se es wude and wilde
<PB REF="00000223.tif" N="85"></L>
<L>With moni stormes &amp; mekill wathe,</L>
<L>&THORN;at vnto &thorn;e might sune do scathe;</L>
<L>I wold noght for no werldes gude</L>
<L N="340">&THORN;at &thorn;ou fore euyl opon &thorn;e flude.</L>
<L>And &thorn;arfore, gude wife, wun at home</L>
<L>And kepe our catell vnto my come &mdash;</L>
<L>So es wele better, &thorn;an forto be</L>
<L>In grete perils opon &thorn;e see."</L>
<L N="345">&THORN;an fel scho doune vnto his fete</L>
<L>And sore bigan scho forto grete &mdash;</L>
<L>Als wemen wil noght sone forsake</L>
<L>&THORN;aire purpos &thorn;at &thorn;ai to wil take &mdash;</L>
<L>Sho cried loud: "lord, god forbede</L>
<L N="350">&THORN;at I allone here life suld lede</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou wend vnto vnkuth land!</L>
<L>&THORN;at was to my hert hard tithand.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. was st. war.</NOTE></L>
<L>I wil noght let for fa ne frende</L>
<L>Bot whore &thorn;ou wendes will I wende,</L>
<L N="355">And when &thorn;ou restes rest sall I,</L>
<L>And when &thorn;ou rises I am redy;</L>
<L>With &thorn;e, lord, will I lif and lend</L>
<L>And tak what grace so god wil send."</L>
<L>&THORN;e gude man saw it was no bute</L>
<L N="360">Ogayns hir wil more forto mote;</L>
<L>He graunted hir with him to gang.</L>
<L>And ordand &thorn;am a schip ful strang</L>
<L>And vitaild it with alkins thing</L>
<L>&THORN;at nedeful was to &thorn;aire lifing.</L>
<L N="365">To Mari Maudlayne he bitaght</L>
<L>Al &thorn;at he weldid of werldly aght;</L>
<L>His eritage and all o&thorn;er thing</L>
<L>Putted he vnto hir kepeing.</L>
<L>It was hir will so &thorn;at &thorn;ai two</L>
<L N="370">Suld to hir maister saint Peter go.</L>
<L>Crosses on &thorn;aire shulders gan scho schere,</L>
<L>For &thorn;at &thorn;e deuils suld &thorn;am noght dere;</L>
<L>Sho blisced &thorn;am with gude entent,</L>
<L>And so vnto &thorn;aire ship &thorn;ai went.</L>
<L N="375">Ful mekil mirth &thorn;an made &thorn;ai two.</L>
<L>Bot efterward wakkind &thorn;aire wo.</L>
<L>When &thorn;ai war sayled so out of sight</L>
<L>&THORN;e space of a day and a night,</L>
<L>&THORN;e wind bigan rudely to rise</L>
<L N="380">And &thorn;e see to bolne on wunder wise;</L>
<L>Grete stormes wex with weders wik</L>
<L>And &thorn;e wawes went wunder thik.</L>
<L>Al war &thorn;ai in grete drede to droune,<MILESTONE N="159" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>For ferd &thorn;e lady &thorn;an fell in swoune;</L>
<L N="385">Ilkone &thorn;ai war ful will of rede,</L>
<L>Bot scho was moste like to be ded.</L>
<L>So was scho stond with weders wilde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at sone trauaild scho of childe;</L>
<L>Scho sesid noght, fro (s)cho had bygun,</L>
<L N="390">Till scho was deliuerd of a sun.</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;an for reuth might hertes riue:</L>
<L>Scho lay ded, and &thorn;e childe o-liue.</L>
<L>&THORN;at was a siteful syght to se</L>
<L>And to all gude men grete pete.</L>
<L N="395">Bot &thorn;e prince, als no wunder was,</L>
<L>Cryed ful loud allas, allas;</L>
<L>"A, wife, he said, ful wo es me</L>
<L>&THORN;at I &thorn;is sight suld on &thorn;e se!"</L>
<L>&THORN;e childe soght by cours of kinde</L>
<L N="400">Efter &thorn;e fude, &thorn;e pap to finde,</L>
<L>Sethin it swelid and turned &amp; tauyd &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;e fader fel and for reuth raued.</L>
<L>And al-if he had sorows ful sore,</L>
<L>&THORN;e schipmen made his murnyng more</L>
<L N="405">When &thorn;ai al samyn said &thorn;is wurd:</L>
<L>"&THORN;is ded body bus ouer &thorn;e burd,</L>
<L>For are will noght &thorn;is weder sese" &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;e knightes care &thorn;us &thorn;ai encrese.</L>
<L>His care was mikill for his wife,</L>
<L N="410">And more for his sun &thorn;at had life,</L>
<L>&THORN;e whilk he wist bud nedes dy,</L>
<L>For it had noght left to lif by.</L>
<L>To him &thorn;at was a bitter brayd</L>
<L>And to him-self al &thorn;us he sayd:</L>
<L N="415">"Allas, cayteff, &thorn;ou ert bigilde;</L>
<L>Whi couayt &thorn;ou to haue a childe,</L>
<L>Forto haue liking in &thorn;i life?</L>
<L>Now has &thorn;ou lorn both child &amp; wife.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou &yogh;ernid one, and loses two.</L>
<L N="420">Allas for dole, whi did &thorn;ou so?"</L>
<L>&THORN;e schipmen fast bigan to cry:</L>
<L>"cast ouer &thorn;e burd &thorn;is dede body,</L>
<L>Els wil &thorn;is storm noght sese!" &thorn;ai said.</L>
<L>&THORN;e knight &thorn;an knelid &amp; to &thorn;am prayd</L>
<L N="425">&THORN;at &thorn;ai wold bide a litell space,</L>
<L>To luke if god wold send his grace
<PB REF="00000224.tif" N="86"></L>
<L>&THORN;e lady vnto life forto restore.</L>
<L>And als &thorn;ai war so wepeand sore,</L>
<L>Fer in &thorn;e se &thorn;ai saw a playne.</L>
<L N="430">&THORN;an was &thorn;e knight ful ferly fayn.</L>
<L>Sune when &thorn;ai (se) &thorn;e soyle was sad(!),<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. &thorn;e seyle (oder soyle) st. se &thorn;e yle? oder es fehlt se od. saw.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e weders sesid, and &thorn;ai war glad.</L>
<L>&THORN;e knight &thorn;an prayd &amp; hight &thorn;am mede</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;at land him forto lede,</L>
<L N="435">&THORN;at &thorn;o bodis might beried be,</L>
<L>Leuer &thorn;an sunken in &thorn;e se.</L>
<L>And als &thorn;e knight praid &amp; cumand,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai set &thorn;aire schip nere to &thorn;e land.</L>
<L>Into a bote &thorn;an both &thorn;ai kepid</L>
<L N="440">&THORN;e bodi and &thorn;e child &thorn;at wepid &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;arof &thorn;ai kouth no better rede;</L>
<L>For faut of fude it bihoued be dede.</L>
<L>&THORN;ore fand &thorn;ai roches hard of stone;</L>
<L>And toles to wirk with had &thorn;ai none,</L>
<L N="445">So &thorn;at &thorn;ai might mak no graue.</L>
<L>Bot vnder a crag &thorn;ai fand a kaue:</L>
<L>&THORN;e knight &thorn;ore laid his mantil doune</L>
<L>And &thorn;e ded body &thorn;ar oboune,</L>
<L>He put &thorn;e child vnto &thorn;e pap,</L>
<L N="450">And ouer &thorn;am laid his mantil lap;</L>
<L>Ful sore he wepid and wrong his hend</L>
<L>And vnto god &thorn;am both bikend.</L>
<L>And als he went sore wepand &thorn;ein,</L>
<L>On Mari Maudlayn gun he him pleyn:</L>
<L N="455">"A, Mari, he said, what moued &thorn;e</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou suld cum to my cuntre</L>
<L>With &thorn;i wordes so me to plese,</L>
<L>And sethin be caus of mi dissese?</L>
<L>If it had noght &thorn;i counsail bene,</L>
<L N="460">&THORN;is grete sorow had neuer (be) sene.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Im Ms. fehlt be?</NOTE></L>
<L>Whi wold &thorn;ou prai so for mi wife</L>
<L>To haue a childe and lose hir life?</L>
<L>Allas, &thorn;at euer &thorn;ou met with me!</L>
<L>For all my los es lang on &thorn;e.</L>
<L N="465">I was bousom, what &thorn;ou wald bid,</L>
<L>And grete kindnes to &thorn;e I kid</L>
<L>When I &thorn;e left bothe land and rent</L>
<L>And for &thorn;i wurdes &thorn;ir wais I went.</L>
<L>And sen I was to &thorn;e so kinde,</L>
<L N="470">In &thorn;is meschefe of me haue mynde;</L>
<L>And if &thorn;i god be of swilk might</L>
<L>Als &thorn;ou has techid day and night,</L>
<L>Ordayns now so yow bitwene</L>
<L>&THORN;at his might may on me be sene,</L>
<L N="475">And send me cumfort of my care!"</L>
<L>To schip ogayn &thorn;an gun he fare.</L>
<L>&THORN;e weders fand &thorn;ai gude and gayne,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at &thorn;ai raue up in Romayne.</L>
<L>&THORN;e knight sone, when he landid was,</L>
<L N="480">Soght vnto &thorn;e papes palas.</L>
<L>And sone, when he come him byforn</L>
<L>And &thorn;e pape saw his schulder schorn</L>
<L>With &thorn;e takinyng of &thorn;e croyce,</L>
<L>&THORN;an askid he him with opyn voyce</L>
<L N="485">In what cuntre he was at home,</L>
<L>And &THORN;e caus whi he &thorn;eder come.</L>
<L>&THORN;an said &thorn;e knight with sighin sore<NOTE PLACE="foot">sighin st. sighing.</NOTE></L>
<L>Al on what wise he ferd byfore:</L>
<L>How he was in his awin cuntre</L>
<L N="490">A prince &thorn;at gouernd grete pouste,</L>
<L>And how &thorn;e Maudelayne with him dweld</L>
<L>And all his gudes in hir handes held,</L>
<L>And how he had thurgh hir counsayl</L>
<L>Takyn hym vnto swilk trauayl:</L>
<L N="495">"And, sir, he said, scho told to me</L>
<L>&THORN;at hir god was of swilk pouste,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he might all men wele releue:</L>
<L>And all es turned me to mischeue."</L>
<L>And &thorn;an he tolde of his dede wyue,</L>
<L N="500">And how he left his sun o-lyue</L>
<L>Ligand in &thorn;e krag of stone &mdash;</L>
<L>"Was neuer man so wil of wone!</L>
<L>Al my liking I leuyd &thorn;ore" &mdash;</L>
<L>And with &thorn;o wurdes he wepid sore.</L>
<L N="505">Saint Peter, when he &thorn;ir wurdes herd,</L>
<L>Ful hendly to him he answerd,</L>
<L>He said: "dere brother, drede &thorn;e noght!</L>
<L>Efter wise counsail has &thorn;ou wroght.</L>
<L>Lat stabyll faith in &thorn;e be fest,</L>
<L N="510">And all sal turn &thorn;e to &thorn;i best.</L>
<L>And wit &thorn;ou wele, goddes might es more</L>
<L>&THORN;an to leche &thorn;i wife &thorn;at ligges &thorn;ore</L>
<L>And when him list rais hir fro slepe,</L>
<L>And &thorn;i &yogh;ong sun sauely to kepe;</L>
<L N="515">Oure god may gif life als him list,</L>
<L>For in him may no might be mist,
<PB REF="00000225.tif" N="87"></L>
<L>Of al sorous mai he socure send,</L>
<L>And al &thorn;at es mis may he mend.</L>
<L>&THORN;arfore in trouth luke &thorn;ou be trew,</L>
<L N="520">And al &thorn;i solace sall be new."</L>
<L>&THORN;e knight said: "sir, &thorn;at wold I fain."<NOTE PLACE="foot">king in knight corr.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;an saynt Peter said ogayne:</L>
<L>"Sir, bi &thorn;i cros &thorn;e Maudlayn mened</L>
<L>To Jerusalem &thorn;at &thorn;ou suld wende:</L>
<L N="525">And &thorn;arfore &thorn;eder mak &thorn;e boun</L>
<L>In mynde of Cristes passioun</L>
<L>And do honure in ilka stede</L>
<L>Whore he sufferd bifore his ded!</L>
<L>I sall wend with &thorn;e pase ful playne,</L>
<L N="530">To-tyme &thorn;at &thorn;ou cum heder ogayne:</L>
<L>&THORN;arfore of no thing haue &thorn;ou drede!"</L>
<L>On &thorn;is maner &thorn;e knight furth &yogh;ede</L>
<L>To Jerusalem. And when he come &thorn;ore,</L>
<L>He fand saynt Peter him bifore,</L>
<L N="535">&THORN;at to ilk place playnli him techid</L>
<L>Whore Crist vnto his pople prechid;</L>
<L>And sethin vnto sere place &thorn;ai went</L>
<L>Whore Crist had sufferd sere turment,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e mount, &amp; to many o&thorn;er stede,</L>
<L N="540">Whore he apperd efter his ded,</L>
<L>And sethin whore he to heuin ascend,</L>
<L>And whore he sal cum to mak end.</L>
<L>And when he had &thorn;ir werkis wroght,</L>
<L>To Rome ogayn sadly he soght.</L>
<L N="545">Saint Peter &thorn;ore redy he fand</L>
<L>And tolde to him al &thorn;is tithand,</L>
<L>How he had soght &thorn;ir places sere.</L>
<L>And in &thorn;is space war spend two &yogh;ere.</L>
<L>&THORN;an said &thorn;e knight: he wold ful fayn</L>
<L N="550">With &thorn;e popes will wend home ogayn.</L>
<L>Saint Peter &thorn;e trouth vnto him tolde</L>
<L>And bad him wend, when so he wold.</L>
<L>A schip &thorn;an ordand he gude spede</L>
<L>With al thing &thorn;at &thorn;ai of had nede.</L>
<L N="555">And when &thorn;ai war al redy boun,</L>
<L>&THORN;an toke he &thorn;e popes benysoun.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai went &amp; wold no langer dwell.</L>
<L>And als god wolld, so it bifell:</L>
<L>By &thorn;at ilk ile &thorn;aire way was graid</L>
<L N="560">Whore &thorn;e knight had his ladi layd.</L>
<L>&THORN;e knight &thorn;arto toke ful gude hede</L>
<L>And praid &thorn;e schipmen for &thorn;aire mede</L>
<L>To set &thorn;aire bote vnto &thorn;at hill;</L>
<L>And hastily &thorn;ai wroght his will.</L>
<L N="565">And als &thorn;e knight luked to &thorn;e land,</L>
<L>He saw a childe sit on &thorn;e sand</L>
<L>Nakid &amp; nemely for &thorn;e nones</L>
<L>Playand it with precius stones.</L>
<L>And when it saw &thorn;e schip cum &thorn;ore</L>
<L N="570">And had noght sene swilk sight bifore,</L>
<L>For ferd it crepid ful fast oway</L>
<L>To &thorn;e mount whore &thorn;e moder lay;</L>
<L>It lurked vnder &thorn;e mantill lapp</L>
<L>And lay and plaid it with &thorn;e pap.</L>
<L N="575">&THORN;e knight it saw and thoght ferly,<MILESTONE N="160" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And efter it fast he gun him hy.</L>
<L>His wife lay &thorn;ore als he hir leuyd.</L>
<L>&THORN;e childe up in his hand he heuyd,</L>
<L>He cherist it with lufly chere,</L>
<L N="580">And &thorn;an he said on &thorn;is manere:</L>
<L>"Blist be &thorn;ou, Maudelayn, euermare!</L>
<L>I loue &thorn;e, lady, and &thorn;i lare,</L>
<L>&THORN;at thurgh &thorn;i might on &thorn;is manere</L>
<L>Has saued &thorn;is childe al &thorn;ies two &yogh;ere.</L>
<L N="585">Dere lady, haue mercy on me,</L>
<L>For maystri es it none to &thorn;e</L>
<L>To saue my wife, wele if &thorn;ou will!</L>
<L>For saint Peter said me vntill</L>
<L>God might warisch mi wife &thorn;at slepid".</L>
<L N="590">And als he spak &thorn;ir wurdes &amp; wepid,</L>
<L>&THORN;e lady wakkind &amp; with him spak &mdash;</L>
<L>Ful mekil Joy &thorn;an gun he mak.</L>
<L>Sho rase yp right als scho was laid,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ir wurdes als sone scho sayd:</L>
<L N="595">"I loue &thorn;e, Maudelayn, in my minde:</L>
<L>Mekill es &thorn;i might omang man-kinde.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou was my gide in mi moste grefe</L>
<L>And midwif in moste mischefe;</L>
<L>Mi sun &thorn;us has &thorn;ou saued here,</L>
<L N="600">And went with me al &thorn;ir two &yogh;ere".</L>
<L>&THORN;an had &thorn;e knight liking in life</L>
<L>And loud he sayd: "lifs &thorn;ou, mi wife?</L>
<L>Sum wurd of gladnes to me gif!"</L>
<L>"Syr, scho sayd, for suthe I lyf.</L>
<L N="605">Fro pilgrimage now com I hame:</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou has done, I did &thorn;at same.
<PB REF="00000226.tif" N="88"></L>
<L>Mi mayster Peter with &thorn;e went</L>
<L>And tolde &thorn;e to Cristes monument<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. tolde st. toke?</NOTE></L>
<L>And to &thorn;e mount &amp; moni a stede</L>
<L N="610">Whore Crist was sene &amp; sufferd ded;</L>
<L>And right als Peter went with &thorn;e,</L>
<L>So Mari Maudelayn was with me;</L>
<L>Scho led me into ilka place,</L>
<L>Both fer and nere, folowand &yogh;oure trace.</L>
<L N="615">And to proue &thorn;is suth &thorn;at I say:</L>
<L>I wote wele how &yogh;e wroght alway".</L>
<L>On raw scho rekind les and more</L>
<L>And said: &thorn;us did &yogh;e &thorn;ore and &thorn;ore;</L>
<L>So al &thorn;e gates &thorn;at he had gone</L>
<L N="620">Scho tolde fully, and faylid of none.</L>
<L>&THORN;an was &thorn;e knight ful glad &amp; blith</L>
<L>And thankid &thorn;e Maudelain monysith.</L>
<L>He toke his wife and &yogh;ong boy</L>
<L>And went to schip with mekill Joy &mdash;</L>
<L N="625">&THORN;arfro he went with mekil payn</L>
<L>And with grete mirth he come ogayn.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai sayled furth and sune &thorn;ai come</L>
<L>To Marcyll, whore &thorn;ai wer at home.</L>
<L>And in &thorn;at cete sone &thorn;ai fand</L>
<L N="630">&THORN;e Maudelayn and hir men precheand:</L>
<L>Fast fell &thorn;ai doun bifor hir fete</L>
<L>And for gladnes ilkone &thorn;ai grete.</L>
<L>And sethin &thorn;ai tolde with trew entent</L>
<L>How &thorn;ai had wroght ay sen &thorn;ai went,</L>
<L N="635">How &thorn;ai had sorous fell to fele</L>
<L>And sethin how &thorn;ai war cumfort wele.</L>
<L>&THORN;an war &thorn;ai fayn ilkone in-fere</L>
<L>And thankid god with ful gude chere.</L>
<L>And &thorn;us was &thorn;is prince and his wife</L>
<L N="640">Trewly turned to cristen life;</L>
<L>Saynt Maximine &thorn;am both baptist</L>
<L>And confermid &thorn;am in law of Crist;</L>
<L>&THORN;aire &yogh;ong sun also baptist he</L>
<L>And kend him cristen man to be.</L>
<L N="645">In Cristes faith when &thorn;ai war fest,</L>
<L>Al &thorn;aire maumettes doun &thorn;ai kest,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai brak &thorn;am doun &amp; did &thorn;am schame,</L>
<L>And bigged kirkes in Cristes name.</L>
<L>And La&yogh;ar ordand &thorn;ai to be</L>
<L N="650">Bisschop in &thorn;at same cete,</L>
<L>With prestes and clerkes on sides sere,</L>
<L>To serue to god on gude manere.</L>
<L>So al &thorn;e puple turned &thorn;ai</L>
<L>And conuert &thorn;am to Cristes lay.</L>
<L N="655">And sethin, als god turned &thorn;aire entent,</L>
<L>Vnto a no&thorn;er cete &thorn;ai went</L>
<L>And turned &thorn;e folk to cristen lare,</L>
<L>And Maxymiyne made &thorn;ai bisschop &thorn;are;</L>
<L>And thurgh him was grete vertu schewd</L>
<L N="660">Off Cristes law to lerd and lewd.</L>
<L>&THORN;e prince &amp; his sun and his wife</L>
<L>With ioy and liking led &thorn;are lyfe,</L>
<L>In Cristes law ay gun &thorn;ai lend</L>
<L>And to him went &thorn;ai at &thorn;aire end.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="section">
<HEAD>De vita beate Marie Magd. in heremo viuente.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="665">Mari &thorn;an gun purpose take</L>
<L>All werldly sight forto forsake.</L>
<L>Scho toke hir leue at more and les</L>
<L>And went allone to wildernes.</L>
<L>Scho fand &thorn;are logeing, in to lend,</L>
<L N="670">&THORN;at was ordand with angels hend;</L>
<L>And in &thorn;at loge scho lengid allone,</L>
<L>To thritty winters wer all gone.</L>
<L>In al &thorn;at tyme scho was vnknawn,</L>
<L>And scho knew no life bot hir awin;</L>
<L N="675">In al &thorn;at sesoun none hir soght</L>
<L>Ne nonekins beld vnto (hir) broght.</L>
<L>Of fruit &thorn;ore had scho no confort,</L>
<L>Ne of herbis had scho no disport,</L>
<L>Ne water was &thorn;ore none hir nere.</L>
<L N="680">Wharfore men might haue knawing clere</L>
<L>&THORN;at scho was fed with angels fode</L>
<L>Of god, and of none erthely gude.</L>
<L>Euer-ilkaday by oures seuyn</L>
<L>War angels sent to hir fro heuyn;</L>
<L N="685">&THORN;ai raysed hir vp into &thorn;e ayre</L>
<L>And fed hir &thorn;ore with fude ful faire;</L>
<L>Ful mekil m(i)rth and solempne sang</L>
<L>Might scho here made &thorn;am omang.</L>
<L>More fully was scho so refete</L>
<L N="690">&THORN;an with any erthly drink or mete.</L>
<L>And when &thorn;e angels &thorn;us had done,</L>
<L>In hir fell &thorn;ai fet hir sone.</L>
<L>Ful thritty &yogh;ere scho &thorn;ore habid.
<PB REF="00000227.tif" N="89"></L>
<L>And on a tyme &thorn;an &thorn;us bityd:</L>
<L N="695">Ane haly preste had purpose tone</L>
<L>&THORN;at he in wildernes wald lif allone;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. wilde mit &uuml;berschr. rnes. Ms. alkone.</NOTE></L>
<L>To &thorn;at wildernes gun he pas<NOTE PLACE="foot">gun fehlt?</NOTE></L>
<L>Whore Mary Maudlain wunand was.</L>
<L>And &thorn;ore he logid him als him list;</L>
<L N="700">Bot of hir wunyng noght he wist,</L>
<L>For no man might cum to hir place</L>
<L>Ne se it, bot god gaf &thorn;am grace.</L>
<L>And opon a day so it byfell,</L>
<L>Als &thorn;is ilk preste sat in his sell,</L>
<L N="705">God gaf hym grace to here and se</L>
<L>Sum poyntes of his owin preuete:</L>
<L>He herd a noys and nobil steuyn</L>
<L>Of angels &thorn;at war sent fro heuyn.</L>
<L>&THORN;an prayd he god with gude entent</L>
<L N="710">&THORN;at he might wit more what it ment.</L>
<L>Toward &thorn;at stede he went in hy</L>
<L>Whore he herd made &thorn;at melody.</L>
<L>And als he lukid ogayn &thorn;e light,</L>
<L>Ful sone he saw a solempne sight:</L>
<L N="715">Of angels &thorn;at fro heuyn descend;</L>
<L>And on &thorn;at loge he saw &thorn;am lend,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai toke vp Mary &thorn;am al omang<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. onang.</NOTE></L>
<L>With mynstralsy and meri sang</L>
<L>Into &thorn;e ayre, and &thorn;ore &thorn;ai last</L>
<L N="720">Vntil ane oure was fully past,</L>
<L>And sethin he saw al hou &thorn;ai come</L>
<L>With mekill blis &amp; broght hir home,</L>
<L>In hir loge, &thorn;an &thorn;ai hir left.</L>
<L>And sethen he saw &thorn;am fetche hir eft</L>
<L N="725">And serue hir on &thorn;e same manere.</L>
<L>&THORN;is had he grete liking to lere.</L>
<L>Ner to &thorn;at place &thorn;e prest him flit,</L>
<L>More of &thorn;at werk for he wold wit;</L>
<L>He praid to god with gude entent</L>
<L N="730">More forto wit, and ner he went.</L>
<L>And when he had &thorn;e gate all gone</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;e space of casting of a stone,</L>
<L>His lims bigan fayntly to fail,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at he might no ferr trauail;</L>
<L N="735">And his hert was so affrayd,</L>
<L>&THORN;at home to gang he him puruayd.</L>
<L>And als sone als he turned ogayn,</L>
<L>His lims &thorn;an had &thorn;are power playn.</L>
<L>And eft he turned toward &thorn;at stede:</L>
<L N="740">&THORN;an wex &thorn;ai waik als &thorn;ai war ded.</L>
<L>&THORN;is made him meruayld in his mode;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. meruayd mit &uuml;bergeschr. l.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bot &thorn;arby wele he vnderstode</L>
<L>&THORN;at all &thorn;is sight was of godsande:</L>
<L>&THORN;arfore he durst no ferrer fande;</L>
<L N="745">Ful wele he hopid &thorn;at mans might</L>
<L>Suld cum no ner to se &thorn;at sight.</L>
<L>And fayn he wold &thorn;at place haue spied,</L>
<L>&THORN;arfore o ferrom fast he cried:</L>
<L>"On goddes byhalue I coniore &thorn;e,</L>
<L N="750">Man or beste, whe&thorn;ir so &thorn;ou be,</L>
<L>Or any creature of resoun els,</L>
<L>&THORN;at in &thorn;at loge lendis &amp; dwels:</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou speke with me, &amp; &thorn;ou may,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e suth of &thorn;i self me say</L>
<L N="755">&THORN;at schews &thorn;ir wunders on &thorn;is wise!"</L>
<L>And when he had rehercid &thorn;is thrise:</L>
<L>Mary him answerd on &thorn;is manere:</L>
<L>"Cum nerr! scho said, and &thorn;ou sall here.</L>
<L>Al &thorn;at &thorn;i hert &yogh;ernis, sal &thorn;ou haue</L>
<L N="760">And knaw what &thorn;ou will efter craue".</L>
<L>Grete light he saw bifore hym ferr,</L>
<L>And, als he durst, &thorn;an drogh he nerr.</L>
<L>And when he had went half &thorn;e way,</L>
<L>He herd a woman &thorn;us speke and say:</L>
<L N="765">"Sir, scho said, ne menes &thorn;e noght<MILESTONE N="161" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Of a woman &thorn;at wikkedly wroght &mdash;</L>
<L>Mari Maudelayn sum name hir wald,</L>
<L>And Mari &thorn;e synner sum hir cald;</L>
<L>With sere men was scho serely namid,</L>
<L N="770">For of grete foly was scho defamid.</L>
<L>And sethin hir bitter bale to bete,</L>
<L>With hir teris wesch scho Cristes fete,</L>
<L>Hir sin scho scheud with sorow sare,</L>
<L>And so scho gat forgifnes &thorn;are.</L>
<L N="775">Haues &thorn;ou oght minde of &thorn;at woman?"</L>
<L>&THORN;e prest vnto hir answerd &thorn;an:</L>
<L>"&YOGH;a, sertes, he said, I knew hir wele</L>
<L>And of hir dedis I knew sum dele;</L>
<L>And haly kirk of hir mase minde</L>
<L N="780">For ensaumple omang man-kinde;</L>
<L>Euermore sal hir life be kend,
<PB REF="00000228.tif" N="90"></L>
<L>To gif men will &thorn;air mis to mend.</L>
<L>It es now thritty &yogh;ere and more</L>
<L>Sen scho was went, men wote noght whore;</L>
<L N="785">Sethin was scho noght sene in no stede,</L>
<L>&THORN;arfore men demes &thorn;at scho es dede".</L>
<L>&THORN;an said Mary: "I am &thorn;at same.</L>
<L>So lang I haue bene here at hame,</L>
<L>Gouerned wele thurgh goddes might,</L>
<L N="790">And fere out of all erthly sight,</L>
<L>With cumpany of angels clene:</L>
<L>Als &thorn;i-self sumdele has sene,</L>
<L>How &thorn;ai heue me vp in &thorn;e ayre<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. heue oder haue?</NOTE></L>
<L>And fedes me &thorn;ore with fode ful faire,</L>
<L N="795">With mirth &thorn;at no-man mesure mai.</L>
<L>So do &thorn;ai seuyn oures ilka day.</L>
<L>Now am I warned thurgh goddes will</L>
<L>&THORN;at cours of kinde I sal fulfill,</L>
<L>To wend out of &thorn;is werldly life</L>
<L N="800">And wun in welth with-outen strife.</L>
<L>&THORN;arfore mine erand sal &thorn;ou wende</L>
<L>Vnto saynt Maximyne, mi frende,</L>
<L>&THORN;at es bisschop of Aquens cete,</L>
<L>And say him &thorn;is message fro me:</L>
<L N="805">All of &thorn;e sight &thorn;at &thorn;ou has sene,</L>
<L>And tel him &thorn;us &yogh;ow two bitwene:</L>
<L>On pase-day next for any thing,</L>
<L>When men redes of Cristes rising,</L>
<L>When he has sayd solempne seruise</L>
<L N="810">Bid hym wirk &thorn;an on &thorn;is wise:</L>
<L>Wend him-allone, or it be day,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e place whore he vses to pray,</L>
<L>And sai him &thorn;at, when he cums &thorn;ore,</L>
<L>He sall find me &thorn;an him bifore:</L>
<L N="815">&THORN;an sal I tell him mine entent.</L>
<L>Go, say him &thorn;us how I &thorn;e sent!"</L>
<L>&THORN;e prest had ferly of all &thorn;is fare;</L>
<L>Him thoght als it ane angel ware</L>
<L>&THORN;at spak to him on &thorn;is manere:</L>
<L N="820">So was &thorn;e voice heuynly and clere.</L>
<L>Bot on &thorn;o wurdes ful wele he thoght</L>
<L>And to cete sone he soght</L>
<L>Whore Maximyne was bischop in.</L>
<L>And sone, when he might to him wyn,</L>
<L N="825">He haylsid him with wurdes hende</L>
<L>And sone he tolde him tale till ende<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. him st. his?</NOTE></L>
<L>How he had with Maudlayn met</L>
<L>And how scho him so gudely grett,</L>
<L>And furth he tolde &thorn;am two bitwene</L>
<L N="830">Of &thorn;e sightes &thorn;at he had sene.</L>
<L>When Maximyne had herd &thorn;is tale,</L>
<L>Him thoght his hert was neuer so hale;</L>
<L>And so fayn was he of &thorn;at fare,</L>
<L>&THORN;at so grete Joy had he neuer are;</L>
<L N="835">He loued god with ful gude entent</L>
<L>&THORN;at swilk fande vnto him was sent.</L>
<L>For al men wend in ilka stede</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e Maudlayn had bene dede;</L>
<L>&THORN;arfore &thorn;e bisschop was ful glad</L>
<L N="840">&THORN;at he of hir swilk tythinges had.</L>
<L>&THORN;e preste &thorn;ore still with him he held</L>
<L>And to &thorn;at tyme graythly &thorn;ai teld.</L>
<L>And when it come to &thorn;at sesoun,</L>
<L>&THORN;e tyme of Cristes Resureccioun,</L>
<L N="845">Saint Maximyne with hert ful light</L>
<L>Was in his prayers al &thorn;at night,</L>
<L>And efter midnyght &thorn;ai puplist</L>
<L>&THORN;e resurreccioun of Jhesu Crist.</L>
<L>And when &thorn;at seruis was aldone,</L>
<L N="850">To his chapell he went allone.</L>
<L>And, als &thorn;e prest had told bifore,</L>
<L>&THORN;e Maudelayn fand he redi &thorn;ore,</L>
<L>With faire cumpani, als him thoght,</L>
<L>Of angels &thorn;at hir &thorn;eder broght,</L>
<L N="855">And euer him thoght scho stode &thorn;at stound</L>
<L>Two cubites heght vp fro &thorn;e grounde;</L>
<L>Hir hend scho held up to &thorn;e heuyn,</L>
<L>Prayand to god with stabil steuyn.</L>
<L>&THORN;e bisschop saw &thorn;is sight o ferr,</L>
<L N="860">And for drede durst he noght cum ner &mdash;</L>
<L>In hert he was sumdele affraid.</L>
<L>And sone &thorn;e Maudelayn to him sayd:</L>
<L>"Fader, cum ner and speke with me!</L>
<L>Whi suld &thorn;ou fro &thorn;i doghter fle?"</L>
<L N="865">&THORN;o wurdes ful mekil amend his chere</L>
<L>And, als he durst, he drogh hir nere.</L>
<L>Hir face to luke on was so light</L>
<L>And so schineand vnto his sight:</L>
<L>Hym thog(ht) he might luke langer space</L>
<L N="870">On &thorn;e suns beme &thorn;an on hir face.
<PB REF="00000229.tif" N="91"></L>
<L>"A, ladi, he sayd, ful wele es me</L>
<L>&THORN;at I &thorn;is semeli sight mai se!</L>
<L>I wend &thorn;ou had bene ded forlang,</L>
<L>Now wote I wele my wit was wrang.</L>
<L N="875">I loue &thorn;e, lady, loud and still,</L>
<L>And boun I am to wirk &thorn;i will".</L>
<L>Scho said: "my mayster Maximyne,</L>
<L>In faith luke &thorn;ou be fast and fyne</L>
<L>And trewly trow, I am &thorn;at same</L>
<L N="880">&THORN;at was cristend in Cristes name,</L>
<L>&THORN;at gat forgifnes thurgh his grace,</L>
<L>And wund with &thorn;e a sertan space;</L>
<L>And sen-tyme &thorn;at we two gun twin,</L>
<L>Wildernes I haue wund in</L>
<L N="885">More &thorn;an &thorn;e space of thretti &yogh;ere,</L>
<L>With cumpany of angels clere:</L>
<L>&THORN;ai haue me fed with angels fode</L>
<L>And susstaynd me with gastly gude.</L>
<L>Now am I warned &thorn;at I sall wende</L>
<L N="890">Vnto &thorn;e welth with-outen ende.</L>
<L>And for &thorn;at caus I cum to &thorn;e,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;i hand howsild forto be,</L>
<L>And my body in erth to bring &mdash;</L>
<L>I ask of &thorn;e none o&thorn;er thing".</L>
<L N="895">&THORN;e bisschop &thorn;an ful hastily</L>
<L>Gert call togeder al his clergy</L>
<L>With &thorn;e prest &thorn;at &thorn;e bodwurd broght.</L>
<L>And when &thorn;ai war al samyn soght,</L>
<L>He broght &thorn;e solempne sacrament,</L>
<L N="900">And scho toke it with gude entent.</L>
<L>And with ful mekil deuocioune</L>
<L>&THORN;an on &thorn;e ground scho laid hir doune</L>
<L>Lukeand to heuyn, and so in haste</L>
<L>Vnto god scho gaffe hir gaste.</L>
<L N="905">&THORN;e angels went with bemis light</L>
<L>Bereand it up to heuyn on hight.</L>
<L>In &thorn;at stede was ful nobil smell,</L>
<L>Swetter &thorn;an ani tung might tell,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at swettnes lasted always</L>
<L N="910">More &thorn;an &thorn;e space of seuyn days.</L>
<L>&THORN;e bisschop berid hir body,</L>
<L>With wirschip, als it was wurthi,</L>
<L>And ordand, when he suld be dede,</L>
<L>To beri him-self in &thorn;at same stede,</L>
<L N="915">&THORN;at &thorn;ai in ded might samyn lend</L>
<L>Als &thorn;ai in life war frendes kend.</L>
<L>Sethin at hir graue grete ferlis fell,</L>
<L>Als men may in sere storis tell. &mdash;</L>
<L>Of hir we suld ensaumple take,</L>
<L N="920">&THORN;at sinful er, sins to forsake</L>
<L>And with penance amend our mis</L>
<L>And kepe vs klene and cum to blis</L>
<L>And lend in life &thorn;at lastes ay &mdash;</L>
<L>God wis vs forto wend &thorn;at way!</L>
<L N="925">Sant Maximyne lifde efter still</L>
<L>An(d) sethin he died at goddes will.</L>
<L>His body was enterd right &thorn;ore</L>
<L>Als him-self had ordand bifore.</L>
<L>Bot efter &thorn;e dede of saynt Maximyne</L>
<L N="930">Was &thorn;at pople put vnto grete pine:</L>
<L>Payenis come to &thorn;at cuntre</L>
<L>And destroyd all &thorn;at same cete</L>
<L>Whore Mari Maudelayn lai in graue.</L>
<L>Bot sethin, als god vouched saue,</L>
<L N="935">Efter Cristes ascension fell it syne</L>
<L>Seuyn hundreth &yogh;ere fourty &amp; nyne,</L>
<L>In tyme of Charls, &thorn;e nobil king,</L>
<L>&THORN;an bifell &thorn;is ferly thing:</L>
<L>A duke in Burgoyne was dwelland,</L>
<L N="940">&THORN;at had lordschips in moni a land;</L>
<L>He had a lady meke and milde,</L>
<L>Bot bitwix &thorn;am &thorn;ai had no childe.</L>
<L>Oft prayd &thorn;ai god with hert &amp; hend</L>
<L>&THORN;at he a childe suld to &thorn;am send.</L>
<L N="945">To do almus &thorn;e duke was glad</L>
<L>Til &thorn;at he hopid mister had;</L>
<L>Mynsters made he mani one</L>
<L>And kirkes les(!) of lyme and stone.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. les st. als?</NOTE></L>
<L>Oft herd he tell bi proces playne</L>
<L N="950">Grete might of Mari Maudelayne;</L>
<L>&THORN;arfore to hir oft gun he pray,</L>
<L>And for hir made he ane abbay,</L>
<L>With monkes, forto rede and sing,</L>
<L>And ane abbot &thorn;are ouerling,</L>
<L N="955">To gouern &thorn;am in gude degre.</L>
<L>And on a night warned was he<MILESTONE N="162" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e Maudlayn graue suld be soght</L>
<L>And hir bones suld be &thorn;eder broght.</L>
<L>On &thorn;e morn he toke with gude entent</L>
<L N="960">&THORN;e counsail of &thorn;e hale couent.
<PB REF="00000230.tif" N="92"></L>
<L>And hastili &thorn;ai ordand &thorn;en</L>
<L>One of &thorn;aire monkes and o&thorn;er men</L>
<L>And bad &thorn;ai suld let for no spens</L>
<L>To seke to &thorn;e cete of Aquens:</L>
<L N="965">If &thorn;ai might find &thorn;e Maudlayn graue</L>
<L>And hir relikis &thorn;ore forto haue,</L>
<L>To bring &thorn;am home both more and les,</L>
<L>To be wirschiped, als wurthy es.</L>
<L>&THORN;an &thorn;is ilk monk and his men&yogh;e</L>
<L N="970">Soght vnto &thorn;at same cete.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai fand it wasted and all destroid</L>
<L>With payenis &thorn;at &thorn;e pople noyed.</L>
<L>Bot, als god &thorn;an wold it wore,</L>
<L>A toumb of marble fand &thorn;ai &thorn;ore</L>
<L N="975">And writen it with letters playne</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ore lay Mary Maudelayne.</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;ai durst noght touche it &thorn;at tyde</L>
<L>For hathen folk &thorn;at &thorn;am asspide.</L>
<L>Bot on &thorn;at night wele war &thorn;ai lerd:</L>
<L N="980">&THORN;e Maudelayn to &thorn;at monk aperd:</L>
<L>Scho bad him he suld haue no drede</L>
<L>Bot, als he thoght, do furth his dede;</L>
<L>Ful wele scho hight him forto were,</L>
<L>&THORN;at no-thing suld vnto &thorn;am dere.</L>
<L N="985">&THORN;an &thorn;is monk was wunder glad</L>
<L>&THORN;at he of hir so gude herting had.</L>
<L>And al &thorn;at o&thorn;er night &thorn;ai wuke</L>
<L>And al &thorn;o relikes vp &thorn;ai toke.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai closid &thorn;am in cases clene</L>
<L N="990">And furth &thorn;ai went, &amp; war noght sene.</L>
<L>And so fel, when &thorn;ai come &thorn;at while</L>
<L>Fro &thorn;aire Abbay bot half a mile:</L>
<L>&THORN;e relikis wold no ferrer flyt,</L>
<L>And whi it was &thorn;ai kouth noght wit.</L>
<L N="995">Sum left &thorn;ai &thorn;ore, &thorn;am forto tent,</L>
<L>And sum vnto &thorn;e abbay went;</L>
<L>&THORN;ai told &thorn;e abbot al &thorn;is tale.</L>
<L>And he ordand by counsail hale</L>
<L>To wend with fare processioune<NOTE PLACE="foot">fare-faire.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1000">And bring &thorn;o relikes so to toune.</L>
<L>When &thorn;ai on &thorn;is wise ordand ere,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai war &thorn;an ful light to bere.</L>
<L>To &thorn;e abbay war &thorn;o relikes broght,</L>
<L>And grete wirschip was to &thorn;am wroght.</L>
<L N="1005">And sethin war scheud in &thorn;at Abbay</L>
<L>Ful mony miracles ilka day,</L>
<L>Of seke men &thorn;at war sore bistad,</L>
<L>And al folk helid &thorn;at mister had.</L>
<L>And noght allone for &thorn;e life space,</L>
<L N="1010">Bot vnto ded men did scho grace</L>
<L>And gastly gert scho &thorn;am be hale,</L>
<L>Als men may se by ane schort tale.</L>
<L>In &thorn;at land &thorn;an lifd a knyght</L>
<L>&THORN;at lufd Maudlayn with al his might;</L>
<L N="1015">Euer-ilk &yogh;ere ones to hir he soght</L>
<L>And grete wirschip vnto hir wroght.</L>
<L>And sethin bifell him in a stede</L>
<L>Sudaynli forto be dede</L>
<L>With-outen schrift or howsell tane.</L>
<L N="1020">&THORN;arfore his frendes war will of wane.</L>
<L>His kinred and his frendes dere</L>
<L>Toke &thorn;e body vp on a bere,</L>
<L>Vnto biriell it forto bring.</L>
<L>And &thorn;us &thorn;ai said in &thorn;aire sorowing:</L>
<L N="1025">"A, Mari Maudlain, mekil of might,</L>
<L>Whi has &thorn;ou &thorn;us sufferd &thorn;i knight,</L>
<L>&THORN;at to &thorn;i seruis ai was swift,</L>
<L>To dy with-outen housil &amp; schrift?</L>
<L>&THORN;ou might wele, &amp; it war &thorn;i will,</L>
<L N="1030">Haue ordand better hap him till".</L>
<L>&THORN;an sudanly with-outen more</L>
<L>He, &thorn;at lay ded lang time bifore,</L>
<L>Turned to life omang &thorn;am all,</L>
<L>And bad &thorn;am a prest to him call.</L>
<L N="1035">He schraue him with gude entent</L>
<L>And sethin resayued his sacrament.</L>
<L>And when he had on &thorn;is wise done,</L>
<L>Doun he lay and died als sone.</L>
<L>His frendes &thorn;an war ferly fayne</L>
<L N="1040">And loued al Mari Maudelayne,</L>
<L>&THORN;at dose swilk socure in sere stede</L>
<L>Both vnto quik and vnto dede.</L>
<L>Now god, &thorn;at al &thorn;ir mightes mase</L>
<L>And vnto Maudlayn gaf swilk grace</L>
<L N="1045">In erth here to forsake hir syn</L>
<L>And sethin to endles welth to win,</L>
<L>Vnto his kingdom he vs ken,</L>
<L>Thurgh prayer of Maudlayn! Amen.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="18" TYPE="legend"><PB REF="00000231.tif" N="93">
<HEAD>18. De sca Cristina virgine et martire.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Gude maydins suld we mak in minde<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. mak st. haf?</NOTE></L>
<L>And of saint Cristine carp bi kinde,</L>
<L>How scho was cumen of gentil kin &mdash;</L>
<L>Bot fals godes al troud &thorn;ai in.</L>
<L N="5">Sho was ful fayre of hide and hew</L>
<L>And lufd of all men &thorn;at hir knew.</L>
<L>And for scho was so wynly wroght,</L>
<L>Ful mani vnto hir fader soght</L>
<L>And ful grete riches vnto him bed,</L>
<L N="10">His doghter to &thorn;aire wife to wed.</L>
<L>Bot hir fader for hir fairhede</L>
<L>Said, scho suld do none o&thorn;er. dede</L>
<L>Bot dwel ay in &thorn;air goddes seruise.</L>
<L>&THORN;arfore he ordand on &thorn;is wise:</L>
<L N="15">Cristine, his doghter, he did him-selue</L>
<L>In a toure, with maydins twelue.</L>
<L>He cumand &thorn;at &thorn;ai &thorn;ore suld haue</L>
<L>Al &thorn;at &thorn;ai wold efter craue;</L>
<L>Diuers godes &thorn;ore gert he make</L>
<L N="20">Of gold and siluer for &thorn;aire sake,</L>
<L>And bad &thorn;at &thorn;ai suld do no-thing</L>
<L>Bot to &thorn;o gods do &thorn;aire wirschiping.</L>
<L>Bot Cristine &thorn;arto had no haste:</L>
<L>Scho was fulfild of &thorn;e hali gaste;</L>
<L N="25">All fals goddes sone scho refusid</L>
<L>And to wirschip a god scho vsed.</L>
<L>Hir maydins wirschip to &thorn;am did;</L>
<L>And hir awin ofrand ai scho hid</L>
<L>And gaf it sethin with hert glad</L>
<L N="30">To help pure men &thorn;at mister had.</L>
<L>Hir maydins sune persayuid hir dede.</L>
<L>And one vnto hir fader &yogh;ede,</L>
<L>Scho said: "sir, &thorn;i doghter dispise</L>
<L>Vnto oure gods to do seruise;</L>
<L N="35">Hir ofrand preueli scho hides</L>
<L>And dose it on sum o&thorn;er sides.</L>
<L>And als, sir, we here by hir saw</L>
<L>Scho lattes mekil bi Cristes law".</L>
<L>Hir fader &thorn;an was ful euil payd.</L>
<L N="40">He went and softly to hir sayd:</L>
<L>"Mi doghter dere, in my blissing<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. in st. on.</NOTE></L>
<L>Honure our goddes ouer al thing!"</L>
<L>&THORN;an answerd scho on &thorn;is manere:</L>
<L>"Cal me na-more &thorn;i doghter dere,</L>
<L N="45">Bot for his doghter &thorn;ou me deme</L>
<L>To wham right sacrifice wil seme,</L>
<L>&THORN;at es noght ded god, made with hend,</L>
<L>Bot god &thorn;at lifs with-outen end".</L>
<L>&THORN;an said hir fader: "doghter dere,</L>
<L N="50">At me, &thorn;i fader, suld &thorn;ou lere</L>
<L>Noght to wirschip a god allone,</L>
<L>For drede &thorn;at o&thorn;er gods ilkone</L>
<L>Wold be wroth to &thorn;e in-fere".</L>
<L>&THORN;an answerd scho on &thorn;is manere:</L>
<L N="55">"&THORN;ou sais better &thorn;an &thorn;ou can knaw.</L>
<L>I mak mine ofrand, als me aw,</L>
<L>To fader and sun and hali gaste".</L>
<L>Herto &thorn;an answerd he in haste:</L>
<L>"Whi suld noght o&thorn;er gods be</L>
<L N="60">Wirschipd als wele als &thorn;o thre?"</L>
<L>Scho said: "al-if I tell &thorn;am fere,</L>
<L>All es a god with-outen pere,</L>
<L>All in a might and a god-hede &mdash;</L>
<L>To neuin me o&thorn;ir it es no nede".</L>
<L N="65">&THORN;an wist he noght what he suld say,</L>
<L>Bot al for wroth he went oway.</L>
<L>Al &thorn;o maumetis &thorn;an toke Cristine</L>
<L>&THORN;at war of gold and siluer fyne,</L>
<L>Sum scho brak and sum scho melt,</L>
<L N="70">And vnto pouer men scho it delt.<NOTE PLACE="foot">l. &thorn;e gold st. it?</NOTE></L>
<L>Hir fader come a-nother day</L>
<L>And fand his gods all waste oway;</L>
<L>&THORN;e o&thorn;er maydins to him teld</L>
<L>Al-how his doghter doun &thorn;am feld</L>
<L N="75">And gaf &thorn;e gold to pouer men fode.</L>
<L>&THORN;an for wroth he was nere wode.</L>
<L>He bad, XII wight men in &thorn;at stede</L>
<L>Suld spoil hir and ding hir to dede.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai bet hir, nakid bot hir ferk,</L>
<L N="80">Till &thorn;ai war all wery of werk;</L>
<L>&THORN;ai war ful prest to do hir payne,</L>
<L>Till &thorn;ai had lost both might &amp; mayne.
<PB REF="00000232.tif" N="94"></L>
<L>&THORN;e mayden was no-thing affrayd,</L>
<L>Bot to hir fader al &thorn;us scho said:</L>
<L N="85">"&THORN;ou man, &thorn;at es withouten schame,</L>
<L>Cal now opon &thorn;i gods by name</L>
<L>And bid &thorn;am, if &thorn;ai be of mayne,</L>
<L>Go gif &thorn;ir men &thorn;aire might ogayne!</L>
<L>For to me mai &thorn;ai do no skathe".</L>
<L N="90">&THORN;an wex he wude &amp; wunder wrathe.</L>
<L>In depe prison he did hir cast</L>
<L>And with cheynis bad he bind hir fast.</L>
<L>When hir moder herd of al &thorn;is fare,</L>
<L>In hert scho had ful mekill kare;</L>
<L N="95">Vnto &thorn;e presun gun scho wend</L>
<L>And rafe hir clothes with hir hend,</L>
<L>Scho fell vnto hir doghter fete<MILESTONE N="163" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And &thorn;us scho said, &amp; sore gun grete:</L>
<L>"A, doghter, haue mercy on me!</L>
<L N="100">I haue no comfort bot of &thorn;e.</L>
<L>Dere doghter, trow &thorn;i fader rede,</L>
<L>Els bringes &thorn;ou me vnto mi dede".</L>
<L>Cristyne &thorn;an answerd to hir &thorn;ore:</L>
<L>"&THORN;i doghter cal &thorn;ou me namore!</L>
<L N="105">&THORN;e es no bote me forto blame,</L>
<L>I trist me in my goddes name.</L>
<L>For al &thorn;e murning &thorn;ou mai make</L>
<L>His seruis sal I neuer forsake".</L>
<L>Hir moder saw scho wroght in vain,</L>
<L N="110">And ful wroth went scho home ogayn,</L>
<L>ffcho told &thorn;e fader all how scho ferd</L>
<L>And how hir doghter hir answerd.</L>
<L>&THORN;an gert hir fader sone on &thorn;e morn</L>
<L>Bring hir to bar furth him byforn;</L>
<L N="115">He bad hir to his goddes assent,</L>
<L>Or with sere payne scho suld be schent;</L>
<L>His doghter suld scho noght be cald</L>
<L>Ne for hir fader him forto hald,</L>
<L>Bot so scho suld lofe al hir prise.</L>
<L N="120">&THORN;an answerd Cristin wurdes wise:</L>
<L>"Sertis, scho said, if &thorn;ou tak kepe,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou dose to me ful grete wirschipe;</L>
<L>For vnto me it war grete euyll</L>
<L>To be cald doghter of &thorn;e deuill.</L>
<L N="125">All &thorn;at er of &thorn;e deuils kynde,</L>
<L>For &thorn;aire fader &thorn;ai sall him fynde.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou es &thorn;e sun of Satanas,</L>
<L>For all &thorn;i hert to him &thorn;ou has;</L>
<L>And vnto Crist my hert es knit".</L>
<L N="130">&THORN;an was he wude, out of his wit.</L>
<L>He cumand men to go bilyue<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. tu st. to.</NOTE></L>
<L>With nayles and hokes hir flesch to riue.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai war willy to wirk hir wogh,</L>
<L>Hir tendir flessh &thorn;ai all to-drogh.</L>
<L N="135">Scho tuke a pece vp in &thorn;at place</L>
<L>And kest it in hir faders face:</L>
<L>"Tirand, scho said, mased out of minde,</L>
<L>Tak &thorn;ore and ett of &thorn;ine owin kinde!"</L>
<L>&THORN;an on a quele he did hir fest</L>
<L N="140">And fire with oyle vnder it kest.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai had furguns and moni a croke,</L>
<L>So forto smore hir in &thorn;at smoke.</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;e fire so fro hir it withdrogh:</L>
<L>A thowsand and fifty &thorn;ore it slogh.</L>
<L N="145">Of al &thorn;at fire feld scho nankin sare,</L>
<L>Ne noi&thorn;er was hurt hide ne hare.</L>
<L>Hir fader of &thorn;is demid &yogh;itt</L>
<L>&THORN;at all was wroght by deuils wit;</L>
<L>He ne wist in werld what him wast best.</L>
<L N="150">In prisoun fast he did hir fest,</L>
<L>And on &thorn;e night &thorn;an next folowand</L>
<L>Vnto his men &thorn;us he cumand:</L>
<L>A heuy stone to hir hals at bind</L>
<L>And fest hir hend fast hir bihynd</L>
<L N="155">And kast hir fer out in &thorn;e se:</L>
<L>So hopid he best venged to be.</L>
<L>His men fulfild his cumandment.</L>
<L>Bot angels sune war to hir sent</L>
<L>And kepid hir hale bitwix &thorn;aire hend;</L>
<L N="160">And Crist him-self to hir descend,</L>
<L>He baptist hir &thorn;ore in &thorn;e see</L>
<L>And &thorn;us he said: "I baptis &thorn;e</L>
<L>In &thorn;e name of mi fader in heuyn</L>
<L>And in my name, his sun to neuyn,</L>
<L N="165">And in name of &thorn;e haly gast also".</L>
<L>&THORN;an saynt Mighell he toke hir to,</L>
<L>He bad him lede hir vnto &thorn;e land;</L>
<L>And sune he did als he cumand.</L>
<L>Sune when hir fader herd &thorn;is tale,</L>
<L N="170">In hert he had ful mekill bale.</L>
<L>He gert fetche hir furth him bifore</L>
<L>And &thorn;us he said vnto hir &thorn;ore:
<PB REF="00000233.tif" N="95"></L>
<L>"What deuils werkes er &thorn;e within,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at no fyre may &thorn;e bryn?</L>
<L N="175">To fend &thorn;e er &thorn;i fendes ay boun,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at no waters may &thorn;e drown.</L>
<L>I se &thorn;i witchecraft &thorn;e warand</L>
<L>Als wele in water als on land".</L>
<L>He was so stonayd in &thorn;at stunt:</L>
<L N="180">He strake him self fast in &thorn;e frunt.</L>
<L>And &thorn;an said Cristyne him vnto:</L>
<L>"Vn-happy fole, whi fares &thorn;ou so?</L>
<L>Crist has graunted to me swilk mede,</L>
<L>&THORN;at of &thorn;i paynes haue I no drede."</L>
<L N="185">&THORN;an eft in prison was scho broght.</L>
<L>And on &thorn;e morn he him bithoght</L>
<L>With sum quaintise hir to quell.</L>
<L>And on &thorn;at same night so bifell:</L>
<L>For wo he was so will of rede,</L>
<L N="190">&THORN;at on &thorn;e morn was he funden ded.</L>
<L>And Cristyne dweld in prison still,</L>
<L>Ay redy to wirk goddes wyll.</L>
<L>So when hir fader was funden dede,</L>
<L>A-no&thorn;er curst come in his stede,</L>
<L N="195">A tyrant and mayster of maumetry;</L>
<L>To Cristyne had he grete enuy.</L>
<L>When he sere suteltese vp soght</L>
<L>And in none wise might turn hir thoght:</L>
<L>A credill of iren for hir he makes</L>
<L N="200">And hinged it up on iren stakes;</L>
<L>Vnder it gert he mak grete fire</L>
<L>And kest in oyle, to mak it schire.</L>
<L>Sethin toke &thorn;ai hir with bitter brayd</L>
<L>And in &thorn;at credel allone hir layd;</L>
<L N="205">&THORN;an put &thorn;ai to rosyn and pik,</L>
<L>To smor hir in &thorn;e smoke so thik.</L>
<L>Ful wight men gert he to it go</L>
<L>with crokes to draw it to and fro:</L>
<L>To haste hir sone forto be ded</L>
<L N="210">Or els to turn vnto his rede.</L>
<L>Cristine herfore was noght affraid,</L>
<L>Bot loueand god al &thorn;us scho said:</L>
<L>"Loued be &thorn;ou, lord, of mercy milde,</L>
<L>Sen I am a new-cristend childe,</L>
<L N="215">&THORN;at suffers &thorn;am &thorn;us to rok me,</L>
<L>Als a &yogh;ung childe aw forto be."</L>
<L>Ful wroth &thorn;an was &thorn;e domesman,</L>
<L>And to his men he cumand &thorn;an:</L>
<L>Hastily hir heuid forto schaue</L>
<L N="220">And mak hir nakid, like a knaue,</L>
<L>And thurgh &thorn;e cete lede hir syne</L>
<L>To &thorn;aire god &thorn;at hight Appoline</L>
<L>And ger hir to him mak ofrand.</L>
<L>Ful sone &thorn;ai did als he cumand.</L>
<L N="225">Bot al-if &thorn;ai so made hir bare,</L>
<L>God couerd hir ful wele with hare.</L>
<L>And when scho come &thorn;aire god bifore,</L>
<L>On &thorn;is wise said scho to him &thorn;ore:</L>
<L>"I bid &thorn;e, deuil, no langer dwell!"</L>
<L N="230">&THORN;an vnto pouder als fast he fell.</L>
<L>&THORN;e men war ferd and fast &thorn;ai ran</L>
<L>And tolde &thorn;is to &thorn;e domesman,</L>
<L>How &thorn;at his god was fallen doune.</L>
<L>For sorow als fast he fell in swoune</L>
<L N="235">And hastily he gaf his gaste</L>
<L>To him &thorn;at he had seruid maste.</L>
<L>&THORN;an was Cristine in prison done.</L>
<L>And efter him &thorn;ai had ful sone</L>
<L>Ano&thorn;er Juge, Julianus hight,</L>
<L N="240">&THORN;at Cristes law mered at his might.</L>
<L>He gert Cristine bifor him bring;</L>
<L>Bot for him wold scho do no-thing</L>
<L>Ne to his law arly ne late.</L>
<L>&THORN;an gert he hete ane ouen ful hate;</L>
<L N="245">And when &thorn;e fire was best to brin,</L>
<L>&THORN;an gert he cast Cristyne &thorn;arin;</L>
<L>&THORN;ai closed it ful fast bifore.</L>
<L>And fiue days so dweld scho &thorn;ore,</L>
<L>At hir awyn lift to fit or gang,</L>
<L N="250">With mekill mirth of angell sang;</L>
<L>Of al &thorn;e fire scho felid no warm.</L>
<L>&THORN;an come scho furth with-outen harm.</L>
<L>&THORN;an Juliane hert was heuy als lede,</L>
<L>And sayd scho wroght by deuils rede.</L>
<L N="255">And sone he sent efter a man</L>
<L>&THORN;at mikell of wunder craftes can:</L>
<L>Wild wurmes couth he charm &amp; chaunt;</L>
<L>His craft he bad him with hir haunt.</L>
<L>Two scorpions to hir he kest,</L>
<L N="260">And two nedders on hir he fest,</L>
<L>And a wilde wurme on ai&thorn;er pap.</L>
<L>Bot fro heuyn (was) sent hir slike happ:</L>
<L>&THORN;ai merrid hir noght, bod made hir clene.</L>
<L>&THORN;arat &thorn;e Juge was wunder tene,</L>
<L N="265">To &thorn;e enchaunture in tene he sayd:</L>
<L>"Go ger &thorn;i bestes vnto hir brayd
<PB REF="00000234.tif" N="96"></L>
<L>To-tyme &thorn;ai ger hir fayntly fall"!</L>
<L>And he said: "right so I sall".</L>
<L>He bad &thorn;o bestes opon hir bite:</L>
<L N="270">And to him &thorn;an turned &thorn;ai tyte</L>
<L>And so &thorn;ai bate him in &thorn;at stede,</L>
<L>&THORN;at doun he fell bifor &thorn;am dede.</L>
<L>&THORN;an Cristine bad &thorn;o wurmes go</L>
<L>To wildernes whore &thorn;ai come fro,</L>
<L N="275">&THORN;at &thorn;aire malice namore war kyd.</L>
<L>And als scho cumand, sune &thorn;ai did.</L>
<L>Thurgh gods might &thorn;e man scho raysd &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;arfore &thorn;e folk ful mekill hir praisd.</L>
<L>Julian &thorn;an was wunder wrothe.</L>
<L N="280">He bad schere of hir pappes bothe.</L>
<L>His men war glad &thorn;arto to gang,</L>
<L>For &thorn;am thoght scho lifed ouer-lang.</L>
<L>When &thorn;ai war schorn, al men might se</L>
<L>How milk went out whore blude suld be.</L>
<L N="285">&THORN;an was &thorn;e terant wunder tene,</L>
<L>And for (to) him hir karping kene<NOTE PLACE="foot1">im Ms. fehlt to, oder ein Verb (greuid).</NOTE></L>
<L>More wikkedly he wold him wreke,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at scho suld no langer speke:</L>
<L>Hir tung out of hir heuid &thorn;ai reft.<MILESTONE N="164" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="290">Bot &thorn;arfore was hir speche noght left,</L>
<L>Scho spak &thorn;an als scho did biforn;</L>
<L>And toke hir tung &thorn;at was of schorn,</L>
<L>To Juliane face scho gert it flee</L>
<L>And &thorn;arwith strake scho out his ee.</L>
<L N="295">And vengeance so was on him tone,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he was blind als any stone.</L>
<L>He charged his men &thorn;an in &thorn;at stede</L>
<L>To schote at hir, till scho war dede.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai toke scharp arows in &thorn;at tyde</L>
<L N="300">And schot hir thurgh on ilka syde.</L>
<L>God set hir tyme, als he vouched saue,</L>
<L>When he hir sawl to him wald haue.</L>
<L>With schoteing so &thorn;an made scho end,</L>
<L>In lastand life ay forto lend.</L>
<L N="305">And so with Crist ay lifs Cristyn &mdash;</L>
<L>God graunt vs to &thorn;at life to wyn! amen.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="19" TYPE="legend">
<HEAD>19. De sancto Jacobo apostolo maiore historia.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Saynt James, apostel of Jhesu Crist<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Diese Legende folgt im Ms. Tib. hinter Peter und Paul, fol. 248 b Col. 1, wird aber erst in der 2. Col., V. 18, leserlich.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; brother of John Euangelist,</L>
<L>"James &thorn;e more" named he es,</L>
<L>Bi-caus a-no&thorn;er es namid "&thorn;e les".</L>
<L N="5">He prechid thurgh al &thorn;e Jury</L>
<L>And thurgh &thorn;e land of Samary.</L>
<L>He witnest al with wurdes bolde</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e prophetes bifore had tolde,</L>
<L>And vnto &thorn;e puple he puplist</L>
<L N="10">&THORN;at &thorn;ai war fulfild in Crist:<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Ms. in st. with.</NOTE></L>
<L>First of a mayden how he was born</L>
<L>To saue our faders &thorn;at fell biforn,</L>
<L>And sethin how he was ded on rude</L>
<L>And boght vs with his blisced blude,</L>
<L N="15">And rase ogayn in flehs and fell</L>
<L>And se&thorn;in fet his frendes fro hell,</L>
<L>And how he stegh to heuyn ogain &mdash;</L>
<L>Al prechid he with wurdes playn.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">V. 18 (Al)preched he plainly . . . steuyn.</NOTE></L>
<L>So it bifel &thorn;ore in &thorn;at land<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&thorn;are.</NOTE></L>
<L N="20">A wikked terand was wunand,</L>
<L>A domesman for &thorn;e deuil of hell,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">seruand st. domesman.</NOTE></L>
<L>To cristen folk ful fers and fell;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">men st. folk.</NOTE></L>
<L>Hermogines &thorn;an was his name.</L>
<L>And when he herd how nobil fame</L>
<L N="25">Of saint Jams wex with al bidene,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">24&mdash;5) Reinw&ouml;rter zerst&ouml;rt.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">saint fehlt. James.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;an in his hert he had grete tene.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&thorn;an fehlt.</NOTE></L>
<L>And when he wist what wai he went,</L>
<L>One of his seruands to him he sent,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">27&mdash;8) He spird in what waies &thorn;at he went, And his seruand to him he sent.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000235.tif" N="97"></L>
<L>His steward, &thorn;at was named Philit,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">cald.</NOTE></L>
<L N="30">And bad him &thorn;at he suld go wit<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&thorn;e st.&thorn;at. ga.</NOTE></L>
<L>Whi he went so obout prechand<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&yogh;ode. precheand.</NOTE></L>
<L>And made swilk maystris in his land;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">maystrise.</NOTE></L>
<L>"And bot he sese by wurd of &thorn;e,</L>
<L>Bynd him and bring him to me!"<NOTE PLACE="foot2">33&mdash;4) And bot he deny al to-geder, Bind him fast and bring him hider.</NOTE></L>
<L N="35">&THORN;an Philit toke with him cumpany<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Philete. with fehlt.</NOTE></L>
<L>And to James went &thorn;ai hastily;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">And vnto James he went in hi.</NOTE></L>
<L>And phariseus, ful mekil schrews,<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Ms. pharisenes.</NOTE></L>
<L>Went forto wit of his thews,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">spir st. wit.</NOTE></L>
<L>Forto atteyn him in sum thing,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">And to ateine him with.</NOTE></L>
<L N="40">&THORN;at &thorn;ai might wrye him to &thorn;e king.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">moght.</NOTE></L>
<L>When Philit met Jams in &thorn;e way,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">mete.</NOTE></L>
<L>Sune to him &thorn;us gun he say:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Als sone bigan he forto say.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Of moni maistris &thorn;ou &thorn;e mels,</L>
<L>And fals tales to &thorn;e folk &thorn;ou tels.</L>
<L N="45">For Crist, &thorn;at come in &thorn;e werld to wun,</L>
<L>Was neuer god ne godes sun:</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou sais he es god allone,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou of his men es one.</L>
<L>And for&thorn;i, bot &thorn;ou flit &thorn;e ferr,</L>
<L N="50">For his sake &thorn;ou sal far (&thorn;e) werr;</L>
<L>And tite bot if &thorn;ou turn &thorn;i hert,</L>
<L>With greuance grete &thorn;ou sal be gert".<NOTE PLACE="foot2">43&mdash;52) Tib. liest: Crist &thorn;at come in werld to won, Was neuer verray goddes sun. &THORN;ou tels &thorn;e folk whare &thorn;ou has gane, &THORN;at &thorn;ou ert of his men&yogh;e ane. And &thorn;arfore bot &thorn;ou flit &thorn;e ferr, For his sake may &thorn;ou far &thorn;e werr. &THORN;ou cals him god sun and nane els, It es nothing trew &thorn;at &thorn;ou tels.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">51&mdash;52) fehlen.</NOTE></L>
<L>Saint Jams, fulfild of &thorn;e hali gaste,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&THORN;an st. Saint. James.</NOTE></L>
<L>Answerd vnto him in haste;</L>
<L N="55">With moni resouns more and les,</L>
<L>And haly writ euer to witnes,</L>
<L>He proued him by &thorn;e prophetis saw</L>
<L>And bi lessons of &thorn;aire awyn law<NOTE PLACE="foot2">55&mdash;58: And proued him bi reson and skill, And toke ay haly writ &thorn;artill, And resons of &thorn;e prophet saw, And als aleged by &thorn;aire law.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at Jhesus was goddes sun verrayli,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">god sun verray.</NOTE></L>
<L N="60">So &thorn;at he kouth noght it deny;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">might noght say nay.</NOTE></L>
<L>And so by clergi ouercome he</L>
<L>&THORN;e steward and all his men&yogh;e.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">61&mdash;2) And so ouercome he with clergy Him and all his compani.</NOTE></L>
<L>And all confusid by proces playne<NOTE PLACE="foot2">confused. plain.</NOTE></L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e king &thorn;ai went ogayne.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">he turnep ogain.</NOTE></L>
<L N="65">&THORN;e steward told &thorn;an albidene<NOTE PLACE="foot2">And tald vnto him alb.</NOTE></L>
<L>How &thorn;at he had herd and sene &mdash;</L>
<L>And phariseus &thorn;at with him ware<NOTE PLACE="foot2">farisews.</NOTE></L>
<L>Vnto his wurdes gude witnes bare.</L>
<L>And omang al &thorn;e folk in-fere<NOTE PLACE="foot2">68 ff. fol. 249.</NOTE></L>
<L N="70">&THORN;e steward said in &thorn;is manere:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">on.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Sir, trow my tales, for &thorn;ai er trew!</L>
<L>James, &thorn;e seruand of Crist Jhesu,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Crist fehlt.</NOTE></L>
<L>May &thorn;ou noght cumpas to ouercum,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">On none wise may &thorn;ou ouercom.</NOTE></L>
<L>For he es apostell of grete wisdom.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">man st. apostell.</NOTE></L>
<L N="75">In Jhesu name, whore so he wendes,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">ware st. whore.</NOTE></L>
<L>Out of sere men he chaces fendes,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">sere fehlt.</NOTE></L>
<L>Blind men gers he haue &thorn;aire sight<NOTE PLACE="foot2">And blind.</NOTE></L>
<L>And croked men to gang ful right,</L>
<L>Of lepir lechis he man and wife</L>
<L N="80">And raises folk fro ded to life.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">79&mdash;80) Of meselry he makes men clene And raises men fra ded bidene.</NOTE></L>
