<L>Sore sal &thorn;ou rew &thorn;am al &thorn;i sithe".</L>
<L N="110">He bad his men go bind him swithe,<NOTE PLACE="foot">109&mdash;10) His men &thorn;an cald he at &thorn;e last And gert &thorn;am bind his steward fast.</NOTE></L>
<L>Both his fete in iren bandes<NOTE PLACE="foot">bath.</NOTE></L>
<L>And to his bak both his handes:<NOTE PLACE="foot">And at his bac &thorn;ai band his handes.</NOTE></L>
<L>So might he nou&thorn;ir stir ne braid.<NOTE PLACE="foot">&THORN;at he might now&thorn;er stir.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;an vnto him &thorn;us he said:</L>
<L>Videamus si Jacobus tuus soluat te.</L>
<L N="115">"Sertes, he said, now sal we se</L>
<L>If &thorn;i Jams now may lese &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">James. now fehlt.</NOTE></L>
<L>Fro &thorn;ir bandes &thorn;at &thorn;ou es in fest.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Of.</NOTE></L>
<L>Now lat se, baldly do &thorn;i best!"<NOTE PLACE="foot">117) ff. 2. Col. die Versenden sind oft nicht leserlich.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;an &thorn;e steward cald a childe,<NOTE PLACE="foot">had st. cald.</NOTE></L>
<L N="120">His sun, &thorn;at was both meke &amp; milde,<NOTE PLACE="foot">A sun.</NOTE></L>
<L>And vnto saint Jams he him sent<NOTE PLACE="foot">And &thorn;at sun vnto James . .</NOTE></L>
<L>To tel him of his grete turment.</L>
<L>&THORN;e childe went wittily and wele<NOTE PLACE="foot">And sone when &thorn;at &thorn;e childe com . .</NOTE></L>
<L>And told to &thorn;e appostil ilk a dele,<NOTE PLACE="foot">And tald to James of Philete (fare?).</NOTE></L>
<L N="125">How his fader had ful euyl fare</L>
<L>For he louid &thorn;e appostils lare.<NOTE PLACE="foot">125&mdash;6 fehlen.</NOTE></L>
<L>And when saynt James wist how al went,<NOTE PLACE="foot">He wist ful wele &thorn;an how it went</NOTE></L>
<L>Gude socure ful sone to him he sent;<NOTE PLACE="foot">And socore sone.</NOTE></L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e child he said in hi:</L>
<L N="130">"&THORN;i fader sal be helpid hastily",<NOTE PLACE="foot">He sall be.</NOTE></L>
<L>His sudari to him toke he<NOTE PLACE="foot">sodari. to him fehlt. &thorn;an takes he.</NOTE></L>
<L>And said: "sun, bere &thorn;is thing with &thorn;e!<NOTE PLACE="foot">sais.</NOTE></L>
<L>Touche him &thorn;arwith, if &thorn;ou can,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Towch.</NOTE></L>
<L>And bid him say &thorn;ir wurdes &thorn;an:</L>
<L>Dominus soluit compeditos e. c. &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">wordes.</NOTE></L>
<L N="135">God lesis &thorn;am &thorn;at er in prisoune,<NOTE PLACE="foot">leses.</NOTE></L>
<L>God raises &thorn;am &thorn;at er casten doune".<NOTE PLACE="foot">And st. god.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e childe &thorn;an toke &thorn;e appostels sudary,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&THORN;an &thorn;e child to (!) &thorn;e sudary,</NOTE></L>
<L>And vnto his fader he went in hy<NOTE PLACE="foot">And went to &thorn;e steward in hy.</NOTE></L>
<L>And sone he said &thorn;e appostell will</L>
<L N="140">And also &thorn;e wurdes, he told him till.<NOTE PLACE="foot">139&mdash;40) fehlen.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e sudary on him he cast:<NOTE PLACE="foot">And sone when he it on him cast,</NOTE></L>
<L>And sudanly his bandes brast.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Al his bandes in sunder brast.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e kinges faith he forsoke &thorn;an<NOTE PLACE="foot">for|soke he.</NOTE></L>
<L>And to saint James ful sune he wan;<NOTE PLACE="foot">And vnto James.</NOTE></L>
<L N="145">He cursed &thorn;e king als fendes lym<NOTE PLACE="foot">And weried fast &thorn;a . . .</NOTE></L>
<L>And als al &thorn;o &thorn;at war with him.<NOTE PLACE="foot">And als al &thorn;a . . Die folg. 8 Verse sind ganz zerst&ouml;rt.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;an was Hermogines ful wo,</L>
<L>When his steward was went him fro.</L>
<L>And for he saw his grete sorceri</L>
<L N="150">Failid him &thorn;an &thorn;ore so fayntly,</L>
<L>Experimentes &thorn;an ordand he</L>
<L>And raised deuils grete plente.</L>
<L>By coniureing &thorn;ai come him till
<PB REF="00000237.tif" N="99"></L>
<L>And bad him say to &thorn;am his will;<NOTE PLACE="foot">And asked him what . .</NOTE></L>
<L N="155">&THORN;ai sayd: "we er redy to wende<NOTE PLACE="foot">&THORN;ai sayd we er . .</NOTE></L>
<L>And wirk &thorn;i will als for oure frende".<NOTE PLACE="foot">Whare so &thorn;ou w . .</NOTE></L>
<L>"A, frendes, he said, me es ful wo!<NOTE PLACE="foot">frendes fehlt.</NOTE></L>
<L>My fals steward es went me fro;</L>
<L>Left my law haly has he<NOTE PLACE="foot">And left.</NOTE></L>
<L N="160">And now dispises both yow and me,<NOTE PLACE="foot">now fehlt. despises</NOTE></L>
<L>And to a lurdan es he gone<NOTE PLACE="foot">And till ano&thorn;er he has him . .</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at serued him wham we haue slone &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ane of his men &thorn;at s . .</NOTE></L>
<L>Jams &thorn;ai tel &thorn;at lurdan hat.<NOTE PLACE="foot">James he says &thorn;e lurd(an) . .</NOTE></L>
<L>Mi frendes, I pray yow, fetchis him &thorn;at,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&THORN;arfore I pray &yogh;ow . .</NOTE></L>
<L N="165">And whore-so-euer &thorn;ai mai be funden<NOTE PLACE="foot">And fehlt. Whare. he st. &thorn;ai.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bringes &thorn;am bothe vnto me bunden!<NOTE PLACE="foot">And bring.</NOTE></L>
<L>So &thorn;at I may sune vengid be<NOTE PLACE="foot"><P>Hier beginnt die R&uuml;ckseite, deren erste Col. fast ganz zerst&ouml;rt ist. Die 2. Col. (215 ff.) ist deutlich. &mdash;</P><P>W&auml;hrend in Ms. Tib. die Hand dieselbe bleibt, tritt in Ms. Harl. mit fol. 165 eine andere Hand ein, welche den Rest der Sammlung geschrieben hat. Von hier ab stimmt Harl. buchst&auml;blich mit Tib. &uuml;berein, manche Fehler abge|rechnet, die der Schreiber hineingebracht hat. Auch in sprachlicher Beziehung verschwinden die Unterschiede der Texte; Harl. schreibt jetzt meist &thorn;a, &thorn;are, whare, fra, bath u. a. mit a, gan st. gun, slike, in den Endungen &ouml;fter e, (ed, es, er, en.) Eigenth&uuml;mlich ist jedoch in graphischer Beziehung die Schreibung z st. &yogh;, u st. v; h&auml;ufig ist w st. wh und wh st. w; &thorn; und y (beide sind gleich) haben ein der Abbrev. f&uuml;r <I>er</I> &auml;hnliches H&auml;kchen.</P></NOTE></L>
<L>On &thorn;at gadling &thorn;at greuis me.</L>
<L>With grete paynis I sall him greue</L>
<L N="170">&THORN;at bringes my men in misbileue."<NOTE PLACE="inter"><B>(Hier beginnt andere Hand.)</B></NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;an &thorn;ir fendes war wonder faine<MILESTONE N="165" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And said itt suld be done sertaine,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H serstaine.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ai suld noght leue for thin ne thik</L>
<L>Till &thorn;ai war broght bath ded or quik.</L>
<L N="175">And furth &thorn;ai flow, als he &thorn;am bad &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;an was &thorn;e lurdan wonder glad.</L>
<L>&THORN;e fendes flow furth in &thorn;e ayre:</L>
<L>And angels come ful bright and faire,</L>
<L>&THORN;at fra god him-self war sent,</L>
<L N="180">And (&thorn;a) fendes with fire &thorn;ai brent.<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;a fehlt.</NOTE></L>
<L>When &thorn;ai kome ouer &thorn;at ilk stede</L>
<L>Whare Jams was kneland in his bede,</L>
<L>No ferrer might &thorn;ai fendes founde,</L>
<L>Bot doun &thorn;ai fell unto &thorn;e grounde.</L>
<L N="185">And unto James &thorn;us gan &thorn;ai cry:</L>
<L>"Man, of us &thorn;ou haue mercy!</L>
<L>For goddes appostel we &thorn;e knaw,</L>
<L>&THORN;ar-fore &thorn;is uengance fra us draw,</L>
<L>Or-time &thorn;at we brin unto noght!</L>
<L N="190">For sere sorou es till us soght."</L>
<L>&THORN;an answard Jams on &thorn;is manere</L>
<L>And said: "deuils, wat do ze here?</L>
<L>Heyn oway I rede ze fle.<NOTE PLACE="foot">H heyn oder he&thorn;(i)n?</NOTE></L>
<L>Wharto cum ze unto me?"</L>
<L N="195">&THORN;ai sayd ogaine &thorn;an wordes slike:</L>
<L>"Hermogines, &thorn;e heritike,</L>
<L>Has sent us heder for &thorn;is thing:</L>
<L>&THORN;at we swld &thorn;e till him bring</L>
<L>And Philet &thorn;at was his serwand,</L>
<L N="200">Bunden fast both fote and hand.</L>
<L>Bot sone so we come hederward,</L>
<L>Goddes angels has us bun ful hard</L>
<L>With cheynes of fire obout us bent,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at we swffer grete turment.</L>
<L N="205">And sen we knaw &thorn;ou power has,</L>
<L>We pray &thorn;e help, and lat us pas!"</L>
<L>&THORN;an Jams lift upp his hand &amp; sayd:</L>
<L>"&THORN;e angell &thorn;at &thorn;a bandes on layd,</L>
<L>He tak &thorn;am fra zow sone in hy,</L>
<L N="210">In &thorn;e name of god all-mighty,</L>
<L>Fadyr and sun a(n)d haly gaste.</L>
<L>So &thorn;at ze sall wende in haste</L>
<L>Vnto Hermogines ogayne &mdash;</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;at ze do him nokins paine!</L>
<L N="215">Bot sen he bad zow bring me &thorn;eder</L>
<L>And Philet, bunden bath togeder,</L>
<L>I cumand zow biliue &thorn;at ze</L>
<L>Go bind him, and bringes him to me &mdash;
<PB REF="00000238.tif" N="100"></L>
<L>Bot hurtes him noght in lim ne lith &mdash;</L>
<L N="220">For a word wil I speke him with".<NOTE PLACE="foot">T will.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;an &thorn;ir fendes wald neuer sese</L>
<L>To &thorn;ai come till Hermogines.</L>
<L>And he was faine of &thorn;aire cuming</L>
<L>And trowed he suld here gude ti&thorn;ing.</L>
<L N="225">He said: "whare er &thorn;a lurdans twa?"</L>
<L>&THORN;ai said: "nay, nay, it bese noght swa",</L>
<L>&THORN;ai stirt bifor him and bihind,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H bilund.</NOTE></L>
<L>With bandes of yren him forto bind.<NOTE PLACE="foot">h in with &uuml;berschr.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;an loud he cried and said &thorn;am to:<NOTE PLACE="foot">T lout, H lout in loud corr.</NOTE></L>
<L N="230">"Harrow deuill! wat sal ze do?"<NOTE PLACE="foot">H wat, T what.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ai said: "sir, bind &thorn;e nedes us bus</L>
<L>And lede &thorn;e unto Jams with us</L>
<L>And to Philet &thorn;at fra &thorn;e fled.</L>
<L>And warne it war us forbed<NOTE PLACE="foot">warne = ne war it.</NOTE></L>
<L N="235">To do &thorn;e harm or hurt &thorn;e sare,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou suld far ill, or &thorn;ou come &thorn;are,</L>
<L>For sorow we had for &thorn;i sake,</L>
<L>When &thorn;ou sent us &thorn;am to take.</L>
<L>&THORN;arfore lend we no langer here!"</L>
<L N="240">&THORN;ai herled him furth with hidose bere.<NOTE PLACE="foot">T harled H herled. H hudose.</NOTE></L>
<L>Vnto James come &thorn;ai in &thorn;at tyde</L>
<L>And unto him al &thorn;us &thorn;ai cried:</L>
<L>"Put &thorn;is man in oure pouste:</L>
<L>And ful sone saltou uenged be</L>
<L N="245">Of harmes &thorn;at he has done &thorn;e till;</L>
<L>And of him sall we haue oure wil</L>
<L>For &thorn;e brining &thorn;at on us encrest</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e angels, till &thorn;ou it fest".</L>
<L>&THORN;an said Jams unto &thorn;e fendes:</L>
<L N="250">"Lo, Philit here bifor zow wendes:</L>
<L>Whi bind ze noght him in zowre band,</L>
<L>Als Hermogines zow cummand?"<NOTE PLACE="foot">T cumand.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;an answerd &thorn;e fendes ogaine</L>
<L>And said: "&thorn;ou wate &thorn;i-self sertayne</L>
<L N="255">&THORN;at we may haue no pouste</L>
<L>Of thing &thorn;at towches unto &thorn;e".<NOTE PLACE="foot">T touches.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;an cumand James &thorn;am forto wend</L>
<L>To &thorn;aire woning with-owten end,<NOTE PLACE="foot">T ende.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;at &thorn;ai suld no harm do &thorn;an</L>
<L N="260">Now&thorn;er unto beste ne man.</L>
<L>A hidose cry &thorn;an raysed &thorn;ai,</L>
<L>And on &thorn;is wise &thorn;ai went oway.</L>
<L>Hermogines &thorn;an bunden stode</L>
<L>Byfor saynt James with drery mode.</L>
<L N="265">And Jams to Philet said &thorn;is saw:<NOTE PLACE="foot">T James.</NOTE></L>
<L>"&THORN;e scole of god for &thorn;ou sal knaw:</L>
<L>&THORN;at es ay to be milde of mode</L>
<L>And ogaynes euill forto do gude:</L>
<L>&THORN;is man &thorn;at band &thorn;e lith and lim,</L>
<L N="270">I bid &thorn;e now &thorn;at &thorn;ow lese him.<NOTE PLACE="foot">T &thorn;ou.</NOTE></L>
<L>He cumanded &thorn;at &thorn;ou suld be bun</L>
<L>With fendes, whare &thorn;ou might be fun:</L>
<L>And now, sen he es bunden swa,</L>
<L>Lese &thorn;ou him and lat him ga!"</L>
<L N="275">&THORN;an Philet, als saint Jams cumandes,</L>
<L>Leses him out of his bandes.</L>
<L>When &thorn;at terrant sau in sight<NOTE PLACE="foot">T terant, H terrant.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at in James was so mekill might,</L>
<L>To lese and bind so at his will:<NOTE PLACE="foot">in H ist d in bind v. a. Hand klein &uuml;berschr.</NOTE></L>
<L N="280">He wald noght gang, bot stode ful still,</L>
<L>And sone bigan to think in thoght</L>
<L>&THORN;at he wikkedly had wroght.</L>
<L>Vnto saint Jams he spac gude spede</L>
<L>And asked forgifnes of his dede.</L>
<L N="285">Saint Jams &thorn;an said him untill:</L>
<L>"Wend furth fre, whare so &thorn;ou wil!<NOTE PLACE="foot">T will.</NOTE></L>
<L>For it falles noght in oure techeing</L>
<L>To conuert men here, for no thing,</L>
<L>Ogains &thorn;aire wil we(le) forto do,<NOTE PLACE="foot">T wele, H we.</NOTE></L>
<L N="290">Bot &thorn;aire entent war set &thorn;ar-to.</L>
<L>And &thorn;arfor on &thorn;i way &thorn;ou wend,</L>
<L>Vntill &thorn;i mode be better mend!"</L>
<L>&THORN;an said he: "sir, sen I sall wende &mdash;</L>
<L>I knaw &thorn;e felnes of &thorn;e fende,</L>
<L N="295">I wate wele &thorn;ai will do me dere,</L>
<L>Bot if &thorn;ou wald me wiss and were;</L>
<L>&THORN;ai wil tak me, wen I ga,<NOTE PLACE="foot">T when.</NOTE></L>
<L>And with diuers paynes me sla".</L>
<L>&THORN;an said saint Jams: "I sal &thorn;e saue:</L>
<L N="300">My staf here with &thorn;e sal-tou haue,<NOTE PLACE="foot">T saltou.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000239.tif" N="101"></L>
<L>&THORN;at sal &thorn;e were, whare so &thorn;ou wendes,</L>
<L>For all &thorn;e felnes of &thorn;e fendes".</L>
<L>&THORN;e appostel staf &thorn;an toke he &thorn;are<NOTE PLACE="foot">Tappostell.</NOTE></L>
<L>And hame ogain fast gan he fare.</L>
<L N="305">And graithly up he laites and lukes</L>
<L>All his bagges and all his bokes,</L>
<L>&THORN;at his lawes war wreten in</L>
<L>Of sorceri and deuils gin,</L>
<L>And all his fals experimentes</L>
<L N="310">In hampers hastly he &thorn;am hentes,</L>
<L>And all his gaudes of deuils gere<NOTE PLACE="foot">T al.</NOTE></L>
<L>Gerd he his seruandes with him bere,<NOTE PLACE="foot">T gert.</NOTE></L>
<L>And also sum him-seluen bare,</L>
<L>Vnto James. and when he come &thorn;are,</L>
<L N="315">Fire and &thorn;am to-geder he broght</L>
<L>And forto brin &thorn;am was his thoght.</L>
<L>And James bad, he suld noght so,</L>
<L>"For-why &thorn;e smoke grete harm may do</L>
<L>Vnto men &thorn;at it suld fele:</L>
<L N="320">For in &thorn;am es so mekill unsele.</L>
<L>Bot fill &thorn;a sachels ful of stanes</L>
<L>And kast in &thorn;e se all at anes,</L>
<L>And lede also by &thorn;am ze bind,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at neuer man &thorn;am efter find".</L>
<L N="325">Hermogines kest all in &thorn;e se.</L>
<L>And unto James ogaine come he,</L>
<L>And doun he fell unto his fete</L>
<L>And praied him his bale to bete:</L>
<L>"Deliuerer of saules, he said,</L>
<L N="330">Sen &thorn;at slike grace to &thorn;e es graid</L>
<L>Mans mis forto amend,</L>
<L>My life es halely in &thorn;i hend:</L>
<L>Forgif me &thorn;at I did to &thorn;e,</L>
<L>And haue mercy and rew on me,</L>
<L N="335">Sen &thorn;ou sais it es godes will</L>
<L>Forto do gude ogaynes ill!"</L>
<L>Hermogines conuersus est ad dominum.</L>
<L>&THORN;an said saint James wit gude entent:</L>
<L>"If &thorn;ou will uerraily repent<NOTE PLACE="foot">H it st. if.</NOTE></L>
<L>Al &thorn;i misdedes more and les,</L>
<L N="340">&THORN;an uerraily gettes &thorn;ou fo(r)gifnes".</L>
<L>&THORN;an said Hermogines to him &thorn;are:</L>
<L>"Say me, what I sal do mare?</L>
<L>I haue forsaken mi fals lay</L>
<L>And kasten al my bokes oway".</L>
<L N="345">Saint Jams answerd unto him &thorn;en.<NOTE PLACE="foot">d in answerd kl. &uuml;berschr.</NOTE></L>
<L>"&THORN;ou sall do &thorn;us, als I &thorn;e ken:</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;aire howses wend saltou</L>
<L>Wham &thorn;ou turned on &thorn;i lare to trow,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at &thorn;ou said &thorn;ou suthfast knew</L>
<L N="350">Tel &thorn;am now it es noght trew!</L>
<L>And all &thorn;i maumettes more and myn</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou first affied &thorn;e in,</L>
<L>Riue &thorn;am sunder, or &thorn;ou rest,</L>
<L>And all in-to &thorn;e se &thorn;am kest!</L>
<L N="355">And tresore falsly won to hend,</L>
<L>In gude dedes &thorn;ou sal despend!</L>
<L>Forsake &thorn;at filth &thorn;at &thorn;e has fylde,</L>
<L>And fra &thorn;e fende bicum goddes childe!"</L>
<L>Hermogines &thorn;an with gude will</L>
<L N="360">Hight all hertly to fulfill.</L>
<L>Baptime he toke with gude entent,</L>
<L>And toke his leue and furth he went.<MILESTONE N="166" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Baldly he did als James him bad,</L>
<L>And sone in trowth he wex so sad</L>
<L N="365">And so parfite goddes lawes to lere,</L>
<L>&THORN;at god thurgh him wroght wonders sere.</L>
<L>&THORN;an &thorn;e iews persaiued sone</L>
<L>Slike dedes, thurgh him was done,</L>
<L>And how &thorn;at James him turned had:</L>
<L N="370">&THORN;an in &thorn;are hertes &thorn;ai war unglad.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai gaderd mone grete plente</L>
<L>And hired men with &thorn;am to be,</L>
<L>James on al wise forto noy</L>
<L>And Philet als forto destroy.</L>
<L N="375">And langer &thorn;an &thorn;ai wald noght lett</L>
<L>Bot toke him &amp; in preson sett,</L>
<L>And tald &thorn;is mater les and mare</L>
<L>Till &thorn;aire bisschop Abiathar.</L>
<L>And he gat men of his assent</L>
<L N="380">And to king Herod with him went;</L>
<L>And a rape about his nec &thorn;ai band</L>
<L>And herled him furth so in &thorn;aire hand.</L>
<L>So when &thorn;ai come to Herod, &thorn;e king,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai tald him all &thorn;is ill ti&thorn;ing,</L>
<L N="385">Whare &thorn;at he had went and how</L>
<L>He turned &thorn;e folk on him to trow:</L>
<L>"Hermogines, &thorn;ai said, turned he has</L>
<L>And all &thorn;e men &thorn;at with him was".</L>
<L>When Herod had herd all &thorn;is tale,
<PB REF="00000240.tif" N="102"></L>
<L N="390">Him thoght &thorn;at he might brist for bale.</L>
<L>He said: "we will noght with him striue,</L>
<L>Bot go, haues of his heuid biliue!</L>
<L>So &thorn;at ilk a fendes lime</L>
<L>May tak bifining bi him<NOTE PLACE="foot">H bifining.</NOTE></L>
<L N="395">For to missay oure goddes mare</L>
<L>Or mak slike dray als he did are".</L>
<L>&THORN;an langer &thorn;are &thorn;ai wald noght stand</L>
<L>Bot led him furth fast in a band</L>
<L>To &thorn;e stede whare &thorn;ai suld him quel.</L>
<L N="400">And als &thorn;ai went, so it bifell:</L>
<L>With a man &thorn;ai met in hy</L>
<L>&THORN;at had bene lang in parlesy;</L>
<L>And loud he cried, fra he him knew:</L>
<L>"James, &thorn;e appostell of Jhesu,</L>
<L N="405">Haue mercy on me, man of main,</L>
<L>And liuer me out of my payne!"</L>
<L>&THORN;an said saint James &thorn;ir wordes fre:</L>
<L>"In his name I cumand &thorn;e,</L>
<L>For was luf I sal suffer ded,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H was, T whas.</NOTE></L>
<L N="410">&THORN;at &thorn;ou rise up hale in &thorn;is stede</L>
<L>And so be saved of all &thorn;i sare".<NOTE PLACE="foot">H saved aus sawed corr., T saued. H &thorn;ai, T &thorn;i.</NOTE></L>
<L>And so was &thorn;e man helid &thorn;are.</L>
<L>&THORN;an was &thorn;are ane, hight Josias,</L>
<L>Ane of &thorn;e bisschop men he was,</L>
<L N="415">And &thorn;at was he, &thorn;e suth to wit,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e rape bi James nec knit,</L>
<L>To lede him till his ded ful right.</L>
<L>And als sone when he sau &thorn;is sight,</L>
<L>&THORN;e rape he left and lete it lese,</L>
<L N="420">And doun he fell appon his knese<NOTE PLACE="foot">H appon, T opon.</NOTE></L>
<L>And unto Jams &thorn;us gan he say:</L>
<L>"Apostel of Jhesu, I &thorn;e pray</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou my trispas forgif me</L>
<L>And mak me ane of &thorn;i menze!"</L>
<L N="425">&THORN;an was &thorn;e bisschop wonder wrathe,</L>
<L>And biliue gert bind &thorn;am bathe</L>
<L>And said: bot he turned his entent,</L>
<L>Wit James suld he suffer turment.</L>
<L>Josias &thorn;an answerd ogaine</L>
<L N="430">And said: "&thorn;arfore am I ful faine.</L>
<L>&THORN;i goddes and &thorn;e both I defy,</L>
<L>And weried be &thorn;at company!<NOTE PLACE="foot">T cumpani.</NOTE></L>
<L>And blisced be Jhesu Crist allane,</L>
<L>For he es god, and o&thorn;er nane!"</L>
<L N="435">&THORN;e bisschop &thorn;an gert bete him sare;</L>
<L>And euer his trowth was mare &amp; mare.</L>
<L>&THORN;e bisschop &thorn;an to Herod sent</L>
<L>On him forto gif iugement.</L>
<L>And hastily him demed he</L>
<L N="440">With James heuedid forto be.</L>
<L>And so when &thorn;at he demed was,</L>
<L>Saint Jams baptist Josias</L>
<L>And made him in his trowth ful trew<NOTE PLACE="foot">in fehlt T.</NOTE></L>
<L>Anely in his lord Jhesu.<NOTE PLACE="foot">H anely, e aus d corr., T anly.</NOTE></L>
<L N="445">And so at anes in &thorn;at stede</L>
<L>Bousomly &thorn;ai toke &thorn;aire dede</L>
<L>And marters war &thorn;ai made ful euyn,</L>
<L>And so went to &thorn;e bliss of heuyn</L>
<L>And wons in welth with-outen ende &mdash;</L>
<L N="450">God wis us all &thorn;eder to wende!"</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="20" TYPE="legend">
<HEAD>20. In festo sci Petri ad uincula<NOTE PLACE="foot">Siehe Tib. fol. 251&mdash;252a 1.</NOTE>).</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Saint Peter, &thorn;at was pape of Rome</L>
<L>And curature of cristendome,</L>
<L>In Jerusalem prechid he<NOTE PLACE="foot">T Jherusalem.</NOTE></L>
<L>And in sere places in &thorn;at cuntre,</L>
<L N="5">&THORN;e same tyme &thorn;at saint Jams was tane</L>
<L>And with king Herod sakles slane.</L>
<L>And when king Herod wist ilkdele</L>
<L>How &thorn;at it payed &thorn;e iewes wele
<PB REF="00000241.tif" N="103"></L>
<L>&THORN;at James was so done to ded:</L>
<L N="10">&THORN;ar-fore he soght in ilka stede</L>
<L>Cristen men where he migh(t) ta,</L>
<L>And many ane he stroyed swa.</L>
<L>And saint Peter at &thorn;e last<NOTE PLACE="foot">T And <I>to</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>He pursued and in preson cast,</L>
<L N="15">And &thorn;are to kepe him he cumand, &mdash;</L>
<L>For &thorn;are hegh fest was nere cumand</L>
<L>&THORN;at pasch was cald in &thorn;at cuntre:</L>
<L>&THORN;an used &thorn;ai grete solempnite</L>
<L>And in &thorn;at day &thorn;ai wald noght do</L>
<L N="20">Thing &thorn;at ani charge fell to.<NOTE PLACE="foot">T any.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;arfore Herod, &thorn;at fals feloune,</L>
<L>Set saint Peter in presoun</L>
<L>And thoght wele &thorn;at he suld be slane</L>
<L>When &thorn;aire fest war fulli gane.<NOTE PLACE="foot">T fully.</NOTE></L>
<L N="25">He was set in a dongon depe,</L>
<L>And sextene knightes him forto kepe.</L>
<L>And &thorn;e men &thorn;at went with him are,</L>
<L>Praied ful fast for his wele-fare,</L>
<L>To Crist &thorn;ai cald with gude entent,</L>
<L N="30">With-o(u)ten hali kirkes cumandment.<NOTE PLACE="foot">H with oten.</NOTE></L>
<L>So it fell on &thorn;e night biforn</L>
<L>&THORN;at he suld die opon &thorn;e morn:</L>
<L>In &thorn;e preson he fell in slepe,</L>
<L>Bitwene &thorn;e knightes &thorn;at gan him kepe,</L>
<L N="35">Bun with cheynes strang and store;</L>
<L>And stalworth men stode at &thorn;e dore,</L>
<L>And al obout &thorn;e hows &thorn;ai stode,</L>
<L>It forto zeme with wapin gude.</L>
<L>And at midnight &thorn;e men ilkane</L>
<L N="40">Fell in slepe, and waked nane.</L>
<L>In-to &thorn;e preson come a gleme</L>
<L>Brighter &thorn;an &thorn;e sunes beme,</L>
<L>And ane angell come in &thorn;at tide</L>
<L>And towched Peter on &thorn;e side;</L>
<L N="45">He said unto him on &thorn;is wise:</L>
<L>"Smertly bid I &thorn;e up rise!"</L>
<L>&THORN;e cheynes fell &thorn;an fra his hend,</L>
<L>And up he rase, als he him kend.</L>
<L>&THORN;an sayd &thorn;e angel to him sone:</L>
<L N="50">"Do on &thorn;i gere, biliue haue done!</L>
<L>Al &thorn;i clathes &thorn;ou do on &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">H And al, and fehlt in T.</NOTE></L>
<L>And hose and schose, and folou me!"</L>
<L>&THORN;an did he als &thorn;e angel bad,</L>
<L>A(n)d folowed furth with hert glad;</L>
<L N="55">And no-thing wist he what it ment,</L>
<L>Bot with &thorn;e angell euyn he went;</L>
<L>And in his hert he trowed bitwene</L>
<L>Sum uisioun &thorn;at he had sene.</L>
<L>Both furth &thorn;ai went omang &thorn;am all,<NOTE PLACE="foot">T Bot.</NOTE></L>
<L N="60">Til &thorn;ai war past &thorn;e secund wall,</L>
<L>And till &thorn;e zates past &thorn;ai plaine:</L>
<L>&THORN;at euyn was opind &thorn;am ogayne.</L>
<L>When he was broght &thorn;us on &thorn;is wise</L>
<L>Fra &thorn;e daunger of his enmyse</L>
<L N="65">And, whare he wald, ful wele might ga,</L>
<L>&THORN;an &thorn;e angell past him fra &mdash;</L>
<L>And how he went &thorn;an wist he noght.</L>
<L>&THORN;are stode he stil and him bithoght,<NOTE PLACE="foot">T still.</NOTE></L>
<L>And musand on &thorn;is ferly fare</L>
<L N="70">On what manere he might cum &thorn;are.</L>
<L>Fra &thorn;e presoun whare he was laid,</L>
<L>And to him-self al &thorn;us he said:</L>
<L>Nunc scio uere quia misit deus e. c.<NOTE PLACE="foot">H felt st. self.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Now wate I wele in mine entent</L>
<L>&THORN;at god of heuyn his angel sent,</L>
<L N="75">Me to bring &thorn;us of my bandes</L>
<L>And help me out of Herodes handes</L>
<L>And fra &thorn;e despite of &thorn;e iewes</L>
<L>&THORN;at me ilkaday with euyl pursues".</L>
<L>&THORN;an loued he god hertly omang</L>
<L N="80">And thoght wheder him was best to gang.</L>
<L>To Mari hows he whent onone<NOTE PLACE="foot">whent st. went.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at moder was of James and John:</L>
<L>For &thorn;are war of his frendes Inew</L>
<L>&THORN;at in &thorn;e trowth of Crist war trew</L>
<L N="85">And lufed him right wele I-nogh &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;arfore unto &thorn;am he drogh.</L>
<L>He knokked on &thorn;e zate with gude will:</L>
<L>And sone a maiden come &thorn;ar-till.</L>
<L>And when scho saw &thorn;are Peter stand;</L>
<L N="90">In ogain scho went rinand,</L>
<L>&THORN;e zates still zit left scho sperde,</L>
<L>And tald &thorn;am hou scho Peter herde,</L>
<L>Scho said &thorn;am &thorn;at &thorn;e zate he stode.<NOTE PLACE="foot">H &thorn;at st. at.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;ai threpid on hir scho was wode:</L>
<L N="95">"Woman, &thorn;ou ert wode, &thorn;ai sayd,
<PB REF="00000242.tif" N="104"></L>
<L>Peter es fast in preson laid</L>
<L>And suffers payn withouten pere.</L>
<L>Wald god &thorn;at he war now here!"</L>
<L>&THORN;e mayden affermid ay mare and mare</L>
<L N="100">Herdely &thorn;at he was &thorn;are.</L>
<L>And &thorn;us whils &thorn;ai war in debate,<MILESTONE N="167" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Peter knokked eft at &thorn;e zate.</L>
<L>And sum of &thorn;am said: "lat it stand!</L>
<L>It es his gaste, I will warand".</L>
<L N="105">&THORN;e thrid time Peter knokked fast:</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e zate went &thorn;ai at &thorn;e last.</L>
<L>And when &thorn;ai saw saint Petir &thorn;are,</L>
<L>Of him &thorn;ai all awonderd ware</L>
<L>And in &thorn;aire hertes had &thorn;ai dred(e),</L>
<L N="110">How he out of preson zede;</L>
<L>Bot of his come war &thorn;ai ful glad.</L>
<L>And with his hand be stil he bad,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H bestil, T be still.</NOTE></L>
<L>So &thorn;at &thorn;ai suld speke nomare</L>
<L>Ne no-man wit &thorn;at he war &thorn;are.</L>
<L N="115">Bot in he went and to &thorn;am talde</L>
<L>Al-how he wan out of halde</L>
<L>And how oure lord him helpid had</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;e stede whare he was stad</L>
<L>Omang his famen, bundun fast</L>
<L N="120">Wit iren sheynes and lokkes to last;</L>
<L>"And &thorn;arfore, said he, luke ze tell</L>
<L>Al &thorn;is ferly als it fell</L>
<L>Unto James and my bre&thorn;er hende!</L>
<L>And haues guday, for I will wende!"</L>
<L N="125">&THORN;an went he till ano&thorn;er land,</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e pople ay precheand.</L>
<L>And in &thorn;at fer cuntre he dweld,</L>
<L>Till Herod and his force was feld. &mdash;</L>
<L>Bot how it fell, now will we loke,</L>
<L N="130">With Herod and with &thorn;am &thorn;at woke.</L>
<L>On &thorn;e morn, when he was gane,</L>
<L>Sir Herod said he suld be slane;</L>
<L>And unto presoun sone he sent</L>
<L>And bad bring him furth in present.</L>
<L N="135">Bot or &thorn;ai wist, he was oway.</L>
<L>&THORN;an had &thorn;ai no word forto say.</L>
<L>Omang &thorn;am &thorn;an was mekill kare.</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;arof will we speke nomare;</L>
<L>Vnto oure proces will we pas</L>
<L N="140">And tell wat &thorn;e encheson was</L>
<L>Whi &thorn;is ilk fest was namen swa<NOTE PLACE="foot">H namen st. named.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of saint Peter ad uincula.<NOTE PLACE="inline">Causa quare dicitur ad uincula.</NOTE></L>
<L>A duke dwelled in Rome sum tyme</L>
<L>&THORN;at fele folk had under him:<NOTE PLACE="foot">H felle, T fele.</NOTE></L>
<L N="145">Lord he was of &thorn;e Romaynes;</L>
<L>And cristen men he did grete paynes,</L>
<L>&THORN;am to defoul wald he noght fyne;</L>
<L>And his name was cald Quirine.</L>
<L>He had a doghter &thorn;at was him dere,</L>
<L N="150">And scho was set in sekkenes sere</L>
<L>&THORN;at derid hir gretly day and night;</L>
<L>And Balbinie &thorn;at ilk mayden hight.</L>
<L>&THORN;is ilk duke, of wham ze herd,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H he st. ze.</NOTE></L>
<L>Had in his preson ful fast sperd</L>
<L N="155">Alisander, &thorn;e pape of Rome,</L>
<L>For maintenance of cristendom.</L>
<L>And &thorn;is ilk maiden trowed wele &thorn;an</L>
<L>&THORN;at Alisander was haly man</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;are was set in preson strang;</L>
<L N="160">&THORN;arfore oft gan scho till him gang</L>
<L>And kissed &thorn;e fetters on his fete,</L>
<L>And th(o)ght he might hir bales bete.</L>
<L>&THORN;us come scho oft, at no-man wist,<NOTE PLACE="foot">at=&thorn;at.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; his scheynes ful swetely kist,<NOTE PLACE="foot">T cheynes.</NOTE></L>
<L N="165">Hopeand he was a haly man.</L>
<L>An Alisander said to hir &thorn;an:<NOTE PLACE="foot">H u. T An.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Sese! he said, my dogter dere,</L>
<L>And kys namore my fetters here!</L>
<L>Bot seke &thorn;a fetters sone &thorn;ou sall</L>
<L N="170">&THORN;at saint Peter was bun withall</L>
<L>In Jerusalem, when he was tane</L>
<L>With Herod &thorn;at wald him haue slane;</L>
<L>And kis &thorn;a fetters sone &thorn;ou sale,</L>
<L>And, doghter, so saltou be hale.</L>
<L N="175">And by &thorn;at signe saltou se</L>
<L>&THORN;at a ful haly man was he."</L>
<L>&THORN;e maiden thanked him of his saw</L>
<L>And toke hyr leue with lowting law.<NOTE PLACE="foot">T louting.</NOTE></L>
<L>Vntill hir fadir sone scho ferd<NOTE PLACE="foot">T fader.</NOTE></L>
<L N="180">And tald him all how scho had herd,</L>
<L>How Alisander said scho sold</L>
<L>Be helid wele, iff &thorn;at scho wolde
<PB REF="00000243.tif" N="105"></L>
<L>Kis &thorn;e bandes, hir bales to bete,</L>
<L>&THORN;at war opon saint Peters fete</L>
<L N="185">In Jerusalem when he had paine.</L>
<L>&THORN;an was hir fader ferly faine:</L>
<L>"If &thorn;is be funden suth, said he,</L>
<L>&THORN;an sal &thorn;e pape deliuerd be."</L>
<L>Ful sone he ordan knightes hende<NOTE PLACE="foot">H ordan (so &ouml;fter), T ordand</NOTE></L>
<L N="190">Unto Jherusalem forto wende,</L>
<L>To seke whar &thorn;e fetters might be funden</L>
<L>&THORN;at saint Peter with was bunden.<NOTE PLACE="foot">T bun.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;an went &thorn;ai furth, als he cumand,</L>
<L>And soght, till &thorn;ai &thorn;a fetters fand.</L>
<L N="195">Of &thorn;e finding war &thorn;ai faine,</L>
<L>And hastili went hame ogaine.<NOTE PLACE="foot">T hastily.</NOTE></L>
<L>And when &thorn;e duke &thorn;e ffetters se,</L>
<L>"Gose to my doghter! sone said he,</L>
<L>For sertanly we sall asay</L>
<L N="200">Whe&thorn;er &thorn;e pape said suth or nay."</L>
<L>&THORN;an &thorn;e dukes doghter dere</L>
<L>Kissed &thorn;e fetters with ful gude chere:</L>
<L>And hastily was scho helid &thorn;an.</L>
<L>Ful meri made &thorn;ai ilka man.<NOTE PLACE="foot">T mery.</NOTE></L>
<L N="205">&THORN;e duke &thorn;an for his doghter sake</L>
<L>Cumand &thorn;e pape fro presown take,</L>
<L>And turned him unto Jhesu Crist</L>
<L>And of &thorn;e pape &thorn;are was baptist,</L>
<L>And his menze euerilkane</L>
<L N="210">Vnto Jhesu has &thorn;am tane.</L>
<L>And &thorn;e maiden &thorn;at I of mene</L>
<L>Vnto Crist ay keped hir clene.</L>
<L>Pape Alisander for &thorn;is resoune,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H his, T &thorn;is.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at he past &thorn;us out of presoune</L>
<L N="215">Anly for &thorn;ir fetters sake:</L>
<L>&THORN;arfore a kirk sone gert he make</L>
<L>And haloude it in saint (Peter) name<NOTE PLACE="foot">Peter fehlt in H u. T.</NOTE></L>
<L>And "ad uincula" &thorn;ai cald &thorn;e same &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at es, als klerkes understandes,</L>
<L N="220">In honowre of &thorn;a blisced bandes<NOTE PLACE="foot">H &thorn;ai in &thorn;a corr.</NOTE></L>
<L>Whilk on saint Peter fete war fest</L>
<L>When he was in preson kest.</L>
<L>And when &thorn;at kirk al endid was,</L>
<L>&THORN;e cheynes war ordand in a case</L>
<L N="225">Of siluer and of gold ful schene,</L>
<L>So forto be keped clene.</L>
<L>And many folk &thorn;an of &thorn;e land</L>
<L>Come &thorn;eder with ful grete ofrand,</L>
<L>To kis &thorn;e cheines in &thorn;at place;</L>
<L N="230">And god thurgh gudenes of his grace</L>
<L>Wroght uertu &thorn;are of folk in-fere</L>
<L>And helid men of sekenes sere,</L>
<L>And so to blis he gan &thorn;am bring &mdash;</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;at lord be ay loueing!</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="21" TYPE="legend">
<HEAD>21. De sancto Sixto episcopo, magistro Laurencii<NOTE PLACE="foot">S. Tib. fol. 252a2&mdash;253.</NOTE>).</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>In tyme of Decius Cesare,</L>
<L>&THORN;at used fals goddes and fendes lare,</L>
<L>A terand with him dwelled &thorn;an</L>
<L>&THORN;at named was Valiriane.</L>
<L N="5">Saint Sixt (sest) noght for &thorn;aire aw<NOTE PLACE="foot">in H fehlt sest (T unlesbar).</NOTE></L>
<L>To turne &thorn;e folk till Cristes law;</L>
<L>Mani men gert he be baptist<NOTE PLACE="foot">H gret st. gert.</NOTE></L>
<L>And turn &thorn;am unto Jhesu Crist.</L>
<L>&THORN;arat had &thorn;ir terantes tene.</L>
<L N="10">And sune &thorn;ai ordand &thorn;am bitwene</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;is ilk bisschop suld be tane</L>
<L>And with bitter paynes slane,</L>
<L>Bot if he wald mak sacrafise</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;aire goddes &thorn;at he despice.</L>
<L N="15">And to fulfill &thorn;aire fals entent,</L>
<L>Efter &thorn;e bisschop sone &thorn;ai sent
<PB REF="00000244.tif" N="106"></L>
<L>And broght him &thorn;eder, and al his men</L>
<L>And all his clerkes &thorn;at &thorn;ai kouth ken.<NOTE PLACE="foot">H kuouth.</NOTE></L>
<L>And when &thorn;ai all bifor him ware,</L>
<L N="20">Vnto &thorn;e bisschop said he &thorn;are:</L>
<L>"wirschip our goddes now, or &thorn;ou wende!<NOTE PLACE="foot">H pou st. &thorn;ou.</NOTE></L>
<L>For &thorn;ai sall lif owten ende<NOTE PLACE="foot">H u. T owten ohne with.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;aire might sal euer endoure &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;ar-fore I bid, &thorn;ou &thorn;am honowre:</L>
<L N="25">And ouer al prestes &thorn;ou sal be prince</L>
<L>&THORN;at er wonand in &thorn;is prouince.</L>
<L>And if &thorn;ow will noght sogates do,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou sal be ensample &thorn;am to,</L>
<L>&THORN;at o&thorn;er sal ensaumple take</L>
<L N="30">More slike maistrise forto make."</L>
<L>Saint Sixt &thorn;an answerd on &thorn;is wise:</L>
<L>"Sir, I mak euermore sacrafice</L>
<L>Vnto my lord, &thorn;e fader of heuyn,</L>
<L>And to his sun Jhesu ful euyn;</L>
<L N="35">Mak sacrafice to &thorn;am will I,</L>
<L>And all &thorn;ai fals goddes I defy."<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ai st. &thorn;i.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;an Decius was wonder wrath,</L>
<L>And Valirian, wode war &thorn;ai bath.</L>
<L>No langar wald &thorn;ai gif him grith,</L>
<L N="40">Bot twa dekins &thorn;ai did him with</L>
<L>Intill a presoun strang and depe,</L>
<L>And cumand knightes &thorn;am to kepe;</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;e dekins in a hows &thorn;ai did;</L>
<L>And in a-no&thorn;er hole him did.<NOTE PLACE="foot">did st. hid.</NOTE></L>
<L N="45">Saint Laurance was of his dekins ane:</L>
<L>And when he herd how he was tane,</L>
<L>He went unto him with gude will</L>
<L>And on &thorn;is wise he spak him till:</L>
<L>"fader, he said, whider gastow</L>
<L N="50">And takes noght &thorn;i sun with &thorn;e now?</L>
<L>Wheder wendes &thorn;ou &thorn;us allane</L>
<L>And of &thorn;i dekins takes with &thorn;e nane?</L>
<L>&THORN;ou was neuer are wont &thorn;arto</L>
<L>With-owten dekin seruise to do:</L>
<L N="55">Also say, sir, &thorn;ou suld noght be<MILESTONE N="168" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="foot">H Also say (T?); say st. sa, oder say ist zu streichen.</NOTE></L>
<L>In preson, bot I war with &thorn;e.</L>
<L>Sen I &thorn;i will haue noght misvsed,</L>
<L>Fader, whi hastou me refused?</L>
<L>Sen I am boun with &thorn;e to ga</L>
<L N="60">And wirk &thorn;i will in wele and wa,</L>
<L>Whi hastou forsaken me?"</L>
<L>And unto him &thorn;an answerd he</L>
<L>And said: "sun, I forsake &thorn;e noght;</L>
<L>Bot herder were to &thorn;e es wroght,</L>
<L N="65">Welle herder paine es puruaid &thorn;e</L>
<L>&THORN;an any es ordand to me.</L>
<L>For I am alde and out of state &mdash;</L>
<L>Ful light pain sone may me mate;</L>
<L>And, sun, &thorn;ou es zong and mighty &mdash;</L>
<L N="70">Ful hard paines saltou haue for-&thorn;i;</L>
<L>And &thorn;e more sal be &thorn;i mede,</L>
<L>And &thorn;arfore luke &thorn;ou haue no drede!<NOTE PLACE="foot">H luke, T luk <I>wele</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Efter thre daies, wen I am went,</L>
<L>Saltou suffer hard turment,</L>
<L N="75">And to heuyn saltou folow nest,</L>
<L>Als dekin aw to folow prest."</L>
<L>Saint Sixt &thorn;an, als sais &thorn;e boke,</L>
<L>Vnto Laurance, his dekin, bitoke</L>
<L>Al &thorn;e tresures of haly kirk,</L>
<L N="80">At his will with &thorn;am to wirk.</L>
<L>And Laurance went whare he might ken</L>
<L>Pouer clerkes or pouer men,</L>
<L>And to widows and maydens zing</L>
<L>Gaf he largely of &thorn;is thing,</L>
<L N="85">To ilkane als he mister kend,</L>
<L>Vntill &thorn;e tresore was all spend.</L>
<L>&THORN;an Decius with grete tene was tane</L>
<L>And said unto Ualiriane:</L>
<L>"Bot &thorn;is bisschop be broght o daw,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H odaw (T?) st. of daw.</NOTE></L>
<L N="90">Sune he sall destroyn oure law,</L>
<L>And no-man sal be rad for &thorn;is</L>
<L>Ano&thorn;er time to do omis;</L>
<L>And if he for &thorn;is dedes dy,</L>
<L>&THORN;an sal o&thorn;er be war &thorn;arby</L>
<L N="95">Forto do despites &thorn;us</L>
<L>ow&thorn;er till oure goddes or us."</L>
<L>&THORN;an answerd Valiriane</L>
<L>And said: "forsuth, he sal be slane,</L>
<L>Ger men haue of his heuid in hy!</L>
<L N="100">&THORN;an sall o&thorn;er be war &thorn;arby.</L>
<L>So rede I we &thorn;a faiturs fese<NOTE PLACE="foot">T u. H fese = fugare, ays. f&ecirc;sian.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at dose till us any dissese."
<PB REF="00000245.tif" N="107"></L>
<L>&THORN;an out of preson gun &thorn;a ta</L>
<L>&THORN;e bisscop an his dekins twa &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">T bisschop. H an (so &ouml;fter), T and.</NOTE></L>
<L N="105">&THORN;e tane hight Filicissimus</L>
<L>And &thorn;at o&thorn;er Acapitus.</L>
<L>Decius Cesar in &thorn;at stede</L>
<L>Demed &thorn;am al thre to ded.</L>
<L>And when &thorn;e dome was zolden swa,</L>
<L N="110">&THORN;an answerd &thorn;e dekins twa</L>
<L>And said te Cesar and Valiriane:<NOTE PLACE="foot">T u. H te st. to. H Cecar.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Ze waful wreches and will of wane,</L>
<L>And ze wald herkin and fulfill</L>
<L>&THORN;at oure fader here telles zow till,</L>
<L N="115">&THORN;an might ze eschew endles paine;</L>
<L>And els, &thorn;aroff ze be sertayne</L>
<L>Withouten end in dole to dwell</L>
<L>And in filth with &thorn;e fende of hell."</L>
<L>&THORN;an Decius was wonder wode</L>
<L N="120">And said to &thorn;am &thorn;at by him stode:</L>
<L>"Gose swith and stroy &thorn;ir lurdans strang!</L>
<L>For sertes now lif &thorn;ai alto lang</L>
<L>Forto hete us endles paine!<NOTE PLACE="foot">H hece.</NOTE></L>
<L>Seses neuer, or &thorn;ai be slaine!"</L>
<L N="125">&THORN;an war &thorn;ai led out of &thorn;at stede</L>
<L>To &thorn;e place ware &thorn;ai suld be ded.<NOTE PLACE="foot">T whare.</NOTE></L>
<L>Sone when saint Laurance herd &thorn;is say,</L>
<L>He come and kepid &thorn;am in &thorn;e way.</L>
<L>And bifell &thorn;at &thorn;ai suld wend(e)<NOTE PLACE="foot">T wende.</NOTE></L>
<L N="130">By a maumettri of &thorn;e fende,</L>
<L>In a temple &thorn;are it stode &mdash;</L>
<L>Decius it held a god ful gude.</L>
<L>And when saint Sixt come nere &thorn;erby,</L>
<L>He said: "Jhesus, god sun mighty,</L>
<L N="135">&THORN;at god and lord es of renowne,</L>
<L>He destroy &thorn;e and bring &thorn;e doune</L>
<L>And chace &thorn;e, foul fende, unto hell,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at &thorn;ou here no langer dwel."<NOTE PLACE="foot">T dwell.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;an sone &thorn;e fende gan &thorn;e&thorn;in found</L>
<L N="140">And &thorn;e temple fell to ground.</L>
<L>Here-of &thorn;e folk grete fe(r)ly thoght<NOTE PLACE="foot">T u. H fely.</NOTE></L>
<L>And said it suld ful dere be boght:</L>
<L>In hertes &thorn;ai war gretly anoyede</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;aire goddes war so destroyde.</L>
<L N="145">Laurence &thorn;an come him untill</L>
<L>And said: "sir, if (it) war &thorn;i will,</L>
<L>Suffer me with &thorn;e to dy</L>
<L>And leue me noght now so lightly!</L>
<L>For I haue done als &thorn;ow me bad:</L>
<L N="150">&THORN;e tresore of &thorn;ine &thorn;at I had,</L>
<L>Ilkadele it es despe(n)d.<NOTE PLACE="foot">H desped.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;arfore lat me with &thorn;e wend!"</L>
<L>Sone &thorn;an, als &thorn;e knightes herd &thorn;ore</L>
<L>&THORN;at he had &thorn;e bisschoppes tresore,</L>
<L N="155">&THORN;ai toke saint Laurence in &thorn;at stede</L>
<L>And sayd: forsuth, he suld be dede</L>
<L>Bot if he broght &thorn;e gudes onane</L>
<L>&THORN;at he of &thorn;e bisschop had tane.</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e cete &thorn;ai him sent,</L>
<L N="160">Of &thorn;e Emperoure to haue iugement.</L>
<L>&THORN;e bischop &thorn;are to dede &thorn;ai broght,</L>
<L>And his twa dekins left &thorn;ai noght;</L>
<L>Of &thorn;ai strake &thorn;aire heuedis euyn.</L>
<L>And hastyly &thorn;ai went to heuyn.</L>
<L N="165">Cristen men &thorn;an, &thorn;at &thorn;ar wase,</L>
<L>Beried &thorn;aire bodis in &thorn;at place</L>
<L>And honord &thorn;am oft in &thorn;aire dede,</L>
<L>Als mekill als &thorn;ai durst for drede.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="22" TYPE="legend">
<HEAD>22. De sco Laurencio historia<NOTE PLACE="foot">S. Tib. fol. 253&mdash;255 a 1.</NOTE>).</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Laurence was in preson strang,</L>
<L>Wikkedly and al with wrang,</L>
<L>For &thorn;e tresore &thorn;at he had tane</L>
<L>Of saint Sixt, &thorn;at was sakles slane.</L>
<L N="5">Tane he was out of &thorn;e toure</L>
<L>And broght byfor &thorn;e Emperore,</L>
<L>Acount &thorn;are graythly forto zelde</L>
<L>Of gudes &thorn;at war gifen him in welde.
<PB REF="00000246.tif" N="108"></L>
<L>&THORN;e Emperoure &thorn;an sone onane</L>
<L N="10">Bytoke him to Valiriane,</L>
<L>&THORN;at next him-self was maister maste,</L>
<L>And &thorn;us he cumand him in haste</L>
<L>&THORN;at he suld bisyli enquere</L>
<L>Of (&thorn;e) tresore and gudes sere<NOTE PLACE="foot">T &thorn;e, fehlt in H.</NOTE></L>
<L N="15">&THORN;at he had of &thorn;e bisschop tane,</L>
<L>And bring &thorn;am to him euer-ilkane:</L>
<L>"And &thorn;us, he said, when &thorn;ou has done,</L>
<L>Ger him make sacrifice &thorn;an sone,</L>
<L>vnto oure godes of grete renowne!</L>
<L N="20">And (if) he &thorn;arto be noght boune<NOTE PLACE="foot">T And if, in H fehlt if.</NOTE></L>
<L>Or will noght do efter &thorn;i rede,</L>
<L>With diuers paynes luke he be dede!"<NOTE PLACE="foot">T ded.</NOTE></L>
<L>Valiriane did als he him bad,</L>
<L>And kald &thorn;e menze &thorn;at he had;</L>
<L N="25">Untill a-no&thorn;er he toke him tyte,</L>
<L>Was a vicare, hight Ipolite,</L>
<L>And bad him he suld bind him sare</L>
<L>Till he grante whare &thorn;e tresore ware.</L>
<L>And Ipolit &thorn;an did him doune</L>
<L N="30">Ware many o&thorn;er war in presoune.<NOTE PLACE="foot">T whare.</NOTE></L>
<L>And so he sat with sorows sere</L>
<L>With many theues and theues fere.<NOTE PLACE="foot">H sere st. fere (T?).</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;are sat a man in paines strang</L>
<L>&THORN;at in &thorn;e presoun had bene lang,</L>
<L N="35">And for &thorn;e sorow, he was in sett,</L>
<L>Day and night so had he grett</L>
<L>&THORN;at both his eghen war waxen blind,</L>
<L>And help &thorn;ar-fore might he none find.</L>
<L>Sone, when saint Laurence wist his state,</L>
<L N="40">He said: "&thorn;i bale forto abate,</L>
<L>Trow in Crist and cristend be:</L>
<L>And sone &thorn;an sal he lighten &thorn;e!</L>
<L>If &thorn;ou to him will turn &thorn;e right,</L>
<L>Hastili sal tou haue &thorn;i sight."</L>
<L N="45">&THORN;e blind man &thorn;an, ful sare gretand,</L>
<L>Said: "I trow and understand</L>
<L>&THORN;at Jhesus es god of mightes maste,</L>
<L>&THORN;at born was of &thorn;e maiden chaste.</L>
<L>Vnto his trowth here I me take,</L>
<L N="50">And al fals maumettes I forsake.</L>
<L>And so &thorn;at I may saued be,</L>
<L>For Jhesu luf &thorn;ou baptif me!"</L>
<L>Saint Laurence &thorn;an baptist him right:</L>
<L>And hastily he had his sight.</L>
<L N="55">He loked obout him in &thorn;at place</L>
<L>And loued god of his grete grace</L>
<L>And &thorn;ir wordes said he in his steuin:</L>
<L>"Loued be &thorn;at lord Jhesus in heuyn</L>
<L>&THORN;at me has done &thorn;is gracius chance</L>
<L N="60">Thurght prayer of blisced Laurence!</L>
<L>For blind I was, now may I se.</L>
<L>Ouer al o&thorn;er blisced mot he be!"</L>
<L>And many blind men of &thorn;e land,</L>
<L>Als sone als &thorn;ai herd &thorn;is ti&thorn;and</L>
<L N="65">&THORN;at Laurence was &thorn;are of slike might,</L>
<L>Come unto him, and had &thorn;aire sight.</L>
<L>Ipolitus, his keper, &thorn;an</L>
<L>Saw he was so haly a man:</L>
<L>In his hert he dred &thorn;e mare</L>
<L N="70">And &thorn;us he said unto him &thorn;are:</L>
<L>Ostende michi thesauros!</L>
<L>"Shew &thorn;e tresores unto me,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at &thorn;ou may saued be!</L>
<L>Els bese &thorn;ou put to mekil paine".</L>
<L>&THORN;an said Laurence to him ogaine;</L>
<L N="75">"A, Ipolite! and &thorn;ou will knau<MILESTONE N="169" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;e kindly course of Cristes lau</L>
<L>And trow in him with main and mode</L>
<L>&THORN;at boght &thorn;e with his precius blude,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e tresore &thorn;an &thorn;ou sal be kend</L>
<L N="80">And haue &thorn;e life with-outen end".</L>
<L>&THORN;an Ipolite his law forsoke</L>
<L>And unto Jhesu Crist him toke;</L>
<L>Of Laurence has he baptime tane;</L>
<L>And all his menze euer-ilkane<NOTE PLACE="foot">T ilkone.</NOTE></L>
<L N="85">Forsoke &thorn;aire maumettes les and mare</L>
<L>And trowed in Crist and baptist ware.</L>
<L>Ipolit &thorn;an said him &thorn;ir saws:</L>
<L>"Sir, als &thorn;i-self &thorn;e suth wele knaws,</L>
<L>Valirian, als &thorn;e Emperoure bad,</L>
<L N="90">Comanded me with wordes sad</L>
<L>&THORN;at I suld hald &thorn;e here in paine</L>
<L>And &thorn;e tresore fast of &thorn;e frayne,</L>
<L>An se&thorn;in bring &thorn;e him untill.</L>
<L>Say me, here-of wat es &thorn;i will?"</L>
<L N="95">&THORN;an said Laurence: "we will go &thorn;eder
<PB REF="00000247.tif" N="109"></L>
<L>Baldly, we bath to-geder.</L>
<L>And dout &thorn;e no-thing of &thorn;aire scath!</L>
<L>For blis es ordan till us bath".</L>
<L>When &thorn;ai come in Valirian sight,</L>
<L N="100">Vnto saint Laurence said he right:</L>
<L>"How likes &thorn;e &thorn;i paines smert?</L>
<L>Put frawerdnes out of &thorn;i hert</L>
<L>And chinchehede and couatyse,<NOTE PLACE="foot">chinchehede = avaritia.</NOTE></L>
<L>And tel ware al &thorn;e tresore lise</L>
<L N="105">&THORN;at we knaw wele left with &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">H bisscheppes.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of &thorn;i bisschoppes awin liuere.</L>
<L>Tel us titte whare &thorn;ou it did!</L>
<L>For we wate wele &thorn;ou has it hid".</L>
<L>&THORN;an sais saint Laurence: "sir, gif me</L>
<L N="110">Respite of twa dayes or thre:</L>
<L>And &thorn;an I sall schew zow ful sone</L>
<L>Whare I haue all &thorn;e tresore done".</L>
<L>Valirian said: "on &thorn;at couenant</L>
<L>&THORN;ine asking unto &thorn;e I grante,</L>
<L N="115">So &thorn;at &thorn;ou bring till Decius</L>
<L>&THORN;e tresore &thorn;an, als &thorn;ou hetes us".</L>
<L>Laurence &thorn;an with-outen fayl<NOTE PLACE="foot">T u. H sayl st. fayl.</NOTE></L>
<L>Gederd togeder grete pouerayl<NOTE PLACE="foot">T poue rayl.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of croked men and als of blind,</L>
<L N="120">And al seke folk &thorn;at he moght find</L>
<L>In-till &thorn;e toun with him he tase,</L>
<L>And hid &thorn;am in Ipolit place,</L>
<L>And mete and drink &thorn;are he &thorn;am fand,</L>
<L>Vntill &thorn;e day &thorn;at was ordand.</L>
<L N="125">In &thorn;at mene wile Valiriane<NOTE PLACE="foot">T while.</NOTE></L>
<L>Went to &thorn;e Emperoure onane,</L>
<L>"Sir, he said, Laurence and I</L>
<L>Has assigned day sertanly</L>
<L>To bring &thorn;e tresores in present,</L>
<L N="130">Efter &thorn;ir thre daies er went".</L>
<L>&THORN;an was Decius ful wele paid,</L>
<L>"I thank &thorn;e, sir, suthly", he said.</L>
<L>And samyn &thorn;are &thorn;ai dwelled and plaid &mdash;</L>
<L>For of &thorn;is purpose war &thorn;ai paid.</L>
<L N="135">When &thorn;e th(r)e daies to end war went,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H the, T thre.</NOTE></L>
<L>Laurence proferd him in present</L>
<L>Bifore Decius and Valiriane.</L>
<L>And unto him &thorn;us said &thorn;e tane:</L>
<L>"Whare er &thorn;e tresores &thorn;at &thorn;ou hight</L>
<L N="140">To bring &thorn;is day bifor oure syght?"</L>
<L>&THORN;an Laurence gedard alto-geder<NOTE PLACE="foot">T u. H gedard.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e pouer folk and broght &thorn;am &thorn;eder</L>
<L>Bifor &thorn;am all in &thorn;e palayse,</L>
<L>And with high uoice &thorn;ir wordes he sais:</L>
<L N="145">"Lo here tresore &thorn;at neuer sal fail</L>
<L>And vnto man may most ava(i)le!<NOTE PLACE="foot">H avale, T availe.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;is tresore sal neuermore be les &mdash;</L>
<L>With-owten end waxand it es;</L>
<L>It will noght wast oway als wede,</L>
<L N="150">It helpes man in his moste nede".</L>
<L>Decius &thorn;an was wonder wrath.</L>
<L>"Wha lad! he said, scornes &thorn;ou vs bath?<NOTE PLACE="foot">T u. H wha lad; wha st. wa.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ful dere boght sone sall it be!"</L>
<L>Hastily &thorn;an cumand he</L>
<L N="155">His turmentoures tite him to take</L>
<L>And naked in &thorn;at stede him make,</L>
<L>And seyn bete his body bare<NOTE PLACE="foot">T se&thorn;in, H seyn, oder se&thorn;n? (so &ouml;fter); seyn wird im Ev. Nic. v. 1069 vom Reim gefordert. H betes, T bete.</NOTE></L>
<L>With scorpions &thorn;at uenym ware.</L>
<L>&THORN;an turmentoures toke him in hy</L>
<L N="160">And bet opon him bit(t)erly,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H biterly, T bitterly.</NOTE></L>
<L>Vntill his body was al blode,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H als.</NOTE></L>
<L>Als (he) befor &thorn;e Emperoure stode.<NOTE PLACE="foot">he fehlt in T u. H. T bifor.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e Emperoure gert bring in present</L>
<L>Diuers maners of turment</L>
<L N="165">And said &thorn;an: "al &thorn;is turmentri</L>
<L>Sal be spended in &thorn;i body</L>
<L>Bot if &thorn;ou wightly turn &thorn;i mode</L>
<L>And honore oure goddes &thorn;at er gude".</L>
<L>&THORN;an answerd Laurence and to him said:</L>
<L N="170">"&THORN;ou wreched wight, I am wele payd</L>
<L>To suffer all &thorn;ir paynes strang,</L>
<L>For &thorn;am haue I desired lang.</L>
<L>&THORN;ir thinges er turment unto &thorn;e:<NOTE PLACE="foot">H chinges.</NOTE></L>
<L>For with &thorn;am saltou turmentid be;</L>
<L N="175">Vntill us &thorn;ai er liking
<PB REF="00000248.tif" N="110"></L>
<L>And <I>ioy</I>, &thorn;at neuer sall haue ending".<NOTE PLACE="foot">H &thorn;ou st. joy, T ioy.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;an was Decius wel nere wode</L>
<L>And &thorn;us he said with eger mode:</L>
<L>"Sen &thorn;ou sais it es ioy to zow,</L>
<L N="180">Say us whare ma er slike als &thorn;ou:</L>
<L>And we sal bring &thorn;am to &thorn;e here,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ze may mak ioy all in-fere".</L>
<L>&THORN;an said saint Laurence: "sir, &thorn;ou raues,</L>
<L>&THORN;ow whate noght &thorn;ou efter crawes;<NOTE PLACE="foot">T u. H whate st. wate; in beiden fehlt what vor &thorn;ou. T craues.</NOTE></L>
<L N="185">Slike als I er high in heuyn,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou ert noght worth te here &thorn;aire steuyn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">H te st. &thorn;o.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ai may noght be knawen vnto &thorn;e,</L>
<L>For sinful men may none &thorn;am se".</L>
<L>&THORN;an was Decius ire ful grete.<NOTE PLACE="foot">T u. H &thorn;at st. &thorn;an.</NOTE></L>
<L N="190">With staues he bad &thorn;ai suld him bete<NOTE PLACE="foot">H stanes.</NOTE></L>
<L>And pelt on him with plumes of lede</L>
<L>And with scorpions, till he be ded;</L>
<L>Iren plates he gert &thorn;am glew</L>
<L>And lap until his sides ay new.</L>
<L N="195">Of &thorn;at play was saint La(u)rance paid<NOTE PLACE="foot">H Larance, a aus o corr., T Lourance.</NOTE></L>
<L>And smyland to &thorn;e king he said:</L>
<L>"Lo, wreche, he said, now may &thorn;ou se</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;i pain no-thing deres me.</L>
<L>I fele no-thing of all &thorn;is fare,</L>
<L N="200">Al-if &thorn;ai did me mekill mare".</L>
<L>Omang &thorn;am &thorn;an &thorn;are was a knight,</L>
<L>A rightwis man, &thorn;at Romane hight:</L>
<L>Thurgh wordes of saint Laurence &thorn;are</L>
<L>He turned him to Cristes lare.</L>
<L N="205">And of &thorn;e sight, he &thorn;are gan se,</L>
<L>Vnto saint Laurence &thorn;us said he:</L>
<L>"I se a childe bifor &thorn;e stand</L>
<L>With a faire towail in his hand</L>
<L>Driand &thorn;i fless and makes it clene,</L>
<L N="210">&THORN;at no solping &thorn;aron es sene.<NOTE PLACE="foot">solping v. sulpen solpen-inquinare.</NOTE></L>
<L>In Cristes name I cumand &thorn;e</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou noght forsake me,</L>
<L>Bot lat me with &thorn;e suffer dede!"</L>
<L>&THORN;an saint Laurence in &thorn;at stede</L>
<L N="215">Toke clere water of &thorn;e brim</L>
<L>And blisced it and baptist him,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H bliscedit.</NOTE></L>
<L>And bad him be bousom and baine</L>
<L>For Cristes sake to suffur payne.</L>
<L>And Romane hight with hertte glad</L>
<L N="220">To do bousumly als he bad.</L>
<L>Wen Decius herd &thorn;ir dedes bidene,<NOTE PLACE="foot">T when.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;an in his hert he had grete tene,</L>
<L>And als smertly &thorn;are in stede</L>
<L>He demed Romane to be dede.</L>
<L N="225">&THORN;ai harled him out of toun in hy</L>
<L>And strake &thorn;e heuid fra his body.</L>
<L>So was he made a ma(r)ter clene<NOTE PLACE="foot">H mater.</NOTE></L>
<L>And went to heuin with-owten wene.</L>
<L>When he &thorn;us unto ded was broght,</L>
<L N="230">Decius &thorn;an him umbi-thoght</L>
<L>How saint Laurence munde be schent.</L>
<L>And hastily efter him he sent,</L>
<L>He bad &thorn;am bring him him to.</L>
<L>And &thorn;an was Ipolit ful wo,</L>
<L N="235">And sare wepeand with drery chere</L>
<L>He said to him on &thorn;is manere:</L>
</LG>
<P>Quare non uociferor ego?</P>
<LG>
<L>"Whi am I noght cald to kum</L>
<L>With &thorn;e to tak marterdom,</L>
<L>Sen I am a cristen man?</L>
<L N="240">Whi sal I noght wend with &thorn;e &thorn;an?"</L>
<L>Saint Laurence said: "lat be &thorn;i care,</L>
<L>Mak gude chere and murn nomare!</L>
<L>Bot pray to Crist in preuete,</L>
<L>And of his grace he sall gif &thorn;e,</L>
<L N="245">And se&thorn;in he sall efter &thorn;e send,</L>
<L>To won in welth with-outen end".</L>
<L>To Decius &thorn;an was Laurence led,</L>
<L>Omang his enmis straytly sted.</L>
<L>And bifor Decius war broght</L>
<L N="250">Sere turmentries, al newly wroght:</L>
<L>Plummes of lede at battes grete,</L>
<L>And iren plates redy to hete,</L>
<L>Cambes and pin(n)es, scharp puruaid,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H pines, T scheint pines zu l.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ane iren bed, on to be laid &mdash;</L>
<L N="255">&THORN;at was a roftiren, lang and grete &mdash;</L>
<L>With mani staues, on him to bete,</L>
<L>Forkes of iren and kobilstanes &mdash;</L>
<L>Al &thorn;is was &thorn;are broght at anes.
<PB REF="00000249.tif" N="111"></L>
<L>Decius &thorn;an to Laurence said:</L>
<L N="260">"Al &thorn;is gere &thorn;at here es graid,</L>
<L>In &thorn;i body sal be spend,</L>
<L>Or &thorn;is night be broght till end,</L>
<L>Bot if &thorn;ou on oure goddes trow</L>
<L>And honore &thorn;am and to &thorn;am bow.</L>
<L N="265">And &thorn;arfore leue &thorn;i fals bileue,<MILESTONE N="170" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And &thorn;an sal no-man do &thorn;e greue;</L>
<L>And bot &thorn;ou do, all &thorn;is night lang</L>
<L>Saltou suffer paynes strang</L>
<L>And euer pas fra pain to paine".</L>
<L N="270">&THORN;an saint Laurence said ogayne:</L>
<L>"My night, he said, has no mirknes,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H mirkines.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bot in ay lastand light (it) es;<NOTE PLACE="foot">T it, fehlt in H.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;arfore I drede &thorn;i pain no-thing".</L>
<L>&THORN;an Decius thoght grete hething</L>
<L N="275">&THORN;at Laurence was noght for him rad,</L>
<L>And to his turmentoures he bad</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ai suld tak kobill-stane</L>
<L>And ding his teth out al at anes.</L>
<L>And when &thorn;ai with &thorn;e stanes him dang,</L>
<L N="280">He stode ay laghand &thorn;am omang,</L>
<L>Als he war of &thorn;aire play wele paid,</L>
<L>And unto god al&thorn;us he saide:</L>
</LG>
<P>Gracias ago tibi, domine.</P>
<LG>
<L>"Lord, I loue &thorn;e of &thorn;i grace</L>
<L>&THORN;at unto me &thorn;ir mirthes mase,</L>
<L N="285">For &thorn;ou es god ouer alkins thing.</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e, lord, be ay loueing!"</L>
<L>&THORN;an Decius saw al was in uayne</L>
<L>And &thorn;at he sett noght bi his paine:</L>
<L>"Biliue, he said, do here be broght</L>
<L N="290">&THORN;e bed of iren &thorn;at ze haue wroght!</L>
<L>And &thorn;aron sall he lig and rest,</L>
<L>Vntill his hert for bales brest".</L>
<L>&THORN;an &thorn;e bed &thorn;ai brog(ht) furth right</L>
<L>And set it bifore Decius sight.</L>
<L N="295">Thre sides endlang had it &thorn;an,</L>
<L>Ilkane of &thorn;e lenkith of a man,</L>
<L>And ouer-thewert with barres brade &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;us als a rostiren was it made.</L>
<L>Saint Laurence was made naked &thorn;an</L>
<L N="300">Bifor Decius and Valirian,</L>
<L>And with sere paynes turment fast,</L>
<L>And seyn on &thorn;e rostiren cast</L>
<L>And bun &thorn;arto with iren bandes,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he suld noght stir fete ne handes.</L>
<L N="305">With iren forkes &thorn;ai made &thorn;e fire,</L>
<L>And stabbed &thorn;am depe in his lire;</L>
<L>Sum of &thorn;am blew on sides sere</L>
<L>With belows, for it suld brin clere;</L>
<L>So &thorn;ai made &thorn;e fire so strang,</L>
<L N="310">&THORN;at none of &thorn;am might nere it gang.</L>
<L>&THORN;an was Decius wele paid</L>
<L>And to saint Laurence &thorn;us he said:</L>
<L>"Unto oure goddes mak sacrafise!"</L>
<L>Saint Laurence answerd on &thorn;is wise:</L>
<L N="315">"Mi-self in ofrand here I make</L>
<L>And in sacrafise for goddes sake:<NOTE PLACE="foot">T godes.</NOTE></L>
<L>For sacrafice to Jhesu dere</L>
<L>Er spirites &thorn;at er turment here.</L>
<L>Wreche, he said, &thorn;ou mai be balde</L>
<L N="320">&THORN;at &thorn;i coles unto (me) er calde;<NOTE PLACE="foot">me fehlt in T u. H.</NOTE></L>
<L>Vnto me &thorn;ai gif keleing,</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e hete with-outen ending:</L>
<L>&THORN;at es to say, &thorn;e fire of hell</L>
<L>Whare &thorn;ou sall with &thorn;i deuils dwell".</L>
<L N="325">&THORN;an Decius for wrath wex all wan.<NOTE PLACE="foot">T al.</NOTE></L>
<L>And to him said Valirian:</L>
<L>"Whare es &thorn;at fire, &thorn;is wald I craue,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou hetes vs forto haue?"</L>
<L>Saint Laurence answerd &thorn;an in hy:</L>
<L N="330">"Ze waful wreches and unhappy,</L>
<L>In zowre hertes may ze trow</L>
<L>&THORN;at bath unto zowre goddes and zow<NOTE PLACE="foot">H geddes.</NOTE></L>
<L>Es ordand a fire with &thorn;e fende,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ay sall brin and neuer ende".<NOTE PLACE="foot">H brind, T brin.</NOTE></L>
<L N="335">&THORN;an all &thorn;e folk &thorn;at obout stode</L>
<L>Had mekill meruaile in &thorn;aire mode<NOTE PLACE="foot">H haud st. had; meruailein in.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of &thorn;e Emperoure werkes wikk<NOTE PLACE="foot">T wik.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at gert Laurence be rosted al quik.</L>
<L>Saint Laurence lay with laghand chere</L>
<L N="340">And said to god on &thorn;is manere:</L>
<L>"Of all &thorn;i lane, lord, loue I &thorn;e</L>
<L>&THORN;a(t) &thorn;us vouchessaue to comfort me".<NOTE PLACE="foot">T u. H &thorn;a st. &thorn;at. T vowchessaue.</NOTE></L>
<L>He lifted his eghen vnto Jhesus
<PB REF="00000250.tif" N="112"></L>
<L>And &thorn;us he spak to Decius:</L>
<L N="345">"Lo, wreche, he said, now may &thorn;ou se</L>
<L>&THORN;e ta side es rosted of me.</L>
<L>Turn &thorn;at now &thorn;at rostes les,</L>
<L>And ett of &thorn;at &thorn;at rosted es!</L>
<L>For me saltou neuer mak untrew</L>
<L N="350">In &thorn;e trowth of mi lord Jhesu".</L>
<L>&THORN;an eft-sones saint Laurence praied</L>
<L>Vnto Jhesu and &thorn;us said:</L>
<L>"I loue &thorn;e, lord in maieste,</L>
<L>For I am worthi to haue entre<NOTE PLACE="foot">H wrothi.</NOTE></L>
<L N="355">At heuyn zates w(h)are mirth es maste".<NOTE PLACE="foot">H wisare st. whare.</NOTE></L>
<L>And with &thorn;is worde he gaf &thorn;e gaste.</L>
<L>When Decius wist &thorn;at he was dede,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H whem. T ded.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;an past he sone out of &thorn;at stede</L>
<L>And toke Valirian him till,</L>
<L N="360">And left &thorn;e body ligan still<NOTE PLACE="foot">H ligan, T ligand?</NOTE></L>
<L>On &thorn;e rostiren with coles blake.</L>
<L>And noman durst it &thorn;e&thorn;in take.</L>
<L>Vntill &thorn;e morn &thorn;at Ipolit</L>
<L>Sent word untill a preste ful tyte,</L>
<L N="365">&THORN;at Iustine hight, and tald (him) how<NOTE PLACE="foot">T him, fehlt in H.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;is dekin was ded now</L>
<L>And how &thorn;e body lay &thorn;are still.</L>
<L>&THORN;an Iustine come ful sone him till</L>
<L>And helpid him &thorn;e cors to graue.</L>
<L N="370">&THORN;aire mede in heuin ful wele &thorn;ai hawe.<NOTE PLACE="foot">T haue.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at mede god grante vs, man and child,</L>
<L>Thrught praier of his moder mild!<NOTE PLACE="foot">T thrugh, milde.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="23" TYPE="legend">
<HEAD>23. Assumpcio beate Marie virginis.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>S. Tib. fol. 255a2&mdash;258. I T Mary.</P></HEADNOTE>
<DIV3 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Of Mari milde now will I mene,</L>
<L>&THORN;at of all heuyns es corond quene<NOTE PLACE="foot">T al.</NOTE></L>
<L>And lady of all erth to tell<NOTE PLACE="foot">T al.</NOTE></L>
<L>And also Emperise of hell.</L>
<L N="5">Forto bigin now am I boun</L>
<L>Of hir haly assumpsioune,</L>
<L>How scho was tane to heuin on hight</L>
<L>And lendes euer in lastand light.</L>
<L>When Jhesus Crist had sufferd payne,</L>
<L N="10">Was resin and went to heuin ogayne:</L>
<L>Grete murnig made his moder milde<NOTE PLACE="foot">H murnig, T murn|ing.</NOTE></L>
<L>For missing of hir mightful schilde.<NOTE PLACE="foot">T childe.</NOTE></L>
<L>Scho and saint John, Cristes cosin dere,</L>
<L>Dwelled in &thorn;e temple bath in-fere,</L>
<L N="15">With o&thorn;er also of hir kin,</L>
<L>&amp; many seke men dwellid &thorn;arin.</L>
<L>Scho serued bath to seke and hale</L>
<L>And was ful boun to bete &thorn;aire bale,</L>
<L>Wilfuli to wasche and wring<NOTE PLACE="foot">T wilfully.</NOTE></L>
<L N="20">And in &thorn;aire beddes &thorn;am for to bring.</L>
<L>And euer scho thinkes euyn and morn</L>
<L>On Jhesus &thorn;at was of hir born;</L>
<L>And he sent oft angels hir till</L>
<L>To comfort hir, als was his will.</L>
<L N="25">Saint Jon euer was with her nere</L>
<L>And zemid hir als his moder dere &mdash;</L>
<L>For of hir had he tane kepeing,</L>
<L>When Crist opon &thorn;e rode gan hing.</L>
<L>&THORN;arfor to hir he toke entent<NOTE PLACE="foot">T &thorn;arfore.</NOTE></L>
<L N="30">And with hir was, ware so scho went.</L>
<L>And when &thorn;e daies war broght till ende</L>
<L>&THORN;at Mari of &thorn;is werld suld wende:</L>
<L>Crist sent hir angels doun fra heuyn,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H angels (T?) st. an angel.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at till hir said with milde steuyn:</L>
<L N="35">"Mari mild, now mak gude chere!</L>
<L>I am &thorn;i suns awin messangere,</L>
<L>Fra heuyn &thorn;us am I cumen to &thorn;e.</L>
<L>My lord gretes &thorn;e wele by me,
<PB REF="00000251.tif" N="113"></L>
<L>And here a palme he has &thorn;e sent &mdash;</L>
<L N="40">Takit of me with gude entent!</L>
<L>Als takining to &thorn;e es it send,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H send, d aus t corr.</NOTE></L>
<L>For &thorn;ou sal here no langer lend.<NOTE PLACE="foot">T sall.</NOTE></L>
<L>He wate wele &thorn;at it es &thorn;i will</L>
<L>And &thorn;i zernig, to cum him till;<NOTE PLACE="foot">H T zernig.</NOTE></L>
<L N="45">&THORN;arfore he will send efter &thorn;e</L>
<L>Ful sone with angels grete plente<NOTE PLACE="foot">H wist st. with.</NOTE></L>
<L>And bring &thorn;e unto endles blis,</L>
<L>Whare &thorn;ou of mirth sal neuer mis.</L>
<L>And all &thorn;e angels think ful lang</L>
<L N="50">Till-tyme &thorn;at &thorn;ou be us omang.</L>
<L>And &thorn;arfore, lady, redy &thorn;e,<NOTE PLACE="foot">redy ist Verb = paratum facere (so &ouml;fter).</NOTE></L>
<L>For here saltou noght ful lang be!"</L>
<L>&THORN;an said &thorn;e maiden, mekill of might,</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;at angell schineand bright:<NOTE PLACE="foot">H briught.</NOTE></L>
<L N="55">"Sen &thorn;at my sun has sent me till,</L>
<L>He&thorn;in to wende, als es his will:</L>
<L>Can &thorn;ou oght tell me, I &thorn;e pray,</L>
<L>If he settes any sertain day,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at I may my frendes warn,</L>
<L N="60">Sen I &thorn;aire cumpani sall tharn?"</L>
<L>&THORN;an said &thorn;e angell: "trow &thorn;ou me,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou sall bide here bot daies thre;</L>
<L>On &thorn;e thrid day &thorn;ou sall be fett</L>
<L>With angels and by &thorn;i sun sett.</L>
<L N="65">&THORN;is palme to taken I haue &thorn;e broght,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou sall trow and dowt it noght".</L>
<L>&THORN;an said &thorn;e laydy faire and fre:<NOTE PLACE="foot">H laydy, T lady, so auch 182.</NOTE></L>
<L>"My sun mot loued be and blisced be<NOTE PLACE="foot">Das I. be ist zu tilgen (T?).</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at swilk message wald send me till!</L>
<L N="70">I sal be redy at his will,</L>
<L>Forto fulfyll al his entent".</L>
<L>&THORN;e angel &thorn;an to heuyn es went.</L>
<L>Mari toke &thorn;an &thorn;e palme in hand</L>
<L>And thanked hir sun of his sand.<NOTE PLACE="foot">T sande.</NOTE></L>
<L N="75">Sone scho went untill hir bed<NOTE PLACE="foot">bed = bedroom.</NOTE></L>
<L>And of hir clathes scho hir uncled,</L>
<L>Of scho did al hir atyre,</L>
<L>And wesche hir clene in water schire;</L>
<L>And when scho had on &thorn;at wise done,</L>
<L N="80">A-no&thorn;er wede scho did hir one.</L>
<L>So when scho was all new araid,<MILESTONE N="171" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Vnto Jhesu, hir sun, scho praid:</L>
<L>"Son, scho said, I thank it &thorn;e</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou will &thorn;us think on me.</L>
<L N="85">And als &thorn;ou chese to be my childe,</L>
<L>I pray &thorn;e now, fra schame (me) schilde,<NOTE PLACE="foot">me fehlt in T u. H.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e fende haue now no might</L>
<L>Me forto dere by day ne nigh(t);</L>
<L>And, dere son, when I ded sal be,</L>
<L N="90">Saue me, &thorn;at I noght him se &mdash;</L>
<L>For he es glad men saule to greue</L>
<L>And to bring men in misbileue!</L>
<L>And, my dere sun, suffer him noght</L>
<L>Descame &thorn;am &thorn;at &thorn;ou dere has boght;</L>
<L N="95">Bot of man-kind &thorn;ou haue pete</L>
<L>For &thorn;e luf &thorn;ou aw to me,</L>
<L>And fra &thorn;e fende &thorn;ou &thorn;am defend,</L>
<L>And len &thorn;am so &thorn;aire mis to mend,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ai may wende, sun, at &thorn;i will</L>
<L N="100">Vnto &thorn;e blis &thorn;ou boght &thorn;am till!"</L>
<L>When Mary &thorn;us had m(a)de hir bone,</L>
<L>Vntill hir frendes went scho sone</L>
<L>And unto hir kinsmen al-so,</L>
<L>And on &thorn;is wise scho tald &thorn;am to:</L>
<L N="105">"Dere frendes, scho said, my son</L>
<L>Will, I no langer with zow won;</L>
<L>In blis with him he will I be.</L>
<L>&THORN;arfore I pray par charite:</L>
<L>If I haue trispast oght zow till,</L>
<L N="110">&THORN;at ze forgif me with gude will,</L>
<L>And at my migh(t) I will it mend".</L>
<L>&THORN;arto &thorn;an held scho up hir hend</L>
<L>And praied god to zelde &thorn;am sone</L>
<L>All &thorn;e gude &thorn;ai had hir done.</L>
<L N="115">&THORN;an all hir frendes, &thorn;at war hir by,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;is ti&thorn;inges war sary;</L>
<L>All-if &thorn;ai wist scho went to blis,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai murned, for &thorn;ai suld hir mis.</L>
<L>"Lady, &thorn;ai said, how sall we do</L>
<L N="120">Or fare, if &thorn;at &thorn;ou founde us fro?</L>
<L>Dere lady, &thorn;ai said, turn &thorn;i thoght!</L>
<L>Lif here with us and leue us noght!</L>
<L>For till us has &thorn;ou serued swa:</L>
<L>If we &thorn;e want, us mun be wa".
<PB REF="00000252.tif" N="114"></L>
<L N="125">&THORN;e maiden &thorn;an spac &thorn;am untill:</L>
<L>"Leues zowre murnig and be still,</L>
<L>And makes all solace, for my sake,</L>
<L>For &thorn;e ioy &thorn;at I sall take!</L>
<L>And dred ze for me neuer a dele!</L>
<L N="130">For hard paines sall I none fele,</L>
<L>And my sune wele will me were</L>
<L>&THORN;at no deuils sall do me dere;<NOTE PLACE="foot">T sal.</NOTE></L>
<L>Unto blis will him-self me fetche,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at no doles ne sall me dretche".</L>
<L N="135">Als Mari spak &thorn;us with hir kin,</L>
<L>Saint Jon, hir keper, &thorn;an come in.</L>
<L>He saw &thorn;am al lat sarili,</L>
<L>And grete meruail he had for&thorn;i &mdash;</L>
<L>For in &thorn;at time zit wist he noght</L>
<L N="140">Of &thorn;e bodword, &thorn;e angell broght.<NOTE PLACE="foot">T angel.</NOTE></L>
<L>He said: "lady, wat ailes &thorn;e?</L>
<L>And what es &thorn;is &thorn;at I here se?</L>
<L>Tel me, lady, in &thorn;is stede! &mdash;</L>
<L>For me war lewer to be ded<NOTE PLACE="foot">T leuer.</NOTE></L>
<L N="145">&THORN;an &thorn;ou suld suffer any sch(ame),<NOTE PLACE="foot">T u. H sch. ., nicht ausgeschr.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wharfor mi lord might me blame".<NOTE PLACE="foot">T wharfore.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;an Mary till him gan hir mene &mdash;</L>
<L>Ful trew luf was &thorn;am bitwene &mdash;</L>
<L>"Jon, scho said, I sall &thorn;e neuyn:</L>
<L N="150">Jhesus, mi sun, &thorn;at wons in heuyn,</L>
<L>To me has sent a messangere:</L>
<L>He will no langer &thorn;at I won here &mdash;</L>
<L>And, sertes, and I durst say for sin,</L>
<L>Me rewes &thorn;at we twa sal twin.</L>
<L N="155">Bot, als mi sun sendes efter me,</L>
<L>So wate I wele he will for &thorn;e &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;is hardily I dar &thorn;e hete;</L>
<L>&THORN;arfore be mery, till we mete &mdash;</L>
<L>My sun ful wele wil quite &thorn;e</L>
<L N="160">&THORN;e seruise, &thorn;ou has done to me.</L>
<L>And, Jon, of o thing I &thorn;e pray:</L>
<L>When my saul es he&thorn;in oway,</L>
<L>Lat noght my famen cum &thorn;at while</L>
<L>Mi body here forto reuile!</L>
<L N="165">For unto me &thorn;ai haue enuy &mdash;</L>
<L>And &thorn;at, me think, es no ferly:</L>
<L>How su(l)d &thorn;ai bot &thorn;ai hated me<NOTE PLACE="foot">H sud.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at hanged mi sun on a tre?</L>
<L>&THORN;arfor I drede: when I am gane,</L>
<L N="170">&THORN;at mi body bese fra zo tane<NOTE PLACE="foot">H zo, T &yogh;ow.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;arto done sum despite;</L>
<L>For &thorn;e iews luf me so lite".</L>
<L>Saint Jon said: "we sall &thorn;e zeme,</L>
<L>&THORN;at noman sal &thorn;e fra us fleme.</L>
<L N="175">Bot, dere lady, sen it es so</L>
<L>&THORN;at we most nedes part in two:</L>
<L>Sai me, when he has set &thorn;e tyme,</L>
<L>&THORN;i sun, &thorn;at &thorn;ou sal wend to him?"</L>
<L>"Jon, scho said, &thorn;ou sall me se</L>
<L N="180">Here in &thorn;is liue bot daies thre".</L>
<L>&THORN;an wepe saint Jon with hert sare</L>
<L>And said: "laydy, how sall I fare?</L>
<L>Wha sall me wis, when &thorn;ou es dede?</L>
<L>Now mun I be full will of rede".</L>
<L N="185">Scho said: "Jon, wepe noght, bot be still!</L>
<L>Mi sun sall send angels &thorn;e till</L>
<L>To wis &thorn;e, whare &thorn;ow sall wende,</L>
<L>And to defend &thorn;e fra &thorn;e fende;</L>
<L>And I sall pray unto my sun</L>
<L N="190">&THORN;at &thorn;ou sall kum and with us won".</L>
<L>Whils Mari spac &thorn;us to saint Jon,</L>
<L>In come &thorn;e appostels euer-ilkone.</L>
</LG>
<P>Appostoli in vnum sunt congregati.</P>
<LG>
<L>All att anes come &thorn;ai home,</L>
<L>And noman wist of o&thorn;er come,</L>
<L N="195">For ilkane come fra fere cuntre &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at was a wonder sight to se &mdash;</L>
<L>And none of &thorn;am of o&thorn;er wist.</L>
<L>&THORN;an ilkone of &thorn;am o&thorn;er kist;</L>
<L>Ful faine ilkone of o&thorn;er was,</L>
<L N="200">All sayd &thorn;ai deo gracias.</L>
<L>Ful glad &thorn;an was oure lady</L>
<L>Of &thorn;at blissed cumpani.</L>
<L>And saint Jon said with hert fre:<NOTE PLACE="foot">T wit.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Lord, loueing mot to &thorn;e be,</L>
<L N="205">&THORN;at &thorn;us has &thorn;ine apostels send</L>
<L>To zeme &thorn;i moder at hir end</L>
<L>And to comfort hir in &thorn;is case &mdash;</L>
<L>Sen ilkone war now in sere place".</L>
<L>&THORN;an said saint Peter till saint Jone:</L>
<L N="210">"Whi semes &thorn;ou so sari man?
<PB REF="00000253.tif" N="115"></L>
<L>Me think &thorn;ou suld &thorn;e merier be,</L>
<L>Sen we er cumen all unto &thorn;e".</L>
<L>&THORN;an said saint Jon: "I sall say &thorn;e.</L>
<L>Bot first I pray &thorn;e, tell &thorn;ou me</L>
<L N="215">How &thorn;at ze war heder led</L>
<L>&THORN;at war all in sere cuntrese spred".</L>
<L>Saint Peter said: "so mot I the,</L>
<L>I was in a ful fer cuntre</L>
<L>And prechid &thorn;e folk of &thorn;e land.</L>
<L N="220">Haldand mi boke in my hand:</L>
<L>And heder come I soday(n)ly &mdash;</L>
<L>And on what maner, wate noght I".</L>
<L>&THORN;us &thorn;an said &thorn;ai al in-fere:</L>
<L>How ilkone was in landes sere</L>
<L N="225">And none of &thorn;am kouth think in thoght<NOTE PLACE="foot2">H kuouth.</NOTE></L>
<L>On what wise &thorn;ai war &thorn;eder broght.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">H wath, T what.</NOTE></L>
<L>When saint Jone al &thorn;aire wordes herd,</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;am &thorn;us he answerd:</L>
<L>"Listens now a wonder thing:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">H word, T wonder.</NOTE></L>
<L N="230">&THORN;is es &thorn;e cause of zowre cuming.</L>
<L>Oure lady, &thorn;e moder of Jhesus,</L>
<L>Ordans hir to wend fra us:</L>
<L>Oure lord, hir sun, has for hir send,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at scho may no langer lend;</L>
<L N="235">And sertes it es his will &thorn;at we</L>
<L>Al samyn at hir biring be.</L>
<L>&THORN;arfore to hir now will we wende,</L>
<L>&amp; hailses hir with wordes hende!"</L>
<L>Sone &thorn;ai did als saint Jon bad,</L>
<L N="240">And of &thorn;aire come was scho ful glad.</L>
<L>"Lady, &thorn;ai said, loued mot &thorn;ou be!</L>
<L>&THORN;i sun &thorn;us has vs sent to &thorn;e</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e forto tak entent</L>
<L>And to be at &thorn;ine enterment".</L>
<L N="245">&THORN;an answerd scho to &thorn;am ilkane:</L>
<L>"I loue mi sun of all his lane.</L>
<L>And hertly pray I zow of &thorn;is:</L>
<L>When I am went to heuyn blis,</L>
<L>Zemes my body, if ze may,</L>
<L N="250">&THORN;at &thorn;e iews stele it noght oway!<NOTE PLACE="foot2">H steleit (it ist &ouml;fter an d. Verb gebunden).</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ai wil it brin and do it schame.</L>
<L>Bot, Jhesus, for &thorn;i haly name</L>
<L>Lat &thorn;am neuer &thorn;e body brin</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e liked to lig in!"</L>
<L N="255">Ane angell &thorn;an biside hir light</L>
<L>And said to hir &thorn;ir wordes right:</L>
<L>"Mari, no-thing drede &thorn;ou &thorn;e!</L>
<L>&THORN;i bone es herd of Jhesu fre.</L>
<L>&THORN;e iws sal haue no maistri</L>
<L N="260">Of &thorn;e, ne none &thorn;at es &thorn;e bi.</L>
<L>Drede &thorn;e noght bi night ne day!"</L>
<L>And with &thorn;at word he went oway.</L>
</LG>
<P>Migracio Marie de mundo.</P>
<LG>
<L>On &thorn;e thrid day, als Crist puruaid,</L>
<L>Oure lady on hir bed her laid,</L>
<L N="265">And &thorn;e appostels in &thorn;at tide</L>
<L>Sat obut on ilka side</L>
<L>And made &thorn;aire prayers in &thorn;at place,</L>
<L>Bideand &thorn;e come of goddes grace.</L>
<L>Obout &thorn;e midday it bifell:</L>
<L N="270">Omang &thorn;am come so nobill smell<MILESTONE N="172" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And so swete noise, &thorn;at none tok kepe,</L>
<L>Bot hastili all fell in slepe.</L>
<L>&THORN;an Mari bad &thorn;e apostels wake:</L>
<L>And so &thorn;ai did all for hir sake.</L>
<L N="275">Sum of hir kin also scho cald</L>
<L>And bad &thorn;ai suld &thorn;am wakeand hald:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">H wake and.</NOTE></L>
<L>"&THORN;e time es cumen, sone sall I wende</L>
<L>Vnto welth with-outen ende."</L>
<L>Scho toke &thorn;e palme &thorn;at Crist had sent,</L>
<L N="280">And gaf it Jon with gude entent:</L>
<L>"Jon, scho said, &thorn;is gif I the,</L>
<L>For &thorn;ou has wele zemed me.</L>
<L>Bere it with &thorn;e, whare &thorn;ou gase:</L>
<L>It sall defend &thorn;e fra &thorn;i fase."</L>
<L N="285">Jon toke &thorn;e palme &thorn;an als werede<NOTE PLACE="foot1">werede dulce, ags. weorede.</NOTE></L>
<L>And thanked hir of all gude dede.</L>
<L>&THORN;an come Jhesus, hir sun mighty,</L>
<L>And broght with him grete kumpani</L>
<L>Of angels and of saintes sere,</L>
<L N="290">&THORN;at folowd him ful faire in-fere<NOTE PLACE="foot2">H fere st. fere.</NOTE></L>
<L>With mekill mirth of munstralsy &mdash;</L>
<L>Herd neuer man slike melody.</L>
<L>Ful mekill mirth had Mari milde,</L>
<L>When scho saw hir semly childe,</L>
<L N="295">Scho said: "sun, blisced mot &thorn;ou be,</L>
<L>&THORN;at uowches safe to uisit me!</L>
<L>&THORN;e time be blisced, euyn and morn,
<PB REF="00000254.tif" N="116"></L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou was of mi body born!"</L>
<L>Vnto hir &thorn;an said Jhesu fre:</L>
<L N="300">"Moder, blith now loke &thorn;ou be</L>
<L>And of no thing haue &thorn;ou no drede!</L>
<L>For with mi-self I sall &thorn;e lede;</L>
<L>Whare I am king, &thorn;ou sall be quene,</L>
<L>With more blis &thorn;an men may mene.</L>
<L N="305">And be noght ferd in &thorn;i passing,</L>
<L>For &thorn;ou sal se none euil thing &mdash;</L>
<L>Of no thing sall tou se ne here</L>
<L>Bot of me and mine angels clere.</L>
<L>And, moder, for &thorn;e luf of &thorn;e</L>
<L N="310">I sall haue mercy and pete</L>
<L>Of all man-kind, for &thorn;i prayere,<NOTE PLACE="foot">T al.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at suld be lorn, if &thorn;ou ne were;</L>
<L>And wha &thorn;e honors in word or dede,</L>
<L>Of me sall &thorn;ai haue &thorn;aire mede."</L>
<L N="315">&THORN;an said Mari, his moder fre:</L>
<L>"Of all sons blisced mot &thorn;ou be,</L>
<L>And blisced be &thorn;e time, euin and morn,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou was of my body born!"</L>
<L>&THORN;an lifted he his haly hand<NOTE PLACE="foot">T hay st. haly.</NOTE></L>
<L N="320">And blisced hir, als alweldand.</L>
<L>&THORN;an cald he Mighell him unto</L>
<L>And said him how &thorn;at he suld do:</L>
<L>"&THORN;ou, and &thorn;i felaus all infere,</L>
<L>Luke ze zeme wele my moder dere!"</L>
<L N="325">&THORN;an scho transed &thorn;are als fast,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e saul fra &thorn;e body past.</L>
<L>And angels war &thorn;are ful redy</L>
<L>To kepe hir in &thorn;air company,</L>
<L>And bare hir saul to blis of heuin,<NOTE PLACE="foot">T bare, H bere.</NOTE></L>
<L N="330">With more mirth &thorn;an men mai neuyn.</L>
<L>And hastili when scho come &thorn;are,</L>
<L>Al &thorn;e saintes &thorn;at &thorn;ar ware</L>
<L>Honord hir halely bidene,</L>
<L>And &thorn;are &thorn;an was scho corond que(ne).<NOTE PLACE="foot">T u. H que.</NOTE></L>
<L N="335">And with hir sun so &thorn;are scho dwells</L>
<L>Obouen al halows and angels.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="section">
<HEAD>De corpore beate Marie virginis.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>When Mari saul, als I said are,<NOTE PLACE="foot">in H u. T ist an Mari es ausrad.</NOTE></L>
<L>Was redy unto heuyn at fare,</L>
<L>&THORN;an to saint Peter said Jhesus:</L>
<L N="340">"Peter, he said, I bid &thorn;e &thorn;us,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou zeme wele on al manere<NOTE PLACE="foot">T all.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e body of mi moder dere.</L>
<L>Of hir body was I born,</L>
<L>For-&thorn;i I will noght, it be lorn</L>
<L N="345">Ne &thorn;at none do it velany.</L>
<L>&THORN;arfore vnto &thorn;e cumand I,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou tak &thorn;i felaws al to &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">T all.</NOTE></L>
<L>And help hir body to beried be;<NOTE PLACE="foot">H bereed.</NOTE></L>
<L>To &thorn;e vale of Josaphath ze wend</L>
<L N="350">And beri hir &thorn;are with zowre hend,</L>
<L>And gose with faire processioune</L>
<L>Thurgh Jherusalems toune;</L>
<L>Sing ze sall on faire manere,</L>
<L>And foure of zou sal bere &thorn;e bere!</L>
<L N="355">And of none enmise drede haue ze,</L>
<L>For I sal all-way with zow be,</L>
<L>And fra all wathes I sall zow were,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at none enmis sall zow dere."</L>
<L>&THORN;an gaf he &thorn;am all his blissing</L>
<L N="360">And went to heuyn, whare he es king.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai gederd samin with hert glad</L>
<L>And toke &thorn;e bere, als he &thorn;am bad,</L>
<L>And bare it thurgh &thorn;e cete</L>
<L>With ful grete solempnite,</L>
<L N="365">With tapers and with torches clere,</L>
<L>Ilk man on &thorn;aire best manere;</L>
<L>With &thorn;am went many of hir kin</L>
<L>And all hir frendes, more and min.</L>
<L>&THORN;e iewes, when &thorn;ai herd &thorn;is sang,</L>
<L N="370">Asked ilkaman o&thorn;er omang,</L>
<L>Wat was al &thorn;at din bidene<NOTE PLACE="foot">T what.</NOTE></L>
<L>And what &thorn;at mekill noise might mene.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai said, &thorn;e appostels all in-fere</L>
<L>Bare Mari body opon a bere.</L>
<L N="375">&THORN;an iewes war wonder tene</L>
<L>And &thorn;us-gat said &thorn;ai all bi-dene:</L>
<L>"Allas, &thorn;ai said, for werldes schame!</L>
<L>And scho be biried, we er to blame!<NOTE PLACE="foot">H birred.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ilk man tak wapin strang,</L>
<L N="380">And gowe tak &thorn;am als &thorn;ai gang</L>
<L>And cast &thorn;am ilk-one in &thorn;e mire</L>
<L>And brin &thorn;e body in a fire!
<PB REF="00000255.tif" N="117"></L>
<L>For sertes, it war a scorn &thorn;at we</L>
<L>Suld suffer hir grauen to be."</L>
<L N="385">&THORN;an went &thorn;ai furth with grete enuy</L>
<L>And laid hand on &thorn;e bere in hi,</L>
<L>To draw it doune vnto &thorn;e grownd.</L>
<L>Bot god toke vengance in &thorn;at stound:</L>
<L>On &thorn;e ihews he tok slike wreke,</L>
<L N="390">&THORN;at sum might nower gang ne speke.<NOTE PLACE="foot">l. no&thorn;er?</NOTE></L>
<L>And a prince was &thorn;are of &thorn;aire lau<NOTE PLACE="foot">T law,</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at said he suld &thorn;e bere doun drau.<NOTE PLACE="foot">draw.</NOTE></L>
<L>And sone when he his hend on kast,</L>
<L>He might nogh(t) stir, bot stac &thorn;are fast;</L>
<L N="395">He rared &thorn;an with rewful chere</L>
<L>And said to Peter on &thorn;is manere:</L>
<L>"Peter, he said, thinkes &thorn;ou noght,</L>
<L>When we had &thorn;i maister broght</L>
<L>To Kayphas hall, fain was &thorn;ow &thorn;are</L>
<L N="400">To say &thorn;ou saw him neuer are;</L>
<L>And, had I noght helpid &thorn;e &thorn;an,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou had bene schent with mani man.</L>
<L>And sen &thorn;at I &thorn;an helpid &thorn;e,</L>
<L>Now suld &thorn;ou haue sum minde on me</L>
<L N="405">And pray &thorn;i maister for mi sake</L>
<L>&THORN;at he on me tak no wrake!"</L>
<L>&THORN;an said Peter to him ogaine:</L>
<L>"&THORN;i spekeing es hali in uaine;</L>
<L>We may tent till nane o&thorn;er thing</L>
<L N="410">Bot bring &thorn;is body till bering.</L>
<L>And, sir, bot &thorn;ou will trow trewly</L>
<L>&THORN;at Jhesus es god all-mighty</L>
<L>And of &thorn;is ilk body was born,</L>
<L>To saue man-kynd &thorn;at was forlorn,</L>
<L N="415">And &thorn;at him liked to lyght hir in,</L>
<L>And scho maiden with-owten sin &mdash;</L>
<L>And ask him help with hert and hend:</L>
<L>Els may here noman &thorn;e amend."</L>
</LG>
<P>Fergus conuersus &amp; baptizatus est.</P>
<LG>
<L>&THORN;an &thorn;e iew to Crist gan cri:</L>
<L N="420">"I do me, lord, in &thorn;i mercy,</L>
<L>And in &thorn;e will I trewly trow,</L>
<L>Lord, and &thorn;ow will help me now."<NOTE PLACE="foot">T &thorn;ou.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;an son bigan he forto mend</L>
<L>And wex hale bath of hert and hend;</L>
<L N="425">He &thorn;at first was halt and lame,</L>
<L>Bigan &thorn;an to preche Jhesu name.</L>
<L>Saint Peter, when he saw his chere,</L>
<L>Baptist him in water clere</L>
<L>And bad him preche with gude entent</L>
<L N="430">Goddes word, whare so he went.</L>
<L>And for he was a maister man,</L>
<L>Baldly to preche he bygan,</L>
<L>And he turned &thorn;at ilk day</L>
<L>Threty thowsand to Cristes lay.</L>
<L N="435">Saint Peter and &thorn;e appostels in-fere<NOTE PLACE="foot">H he st. &thorn;e.</NOTE></L>
<L>Went furth singand with &thorn;e bere.</L>
<L>To Jos(a)phath &thorn;ai come onane</L>
<L>And berid &thorn;e body under a stane.</L>
<L>&THORN;ar war ful many meruailes wroght</L>
<L N="440">Of sere men &thorn;at &thorn;eder soght.</L>
<L>&THORN;e appostels &thorn;an went to &thorn;e toune</L>
<L>And till &thorn;aire mete &thorn;ai set &thorn;am doune.</L>
<L>And so wen &thorn;ai war &thorn;e&thorn;in went,</L>
<L>Als-sone god has his angels sent,</L>
<L N="445">And broght &thorn;e saul of oure lady</L>
<L>Ogan unto &thorn;e blisced body,<NOTE PLACE="foot">T ogain.</NOTE></L>
<L>And bath to-geder gert &thorn;am wend</L>
<L>To be in blis with-owten end.</L>
<L>When &thorn;e enterment endid was,</L>
<L N="450">To &thorn;e cete-ward come saint Thomas.</L>
<L>In his hert had he grete mornig,</L>
<L>For he was noght at hir pasing;</L>
<L>And wele he wist, when he come hame,</L>
<L>&THORN;at all his bre&thorn;er wald him blame &mdash;</L>
<L N="455">Al bot he, he wist, was &thorn;are;<NOTE PLACE="foot">lies war st. was?</NOTE></L>
<L>For&thorn;i his murnig was &thorn;e mare.<NOTE PLACE="foot">T H murnig.</NOTE></L>
<L>And als he come by &thorn;at ilk place</L>
<L>Whare scho was grauen thurgh goddes grace,<MILESTONE N="173" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="foot">H thrurgh.</NOTE></L>
<L>He saw a brigh(t)nes in &thorn;e aire,</L>
<L N="460">And al obout him bemes faire.</L>
<L>And als he luked up in &thorn;at ligh(t),</L>
<L>He saw oure ladies body brigh(t).<NOTE PLACE="foot">H sawa.</NOTE></L>
<L>He kneled doune and said: "lady,</L>
<L>Of me &thorn;is day &thorn;ou haue mercy!</L>
<L N="465">Ful faine I wald haue cumen &thorn;e till,</L>
<L>And it had bene my lordes will.</L>
<L>Bot, lady, tell me sum takining</L>
<L>&THORN;at I may to my bre&thorn;er bring,
<PB REF="00000256.tif" N="118"></L>
<L>So &thorn;at &thorn;ai may trow in-fere</L>
<L N="470">How &thorn;at I haue sene &thorn;e here!</L>
<L>Els with schame I mun be schent,</L>
<L>For I was fro &thorn;ine enterement."</L>
<L>A faynt of silk &thorn;an toke scho sone,</L>
<L>&THORN;at was obut hir medel done &mdash;</L>
<L N="475">Hir-self ful wele had wroght it all &mdash;</L>
<L>And to him scho lete it fall.</L>
<L>&THORN;an Thomas toke &thorn;e saint in hande</L>
<L>And loued hir hertly of hir sande.</L>
<L>Ful sone &thorn;an was scho hent to heuyn,</L>
<L N="480">With mekill mir(t)h of angel steuyn.<NOTE PLACE="foot">H mirh.</NOTE></L>
<L>And a ful ioyful man was he!</L>
<L>And so he wendes to &thorn;e cete.</L>
<L>He fand his felaws samen in cete<NOTE PLACE="foot">cete=sete.</NOTE></L>
<L>In &thorn;e temple at &thorn;aire mete,</L>
<L N="485">&amp; fast &thorn;ai prechid goddes worde,</L>
<L>Als &thorn;ai sat &thorn;aire at &thorn;e borde.<NOTE PLACE="foot">H &thorn;aire=&thorn;are.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;an Thomas gan bifor &thorn;am stand</L>
<L>And gret &thorn;am with ful glad sembland.</L>
<L>"A, &thorn;ai said, Thomas of Inde!</L>
<L N="490">&THORN;ou ert euermore bihinde!</L>
<L>Whare has &thorn;ou so lang bene,</L>
<L>Whils we haue beried heuyn quene?"</L>
<L>&THORN;an said Thomas to &thorn;am on raw:</L>
<L>"&THORN;at scho es in heuyn, wele I knaw;</L>
<L N="495">Bot &thorn;at ze all vntill hir soght</L>
<L>And ze beried hir &mdash; &thorn;at trow I noght."</L>
<L>&THORN;an answerd to him Peter and Jon</L>
<L>And said: "&thorn;ar-of es wonder none,</L>
<L>For-whi &thorn;ou trowed nog(ht), Thomas,</L>
<L N="500">&THORN;at oure lord Jhesu resin was</L>
<L>Vntill &thorn;ou saw his blody side</L>
<L>And graped within his wondes wide.</L>
<L>Of euil bileue has &thorn;ou ay bene &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">H iou st. &thorn;ou.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;at es on &thorn;i-seluen sene,</L>
<L N="505">&THORN;arfore ertou ay vs fro</L>
<L>When any thing es forto do.</L>
<L>And zit it angers us more now</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou will noght oure tales trow."</L>
<L>&THORN;an said Thomas: "bre&thorn;er, lattes be!</L>
<L N="510">I hawe hir sene latter &thorn;an ze:<NOTE PLACE="foot">T haue.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bodily unto heuyn scho went.</L>
<L>Lo, here a takin scho has zow sent!"</L>
<L>&THORN;e girdel schewed he to &thorn;am &thorn;are.</L>
<L>&THORN;are-of &thorn;ai all awonder ware;<NOTE PLACE="foot">H awonder, T awonderd (in H fehlt d oft nach n u. r).</NOTE></L>
<L N="515">Bot knauing &thorn;are-of al &thorn;ai haue<NOTE PLACE="foot">T knawing.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at it was laid with hir in graue.</L>
<L>&THORN;an said saint Peter &amp; saint Jone<NOTE PLACE="foot">H said said.</NOTE></L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;a o&thorn;er euer-ilkone:</L>
<L>"Wend we tite unto &thorn;e uale,</L>
<L N="520">To se &thorn;e soth of Thomas tale,</L>
<L>If it be als he has said</L>
<L>Of oure lady &thorn;at &thorn;are was laid!"</L>
<L>&THORN;an went &thorn;ai whare &thorn;ai had hir hid.</L>
<L>And &thorn;e toumbe sone &thorn;ai undid:</L>
<L N="525">And in &thorn;e graue no-thing &thorn;ai fand</L>
<L>Bot als floure in &thorn;e grond ligand &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;an loued &thorn;ai god of all his grace.</L>
<L>And hastili in &thorn;at ilk place<NOTE PLACE="foot">T hastily.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ful mekil mirth come &thorn;am omang</L>
<L N="530">Of heuynli blis and angell sang.</L>
<L>And oure lord, Jhesu Crist,</L>
<L>Couerd &thorn;am all in a mist</L>
<L>And ilkane sone he rauist swa</L>
<L>To &thorn;e cuntre &thorn;at he come fra:</L>
<L N="535">Ilkane was in his contre sett</L>
<L>Sodainly als &thorn;ai first mett.<NOTE PLACE="foot">als st. ar?</NOTE></L>
<L>Loued be &thorn;at lord with-owten ende</L>
<L>&THORN;at honurd so his moder hende!</L>
<L>Honore we him both day and nigh(t),</L>
<L N="540">And menske we Mary at oure might,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at we may bide albidene</L>
<L>Whare he es king and sche es quene!</L>
<TRAILER>A M E N.
</TRAILER>

</LG>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="24" TYPE="legend"><PB REF="00000257.tif" N="119">
<HEAD>24. Passio sancti Bartholomei appostoli.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>S. Tib. fol. 258&mdash;260 a I.</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Saint Berthelmeu, als Crist cummand,</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e puple went prechand</L>
<L>And helyd folk &thorn;at he myght finde.</L>
<L>So &thorn;at &thorn;e last he come till Ynde.<NOTE PLACE="foot">T at, H &thorn;at = at, wie 20, 39 (so oft in schott. Mss.).</NOTE></L>
<L N="5">And it bifell opon a day,</L>
<L>Into &thorn;aire temple he toke &thorn;e way</L>
<L>And went &thorn;arin als (a) pylgrym.<NOTE PLACE="foot">T a, fehlt in H.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ful mani folk &thorn;are foloud him,</L>
<L>For many wonders &thorn;at he wroght,</L>
<L N="10">Of seke folk &thorn;at to him soght.</L>
<L>In &thorn;at temple &thorn;an gan dwell</L>
<L>A foul maumet, a fende of hell,<NOTE PLACE="foot">T mawmet.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at said, he kouth hele seke and sare</L>
<L>And maistri had of les a(n)d mare.</L>
<L N="15">Astorot &thorn;e folk him cald,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H Astorot, T Astarot.</NOTE></L>
<L>And for a god &thorn;ai gan him hald:</L>
<L>For sere tymes wald he tell &thorn;am sum</L>
<L>Of thinges &thorn;at war forto cum &mdash;</L>
<L>Of verray god had &thorn;ai no bilde,</L>
<L N="20">&THORN;arfore with fals &thorn;ai war bigilde.</L>
<L>&THORN;is fals fende, &thorn;at I of tell,</L>
<L>Made slike maistrice &thorn;am omell,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ai held him &thorn;aire lord allane,</L>
<L>And o&thorn;er god ne knew &thorn;ai nane:</L>
<L N="25">With fendes craft he gert &thorn;am be</L>
<L>Seke and vgly on to se,</L>
<L>And so he turment more and les<NOTE PLACE="foot">H se, T so.</NOTE></L>
<L>Thurgh diuers maners of sekenes;</L>
<L>And unto &thorn;am, &thorn;at so war graid,</L>
<L N="30">On &thorn;is manere sum tyme he said:</L>
<L>&THORN;ai suld mak sacrafise to him</L>
<L>And he suld hele &thorn;am lith and lym.</L>
<L>And so unto him maniane sogh(t).</L>
<L>Bot neuer-&thorn;e-les he helid &thorn;am noght;</L>
<L N="35">Bot when he of his turmentes sest,</L>
<L>&THORN;an &thorn;aire paines sum-dele relest.</L>
<L>So, when he no fares till &thorn;am send,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he &thorn;am helid, &thorn;an wele &thorn;ai wend,</L>
<L>And right so to &thorn;am wald he tell.</L>
<L N="40">Bot efterwar &thorn;an &thorn;us bifell:</L>
<L>Sone when saint Bertelmeu was cumen,</L>
<L>&THORN;e fendes speche was fra him nomen.</L>
<L>Wont &thorn;ai war answer to haue</L>
<L>Of all &thorn;at &thorn;ai wald efter craue:</L>
<L N="45">And now on him was fallen slike wreke</L>
<L>&THORN;at no-thing might he to &thorn;am speke,</L>
<L>Ne &thorn;am &thorn;at he had hurted sare</L>
<L>Might he no-thing mend &thorn;aire fare &mdash;</L>
<L>And &thorn;e temple was fild ful nere</L>
<L N="50">Of &thorn;am &thorn;at war seke and unfere,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e maumet might answer noght &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;arof &thorn;e folk grete ferli thoght.</L>
<L>&THORN;e bisschoppes and maistres of &thorn;aire lare,</L>
<L>&THORN;at kepers of &thorn;e temple ware,</L>
<L N="55">&THORN;ai hopid it was for sum wreke</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;aire maumett might noght speke.</L>
<L>And to wit what &thorn;is meruail ment,</L>
<L>Vntil a-no&thorn;er toun &thorn;ai went,</L>
<L>Vntill a fende &thorn;at hight Berit,</L>
<L N="60">Of him forto spir and wit</L>
<L>Whi Astarot, &thorn;aire god of might,</L>
<L>Moght noght answer to &thorn;am right,</L>
<L>Als he was won bifore to done.</L>
<L>&THORN;is o&thorn;er fende &thorn;an said ful sone:</L>
<L N="65">"Zowre god es bunden ferly fast</L>
<L>With brinand cheynes, &thorn;at wele wil last,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he may noght his hede up hald</L>
<L>Ne he may noght speke, if he wald:</L>
<L>And al &thorn;at mase a new-cumen schrew,</L>
<L N="70">A lurdan &thorn;at hat Bertelmew."</L>
<L>&THORN;an said &thorn;ai: "what es he &thorn;at,</L>
<L>&THORN;at new es cumen and so hat?"</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;am &thorn;an answerd &thorn;e fende</L>
<L>And said: "&thorn;at man es goddes frende</L>
<L N="75">&THORN;at of all thing es lord and prince.</L>
<L>&THORN;arfore he cumes in &thorn;is prouince<NOTE PLACE="foot">H cum es. puince.</NOTE></L>
<L>Al maumetry forto destroy</L>
<L>&THORN;at unto men of Ynde may noy."</L>
<L>&THORN;an &thorn;e prestes war noght payd</L>
<L N="80">And &thorn;us unto &thorn;e fende &thorn;ai said:
<PB REF="00000258.tif" N="120"></L>
<L>"Sai us sum signe of Bertelmeu,</L>
<L>Wharby we mai knaw &thorn;at schrew</L>
<L>And find him bifore o&thorn;er men!"</L>
<L>&THORN;an sayd &thorn;e fende: "ze sall him ken</L>
<L N="85">Bi signes &thorn;at I sal zow mak:</L>
<L>His hare es crisp and als cole blac,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H colo.</NOTE></L>
<L>His face es (fair) whith-outen threpe<NOTE PLACE="foot">fair fehlt (T?). whith st. with.</NOTE></L>
<L>And his eghen er all outftepe,</L>
<L>His nese es euyn, with thirles small,</L>
<L N="90">His eres with hare er couerd all,</L>
<L>With side berd, and gray hares oma(n)g;</L>
<L>And of stature euyn large and lang;</L>
<L>His clething es both clene and white,</L>
<L>With hemmes of purpure ful parfite &mdash;</L>
<L N="95">And fully sex and twenty zere</L>
<L>Lestes it in-like white and clere,</L>
<L>And als new it semes alway</L>
<L>Als it was on &thorn;e first day.</L>
<L>A hundereth si&thorn;es on ilka night</L>
<L N="100">And als oft on &thorn;e day ful right</L>
<L>Kneles he with milde steuyn</L>
<L>In praiers to &thorn;e fader of heuyn.</L>
<L>His uo(i)ce sownes als trumpes or bemes.</L>
<L>And goddes angels euer him &yogh;emes</L>
<L N="105">And wendes with him ful grete plente,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at he may noght wery be,<MILESTONE N="174" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Ne hunger may he nane haue here;</L>
<L>Bot euer-more mery es his chere.</L>
<L>Vnto him es nothing unknawen,</L>
<L N="110">He spekes all langwage als his awin."</L>
<L>&THORN;us all his signes to &thorn;am he saide,</L>
<L>And &thorn;an he cried oloude and prayde:</L>
<L>"If ze may find him, al-togeder</L>
<L>I pray zow &thorn;at he cum noght heder</L>
<L N="115">Forto mak me swilk a blott</L>
<L>Als he has done till Astharott.</L>
<L>And when ze ilka syde haue soght,</L>
<L>Bot if he will, ze finde him noght;</L>
<L>&amp;, if it be his awin will,</L>
<L N="120">&THORN;an sall ze full sone cum him till."</L>
<L>When he had tald &thorn;us to &thorn;am &thorn;are,</L>
<L>He held him still and spak nomare.</L>
<L>&THORN;an &thorn;a maisters all in-fere</L>
<L>Whent and soght on sides sere<NOTE PLACE="foot">whent st. went.</NOTE></L>
<L N="125">Twa daies all-out till ende;</L>
<L>And takinyng of him none &thorn;ai kend.</L>
<L>So fell: omanges &thorn;am was &thorn;are ane</L>
<L>&THORN;at to &thorn;e fende was fully tane,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e fende &thorn;at was in his body</L>
<L N="130">Omang &thorn;am &thorn;us bigan to cri:</L>
<L>"A, Bertelmew, Cristes appostell gude,</L>
<L>&THORN;i praiers brinnes me bane and blude."</L>
<L>&THORN;e appostell answerd and said &thorn;an:</L>
<L>"Be still and wend out fra &thorn;at man!"</L>
<L N="135">With hidose noise out gan he pass,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H bidouse.</NOTE></L>
<L>And so &thorn;e man deliuerd was.</L>
</LG>
<P>De curacione filie regis per appostolum.</P>
<LG>
<L>A king was in &thorn;at same cete</L>
<L>And had a doghter, faire and fre &mdash;</L>
<L>Polimyus was &thorn;at kinges name,</L>
<L N="140">And his dogter of nobill fame,</L>
<L>In all &thorn;e land was none hir like;</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;e mayden was lunatyke:</L>
<L>In ilk new-mone, als &thorn;e zere zode,</L>
<L>Was scho witles and nere wode.</L>
<L N="145">And sone, when &thorn;at &thorn;e king her(d) tell<NOTE PLACE="foot">H her, T herd.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of &thorn;is man how it bifell</L>
<L>&THORN;at was deliuerd of &thorn;e schrew</L>
<L>Thurgh &thorn;e appostel Berthelmew:</L>
<L>Messengers ful sone he sent<NOTE PLACE="foot">T messangers.</NOTE></L>
<L N="150">To bring &thorn;e appostell in present,</L>
<L>Forto asay on all manere</L>
<L>If he might hele his doghter dere.</L>
<L>Sone when he come bifor &thorn;e king,</L>
<L>&THORN;are he fand &thorn;e maiden zing</L>
<L N="155">Bun with cordes, ful fast knitt,<NOTE PLACE="foot">T knit,</NOTE></L>
<L>Als wode woman, out of hir witt.<NOTE PLACE="foot">wit.</NOTE></L>
<L>He bad &thorn;ai suld hir bandes vndo.</L>
<L>And &thorn;an &thorn;e seruandes said him to:</L>
<L>"Scho es so f(ell) and all unfere,<NOTE PLACE="foot">T fell, in H. unlesbar.</NOTE></L>
<L N="160">&THORN;at none of us dar negh hir nere,</L>
<L>Ne no-man may habide hir brade."<NOTE PLACE="foot">T braide.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e appostel &thorn;an answer and said:<NOTE PLACE="foot">T appostell. T answerd.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Scho has na force zow forto fere:</L>
<L>I haue him bun &thorn;at did hir dere.</L>
<L N="165">&THORN;arfore ga lese hir bandes grete
<PB REF="00000259.tif" N="121"></L>
<L>And cumforth hir with drink and mete!"<NOTE PLACE="foot">H cumforth, T?</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;an &thorn;ai went with hert glad</L>
<L>And lesed hir, als &thorn;e appostel bad:</L>
<L>&THORN;e fend &thorn;an had namore powere</L>
<L N="170">Hir forto noy on no manere.</L>
<L>On &thorn;is wise scho was warist.</L>
<L>And &thorn;e appostell oway vanist.</L>
<L>&THORN;an &thorn;e king was wonder glad</L>
<L>&THORN;at his dogter hir hele had,<NOTE PLACE="foot">T doghter.</NOTE></L>
<L N="175">And ful mekil mane he ment<NOTE PLACE="foot">T mekill.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e appostell so was went.</L>
<L>He gert charge camels, stiff of banes,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H gret, T gert.</NOTE></L>
<L>With siluer and go(l)d and precius stanes</L>
<L>And also with full riche wede,<NOTE PLACE="foot">T. ful.</NOTE></L>
<L N="180">Vnto &thorn;e appostell forto lede.</L>
<L>Furth &thorn;ai went and him &thorn;ai soght</L>
<L>All &thorn;e day, and fand him noght;</L>
<L>He saw &thorn;am seke him fer and nere,</L>
<L>Bot he wald noght to &thorn;am appere.</L>
<L N="185">At euyn &thorn;ai come with pase ful plaine<NOTE PLACE="foot">H And, T At.</NOTE></L>
<L>Vnto (&thorn;e) kinges palas ogayne.<NOTE PLACE="foot">T &thorn;e, fehlt in H.</NOTE></L>
<L>Opon &thorn;e morn &thorn;an &thorn;us it ferd:</L>
<L>When all &thorn;e zates and durs war sperd,</L>
<L>&THORN;e appostell come arly at morn</L>
<L N="190">In to &thorn;e chamber &thorn;e king biforn,</L>
<L>And on &thorn;is wise to him said he:</L>
<L>"Sir, warto sendes &thorn;ou to seke me</L>
<L>with siluer and co(l)d and riche clething?<NOTE PLACE="foot">H cod, T cold st. gold, zur Alliter.?</NOTE></L>
<L>I tent noght to swilk maner of thing.</L>
<L N="195">Vnto &thorn;am swilk giftes er gude</L>
<L>&THORN;at to &thorn;e werld will turn &thorn;aire mode;<NOTE PLACE="foot">H werid.</NOTE></L>
<L>And I couait no-thing &thorn;at es</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e werld ne to &thorn;e ffless.</L>
<L>Bot, sir, I wald welle att &thorn;ou kneu<NOTE PLACE="foot">T wele, knew.</NOTE></L>
<L N="200">I am appostel of Jhesu,<NOTE PLACE="foot">T appostell.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; in his name I sall destroy</L>
<L>All maumettries &thorn;at men may noy;</L>
<L>And deuils &thorn;at has unto zo spoken<NOTE PLACE="foot">H zo, T &yogh;ow.</NOTE></L>
<L>At my bidig &thorn;aire mouthes er loken,<NOTE PLACE="foot">T H bidig, T mowthes.</NOTE></L>
<L N="205">&THORN;at &thorn;ai may tell to more no les</L>
<L>No-thing bot &thorn;aire awin wikkednes."</L>
<L>&THORN;an &thorn;e king ful sune vp rase</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e temple &thorn;e way he tase</L>
<L>Whare Berit was, &thorn;at wikked fende,</L>
<L N="210">And &thorn;e appostell gan with him wende.</L>
<L>And &thorn;are &thorn;ai fand &thorn;e folk vnwise</L>
<L>Ful fast makand sacrafice;<NOTE PLACE="foot">T sacrafise.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ai honord him als god mighty.</L>
<L>And &thorn;an &thorn;e fende bigan to cry:</L>
<L N="215">"Ses, wreches, and he&thorn;in fle<NOTE PLACE="foot">T Ses, H Ses od. Gos?</NOTE></L>
<L>And mak no sacrafise to me!</L>
<L>In auenture &thorn;at ze haue slike ill</L>
<L>Als now es bitid me vntill,</L>
<L>&THORN;at bundun es with cheynes of fire<NOTE PLACE="foot">H bundun, T bunden.</NOTE></L>
<L N="220">With angels of ane, &thorn;at es lord and sire,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e iews did on &thorn;e rode</L>
<L>For &thorn;ai his might noght vnderstode &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;ai trowed he suld be ded for ay,</L>
<L>Bot he rase on &thorn;e third day,<NOTE PLACE="foot">T thrid.</NOTE></L>
<L N="225">And thurgh his rising stroyed he ded;</L>
<L>And se&thorn;en he sent in diuers stede</L>
<L>Appostels, his passioune forto preche</L>
<L>And gastely thurgh his law to leche.</L>
<L>Of whilk appostels ane es here,</L>
<L N="230">&THORN;at has me bunden on &thorn;is manere.</L>
<L>And &thorn;arfore prayes to him for me</L>
<L>&THORN;at I might wende to sum cuntre<NOTE PLACE="foot">H wonde od. wende?</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at none of his felaws in ware,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at he dere me now nomare".</L>
<L N="235">&THORN;an said &thorn;e appostels on &thorn;is manere:</L>
<L>"Whi saues &thorn;ou noght &thorn;i seruandes here</L>
<L>&THORN;at honors &thorn;e with all &thorn;ai(r) mayne?"</L>
<L>And &thorn;an &thorn;e fende answerd ogaine:</L>
<L>"In werld, he said, sent er we &thorn;us</L>
<L N="240">To turment &thorn;am &thorn;at trowes in vs,</L>
<L>And noght, to ger &thorn;aire bales blin,</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;aire sawles with vs forto vin".<NOTE PLACE="foot">H vin st. win.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;an said &thorn;e appostell with milde mode</L>
<L>Vnto all &thorn;e folk &thorn;at &thorn;are stode:</L>
<L N="245">"Lo here zowre god &thorn;at ze on trow,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ze hope sal deliuer zow</L>
<L>And mak zow hale in lith and lim!</L>
<L>Now may he now&thorn;er help zow ne him.</L>
<L>And if ze will I for zow speke,
<PB REF="00000260.tif" N="122"></L>
<L N="250">&THORN;is maumetry I bid ze breke</L>
<L>And kast &thorn;is temple to &thorn;e grownde!"</L>
<L>&THORN;an, als &thorn;e king cumand &thorn;at stounde,</L>
<L>Rapes and crokes &thorn;aron &thorn;ai kast,</L>
<L>And fele folk droght &thorn;arat ful fast;</L>
<L N="255">Bot euer stode &thorn;e temple still.</L>
<L>And &thorn;an &thorn;e appostell said &thorn;am till:</L>
<L>"Leses zowre rapes owai, I bid".</L>
<L>And als he cumand, so &thorn;ai did.</L>
<L>And &thorn;an he said unto &thorn;e fende:</L>
<L N="260">"If &thorn;ow will I noght ger &thorn;e wende<NOTE PLACE="foot">I noght st. noght I? T?</NOTE></L>
<L>And he&thorn;in pas to pine of hell,</L>
<L>&THORN;is temple bid I &thorn;at &thorn;ou fell;</L>
<L>And wende in-to sum vncuth ile,</L>
<L>Neuer more men to bigile!"</L>
<L N="265">&THORN;an &thorn;e fende come out in hy</L>
<L>And kest doune all his maumetri;</L>
<L>And when all was doun and undone,</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;aire sight &thorn;an was he sone.</L>
<L>&THORN;an all &thorn;e folk bigan to cry:</L>
<L N="270">"&THORN;ar es a god and al-mighty,</L>
<L>And a lord &thorn;at all men leches,</L>
<L>Of wham &thorn;at &thorn;is appostell preches".</L>
<L>&THORN;an bifell on &thorn;is manere:</L>
<L>Als &thorn;e appostell made his praiere,</L>
<L N="275">Ane angell omang &thorn;am gan apere,</L>
<L>&THORN;at als &thorn;e sun was schineand clere,</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e foure parties he went</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e temple with gude entent</L>
<L>And in &thorn;e stanes he purtraid</L>
<L N="280">&THORN;e signe of &thorn;e cros, and &thorn;us-gat said:</L>
<L>"Mi lord of heuin has sent me heder</L>
<L>Forto scheu &yogh;ow all-to-geder</L>
<L>How ze sall wirk his will all-way;</L>
<L>And &thorn;us he bad I suld zow say:</L>
<L N="285">Als ze ar clensed of zowre sekenes,</L>
<L>Right so &thorn;is temple clensed es</L>
<L>Of all maner of fulth of sin</L>
<L>Of him &thorn;at are dwelled &thorn;arein,</L>
<L>&THORN;at sone sall wend out of &thorn;is land,</L>
<L N="290">Als &thorn;e appostell has cumand.</L>
<L>Bot mi lord has cumand me</L>
<L>&THORN;at, or he went, ze sall him se,</L>
<L>Forto schew zow how foul he es</L>
<L>&THORN;at ze hawe trowed in more and les.</L>
<L N="295">And, when ze him here up rered,<NOTE PLACE="foot">se fehlt?</NOTE></L>
<L>Luke &thorn;at ze be noght afferd,</L>
<L>Bot makes &thorn;is signe on zow ilkane</L>
<L>&THORN;at I haue purtraid in &thorn;is stane,</L>
<L>And so cros on zow ze bere &mdash;</L>
<L N="300">For &thorn;an no deuils may do zow dere;</L>
<L>In zowre fruntes &thorn;at signe mak ze,</L>
<L>And so all euill sall fra zow fle".</L>
<L>&THORN;an &thorn;is angell, schinand bright,</L>
<L>Schewed &thorn;am a ful grisely sight:</L>
<L N="305">A fende blacker &thorn;an any cole,</L>
<L>And taterd als a filterd fole &mdash;</L>
<L>None erthly man might him haue sene,</L>
<L>Had noght might of &thorn;e angell bene;</L>
<L>His face was foule with eghen un-mete,</L>
<L N="310">And fowl hare doune till his fete,</L>
<L>His eghen glored als any glede,</L>
<L>And of his mouth and his nese zede</L>
<L>Brandes, als of thonors blast,</L>
<L>And bath his hend was bunden fast</L>
<L N="315">Vntill his bac with cheines of fire &mdash;</L>
<L>To se, he was a selkuth syre!</L>
<L>&THORN;an sayd &thorn;e angell him untill:</L>
<L>"Sen &thorn;ou has done &thorn;e appostels will</L>
<L>And clensed &thorn;is temple and mad it clene,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H madit.</NOTE></L>
<L N="320">I sall lese all &thorn;i bandes bidene;</L>
<L>And I cumand &thorn;at &thorn;ou wende</L>
<L>Whare neuer man sall lif ne lende".</L>
<L>&THORN;an &thorn;e fende hidosely berede<NOTE PLACE="foot">berede v. beren to cry.</NOTE></L>
<L>And went, and neuer efter apperde.</L>
<L N="325">&THORN;an efterward bifell it &thorn;us</L>
<L>&THORN;at iche king Polimius<NOTE PLACE="foot">H rche, st. iche? T?</NOTE></L>
<L>And his wife and his doghters twa,</L>
<L>And all his hous-menze alswa,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e appostell baptist ware;</L>
<L N="330">And all his lord-schip leued he &thorn;are,</L>
<L>&THORN;e appostell counsail did he dan,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H dan st. &thorn;an, zur Alliter.?</NOTE></L>
<L>And so bicome a cristen man.</L>
<L>&THORN;an &thorn;e bisschoppes war ful breme</L>
<L>&THORN;at had &thorn;at maumet forto zeme,</L>
<L N="335">And grete despite in hert &thorn;am thoght</L>
<L>&THORN;at all &thorn;aire werk was worthed to noght.</L>
<L>And gladly wald &thorn;ai venged be,</L>
<L>&THORN;arfore &thorn;ai went till a cete</L>
<L>Whare a king wold, ful prowde in prese,<NOTE PLACE="foot">I. weld.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000261.tif" N="123"></L>
<L N="340">&THORN;at named was &thorn;an Astriges,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H namen in named corr.</NOTE></L>
<L>And he was bro&thorn;er, be ze balde,</L>
<L>Of Polimius &thorn;at I of talde.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai hopid, he suld be greued sone</L>
<L>When he wist how his bro&thorn;er had done.</L>
<L N="345">&THORN;arfore &thorn;ai went halely in-fere</L>
<L>And tald to him on &thorn;is manere:</L>
<L>"&THORN;i bro&thorn;er, sir, Polimius</L>
<L>Has left his law and &thorn;e and vs,</L>
<L>And made him ane of his menze</L>
<L N="350">&THORN;at has fordone our god so fre</L>
<L>And also gert oure temple fall.</L>
<L>&THORN;is es grete despite till us all".</L>
<L>&THORN;us o&thorn;er bischoppes bare record</L>
<L>And pleined &thorn;am bifor &thorn;e lord.</L>
<L N="355">&THORN;e king &thorn;an thoght grete despite</L>
<L>And fast bigan he forto flite</L>
<L>And sware: "bi him &thorn;at all has wroght,</L>
<L>&THORN;is bargan sal ful dere be boght".</L>
<L>A thowsan armed men he sent<NOTE PLACE="foot">T thowsand.</NOTE></L>
<L N="360">And with &thorn;e bisschoppes furth &thorn;ai went,</L>
<L>And straitly to &thorn;am he cumand</L>
<L>&THORN;at, whare so &thorn;ai &thorn;e appostell fand,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai suld him bind in bandes ill</L>
<L>And bring &thorn;at traitur him untill.</L>
<L N="365">&THORN;ai soght him &thorn;an, to &thorn;ai him fand,</L>
<L>And did all als &thorn;e king cumand;<NOTE PLACE="foot">H ling st. king.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ai gaf him many unskilwis scorn</L>
<L>And broght him furth &thorn;e king biforn.</L>
<L>&THORN;an said &thorn;e king: "boy, &thorn;ou ert he</L>
<L N="370">&THORN;at stroies oure goddes of grete pouste</L>
<L>And gers my bro&thorn;er &mdash; I here say &mdash;</L>
<L>Leue right-wis trowth, to trow &thorn;i lay?"</L>
<L>&THORN;an said &thorn;e appostell: "suth it es,</L>
<L>I haue him turned to rightwisnes</L>
<L N="375">Fra &thorn;e fals law of &thorn;e fende</L>
<L>&THORN;at ledes to wa with-owten ende,</L>
<L>And teched him forto trow ful euyn</L>
<L>Opon all-mighty god of heuyn</L>
<L>&THORN;at euer sal be and ai has bene".</L>
<L N="380">&THORN;an said &thorn;e king to him in tene:</L>
<L>"&THORN;e feme sall I do &thorn;e unto<NOTE PLACE="foot">H seme = same.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou has gert my bro&thorn;er do;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou has gert him thurgh falshed fine</L>
<L>Forsake his goddes and trow on &thorn;ine:</L>
<L N="385">Right so (s)all I ger &thorn;e forsake</L>
<L>All &thorn;i goddes and wirschip make</L>
<L>Vnto my goddes of mekill mayne".</L>
<L>&THORN;e appostell &thorn;an answerd ogaine</L>
<L>And said: "&thorn;at god of wikked lare,<NOTE PLACE="foot">T H all st. sall.</NOTE></L>
<L N="390">&THORN;e whilk &thorn;i bro&thorn;er honord are,</L>
<L>I band him, &thorn;at he might noght speke,</L>
<L>And gert him se&thorn;in his temple breke.</L>
<L>And if &thorn;ou may with &thorn;i powere</L>
<L>Do till my god on &thorn;is manere,</L>
<L N="395">Par auenture &thorn;an &thorn;ou may me make</L>
<L>Lightly his law to forsake.</L>
<L>And for&thorn;ermar, sir, with &thorn;i leue,</L>
<L>If &thorn;ou my god may no-thing greue,</L>
<L>I sall destroy &thorn;i goddes ilkane,</L>
<L N="400">And turn &thorn;ou to my god allane".</L>
<L>Als &thorn;ai war &thorn;us in &thorn;is carping,</L>
<L>Ti&thorn;andes come unto &thorn;e king</L>
<L>&THORN;at his god of grete renowne,</L>
<L>&THORN;at Baldach hight, was fallen done</L>
<L N="405">And naman wist whare he was went,</L>
<L>And his kepers grete harmes had hent.</L>
<L>&THORN;an &thorn;e kyng was wonder wrath,</L>
<L>Sunder he rafe peloree and clath.<NOTE PLACE="foot">H peloree, T pelore. T clathe.</NOTE></L>
<L>He gert his men &thorn;e appostell bete</L>
<L N="410">Bifor him &thorn;are with staues grete</L>
<L>And se&thorn;in, for he suld suffer wa,</L>
<L>He cumand &thorn;at &thorn;ai suld him fla,</L>
<L>And heuid him &thorn;an he gan &thorn;am bid.</L>
<L>And als he bad, right so &thorn;ai did:</L>
<L N="415">First &thorn;e hide of &thorn;ai flogh</L>
<L>And wroght opon him wa Inogh,</L>
<L>And se&thorn;in strake &thorn;ai of his heuyd &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;us for his lord &thorn;e life he leuyd.</L>
<L>&THORN;an Polimyus and o&thorn;er ma,</L>
<L N="420">&THORN;at with him are war won to ga,</L>
<L>Made a toumbe ful hastily</L>
<L>And berid &thorn;are his blissed body.</L>
<L>And efterward Polimius</L>
<L>Was bisschop, als &thorn;e buke sais vs,</L>
<L N="425">And turned mani ane to be trew</L>
<L>In &thorn;e law of oure lord Jhesu.</L>
<L>Vnto wham be ay loueing,</L>
<L>And till his blis us all he bring!</L>
<TRAILER>A M E N.
</TRAILER>

</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="25" TYPE="legend"><PB REF="00000262.tif" N="124">
<HEAD>25. De decollacione sci Johannis baptiste.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>S. Tib. fol. 260 a 1&mdash;262.</P></HEADNOTE>
<DIV3 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;are was ane Philyp king sum tyde</L>
<L>Of Yturie and of Trachonide,</L>
<L>And &thorn;is ilk Philip was &thorn;e sun</L>
<L>Of elder Herod, &thorn;e fals felun,</L>
<L N="5">In was daies, als it es red,</L>
<L>Jhesus vntill Egipt fled.</L>
<L>Efter &thorn;at Herod was ano&thorn;er,</L>
<L>And &thorn;is ilk Philip was his bro&thorn;er.</L>
<L>&THORN;is &yogh;onger Herod &thorn;an was he</L>
<L N="10">&THORN;at regned seyn in Galile,<NOTE PLACE="foot">T se&thorn;in, H seyn od. se&thorn;n?</NOTE></L>
<L>In whas daies Crist was done on rode</L>
<L>And made mans raunsoune with his blude.</L>
<L>And als it es talde in story,</L>
<L>Areth, &thorn;e king of Araby,</L>
<L N="15">Gaf his doghter to king Philip<MILESTONE N="176" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>In mariage, with grete wirschip &mdash;</L>
<L>Hir name was cald Herodias;</L>
<L>To king Philip wedded scho was.</L>
<L>And seyn bifell efter &thorn;at while:<NOTE PLACE="foot">T se&thorn;in, H seyn od. se&thorn;n?</NOTE></L>
<L N="20">&THORN;e king Areth thurgh li&thorn;er gile</L>
<L>And king Herod to-geder spak</L>
<L>&THORN;at he suld his doghter tak</L>
<L>Fra kyng Philip, &thorn;at faire hir led,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at king Herod suld hir wed.</L>
<L N="25">So Herod his awin wife forsoke,</L>
<L>And king Areth his doghter toke</L>
<L>And to king Herod he hir gafe,</L>
<L>Fra Philip, forto hald and haue.</L>
<L>His bro&thorn;er wife &thorn;us weded he;</L>
<L N="30">For he was man of more pouste,</L>
<L>Fra his bro&thorn;er &thorn;us he hir held.</L>
<L>In spousebrek so &thorn;ai samin dweld.</L>
<L>In &thorn;is same time Jon baptist</L>
<L>Went prechand &thorn;e law of Crist.</L>
<L N="35">And sone, when he herd tithing tell</L>
<L>Of &thorn;is fare how it bifell,</L>
<L>How Herod had his wife refused</L>
<L>And his bro&thorn;er wife wrang vsed:</L>
<L>To Galile his gate he graid</L>
<L N="40">And unto him al &thorn;us he said:</L>
<L>"Herod, he said, &thorn;ou dose grete greue!</L>
<L>For bi &thorn;e law hastou na leue</L>
<L>To hald &thorn;i bro&thorn;er wife in spouse-breke;</L>
<L>On &thorn;e sal cum uengance and wreke.</L>
<L N="45">Leue and mend &thorn;i sinful dedes!</L>
<L>Ogains &thorn;e law &thorn;i life &thorn;ou ledes".</L>
<L>Herodias felouns and kene,</L>
<L>&THORN;at Philip wife byfore had bene,</L>
<L>When scho wist hou saint Jon said:</L>
<L N="50">To him scho was ful euil payde.</L>
<L>And by hir rede and hir resoune</L>
<L>Herod did him in depe presoune.</L>
<L>And &thorn;an both night and day scho soght</L>
<L>How &thorn;at he might to ded be broght.</L>
<L N="55">And king Herod at hir requeste,</L>
<L>Him for to sla, in hert he keste.</L>
<L>Oft he thoght him forto sla,<MILESTONE N="176" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Bot for drede durst he noght do swa:</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e pople he had grete dout</L>
<L N="60">&THORN;at wonde in &thorn;at cuntre obut &mdash;</L>
<L>For all folk held him a prophete,</L>
<L>Of uertuse and of mightes grete;</L>
<L>And also Herod ful wele knew</L>
<L>&THORN;at he was haly, gude an trew.</L>
<L N="65">&THORN;arfore he him in preson zemed &mdash;</L>
<L>A feyned suffrance wele it semed.</L>
<L>His wordes to here oft-si&thorn;es he soght,</L>
<L>And efter his wordes sum thinges he wroght;</L>
<L>Bot he held him in strang prisoune,</L>
<L N="70">For he sau &thorn;at all folk was boune</L>
<L>His biding and his will to do</L>
<L>Of all &thorn;at euer he talde &thorn;am to;</L>
<L>And better him thoght to sla him sone,</L>
<L>Or any more meruailes war done &mdash;</L>
<L N="75">For els he thoght all folk suld knaw</L>
<L>How he lifed ogains &thorn;e law,</L>
<L>And so he thoght &thorn;ai suld him dere,</L>
<L>Gret penance to ger him bere.</L>
<L>Lo, al &thorn;us for suspecione</L>
<L N="80">Was saint Jon sett in presoune,</L>
<L>In a kastell, with pine and wa,</L>
<L>&THORN;at namen was Macheronta;<NOTE PLACE="foot">H namen.</NOTE></L>
<L>Many day &thorn;are gan he dwell.
<PB REF="00000263.tif" N="125"></L>
<L>And efterward &thorn;us it bifell:</L>
<L N="85">A sertan day in ilka zere</L>
<L>Held king Herod solempne and dere</L>
<L>And made gret festes in zeres biforn:</L>
<L>For on &thorn;at ilk day was he born;</L>
<L>And bi &thorn;at eaus, &thorn;e suth to say,</L>
<L N="90">A reall feste he made &thorn;at day,</L>
<L>With men &thorn;at war of most pouste</L>
<L>Of all &thorn;e landes in Galile.</L>
<L>&THORN;ar ware minestrals many &amp; inogh<NOTE PLACE="foot">&amp; ist zu tilgen?</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at diuers gle &thorn;at day furth drogh,</L>
<L>Tregetoures in halles and hales,</L>
<L N="95">And als dissores with diuers tales &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;are was all maners of menistralsyes</L>
<L>&THORN;at used es at grete mangeryes.</L>
<L>Saltacio filie Herodiadis.</L>
<L>A doghter had Herodias,</L>
<L N="100">A gentill damisell scho was.</L>
<L>And (in) scho come in-to &thorn;e hall<NOTE PLACE="foot">T in, fehlt H.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bifor &thorn;e king and his gestes all.</L>
<L>&THORN;e mayden &thorn;are bigan to play</L>
<L>Ful sotilly, &thorn;e suth to say,</L>
<L N="105">Scho daunced and tumbild diuers saut</L>
<L>Ful faire and wele, with-outen faut,</L>
<L>&THORN;at all &thorn;e gestes bigane to glade</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e gle &thorn;at &thorn;is maiden made;</L>
<L>Scho made men meri most and leste</L>
<L N="110">&THORN;at cumen war to &thorn;e kinges feste.</L>
<L>Warfore &thorn;e king grette athes sware<NOTE PLACE="foot">T wharfore.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bifor all lordes &thorn;at war ware:<NOTE PLACE="foot">l. &thorn;are st. ware?</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e maiden of him suld haue</L>
<L>Wat so scho wald efter craue,<NOTE PLACE="foot">T what.</NOTE></L>
<L N="115">And on &thorn;is wise he said hir till:</L>
<L>"Aske of me, mayden, what &thorn;ou will,</L>
<L>And gladly sall I gif (it) &thorn;e,<NOTE PLACE="foot">T it, fehlt in H.</NOTE></L>
<L>Half-dele my kingdome it it be",<NOTE PLACE="foot">H lingdome.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;arto athes gan he swere,</L>
<L N="120">All folk &thorn;aron witnes to bere.</L>
<L>And when &thorn;e king &thorn;usgat had sworn</L>
<L>To &thorn;e maiden &thorn;at plaied him biforn,</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;e hall full sone scho gase</L>
<L>Vntill hir moder Herodias,</L>
<L N="125">What scho suld craue &thorn;are forto spir,</L>
<L>And on &thorn;is wise scho said till hir:</L>
<L>"Moder, scho said, my lord, &thorn;e king,</L>
<L>Has graunted to me myne asking:</L>
<L>If I ask halfdele his kingdom,</L>
<L N="130">To gif it me, he es bousom;</L>
<L>&THORN;arto he has sworn athes sad".</L>
<L>&THORN;an vas &thorn;e moder meri and glad,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H vas, T was.</NOTE></L>
<L>And sone, when scho &thorn;ir wordes herd,</L>
<L>Till hir doghter &thorn;us scho answerd:</L>
<L N="135">"Doghter, wend vnto &thorn;e king</L>
<L>And luke &thorn;ou ask none o&thorn;er thing</L>
<L>Bot Jon heued, of baptist, to be</L>
<L>In a disch deliuerd unto &thorn;e;</L>
<L>In &thorn;e kinges presoun he dwelles;<NOTE PLACE="foot">T dwells.</NOTE></L>
<L N="140">Ask his heuyd and no-thing els!"</L>
<L>&THORN;e may was till hir biding baine,</L>
<L>In to &thorn;e hall scho went ogayne,</L>
<L>Baldly forto ask hir bone,</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e king &thorn;us said scho sone:</L>
<L N="145">"Mi lord, scho said, als &thorn;ou hight me,</L>
<L>&THORN;is bone now will I ask of &thorn;e:</L>
<L>&THORN;ou gif to me Jon, &thorn;e Baptist, heuid,</L>
<L>&THORN;at of(t) my moder rest has reued,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H of, T oft.</NOTE></L>
<L>And in a diff &thorn;at it be laid!</L>
<L N="150">Forto fulfill &thorn;at &thorn;ou are said."</L>
<L>&THORN;an chaunged &thorn;e kinges mode,</L>
<L>Vhen he hir asking understode;<NOTE PLACE="foot">H vhen, T when.</NOTE></L>
<L>And for he had so said hir to,</L>
<L>He wist noght what was best to do.</L>
<L N="155">What for &thorn;e ath &thorn;at he had sworne</L>
<L>So many kinges and princes biforn,</L>
<L>And for &thorn;e nowmber of folk ful grete</L>
<L>&THORN;at samen sat &thorn;are att &thorn;e mete,</L>
<L>He wald o nane wise greue &thorn;e barn</L>
<L N="160">Ne &thorn;at scho suld hir asking tharn,</L>
<L>Sen it es swa granted in &thorn;aire present.<NOTE PLACE="foot">H it es swa, T it was, swa fehlt.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bot unto preson sone he sent</L>
<L>And bad men suld Jon heuyd of smite</L>
<L>And gif it till (&thorn;at) mayden tite,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at fehlt in T u. H.</NOTE></L>
<L N="165">To bere it att hir will oway,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H bereit.</NOTE></L>
<L>For mirth &thorn;at scho has made &thorn;is day.</L>
<L>Turmentoures &thorn;an made &thorn;am boune</L>
<L>And went ful prestly to prisoune
<PB REF="00000264.tif" N="126"></L>
<L>Whare saint Jone sat in a hole,</L>
<L N="170">Ful redy-boun &thorn;e ded to thole.</L>
<L>Whith loud uoice &thorn;an &thorn;us he cried<NOTE PLACE="foot">T u. H whith.</NOTE></L>
<L>To god, in wham he him affied,</L>
<L>And said: "my lord mighty and fre,</L>
<L>Mi spirit zeld I vnto &thorn;e,</L>
<L N="175">At &thorn;i will ay forto welde."</L>
<L>&THORN;an to &thorn;e strake his heuyd he helde.</L>
<L>&THORN;e turmentoure his swerd out drogh</L>
<L>And so in preson he him slogh;</L>
<L>&THORN;e cors &thorn;are ligand still he leuid</L>
<L N="180">And to &thorn;e maiden he gaf &thorn;e heuid</L>
<L>In a dissche, als &thorn;e king bad.</L>
<L>And furth scho went with hert glad</L>
<L>And broght it hir moder unto,</L>
<L>All hir will &thorn;ar-with to do.</L>
<L N="185">And still scho held it with hir-selue,</L>
<L>For-&thorn;i &thorn;at no-man suld it delue<MILESTONE N="177" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Ne with &thorn;e body it forto laine,</L>
<L>For dout &thorn;at he suld rise ogayne.</L>
<L>&THORN;e body still in preson dweld,</L>
<L N="190">And &thorn;e heuid with hir scho held;</L>
<L>And hir wit was on &thorn;is wise:</L>
<L>For &thorn;at &thorn;ai suld nogh(t) samin rise.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="section">
<HEAD>Translacio corporis Johannis baptiste.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And Jons desciples, when &thorn;ai herd</L>
<L>How &thorn;at he was in preson sperd</L>
<L N="195">And &thorn;are was ded bi marterdom,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai samned &thorn;am, &thorn;eder to com.</L>
<L>&THORN;e cors &thorn;ai fand &mdash; and made grete care &mdash;</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;e heuid fand &thorn;ai noght &thorn;are.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai bare &thorn;e cors, als men may wit,</L>
<L N="200">To Samari and beried itt:</L>
<L>&THORN;ai laid it in a graue of stane<NOTE PLACE="foot">T &thorn;ai, H &thorn;an.</NOTE></L>
<L>In &thorn;e cete, cald Sebastiane.</L>
<L>Whare mighty god grete merci wroght</L>
<L>To all &thorn;e folk &thorn;at &thorn;eder soght:</L>
<L N="205">&THORN;e domb and defe and blind ful fele,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e st. to?</NOTE></L>
<L>And of all hurtes &thorn;are had men hele.</L>
<L>&THORN;arfore cristen-men day bi day</L>
<L>Come to seke him, &thorn;are he lay,</L>
<L>And sum hethen of hertes meke</L>
<L N="210">Had deuocioune him to seke.</L>
<L>&THORN;e iews and sarzins saw ful tite</L>
<L>And in hertes had &thorn;ai grete despite</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;is cors suld so honord be</L>
<L>And soght with folk of fer cuntre.</L>
<L N="215">&THORN;is was lang efter he was slane,</L>
<L>In &thorn;e Emperour daies sir Juliane,</L>
<L>&THORN;at redy was all wrang to wirk,</L>
<L>And grete enmy to haly kirk.</L>
<L>&THORN;e hathen men by his assent</L>
<L N="220">Vnto saint Jones graue &thorn;ai went</L>
<L>And &thorn;e banes, &thorn;at &thorn;ai fand,</L>
<L>Sparpilled &thorn;ai wide in &thorn;e land</L>
<L>And lef(t) &thorn;are nothing in &thorn;e graue</L>
<L>&THORN;at cristen men in minde might haue.</L>
<L N="225">And zit &thorn;e miracles neuer fest,</L>
<L>Bot at his banes euer &thorn;ai encrest:</L>
<L>For, whare men might his banes find,</L>
<L>Helid was bath halt and blind;</L>
<L>And &thorn;ar-fore soght bath seke and sare,</L>
<L N="230">Till &thorn;ai wist whare his relikes ware.</L>
<L>And cristen men oft preuely</L>
<L>Gat sum banes of his bodi.</L>
<L>When hathen men toke kepe her to,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H hir st. her.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;am thoght grete spite men so suld do.</L>
<L N="235">Thurgh biding of &thorn;e Emperoure,</L>
<L>And cristen men to dishonoure,</L>
<L>And also for despite and schame</L>
<L>And in stroying of Cristes name</L>
<L>&THORN;ai soght ful warlay for (&thorn;e) nanes<NOTE PLACE="foot">H warlay (T?) st. warly. &thorn;e fehlt.</NOTE></L>
<L N="240">And gederd to-geder all &thorn;e banes</L>
<L>Of Jon baptist, &thorn;at &thorn;ai might find &mdash;</L>
<L>Bot cristen men held sum bihind &mdash;</L>
<L>And all &thorn;ai brent &thorn;am in a fire,</L>
<L>To destroy cristen mens desire.</L>
<L N="245">Powder saw &thorn;ai in &thorn;e wind,<MILESTONE N="177" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>For cristen men suld no-thing find.</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;e finger of Jon baptist,</L>
<L>With &thorn;e whilk he puplist Crist</L>
<L>In &thorn;e flom, when he said &thorn;us in steuin</L>
<L N="250">"Lo here &thorn;e lamb of god of heuyn":</L>
<L>In &thorn;e fire it wald noght brin,
<PB REF="00000265.tif" N="127"></L>
<L>All-if it oft war cast &thorn;are-in.</L>
<L>Omang &thorn;e ha&thorn;en folk &thorn;are stode</L>
<L>Cristen men ful haly and gude</L>
<L N="255">&THORN;at fra sere stedes war cumen &thorn;eder:</L>
<L>&THORN;e relikes gederd &thorn;ai to-geder,</L>
<L>Bath &thorn;at &thorn;are might funden be</L>
<L>And at &thorn;ai had in preuete;<NOTE PLACE="foot">at = &thorn;at.</NOTE></L>
<L>Thurght ordinance of god mighty</L>
<L N="260">Of his banes gat &thorn;ai grete party.</L>
<L>Vnto Jerusalem &thorn;ai &thorn;am broght,</L>
<L>And worthi place for &thorn;am &thorn;ai wroght</L>
<L>And did &thorn;am &thorn;are in sacrary,</L>
<L>With wirschip, als &thorn;ai war wor(&thorn;)y.<NOTE PLACE="foot">H wory.</NOTE></L>
<L N="265">Saint Tecle, &thorn;e haly maiden, in &thorn;at,</L>
<L>&THORN;at fynger of saint Jone scho gat</L>
<L>&THORN;at fire to brin had no pouste,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e&thorn;in scho broght it ouer &thorn;e see</L>
<L>To Moryens cete &thorn;at tide,</L>
<L N="270">Whare saint Jon kirk es edifide.</L>
<L>&THORN;us come &thorn;e banes of his body</L>
<L>To Jerusalem fra Samary,</L>
<L>Till Alexander se&thorn;in come &thorn;ai,</L>
<L>&THORN;are to be honord till &thorn;is day.</L>
</LG>
<P>Inuencio capitis sci Johannis bapt.</P>
<LG>
<L N="275">Se&thorn;in bifell &thorn;at Jon baptist heuid,</L>
<L>&THORN;at with Herodias was leuid,</L>
<L>In erth priuely was it broght.</L>
<L>Bot it held klene and corumpped noght.</L>
<L>And efter many zeres war past,</L>
<L N="280">God wald it war schewed at &thorn;e last.</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;e est, bifell it swa,</L>
<L>To Jerusalem come monkes twa,</L>
<L>&THORN;are to mak deuote praiers.</L>
<L>And saint Jon vnto &thorn;am appers</L>
<L N="285">And schewed &thorn;am of &thorn;is hed in dreme</L>
<L>&THORN;at hid was in Jerusalem.</L>
<L>And when it vnto &thorn;am was kid,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai raised it, ware it was hid;<NOTE PLACE="foot">T u. H ware st. whare.</NOTE></L>
<L>To &thorn;e cete of Fenifce &thorn;ai it bare</L>
<L N="290">With all folk to be honord &thorn;are.</L>
<L>A(n)d &thorn;are it dwelled bot &yogh;eres fone &mdash;</L>
<L>Als Jhesus wald, so was it done.</L>
<L>A ha&thorn;en man &thorn;e heuyd stale</L>
<L>And bare it &thorn;e&thorn;in in-till a dale.</L>
<L N="295">&THORN;e monkes and o&thorn;er men it mist</L>
<L>And, whare it was, no-thing &thorn;ai wist.</L>
<L>&THORN;is man had hid &thorn;e heuid swa</L>
<L>In a hirn of a waste wra,<NOTE PLACE="foot">wra, altisl. r&acirc; = corner.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at no-man wist ne might it knau,<NOTE PLACE="foot">T knaw.</NOTE></L>
<L N="300">Durand efter ful lang thraw.</L>
<L>And efter &thorn;at ful many a day</L>
<L>A religius man of ane abay,<NOTE PLACE="foot">T abbay.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at vnto name was cald Marcell,</L>
<L>Went in wildernes to dwell;</L>
<L N="305">He toke him to life of heremite,</L>
<L>And in &thorn;at stede he him abite</L>
<L>Whare saint Jones hewid was hid:<NOTE PLACE="foot">T heuid.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;are vnto him &thorn;an was kid.</L>
<L>&THORN;e bisschop of Alexander &thorn;an</L>
<L N="310">Herd tell of &thorn;is hali man,</L>
<L>How he had funden saint Jones heuyd,</L>
<L>Of wham relikes with him was lewyd.<NOTE PLACE="foot">T leuyd.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;eder he went (&amp;) zern gan craue</L>
<L>To his relikes &thorn;e heuid to haue.</L>
<L N="315">Thurg(h) his asking and goddes grace</L>
<L>&THORN;e heuid he broght out of &thorn;at place</L>
<L>To his relikes in his cete,</L>
<L>In grete wirschip ay forto be.</L>
<L>And seyn yt was broght, for ser|taine,<NOTE PLACE="foot">T se&thorn;in.</NOTE></L>
<L N="320">In to &thorn;e cuntres of Aquitaine.</L>
<L>And &thorn;are it es derly to hald</L>
<L>In a cete &thorn;at Ambianence es cald. &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;us was saint Jon heuedid in hy</L>
<L>For &thorn;e foul sin of a-vowtry.</L>
<L N="325">God len us so to leue all sin,</L>
<L>&THORN;at we vntill his welth may win!</L>
<TRAILER>A M E N.
</TRAILER>

</LG>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="26" TYPE="legend"><PB REF="00000266.tif" N="128">
<HEAD>26. In festo exaltacionis sancte crucis.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>Diese Leg. ist abgedruckt in Morris "Legends of the holy Rood", p. 122.</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A king sum-tyme in cuntre was<MILESTONE N="177" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;at had to name king Chodroas;</L>
<L>A sun he had, &thorn;at was his ayre,</L>
<L>And o&thorn;er menze many and faire;</L>
<L N="5">Of &thorn;e cuntre of Pers was he king</L>
<L>And all &thorn;e land at his dedeing.<NOTE PLACE="foot">l. ledeing?</NOTE></L>
<L>He gert ilk cete and ilk toune</L>
<L>Vnto his biding be so boune,</L>
<L>&THORN;at in a trone up he him sett</L>
<L N="10">And cumand &thorn;am with-owten lett</L>
<L>&THORN;at king of kinges &thorn;ai suld him call</L>
<L>And allso god grettest of all</L>
<L>And lord of lordes, both loud and still,</L>
<L>And none on molde mete him untill.<NOTE PLACE="foot">H melde, T molde.</NOTE></L>
<L N="15">Zit was noght &thorn;is in &thorn;at sesowne</L>
<L>Inogh till his confusione;<NOTE PLACE="foot">T confusioune.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bot to Jerusalem he went</L>
<L>And said: all suld be schamely schent</L>
<L>&THORN;at trowed on Crist or on his lay.</L>
<L N="20">&THORN;ar-to he dose all &thorn;at he may:</L>
<L>In Jerusalem &thorn;aire kirkes he stroyde</L>
<L>And cristen men ful gretly noyed.</L>
<L>He toke his wai &thorn;an to &thorn;e graue</L>
<L>Whare Crist was layd, &thorn;at vs sall saue,<NOTE PLACE="foot">T sal.</NOTE></L>
<L N="25">It to destroy with all his mayn.</L>
<L>Bot for ferdnes he turned ogayne</L>
<L>And durst do no-thing at &thorn;e kyrk.</L>
<L>Bot wikkedly &thorn;us gan he wirk: &mdash;</L>
<L>Saint Eline, &thorn;e nobill quene,</L>
<L N="30">&THORN;at lang bifore his tyme had bene,</L>
<L>Fand &thorn;e cors &thorn;at men cald &thorn;e rode,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H cors, T cros, wie 284.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at Jhesus died on for oure gude,</L>
<L>And to Jerusalem scho it broght<NOTE PLACE="foot">T Jherusalem.</NOTE></L>
<L>And graithed it &thorn;are, als hir gude thoght,</L>
<L N="35">In siluer and go(l)d al bidene,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H god, T gold.</NOTE></L>
<L>For &thorn;at it suld be kepid clene;</L>
<L>And &thorn;at same kirk gert scho make</L>
<L>Coriosly for &thorn;at cros sake:</L>
<L>For men suld hald &thorn;at haly tre</L>
<L N="40">In honore als it aw to be &mdash;:</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;is ilk king Chosdroass<NOTE PLACE="foot">H chosoroass.</NOTE></L>
<L>When he wist whare &thorn;is ilk cros was,</L>
<L>He gert his men with grete maystry</L>
<L>Haue it forth with him in hy</L>
<L N="45">Out of Jerusalem cete,</L>
<L>And broght it whare him liked to be.</L>
<L>When he was &thorn;us cumen hame ogayn,</L>
<L>Of his iorne he was ful fayne.</L>
<L>And hastili &thorn;an gert he dight<NOTE PLACE="foot">H &thorn;ant.</NOTE></L>
<L N="50">A faire toure all off siluer bright:</L>
<L>He made it nobilly for &thorn;e nanes,</L>
<L>Within all ful of precius stanes;</L>
<L>A trone of gold &thorn;arin he sett</L>
<L>With precius stanes all ouer-plett,</L>
<L N="55">And &thorn;arein gert he gayly dyght</L>
<L>Like son and mone and sternes bright</L>
<L>Also zit gert he mak &thorn;arin</L>
<L>Propirtese by preue gyn,</L>
<L>&THORN;at it was like untill a heuyn,</L>
<L N="60">And rayn &thorn;arfro cumand ful euyn,</L>
<L>And preue whistils war omang</L>
<L>Made euyn like to angels sang.</L>
<L>&THORN;are in &thorn;at toure, als him gude thoght,</L>
<L>A sege untill him-self he wroght,</L>
<L N="65">And &thorn;are he gert with mekill pride</L>
<L>Set &thorn;e haly cros him biside.</L>
<L>&THORN;ar als a god he sat in stall,</L>
<L>And so he bad men suld him call.</L>
<L>His kingdom and all his riallte</L>
<L N="70">Vntill his sun haly gaf he,</L>
<L>And on &thorn;is wise &thorn;at curst caytiue</L>
<L>In maumetry wald lede his liue.</L>
<L>And so he did full many a day,</L>
<L>Ledeand &thorn;e folk in fendes lay.</L>
<L N="75">&THORN;us with &thorn;e deuil we lat him dwell,
<PB REF="00000267.tif" N="129"></L>
<L>And of his son I sall now tell.</L>
<L>A nobill king of cristendum,</L>
<L>&THORN;at namen was Heraclium,</L>
<L>Was gouernowre of grete (empire)<NOTE PLACE="foot">Das Reimwort fehlt in H. T?</NOTE></L>
<L N="80">Souerainly als lord and syre;</L>
<L>Childer he had and worthly wife,</L>
<L>In Cristes law he led his life.</L>
<L>&THORN;an &thorn;is son of Chosdroas</L>
<L>In his hert euill angerd was</L>
<L N="85">&THORN;at &thorn;is cristen king had name</L>
<L>More &thorn;an he or his sire at hame.</L>
<L>&THORN;arfore he ordand him in hy</L>
<L>And gaderd a grete cumpani</L>
<L>Of sarzins by his assent,</L>
<L N="90">And with ful grete ost es he went</L>
<L>With &thorn;is cristen king to fight</L>
<L>And to destroy him, if he might.</L>
<L>Bot sone Eraclius herd tell</L>
<L>Of &thorn;is falshed how it bifell.</L>
<L N="95">He ordand him full hastily</L>
<L>Of cristen men grete cumpany.</L>
<L>Bot, als it was oure lordes will,</L>
<L>When aither come o&thorn;er vntill</L>
<L>In place whare &thorn;ai swld batayl take,</L>
<L N="100">On &thorn;is wisse gan &thorn;ai couenant make.</L>
<L>A water was &thorn;am twa bytwene</L>
<L>And a brig all ouer it clene.</L>
<L>&THORN;e sarzyn was mekill of brede and lenth</L>
<L>And traisted mikill in his awin strenkth:</L>
<L N="105">&THORN;arfore &thorn;is forward gan he ma:</L>
<L>To do &thorn;e batail bitwix &thorn;am twa,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at &thorn;e cristend man suld mete him<MILESTONE N="178" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>In middes &thorn;e brig, was ouer &thorn;e brim;</L>
<L>And whe&thorn;er so might maistri win,</L>
<L N="110">On his side suld &thorn;e bataill blin,</L>
<L>And he suld haue in his pouste</L>
<L>All &thorn;at &thorn;ai bath had, land and fe.</L>
<L>To &thorn;is couenant assented &thorn;ai bath,</L>
<L>And &thorn;arto band &thorn;ai &thorn;am with ath:</L>
<L N="115">&THORN;at, if &thorn;aire men on ow&thorn;ir side</L>
<L>Come forto help &thorn;am in &thorn;at tide,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai suld be cut for &thorn;aire iornay</L>
<L>&THORN;aire armes and &thorn;aire legges oway</L>
<L>And so be kasten in &thorn;e flode,</L>
<L N="120">And saue &thorn;am suld none erthly gude.</L>
<L>When bath &thorn;e sides war sworn &thorn;ar-till</L>
<L>&THORN;is couenand lely to fulfill,</L>
<L>&THORN;e twa lordes on &thorn;e brig met.<NOTE PLACE="foot">H lorde. lordes. bring st. brig.</NOTE></L>
<L>And ai&thorn;er hard on o&thorn;er set,</L>
<L N="125">Ful fast &thorn;are faght &thorn;ai tow in-fere,</L>
<L>And none o&thorn;er durst negh &thorn;am nere.</L>
<L>&THORN;an cristen men with hertes fre</L>
<L>Prayed to Jhesu Crist &thorn;at he</L>
<L>Suld send &thorn;aire prince &thorn;e victory,</L>
<L N="130">Als he for &thorn;am on rode wald day;</L>
<L>And all &thorn;ai praied &thorn;an with a voice:</L>
<L>"Thurgh vertu of &thorn;i haly croyce</L>
<L>Whar-thurgh &thorn;ou wan &thorn;e victori</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e fende, oure fals enmy,</L>
<L N="135">&THORN;ou grante &thorn;is day oure prince to wyn</L>
<L>&THORN;e maistri ouere zon fals sarzyn".</L>
<L>On &thorn;is manere all prayed &thorn;ai fast.</L>
<L>And Jhesus herd &thorn;am at &thorn;e last</L>
<L>And ordand to his trew serwand</L>
<L N="140">Of &thorn;e sarzin to hawe ouer-hand<NOTE PLACE="foot">H euer st. ouer.</NOTE></L>
<L>And to destroy him in &thorn;at place &mdash;</L>
<L>Blisced be he &thorn;at gaf slike grace! &mdash;</L>
<L>Sone when &thorn;e sarzins saw &thorn;is sight</L>
<L>How &thorn;aire maister to ded was dight,</L>
<L N="145">Swilk drede in hert had &thorn;ai ilkane,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ai oblist &thorn;am noght allane</L>
<L>To hald &thorn;e couenand made byforne,</L>
<L>Bot new athes all haue &thorn;ai sworn:</L>
<L>With Eraclius forto stand</L>
<L N="150">In ill and gude, with hert and hand;</L>
<L>And wilfully all hale hete &thorn;ai</L>
<L>Forto leue on Cristes lay</L>
<L>And forto bycum cristen men</L>
<L>And Crist for &thorn;aire god euer to ken.</L>
<L N="155">Sone when Eraclius saw &thorn;at sight,</L>
<L>He resayued &thorn;am with hert ful light,</L>
<L>And cownsaild &thorn;am with wordes fre</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ai suld all baptist be</L>
<L>And trow in Crist with gude entent.</L>
<L N="160">And to his saw all &thorn;ai assent:</L>
<L>So war &thorn;ai baptist all &thorn;at day,
<PB REF="00000268.tif" N="130"></L>
<L>And lifed euer in Cristes lay.</L>
<L>Heraclius, when &thorn;is was done,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H Veraclius, T Heraclius.</NOTE></L>
<L>In-to Pers puruaid him ful sone,</L>
<L N="165">And with him all &thorn;at cumpany</L>
<L>&THORN;at bifore lifed in maumetry.</L>
<L>And als he went thurgh-out &thorn;at land,</L>
<L>All &thorn;e folk &thorn;at he &thorn;are fand</L>
<L>Ou&thorn;er war &thorn;ai baptist sone</L>
<L N="170">Or els &thorn;ai war vnto ded done.</L>
<L>&THORN;us conquert he all &thorn;at cuntre.<NOTE PLACE="foot">T conquerd.</NOTE></L>
<L>Till he come tyll &thorn;at same cete</L>
<L>Whare Cosdroas so sitand es</L>
<L>Als a god, in grete reches.</L>
<L N="175">Into &thorn;e toure he went full sone</L>
<L>And fand him sitand in his trone,</L>
<L>Dubbed obut with pricius stanes</L>
<L>And dight ful nobilly for &thorn;e nanes;</L>
<L>Biside him stode &thorn;at haly tre</L>
<L N="180">&THORN;at &thorn;ai had soght so forto se.</L>
<L>And souerainly for &thorn;at tre sake</L>
<L>Wirschip to him gan &thorn;ai make.</L>
<L>&THORN;an Cosdroas was full affraid.<NOTE PLACE="foot">T ful affrayd.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;us Eraclius to him said:</L>
<L N="185">"If &thorn;o will haue &thorn;i life in land,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H &thorn;o, T &thorn;ou.</NOTE></L>
<L>Als I say sall &thorn;ou vnderstand.<NOTE PLACE="foot">T sal.</NOTE></L>
<L>For &thorn;ou has done &thorn;is tre honore<NOTE PLACE="foot">T honowre.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at bare Jhesu, oure sauyore &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">T sauyoure.</NOTE></L>
<L>All-if &thorn;ou did it noght for him:</L>
<L N="190">Vnto &thorn;e grante I life and lym</L>
<L>At &thorn;e reuerence of &thorn;is haly tre,</L>
<L>If &thorn;o will trow in Jhesu fre</L>
<L>And forsake all &thorn;i mawmetry</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou and &thorn;i folk yn affy,</L>
<L N="195">And turn &thorn;e unto Jhesu Crist</L>
<L>&amp; in his name will be baptist.</L>
<L>&THORN;i life in land &thorn;an haue &thorn;ou sall</L>
<L>And all &thorn;i kingdom still withall.</L>
<L>And if &thorn;ou will noght do &thorn;is rede,</L>
<L N="200">With my swerd &thorn;ou sal be dede".<NOTE PLACE="foot">T swerde.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;is sarzin wald noght turn his mode,</L>
<L>To leue his fals goddes for no gude.</L>
<L>&THORN;arfore Eraclius ful sone</L>
<L>Strake of his heuyd with-outen hone,</L>
<L N="205">And bad &thorn;at he su(l)d haue beriing<NOTE PLACE="foot">T sul.</NOTE></L>
<L>By-caus &thorn;at he had bene a king.</L>
<L>&THORN;an &thorn;ai toke &thorn;at haly tre</L>
<L>With ful grete solempnite</L>
<L>And bare it furth so &thorn;am omang,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H if st. it.</NOTE></L>
<L N="210">With himpnes and with nobil sang.</L>
<L>And all &thorn;e folk &thorn;an war ful glad</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ai &thorn;is haly tre &thorn;us had.</L>
<L>Hamward &thorn;ai toke &thorn;e way in hy,</L>
<L>With mekill mirth and melody.</L>
<L N="215">And als &thorn;ai come in &thorn;e strete</L>
<L>Doun ouer &thorn;e mownt of Olyuete,</L>
<L>Als it fell in &thorn;are iornay,</L>
<L>To Jerusalem &thorn;e redy way,</L>
<L>Graithly furth &thorn;ai held &thorn;e gate</L>
<L N="220">Vnto &thorn;ai come till &thorn;at ilk zate</L>
<L>Whare Jhesus Crist went in ful playn</L>
<L>When he come &thorn;eder at suffer payn;</L>
<L>And mekill folk of &thorn;at same toune</L>
<L>&THORN;at war cumen with processiowne,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H &thorn;at st. &thorn;ar.</NOTE></L>
<L N="225">For wirschip of &thorn;e haly tre,</L>
<L>And sum, &thorn;at reall sight to se.</L>
<L>Eraclius him-self gan ride</L>
<L>Bifor &thorn;e prese with mekill pride;</L>
<L>And o&thorn;er lordes &thorn;at with him ware,</L>
<L N="230">&THORN;e haly cros oma(n)g &thorn;am bare.<NOTE PLACE="foot">T omang.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;us with grete solempnite</L>
<L>Entred &thorn;ai to &thorn;at cete.</L>
<L>Bot when &thorn;ai neghed &thorn;e zates nere,</L>
<L>&THORN;is meruaill fell on &thorn;is manere:<NOTE PLACE="foot">T meruayl.</NOTE></L>
<L N="235">&THORN;e zates, &thorn;at bifore war wide,</L>
<L>Closed samyn sone in &thorn;at tyde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at kenyng of zate was &thorn;are nane,</L>
<L>Bot all closed alls a wall of stane;</L>
<L>So &thorn;at &thorn;ai might no takning se</L>
<L N="240">On whilk syde &thorn;ai suld haue entre.</L>
<L>Sone when &thorn;ai saw &thorn;is wonder dede,</L>
<L>In &thorn;aire hertes &thorn;ai had grete drede.</L>
<L>Eraclius and o&thorn;er ma,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H Erachius.</NOTE></L>
<L>When &thorn;ai saw &thorn;at it was swa,</L>
<L N="245">&THORN;ai praied Jhesus, oure sawiowre,
<PB REF="00000269.tif" N="131"></L>
<L>In &thorn;at case &thorn;am to socoure</L>
<L>Thurgh uertu of &thorn;at haly tre,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ai might win to &thorn;at cete &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;us praied &thorn;ai all with drery steuyn,</L>
<L N="250">Heueand up &thorn;aire heuides till heuyn.</L>
<L>And als &thorn;ai loked so up on hight,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai saw ane angell schineand bright</L>
<L>Euyn opon &thorn;e wall standand</L>
<L>And &thorn;e signe of &thorn;e cros in his hand;</L>
<L N="255">He stode obouen whare &thorn;e zate suld be,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ir wordes on &thorn;is wise sayd he,</L>
<L>He said: "when Crist, of heuyn king,</L>
<L>&THORN;at lord es of all erthly thing,</L>
<L>&THORN;is same wai to &thorn;is cete went</L>
<L N="260">&THORN;are forto suffer grefe turment,<NOTE PLACE="foot">grefe st. grete?</NOTE></L>
<L>In at &thorn;is zate he toke &thorn;e way;</L>
<L>Bot he come all on o&thorn;er array:</L>
<L>Grete hors for him none ordand was,</L>
<L>Bot sitand on a simple ass;</L>
<L N="265">He was noght cled in kinges clething,</L>
<L>Bot pouerly went he in all thing;</L>
<L>He went noght with grete minstralsy,</L>
<L>Bot in his prayers ful preuely &mdash;</L>
<L>Ensaumple suthly forto gif</L>
<L N="270">To &thorn;am &thorn;at in his law wald lif,</L>
<L>In him to trow with trew entent</L>
<L>And mekely to wende als he went".</L>
<L>When &thorn;is was said, he went up euyn</L>
<L>With grete light till oure lord in heuyn.</L>
<L N="275">&THORN;e Emperoure &thorn;an Eraclius</L>
<L>Ful hertly thanked dere Jhesus,</L>
<L>And all &thorn;e folk &thorn;at with him ware</L>
<L>War ful faine of &thorn;is ferly fare.</L>
<L>Sone of his stede doun es he light.</L>
<L N="280">And kest of all his clething bright,</L>
<L>His corown and his kinges array</L>
<L>And his dubbing he did oway,</L>
<L>And barefot went he on his fete,</L>
<L>Bereand &thorn;e cors by &thorn;e strete.</L>
<L N="285">And on &thorn;is maner did &thorn;ai all.</L>
<L>And when &thorn;e king come nere &thorn;e wall:</L>
<L>It opind and wex zates wide,</L>
<L>Als it had bene bifor &thorn;at tyde.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai entred &thorn;an with solempne sang,</L>
<L N="290">Ful mekill mirth was &thorn;am oma(n)g.</L>
<L>And &thorn;e cros bare &thorn;ai &thorn;am bitwene</L>
<L>Till &thorn;e stede whare it bifore had bene,</L>
<L>And up &thorn;ai set it really,</L>
<L>And honord it als was worthi.</L>
<L N="295">&THORN;at day &thorn;are thurgh &thorn;e cors allane</L>
<L>War miracles wroght ful mani ane:</L>
<L>Of sere blind men &thorn;at had &thorn;aire sight,</L>
<L>And crokid men war made ful right,</L>
<L>Of parlesy war helid grete wane,</L>
<L N="300">And dum and defe ful mani ane,</L>
<L>And leprous men had hele in haste,</L>
<L>And out of many war deuils chaste.</L>
<L>&THORN;us war &thorn;ai held ful grete plente</L>
<L>Thurgh vertu of (&thorn;at) haly tre</L>
<L N="305">&THORN;at bare Jhesu, oure sawiowre &mdash;</L>
<L>Vnto him be euer honowre!</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="27" TYPE="legend">
<HEAD>27. In festo sci Mathei appostoli et euang. historia.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>S. Tib. fol. 263 b-266 a 2.</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Saint Mathew, &thorn;e appostell of Crist</L>
<L>&THORN;at named es ewangelist,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H namen in named corr.</NOTE></L>
<L>When Crist, his mayister, to heuyn assend,</L>
<L>In liue lang efter gan he lend</L>
<L N="5">And went ful fer in feld and town</L>
<L>And preches of Cristes passioune.</L>
<L>And till a cuntre come he swa</L>
<L>&THORN;at cald was Ethiopia;</L>
<L>&THORN;are he preched and baptist all</L>
<L N="10">&THORN;at vnto rightwis fath wald fall.</L>
<L>And in &thorn;at seme cuntre war sted<NOTE PLACE="foot">H seme = same (vgl. mede, seke).</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000270.tif" N="132"></L>
<L>Tow mawmettes, &thorn;at &thorn;e folk mis-led,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H tow st. two.</NOTE></L>
<L>Zaroes and Arfaxat &thorn;ai hight,</L>
<L>And haldan goddes of ful grete might;<NOTE PLACE="foot">H haldan, T?.</NOTE></L>
<L N="15">In a cete wonand &thorn;ai war</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;an was named Naddabar,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e king was named &thorn;us,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;at same cuntre, Eglippus.</L>
<L>And &thorn;ir two mawmettes, fendes of hell,</L>
<L N="20">&THORN;at in &thorn;is same cete gan dwell,</L>
<L>Biswiked so both king and quene,</L>
<L>And all folk wend &thorn;ai goddes had bene;</L>
<L>And for sere wonders &thorn;at &thorn;ai wroght</L>
<L>Folk of sere cetece to &thorn;am soght</L>
<L N="25">And offerd giftes grete plente;<NOTE PLACE="foot">H efterd st. offerd (so auch Allerseelen V. 337).</NOTE></L>
<L>So did &thorn;e king and his menze.</L>
<L>&THORN;e meruailes of &thorn;ir mawmettes two</L>
<L>Thwrgh all &thorn;e cuntre kindeld so,</L>
<L>&THORN;at many men of unkuth landes,</L>
<L N="30">When &thorn;ai herd of swilk ti&thorn;andes,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H whem.</NOTE></L>
<L>Soght unto &thorn;am, grete and small,</L>
<L>Als to &thorn;aire goddes grettest of all.</L>
<L>And folk so in mistrowth to bring,</L>
<L>&THORN;is was &thorn;aire maners of wirking:</L>
<L N="35">Thurg deuils craft &thorn;ai made men dom<NOTE PLACE="foot">T thurgh. H crast.</NOTE></L>
<L>And eghen sight &thorn;ai toke fro sum,</L>
<L>And sum croked, &thorn;at &thorn;ai might noght ga:</L>
<L>And all &thorn;at &thorn;ai mahaymid swa</L>
<L>Soght to &thorn;am als goddes gude in(o)ght;<NOTE PLACE="foot">T gudeingh, H gudeinght.</NOTE></L>
<L N="40">And when &thorn;aire hurthyng withdrogh,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H hurthyng, T hurtyng. &thorn;ai fehlt?</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e folk war &thorn;an ful faine and wend<NOTE PLACE="foot">T wen.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ai had helid &thorn;am with &thorn;aire hend.</L>
<L>Wormes and serpens commanded &thorn;ai<NOTE PLACE="foot">T serpentes, H serpens.</NOTE></L>
<L>To bite men both night and day;</L>
<L N="45">And &thorn;e maumettes restreyned &thorn;aire bit,<NOTE PLACE="foot">And st. when? T mawmettes.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;an wend &thorn;e folk &thorn;ai had helid it.<NOTE PLACE="foot">H heledit.</NOTE></L>
<L>Saint Mathew, &thorn;e appostell fre,<NOTE PLACE="foot">T appostel.</NOTE></L>
<L>When he come to &thorn;at same cete,</L>
<L>Ogains &thorn;ir mawmettes gon he preche</L>
<L N="50">And &thorn;e trowth of Crist to teche.</L>
<L>He helid all &thorn;at to him wald cum,</L>
<L>Whilk &thorn;e deuils had made defe and dom;</L>
<L>And serpentes &thorn;at &thorn;e deuils raysed &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at made &thorn;am be ful mekill praysd<NOTE PLACE="foot">T mekil.</NOTE> &mdash;</L>
<L N="55">&THORN;e appostell, neuynand Cristes name,</L>
<L>Made &thorn;am to lig blind and lame;</L>
<L>And men &thorn;at &thorn;ai bifore had bitten</L>
<L>And with &thorn;aire tanges ful sare smetyn,<NOTE PLACE="foot">tanges st. tunges?</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e appostell thurgh name of Jhesu</L>
<L N="60">Made &thorn;am hale of hide and hew.</L>
<L>So in &thorn;at cete wond a man</L>
<L>&THORN;at Eunuchus was named &thorn;an,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H enmuchus.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e whilk had bene bifore baptiste</L>
<L>Of saint Philip, &thorn;e appostell of Crist;</L>
<L N="65">And when he herd of Mathew tell,</L>
<L>In his hows he did him dwell.</L>
<L>And &thorn;eder soght both more and les</L>
<L>&THORN;at war angerd with ani sekenes:</L>
<L>And sone al hale &thorn;ai turned hame</L>
<L N="70">Thurgh &thorn;e neuyning of Jhesu name;</L>
<L>And till &thorn;e pople so he prechid</L>
<L>And rightwis trowth so to &thorn;am techid,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H right wistrowth.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at all &thorn;e folk awonderd ware</L>
<L>Of his speking a(n)d of his lare.</L>
<L N="75">When it was to &thorn;e mawmettes kid</L>
<L>How &thorn;e appostell &thorn;aire dedes vndid,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai ordand &thorn;am him forto greue &mdash;</L>
<L>Bot god &thorn;arto wald gif no leue.</L>
<L>Men come ware Mathew gan dwel,</L>
<L N="80">And vnto him &thorn;us gan &thorn;ai tell:</L>
<L>"&THORN;e mawmettes cumes with ful grete rout,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H cum es, T cumes.</NOTE></L>
<L>And many dragons &thorn;am obout".</L>
<L>And so &thorn;ai did right als &thorn;ai said.</L>
<L>&THORN;e folk for &thorn;am war ful affraid:</L>
<L N="85">For &thorn;e dragons wonder wele<NOTE PLACE="foot">H won|derd, T wonder.</NOTE></L>
<L>War armed with scales stif als stele;</L>
<L>Out at &thorn;aire nese come brinand schire</L>
<L>Windes of bronstane and of fire,</L>
<L>And swilk stink come of it allane</L>
<L N="90">&THORN;at it slogh men ful mani ane.</L>
<L>Saint Mathew sayned him with gude will</L>
<L>And sone bigan to gang &thorn;am till.
<PB REF="00000271.tif" N="133"></L>
<L>Eunuchus sau how &thorn;at it fore:<NOTE PLACE="foot">T saw.</NOTE></L>
<L>And hastily he sperd &thorn;e dore<NOTE PLACE="foot">H spred, T sperd.</NOTE></L>
<L N="95">And defendid Mathew furth to pas.</L>
<L>And for&thorn;ermar &thorn;an &thorn;us he aff:</L>
<L>"Sir, at &thorn;e window, if &thorn;ou will,</L>
<L>Sall I speke &thorn;ir mawmettes till.</L>
<L>And stand &thorn;ou still, oure wordes to here!"</L>
<L N="100">&THORN;an answerd he on &thorn;is manere:</L>
<L>"Opin &thorn;e dore, lat me pas out!</L>
<L>For of zon deuils haue I no dout.</L>
<L>And at &thorn;e window may &thorn;ou se</L>
<L>What hardines in &thorn;am sal be."<NOTE PLACE="foot">T sall.</NOTE></L>
<L N="105">&THORN;e dore &thorn;ai opind &thorn;an als fast,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e appostel furth es past.</L>
<L>&THORN;e dracones sone, when &thorn;ai him mete,<NOTE PLACE="foot">T dragones, H dracones.</NOTE></L>
<L>Fell bifor &thorn;e appostel fete,</L>
<L>And still &thorn;ai lay &thorn;are in &thorn;at stede,</L>
<L N="110">Domb and defe als &thorn;ai war ded.<NOTE PLACE="foot">H ward, T war.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;an said &thorn;e appostel, &thorn;are he stode,</L>
<L>To &thorn;a maumettes with milde mode:</L>
<L>"Whare es zowre craft, ze deuils? I sai,</L>
<L>Raise vp zowre menze, if ze may!"</L>
<L N="115">&THORN;an &thorn;ir deuils did &thorn;aire payne</L>
<L>&THORN;aire dragons forto rais ogayne;</L>
<L>Bot all &thorn;aire might moght none auaile:</L>
<L>Now&thorn;er stird &thorn;ai top ne taile.</L>
<L>&THORN;e appostell &thorn;an thurgh Jhesu might</L>
<L N="120">Raised &thorn;am ogayn ful right,</L>
<L>And fro &thorn;e cete gert &thorn;am fare,</L>
<L>&THORN;at neuer man saw of &thorn;am mare.</L>
<L>&THORN;e mawmettes fast er fled owai</L>
<L>And durst namore be sene &thorn;at dai.</L>
</LG>
<P>De resuscitacione filii regis Eglippi.</P>
<LG>
<L N="125">Sone efter &thorn;is grete nois bigan</L>
<L>In &thorn;at cete with many man:</L>
<L>&THORN;e kinges sun with ded was tane;</L>
<L>&THORN;arfore men morned many ane.</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;e twa mawmettes come in hy</L>
<L N="130">Vnto &thorn;e king ful hastily</L>
<L>And said &thorn;ai suld his sun up raise;</L>
<L>And &thorn;are-obut &thorn;ai wroght sere wais.<NOTE PLACE="foot">T obout.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bot when &thorn;aire gaudes might nogh(t) gayne,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e king &thorn;ai said: "sir, for sertayne,</L>
<L N="135">&THORN;i sun es rauist fro &thorn;e full fer<NOTE PLACE="foot">H for st. fro.</NOTE></L>
<L>And sall be a god, als we er;</L>
<L>Ful mekill might sal be him in,</L>
<L>To honore &thorn;e and all his kyn."</L>
<L>When Eunuchus herd &thorn;is thything,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H thy|thing.</NOTE></L>
<L N="140">What care was cumen unto &thorn;e king:</L>
<L>At his prayer &thorn;e appostell was</L>
<L>Led unto &thorn;e kinges palas.</L>
<L>And with him whent grete compani,<NOTE PLACE="foot">T u. H whent.</NOTE></L>
<L>With wirschip, als he was wor&thorn;i.</L>
<L N="145">&THORN;an (&thorn;e) quene, dam Eufenise,<NOTE PLACE="foot">T &thorn;e, fehlt in H.</NOTE></L>
<L>A woman &thorn;at was war &amp; wise,</L>
<L>Fell bifor &thorn;e appostell fete</L>
<L>And praied him hir bale to bete,</L>
<L>And said: "welkumd, sir, ertu heder!<NOTE PLACE="foot">l. welkum?</NOTE></L>
<L N="150">I knaw &thorn;i cuning al-to-geder,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H c&umacr;nig.</NOTE></L>
<L>I wate &thorn;at &thorn;ou ert cumen fro Crist,</L>
<L>Both his appostell and ewangelist,</L>
<L>To couer &thorn;am &thorn;at to him will craue</L>
<L>And his seruandes of sin to saue.</L>
<L N="155">Neuyn his name, sir, in &thorn;is stede</L>
<L>Ouer my sun, &thorn;at here es dede:</L>
<L>And wele I trow with might and mayn</L>
<L>&THORN;at he sall rise to life ogayn."</L>
<L>Here-of &thorn;e appostel was wele payd</L>
<L N="160">And all &thorn;us unto hir he said:</L>
<L>"Preching of me zit none herd &thorn;ou</L>
<L>And telles to me &thorn;at &thorn;ou will trow!</L>
<L>And &thorn;arfore tell I &thorn;e gayn</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;i sun sall be safe, sertayne."</L>
<L N="165">He toke &thorn;e child &thorn;an by &thorn;e hand</L>
<L>And said &thorn;ir wordes, &thorn;are standand:</L>
<L>"In &thorn;e name and &thorn;e powere</L>
<L>Of Jhesu Crist, my maister dere</L>
<L>&THORN;at for us died &thorn;e cros opon,</L>
<L N="170">I bid, &thorn;ou rise vp, Eustanon!"</L>
<L>And alsone rase &thorn;e childe fro ded.</L>
<L>&THORN;an was full grete ioy in &thorn;at stede.<NOTE PLACE="foot">H gretee oder grette?</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000272.tif" N="134"></L>
<L>And (&thorn;e) king, when he saw &thorn;is dede,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e fehlt in H; T?</NOTE></L>
<L>In his hert he had grete drede</L>
<L N="175">And to &thorn;e appostell bad bring</L>
<L>Besandes and many riche ring,</L>
<L>&amp; a coron of go(l)d ful bright<NOTE PLACE="foot">H god st. gold.</NOTE></L>
<L>Als to him &thorn;at was moste of might,</L>
<L>And a mantill of purpure pall</L>
<L N="180">Als lord and maister moste of all.</L>
<L>He sent bedels furth forto cry<MILESTONE N="180" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&amp; bad &thorn;ai suld cumand in hy</L>
<L>&THORN;e folk to cum se, more and les,</L>
<L>Grete god in a mans liknes.<NOTE PLACE="foot">181&mdash;184) sind in H nachgeschrieben.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot">H likines.</NOTE></L>
<L N="185">&THORN;e appostell, when (he) herd &thorn;aire bere,<NOTE PLACE="foot">T he, fehlt in H.</NOTE></L>
<L>Answard &thorn;ar-to on &thorn;is manere:</L>
<L>"I am nogh(t) god, for soth, said he,</L>
<L>Bot I am ane of Cristes menze,</L>
<L>And in his name I haue bigun</L>
<L N="190">And raised right &thorn;e kinges sun."</L>
<L>&THORN;an &thorn;e folk of &thorn;at cete</L>
<L>Gederd samin ful grete plente,</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e appostell haue &thorn;ai soght,</L>
<L>And grete giftes to him &thorn;ai brogh(t)<NOTE PLACE="foot">H giftes.</NOTE></L>
<L N="195">Of gold and siluer and precius stanes,</L>
<L>And o&thorn;er nobillay for &thorn;e nanes</L>
<L>&THORN;ai proferd him ful grete plente.</L>
<L>And unto &thorn;am &thorn;us answard he:</L>
<L>"Takes zowre gold and siluer bright</L>
<L N="200">Hethin owai out of my syght,</L>
<L>And takes all &thorn;is &thorn;at ze me bring,</L>
<L>And all &thorn;at I had of &thorn;e king!</L>
<L>And sen Jesus at oure prayere</L>
<L>Has raised his sun on &thorn;is manere,</L>
<L N="205">Makes a kirk for Jhesu sake</L>
<L>&THORN;at ze mai in zowre prayers make!</L>
<L>And &thorn;eder sall ze gader in-fere,</L>
<L>Goddes word and his lawes to lere."</L>
<L>At his word &thorn;ai bigan to wirk</L>
<L N="210">And sexty men sone mede a kirk,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H mede = made.</NOTE></L>
<L>And efter &thorn;at in thretty dais</L>
<L>Was it endid, &thorn;e stori sais.</L>
<L>When it was endid in all thing,</L>
<L>&THORN;e appostell named it &thorn;us: "risig" &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">H T risig.</NOTE></L>
<L N="215">Bi rison &thorn;at it was bigun</L>
<L>Thurg raising of &thorn;e kinges sun.</L>
<L>And to &thorn;at kirk &thorn;e folk fast presed,</L>
<L>And Cristes law so fast encresed.</L>
<L>Saint Mathew &thorn;an still dwelled &thorn;are</L>
<L N="220">Twenti zere and thre or mare,</L>
<L>Als bisschop suld, in grete degre.</L>
<L>And many prestes ordand he</L>
<L>And bisschoppes made he in &thorn;at land</L>
<L>And dekins, under &thorn;am to stand.</L>
<L N="225">He wroght fele kirkes on &thorn;is wise,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H rison.</NOTE></L>
<L>So forto mayntene goddes seruise.</L>
<L>And all &thorn;e folk turned unto Crist</L>
<L>And come to him and war baptist.</L>
<L>&THORN;e king Eglippus he baptist al-swa,</L>
<L N="230">And his quene Eufenissa,</L>
<L>And his sun &thorn;at raised was,<NOTE PLACE="foot">T son.</NOTE></L>
<L>And (all) &thorn;e pople in his palas.<NOTE PLACE="foot">T all, fehlt in H.</NOTE></L>
<L>His doghter Effeg(e)nia<NOTE PLACE="foot">H Effegnia.</NOTE></L>
<L>In maydenhed gan baptym ta,</L>
<L N="235">To &thorn;e appostell gan scho vnder-take<NOTE PLACE="foot">H manydenhed.</NOTE></L>
<L>At kepe hir clene for Cristes sake.<NOTE PLACE="foot">H seke, T sake.</NOTE></L>
<L>And Eufranon, &thorn;at raised was,</L>
<L>Till a bisschop he ordand has</L>
<L>And mede him maister of mani (men),<NOTE PLACE="foot">H mede = made.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot">T made. T men, fehlt in H.</NOTE></L>
<L N="240">Cristes laus to &thorn;am at ken.</L>
<L>Lang efterward &thorn;an fell it &thorn;us</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;is gude king Eglippus</L>
<L>Died and to god gaf his gaste,</L>
<L>And his sun efter him in haste.</L>
<L N="245">And &thorn;e empire &thorn;an halely zode</L>
<L>Till his bro&thorn;er son, als haire of blode &mdash;</L>
<L>Hirtacus hight &thorn;at ilk man,</L>
<L>&THORN;at for &thorn;aire king was corond &thorn;an.</L>
<L>And hastily, when he was king,</L>
<L N="250">Sone he vmthoght him of &thorn;is thing:</L>
<L>&THORN;at unto his wife wald he ta</L>
<L>&THORN;e kinges doghter, Effigenia,</L>
<L>&THORN;at of &thorn;e appostell had baptist bene,</L>
<L>Unto Criste forto kepe hir clene,
<PB REF="00000273.tif" N="135"></L>
<L N="255">&amp; of him had scho abit tane,</L>
<L>In chastite to lif allane,</L>
<L>And maistres was scho made alswa</L>
<L>Of two hundreth maydens or ma.</L>
<L>King Hirtacus &thorn;e appostell praies<NOTE PLACE="foot">T appostel.</NOTE></L>
<L N="260">And on &thorn;is wise to him he sais:</L>
<L>"Half my kingdom sall &thorn;ou haue</L>
<L>To do &thorn;is thing &thorn;at I will craue:</L>
<L>No-thing bot help with-owten strif</L>
<L>&THORN;at Effigenia war my wife."</L>
</LG>
<P>Causa quare mortuus est appostolus.</P>
<LG>
<L N="265">Here-of &thorn;e appostell was noght payd</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e king al &thorn;us he sayd:</L>
<L>"Dere sun, he said, ne wate &thorn;ou noght</L>
<L>How wisely &thorn;at woman has wroght?</L>
<L>In hir fadir tyme biforn</L>
<L N="270">To chastite &thorn;an was scho sworn</L>
<L>And spowse &thorn;an was scho made ful euyn</L>
<L>To Jhesu Crist, &thorn;e king of heuyn,</L>
<L>And hali abit has scho tane,</L>
<L>To serue him als lord allane.</L>
<L N="275">How suld it ani-wise be sua<NOTE PLACE="foot">T swa.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou hir to &thorn;i spouse sold ta</L>
<L>&THORN;at es spowsed lang tyme or now</L>
<L>Vntill a migtier king &thorn;an &thorn;ou?"</L>
<L>And alsone als king Hirtacus</L>
<L N="280">Herd &thorn;e appostell answer &thorn;us,</L>
<L>Oway he went and was ful wrath</L>
<L>And thoght to wait him with sum skath,</L>
<L>Bot furth he went &thorn;an on &thorn;is wise.</L>
<L>And &thorn;e mayden to &thorn;e appostell crise:</L>
<L N="285">"I pray &thorn;e, blis me with &thorn;i hand</L>
<L>Thwrgh him to wham &thorn;ou es serwand,<NOTE PLACE="foot">T thurgh, seruand.</NOTE></L>
<L>And all &thorn;ir maydens euerilkane!</L>
<L>For wele I wate, we mun be slane:</L>
<L>Zon cursed king oure bane will be</L>
<L N="290">&THORN;at mani a tyme has manast me."</L>
<L>&THORN;e appostell blisced &thorn;am euerilkane,</L>
<L>And bad &thorn;am traist in Crist allane</L>
<L>And drede noght forto dy for him</L>
<L>&THORN;at for &thorn;am died with panes grim.<NOTE PLACE="foot">T u. H panes.</NOTE></L>
<L N="295">&THORN;ai granted all with gude entent,</L>
<L>&THORN;an till his mes &thorn;e appostell went.</L>
<L>And when his mes was said and done,</L>
<L>To Jhesu Crist he made his bone</L>
<L>&THORN;at he suld so his seruandes saue,</L>
<L N="300">Fro right trowth &thorn;at &thorn;ai noght raue.</L>
<L>And, als it was oure lordes will,</L>
<L>In &thorn;e kirk so dw(e)lled he still.</L>
<L>Praiand to god with gude entent:</L>
<L>Vntill &thorn;e king his men had sent</L>
<L N="305">And bad &thorn;am &thorn;at he suld be slane.</L>
<L>Into &thorn;e kirk &thorn;ai come ilkane.</L>
<L>And he &thorn;at was &thorn;aire slaghter man<NOTE PLACE="foot">T &thorn;at, H had.</NOTE></L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e appostell playnly ran</L>
<L>And bare him thurgh with-owten let,</L>
<L N="310">&THORN;at &thorn;e swerd and &thorn;e auter met.</L>
<L>On &thorn;is wise was he marterd &thorn;are</L>
<L>And whent to blis for euermare.</L>
<L>And when &thorn;e folk herd say als sone</L>
<L>How &thorn;e king &thorn;is dede had done,</L>
<L N="315">Till his palais &thorn;ai went with fire:</L>
<L>To brin him &thorn;are was &thorn;aire desire;</L>
<L>Ilkone &thorn;ai swore &thorn;ai swld him brin</L>
<L>All quik his awin palas within.</L>
<L>&THORN;an to &thorn;am went bisschop and priste</L>
<L N="320">And all dekins &thorn;at war &thorn;am neste,</L>
<L>And all men of religioune,</L>
<L>&THORN;at vnto godes bidinges war boun,</L>
<L>Praied &thorn;e folk faire forto blin,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ai suld noght &thorn;e king so brin;</L>
<L N="325">&THORN;ai said: "ilkone us war ful lath</L>
<L>&THORN;at ze to him suld do slike skath,</L>
<L>For-whi it es oure lordes will</L>
<L>&THORN;at we do gude ogaynes ill.</L>
<L>Bot we will halow with gude chere</L>
<L N="330">&THORN;e marterdom of oure maister dere</L>
<L>And entre him, als es worthi &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">entre = inter.</NOTE></L>
<L>For god will quite all right wisly.</L>
<L>And lat us resaiue with gude will</L>
<L>What grace so god will send vs till."</L>
<L N="335">Efter &thorn;is cownsall &thorn;an &thorn;ai wroght,</L>
<L>To berying faire &thorn;ai him broght.</L>
<L>And furth in Cristes law gan &thorn;ai lend,</L>
<L>Als &thorn;e appostell had &thorn;am kend.</L>
<L>&THORN;an Hirtachus, &thorn;at cursed king,</L>
<L N="340">Sone efter gert samyn bring</L>
<L>Al &thorn;e burgas wiues of &thorn;at cete
<PB REF="00000274.tif" N="136"></L>
<L>And vnto &thorn;am &thorn;us cumand he:</L>
<L>"Smertly, he said, luke &thorn;at ze ga</L>
<L>Vntill &thorn;e maiden Effigenia</L>
<L N="345">And luke if ze hir hert may bring</L>
<L>For to be at my biding."</L>
<L>&THORN;e kinges (sand) sone haue &thorn;ai broght;<NOTE PLACE="foot">sand fehlt in H (T?).</NOTE></L>
<L>Bot all &thorn;at trauail was for noght:</L>
<L>&THORN;ai might wit no maner of gin</L>
<L N="350">Vnto &thorn;e kinges will hir win.</L>
<L>And when &thorn;e king &thorn;is vnder-stode,</L>
<L>He was so wroth: nere wex he wode.</L>
<L>And sone he gert ordayn a fire</L>
<L>Of kiddes and brandes brinand schire</L>
<L N="355">All obout &thorn;am in compas</L>
<L>Whare Effigenia and hir madins was,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H madims.</NOTE></L>
<L>Seruand god both night and day,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H might st. night.</NOTE></L>
<L>And "sertainly" &thorn;e king gan say,</L>
<L>"&THORN;e beggers sall be brint-ilkane,</L>
<L N="360">And oliue sall be leuid nane."</L>
<L>Bot when &thorn;e fire was best brinand,</L>
<L>Als &thorn;e king bifore cumand:<NOTE PLACE="foot">H And st. Als (T?).</NOTE></L>
<L>Effigenia had grete care,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H Effigemia.</NOTE></L>
<L>And hir madens had mekil mare;</L>
<L N="365">Scho put hir all in goddes will:</L>
<L>And sone ane angell come hir till,</L>
<L>And saint Mathew he come him with</L>
<L>&THORN;at in &thorn;at stede had gifen hir grith;</L>
<L>With bright bemes &thorn;ai both var braid;<NOTE PLACE="foot">H var = war.</NOTE></L>
<L N="370">And all &thorn;us vnto hir &thorn;ai said:</L>
<L>"Effigenia, drede &thorn;e noght!</L>
<L>For &thorn;is fire, &thorn;at &thorn;us es wroght,<MILESTONE N="181" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>It sall noght harm &thorn;e hide ne hew&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;arfore luke &thorn;ou in trowth be trew!</L>
<L N="375">For he &thorn;at has ordand &thorn;is payn,</L>
<L>Vnto him sal it turn ogain</L>
<L>And brin his palais doun &thorn;is day."</L>
<L>When &thorn;is was said, &thorn;ai went oway.</L>
<L>And grete wind fra god was sent,</L>
<L N="380">And all &thorn;e fire, right als it brent,</L>
<L>Vnto kinges palays it stert</L>
<L>And &thorn;are it brent, als god it gert,</L>
<L>So wightly, &thorn;at no-man might win</L>
<L>To liuer noght at was &thorn;arin,</L>
<L N="385">An unnethis &thorn;e king and his sun</L>
<L>With &thorn;e life oway er wun.</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;at sun ful sone onane</L>
<L>With a wikked euill was tane,</L>
<L>So, for grete paine he rared and cride,</L>
<L N="390">And so, calland &thorn;e deuill, he died.</L>
<L>&THORN;e king also, suthly to tell,</L>
<L>Was smetyn with ane euill of hell</L>
<L>Right fro &thorn;e heuid unto &thorn;e hele,</L>
<L>&THORN;at no-thing mig(ht) his cares kele.</L>
<L N="395">And for his euil was incurabill,</L>
<L>&THORN;us foul him fell, with-owten fabill;</L>
<L>He stikked him-self opon his swerde</L>
<L>And went to him &thorn;at him so lerid:</L>
<L>&THORN;at was &thorn;e deuill, his mayster dere&mdash;</L>
<L N="400">God schilld his seruandes fro &thorn;at fere!</L>
<L>And Effig(e)nia in all thing</L>
<L>Led hir life to goddes louing</L>
<L>And lifed and died in goddes seruice&mdash;</L>
<L>God grant us to wirk on &thorn;at uice,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H uice = wise.</NOTE></L>
<L N="405">So &thorn;at oure sawls may saued be&mdash;</L>
<L>Sais all amen, par charite! A. M. E. N.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e godspell also of &thorn;e mess</L>
<L>Untill us ful wele witnes</L>
<L>How saint Mathew, &thorn;at we of mene,</L>
<L N="410">A toller was, with-owten wene,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H tolled, T toller.</NOTE></L>
<L>And kepid toll in a cete,</L>
<L>And ful werldly man was he.</L>
<L>Till ore lorde Crist, als was his will,</L>
<L>Come on a tyme &thorn;at cete vntill:</L>
<L N="415">And sone he saw whare Mathew sat&mdash;</L>
<L>With tolling mikell gude he gat.</L>
<L>And unto him all &thorn;us said he:<NOTE PLACE="foot">T al.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Leue &thorn;at craft and folow me!"</L>
<L>And als sone als he herd &thorn;at steuyn,</L>
<L N="420">He was so fild of grace fro heuyn:</L>
<L>All erthly gude sone he forsoke</L>
<L>And with Jhesu &thorn;e way he toke&mdash;</L>
<L>Al failand thing forsoke he fast</L>
<L>And soght riches &thorn;at euer sall last,</L>
<L N="425">Ensawmple untill us at gif</L>
<L>To do &thorn;e same here, whils we lif.<NOTE PLACE="foot">H he we.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000275.tif" N="137"></L>
<L>&THORN;is same Mathew bifor &thorn;at tyme,</L>
<L>Als saint Luce witnes of hym,<NOTE PLACE="foot">T Luke.</NOTE></L>
<L>In his hows made to Crist a feste</L>
<L N="430">With o&thorn;er men &thorn;at war oneste.</L>
<L>And als he was &thorn;are at &thorn;e mete,</L>
<L>Vnto him come nowmber ful grete</L>
<L>Of puplicanes and phariseus,<NOTE PLACE="foot">T pharisews.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at sum war gude men and sum schrews.</L>
<L N="435">And &thorn;ase ilk &thorn;at war sinful men,</L>
<L>Said to his desciples &thorn;en:</L>
<L>"Whi ettes zowre maister in &thorn;ir wanes</L>
<L>With so many puplicanes?</L>
<L>Vs think, him aght wele to forbere</L>
<L N="440">To ett with &thorn;am &thorn;at sinful ere."</L>
<L>&THORN;us &thorn;ai &thorn;at neuer bifore had knawn</L>
<L>Now&thorn;er o&thorn;er mens hertes ne &thorn;aire awin,</L>
<L>Enchesond him in &thorn;at he wroght.</L>
<L>Bot he &thorn;at knaws both dede and thoght,</L>
<L N="445">With soft wordes, &thorn;am forto lere,</L>
<L>Answard to &thorn;am on &thorn;is manere:</L>
</LG>
<P>Non est opus ualentibus medicus, sed male habentibus.</P>
<LG>
<L>"It es no nede, he sais, to teche</L>
<L>A hale man forto haue a lache,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H lache st. leche.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bot &thorn;e man &thorn;at feles sekenes sare</L>
<L N="450">Nedes to layt a leches lare."</L>
<L>&THORN;us said he, sinful men to blame</L>
<L>And &thorn;am to strenkith &thorn;at trowed his name</L>
<L>And &thorn;am &thorn;at trew trowth wald bigin</L>
<L>More stabilly forto stand &thorn;arin.</L>
<L N="455">And &thorn;am &thorn;at in grete pride wald rise</L>
<L>Cald he to mekenes on &thorn;is wise,</L>
<L>With faire liknes he wald &thorn;am lere,</L>
<L>When &thorn;at he said on &thorn;is manere:</L>
<L>"Whare so ze wend in ilka way,</L>
<L N="460">Of me on &thorn;is wise luke ze say</L>
<L>&THORN;at I luf mercy on all wise</L>
<L>More &thorn;an I do sacrafice."<NOTE PLACE="foot">T sacrifise.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at es to mene: I will, men be</L>
<L>Mercifull in ilk degre</L>
<L N="465">And schew gude werkes in word &amp; hand,</L>
<L>More &thorn;an to mak till me ofrand.</L>
<L>Lo how faire he teches &thorn;are</L>
<L>&THORN;o men &thorn;at mislifand ware<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;o st. to?</NOTE></L>
<L>To mend &thorn;am-self of all misdede,</L>
<L N="470">And to help o&thorn;er &thorn;at had nede,</L>
<L>And alkins greuance to forgif,</L>
<L>And lely in &thorn;e lawes to lif</L>
<L>And wirschip god euer on al wise&mdash;</L>
<L>And se&thorn;in mak &thorn;aire sacrafice.</L>
<L N="475">And for&thorn;er-mar &thorn;am forto ken</L>
<L>&THORN;at said he ette with synful men,</L>
<L>And his lare lely &thorn;am to lere,</L>
<L>Zit said he more on &thorn;is manere:</L>
<L>"I come noght forto call allane</L>
<L N="480">Right-wis men, and o&thorn;er nane,</L>
<L>Bot I come forto call parchance</L>
<L>Synful men unto penance</L>
<L>And &thorn;am to teche, I come ful euyn,</L>
<L>How &thorn;ai sall win &thorn;e blis of heuyn."</L>
<L N="485">Now in &thorn;is godspel may men se</L>
<L>How Jhesu, ful of all bownte,</L>
<L>No hething in his hert wald think</L>
<L>With sinfull men to ett and drink&mdash;</L>
<L>And was, by-cause &thorn;at his techeing</L>
<L N="490">Vnto amendment might &thorn;am bring.</L>
<L>Bot sum had hertes hard als stanes,</L>
<L>And sum come when he cald &thorn;am anes&mdash;</L>
<L>Als saint Mathew with hert glad</L>
<L>Forsoke all hally &thorn;at he had,</L>
<L N="495">Land and linage, robes and rent,</L>
<L>And folod Crist with gude entent.<NOTE PLACE="foot">T folowd.</NOTE></L>
<L>Forsake we so &thorn;is werldes gude,</L>
<L>&THORN;at euer es fayland als &thorn;e flode,</L>
<L>And folow we Crist for heuen blis&mdash;</L>
<L N="500">Alweldand god &thorn;at wai us uis. Amen.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="28" TYPE="legend"><PB REF="00000276.tif" N="138">
<HEAD>28. Hic incipit passio apostolorum Simonis et Jude<NOTE PLACE="foot">S. Tib. fol. 266a 2&mdash;268a 1.</NOTE>).</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Saint Simon and saint Judas</L>
<L>Samyn playnly gan &thorn;ai pas</L>
<L>In sere cuntrese and sere land,</L>
<L>&THORN;e passion of Crist ful fast precheand.</L>
<L N="5">And &thorn;e wai right gan &thorn;ai hald</L>
<L>Vntill a land &thorn;at Pers was cald,</L>
<L>And &thorn;are &thorn;ai baptist folk ful fele</L>
<L>And techid &thorn;am right way to wele.</L>
<L>And &thorn;a two mawmettes fand &thorn;ai &thorn;are</L>
<L N="10">Of &thorn;e whilk we spak langare,</L>
<L>&THORN;at wonid in Ethiopia<NOTE PLACE="foot">T wond.</NOTE></L>
<L>And seyn fled saint Mathew fra;<NOTE PLACE="foot">T se&thorn;in, H seyn.</NOTE></L>
<L>Now in Perse &thorn;ai war wonand</L>
<L>And fobbed fele folk in &thorn;at lande.</L>
<L N="15">A duke &thorn;are wond, hight Varadac,</L>
<L>&THORN;at grete maistri thurgh &thorn;am gan mak;</L>
<L>And he was duke vnder &thorn;e king</L>
<L>&THORN;at Babiloyne had in kepeing.</L>
<L>A batayl had he vndertane&mdash;</L>
<L N="20">Thurgh deming of &thorn;ir deuils allane&mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">T demig.</NOTE></L>
<L>To fight ogains &thorn;e folk of Ynde</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;are pople bifore had pinde.</L>
<L>&THORN;an in &thorn;is ilk dukes cumpani</L>
<L>War many &thorn;at lifd on maumetri,</L>
<L N="25">For &thorn;ir ilk deuils said vnto sum</L>
<L>Cases &thorn;at suld efter cum.</L>
<L>And when &thorn;ai war to batail bown,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e mawmettes went &thorn;ai wit renown</L>
<L>To wit at &thorn;am &mdash; for &thorn;an was nede&mdash;</L>
<L N="30">How &thorn;ai suld in &thorn;e batayl spede.</L>
<L>Bot when &thorn;ai come &thorn;air goddes unto,<NOTE PLACE="foot">T &thorn;aire, H &thorn;ai mit &uuml;bschr. r.</NOTE></L>
<L>Als &thorn;ai bifore war won to do</L>
<L>&THORN;ai asked resons maniane;</L>
<L>Bot answer of &thorn;am had &thorn;ai nane;</L>
<L N="35">Ful still &thorn;ai stode and answerd noght&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;areof &thorn;e folk grete ferly thoght.</L>
<L>And when &thorn;ai saw no bote might be,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai went till ano&thorn;er cete,</L>
<L>Whare o&thorn;er deuils war halden in close</L>
<L N="40">And tald &thorn;e pople sere purpose;</L>
<L>&THORN;ai asked &thorn;am, when &thorn;ai come &thorn;are:</L>
<L>Whi &thorn;aire goddes gaf none answare,</L>
<L>Sen &thorn;ai had tald to &thorn;am biforn</L>
<L>Ful mani meruailes euyn and morn,</L>
<L N="45">And now in &thorn;aire most nede &thorn;ai fail</L>
<L>When &thorn;ai er boun unto batail.</L>
<L>&THORN;an answerd &thorn;e fendes in hi<NOTE PLACE="foot">T hy,</NOTE></L>
<L>And sayd: "&thorn;is es encheson whi<NOTE PLACE="foot">why.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at zowre god gifes to zow no rede:<NOTE PLACE="foot">H ne st. no.</NOTE></L>
<L N="50">&THORN;are are two appostels in &thorn;at stede,</L>
<L>Simon a(n)d Judas hat &thorn;ai right,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H ad.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;ai er of so mikill might,</L>
<L>&THORN;at, sen &thorn;ai come in zowre cete,</L>
<L>Zowre goddes to speke has no poste".</L>
<L N="55">Sone when &thorn;e duke herd &thorn;usgat say,</L>
<L>Hame ogaine he toke &thorn;e way,</L>
<L>And grath men sone gert he ga</L>
<L>Forto seke &thorn;e appostels twa.</L>
<L>Vntill &thorn;ai fand &thorn;am, haue &thorn;ai soght,</L>
<L N="60">Vntill &thorn;e duke &thorn;ai both er broght.</L>
<L>And hastily, when &thorn;ai come &thorn;are,<MILESTONE N="182" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>He asked &thorn;am: was men &thorn;ai ware<NOTE PLACE="foot">H was = whas.</NOTE></L>
<L>And wat cuntres &thorn;ai war cumen fra<NOTE PLACE="foot">T what.</NOTE></L>
<L>And weder &thorn;ai war boun to ga,</L>
<L N="65">And for wat reson, asked he,<NOTE PLACE="foot">T what.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ai war cumen to &thorn;at cete.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai answerd &thorn;an right, als &thorn;ai knew,</L>
<L>And say: "sir, we er of Ebreu</L>
<L>And seruandes vnto Jhesu Crist,</L>
<L N="70">&THORN;at in flom Jordan was baptist</L>
<L>And died on &thorn;e mount Caluary,</L>
<L>Man sawl vntill his blis at by;</L>
<L>And, sir, for zowre saluacioun</L>
<L>&THORN;us er we cumen unto &thorn;is toune:</L>
<L N="75">So &thorn;at ze may knaw by oure steuyn</L>
<L>&THORN;e might of oure lord god in heuyn".</L>
<L>&THORN;e duke &thorn;an, when he herd &thorn;is saw,</L>
<L>Sumdele bigan he Crist to knaw
<PB REF="00000277.tif" N="139"></L>
<L>And, all &thorn;aire tale when he had herd,</L>
<L N="80">Vnto &thorn;am &thorn;us he answerd:</L>
<L>"To bataill bus me wend &thorn;is tyde&mdash;</L>
<L>Langer I haue no tome to bide;</L>
<L>When I cum hame ano&thorn;er day,</L>
<L>&THORN;an sal i here how ze wil say".</L>
<L N="85">&THORN;e appostels &thorn;an answerd gude spede</L>
<L>And said: "sir, sertes, now es more nede</L>
<L>Him forto knaw and to him craue</L>
<L>Thurgh wham &thorn;ou may &thorn;e maistri haue&mdash;</L>
<L>For he may help &thorn;e in batayle,</L>
<L N="90">When &thorn;i mawmettes may noght auail".</L>
<L>&THORN;an said &thorn;e duke: "sen &thorn;at I se</L>
<L>Oure goddes to speke haue no pouste,</L>
<L>Bot euer, sen ze come, er &thorn;ai dom:</L>
<L>Say ze vs what thing es to com!"</L>
<L N="95">(&THORN;e) appostels answerd in &thorn;at tide<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e fehlt in T u. H.</NOTE></L>
<L>And said: "sir, bot a while abide!</L>
<L>We sal bid &thorn;ir deuils tell zow &thorn;an</L>
<L>What thing es to cum &mdash; if &thorn;ai can".</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;aire mawmettes er &thorn;ai went.</L>
<L N="100">&THORN;e appostels said in &thorn;aire present:</L>
<L>"Sais now, ze deuils, withowten greue</L>
<L>What so zow likes &mdash; we gif zow leue,</L>
<L>And ouer we cumand zow to say</L>
<L>What es to cum, if &thorn;at ze may".</L>
<L N="105">&THORN;ai spak &thorn;an, &thorn;at bifore war dom,</L>
<L>And said: grete bataill was to com,<NOTE PLACE="foot">T batayl.</NOTE></L>
<L>And possibill, men to be slane</L>
<L>On ai&thorn;er syde ful maniane.</L>
<L>When &thorn;e appostils &thorn;ir wordes herd,</L>
<L N="110">With mikill ioy in hert &thorn;ai ferd</L>
<L>And loud &thorn;ai logh at &thorn;is saying.</L>
<L>And &thorn;arefore thoght &thorn;e duke hething,</L>
<L>He said: "whi laugh ze so gude spede,<NOTE PLACE="foot">T lagh.</NOTE></L>
<L>And I in hert haue mekill drede</L>
<L N="115">For &thorn;ir wordes I here haue herd?"</L>
<L>&THORN;an &thorn;e appostells &thorn;us answerd:</L>
<L>"Drede &thorn;e noght, bot glad &thorn;o be<NOTE PLACE="foot">H &thorn;o, T &thorn;ou.</NOTE></L>
<L>For whe come to &thorn;is cuntre!<NOTE PLACE="foot">T u. H whe.</NOTE></L>
<L>With us &thorn;an entred pese a(n)d rest,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H ad.</NOTE></L>
<L N="120">&THORN;at with &thorn;e folk es fully fest;</L>
<L>Batayl sall none negh zow nere&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;arfore bese meri and mak gude chere!</L>
<L>And forto proue &thorn;is &thorn;at we say:</L>
<L>We bid &thorn;e noght bot bide a day,</L>
<L N="125">And tomorn in &thorn;is same tyme</L>
<L>In &thorn;e thrid howre, &thorn;at men cals prime,</L>
<L>Sall men of Ynde cum unto &thorn;e,</L>
<L>Sent fro &thorn;e king of &thorn;at cuntre,</L>
<L>&THORN;at to &thorn;e sall mak faith ful fast</L>
<L N="130">And pese bitwene &thorn;e landes to last&mdash;</L>
<L>And neuer, to &thorn;e at bede bataile.<NOTE PLACE="foot">H tataile.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;is sall &thorn;ou find with-owten faill".</L>
<L>&THORN;aire bisschoppes &thorn;an, both olde and zing,</L>
<L>&THORN;at had &thorn;ir maumett in keping,</L>
<L N="135">With grete laghter &thorn;ai gan out-braid</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e duke all &thorn;us &thorn;ai said:</L>
<L>"Sir duke, be war of bitter bales</L>
<L>And trow noght on &thorn;ir fals men tales!</L>
<L>Oure goddes, &thorn;at euer er trew als stele,</L>
<L N="140">Haue tald &thorn;e wittily and wele</L>
<L>What auenture sall bitide &thorn;e till,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou may be war, if &thorn;ou uill.<NOTE PLACE="foot">H uill, T will.</NOTE></L>
<L>And ordain &thorn;e, sir, &thorn;am ogayn!</L>
<L>For all &thorn;aire tales es bot a trayne;</L>
<L N="145">Forto ger &thorn;e dwell here still</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;ine enmis cum &thorn;e till.</L>
<L>And, sir, if &thorn;ou wirk on &thorn;is wise,</L>
<L>All &thorn;e land ogains &thorn;e will rise".</L>
<L>&THORN;an said &thorn;e appostels both in-fere</L>
<L N="150">Vnto &thorn;e duke on &thorn;is manere:</L>
<L>"A moneth, sir, bid we noght bide,<NOTE PLACE="foot">T sertain.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bot a day, till a sertan tide;</L>
<L>And tomorn bi prime of &thorn;e day</L>
<L>Sall &thorn;ou se soth all (&thorn;at) we say.<NOTE PLACE="foot">T all &thorn;at, &thorn;at fehlt in H.</NOTE></L>
<L N="155">&THORN;e men of Ynd sal cum to &thorn;e</L>
<L>And bring &thorn;e giftes grete plente</L>
<L>And bicum &thorn;i men tomorn,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H &thorn;ai st. &thorn;i.</NOTE></L>
<L>More &thorn;an euer &thorn;ai war biforn,</L>
<L>And trowage sall &thorn;ai grante to giff<NOTE PLACE="foot">T gif.</NOTE></L>
<L N="160">Vnto &thorn;is land, ay whils &thorn;ai lif".</L>
<L>All &thorn;at day &thorn;e duke gan dwel.</L>
<L>And sone on &thorn;e morn it bifell:</L>
<L>Messangers come fro Ynde and said
<PB REF="00000278.tif" N="140"></L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;aire princes war puruaid<NOTE PLACE="foot">H puruadid, T puruayd.</NOTE></L>
<L N="165">To cum and oblis &thorn;am, right &thorn;ore<NOTE PLACE="foot">T obliss.</NOTE></L>
<L>Alls &thorn;e appostels tald bifore;</L>
<L>All was fulfild fayre and wele</L>
<L>Als &thorn;ai had said euer-ilkadele.</L>
<L>&THORN;an &thorn;e duke was wonder wrath</L>
<L N="170">With &thorn;e mawmettes and &thorn;e bisscoppes bath,</L>
<L>And a grete fire he gert bigin</L>
<L>All &thorn;o bisschopes forto brin<NOTE PLACE="foot">T bisschoppes.</NOTE></L>
<L>And prestes &thorn;at on &thorn;e mawmettes leuid<NOTE PLACE="foot">T mamettes.</NOTE>;</L>
<L>For &thorn;ai so gretly had him greuyd,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H gertly, T gretly.</NOTE></L>
<L N="175">With pain, he said, he sul &thorn;am spill.</L>
<L>And &thorn;an &thorn;e appostels said him till:<NOTE PLACE="foot">T appostells.</NOTE></L>
<L>"We pray &thorn;e, sir, to turn &thorn;i rede!</L>
<L>Lat us noght be caus of &thorn;aire ded!</L>
<L>For we er sent to saue man kinde,</L>
<L N="180">And noght, forto gar &thorn;am be pinde".</L>
<L>&THORN;e dukes malis &thorn;us &thorn;ai sesid &mdash;</L>
<L>And malice in &thorn;e maumettes encresid:</L>
<L>Serpentes raised &thorn;ai maniane,</L>
<L>To bite &thorn;e folk in fless and bane:</L>
<L N="185">&THORN;e appostels wend &thorn;ai so to stroy.</L>
<L>Bot unto &thorn;am &thorn;ai might noght noi:</L>
<L>At &thorn;e appostell biding sone &thorn;ai went<NOTE PLACE="foot">H And, T At.</NOTE></L>
<L>Till &thorn;am ogain &thorn;at &thorn;am had sent,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e maumettes &thorn;ai bate so sare:<NOTE PLACE="foot">T mamettes.</NOTE></L>
<L N="190">Als wolues bigan &thorn;ai forto rare.</L>
<L>&THORN;an said &thorn;e duke: "lat &thorn;am allane!</L>
<L>Of &thorn;aire awyn fande &thorn;ai sall be slane,</L>
<L>To ded &thorn;ai sall be biten bath".</L>
<L>&THORN;e appostels said: "&thorn;at war vs lath,</L>
<L N="195">For we er sent fro ded to rayse,</L>
<L>And noght, forto sla, by no wais &mdash;</L>
<L>Swilk dedes sall noght be done by us".</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e serpentes &thorn;an said &thorn;ai &thorn;us:</L>
<L>"We cumand to zow &thorn;at ze ga</L>
<L N="200">Vnto &thorn;e stedes &thorn;at ze come fra!</L>
<L>And all &thorn;e venym with zow ze win</L>
<L>&THORN;at ze haue zetted &thorn;ir mawmettes in".<NOTE PLACE="foot">T heue.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;an had &thorn;o mawmettes welle more paine</L>
<L>When &thorn;e serpentes come ogayne</L>
<L N="205">And sowked &thorn;aire blode out bidene,<NOTE PLACE="foot">T blude.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;aire venym forto haue out clene.</L>
<L>&THORN;an fro &thorn;at cete gan (&thorn;ai) fare,<NOTE PLACE="foot">T &thorn;ai, fehlt in H.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at neuer man saw of &thorn;am mare.</L>
<L>And &thorn;e maumettes both in-fere</L>
<L N="210">Dwelled still &thorn;are all &thorn;at zere,</L>
<L>And sere folk zit to &thorn;am soght</L>
<L>For wikked wonders &thorn;at &thorn;ai wroght.</L>
<L>And &thorn;an att praier of &thorn;e king</L>
<L>And also at &thorn;e dukes prayng</L>
<L N="215">In Babiloine &thorn;e appostels dwelled</L>
<L>And fals bileue ful fast &thorn;ai felled;</L>
<L>&THORN;ai baptist sexti folk and ten,</L>
<L>With-owten childer and women.</L>
<L>&THORN;e king was baptist and &thorn;e quene</L>
<L N="220">And &thorn;aire menze all bidene,</L>
<L>&THORN;e duke also has baptym tane</L>
<L>And his menze ful many ane.</L>
<L>&THORN;e appostels thurgh precheing lele</L>
<L>Gederd &thorn;am desciples fele,</L>
<L N="225">Sum ordaind &thorn;ai pristes to be,</L>
<L>And dekins in lawer degre,</L>
<L>And o&thorn;er clerkes, to rede and sing</L>
<L>Lessons unto goddes loueing;</L>
<L>And haly kirk &thorn;us onord &thorn;ai</L>
<L N="230">In word and dede both night and day.</L>
<L>Of sekenes helid &thorn;ai all and sum</L>
<L>&THORN;at in trew trowth wald to &thorn;am cum.</L>
<L>De diacono false deffamato.</L>
</LG>
<P>On a tyme so it bifelle:</P>
<LG>
<L>A dekin, &thorn;at with &thorn;am gan dwell,</L>
<L N="235">Was blamed with grete felony</L>
<L>&THORN;at he suld haue done licheri</L>
<L>With ane &thorn;at was his sib woman;</L>
<L>And fell: &thorn;e child was born new &thorn;an.</L>
<L>To &thorn;e appostels was he wried for&thorn;i,</L>
<L N="240">Bot he denied vitterly.<NOTE PLACE="foot">H demed.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e appostels, when &thorn;ai herd &thorn;is thing,</L>
<L>Did &thorn;e childe bifor &thorn;am bring.<NOTE PLACE="foot">H brog st. bring.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e frendes broght it furth &thorn;am biforn:</L>
<L>And &thorn;ai asked when &thorn;e child was born.</L>
<L N="245">&THORN;e frendes answerd in &thorn;at time</L>
<L>And said: "&thorn;is day at &thorn;o houre of prime<NOTE PLACE="foot">H &thorn;o st. &thorn;e.</NOTE></L>
<L>Was he born of his moder milde".
<PB REF="00000279.tif" N="141"></L>
<L>&THORN;an said &thorn;e &abreve;ppostels to &thorn;e childe:</L>
<L>"In &thorn;e name of Jhesu almighty</L>
<L N="250">Speke, sun, and say vs swthfastly<NOTE PLACE="foot">T suthfastly.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e suth of all &thorn;is foul defame<MILESTONE N="183" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Whare-of &thorn;is dekin beres &thorn;e blame;</L>
<L>Say vs if he haue it wroght,</L>
<L>Whether he be blame-worthi or noght".</L>
<L N="255">&THORN;e childe, all-if he war so zong,</L>
<L>Spak all opinly with tong</L>
<L>And said: "&thorn;is dekin, &thorn;at &thorn;us es blamed,</L>
<L>Ful falsly es he defamed.</L>
<L>He es a gude man an a chaste,<NOTE PLACE="foot">T and.</NOTE></L>
<L N="260">Flesly syn neuer zit he taste".</L>
<L>&THORN;an many folk of &thorn;at cete</L>
<L>Made loueing unto Jhesu fre</L>
<L>And (in) his name &thorn;ai war baptist;<NOTE PLACE="foot">in H fehlt in.</NOTE></L>
<L>With all &thorn;e pople &thorn;is was poplist.</L>
<L N="265">&THORN;e bisschoppes &thorn;at &thorn;e maumettes zemid,</L>
<L>With all &thorn;aire maumettri war flemid.</L>
<L>Vntill a no&thorn;er land &thorn;ai went,</L>
<L>And many folk fowlly &thorn;ai schent;</L>
<L>A temple wightly gan &thorn;ai ma,</L>
<L N="270">And &thorn;ore &thorn;ai set &thorn;ir deuils twa,</L>
<L>Ful richely right for &thorn;e nanes</L>
<L>In gold and siluer and precius stanes;</L>
<L>A liknes of &thorn;e mone &thorn;ai made</L>
<L>All of siluer with bemes brade,</L>
<L N="275">And liknes of &thorn;e son &thorn;ai dight</L>
<L>All of gold with bemis bright:</L>
<L>&THORN;ai set &thorn;aire maumettes &thorn;are bitwene<NOTE PLACE="foot">H galy = gaily.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ful galy, als &thorn;ai goddes had bene.<NOTE PLACE="foot">T u. H migh.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ful many vntill &thorn;am soght,</L>
<L N="280">And grete reches to &thorn;am &thorn;a(i) broght.</L>
<L>And &thorn;us &thorn;ai dwellid many day:</L>
<L>Vntill &thorn;e appostels come &thorn;are oway</L>
<L>Prechand to folk in places sere.</L>
<L>And &thorn;an byfell on &thorn;is manere.</L>
<L N="285">&THORN;e appostels in &thorn;at same cete</L>
<L>Toke &thorn;aire ines a while to be;</L>
<L>And als sone als &thorn;ai war cumen &thorn;are,</L>
<L>&THORN;e maumettes &thorn;an migh(t) speke nomare.</L>
<L>Here-of &thorn;e bisschoppes sone herd tell.</L>
<L N="290">And when &thorn;ai wist whare &thorn;ai gan dwell,</L>
<L>Vntill &thorn;at hows wightly &thorn;ai went</L>
<L>With mani sarzins of &thorn;aire assent</L>
<L>&amp; till &thorn;e husband &thorn;ai said sone:</L>
<L>"Send us furth &thorn;a deuils, haue done!</L>
<L N="295">&THORN;at enmis er and has bene ay</L>
<L>To &thorn;am &thorn;at er oure goddes verray;</L>
<L>Or els, forsuth, we sall ger brin</L>
<L>&THORN;e and all &thorn;at er &thorn;arin,<NOTE PLACE="foot">l. &thorn;e hows?</NOTE></L>
<L>Bot if ze smertly zow avise</L>
<L N="300">And till oure goddes mak sacrifice".<NOTE PLACE="foot">T sacrifise.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e folk &thorn;an war for &thorn;am adred</L>
<L>And &thorn;e appostels furth &thorn;ai led.</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e temple &thorn;ai come in hy:</L>
<L>And sone &thorn;e deuils bigan to cry:</L>
<L N="305">"Warto cum ze vntill vs,</L>
<L>Appostels of ay-lifand Jhesus?</L>
<L>In zowre cumyng both bane and lire</L>
<L>Of oure bodis er brint with fire".</L>
<L>&THORN;an &thorn;e bisschoppes with grete tene</L>
<L N="310">And o&thorn;er sarsyns cant and kene<NOTE PLACE="foot">cant strenuus.</NOTE></L>
<L>Said, &thorn;e appostels suld be broght</L>
<L>To ofer, whe&thorn;er &thorn;ai wald or noght.</L>
<L>So als &thorn;ai stode, a voyce ful euyn<NOTE PLACE="foot">H voyte.</NOTE></L>
<L>Spak vnto &thorn;am doun fra heuyn</L>
<L N="315">And bad &thorn;am chese ane of &thorn;ir twa:</L>
<L>Marterdom if &thorn;ai wald ta</L>
<L>And tak &thorn;e coron of heuyn clere,</L>
<L>Or els to chese on &thorn;is manere:</L>
<L>Sodan vengance on all &thorn;a</L>
<L N="320">&THORN;at in &thorn;at place pursued &thorn;am twa &mdash;</L>
<L>And sodanly it sall be graid.</L>
<L>&THORN;e appostels answerd &thorn;an and sayd:</L>
<L>"Mercy of god es more to craue</L>
<L>&THORN;an any vengance here to haue.</L>
<L N="325">&THORN;arfore &thorn;ir men, lord, lat &thorn;ou lif</L>
<L>And &thorn;e coron till us &thorn;ou gif!"</L>
<L>All &thorn;e pople &thorn;at &thorn;is voice herd</L>
<L>With mekill ferly all &thorn;ai ferd.</L>
<L>&THORN;e appostels pesed all &thorn;at prisent<NOTE PLACE="foot">T u. H prisent.</NOTE></L>
<L N="330">And said: "all pople, takes entent!</L>
<L>&THORN;e son, all wate ze weterly,</L>
<L>Es creature of god mighty,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e mone als for sertaine
<PB REF="00000280.tif" N="142"></L>
<L>Es suget unto his souerayne;</L>
<L N="335">Bot &thorn;ir maumettes &thorn;at with &thorn;am dwells<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Ms. propthes.</NOTE></L>
<L>Er foul fendes and no-thing els.</L>
<L>And suthly now &thorn;at it so be,</L>
<L>Here in sight ze sall &thorn;am se;</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;at ane sall speke my bro&thorn;er</L>
<L N="340">And I sall say unto &thorn;at o&thorn;er,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ai sall brek &thorn;aire seges bath;</L>
<L>And to zow sall &thorn;ai do no skath &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;arfore, when ze sall &thorn;am se,</L>
<L>No-thing abaist luke &thorn;at ze be!"</L>
<L N="345">Simon &thorn;an &thorn;us has bigun</L>
<L>To &thorn;e maumet mede in &thorn;e sun:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">T mawmet. H mede, T made.</NOTE></L>
<L>"&THORN;ou wikked deuill of hell, said he,</L>
<L>In Cristes name I cumand &thorn;e,</L>
<L>Wend out of &thorn;at sege in hy</L>
<L N="350">And brek doun all &thorn;i maumetri!</L>
<L>For doun in hell sall be &thorn;i hame".</L>
<L>And when Judas had said &thorn;e same,</L>
<L>Two fendes sone &thorn;aire sege forsoke,</L>
<L>War blak and ugly on to loke;</L>
<L N="355">&THORN;ai romide and made sorow Inogh,</L>
<L>And al &thorn;aire dubbing doun &thorn;ai drogh.</L>
<L>&THORN;e bisschoppes saw &thorn;at all was schent:</L>
<L>Ilkon &thorn;aire wapin in hand has hent,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">T has, H was.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ai brac &thorn;e appostels fles and banes<NOTE PLACE="foot2">T fless.</NOTE></L>
<L N="360">And made &thorn;am marters both at anes;</L>
<L>&THORN;aire heuides strake &thorn;ai of in-fere.</L>
<L>Vnto god &thorn;ai war ful dere.</L>
<L>&THORN;arfore he sent, when &thorn;ai war ded,</L>
<L>A light leuening unto &thorn;at stede,</L>
<L N="365">And brint &thorn;e temple into &thorn;e ground;</L>
<L>And &thorn;e two mawmettes in &thorn;at stound</L>
<L>War smetin with a thonore blast &mdash;</L>
<L>Vntill askes &thorn;ai fell als fast.</L>
<L>&THORN;an &thorn;e king by commun rede</L>
<L N="370">Did &thorn;e bisschoppes unto dede</L>
<L>And gert &thorn;e appostels beried be</L>
<L>With ful grete solempnite,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">H gretete.</NOTE></L>
<L>And wroght a kirk &thorn;aire for &thorn;aire sake,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">H &thorn;aire = &thorn;are.</NOTE></L>
<L>Minde of &thorn;am euermore to make.</L>
<L N="375">&THORN;us &thorn;ai died with grete turment.</L>
<L>&THORN;aire sawles sone to heuyn war hent</L>
<L>And &thorn;are &thorn;ai lif in lastand blis &mdash;</L>
<L>All-weldan god &thorn;eder vs wis!</L>
<TRAILER>A M E N.</TRAILER>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="29" TYPE="legend">
<HEAD>29. De omnibus sanctis historia<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Die folg. beiden Leg. auf Allerheiligen und Allerseelen fehlen in Ms. Tib.</NOTE>).</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Here may men lere, who lithes my steuyn,</L>
<L>A fest of all halowes in heuyn,</L>
<L>First of Mari, goddes moder dere,</L>
<L>And sethin of o&thorn;er saintes sere:</L>
<L N="5">Of angels, prophetes, and appostels gude,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">T mawmettes.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of marters, and maydens myld of mode &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;is feste es ordand of &thorn;am all.</L>
<L>And &thorn;e caus why, say zow I sall.</L>
<L>It was ordan, who lykes to luke,</L>
<L N="10">For resons foure, we find in buke:</L>
<L>&THORN;e first caus whi men wald it wirk,</L>
<L>Was for &thorn;e halowyng of a kyrk</L>
<L>&THORN;at first was temple for &thorn;e fendes</L>
<L>And sethin a kyrk for goddes frendes</L>
<L N="15">&THORN;e secund caws was for &thorn;is skill:</L>
<L>For men in &thorn;is fest myght ful-fill</L>
<L>&THORN;aire det, of whilk &thorn;ai war in dout,</L>
<L>To halows als &thorn;aire festes falles obout.</L>
<L>&THORN;e third: for &thorn;at men suld amend</L>
<L N="20">&THORN;aire trispas both with hert &amp; hend
<PB REF="00000281.tif" N="143"></L>
<L>In &thorn;is fest for all bidene<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. his st. &thorn;is.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ai bifore had rekles bene.</L>
<L>&THORN;e ferth: fore we suld lightly spede</L>
<L>To waste oure syn &amp; win us mede</L>
<L N="25">And haue what we will efter call,</L>
<L>When &thorn;at we hertly pray &thorn;am all.</L>
<L>&THORN;ir foure skils sall be declard</L>
<L>More plainely, who will tak reward.</L>
<L>Bot to &thorn;e first es forto tell</L>
<L N="30">Of &thorn;e kyrk halowing how it befell.</L>
<L>&THORN;e men of Rome, als it es red,</L>
<L>When &thorn;ai of all &thorn;e werld war dred</L>
<L>And had lordschip of ilk a land,</L>
<L>&THORN;an on &thorn;is manere &thorn;ai ordand:</L>
<L N="35">A temple made &thorn;ai &thorn;am bytwene,</L>
<L>More strang &thorn;an euer bifore had bene,</L>
<L>And Panteon &thorn;ai calde &thorn;e name &mdash;</L>
<L>"&THORN;e hows of goddes" &thorn;at menes &thorn;e same.</L>
<L>And in &thorn;e middes &thorn;an ordand &thorn;ai</L>
<L N="40">A sege ful reall of array,</L>
<L>In whilk hight places &thorn;ai honoure wald<NOTE PLACE="foot">hight st. high (vgl. thurght). l: place?</NOTE></L>
<L>A mawmet &thorn;at &thorn;aire god was cald,</L>
<L>And les mawmettes of tre or stone;</L>
<L>For ilk prouince was ordand one,</L>
<L N="45">And &thorn;ai war set &thorn;ore all obout,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e god of Rome ilkone to lout:</L>
<L>In signe &thorn;at Rome was lord allone</L>
<L>Of other prouince euerilkone,</L>
<L>To take of &thorn;am suyt and seruice.</L>
<L N="50">And when so any prouince wald rice<NOTE PLACE="foot">rice st. rise.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ogaines Rome, or rebell be,</L>
<L>&THORN;an by &thorn;aire mawmet myght &thorn;ai se:</L>
<L>For he &thorn;at war god of &thorn;at place,</L>
<L>Fro &thorn;e god of Rome suld turne his face,</L>
<L N="55">In takin &thorn;at he wald noght be<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. tanik st. takin.</NOTE></L>
<L>No langer vnder his powste.</L>
<L>&THORN;e lordes of Rome wald ordan &thorn;en</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;at prouince armed men</L>
<L>And ouercum &thorn;am with power plaine;</L>
<L N="60">&THORN;an wald &thorn;aire god turne him ogaine</L>
<L>And lout unto &thorn;e god of Rome.<MILESTONE N="184" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;us all &thorn;e werld dowted &thorn;aire dome.</L>
<L>And for &thorn;ai war so halden in prise,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai held &thorn;aire goddes witty &amp; wise</L>
<L N="65">And honord &thorn;am efter &thorn;aire might,</L>
<L>In worde and dede, both day &amp; night.</L>
<L>&THORN;an sum men said &thorn;at &thorn;ai suld make</L>
<L>Sere temples for sere goddes seke,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at ilk mawmet might haf ane,</L>
<L N="70">To be honord by hym allane.</L>
<L>Bot for &thorn;aire cete suffist noght</L>
<L>So many temples to haue wroght,</L>
<L>By hale assent &thorn;ai say &thorn;ai sall</L>
<L>Ordain a temple for &thorn;am all.</L>
<L N="75">Swilk temple, &thorn;ai said, suld be</L>
<L>Als meruaylus in all degre,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. meruaylis.</NOTE></L>
<L>Both in heght and brede &amp; lenkitth,</L>
<L>Als myght be made by mans strenkith.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai toke &thorn;aire rowm ful right &amp; rownd</L>
<L N="80">And broght &thorn;e werk obouen &thorn;e ground.</L>
<L>And &thorn;an &thorn;ai ordand on &thorn;is wise:</L>
<L>&THORN;at euer als &thorn;e walles suld rise,</L>
<L>With erth it was ay fild within,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at, what-tyme als &thorn;ai myght win</L>
<L N="85">Ouer &thorn;ase walles to rais a roue,</L>
<L>&THORN;e erth suld bere &thorn;e werk o-boue &mdash;</L>
<L>And so als on a hardind hill</L>
<L>&THORN;ai raised a rofe right at &thorn;aire will.</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;ai &thorn;at &thorn;an war maisters &thorn;ore</L>
<L N="90">Ordand on &thorn;is wise bifore:</L>
<L>&THORN;at euer als men &thorn;e erth down held,</L>
<L>&THORN;aire mone omang it &thorn;ai meld &mdash;</L>
<L>And &thorn;at was ordand for &thorn;is thing:</L>
<L>To pay for &thorn;e erth-out-bering,</L>
<L N="95">So &thorn;at it suld noy right noght.</L>
<L>For, when &thorn;e temple was all wroght</L>
<L>And ordand, als it aght to be,</L>
<L>&THORN;e king gert cry in &thorn;e cete:</L>
<L>Who-so wolde bere erth, more or myn,</L>
<L N="100">Sulde haue all &thorn;at &thorn;ai fand &thorn;arin.</L>
<L>And for &thorn;ai fand &thorn;ore faire mone,</L>
<L>Of berers had &thorn;ai grete plente,</L>
<L>And for &thorn;aire finding war &thorn;ai blith:</L>
<L>So was &thorn;e temple void als-swith.</L>
<L N="105">Bot first &thorn;e Romayns ordand has</L>
<L>A pynacle all of burned bras</L>
<L>Obouen &thorn;e temple forto stand,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. oboued.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at myght be sene ouer all &thorn;at land;
<PB REF="00000282.tif" N="144"></L>
<L>And in &thorn;at pynacle myght men se</L>
<L N="110">Sere wais unto sere cuntre.<NOTE PLACE="foot">urspr. cuntres; s ausrad.</NOTE></L>
<L>Whilk pynacle sethin was takin oway,</L>
<L>By deuils craft, als clerkes say,</L>
<L>And set down in &thorn;at same cete &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at zitt a selkouth es to ce.<NOTE PLACE="foot">ce st. se.</NOTE></L>
<L N="115">And (&thorn;e) temple whare it stode bifore<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e fehlt.</NOTE></L>
<L>Es opin and sall be euermore.</L>
<L>Fel efterward fwll many a zere,</L>
<L>When Rome of Crist had knawyng clere:</L>
<L>Saint Boniface &thorn;at pape was &thorn;ore,</L>
<L N="120">&THORN;e ferth efter gude pape Gregore,</L>
<L>&THORN;at was sex hundreth zere and fiue</L>
<L>Fro Crist come to &thorn;is erthly lyfe,</L>
<L>He purchast of &thorn;e Emperore,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;an was of Romayns gouernowre,</L>
<L N="125">&THORN;is ilk temple, &thorn;at &thorn;an was waste</L>
<L>And ordand was for mawmettes maste.</L>
<L>When he had getyn plaine powere,</L>
<L>&THORN;an ordand he on &thorn;(i)s manere:</L>
<L>In somertyde on &thorn;e elleuynd day</L>
<L N="130">&THORN;at falles in &thorn;e moneth of May,</L>
<L>&THORN;an gert he void both les and more</L>
<L>&THORN;at in &thorn;at temple was bifore</L>
<L>Ordand for &thorn;e deuils lay.</L>
<L>And when &thorn;ai war all wast oway,</L>
<L N="135">&THORN;an halowed he &thorn;at haly place,</L>
<L>And gert be puplist in ilk place</L>
<L>&THORN;at haly kirk men suld it call</L>
<L>Of saint Mari and marters all &mdash;</L>
<L>And it es namyd zitt in &thorn;is stownd</L>
<L N="140">&THORN;e kirk of "saint Mari &thorn;e rownd."</L>
<L>&THORN;at solempne fest in somertyde</L>
<L>Of all cuntres on ilk a side</L>
<L>Was honorde in &thorn;at haly place.</L>
<L>Till efterwarde a full grete space</L>
<L N="145">A-no&thorn;er pape, &thorn;at Gregore hight,</L>
<L>When &thorn;at he saw &thorn;is solempne sight</L>
<L>Was ordand &thorn;at tyme in &thorn;e zere</L>
<L>When corn and wyne was wonder dere,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at &thorn;e folk &thorn;at &thorn;eder zode</L>
<L N="150">Fayled oft for faut of &thorn;e fode:</L>
<L>He ordand it bi his counsaile,</L>
<L>In manere &thorn;at myght more ava(i)le,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. avalie.</NOTE></L>
<L>To be &thorn;e first day of Nouembre,</L>
<L>In &thorn;e moneth neght bifore Decembre,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. neght st. next.</NOTE></L>
<L N="155">When corn and wyne in werld es wun</L>
<L>And alkyns fode &thorn;an may be fun &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;is hegh fest &thorn;an ordan he</L>
<L>Thurgh all &thorn;e werld suld halowed be</L>
<L>In honore of &thorn;e saintes all</L>
<L N="160">&THORN;at euer has bene, or zit be sall.</L>
<L>So &thorn;is ilk place, &thorn;at was puruaid</L>
<L>For deuils seruice, als are said,</L>
<L>Now es it ordand for euer-more</L>
<L>All halowes forto be honord &thorn;ore,</L>
<L N="165">And &thorn;at was made for mawmettes mirk</L>
<L>Now it es halowed and haly kyrk.</L>
<L>&THORN;e secund skill, to understand,</L>
<L>Whi &thorn;is high fest was first ordand,</L>
<L>Es for-&thorn;i, &thorn;at men may noght newyn</L>
<L N="170">Half &thorn;e halows &thorn;at er in heuin,</L>
<L>To honore &thorn;am in &thorn;aire degre</L>
<L>Als &thorn;ai war wele worthy to be.</L>
<L>For sum clerk sais on &thorn;is manere:</L>
<L>Yf ilk a day thurgh-out &thorn;e zere</L>
<L N="175">Myght fyue thousand unto hym falld,</L>
<L>&THORN;e tende part suld noght be tald</L>
<L>Of halows. And if we take hede,</L>
<L>Of all &thorn;aire help here haue we nede.</L>
<L>For-&thorn;i es ordand &thorn;at we may</L>
<L N="180">Honore &thorn;am all on a day</L>
<L>And ask of &thorn;am what we will craue &mdash;</L>
<L>God graunt us grace &thorn;aire help to haue.</L>
<L>&THORN;e third point now, or we pas,</L>
<L>Es, whi &thorn;is fest first ordand was:</L>
<L N="185">By-caws men suld &thorn;e tyme restore</L>
<L>&THORN;at has bene spended mys byfore;</L>
<L>For all-yf we haue halowd here</L>
<L>Many festes of saintes sere</L>
<L>And halowd many haly daies,</L>
<L N="190">Oure note es no-thing for to prays,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. onore st. oure.</NOTE></L>
<L>For we do noght by morn ne none</L>
<L>Als suld on haly dais be done.</L>
<L>We spend in lust and couatyse</L>
<L>&THORN;at suld be spend in goddes seruyse</L>
<L N="195">And in his name &thorn;at aw &thorn;e day,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he for us to god sul pray.
<PB REF="00000283.tif" N="145"></L>
<L>And yf we to &thorn;aire wirschip wirk,</L>
<L>Outher in hows or haly kirk,</L>
<L>We do it oft so reklesly,</L>
<L N="200">&THORN;at no reward es tane &thorn;arby &mdash;</L>
<L>Oure hertes er so on erthly thing,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. onore st. oure.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at reues us list of goddes louing;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. list. st. lust?</NOTE></L>
<L>Sum men in kirk slomers and slapes,</L>
<L>Sum tentis to iangillyng &amp; iapes.</L>
<L N="205">Bot in &thorn;is feste men may amend</L>
<L>&THORN;at on &thorn;(i)s maners es mis-spend,</L>
<L>All halows for to honore right &mdash;</L>
<L>God graunt us &thorn;ar-to mynde &amp; myght.</L>
<L>&THORN;e ferth skill ful faire es fun</L>
<L N="210">Whi &thorn;at &thorn;is fest was first bygun:</L>
<L>For &thorn;at we suld more lightly haue<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. liohtly.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of god what we will of hym craue,</L>
<L>And lightlyer for he sall us here</L>
<L>When we to hym make oure prayere:</L>
<L N="215">Yf it be right &thorn;at we for pray</L>
<L>And ask yt on &thorn;is high haly-day.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. askyd st. ask yt.</NOTE></L>
<L>For als we pray with will &amp; steuyn</L>
<L>To all &thorn;e halows &thorn;at er in heuyn</L>
<L>And honors &thorn;am with gude entent,</L>
<L N="220">Right so &thorn;ai sall by one assent</L>
<L>Pray god for us &thorn;at we sall spede<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. prays.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of thing &thorn;at fittes for oure saul mede</L>
<L>Or &thorn;at es nedefull here till us.</L>
<L>Ensample schewes it bus be &thorn;us.</L>
<L N="225">For yf god will here one or towo,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. towo st. two.</NOTE></L>
<L>More lightly &thorn;an will he here mo:</L>
<L>&THORN;an will he gladly here &thorn;is day</L>
<L>When all halows unto him pray.</L>
<L>And &thorn;at &thorn;ai pray for us in-fere,</L>
<L N="230">Here by a visioune may men lere</L>
<L>&THORN;at was schewed in &thorn;e zere folowand<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. scheweud.</NOTE></L>
<L>When &thorn;is ilk fest was first ordand.</L>
<L>It bifell on al halow night</L>
<L>In Peter kirk at Rome ful right:</L>
<L N="235">He &thorn;at was keper of &thorn;at kyrk</L>
<L>Set all his witt gude werkes to wirk,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at nyght for all halowes seke<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. seke = sake.</NOTE></L>
<L>In his prayers wald he wake.</L>
<L>Byfore ilk auter kneled he doun</L>
<L N="240">And praied with gude deuocioune.</L>
<L>So at &thorn;e last, or he toke kepe,</L>
<L>Bifore &thorn;e hight auter he fel on slepe.</L>
<L>And als he in &thorn;at stede was sted,</L>
<L>His spirit was furth fro him led</L>
<L N="245">Unto a place, whore he had sight</L>
<L>Of god him-self sitand on hight,<NOTE PLACE="foot">d in sitand ist v. a. H. &uuml;berschr.</NOTE></L>
<L>Als a king with corown clene,</L>
<L>With more myrth &thorn;an men may of mene,</L>
<L>And all his angels him obout,</L>
<L N="250">Vnto him forto loue and lout.</L>
<L>A quene come with a dyademe,</L>
<L>&THORN;at goddes moder, him thoght, suld seme,</L>
<L>Als brigh(t) als sun es in &thorn;e ayre;<MILESTONE N="185" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And with hir felischip ful faire</L>
<L N="255">Of uirgins and women gude.</L>
<L>And sone &thorn;e kyng him-self up stode</L>
<L>And toke his moder saint Mari</L>
<L>And set hir on a sege him bi.</L>
<L>Sune efter &thorn;at &thorn;an saw he more:</L>
<L N="260">A man, was cled in camel-hore,</L>
<L>And with him folowd fast in hy</L>
<L>Of faire alde men grete cumpany.</L>
<L>And efter &thorn;am &thorn;an folowed nere</L>
<L>Ane, reuest als he a bisschop were,</L>
<L N="265">And with him come fele folk parfite,</L>
<L>All ordand in &thorn;at same abite.</L>
<L>&THORN;an come &thorn;are knightes, semly to se,</L>
<L>And o&thorn;er folk ful grete plente</L>
<L>Of diuers state and diuers steuyn,</L>
<L N="270">Of all degrese under &thorn;e heuyn.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. de grese.</NOTE></L>
<L>Byfore &thorn;e kyng all knelid &thorn;ai downe</L>
<L>With reuerence and deuocioune.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. deuocicioune.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;an he &thorn;at had bisschopps array,</L>
<L>Bigan &thorn;ore matins of &thorn;e day:</L>
<L N="275">And all &thorn;e pople &thorn;ore in present</L>
<L>Answerd to him with hale entent.</L>
<L>&THORN;is keper was sumdele adred.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. his st. &thorn;is.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bot sone &thorn;e angel, &thorn;at him led,</L>
<L>Said to him what it suld mene,</L>
<L N="280">All &thorn;is sight, &thorn;at he had sene:</L>
<L>First of god and his angels clere,</L>
<L>Sythen of Mari, his moder dere;</L>
<L>He &thorn;at in camell-hare es cled</L>
<L>And o&thorn;er &thorn;at ware with hym sted,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. o&thorn;ier.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000284.tif" N="146"></L>
<L N="285">He said, him-self was John baptist</L>
<L>And o&thorn;er prophetes war poplist;</L>
<L>&THORN;e kny gtes, he said, war merters gude<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. kyngtes. meriters.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at here for Crist had sched &thorn;aire blode;</L>
<L>And all &thorn;at folod efter &thorn;am &thorn;en</L>
<L N="290">War parfite folk, men and women;</L>
<L>All cum &thorn;ai bifore god &thorn;is day</L>
<L>Vnto him forto knele and pray</L>
<L>For mede both unto man and wife</L>
<L>&THORN;at honors &thorn;am here in &thorn;is life &mdash;</L>
<L N="295">&THORN;arfore es gude, men &thorn;am honowre</L>
<L>&THORN;at here of syn will haue socoure.</L>
<L>When all &thorn;is &thorn;us to end was red,</L>
<L>&THORN;e angell forthermare him led:</L>
<L>In other place he lete him se</L>
<L N="300">Ful sutill men in sere degre:</L>
<L>Sum &thorn;ore war full richely cled,</L>
<L>Ful faire of face and fully fed,</L>
<L>Sum grete myrth omang &thorn;am maked;</L>
<L>Sum war full nedy and full nakyd;</L>
<L N="305">Sum had of welthes full gude wone,</L>
<L>Sum cried for help and had righ(t) none.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. tried.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e angell spak &thorn;an in &thorn;at space</L>
<L>And purgatori he cald &thorn;at place;</L>
<L>All &thorn;o war sawls, he said, sertain,</L>
<L N="310">Whilk sum had ioy and sum had pain;</L>
<L>He said: &thorn;o &thorn;at in lykyng lendes</L>
<L>&THORN;ai haue gude help of lifand frendes,</L>
<L>And &thorn;o &thorn;at er of blisses bare</L>
<L>Has noman to mend &thorn;aire misfare.</L>
<L N="315">&THORN;e angell said &thorn;an to &thorn;is man:</L>
<L>"Go tell &thorn;an, als graythly als &thorn;ou can,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;an ist wol zu tilgen.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;is uisioun unto &thorn;e pope of Rome,</L>
<L>And do &thorn;ou &thorn;an efter his dome!"</L>
<L>&THORN;is man, &thorn;at had &thorn;e kyrk to kepe,</L>
<L N="320">Waknyd &thorn;an out of his slepe,</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e pope he tolde ilk dele,</L>
<L>Als &thorn;e angell him warned wele.</L>
<L>And when &thorn;e pape had herd &thorn;is tale,</L>
<L>He ordand bi ys counsail hale<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. &thorn;s oder ys st. his.</NOTE></L>
<L N="325">To make a feste, men to honowre,</L>
<L>All faued sawles vnto socoure:</L>
<L>&THORN;at erthly men sall for &thorn;am pray</L>
<L>And honore &thorn;am all on &thorn;at day,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ai may haue help generall</L>
<L N="330">&THORN;at has no speciall help to call.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="30" TYPE="legend">
<HEAD>30. Commemoracio fidelium defunctorum.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;is fest es knawe n omang man-kinde<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. knawed.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; cald "of cristen sawles &thorn;e mynde",</L>
<L>For mynde &thorn;is day es made sertaine</L>
<L>For all &thorn;e sawles &thorn;at suffers paine,</L>
<L N="5">&THORN;at er in way for to be saue</L>
<L>And myster has mans help to haue.</L>
<L>Bokes beris witnes morn a(n)d none:</L>
<L>&THORN;are may no sawl &thorn;at syn has done</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e blys of heuyn up wyn,</L>
<L N="10">Or it be klensyd clene of syn &mdash;</L>
<L>And &thorn;at es noght done, or &thorn;ai end;</L>
<L>Help of &thorn;aire frendes may mykel amend.</L>
<L>For if a man do so mykel syn</L>
<L>And schriue hym clene of more &amp; myn,</L>
<L N="15">And do noght &thorn;e penance here with will:</L>
<L>In purgatori he sall ful-fill,</L>
<L>Vnto his penance so fer sprede<NOTE PLACE="foot">im Ms. fehlt be?</NOTE></L>
<L>To make amendes for his misdede.</L>
<L>And if &thorn;e preste, &thorn;at schryues &thorn;e,</L>
<L N="20">Vn-timand or so rekles be</L>
<L>&THORN;at he gif &thorn;e noght penance right</L>
<L>&THORN;at es pursuand for &thorn;i plight:</L>
<L>Bot if &thorn;ou haue repentance more</L>
<L>And with sorow make asseth &thorn;erfore,</L>
<L N="25">In purgatori &thorn;ou sall be pynde,</L>
<L>To-tyme &thorn;i saul be fully finde &mdash;
<PB REF="00000285.tif" N="147"></L>
<L>Bot penance &thorn;at &thorn;e preste gyfes &thorn;e,</L>
<L>All-if it neuer so littill be,</L>
<L>Fro &thorn;e fende it sall &thorn;e saue<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. haue st. saue.</NOTE></L>
<L N="30">And help &thorn;e blis in heuyn to haue.</L>
<L>Bot all &thorn;at &thorn;ou here suffers les<NOTE PLACE="foot">l. for st. bot?</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;an &thorn;i euyll wirkyng wurthi es,</L>
<L>&THORN;i saul sall suffer penance wer</L>
<L>In purgatory, or yit pas fer.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. yit od. &thorn;it st. it.</NOTE></L>
<L N="35">No syn sall fro penance be sparde,</L>
<L>Ne no gude werk with-out rewarde.</L>
<L>Bot if a saule suffer, als I say,</L>
<L>And lifand frendes here for it pray,</L>
<L>God settes to-geder &thorn;e paynes &thorn;ore</L>
<L N="40">And &thorn;e prayers &thorn;at er made &thorn;arfore:</L>
<L>&THORN;at he &thorn;at suld two monethes haue</L>
<L>In a moneth he may be saue,</L>
<L>And he &thorn;at suld haue pain a zere</L>
<L>In mykell les he may be clere.</L>
<L N="45">And if men for him syng or rede</L>
<L>Langer &thorn;an he of help has nede,</L>
<L>&THORN;an sall &thorn;o prayers forther pas</L>
<L>And help &thorn;am &thorn;at more myster has,</L>
<L>Or to &thorn;am-self here turn ogaine:</L>
<L N="50">So mend &thorn;aire life and les &thorn;aire pain.</L>
<L>&THORN;an es it wisdom wele to do</L>
<L>Here, whils we haue tyme &thorn;erto,</L>
<L>And suffer penance for oure syn,</L>
<L>Or life and sawll in swnder tw(i)n,<MILESTONE N="186" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="55">And namely, whils we er in myght.</L>
<L>For of saint Austine rede we right,</L>
<L>He sais: "a child &thorn;at es baptist</L>
<L>And dies &thorn;an graythly, I ges</L>
<L>&THORN;at he es sekyr of heuyn blis;</L>
<L N="60">And als man &thorn;at dose no mys</L>
<L>Bot liffes wele with all his myght,</L>
<L>Men may wele deme he dies right;</L>
<L>And als-so he &thorn;at has done syn</L>
<L>And makes amendes for more &amp; myn</L>
<L N="65">With penance, whils he power has,</L>
<L>To seker place we trow he pas,</L>
<L>And to haue blis he may be balde.</L>
<L>Bot he &thorn;at bides to he alde,</L>
<L>And of his mis will noght amend</L>
<L N="70">To his life be at &thorn;e last end:</L>
<L>And if he &thorn;an repentance haue,</L>
<L>We er noght seker he sall be saue</L>
<L>With-out grete trist of goddes mercy</L>
<L>And grete penance in purgatory".</L>
<L N="75">&THORN;an es it wit, sen we it chese,</L>
<L>&THORN;e sekyr way &thorn;at we noght lese;</L>
<L>For better es penance here to fulfill</L>
<L>&THORN;an efter be greued ogains oure will.</L>
<L>If we do penaunce, to haue blis,</L>
<L N="80">&THORN;an of oure mede may we noght mis;</L>
<L>And if we do it all for drede,</L>
<L>&THORN;an lightly may we lose oure mede.</L>
<L>And if we do it here lifand,</L>
<L>&THORN;an may we stabilly un(der)stand</L>
<L N="85">&THORN;at we sall wend &thorn;e seker way</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e life &thorn;at lastes ay.</L>
<L>And pain &thorn;at sawls has efter dede,</L>
<L>No-man wate here in what stede.</L>
<L>For purgatori, als elerkes tell,</L>
<L N="90">Es a place noght fer fro hell.</L>
<L>Bot o&thorn;er places sum sawles hald</L>
<L>&THORN;at purgatori may be cald,</L>
<L>For god has ordand sawles to be</L>
<L>In sere places and in sere degre,</L>
<L N="95">Whils &thorn;ai &thorn;aire penaunce sall ful-fill &mdash;</L>
<L>And &thorn;at es done for (cer)taine skill.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. fortaine.</NOTE></L>
<L>Sum sawles er pyned in certaine place,</L>
<L>Forto be sped in lytel space;</L>
<L>Sum sawles to sertaine place er send,</L>
<L N="100">Sum lifand men for to amend;</L>
<L>And sum to pyne er sent ful sone</L>
<L>In places whare &thorn;aire sin was done,</L>
<L>For lifand men &thorn;at war &thorn;am lefe</L>
<L>May help for to mend &thorn;aire myschefe,</L>
<L N="105">And sum men er warned by swilk thing<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. warnend.</NOTE></L>
<L>For to amend &thorn;aire mislifyng.</L>
<L>Sum sawles to esy places wendes</L>
<L>Thurgh prayers of wele-lifand frendes.</L>
<L>Sum sawles has power for to say</L>
<L N="110">To lifand men what mend &thorn;am may,</L>
<L>So titter forto bete &thorn;aire bale.<MILESTONE N="186" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Als may be trowed here bi a tale:</L>
<L>How sir Thebalde, &thorn;e bisschop gude,</L>
<L>Sent his fisshers to &thorn;e flode
<PB REF="00000286.tif" N="148"></L>
<L N="115">In heruest, when &thorn;e sun was hate.</L>
<L>And als &thorn;ai fisshed, bifell &thorn;usgate:</L>
<L>A grete yse toke &thorn;ai &thorn;am bi-twene,</L>
<L>Als it in winter-tyme had bene.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. in st. it.</NOTE></L>
<L>And of &thorn;at finding war &thorn;ai faine,</L>
<L N="120">By-caus &thorn;aire lord had sertaine paine,</L>
<L>Of a bryning, was in his fete &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at ise &thorn;ai hopid suld slake &thorn;e hete.</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e bisschop &thorn;ai haf it broght,</L>
<L>And mykell it hesid him, als him thoght,<NOTE PLACE="foot">hesid = esid.</NOTE></L>
<L N="125">Forto haue &thorn;e hete oway;</L>
<L>And so he did full many a day.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. he st. hit?</NOTE></L>
<L>Till on a tyme &thorn;at yse bigan</L>
<L>To make noys, als a lifand man.</L>
<L>And when &thorn;e bisschop herd &thorn;e same,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. &thorn;e se same (der Schreiber wollte seme schreiben).</NOTE></L>
<L N="130">He coniord it in Cristes name</L>
<L>&THORN;at it suld say him what it was.</L>
<L>And sone &thorn;e ise &thorn;us answerd has:</L>
<L>"I am a sawl, and suffers paine</L>
<L>&THORN;at was eniond for sin sertaine;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. einond.</NOTE></L>
<L N="135">A sertaine tyme here sall I dwell.</L>
<L>Bot wolde &thorn;ou do als I sall tell:</L>
<L>Thritty messes and &thorn;ou wald syng</L>
<L>On thritty dayes with-outen sesing:</L>
<L>By &thorn;o messes war broght till ende,</L>
<L N="140">Vnto welth &thorn;an suld I wende".</L>
<L>&THORN;e bisschop graunted gudely &thorn;an.</L>
<L>And on &thorn;e morn sone he bigan</L>
<L>And for &thorn;at sawl he praied fast,</L>
<L>To fiften dayes war fully past.</L>
<L N="145">&THORN;e sextend day, als he bigan</L>
<L>His mes, unto him come a man</L>
<L>&THORN;at was sent by &thorn;e fendes qua(i)ntyse,</L>
<L>And said unto him on &thorn;is wise:</L>
<L>"Sir, all &thorn;is cete, for sertaine,</L>
<L N="150">Ilk man es resyn other ogaine;</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;ou go rewle &thorn;am bi &thorn;i rede<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. &thorn;e st. &thorn;i.</NOTE></L>
<L>And gar &thorn;am sese, sune be &thorn;ai dede".<NOTE PLACE="foot">be = shall be.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e bisschop wightly went his way,</L>
<L>And so he left his mes &thorn;at day;</L>
<L N="155">Bot sone he fand &thorn;is tale untrew.</L>
<L>And on &thorn;e morn bigan he new</L>
<L>And for &thorn;at sawl his mes he sais,</L>
<L>And so he did ful twenty dayes.</L>
<L>And &thorn;an &thorn;e fend by his powere</L>
<L N="160">Sent a-nother fals messangere:</L>
<L>&THORN;at he sulde ger &thorn;e cete rise,</L>
<L>For it was vmsett with enmyse;</L>
<L>And so &thorn;at day his mes he left.</L>
<L>And on &thorn;e morn began he eft,</L>
<L N="165">For he wald sese &thorn;at sawl of pyne.</L>
<L>&THORN;an sang he twenty daies &amp; nyen.<NOTE PLACE="foot">nyen st. nyne.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e thrittid day to mes he zede:</L>
<L>And right so reuyst als he stode,</L>
<L>&THORN;e fende his sand unto him sent,</L>
<L N="170">And said: &thorn;e cete suld be brent</L>
<L>And all his palas sone suld brin,</L>
<L>Bot help hastily be sett &thorn;are-in.</L>
<L>&THORN;e bisschop said: if so wore,</L>
<L>His mes he wold nogh(t) leue &thorn;erfore.</L>
<L N="175">And so he said &thorn;e mes till hende.<NOTE PLACE="foot">hende = ende.</NOTE></L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e cete &thorn;an gan he wende:</L>
<L>And saue he saw euerilk dele &mdash;</L>
<L>And &thorn;arby wist he wonder wele</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e deuil had done &thorn;at gyle.</L>
<L N="180">And sune he went in &thorn;at same while</L>
<L>In to his chaumber, whore &thorn;e yse lay:</L>
<L>He fand it molten and waste oway &mdash;</L>
<L>And wele &thorn;e bisschop trowed by &thorn;is</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e sawl was went to blis. &mdash;</L>
<L N="185">Al-so sum sawles, als I are said,</L>
<L>In sertaine places has paine puraaid</L>
<L>For to amend men &thorn;at here dwell.</L>
<L>Als men may by ensample tell:</L>
<L>How a skole-maister in a stede</L>
<L N="190">Had a scoler &thorn;at drogh to dede;</L>
<L>&THORN;at scoler was of grete degre</L>
<L>Both of cunyng and dignyte,</L>
<L>And grete pride had he nyght &amp; day</L>
<L>Of cunyng and of riche array.</L>
<L N="195">His maister prayed and charged hym hard</L>
<L>&THORN;at he suld tel him efterward</L>
<L>All of his fare and his astate.</L>
<L>And efterwarde bifell &thorn;usgate:</L>
<L>Efter &thorn;is life, als he was lerd,</L>
<L N="200">Vnto his maister he aperd;
<PB REF="00000287.tif" N="149"></L>
<L>In a cape of parchemyn was he cled,</L>
<L>With rolles &thorn;at myght wele be red,</L>
<L>For &thorn;ai war wretyn wele &amp; clere</L>
<L>On ilk a syde with sophims sere;<NOTE PLACE="foot">sophim sophisma, auch 218, 251.</NOTE></L>
<L N="205">His cape with-in was ful of fire.</L>
<L>&THORN;e maister &thorn;an had grete desire</L>
<L>To wit whi he was &thorn;us arraid.</L>
<L>And &thorn;an &thorn;e sperit vnto him said:</L>
<L>"I am &thorn;e same skoler, said he,</L>
<L N="210">&THORN;at &thorn;ou prayed suld come vnto &thorn;e</L>
<L>Forto schew &thorn;e myne asstate;</L>
<L>And I sall tell &thorn;e alls I wate.</L>
<L>&THORN;is ilk cape &thorn;at &thorn;ou sese me were,</L>
<L>Es more heuy, me forto dere,</L>
<L N="215">&THORN;an if it war &thorn;e grettest toure</L>
<L>&THORN;at here es made for mans socoure;</L>
<L>And all &thorn;ir resons &thorn;at &thorn;ou here sese</L>
<L>War my sophims and sotiltese.</L>
<L>&THORN;is cape I bere for &thorn;e delyte</L>
<L N="220">&THORN;at I had, slike uain werk to write;</L>
<L>&THORN;is fire, &thorn;ou sese on ilk a syde,</L>
<L>Es put unto me for &thorn;at pride</L>
<L>&THORN;at I had of my riche clethyng,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. richee.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of pelure and of prechius thing &mdash;</L>
<L N="225">It brinnes me both nygh(t) &amp; day".</L>
<L>And &thorn;an &thorn;e maister gun him pray</L>
<L>&THORN;at he suld put furth fote or hand,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at he myght wele understand</L>
<L>Yf it war suth &thorn;at he &thorn;are said.</L>
<L N="230">And &thorn;an &thorn;e sperit, als he hym praid,</L>
<L>Put furth his hand out of his cape:</L>
<L>And of his finger fell doun a drope</L>
<L>In (&thorn;e) maister hand, hate als a cole,</L>
<L>And more smertly it made a hole</L>
<L N="235">&THORN;an suld ane arrow out of a bow &mdash;</L>
<L>Him thoght his hand brent on a low.</L>
<L>&THORN;e sperit said: "slike paine I fele,</L>
<L>And so hate am I euerilkadele.</L>
<L>Byd &thorn;ou my frendes for me pray!"</L>
<L N="240">When &thorn;is was said, he went oway &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;e maister wist noght how he zede.<NOTE PLACE="foot">zode in zede corr.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bot in his hert he had grete drede</L>
<L>And on &thorn;e morn he talde &thorn;is tale</L>
<L>Oma(n)g his scolers, grete &amp; smale,</L>
<L N="245">How he had with his skoler bene,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e signe in his hand was sene.</L>
<L>And unto &thorn;am he told &thorn;ir vers</L>
<L>&THORN;at here er sett, &thorn;us to rehers:</L>
</LG>
<P>Linquo choax ranis, cra coruis vanaque vanis.</P>
<P>Ad logicam pergo que mortis non timet ergo. et ce. et ce. et ce.</P>
<LG>
<L>"All uain stodis I here forsake &mdash;</L>
<L N="250">To froskes in feld I &thorn;am bitake;</L>
<L>Fynd sophims, &thorn;at clerkes in affyes,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. fynd. st. fyne.</NOTE></L>
<L>I leue to crakes &thorn;at crobbes &amp; cryes;<NOTE PLACE="foot">I. crokes?</NOTE></L>
<L>All sutill sayinges and unsertayne</L>
<L>I leue &thorn;am all, uoid thing and uaine.</L>
<L N="255">All werldly welth I will forsake,</L>
<L>And to goddes lawes I will me take".</L>
<L>To religioun he gan him drawe</L>
<L>And lifed and died in goddes lawe. &mdash;</L>
<L>Sum sawles swilk places er pined in</L>
<L N="260">Whore &thorn;ai had &thorn;aire delyte in syn.</L>
<L>Als it es red in a story</L>
<L>&THORN;at made es of &thorn;e gaste of Gy:</L>
<L>He had penaunce &amp; pyned his wife</L>
<L>For lust &thorn;at was done in his life,</L>
<L N="265">And pyned he was in &thorn;at same stede</L>
<L>Ware he did syn bifore his dede.</L>
<L>And ensaumple we find &thorn;ar-fore</L>
<L>By a tale of saint Gregore:</L>
<L>Of a preste &thorn;at used ful lang</L>
<L N="270">Vnto &thorn;e bathes oft forto gang.</L>
<L>When he come &thorn;ore, in ilk selown</L>
<L>A man he fand ay redy-bown</L>
<L>To serue him in ilk a dede,</L>
<L>And of him walde he take no mede.</L>
<L N="275">And sum-dele for to zelde he thoght:</L>
<L>Apon a day with him he broght</L>
<L>A lafe, &thorn;at he had blissed bifore,</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e man he bed it &thorn;ore.</L>
<L>&THORN;e man answerd with drery mode</L>
<L N="280">And said: "I use none erthly fode.</L>
<L>&THORN;is, wote I wele, es haloud brede:</L>
<L>To me it myght stand mykell in stede,</L>
<L>Wolde &thorn;ou it dele for (my) mysdede<NOTE PLACE="foot">vor mysdede fehlt my.</NOTE></L>
<L>Vnto pure men &thorn;at has nede.
<PB REF="00000288.tif" N="150"></L>
<L N="285">I am a sawl, &thorn;is &thorn;ou record,</L>
<L>&THORN;at sumtyme of &thorn;is hows was lord;</L>
<L>I am assigned for sertaine space</L>
<L>To haue my penaunce in &thorn;is place.</L>
<L>And wolde &thorn;ou for me messes syng,</L>
<L N="290">Out of my bale &thorn;ou myght me bring.</L>
<L>For als sone als &thorn;ou sall me mys</L>
<L>&THORN;an wit &thorn;ou wele, I am to blis".</L>
<L>&THORN;e preste sang for him daies seuyn</L>
<L>And hert(l)y praid to god of heui(n)<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. herty.</NOTE></L>
<L N="295">To help &thorn;at sawl out fro his paine.</L>
<L>Efter aght dayes he come ogaine;</L>
<L>And when he come, &thorn;e man he myst &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at he was safe, &thorn;arby he wyst. &mdash;</L>
<L>Foure thinges here may men rede<MILESTONE N="187" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="300">&THORN;at to sawles specially may spede:</L>
<L>&THORN;e first, prayers of frendes lifand,</L>
<L>&THORN;e secund, almus gyfen with hand,</L>
<L>&THORN;e thrid es messes for &thorn;am to syng,</L>
<L>&THORN;e fe(r)th es told for trew fastyng.</L>
<L N="305">Now first, &thorn;at &thorn;e prayers of frendes</L>
<L>May help &thorn;e sawles &thorn;at hethin wendes,</L>
<L>&THORN;at es proued wele by saint Gregore</L>
<L>In a tale &thorn;at es tolde last byfore.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. a st. &thorn;e?</NOTE></L>
<L>Als-so saint Gregore telles till us</L>
<L N="310">Of one, &thorn;at high(t) Paschasius;</L>
<L>A dekyn he was of grete degre</L>
<L>And haly man als-so was he.</L>
<L>Byfell, &thorn;at &thorn;e bisschop was dede</L>
<L>And one suld be chosin in his stede.</L>
<L N="315">Parfite men &thorn;an was &thorn;are two,</L>
<L>And all &thorn;ai wold haue one of &thorn;o.</L>
<L>Paschasius gaf his voice in hy</L>
<L>To him he wist was les wurthy.</L>
<L>And for &thorn;at dede, when he was ded,</L>
<L N="320">He sufferd paine in sertain stede.</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e bisschop he sethin aperde</L>
<L>And of his lifyng he him lerde:</L>
<L>"When &thorn;ou was chosen, als &thorn;ou wate,</L>
<L>I wist &thorn;at &thorn;ou was les of state;</L>
<L N="325">Ogains my conciens I assent:</L>
<L>And &thorn;are(fore) am I now turment.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. &thorn;are.</NOTE></L>
<L>Yf &thorn;ou will hertly pray for me,</L>
<L>&THORN;an sall I sone deliuerd be."</L>
<L>&THORN;e bisschop praid with gude entent:</L>
<L N="330">And Pascassius to heuyn es hent. &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;e secund thing &thorn;at saulles may mend,</L>
<L>Es almus gyfen with hert and hend.</L>
<L>&THORN;at witnes whilom, how it was,</L>
<L>A haly man, &thorn;at hight Judas.</L>
<L N="335">Vnto Jerusalem he ones sent</L>
<L>XII M. besaundes of gude payment,</L>
<L>To offer &thorn;are in almus-dede,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. efter st. offer (so schon 27, 25).</NOTE></L>
<L>And all for synfull sawles mede:</L>
<L>So hopid he in hert fully</L>
<L N="340">&THORN;at sawles suld be mend &thorn;are-by</L>
<L>And &thorn;at &thorn;ai suld efter &thorn;are paine</L>
<L>Be raised in endles life ogaine. &mdash;</L>
<L>And &thorn;at almus es of mykil myght,</L>
<L>&THORN;at may men here &amp; rede full right</L>
<L N="345">In a story, faire to lere,</L>
<L>&THORN;at es called Pers Tollonere.</L>
<L>In &thorn;is boke men may it find:<NOTE PLACE="foot">es ist die Homiliensammlung dess. Ms. gemeint, vgl. die Evang.-Gesch. des Ms. Vernon N. 45.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;arfore I leue it here bihind. &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;e third thing &thorn;at ordand es</L>
<L N="350">For help of sawles, es haly mes.</L>
<L>Als may be proued in many place,</L>
<L>&THORN;at now to speke war litell space.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. speke od. spele?</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;at it helpis to lifand men,</L>
<L>Here by ensample may men ken:</L>
<L N="355">Apon a tyme how &thorn;at it fore</L>
<L>Bi men &thorn;at soght for siluerore.</L>
<L>With-in &thorn;e erth so gun &thorn;ai crepe,</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;aire werk was wonder depe.</L>
<L>Down on &thorn;am fell a krag of stone</L>
<L N="360">And sone it slogh &thorn;am all &mdash; bot one,</L>
<L>And he was sted by-twen two stones,</L>
<L>And now&thorn;er brissed flessh no bones;</L>
<L>&THORN;e erth was so fer him obout,</L>
<L>&THORN;at on none wise migh(t) he win out.</L>
<L N="365">His wife wende he war ded for ay.</L>
<L>&THORN;arfore scho ordand ilk a day</L>
<L>For his sawl a mes to sing,</L>
<L>And on &thorn;is maner scho made ofryng:</L>
<L>Euerilkaday a lafe of brede</L>
<L N="370">And a piccher of wine or rede
<PB REF="00000289.tif" N="151"></L>
<L>And a candel of wax, to brin,</L>
<L>&THORN;at god him out of wo suld win.</L>
<L>And on &thorn;is wise scho wroght alway.</L>
<L>To-tyme &thorn;e deuill apon a day &mdash;</L>
<L N="375">At hir doyng he had dedeyne,</L>
<L>And als a frende he gun him feyne:</L>
<L>&THORN;e gude wife apon a day he mett;</L>
<L>Hir almus-dede for he wald lett,</L>
<L>He said &thorn;e mes was done for lang,</L>
<L N="380">And hame ogaine he gert hir gang.</L>
<L>On swilk maner he tyd hir thwise.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. he tyd st. betyd? thwise st. twise.</NOTE></L>
<L>And s(i)&thorn;en bifell on &thorn;is wise:</L>
<L>O&thorn;er mynours &thorn;eder fore,</L>
<L>For to seke &thorn;am syluer-ure,</L>
<L N="385">Whore &thorn;is chaunce was fallen bifore.</L>
<L>And als on of &thorn;am grubbed &thorn;ore,</L>
<L>He herd a uoice under him eri</L>
<L>And bad he suld smyte more softly.</L>
<L>He was aferd &amp; held him still</L>
<L N="390">And cald his felaws him untill.</L>
<L>Eft-sones &thorn;ore in &thorn;e erth he groue:</L>
<L>And all &thorn;ai herd, &thorn;at war oboue,</L>
<L>How one bineth bad him lat be,</L>
<L>"With herd stones &thorn;ou-hurtes me".</L>
<L N="395">&THORN;ai grofe on syde, als sais &thorn;e boke:</L>
<L>And hale and fere furth &thorn;ai him toke.</L>
<L>Here-of had &thorn;ai meruail strang.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai askyd hym how he lifed so lang.</L>
<L>He said: "als god him-self vouched safe,</L>
<L N="400">Ilk day of brede I had a lafe<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. ham. st. had (hauid?).</NOTE></L>
<L>And a vessell with wine &thorn;arin</L>
<L>And a wax-candell, for to brin &mdash;</L>
<L>Out-taken thre dais, &thorn;us I ferd."</L>
<L>And when his wife &thorn;ir wordes herd,</L>
<L N="405">&THORN;an wist scho wele, &amp; to &thorn;am said,</L>
<L>How &thorn;at &thorn;e fende had hir bitraid</L>
<L>&THORN;o thre daies, for to leue hir dede.</L>
<L>&THORN;us to &thorn;e life dose messes mede. &mdash;</L>
<L>Clerkes &thorn;us in &thorn;aire bokes declares:</L>
<L N="410">All folk &thorn;at fro &thorn;is folde here fares,</L>
<L>Outher er &thorn;ai right gude for sertaine,</L>
<L>Or els right euyll &amp; wurthy paine;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. wurtly.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e tone has welth, &thorn;e to&thorn;er has wo,</L>
<L>Or els in mene bi-twix &thorn;ir two.</L>
<L N="415">&THORN;e first, &thorn;at er right gude, may be</L>
<L>Ful wele declared in kyndes thre:</L>
<L>&THORN;e first: baptist &thorn;at dies als-tyte,</L>
<L>&THORN;e secund: merters, &thorn;e third: men parfite</L>
<L>&THORN;at of &thorn;is werld here rekkes noght</L>
<L N="420">Bot vnto heuyn has &thorn;aire thoght &mdash;</L>
<L>Whilk, yf &thorn;ai do here veniall syn,</L>
<L>It takes no rote &thorn;aire sawl with-in</L>
<L>More &thorn;an a drope of water here</L>
<L>Dose in fyre &thorn;at brinnes clere.</L>
<L N="425">For any swilk what man so prays,</L>
<L>It turnes to him-self &thorn;at it sais &mdash;</L>
<L>Als haly bokes beres witnes</L>
<L>On &thorn;is wise, als here writen es:</L>
<L>Oracio mea in sinu meo conuertetur.</L>
<L>To ilkone of &thorn;ir thre degrese</L>
<L N="430">Opins heuin, als clerkes se,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. se st. sese.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;eder wende &thorn;ai, when &thorn;ai dy,</L>
<L>And feles no pain in purgatory.</L>
<L>&THORN;at heuyn opins to new baptist,</L>
<L>Witnes &thorn;us saint Luke of Crist:</L>
</LG>
<P>Jhesu baptizato &amp; orante apertum est celum.</P>
<LG>
<L N="435">Baptime dose al syns downe</L>
<L>By vertu of Cristes passiowne,</L>
<L>Whe&thorn;er &thorn;ai be orriginall<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. whe&thorn;ei.</NOTE></L>
<L>Or dedly syns or veniall.</L>
<L>&THORN;at heuyn opins to marters gude,</L>
<L N="440">Said saint Steuyn &thorn;us, als he stode:</L>
<L>Ecce uide(o) celos apertos et ce.</L>
<L>He said: "lo, I se Jhesu stand</L>
<L>In heuyn opon his fader right hand" &mdash;</L>
<L>And &thorn;at may suthly signify</L>
<L>&THORN;at marters wendes to heuin in hy.</L>
<L N="445">&THORN;at heuyn opins to parfite men,</L>
<L>&THORN;us sais saint Johne, als clerkes ken:</L>
<L>Vidi et ecce hostium apertum est in celo &mdash;</L>
<L>"I saw a dore in heuyn on hight</L>
<L>Opin to men &thorn;at lifes right".</L>
<L>&THORN;us right gude men has all &thorn;aire will. &mdash;</L>
<L N="450">And &thorn;arogayn &thorn;ai &thorn;at er right ill</L>
<L>And er dampned withouten end,
<PB REF="00000290.tif" N="152"></L>
<L>It helpes now&thorn;er to say ne send,</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;at grofe to ger &thorn;am rise;</L>
<L>For saint Austin sais on &thorn;is wise:</L>
<L>Si scirem patrem meum esse in inferno,</L>
<L>non plus orarem pro eo quam pro diabolo:</L>
<L N="455">He sais &thorn;us: "if I saw my syre</L>
<L>Brinand depe in hell-fire,</L>
<L>I wald noght pray his pain to sese</L>
<L>For in hell may be no relese." &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;e third: &thorn;at has done synnes sere,</L>
<L N="460">And noght fulfild &thorn;aire penance here,</L>
<L>Of mes and prayers haue &thorn;ai nede</L>
<L>And als of o&thorn;er almus-dede.</L>
<L>Bot it es to reward all-way<NOTE PLACE="foot1">reward = regard.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ai be gude men &thorn;at sall pray,</L>
<L N="465">And als-so &thorn;at &thorn;aire almus be</L>
<L>Done in parfite charite.</L>
<L>And for &thorn;e ded men suld do sone</L>
<L>Thing &thorn;at &thorn;ai lifand bid be done,</L>
<L>And in grete haste, to make &thorn;am hale.</L>
<L N="470">Als men may here by a tale:</L>
<L>&THORN;at bifell by a knyghtes wife,</L>
<L>To wham he cummand in his life:</L>
<L>A hors of his &thorn;at scho suld sell</L>
<L>And gyf almus pure men omell.</L>
<L N="475">When he was ded, scho had no will</L>
<L>To fell &thorn;at hors, bot held him still.</L>
<L>Efter aght daies, als I am lerd,</L>
<L>&THORN;e knyght untill his wife aperd:</L>
<L>"&THORN;ou has gert me haue pain, he sais,</L>
<L N="480">In purgatori &thorn;ir aght dayis</L>
<L>For &thorn;e hors &thorn;at I bad &thorn;e sell.</L>
<L>&THORN;arfore &thorn;i sawl sall wende to hell,<MILESTONE N="188" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>When &thorn;ou es dede, on &thorn;is same day,</L>
<L>And I sall wun in welth al-way</L>
<L N="485">&THORN;at lastes euer with-outen ende" &mdash;</L>
<L>God wis us to &thorn;at welth at wende.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="31" TYPE="legend">
<HEAD>31. In festo sci Martini episcopi historia.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>S. Tib. fol. 268 a 2&mdash;269 b I.</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Saint Martin was a nobill man,</L>
<L>For in his barnhede he bigan</L>
<L>Forto be mylde and of gude thews,</L>
<L>And forsoke felischip of schrews.</L>
<L N="5">And when he was ten zere of elde,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at he his wit moght welde:</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e kirk he toke &thorn;e way</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e prelate gan he pray</L>
<L>A catecumine him to make &mdash;</L>
<L N="10">&THORN;is word es (&thorn;us) to undertake:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">T &thorn;us, fehlt in H.</NOTE></L>
<L>Trewly to trow in Jhesu Criste</L>
<L>Als cristen man and unbaptiste.</L>
<L>Se&thorn;in was he knight with scheld &amp; spere</L>
<L>With king Constancius in were,</L>
<L N="15">Se&thorn;in with Juliane &thorn;e Emperoure</L>
<L>Was he halden in grete honowre,</L>
<L>&amp; oft he went ogains his will</L>
<L>Cristen men in were to spill.</L>
<L>In &thorn;is same time, whils saint Martyne</L>
<L N="20">Was uncristend cathecumyne:</L>
<L>Als he rade opon a day,</L>
<L>He met a pouer man by &thorn;e way;</L>
<L>And it was cald with weders wete,</L>
<L>Snythand frost with snaw and slete;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">snythand von snythen schneiden (Orm).</NOTE></L>
<L N="25">And &thorn;e pouer man nere nakid was.</L>
<L>Of saint Martyn sum gude he ass.</L>
<L>And Martyn had of him pete:</L>
<L>Half his mantill &thorn;are toke he<NOTE PLACE="foot2">H toke st. tore?</NOTE></L>
<L>Al sunder sone for Cristes sake,</L>
<L N="30">And to &thorn;e pore man he gan it take.</L>
<L>Opon &thorn;e next night &thorn;an folowand,</L>
<L>Als he lay in hys bed slepeand,
<PB REF="00000291.tif" N="153"></L>
<L>To him was schewd a semly sight:</L>
<L>A cumpany of angels bright,</L>
<L N="35">Omang &thorn;am Jhesu Crist was sted,</L>
<L>With &thorn;at side of his mantell cled</L>
<L>&THORN;at he had gifen to &thorn;e pouer man,</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e angels &thorn;us said he &thorn;an:</L>
<L>"Martin, noght zit cristend sis he,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H sis (T?) st. is?</NOTE></L>
<L N="40">With &thorn;is clething has couerd me."</L>
<L>&THORN;us may we lere, whils we here lif</L>
<L>What thing so we to pouer men gif;</L>
<L>And we gif it in goddes name,</L>
<L>To god him-selue we gif &thorn;e same,</L>
<L N="45">And he for &thorn;at ilk almus-dede</L>
<L>Makes vs in heuyn to haue oure mede.</L>
<L>Martyn &thorn;an dede of armes forsoke</L>
<L>And unto Crist haly him toke.</L>
<L>He went unto saint Hillary,</L>
<L N="50">&THORN;at bisschop was litill &thorn;ar-by,</L>
<L>And &thorn;an of him he was baptist</L>
<L>And toke trace of Jhesu Crist.</L>
<L>With tresore, won bifor &thorn;at tide,</L>
<L>Ane abbay bigged he &thorn;ar-biside;</L>
<L N="55">He toke abite and made him boune</L>
<L>To lif in leIe religioune;</L>
<L>Mani monkes wond he with-all,</L>
<L>And he was abbot ouer &thorn;am all.</L>
<L>Thre zere went he, als men redes,</L>
<L N="60">In sere cuntrese for his hows nedes.</L>
<L>When he come hame, a monk he fand</L>
<L>Ded, &thorn;at he had left lifand.</L>
<L>He raised him fro ded to lif &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at meruail saw both man &amp; wife,</L>
<L N="65">For he lifed efter mani a zere.</L>
<L>Zit mai men of mo meruailes here:</L>
<L>A man was hanged &thorn;arbiside</L>
<L>For trispas he had done &thorn;at tide;</L>
<L>When he was fully ded, sertaine,</L>
<L N="70">Saint Martyn gaf him lif ogayne,</L>
<L>And kindely unto him he kend</L>
<L>How he suld his mis amend.</L>
<L>&THORN;e thrid forsuth zit raised he right</L>
<L>Plainly in &thorn;e pople syght:</L>
<L N="75">And was forsuth a maiden clene</L>
<L>&THORN;at fra hir barnhed dome had bene;</L>
<L>He raised hir als gastly leche,</L>
<L>And als he gaf hir grace of speche.</L>
<L>Ful many he hel&iacute;d of sekenes sere</L>
<L N="80">All anly thurgh his praiere,</L>
<L>&amp; with swilk sere miracles made he</L>
<L>Many men to baptist be.</L>
<L>Ore lord Crist wele to him kid</L>
<L>His halinus suld noght be hid:<NOTE PLACE="foot">H halinus = halinis.</NOTE></L>
<L N="85">Chosen he was with grete honours</L>
<L>Forto be bisschop of Tours,</L>
<L>&THORN;at was chef cete of &thorn;e land</L>
<L>And moste puple &thorn;arin dwelland.</L>
<L>&THORN;ar wond he and wrogh(t) wondres seire<NOTE PLACE="foot">H seire = sere.</NOTE></L>
<L N="90">To all &thorn;at oght in anger were;</L>
<L>He helid men both more and les</L>
<L>Of alkins maners of sekenes.</L>
<L>Sum meruailes will I mene omang &mdash;</L>
<L>For all to tell it wer full lang.</L>
<L N="95">In to sere cuntres trauaild he</L>
<L>And baptist popill gret plente;</L>
<L>And all ald temples &thorn;at he fand,</L>
<L>&THORN;at vnto fals goddes war ordand,</L>
<L>If he &thorn;arto had no foysoune,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H foysoyne.</NOTE></L>
<L N="100">With angels help he dang &thorn;am doun.</L>
<L>So come he furth opon a tyme</L>
<L>Till hathin men &thorn;at hated him;<NOTE PLACE="foot">H hathim.</NOTE></L>
<L>He kest doun &thorn;aire tempill of stane.<NOTE PLACE="foot">T tempil.</NOTE></L>
<L>And sone omang &thorn;am was he tane,</L>
<L N="105">And vnto heuiding was he led.</L>
<L>His for him war sare adred;</L>
<L>Bot euer he comfort &thorn;am fulwele<NOTE PLACE="foot">H comfert, T confort.</NOTE></L>
<L>And bad &thorn;ai suld noght drede a dele.</L>
<L>His naked nek he bed furth tyte</L>
<L N="110">To him &thorn;at suld his heuyd of smyte:</L>
<L>Bot, als he suld &thorn;e bisschop quell,</L>
<L>bacward to &thorn;e ground he fell.</L>
<L>His trispas knew he &thorn;an in hy</L>
<L>And of his mis he asked mercy.</L>
<L N="115">A-no&thorn;er said he suld him sla:</L>
<L>Bot sone his fawchone flogh him fra.</L>
<L>When he &thorn;at saw, his mis he knew</L>
<L>And his dede sare gan him rew.
<PB REF="00000292.tif" N="154"></L>
<L>Sone when &thorn;e pople saw &thorn;is sight,</L>
<L N="120">Ful maniane trowed in his might.</L>
<L>Vntill (him) come both seke and sare:<NOTE PLACE="foot">him fehlt in T H.</NOTE></L>
<L>He lechid all &thorn;at lufed his lare,</L>
<L>And mani deuils gert he twin<NOTE PLACE="foot">H gret, T gert.</NOTE></L>
<L>Out of men &thorn;at &thorn;ai war in;</L>
<L N="125">And noght zit men he helid allane,</L>
<L>Bot bestes &thorn;at war with euils tane.</L>
<L>When he had angers grete or smale,</L>
<L>With angels sone he was made hale,</L>
<L>And thing &thorn;at him-self might noght do<NOTE PLACE="foot">T thin.</NOTE></L>
<L N="130">Angels helpid him euer &thorn;ar-to.</L>
<L>Ane blisced Brice his dekin was,</L>
<L>In ilka place whare (he) suld pas.</L>
<L>And oft-sithes, when he sang mes,<NOTE PLACE="foot">T of, H oft.</NOTE></L>
<L>Als haly writ ful wele witnes,</L>
<L N="135">A flawm of fire fro his heuid stode:</L>
<L>In signe &thorn;at he with god was gude</L>
<L>And fulfild of &thorn;e haly gaste,</L>
<L>&THORN;at medcyn es to mankind maste.</L>
<L>A(l) thing with wirschip fulfild he<NOTE PLACE="foot">T all, H a.</NOTE></L>
<L N="140">&THORN;at fell to bisschoppes dignite,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e order held he neuer-&thorn;e-lese</L>
<L>Of religion &thorn;at he first chese.</L>
<L>He had deciples many and sere,<MILESTONE N="169" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And lastand life he gan &thorn;am lere,</L>
<L N="145">Night and day &thorn;ai wond him by,</L>
<L>Mo &thorn;an foure score in cumpany;</L>
<L>And none of &thorn;am, now&thorn;er ald ne zing,</L>
<L>Held unto him-self no thing,</L>
<L>Bot, what so was in &thorn;are pouste,<NOTE PLACE="foot">T &thorn;aire, H &thorn;are.</NOTE></L>
<L N="150">Vnto ilk felaw was it fre.</L>
<L>&THORN;is haly bisschop thurgh goddes grace</L>
<L>Wist bifore a full lang space</L>
<L>When he suld out of &thorn;is werld dy,</L>
<L>And he tald to his cumpany,</L>
<L N="155">When tyme of his dede neghed nere,</L>
<L>And bad &thorn;am comfort &thorn;am in-fere</L>
<L>Ogains &thorn;e tyme &thorn;at he suld wend &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">T sul.</NOTE></L>
<L>"For lang, he said, may I noght lend".</L>
<L>When he was fowre score zere of elde,</L>
<L N="160">Sekenes &thorn;an of(t)-si&thorn;es he feld &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">H of, T oft.</NOTE></L>
<L>And bisschop &thorn;an had he bene here</L>
<L>Fully sex and twente zere &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">H twente, T twenty.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at, als he stode opon a day<NOTE PLACE="foot">H u. T &thorn;at, st. &thorn;an?</NOTE></L>
<L>Goddes word unto &thorn;e folk at say,</L>
<L N="165">At mes omang his menze maste,</L>
<L>Vnto god he gaf &thorn;e gaste.</L>
<L>His menze here uoices in heuyn<NOTE PLACE="foot">T H here st. herd?</NOTE></L>
<L>Of mikill ioy with angel steuyn</L>
<L>&THORN;at unto god made grete loueing</L>
<L N="170">In &thorn;e tyme of his passing.</L>
<L>Of his graueing grete ferly fell,</L>
<L>Als haly writ ful wele will tell.</L>
<L>Saint Ambrose on &thorn;at o&thorn;er side of &thorn;e see</L>
<L>Was bisschop of a riche cete;</L>
<L N="175">And on a day, als he mes sang</L>
<L>In minster mony men omang &mdash;</L>
<L>Custume was &thorn;an and so zit es</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e high-dekin at &thorn;e mes<NOTE PLACE="foot">T &thorn;e, H he.</NOTE></L>
<L>Godspell aw him to rede nane</L>
<L N="180">Or-tyme &thorn;at he haue blissing tane</L>
<L>Of him &thorn;at dose &thorn;e mess &thorn;at day &mdash;</L>
<L>And &thorn;us bifell, &thorn;e suth to say:</L>
<L>&THORN;e dekin turned him obout</L>
<L>And to (&thorn;e) bisschop gan he lout<MILESTONE N="189" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="185">Of him &thorn;an blissed forto be:</L>
<L>And hastily persaiued he</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e bisschop was in slepe.</L>
<L>&THORN;arfore to him &thorn;ai tak gude kepe</L>
<L>And none durst wakin him in &thorn;at place,</L>
<L N="190">Till it was past twa howres space.</L>
<L>When he had slepid two oures or mare,</L>
<L>To waken him wald &thorn;ai noght spare,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai said: "to mes, sir, moste ze gang;</L>
<L>&THORN;e folk habides zow ferly lang,</L>
<L N="195">And he &thorn;at suld zowre godspell rede,</L>
<L>For ze no blissing to him bede".</L>
<L>&THORN;an vnto &thorn;am &thorn;us answerd he:</L>
<L>"All ouer-sone haue ze raised me,</L>
<L>For oure lord god all-welldand</L>
<L N="200">Ha(s) schewed vnto me slepand<NOTE PLACE="foot">T u. H haschewed.</NOTE></L>
<L>A more ferly &thorn;an euer bifell.</L>
<L>And how it was, I will zow tell:<NOTE PLACE="foot">T an.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000293.tif" N="155"></L>
<L>Martin, oure bro&thorn;er, wele ze knew</L>
<L>&THORN;at in his trowth was euer trew,</L>
<L N="205">Ded he es with-owten wene,</L>
<L>And at his bering haue I bene;</L>
<L>And fully haue I noght all done,</L>
<L>By-caus ze raysed me ouer-sone:</L>
<L>Sertain colettes war vn-said,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H T colettes = colectes.</NOTE></L>
<L N="210">Efter &thorn;e cors in erth was laid;</L>
<L>Bot seruis &thorn;at falles to &thorn;e dede</L>
<L>Was done, or euer I past &thorn;e stede".</L>
<L>Here-of &thorn;e folk awonderd ware</L>
<L>And had grete ferly of &thorn;is fare;</L>
<L N="215">&THORN;ai held &thorn;e tyme trewly in minde,</L>
<L>&THORN;e suth for &thorn;ai wald fully finde.</L>
<L>Messangers war sone puruaid,</L>
<L>And fand all suth als he had said:</L>
<L>&THORN;e folk of Toures tald bidene</L>
<L N="220">How Ambrose &thorn;e bisschop &thorn;are had bene</L>
<L>At saint Martins enterement</L>
<L>And sodanly how &thorn;at he went.</L>
<L>&THORN;e messangers when &thorn;ai herd &thorn;is tale</L>
<L>How &thorn;e cuntre recorded it hale,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H recordedit.</NOTE></L>
<L N="225">Hame &thorn;ai went and tald bidene</L>
<L>&THORN;e suth als &thorn;ai had herd and sene.</L>
<L>Whare saint Martin till erth was broght,</L>
<L>Ful mani meruails was &thorn;are wroght.</L>
<L>Or he was grauen, &thorn;is ferly fell,</L>
<L N="230">On &thorn;is manere als I sall tell:</L>
<L>&THORN;are come &thorn;e pople of Pictaui</L>
<L>And said &thorn;ai suld haus his body,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H u. T haus.</NOTE></L>
<L>For he had bene monk &thorn;am omang<NOTE PLACE="foot">H land st. lang.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;aire abbot had he bene lang &mdash;</L>
<L N="235">&THORN;arfore his body wald &thorn;ai haue.</L>
<L>And folk of Towrs ogains &thorn;am straue</L>
<L>And claymed to haue his cors so clene,</L>
<L>By-caus he had &thorn;aire bisscop bene.</L>
<L>So &thorn;ai zemed him both in-fere,</L>
<L N="240">And euyn omang &thorn;am stode &thorn;e bere.</L>
<L>Opon &thorn;e night god schewed his grace</L>
<L>Omang &thorn;e puple in &thorn;at place:</L>
<L>Folk of Pictaui slepeand lay</L>
<L>Till it was wele furth of &thorn;e day;</L>
<L N="245">And folk of Towres &thorn;an albidene</L>
<L>Tuke &thorn;e body up &thorn;am bitwene</L>
<L>And bare it to &thorn;aire awin cete,</L>
<L>Whare god wald it suld beried be.</L>
<L>And als &thorn;ai went so by &thorn;e way,</L>
<L N="250">Seke folk &thorn;at in &thorn;aire beddes lay</L>
<L>Whare helid of &thorn;aire sekenes &thorn;an<NOTE PLACE="foot">H whare st. ware.</NOTE></L>
<L>Thurgh uertu of &thorn;is haly man,</L>
<L>And all &thorn;at herd &thorn;aire melody</L>
<L>Whare helid of him hastily.<NOTE PLACE="foot">H whare st. ware.</NOTE></L>
<L N="255">Two blind men woned in &thorn;at place</L>
<L>&THORN;at lifed allane of &thorn;aire purchace:</L>
<L>For &thorn;ai war blind, men fand &thorn;am fode;</L>
<L>&THORN;arfore &thorn;am thoght &thorn;aire lifing gude.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai went &thorn;am till ane owten-strete,</L>
<L N="260">For &thorn;ai wald noght saint Martyn mete,</L>
<L>And in a hows still &thorn;ai &thorn;am hid,</L>
<L>For no might suld on &thorn;am be kyd.</L>
<L>Sone, when &thorn;e folk, &thorn;at bare &thorn;e bere,</L>
<L>Neghed to &thorn;e cete nere,</L>
<L N="265">By &thorn;at lane went &thorn;ai, for les prece,</L>
<L>Whare &thorn;e blind men &thorn;aire beldin chese.</L>
<L>And als sone als &thorn;ai herd &thorn;e sang</L>
<L>Of &thorn;am &thorn;at with &thorn;e cors gun gang,</L>
<L>Sight was sent &thorn;am both vntill &mdash;</L>
<L N="270">All-if it war noght with &thorn;aire will.</L>
<L>&THORN;us broght &thorn;ai saint Martyn to toun</L>
<L>With ful grete processioune</L>
<L>And beried him opon &thorn;e morn</L>
<L>Euyn als it es tald biforn.</L>
<L N="275">Bot &thorn;e pople of Pictaui,</L>
<L>When &thorn;ai wakend, war sari:</L>
<L>All was oway &thorn;at &thorn;ai fore woke;</L>
<L>Ful drerily &thorn;aire way &thorn;ai toke</L>
<L>Hame ogain, &thorn;aire &thorn;ai come fra,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H &thorn;aire = &thorn;are.</NOTE></L>
<L N="280">Wepand with ful mekill wa.</L>
<L>&THORN;us was saint Martin in his liue</L>
<L>Medcyn vnto man and wiue,</L>
<L>On &thorn;e same wise efter his dede</L>
<L>He wissed all &thorn;at war will of rede.</L>
<L N="285">He wis vs wiseli for to win</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;at welth &thorn;at he wons in.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="32" TYPE="legend"><PB REF="00000294.tif" N="156">
<HEAD>32. De sancto Bricio diacono sancti Martini<NOTE PLACE="foot">S. Tib. fol. 296 b 2&mdash;271 a 2.</NOTE>).</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Saint Brice, when saint Martin was ded,</L>
<L>Was ordand bisschop in his stede,</L>
<L>Als he bifore had till him talde</L>
<L>Whils &thorn;ai both had &thorn;aire wites in walde;<NOTE PLACE="foot">T whills.</NOTE></L>
<L N="5">For, wills saint Martin lifed in land,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H wills, T whills.</NOTE></L>
<L>Saint Brice was euer to him seruand;</L>
<L>And, &thorn;at he suld haue angers sere,</L>
<L>Tald he him, on &thorn;is manere.</L>
<L>So it bifell opon a day,</L>
<L N="10">Als &thorn;ai went both by &thorn;e way:</L>
<L>A seke man kome to seke medcyn</L>
<L>And to be salued of saint Martyne;</L>
<L>And for he knew noght whilk was he,</L>
<L>He asked ane of his menze:</L>
<L N="15">"Whilk es &thorn;e bisschop, I zow pray?"</L>
<L>And Brice, his dekin, &thorn;us gan say:</L>
<L>"Go furth, he said, vntill &thorn;ou finde</L>
<L>A mased man al out of minde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at vses ay for fantasy</L>
<L N="20">Forto stare upward to &thorn;e scy".</L>
<L>&THORN;e seke man soght &amp; sone he fand</L>
<L>&THORN;e bisschop up to heuyn lukeand.</L>
<L>He asked him bute of his bale:</L>
<L>And hastily he was made hale.</L>
<L N="25">When he was helid, right als he wald,</L>
<L>Saint Martin sone his dekin cald</L>
<L>And asked him bitwene &thorn;am twa:</L>
<L>Bi what caus &thorn;at he scorned him swa</L>
<L>To tell &thorn;e pore man he was wode,</L>
<L N="30">For &thorn;at his eghen to heuyn-ward stode &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;us he bigan Brice forto blame.</L>
<L>And he was all confused for schame;</L>
<L>Sone he bigan him to excuse,</L>
<L>Bot on none wise might he refuse</L>
<L N="35">&THORN;e fawes &thorn;at he had said bifor(n) &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">T biforn, H bifor.</NOTE></L>
<L>So barely es it on him born.</L>
<L>&THORN;e bisscop spac &thorn;an wordes fre:<NOTE PLACE="foot">T bisschop.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Suthly, Brice, I say to &thorn;e:</L>
<L>God sall grante &thorn;e graces slike</L>
<L N="40">&THORN;at &thorn;ou sall haue my bisscop-rike<NOTE PLACE="foot">T bisschop.</NOTE></L>
<L>And be bisschop efter my day;</L>
<L>And suthly als to &thorn;e I say</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ow sall in &thorn;at ilk degre<NOTE PLACE="foot">T &thorn;ou.</NOTE></L>
<L>In many angers oft-sithes be</L>
<L N="45">And suffer sere anoyes saltou:</L>
<L>&THORN;an sall &thorn;ou wit wh(a)t me ailes now".<NOTE PLACE="foot">H wht; new, T now.</NOTE></L>
<L>And Brice, when he &thorn;ir wordes herd,</L>
<L>Till his mayster &thorn;us he answerd &mdash;</L>
<L>His wordes to warand will he wene</L>
<L N="50">And his maister more forto tene,</L>
<L>For in hert was he sumdele prowde &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;us he answerd all o-loude:</L>
<L>"Me think, I said suth for sertayn,</L>
<L>For &thorn;ir wordes er haly in vaine".</L>
<L N="55">Saint Martin wald no langer chide,</L>
<L>For wele he wist what suld bitide. &mdash;</L>
<L>When he was ded, als I are tald,</L>
<L>And wroght miracles ful mani fald,</L>
<L>Saint Brice, als said &thorn;is haly man,</L>
<L N="60">Efter him was ordand bisschop &thorn;an.</L>
<L>And haly life &thorn;an gan he lede</L>
<L>In praiers and in almus-dede &mdash;</L>
<L>Proud zit was he sum-tyme sene,</L>
<L>Bot euer his body he keped clene</L>
<L N="65">Fro alkins lust of licheri.</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;us bifell it noght-for&thorn;i,</L>
<L>Als his maister bifore had said,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he suld suffer sere vpbrayd.</L>
<L>Efter his ordinance threty zere</L>
<L N="70">&THORN;an bifell on &thorn;is manere:</L>
<L>A woman &thorn;at his lander was</L>
<L>In &thorn;at tyme had done trispas:</L>
<L>Flesly scho had hir body filde,<NOTE PLACE="foot">T flessly.</NOTE></L>
<L>And was deliuer of a knaue-childe.<NOTE PLACE="foot">T u. H deliuer.</NOTE></L>
<L N="75">To &thorn;e bisschop sum men put &thorn;e blame,</L>
<L>And seyn all &thorn;e pople said &thorn;e same:<NOTE PLACE="foot">H seyn, T se&thorn;in.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bi-caus &thorn;at scho so come and zede</L>
<L>&amp; wessche his clothes, when &thorn;ai had nede.</L>
<L>And halely all &thorn;ai toke to rede</L>
<L N="80">Forto stane him vnto dede.
<PB REF="00000295.tif" N="157"></L>
<L>Vnto him come &thorn;ai on a brayd</L>
<L>And haly &thorn;us to him &thorn;ai sayd:</L>
<L>"A, god &thorn;at ful of mercy es</L>
<L>Has hid ful lang &thorn;i wikkednes</L>
<L N="85">And kepid &thorn;e, &thorn;at &thorn;ou bare no blame:</L>
<L>Bot now sall it cum out with schame;</L>
<L>Lang has bene layned &thorn;i licheri:</L>
<L>&THORN;at turnes &thorn;e now to velani.</L>
<L>Ouer-lang &thorn;i foul handes haue we kisst<NOTE PLACE="foot">H kisst.</NOTE></L>
<L N="90">&THORN;at we wend had bene ful blist.<MILESTONE N="190" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>To uoid it now auailes &thorn;e noght,<NOTE PLACE="foot">T void, H uoid.</NOTE></L>
<L>We wate how wikkedly &thorn;ou has wroght.</L>
<L>With bitter bale boght sall it be!"</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;am all &thorn;an answerd he:</L>
<L N="95">"I am sakles and vnknawand</L>
<L>Of &thorn;is &thorn;at ze put me on hand:</L>
<L>&THORN;at sall ze se, both ald &amp; zing".</L>
<L>&THORN;e child he bad bifor &thorn;am bring.</L>
<L>&THORN;e childes eld was thretty dais,</L>
<L N="100">Als &thorn;e kinred recordes &amp; sais;</L>
<L>&THORN;ai broght it furth bifor &thorn;am all.</L>
<L>And &thorn;e bisschop to Crist gan call</L>
<L>&THORN;at he moght &thorn;are all opinly</L>
<L>Acquite him, als he was worthy.</L>
<L N="105">Vnto &thorn;e childe &thorn;an &thorn;us said he:</L>
<L>"On Cristes bihalf I cumand &thorn;e:</L>
<L>Als he es god son hegh in heuyn,</L>
<L>Omang &thorn;ir men now &thorn;at &thorn;ou neuyn</L>
<L>And say to &thorn;am &thorn;e suth, if I</L>
<L N="110">Gat &thorn;e euer with my body</L>
<L>Or ani wise mi flessche haue filde".</L>
<L>&THORN;an vnto him answerd &thorn;e childe</L>
<L>And said: "mi fader ertou noght,</L>
<L>Now&thorn;er in word ne dede ne thoght".</L>
<L N="115">&THORN;e puple wald noght trow &thorn;is tale,</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;aire ill purpose held &thorn;ai hale,</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e bisschop said &thorn;ai zit:</L>
<L>"For&thorn;ermare we will &thorn;ow witt<NOTE PLACE="foot">T &thorn;ou.</NOTE></L>
<L>And ask who es his fader now,</L>
<L N="120">Sen he sais it es noght &thorn;ou".</L>
<L>&THORN;an answerd Brice to &thorn;am ogayne:</L>
<L>"Me nedes nogh(t) so fer to frayne;</L>
<L>Al-if I bere unworthi blame,</L>
<L>None o&thorn;er now I will defame.</L>
<L N="125">Lat &thorn;am now &thorn;at it nedes untill</L>
<L>Spir and wit what so &thorn;ai will &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at toched me here, has he talde".</L>
<L>&THORN;ai answerd with wordes ful balde</L>
<L>And all &thorn;ai said untill him sone:</L>
<L N="130">"Be deuils craft &thorn;is has &thorn;ou done,<NOTE PLACE="foot">T bi.</NOTE></L>
<L>For sertes it es ogains kinde</L>
<L>A child to speke &thorn;at haues no minde.</L>
<L>&THORN;arfore &thorn;ou sall be neuer &thorn;e ner,</L>
<L>Herefore we hald &thorn;e wele &thorn;e wer".</L>
<L N="135">&THORN;an to him bremely gan &thorn;ai braid</L>
<L>And tenefully to him &thorn;ai said:</L>
<L>"&THORN;ou sall no langer, als &thorn;ou has bene,</L>
<L>Be maister ouer vs all bidene;</L>
<L>Of bisschop wrang &thorn;ou beres &thorn;e name,</L>
<L N="140">&THORN;at so haly es halden at hame</L>
<L>And se&thorn;in es so ill within &mdash;</L>
<L>On &thorn;i-self sal be sene &thorn;i sin!"</L>
<L>Saint Brice zit, forto mak him clere,</L>
<L>Wroght wonderly on &thorn;is manere:</L>
<L N="145">Hate brinand coles stilly he did</L>
<L>In his lap and &thorn;are &thorn;am hid &mdash;</L>
<L>He lapped &thorn;am in his clothes all hate,</L>
<L>And sogat furth he toke &thorn;e gate,</L>
<L>Vnto saint Martyns graue he went</L>
<L N="150">With mikell pople in present.</L>
<L>And doune he kest &thorn;e coles &thorn;are</L>
<L>Omang all &thorn;e men &thorn;at &thorn;are ware:</L>
<L>&THORN;e coles zit ful clere gan brin,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e clothes &thorn;at &thorn;ai lay in</L>
<L N="155">With swete sauore war faire and clene</L>
<L>And no brining opon &thorn;am sene.</L>
<L>&THORN;e bisschop said: "sirs, als ze se</L>
<L>&THORN;ir clothes with-owten brining be,</L>
<L>So es my bodi clene with-in</L>
<L N="160">With-owten filth of fleffly syn &mdash;</L>
<L>Ful wrangwisly I am acused;</L>
<L>And &thorn;arfor haues me now excused!"</L>
<L>&THORN;ir wikked folk and ful of ire,</L>
<L>When &thorn;ai saw &thorn;us of &thorn;e fire,</L>
<L N="165">&THORN;arfore trowed him neuer &thorn;e mare</L>
<L>Ne to despise him wald noght spare;</L>
<L>&THORN;ai angerd him ilk day inlike</L>
<L>And gert him leue his bisschoprike &mdash;
<PB REF="00000296.tif" N="158"></L>
<L>&THORN;a wordes plainly to fulfill</L>
<L N="170">&THORN;at saint Martyn had said him till:</L>
<L>&THORN;at he suld oft-sy&thorn;es angerd be</L>
<L>When he had tane &thorn;at dignite,</L>
<L>And wrangwisly oft be vpbraid &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;us fand he suth all &thorn;at was said:</L>
<L N="175">With &thorn;is falshede and o&thorn;er slike</L>
<L>Was he put fro his bisschoprike,</L>
<L>And (&thorn;e) pople bi ane assent<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e fehlt.</NOTE></L>
<L>Chese a-no&thorn;er, when he was went,</L>
<L>And made him bisschop in his stede.</L>
<L N="180">And Brice went furth ful will of rede,</L>
<L>He went vnto &thorn;e court of Rome</L>
<L>&THORN;are to be rewlid bi rightwis dome;</L>
<L>With him went no grete menze &mdash;</L>
<L>Anely bot a clerk and he.</L>
<L N="185">Als he went wepeand by &thorn;e way,</L>
<L>With sary hert &thorn;us gan he say &mdash;</L>
<L>Thinkand how &thorn;e time gan pas,</L>
<L>Sen saint Martyn his maister was:</L>
</LG>
<P>Merito hec pacior quia peccaui in sanc|tum epm Martinum.</P>
<LG>
<L>He sais: "I am worthi ful wele</L>
<L N="190">To haue &thorn;is dole euerilkadele,</L>
<L>For trispas I haue done lang syne</L>
<L>Ogayns my maister, saint Martyne:</L>
<L>He &thorn;at was haly and mild of mode,<NOTE PLACE="foot">T he &thorn;at, H &thorn;at he.</NOTE></L>
<L>Said I, was fond and sumtyme wode;</L>
<L N="195">When he luked unto heuyn on hight,</L>
<L>I said he raued and did nogh(t) right;</L>
<L>And &thorn;at he did with conciens clere,</L>
<L>Turned I vnto euil manere.</L>
<L>He said me nemly and new</L>
<L N="200">Tales &thorn;at I find now ful trew:</L>
<L>He said I suld to wirschip win</L>
<L>And suffer sere angers &thorn;arin;</L>
<L>Now find I trew all &thorn;at he talde,</L>
<L>With sere defautes ful manifalde".</L>
<L N="205">&THORN;us went he furth makand his mane,</L>
<L>Ful drerily bi him allane.</L>
<L>When he was went, &thorn;e folk of Tours,</L>
<L>&THORN;at did him first ful grete honowrs,</L>
<L>Harmed him bihind his bac</L>
<L N="210">And fast omang &thorn;am gan him lac;</L>
<L>And his preste Justiniane</L>
<L>&THORN;at efter him was left allane,</L>
<L>Bad &thorn;ai tite efter him wende,</L>
<L>Or with sere pain &thorn;ai suld him schinde: &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">T u. H schinde.</NOTE></L>
<L N="215">And furth to Rome-ward gan he fare,</L>
<L>Bot he died lang, or he come &thorn;are.</L>
<L>A bisschop made &thorn;ai sone in hy</L>
<L>&THORN;at named was bisschop Armency,</L>
<L>And he was bisschop seuyn zere</L>
<L N="220">And prelat of ful grete powere.</L>
<L>And so lang dwelled saint Brice in Rome.</L>
<L>Bi &thorn;at ilk time &thorn;e pape gaf dome</L>
<L>&THORN;at he suld be bisschop of Tours</L>
<L>And haue ogain all his honours,</L>
<L N="225">And all &thorn;a cursed &thorn;at did him wrang.</L>
<L>He toke letters and leue to gang.<NOTE PLACE="foot">T u. H he te toke.</NOTE></L>
<L>And als he went so on his way</L>
<L>Fro &thorn;e cete of Rome &thorn;e sext iornay,</L>
<L>On &thorn;e night slepand him thoght &mdash;</L>
<L N="230">Als &thorn;e suth in werk was wroght:</L>
<L>&THORN;e bisschop of Tours, suth to tell,<NOTE PLACE="foot">T bissop.</NOTE></L>
<L>Had taken a feuer ferly fell</L>
<L>And out of &thorn;is life gan he pas &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at wist saint Brice wele &thorn;are he was.</L>
<L N="235">And on &thorn;e morn he said in hi</L>
<L>To &thorn;am &thorn;at war in cumpani:</L>
<L>"Rises upp, he said, smertly and sone,</L>
<L>And haste us he&thorn;in withouten hone,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e cete of Tours will we wende,</L>
<L N="240">To beri our bro&thorn;er and oure frende!</L>
<L>&THORN;e bisschop of &thorn;at same cete<NOTE PLACE="foot">H of &thorn;at of.</NOTE></L>
<L>Hastily sall beried be &mdash;</L>
<L>Ded he es with-owten drede."</L>
<L>Herto his menze toke gude hede.</L>
<L N="245">Sone on &thorn;e morn &thorn;ai toke &thorn;aire wai</L>
<L>And trauailed als fast so &thorn;ai m(ai).<NOTE PLACE="foot">H u. T me st. mai.</NOTE></L>
<L>And astily when &thorn;ai come hame,<NOTE PLACE="foot">T hastily.</NOTE></L>
<L>Als he had said, &thorn;ai fand &thorn;e same:</L>
<L>When &thorn;ai entred at &thorn;e zate,</L>
<L N="250">&THORN;ai met grete pople in &thorn;e gate</L>
<L>Berand a cros thurgh-out &thorn;e toune<NOTE PLACE="foot">T H cros st. cors.</NOTE></L>
<L>With ful grete processioune:
<PB REF="00000297.tif" N="159"></L>
<L>&THORN;at was &thorn;e bisschop to birijing,</L>
<L>Als god had ordand in al thing.<NOTE PLACE="foot">T biriing.</NOTE></L>
<L N="255">&THORN;us when &thorn;e bisschop beried was,</L>
<L>Saint Brice omang &thorn;e pople pas<NOTE PLACE="foot">Brice fehlt in T. T pass.</NOTE></L>
<L>To clayme his right, als was worthi,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he was put fro wrangwisly;</L>
<L>And &thorn;ore he schewed by papes myght</L>
<L N="260">&THORN;at he had reson a(n)d verray right.<NOTE PLACE="foot">H ad.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ore he was resayued ogayn,</L>
<L>And all &thorn;e folk of him ful fain;</L>
<L>Al halely &thorn;e cete of Tours</L>
<L>Welkumd him with grete honowrs.</L>
<L N="265">Seuin zere efter thurgh goddes grace</L>
<L>Was he bisschop in &thorn;at place.</L>
<L>He lifed in luf and charite</L>
<L>And maynte(n)d gudely his degre.<NOTE PLACE="foot">H maynted, T mayntend.</NOTE></L>
<L>And folk &thorn;at him bifore had flemid</L>
<L N="270">War fain to do all als he demid,</L>
<L>And mercy all of him &thorn;ai ass:</L>
<L>And he forgaf &thorn;am &thorn;aire trispas.</L>
<L>When he had bene on &thorn;is manere</L>
<L>Bisschop seuyn and fourty zere,</L>
<L N="275">&THORN;an es he past with panes of ded,<NOTE PLACE="foot">T u. H panes.</NOTE></L>
<L>And Eustache ordand in his stede.</L>
<L>Enterd he was with gude entent.</L>
<L>His saul up into heuyn es hent,</L>
<L>And &thorn;are he praies for folk in-fere</L>
<L N="280">&THORN;at wirschippes him in werldes here.</L>
<L>God len us so here forto lif</L>
<L>&THORN;at we oure gast to him mai gif!</L>
<TRAILER>Amen. Amen. Amen.</TRAILER>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="33" TYPE="legend">
<HEAD>33. De sancta Cecilia historia.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>S. Tib. fol. 271&mdash;274b 1.</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Jhesus Crist, ful of pete,</L>
<L>To mankind es of mercy fre</L>
<L>And schewes his pouste &amp; his might</L>
<L>Of(t)-sithes here unto sum men sight,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">H u. T of.</NOTE></L>
<L N="5">So &thorn;at we may his mightes ken,</L>
<L>Als wele in wemen als in men,</L>
<L>And all-&thorn;ermost in maydens zing</L>
<L>&THORN;at will be boun to his biding.</L>
<L>&THORN;at may men by ensaumple se</L>
<L N="10">Of saint Cecill, &thorn;e mayden fre,</L>
<L>&THORN;at born was of ful gentill blode</L>
<L>And euer was haly &amp; milde of mode,</L>
<L>And in hir hert ful wele scho knew</L>
<L>All &thorn;e lare of oure lord Jhesu.</L>
<L N="15">Vnto him was scho prayand euer,</L>
<L>Night and day, and sesid neuer.</L>
<L>Of pape Urban scho was baptist</L>
<L>And trewly trowed in Jhesu Crist.</L>
<L>With hir frendes scho was ful dere</L>
<L N="20">And with all o&thorn;er folk in-fere,</L>
<L>Bycaus scho was both fayre &amp; gude</L>
<L>And untill all folk milde of mode.</L>
<L>Hir frendes maried hir till a man</L>
<L>&THORN;at named was Valirian;</L>
<L N="25">Zong he was and faire of skin</L>
<L>And komen of ful nobill kyn,</L>
<L>Bot hathin he was &amp; unbaptist</L>
<L>And knew no-thing &thorn;e law of Crist.</L>
<L>Cisill durst none o&thorn;er do</L>
<L N="30">Bot als hir frendes tald hir to.</L>
<L>&THORN;e day was sett: &thorn;ai suld be wed.</L>
<L>In clathes of cold &thorn;ai both war cled;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">H cold = gold.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bot Cicill had &thorn;ar-of no pride &mdash;</L>
<L>Ful hard clething was next hir hid;</L>
<L N="35">Outward scho was richely arrayd,</L>
<L>So alls hir frendes had puruayd.</L>
<L>&THORN;us on &thorn;is wise when &thorn;ai war wed,</L>
<L>Ful fele folk &thorn;aire frendes fed.
<PB REF="00000298.tif" N="160"></L>
<L>When &thorn;e bridal was broght till ende, </L>
<L N="40">&THORN;at ilka man &thorn;aire wai gan wende,</L>
<L>Cicill es &thorn;an to chamber went,</L>
<L>Calland to Crist with gude entent.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai herd grete noyis, &thorn;at war hir nere,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H noyis = noys.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of angels sang and organs clere;</L>
<L N="45">Scho made hir melody omang</L>
<L>And al &thorn;us said scho in hir sang:</L>
</LG>
<P>Fiat cor meum et corpus meum imma|culatum, ut non confundar:</P>
<LG>
<L>&THORN;at es on &thorn;is maner to mene:</L>
<L>"Lord, &thorn;ou mak my hert all clene</L>
<L>And saue my body unfiled within,</L>
<L N="50">So &thorn;at I be noght schent with syn!"</L>
<L>When scho had tald all hir talent</L>
<L>&THORN;us unto god with gude entent,</L>
<L>With hir husband scho went to bed,</L>
<L>Als &thorn;e law wald, for scho was wed.</L>
<L N="55">Bot in hert ful wele scho thoght</L>
<L>To kepe hir clene, if &thorn;at scho moght.</L>
<L>So by hir lord when scho was layd,</L>
<L>Vntill him al &thorn;us scho sayd,</L>
<L>Scho sayd: "sir, if it war zowre will,</L>
<L N="60">A cownsail haue I zow untill,</L>
<L>&THORN;at bus be said now, with zowre leue &mdash;</L>
<L>And, gude syr, luke ze zow noght greue!</L>
<L>Ane angell, syr, of heuyn ful bright</L>
<L>Es my speciall both day and night,</L>
<L N="65">A seruand unto god es he &mdash;</L>
<L>I luf him wele, so dose he me.</L>
<L>And if he wit with any gin</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ow my body file with syn</L>
<L>Or onclene lufing to me bede,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H bising od. lufing? T?</NOTE></L>
<L N="70">He will be wrath for swilk in dede</L>
<L>And vengance will he on zow take,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ze sall all solace forsake</L>
<L>And lose &thorn;e flowre of zowre zowth-hede.</L>
<L>Swilk grewance, sir, es gude to drede."</L>
<L N="75">Valirian &thorn;an wex all wrathe,</L>
<L>For drede he durst do hir no schathe;<NOTE PLACE="foot">schathe = skathe.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of hir wordes he was noght payde</L>
<L>And all &thorn;us unto hir he sayde:</L>
<L>"Woman, if &thorn;ou will &thorn;at I trow</L>
<L N="80">&THORN;ir wordes &thorn;at &thorn;ou sais me now,</L>
<L>Bitwix vs twa here lat me se</L>
<L>Him &thorn;at &thorn;ou sais so lufes &thorn;e!</L>
<L>So &thorn;at I may my-self assay</L>
<L>Whether he be angell uerray,</L>
<L N="85">Seruand unto god of heuyn &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;an sall I do &thorn;i counsaill euyn.</L>
<L>And if &thorn;ou luf ane o&thorn;er man,</L>
<L>Ful sare &thorn;ou sall &thorn;e bargan ban;</L>
<L>Now&thorn;er sall skape with-owten scath,</L>
<L N="90">Bot I my-self sall sla zow bath,</L>
<L>With mikell schame I sall zow schende."</L>
<L>&THORN;an answerd scho with wordes hende:</L>
<L>"Gude sir, scho said, greue noght &thorn;e</L>
<L>If &thorn;ou may noght goddes angel se!</L>
<L N="95">For here may no-man se angell,</L>
<L>Bot if he trow, als I sall tell,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H he be, be fehlt in T.</NOTE></L>
<L>In a god &thorn;at made all thing,</L>
<L>&THORN;at was with-outen bygining</L>
<L>And es and euer-more sall be,</L>
<L N="100">Mast of might and of mercy fre,</L>
<L>And als in his sun Jhesu Criste.</L>
<L>If &thorn;ou will trow &amp; be baptiste,</L>
<L>&THORN;an say I, syr, &thorn;at &thorn;ou sall se</L>
<L>&THORN;e angell &mdash; &thorn;at I tell to &thorn;e.<NOTE PLACE="foot">T &thorn;a st. &thorn;at.</NOTE></L>
<L N="105">And, sir, if &thorn;ou will &thorn;is aff(a)y,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H assy, T assay.</NOTE></L>
<L>Till bisschop Urban tak &thorn;i way</L>
<L>And tell him all &thorn;ir wordes balde,</L>
<L>Right als I haue to &thorn;e talde;</L>
<L>And tell him all &thorn;i life till end,</L>
<L N="110">So &thorn;at he may &thorn;i mis amend!</L>
<L>&THORN;an sall he, when &thorn;i trowth es trew,</L>
<L>Cleth &thorn;e all in clething new:</L>
<L>Whitte clathes and clene sall he gif &thorn;e.<NOTE PLACE="foot">T sal.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;an sall &thorn;ou in my chamber se</L>
<L N="115">&THORN;e bright angell of god of heuyn</L>
<L>&THORN;at lufes me, als I gan &thorn;e neuyn,</L>
<L>And of him &thorn;an saltou haue</L>
<L>What thing so &thorn;ou will efter craue."</L>
<L>&THORN;an thurgh grace of &thorn;e haly gaste</L>
<L N="120">Vp he rase and went in haste</L>
<L>Vntill &thorn;e gude bisschop Urban,</L>
<L>And halely talde he to him &thorn;an,</L>
<L>With him and his wife how it ferd.</L>
<L>And when Urban his tale had herd,
<PB REF="00000299.tif" N="161"></L>
<L N="125">He heuyd his handes to heuyn on hight</L>
<L>And said &thorn;us to god moste of might:</L>
<L>"Lord Jhesu Criste, loued mot &thorn;ou be</L>
<L>&THORN;at sawes &thorn;e sede of chastite</L>
<L>And gifes unto men cha(s)te cownsaylle<NOTE PLACE="foot">H u. T chate.</NOTE></L>
<L N="130">&THORN;at to &thorn;aire sawl m(a)y mekill availe!<NOTE PLACE="foot">H T my st. may.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ou tak &thorn;e fruit now als &thorn;ine awin</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e sede &thorn;ou has in Cicill sawn &mdash;</L>
<L>For it waxes and multiplise,</L>
<L>Als men may se on &thorn;is wise.</L>
<L N="135">A spows scho toke, with hir to dwell,</L>
<L>&THORN;at als a lion was fers and fell</L>
<L>And rebell both by night and day</L>
<L>Ogains &thorn;e lessons of &thorn;i lay:</L>
<L>Now meke to &thorn;e has scho made him</L>
<L N="140">Als a lamb, in sawl and lym &mdash;</L>
<L>For war he noght unto &thorn;e meke,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H moke. </NOTE></L>
<L>Saluyng of me wald he none seke.</L>
<L>And, sen he has to saluyng soght,</L>
<L>Lord, saue him and forsake him noght!"</L>
<L N="145">&THORN;is when he had his praier end,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H &thorn;is = &thorn;us.</NOTE></L>
<L>Byfor &thorn;am sone &thorn;ai saw descend</L>
<L>Ane ald man and stode &thorn;am bitwene,</L>
<L>All cled in lynnen cloth ful clene,</L>
<L>And in his hand he had a boke</L>
<L N="150">All of gold letters, on to luke.</L>
<L>Valirian, (when) he saw &thorn;is sight,<NOTE PLACE="foot">when fehlt in H T.</NOTE></L>
<L>Might noght luke ogains &thorn;at light:</L>
<L>For drede he fell doun in &thorn;at stede</L>
<L>And still he lay als he war ded.</L>
<L N="155">&THORN;e ald man &thorn;an his right hand toke</L>
<L>And lifted him up, and bad him loke</L>
<L>What thing was wretyn in &thorn;at bill</L>
<L>&THORN;at he had &thorn;are broght him till.</L>
<L>Valirian &thorn;an &thorn;e letter tase</L>
<L N="160">And &thorn;us was wretyn in &thorn;at place:</L>
</LG>
<P>Unus dominus. vna fides. vnum bap|tisma.</P>
<LG>
<L>&THORN;at es on &thorn;is maner to mene:</L>
<L>"A god es euer all-bydene,</L>
<L>And als a faith all folk sall haue,</L>
<L>And a baptym, all sawles to saue."</L>
<L N="165">When Valirian had red &thorn;is bill,</L>
<L>&THORN;an said &thorn;e ald man &thorn;us him till:</L>
<L>"Trowes &thorn;ou &thorn;is als &thorn;ou may rede,</L>
<L>Or dwelles zit &thorn;i hert in drede?"</L>
<L>&THORN;an answer &thorn;us Valirian:<NOTE PLACE="foot">H answer, T answerd. T Valerian.</NOTE></L>
<L N="170">"What thingh might be till erthli man &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">T u. H thingh.</NOTE></L>
<L>To rede or els with mowth to neuyn &mdash;</L>
<L>More forto trow vnder &thorn;e heuyn?</L>
<L>In my wit I trow ful wele</L>
<L>&THORN;at here es writen euer-ilkadele."</L>
<L N="175">Whils Valirian &thorn;ir wordes gan say,</L>
<L>&THORN;e ald man was sone o way &mdash;</L>
<L>And how he went, no-thing &thorn;ai wist.</L>
<L>&THORN;an &thorn;e bisschop Valirian baptist</L>
<L>&amp; bad him trow with conciens clene</L>
<L N="180">Als he &thorn;are had herd and sene.</L>
<L>Valirian grantes with gude will<MILESTONE N="192" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="foot">T granted, H grantes.</NOTE></L>
<L>All his bidinges to fulfill.</L>
<L>&THORN;an hame ogain he bad him ga</L>
<L>Vnto Cicill, &thorn;at he come fra,</L>
<L N="185">And confort hir with all his mayne.<NOTE PLACE="foot">H confert.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;us to his wife he went ogayne.</L>
<L>To Cisill chamber sone he went,</L>
<L>To thank hir &thorn;at him so had sent</L>
<L>To get saluing of all his sin</L>
<L N="190">And gude lifing so to bygyn.</L>
<L>Kneleand in praiers he hir fand,</L>
<L>And sone bifor hir saw he stand</L>
<L>Godes angel, schineand so bright,</L>
<L>&THORN;at all &thorn;e hows lemid of light;</L>
<L N="195">Twa corons in his hand he broght &mdash;</L>
<L>So worthi neuer in werld war wroght:</L>
<L>Vnto Ciscill he toke &thorn;e tane,</L>
<L>&THORN;at o&thorn;er unto Valiriane,</L>
<L>Opon &thorn;aire heuides he set &thorn;am rathe,</L>
<L N="200">And all &thorn;us said he to &thorn;am bathe:</L>
<L>"Kepes &thorn;ir corons zow bitwene</L>
<L>With chast bodys and hertis clene!</L>
<L>Fro paradis I haue &thorn;am broght &mdash;</L>
<L>For in &thorn;at ilk place war &thorn;ai wroght;</L>
<L N="205">To zow mi lord has &thorn;am puruayd."</L>
<L>&THORN;an to Ualirian &thorn;us he said:</L>
<L>"For &thorn;at &thorn;ow wald assentand be</L>
<L>Vnto counsail of chastite,
<PB REF="00000300.tif" N="162"></L>
<L>Mi lord Jhesu, of mercy fre,</L>
<L N="210">Sendes &thorn;e &thorn;us bodword by me:</L>
<L>What thing of him so &thorn;ou will craue,</L>
<L>Ask: and sone &thorn;ou sal it haue,</L>
<L>What thing so euer &thorn;ou will of mele &mdash;</L>
<L>So &thorn;at it be to &thorn;i sawl hele."</L>
<L N="215">Valirian &thorn;an made his asking</L>
<L>And said: "I zern none o&thorn;er thing</L>
<L>Ne no-thing es to me so swete</L>
<L>Als es, my bro&thorn;er bale to bete.</L>
<L>Wald my lord, dere Jhesus,</L>
<L N="220">Help my bro&thorn;er Tyburcius</L>
<L>In his law forto be fre</L>
<L>And cristen man, als he mad me,</L>
<L>&THORN;at we might both parfitely lif</L>
<L>And both oure gastes unto him gif!"</L>
<L N="225">When &thorn;e angell &thorn;ir wordes herd,</L>
<L>To Valirian &thorn;us he answerd</L>
<L>And said: "&thorn;i will it sall be done,</L>
<L>For-whi &thorn;ou askes in &thorn;i bone</L>
<L>&THORN;at mi lord likes forto haue</L>
<L N="230">Better, &thorn;an &thorn;e likes if to craue.</L>
<L>&THORN;arfore, als my lord has won &thorn;e</L>
<L>Thurgh Ciscill, his seruand fre,</L>
<L>So thurgh &thorn;e now sall he win</L>
<L>&THORN;i bro&thorn;er out of bandes of sin.</L>
<L N="235">And &thorn;ou and he sall samyn cum</L>
<L>Vntill &thorn;e mede of marterdome."</L>
<L>When &thorn;is was said, he went up euyn</L>
<L>Wit grete brightnes to blis of heuyn.</L>
<L>And Valirian &thorn;an with his wife<NOTE PLACE="foot">H wisth.</NOTE></L>
<L N="240">Ful halily ay led &thorn;aire life.</L>
<L>And efter &thorn;is, right als god walde,</L>
<L>Tyburcyus, &thorn;at I of talde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at bro&thorn;er was to Valiriane,</L>
<L>Opon a day come him-allane</L>
<L N="245">To luke how &thorn;at his bro&thorn;er ferd,</L>
<L>For halines he of him herd.</L>
<L>And als he entred in &thorn;aire hows,</L>
<L>He kissed him, and als his spows,</L>
<L>He kissed Ciscell and said &thorn;us:</L>
<L N="250">"Gude sauore es here omanges vs &mdash;</L>
<L>Of rose and lilyes me think it like &mdash;</L>
<L>Sen I was born, felde I neuer slike,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H lorn.</NOTE></L>
<L>So swete sauore feld neuer man."</L>
<L>&THORN;an spak his bro&thorn;er Ualirian:</L>
<L N="255">"Bro&thorn;er, sen god vowches saue</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou &thorn;is swete sauore may haue,</L>
<L>Hardily now hete I &thorn;e:</L>
<L>If &thorn;ow in trowth will stedfast be<NOTE PLACE="foot">H stedifast, T stedfast.</NOTE></L>
<L>And luf oure lord Jhesus allane,</L>
<L N="260">Vnto whas lare we haue us tane:</L>
<L>&THORN;an sall tou se and here &thorn;e steuyn</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e angell of god in heuyn</L>
<L>And so be saued, for certayne."</L>
<L>Tyburcius said to him ogayne:</L>
<L N="265">"And I might godes angell se, &mdash;</L>
<L>A verrayer takin might noght be:</L>
<L>&THORN;an will I turn vntill his lay."</L>
<L>When Ciscell herd him sogat say,</L>
<L>Down scho fell and kissed his fete,</L>
<L N="270">And &thorn;an scho said &thorn;ir wordes swete:</L>
<L>"Now will I grante, whore so I wende,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou es my kosyn &amp; my dere frende.</L>
<L>For als &thorn;e luf of Jhesu fre</L>
<L>Has made &thorn;i bro&thorn;er assent to me,</L>
<L N="275">So sall he turn &thorn;e forto take</L>
<L>His might &amp; maumetry forsake.</L>
<L>And, sir, sen &thorn;ou es redy now</L>
<L>To tak his trowth &amp; trewly trow,</L>
<L>With &thorn;i bro&thorn;er saltou ga</L>
<L N="280">Vntill &thorn;e bisschop &thorn;at we come fra,</L>
<L>And be bowsom what he will bid."</L>
<L>Als scho has demid right so &thorn;ai did.</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e bisschop was he baptist &thorn;an</L>
<L>And bycome a ful haly man.</L>
<L N="285">So &thorn;at god gaf him slike grace,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he might se in ilk a place<NOTE PLACE="foot">H be st. he.</NOTE></L>
<L>Angels of god ay at his will</L>
<L>And all his liking tell &thorn;am till,<NOTE PLACE="foot">T likeing.</NOTE></L>
<L>And of &thorn;am might he ask and haue</L>
<L N="290">What thing so he wald efter craue.</L>
<L>&THORN;us &thorn;ir bre&thorn;er bot(h) in-fere<NOTE PLACE="foot">H T bot.</NOTE></L>
<L>And Ciscill, &thorn;at was to &thorn;am dere,</L>
<L>Lifed in luf and charite</L>
<L>And honord god in all degre. &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">T al.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<P>Passio sanctorum Tyburcii et Valeriani.</P>
<LG>
<L N="295">Tiburcius and Valiriane,
<PB REF="00000301.tif" N="163"></L>
<L>Fro-time &thorn;at &thorn;ai had baptime tane,</L>
<L>To serue god ay war &thorn;ai boune,</L>
<L>And fast &thorn;ai prechid in feld &amp; toun</L>
<L>Ogains &thorn;aire mawmettes more &amp; min</L>
<L N="300">&THORN;at &thorn;ai bifore affied &thorn;am in.</L>
<L>To tell &thorn;aire life, it war ful lang,</L>
<L>Or meruayles &thorn;at war &thorn;am omang;</L>
<L>Bot in &thorn;is tretice will I tell</L>
<L>What ferlis in &thorn;aire ded byfell</L>
<L N="305">And what wonders god for &thorn;am wrogt</L>
<L>Yn time &thorn;at &thorn;ai to ded war broght.</L>
<L>&THORN;are wond a prince &thorn;are in &thorn;at land</L>
<L>Whare &thorn;ir two bre&thorn;er war precheand &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;ar lifed all on maumettry:<NOTE PLACE="foot">T u. H &thorn;ar, st. &thorn;at?</NOTE></L>
<L N="310">Vnto &thorn;am had he grete enuy</L>
<L>And said, with dole &thorn;ai suld be dede</L>
<L>Bot if &thorn;ai tite wald turn &thorn;aire rede.</L>
<L>Sone he has efter &thorn;am sent.</L>
<L>And when &thorn;ai come in his present,</L>
<L N="315">&THORN;ai prechid so of Cristes lay:</L>
<L>&THORN;e prince had no power to say</L>
<L>Ne forto do na harm &thorn;am till,</L>
<L>Bot sone he granted to wirk &thorn;aire will.</L>
<L>To Cristes law so turned he;</L>
<L N="320">So did all haly his menze,<NOTE PLACE="foot">T halely.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; all &thorn;o men war turned ilkane</L>
<L>&THORN;at suld haue bene &thorn;e bre&thorn;er bane.</L>
<L>And sone when saint Ciscill herd tell</L>
<L>Of all &thorn;is fare how it bifell,</L>
<L N="325">Vnto &thorn;am ful sone scho soght;</L>
<L>And prestes &thorn;edir with hir scho broght,</L>
<L>&THORN;at baptist &thorn;am biliue ilkane,</L>
<L>To lif in Cristes law allane.</L>
<L>When &thorn;is ilk pri(n)ce Maximius<NOTE PLACE="foot">H price.</NOTE></L>
<L N="330">And his menze war baptist &thorn;us,</L>
<L>Saint Ciscill confort &thorn;am ful wele</L>
<L>And bad &thorn;am forsake ilka dele</L>
<L>&THORN;aire mawmetri &thorn;at &thorn;ai on trow,</L>
<L>And unto Jhesu baynly bow;</L>
<L N="335">Scho bad &thorn;am leue &thorn;e werkes of night</L>
<L>And cleth &thorn;am in armurs of light.</L>
<L>Scho said: "zowre cours ze haue fulfild</L>
<L>Ful worthily, als Jhesus willd;<NOTE PLACE="foot">T wild.</NOTE></L>
<L>A grete bataile ouer-cumen haue ze:</L>
<L N="340">And &thorn;arfore sall ze corond be</L>
<L>With corons &thorn;at Criste sall zow gif,</L>
<L>In lastand blis ay forto lif.</L>
<L>&THORN;arfore bese noght abaist, to take</L>
<L>Marterdom for Cristes sake!"</L>
<L N="345">&THORN;ai granted all to do his will</L>
<L>And his biding forto fulfill;</L>
<L>Almachius &thorn;an, &thorn;e cursed king,</L>
<L>When he herd of &thorn;is ti&thorn;ing,</L>
<L>He cumand &thorn;at &thorn;ai suld ilkane</L>
<L N="350">Mak sacrafise or els be slane.</L>
<L>And for &thorn;ai wald noght wirk his will,</L>
<L>Ful hard paines he put &thorn;am till,</L>
<L>And at &thorn;e last with-outen lite</L>
<L>All &thorn;aire heuides he gert of smite.<NOTE PLACE="foot">T heuiddes.</NOTE></L>
<L N="355">And when &thorn;aire bodis so war schent,</L>
<L>&THORN;aire sawles sone to heuyn went,</L>
<L>&THORN;at men might se with-owten mis</L>
<L>How angels led &thorn;am unto blis.</L>
<L>And mani folk for &thorn;at ilk sight</L>
<L N="360">Turned to Crist and trowed right.</L>
<L>Maximius, &thorn;at gude conuers,</L>
<L>Omang &thorn;am gan &thorn;ir wordes reherce,</L>
<L>He said: "I se &thorn;aire sawles ilkane</L>
<L>With angels vnto heuyn be tane</L>
<L N="365">In &thorn;aire wenges, &thorn;at &thorn;ai noght fall,</L>
<L>And like clene uirgins er &thorn;ai all".</L>
<L>Almachius &thorn;e king herd tell</L>
<L>Of all &thorn;is fare how it bifell,</L>
<L>And how Maximius had said,</L>
<L N="370">And how his folk war all affraid:</L>
<L>He cumand smertly on &thorn;e morn<MILESTONE N="193" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>To bring Maximius him byforn,</L>
<L>And grefe turmentes to him he wroght,</L>
<L>Vntill he vnto ded was broght.<NOTE PLACE="foot">T vntil.</NOTE></L>
<L N="375">His saul was hastly hent to heuyn,</L>
<L>With more solace &thorn;an men may neuyn.</L>
<L>Almachius, &thorn;at wikked king,</L>
<L>When he had done &thorn;us al &thorn;is thing</L>
<L>And saw &thorn;us &thorn;at Ualiriane</L>
<L N="380">And all &thorn;ir o&thorn;er saintes war slane,</L>
<L>&THORN;arfore he thinkes in his mode</L>
<L>At geder to him al &thorn;aire gude.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Nach 382 fehlt ein Verspaar.</NOTE></L>
<L>To Valiriane hows first &thorn;ai haste,
<PB REF="00000302.tif" N="164"></L>
<L>For he was man of reches maste.</L>
<L N="385">&THORN;ai come unto Ciscill, his wife,</L>
<L>Stoutly and with ful grete strife</L>
<L>And bad hir lay furth &thorn;e reches</L>
<L>&THORN;at war hir maysters, more &amp; les,</L>
<L>"For als traitur to dede he zode</L>
<L N="390">And (&thorn;e) king sall haue all his gude".<NOTE PLACE="foot">T &thorn;e, fehlt in H.</NOTE></L>
<L>Saint Ciscil gan grete mornig mak;</L>
<L>And so unto &thorn;a men scho spak</L>
<L>&THORN;at all &thorn;ai turned &thorn;am unto Crist.</L>
<L>And in his name &thorn;ai war baptist,</L>
<L N="395">&THORN;ai forsoke all &thorn;aire maumetry</L>
<L>And trowed in Jhesu almighty;</L>
<L>Him &thorn;ai wirschipt als &thorn;e wise</L>
<L>And lifed and died in his seruise.</L>
<L>Bot when Almachius herd of yit,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H yit od. &thorn;it? T?</NOTE></L>
<L N="400">Wode he was, out of his wit.</L>
<L>He bad &thorn;at Ciscill suld be soght</L>
<L>And hastily bifor him broght;<NOTE PLACE="foot">T hastili.</NOTE></L>
<L>And al hir howsing cumand he</L>
<L>&THORN;at it with fire all brint suld be.</L>
<L N="405">Bot first he frained with eger mode,</L>
<L>Whare was all Valirian gude.</L>
<L>And scho said &thorn;at scho gan it take</L>
<L>Vnto pouer men for goddes sake.</L>
<L>At &thorn;a wordes was he full tene</L>
<L N="410">And bad all suld be brint bidene</L>
<L>Hows and catell, more and min,</L>
<L>And als hir-self he bad &thorn;am brin.</L>
<L>And sone, to fulfill his desire,</L>
<L>Al hir place &thorn;ai set in fire;</L>
<L N="415">Hir-self in mides gert &thorn;ai stand,</L>
<L>And all obout &thorn;e fire brinand.</L>
<L>Bot all &thorn;at here(!) to hir was sene</L>
<L>Als scho in ane erber had bene</L>
<L>Clene and faire with flores bright.</L>
<L N="420">So stode scho a day and night,</L>
<L>Prayand to god wit hert ful hale.</L>
<L>And when Almachius herd &thorn;is tale,</L>
<L>He biddes &thorn;am &thorn;at broght &thorn;e ti&thorn;andes</L>
<L>Smite hir hede of, &thorn;ar scho standes.</L>
<L N="425">His slaghter-man to Ciscill went</L>
<L>Whare scho stode in gude entent;</L>
<L>To god hir prayers gan scho make</L>
<L>And bed hir nec furth till &thorn;e strake.</L>
<L>&THORN;e custum was in &thorn;at cuntre</L>
<L N="430">&THORN;at none suld strike bot strakes thre.</L>
<L>And when he had thre strakes hit,</L>
<L>Zit was hir hals noght sunder kit,</L>
<L>Hale war sum of sins and uaines.</L>
<L>And so he left hir in grete paines &mdash;</L>
<L N="435">For &thorn;e lau was, als I said are,</L>
<L>He suld gif thre strakes &amp; nomare.</L>
<L>So opon hir knese scho sat,</L>
<L>Lifand thre daies efter &thorn;at.</L>
<L>And maidens &thorn;at had with hir bene</L>
<L N="440">Come unto hir albidene,</L>
<L>And al &thorn;a daise scho sesed noght</L>
<L>To confurt &thorn;am so als scho moght.</L>
<L>Efter &thorn;e pape Urban scho sent</L>
<L>And tald unto him hir entent:</L>
<L N="445">"Sir, scho said, god has gifen me</L>
<L>In &thorn;is liue &thorn;ir daies thre,</L>
<L>Als I him praied, and by &thorn;is scill:</L>
<L>&THORN;at I might tell to &thorn;e my will.</L>
<L>All my maidens to &thorn;e I gif,</L>
<L N="450">To zeme &thorn;am wele, ay whils &thorn;(a)i lif,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H &thorn;i.</NOTE></L>
<L>And teche &thorn;am wiseli forto wirk;</L>
<L>And in mi name &thorn;ou mak a kirk</L>
<L>&THORN;at mi maidens may dwell in euyn<NOTE PLACE="foot">H eyuyn.</NOTE></L>
<L>And serue god with will and steuyn".</L>
<L N="455">When &thorn;is was said, ful sone in haste</L>
<L>Vnto god scho gaf &thorn;e gaste.</L>
<L>And &thorn;e bischop, when scho was dede,</L>
<L>Beried hir in &thorn;at same stede</L>
<L>And made a kirk of ful grete spens</L>
<L N="460">In wirschip and in grete reuerence</L>
<L>Of Jhesu Crist, oure sawiowre &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">H sawiowire.</NOTE></L>
<L>Vnto wham be euer honore!</L>
<TRAILER>Amen. Amen. Amen.
</TRAILER>

</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="34" TYPE="legend"><PB REF="00000303.tif" N="165">
<HEAD>34. De sancta Katerina historia.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>S. Tib. 274 b 1&mdash;277 b.</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Sum tyme, als men may understand,</L>
<L>In Alisander was wonand</L>
<L>Ane Emperoure of grete bounte,</L>
<L>And Maxsencius to name had he.</L>
<L N="5">When he had regned threty zere,</L>
<L>In gude nobillay and grete powere,</L>
<L>On &thorn;is manere &thorn;an it bifell,</L>
<L>Als men may here &thorn;e s(t)ori tell.<NOTE PLACE="foot">H sori st stori.</NOTE></L>
<L>He wist and wele he vnderstode</L>
<L N="10">&THORN;at he was so mighty of mode,</L>
<L>&THORN;at no-man durst speke him ogayne.</L>
<L>&THORN;arfore he toke &thorn;is purpos playne</L>
<L>&THORN;at he wald wit in all his land</L>
<L>Who durst ogains his biding stand:</L>
<L N="15">His messangers he sent &thorn;at tide</L>
<L>Thurgh-out his land on ilka syde</L>
<L>And bad &thorn;am cri in feld and toune</L>
<L>&THORN;at all &thorn;a &thorn;at trowed on Mahowne,</L>
<L>Riche and pure, and gude and ill,</L>
<L N="20">Suld hastily cum him vntill,</L>
<L>Efter &thorn;aire might ofrand to make</L>
<L>In his temple for Mahown sake&mdash;</L>
<L>So wald he wit by all war soght,</L>
<L>Who wald trow on his goddes or noght.</L>
<L N="25">&THORN;e messangers &thorn;us furth er sent,</L>
<L>And thurgh-out all &thorn;e land &thorn;ai went.</L>
<L>And when &thorn;e folk &thorn;ir ti&thorn;inges herd,</L>
<L>To Alisander ful fast &thorn;ai ferd,</L>
<L>And ilkone efter &thorn;aire powere</L>
<L N="30">Broght reall giftes, mani &amp; sere;</L>
<L>&THORN;e riche men broght giftes grete,</L>
<L>Als mules and asses, schepe &amp; nete,</L>
<L>&amp; pouer men broght in &thorn;aire hand</L>
<L>Smale fowles to &thorn;aire ofrand.</L>
<L N="35">&THORN;us when &thorn;ai war gederd &thorn;eder,</L>
<L>Riche and pouer, ilkone to-geder,</L>
<L>Trumpes and pipes ful grete plente</L>
<L>Blew &thorn;ai, with o&thorn;er maner of gle;</L>
<L>&THORN;e Emperore bifor &thorn;am zode</L>
<L N="40">Bifor his godes &thorn;at he held gude,</L>
<L>&amp; made ofrand in Mahowns name;</L>
<L>Se&thorn;in all &thorn;e pople did &thorn;e same.</L>
<L>So fell it: in &thorn;at same cete</L>
<L>Wond a king curtas &amp; fre,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H curtas, T curtais.</NOTE></L>
<L N="45">A mighti man of nobill fame,</L>
<L>And king Costus &thorn;ai cald his name;</L>
<L>Ane nobill woman was his quene,<NOTE PLACE="foot">T nobil.</NOTE></L>
<L>And childer was none &thorn;am bitwene</L>
<L>Bot a dogter, &thorn;at was &thorn;aire haire,<NOTE PLACE="foot">T doghter.</NOTE></L>
<L N="50">And scho was curtais, mild &amp; faire.</L>
<L>Katerin hight &thorn;at maiden milde;</L>
<L>Fro alkins filth scho was unfilde,</L>
<L>In halines all scho hir held.</L>
<L>And on a day, als scho &thorn;are dweld,</L>
<L N="55">Scho herd grete noise and melody</L>
<L>Of diuers maners of minstralsy.</L>
<L>&THORN;e maiden spird of men, &thorn;at knew,</L>
<L>What was &thorn;at noys scho herd onew.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai said, how &thorn;e folk of &thorn;e land</L>
<L N="60">Vnto &thorn;aire mawmet made ofrand</L>
<L>At &thorn;e Emperours biding.</L>
<L>&amp; when &thorn;e maiden herd &thorn;is thing,</L>
<L>Of hir faders awin menze</L>
<L>Toke scho with hir two or thre</L>
<L N="65">&amp; maidens, &thorn;at to hir assent;</L>
<L>So preuely furth es scho went,</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e temple scho toke &thorn;e way</L>
<L>Whare all &thorn;e folk offerd &thorn;at day.</L>
<L>Scho saw &thorn;are men &thorn;at mighti were</L>
<L N="70">Offer with ful mery chere,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H there st. chere.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; sum scho saw of hertes gude</L>
<L>&THORN;at offerd with ful drery mode &mdash;</L>
<L>For all with maistri war &thorn;ai gert,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H whare, T war.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ai offerd with hand, bot noght with hert.</L>
<L N="75">&THORN;e mayden stode &thorn;us &amp; bihelde</L>
<L>&THORN;aire countenance both in zowth &amp; elde.</L>
<L>When scho had sene &thorn;is ferly fare,</L>
<L>In hir hert scho had grete care;</L>
<L>&THORN;e cors scho made on mowth &amp; tong,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H T cors st. cros.</NOTE></L>
<L N="80">Ful wisely, all-if scho war zong,</L>
<L>To god in hert &thorn;us gan scho pray:</L>
<L>"Lord, &thorn;ou strenkith my steuyn &thorn;is day,
<PB REF="00000304.tif" N="166"></L>
<L>So &thorn;at zone terant me noght schende</L>
<L>Thurg wiles of &thorn;is wikked fende!"</L>
<L N="85">&THORN;an went scho baldly with blithe mode<NOTE PLACE="foot">H mede.</NOTE></L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e emperoure, &thorn;are he stode,</L>
<L>Scho hailsed him with ful milde chere</L>
<L>&amp; said to him on &thorn;is manere:</L>
<L>"Sir Emperoure, to &thorn;e we bring</L>
<L N="90">Hailsing of hele &amp; goddes greting<NOTE PLACE="foot">T greteing.</NOTE></L>
<L>And forto say &thorn;e for &thorn;i sele</L>
<L>How &thorn;ou may wirk wisly &amp; wele,</L>
<L>If &thorn;ou will do all &thorn;is honowre,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou dose here forto socoure</L>
<L N="95">Maumetry and fendes of hell</L>
<L>And &thorn;aire seruandes &thorn;at with &thorn;am dwell,</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;i maker moste of myght<MILESTONE N="194" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&amp; honore him both day and night.</L>
<L>Set &thorn;i minde in his maieste</L>
<L N="100">&amp; knaw &thorn;are es no god bot he,</L>
<L>&THORN;at made &thorn;is midelerth, mone &amp; sun,</L>
<L>&amp; thurgh him es al thing bigun,</L>
<L>&amp; thurgh him sall al be gane,<NOTE PLACE="foot">T all.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; o&thorn;er god es none bot he allane;<NOTE PLACE="foot">95&mdash;104 sind in H nachgetragen.</NOTE></L>
<L N="105">He es god of man and wife</L>
<L>&amp; lord of all &thorn;at lendes in life;</L>
<L>And als he wroght &thorn;ir werdes all,</L>
<L>So gouernes he both grete and small,</L>
<L>For in &thorn;is werld es no gude thing</L>
<L N="110">With-owten his grace &amp; gouernig.</L>
<L>&THORN;arfore unto him turn &thorn;i thoght</L>
<L>&amp; wirschip him &thorn;at &thorn;e has wroght!"</L>
<L>When &thorn;e Emperore &thorn;ir wordes herd,</L>
<L>With grete ferly in hert he ferd</L>
<L N="115">&amp; grete meruail in hert him thoght</L>
<L>Of wordes &thorn;at &thorn;e mayden &thorn;are wroght;</L>
<L>He biheld hir face ful clere</L>
<L>And hir mouth &amp; hir mildly chere.</L>
<L>And when he gan him wele avise,</L>
<L N="120">&THORN;ir wordes said he on &thorn;is wise:</L>
<L>"A, maiden milde, cumly and clene,</L>
<L>&THORN;e semlyest &thorn;at euer was sene!</L>
<L>It es grete pete &thorn;at &thorn;ou noght knaws</L>
<L>Ne es noght lered of Mahouns laws.</L>
<L N="125">For, sertes, if &thorn;ou understode</L>
<L>&THORN;e grete mightes of oure goddes so gude,</L>
<L>&THORN;an wald &thorn;ou leue slike wordes vaine</L>
<L>And untill oure goddes be ful bayne.</L>
<L>Bot, mayden, he said, sen &thorn;ou ert here,</L>
<L N="130">Of oure laws we sall &thorn;e lere;<NOTE PLACE="foot">T our.</NOTE></L>
<L>Swilk vanitese &thorn;ou sall forsake</L>
<L>&amp; till oure goddes &thorn;ine ofrand make.</L>
<L>&THORN;an sal none be to me so dere".</L>
<L>Scho answerd &thorn;an on &thorn;is manere:</L>
<L N="135">"Sir, &thorn;i goddes here I forsake,</L>
<L>&THORN;at er maumettes &amp; fendes blake,</L>
<L>And I tak me to god of heuyn,</L>
<L>For o&thorn;er lord es none to neuyn".</L>
<L>&THORN;e Emperoure, when he herd &thorn;is saw,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H law st. saw. T?</NOTE></L>
<L N="140">In his hert he had grete aw.</L>
<L>With faire wordes thoght he hir to till</L>
<L>And with wiles win all his will,</L>
<L>A preue purpos he puruayd</L>
<L>And al &thorn;us unto hir he said:</L>
<L N="145">"Damisell curtayse and hende,</L>
<L>Vnto my palaise saltou wende,</L>
<L>In play and liking forto lif,</L>
<L>And nobill giftes I sall &thorn;e gif".</L>
<L>&THORN;us with faire wordes he gan hir till.</L>
<L N="150">&amp; so sum-dele ogaines hir will</L>
<L>Vnto his palayis er &thorn;ai went.</L>
<L>And messangers ful sone war sent</L>
<L>In ilka syd of &thorn;at regiowne,</L>
<L>Vnto ilk cete and to ilk toune,</L>
<L N="155">With letters under his preue sele;</L>
<L>He bad: als &thorn;ai wald haue &thorn;aire hele,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ai suld wend hastily</L>
<L>To al &thorn;e maister(s) of clergy,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H maister.</NOTE></L>
<L>Both retorikes and gramarione,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H gramarione, T?</NOTE></L>
<L N="160">And cumand &thorn;am halely bidene</L>
<L>Smertly forth cum hym to</L>
<L>For nedeful thing he had to do,</L>
<L>Of nedefull maters forto trete;</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;arfore hight he giftes grete.</L>
<L N="165">&THORN;e messangers all sides has soght,</L>
<L>And many maysters haue &thorn;ai broght,</L>
<L>Bot fifti grete maisters, &thorn;at ware</L>
<L>Moste witty and wisest of lare&mdash;</L>
<L>Of erthly wit &thorn;ai war moste wise</L>
<L N="170">And ouer all o&thorn;er haldan in prise.<NOTE PLACE="foot">H euer st. ouer (T?).</NOTE></L>
<L>Katerine was in chawmbers queme</L>
<L>And sertaine men set hir to zeme,
<PB REF="00000305.tif" N="167"></L>
<L>Vntill &thorn;ir maisters samanum war soght</L>
<L>And so bifor &thorn;e Emperoure broght.</L>
<L N="175">&THORN;e Emperoure tald &thorn;an his entent</L>
<L>And said: "I haue efter zow sent</L>
<L>Forto destroy by clergi clene</L>
<L>A woman &thorn;at has wroght me tene;</L>
<L>For, sertes, when I hir se with sight,</L>
<L N="180">To speke with hir haue I no migh(t)&mdash;</L>
<L>Scho es so sutill of hir saw</L>
<L>And sertes <I>so</I> cumly none I knaw.<NOTE PLACE="foot">H es st. so, T?</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;arfor I pray zow to assay<NOTE PLACE="foot">H &thorn;atfor.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bi cours of clergy if ze may</L>
<L N="185">Any wit intill hir bring</L>
<L>Vntill oure goddes to mak ofring:</L>
<L>And I sall gif zow for zow(r) dede</L>
<L>Ful riche giftes vntill zowre mede."</L>
<L>&THORN;e mayisters till his saw assent<NOTE PLACE="foot">H mayisters, vgl. palayis 151.</NOTE></L>
<L N="190">Forto fulfill all his entent,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e day was set on &thorn;e morn</L>
<L>&THORN;at scho suld be broght &thorn;am biforn.</L>
<L>Ful sone &thorn;is tithinges herd scho as,<NOTE PLACE="foot">as = has.</NOTE></L>
<L>Katerine, whare scho closed was,</L>
<L N="195">How &thorn;e Emperowre has ordand</L>
<L>Mayisters ogaines hir forto stand:<NOTE PLACE="foot">H mayisters, vgl. palayis 151.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;an scho gaf all hir quarele</L>
<L>Into goddes hand ilkadele.</L>
<L>And for he of hir will was payd,</L>
<L N="200">Ane angell come and to hir sayd:</L>
<L>"Cristes mayden, mekill of might,</L>
<L>Luke &thorn;at &thorn;ou stand stabilly &amp; right!</L>
<L>For god, &thorn;at may &thorn;e moste auayle,</L>
<L>For wham &thorn;ou sall tak &thorn;is batayle,</L>
<L N="205">Es with &thorn;e euer in all &thorn;i dede,</L>
<L>Redy to help &thorn;e in &thorn;i nede;</L>
<L>He sall gif his wordes of might</L>
<L>Into &thorn;i mowth with speche ful right,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e maysters sall haue no mayne</L>
<L N="210">Forto answer &thorn;e ogayne,</L>
<L>Bot thurgh &thorn;e haly wordes of &thorn;e</L>
<L>Vnto Crist sal &thorn;ai turned be</L>
<L>And for his luf be marterd euyn</L>
<L>And entre into (&thorn;e) blis of heuyn."<NOTE PLACE="foot">T &thorn;e, fehlt in H.</NOTE></L>
<L N="215">When &thorn;is was said, &thorn;at angell bright</L>
<L>Whent up to heuyn with mekil light;<NOTE PLACE="foot">T mekill.</NOTE></L>
<L>And scho in prayers dwelled still,</L>
<L>Ay redy unto goddes will.</L>
<L>Opon &thorn;e morn &thorn;e emperoure</L>
<L N="220">Sat in dome with grete honowre,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e maysters him obout</L>
<L>War gederd in a ful grete crowt.</L>
<L>And Katerin was bifor &thorn;am broght,</L>
<L>Haueand oure lord ay in hir thoght.</L>
<L N="225">&THORN;e maysters say scho suld be mated&mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">T sayd.</NOTE></L>
<L>For als a hund all &thorn;ai hir hated.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai made hir resons mani &amp; sere</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;aire goddes war of grete powere</L>
<L>And &thorn;at scho suld, if scho did wele,</L>
<L N="230">Seke unto &thorn;am for hir fele.</L>
<L>When Katerin had &thorn;aire wordes herd,</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;am all &thorn;us scho answerd:</L>
<L>"Herkins me halely on raw</L>
<L>&THORN;at makes zow maysters of &thorn;e law</L>
<L N="235">And also leders of &thorn;e land!</L>
<L>I will ze wit and understand</L>
<L>&THORN;at I am cristend and baptiste</L>
<L>Thurgh &thorn;e sacramentes of Crist,</L>
<L>And o&thorn;er cautels none I knaw</L>
<L N="240">Bot anly lessons of his law.</L>
<L>All zowre sawes here I forsake</L>
<L>And to him haly I me take,</L>
<L>For he has strenkith and wit uerray</L>
<L>And he has lare &thorn;at last sal ay;</L>
<L N="245">He es begining and ending</L>
<L>Of all gudenes and all gude thing,</L>
<L>He has made al thing of noght,</L>
<L>And mankind with his blude he boght,</L>
<L>Se&thorn;in he rase fro ded to life</L>
<L N="250">&amp; stegh to heuyn with-owten (strife),<NOTE PLACE="foot">H with owten tryst, T?</NOTE></L>
<L>And euer in blis he dwelles so</L>
<L>With his fader &thorn;at (he) come fro;<NOTE PLACE="foot">he fehlt in H T.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; diuers uertuse schewed he &thorn;an</L>
<L>&THORN;at he was werray god &amp; man</L>
<L N="255">And es &amp; euer-more sall be,</L>
<L>A mighty god in persons thre.</L>
<L>He es my god, he es my king,</L>
<L>He es my lord &amp; my liking."</L>
<L>When scho had said &thorn;ir wordes &thorn;are,</L>
<L N="260">All &thorn;e maisters les and mare
<PB REF="00000306.tif" N="168"></L>
<L>Wer all awonderd of hir saw</L>
<L>And in &thorn;aire hertes &thorn;ai had grete aw,</L>
<L>&amp; thurgh &thorn;e grace of god so gude</L>
<L>&THORN;ai durst noght speke, bot stil &thorn;ai stode.<NOTE PLACE="foot">T still.</NOTE></L>
<L N="265">&THORN;e emperoure saw &thorn;am stand still,</L>
<L>&amp; greuosly he spak &thorn;am till,</L>
<L>He said: "whi stand ze so for schame,</L>
<L>&amp; er so grete maisters at hame?</L>
<L>Here stand ze als ze had no tung,</L>
<L N="270">To speke ogains a mayden zung."</L>
<L>&THORN;an he &thorn;at was moste of honowre</L>
<L>Said vnto &thorn;e Emperoure:</L>
<L>"Sir, if &thorn;at it be &thorn;i will,</L>
<L>&THORN;is tell we halely &thorn;e untill:</L>
<L N="275">Bot if &thorn;ow can teche us sum law<NOTE PLACE="foot">T &thorn;ou.</NOTE></L>
<L>More worthy &thorn;an oure-self can knaw</L>
<L>Of &thorn;i goddes, by euyn or morn</L>
<L>&THORN;at we haue wirschip(t) here byforn:<NOTE PLACE="foot">T wirschipt, H wirschip.</NOTE></L>
<L>Unto Crist will we turn ilkane<NOTE PLACE="foot">T wil.</NOTE></L>
<L N="280">&amp; hald him for oure lord allane;</L>
<L>For in oure hertes wele we knaw</L>
<L>&THORN;at he es lord of high and law</L>
<L>&amp; god sun uerraily of heuyn,</L>
<L>And o&thorn;er god es none to neuyn."</L>
<L N="285">When &thorn;e emperoure saw how it zode,</L>
<L>For tene and wo he wex nere wode,</L>
<L>&amp; hastily he toke to rede</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ai suld ilkone be dede.</L>
<L>He said: sen &thorn;ai vse heresy,</L>
<L N="290">Brin(t) all sall &thorn;ai be for-&thorn;i.<NOTE PLACE="foot">T brint, H brin.</NOTE></L>
<L>In middes &thorn;e cete gert he make<MILESTONE N="195" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>A grete fire for &thorn;e maisters sake,</L>
<L>And to his men &thorn;at he cumand:<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at st. &thorn;an?</NOTE></L>
<L>To bind &thorn;o maysters fote &amp; hand</L>
<L N="295">And in &thorn;e fire &thorn;am forto cast,<NOTE PLACE="foot">T kast.</NOTE></L>
<L>When it was brinand faire &amp; fast.</L>
<L>And so to do wald &thorn;ai noght spare.</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;is vertu god schewid &thorn;are:</L>
<L>&THORN;at, when &thorn;e fire was brint oway,</L>
<L N="300">Hale in quert ilkone war &thorn;ai &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;e fire had blemist &thorn;am no-thing,</L>
<L>In hide ne hare ne in clething.</L>
<L>Bot so, als &thorn;ai desired maste,</L>
<L>Unto god &thorn;ai gaf &thorn;e gaste &mdash;</L>
<L N="305">No-thing thurgh &thorn;o paynes ill,</L>
<L>Bot anely thurgh our lordes will.</L>
<L>When &thorn;e Emperoure &thorn;is sight had sene,</L>
<L>In hert he had ful mekill tene;</L>
<L>He cumand &thorn;at &thorn;e mayden bright</L>
<L N="310">Suld sone be broght bifor his sight.</L>
<L>And all-if he in hert war tende,</L>
<L>He spac to hir with wordes hende:</L>
<L>"A, worthi maydin mikel of prise,</L>
<L>Worthi woman war and wiffe,</L>
<L N="315">Faire of face, of carping kowth,</L>
<L>Haue mercy, maiden, of &thorn;i zowth!</L>
<L>Do curtaisly, als I cumand,</L>
<L>Unto my goddes mak ofrand:</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou sall in my court ful clene<NOTE PLACE="foot">T sal.</NOTE></L>
<L N="320">Be honord euermore next my quene,</L>
<L>And all &thorn;at in my rewme suld seme</L>
<L>Sal euer be done als &thorn;ou wil deme;</L>
<L>All men sal at &thorn;i biding be</L>
<L>And atendand, als unto me.</L>
<L N="325">In &thorn;is cete I sall do mak<NOTE PLACE="foot">H his st. &thorn;is.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ine awin lyknes with-owten lac</L>
<L>And set it up, als &thorn;ou sall se,</L>
<L>Of all men honord forto be;</L>
<L>And for &thorn;i sake I sal ger dight</L>
<L N="330">A temple all of marbre bright,</L>
<L>Whare &thorn;ou and I sall both in-fere</L>
<L>Honore oure goddes of grete pouere.</L>
<L>How think &thorn;e, mayden, of &thorn;is skill?"</L>
<L>Scho answerd &thorn;an &amp; said him till:</L>
<L N="335">"Sir emperoure, scho said, lat be!</L>
<L>Neuyn namore slike wordes to me!</L>
<L>Criste &thorn;at es my lord allane,</L>
<L>Unto his spowse he has me tane</L>
<L>In trew faith, &thorn;at sall neuer faill;</L>
<L N="340">He es my ioy and my cownsaill,</L>
<L>He es my luf, he es my lorde,</L>
<L>And we tow er so wele acorde<NOTE PLACE="foot">H tow st. two.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at now&thorn;er paine ne erthly gude</L>
<L>Fro his luf may turn my mode."</L>
<L N="345">&THORN;an &thorn;at terant was ful tene</L>
<L>&amp; ordand Katerin paynes kene:</L>
<L>He gert his men tite in &thorn;at tyde</L>
<L>Naken hir both bac and side,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H naked st. naken, T?</NOTE></L>
<L>With scorpions &thorn;an he did hir bete,</L>
<L N="350">&amp; mani o&thorn;er paines grete;
<PB REF="00000307.tif" N="169"></L>
<L>Bot al he saw might noght auale</L>
<L>In hir fait(h) to ger hir faile.<NOTE PLACE="foot">H fait st. faith.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;an in a preson &thorn;ai hir did</L>
<L>Whare scho was all in mirkenis hid,</L>
<L N="355">And wight men set he hir to gete,</L>
<L>&THORN;at scho sul haue no drink ne mete,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H sul st. suld.</NOTE></L>
<L>Se sustinance suld scho haue nane,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H se = so od. st. ne, T?</NOTE></L>
<L>Till twelue daies war cumen &amp; gane.</L>
<L>Bot angels ilk day come hir till:</L>
<L N="360">Of gastly fude scho had hir fill.</L>
<L>&THORN;us in &thorn;at preson gan scho dwell.</L>
<L>And in &thorn;at same tyme so bifell:</L>
<L>Ti&thorn;inges come to &thorn;e Emperore,</L>
<L>&THORN;at, if he wald haue his honowre,</L>
<L N="365">A fer cuntre bud him wend to,</L>
<L>For chargeand thinges &thorn;at war to do;</L>
<L>So hastly was he efter sent:</L>
<L>He ordand him and furth he went.</L>
<L>When he was went, &thorn;an &thorn;us bifell:</L>
<L N="370">&THORN;e emperise, his wife, herd tell</L>
<L>How he had done so grete hething</L>
<L>Vnto Katerin, &thorn;at mayden zing;</L>
<L>To speke with hir &thorn;an has scho thoght</L>
<L>&amp; mend hir mischeues, if scho moght.</L>
<L N="375">A prince, &thorn;at was a nobil man,</L>
<L>To hir in cownsail kald scho &thorn;an</L>
<L>And tald to him al hir entent;</L>
<L>And to hir saw sone he assent,</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e preson forto wende,</L>
<L N="380">Forto speke with &thorn;at mayden hende;</L>
<L>Porfurius was &thorn;e knightes name.</L>
<L>And, forto be with-outen blame,</L>
<L>Opon &thorn;e night bot(h) gan &thorn;ai pas<NOTE PLACE="foot">H bot, (T?).</NOTE></L>
<L>To &thorn;e preson whare &thorn;e mayden was.</L>
<L N="385">Unto &thorn;e kepers spac &thorn;ai so,</L>
<L>&THORN;at to &thorn;e mayden come &thorn;ai two.</L>
<L>And all-if it war in &thorn;e nyght,</L>
<L>Obut ir saw &thorn;ai so grete light,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;am astonaid in &thorn;at stound,</L>
<L N="390">So &thorn;at &thorn;ai fell doun on &thorn;e grownd;</L>
<L>Bot so gude sawore gan &thorn;ai fele,</L>
<L>&THORN;at it confort &thorn;aire hertes wele.</L>
<L>Saint Katerin &thorn;an bad &thorn;am up rise</L>
<L>And spak untill &thorn;am on &thorn;is wise:</L>
<L N="395">"Rises up, scho said, &amp; dredes zow noght!</L>
<L>Bot luke ze be of stabill thoght!</L>
<L>For my lord Crist calles zow to com</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e mede of marterdom."</L>
<L>&THORN;an rase &thorn;ai up, wele in &thorn;are wit:</L>
<L N="400">And saw &thorn;at blissed mayden sit</L>
<L>Omang ful many angels bright,</L>
<L>&THORN;at confort hir with all &thorn;aire might:</L>
<L>&THORN;ai enoynt hir body &amp; made ful clene,</L>
<L>Whare wikked wondes bifore had bene;</L>
<L N="405">&THORN;ai made hir body so in bewte,</L>
<L>&THORN;at wonder was &thorn;aron to se.</L>
<L>&THORN;an said &thorn;e mayden unto &thorn;e quene:</L>
<L>"Dame, luke in hert be trew &amp; clene!</L>
<L>Within thir thre daies saltou wend<NOTE PLACE="foot">T &thorn;ir.</NOTE></L>
<L N="410">Vnto Jhesu, in ioy to lend.</L>
<L>&THORN;arfore drede noght bi morn ne none</L>
<L>&THORN;e erthly paynes, &thorn;at passes sone!</L>
<L>For &thorn;am in heuyn sall-tow haue<NOTE PLACE="foot">T saltou.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ai-lastand ioy, &thorn;i sawl to saue;</L>
<L N="415">For dedly thing, &thorn;at failes als fast,</L>
<L>Gifes god &thorn;e ioy &thorn;at euer sal last,<NOTE PLACE="foot">T sall.</NOTE></L>
<L>And for paine &thorn;at passes in a day</L>
<L>Gifes he &thorn;e blis &thorn;at last sall ay."</L>
<L>Prince Porfuri toke tent here-till</L>
<L N="420">And &thorn;an of hir he asked &thorn;is skill:</L>
<L>"I pray &thorn;e, mayden, tell me right</L>
<L>What mede gifes god until a knight?</L>
<L>Erthly harmes here if &thorn;ai take</L>
<L>&amp; suffers angers for his sake,</L>
<L N="425">What giftes gifes he &thorn;am for-&thorn;i?"</L>
<L>&THORN;an answerd Katerin curtaisly:</L>
<L>"Purfuri, I pray &thorn;e, here:</L>
<L>And by my saying saltou lere</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e hegh kingdom of heuyn</L>
<L N="430">Es like untill a cete euyn</L>
<L>Whare none angers ne noy es in,</L>
<L>Bot all mirth &thorn;at men may of myn;</L>
<L>&amp;, schortly it forto declare,</L>
<L>All &thorn;at gude es &thorn;at es &thorn;are,</L>
<L N="435">And all &thorn;at unto euil may mene</L>
<L>In &thorn;at cete es neuer sene.</L>
<L>None hertes mai think, ne eris here,</L>
<L>Ne eghen se, &thorn;e ioyes sere</L>
<L>&THORN;at god ordans with-owten striue</L>
<L N="440">To &thorn;am &thorn;at lufes him in &thorn;are liue."<NOTE PLACE="foot">H &thorn;are, T &thorn;aire.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000308.tif" N="170"></L>
<L>When &thorn;at &thorn;e mayden &thorn;us had sayd,</L>
<L>Sir Porfuri was ful wele payd,</L>
<L>And also of &thorn;at semly syght</L>
<L>War &thorn;ai both in hert ful light,</L>
<L N="445">And halely hight &thorn;ai to fulfill</L>
<L>Als saint Katerin had said &thorn;am till.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai toke &thorn;aire leue &amp; fro hir went,</L>
<L>Praiand to god with gude entent,</L>
<L>&amp; redy turmentes forto take</L>
<L N="450">&amp; paines to suffer for Cristes sake.</L>
<L>&amp; all &thorn;e knightes in &thorn;at prouince</L>
<L>&THORN;at war rewled by Porfore, &thorn;e prince,<NOTE PLACE="foot">T Porfure.</NOTE></L>
<L>War torned to Crist, of heuyn king,</L>
<L>&amp; went to heuyn at &thorn;aire ending.</L>
<L N="455">&THORN;e emperice so dwelled still,</L>
<L>Redy euer unto goddes will.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Emperore, when he had end</L>
<L>&THORN;e caus &thorn;at gert him fro hame wend,</L>
<L>Hastly hied he hame ogayne</L>
<L N="460">&amp; thogh(t) to puruay Katerin payne.</L>
<L>Bot Jhesu Crist, &thorn;at scho on cride,</L>
<L>Come to confort hir &thorn;at tide,</L>
<L>With mani angels schinand clere,</L>
<L>&amp; said to hir on &thorn;is manere:</L>
<L N="465">"Doghter dere, luke &thorn;ou be kinde</L>
<L>&amp; knaw &thorn;i maker in &thorn;i minde,</L>
<L>For whas luf &thorn;ou has undertane</L>
<L>To suffer paynes &amp; se&thorn;in be slane.</L>
<L>Drede &thorn;ou noght, bot stedfast be!</L>
<L N="470">For I sal alway won with &thorn;e &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">T sall.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;aire paines sal do &thorn;e none-kins ill &mdash;</L>
<L>Till I will tak &thorn;e me vntill."</L>
<L>When &thorn;is was said, he went up euyn</L>
<L>With grete brightnes to blis of heuyn.</L>
<L N="475">&THORN;e Emperore gert on &thorn;e morn</L>
<L>Fetche &thorn;e mayden him biforn,</L>
<L>Forto assay more of hir will.</L>
<L>&amp; al &thorn;us &thorn;an he spak hir till:</L>
<L>"Mayden, he said, &thorn;i-self sall se</L>
<L N="480">Me es wele leuer &thorn;e life of &thorn;e</L>
<L>&THORN;an with turmentes &thorn;e forto lose.<MILESTONE N="196" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;arfore of two &thorn;ou sall haue chose:<NOTE PLACE="foot">T sal.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ow&thorn;er to offer with-outen strif</L>
<L>Vnto my goddes and haue &thorn;i life,</L>
<L N="485">And els, if &thorn;ou will noght do &thorn;is,</L>
<L>To suffer paynes, til &thorn;ou peris &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">T till.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e tone of &thorn;ise bus nedes be."</L>
<L>&THORN;an answerd &thorn;e mayden fre</L>
<L>And said: "I couait for to lif</L>
<L N="490">With Crist, &thorn;at gastly life may gif,</L>
<L>And for his luf I will be faine</L>
<L>Forto dy here with erthly payne;</L>
<L>For, when &thorn;is erthly pain es past,</L>
<L>Sal I haue life &thorn;at euer sall last.</L>
<L N="495">&THORN;arfore ord(a)ine, sir, I &thorn;e pray,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H ordine.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e hardes(t) paine &thorn;ou can puruay!<NOTE PLACE="foot">H hardes.</NOTE></L>
<L>For my will es euer on all wise</L>
<L>Of mi fless to mak sacrifise,</L>
<L>For his sake &thorn;at on &thorn;e tre</L>
<L N="500">Offerd his fless and blude for me."</L>
<L>&THORN;an &thorn;at terant was so tene:</L>
<L>His hertly wo might no-man wene.<NOTE PLACE="foot">H herthly.</NOTE></L>
<L>He cald opon his goddes gude spede,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ai suld help him in &thorn;at nede.</L>
<L N="505">And at &thorn;e last come at his call</L>
<L>Ane of his hine, hight Beliall,</L>
<L>And untill him all &thorn;us said he:</L>
<L>"Sir Emperore, how may &thorn;is be?</L>
<L>Es no penance zit puruaid</L>
<L N="510">&THORN;at might mak &thorn;is maiden flaid,</L>
<L>Ne to ger hir mak sacrifice</L>
<L>Until oure goddes of mekill price?</L>
<L>Ger ordan, als I sall zow say,</L>
<L>Bitwene &thorn;is &amp; &thorn;is day third day</L>
<L N="515">Foure wheles stalworth for &thorn;e nanes,</L>
<L>To riue hir sunder fless and banes,</L>
<L>For in &thorn;e wheles sal stand out</L>
<L>Scharp crokes of iren all obout.</L>
<L>By &thorn;is be made, &thorn;an sall it be</L>
<L N="520">So ill and ugly on to se,</L>
<L>&THORN;at it sall ger hir be ful fain</L>
<L>To mensk oure goddes with al hir main.</L>
<L>&amp; if scho will noght turn hir thoght,</L>
<L>With &thorn;am scho sal to ded be broght".</L>
<L N="525">&THORN;e Emperoure &thorn;an, als he had said,</L>
<L>Gert &thorn;ir wheles be smertly graid</L>
<L>&amp; on &thorn;e thrid day &thorn;am rayse</L>
<L>In middes a place of his palayse.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai war so foul and felly croked:</L>
<L N="530">All folk war ferde &thorn;at on &thorn;am loked;
<PB REF="00000309.tif" N="171"></L>
<L>Two of &thorn;am turned dounwar plaine,</L>
<L>&amp; two turned upward &thorn;am ogayne.</L>
<L>&THORN;an toke &thorn;ai Katerin, mayden clene,</L>
<L>And gert hir stand &thorn;e wheles bitwene,</L>
<L N="535">So &thorn;at scho suld be sunder rent.</L>
<L>Bot Crist ful sone hir socore sent.</L>
<L>Scho stode prayan with mild steuyn,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">H prayan st. prayand,</NOTE></L>
<L>Haldan hir eghen up till &thorn;e heuyn.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">H haldan.</NOTE></L>
<L>And als scho suld to ded be dight,</L>
<L N="540">God of heuyn &thorn;are schewed his might:</L>
<L>Right als &thorn;e wheles bigan to stir,</L>
<L>His angels sent he unto hir,</L>
<L>&THORN;at with grete strakes semeand of thunder</L>
<L>&THORN;e whelis brak &thorn;ai so in-sunder,</L>
<L N="545">&THORN;at foure thowsand of hir enmyse</L>
<L>Lay &thorn;are ded &amp; might noght rise.</L>
<L>&THORN;an was &thorn;are sorow &amp; mikel tenes</L>
<L>Omang &thorn;e iews and &thorn;e payenes,</L>
<L>And mikell ioy to cristen men.</L>
<L N="550">Bot Maxsencius ful wo was &thorn;en</L>
<L>For &thorn;is ilk wonder &thorn;at was wroght;</L>
<L>What he might do &thorn;an wist he noght.</L>
<L>Bot his gude quene, when scho herd tell</L>
<L>Of &thorn;is ferly how it bifell,</L>
<L N="555">In hir hert grete ioy scho had</L>
<L>&amp; furth scho went with sembland glad,</L>
<L>Bifor &thorn;e Emperoure gan scho fare,</L>
<L>&THORN;at was als wode als a wild bare.</L>
<L>For his fare was scho noght affraid,</L>
<L N="560">Bot baldly &thorn;us to him scho sayd:</L>
<L>"Wharto rises &thorn;ou with unright</L>
<L>Ogaynes &thorn;i maker, moste of might?</L>
<L>How grete he es, now may &thorn;ou ken,</L>
<L>God &thorn;at gouer(n)s cristen men,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">H gouers.</NOTE></L>
<L N="565">&amp; how &thorn;i goddes with uain-glory</L>
<L>Er no-thing els bot mawmetry</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e may now&thorn;er help ne rede,</L>
<L>Als &thorn;ou may se proued in &thorn;is stede".</L>
<L>&THORN;an was &thorn;e Emperoure ful tene</L>
<L N="570">And &thorn;us he said untill his quene:</L>
<L>"Whi spekes &thorn;ou so, mine Emperise?</L>
<L>Allas! I wend &thorn;ou had bene wise.</L>
<L>Wher any lurdan of cristen lay</L>
<L>Haue witched &thorn;e, &thorn;ir wordes to say?"</L>
<L N="575">Grete athes &thorn;an to hir he sware</L>
<L>&amp; said: "bot &thorn;ou tite leue &thorn;at lare</L>
<L>And unto my goddes mak ofrand,</L>
<L>&THORN;is paine for &thorn;e sall be ordand:</L>
<L>&THORN;e pappes fro &thorn;i brest sall be raft,</L>
<L N="580">So &thorn;at &thorn;ou sall lang penance taft,</L>
<L>&THORN;i fals goddes to crus and ban;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">H crus st. curs. T?</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;i heuyd sall be smitten of &thorn;an,</L>
<L>And &thorn;i body bron on &thorn;e felde,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">H bron st. born, T?</NOTE></L>
<L>Wild bestes it forto welde".</L>
<L N="585">&THORN;an answerd &thorn;e Emperise</L>
<L>And spak to him &thorn;ir wordes wise:</L>
<L>"Sir, I sall be redy ay<NOTE PLACE="foot2">T sal.</NOTE></L>
<L>Till all &thorn;e paines &thorn;ou can puruay;</L>
<L>I am here redy in &thorn;is stede</L>
<L N="590">For Jhesu sake to suffer ded.</L>
<L>&THORN;e herdar payn I here may haue,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">T harder.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e leuer es me, my sawl to saue".</L></LG>

<P>De passione Regine<NOTE PLACE="foot1">H Regione.</NOTE> et Porphurij militis.</P>

<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>When &thorn;e Emperoure &thorn;ir wordes herd,</L>
<L>Als a wode lyon he ferd;</L>
<L N="595">Langer he had &thorn;ai suld noght stand<NOTE PLACE="foot2">H had, T bad. suld noght stand sind in H v. a. H. zugesetzt.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bot sla hir, als he had cumand.</L>
<L>Ful felly &thorn;an on hir &thorn;ai fest</L>
<L>&amp; rugged hir furth with-owten rest.</L>
<L>Als &thorn;ai so led hir to felde,</L>
<L N="600">Unto saint Katerin scho byhelde</L>
<L>And said to hir &thorn;ir wordes fre:</L>
<L>"Mayden, pray now god for me,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at I for none erthly sight</L>
<L>Lose &thorn;e cor(o)n he has me hight,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">H corn, T coron,</NOTE></L>
<L N="605">Ne &thorn;at no passion bodily</L>
<L>Mak me haue drede forto dy".</L>
<L>&THORN;an to hir said &thorn;e mayden zing:</L>
<L>"Drede &thorn;e for none erthly thing!</L>
<L>For &thorn;is pain &thorn;at sal sone be past</L>
<L N="610">Sall &thorn;ou haue ioy &thorn;at euer sall last.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">T sal.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;is day &thorn;ou passes fra soro &amp; strif</L>
<L>And takes &thorn;e mede of lastand lif".</L>
<L>When &thorn;is was said, &thorn;e kinges men</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;e cete harlid hir &thorn;en.
<PB REF="00000310.tif" N="172"></L>
<L N="615">With iren hokes ful hastily</L>
<L>Drogh &thorn;ai &thorn;e pappes of hir body,</L>
<L>On hokes &thorn;ai hing hir pappes round,</L>
<L>And drogh &thorn;e body till &thorn;e ground,</L>
<L>And se&thorn;in &thorn;ai smate hir heuyd of euyn&mdash;</L>
<L N="620">Hir saul went to blis of heuyn.<NOTE PLACE="foot">T sawl.</NOTE></L>
<L>Purfurius &thorn;an, &thorn;e nobill knight,</L>
<L>Went preuely opon &thorn;e night,<NOTE PLACE="foot">T whent.</NOTE></L>
<L>And toke o&thorn;er of his assent,</L>
<L>And ordain a monument;<NOTE PLACE="foot">T u. H ordain.</NOTE></L>
<L N="625">First he enoint &thorn;e blist body</L>
<L>And groue it &thorn;an ful deuotely.</L>
<L>On &thorn;e morn &thorn;e Emp(er)oure herd say:</L>
<L>&THORN;at body was tane oway</L>
<L>&THORN;at he bad suld to bestes ly;</L>
<L N="630">And &thorn;arfore had he grete enuy.</L>
<L>He gert enquere &thorn;e suth ful tite</L>
<L>Who might do him &thorn;at despite;</L>
<L>Al &thorn;o &thorn;at in &thorn;at tyme war sene,</L>
<L>Said he, suld be ded bidene,</L>
<L N="635">Bot if he might graith knawing haue</L>
<L>Who was so bald hir forto graue.</L>
<L>When Porfuri saw in &thorn;at stede</L>
<L>So mani suld for &thorn;at dede be dede,</L>
<L>Leuer him was allane to dy:</L>
<L N="640">&THORN;arfore he spac ful hardily<NOTE PLACE="foot">T hardyly.</NOTE></L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e Emperoure, &thorn;are he stode:</L>
<L>"Sir, he said, I hald &thorn;e wode.</L>
<L>Erthly bodis more and les<NOTE PLACE="foot">H erithly, T erthly.</NOTE></L>
<L>Forto be grauen, ful kindly es.</L>
<L N="645">Sen &thorn;ou sais sum sall bere &thorn;e blame,<NOTE PLACE="foot">T sal.</NOTE></L>
<L>I say to &thorn;e, I am &thorn;e same;</L>
<L>Seruand to Jhesu Crist am I</L>
<L>And his marter I groue for&thorn;i".</L>
<L>&THORN;an was &thorn;e Emperoure wonder wode,</L>
<L N="650">For tene he trembild als he stode,</L>
<L>And so to rare he gan bigin</L>
<L>&THORN;at all &thorn;e court rang with &thorn;e din.</L>
<L>"Allas, he said, I lif ouer-lang</L>
<L>To suffer all &thorn;ir stowres strang!</L>
<L N="655">Al erthly wele wendes o-way</L>
<L>&THORN;at me suld confort night or day!</L>
<L>Lo here mi nobil knight, allas,</L>
<L>&THORN;at mi keper and confort was,</L>
<L>Mi sekerest help in ilka nede</L>
<L N="660">And mi solace in ilkadede&mdash;</L>
<L>Now es he most man me to noy</L>
<L>&amp; has liking oure lawes to stroy</L>
<L>&amp; grantes him anely forto ken</L>
<L>&amp; serue &thorn;e god of cristen men.</L>
<L N="665">"How think zow, asked he of &thorn;am all,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;is faitur how sall bifall?"</L>
<L>&THORN;an all &thorn;e knightes in &thorn;at present</L>
<L>Vnto Purfuri sone assent</L>
<L>&amp; said &thorn;ai war redy to take</L>
<L N="670">With him &thorn;e ded for Cristes sake.</L>
<L>Maxsencius &thorn;an was mased and mad&mdash;</L>
<L>Slike sorow in his hert he had&mdash;<MILESTONE N="197" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And cumand &thorn;at &thorn;ai suld ilkane</L>
<L>Withowten (hone) alsone be slane:<NOTE PLACE="foot">hone fehlt in H u. T.</NOTE></L>
<L N="675">"&THORN;aire heuides, he said, biliue o strikes</L>
<L>&amp; cast &thorn;aire bodis till dogges in dikes"!</L>
<L>Als he bad, hastily was done.</L>
<L>&THORN;aire sauls went (t)o heuyn ful sone.<NOTE PLACE="foot">H wento, T went to.</NOTE></L>
<L>Maxcencius opon &thorn;e morn</L>
<L N="680">Gert bring saint Katerin him biforn</L>
<L>&amp; with grete uoise &amp; greuose chere</L>
<L>He sayd to hir on &thorn;is manere:</L>
<L>"wikked woman, wo &thorn;e be!</L>
<L>No langer sal &thorn;ou turment me,</L>
<L N="685">Bot one of &thorn;ir two sall &thorn;ou chese:</L>
<L>Whethir &thorn;e es leuer &thorn;i heuid to lese</L>
<L>Or to mak ofrand with gude chere</L>
<L>Unto my goddes of grete powere.</L>
<L>And zit I rede &thorn;ou &thorn;e avise</L>
<L N="690">And to my goddes mak sacrifice,</L>
<L>Or I with schameful ded &thorn;e schende".</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;an answerd &thorn;e mayden hende:</L>
<L>"Terant, scho said, &thorn;i-self sall se</L>
<L>I couait noght to tari &thorn;e.</L>
<L N="695">To what paine so &thorn;ou will me wayue,</L>
<L>I am redy it to resayue;</L>
<L>For any pain &thorn;at &thorn;ou may make</L>
<L>Jhesu sall I neuer forsake;</L>
<L>He es mi lord &amp; his am I&mdash;</L>
<L N="700">&THORN;i fals goddes here I defy".</L>
<L>&THORN;an was &thorn;e Emperoure ful wo</L>
<L>And cumand men biliue to go</L>
<L>With &thorn;at mayden without &thorn;e zates</L>
<L>And smite hir heuy(d) of in &thorn;e gates.<NOTE PLACE="foot">H heuyn.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000311.tif" N="173"></L>
<L N="705">Als &thorn;ai hir led so, to be slane,</L>
<L>Hir folowed maydens manyane</L>
<L>&amp; widows &amp; wiues, wepeand fulsare.</L>
<L>Unto &thorn;am all &thorn;us said scho &thorn;are:</L>
<L>"Worthi wemen, wendes ogayn</L>
<L N="710">&amp; murnes noght, bot more bese fain!</L>
<L>My lord Crist calles me to cum,</L>
<L>At won with him in (his) kingdom".<NOTE PLACE="foot1">his fehlt.</NOTE></L>
<L>When &thorn;is was said, on knese scho knelde</L>
<L>And up unto &thorn;e heuyn bihelde,</L>
<L N="715">Praiand to god on &thorn;is manere:</L>
<L>"Lord Jhesu, mi mayster dere,</L>
<L>Luf of al &thorn;a &thorn;at trowes in &thorn;e,</L>
<L>Ioy and confort of maydens fre!</L>
<L>I thank &thorn;e, lord, mildly omell</L>
<L N="720">&THORN;at &thorn;ou will tak me forto dwell</L>
<L>Omang &thorn;i maydens faire &amp; bright,</L>
<L>Whare I sall euer of &thorn;e haue sight.</L>
<L>Sen &thorn;ou slike grace to me has done,</L>
<L>Lord, I ask of &thorn;e &thorn;is bone:</L>
<L N="725">&THORN;at, who so will for &thorn;i renown</L>
<L>Mak minde of my passioun</L>
<L>Or honors me in word or dede</L>
<L>Or calles to me in time of nede&mdash;</L>
<L>Whe&thorn;er it be in point of ded</L>
<L N="730">Or here when &thorn;ai er will of rede&mdash;</L>
<L>What so &thorn;ai rightwisly will craue,</L>
<L>Lord, grante &thorn;am grace it forto haue!</L>
<L>Here for &thorn;i luf &thorn;is life I end&mdash;</L>
<L>Resayue mi saul unto &thorn;i hend!"</L>
<L N="735">&THORN;us als scho praied with stedfast steuyn,</L>
<L>A uoyce spak &thorn;us to hir fro heuyn:<NOTE PLACE="foot1">H noyce.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Cum unto me, my mayden dere,</L>
<L>Resaiue &thorn;e coron of blisses sere!</L>
<L>Bihald and se in &thorn;i pase plain</L>
<L N="740">How many halows cumes &thorn;e ogain!<NOTE PLACE="foot1">H cum es.</NOTE></L>
<L>Cum unto me, be noght adred!</L>
<L>All &thorn;at &thorn;ow askes, it sall be sped,</L>
<L>And al &thorn;at oght of &thorn;e will craue</L>
<L>Of me fro heuin &thorn;ai sall it haue".</L>
<L N="745">&THORN;an bed scho hir hals till &thorn;e strake,</L>
<L>And so &thorn;ai gan hir marter make.</L>
<L>Milk ran out in stede of blode.</L>
<L>Hir sawll ful sone unto heuyn zode.</L>
<L>&THORN;an come &thorn;are in &thorn;are aller sight</L>
<L N="750">Grete cumpany of angels bright;</L>
<L>&THORN;ai toke &thorn;at bode clene and faire<NOTE PLACE="foot1">bode = bodi.</NOTE></L>
<L>And bare it up into &thorn;e ayre,</L>
<L>And so furt with grete melody</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e mownt of Synay</L>
<L N="755">And beried it &thorn;are &thorn;am omang</L>
<L>With mikel ioy &amp; solempne sang,</L>
<L>Als it was Cristes cumandment;</L>
<L>When &thorn;is was done, to heuyn &thorn;ai went.</L>
<L>And se&thorn;in sekes untill hir graue</L>
<L N="760">All seke &amp; sare, &thorn;at hele will haue,</L>
<L>&amp; unto hir god giffes slike grace</L>
<L>&THORN;at all er helid in &thorn;at place</L>
<L>Thurgh merit of &thorn;at maiden gude</L>
<L>&THORN;at for &thorn;am praied with mild mode.</L>
<L N="765">God grant us grace &thorn;at we may cum,</L>
<L>And be deliuerd thurgh his dome,</L>
<L>Thurgh biseking of saint Katerin</L>
<L>Unto &thorn;at welth &thorn;at he wons in.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Hinter Katharina folgt in Ms. Harl. noch Andreas, fol. 197b, und Anastasia, fol. 199, nachtr&auml;glich mit vacat als an dieser Stelle ung&uuml;ltig bezeichnet, weil Wieder|holungen von in dems. Ms. bereits vorangegangenen Legenden. Darauf folgt end|lich Barlaam und Josaphat, an die Sammlung sich anschliessend; diese Legende ist bereits gedruckt in den "Altenglischen Legenden" 1875, p. 226.</NOTE>
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="appendix"><PB REF="00000312.tif" N="174">
<HEAD>Anhang.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Alexius,
aus Ms. Ashmol. 42 und Ms. Cbr. Gg. V, 31.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>In der Sammlung der "Evangelia dominicalia" der Mss. Ashm. 42 und Cbr. Gg. V, 31 ist nach dem Abschluss der Evangelien noch ein Nachtrag angef&uuml;gt, enthaltend 1) zur Feier des T&auml;ufers Johannes: Evangelium in vigilia s. Johannis Bapt. (Fuit in diebus Herodis), und In die ejusdem s. Johannis ad missam matutinalem (Dixit Zacharias ad angelum), und als Exemplum oder Narratio hierzu die untenstehende Legende von Alexius. 2) Sermo in festo apostolorum Petri et Pauli (gedruckt p. 77 ff.).&mdash; Alexius soll ein Beispiel sein, wie Gott seine Auserw&auml;hlten schon in ihrer Geburt begnadigt; wie Johannes der T&auml;ufer "&thorn;urgh grace" empfangen und seine Geburt von Wundern begleitet ist, so auch Isac und Samuel, Maria u. a.: Of all &thorn;ir was herd tythand Of &thorn;air getyng thorow goddys sand. Dessgleichen Alexius: And a gud child thorow prayer Was gettyn in Rome on &thorn;is manere. &mdash; Von den 2 Hss. verdient offenbar Ms. Ashmol. den Vorzug; doch erscheint es gerathen, beide Hss. abzu|drucken, um zugleich ein Beispiel f&uuml;r das Verh&auml;ltniss und die Sprache dieser wichtigen Homiliensammlungen zu geben.</P></HEADNOTE>
<DIV2 TYPE="legend">
<HEAD>Alexius,</HEAD>
<DIV3 TYPE="version">
<HEAD>a) aus Ms. Ashm. 42. (A gude tale.)</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>In Rome was anes a riche mane,</L>
<L>&THORN;at hight forsothe Eufemyane;</L>
<L>And his wife was calld Aglase,</L>
<L>A gode wommane forsothe scho was.</L>
<L N="5">Riche &thorn;ai ware of gold and fe,</L>
<L>And he senatoure of &thorn;at cite;</L>
<L>He had seruaundes thre thousande,</L>
<L>&THORN;at seruid him to fote and hande;</L>
<L>In sendelle his men&yogh;e he cledde</L>
<L N="10">And daynteli he &thorn;aim fedde.</L>
<L>In honoure liuid Eufemyane</L>
<L>And his wife, a gode womane.</L>
<L>&THORN;us &thorn;is man lange &amp; his wife</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; ioye and blisse &thorn;ai ledde &thorn;aire life.</L>
<L N="15">So gode and almous gern &thorn;ai ware</L>
<L>In all &thorn;aire welthe &amp; riche fare,</L>
<L>&THORN;at in &thorn;aire hall stode aie redie</L>
<L>Thre bordes spred full menskfulli:</L>
<L>A borde, pilgrimes for-to fede,</L>
<L N="20">Ano&thorn;er to pouere &thorn;at had nede,</L>
<L>And the thrid to faderles barnes</L>
<L>&THORN;at helpe of fadir &amp; modir tharnes.
<PB REF="00000313.tif" N="175"></L>
<L>And &thorn;is godeman him-self gon sitte,</L>
<L>Als mani men duse &yogh;itte,</L>
<L N="25">Wi&thorn; gode men of halikirk,</L>
<L>&THORN;at wald goddes werkes wirk,</L>
<L>&THORN;at lufid wele myldenes,</L>
<L>Religioune &amp; halines.</L>
<L>His wife was almous gerne ynoghe</L>
<L N="30">And euer-more to gode thewes droghe.</L>
<L>Of hali life ware &thorn;ai bathe &mdash;</L>
<L>Herd neuer man whare &thorn;ai did scathe.</L>
<L>Of werldes blisse &thorn;ai had gode wane,</L>
<L>&THORN;aim wantid nathinge in erthe bot ane:</L>
<L N="35">For childe betwene &thorn;aim had &thorn;ai nane;</L>
<L>For-thi &thorn;aim tho&yogh;t &thorn;aire blisse all gane,</L>
<L>Sorie &thorn;ai ware &amp; euile paiede,</L>
<L>And oft-sithis to god &thorn;ai praied</L>
<L>&THORN;at he wald for his grete mercie</L>
<L N="40">Sende &thorn;aim som fruite of &thorn;aire bodie.</L>
<L>And sone oure lorde herd &thorn;aire praiere</L>
<L>&amp; gladid tite &thorn;aire heuie chere:</L>
<L>He sente betwix &thorn;aim a knaue-childe,</L>
<L>&THORN;at was bathe gode &amp; meke &amp; mylde.</L>
<L N="45">And when &thorn;is ilk knaue-childe was borne,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai thankid god bothe euene &amp; morne,</L>
<L>And cristnid him wi&thorn; ioye and blisse</L>
<L>And namid him &thorn;are Alexis &mdash;</L>
<L>In oure tonge &thorn;is ilk name schewes</L>
<L N="50">Manne full-fillid of gode thewes.</L>
<L>&THORN;is childe wex fast &amp; wele thraue,</L>
<L>For mikil grace god him gaue.</L>
<L>His fadir sette him sone to boke,</L>
<L>And wele clergie he vndirtoke;</L>
<L N="55">Bot &thorn;o bokis lufid he inwardlie</L>
<L>&THORN;at spak oght of god all-mightie.</L>
<L>Mai i no&yogh;t tell all his godenes,</L>
<L>His wisdome ne his halines.</L>
<L>Bot schortli here i will &yogh;ow schewe</L>
<L N="60">Of his life and his gode thewe. &mdash;</L>
<L>When he was commen forthe in elde,</L>
<L>His fadir wi&thorn; mensk &amp; wi&thorn; belde</L>
<L>Gert him a faire maiden spouse,</L>
<L>And bro&yogh;t hir home till his house:</L>
<L N="65">Scho was of &thorn;e emperoure kinde,</L>
<L>Als we in stories writen finde;</L>
<L>Meke and mylde scho was yno&yogh;e</L>
<L>And aie to godenes scho hir droghe.</L>
<L>At &thorn;air bridale was mikil fare,
<PB REF="00000314.tif" N="176"></L>
<L N="70">And riche gifftis giuen &thorn;are:</L>
<L>Robes riche, siluer and golde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at es to riche men full holde;</L>
<L>&THORN;are was myrthe &amp; gammen &amp; gle,</L>
<L>Mete &amp; drink of wyne clarre,</L>
<L N="75">&THORN;er was ynoghe forsothe to all</L>
<L>&THORN;at was gadird to &thorn;at hall;</L>
<L>&THORN;ai gaue mikil almous for goddes sake</L>
<L>To all pore &thorn;at wald it take.</L>
<L>Ilkman had ioye ynoghe,</L>
<L N="80">And si&thorn;en ilkon home droghe.</L>
<L>When &thorn;is bridegome suld go to bed,</L>
<L>&THORN;at richeli wi&thorn; pall was sprede &mdash;</L>
<L>Gayli was his chaumbir graithid</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; riche clothis, in flore laide:</L>
<L N="85">He graithid him on all manere</L>
<L>Als he suld ligge be his fere.</L>
<L>&THORN;e whe&thorn;er he ne tho&yogh;t it no&yogh;t:<NOTE PLACE="foot">&THORN;e wheder = tamen.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ano&thorn;er &thorn;inge was in his tho&yogh;t.</L>
<L>When all was oute of chaumber gane</L>
<L N="90">Saue he &amp; his wife allane,</L>
<L>He prechid hir of maidenhede</L>
<L>&amp; sithen of &thorn;at mikil mede</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ai sall haue &thorn;at &yogh;emes here</L>
<L>&THORN;aire maidenhed on gode manere &mdash;</L>
<L N="95">Wi&thorn;outen ani priue pride,</L>
<L>&THORN;at fele wymen er wonte to hide</L>
<L>In &thorn;aire hert for &thorn;aire maidenhede:</L>
<L>&THORN;at geres &thorn;aim laytheli tyne &thorn;aire mede:</L>
<L>For who so duse gode dede in rose,</L>
<L N="100">He tynes all &thorn;at euere he duse. &mdash;</L>
<L>When he had saide what he walde,</L>
<L>His Jewellis he gaue hir for-to halde</L>
<L>And sithen he gaue hir a gold ringe,</L>
<L>Bitwene &thorn;aim to be takenynge:</L>
<L N="105">"To &thorn;e tyme, he saide, we first mete &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;are sall we speke wordes swete.</L>
<L>For i will wende myne erande&mdash;</L>
<L>Bot wote i neuer into what lande".</L>
<L>"And &yogh;oure will, scho saide, it be,<NOTE PLACE="foot">And st. at?</NOTE></L>
<L N="110">God bringe &yogh;ow sone againe to me!"</L>
<L>He toke wi&thorn; him siluer and golde</L>
<L>And riche clothis to laie in folde,</L>
<L>&amp; wente him forthe vnto &thorn;e se</L>
<L>And passid oute of his contre.
<PB REF="00000315.tif" N="177"></L>
<L N="115">Sone he fand redi schippinge,</L>
<L>For gold puruaied his farynge.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai had god winde &amp; forthe &thorn;ai wente</L>
<L>Into ferre contre, verraiment.</L>
<L>And sone when he come to lande,</L>
<L N="120">Cytees &amp; tounes faire he fande;</L>
<L>Vnto a citee forsothe he &yogh;ede</L>
<L>And chaungid &thorn;are his riche wede</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; a beggar, &amp; sithen him cledde</L>
<L>In pure clethinge, &amp; &thorn;an faste fledde &mdash;</L>
<L N="125">For he wald &thorn;at naman it wist</L>
<L>&THORN;at he wald liue in hongir &amp; thriste.</L>
<L>Seuene wintir &thorn;are woned he<NOTE PLACE="foot">st. seuene ist seuentene zu lesen; vgl. 351.</NOTE></L>
<L>In begger lyue and pouerte;</L>
<L>In grete myssese he led his life,</L>
<L N="130">And gude praiers was him full rife;</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; haire and brinye his corse he cledde,</L>
<L>And on &thorn;e bare erde he made his bedde,</L>
<L>Brede and watir was his liue-lade;</L>
<L>And he to god his praiers made</L>
<L N="135">&THORN;at naman suld witte whate he was</L>
<L>Or his sawle fra him gon passe. &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;an when Eufemiane his sonne miste</L>
<L>And it forsothe witirli wiste,</L>
<L>He grette and made full euile chere,</L>
<L N="140">And his modir als in-fere.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai gerte him seke on all manere</L>
<L>Full wide-whare, bothe fer and nere,</L>
<L>To seke &thorn;aire dere sonne Alexis,</L>
<L>To bringe him hame mawgre his.</L>
<L N="145">&THORN;ir messangeres &thorn;an wente sperand</L>
<L>Fra toune to toune, fra lande to land,</L>
<L>Bote fand &thorn;ai nane &thorn;at couthe &thorn;aim wisse</L>
<L>To &thorn;at childe, Alexis.</L>
<L>Twa messangers come &thorn;are he was,</L>
<L N="150">Into a towne als &thorn;ai gon passe,</L>
<L>Sittand in strete ymange pore men;</L>
<L>Bote nou&thorn;er of &thorn;aim couthe him ken,</L>
<L>For hard penaunce &amp; honger and nede<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. ford st. for.</NOTE></L>
<L>Had chaungid all his fairehede;</L>
<L N="155">Full raggid and riuen wase his clathis</L>
<L>And full of vermyne, &thorn;at mani lathis,</L>
<L>And &thorn;arefore couthe &thorn;ai no&yogh;t him knawe,</L>
<L>&THORN;are he wi&thorn; beggars satte on rawe.
<PB REF="00000316.tif" N="178"></L>
<L>&THORN;ai gaue almous to &thorn;aim all</L>
<L N="160">And bade, to god &thorn;at &thorn;ai suld call</L>
<L>&THORN;at of &thorn;aire sekinge &thorn;ai mi&yogh;t spede</L>
<L>And Alexis wi&thorn; &thorn;aim hame lede.</L>
<L>Alexis in all his wa,</L>
<L>When he &thorn;aim sawe before him ga,</L>
<L N="165">His awne seruaundes knewe he wele,</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;ai knewe him neuer a dele.</L>
<L>When he of &thorn;aim almous had tane,</L>
<L>&THORN;areof he thankid god onane:</L>
<L>"Lorde, he saide, i thank the,</L>
<L N="170">&THORN;at hie sittis in trinite,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou to daie hase giuene me grace</L>
<L>Almous to take here in &thorn;is place</L>
<L>Off &thorn;aim &thorn;at was wont to be</L>
<L>Myne awne menne &amp; seruid me,</L>
<L N="175">And i vnknawen vnto &thorn;aim!</L>
<L>&THORN;er-of, lorde, i am full faine". &mdash;</L>
<L>Graithe ensaunpile here mai i take<NOTE PLACE="foot">l. &yogh;e st. i?</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;is werldes welthe to forsake,</L>
<L>For it behoues vs all-gate fle,</L>
<L N="180">Cristis dissipils if we will be;</L>
<L>For so did saint Alexis,</L>
<L>Forthi es he in heuene blisse. &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;ir messangeres come hame againe,</L>
<L>&THORN;at made Eufemian full vnfaine</L>
<L N="185">For &thorn;ai saide &thorn;at &thorn;ai had ferre so&yogh;t</L>
<L>To seke Alexis, &amp; fande him no&yogh;t.</L>
<L>So sorowfull tithand bro&yogh;te &thorn;ai hame:</L>
<L>His fadir sorowed, &amp; his dame.</L>
<L>His modir grette &amp; raaue hir hare,</L>
<L N="190">And all hir bodi scho made bare</L>
<L>&amp; did apon hir a sekk clathe,</L>
<L>&THORN;at hir was wonte to be full lathe,</L>
<L>And saide: "for-sothe, i sall neuer be</L>
<L>Blithe, or i mi dere sonne se;</L>
<L N="195">Bot if i mi sonne hals &amp; kisse,</L>
<L>Of sorow mon i neuer misse.</L>
<L>A, mi swete, dere, sonne,</L>
<L>When i was sori, it was &thorn;i wonne</L>
<L>Forto stand me full nere</L>
<L N="200">And to glade my dreri chere.</L>
<L>How sall i liue, and &thorn;ou awaie?</L>
<L>I maie singe of wailewaie</L>
<L>&THORN;at euer i was of modir borne!
<PB REF="00000317.tif" N="179"></L>
<L>For now es mi ioie all forlorne.</L>
<L N="205">Whiles &thorn;at &thorn;ou was beside me,</L>
<L>Euer-more was I in gammen &amp; gle &mdash;</L>
<L>Might i neuer sorie be,</L>
<L>Apon &thorn;e when i mighte se;</L>
<L>Now es mi swete sonne awaie,</L>
<L N="210">Gone es all my gammen &amp; plaie".</L>
<L>Sorowfull was his fadir ynoghe</L>
<L>And sare sighes fra his herte he droghe;</L>
<L>Mikil leuere him had to die</L>
<L>&THORN;an swilk sorowe lange to drie.</L>
<L N="215">And sa sare grette &thorn;at &yogh;onge spouse</L>
<L>&THORN;at Alexis had broghte to house,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &yogh;ou to tell, it ware to tere,<NOTE PLACE="foot">tere difficult.</NOTE></L>
<L>All hir sorowe and hir euile chere.</L>
<L>Scho saide &thorn;at scho suld neuer-mare</L>
<L N="220">Make ioye ne mirthe, bote euer care,</L>
<L>"And wi&thorn; &yogh;ow aie for-to dwell</L>
<L>Till i of mi husband here tell</L>
<L>In whate land &thorn;at he es lent</L>
<L>Or into whate toune he es wente.</L>
<L N="225">For clene maiden will i be,</L>
<L>Till &thorn;at i him wi&thorn; eyene se.</L>
<L>For o&thorn;er man &thorn;an Alexis</L>
<L>Sal i neuer hals ne kisse,</L>
<L>Ne neuer-more in my liue</L>
<L N="230">Sall o&thorn;er man make me wyue".</L>
<L>&THORN;us scho sorowid daie and night,</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e priuelie and in sight. &mdash;</L>
<L>Torne we now to Alexis</L>
<L>&THORN;at lefft for god &thorn;is werldes blisse.</L>
<L N="235">He liuid in pouerte &amp; in fastinge,</L>
<L>In prayere and in wakinge.</L>
<L>Edissa highte &thorn;at ilk cite</L>
<L>&THORN;are he liuede in pouerte.</L>
<L>Be a kinges &yogh;ate he satte</L>
<L N="240">And liued wi&thorn; &thorn;e almous he gatte.</L>
<L>A-pon a daie, als he satte &thorn;are,</L>
<L>He prayed to god wi&thorn; mylde fare</L>
<L>Before ane ymage of oure ladie.</L>
<L>And scho him answerde selcouthelie</L>
<L N="245">And saide: "Alexis, wele &thorn;e be!</L>
<L>&THORN;i gude praiers full wele paies me".</L>
<L>Ano&thorn;er tyme aperid scho</L>
<L>In &thorn;e kirk a man vnto
<PB REF="00000318.tif" N="180"></L>
<L>&THORN;at bothe to &thorn;e kirk tent toke</L>
<L N="250">And to vestmentes &amp; to boke;</L>
<L>Scho bad him take in sone onane</L>
<L>&THORN;at seli pure goddes manne:</L>
<L>"For his penaunce &amp; his praiere</L>
<L>To mi sonne he es full dere".</L>
<L N="255">&THORN;an faste oute of &thorn;e kirk he ranne</L>
<L>For-to seke &thorn;is goddef manne.</L>
<L>Full mani pure men he sawe,</L>
<L>Bote nane of &thorn;aim gon he knawe</L>
<L>Of whaim oure ladi to him spak;</L>
<L N="260">Forthi he ne wiste whaim in to take.</L>
<L>He come rynnand againe forthi</L>
<L>And praied oure ladi inwardeli:</L>
<L>"Ladi, &thorn;i seruaunde haue i so&yogh;te,</L>
<L>And, for-sothe, I knawe him no&yogh;te:</L>
<L N="265">&THORN;erfore, ladie, wisse &thorn;ou me</L>
<L>To him, ife &thorn;i will be!"</L>
<L>&THORN;an &thorn;e ymage of oure ladie</L>
<L>Answerd him aperteli:</L>
<L>"Be &thorn;is taken &thorn;ou sall him kenne<NOTE PLACE="foot">Das Zeichen wird nicht genannt.</NOTE></L>
<L N="270">&THORN;are he sittis ymange pure menne".</L>
<L>And he rynnes forthe &amp; findes him ri&yogh;te,</L>
<L>Als &thorn;e ymage had him highte.</L>
<L>On knees he fell &thorn;an ate his fete,</L>
<L>And full faire he gon him grete</L>
<L N="275">&amp; saide: "gude man, i praie the,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou come in-to &thorn;e kirk wi&thorn; me!</L>
<L>For god, &thorn;at es ofe maste pouste,</L>
<L>To his seruaunde hase chosen &thorn;e".</L>
<L>When Alexis herd &thorn;is sawe,</L>
<L N="280">He sighed and held his heued full lawe,</L>
<L>For his godenes he wald ware hid</L>
<L>And lathe him was &thorn;at ite ware kidde;</L>
<L>Bote no&yogh;te-forthi he wi&thorn; him &yogh;ede,</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e kirk he gon him lede.</L>
<L N="285">&THORN;e folk herd &thorn;is myracle swete:</L>
<L>And knelid before Alexis fete,</L>
<L>And in riche sete &thorn;ai him sette</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; faire wordes &thorn;ai him grette.</L>
<L>Alexis of &thorn;is was noghte payed</L>
<L N="290">And to him-selfe &thorn;usgates he sayed:</L>
<L>"&THORN;ou &thorn;at made all thinge iwisse,
<PB REF="00000319.tif" N="181"></L>
<L>Wate full wele whate mi will is:</L>
<L>Neuer swilk wirschipe forto haue,</L>
<L>Ofe man ne wife, maiden ne knaue.</L>
<L N="295">Faire ofe &thorn;is contre &thorn;ou bringe me<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. faire st. fer?</NOTE></L>
<L>And send me plase of priuete!</L>
<L>For is nathinge &thorn;at i hate mare</L>
<L>&THORN;an to be menskid, or wele fare".</L>
<L>Sone effter on a mirk nighte</L>
<L N="300">Oute ofe &thorn;ate toune he fled, for sighte,</L>
<L>And come to &thorn;e toune ofe Laodise,</L>
<L>&THORN;ate es gode toune ofe marchandise.</L>
<L>In-to &thorn;e se he schippid &thorn;are:</L>
<L>For in-to Tarsis he tho&yogh;te to fare,</L>
<L N="305">To dwell &thorn;are in sainte Paule kirk</L>
<L>In pouerte, &amp; goddef will to wirk.</L>
<L>Bote god tornid &thorn;e wind belife</L>
<L>And gerte &thorn;e schippe in Rome ryue.</L>
<L>And when Alexis come to land,</L>
<L N="310">His fadir he mette fra &thorn;e kirk comand.</L>
<L>And faire he gon his fadir grete</L>
<L>And saide to him &thorn;ir wordes swete:</L>
<L>"Lorde, of me &thorn;ow haue mercie,</L>
<L>A pure nedefull man am I;</L>
<L N="315">&THORN;ou giue me mete par charite</L>
<L>Of releue &thorn;ate &thorn;ou leues before &thorn;e!</L>
<L>And if &thorn;ou lufe ani mane</L>
<L>&THORN;at in pilgrimage es gane,</L>
<L>I sall praie god wi&thorn; mode &amp; maine</L>
<L N="320">&THORN;at he sende him sone againe</L>
<L>And &thorn;ate he com hale and sounde,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;-outen wemme, wi&thorn;-outen wounde,</L>
<L>In foreward &thorn;at &thorn;ou do me gude</L>
<L>And helpe me to my lyues fude".</L>
<L N="325">Full still &thorn;an stode Eufemiane,</L>
<L>To lithe and listen &thorn;is pure mane;</L>
<L>On Alexis, his sonne, so he tho&yogh;te,</L>
<L>&THORN;at him nerehand to dede had bro&yogh;te,</L>
<L>&THORN;at in pilgrimage was wente,</L>
<L N="330">Bote he ne wiste whare he was lente;</L>
<L>Forthi for him he sighid sare</L>
<L>And wepid for sorowe &amp; for care.</L>
<L>And for he tho&yogh;te &thorn;an of his sonne,</L>
<L>He gerte his sorowe more monne,</L>
<L N="335">And he saide: "man, for mi sonne sake</L>
<L>Into mi house i will &thorn;e take,</L>
<L>And &thorn;are i sall &thorn;e clethe &amp; fede</L>
<L>And fynde &thorn;e all &thorn;at &thorn;e es nede".
<PB REF="00000320.tif" N="182"></L>
<L>"Now god, he saide, in trinite,</L>
<L N="340">Leue sir, for&yogh;elde ite &thorn;e!"</L>
<L>Hame to his howse he him ledde,</L>
<L>And in his howse made him a bedde</L>
<L>In a chaumbir be him ane,</L>
<L>And a keye he gon him tane,</L>
<L N="345">To come &amp; ga ate his will;</L>
<L>And bad his men his will fullfill,</L>
<L>And comaunde &thorn;aim all wi&thorn; gode mode</L>
<L>To giue him his liues fode.</L>
<L>&THORN;us liuide he &thorn;are wi&thorn; almous</L>
<L N="350">In his awne fadir howse</L>
<L>O&thorn;ir wintirs seuentene,</L>
<L>And suffrid paynes mani &amp; kene;</L>
<L>His penaunce chaungid all his hewe,</L>
<L>So &thorn;ate nane in werld him knewe.</L>
<L N="355">&THORN;e fende to him was full wrathe</L>
<L>And tysid men to do him lathe.</L>
<L>For wantonne barnes of &thorn;e house,</L>
<L>&THORN;at was fedde &thorn;are wi&thorn; almouse,</L>
<L>Come to him on nightir tale</L>
<L N="360">For to do him mikil bale:</L>
<L>For som him toke be &thorn;e berde,</L>
<L>For to make him all ferde,</L>
<L>Som keste on him dihsse-wehssinge</L>
<L>And did him mani o&thorn;ir hethinge,</L>
<L N="365">Som keste atte him stone &amp; clotte,</L>
<L>Som plaied wi&thorn; him sitti-sotte.</L>
<L>And all he tholid wi&thorn; gode will,</L>
<L>Goddes biddinge to full-fill,</L>
<L>And praied for &thorn;aim &thorn;at did him scathe&mdash;</L>
<L N="370">For he forgaue &thorn;aim all &thorn;aire lathe,</L>
<L>And praied &thorn;at god suld &thorn;aim grace sende</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ai mighte &thorn;aire lif amende. &mdash;</L>
<L>Tholemodenes here maie &yogh;e lere</L>
<L>&THORN;ate gladli will &thorn;is tale here;</L>
<L N="375">Here maie &yogh;e se &thorn;at tholemodenes</L>
<L>To cristen man so gode thinge es,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. men st. man.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at wrange ne woghe ne werldes scathe</L>
<L>Maie do atte him ne make him wrathe;</L>
<L>For ite is rute ofe all gudenes,</L>
<L N="380">Faire speche and mekenes. &mdash;</L>
<L>Sone effter god sente his sande</L>
<L>To Alexis, gude tithande,</L>
<L>And bad &thorn;ate he suld make him &yogh;are
<PB REF="00000321.tif" N="183"></L>
<L>Oute of &thorn;is werld forto fare.</L>
<L N="385">He thankid god full inwardli</L>
<L>Of his grace and his mercie;</L>
<L>&THORN;an he callid to him his knaue</L>
<L>And bad &thorn;ate he suld ger him haue</L>
<L>Parchemyne and inke bathe:</L>
<L N="390">And he ite bro&yogh;t to him full rathe.</L>
<L>&THORN;an his life all &thorn;are wrate he,</L>
<L>&THORN;at, when he ware dede, &thorn;ai mighte se,</L>
<L>Whase sonne he was, &amp; whate he highte;</L>
<L>And all his life he wrate full ri&yogh;te:</L>
<L N="395">How he had liued in beggarhede</L>
<L>In mikil missese and in nede</L>
<L>Euenli foure &amp; thritti &yogh;ere,</L>
<L>In mikil pouerte, in stedes sere,</L>
<L>And how he fra his wife wente</L>
<L N="400">And in whate toune he was lente,</L>
<L>And how he gaue his gold ringe</L>
<L>To his wife atte his partinge</L>
<L>And saide ite suld be takeninge</L>
<L>Betwene &thorn;aim atte &thorn;aire firste metinge.</L>
<L N="405">When he had made all &thorn;is writte,</L>
<L>Faste in his hand he loukid ite,</L>
<L>And laide him doune on his bedde:</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; harde sekenes was he stedde.</L>
<L>&THORN;an god of heuene schewid sone</L>
<L N="410">&THORN;e mikil gode &thorn;ate he had done.</L>
<L>For on &thorn;e palme-sonondaie,</L>
<L>When folk in kirk began to praie,</L>
<L>A voyse was in &thorn;e mynstir herde &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at made all &thorn;e folk full ferde;</L>
<L N="415">&THORN;e voice saide: "comes all to me</L>
<L>&THORN;at suffirs pyne and pouerte!</L>
<L>And i sall lethe wi&thorn;-outen faile</L>
<L>&YOGH;oure lange tene &amp; &yogh;oure trauaile</L>
<L>And bringe &yogh;ow to heuene blisse,</L>
<L N="420">&THORN;er no pyne ne trauaile is".</L>
<L>&THORN;e folk on knees fell in thrange</L>
<L>And kyrieleyson thries &thorn;ai sange.</L>
<L>&THORN;e voise effte-sones spak in hye</L>
<L>And bad &thorn;aim seke wightlie</L>
<L N="425">Goddes seruaunde "&thorn;at es full meke,</L>
<L>For in &thorn;is citee lyes he seke".</L>
<L>&THORN;e folk wiste neuer whate ite mente,</L>
<L>Ne ofe whaim &thorn;ai had na tente.
<PB REF="00000322.tif" N="184"></L>
<L>Neuer &thorn;e latter &thorn;ai him soghte,</L>
<L N="430">Bote Alexis &thorn;ai fande no&yogh;te,</L>
<L>Als &thorn;e voise to &thorn;aim &thorn;is talde.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Der Vers scheint fehlerhaft.</NOTE></L>
<L>His gaste to god Alexis &yogh;alde:</L>
<L>On &thorn;e godefridaie atte morne</L>
<L>Full godirhaile was he borne.</L>
<L N="435">&THORN;e pape of Rome &amp; his clergie</L>
<L>&THORN;at daie wente to &thorn;e kirk arelie,</L>
<L>Goddes seruis &thorn;are for to saie</L>
<L>And to Jesu for to praie;</L>
<L>And so did twa emperours,</L>
<L N="440">And lawde folk, to here &thorn;aire houres.</L>
<L>&amp; all &thorn;ai tho&yogh;te apon &thorn;ate steuene</L>
<L>&THORN;at god had sente &thorn;aim fra heuene.</L>
<L>&THORN;e pape gerte &thorn;aim praie all than</L>
<L>&THORN;at god suld sende &thorn;aim &thorn;at man</L>
<L N="445">Of whaim &thorn;e voise fro heuene had spokene,</L>
<L>Whare and in whate plase &thorn;at he was lokene.</L>
<L>&THORN;e folk did his comaundmente</L>
<L>And praied god wi&thorn; gode entente,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai saide: "lorde full of mercie,</L>
<L N="450">On &thorn;e we call, on &thorn;e we crie,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou swete lorde, now vs wisse</L>
<L>In whate stede &thorn;i seruaund is,</L>
<L>&THORN;at we thorghe him mai loue &thorn;e</L>
<L>When we his swete bodi se!"</L>
<L N="455">&THORN;an sone &thorn;ai herde a voise saie</L>
<L>&THORN;at in Eufemiane house he laie,</L>
<L>"Loke &thorn;are, &amp; &yogh;e sall find redie</L>
<L>&THORN;e hali bodie of Alexi".</L>
<L>&THORN;e folk &thorn;an full faine was ofe &thorn;is</L>
<L N="460">When &thorn;ai herd of Alexis &mdash;</L>
<L>For him was mikil wa in Rome</L>
<L>For &thorn;ai ne wiste whare he become.</L>
<L>&THORN;e pape ofe Rome &amp; his clergie</L>
<L>Tho&yogh;te of &thorn;is full grete ferlie,</L>
<L N="465">&THORN;ai askid sone Eufemyane</L>
<L>Whi he helid goddes mane.</L>
<L>He answerd &thorn;aim &amp; saide &thorn;aim: "naie,</L>
<L>I knawe o nane, be mi laie!"</L>
<L>&THORN;e pape made processioune</L>
<L N="470">Of lerid and lawde &thorn;orghe &thorn;e toune,</L>
<L>And wente to Eufemyane palaise,
<PB REF="00000323.tif" N="185"></L>
<L>For sothe, als &thorn;e boke vs saise,</L>
<L>&THORN;at hali bodie for-to seke</L>
<L>&THORN;at goddes voice ofe gon speke.</L>
<L N="475">Eufemiane spirid ate his men&yogh;e,</L>
<L>In his house if ani mighte be</L>
<L>&THORN;ate was so wele wi&thorn; Jesue</L>
<L>Als &thorn;e voise saide, of vertue.</L>
<L>And &thorn;ai answerde &amp; saide, naie,</L>
<L N="480">&THORN;at no swilk man knewe &thorn;ai,</L>
<L>Nou&thorn;er comand ne gangand</L>
<L>Ne in his palaise wonande.</L>
<L>As Eufemiane stode &thorn;us spereand,</L>
<L>So come &thorn;at ilk knaue rynnand</L>
<L N="485">&THORN;at had seruid Alexis,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;an was wente to heuene blisse.</L>
<L>"Sir, he saide, ite mai wele be</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;at ilk man es he</L>
<L>To &yogh;eme &thorn;at &yogh;e betaghte to me,</L>
<L N="490">&THORN;at &yogh;e gaue mete par charite.</L>
<L>I haue him sene grete penaunce do</L>
<L>And lede his life in mikil vnro:</L>
<L>I trowe forsothe &thorn;at ite is he,</L>
<L>For he was hali, als think me.</L>
<L N="495">Full lange hase he sekenes dried</L>
<L>And to daie ate morne he died".</L>
<L>When Eufemiane herd &thorn;is tithand,</L>
<L>Na langere mighte he &thorn;are still stand</L>
<L>Bote als a man &thorn;at ware wode</L>
<L N="500">To Alexis bedde he &yogh;ode,</L>
<L>And saide: "&thorn;ou man, par charite,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;i grase &thorn;ou tell me &mdash;</L>
<L>For i hald me no&yogh;te worthi</L>
<L>For to touche &thorn;i hali bodie &mdash;</L>
<L N="505">No&yogh;te-for&thorn;i i praie to the</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou &thorn;i gudenes schewe to me:</L>
<L>Saie me, for &thorn;e lufe of sainte Jame,</L>
<L>Wheyne &thorn;ou come, whate es thi name?"</L>
<L>&THORN;us he callid wondir offte</L>
<L N="510">Bothe wi&thorn; hye wordis (and) sofft.<NOTE PLACE="foot">and fehlt im Ms.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bote worde ofe him mighte he (gete) nane,<NOTE PLACE="foot">gete fehlt im Ms.</NOTE></L>
<L>For he was dede als a stane.</L>
<L>&amp; Eufemiane wele tho&yogh;t</L>
<L>&THORN;at Alexis answere wald no&yogh;te:</L>
<L N="515">&THORN;an ner he come &amp; did awaie</L>
<L>&THORN;e pure clathis &thorn;ate on him laie,
<PB REF="00000324.tif" N="186"></L>
<L>And Alexis &thorn;are he fande</L>
<L>Still, callde, dede liggande.</L>
<L>And swilk a smell als he &thorn;are smellid</L>
<L N="520">Neuer nane before he fellid &mdash;</L>
<L>For all &thorn;e spice &thorn;ate es in Spaine,</L>
<L>And all &thorn;e floures in grete Almaine</L>
<L>Gaue neuer sauoure halfe so swete</L>
<L>Als was ofe him, fra toppe to fete.</L>
<L N="525">In haire and brinie was he cledde,</L>
<L>Ofe smale stanes was his bedde,</L>
<L>Vndir his heuede laie a stane &mdash;</L>
<L>Soffter &thorn;inge &thorn;an was &thorn;are nane.</L>
<L>In his hand was a boke,</L>
<L N="530">Bote whate ite was, mighte na-man loke.</L>
<L>&THORN;an &yogh;ode Eufemiane in hye</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e pape &amp; his clergie</L>
<L>And talde &thorn;e pape als he fand,</L>
<L>And of &thorn;e boke in his hand.</L>
<L N="535">When &thorn;e pape herd &thorn;is ferlie,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; him he toke all his clergie,</L>
<L>And come full sone to &thorn;ate bodie</L>
<L>And stode and askid ite mercie:</L>
<L>"Lorde, he saide, &thorn;ou schew me</L>
<L N="540">&THORN;e mikil vertue &thorn;at es in &thorn;e,</L>
<L>&THORN;at we mai loue god ofe heuene</L>
<L>&THORN;at wissid vs to &thorn;e &thorn;orghe his steuene</L>
<L>And schewe vs here &thorn;is ilk lettire,</L>
<L>&THORN;at we maie all be &thorn;e better</L>
<L N="545">And to knawe &thorn;i halines</L>
<L>And &thorn;e vertue &thorn;ate in &thorn;e es".</L>
<L>When he had made his orisoune,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; drede ofe herte he stoupid doune:</L>
<L>And toke &thorn;e lettire oute of his hande,</L>
<L N="550">&amp; grete ferlie &thorn;are-in he fande.</L>
<L>He gaue ite a clerke, &thorn;at stode him nere,</L>
<L>And bad him rede, &thorn;ate all mi&yogh;t here.</L>
<L>&THORN;e clerk began ite for-to rede,</L>
<L>And Eufemiane began to wede</L>
<L N="555">When he &thorn;ate lettir vndirstode;</L>
<L>For sorow all-moste he wex wode,</L>
<L>For he beganne to grete &amp; crie</L>
<L>&amp; fell apon &thorn;ate dede bodie.</L>
<L>&THORN;e mikil sorow &amp; &thorn;e care</L>
<L N="560">&THORN;at Eufemiane makid &thorn;are</L>
<L>May naman tell be &thorn;e haluendele,
<PB REF="00000325.tif" N="187"></L>
<L>Thofe his tonge ware made ofe stele.</L>
<L>When Aglaes, his wife, herde &thorn;is</L>
<L>&THORN;at he was hir sonne Alexis</L>
<L N="565">&THORN;at in bed dede laie &thorn;are,</L>
<L>Scho beganne to roupe &amp; rare,</L>
<L>And ofe hir heued scho drewe &thorn;e hare,</L>
<L>For had scho neuer so mikil care.</L>
<L>His wife kome &thorn;an wi&thorn; sorowfull late,</L>
<L N="570">Wi&thorn; goulinge, &amp; wi&thorn; rewfull grate,</L>
<L>Als scho wald all to watir writhe &mdash;</L>
<L>So was scho sarie &amp; vnblithe.</L>
<L>Will i of &thorn;is na langer spelle,</L>
<L>Bote forthe oure storie wil i tell.</L>
<L N="575">When &thorn;is folk sawe &thorn;is ferlie,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai loued god all-mightie.</L>
<L>And &thorn;e pape and his clergie</L>
<L>To &thorn;e <I>cors</I> &yogh;ede full dereworthelie<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. pape st. cors.</NOTE></L>
<L>And wande ite in full riche folde,</L>
<L N="580">&THORN;at brighte schane als duse &thorn;e golde.</L>
<L>To &thorn;e kirk &thorn;ai wald him bere;</L>
<L>Bote mighte naman &thorn;e corse stere</L>
<L>For prees of man &thorn;ate was so strange,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. man st. men.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at nane mighte stere for mikil thrange:</L>
<L N="585">For seke men &thorn;at had vnhele</L>
<L>And dombe men &thorn;at mi&yogh;te no&yogh;te mele,</L>
<L>Deefe men &thorn;at mi&yogh;te no&yogh;te here</L>
<L>And halte men &thorn;at mi&yogh;te no&yogh;te stere,</L>
<L>Blind men &thorn;at wantid sight,</L>
<L N="590">Mesele men &thorn;at had no mighte:</L>
<L>All ware &thorn;ai made hale &amp; fere,</L>
<L>Als swithe als &thorn;ai neghid &thorn;e bere</L>
<L>&THORN;are sainte Alexe corse was loken,</L>
<L>For whaim &thorn;e steuen before had spoken.</L>
<L N="595">For-thi was &thorn;are swilk prees &amp; thrange,</L>
<L>&THORN;at nane mighte gete gate to gange.</L>
<L>&THORN;e wise men of Rome &thorn;e whiles</L>
<L>Vmbe-tho&yogh;te &thorn;aim ofe wyles,</L>
<L>How &thorn;ai mighte breke &thorn;ate grete thrange,</L>
<L N="600">To gete &thorn;aim gate for to gange:</L>
<L>&THORN;ai strewid penyes in &thorn;e strete</L>
<L>To ger &thorn;e pure luke to &thorn;aire fete;</L>
<L>&THORN;e riche gatte &thorn;aim gate before,</L>
<L>&THORN;e whilis &thorn;ai gadird penyes &thorn;ore.</L>
<L N="605">Bote for all &thorn;is vnne&thorn;es mighte &thorn;ai</L>
<L>Wynne to &thorn;e kirk &thorn;at ilk daie.
<PB REF="00000326.tif" N="188"></L>
<L>&THORN;e kirk es ofe sainte Bonifase</L>
<L>Whare &thorn;ai layde goddes grase.</L>
<L>Seuene daies &thorn;an woke &thorn;ai &thorn;are,</L>
<L N="610">Wi&thorn; mikil welthe &amp; mikil fare,</L>
<L>And wro&yogh;t &thorn;are a riche schrine</L>
<L>And laide Alexis corse &thorn;are-ine.</L>
<L>Whare euermare, till &thorn;is werld standes,</L>
<L>Er all sekemen lousid of bandes;</L>
<L N="615">&THORN;are wirkis god for Alexis,</L>
<L>For to him full dere he is.</L>
<L>Oure lorde bringe vs to &thorn;at blisse</L>
<L>And late vs neuer of &thorn;at ioye misse,</L>
<L>&THORN;are sainte Alexis for his mekenes</L>
<L N="620">Full nere god in heuene es.</L>
<L>Oure lorde, Jhesu Criste, vs spede</L>
<L>To do penaunce, &amp; &thorn;idir vs lede. Amen.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Now haue i bro&yogh;te &thorn;is tale till ende,</L>
<L>I rede &thorn;ate we oure life amende</L>
<L N="625">And praie god &thorn;at he vs mekenes send</L>
<L>And vs fra pride ofe hertte defende.</L>
<L>For all &thorn;is lange tale i haue talde</L>
<L>To ger &yogh;ow in &yogh;oure hertes halde</L>
<L>&THORN;e mekenes of sainte Alexis,</L>
<L N="630">To ger &yogh;ow se whate meknes is.</L>
<L>For mekenes es &thorn;e beste thewe</L>
<L>&THORN;at ani man in dede maie schewe.</L>
<L>For &thorn;is mekenes, ofe whilk i mene,</L>
<L>Gerte Marie be modir and qwene:</L>
<L N="635">Goddes modir, &amp; qwene of heuene;</L>
<L>Forthi full blissefull es scho to neuene,</L>
<L>Als scho hir-selfe saise in a sange.</L>
<L>Full wele es &thorn;aim hir lufe mai fange</L>
<L>And in mekenes folowe hir trace.</L>
<L N="640">For god giues meke men his grace</L>
<L>And geris &thorn;aim come to &thorn;at blisse</L>
<L>&THORN;at to all mekemen graithid is.</L>
<L>Oure lorde of heuene &thorn;idir vs bringe,</L>
<L>&THORN;are euer es ioye wi&thorn;-outen gretinge,</L>
<L N="645">And leue vs so oure liue to lede</L>
<L>&THORN;at we mai all haue heuene to mede!</L>
<TRAILER>Amen.
</TRAILER>

</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="version"><PB REF="00000312.tif" N="174">
<HEAD>b) aus Ms. Gg. V, 31.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>In Rome was ones a ryche mane,</L>
<L>Hys name was haten Eufemyan;</L>
<L>Hys wyf was called Aglas,</L>
<L>&THORN;at a gud woman was.</L>
<L N="5">Riche &thorn;ai war of gold and fe,</L>
<L>And he was senetour of &thorn;at cete.</L>
<L>He had seruandys thre thousand</L>
<L>&THORN;at serued hym in &thorn;at land.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai war in sylk &amp; sendell clede;</L>
<L N="10">In mekell onour &thorn;aire lyf &thorn;ai lede.</L>
<L>So gude and almus gerne &thorn;ai war</L>
<L>In all &thorn;aire welth and ryche fare,</L>
<L>&THORN;at in &thorn;aire hall stode ay redy</L>
<L>Thre bordys sperde menskfully:</L>
<L N="15">On to pylgrymes for to fede,</L>
<L>An-o&thorn;er to pouer &thorn;at had nede,</L>
<L>&THORN;e thredde tyll faderles barnes</L>
<L>&THORN;at helpe of fader &amp; moder tharnes;
<PB REF="00000313.tif" N="175"></L>
<L>&THORN;ai war almus-gern ynoghe</L>
<L N="20">And ay tyll gud &thorn;ewes drowhe.</L>
<L>Of werldes gud had &thorn;ai gud wane,</L>
<L>Bot chylde bytwen &thorn;aim had &thorn;ai nane.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai prayd god of hys mercy</L>
<L>To send &thorn;aim chyld of &thorn;aire body.</L>
<L N="25">God sent &thorn;am sone a knaf-chyld,</L>
<L>&THORN;at was to god meke and mylde.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai crysten hym wi&thorn; ioy and blys</L>
<L>And named hym Alixis.</L>
<L>&THORN;is chyld wex and wel thraf,</L>
<L N="30">And mekyll grace god hym gaf.</L>
<L>Hys fader sett hym sone to boke,</L>
<L>And wel to clergy he toke,</L>
<L>And euer he lofed inwardly</L>
<L>Bokes &thorn;at spak of god almyghty. &mdash;</L>
<L N="35">Efter, when he come tyll elde,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; mekell mensk and wi&thorn; belde,</L>
<L>Hys fader hym gert a wyf spous</L>
<L>And broght hyr home vntill hys hous:</L>
<L>Sho was of &thorn;e Emperour kynde,</L>
<L N="40">Als we may in story wreten fynd;</L>
<L>Meke and mylde scho was ynowhe</L>
<L>And ay tyll thewes gude drowhe.</L>
<L>At &thorn;aire brydale was mekyll fare,
<PB REF="00000314.tif" N="176"></L>
<L>And rych gyftes gyfen thare;</L>
<L N="45">&THORN;are was myrth maken(!) and gle,<NOTE PLACE="foot">myrth a. R. nebengeschr.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of all ryches grete plente,</L>
<L>&THORN;are was almus and ioye ynoghe,</L>
<L>And sythen ilk man home drowhe.</L>
<L>When &thorn;is bryd-gome suld go to bed,</L>
<L N="50">&THORN;at rychely wi&thorn; pal was spred &mdash;</L>
<L>Gladly was &thorn;e chambre graythett</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; ryche cle&thorn;es, in flor layd:</L>
<L>He graythed hym on all manere</L>
<L>Als he suld lyg by hys fere.</L>
<L N="55">&THORN;o wheder he ne wald noght:<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;o st. &thorn;e.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ane o&thorn;er thyng was in hys thoght.</L>
<L>When all ware owt of chaumer gane<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. ch&amacr;mer.</NOTE></L>
<L>Saf he and hys wyf al-ane,</L>
<L>He preched hyr of mayden-hede</L>
<L N="60">And als-so of &thorn;at mekel mede</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ai sall haue &thorn;at &yogh;emes here</L>
<L>&THORN;aire maydenhed on gud manere &mdash;</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;-owt any pryue pryde<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. pryue pryue.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at many women wyll kyde</L>
<L N="65">In &thorn;aire hert for &thorn;aire maydenhede:</L>
<L>&THORN;at gerrs &thorn;am lathly tyne &thorn;aire mede:</L>
<L>For who so dos gud dede in ros,</L>
<L>He tines all &thorn;at euer he dos. &mdash;</L>
<L>When he had sayd &thorn;us what he walde,</L>
<L N="70">Hys Jeweles he gaf hyr tyll halde</L>
<L>And sythen he gaf hyr a rynge,</L>
<L>Bytwene &thorn;aim to be toknynge.</L>
<L>He sayd: "wyf, I wyll my erand(!),</L>
<L>Bot I wate neuer in-tyll what land".</L>
<L N="75">Scho sayd: "syr, at &yogh;our wyll yt be.</L>
<L>God bryng &yogh;ow sone agayne to me!"</L>
<L>He toke wi&thorn; hym gold plente</L>
<L>And went hym forth full priuele.
<PB REF="00000315.tif" N="177"></L>
<L>God puruayd wele hys farynge:</L>
<L N="80">And sone he fand redy schyppynge.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai had gud wynd and forth &thorn;ai went,</L>
<L>Tyll far contre was &thorn;aire entent.</L>
<L>And when he come &thorn;are on lande,</L>
<L>Cetes and to&umacr;nes full fayr he fande.</L>
<L N="85">In-tyll a cete sone he &yogh;ede</L>
<L>And changed all hys rich wed</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; a begger, and sythen hym clede</L>
<L>In begger wede, and fast he flede &mdash;</L>
<L>For he wa(l)d &thorn;at noman wyste</L>
<L N="90">&THORN;at he wald lyf in honger &amp; thryste.</L>
<L>Seuynten wynter &thorn;are woned he</L>
<L>In begger lyf and pouerte;</L>
<L>In grete myschef he led hys lyfe,</L>
<L>And gude bedys were hym full ryfe;</L>
<L N="95">Wi&thorn; hayre and breny he hym cled,</L>
<L>And on &thorn;e bare erthe he made hys bede,</L>
<L>Brede and water was hys lyflade,</L>
<L>And tyll god hys prayers made</L>
<L>&THORN;at non sall wit what he was<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. w<SUP>t</SUP> = wit.</NOTE></L>
<L N="100">By-fore &thorn;e soule fro hym suld passe. &mdash;</L>
<L>And when hys fader hys sonne myste,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he was gone wytterly wyste,</L>
<L>He gret and made full yuell chere,</L>
<L>And hys wyf als sore in-fere.</L>
<L N="105">&THORN;ai gert hym seke fer and nere</L>
<L>Full wyde-ware, on all manere,</L>
<L>To seke &thorn;aire sone Alixis</L>
<L>And brying hym home maugre hys.</L>
<L>&THORN;is messangers went spyand</L>
<L N="110">Fro toune to toun, fro lande to lande,</L>
<L>Bot fande &thorn;ai nane &thorn;at couth &thorn;aim wyse</L>
<L>Vntyll &thorn;aire maister Alixis.</L>
<L>Two messangers come &thorn;are he was,</L>
<L>In a toun als &thorn;ai gan pas,</L>
<L N="115">Syttand omang pouere men;</L>
<L>Bot couth &thorn;ai no-gates hym ken:</L>
<L>For hard penance and hunger and nede</L>
<L>Was changed al hys fayred;</L>
<L>Full ragged and reuen was hys clathes,</L>
<L N="120">And full of vermen, &thorn;at many lathes:</L>
<L>For-thy couth &thorn;ai noght hym knawe,</L>
<L>&THORN;are he wi&thorn; beggers sate on rawe.
<PB REF="00000316.tif" N="178"></L>
<L>&THORN;ai gaf almus to &thorn;am al</L>
<L>And bad, til god &thorn;at &thorn;ai suld cal</L>
<L N="125">&THORN;at &thorn;ai suld fare wele in &thorn;aire nede</L>
<L>And of &thorn;aire erand &thorn;ai suld wele spede.</L>
<L>Alixis knewe &thorn;aim full wele,</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;ai knew him neuer a dele.</L>
<L>"Lorde, he sayd, I thank the,</L>
<L N="130">&THORN;are &thorn;ou sittes in thy trinite,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ow &thorn;is day has gyfen me grace</L>
<L>Amus to take in &thorn;is place<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. amus st. almus.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of &thorn;am &thorn;at wont war to be</L>
<L>Myn owen men and serued me."</L>
<L N="135">&THORN;ire mensangers come home agayne,</L>
<L>&THORN;at made Eufemyam vn-fayn</L>
<L>For &thorn;ai say: "ser, we haf fer soghte</L>
<L>To seke Alixis, bot we herd noghte."</L>
<L>Hys fader Eufemiane was ful wa,</L>
<L N="140">And so was hys moder al-swa.
<PB REF="00000317.tif" N="179"></L>
<L>Hys wyf sayd: scho suld neuer mare</L>
<L>Make ioye, bot euer care,</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; Eufemyane dwell</L>
<L>Tyll scho herd of hyr husband spell:</L>
<L N="145">"For o&thorn;ere man &thorn;en Alixis</L>
<L>Sal I neuer hals ne kys,</L>
<L>For neuer-more in my lyue</L>
<L>Sal o&thorn;ere man mak me wyfe." &mdash;</L>
<L>Turne we now tyl Alixis</L>
<L N="150">&THORN;at left for god &thorn;is werldys blys.</L>
<L>He lyfed in herd fastynge,</L>
<L>In prayers and in wakynge.</L>
<L>Edissa hyght &thorn;at ilk cete</L>
<L>&THORN;are he leued in pouerte.</L>
<L N="155">At a kynges &yogh;ate he sate</L>
<L>And lyued wi&thorn; almus &thorn;at he gate.</L>
<L>Apon a day, als he sate &thorn;are,</L>
<L>Prayd he god wi&thorn; myld fare</L>
<L>Byfore an ymage of oure lady.</L>
<L N="160">&THORN;e ymage answerd selcouthly:</L>
<L>"Well, Alixis, moght &thorn;ou be!</L>
<L>&THORN;i gude prayers payes me."</L>
<L>And ane o&thorn;er tyme scho apered than</L>
<L>In &thorn;e kyrk tyl an old man.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Nach 164 fehlen deutlich einige Verse.</NOTE></L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L N="165">
<PB REF="00000318.tif" N="180">Many pouere men he saw,</L>
<L>Bot nan of &thorn;am couth he knawe.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. man st. nan.</NOTE></L>
<L>He come rymand(!) in for-thy<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. rymand, wie 351.</NOTE></L>
<L>And prayed oure lady inwardly,</L>
<L>He sayd: "lady, wys &thorn;ow me</L>
<L N="170">Tyll hym, yf &thorn;i wyll be!"</L>
<L>&THORN;e ymage sayd: "&thorn;ow sall hym ken"</L>
<L>And told hym a taken &thorn;en.</L>
<L>And he &thorn;an forth, and tald ryght<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. &thorn;an st. ran?</NOTE></L>
<L>Als &thorn;e ymage had hym hyght.</L>
<L N="175">On knes he fell at hys fete</L>
<L>And full sore bygan to grete</L>
<L>And sayd: "syr, I pray the,</L>
<L>&THORN;ow come in-tyll &thorn;e kyrk wi&thorn; me!</L>
<L>For god, &thorn;at ys of moste pouste,</L>
<L N="180">Tyll hys seruand has chosen &thorn;e."</L>
<L>When Alixis herd &thorn;is sawe,</L>
<L>He sighed and helde hys heued lawe,</L>
<L>For hys gudnes he wald war hyd</L>
<L>And lathe hym war yt war kyd.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. war st. was.</NOTE></L>
<L N="185">And for-&thorn;i wi&thorn; hym he &yogh;ede,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. And st. No&yogh;t.</NOTE></L>
<L>And tyll &thorn;e kyrk he gan hym lede.</L>
<L>&THORN;e folk herd of hys wordys swete<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. hys st. &THORN;is.</NOTE></L>
<L>And fell by-for Alixis fete,</L>
<L>In rych cete &thorn;ai hym sett</L>
<L N="190">And wi&thorn; fayr wordys hym gret.</L>
<L>Alixis &thorn;are-of was ill payd</L>
<L>And tyll hym-self &thorn;us he sayd:</L>
<L>"&THORN;ou &thorn;at made all thyng Iwys,
<PB REF="00000319.tif" N="181"></L>
<L>&THORN;ow wayte wele what my wyl ys:</L>
<L N="195">Neuer worschyppe for-tyll haue,</L>
<L>Of man ne wyf, mayden ne knawe.</L>
<L>Owt of &thorn;is contre, lorde, bryng me</L>
<L>And send me grace of priuete!</L>
<L>&THORN;are ys no-thyng &thorn;at I hate mare</L>
<L N="200">&THORN;an to be mensked, or well fare."</L>
<L>Sone apon a merke nyghte</L>
<L>Owt of &thorn;at toune he fled, for syghte,</L>
<L>And come to &thorn;e cete of Leddys,</L>
<L>A nobil toun of marchandys.</L>
<L N="205">In-to &thorn;e se he schyppyd thare:</L>
<L>For in-tyll Aces he toght to fare,</L>
<L>To dwelle in saynt Powell kyrk</L>
<L>In pouert, goddys wyll to wyrk.</L>
<L>Bot god turned &thorn;e wynd by-lyue</L>
<L N="210">And in Rome made &thorn;aim to ryue.</L>
<L>And when Alixis come to land,</L>
<L>Hys fader he mete to(!) kyrk comand.</L>
<L>And fayr he gan hys fader grete</L>
<L>And sayd tyll hym wi&thorn; wordys swete:</L>
<L N="215">"Lord, of me &thorn;ou haf mercy,</L>
<L>A pouer nedfull man am I;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou gyf me mete pur charite</L>
<L>Of relyf &thorn;at leues byfor &thorn;e!</L>
<L>For if &thorn;ou lofed euer any-ane</L>
<L N="220">&THORN;at in pylgrimage ys gane,</L>
<L>And(!) I sall pray wi&thorn; myght &amp; mayn<NOTE PLACE="foot">And ist zu tilgen.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at god sal send hym &thorn;e agayne,</L>
<L>In forward &thorn;at &thorn;ou do me gude</L>
<L>And helpe me tyll my lyues fode."</L>
<L N="225">Styll stode Eufemyan,</L>
<L>To lythe and lyste &thorn;e pouer man;</L>
<L>On Alixis, hys son, he thoghte,</L>
<L>&THORN;at hym nere-hand to ded had broghte.</L>
<L>For-&thorn;i bygan he to wepe sare</L>
<L N="230">And wyped hys e&yogh;en wi&thorn; mekel care.</L>
<L>He sayd: "man, for my son sake</L>
<L>In-to my hows I wyll &thorn;e take</L>
<L>And euer-more &thorn;e clethe and fede</L>
<L>And fynd &thorn;e all &thorn;at &thorn;e ys nede."
<PB REF="00000320.tif" N="182"></L>
<L N="235">"Now god, &thorn;at ys in trinite,</L>
<L>Syr, he sayd, for&yogh;elde yt the!"</L>
<L>Home wi&thorn; hym he hym lede,</L>
<L>And in hys hows made hym a bede</L>
<L>In a chambyr by hym ane,</L>
<L N="240">&THORN;ar-tyll a kaye he gan hym tane,</L>
<L>To come and gang at hys wyll;</L>
<L>And bad hys men hys wyll fulfyll,</L>
<L>And comande &thorn;am wi&thorn; gude mode</L>
<L>&THORN;ai suld hym serue of lyfes fode.</L>
<L N="245">&THORN;us leued he &thorn;are wi&thorn; almus</L>
<L>In his owen fader hous</L>
<L>O&thorn;er wynters seuentene,</L>
<L>And sufferd paynes many and kene;</L>
<L>Hys penance changed all hys hewe,</L>
<L N="250">So &thorn;at none in werld hym knewe.</L>
<L>&THORN;e fend tyll hym was full wrath</L>
<L>And tyced men to do hym skath.</L>
<L>For wanton barnes of &thorn;e hous,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ar war fed wi&thorn; almus,</L>
<L>Come tyll hym by nyghter tale</L>
<L N="255">For to skorne and do hym bale:</L>
<L>Some wald pul hym by &thorn;e berde,</L>
<L>For to make hym for &thorn;am aferde,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai kest on hym disch-waschyngs</L>
<L>And dyd hym many o&thorn;er thyngs,</L>
<L N="260">Some kest at hym stone and clotte,</L>
<L>Some playd wi&thorn; hym sitt-fotte(!).<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. sitt fotte; Ms. Ashm. hat die richtige Lesart.</NOTE></L>
<L>And all tholed he wi&thorn; glad wyll,</L>
<L>Goddys wyll &amp; byddyng to fulfyll;</L>
<L>He forgaf &thorn;aim all &thorn;aire lathe</L>
<L N="265">And prayd for &thorn;aim &thorn;at dyd hym skathe. &mdash;</L>
<L>Tholmodnes here may &yogh;e lere,</L>
<L>&THORN;at lykes &thorn;is tale forto here;</L>
<L>For &thorn;at ys rote of all gudnes,</L>
<L>Fayr speche and meknes. &mdash;</L>
<L N="270">Sone &thorn;ar-efter sente god a sande</L>
<L>&THORN;at broght Alixis gud tyth(a)nde:</L>
<L>A angell bad hym make hym &yogh;are,
<PB REF="00000321.tif" N="183"></L>
<L>Owt of &thorn;is werld suld he fare.</L>
<L>He thanked god &thorn;an inwardly</L>
<L N="275">Of hys grace and hys mercy;</L>
<L>&THORN;an he called tyll hym hys knawe</L>
<L>And sayd: "lef sone, &thorn;ow ger me haue</L>
<L>Parchamyn an ynk bath!"</L>
<L>And he broght tyll hym rath.</L>
<L N="280">&THORN;an all hys lyf &thorn;are wrate he,</L>
<L>When he war ded, at &thorn;ai myght se,</L>
<L>Whas sone he was, and what he hyght;</L>
<L>And all hys lyf he wrate ryght:</L>
<L>In grete pouert in stedys sere</L>
<L N="285">Had he leued foure and thretty &yogh;ere,</L>
<L>And how he fro hys wyf went</L>
<L>And all &thorn;e stede he in lente,</L>
<L>And how he gaf hys gold ryng</L>
<L>Tyll hys wyf at hys partyng.</L>
<L N="290">When he had made all &thorn;is wrytt,</L>
<L>Fast in hys hand he lowked yt.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; hard seknes &thorn;an was he stede</L>
<L>And layd hym doun apon hys bed.</L>
<L>And euen on palme-sononday,</L>
<L N="295">When folk in kyrk bygan to pray:</L>
<L>A voyce was in &thorn;e mynster herde</L>
<L>&THORN;at made all &thorn;e folk full ferde:</L>
<L>&THORN;e voyce sayd: "come al to me</L>
<L>&THORN;at suffers payne and pouerte!</L>
<L N="300">For I sall qwyte wi&thorn;-owt fayle</L>
<L>&YOGH;oure lang tene and &yogh;our trayuayll."</L>
<L>&THORN;e fell of knes(!) fell full thrang,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. &THORN;e fell of knes st. &thorn;e folk on knes.</NOTE></L>
<L>And clerkys kyrieleyson sang.</L>
<L>&THORN;e voys &thorn;an spak eft-sones wi&thorn; cry</L>
<L N="305">And bad &thorn;am seke wytterly</L>
<L>Goddys seruand "&thorn;at ys full meke,</L>
<L>For in &thorn;is cete lygges he seke."
<PB REF="00000322.tif" N="184"></L>
<L>&THORN;e folk ran fast abowte and soght,</L>
<L>Bot Alixis fand &thorn;ai noght.</L>
<L N="310">Full gud and haly was he born:<NOTE PLACE="foot">gud and haly aus goddirhaile (to goder haile) verdorben.</NOTE></L>
<L>He dyed on gud-fryday at morn.</L>
<L>&THORN;e pape of Rome and clergy</L>
<L>&THORN;at day went to &thorn;e kyrke arely,</L>
<L>And so dyd two Emperoures,</L>
<L N="315">And lered folk, tyll here &thorn;aire oures.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai thoght wele a-pon &thorn;at steuen</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ai on palme-sononday herd euen.</L>
<L>&THORN;e pape gert &thorn;am pray all &thorn;an</L>
<L>&THORN;at god suld send &thorn;am &thorn;at man</L>
<L N="320">Of wham &thorn;e voys of heuen had spokyn,</L>
<L>And in what place &thorn;at he war lokyn.</L>
<L>&THORN;e folk dyd hys comandment</L>
<L>And prayd god wi&thorn; gud entent.</L>
<L>And als &thorn;e folk hertly gan pray,</L>
<L N="325">Son &thorn;ai herd a voys say:</L>
<L>"In Eufemyan hous he lyes,</L>
<L>&THORN;e haly body of Alixis."</L>
<L>&THORN;e folk full fayne war of &thorn;is</L>
<L>When &thorn;ai herd of Alixis &mdash;</L>
<L N="330">For hym &thorn;ai war wa in Rome</L>
<L>For thay ne wyst wyder he bycome.</L>
<L>&THORN;e pape &thorn;en asked Eufemyan</L>
<L>Why he layned goddys man.</L>
<L>He answerd and sayd nay</L>
<L N="335">He knew hym, by hys fay.<NOTE PLACE="foot">im Ms. fehlt noght.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e pape &yogh;ede wi&thorn; procession</L>
<L>Of lerd and lewed ryght &thorn;orow &thorn;e toun</L>
<L>And went tyll Eufemyan palays,
<PB REF="00000323.tif" N="185"></L>
<L>Als &thorn;e boke for-soth vs says,</L>
<L N="340">&THORN;at holy body for-to seke</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e voys befor of speke.</L>
<L>Eufemyan spered at hys meyne,</L>
<L>In hys hous if any myght be</L>
<L>&THORN;at was so wele wi&thorn; Jhesu</L>
<L N="345">Als &thorn;e voys sayd, of vertu.</L>
<L>And &thorn;ai answerd and sayd nay,</L>
<L>&THORN;at non swylk knew &thorn;ai,</L>
<L>Nowther comand ne gangand</L>
<L>Nor in hys palays non wonnand.</L>
<L N="350">Als Eufemyan stod sperand,</L>
<L>So come &thorn;at ilke knaw rymand<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. rymand.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at serued Alixis,</L>
<L>&THORN;at than was went tyll heuen blys.</L>
<L>"Syr, he sayd, &thorn;at may wele be</L>
<L N="355">&THORN;at &thorn;is ilk man ys he</L>
<L>To &yogh;eme &thorn;at &yogh;e bytaght me,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &yogh;e gaf mete par charyte.</L>
<L>I haf hym sene grete penance (do)<NOTE PLACE="foot">do fehlt.</NOTE></L>
<L>And led hys lyf in mykell vn-ro:</L>
<L N="360">I trow ryght wele &thorn;at yt ys he,</L>
<L>For he was holy, af thoght me.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. al st as.</NOTE></L>
<L>Full lang has he seknes dryed</L>
<L>And &thorn;is day at morne he dyed."</L>
<L>When Eufemyan had hard &thorn;is tythands,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. tythands st. tythande.</NOTE></L>
<L N="365">Moght he no langer styll stand</L>
<L>Bot als a man &thorn;at war wode</L>
<L>Tyll Alixis bed he &yogh;ede,</L>
<L>And sayd: "&thorn;ou man, par charite</L>
<L>Of &thorn;i grace &thorn;ou tell me &mdash;</L>
<L N="370">For I hald me noght worthy</L>
<L>For-to touch thy body:</L>
<L>Say me for luf of saynt Jame</L>
<L>Wethen &thorn;ou come, wat ys &thorn;i name?"</L>
<L>&THORN;us he called wonder oft</L>
<L N="375">Wi&thorn; hegh wordys and wi&thorn; soft.</L>
<L>Bot worde of hym gatte he nane,</L>
<L>For he was ded als a stane.</L>
<L>And when Eufemyan well thoght</L>
<L>&THORN;at Alixis answerd noght,</L>
<L N="380">Nere he come and dyd oway</L>
<L>&THORN;e pouer clo&thorn;es &thorn;at on hym lay,
<PB REF="00000324.tif" N="186"></L>
<L>And Alixis fone he fand</L>
<L>Cald, ded &thorn;are lyggand.</L>
<L>And swylk a smell als he &thorn;are smeld,</L>
<L N="385">Neuer &yogh;et none he feled &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;ar was neuer spice so swete</L>
<L>Als he smelled, fro top to fete.</L>
<L>In hayr was hys body cled,</L>
<L>Of small stones was his bede,</L>
<L N="390">Vnder hys heued lay a stane &mdash;</L>
<L>Softer thyng was &thorn;are nane.</L>
<L>In his hand was a boke,</L>
<L>Bot what was yt, myght noman luke.</L>
<L>&THORN;e pape come sone to &thorn;at body</L>
<L N="395">And stode and asked yt mercy:</L>
<L>"Lorde, sayd &thorn;e pope, &thorn;ow schew me</L>
<L>&THORN;e mekell vertu &thorn;at ys in &thorn;e,</L>
<L>And schew vs here &thorn;is ilk letter</L>
<L>&THORN;at we all may be &thorn;e better,</L>
<L N="400">&THORN;at we may knaw &thorn;i halynes</L>
<L>And &thorn;e vertu &thorn;at in &thorn;e es."</L>
<L>When he had made &thorn;is oryson,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; gretand chere he stoped doun:</L>
<L>And toke &thorn;e letter owt of hys hand,</L>
<L N="405">And grete ferly &thorn;are-on he fand.</L>
<L>He toke yt a clerk, &thorn;at stode hym nere,</L>
<L>And bad hym rede, &thorn;at &thorn;ai myght here.</L>
<L>&THORN;e clerk bygan for-to rede,</L>
<L>And Eufemyan bygan to wede</L>
<L N="410">When he &thorn;at letter understode;</L>
<L>For sorow almast wex he wode,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. wer st. wex.</NOTE></L>
<L>For he bygan to grete and cry</L>
<L>And fell a-pon &thorn;at ded body.</L>
<L>&THORN;e mekell sorow and &thorn;e care</L>
<L N="415">&THORN;at Eufemyan made &thorn;are</L>
<L>May noman tell halfondell,
<PB REF="00000325.tif" N="187"></L>
<L>&YOGH;of hys tong war made (of) stell.<NOTE PLACE="foot">of fehlt.</NOTE></L>
<L>When Aglas, hys wyf, herd &thorn;is</L>
<L>&THORN;at he was hyr son Alixis</L>
<L N="420">&THORN;at in bed ded lay thare,</L>
<L>Scho bygan to rope and rare.</L>
<L>Hys wyf come &thorn;an wi&thorn; sory late,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; crying and wi&thorn; sori grate &mdash;</L>
<L>No ferly &yogh;of scho war vn-blyth;</L>
<L N="425">Scho fore als scho to water wald wryth.</L>
<L>When &thorn;e folk saw &thorn;is ferly,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. sow od. saw?</NOTE></L>
<L>Faste &thorn;ai loued god almyghty.</L>
<L>&THORN;e pope wi&thorn; all hys clergy</L>
<L>Come tyll &thorn;e cors worthyly.</L>
<L N="430">Tyll &thorn;e kyrk &thorn;ai wald hym bere:</L>
<L>Bot myght &thorn;ai nogh &thorn;e cors stere</L>
<L>For prese of men &thorn;at was so strang,</L>
<L>&THORN;at noman myght for o&thorn;er gang:</L>
<L>For seke men &thorn;at had vnhele,</L>
<L N="435">For dom men &thorn;at myght noght mele,</L>
<L>For def men &thorn;at myght noght here,</L>
<L>And alt men &thorn;at myght (noght) stere,<NOTE PLACE="foot">noght fehlt.</NOTE></L>
<L>And blynd men &thorn;at had no syght,</L>
<L>And mesell men &thorn;at wanted myght,</L>
<L N="440">All war &thorn;ai made hall in-fere,</L>
<L>Als swythe als &thorn;ai neghed &thorn;e bere</L>
<L>&THORN;are saynt Alixis cors was loken,</L>
<L>For wham &thorn;e steuen of god had spokyn.</L>
<L>For-thy was &thorn;ar swylk prese and thrange.</L>
<L N="445">&THORN;at nane myght get gate to gange.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai streued penys in &thorn;e strete,</L>
<L>To ger pouer lok tyll &thorn;air fete.</L>
<L>And &yogh;et vnneys myght &thorn;ai</L>
<L>Wyn to &thorn;e kyrk for pres &thorn;at day.
<PB REF="00000326.tif" N="188"></L>
<L>&THORN;e kirk es ofe sainte Bonifase</L>
<L>Whare &thorn;ai layde goddes grase.</L>
<L>Seuene daies &thorn;an woke &thorn;ai &thorn;are,</L>
<L N="610">Wi&thorn; mikil welthe &amp; mikil fare,</L>
<L>And wro&yogh;t &thorn;are a riche schrine</L>
<L>And laide Alexis corse &thorn;are-ine.</L>
<L>Whare euermare, till &thorn;is werld standes,</L>
<L>Er all sekemen lousid of bandes;</L>
<L N="615">&THORN;are wirkis god for Alexis,</L>
<L>For to him full dere he is.</L>
<L>Oure lorde bringe vs to &thorn;at blisse</L>
<L>And late vs neuer of &thorn;at ioye misse,</L>
<L>&THORN;are sainte Alexis for his mekenes</L>
<L N="620">Full nere god in heuene es.</L>
<L>Oure lorde, Jhesu Criste, vs spede</L>
<L>To do penaunce, &amp; &thorn;idir vs lede. Amen.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Now haue i bro&yogh;te &thorn;is tale till ende,</L>
<L>I rede &thorn;ate we oure life amende</L>
<L N="625">And praie god &thorn;at he vs mekenes send</L>
<L>And vs fra pride ofe hertte defende.</L>
<L>For all &thorn;is lange tale i haue talde</L>
<L>To ger &yogh;ow in &yogh;oure hertes halde</L>
<L>&THORN;e mekenes of sainte Alexis,</L>
<L N="630">To ger &yogh;ow se whate meknes is.</L>
<L>For mekenes es &thorn;e beste thewe</L>
<L>&THORN;at ani man in dede maie schewe.</L>
<L>For &thorn;is mekenes, ofe whilk i mene,</L>
<L>Gerte Marie be modir and qwene:</L>
<L N="635">Goddes modir, &amp; qwene of heuene;</L>
<L>Forthi full blissefull es scho to neuene,</L>
<L>Als scho hir-selfe saise in a sange.</L>
<L>Full wele es &thorn;aim hir lufe mai fange</L>
<L>And in mekenes folowe hir trace.</L>
<L N="640">For god giues meke men his grace</L>
<L>And geris &thorn;aim come to &thorn;at blisse</L>
<L>&THORN;at to all mekemen graithid is.</L>
<L>Oure lorde of heuene &thorn;idir vs bringe,</L>
<L>&THORN;are euer es ioye wi&thorn;-outen gretinge,</L>
<L N="645">And leue vs so oure liue to lede</L>
<L>&THORN;at we mai all haue heuene to mede!</L>
<TRAILER>Amen.</TRAILER>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="450">&THORN;e kyrk ys of seynt Bonefas</L>
<L>&THORN;are &thorn;ay layd hym wi&thorn; goddys grace.</L>
<L>Seuen dayes woke &thorn;ai &thorn;are,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; mekell welth and mekel fare,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai wroght &thorn;are a ryche shryne</L>
<L N="455">And layd Alixis cors &thorn;are-ynne.</L>
<L>&THORN;ar wyrches god meraclys manyfolde</L>
<L>And louses of band &yogh;onge and holde.</L>
<L>Now haf I broght &thorn;is tale to ende,</L>
<L>I rede &thorn;at we our lyfes amende</L>
<L N="460">And thynk of &thorn;e meknes of Alixis:</L>
<L>&THORN;an may we be sekyr of blys.</L>
<L>For meknes ys &thorn;e best thew</L>
<L>&THORN;at any man in ded may schew.</L>
<L>For &thorn;is meknes &thorn;at I of mene</L>
<L N="465">Ger(t) Mary be moder, of heuen qwene,</L>
<L>Als-so hyr-self says in a sang &mdash;</L>
<L>Full wele ys &thorn;am hyr luf may fang.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai may be seker of heuen mede &mdash;</L>
<L>Oure lord vs blys and &thorn;eder vs lede.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="legend"><PB REF="00000327.tif" N="189">
<HEAD>Aus Barbour's Legendensammlung, St. Machor, al. Moris.
Ms. Cbr. Gg. II, 6, fol. 190b. (Schottischer Dialect, Mundart von Aberdeen).</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>Aus der zweiten n&ouml;rdlichen Legendensammlung, der des schottischen National|dichters Barbour (von ihm noch im hohen Alter, gr&ouml;sstentheils nach der Legenda Aurea gedichtet), theile ich hier vorl&auml;ufig das wichtigste St&uuml;ck mit: die Legende von Machor oder Moris, welche, da eine lateinische vita dieses Heiligen bis jetzt nicht aufgefunden ist, selbst die Stelle der Quelle vertritt. Die Zeit dieses Heiligen, der als Kind Mocumba (oder Mocumma) hiess, von seinem Lehrer Colman den Namen Machor empfing (vgl. v. 475), endlich vom Pabst bei seiner Ernenunng zum Bischof von Aberdeen Moris genannt wurde (vgl. v. 1465), sowie seines Lehrers S. Colman und seines Zeitgenossen S. Devenick, des Apostels von Cathnes (seine Be|gegnung mit Machor s. v. 819 ff., sein Tod v. 1339 ff), ist in Dunkel geh&uuml;llt<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Die schott. Annalisten setzen den Tod Dewenicks um 887, in die Regierung des Soluathius (Selvach); aber die K&ouml;nige dieses Stammes lebten im 8. Jahrh. Wahrscheinlich geh&ouml;ren diese Heiligen ins 6. Jahrh.; vgl. A Dictionary of christian biography, litterature, sects and doctrines ed. by Will. Smith and Henry Wace, London 1877, vol. I A &mdash; D (s. v. Devenick), wo als H&uuml;lfs|mittel aufgef&uuml;hrt sind: Forbes Kalend. of Scott. Saints, Boethius Scott. Hist. B. IX, Dempster Hist. Eccles. Gent. Scot. I, Camerarius De Scot. Fort., King Calendar.; ausserdem Breviarium Aberdon.</NOTE>). Die einzige Hs., Ms. Cbr. Gg. II, 6, c. 1450, von verschiedenen H&auml;nden ge|schrieben, ist &uuml;beraus schwer lesbar. In Machor fehlt leider ein Blatt nach v. 1014 zu 81 Versen. Bei v. 828 tritt eine andere Hand ein, vielleicht dieselbe welche den Anfang des Ms. geschrieben; die Fortsetzung scheint erst sp&auml;ter nachgetragen, nach einer Notiz am Rande: Caret de fine sce Mauchcarii et de sca Katerina. Die Aufl&ouml;sung der zahlreichen Abk&uuml;rzungen des Ms. ist nach der sonstigen Schreib|weise des Ms. zu regeln. Das sonst <I>er</I> bezeichnende H&auml;kchen <GAP> kann durch <I>er</I> und <I>ir yr</I> (<I>ire yre</I>) und <I>r</I> wiedergegeben werden, bezeichnet aber in M<GAP>tine, &thorn;<GAP> u. q<GAP> <I>ar</I> (q<GAP> = quar oder quhare), h<GAP> ist hir oder hyr hyre. Obengeschriebenes t vertritt sowohl die schottische Schreibung cht in nicht, nocht, als auch th in blyth swyth, endlich auch die Endung it yt in louit 87, sperit 505, 585. Der Strich &uuml;ber den Vokalen, wie in n&amacr;, m&amacr;, bedeutet <I>me</I> oder <I>ne</I>; <GAP> ist <I>ne</I>; oft findet sich <GAP> und Strich zusammen: da ist wohl nur durch <I>e</I> aufzu|l&ouml;sen (vielleicht ist aber so<GAP> durch sovne zu geben). able mit Schleife ist abile. p mit durchgezogenem Strich kann par (z. B. in parel = peril), per und por (in temporale) bezeichnen.</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For &thorn;at oyse is generale<MILESTONE N="190b" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="foot1">oyse = use.</NOTE></L>
<L>In haly kyrk vniuersale:</L>
<L>In worschipe of god &amp; lowing</L>
<L>Of halowis to say &amp; syng</L>
<L N="5">&THORN;e farleis &thorn;at in &thorn;ame were<NOTE PLACE="foot1">till = quhill.</NOTE></L>
<L>Thru god, til &thorn;ai ware duelland he(re);<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Ms. he st. here.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bot befor vthyre I wald fayne,<MILESTONE N="191" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&amp; I had cunnyng, set my mayne</L>
<L>Sume thing to say of sancte Moryse,</L>
<L N="10">&THORN;at in his tyme was ware &amp; wis
<PB REF="00000328.tif" N="190"></L>
<L>&amp; in &thorn;e erd of sic renowne,</L>
<L>&amp; als in hewine sa hye patrone</L>
<L>Of Aberdene in &thorn;e cite</L>
<L>Thru haly lif was wont to be.</L>
<L N="15">Bot Jhesu Crist in &thorn;e ewangele,</L>
<L>Quhene at he techit, sad sume quhyle:</L>
<L>&THORN;at na profet, quhat euir he be,</L>
<L>Is accept in his cunctre.</L>
<L>&amp; suth is &thorn;at prophesy</L>
<L N="20">In sanct Morys werraly:</L>
<L>For quhene are in &thorn;is land, at wat</L>
<L>His birth, his lif &amp; syne his stat,<NOTE PLACE="foot">quhene quhone = few. at = &thorn;at.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; hou eftyre gret trawal one chance<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. syne one, syne ist zu tilgen.</NOTE></L>
<L>God mad hyme to rest syne in France,</L>
<L N="25">Ine Toroune, til honouryt be,</L>
<L>Set &thorn;are a strangere was he,</L>
<L>&amp; fetryt is by sancte Martyne<NOTE PLACE="foot">zum Reim vgl. 1743.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; haldine &thorn;are in gret lowing.</L>
<L>Bot in &thorn;is land we kene hyme nocht,</L>
<L N="30">Quhare he wondir werkis wrocht,</L>
<L>As I sal schortly tel sume thing,</L>
<L>Begynnand fyrst at his gettyng</L>
<L>&amp; of his byrth, &amp; hou &thorn;at he</L>
<L>Schupe hyme to god plesand to be.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="35">A king quhyle was in Irland</L>
<L>To mane &amp; god wel lifand,</L>
<L>&amp; had Syaconus to name.</L>
<L>&amp; his wyf, of gud fame,</L>
<L>&THORN;e quene Synchene mene callit &thorn;are:</L>
<L N="40">&THORN;at a sone to &thorn;e king bare.</L>
<L>&amp; gert ful mychty mene hyme ta</L>
<L>&amp; bere &amp; cal hyme Mocumma,<NOTE PLACE="foot">bere zur Taufe tragen.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; to fostyre be-tuk hyme &thorn;ane</L>
<L>Til ane, callit Colmane.</L>
<L N="45">&THORN;e quhilk had riches at wil,</L>
<L>For-&thorn;i he tuk &thorn;e child hyme til</L>
<L>&amp; gat a nuryse gud in hy.</L>
<L>&THORN;e quylk hyme fostrit tenderly.</L>
<L>&amp; he thrawe, &thorn;at wele fostrit was.</L>
<L N="50">&amp; as he greu, sa godis grace</L>
<L>Greu in hyme ay, sa &thorn;at he</L>
<L>With angelis wald oft visyt be.</L>
<L>&THORN;ane tyd &thorn;e kyng a tyme to ryd</L>
<L>In &thorn;e cunctre nere besyd,</L>
<L N="55">Quhare dweland wes &thorn;is Colmane;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. colm&amacr;</NOTE></L>
<L>Bot knawlag had &thorn;e king nane</L>
<L>&THORN;at his sovne wes fostryt &thorn;are.</L>
<L>Bot as he by &thorn;e house cane sare,</L>
<L>He saw angelis sare &amp; brycht</L>
<L N="60">One &thorn;e ruf of &thorn;at house lycht</L>
<L>&amp; ost come ydyr out of hewine</L>
<L>&amp; entryt syngand with a stewyne.</L>
<L>&THORN;e king, &thorn;at saw &thorn;is, had ferly</L>
<L>&amp; speryt at &thorn;ame, ware hyme by:</L>
<L N="65">Quha aucht &thorn;e house, he saw &thorn;are,</L>
<L>&amp; quha &thorn;are duelt in &thorn;at sychware.</L>
<L>&amp; sad &thorn;ai: "sa haf we blyse,</L>
<L>&YOGH;oure sone fostrit &thorn;are-ine is."</L>
<L>&THORN;e kyng, &thorn;at Joyful &thorn;ane was,</L>
<L N="70">Ine-to &thorn;e house but mare cane pas</L>
<L>&amp; til his sone beheld ine hy,</L>
<L>Quhare he cane in &thorn;e credil ly:</L>
<L>&amp; saw &thorn;e angelis to &amp; fra</L>
<L>Cume ofte &amp; hyme confort ma,</L>
<L N="75">About his credil gangand</L>
<L>With melody &amp; angel sang.</L>
<L>&THORN;is quhene &thorn;e king had herd &amp; sene,</L>
<L>&THORN;e Joy he had, wald na-mane wene!</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;are na vthyr bot he<NOTE PLACE="foot">im Ms, fehlt was?</NOTE></L>
<L N="80">&THORN;at tholyt was &thorn;at sicht to se.</L>
<L>His handis &thorn;ane he held one hicht</L>
<L>&amp; lowit god at al his mycht</L>
<L>&THORN;at sik a sone had til hyme send,</L>
<L>&amp; prayt he suld hyme defend</L>
<L N="85">Fra alkine Il, &amp; grant &thorn;at he</L>
<L>In his seruice mycht growand be &mdash;</L>
<L>Bot quhat-kine wyse he god louit</L>
<L>Or hou &thorn;at he his sone blyssit,</L>
<L>It ware ful lang here to say.</L>
<L N="90">Nocht-&thorn;ane, or he &yogh;ed away,</L>
<L>For god had latine hyme se &thorn;at sycht,</L>
<L>He gaf of heretabile rycht</L>
<L>To godis seruice al &thorn;at tone</L>
<L>In-to fre possessione,<MILESTONE N="192" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="95">&amp; wend his way blyth &amp; glad</L>
<L>For It, he sa sene had.</L>
<L>&amp; quhene he come hame, to &thorn;e quene
<PB REF="00000329.tif" N="191"></L>
<L>Tald al &thorn;at he had herd &amp; sene:</L>
<L>&THORN;at rycht blyth was of &thorn;at thing</L>
<L N="100">&amp; &yogh;auld to god gret lowing.</L>
<L>&amp; ekyt &thorn;are deuocione</L>
<L>In almous-ded and oracione,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. scheinbar alman.</NOTE></L>
<L>Prayand to god Ithandly</L>
<L>&THORN;at he wald for his gret mercy</L>
<L N="105">Sa kepe &thorn;are child furth, &thorn;at he</L>
<L>A lele seruand til hymc mycht be.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Syne eftyre it tyd of case</L>
<L>&THORN;at quhene Sychene deliuer was</L>
<L>Of a knaf-child: &thorn;at deit rycht &thorn;ane,</L>
<L N="110">Or mene with hyme to baptyme wane.</L>
<L>&THORN;ane was gret dule mad &amp; care</L>
<L>Oure al &thorn;e cunctre, here &amp; &thorn;are.</L>
<L>Bot nane sa mykil sorou mad</L>
<L>As kyng &amp; quhene, &thorn;at mast cause had &mdash;</L>
<L N="115">For it is mast sorow of ane</L>
<L>Barne to be fra &thorn;e gettare sa tane.</L>
<L>Nocht-&thorn;ane &thorn;e king hyme thocht</L>
<L>&THORN;at to mak doul it gaynit nocht,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;ane, for &thorn;e dynt of ded,</L>
<L N="120">Agane &thorn;e quhilk is na remed.</L>
<L>&THORN;are-for he bad to &thorn;ame hyme by</L>
<L>To tak &thorn;e ded barne, with al hy</L>
<L>Sped &thorn;aime with It for-to ga<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. doul od. duil.</NOTE></L>
<L>Quhare his sone is, Mocumma,</L>
<L N="125">&amp; vndir his clathis by hyme lay,</L>
<L>&amp;, quhat suld word &thorn;ar-of, assay;<NOTE PLACE="foot">word = fieri.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; quhene &thorn;ai, as he bad, has done,</L>
<L>&THORN;e barne &thorn;ai suld agane bring sone &mdash;</L>
<L>Sa &thorn;at he suld na sorow mak,</L>
<L N="130">Bot se quhat end it suld tak:</L>
<L>For be &thorn;e sicht, he had sene,</L>
<L>Trewly he trewit but ony wene</L>
<L>&THORN;at thru &thorn;e tweching anerly</L>
<L>Of Mocumma &thorn;at barne in hy</L>
<L N="135">Suld turne to lyf. &amp; but delay,</L>
<L>As he bad, sa did &thorn;ai,</L>
<L>&amp; tuk &thorn;e ded barne &thorn;at wes fare</L>
<L>&amp; laydit by &thorn;e kingis ayre<NOTE PLACE="foot">laydit = layd it.</NOTE></L>
<L>In credil, til his nakit flesch</L>
<L N="140">Vndir his clathis, &thorn;o it cald was.</L>
<L>Bot mene gret wondir &thorn;ane se mocht</L>
<L>Of hyme &thorn;at ded &thorn;are was brocht:</L>
<L>Fra he his bruthyre twechit had,</L>
<L>Fra ded to lyf he come but bad,</L>
<L N="145">&amp; fquelyt gret &amp; raryt &yogh;arne,</L>
<L>As kynd gas to sic a barne.</L>
<L>&THORN;e gud mane<NOTE PLACE="foot">l. mene?</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;ane &thorn;at brocht hyme &thorn;are,</L>
<L>&THORN;at had mad fyrst dule &amp; care,</L>
<L>Quhene &thorn;ai saw &thorn;is gret ferly,</L>
<L N="150">Joyful &thorn;ai ware, &amp; in hy</L>
<L>&THORN;e &yogh;ong barne tuk &amp; hame had</L>
<L>To king &amp; quene. &thorn;at Joy mad,</L>
<L>&YOGH;ey, mare &thorn;ane ma nemmyt be,</L>
<L>Quhene &thorn;ai &thorn;are barne lifand cane se.</L>
<L N="155">Quhat confluens of &yogh;ung &amp; ald</L>
<L>&THORN;ane was &thorn;are, ma nocht be tald,</L>
<L>Na os &thorn;e merwal quhat wondring</L>
<L>Na hou to god was mad lowyng &mdash;</L>
<L>&amp; anerly &thorn;at was nocht &thorn;are,</L>
<L N="160">Bot thru &thorn;e kirk wyd-quhare.</L>
<L>&THORN;e chyld &thorn;ane to &thorn;e kirk &thorn;ai had</L>
<L>&amp; gert it hofine be but bad,</L>
<L>&amp; it fostrit tenderly,</L>
<L>As his stat wald, delytabli.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="165">Sone eftyre a ferly fel</L>
<L>Alsa gret, as I hard tel.</L>
<L>Eftyre of tyme &thorn;e proce&szlig;,</L>
<L>Quhare Mocumma fostrit was</L>
<L>It tyd his noryse sor to be</L>
<L N="170">Sitand, &amp; had hyme one hyr kne,</L>
<L>Be &thorn;e fyre, al hyre-alane,</L>
<L>For &thorn;e lawe &thorn;are gat ware gane.<NOTE PLACE="foot">lawe laif = reliquum.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; it hapnyt hyre in hy</L>
<L>Oute &thorn;e house to here gret cry:</L>
<L N="175">&THORN;are-of scho gret ferly had;</L>
<L>&amp; for-to wit quhy it was mad,</L>
<L>Scho stert vpe: &amp; &thorn;are-with-al</L>
<L>&THORN;e barne fra hyre handis cane fal</L>
<L>In &thorn;e fyre, &thorn;at was sa gret</L>
<L N="180">&THORN;at nane mycht nicht it for het.<NOTE PLACE="foot">night = nigh.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; scho, &thorn;at &thorn;e barne saw sa<MILESTONE N="193" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>In &thorn;e fyre, had sa gret wa</L>
<L>&amp; sa abaysit cane stand,
<PB REF="00000330.tif" N="192"></L>
<L>&THORN;at scho had no&thorn;ir fut na hand</L>
<L N="185">To helpe &thorn;e barne, bot lud cane cry.</L>
<L>&YOGH;et &thorn;e barne stil cane ly,</L>
<L>Ay kepand it sa godis grace</L>
<L>&THORN;at in &thorn;e fyre vnbrynt it was.</L>
<L>&THORN;ane rayrit scho loud &amp; raf hir hare</L>
<L N="190">&amp; beft hyre self &amp; mad sic care,</L>
<L>&THORN;at of hyre wit scho &yogh;ed nere wod</L>
<L>For sorow of &thorn;at frely fud,</L>
<L>Eftyre helpe criand Ithanly.</L>
<L>Til al &thorn;e last &thorn;are come in hy</L>
<L N="195">Ful fele, &thorn;at herd hir mak sic care,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. gert st. hert.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; fand &thorn;e barne &yogh;et lyand &thorn;are,</L>
<L>&amp; hynt It out: &amp; syne It fand</L>
<L>As in &thorn;e credil it ware lyand;</L>
<L>&amp; sume saw angelis ay repare,</L>
<L N="200">&THORN;at It kepit elyk fare</L>
<L>Fra wemmyne of &thorn;e fyre sa brath</L>
<L>O&thorn;ir in body or in clath.</L>
<L>&THORN;ane gert &thorn;ai &thorn;e bellis ryng<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. <ABBR>bell</ABBR>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; te deum laudamus syng,</L>
<L N="205">&amp; lowit god increly</L>
<L>&THORN;at had kyd sic ferly</L>
<L>&amp; schewit &thorn;are sa mykil mycht</L>
<L>In &thorn;at &yogh;ung barne til al <I>&thorn;ar</I> sycht,</L>
<L>Gerrand &thorn;at elyment &thorn;at he</L>
<L N="210">Had gert, obeysand til hyme be.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ane vthyr (tyme) als befel<NOTE PLACE="foot">tyme fehlt im Ms.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;is nuryse, I of tel,</L>
<L>For&yogh;etil of &thorn;e mykil wath</L>
<L>&THORN;at tyd &thorn;e barne for-outyne skath,</L>
<L N="215">Ane erand had to do <I>&thorn;ar</I>-owt.</L>
<L>Bot for scho of &thorn;e barne had dout</L>
<L>To lewe It in &thorn;e house alane,</L>
<L>For al vthire away ware gane:</L>
<L>&amp; in a fat &thorn;at stud hyre by,</L>
<L N="220">Brad &amp; depe, &amp; &thorn;ane dry,</L>
<L>Weppit in clathis &thorn;e barne cane lay</L>
<L>Ful tenderly. &amp; &yogh;ed hyre way,</L>
<L>Wenand it mycht &thorn;are be stil</L>
<L>But parel, til scho come It til.</L>
<L N="225">&amp; quhene scho hyre gat ware gane,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e men&yogh;e in come ane,</L>
<L>Vnwitand &thorn;e barne wes &thorn;are,</L>
<L>&amp; fillyt &thorn;e fat but ony mare</L>
<L>Of watir richt vpe to &thorn;e bra,</L>
<L N="230">&amp; syne of &thorn;e house cane ga.</L>
<L>&THORN;ane eftyr &thorn;e nuryse come,</L>
<L>&THORN;at had hyre hart out of home</L>
<L>For thochtful scho wes of &thorn;e barne:</L>
<L>&amp; to &thorn;e fat sped hyre &yogh;arne:</L>
<L N="235">&amp; fand it fillit to &thorn;e bra &mdash;</L>
<L>It wes na were, &thorn;ane scho wes wa!</L>
<L>&THORN;ane &thorn;e mane callit scho, &thorn;e fat cane fil,</L>
<L>&amp; speryt quhare put he &thorn;e barne til</L>
<L>&THORN;at in &thorn;e grond of &thorn;e fat lay.</L>
<L N="240">&amp; he schortly til hyre cane say</L>
<L>&THORN;at he wist nocht of &thorn;at barne,</L>
<L>Bot hopyt wele It was forfarne</L>
<L>Gyf scho lad It &thorn;are: for he,</L>
<L>Vnwittand it &thorn;are suld be,</L>
<L N="245">Fillyt &thorn;e fat &amp; held is way.</L>
<L>Quhene scho hard hyme so-get say,</L>
<L>Scho rugyt of hyre hed &thorn;e hare</L>
<L>&amp; squelit fa(s)t &amp; hie cane rare,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. fat od. far?</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; with hyre handis skartyt hir face</L>
<L N="250">&amp; al &thorn;e lawe &thorn;at nakit wes,</L>
<L>&amp; with hyre newis reft hir brest,</L>
<L>Al &thorn;at scho mycht wyne to nest,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. nest od. rest?</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; callit hyre-self ful pytisly</L>
<L>Of wrech, &thorn;at sa reklesly,<NOTE PLACE="foot">of = oft.</NOTE></L>
<L N="255">&THORN;at in hyre fawt sic a barne</L>
<L>&THORN;e tothyre tyme &yogh;et sa forfarne(!),</L>
<L>&amp; for &thorn;at knawine wes hir gylty</L>
<L>To mane &amp; god al-mychty.</L>
<L>&THORN;ane ruschit mene to spere</L>
<L N="260">&THORN;e cause quhy scho mad sic bere.</L>
<L>&amp; quhene &thorn;ai &thorn;e manere wist,</L>
<L>&THORN;e fat &thorn;ai tyd done but mare fyrst:<NOTE PLACE="foot">tyd - pulled, v. ags. te&oacute;n, theg Troy. B. 7628.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; fand &thorn;e barne hale &amp; fere,</L>
<L>As watir neuir had nychd It nere,</L>
<L N="265">Bot als dry It was sene</L>
<L>As in &thorn;e credil it had bene.</L>
<L>Bot angelis, as &thorn;ai did before,</L>
<L>It kepit &thorn;ane, myne no mare,</L>
<L>Fra wath of watir quhare It lay,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. wath?</NOTE></L>
<L N="270">As in &thorn;e fyre befor did &thorn;ai.
<PB REF="00000331.tif" N="193"></L>
<L>For he &thorn;at quyk sawit Moyses,</L>
<L>In &thorn;e watir quhene he put wes,</L>
<L>Has defendit &thorn;is barne here</L>
<L>&THORN;at lyk was to be ine gret were.</L>
<L N="275">Quhat is &thorn;are mare to say, but &thorn;ane</L>
<L>Ful ioiful wes mony mane<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. woful st. ioiful.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; mykil lowyng wes &thorn;ane mad</L>
<L>To god of hewine, &thorn;at sa gret had</L>
<L>Merwale in &thorn;at barne sa kyd,</L>
<L N="280">Quhene it was in &thorn;e watir hyd.</L>
<L>&THORN;ane wes &thorn;e nuryse for Joy gretand,</L>
<L>Quhene scho hyre fostir-sowne fand.</L>
<L>Lord Crist, &thorn;ire werkis are &thorn;ine,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;is gerris &thorn;i halowis schyne</L>
<L N="285">Be merwalis &amp; vertuise sere,</L>
<L>&THORN;e quhilkis &thorn;ai wrocht, til &thorn;ai were</L>
<L>Here lifand! &amp; lowyng to &thorn;e be,</L>
<L>A god in personis thre!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Of &thorn;is barne &thorn;is wes begynnyng</L>
<L N="290">For-to grew in hewynly thing,</L>
<L>For ferlys &thorn;at fare ware &amp; sere,</L>
<L>As &yogh;e sume part herd has here.</L>
<L>&amp; ay ine body as he grew,</L>
<L>He grew in vertu fare Inuch.</L>
<L N="295">&amp; fra he cuth spek grathly,</L>
<L>He wes set to &thorn;e schole ine hy,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;are ine his begynnyng leyryt,</L>
<L>Sic as til &yogh;ung mene afferyt:</L>
<L>In gud thowis to haf delyt</L>
<L N="300">&amp; in vertuyse to be parfyt.</L>
<L>&amp; quhene he come to rypare eld,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he mycht hyme-self &yogh;eld,</L>
<L>He sat his hart one heare thing:<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. &yogh;eld st. weld?</NOTE></L>
<L>To here &amp; haf vndirstanding;</L>
<L N="305">&amp; quhat his hart printyt withine,<NOTE PLACE="foot">wes fehlt?</NOTE></L>
<L>He held wele, &amp; fled ay syne.</L>
<L>&amp; be he come to sewine &yogh;ere,</L>
<L>He cuth langage spek sere</L>
<L>&amp; vndirstand &thorn;ame rycht wele &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. vndirst&amacr;and.</NOTE></L>
<L N="310">God had hyme send sa gret cele!<NOTE PLACE="foot">cele = zele.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; als of &thorn;at eld was he</L>
<L>Lik to a formulare to be,</L>
<L>Of quhame mene suld behald &thorn;e ded</L>
<L>&THORN;at god honoure wald &amp; dred,</L>
<L N="315">&amp; &thorn;are-with hou &thorn;ai suld be</L>
<L>To &thorn;are nytboure in cheryte.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>(I)n &thorn;e land &thorn;at tyme &thorn;ane was</L>
<L>A mane &thorn;at schane os halynes</L>
<L>&amp; led his lyf but ony blame.</L>
<L N="320">For-&thorn;i of hyme fere rane &thorn;e name,</L>
<L>Sa fare, &thorn;at &thorn;e forsad kyng</L>
<L>Was wytryt wele of his lyfyng,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;at he come of kingis kyne &mdash;</L>
<L>Sik as wes Irland withine,</L>
<L N="325">&amp; Columbe had to his name,</L>
<L>A mane &thorn;at was but ony blame.</L>
<L>Sic request he hyme &thorn;ane mad</L>
<L>&THORN;at he come til hyme but abad.</L>
<L>&THORN;e kyng &thorn;ane with hyme tretit sa</L>
<L N="330">&THORN;at he tuk with hyme Mocumba,</L>
<L>For-til enforme fyrst &amp; lere</L>
<L>In vertuse, &amp; in science sere.</L>
<L>&amp; he, &thorn;at abil was &amp; &yogh;yng,</L>
<L>Folouyt his master in al thing</L>
<L N="335">&amp; wald consawe ful sutelly</L>
<L>Quhat-euire he taucht, in-til hy,</L>
<L>&amp; in his hart wele held It &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. weld st. wele.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ay retentywe he had a wyt &mdash;</L>
<L>&amp; had hyme in sik degre</L>
<L N="340">&THORN;at his ourmene be sutelte &mdash;</L>
<L>&amp; les &thorn;ane he in gret meknes &mdash;</L>
<L>He wald oure-cume. &amp; neuir-&thorn;e-les</L>
<L>He kepyt ay his innocens</L>
<L>Of al mane but offens,</L>
<L N="345">&amp; growand ay furth he wes</L>
<L>In vertu and in gudnes.</L>
<L>&amp; for he doutyt for-to fal,</L>
<L>Til abstinens he gef hyme al</L>
<L>&amp; held his flesch vndirlout,</L>
<L N="350">For dred: it suld worth stout</L>
<L>Agane &thorn;e saul &amp; gere hyme syne</L>
<L>&amp; let hyme hewinis blis to wyne;</L>
<L>&amp; gef hyme to prayere &amp; to wak,</L>
<L>Hyme to god seruand to mak.</L>
<L N="355">&amp; god his hart abile ay mad</L>
<L>To lere &thorn;at he wald but bad:</L>
<L>Sa that of thre moneth &thorn;e space<MILESTONE N="195" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Al warldis wit be godis grace
<PB REF="00000332.tif" N="194"></L>
<L>&amp; seruice als of haly kyrk</L>
<L N="360">He leryt al, &amp; wes nocht Irk.</L>
<L>&amp; here-of suld na-mane ferly,</L>
<L>Gyf he consyderit suthfastly</L>
<L>&THORN;at, quhare &thorn;e haly gast wil be</L>
<L>Master, but dyffyculte</L>
<L N="365">He ma gere mane consawe althing,</L>
<L>But bysynes or trawalyng: &mdash;</L>
<L>As of Salamon we red,</L>
<L>&THORN;at wes &thorn;e wysest mane but dred:</L>
<L>With-in &thorn;e space of a nycht</L>
<L N="370">Of al &thorn;at wit he gat &thorn;e slycht</L>
<L>Thru teching of &thorn;e haly gest,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. theching. Ms. gest = gast.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at is best master, in-til hast &mdash;</L>
<L>For to god, as we ma se,</L>
<L>Nathing may inpossibile be.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="375">Thane, fra sanct Colme had persawing</L>
<L>Hou clerly godis grace cane schyne</L>
<L>In Mocumma, be syndry thingis sere</L>
<L>&THORN;at in hyme he saw apere,</L>
<L>Til his disciplis sad of hyme:</L>
<L N="380">"&YOGH;one mane, &thorn;at schenis as a &yogh;eme,</L>
<L>I ame nocht dingne to lere, trewly,</L>
<L>Fore angelis of-tyme sene haf I<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. of = oft.</NOTE></L>
<L>Repare til hyme &amp; kene hyme al</L>
<L>&THORN;at he wald lere, gret &amp; smal,</L>
<L N="385">&amp; namely, hou he haly wryt</L>
<L>Sal vndirstand &amp; expond It".</L>
<L>Quhene &thorn;ai herd &thorn;is, &thorn;ai had inwy</L>
<L>Agane Mocumma, fellonny</L>
<L>&amp; dyspyt, be-cause &thorn;at he</L>
<L N="390">Wes lowit in &thorn;at degre.</L>
<L>Bot sancte Colme, &thorn;at &thorn;are enwy</L>
<L>Persawit &amp; &thorn;are fellonny,</L>
<L>Lowit Mocumma fere &thorn;e mare</L>
<L>&amp; honouryt hyme, &thorn;ane he did yare,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;are st. yare od are.</NOTE></L>
<L N="395">&amp; of with hyme held carpyng<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. of = oft.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of lestand lyf &amp; hevynly thing,</L>
<L>&amp; wald hyme schaw al priwete</L>
<L>&THORN;at in his thocht consawit he.</L>
<L>Nocht-be-&thorn;i, &thorn;ocht Mocumma</L>
<L N="400">Wist his master lufit hyme sa,</L>
<L>As he be sere assay cane fele,</L>
<L>&YOGH;et pridyt he hyme nocht a dele,</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;e sammyne humylyte,</L>
<L>He had befor, ay kepyt he,</L>
<L N="405">Ine honest conuersacione</L>
<L>&amp; stratnes of relygione.</L>
<L>For&thorn;i &thorn;e grace of god grew ay</L>
<L>In hyme, bath nicht &amp; day.</L>
<L>&THORN;ane rane &thorn;e fame of hyme rycht wyd<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. &thorn;ane st. rane.</NOTE></L>
<L N="410">In al Irland in al syd.</L>
<L>Ful gret Ioy sancte Colme &thorn;ane mad</L>
<L>&THORN;at he sic a discipil gottine had,</L>
<L>&amp; Mocumma was rycht glad</L>
<L>&THORN;at he sic a master had.</L>
<L N="415">&amp; for &thorn;are cause, &thorn;at sa haly ware,</L>
<L>Mene come to &thorn;ame of landis fare,</L>
<L>Til haf &thorn;are informacione,</L>
<L>&amp; alsa for &thorn;are benysone;</L>
<L>&amp; &yogh;et come fore-owt ma</L>
<L N="420">&THORN;ane to sanct Columbe, to sancte Mo|cumma,</L>
<L>For ferly &thorn;ai had &thorn;at he</L>
<L>In sa schort tyme suld haly be;</L>
<L>Bryngand hyme gyftis fare &amp; gret,</L>
<L>As for his clething &amp; his met.</L>
<L N="425">Bot &thorn;are-of he wald nocht,</L>
<L>For he by warldis gud set nocht,</L>
<L>&amp; namely for his fadir sak</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;are-of wald he nocht tak.</L>
<L>&amp; for he wald nocht knawyne be</L>
<L N="430">With &thorn;e mene of his cunctre,</L>
<L>He determyt in his thocht</L>
<L>&THORN;at dwel &thorn;are langare wald he nocht</L>
<L>Bot passyt in vnchut land but bad<NOTE PLACE="foot">l. pass.</NOTE></L>
<L>Quhare na-mane knawlag of hyme had.</L>
<L N="435">&amp; sa to do &thorn;at he his wil</L>
<L>Set, sad his maistere til.<NOTE PLACE="foot">nach set fehlt hat?</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at of his purpos wes blyth,</L>
<L>Fore-&thorn;i he sad til hyme alswith:</L>
<L>"Der sone in Crist, I lowe god ay</L>
<L N="440">&THORN;at &thorn;e has leryt &thorn;us to say:</L>
<L>For It, &thorn;at &thorn;u has sad me til,</L>
<L>Of ful parfyt mene is &thorn;e wil.</L>
<L>&amp; now, dere sone, I sal tel &thorn;e</L>
<L>Al vtrely myne priwete:
<PB REF="00000333.tif" N="195"></L>
<L N="445">&THORN;at is, &thorn;at myne wil has bene ay</L>
<L>Of myne kith to pa&szlig; my way,</L>
<L>With-&thorn;i &thorn;at I had &thorn;e wil</L>
<L>Of &thorn;i kyne &amp; myne &thorn;are-til.</L>
<L>Bot for &thorn;i kyne I lettyt mare,</L>
<L N="450">&THORN;at, gyf &thorn;u sa dide, wald haf care,<MILESTONE N="196" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>For &thorn;u &thorn;are fuffrane Ioy is now.<NOTE PLACE="foot">suffrane = sovereign.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;are-for, wil &thorn;u myne consal trew,</L>
<L>&THORN;u wyne &thorn;are gud luf &amp; lewe &mdash;</L>
<L>For sa-gat ma we best eschewe &mdash;</L>
<L N="455">&amp;, &thorn;at done, cum agane me til!</L>
<L>&THORN;ane ma we pase quhare-euir we wil".</L>
<L>&THORN;e &yogh;ung mane sad: "<I>ser</I>, I haf nane</L>
<L>Fadir now bot god alane,</L>
<L>Fore quhame fadir &amp; modir bath</L>
<L N="460">I wil forsak, &thorn;o &thorn;aime be lath.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. to st. &thorn;o.</NOTE></L>
<L>For &thorn;u nixt god is my fadir,</L>
<L>&amp; haly kyrk is my modir,</L>
<L>For-&thorn;i I wil lewe be na wyse</L>
<L>&THORN;i cumpany na &thorn;i seruice.</L>
<L N="465">Fore quhare &thorn;u gays, wil I ga,</L>
<L>Til ded tak ane of ws twa".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>His master &thorn;ane gret ferly had</L>
<L>&amp; in his hart gret Ioy he mad,</L>
<L>Quhene he &thorn;e gret deuocione</L>
<L N="470">Of hyme herd &amp; &thorn;e perfeccione.</L>
<L>&THORN;ane sad he: "sone, til &thorn;u in &yogh;uthad</L>
<L>Was stad, a barnis name &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> had;</L>
<L>Bot for &thorn;u &yogh;uthad has warpyst</L>
<L>&amp; is parfyt mane in Cryst,</L>
<L N="475">&THORN;u sal be callyt "Machore"</L>
<L>&amp; lewe &thorn;e name &thorn;u had before".<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. bofore.</NOTE></L>
<L>Sanct Colme gert &thorn;ane aparel</L>
<L>A bat fture with wetale,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. bast st. bat.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; sped hyme to &thorn;e se but mare,</L>
<L N="480">With al &thorn;at wald with hyme fare,</L>
<L>His ferme hope in hyme setand</L>
<L>&THORN;at has to stere bath se &amp; land.</L>
<L>&THORN;ane Machore fyrst in &thorn;e bat wane,</L>
<L>&amp; reprowyt &thorn;e maister-mane</L>
<L N="485">Of his tary &amp; his slawnes,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he to saile sa lethand wes.</L>
<L>&THORN;ane, helpand god, &thorn;ai saylyt a quhyle,</L>
<L>Til &thorn;ai come nere &thorn;e Ile</L>
<L>Of Iy, &amp; &thorn;are saile strak,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. iy od. ry? Ile of Iy wol das jetzige Iona.</NOTE></L>
<L N="490">&THORN;ane &thorn;are thocht land to tak.</L>
<L>Ane Melluma in &thorn;at sychware</L>
<L>Come to &thorn;e se &amp; saw &thorn;ame &thorn;are,</L>
<L>&amp; knew sanct Colme, &amp; wes blyth,</L>
<L>&amp; at hyme speryt alswyth</L>
<L N="495">Gyf he one land wald be.</L>
<L>&amp; he sad &yogh;a. &THORN;ane in &thorn;e se</L>
<L>&THORN;e carle wod to &thorn;e bat but bad.</L>
<L>&amp; to &thorn;e land quhene he &thorn;ame had,</L>
<L>&THORN;ane sad sancte Colme: "ar we al here?"</L>
<L N="500">Sad Melluma: "&yogh;a, now, <I>ser</I>".</L>
<L>Sanct Colme gert &thorn;ame cume hyme before</L>
<L>To se: &amp; myssit sancte Machore,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &yogh;et in his prayere lay.</L>
<L>Sanct Colme &thorn;ane to &thorn;e carle cane say:</L>
<L N="505">"&YOGH;et wantis ane, &amp; Is mare</L>
<L>With god of hewine &thorn;ane we al are".</L>
<L>&THORN;ane passit &thorn;e carle &amp; sperit gyf he</L>
<L>To &thorn;e land dry borne wald be.</L>
<L>&YOGH;a, sad he. &amp; but mare</L>
<L N="510">Dry to &thorn;e land he hyme bare.</L>
<L>&THORN;ane Colme of his cummyne wes blyth,</L>
<L>&amp; athyre kyssyt vthyre swyth</L>
<L>&amp; recommendyt gretumly</L>
<L>Of vertuse lyf &amp; of haly.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="515">Thane sad sanct Colme: "bru&thorn;ir, blissit be</L>
<L>&THORN;is place! &amp; pray to god &thorn;at he</L>
<L>Send his angel to blyse It,</L>
<L>Sene we to cume here, is hapnyt".</L>
<L>&amp; as he sad quhene &thorn;ai had done,</L>
<L N="520">Oure al &thorn;e Ile &thorn;ai passit sone:</L>
<L>&amp; fand it rycht profytabile</L>
<L>&amp;, to duel in, gud &amp; abile.</L>
<L>&amp; out of Irland in a quhyle</L>
<L>Mene may wele sayle in &thorn;at Ile.</L>
<L N="525">&amp; as &thorn;ai socht had &thorn;e place,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai sand quhare a fare sted was,</L>
<L>En-hournyt with treis sere<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. en hournyt = enournyt.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; spryngand wellis fare &amp; clere.</L>
<L>&THORN;ane sad sancte Colme: he wald &thorn;are</L>
<L N="530">Duel &amp; pas na forthyrmare.</L>
<L>A mansione &thorn;ane fyrst &thorn;ai mad
<PB REF="00000334.tif" N="196"></L>
<L>To sancte Colme, &amp; but bad,</L>
<L>&amp; syne a mansione sufficiandly</L>
<L>&THORN;ai mad to sancte Machore in hy,</L>
<L N="535">&amp; til al &thorn;e lawe &thorn;ai wrocht</L>
<L>Placis, til in dwel, as &thorn;ai rycht thocht.</L>
<L>Sancte Colme duelt &thorn;are-in &thorn;ane</L>
<L>As abot, and haly mane.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Syne &thorn;ai saw ane vthire Ile,</L>
<L N="540">&THORN;at &thorn;ai mocht saile to in a quhile,</L>
<L>&THORN;at Mule hycht. &amp; &thorn;are to preche</L>
<L>&amp; cristine folk als to teche,</L>
<L>Sancte Colme send his dyscypil here,</L>
<L>Sancte Machore, &thorn;at wes hyme nere.</L>
<L N="545">&THORN;e quhilk, as he come in &thorn;at land,<MILESTONE N="197" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Sewine myssale vgly he fand:</L>
<L>&amp; askyt of hyme sume thing</L>
<L>Of cheryte, &amp; his blyssyng.</L>
<L>In godis name he bad &thorn;ame pase</L>
<L N="550">To sume watir &thorn;at by was,</L>
<L>&amp; wesch &thorn;ame. &amp; sa dyd &thorn;ai:</L>
<L>&amp; gat &thorn;are hele but delay.</L>
<L>&amp; as &thorn;ai clene ware, with a stewine</L>
<L>Machore &thorn;ai lowyt &amp; god of hewine. &mdash;</L>
<L N="555">&amp; quhene he &thorn;are had bene a quhile</L>
<L>&amp; prechyt oure-al &thorn;e ewangel,</L>
<L>He come to &thorn;e Ile of Iy</L>
<L>Til his master. &amp; wes besy</L>
<L>To study in-to haly wryt,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. iy od. ry? Ile of Iy wol das jetzige Islay.</NOTE></L>
<L N="560">&amp; oft-tyme put Ite to wryt.</L>
<L>&amp; as he a nycht cane wryt</L>
<L>A thing quhare-in he had delyt,</L>
<L>Before &thorn;e end of It mad,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. &thorn;e st. he.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e lycht hyme fal&yogh;et. &amp; &thorn;ane he had</L>
<L N="565">Ferme hope in god of hewine:</L>
<L>One his fyngyre end blew ewine:</L>
<L>&THORN;at as a candil brynnand lycht</L>
<L>&amp;, til done he had, gef hyme sycht.</L>
<L>&amp; sa hapnyt (in) &thorn;at sychware<NOTE PLACE="foot">in fehlt im Ms.</NOTE></L>
<L N="570">A lytil barne for-til be &thorn;are,</L>
<L>&amp; saw hou &thorn;is ferly fel,</L>
<L>&amp; to &thorn;e commone cuth it tel.</L>
<L>&THORN;ane had &thorn;ai fare mare Il-wil</L>
<L>&THORN;ane befor sancte Machore til,</L>
<L N="575">Namely for &thorn;ai mycht nocht</L>
<L>Sic merwalis wyrk as he wrocht.</L>
<L>Syne as Il mene tuk to rede</L>
<L>Nedly for-til haf hyme dede.</L>
<L>Bot for &thorn;ai durst nocht opynly,</L>
<L N="580">For his master, do sic foly,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai, to fulfil &thorn;are entent,</L>
<L>Poysone with ane innocent &mdash;</L>
<L>Say &thorn;ai suld &thorn;e les It think &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">say = sa.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot">umzusetzen.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ai send hyme myngyt into drink.<NOTE PLACE="foot">umzusetzen.</NOTE></L>
<L N="585">Sancte Machore sperit at &thorn;e barne</L>
<L>Quha &thorn;e drink send hyme, rycht &yogh;arne.</L>
<L>&amp; he sad hyme &thorn;e suth hale.</L>
<L>&THORN;ane wyst sancte Machore be his tale</L>
<L>&THORN;at in &thorn;at drynk wes fellone gyle.</L>
<L N="590">&YOGH;et &thorn;ane he tuk It &amp; cane smyle</L>
<L>&amp; sad: "&thorn;ar is brethyre fals</L>
<L>&amp; fra cheryte ful fare als,</L>
<L>&THORN;at me of &thorn;is warld wald bryng</L>
<L>&THORN;at neuire myse did &thorn;ame in ony thing!</L>
<L N="595">&amp; now war ful gud to me</L>
<L>To be vysit &amp; with god sene be &mdash;</L>
<L>&amp;, as god wil, sa mot It be."</L>
<L>With &thorn;at &thorn;e cop ine hand tuk he</L>
<L>&amp; sanyt it dewotly.</L>
<L N="600">&THORN;are mycht mene se a gret ferly:</L>
<L>Hou &thorn;e cop he heldit done</L>
<L>&amp; al &thorn;at was fel poyssone</L>
<L>Fel of &thorn;e cope, &amp; hou &thorn;e lafe</L>
<L>&THORN;are-of to &thorn;e cop clafe.</L>
<L N="605">Syne &thorn;at lycure he drank &thorn;are</L>
<L>But felyng of ony sare.</L>
<L>&THORN;e chyld syne tald &thorn;ame &thorn;at hyme send</L>
<L>As he saw, fra end to end.<NOTE PLACE="foot">607&mdash;8 umzusetzen.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ane sancte Machore prayt hartly</L>
<L N="610">God to forgyf &thorn;aime &thorn;at foly.<NOTE PLACE="foot">609&mdash;10) umzusetzen.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; as &thorn;ai herd sik tything</L>
<L>Of &thorn;at barne, of &thorn;at ferly thyng,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai ware inflammyt of &thorn;e fyre</L>
<L>Of inwy &thorn;ane, and in gret yre</L>
<L N="615">To &thorn;are maistere but delay</L>
<L>Come &amp; &thorn;usgad cane say:<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. &thorn;usgad st. &thorn;usgat.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Machore gerris mene be sorcery</L>
<L>Trowis he dowis merakile opynly,<NOTE PLACE="foot">l. trow? dowis = dois.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; sympil mene in-to &thorn;are sycht</L>
<L N="620">Dissawis thru &thorn;e dewylis mycht,
<PB REF="00000335.tif" N="197"></L>
<L>&amp; is contrare til ws ay.</L>
<L>For-&thorn;i suthly, <I>ser</I>, we say</L>
<L>&THORN;at we wil hale lef &thorn;e,</L>
<L>&amp; he langere with &thorn;e be.</L>
<L N="625">For-&thorn;i chese, quhethyr &thorn;u wil</L>
<L>Gyf ws oure lewe or hald hyme stil!"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And &thorn;are maister herand hou &thorn;ai</L>
<L>Sa specialy &thorn;is tale cane say,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. sp&amacr;ly,</NOTE></L>
<L>He was in perplexyte,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. proplexite.</NOTE></L>
<L N="630">Seand hou ane behowit to be:</L>
<L>O&thorn;ire to do away in haste</L>
<L>His printyce &thorn;at he lufyt mast,</L>
<L>Ore &thorn;aime &thorn;at he had fostryt ay</L>
<L>Fra &yogh;outhed to &thorn;at day.</L>
<L N="635">He prayt &thorn;ame to hald &thorn;aime stil</L>
<L>&amp; he suld syne ouretak <I>&thorn;ar</I> wil.</L>
<L>&THORN;ane he kyst in his thocht</L>
<L>In &thorn;at case he best do mocht<MILESTONE N="198" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Makand a-syth to &thorn;ame bath,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. mak and.</NOTE></L>
<L N="640">&amp;, for to kepe Machore of skath,</L>
<L>Thocht he wald with wilis dele,</L>
<L>For sawete of &thorn;ame &amp; &thorn;are hele.</L>
<L>Saincte Machore he callyt a day</L>
<L>&amp; til hyme &thorn;us-gat cane say:</L>
<L N="645">"My dere bruthyre, in priwete</L>
<L>I haf for-to say to &thorn;e &mdash;</L>
<L>&amp; fyrst I pray &thorn;e, &thorn;u wil</L>
<L>Be na way tak (it) ine-til Il.<NOTE PLACE="foot">it fehlt.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bruthyre, &thorn;u wat &thorn;at quhyle</L>
<L N="650">Jhesu sad in &thorn;e ewangyle:</L>
<L>"'Quha lufis his saule mare &thorn;ane me,</L>
<L>Ma be na way my serwand be'"</L>
<L>&amp; til his printyse cane he say:</L>
<L>"'Passis thru &thorn;e warld oure way<NOTE PLACE="foot">oure = &yogh;oure.</NOTE></L>
<L N="655">&amp; til al mene &thorn;e ewangelis teche</L>
<L>&amp; to tak baptysme &thorn;ame preche!'"</L>
<L>Hou ma we &thorn;ane &thorn;is word fulfil,</L>
<L>&THORN;at in a nuk here lyis stil</L>
<L>&amp; bot of oure-self thinkis nocht</L>
<L N="660">&amp; of sawle-hele na-thing wrocht</L>
<L>Of fele folk, &thorn;at wyd-quhare</L>
<L>In fawt of techyng tynt are &mdash;</L>
<L>&amp; namely, sene we haf mycht</L>
<L>Of body &amp; of science slycht?</L>
<L N="665">Ryse we &thorn;are-for &amp; dres&szlig; ws til</L>
<L>Godis bydyng to fulfil!</L>
<L>&amp; for my eld, as &thorn;u ma se,</L>
<L>To lyf in quyet accordis me,</L>
<L>&amp; for &thorn;u &yogh;ongare is &thorn;ane I,</L>
<L N="670">Scharpare of wyt &amp; mare mychtty:</L>
<L>In godis name &thorn;u tak one hand</L>
<L>To pas in-to fere land,</L>
<L>&amp; preche godis word alquhare</L>
<L>To &thorn;ame at in wane-treucht are,</L>
<L N="675">&amp; pre&szlig; &thorn;e bysyly for-to wyne</L>
<L>&THORN;are sawlis &thorn;at lyis in syne!"</L>
<L>Sancte Machore sad: "master dere,</L>
<L>Gud is I do as &yogh;e me lere,</L>
<L>For &yogh;oure prayere &amp; &yogh;oure consele &mdash;</L>
<L N="680">For &thorn;at to me ma mast awale."</L>
<L>Qua&thorn; he: "with myne oracione,</L>
<L>Mad hartly with deuocione,</L>
<L>I sal helpe &thorn;e but fen&yogh;eyng,</L>
<L>&amp; helpe &thorn;e in al vthyre thyng;</L>
<L N="685">Eftyr my possybilyte,</L>
<L>Dere sone, I sal helpe &thorn;e."</L>
<L>Sewine mene &thorn;ane he taucht hyme til</L>
<L>To serwe hyme &amp; to do his wyl,</L>
<L>&amp; byschape-staf gef hyme alsa</L>
<L N="690">&amp; belt, and of his clathis twa,</L>
<L>&amp; bukis &thorn;at ware necessare</L>
<L>To hyme to prech godis lare;</L>
<L>&amp; ordenyt hyme a galay,</L>
<L>&amp; wytale &thorn;are-in gert he lay.</L>
<L N="695">&amp; &thorn;us to mak quyet &amp; pece</L>
<L>Of It he wyst fellonny was,</L>
<L>&THORN;are-for, as Machore was redy</L>
<L>To pas &thorn;e se, sancte Colme in hy</L>
<L>Gert al his printey&szlig; cume before</L>
<L N="700">Hyme, in absence of sancte Machore,</L>
<L>&amp; sad to &thorn;ame: "sonnis dere,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. s&omacr;nis.</NOTE></L>
<L>I haf &yogh;ou fostryt mony &yogh;ere,</L>
<L>&amp; wat, gyf &yogh;e wil one meyne,</L>
<L>&THORN;at I al-way has besy bene</L>
<L N="705">Til infourme &yogh;u in cheryte</L>
<L>&amp; in sawle-hele thochty to be;</L>
<L>&amp;, for &yogh;oure hartis are herd as flynt</L>
<L>&amp; ek, I haf myne trawale tynt.<NOTE PLACE="foot">ek (ak?) = oak.</NOTE></L>
<L>For in &yogh;oure hartis &yogh;e had Ithandly
<PB REF="00000336.tif" N="198"></L>
<L N="720">&THORN;at &yogh;one haly mane ay inwy<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at = at, wie 736 u. &ouml;.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; &yogh;e ware bowne ay to do Il</L>
<L>Til hyme, &thorn;at neuir mys did &yogh;u til."</L>
<L>Quhene he had &thorn;is sad &amp; mare,</L>
<L>&THORN;ane &thorn;ai repentyt &thorn;ame sare</L>
<L N="725">It &thorn;at &thorn;ai had done before</L>
<L>Agane cheryte to sancte Machore,</L>
<L>&amp; sad: "fadyre, wele wat we,</L>
<L>We haf mysdone in &thorn;at degre.</L>
<L>Bot now reconsel ws hyme til</L>
<L N="730">&amp; now ws get his gud wil!"</L>
<L>Sancte Colme &thorn;ane, &thorn;at besy was</L>
<L>Betwene &thorn;ame forto mak pece,</L>
<L>Callyt Machore &amp; tretyt sa</L>
<L>&THORN;at he betwene &thorn;ayme pes cane ma.</L>
<L N="735">Sancte Machore &thorn;ane his lewe tuk rath</L>
<L>At master &amp; &thorn;at brethyre bath,</L>
<L>&THORN;at with hyme to &thorn;e se cane pas,</L>
<L>Repentand &thorn;ame of &thorn;are trespas;</L>
<L>&amp; of now lewe has tane<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. of = oft.</NOTE></L>
<L N="740">&amp; kyssyt &thorn;ame euire-ilkane.</L>
<L>His maister &thorn;ane &amp; he mad wa</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ame worthyt part in-twa,</L>
<L>&amp; kyssyt oft &thorn;at &thorn;are partyng</L>
<L>With regrat &amp; with gretyng,</L>
<L N="745">&amp; Ilkane cane vthyre blyse<MILESTONE N="199" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>With wordis of gret teyndernes.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Thane to &thorn;e galay went Machore,</L>
<L>&amp; sancte Colme quhare he wes before.</L>
<L>&amp;, helpand god, saylyt &thorn;e se</L>
<L N="750">But distrowbylance in dais thre</L>
<L>&amp; ewine north in Scotland</L>
<L>Arywyt. quhare &thorn;ai fand dwelland</L>
<L>A cristine mane &thorn;at Farcare hycht,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ryches had &amp; mykil mycht:</L>
<L N="755">&THORN;at prayt &thorn;ame for-to say</L>
<L>Quhene &thorn;ai come &amp; quhat ware &thorn;ai.</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;ai sad hyme &thorn;e suth alswith.</L>
<L>&THORN;ane wes &thorn;is Farcare ferly blyth,</L>
<L>Quhene he sene had sancte Machor&mdash;</L>
<L N="760">For he hard spek of hyme befor.</L>
<L>&amp; because of his renowne</L>
<L>&THORN;is Farcare had hyme til his towne,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. hed.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; al &thorn;at nedful til hyme was</L>
<L>Gert get til hyme, mare &amp; les;</L>
<L N="765">Thankand god abeowe &thorn;e lawe</L>
<L>&THORN;at he wes worthy sik gest til haf:</L>
<L>For he in scort tyme gert hyme be</L>
<L>Parfyt in double cheryte,</L>
<L>&THORN;at is to say: with god &amp; mane.</L>
<L N="770">&amp; &thorn;are-with his luf he wane,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he sad til hyme: "fadir dere,</L>
<L>Lo al &thorn;is landis are myne here</L>
<L>&amp; h(i)s my herytag al.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. hs.</NOTE></L>
<L>For-&thorn;i &thorn;us place tak &thorn;u sal<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;us st. &thorn;is.</NOTE></L>
<L N="775">To mak quhare-euire &thorn;u wil a place.</L>
<L>&amp; gyf ony of myne ospryng percase</L>
<L>Gane-sais It, waryt mot he (be),<NOTE PLACE="foot">be fehlt im Ms.</NOTE></L>
<L>Til he thole &thorn;e brukyt fre."</L>
<L>Sancte Machore &thorn;ane thankfully<NOTE PLACE="foot">brukyt = bruk yt.</NOTE></L>
<L N="780">His gyft tuk, &amp; al &thorn;e place by</L>
<L>Socht to &amp; fra, til he fand</L>
<L>A sted, til hyme wes gannand,</L>
<L>Besyd a watyr bank, &thorn;at rane</L>
<L>Ine-to &thorn;e se, &amp; lyk was &thorn;ane</L>
<L N="785">As It a byschopis staf had bene.</L>
<L>&amp; fra sancte Machore had It sene,</L>
<L>Til his dysciplis cane say:</L>
<L>"Lo here myne dwelling-place for ay!</L>
<L>For my master to me cane tel</L>
<L N="790">&THORN;at I in sik place suld dwel."</L>
<L>&THORN;ane gert he bygyne &thorn;are be mad</L>
<L>Til hyme, as he mystere had,</L>
<L>&amp; syne til al &thorn;e lawe gert he</L>
<L>Bygyng mak in &thorn;are degre.</L>
<L N="795">&amp; eftyr &thorn;at he gert wyrk</L>
<L>Be craftly mene a costlyk kyrk&mdash;</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;at mene callyt &yogh;et<NOTE PLACE="foot">l. callis.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of sancte Machore &thorn;e seg ore set.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Sere warkmene syne on a day<NOTE PLACE="foot">sa = say.</NOTE></L>
<L N="800">&THORN;at had gret thryst, cane til hyme sa:</L>
<L>"Dere fadir, wit &yogh;e, quhene we swink</L>
<L>&THORN;at we haf gret fawt of drynk.</L>
<L>Help vs &thorn;are-for, gyf &yogh;e may!"</L>
<L>&THORN;ane sancte Machore but delay</L>
<L N="805">Gat gud vatere in fusione&mdash;</L>
<L>&amp; seruis &yogh;et til al &thorn;e towne</L>
<L>&amp; springis &yogh;et, as It did &thorn;ane
<PB REF="00000337.tif" N="199"></L>
<L>At prayere of &thorn;at haly mane.</L>
<L>&amp; fele &thorn;at of &thorn;at watir drank</L>
<L N="810">Gat hele, &amp; hartly god cane thank.</L>
<L>&THORN;at was &thorn;e fyrst merwal &thorn;at he</L>
<L>Wrocht &thorn;at Quhene &thorn;at mene mycht se,<NOTE PLACE="foot">?= quhene; Ms. <ABBR>quhe</ABBR>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at now &thorn;e name has Scotland,</L>
<L>Bot Pychtis &thorn;ane in It ware duelland.</L>
<L N="815">&THORN;ane come til hyme of placis sere</L>
<L>Mony printeise, &thorn;at redy were</L>
<L>Til vndir-ly his dyscypline</L>
<L>&amp; fore-to tak of hyme teching.&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;ane duelt a mane nere-by</L>
<L N="820">Relygiouse &amp; rycht hali,</L>
<L>&THORN;at to name had Dewynik,</L>
<L>&THORN;at godis &yogh;ok bare one his nek:</L>
<L>&amp; to sancte Machore come a day</L>
<L>&amp; til hyme &thorn;is he cane say:</L>
<L N="825">"Gud ser, behald, &amp; &thorn;u ma se</L>
<L>Hou fele folk in &thorn;is cunctre</L>
<L>Are &yogh;et habandonyt mony wise<NOTE PLACE="inter">(<B>Hier beginnt andere Hand.</B>)</NOTE></L>
<L>To mak till mawmentis seruice;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Hier beginnt andere Hand; a. R. steht: Caret de fine sce Mauchcarii et de sca Katerina.</NOTE></L>
<L>And <I>&thorn;ar</I> are ner-hand nane to schav<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. &thorn;us st. &thorn;are.</NOTE></L>
<L N="830">Goddis word or ger mene knaw<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. her st. ger.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e nerrest get till h&emacr;wynis blis.</L>
<L>For&thorn;i, master, my consall is</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;u in &thorn;is cunctre duel still,</L>
<L>Goddis wangel forto preche till</L>
<L N="835"><I>&THORN;us</I> Poictis, at are lath to trew.<MILESTONE N="200" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. scheinbar pontis, 861 poyntis.</NOTE></L>
<L>And I with goddis helpe will now</L>
<L>To &thorn;ame of Catnes but mare gang,</L>
<L>&THORN;at cristine treucht is miskennand lang,</L>
<L>Amang &thorn;aime goddis vord to schaw,</L>
<L N="840">To ger &thorn;aime god parfitly knaw."</L>
<L>Sanct Machor sad: "&thorn;at quhe&thorn;ir na we,</L>
<L>Sal ilkane vthire eftire se?"</L>
<L>&amp; he sad: "&yogh;his, &yogh;eit forow Criste</L>
<L>Ve sal eft met in his bewiste</L>
<L N="845">&amp; bruk vith hyme ay-lestand bli&szlig;.</L>
<L>Bot, dere fadir, I pray &thorn;e &thorn;us,</L>
<L>For ded nerhand abidis me</L>
<L>To tak: fra I be gane fra &thorn;e,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;u wald, eftir I be dede,</L>
<L N="850">Ger bring my body to &thorn;is stede</L>
<L>&amp; ger It grawine be, quhar I</L>
<L>Had mad my duelling Ithandly."</L>
<L>And he heicht hyme he suld do swa.</L>
<L>Atheris &thorn;ar lewe with &thorn;at cane ta.</L>
<L N="855">And Dewinick cane to Catnes pa&szlig;,</L>
<L>To folk &thorn;at &thorn;ane wntreuchtfull wa&szlig;,</L>
<L>And sped sa weile in schort tyme &thorn;are</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;aime parfit in godis lare</L>
<L>He mad. bot &yogh;et &thorn;ane sanct Machor</L>
<L N="860">Furth prechit, as he did befor,</L>
<L>The Poyictis, &amp; swa sped &thorn;at he</L>
<L>Gert mast part of &thorn;aime cristinit be,</L>
<L>&amp; namely he gert master-mene</L>
<L>Trew, &thorn;at wntreuchfull war to &thorn;ane;</L>
<L N="865">Bath thru &thorn;e lare he cane &thorn;aime lere</L>
<L>And thru schauyng of merwalis sere.</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;ar templis distroyt wyd-quhare,</L>
<L>And ydolis &thorn;at in-to &thorn;aime ware.</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;usgat lang tyme trawalyt he</L>
<L N="870">Of goddis corne wynnare to be.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Syne tyd o&ntilde;e a tyme to gang<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. o&ntilde;e = onne?</NOTE></L>
<L>Apone &thorn;e feild his corne ymange:</L>
<L>And saw a bare mekill &amp; gret</L>
<L>Defoull &thorn;e corne with feit &amp; ete,</L>
<L N="875">&amp; do gret skath. &amp; &thorn;ane sad he:</L>
<L>"In goddis name I commawnd &thorn;e</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;u in &thorn;at sted stand still."</L>
<L>&amp; ono&ntilde;e sanct Machor come hyme till</L>
<L>And strak hyme with his staif o&ntilde;ane:</L>
<L N="880">And he sowne turnyt till a stane,</L>
<L>And in &thorn;at schape sa standis he,</L>
<L>A &yogh;ard-stane, as mene &yogh;eit ma se.&mdash;</L>
<L>Syne Machor come in a place</L>
<L>And saw a mane &thorn;at mykill vas</L>
<L N="885">&amp; in &thorn;at cuntre duelling mad,</L>
<L>&amp; to his richt name Dinone had,</L>
<L>&amp; was payene &amp; rycht crafty</L>
<L>In sendis warkis &amp; sorcery:</L>
<L>And he wald oftymys ger mene vene</L>
<L N="890">&THORN;at sewine hedis one hyme had bene.</L>
<L>And quhene sanct Machor sene hyme had,
<PB REF="00000338.tif" N="200"></L>
<L>He ferlyt first, &amp; syne but bad</L>
<L>A psalme he sad begynnand &thorn;us</L>
<L>Of scriptur: Exurgat deus.</L>
<L N="895">&amp; or he of &thorn;at psalme mad end,</L>
<L>Thru goddis mycht It wes well kend</L>
<L>&THORN;at he na hedis had but ane.</L>
<L>For-&thorn;i &thorn;at tyrand, or he fane,</L>
<L>Of sanct Machor fell to &thorn;e fet</L>
<L N="900">&amp; for his sonnis sare cane gret,<NOTE PLACE="foot">sonnes = sinnis.</NOTE></L>
<L>Prayand hyme for goddis sak</L>
<L>&THORN;at he wald cristine mane hyme mak.</L>
<L>&amp; he sad hyme: with-&thorn;i &thorn;at he</L>
<L>Wald lewe his sorcery &amp; be</L>
<L N="905">Gud cristine mane &amp; cristine fay</L>
<L>Fra-&thorn;ine furth treuli kep alvay:</L>
<L>Anentis god he suld hyme wyne</L>
<L>Forgiffnes of his mykill syne.</L>
<L>&amp; he hicht &thorn;at with full gud will</L>
<L N="910">All haill his byding till fulfill.</L>
<L>&amp; sanct Machor gert hyme nocht-&thorn;ane</L>
<L>Resawe baptyme &amp; swa hyme wane,</L>
<L>&amp; tacht hyme weill in cristine fay,</L>
<L>&amp; leit hyme syne pas hyne his vay.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="915">Ane vthir tyme sanct Machor &yogh;ed</L>
<L>Prechand &amp; sawand godis sed,</L>
<L>Mene brocht a mane &thorn;at was blind-borne,</L>
<L>&amp; seit hyme sanct Machor beforne</L>
<L>&amp; prayt hyme ful fare &thorn;at he</L>
<L N="920">Thru his prayere wald gere hyme se.</L>
<L>&amp; he, &thorn;at reucht ay in hert had,</L>
<L>Tuk wattir &amp; blissit it but bad</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;are-with-all ennoyntit richt &thorn;ane</L>
<L>Oure-corce &thorn;e eyne of &thorn;at blind mane</L>
<L N="925">&amp; sad till hyme: "luk vpe and se!"</L>
<L>&amp; as he bad, richt swa did he:</L>
<L>&amp; saw als clerly all-kine thinge</L>
<L>As he of sicht had neuir merring,</L>
<L>&amp; he, &thorn;at na tyme saw befor,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. styme.</NOTE></L>
<L N="930">Saw &thorn;ane, &amp; lowyt sanct Machor,</L>
<L>Quhame thru &thorn;e sicht god swa hyme gefe.</L>
<L>&amp; one &thorn;e same did &thorn;e laiffe</L>
<L>&THORN;at saw or herd &thorn;is gret ferly,</L>
<L>&YOGH;auld thank to god full increly.</L>
<L N="935">Ane vthir tyme, as he cane stand</L>
<L>Goddis word to folk prechand</L>
<L>&THORN;at stud a-bout hyme in-virroune,</L>
<L>Mene brocht a dede cors ovt of tovne</L>
<L>&amp; lad It done befor his feite,</L>
<L N="940">With lamentacione and greite,</L>
<L>&amp; Synchenus to name he had.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. Syncheng?</NOTE></L>
<L>Sanct Machor &thorn;ane speryt but bad</L>
<L>Quhene &thorn;at he was, or of quhat kine.</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;ai per ordir tald till hyme,</L>
<L N="945">&amp; als, &thorn;at he of kine was nere</L>
<L>To gud sanct Colme, to god sa dere.</L>
<L>&amp; fra sanct Machor &thorn;at herd tell,</L>
<L>Apone his kneis sone he fell</L>
<L>&amp; prayt till god o&ntilde;e sic a wyse</L>
<L N="950">&THORN;at at ded mane lof &amp; cane ryse.</L>
<L>&amp; swa with prooff of mychtfull dede<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. prooff?</NOTE></L>
<L>He strinthit alvay godis sede,</L>
<L>&amp; ferleis wrocht he &thorn;ane sa feile</L>
<L>&THORN;at he mad mony payene leile,</L>
<L N="955">For he to &thorn;aime was sic myrroure</L>
<L>&THORN;at he gert &thorn;aime leif &thorn;are erroure.</L>
<L>God grant ws grace &thorn;at we do swa,</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;is lyff or &thorn;at we ga!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Off &thorn;is sanct Machor &thorn;e fame rane</L>
<L N="960">Thru sere land till full mony mane,</L>
<L>Of ferleis &thorn;at thru hyme god wrocht.</L>
<L>For &thorn;at of syndry landis mene hyme socht,</L>
<L>For-to purches his benysone<MILESTONE N="202" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And haf of hyme instruccione.</L>
<L N="965">Amang vthire twa of Irland</L>
<L>&THORN;at herd tell of hyme tythand,</L>
<L>&amp; &yogh;ung, sume-dele lettryt ware,</L>
<L>Till hyme sa besely cane spere</L>
<L>And socht sa lang, til &thorn;ai hyme fand</L>
<L N="970">Quhare I sad are, in-to Scotlond,</L>
<L>&YOGH;arnand till haf instruccione</L>
<L>Of hyme and informacione,</L>
<L>&amp; how &thorn;ai suld haly wryt</L>
<L>Wndirstand and vndo It.</L>
<L N="975">&amp; he resawit &thorn;amme full weile</L>
<L>&amp; all &thorn;are &yogh;arnyng ilke dele</L>
<L>He tyd &thorn;ame &amp; full sobirly<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. tyd st. cyd?</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000339.tif" N="201"></L>
<L>Enformyt &thorn;aime, full parfytly,</L>
<L>Of cristine treucht, of lyf &amp; sall</L>
<L N="980">Ay laste, &amp; of sawle-heile with-all,</L>
<L>&amp; mony vthir spedfull thing.</L>
<L>Bot he in &thorn;ame tint his techig:<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. tint od. ruit? scheint runt.</NOTE></L>
<L>For, fra &thorn;at &thorn;ai &thorn;are leif had tane,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai na tyme for to scorne hyme fane,</L>
<L N="985">&amp; his lare and amonesting</L>
<L>&THORN;ai sad was richt nocht but hethig,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;are-with callit hyme ypocriyt.</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;ane reuengit was full tyt:</L>
<L>For nocht fere &thorn;ine in-till a sted</L>
<L N="990">Suddanly &thorn;ai ware all deide</L>
<L>&amp; schot in-till (a) gong stinkand,<NOTE PLACE="foot">gong latrina, lacuna.</NOTE></L>
<L>Quhar nane of freyndis &thorn;aime sand.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>I(t) hapnyt a tyme in-to Ware,</L>
<L>Quhill sanct Machor was du(e)lland &thorn;are,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. dulland.</NOTE></L>
<L N="995">&THORN;at he for faut of weile-tyd land<NOTE PLACE="foot">l. sand? Ms. land.</NOTE></L>
<L>Gert teile a mekill feild of land</L>
<L>&amp;, &thorn;ocht It was leyne and dry,</L>
<L>He socht to saw &thorn;are bare &amp; ry,</L>
<L>In goddis larges, assouerand,</L>
<L N="1000">&THORN;at it suld grow weile in &thorn;at land.</L>
<L>Nocht-&thorn;ane his seruandis had ferly</L>
<L>&THORN;at he gert teile ald land &amp; dry,</L>
<L>&amp; namely, for &thorn;ai west but dred</L>
<L>To saw &thorn;at land he had no sede.</L>
<L N="1005">&THORN;ane he sad to &thorn;aime &thorn;at swa thocht:</L>
<L>"God is mychty to helpe &mdash; dred nocht &mdash;</L>
<L>Quhar mane na liklines ma se."</L>
<L>To twa of his prenteis sad he:</L>
<L>"Hald &yogh;oure gat to my lord Ternane,</L>
<L N="1010">Sa hyme: for sede haf I nane</L>
<L>Quhar-with my feilde &thorn;at I saw may,</L>
<L>Hyme in-to sic distres I pray</L>
<L>At he at &thorn;is tyme wald help me</L>
<L N="1014">Of his seide with sic quantite."</L>
<L>. . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inter"><B>Hier fehlt 1 Blatt im Ms.</B> . . . . .<MILESTONE N="202" UNIT="folio"></NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at a gret bane of it rycht tyt</L>
<L>In-till his thrort clewit sa faste,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he to de was sare agaste,</L>
<L>For he mycht swely it for na slicht</L>
<L N="1200">Na out till put it had na mycht.</L>
<L>&THORN;ane was &thorn;at wrecche wondir wa,</L>
<L>Persawand weile he was sted swa:</L>
<L>For he tholit in-till &thorn;at houre</L>
<L>Lyk to &thorn;e dede mony herd schure.</L>
<L N="1205">&amp; alswa had he schame to tell</L>
<L>Quhy he &thorn;at fische, to &thorn;e tend fell,</L>
<L>For his delit had etene &thorn;ane,</L>
<L>&THORN;at acht was to &thorn;at haly mane.</L>
<L>&YOGH;eit &thorn;ane with quaquand voice sad he</L>
<L N="1210">To &thorn;aime &thorn;at vare is maste priwe:</L>
<L>"To me, &thorn;at sted is in &thorn;is wath,</L>
<L>Yhone goddis mane &yogh;e bring me rath!</L>
<L>For I will grant hyme but delay</L>
<L>&THORN;e thing quharfor he cane me pray."</L>
<L N="1215">His meng&yogh;e &thorn;ane foroutine more</L>
<L>Passit and brocht hyme sanct Machor.</L>
<L>Fra quhame he askit forgewine,</L>
<L>&amp; he had nytit hyme his askine;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. &amp; = if.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;ar-for mekly prayt he</L>
<L N="1220">&THORN;at he wald (help) of his pitte;<NOTE PLACE="foot">help fehlt.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;at erth &thorn;at he askit hade</L>
<L>He gaf hyme &thorn;are but langer bade.</L>
<L>Sanct Machor blissit hyme one-ane:</L>
<L>Out of his hals &thorn;ane lape &thorn;e bane,</L>
<L N="1225">&amp; he mad haile als smertly was</L>
<L>As mane &thorn;at neuir weste of seknes.</L>
<L>Sanct Machor &thorn;ane mesuryt &thorn;e place,</L>
<L>&THORN;at lang &amp; brad &amp; richt plane was,</L>
<L>And in a litill tyme gert wirk</L>
<L N="1230">Of treis fare a cumly kirk. &mdash;</L>
<L>&amp; quha-sa reddis &thorn;us, ma see</L>
<L>How besy &thorn;at gudmene suld be</L>
<L>For-till obeis in althing</L>
<L>Of haly mene to &thorn;e bidding,</L>
<L N="1235">&amp; namely and one alkine wise</L>
<L>Quhar it twechis godis seruice.</L>
<L>For, lo, he &thorn;at litill before</L>
<L>Mad rud answare to sanct Machor</L>
<L>Thru priyd &amp; awaris gnedy,</L>
<L N="1240">And goddis mane dispituisly</L>
<L>Fra his presens chasit away,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. <ABBR>pns</ABBR> = presens od. provins?</NOTE></L>
<L>Is now ful fayne hyme forto pray
<PB REF="00000340.tif" N="202"></L>
<L>&amp; spek ful reuerendly hyme till</L>
<L>&amp; als to grant hyme all his will. &mdash;</L>
<L N="1245">&THORN;is is litill of It we rede</L>
<L>Of sant Machor his mykill dede</L>
<L>&amp; of &thorn;e merwalis &thorn;at he wrocht,</L>
<L>To Pectis land fra &thorn;at he socht:</L>
<L>For I cane nocht &thorn;e teynd part tell</L>
<L N="1250">Of gret ferleis &thorn;at thru hyme fell.</L>
<L>Bot gyf &thorn;at I say suthfastly,</L>
<L>It was nocht thru hyme anerly,</L>
<L>Bot god was &thorn;e mychty makare</L>
<L>&amp; sanct Machor &thorn;e furth schewere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1255">Sanct Machor &thorn;ane set all his wit</L>
<L>To cune parfitly haly writ,</L>
<L>&THORN;ocht &thorn;at he &thorn;ar parfit was<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. &thorn;ar st. &thorn;arin.</NOTE></L>
<L>Thru plentwis gyft of goddis grace.</L>
<L>In-till his study sait a day,</L>
<L N="1260">Quhene ane come &amp; cane till hyme say</L>
<L>"Syre, sanct Ternane, &thorn;e bischope nere,</L>
<L>Is cumyne to spek with &yogh;ou here,</L>
<L>&amp; of his clerkis gret party."</L>
<L>Sanct Machor &thorn;ane with gret hy</L>
<L N="1265">Left &thorn;e study &amp; &thorn;e buk,</L>
<L>&amp; of his clerkis with hyme tuk,</L>
<L>And met sanct Ternane reuerendly</L>
<L>And halist hyme &amp; his cumpany;</L>
<L>&amp; he hailsit hyme aganes his,</L>
<L N="1270">&THORN;ane cane athir wthire kis.</L>
<L>&amp; sanct Machor till his herbry</L>
<L>Sanct Ternane leid full reuerendly,</L>
<L>&amp; firste in kirk entrit &thorn;ai bath</L>
<L>&amp; to &thorn;are vrisone went rath,</L>
<L N="1275">&amp; syne &thorn;ai blissit athir wthire,</L>
<L>&THORN;e bischope first &amp; syne &thorn;e tothire;</L>
<L>Syne eftire all &thorn;e cumpany</L>
<L>Has kissit entrechangeably.</L>
<L>&amp; he &thorn;ane &thorn;ame resawit had,</L>
<L N="1280">A schort sermone full wisly mad</L>
<L>Of paciens &amp; cherite,</L>
<L>Recommendand humilite.</L>
<L>Syne eftire, as &thorn;e custume was,</L>
<L>He led hyme quhar he suld tak ese,</L>
<L N="1285">&amp; mad hyme mery forto fare,</L>
<L>&amp; als &thorn;ame all &thorn;at with hyme ware.<MILESTONE N="203" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Sanct Machor &thorn;ane full gret Joy made</L>
<L>&THORN;at he sa dere worthy gaste hade,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;e bischope full fane &thorn;at wane</L>
<L N="1290">&THORN;e knawlage of sa haly mane.</L>
<L>&THORN;ane held &thorn;ai wele lang sermonyng</L>
<L>Of haly lyf &amp; hewinlik thing;</L>
<L>&amp; till &thorn;at &thorn;ai sait at &thorn;e burd,</L>
<L>Amang &thorn;aime wes nane vthire word</L>
<L N="1295">Bot fed &thorn;aime self with gastly fud</L>
<L>&amp; gaynand drink &thorn;are-to &amp; gud.</L>
<L>&THORN;ane come to &thorn;aime gret company</L>
<L>Of deuot mene, &thorn;at encrely</L>
<L>Requiryt &thorn;aime with awisment:<NOTE PLACE="foot">with st. of?</NOTE></L>
<L N="1300">&THORN;at &thorn;ai with goddis Jugment<NOTE PLACE="foot">with st. of?</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e priwete mare opynly</L>
<L>Wald expone &thorn;aime &amp; expresly.</L>
<L>&THORN;e bischope &thorn;ane wondrit was</L>
<L>Of &thorn;are wnwit &amp; simpilnes,</L>
<L N="1305">Sad to &thorn;ame: "my childere dere,</L>
<L>&THORN;is demand &thorn;at &yogh;e askis ws here</L>
<L>Is a demawnd with-out profyt.</L>
<L>For quhat mane is he sa parfyt</L>
<L>&THORN;at cane tell godis priuete,</L>
<L N="1310">&THORN;at be na way ma witine be?</L>
<L>Na manis wit ma strek &thorn;artill</L>
<L>To consawe it thru kindly skill</L>
<L>&THORN;at he in-till his forseyng</L>
<L>Reseruit till his awne witting.</L>
<L N="1315">&amp; &thorn;arefor rycht gret foly is</L>
<L>To &yogh;ou to spere or tret of &thorn;is."</L>
<L>Sanct Machor als &thorn;at &thorn;aime cane smyll,</L>
<L>Sayand: "a wismane sad wmquhill:</L>
<L>Sek na heyere thing &thorn;ane yhe</L>
<L N="1320">Na stallowart, be na degre!</L>
<L>For quha is, goddis wit ma knaw</L>
<L>Or &yogh;it his consall hey or law?</L>
<L>For godis priue dome ma nocht<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. deme.</NOTE></L>
<L>Na all his gattis &yogh;et be socht.</L>
<L N="1325">For&thorn;i full gret foly it is</L>
<L>To spere &thorn;at manis wit excedis,</L>
<L>Or for-till haf of It k(n)awine<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. kawine.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at he ma cume to for na thing.</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;arfor lewe forthir to spere</L>
<L N="1330">&THORN;e thing &thorn;at &yogh;e ma neuir nicht nere!<NOTE PLACE="foot">nicht = nigh.</NOTE></L>
<L>For sperer of his maieste
<PB REF="00000341.tif" N="203"></L>
<L>Fra his Joy sall doune thrungine be."</L>
<L>&amp; all &thorn;a &thorn;at &thorn;is demaund mad</L>
<L>Stud &thorn;ane stane-still &amp; gret schame had.</L>
<L N="1335">Sone eftir &thorn;is &thorn;ai ras ilkane</L>
<L>&amp; lewid, to &thorn;are awne ar gane,</L>
<L>&amp; with euire commone blissing</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ai mad &thorn;at haly departing.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Nocht lang eftire apone a day</L>
<L N="1340">(To) sanct Machor a mane cane say:<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. Of st. To.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at sanct Dewynnik In-to Catnes</L>
<L>Thru gret eilde fal&yogh;eit &amp; ded was;</L>
<L>"&amp; quhene he o&ntilde;e his dedstra lay,</L>
<L>To &thorn;aime &thorn;at nest war he cane say:</L>
<L N="1345">" "Sene &thorn;at &yogh;e se ded sall me tak,</L>
<L>I coniure &yogh;ou for godis sak</L>
<L>&THORN;at yhe for na trawall be Irke</L>
<L>To bere my body to sume kirk,</L>
<L>Quharfor sanct Machor has keping,</L>
<L N="1350">&amp; pray hyme for &thorn;e hewynnis king</L>
<L>&THORN;at he meyne one &amp; thochtfull be</L>
<L>Of his hicht &thorn;at he mad to me</L>
<L>Of his gud will at our partyng.'"</L>
<L>With &thorn;is of spek he mad ending</L>
<L N="1355">&amp; &yogh;aulde &thorn;e gast but mare abad.</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;ai &thorn;at &thorn;is commawndment had,</L>
<L>To tak his body war nocht Irk</L>
<L>&amp; one a bere brocht till a kirk</L>
<L>&THORN;at was bot litill fra &thorn;at place</L>
<L N="1360">&THORN;at befor to &thorn;aime lentyne was."<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. lentynd.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; quhene &thorn;at sanct Machor &thorn;is tale</L>
<L>Has herd as I haf tald &yogh;<SUP>u</SUP> hale,</L>
<L>He mad regrat &amp; had disese.</L>
<L>Bot, for he durst nocht god disples,</L>
<L N="1365">&THORN;at nycht but slepe all haile he lay</L>
<L>In his prayere, till it wes day:</L>
<L>&amp; in &thorn;at kirk with fleschely eyne</L>
<L>Full feile brycht angelis he has sene</L>
<L>Fle vpe &amp; doune, makand &thorn;aire play,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. &thorn;aime.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1370">Quhar at &thorn;e cors of Dewynnik lay.</L>
<L>&THORN;ane was sanct Machor blyth &amp; glad</L>
<L>For &thorn;is fare sicht &thorn;at he sene had.</L>
<L>&amp; one &thorn;e morne quhene it was day,</L>
<L>Till his discipulis &thorn;is cane say:</L>
<L N="1375">"Lowe we all god, my bro&thorn;ir dere,</L>
<L>&THORN;at has ws send a gud gestenere!<MILESTONE N="204" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;arfor mak we ws redy tyt</L>
<L>Hyme, as a spe afferis, to visidte</L>
<L>&amp; &yogh;eld till hyme forout delay</L>
<L N="1380">&THORN;at office &thorn;at ws acht to say</L>
<L>For worthi mene, quhene &thorn;ai ded are!"</L>
<L>With &thorn;at &thorn;ai passit furthmare</L>
<L>To &thorn;e kirk quhar at sanct Machor</L>
<L>&THORN;e angelis play had sene befor.</L>
<L N="1385">Bot &thorn;ai &thorn;at &thorn;e cors brocht &thorn;iddire,</L>
<L>with It had gane &thorn;ar way to-giddir</L>
<L>Ner-by of Creskane to &thorn;e hill,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;ar abad, to reste in will.</L>
<L>Bot sanct Machor foroutyne firste<NOTE PLACE="foot">firste = friste.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1390">Folouit &amp; fand &thorn;aime &thorn;ar tak reste.</L>
<L>&amp; he &amp; his &thorn;ar with &thorn;ame abad,</L>
<L>Till &thorn;ai &thorn;e seruice all had mad</L>
<L>&THORN;at to sic deide mene suld parteyne,</L>
<L>Ar ony wink come in &thorn;ar eyne.</L>
<L N="1395">&amp; syne bare &thorn;e cors deuotely</L>
<L>Till a place callit Banchory.</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;are solempni with honoure</L>
<L>&THORN;ai grathit for it a sepulture,</L>
<L>&amp; one hyme &thorn;are &thorn;ai mad a kirk.</L>
<L N="1400">Quhar god &yogh;eit cesis nocht to wirk</L>
<L>Thru his prayere ferleis full fele,</L>
<L>To sek and sar folk gyfand heile.</L>
<L>Mene callis &thorn;at place quar he lay</L>
<L>Banchory Dewynnik till &thorn;is day.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Diese Kirche, Banchory-Dewynnik, liegt nahe bei Aberdeen.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1405">Syne eftir &thorn;is tyme It befell</L>
<L>&THORN;at fra sanct Colme quar he cane duell,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. fra sanct Colme st. sanct Colme fra.</NOTE></L>
<L>In Scotland come, because &thorn;at he</L>
<L>As pilgerame thocht at Rome to be.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. pilgerame mit &uuml;berschrieb. e.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; fra sanct Machor had witting</L>
<L N="1410">In-to &thorn;e land of his cumyng,</L>
<L>He fane nocht quhill he with hyme met.</L>
<L>&amp; athire of &thorn;ame for Ioy gret:</L>
<L>&THORN;ai war sa fane &thorn;at &thorn;ai met were.</L>
<L>Sanct Machor &thorn;ane at hyme cane spere,</L>
<L N="1415">In pilgrimag gif he wald pas</L>
<L>To Rome, as till hyme tald was.</L>
<L>&amp; he sad &yogh;a. &amp; sanct Machor
<PB REF="00000342.tif" N="204"></L>
<L>&THORN;ane blithar (was) &thorn;en euir befor,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. &thorn;ane st. was.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; sad: "with &yogh;our leif, faddire dere,</L>
<L N="1420">&YOGH;e sall nocht pas &amp; lewe me here.</L>
<L>For-&thorn;i, sire, graunt me &yogh;our gud will!"</L>
<L>&amp; he consentit sone hyme till.</L>
<L>&THORN;ane but abad &thorn;ai mad &thorn;aime &yogh;are,</L>
<L>&amp; all thing &thorn;at was necessare</L>
<L N="1425">For &thorn;are passing, &thorn;ai mad redy,</L>
<L>&amp; held &thorn;are gat in cumpany.</L>
<L>Bot It ware langsume for-to say</L>
<L>The wondir &thorn;at god in &thorn;e way</L>
<L>Wrocht for &thorn;ame, or &thorn;ai come to Rome,</L>
<L N="1430">For &thorn;ai exced all manis dowme.</L>
<L>Bot at &thorn;e last with swink &amp; swet</L>
<L>Hiddir &thorn;ai come, &amp; trawall gret,</L>
<L>&amp; wisit first Petir &amp; Paule,</L>
<L>Quhare pardone is &amp; heile of saule,</L>
<L N="1435">&amp; socht syne wthir placis sere</L>
<L>Quhar feile was to god full dere.</L>
<L>Of haly kirk &thorn;e cure had tane</L>
<L>A paipe of Rome, a master-mane,</L>
<L>Gregor, &thorn;at was of gret renovne</L>
<L N="1440">&amp; of haly opunyone.</L>
<L>&THORN;e quhilk quhene he had herd &thorn;at &thorn;ai</L>
<L>War cumyne &thorn;ar, but mare delay</L>
<L>He send for &thorn;aime full reuerendly</L>
<L>&amp; gert &thorn;aime cume till hyme in hy.</L>
<L N="1445">&amp; &thorn;ame resawit as his dere</L>
<L>Richt tenderly &amp; with gud chere,</L>
<L>&amp; syne full mykill sperit he</L>
<L>&THORN;e cause quhy &amp; of sa fere cuntre</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ai come &thorn;ar. &amp; &thorn;ai alsone</L>
<L N="1450">With schort spek has &thorn;e cause vndone,</L>
<L>Sayand: "&thorn;e cause of &thorn;is trawall</L>
<L>&THORN;at we haf tane one hand, but fale</L>
<L>Is for-to wyne lestand remede</L>
<L>Till our sawlis eftire our dede.</L>
<L N="1455">Ane wthir cause als haf we eke:</L>
<L>Petire &amp; Paule here for-to seke</L>
<L>&amp; mony wthir in &thorn;is stede,</L>
<L>For godis sak &thorn;at tholit dede;</L>
<L>&amp; for-till haf &yogh;oure benysone</L>
<L N="1460">&amp; &yogh;oure gud informacione".</L>
<L>The pape sanct Machor &thorn;ane cane call</L>
<L>Till hyme &amp; of &thorn;e Pectis all</L>
<L>Mad bischope for his tyme to be.</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;are-with his name changit he</L>
<L N="1465">And callit hyme Morise, &thorn;at befor</L>
<L>Llang tyme to name had Machor &mdash;<MILESTONE N="205" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&amp; swa as he had namys thre:</L>
<L>Mocumna first in his cunctre,</L>
<L>&amp; syne Machor, in-to &thorn;e land</L>
<L N="1470">Of Pectis quhill he was duelland.</L>
<L>&THORN;e pape sanct Gregor &thorn;ar-with-all</L>
<L>A-pone a day till hyme cane call</L>
<L>&amp; informyt hyme sowne &amp; weile</L>
<L>In all &thorn;e office ilke deile</L>
<L N="1475">&THORN;at suld parteyne to bischapis stat,</L>
<L>&amp; mekly sad hyme syne &thorn;is-gat:</L>
<L>"Lo, bruthir &amp; in Criste sone dere,</L>
<L>Thru wescheyng of our handis here,</L>
<L>&THORN;e haly gast als callit &thorn;e,</L>
<L N="1480">Of bischape to &thorn;e dignite</L>
<L>&THORN;at is schosine &amp; to &thorn;e hicht:</L>
<L>Trawale &thorn;at for all thi mycht</L>
<L>In goddis wyne-&yogh;arde forto vyne</L>
<L>Feile folk &thorn;at bundine ar with syne!</L>
<L N="1485">&THORN;e wark of wangeliste &thorn;u do</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;e office, &thorn;at is &thorn;e to</L>
<L>Committit, fulfill ilke day,</L>
<L>&amp; vnreprofit kepe &thorn;e ay,</L>
<L>&amp; gaynand &amp; vnchangeabili,</L>
<L N="1490">As &thorn;u se ned is, &thorn;u chasty,</L>
<L>In pacience argw, and pray</L>
<L>&amp; in doctrine be besy ay!"</L>
<L>&amp; quhene &thorn;e pape one &thorn;is-kine wise</L>
<L>Had weile informyt sanct Morise</L>
<L N="1495">&amp; blissit hyme &amp; sanct Colme bath,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai tuk &thorn;are leif &amp; sped &thorn;aime rath</L>
<L>Towart &thorn;ar cunctre for-to gang.</L>
<L>&amp; one &thorn;ar way trawalit sa lang</L>
<L>&amp; ythandly, or &thorn;ai wald fyne,</L>
<L N="1500">Till &thorn;ai, quhar sanct Martyne<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. Till &thorn;ai come quhar.</NOTE></L>
<L>Lyis, war cumyne apone chaunce,</L>
<L>To Torone, to &thorn;e tovne of France.</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;are &thorn;e bischope of &thorn;at stede</L>
<L>Vith his clergy met &thorn;aime &amp; leide</L>
<L N="1505">In-to &thorn;e cite ful reuerendly,
<PB REF="00000343.tif" N="205"></L>
<L>&amp; purwayt for &thorn;aime gud herbry</L>
<L>&amp; gert fynd &thorn;aime, till &thorn;ai war &thorn;are,</L>
<L>All &thorn;at to &thorn;aime was necessare.</L>
<L>For god has schauyt hyme &thorn;at &thorn;ai</L>
<L N="1510">War thankfull seruandis till hyme ay.</L>
<L>For-&thorn;i &thorn;e tyme &thorn;at &thorn;ai duelt &thorn;are</L>
<L>He did &thorn;ame honor fer &thorn;e mare,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. fer od. for?</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; did his mycht with full gud will</L>
<L>To gere &thorn;ame bath duell with hyme still.</L>
<L N="1515">Bot sanct Colme, &thorn;at wald na-wa be</L>
<L>For na requeste fra his cunctre,</L>
<L>His wayag hamewart tuk in hy:</L>
<L>&THORN;ane of &thorn;e cite &thorn;e clergy</L>
<L>Full increly mad hyme requeste:</L>
<L N="1520">Sene &thorn;at he duell nocht wald, at &thorn;e leste</L>
<L>&THORN;at he wald thole ane of his &thorn;are</L>
<L>Duell, for-to preche goddis lare.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Thane was sanct Colme full gretumly</L>
<L>Abaisit, &amp; his cumpany,</L>
<L N="1525">&amp;, haffand ferly, held &thorn;ame still.</L>
<L>Bot sanct Morise of goddis will</L>
<L>Sad till his master: "fadire dere,</L>
<L>Quhat-euire it be &thorn;at in &thorn;is were</L>
<L>&THORN;at quhemfull be to &yogh;ou to do,</L>
<L N="1530">As god hyme-selfe has sad ws to</L>
<L>It sall be done, I sa be me,</L>
<L>How paynefull or how hard It be".</L>
<L>"&amp; &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP>, qua&thorn; he to sanct Morise,</L>
<L>Blissit be ay, &amp; now blissit is:</L>
<L N="1535">For-&thorn;i with Martyne &amp; with me</L>
<L>Sall hewynlik are &amp; falow be<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. are = heir.</NOTE></L>
<L>In hewynnis blis&szlig;, quhene &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> art dede.</L>
<L>Bot &yogh;et sall &thorn;u duell in &thorn;is stede</L>
<L>Thre &yogh;ere, in godis corne to wirk</L>
<L N="1540">&amp; strenth and comfort haly kirk.</L>
<L>&THORN;arefor strywe furth ay stalouartly</L>
<L>For-to confund oure ennymy,</L>
<L>&amp; with preching &amp; techyne wyne</L>
<L>Fra hyme &thorn;at he hankis in syne,</L>
<L N="1545">&amp; in gud wark &thorn;i cur&szlig; fulfill,</L>
<L>Quhill god in hewine &thorn;e tak hyme till</L>
<L>&amp; of richtwisnes &thorn;i full far crowne</L>
<L>&THORN;e giff in hewine to &thorn;i werdoune".</L>
<L>&amp; quhene he &thorn;us had sad &amp; mare,</L>
<L N="1550">But bad he buskit hyme to fare.</L>
<L>Bot sanct Morise, &thorn;at was ful wa</L>
<L>For-to depart his mastere fra:</L>
<L>To ger hyme duell a wile, cane lay</L>
<L>His hand one hyme &amp; &thorn;usgat say:</L>
<L N="1555">"My dere fadire, quhat, thinkis &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP></L>
<L>As alyene to leff me now</L>
<L>Ymang vnknawine mene &amp; swa<MILESTONE N="206" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;i way in-to &thorn;i cunctre ga,</L>
<L>Or but lewe and &thorn;e benysone</L>
<L N="1560">Of sanct Martyne pas of towne?</L>
<L>It was nocht spedfull be na way".</L>
<L>&THORN;ane cane his maister till hyme say:</L>
<L>"Dere sone, suppos &thorn;at I hame fare,</L>
<L>Forsuth &thorn;e lewe sall I neuir-mare.</L>
<L N="1565">Bot god &thorn;is place has grathit &thorn;e</L>
<L>&YOGH;et all thire thre &yogh;ere in to be,</L>
<L>&amp; eftir of &thorn;at curs &thorn;e stryff</L>
<L>To hafe reward &amp; lestand lyffe.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. ho st. to.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bot &yogh;et, &thorn;i &yogh;arnyng till fulfill,</L>
<L N="1570">We will ga now &thorn;e bischope till</L>
<L>&amp; ask of new his benysone</L>
<L>&amp; leife, &thorn;at I ma pa&szlig; of towne".</L>
<L>&THORN;e bischope rase &thorn;ane &amp; hyme met</L>
<L>&amp; tuk hyme &amp; by hym set,</L>
<L N="1575">&amp; fandit giff he ger hyme mocht</L>
<L>Leif his purpos &amp; chang his thocht;</L>
<L>Bot he mycht nocht for na-kyne thing</L>
<L>Ger hyme leif purpos na etling.</L>
<L>With &thorn;at &thorn;e nycht come: &amp; &thorn;at auld,</L>
<L N="1580">&THORN;at for na prayere &thorn;ane duell wald,</L>
<L>Tuk leif &amp; haile &thorn;e benysone</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e bischope, &amp; mad hyme bowne</L>
<L>In sanct Martynis kirk to walk<NOTE PLACE="foot">walk = wak; lk st. k ist Eigenth&uuml;mlichkeit schott. Mss.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; fulfill clergy for his sak.</L>
<L N="1585">&amp; all &thorn;e nycht in prayer lay</L>
<L>Befor &thorn;e fertire to &thorn;e day.</L>
<L>&amp;, as mene sais, &thorn;at nycht but were</L>
<L>To sanct Colme walkand cane apere<NOTE PLACE="foot">walk = wak; lk st. k ist Eigenth&uuml;mlichkeit schott. Mss.</NOTE></L>
<L>Sanct Martyne suthfully &amp; bad</L>
<L N="1590">Llang tyme and spekyne with hyme mad,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;ar &thorn;e buk of &thorn;e wangele</L>
<L>&THORN;at in &thorn;e grawe was lad sume-quhyle
<PB REF="00000344.tif" N="206"></L>
<L>Besyd hyme, quhar he grawine was,</L>
<L>He gef hyme frely in &thorn;at place:</L>
<L N="1595">&THORN;e quhilk all his lyftyme held he</L>
<L>As a relik in gret daynte</L>
<L>&amp; left It, quhene he cane disses&szlig;,</L>
<L>In-till his kirk, as resone was.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Thane one &thorn;e morne, quhene it was day,</L>
<L N="1600">He buskit hyme to gang his way</L>
<L>But langar howne till his land,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. but langar but.</NOTE></L>
<L>To Martyne hyme recommendand.</L>
<L>&THORN;ane folouyt hyme out of &thorn;e towne</L>
<L>A fer way with processione</L>
<L N="1605">Sanct Morise, with gret cumpany</L>
<L>Of lawide mene and of clergy;</L>
<L>&amp; sa partyt, &thorn;ocht &thorn;ai war lath,</L>
<L>With oft blissing &amp; regrat bath &mdash;</L>
<L>For it is a full noyus thing</L>
<L N="1610">Of dere frendis &thorn;e departynge.</L>
<L>Quhene day was gane &amp; It was nycht,</L>
<L>&THORN;e bischope of &thorn;e place hyme dycht</L>
<L>To slepe: &amp; sanct Martyne but were</L>
<L>Till hyme slepand &thorn;ar cane apere</L>
<L N="1615">&amp; sad till hyme: "lof god in hicht</L>
<L>&amp; blissis hyme with all &yogh;our mycht</L>
<L>&amp; he is name of alkine wyse,<NOTE PLACE="foot">he erh&ouml;hen.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; trew: his seruand sanct Morise</L>
<L>Has visit &yogh;ou and throu his grace</L>
<L N="1620">Benefice has ekit to &thorn;e place.</L>
<L>For-&thorn;i of Twrane &thorn;e cite</L>
<L>May mak Ioy als &amp; blith be,</L>
<L>&THORN;at sanct Morise yhone patrone</L>
<L>Has gottine, &amp; me, to helpe &yogh;one llone.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. llone (= lane Flecken) od. bone (= boun ready)? [od. &yogh;oue bone? --Corrigenda]</NOTE></L>
<L N="1625">For he till god sa thankfull is,</L>
<L>&THORN;at in-till hewine with prophettis</L>
<L>And patriarkis he sall be</L>
<L>Rewardit in-to lyk degre:</L>
<L>For &thorn;ai till hyme war as samplar</L>
<L N="1630">To lewe his kyne &thorn;at mychty war,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;is gret pilgrimag to tak,</L>
<L>As did Abrahame for goddis sak,</L>
<L>&amp; lewe all warldis welth &amp; keyne<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. keyne st. kyne.</NOTE></L>
<L>Reward in lestand lyf to wyne".</L>
<L N="1635">&THORN;e bischope &thorn;ane waknyt of slepe</L>
<L>&amp; to &thorn;is visione tuk gud kepe,</L>
<L>&amp; his clergy cane till hyme call</L>
<L>&amp; word for word he tald &thorn;aime all</L>
<L>As I befor here tald till &yogh;ow.</L>
<L N="1640">&amp; &thorn;ai, &thorn;at richt weile cane hyme trev,</L>
<L>Hewyt vpe &thorn;ar handis to &thorn;e hewyne</L>
<L>&amp; lowit god all with a stewine.</L>
<L>&THORN;ane all &thorn;e folk of &thorn;at cyte,</L>
<L>Ewire-ilke mane in his degre,</L>
<L N="1645">With contryt will &amp; ane assent</L>
<L>To sanct Morise but mare ar went</L>
<L>&amp; hyme as fadire &amp; saule-hyrd</L>
<L>Resauit sone, as &thorn;ame weile byrde.</L>
<L>&amp; als &thorn;e bischape of &thorn;e place,</L>
<L N="1650">&THORN;at with &thorn;e puple pute was,</L>
<L>Of all his bischoprik &thorn;e cure</L>
<L>Betaucht till hyme, of gret honour,</L>
<L>Of sprituale &amp; of temporale thing,</L>
<L>All to demayne at his lykine,</L>
<L N="1655">Swa &thorn;at to his dowme gret &amp; small</L>
<L>&THORN;at suld be downe, partenyt all.</L>
<L>&amp; fra &thorn;at he sic charge tuk,</L>
<L>He trawalyt besyly &amp; wok</L>
<L>Till his discipulis for-to preche</L>
<L N="1660">&amp; als &thorn;e puple besyly teche,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;e bidding of &thorn;e postill</L>
<L>Full ythandly he tacht &thorn;aime till,</L>
<L>&amp; of gud lyf &amp; honeste</L>
<L>Gud ensamplar to &thorn;aime first was he:</L>
<L N="1665">For he hyme-self in word &amp; deide</L>
<L>But ony (repre)ff ay cane leyde.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. undeutlich, l. repreff?</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e clergy &thorn;ane full gret Ioy mad</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ai sa worthy faddire had,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;e puple, as &thorn;aime weile byrd,</L>
<L N="1670">Was fayne &thorn;at gottine had sic ane hird.</L>
<L>Sanct Morise wes duelland &thorn;are,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Nach 1671 fehlt ein Vers.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="inline">. . . . .</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e kirk sa weile ay gouernand</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ar fell nocht in-to &thorn;e lande</L>
<L N="1675">Pestilence of beste na mane;</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;ar-to weddire had &thorn;ai &thorn;ane</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ai wane froyt of land &amp; se</L>
<L>Thru his prayere in gret pleynte.</L>
<L>&amp;, till it hapnyt hyme of chaunce
<PB REF="00000345.tif" N="207"></L>
<L N="1680">So lang tyme for-to duel in Fraunce,</L>
<L>Mony merwale god for hyme wrocht:</L>
<L>&THORN;at I in-to &thorn;is buk wryt nocht,</L>
<L>For bath it war langsume to do</L>
<L>&amp; I cane tak na tyme &thorn;arto;</L>
<L N="1685">Bot sped me schortly for-to tell</L>
<L>Of his ending how it befell.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Tharefor, quhene &thorn;at he duelt had &thorn;are</L>
<L>Thre &yogh;ere haile &amp; half but mare,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. twre.</NOTE></L>
<L>He fell in-till a lytill fewire,</L>
<L N="1690">&THORN;at quhile for cald will ger mene cheuire.</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;at seknes sa fast hyme socht</L>
<L>&THORN;at hyme full nere till end It brocht.</L>
<L>Sex days &thorn;ane with sic herd stryfe</L>
<L>Befor &thorn;at he passit &thorn;is lyfe,<NOTE PLACE="foot">of fehlt.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1695">He gert his clerkis mak his grawe</L>
<L>&amp; in-till his orator hyme haf</L>
<L>&amp; his discipulis till hyme call.</L>
<L>He gret &amp; sad &thorn;is till &thorn;aime all:</L>
<L>"My sonnys der, now ame I feit</L>
<L N="1700">Of alkine flesche to &yogh;eld &thorn;e deit,</L>
<L>&amp; sall be mad sowne, as yhe see,</L>
<L>Of fleschlyk presone quyt &amp; fre.</L>
<L>Lowit be &thorn;at me has gewine</L>
<L>Grace, my stryf I haf weile strifine!</L>
<L N="1705">For-thi gud thing It is to me</L>
<L>To be lousit &amp; with hyme be.</L>
<L>For it nedis me nocht, I trev,</L>
<L>In flesche to duell langer for &yogh;ou,</L>
<L>For &yogh;e ar parfyt in althing,</L>
<L N="1710">Of grace haffand na-kyne wanting.</L>
<L>&THORN;arfor, dere sonnis, beis nocht Irk</L>
<L>With gud werkis to strynth &thorn;e kirk,</L>
<L>&amp; with gud dedis feit &yogh;our will</L>
<L>Godis byding ay till fulfill!</L>
<L N="1715">Alkyne wicis &yogh;e put away,</L>
<L>&amp; luk &yogh;e cristine treucht hald ay,</L>
<L>And ferme in pece &amp; cheryte</L>
<L>&amp; nithbour lof luk ay &yogh;e be!"</L>
<L>Quhene &thorn;at he &thorn;is had sad &amp; mare,</L>
<L N="1720">&THORN;ai war dissessit &amp; gret full sare,</L>
<L>&amp; sad: "der faddire, quhy, will &thorn;u</L>
<L>All dissolat ws leif ws now?"</L>
<L>&amp; he sad to &thorn;ame: "sonnis dere,</L>
<L>I leif &yogh;ou nocht dissolat here,</L>
<L N="1725">I sall euer-mar with &yogh;ou be</L>
<L>Bath quyk &amp; deide in all degre,</L>
<L>Anent god ay intercessoure</L>
<L>For &yogh;oure weilfar &amp; &yogh;our honour".</L>
<L>&THORN;e hou&szlig; &thorn;ane gert he deuod all</L>
<L N="1730">Of &thorn;aime &thorn;at &thorn;ar war, gret &amp; small;</L>
<L>Outane &thorn;e bischopis, &thorn;at come &thorn;ar</L>
<L>To wisit hyme in &thorn;at sichwar,</L>
<L>&amp; sic wthir religiouse,</L>
<L>He gert duell still in-till &thorn;e house,</L>
<L N="1735">&amp; prayt &thorn;aime for godis sak</L>
<L>&THORN;e takine of &thorn;e cors to mak<MILESTONE N="208" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>One &thorn;ar froynttis, &thorn;at &thorn;ai mocht se</L>
<L>&amp; here &thorn;e thing &thorn;at &thorn;ane saw he.</L>
<L>&amp; as he bad, sa haf &thorn;a downe:</L>
<L N="1740">&amp; &thorn;ai bath herd &amp; saw alsone</L>
<L>&amp; by his heid &thorn;ane saw &thorn;ai stand</L>
<L>Jhesus his postulis XII ymang,</L>
<L>&amp; sanct Colme &amp; sanct Martyng<NOTE PLACE="foot">Martyng st. Martyne, wie &ouml;fter in schott. Mss. in Endungen yng st. yne u. yne st. yng im Part. (vgl. im Reim V. 27).</NOTE></L>
<L>Be-syd his bed &thorn;ai saw stand syne;</L>
<L N="1745">&THORN;ane spak swet Jhesu, god of hewine,</L>
<L>To sanct Moryse with full myld stewine:</L>
<L>"Sanct Morise, cum &amp; with me wone</L>
<L>In-to my fadir rik but hone!"</L>
<L>&amp; with &thorn;at wordis he ras full rath</L>
<L N="1750">&amp; gat apone his kneis bath</L>
<L>&amp; sad, as hale &amp; fere war he:</L>
<L>"In manus tuas, domine,</L>
<L>My saule I gyf". &amp; sayand swa</L>
<L>He &yogh;auld &thorn;e gast. &amp; It cane ta</L>
<L N="1755">Feile angelis &amp; bar in hewyne,</L>
<L>With mekill sang &amp; full swet stewine.</L>
<L>&THORN;e bischope &thorn;ane &amp; his clergy</L>
<L>A costly kirk gert mak in hy</L>
<L>Of siluir, weile gilt, for &thorn;e nanys,</L>
<L N="1760">&amp; ennornyt with costlyk stanys,</L>
<L>&amp; mad sanct Moryse &thorn;are to ly,</L>
<L>Enbawmyt weile &amp; richly,</L>
<L>&amp; his sepultur mad &thorn;ai syne</L>
<L>Ewine syd be syd to sanct Martyne.</L>
<L N="1765">Quhar god throw his gud prayer ay</L>
<L>Cesis neuir &yogh;eit nicht na day</L>
<L>Ferly werkis for-to wirk,
<PB REF="00000346.tif" N="208"></L>
<L>To fereme our treucht &amp; strinth of kirk,</L>
<L>In lofyng of hyme &thorn;at of nocht</L>
<L N="1770">&THORN;is warld &amp; &thorn;e lawe has wrocht.</L>
<L>For &thorn;ar is wrocht euire-ilke day</L>
<L>Sa gret wondir, &thorn;at Ine tell may,</L>
<L>Of sanct Morise throw &thorn;e prayere</L>
<L>To folk bundine with seknes sere;</L>
<L N="1775">&THORN;at I dar nocht record all now,</L>
<L>For sume perchaunce suld me mistrew.</L>
<L>For deiff mene &thorn;ar gettis heryng,</L>
<L>&amp; blynd mene als parfyt seyng,</L>
<L>&amp; halt mene als &thorn;ar gettis bute</L>
<L N="1780">&THORN;at seknes has in schank or fut,</L>
<L>&amp; dume mene als &thorn;ar gettis speke</L>
<L>&THORN;at mekly will sanct Morise sek,</L>
<L>&amp; full feille mene of parlesy</L>
<L>Gettis &thorn;ar heile &thorn;ar parfytly;</L>
<L N="1785">&amp; sume, throu ydropesy sa gret</L>
<L>Swolne, &thorn;at &thorn;ai ma ete no mete,</L>
<L>&amp; mad swampe, &thorn;ar thru &thorn;e prayere</L>
<L>Of sanct Morise (are) haile &amp; fere;</L>
<L>&amp; sume &thorn;at brawne wod of &thorn;ar wyt</L>
<L N="1790">War mad &amp; wterly tynt It,</L>
<L>&amp; helpe has socht at sanct Morise,</L>
<L>Recouerit wit &amp; war mad wise;</L>
<L>&amp; sume &thorn;at payne had of &thorn;e stane,</L>
<L>Or seknes in-to flesch or bane,</L>
<L N="1795">Or quhatkine vthir Infirmyte</L>
<L>&THORN;at mane or womane had, gyf he</L>
<L>Or scho sanct Morise socht increly,</L>
<L>At hyme &thorn;ar heile &thorn;ai gat in hy,</L>
<L>Throw mycht of giffar of all grace,</L>
<L N="1800">To quhome he ay trew seruand was.</L>
<L>&amp; swa gif god &thorn;at I ma be</L>
<L>His seruand in-to sic degre,</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;is lyf &thorn;at I ma twyne</L>
<L>But schame or deit or dedly syne!</L>
<TRAILER>Explicit wita sci Macharij.
</TRAILER>

</LG>
</DIV2>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="2" TYPE="part"><PB REF="00000347.tif" N="[209]">
<HEAD>II. Einzellegenden.
<PB REF="00000348.tif" N="211">
</HEAD>

<DIV2 N="1" TYPE="legend"><PB REF="00000349.tif" N="210">
<HEAD>I. St. Eustas.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P><NOTE PLACE="foot">[The footnotes contain] Varianten des Ms. Ashm. 61, fol. 1.</NOTE>Ms. Digby 86, fol. 122b. (c. 1290). Die folg. 2 Leg. des Ms. Digby 86 (c. 1290 geschrieben) geh&ouml;ren zu den &auml;ltesten Leg.; sie sind echt volksth&uuml;mlich, Eustas zugleich echt episch in dem st&auml;ten Forttriebe der Handlung u. in der F&uuml;lle der Stimmung. Der Dialect ist s&uuml;dlich. Dieselbe Stropfen|form findet sich in anderen gleichzeitigen, legendarischen und moralischen, Gedichten wieder, sie unterscheidet diese Gruppe von den Gedichten in vierzeiligen Stropfen und Langversen, wie Gregorius, Mergrete, Katerine, die der Zeit nach noch vor jenen vorauszuliegen scheinen. Dieselbe Hs. enth&auml;lt die Spr&uuml;che des h. Bernhard u. Spr&uuml;che des h. Beda ("&thorn;e sawe of seint Bede prest", in 372 V., nach dem &auml;lteren Ms. Jes. Coll. Oxf. edirt in Morris An old Engl. Miscellany p. 72 u. d. T. Sinners Beware, von ders. Stropfenform und wohl von dems. Dichter wie die Leg. vom Psalter), ein Ged. von den 11 Peinen der H&ouml;lle (aus Ms. Jes. Coll. ed. in Morris An old E. Misc. p. 147) und Maximian (od. Klagen eines Greises &uuml;ber das Alter, bisher ungedruckt). &mdash; Eine weit j&uuml;ngere und schlechte Hs. des Eust. findet sich in Ms. Ashm. 61 fol. 1. &mdash; Andere Ver|sionen derselben Leg. sind enthalten in der s&uuml;dengl. Legenden- und nordengl. Homilien|sammlung. Eine sp&auml;tere Leg. ist endlich: The worthie hystorie of the moste noble and valiaunt knight Placidas, otherwise called Eustas, who was martyred for the pro|fession of Jhesus Christ, gathered in Engl. verse by John Partridge, in the year of our lord 1566. Imprinted at London by Henrye Denham for Thomas Hacket: and are to be solde at his shoppe in Lumbarde streate, in 1380 V.; wiederabgedruckt f&uuml;r den Roxb. Cl. 1873 u. d. T.: The hystorie of the moste noble knight Plasidas and other rare pieces, collected into one Book by Samuel Pepys, and forming part of the Pepysian library at Magd. Coll. Cbr. (dies. Sammlung des Pepys enth&auml;lt auch die Leg. von Sir John Oldcastle). Dieses Ged. des J. Partridge beginnt: Sometyme in Romane lande there was A king of noble fame, Who was full faine in martiall feates And Traian had to name. &mdash;</P></HEADNOTE>
<HEAD>Ci comence la vie seint Eustace qui out noun Placidas.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Alle &thorn;at louie&thorn; godes lore,<NOTE PLACE="foot">(A)l &thorn;at be on godys lore,</NOTE></L>
<L>Olde and &yogh;onge, lasse and more,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lytell, mykyll, lesse &amp; more,</NOTE></L>
<L>Lestne&thorn; hone stounde<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lystyns to me a stounde.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of a kni&yogh;t of he&thorn;enesse,<NOTE PLACE="foot">knyght. hethenes.</NOTE></L>
<L N="5">&THORN;at heuede muche in her&thorn;e blisse,<NOTE PLACE="foot">myche hade of werldys.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of gold and ponewes rounde.<NOTE PLACE="foot">penyes.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>He was .I.-hoten Placidas,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Hys name hyght.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wi&thorn; Troian &thorn;e enperour he was,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Tracyan. emperoure.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ri&yogh;t wis mon of rede;<NOTE PLACE="foot">wyse mane.</NOTE></L>
<L N="10">Wi&thorn; &thorn;e riche he was god,<NOTE PLACE="foot">pore. wele gode.</NOTE></L>
<L>And wi&thorn; &thorn;e pouere milde mod,<NOTE PLACE="foot">ryche. of mode.</NOTE></L>
<L>And ri&yogh;t-ful mon of dede.<NOTE PLACE="foot">And gode in euery dede.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000350.tif" N="212"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Of honting he cou&thorn;e .I.-nou,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Of fre huntyng. Inou&yogh;he.</NOTE></L>
<L>In heye wode and vnder bou<NOTE PLACE="foot2">In holte &amp; vnder &thorn;e wode-bou&yogh;he.</NOTE></L>
<L N="15">And in wilde felde.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">in the.</NOTE></L>
<L>He rod on hunting on a day:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">rode. dey.</NOTE></L>
<L>On hert he founde, &thorn;er he lay<NOTE PLACE="foot2">A. found. ley.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wel faire ounder on helde.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Welle feyre vnder &thorn;e lynde.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e hert wes muchel, of heie cinde,<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Ms. tinde?</NOTE></L>
<L N="20">&THORN;er he wes ounder wode linde,</L>
<L>Mest he wes of alle;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">19&mdash;21) fehlen.</NOTE></L>
<L>O&thorn;ere hertes and hindes mo,</L>
<L>More and lasse, &thorn;er weren also,</L>
<L>He stod stiuest of alle.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">22&mdash;4) Of many hertys &amp; bestys also, Of more &amp; lesse &thorn;er wer moo, He was &thorn;e feyrest of alle.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="25">&THORN;e muchele hert atorn away,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">The gretyst hert fled hys wey.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e kni&yogh;t rod after ni&yogh;t and day<NOTE PLACE="foot2">rode a. all a dey.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bi him-self al-one,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">selffe.</NOTE></L>
<L>Oout in an o&thorn;er kinges londe:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">In-tylle an odour kyngys.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;er him gan &thorn;e hert astonde<NOTE PLACE="foot2">There ganne. to withstonde.</NOTE></L>
<L N="30">Ovpon a roche of stone.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">vpone.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e hert bitur(n)de is hornes heye,<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Ms. biturde.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">turned hys. hy&yogh;e.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ere he wes ounder wode-leye,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">There he stode vnder &thorn;e wode lynde (!).</NOTE></L>
<L>And seyde: "Placidas,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">seyd sir.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ou art a kni&yogh;t of hounting fre &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Thow arte. huntyng.</NOTE></L>
<L N="35">&THORN;ou me driuest and .I. &thorn;e fle &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">foloys.</NOTE></L>
<L>Rid nou &thorn;i softe pas!<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Ryde softer thy pace.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bituene min hornes &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t loke,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Betwene my h. &thorn;at are so hy&yogh;e,</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e feirest &thorn;ing &thorn;at stont in boke<NOTE PLACE="foot2">To me &amp; &thorn;ou wolde cast thyne ey&yogh;e,</NOTE></L>
<L>Wel sone &thorn;ou salt ise:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Well sone thane myght &thorn;ou see: Darauf folgt: The feyrest syght &thorn;at may be thou&yogh;ht Or yne &thorn;is werlde &thorn;at may be wro&yogh;ht Or euer in erthe may be: Jhesu Cryst onne crosse Iwys, That hath &thorn;e broght in all &thorn;is blys, Thou huntys after &thorn;is tyde. The truthe wele sone &thorn;ou schall se, Iff &thorn;ou wyll tourne thy face to me, Fore ferthere &thorn;ou may not ryde (A. hat also eine Stropfe mehr).</NOTE></L>
<L N="40">Jhesu Cristes creis .I.-wis,</L>
<L>&THORN;at sal &thorn;e bringen alle blis</L>
<L>And hounte&thorn; after &thorn;e".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e li&yogh;t of heuene and &thorn;e glem,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">in a leme.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bri&yogh;ttore &thorn;en &thorn;e sunne bem,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Bry&yogh;ter than is &thorn;e sone beme.</NOTE></L>
<L N="45">Ovpon &thorn;at hert ali&yogh;tte.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">gane lyght.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e hert spak, alse a mon hit were,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">spake as a man it.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;at feire kni&yogh;te &thorn;ere &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">So fayre to &thorn;e knyght ryght there,</NOTE></L>
<L>Ich wot, hit wes oure dri&yogh;te.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">And seyd to hym with ryght.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Placidas, ich seye hit &thorn;e,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">I sey to.</NOTE></L>
<L N="50">&THORN;i nome shal .I.-chaunged be,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">That &thorn;i name changyd schalle be,</NOTE></L>
<L>Cristindom &thorn;ou shat fonge.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">And crystindome vnderfonge.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ich am Jhesu Crist of heuene<NOTE PLACE="foot2">It is.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at speke wi&thorn; &thorn;e wi&thorn; milde steuene.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">spekys to.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ne dwel &thorn;ou nout to longe!<NOTE PLACE="foot2">duell. not.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="55">&THORN;ou nim &thorn;ine children and &thorn;i wif,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Thou take thi chylder. wyfe.</NOTE></L>
<L>And wende&thorn; al wi&thorn;-oute strif<NOTE PLACE="foot2">wend. withouten stryffe.</NOTE></L>
<L>And cristine&thorn; ou bitime!<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&amp; crystyne &yogh;ou be tyme.</NOTE></L>
<L>I-nou &yogh;e sulen .I.-fondet be</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; care and howe, &thorn;ou and hoe,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">58&mdash;9) Fore oftyne-tyme &yogh;ou schall be lede, With sorow &amp; care &yogh;e schall be fedde,</NOTE></L>
<L N="60">Al for loue of mine".<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Fore loue of me &amp; myne. Darauf hat A 2 Stropfen mehr: "Leue lord, seyd he, My crysten name thow gyffe to me, Or &thorn;at I hens wende". "Now &thorn;ou hyght Placydas, Thow schall hyght sir Ewstas, In werld withouten ende". &mdash; Home-ward he went fast anone, And told it hys wyffe at home. They thankyd gode dey &amp; nygh(t). "Syre, sche seyd, we wyll gone, And become cristynd anone, In &thorn;e name of god all-myght.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>He nom is children and is wif,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">toke his chylder &amp; his wyffe.</NOTE></L>
<L>And wenten al wi&thorn;-outen strif<MILESTONE N="123" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="foot2">&amp; went forthe withoutyne stryffe</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000351.tif" N="213"></L>
<L>To &thorn;at follovstone;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">To &thorn;e fonte-stone.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ere hy weren .I.-cristned bein,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">There &thorn;<SUP>i</SUP> wer cristyne tho.</NOTE></L>
<L N="65">His wif and hise children tweine &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">his childer two.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;o nes he nout alone.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Ne was he not a.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Wilen he hei&yogh;te Placidas,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Some tyme.</NOTE></L>
<L>And nou he is cristned Ewstas &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Now he hyght sir E.</NOTE></L>
<L>".I.-herd be god almi&yogh;tte!"<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Blyssed be. all-myght.</NOTE></L>
<L N="70">In-to &thorn;at heye wode anon</L>
<L>Al abouten hy weren agon</L>
<L>And &thorn;onkeden oure dri&yogh;tte.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e kni&yogh;t wi&thorn; hise .I.-feren &thorn;re</L>
<L>Ounder one linde-tre</L>
<L N="75">Reste him hone stounde.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">70&mdash;5) Betwene &thorn;e vndrone &amp; &thorn;e none, I wote, &thorn;is dede it was done, Ne was it not be nyght. &mdash; To &thorn;e wodde &thorn;<SUP>i</SUP> wente anone, Als-so swyth as &thorn;<SUP>i</SUP> myght gone, Ne restyd &thorn;ei no stounde.</NOTE></L>
<L>Alse wes ounder wode-bowe,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">As &thorn;<SUP>i</SUP> went vnder &thorn;e wodde bowe,</NOTE></L>
<L>Wel gode tidingges him come .I.-nowe<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Of god t. &thorn;er come Inow.</NOTE></L>
<L>From hevene to &thorn;e grounde:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Fro h. to them on g.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>On aungele seyde, &thorn;at wes bri&yogh;t:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">An angelle seyd &thorn;at was fulle bryght.</NOTE></L>
<L N="80">"Sire Eustace, godes kni&yogh;t,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Ewstas godys.</NOTE></L>
<L>.I.-blesced mote &thorn;ou be!<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Blyssyd. bene.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ine children and &thorn;i wif<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Thi-selue, &thorn;i chylder &amp; &thorn;i wyfe</NOTE></L>
<L>Sulen hauen &thorn;at eche lif<NOTE PLACE="foot1">eche, ags. &ecirc;ce, eternal, wie 202.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">Schall in Ioy lede &yogh;our lyfe</NOTE></L>
<L>And alle blisse .I.-se.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">And heue(n)s blys schall sene.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="85">&THORN;ey &thorn;ou lete lond and lede,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Thoffe &thorn;ou les both.</NOTE></L>
<L>Halle and bour and heye stede,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">bowre, palfray &amp; st.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ne be &thorn;ou nout sori!<NOTE PLACE="foot2">not sorye.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ou art .I.-turnd to cristindome:</L>
<L>&THORN;e fend &thorn;e wille sechen .I.-lome</L>
<L N="90">And ofte &thorn;e fondi.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">88&mdash;90) Now &thorn;ou hast cristindome, vnderstond, The fend wyll &yogh;erne &thorn;e forto fonde, Now &thorn;ou arte made holye.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Wende&thorn;, qua&thorn; &thorn;e aungele, godes way,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Wend &yogh;e forthe into &yogh;our waye</NOTE></L>
<L>Wytie&thorn; oure soule ni&yogh;t and day,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">And kepe &yogh;our saulys, daye.</NOTE></L>
<L>And do&thorn; bi mine rede!<NOTE PLACE="foot2">And do as I &yogh;ou rede.</NOTE></L>
<L>Alle &yogh;e sulen mid-.I.-wis<NOTE PLACE="foot2">All &yogh;e schalle fore sothe Iwys.</NOTE></L>
<L N="95">For &thorn;e loue of swete Jhesus</L>
<L>Mid martirdom ben dede".<NOTE PLACE="foot2">In. be.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>To his hous he wente anon,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Syre Eustas wente hym home</NOTE></L>
<L>So swi&thorn;e so he mi&yogh;tte gon,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Also swyth as. gone.</NOTE></L>
<L>Mid wif and children two.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">With wyfe. childer.</NOTE></L>
<L N="100">&THORN;o weren is seep afelde .I.-biten,</L>
<L>&THORN;e &thorn;onre heuede his hors forsmiten &mdash;</L>
<L>A fote he moste go.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">100&mdash;2) He found his schepe in folde wer betyne, And thonder his hors to deth had smyten, On fote ne myght &thorn;<SUP>i</SUP> gone (!).</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Al &thorn;at he louede, him wente fram,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">All &thorn;at hym louyd wente hym fro.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bote is wif and is children twam.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">his. childer two.</NOTE></L>
<L N="105">Hof londe hy mosten wende.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Sone &thorn;<SUP>i</SUP> must wende.</NOTE></L>
<L>Er hit dawede li&yogh;t of day,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Erly or it was any daye.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wel stilleliche hy wenten away<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Stylly &thorn;<SUP>i</SUP> stalkyd away (Ms. awas).</NOTE></L>
<L>Bi one wodes ende.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">a woddys.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Toward Egipte hy gunnen fare,</L>
<L N="110">ffore .I.-bounden al wi&thorn; kare,</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; loue mourninge</L>
<L>Of Crist &thorn;at alle &thorn;inge shop</L>
<L>And &thorn;at on er&thorn;e rod and stop,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; spere &thorn;at let him stinge.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">109&mdash;114) fehlen.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="115">To one water hy comen gon:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">a. &thorn;<SUP>i</SUP> gane gone.</NOTE></L>
<L>A ship hy founden &thorn;er anon.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">A schype &thorn;<SUP>i</SUP> founde sone anone.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;er houer hy mosten seyle.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Thei went &thorn;er-tylle.</NOTE></L>
<L>In-to &thorn;at ship he dede him &thorn;o,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&thorn;e. &thorn;<SUP>i</SUP> went tho.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000352.tif" N="214"></L>
<L>His wif, ise &yogh;onge children two.<NOTE PLACE="foot">&amp; his chylder.</NOTE></L>
<L N="120">&THORN;at water wes sturne and eille.<NOTE PLACE="foot">The w. was sterne &amp; ylle.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e shippesman bihoeld &thorn;at kni&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="foot">The schypmene byhold &thorn;at ilke k.</NOTE></L>
<L>And se&thorn;&thorn;en &thorn;e leuedi, &thorn;at wes bri&yogh;t:<NOTE PLACE="foot">And &thorn;at lady &thorn;at was so bryght.</NOTE></L>
<L>Hoe &thorn;ouhte him feir and shene.<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;i thought hyre fare.</NOTE></L>
<L>To him he seyde after &thorn;an:</L>
<L N="125">"Wer hevedest &thorn;ou &thorn;is fayre wimman?<NOTE PLACE="foot">Where hadyst. feyre womane.</NOTE></L>
<L>Hoe shal ben min, ich wene".<NOTE PLACE="foot">Sche. be. I. Darauf hat A. folg. 2 Stropfen: Out of &thorn;e schype he drew hym tho, And his &yogh;onge childer two &mdash; Full woo was hym &thorn;erfore! The lady cryed &amp; mad gret dynne, And fro hyre lorde was loth to twyne, And weppyd &amp; sy&yogh;ede sore. &mdash; The knyght sette hym done apone a stone (= 127), And se hys wyfe was fro hym go, Takyne fro hym with wronge. He seyd alas &thorn;at he was borne! Hys wytte fro hym ny&yogh;e-hond was lorne, Hym thou&yogh;t hys lyfe to longe. Die 2 ersten V. der folg. Strophe: After &thorn;e schype his eye he caste: Out of his syght than was sche paste.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="inter">. . . . .(<B>Hier fehlen eine oder zwei Strophen.</B>)</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A-doun he sette him on an ston</L>
<L>And reste his werie bon,</L>
<L>Bioeld hise children two:<NOTE PLACE="foot">He behelde hys.</NOTE></L>
<L N="130">"Me &thorn;inke&thorn;, min herte wile bleden.<NOTE PLACE="foot">thinke my. wylle all to-bled.</NOTE></L>
<L>Hou shal ich ou moderlese feden?<NOTE PLACE="foot">I &yogh;ou moderles fede.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ne wes me nevere &thorn;us wo".<NOTE PLACE="foot">Now was me neuer so wo.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>So longe for&thorn; his wey he nom,<NOTE PLACE="foot">way. toke.</NOTE></L>
<L>To one watere &thorn;at he com.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Tyll &thorn;at &thorn;<SUP>i</SUP> come vnto a broke.</NOTE></L>
<L N="135">&THORN;er ouer he moste fare.<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;<SUP>i</SUP> muste.</NOTE></L>
<L>Waden he moste &mdash; &thorn;e water wes cheld,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Wade &thorn;<SUP>i</SUP> muste, &thorn;e water was scheld.</NOTE></L>
<L>In ey&thorn;er side wilde feld:<NOTE PLACE="foot">By e&thorn;er. &thorn;e wylde.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e more wes his care.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Welle mekyll was hys care.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>He nom his on child on his arm &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">toke. o. in. arme.</NOTE></L>
<L N="140">Ich wot, he ne dede him non harm &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">The o&thorn;er he wende schuld haue no herme.</NOTE></L>
<L>And bar hit ouer to londe.<NOTE PLACE="foot">He bare hym. to &thorn;e.</NOTE></L>
<L>Sone he seyd in his mod:<NOTE PLACE="foot">Doune he sette in hys mode (!).</NOTE></L>
<L>"Godes help his euere god:<NOTE PLACE="foot">Godys grace, he seyd, is euermore gode.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at ich wel ounder-stonde.<NOTE PLACE="foot">I. wel fehlt.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="145">"Sitte nou stille, sone min,<NOTE PLACE="foot">styll. myne.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e wyles ich fecche bro&thorn;er &thorn;in,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Tyll &thorn;at I fette.</NOTE></L>
<L>And tou shalt hauen &thorn;i mede.<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ou schall haue.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ich wille to &thorn;e comen anon,<NOTE PLACE="foot">I schalle come to &thorn;e anone,</NOTE></L>
<L>So sone so ich hit may don;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Als-so sone as I may gone.</NOTE></L>
<L N="150">Ne &thorn;arf &thorn;e nout adrede".<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ne make &thorn;ou no drede.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>In-to &thorn;at water he wente a&yogh;eyn,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e w. agayne.</NOTE></L>
<L>Fort he com in &thorn;at depe strem,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Tyll &thorn;at he come to &thorn;e myddys streme.</NOTE></L>
<L>And lokede in hey&thorn;er side:<NOTE PLACE="foot">lokyd hym bysyde.</NOTE></L>
<L>A wilde lioun &thorn;er com gon<NOTE PLACE="foot">he saw &thorn;er gone.</NOTE></L>
<L N="155">And kipt his &yogh;onge sone anon,<NOTE PLACE="foot">He toke.</NOTE></L>
<L>On him he &yogh;enede wide.<NOTE PLACE="foot">gapyd.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e lioun ber &thorn;e kni&yogh;t child wi&thorn; him,<NOTE PLACE="foot">That. bare &thorn;at child.</NOTE></L>
<L>A-wey he wende wro&thorn; and grim.<NOTE PLACE="foot">That was both grete, stoute &amp; gryme.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e kni&yogh;t wes ney .I.-swowe,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ne was he neuer so wo. Dann folgt: Than was sir Eustas sorye, Fore both his childer wer borne awaye; He felle in swounyng tho. Die folg. Stropfe fehlt.</NOTE></L>
<L N="160">Wore he wes in &thorn;at water depe;</L>
<L>Hit nes no wonder &thorn;ey he wepe,</L>
<L>Of care he heuede .I.-nowe!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;o he hof swoning aros,</L>
<L>He lokede oup and him agros;</L>
<L N="165">To londe he moste te.</L>
<L>A wonder &thorn;ing he sey him &thorn;ar:</L>
<L>A wolf his o&thorn;er child at-bar.</L>
<L>.I.-swowen he fel on kne.
<PB REF="00000353.tif" N="215"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;o he of swoning aros,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Bot whene he fro swonyng rose,</NOTE></L>
<L N="170">He lokede oup and him agros,<NOTE PLACE="foot">He lokyd vp &amp; forth he gose,</NOTE></L>
<L>His wit wes ney forloren.<NOTE PLACE="foot">His wytte was ney&yogh;e hym fro.</NOTE></L>
<L>Euere he &thorn;ouhte on Jhesu Crist,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Bot euer he thought onne.</NOTE></L>
<L>On his de&thorn;, on his ouprist,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&amp; his vp-ryste.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at for ous wes .I.-boren.<NOTE PLACE="foot">fehlt.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="175">"God almi&yogh;tten, &thorn;ou hit wost,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Jhesu Cryste in trinyte,</NOTE></L>
<L>Fader and sone and holi gost!<NOTE PLACE="foot">All-my&yogh;hty god, &thorn;ou comforth me.</NOTE></L>
<L>To &thorn;e ich mene mi mone,<NOTE PLACE="foot">I make.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of mi spouse &thorn;at wes so trewe,</L>
<L>Fayr and hende and bri&yogh;t of hewe &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">178&mdash;9) umgestellt: So feyere a womane of hyde &amp; hew, Of my wyfe &thorn;at was so trew.</NOTE></L>
<L N="180">Welle wo is me al-one!<NOTE PLACE="foot">So wo is me alone.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For mine sones &thorn;at ben forloren,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Of my chyldren &thorn;at be forelorne.</NOTE></L>
<L>Mid wilde bestes awey .I.-boren &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">With. awaye borne.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ne bide ich newer-eft none.<NOTE PLACE="foot">I may now sey alas!</NOTE></L>
<L>To wecche lond ma ich toe?</L>
<L N="185">Hou longe sal ich liues boe?</L>
<L>Ne con ich me no wone.<NOTE PLACE="foot">184&mdash;6) Tyll vncouthes (!) londys I wylle go. How longe schall (I) lyue so? That euer I borne was!</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Of Iop ich wile bi&thorn;enchen me,<NOTE PLACE="foot">On Iob I wylle bethinke me,</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at longe hevede in blisse .I.-be<NOTE PLACE="foot">&THORN;at euer had in blysse be.</NOTE></L>
<L>And se&thorn;&thorn;en sel into care.<NOTE PLACE="foot">sethen. in.</NOTE></L>
<L N="190">Louerd, for &thorn;e loue of &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">lord.</NOTE></L>
<L>To sori nulle ich newer be,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ne wylle I neuer to sory be,</NOTE></L>
<L>Fare hou ich fare.<NOTE PLACE="foot">How so euer I fare.</NOTE><MILESTONE N="124" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ich habbe .I.-wopen al mine fille,<NOTE PLACE="foot">I. wepyne. my.</NOTE></L>
<L>.I. nelle nammore, ich wile be stille:<NOTE PLACE="foot">&THORN;er bade no-mane me &yogh;it be stylle,</NOTE></L>
<L N="195">Godes help is fulney".<NOTE PLACE="foot">Fore goddys helpe is ny&yogh;e.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;o com &thorn;er on aungele of heuene<NOTE PLACE="foot">There comme an. fro.</NOTE></L>
<L>And spek wi&thorn; him wi&thorn; milde steuene,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&THORN;at spake to.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of god, &thorn;at wes on hey:<NOTE PLACE="foot">Frome Cryst &thorn;at wonetht one hy&yogh;e.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Be nou stille and glad, Eustace!<NOTE PLACE="foot">Blyssede be &thorn;ou, sir Eustas.</NOTE></L>
<L N="200">In heuene is .I.-maked &thorn;i place,<NOTE PLACE="foot">made &thorn;i mery p.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ere &thorn;ou shalt murie boen.<NOTE PLACE="foot">schall blythe bene.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ine children and &thorn;i wif<NOTE PLACE="foot">Thi-selue, thy chylder &amp; thi wyfe</NOTE></L>
<L>Sulen haven &thorn;at eche lif<NOTE PLACE="foot">Schall &thorn;at merye lyfe</NOTE></L>
<L>And alle blisse .I.-soen".<NOTE PLACE="foot">And alle &thorn;at Ioy sene.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="205">So longe for&thorn; he wente his way,<NOTE PLACE="foot">he wente forth in. wey.</NOTE></L>
<L>Hise bedes biddinde ni&yogh;t and day,<NOTE PLACE="foot">His bedys bedand. dey.</NOTE></L>
<L>To toune &thorn;at he com.<NOTE PLACE="foot">tylle &thorn;at he camme.</NOTE></L>
<L>sswinken and sweten he moste &thorn;o,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Suynkyng &amp; suetyng he muste tho (!),</NOTE></L>
<L>Wor his spending wes al atgo:<NOTE PLACE="foot">Fore his spendyng was alle go;</NOTE></L>
<L N="210">Wel evene he hit ounder-nom,<NOTE PLACE="foot">To woche (!) he must thane.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Wi&thorn; bowe and arewen and wi&thorn; horn<NOTE PLACE="foot">bow. arowys. horne.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wor-to witien monne corn,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Forto kepe o&thorn;er mens corne.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bi day and eke bi ni&yogh;tt,</L>
<L>Weddes nimen and orf to puinde&mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Weddys to take &amp; bestys to pynde,</NOTE></L>
<L N="215">&THORN;ereto nes him nout .I.-cunde.<NOTE PLACE="foot">&THORN;at was hym not commyne of kynde.</NOTE></L>
<L>He wes hayward and kni&yogh;t!<NOTE PLACE="foot">fehlt.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Fiftene &yogh;er he wonede &thorn;ere,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Fyftyne wynter he was there.</NOTE></L>
<L>Er men westen were he were.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Or. wyst whens.</NOTE></L>
<L>.I.-sout he wes wel &yogh;erne:<NOTE PLACE="foot">His mete forto eyrene.</NOTE></L>
<L N="220">&THORN;e enperour him sende to seche<NOTE PLACE="foot">The e. dyde hym to.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wi&thorn; men, &thorn;at weren wise of speche,<NOTE PLACE="foot">ware mylde.</NOTE></L>
<L>Kni&yogh;ttes starke and sterne.<NOTE PLACE="foot">bothe styffe st. starke.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000354.tif" N="216"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ouer &thorn;at corn &thorn;er comen &thorn;re<NOTE PLACE="foot2">corne. &thorn;er fehlt.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ridinde men of one ble,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Ridinge.</NOTE></L>
<L N="225">And he hoem &thorn;ere .I.-mette.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">With hym &thorn;er they mette.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e kni&yogh;ttes weren on horse heye,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">rydyne on horsys hye.</NOTE></L>
<L>Mid wordes milde, fayre and sleye<NOTE PLACE="foot2">With wordys. feyre. scly&yogh;e.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ene hayward .I.-grette.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&THORN;at heyward fare &thorn;<SUP>i</SUP> grette.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e hayward nom and bleu his horn,</L>
<L N="230">For he wes wardein of &thorn;at corn;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">229&mdash;30) umgesetzt: Fore he was wardane ouer &thorn;at corne, The heywerd stod &amp; blow his horne.</NOTE></L>
<L>Here wed he bad hem &yogh;elde.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&thorn;er wedde he bade theme &yogh;elde.</NOTE></L>
<L>He axede wat hy souhten &thorn;are,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">askyde what &thorn;<SUP>i</SUP> soughtyne &thorn;er.</NOTE></L>
<L>And wy hy weren so .I.-fare<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&thorn;<SUP>i</SUP> went ouer so ferre.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ouer &thorn;at heued felde.<NOTE PLACE="foot1">heued = ags. eowde, herd?</NOTE>,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">hy&yogh;e st. heued.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="235">"Sire, we ben kni&yogh;ttes, fer .I.-fare<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Syre, &thorn;<SUP>i</SUP> seyd, be not dysplesyde,</NOTE></L>
<L>For to sechen wide-ware<NOTE PLACE="foot2">We knaw &thorn;at we haue &yogh;ow dessesyde,</NOTE></L>
<L>After one monne:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Fore we seke after a mane.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e enperoures cunsiler<NOTE PLACE="foot2">We bene &thorn;e emperoures consylerys.</NOTE></L>
<L>.I.-sout we awen fer and ner,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">We haue hym sou&yogh;te bothe ferre &amp; nere,</NOTE></L>
<L N="240">Ne con him ous noman kenne.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Bot fynd hym nought we canne.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Wiseste kni&yogh;t of alle he was,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">A nobulle knyght fore-sothe he was.</NOTE></L>
<L>His nome wes hoten Placidas.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">name. was callyd sir.</NOTE></L>
<L>On honting hout he ferde,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">oute he farede.</NOTE></L>
<L>Nevereft se&thorn;&thorn;en ne com he hom,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Neuer sethyne comme home.</NOTE></L>
<L N="245">Ne no tidinge from him ne com<NOTE PLACE="foot2">ne fehlt vor come.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at ani mon hy-herde.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&THORN;at no-mane sethen of herde.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Here we hauen .I.-founde &thorn;e,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">haue foundyne.</NOTE></L>
<L>We wenen wel &thorn;at &thorn;ou hit be</L>
<L>Bi &thorn;ine fayre chere;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">248&mdash;9) By a wounde &thorn;at I se On the &thorn;at stondys here.</NOTE></L>
<L N="250">Ovp-on &thorn;i neb is an wonde:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">One thy nose &thorn;er is a wounde:</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ere-bi we hauen wel .I.-founde<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Werby we haue &thorn;e here founde,</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou art oure .I.-fere".<NOTE PLACE="foot2">And &thorn;ou schall bene owre fere.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Nay, qua&thorn; he, hou mi&yogh;tte hit be?<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Nay, sires, so mote I thene,</NOTE></L>
<L>Were suldich houre fere be?<NOTE PLACE="foot2">I may not &yogh;our feloy bene.</NOTE></L>
<L N="255">Ne am ich a pouere mon?"<NOTE PLACE="foot2">I ame a pore mane.</NOTE></L>
<L>"&THORN;ou most wi&thorn; ous to &thorn;e enperour,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">muste. vs.</NOTE></L>
<L>For to fongen &thorn;at honour<NOTE PLACE="foot2">haue thy.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou were erroure on".<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&THORN;at thou wer wonte to hanne.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;o nom sire Eustas his leue &thorn;are,</L>
<L N="260">Mid hise .I.-feren he is .I.-fare.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">259) ff. Syre Eustas se &thorn;at he muste nedes Forto go forth with &thorn;es knyghtys Vnto &thorn;e kyngys courte. Darauf folgt: He toke hys leue at grete &amp; smalle, At mane &amp; wyfe &amp; gentylles alle; &thorn;<SUP>i</SUP> were lothe to departe. Forthe he wente with theme alle thre, With &thorn;e emperour forto be; T(o) &thorn;e kyngys courte he came. (A. hat eine Strophe mehr).</NOTE></L>
<L>To kingges court he com.</L>
<L>&THORN;ere wes ioye and blisse .I.-nouh!<NOTE PLACE="foot2">was ioy. Inou&yogh;he.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e enperour on him he louh,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">onne hym low&yogh;he.</NOTE></L>
<L>And kni&yogh;t and sweyn and grom.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">And knyghtys, squyre &amp; grome.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="265">He tolde his louerd of his care,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">told. lord.</NOTE></L>
<L>His stronge lif, his harde fare,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">In strange lyffe is herd.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ord and eque &thorn;an ende,<NOTE PLACE="foot1">eque = eke.</NOTE>,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Fro begynning to &thorn;e ende.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e of lere and of bi&yogh;ete<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Bothe of hys swynke &amp; of hys suete,</NOTE></L>
<L>And of soure and eke of swete,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Of his treuthe &amp; of hys byhete,</NOTE></L>
<L N="270">&THORN;at god him wolde sende.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Of all &thorn;at god hym sende.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000355.tif" N="217"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Hit nes &thorn;er-after no&thorn;ing long<NOTE PLACE="foot">It was. no&thorn;ing fehlt.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ere ne com a werre strong<NOTE PLACE="foot">ne fehlt.</NOTE></L>
<L>Oup-on &thorn;e enpereour.</L>
<L>&THORN;idere wente monie a kni&yogh;t,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Theder. many a.</NOTE></L>
<L N="275">Wel .I.-armet to &thorn;at fi&yogh;t,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Wel Iarmede, I &yogh;ou a ply&yogh;ht.</NOTE></L>
<L>To sawuen his honour.<NOTE PLACE="foot">saue.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;idere comen kni&yogh;ttes tweyne,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Theder went. two.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wel gode in fi&yogh;te hy weren beyne,<NOTE PLACE="foot">And &thorn;<SUP>i</SUP> wer to fyght also.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wi&thorn; hors and armes gode.<NOTE PLACE="foot">hernes gode.</NOTE></L>
<L N="280">&THORN;ere nes non at &thorn;are plawe<NOTE PLACE="foot">&THORN;er was none in all &thorn;at playe</NOTE></L>
<L>Wi&thorn; sheld and spere out .I.-drawe<NOTE PLACE="foot">With spere &amp; suerd &thorn;at ilke dey,</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at hoere dunt atstode.<NOTE PLACE="foot">&THORN;at there dynte ne withstode.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;o hy heueden wel .I.-fouhte &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">When &thorn;<SUP>i</SUP> hade fouutene alle &thorn;e deye</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at hit wes wel, al so hem &thorn;ouhte &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">And scomfet &thorn;e o&thorn;er syde aweye,</NOTE></L>
<L N="285">Hy wenten to hoere inne.<NOTE PLACE="foot">&THORN;<SUP>i</SUP> went bothe to one inne.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wel gode .I.-feren hy bicomen,<NOTE PLACE="foot">There gode feloys &thorn;<SUP>i</SUP> becomme,</NOTE></L>
<L>At one house hoere in hy nomen,<NOTE PLACE="foot">As &thorn;<SUP>i</SUP> hade bene queynted at home,</NOTE></L>
<L>Wi&thorn;-outen vuel enginne.<NOTE PLACE="foot">By grace of god, I wene.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>To-gadere hy eten of one disse,<NOTE PLACE="foot">To-geder &thorn;<SUP>i</SUP> dyde syte at mete</NOTE></L>
<L N="290">Bo&thorn;e of flesse and of ffisse,<NOTE PLACE="foot">And bothe of one dyssche &thorn;<SUP>i</SUP> ete.</NOTE></L>
<L>And maden hem wel bli&thorn;e.<NOTE PLACE="foot">hem fehlt. fulle.</NOTE></L>
<L>After mete hy tolden tales<NOTE PLACE="foot">met. &thorn;<SUP>i</SUP> tolde talys.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of hoere auentures fales<NOTE PLACE="foot">Of auentures &amp; herd batayles</NOTE></L>
<L>And of here liwes si&thorn;e.<NOTE PLACE="foot">And of all &thorn;er lyfe.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="295">&THORN;e &yogh;ongore bro&thorn;er of hem twam<NOTE PLACE="foot">The &yogh;onge man of the two</NOTE></L>
<L>His bro&thorn;er exede after &thorn;an<NOTE PLACE="foot">Son askyd &thorn;e o&thorn;er tho.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of wat cunne he were.<NOTE PLACE="foot">kynne &thorn;at he.</NOTE></L>
<L>He seet stille and sihtte sore,<NOTE PLACE="foot">satte. sy&yogh;ede.</NOTE></L>
<L>Litel he spak and &thorn;ouhte more,<NOTE PLACE="foot">And seyd lytell &amp; thou&yogh;t more</NOTE></L>
<L N="300">Wi&thorn; drowpninde chere.<NOTE PLACE="foot">With a wele sade chere.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Sire, wiltou mi cunsail hele,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Sir, wyll &thorn;ou my counsylle hylle.</NOTE></L>
<L>&YOGH;if hic &thorn;e telle of mi wele<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ife I. wylle.</NOTE></L>
<L>And also of mi sore?<NOTE PLACE="foot">care.</NOTE></L>
<L>A riche mannes sone ich was,<NOTE PLACE="foot">A riche man my fader was,</NOTE></L>
<L N="305">Mi fader hey&yogh;tte Placidas,<NOTE PLACE="foot">His name hyght sir P.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at wide heuede .I.-fare.<NOTE PLACE="foot">God gyffe hym wele to fare.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Mi fader wes a wel fair kni&yogh;t,<NOTE PLACE="foot">was a dou&yogh;ty k.</NOTE></L>
<L>And mi moder a leuedi bri&yogh;t,<NOTE PLACE="foot">lady.</NOTE></L>
<L>And hadden riche .I.-won.<NOTE PLACE="foot">And ruddy of alle hew.</NOTE></L>
<L N="310">We weren &yogh;onge children two,<NOTE PLACE="foot">were &yogh;on sones.</NOTE></L>
<L>Mi litele bro&thorn;er and ich also,<NOTE PLACE="foot">My &yogh;onger broder &amp; I also.</NOTE></L>
<L>In halle and bour of ston.<NOTE PLACE="foot">boure. stone.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Mi fader nom ous alle &thorn;re,<NOTE PLACE="foot">toke vs.</NOTE></L>
<L>Mi dame, mi bro&thorn;er and me,<NOTE PLACE="foot">moder st. dame.</NOTE></L>
<L N="315">&THORN;orou grace of oure dri&yogh;te,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Thorow &thorn;e grace of god all-myght.</NOTE></L>
<L>And ladd ous to &thorn;at fonston<NOTE PLACE="foot">&amp; lede vs to a founte-stone</NOTE></L>
<L>And lete ous cristni sone anon<NOTE PLACE="foot">And crystinde vs &thorn;er anone,</NOTE></L>
<L>In &thorn;e name of god almi&yogh;te.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ne was it not by nyght.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Se&thorn;&thorn;en, ich ounderstonde me,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Sethyne I vnderstode.</NOTE></L>
<L N="320">We fellen In-to pouerte<NOTE PLACE="foot">felle.</NOTE></L>
<L>And wenten ous out of londe.<NOTE PLACE="foot">wentene. ous fehlt. oute.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ouer a water brod and dep<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ouer a water we schuld haue gone,</NOTE></L>
<L>We seileden, and mi moder wep<NOTE PLACE="foot">Oure moder &thorn;er fro vs was tane,</NOTE></L>
<L>And wrong hire honde.<NOTE PLACE="foot">With falsyde borne onne honde.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="325">Mi moder wes a fair wimmon,<NOTE PLACE="foot">was. woman.</NOTE></L>
<L>In al &thorn;at londe nes swich non<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lyke in &thorn;is werlde was none</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000356.tif" N="218"></L>
<L>Of huide ne of hewe.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&thorn;at onne water fare.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e shipes man ire ous binom,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&thorn;e schypmane toke here vs frome,</NOTE></L>
<L>Wi&thorn;-oute tale, wi&thorn;-houte dom.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Wi&thorn;outen law or o&thorn;er dome.</NOTE></L>
<L N="330">&THORN;o wes oure care newe!<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Than wexed new alle oure care.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>We wenten &thorn;orou &thorn;e wildernesse,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">We went throghe a.</NOTE></L>
<L>Mid weping and mid sorinesse,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">with. soroufulnes.</NOTE></L>
<L>And comen to one watere.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">We comme to a streme.</NOTE></L>
<L>Mi fader me nom and ouer ber,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">toke. me bere.</NOTE></L>
<L N="335">And mi bro&thorn;er lette ben &thorn;er<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Ms. bro&thorn;e&thorn;.</NOTE>,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">broder he lefte there,</NOTE></L>
<L>To loken oure hatere.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Tyll &thorn;at he comme ageyne.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A wilde lioun &thorn;er com gon<NOTE PLACE="foot2">gane st. com.</NOTE></L>
<L>And kipte me wel sone anon<NOTE PLACE="foot2">And cau&yogh;ht me in his mouthe anone,</NOTE></L>
<L>And bar me in his mou&thorn;e.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">And bore me faste aweye.</NOTE></L>
<L N="340">And &thorn;e shepherdes &thorn;at .I.-seye,</L>
<L>And blewen out horn in &thorn;e leye</L>
<L>Bi nor&thorn;e and eke bi sou&thorn;e.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">340&mdash;2) The schypherdys schepe, When &thorn;<SUP>i</SUP> hym se, &thorn;<SUP>i</SUP> dyde hym mete And schrewydly dyde hym freye.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Wel softeliche ich wes ared</L>
<L>And brout in a softe bed,</L>
<L N="345">.I.-herd be god almi&yogh;tte!<NOTE PLACE="foot2">343&mdash;5) Thus fro &thorn;e lyone I was tane, And bro&yogh;ht me vp with bourde &amp; game; Thanke be gode all-myght!</NOTE></L>
<L>A riche man of &thorn;at ilke londe<NOTE PLACE="foot2">ilke fehlt.</NOTE></L>
<L>Al &thorn;at me ned wes, he me founde<NOTE PLACE="foot2">All &thorn;at nedyde. fonde.</NOTE></L>
<L>And dobede me to kni&yogh;tte."<NOTE PLACE="foot2">dubyde. a st. to.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"A, bro&thorn;er, let me tellen &thorn;e:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">A broder late me telle &thorn;e.</NOTE></L>
<L N="350">A wolf &thorn;ere com and kipte me<NOTE PLACE="foot2">camme. cau&yogh;ht.</NOTE></L>
<L>And ber me in his mou&thorn;e.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">bore. mothe.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e ploumen wel &thorn;at .I.-seye,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Plow|mene &thorn;at syght &thorn;<SUP>i</SUP> se,</NOTE></L>
<L>And blewen hout horn in &thorn;e leye,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">And to hym fast &thorn;<SUP>i</SUP> dyde hy&yogh;e,</NOTE></L>
<L>Stark men and cou&thorn;e.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Stronge mene, &amp; welle &thorn;<SUP>i</SUP> cowthe.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="355">Wel softeliche hy me aredde.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">The wolfe fore fere do (u)ne me leyde.</NOTE></L>
<L>And se&thorn;&thorn;en a levedi me fedde<NOTE PLACE="foot2">lady me hath fedde.</NOTE></L>
<L>And dobbede me to kni&yogh;tte;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">dubyde. a st. to.</NOTE></L>
<L>Hoe fond me palefrey and stede,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Sche me fonde.</NOTE></L>
<L>Helm and brunie and o&thorn;er wede,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Helme, habyrione &amp; odour wede,</NOTE></L>
<L N="360">And swerd and spere wel bri&yogh;tte."<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Spere &amp; swerde full bryght.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Here moder al &thorn;is .I.-herdde<NOTE PLACE="foot2">There. herde.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ere hoe wes in on orcherdde,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&THORN;er as sche was in a &yogh;erde.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wepinde al for blisse.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Sche wepe.</NOTE></L>
<L>To hire bour hoe wende anon,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">sche went.</NOTE></L>
<L N="365">So swi&thorn;e so hoe mi&yogh;tte gon,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Also swyth as sche couthe gone.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wi&thorn; mikel gladnesse.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">fulle mykille.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;er com ride sire Ewstas<NOTE PLACE="foot2">camme rydinge.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;er his wif at inne was,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">There &thorn;at lady inne was.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e kni&yogh;tes for to seche.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">to sekyne swythe.</NOTE></L>
<L N="370">Hoe bihoeld &thorn;at fayre kni&yogh;t,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Sche beheld &thorn;at sembly kn(y)ght.</NOTE></L>
<L>And he &thorn;at lewedi, &thorn;at wes bri&yogh;t,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">lady. was so bryght</NOTE></L>
<L>Mid chere wel loueliche.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">With chere fayre &amp; blythe.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Dame, quad he, sey &thorn;ou me,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">he seyd. tell.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wat men her houte at inne be<NOTE PLACE="foot2">here. houte fehlt.</NOTE></L>
<L N="375">At &thorn;isse nekste howse?"<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&thorn;is nexte.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Sire, quad hoe, kni&yogh;ttes tweyne.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Syre, I knaw &thorn;er k. two.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wel &thorn;ou shalt .I.-cnowen beyne &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">schall theme know also.</NOTE></L>
<L>Welcome, mi leue spowse!<NOTE PLACE="foot2">lefe.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Mi louerd, ich .I.-cnowe &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot2">we(l) I knaw the.</NOTE></L>
<L N="380">Bi one wonde, &thorn;at ich .I.-se<NOTE PLACE="foot2">a. I se.</NOTE></L>
<L>Oupon &thorn;i neb .I.-sene.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">nose is sene.</NOTE></L>
<L>Lemman, ich haue harde .I.-fare,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">A, lord, I hade herde fare</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000357.tif" N="219"></L>
<L>.I.-lad mi lif in mikel kare,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">And lede my lyue in mykyll care,</NOTE></L>
<L>Ich wot, and nouht ne wene.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">I tell &yogh;ou now by|dene. Darauf hat A. eine Strophe mehr: Fro the I was take with a schypman, And wened I schulde haue be his leman, He was not of my laye. A knyght &thorn;er was in &thorn;at schyppe, That fro &thorn;e schypmane he dyde me helpe And brou&yogh;ht me safe awaye.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="385">Mi lefman, wille we gon<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Suete lord, wyll &yogh;e gone.</NOTE></L>
<L>To &thorn;is nekste house a-non,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">nexte hous anone.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ere hy ben hole and sounde!<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&YOGH;our chylder &thorn;er they be</NOTE></L>
<L>And make we Joye and mikel blis!<NOTE PLACE="foot2">And make grete Joye in &thorn;at house</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;onked be swete Jhesus,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">And thanke owre lorde, suete Jhe|sus,</NOTE></L>
<L N="390">Of kare we ben ounbounde."<NOTE PLACE="foot2">And gode in trinyte.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bo&thorn;e hy wenten &thorn;idere anon,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&thorn;<SUP>i</SUP> went &thorn;eder.</NOTE></L>
<L>So swi&thorn;e so hy mi&yogh;ten gon.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Also swyth as &thorn;<SUP>i</SUP> my&yogh;ht gone</NOTE></L>
<L>Welcomed hy weren fayre.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">And come into &thorn;e halle. Darauf hat A. folg. 6 Verse mehr: And when &thorn;at &thorn;<SUP>i</SUP> there sonnes se, &THORN;<SUP>i</SUP> thankyd god in trinyte And also suet seynt Palle. The two kny&yogh;htys &thorn;er fader knew And sone onne kneys sone &thorn;<SUP>i</SUP> flewe And thankyd god all|myght. Dann folgt: Fore joye &thorn;at they togeder wer mette All fowre full faste &thorn;<SUP>i</SUP> dyde wepe, And so dyde many a wyght.</NOTE></L>
<L>Men beden hem sitten and drinken vin</L>
<L N="395">Wi&thorn; coupe and eke wi&thorn; maselin,</L>
<L>And maden hem chere fayre.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Sire Ewstace tolde hem of his kare,</L>
<L>His stronge lif, his harde fare.</L>
<L>&THORN;e kni&yogh;ttes wepen for blisse &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">397&mdash;9) Syre Eustas ganne to telle tho Of his Joy &amp; of hys wo &THORN;at he hade bene inne.</NOTE></L>
<L N="400">Ne mi&yogh;tte here non wi&thorn; o&thorn;er speke,</L>
<L>Ne no word out of hem atbreke,</L>
<L>Bote wepe and cluppe and cusse.<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Ms. &thorn;a.</NOTE>,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">400&mdash;2) Than &thorn;er was none at &thorn;at borde That fore wepynge myght speke a worde, Nor none in &thorn;at Inne. Darauf hat A. noch folg. Strophe: So glad of odour Ichone &thorn;<SUP>i</SUP> were: &THORN;<SUP>i</SUP> kyssed &amp; made gode chere And fyllede &thorn;e wyne anone, And tolde how &thorn;<SUP>i</SUP> wer crystinde And thou&yogh;ht &thorn;er care was with-stond And sorow was fro theme gone.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e enperovr .I.-herde &thorn;is<NOTE PLACE="foot2">herd telle of &thorn;is</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at hy maden ioye and blis,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">How &thorn;<SUP>i</SUP> wer in Joy &amp; blysse.</NOTE></L>
<L N="405">And cristine &thorn;at hy were.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">crystinde. &thorn;<SUP>i</SUP>.</NOTE></L>
<L>He sente kni&yogh;ttes sone anon,</L>
<L>For to fecchen euer-ich on<NOTE PLACE="foot2">To seke theme vp euerych-one.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at hy founden &thorn;ere.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&thorn;<SUP>i</SUP>. were st. &thorn;ere.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>He let hem don in prisoun strong,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Statt 409&mdash;14 hat A. folg. V.: When &thorn;<SUP>i</SUP> wer before hym brou&yogh;ht, Them to scle it was his thou&yogh;ht: And so fore-sothe he dyde. Fore all-my&yogh;hty godys sake The deth to &thorn;em &thorn;<SUP>i</SUP> wolde take, What deth as he them bedde.</NOTE></L>
<L N="410">Liouns and leuparz hem among</L>
<L>And bestes sui&thorn;e fele.</L>
<L>&THORN;e bestes, &thorn;a(t) weren stronge and wilde,</L>
<L>&THORN;ey weren of hem glade and milde:</L>
<L>Ne mi&yogh;tten hoe hoem qvelle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="415">He let hem don in bolen of bras,</L>
<L>Euerich in his, wel so&thorn; hit was,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">415&mdash;6) He dyde them in a panne of brasse, Also hote as euer it was,</NOTE></L>
<L>And beten fuir abouten.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">And made fyere abowtyne.</NOTE></L>
<L>Alle hy weren &thorn;ere .I.-brende,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">All fowre &thorn;erin he brente.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e soules in to heuene wende &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&THORN;er saulys onto h. wente.</NOTE></L>
<L N="420">Of pine hy weren wi&thorn;houten.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Of payne &thorn;<SUP>i</SUP> wer w.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bidde we alle seint Eustace<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Beseke. all.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at he do hous hauen grace,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">graunte vs all g.</NOTE></L>
<L>To heuene for to wende,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at we moten &thorn;ere wone</L>
<L N="425">Wi&thorn; Jhesu, seinte Marie sone,</L>
<L>Euere wi&thorn;-houten hende. Amen.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">424&mdash;6) To Jhesu, seynt Mary sonne, And &thorn;er withouten ende to wonne. God &thorn;at grace vs sende. Amen. Explicit vita sci Eustachii.</NOTE>
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="2" TYPE="legend"><PB REF="00000358.tif" N="[220]">
<HEAD>2. Coment le sauter noustre dame fu primes cuntroue.
<NOTE PLACE="foot">Varianten des Ms. Auchinl:</NOTE>Ms. Digby 86, fol. 130.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>Dasselbe Gedicht findet sich in dem bekannten, etwas j&uuml;ngern Ms. Auchinl fol. 259 (c. 1410) und ist hieraus edirt in David Laing's A Penniworth of Witte (f&uuml;r den Abbotsf. Club). In Ms. Dig. ist von fol. 131 unten ein St&uuml;ck schr&auml;g abgeschnitten, wodurch mehrere Verse ganz oder theilweise zerst&ouml;rt sind. Das Fehlende ist aus Ms. Auch. erg&auml;nzt.</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Leuedi swete and milde,</L>
<L>For loue of &thorn;ine childe</L>
<L>&THORN;at is foul of mi&yogh;tte,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Jhesu st. &thorn;at is. ful of mi&yogh;t.</NOTE></L>
<L>Me, &thorn;at am to wilde,<NOTE PLACE="foot">so st. to.</NOTE></L>
<L N="5">From shome &thorn;ou me shilde,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Fram schame. schylde.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bi day and eke bi ni&yogh;tte!<NOTE PLACE="foot">eke fehlt. ni&yogh;t.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ich wille biginnen here<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ichil bigennen.</NOTE></L>
<L>And tellen &thorn;e manere</L>
<L>Nou at &thorn;isse stounde<NOTE PLACE="foot">Now in &thorn;is.</NOTE></L>
<L N="10">Of &thorn;i sauter here,</L>
<L>Mid wel gode chere,<NOTE PLACE="foot">wi&thorn;.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ou hit wes .I.-founde.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Hou it was y-founde.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Send me &thorn;ine grace<NOTE PLACE="foot">Sende. &thorn;i.</NOTE></L>
<L>Nou in &thorn;isse place,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Now. &thorn;is.</NOTE></L>
<L N="15">So wel for to done!<NOTE PLACE="foot">wele.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ich nou bidde &thorn;i grace,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Y bid &thorn;e &thorn;i.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;erto lif and space.<NOTE PLACE="foot">And fehlt. liif.</NOTE></L>
<L>Here nou mine bone!<NOTE PLACE="foot">y-here now mi.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A riche man was wile,<NOTE PLACE="foot">while.</NOTE></L>
<L N="20">&THORN;at nolde none gile;<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at loued no.</NOTE></L>
<L>He louede holi chirche.<NOTE PLACE="foot">loued.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bi-sides him a mile<NOTE PLACE="foot">Bisiden.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>On abbey of seint Gile<NOTE PLACE="foot">An abbay. seyn.</NOTE></L>
<L>His helderne gonne werche.<NOTE PLACE="foot">eldren. dede st. gonne. wirche.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="25">God lif &thorn;is man ladde.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Gode liif.</NOTE></L>
<L>One sone he hadde,<NOTE PLACE="foot">On.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at gode dedes dede.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; clo&thorn; and wi&thorn; bedde</L>
<L>His sone faire he sredde<NOTE PLACE="foot">fair. schredde.</NOTE></L>
<L N="30">In &thorn;at ilke stede.<NOTE PLACE="foot">In &thorn;ilke.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Monk he &thorn;ere bicom,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Monke &thorn;erin he bicam. Hierauf sind 13 Zeilen ausgeschnitten.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wi&thorn; abit he &thorn;er nom,</L>
<L>Bi his fader wille.</L>
<L>Him louede god and mon &mdash;</L>
<L N="35">So feire he bigon,</L>
<L>Wor euere he wes stille.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>His fader him bimenede</L>
<L>&THORN;at he &thorn;erinne wende</L>
<L>So &yogh;ong sholde, .I.-wis.</L>
<L N="40">He dede after him sende</L>
<L>"&THORN;at is nou &thorn;at ende",</L>
<L>And made him muchel blis.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A maister hadde his sone</L>
<L>&THORN;at wi&thorn; him wef .I.-come,
<PB REF="00000359.tif" N="221"></L>
<L N="45">Cointe .I.-nou and sley;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Queint man and slei&yogh;e.</NOTE></L>
<L>Hit wes his .I.-wone<NOTE PLACE="foot2">For it was euer his wone,</NOTE></L>
<L>To techen alle and some<NOTE PLACE="foot2">To teche him bi costome.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e ordre, fer and ney.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">order. nei&yogh;e.</NOTE></L>
<L>He hede ofte aboute<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&yogh;ede for&thorn; about.</NOTE></L>
<L N="50">Wi&thorn;-innen and wi&thorn;-oute<NOTE PLACE="foot2">inne. out.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;e louerd on day.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">lord. a st. on.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e sone he lek(!) &thorn;er oute:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">His sone he lete &thorn;er out.</NOTE></L>
<L>He hede for to aloute &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&yogh;ede fer to.</NOTE></L>
<L>Tellen ich ou may &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&yogh;ou.</NOTE></L>
<L N="55">&THORN;e leuedi ful of mi&yogh;tte<NOTE PLACE="foot2">mi&yogh;t.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at bar oure dri&yogh;tte,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">our dri&yogh;t.</NOTE></L>
<L>In a chapele &thorn;ere,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">chapel.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bi day and eke bi ni&yogh;tte<NOTE PLACE="foot2">eke fehlt. ni&yogh;t.</NOTE></L>
<L>Out wen he comen mi&yogh;tte,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">When he &thorn;er-to com mi&yogh;t.</NOTE></L>
<L N="60">Were ware he were.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">where st. ware.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ou alle ich telle may:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&YOGH;ou al tellen y may.</NOTE></L>
<L>On houndred ewche day<NOTE PLACE="foot2">An hundred ich.</NOTE></L>
<L>He gretingges seyde.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Greteinges he seyd.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wel he held his lay<NOTE PLACE="foot2">wele.</NOTE></L>
<L N="65">And &thorn;e ordre, bi mi fay!<NOTE PLACE="foot2">order. par ma fay.</NOTE></L>
<L>For loue of &thorn;at meyde.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">mayde.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wel he hedde hi-wrout,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">wele. hadde y-wrou&yogh;t.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wor god wes his &thorn;out:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">For gode was. &thorn;ou&yogh;t.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at wes wel .I.-sene;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">was wele y-sen.</NOTE></L>
<L N="70">He ne les hit nohut,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">no lesse it nou&yogh;t.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wor he hit hadde about<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Heuen he hadde y-bou&yogh;t.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;orou his gode bene.<MILESTONE N="131" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="foot2">&THORN;urgh. ben.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ne let he none stounde<NOTE PLACE="foot2">No lete. non.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at he ne fel to grounde<NOTE PLACE="foot2">no.</NOTE></L>
<L N="75">And on knewes bat<NOTE PLACE="foot2">And a knowes badde.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;oute of &thorn;e wonde<NOTE PLACE="foot2">And &thorn;ou&yogh;t on &thorn;e fif wounde.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at god for al &thorn;e mounde<NOTE PLACE="foot2">all.</NOTE></L>
<L>On rode heuede .I.-sprad.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">hadde. y.</NOTE></L>
<L>On houndret to &thorn;e meyde<NOTE PLACE="foot2">An hundred. maide.</NOTE></L>
<L N="80">Aue maries he seyde<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Greteinges he seyd.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bi tale heche daye.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">ich day.</NOTE></L>
<L>He hit nout ne aleyde,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">He nou&yogh;t it no layd.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ac so wel he pleyde &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">wele. playd.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ri&yogh;t so&thorn; for to saye &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">so&thorn;e. say.</NOTE></L>
<L N="85">&THORN;at he sau wel bri&yogh;tte<NOTE PLACE="foot2">sei&yogh;e. bri&yogh;t.</NOTE></L>
<L>Oure leuedi foul of mi&yogh;tte<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Our. ful. mi&yogh;t.</NOTE></L>
<L>A settres-day, .I.-wis,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">On a saterday ywis.</NOTE></L>
<L>Were hoe sat wel ri&yogh;tte<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Where sche. up st. wel. ri&yogh;t.</NOTE></L>
<L>.I.-clo&thorn;ed half bi si&yogh;tte,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Half clo&thorn;ed. si&yogh;t.</NOTE></L>
<L N="90">And seyde to him &thorn;is:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">seyd.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Mi monk, ne dred &thorn;e nout,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">no drede. nau&yogh;t.</NOTE></L>
<L>For .I. &thorn;e haue .I.-bout<NOTE PLACE="foot2">y-lau&yogh;t.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;e ich wille take.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">y &thorn;e wil.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ou hauest so goed fulwraut(!):<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&thorn;ou hast don a gode frau&yogh;t,</NOTE></L>
<L N="95">Ne worst &thorn;ou nout bikaut:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">No bestow nou&yogh;t bi-cau&yogh;t.</NOTE></L>
<L>Goed ne shal &thorn;e lake.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">God. schal.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ich &thorn;onke &thorn;e her nou&thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot2">y &thorn;anke. here.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou wi&thorn; &thorn;ine mou&thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot2">For &thorn;atow. &thorn;i.</NOTE></L>
<L>Me hauest .I.-paied wel;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">hast paid so wel.</NOTE></L>
<L N="100">Bi nor&thorn;e and eke bi (sou&thorn;e)<NOTE PLACE="foot2">nor&thorn;. eke fehlt.</NOTE></L>
<L>Hit shal ben w(el cou&thorn;e)<NOTE PLACE="foot2">It schal be wel cou&thorn;e.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ine dedes (euerich del).<NOTE PLACE="foot2">eueridel.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000360.tif" N="222"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ac &thorn;ou m(ost more say)</L>
<L>Wor (me now euche day)<NOTE PLACE="foot">For. ich day.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot1">100&mdash;104 Im Ms. ist ein St&uuml;ck des Blattes schr&auml;g abgeschnitten. Das Fehlende ist aus Ms. Auch. erg&auml;nzt.</NOTE></L>
<L N="105">Fifti al bi score</L>
<L>Of aue maries,</L>
<L>Fifti on day &thorn;ries.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Fifti fehlt(!). Ich day &thorn;ries.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wite nou were-fore:<NOTE PLACE="foot">wharfore.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;at is ri&yogh;t mi sauter.</L>
<L N="110">And &thorn;ou shalt witen her<NOTE PLACE="foot">it schalt y-wite here.</NOTE></L>
<L>Hou hit shal ben do:<NOTE PLACE="foot">it schal be.</NOTE></L>
<L>Fifti seye bi-fore,<NOTE PLACE="foot">say.</NOTE></L>
<L>Tene euere bi score,<NOTE PLACE="foot">And euer ten.</NOTE></L>
<L>And on anteme &thorn;erto,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e antemis.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="115">In tokning of &thorn;e blisse<NOTE PLACE="foot">tokne.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at fel me midi-wisse<NOTE PLACE="foot">wi&thorn;-y-wis.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;e aungele to me com<NOTE PLACE="foot">angel. cam.</NOTE></L>
<L>And seyde me tidinge<NOTE PLACE="foot">seyd. tiding.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at of me sholde springe<NOTE PLACE="foot">schuld spring.</NOTE></L>
<L N="120">He &thorn;at is god and mon.<NOTE PLACE="foot">God bicome a man.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>After sey wel sone<NOTE PLACE="foot">say &thorn;ou sone.</NOTE></L>
<L>Fifti mididone<NOTE PLACE="foot">middidone.</NOTE></L>
<L>Al for &thorn;at ilke blisse<NOTE PLACE="foot">ich blis.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at he wi&thorn;-outen (sore)</L>
<L N="125">Wolde of me ben (bore)&mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">wald. be.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou &thorn;er-(of ne misse)!<NOTE PLACE="foot">&THORN;erof &thorn;at &thorn;ou no misse.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;er aft(er &thorn;ou shalt say)<NOTE PLACE="foot">ich day.</NOTE></L>
<L>Eft (fifti euche day)</L>
<L>Bi (&thorn;ine fingres ten)</L>
<L N="130">O(f aue maries)</L>
<L>(Euche day &thorn;ries&mdash;</L>
<L>Telle hit fele men!&mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Fifti at &thorn;en ende,</L>
<L>For I shulde wende</L>
<L N="135">To mi sone &thorn;o,</L>
<L>For blis, and for to amende,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he to me gan sende),<NOTE PLACE="foot">131&mdash;137) Die in D. fehlenden Verse lauten in A.: Ich day &thorn;ries. Telle it fele men. Fifti at &thorn;e nende, For y schuld wende To my sone &thorn;o, For blis and forto amende &THORN;at he to me gan sende.</NOTE></L>
<L>To me comen and go:<NOTE PLACE="foot1">124&mdash;138 Im Ms. ist ein St&uuml;ck des Blattes schr&auml;g abgeschnitten. Das Fehlende ist aus Ms. Auch. erg&auml;nzt.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>He broute me to blisse,<NOTE PLACE="foot">brou&yogh;t. to &thorn;e blis.</NOTE></L>
<L N="140">&THORN;at neuere ne shal misse,<NOTE PLACE="foot">neuer no schal mis.</NOTE></L>
<L>In &thorn;at ilke stounde.<NOTE PLACE="foot">ich.</NOTE></L>
<L>Blesced be &thorn;at time<NOTE PLACE="foot">Blisced. &thorn;e.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at alle brovte of pine<NOTE PLACE="foot">&THORN;at he brou&yogh;t out of pine</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at weren &thorn;erinne .I.-bounde!"<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at fehlt. &THORN;er-in were y bounde.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="145">"A, leuedi, .I. &thorn;e grete,<NOTE PLACE="foot">y.</NOTE></L>
<L>For &thorn;ou art fair and swete</L>
<L>And goed, to serui wel.<NOTE PLACE="foot">gode. serue.</NOTE></L>
<L>Graunte me &thorn;in ore,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Graunt. &thorn;i nore.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wor .I. shal euere-more<NOTE PLACE="foot">For y schal euer-more.</NOTE></L>
<L N="150">Don &thorn;is euerich del.<NOTE PLACE="foot">eueri.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>If ich dourste and cou&thorn;e,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;if y durst.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ich wolde .I.-witen nou&thorn;e,<NOTE PLACE="foot">wald wite.</NOTE></L>
<L>Leuedi, here of &thorn;e:</L>
<L>Wi &thorn;e faille&thorn; gore,<NOTE PLACE="foot">whi. failes.</NOTE></L>
<L N="155">ssleue and nammore<NOTE PLACE="foot">Sleuen. no more.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of clo&thorn; &thorn;at ich .I.-se?"<NOTE PLACE="foot">Of clo&thorn; ich on &thorn;e se.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"&THORN;is clo&thorn; &thorn;ou me &yogh;eue<NOTE PLACE="foot">clo&thorn;e.</NOTE></L>
<L>(On se)ttresday(!) a&yogh;ein eue,<NOTE PLACE="foot">On Friday at eue.</NOTE></L>
