<DIV2 N="3" TYPE="legend"><PB REF="00000363.tif" N="[225]">
<HEAD>3. Seynt Mergrete.
<NOTE PLACE="foot">Diese Hs. enth&auml;lt: 1) vita Ricardi regis primi, 2) Ysumbra, 3) Katerine, 4) Matutinas de cruce, 5) King Athelstons deth, 6) Beffs de Hamptoun, 7) de spiritu Guidonis.</NOTE>Ms. Auchinl. fol. 16b. (c. 1310).</HEAD> 
<HEADNOTE><P>Ms. Auchinl., aus dem Anfang des 14. Jhrhds., enth&auml;lt folg. Legenden: 1) Grego|rius fol. 1, Anfang fehlt, im Ms. als 6. St&uuml;ck bezeichnet (die ersten 5 sind ausgefallen), 2) Adam und Eva (2 Fragmente), 3) Mergrete, 4) Katherine, 5) eine Marienlegende, Anfang fehlt, (beginnt: An angel sche sent to him anon, He gret &thorn;e clerk wi&thorn; milde steuen, Into &thorn;e chaumber when he gan gon, He was bri&yogh;ter &thorn;an ani leuen), 6) Mag|dalene fol. 62&mdash;5, Anfang fehlt, 7) Geburt Marias und Christi (in Turnbull's Ausg. be|titelt Joachim &amp; Anna), unvollendet, 8) die Entstehung des Psalters Mari&auml; (auch in Ms. Digby 86). Hiervon sind N. 1, 3, 7, 4, 6 abgedruckt in (Turnbull's) "Legendae Catholicae, a lytle boke of Seyntlie Gestes", Edinb. 1840; N. 2 u. 8 in D. Laing's "A Penniworth of witte" 1857 (f&uuml;r den Abbotsford Club); Adam und Eva, und Magda|lene erschienen ausserdem in der "Sammlung altengl. Leg." Heilbronn 1878, p. 139 u. 163 ff. Das Gedicht von der Geburt Marias u. Christi ist ein Theil des l&auml;ngeren, das alte und neue Testament umfassenden Gedichtes in Langversen (diese sind im Ms. Auch. in Kurzzeilen aufgel&ouml;st), welches in mehreren Mss. der s&uuml;dengl. Legendensamm|lung erhalten ist; es beginnt mit den Uebergangsversen am Ende des 1. Theiles (alt|testamentliche Gedichte) und stimmt von V. 11 an gr&ouml;sstentheils &uuml;berein mit dem in den "Altengl. Leg." Paderborn 1875 p. 65 ff. aus Ms. Ashm. 43 und Egert. 1993 ge|druckten Gedichte von V. 81 ab; andere Mss. sind Ms. Vernon fol. 6 b., Trin. Coll. Cbr. R. 3, 25 fol. 20, Lamb. 223 fol. 33, John's Coll. Cbr. B, 6 fol. 25; vgl. "Altengl. Leg." p. XIV Anm. 1. &mdash; Mergrete und Katherine sind im Ms. in Halbversen und acht|zeiligen Strophen geschrieben; das Original hatte offenbar Langverse und vierzeilige Strophen. Der &auml;lteste Text dieser Merg. hat in der That diese Strophenform, es ist das, nach einem leider! verloren gegangenen Cbr. Ms. in Hickes' Thesaurus I. p. 224 abgedruckte Gedicht (nach Hickes' Text wieder abgedruckt in O. Cockayn's S. Marh.); die 1. Strophe lautet:</P><LG TYPE="stanza"><L>Olde and yonge, i prei ou oure folies forto lete,</L><L>&THORN;enchet on god &thorn;at yef ou wit oure sunnes to bete!</L><L>Here i mai tellen ou wi&thorn; wordes feire ant swete</L><L>&THORN;e vie of one meidan, was hoten Maregrete.</L></LG><P>Die Gedichte in dieser Strophenform geh&ouml;ren wohl noch in die erste H&auml;lfte des 13. Jhrhds. und zu den &auml;ltesten Erzeugnissen der altengl. Litt. &mdash; Eine j&uuml;ngere (schlechte) Nachbildung der Merg. enth&auml;lt Ms. Ashm. 61 fol. 145 (c. 1450). &mdash; Eine zweite Hs. der Katherine fand ich in Ms. Caj. Coll. Cbr. 175 fol. 107 (14. Jhrht.), die besonders dadurch werthvoll ist, dass sie den im Ms. Auch. ausgefallenen Schluss (V. 661&mdash;794) enth&auml;lt; hier sind die H&auml;lften der im Ms. Auch. bereits aufgel&ouml;sten Langverse wieder unter sich durch den Reim verbunden und dadurch in der That achtzeilige Strophen gebildet<NOTE PLACE="foot">E. K&ouml;lbing hatte die G&uuml;te, die Correctur der 2 folg. Legenden des Ms. Auch. nochmals mit dem Original zu vergleichen.</NOTE></P></HEADNOTE>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<PB REF="00000364.tif" N="226">
<L>Al &thorn;at ben in dedly sinne &verbar; and &thorn;enk wi&thorn; merci to mete,</L>
<L>Leue in Crist &thorn;at &yogh;aue &yogh;ou witt &verbar; &yogh;our sinnes forto bete.</L>
<L>Listen, and &yogh;e schul here telle &verbar; wi&thorn; wordes fair and swete</L>
<L>&THORN;e vie of on maiden, &verbar; men clepe&thorn; seyn Mergre(te).</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="5">Hir fader was a patriarke, &verbar; as y &yogh;ou telle may,</L>
<L>In Antiage he was born &verbar; opon &thorn;at false lay;</L>
<L>Feble was his hert, &verbar; vnstable was his fay,</L>
<L>Deue &thorn;inges and doumbe &verbar; he serued ni&yogh;t and day.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Teodosus was his name. &verbar; in god no leued he nou&yogh;t:</L>
<L N="10">He leued opon his fals godes &verbar; wi&thorn; hondes &thorn;at were wrou&yogh;t;</L>
<L>Wicked weren his werkes &verbar; and feble was his &thorn;ou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And euer he &thorn;ou&yogh;t to bring &verbar; cristendom to nou&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>As &thorn;ai liued togider, &verbar; &thorn;e king and &thorn;e quene,</L>
<L>Maiden Mergrete &verbar; was geten hem bitvene,</L>
<L N="15">&THORN;at se&thorn;&thorn;en leued on Jhesu Crist &verbar; and hadde michel tene,</L>
<L>And miche pine &thorn;oled se&thorn;&thorn;e &verbar; hir bodi, &thorn;at was so schene.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>While &thorn;e quen &yogh;ede wi&thorn; child, . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="foot">Hier sind im Ms. 11 Halbzeilen mit der Illustration der R&uuml;ckseite ausgeschnitten.</NOTE></L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L N="20">. . . . .</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L>&THORN;at it were to de&thorn; brou&yogh;t &verbar; wi&thorn;outen more striif.</L>
<L>&THORN;o hye herd &thorn;at tiding, &verbar; sche wex a careful wiif.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="25">Anon so Mergrete was yborn, &verbar; hir moder was wel wo,</L>
<L>For hir fader hadde beden &verbar; to de&thorn; &thorn;at sche schuld go.</L>
<L>Sche &thorn;ou&yogh;t to saue &thorn;e childes liif &verbar; and bring hir out of wo:</L>
<L>Ful priueliche and stille &verbar; to Azie sche sent hir &thorn;o.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Into Azies-ward &verbar; &thorn;e child was taken to loke.</L>
<L N="30">Anon as sche was of eld, &verbar; Mergrete was sett to boke.</L>
<L>Hir felawes &thorn;at hir lyen bi, &verbar; at ich time &thorn;at &thorn;ei woke,</L>
<L>Hou Mergrete was in hir bedes &verbar; gode hede &thorn;ai toke.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e norice &thorn;at hir &yogh;emed, &verbar; sche &yogh;emed hir wi&thorn; winne;</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;ai loued hir ful wele, &verbar; &thorn;e hous &thorn;er sche wond inne.</L>
<L N="35">Anon as sche cou&thorn;e witt, &verbar; michel sche hated sinne;</L>
<L>Sche toke hir to Jhesu Crist, &verbar; hir form liif to biginne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Anon as &thorn;e mayden was &verbar; o fiftene winter eld,</L>
<L>Hir norice schepe &verbar; sche &yogh;emed on &thorn;e feld.</L>
<L>Hir felawes &thorn;at hir wi&thorn; were &verbar; ful &yogh;ern &thorn;ai hir biheld</L>
<L N="40">Hou sche maked hir praier &verbar; to Jhesus, &thorn;at al may weld.
<PB REF="00000365.tif" N="227"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Olibrious was lord, &verbar; as we heren telle,</L>
<L>Of Antiage and Azie, &verbar; to &yogh;euen and to selle.</L>
<L>He serued bo&thorn;e ni&yogh;t and day &verbar; &thorn;e foule fendes of helle.</L>
<L>Al &thorn;at leued on Jhesu Crist &verbar; Olibrious &thorn;ou&yogh;t to quelle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="45">Fram Antiage into Asie &verbar; er miles ten &amp; fiue.<MILESTONE N="17" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. tene mit auspunkt. e.</NOTE></L>
<L>For to stru &thorn;e cristen folk &verbar; (he hiede him biliue).<NOTE PLACE="foot">Hick. he hiede him biliue; Ms. Auch. liest unrichtig: and bringen hem oliue.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ai sey&yogh;e maiden Mergrete &verbar; schepe biforn hir driue:</L>
<L>Olibrious for hir fairnesse &verbar; &yogh;erned hir to wiue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>He seyd to his kni&yogh;tes: &verbar; "a fair maiden y se;</L>
<L N="50">Kestes hir opon hors, &verbar; and sche schal wende wi&thorn; me.</L>
<L>And &yogh;if ich may enquere &verbar; of kin &thorn;at sche be fre,</L>
<L>Of alle &thorn;e wimen &thorn;at y wot &verbar; best hir schal be.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And for hir michel feirhed, &verbar; &yogh;if sche be born of &thorn;ral.</L>
<L>Hir mariage &verbar; no tine&thorn; sche nou&yogh;t al:</L>
<L N="55">Wele y schal hir clo&thorn;e &verbar; in sikelatoun and pal,</L>
<L>Sche schal be mi leman &verbar; and haue gold to wal.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e seriaunce went, as he hem bad, &verbar; to maiden Mergrete,</L>
<L>&THORN;er sche &yogh;emed hir norice schepe &verbar; o dayes bi &thorn;e strete.</L>
<L>Michel it was &thorn;at &thorn;ai hir bede, &verbar; and more &thorn;ai hir bihete;</L>
<L N="60">&THORN;e &thorn;ou&yogh;tes of hir hert &verbar; wald sche nou&yogh;t forlete.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e seriaunce of her erand &verbar; wald hir nou&yogh;t biswike:</L>
<L>"Damisel, we say it &thorn;e &verbar; ful wele may &thorn;e like.</L>
<L>Olibrious is louerd &verbar; of Antiage rike,</L>
<L>He &yogh;erne&thorn; &thorn;e to wiue, &verbar; he nil &thorn;e nou&yogh;t biswike".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="65">&THORN;an maiden Mergrete, &verbar; bri&yogh;t so ani leuen,</L>
<L>Sche hem answerd &verbar; wi&thorn; ful mild steuen:</L>
<L>"Ichaue &yogh;euen mi maidenhed &verbar; to Jhesus Crist of heuen,</L>
<L>&YOGH;eme it, &yogh;if his willes is, &verbar; for his name seuen.<NOTE PLACE="foot">l. wille, namen.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Jhesu Crist mi lord, &verbar; to &yogh;ou y me rend;</L>
<L N="70">In &yogh;ou was no bigining, &verbar; no neuer schal ben ende;</L>
<L>&YOGH;if it be &yogh;our wille, &verbar; &yogh;our angel &yogh;e me sende!</L>
<L>Fram &thorn;is foule Sara&yogh;ins &verbar; y may me nou&yogh;t defende.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Al mi kin ichaue forsake &verbar; into mi nei&yogh;d kne;</L>
<L>Jhesu Crist, mi lord, &verbar; y toke me to &thorn;e;</L>
<L N="75">Ble&thorn;eliche wald y, for &thorn;i loue &verbar; martird to be.</L>
<L>&THORN;is houndes me han bisett, &verbar; &thorn;at I no may nou&yogh;t fle".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e seriaunce o&yogh;ain went &verbar; and told al her sawe.</L>
<L>"Lord, of &thorn;i pouste &verbar; no &yogh;iue&thorn; sche nou&yogh;t an hawe;</L>
<L>Sche take&thorn; hir to Jhesu Crist, &verbar; to warantise wil sche drawe.</L>
<L N="80">Of al &thorn;at &yogh;e may hir do, &verbar; no stont hir non awe".
<PB REF="00000366.tif" N="228"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;an it spac Olibrious &mdash; &verbar; weri him sonne and mone! &mdash;</L>
<L>"Of al min seriance &verbar; gode haue y none.</L>
<L>Bringe&thorn; hir bifor me! &verbar; y turn hir mode ful sone,</L>
<L>Y do hir leue opon mi god, &verbar; &thorn;riies ar it be none".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="85">&THORN;e seriaunce o&yogh;ain went, &verbar; sone &thorn;ai gan hir mete;</L>
<L>&THORN;ai leyd hondes hir opon &verbar; and brou&yogh;t hir to &thorn;e strete.</L>
<L>Sche com bifor Olibrious. &verbar; sone he gan hir grete,</L>
<L>He axed hir what sche hi&yogh;t. &verbar; sche seyd: Mergrete.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Maiden Mergrete, &verbar; mi leman schaltow be.</L>
<L N="90">Ichold &thorn;e for mi wiif, &verbar; &yogh;if &thorn;ou be of kin fre;</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ow be of &thorn;raldam born, &verbar; y giue &thorn;e gold and fe.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou schalt be mi leman, &verbar; so long so it be".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e maiden him answerd &verbar; sone opon on:</L>
<L>"Cristen woman icham &verbar; and houen in fun-ston.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. heuen?</NOTE></L>
<L N="95">Blisced be mi lord, &verbar; to wham ichaue me tan!</L>
<L>No wil y nou&yogh;t leue is loue &verbar; for non o&thorn;er man".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Trowestow &thorn;at Jhesu liues, &verbar; &thorn;at was don on rode?</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou trowest &thorn;at he liues, &verbar; ich hold &thorn;e for wode.</L>
<L>Endelong his side &verbar; ran &thorn;e water and &thorn;e blod,</L>
<L N="100">&THORN;e coroun was of &thorn;ornes &verbar; &thorn;at on his heued stode".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e maiden him answerd, &verbar; so &thorn;e angel hir kende:</L>
<L>"He dede him on &thorn;e rode, &verbar; al cristen folk to amende.</L>
<L>And se&thorn;&thorn;en into helle &verbar; &thorn;e holy gost he sende,</L>
<L>To del(i)uer ous of &thorn;e pine, &verbar; &thorn;at &thorn;ou schalt in ende".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="105">Wele &thorn;ou&yogh;t &thorn;at sarra&yogh;in &verbar; it was him no bote</L>
<L>To striue wi&thorn; &thorn;at maiden &mdash; &verbar; hir hert was so gode.</L>
<L>He comand &thorn;at sche bounden ware, &verbar; bo&thorn;e hond and fot,</L>
<L>And se&thorn;&thorn;en into prisoun don, &verbar; to turnen hir mode.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Maiden Mergrete &verbar; o ni&yogh;t in prisoun lay.</L>
<L N="110">Sche was brou&yogh;t biforn him &verbar; opon &thorn;at o&thorn;er day.</L>
<L>"Maiden Mergrete, he seyd, &verbar; &thorn;ou trowe opon mi lay!</L>
<L>Jhesu &thorn;atow leuest on, &verbar; &thorn;ou do him al oway!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Trowe on me &amp; be mi wiif: &verbar; wele &thorn;ou schalt spede;</L>
<L>Antioge and Azie &verbar; &thorn;ou schalt haue to mede;</L>
<L N="115">Sikelatoun and purpel-pal &verbar; &thorn;at schal be &thorn;i wede,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;e best metes in mi lond &verbar; wele y schal &thorn;e fede".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"&THORN;ine wicke redes, sche seyd, &verbar; y do out of mi &thorn;ou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Y take me to Jhesu Crist &verbar; &thorn;at wi&thorn; hondes me wrou&yogh;t;</L>
<L>Al &thorn;is midlerd &verbar; maked he of nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="120">And se&thorn;&thorn;en into helle &verbar; &thorn;e holy gost he brou&yogh;t".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;an it spac Olibrious: &verbar; "now it schal be sene.</L>
<L>Honge&thorn; hir vp bi &thorn;e fete &verbar; for hir lordes tene,
<PB REF="00000367.tif" N="229"></L>
<L>On wham &thorn;at sche leues &verbar; and whi sche is so kene;</L>
<L>And bete&thorn; hir wi&thorn; scourges, &verbar; til &yogh;e ded hir wene!"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="125">&THORN;e seriaunce dede as he hem bad, &verbar; wi&thorn; &thorn;e may &thorn;ai gan striue,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; swepes and wi&thorn; scourges, &verbar; bo&thorn;e man and wiue, &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;e blod ran of hir flesche, &verbar; as water do&thorn; fram cliue, &mdash;</L>
<L>Til &thorn;ai wende al same &verbar; &thorn;e maiden were oliue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;an it spac Olibrious, &verbar; bi hir &thorn;er he stode,</L>
<L N="130">And seyd: "Maiden Mergrete, &verbar; &thorn;enke &thorn;e &thorn;is paines gode?</L>
<L>Trowe on min goddes &verbar; and wende &thorn;ou &thorn;i mode!</L>
<L>Haue merci on &thorn;i white flesche! &verbar; men spille&thorn; &thorn;i blod".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Blisced be mi lord, &verbar; &thorn;at was born in Bedlem<MILESTONE N="18" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Of &thorn;at swete maiden, &verbar; bri&yogh;t so ani lem!</L>
<L N="135">&THORN;ou do as &thorn;e teches &verbar; Satanas, &thorn;i nem.</L>
<L>Me &thorn;enke &thorn;is paines swetter &verbar; &thorn;an ani milkes rem".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;an it spac Olibrious: &verbar; "ha&thorn; sche non ah&yogh;e?</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e paines &yogh;e hir do, &verbar; hir &thorn;enke it bot plawe.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &yogh;our croked nayles &verbar; &thorn;e hide of &yogh;e drawe,</L>
<L N="140">As clene fram &thorn;e bon &verbar; has houndes it hadde knawe!"<NOTE PLACE="foot">knawe st. gnawe.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Alle &thorn;e curssed &thorn;eues &verbar; were ful glad in &thorn;ou&yogh;t;</L>
<L>To do &thorn;e kinges hest &verbar; &thorn;ai no targed nou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Anon as &thorn;e turmentours &verbar; to Mergrete were ybrou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai to-drowen hir white flesche &verbar; wi&thorn; iren croke(d)ly wrou&yogh;t.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. crokekely.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="145">Sum &thorn;at bi hir stoden, &verbar; her hertes were wel sore</L>
<L>And seyd sore wepeand: &verbar; "Mergrete, &thorn;i nore!</L>
<L>Do after Olibrious &verbar; and leue opon his lore!</L>
<L>Haue merci on &thorn;i fair bodi &verbar; and &thorn;ole &thorn;is paines no more!"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Mergrete answerd &verbar; to hem &thorn;at bi hir stode:</L>
<L N="150">"I do me out of &yogh;our conseyl: &verbar; &yogh;our redes be nou&yogh;t gode;</L>
<L>Y take me to Jhesu Crist, &verbar; &thorn;at was don on &thorn;e rode.</L>
<L>Al &thorn;e pine &thorn;at ich &thorn;ole &verbar; it is &thorn;e soules fode".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Sche loked vp to Jhesu Crist, &verbar; Mergrete, and si&yogh;ed sore</L>
<L>And seyd: "swete Jhesu Crist, &verbar; y leue opon &thorn;i lore.</L>
<L N="155">For &thorn;is men &thorn;at pin me &thorn;us, &verbar; y crie, lord, &thorn;i nore:</L>
<L>For&yogh;if hem and lete me suffre! &verbar; for me &thorn;ou suffredest more",</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;an it spac Olibrious &mdash; &verbar; werri him sonne and mone! &mdash;:</L>
<L>"F&oacute;rso&thorn;e, wenche, &thorn;i god is nou&yogh;t &verbar; to whom &thorn;ou biddest &thorn;i bone.</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;ou leue on our godes &verbar; and forsake him sone,</L>
<L N="160">Y warn &thorn;e wele, for al his help &verbar; &thorn;ine liif-days ben al don".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Mergrete answerd &verbar; Olibrious anon:</L>
<L>"&THORN;ine godes &thorn;atow leuest on &verbar; er dom so &thorn;e ston.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou hast pouer to reue me &verbar; mi flesche fram &thorn;e bon;</L>
<L>To reue me mi soule &verbar; pouwer hastow non".
<PB REF="00000368.tif" N="230"></L>
<L N="165">&THORN;an seyd Olibrious: &verbar; "bot &thorn;ou turn &thorn;i &thorn;ou&yogh;t</L>
<L>Smertliche and sone, &verbar; to de&thorn; &thorn;ou schalt be brou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Bot first &thorn;ou schalt to prisoun &verbar; and m(i)chel wo be wrou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&THORN;i god &thorn;at &thorn;ou leuest on &verbar; he no schal help &thorn;e nou&yogh;t".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Mergrete answerd &thorn;o &verbar; milde wordes and stille:</L>
<L N="170">"Certes, wreche, of al &thorn;i &thorn;ret &verbar; &thorn;at &thorn;ou may do me tille</L>
<L>Icham redi to suffre here &verbar; al mi lordes wille;</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou schalt to &thorn;e pine of helle &verbar; for &thorn;ine werkes ille".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Of Olibrious lokeing &verbar; men mi&yogh;t ben agast.</L>
<L>"Take&thorn; Mergrete, he seyd, &verbar; and fetere&thorn; hir ful fast,</L>
<L N="175">And in &thorn;e deppest prisoun &verbar; &thorn;erin &yogh;e schullen hir cast,</L>
<L>And lete hir cole hir bodi &thorn;are, &verbar; for hir wordes vnwrast".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ei Mergrette were to-drawe &verbar; &thorn;e flesche fram &thorn;e bon,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. Mergretre.</NOTE></L>
<L>Pite of &thorn;at maiden &verbar; Olibrious hadd non.</L>
<L>Wel hard was Mergrete &verbar; biset among her fon &mdash;</L>
<L N="180">Saue &thorn;e help of Jhesu Crist &verbar; help no hadde sche non.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Into prisoun fetred &verbar; Mergrete was brou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Jhesu Crist of heuen &verbar; was algat in hir &thorn;ou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>And &mdash; yblisced mot he be! &mdash; &verbar; he ne for&yogh;at hir nou&yogh;t:</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;e court of heuen &verbar; comfort hir was brou&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="185">Sone after &thorn;at Mergrete &verbar; was in prisoun done,</L>
<L>&THORN;er com an angel fram heuen, &verbar; long er it war none,</L>
<L>And brou&yogh;t Margrete a staf &verbar; &thorn;at hye schuld vnder-fon,</L>
<L>Fourmed after &thorn;e rode tre &verbar; &thorn;at god was on ydon.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;an seyd &thorn;at angel &verbar; to Mergrete, &thorn;e bri&yogh;t:</L>
<L N="190">"Jhesu Crist mi lord, &verbar; &thorn;at is ful of mi&yogh;t,</L>
<L>To wite &thorn;e fram &thorn;ine enemis &verbar; and to saue &thorn;i ri&yogh;t,</L>
<L>He ha&thorn; sent &thorn;e &thorn;is staf, &verbar; o&yogh;ain &thorn;e fende to fi&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Maiden Mergrete, he seyd, &verbar; drede &thorn;e no-wi&yogh;t!</L>
<L>&THORN;i sete is made in heuen &verbar; bifor mi lord so bri&yogh;t.</L>
<L N="195">No is no tong in er&thorn;e &verbar; no non ei&yogh;e-si&yogh;t</L>
<L>&THORN;at may telle &thorn;e ioie &verbar; was made of &thorn;e &thorn;is ni&yogh;t".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e angel into paradis &verbar; went o&yogh;ain ful heuen.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. heuen = euen.</NOTE></L>
<L>And maiden Mergrete &verbar; wi&thorn; a milde steuen</L>
<L>&THORN;onked swete Jhesu Crist &verbar; and his names seuen,</L>
<L N="200">&THORN;at hir hadde swiche confort sent &verbar; out of &thorn;e blisse of heuen.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Maiden Mergrete &thorn;o &verbar; loked hir biside:</L>
<L>And sei&yogh;e a lo&thorn;lich dragoun &verbar; out of an hirn glide;</L>
<L>His ei&yogh;en wer ful griseliche, &verbar; his mou&thorn;e &yogh;ened wide.</L>
<L>And Mergrete mi&yogh;t nowhar fle, &verbar; &thorn;er sche most abide.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="205">Maiden Mergrete &verbar; stod stille so ani ston.</L>
<L>And &thorn;at lo&thorn;liche worm &verbar; to hir-ward gan gon,
<PB REF="00000369.tif" N="231"></L>
<L>He toke hir in his foule mou&thorn;e &verbar; and swalled hir, flesche and bon.</L>
<L>Anon he to-brast &mdash; &verbar; damage no hadde sche non.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Maiden Mergrete &verbar; opon &thorn;e dragoun stode,</L>
<L N="210">Bli&thorn;e was hir hert &verbar; and ioieful was hir mode.</L>
<L>"Blisced wor&thorn; Jhesu Crist, &verbar; his vertus er wel gode:</L>
<L>Slayn is &thorn;e d(r)agoun &verbar; &thorn;urch vertu of &thorn;e rode!"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Maiden Mergrete &verbar; went &thorn;e dragoun fro:</L>
<L>Sche sei&yogh;e a wele fouler &thorn;ing &verbar; sitten in a wro:</L>
<L N="215">He hadde honden on his knes &verbar; and ei&yogh;e on euerich to &mdash;</L>
<L>Mi&yogh;t &thorn;er neuer lo&thorn;er &thorn;ing &verbar; opon er&thorn;e go.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Sche &yogh;ede to &thorn;at foule wi&yogh;t, &verbar; wi&thorn; &thorn;e croice in hir hond,</L>
<L>And &thorn;urch &thorn;e mi&yogh;t of Jhesu Crist &verbar; wi&thorn; hir wimpel sche him bond,</L>
<L>Sche toke him bi &thorn;e temples, &verbar; about sche him swong,</L>
<L N="220">Sche set hir fot in his nek, &verbar; to &thorn;e er&thorn;e sche him &thorn;rong.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Say me sone, &thorn;ou foule wi&yogh;t &verbar; and &thorn;ou lo&thorn;eliche &thorn;ing,<MILESTONE N="19" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Who &thorn;an is &thorn;i lord &verbar; and who is &thorn;i king,</L>
<L>And who &thorn;e hider sent &verbar; to make me sturbling?</L>
<L>Sei&yogh;e y neuer, se&thorn;&thorn;en y was born, &verbar; so lo&thorn;eliche a &thorn;ing."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="225">"Leuedi, for &thorn;i lordes loue &verbar; &thorn;ou may ful wele fond &mdash;</L>
<L>Left a litel &thorn;i fot &verbar; &thorn;at in mi nek stond!</L>
<L>For michel haue y walked &verbar; bi water and bi lond,</L>
<L>Nas y neuer are bounden &verbar; in so hard bond.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ruffin was mi bro&thorn;er, &verbar; &thorn;e dragoun &thorn;at &thorn;ou slou&yogh;;</L>
<L N="230">Whiles he was on liue, &verbar; he wrou&yogh;t wonder anou&yogh;:</L>
<L>He maked &thorn;eues to stele o ni&yogh;t, &verbar; o day to ligge and gou&yogh;,</L>
<L>And &yogh;elt hem her seruise &verbar; wi&thorn; wel michel wou&yogh;.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>In a dragoun fourme &verbar; sent he was to &thorn;e,</L>
<L>For to spille &thorn;i memorie &verbar; o&thorn;er to quelle &thorn;e.</L>
<L N="235">Broften is he of peces, &verbar; and bounden hastow me.</L>
<L>A maiden ha&thorn; ous ouercomen, &verbar; litel is our pouste!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Belgys is mi name &mdash; &verbar; nis no bot to ly&yogh;e.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. Belsys? Hick. Belsebug.</NOTE></L>
<L>No may ich in non wise &verbar; &thorn;is pain long drey&yogh;e.</L>
<L>Is nou&yogh;t mi gat in er&thorn;e: &verbar; wi&thorn; &thorn;e winde y fleye.</L>
<L N="240">Al y fond for to quelle &verbar; &thorn;at y see wi&thorn; ei&yogh;e.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;er ich finde a wiif &verbar; &thorn;at li&yogh;ter is of barn,</L>
<L>Y com &thorn;er also sone &verbar; as euer ani arn;</L>
<L>&YOGH;if it be vnblisced, &verbar; y croke it fot or arm,</L>
<L>O&thorn;er &thorn;e wiif hir-seluen &verbar; of childebed be forfarn.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. childehed.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="245">&YOGH;if &thorn;ou wilt al wite, &verbar; astow may ful wel,</L>
<L>Loke in ich a strete: &verbar; &thorn;ou findes it eueridel.</L>
<L>Y pray &thorn;e for &thorn;i lordes loue, &verbar; &thorn;ou binde me wi&thorn; stiel,</L>
<L>&THORN;at y no may wi&thorn; &thorn;ine men &verbar; neuer striue adel.
<PB REF="00000370.tif" N="232"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Salamon &thorn;e wise, &verbar; til he was oliue,</L>
<L N="250">He dede ous in a bras fat &verbar; and delued ous vnder cliue.</L>
<L>When he was oliue farn, &verbar; &thorn;ai lete ous out driue,</L>
<L>&THORN;e men out of Babiloine, &verbar; &thorn;e bras fat &thorn;ai gun riue:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ai wend to finde gold anou&yogh; &verbar; and lete ous alle go.</L>
<L>Sum wer swifter &thorn;an &thorn;e winde, &verbar; and sum &thorn;an &thorn;e ro.</L>
<L N="255">&YOGH;ete &thorn;er er in er&thorn;e &verbar; ten &thorn;ousend and mo.</L>
<L>Al &thorn;at trowe on Jhesu Crist &verbar; &thorn;ai fond at wirche ful wo."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Be stille, &thorn;ou foule gost, &verbar; and decende into helle!</L>
<L>Be &thorn;ou neuer so hardi &verbar; more man to quelle!</L>
<L>Y pray mi lord Jhesu Crist &verbar; &thorn;i pouste &thorn;at he felle."</L>
<L N="260">He sank into er&thorn;e, &verbar; so ston in drau&yogh;t-welle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>On &thorn;at o&thorn;er day &verbar; after it was non,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. is st. it.</NOTE></L>
<L>Olibrious comand &verbar; sche were of prisoun don.</L>
<L>&THORN;e holy gost of heuen &verbar; he com to hir ful sone,</L>
<L>&THORN;e rode token in hir hond &verbar; &thorn;at Crist was on don.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="265">&THORN;an it spac Olibrious &mdash; &verbar; Crist &yogh;iue him iuel dede! &mdash;:</L>
<L>"Maiden Mergrete, he seyd, &verbar; hastow taken &thorn;i rede?</L>
<L>Wiltow be mi leman, &verbar; y finde &thorn;e clo&thorn; and mete.</L>
<L>Trowe on mi godes anon, &verbar; or &thorn;i liif &thorn;ou schalt forlete."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"&THORN;ine godes &thorn;ai be doumbe &verbar; &thorn;at &thorn;ou trouwest inne;</L>
<L N="270">&THORN;ai er ich a dele &verbar; ful of sake and sinne;</L>
<L>&THORN;ai er comen out of helle, &verbar; of Satanas kinne.</L>
<L>&THORN;an &thorn;ou wenes best to liue, &verbar; &THORN;ou schalt to helle winne.<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;an = when.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Y rede &thorn;ou leue on Jhesu Crist &verbar; &thorn;at al &thorn;e world ha&thorn; wrou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Fader and sone and holy gost, &verbar; &thorn;at al &thorn;ing made of nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="275">And wi&thorn; his swete blod &verbar; he ha&thorn; ous alle bou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Leue on him and be cristen man, &verbar; and lete &thorn;i wicke &thorn;ou&yogh;t!"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;an spac Olibrious, &verbar; &thorn;er he sat on his des:</L>
<L>"Ichil bileue on mi godes &verbar; &thorn;at y formast ches;</L>
<L>For min godes be trewe, &verbar; and &thorn;ine er fals and les &mdash;</L>
<L N="280">While &thorn;ou leuest on him, &verbar; &thorn;ou schalt haue no pes."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Maiden Mergrete &verbar; answerd, &thorn;er sche stode:</L>
<L>"Yblisced be Jhesu Crist, &verbar; his help it is ful gode.</L>
<L>Y no doute &thorn;e no&thorn;ing, &verbar; be &thorn;ou neuer so wode,</L>
<L>Mi trust is al on Jhesu Crist &verbar; &thorn;at for ous schadde his blod."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="285">Olibrious on Mergrete &verbar; anon he gan to grenne,</L>
<L>And seyd to his turmentours: &verbar; "a pine y wil &yogh;ou kenne.</L>
<L>Take&thorn; and walle&thorn; oyle &verbar; and lete opon hir renne!</L>
<L>And bot &thorn;e wiche turn hir mode, &verbar; to de&thorn; &yogh;e schul hir brenne."
<PB REF="00000371.tif" N="233"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For&thorn; went &thorn;o turmentours &mdash; &verbar; sorwe hem mot bitide! &mdash;</L>
<L N="290">And setten oyle opon &thorn;e fer, &verbar; &thorn;ai nold no lenger abide.</L>
<L>Opon hir fair bodi &verbar; adoun &thorn;ai lete it glide.</L>
<L>Jhesu sent his angels doun &verbar; to stond bi hir side.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e angels stode hir so nei&yogh;e &verbar; &thorn;at no&thorn;ing mi&yogh;t hir greue,</L>
<L>And hir hert was ful gode &verbar; to godes owhen biheue.</L>
<L N="295">Olibrious was abouten &verbar; to turn hir bileue,</L>
<L>And euer sche held to Jhesu Crist, &verbar; &thorn;at made Adam and Eue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Maiden, qua&thorn; Olibrious, &verbar; is &thorn;i rede ytake?</L>
<L>Wiltow leue on Mahoun &verbar; and &thorn;i god forsake?</L>
<L>Ywis, bot &thorn;ou turn &thorn;i mode, &verbar; &thorn;i sorwe biginne&thorn; to wake,</L>
<L N="300">&THORN;ou schalt &thorn;ole de&thorn; to-day &verbar; for &thorn;i lordes sake."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Mergrete him answerd &verbar; mildeliche and stille:</L>
<L>"&YOGH;if y schal dye for his loue, &verbar; icham at his wille.</L>
<L>&THORN;ei &thorn;ou reue me mi liif, &verbar; y nil nou&yogh;t turn &thorn;e tille;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou schal nou&yogh;t mi soule greue &verbar; for al &thorn;ine pines ille."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="305">Olibrious was nei&yogh;e wode &verbar; for wret&thorn;e of &thorn;at wenche.</L>
<L>Opon a grete wickednisse &verbar; he gan him bi&thorn;enche:</L>
<L>In a fat ful of water &verbar; he bad men schuld hir sinche,</L>
<L>And bot sche wald turn hir mode, &verbar; &thorn;erin men schuld hir drenche.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Alle &thorn;e wicke turmentours &mdash; &verbar; hong mot &thorn;ay hei&yogh;e! &mdash;<MILESTONE N="20" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="310">Fast &thorn;ai were about &verbar; &thorn;at Mergrete schuld dye:</L>
<L>&THORN;ai fild a fat ful of water &verbar; fast bi &thorn;e ei&yogh;e;</L>
<L>To drenche Mergrete &thorn;erinne &verbar; fast &thorn;ai gun heye.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;an spac &thorn;at maiden, &verbar; Mergrete, &thorn;at was so fre:</L>
<L>"Jhesu Crist mi louerd &mdash; &verbar; yblisced mot &thorn;ou be! &mdash;</L>
<L N="315">&YOGH;if it be &thorn;i wille, &verbar; &thorn;e water &thorn;at y se,</L>
<L>Lete me cristen &thorn;erinne &verbar; in &thorn;e name of &thorn;e!"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e turmentours token hir, &verbar; bo&thorn;e bon and fel,</L>
<L>And wold drenche hir &thorn;erinne &mdash; &verbar; &thorn;ai wende do ful wel.</L>
<L>To confort &thorn;at maiden, &verbar; an angel was ful snel,</L>
<L N="320">&THORN;at swete Jhesus Crist hir sent &verbar; to confort hir ful wel.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Alle &thorn;e pople sei&yogh;e &thorn;ere &verbar; an angel com fle</L>
<L>And toke Mergrete of &thorn;e water, &verbar; &thorn;at &thorn;ai al mi&yogh;t se.</L>
<L>&THORN;e fat brast on peces, &verbar; &thorn;e folk bigan to fle.</L>
<L>Olibrious &thorn;at was king &verbar; a sori man was he!<NOTE PLACE="foot">Die letzte Halbzeile ist im Ms. unten nachge|tragen.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="325">&THORN;o &thorn;e popel sei&yogh;en &verbar; al &thorn;e fat to-driue,</L>
<L>To forsake Mahoun &verbar; &thorn;ai heyed hem biliue</L>
<L>And leued opon Jhesu Crist, &verbar; fif &thorn;ousend and fiue.</L>
<L>Olibrious lete slen hem alle &verbar; and bringen hem oliue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Anon bifor Olibrious &verbar; &thorn;e turmentours ronne</L>
<L N="330">And seyd: "sir, it is for nou&yogh;t &verbar; al &thorn;at we han bigonne.</L>
<L>&THORN;er com fleyand bestes, &verbar; as bri&yogh;t as ani sonne,</L>
<L>And sauen hir fram harm &verbar; for al &thorn;at euer we conne."<NOTE PLACE="foot">sauen st. saued.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000372.tif" N="234"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Olibrious was nei&yogh;e wode, &verbar; ailed him no game.</L>
<L>He cleped for&thorn; a turmentour: &verbar; was he no&thorn;ing lame,</L>
<L N="335">A strong manqueller, &verbar; Malcous was his name.</L>
<L>Olibrious bi&thorn;ou&yogh;t him &verbar; to do Mergrete schame.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Malcous, qua&thorn; Olibrius, &verbar; go and hei&yogh;e &thorn;e swi&thorn;e!</L>
<L>Lade &thorn;is wiche out of toun &verbar; and bring hir oliue,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;i swerd smite of hir hed &verbar; and lat &thorn;e blod out driue!</L>
<L N="340">No schal sche neuer after &thorn;is day &verbar; more o&yogh;ains me striue."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Malcous tok Mergrete &verbar; and ladde hir out of toun &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;er was &thorn;e stede to heued men, &verbar; a litel biside adoun.</L>
<L>And seyd: "maiden, stoupe here, &verbar; &thorn;er whiles y schaue &thorn;i croun,</L>
<L>And y schal maken al blodi &verbar; &thorn;ine lockes &thorn;at ben broun."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="345">&THORN;er suwed Mergrete to &thorn;e de&thorn; &verbar; al &thorn;at mi&yogh;ten go;</L>
<L>Mani was &thorn;at moder child &verbar; &thorn;at for hir de&thorn; was wo.</L>
<L>&THORN;e &thorn;onder gan to brest, &verbar; &thorn;e sonne wex al blo:</L>
<L>&THORN;e pople fel adoun to grounde, &verbar; &thorn;ai nist of wele no wo.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;er com an angel fram heuen, &verbar; &thorn;at was bri&yogh;t of ble,</L>
<L N="350">And seyd: "Mergrete, &verbar; yblisced mot &thorn;ou be!</L>
<L>Jhesus Crist of heuen &verbar; sent &thorn;e word bi me:</L>
<L>In &thorn;e blisse of heuen &verbar; coround schaltow be."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Milde Mergrete, &verbar; &thorn;at was so gode a mayde,</L>
<L>&THORN;o sche herd &thorn;e angel voice, &verbar; sche bigan to abrayd.</L>
<L N="355">&THORN;e tidinges &thorn;at he brou&yogh;t hir &verbar; nei&yogh;e hir hert sche leyd,</L>
<L>And sett hir doun opon hir kne &verbar; and &thorn;is wordes sche seyd:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Blisced be Jhesu Crist &verbar; &thorn;at ha&thorn; me sent &thorn;at sond,</L>
<L>And dyed on &thorn;e rode tre &verbar; to bring ous out of bond.</L>
<L>Lord, ich biseke &thorn;e, &verbar; lete mi biding stond</L>
<L N="360">Of &thorn;at ichil biseke &thorn;e &verbar; for sinful men in lond!"&mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Mergrete &thorn;e milde, &verbar; &thorn;at was godes mayde,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou&yogh;t opon &thorn;e wordes &verbar; &thorn;e dragoun in prisoun seyd:</L>
<L>&THORN;at deuels &yogh;ede in er&thorn;e &verbar; women for to breyd<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. vp breyd, mit auspunkt. vp.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at were traueland of child &verbar; or doun in childe-bed leyd. &mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="365">&THORN;an bad Mergrete &verbar; to Jhesu, &thorn;at was so fre:</L>
<L>"&YOGH;if ani woman trauayl &verbar; and hard clepe&thorn; to me,</L>
<L>Deliuer hir, lord, wi&thorn; ioie &verbar; &thorn;urch vertu of &thorn;e tre</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou dest &thorn;i body on &verbar; to make ous al fre!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Alle &thorn;at mi passioun &verbar; heren o&thorn;er rede</L>
<L N="370">O&thorn;er &thorn;at in mi name &verbar; don ani almos-dede,</L>
<L>Jhesu Crist, mi lord, &verbar; wi&thorn; honour &thorn;ou hem fede,</L>
<L>&THORN;e swete blis of heuen &verbar; grant hem, lord, to mede!"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;er com a voice fram Jhesu Crist, &verbar; &thorn;at sitt in trinite,</L>
<L>And seyd to maiden Mergrete: &verbar; "yblisced mot &thorn;ou be!
<PB REF="00000373.tif" N="235"></L>
<L N="375">Of &thorn;atow hast me bisou&yogh;t &verbar; &thorn;i bone graunt y the.</L>
<L>&amp; in &thorn;e blisse of heuen &verbar; &thorn;ou schalt won wi&thorn; me."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;at maiden Mergrete &verbar; hadde herd &thorn;at miri steuen</L>
<L>&THORN;at com fram swete Jhesu Crist &verbar; out of &thorn;e blis of heuen:</L>
<L>Bifor Malcous sche kneled &verbar; opon hir knes ful euen</L>
<L N="380">And bad him smite of hir heued, &verbar; mo times &thorn;an seuen.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Sche crid opon Malcous &mdash; &verbar; nold sche neuer blinne:</L>
<L>"Malcous, smite of mi heued! &verbar; for&yogh;iue y &thorn;e &thorn;e sinne".</L>
<L>"&THORN;at nold y do, he seyd, &verbar; for al &thorn;is warld to winne:</L>
<L>&THORN;i louerd ha&thorn; wi&thorn; &thorn;e speke &verbar; in wham &thorn;ou leuest inne."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="385">"Malcous, qua&thorn; Mergrete, &verbar; forso&thorn;e y telle &thorn;e:</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;ou smite of min heued, &verbar; &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t nou&yogh;t saued be.</L>
<L>Haue ydon and smite it of! &verbar; and y wil bid for &thorn;e</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou schalt haue &thorn;e blis &verbar; &thorn;at Jhesu ha&thorn; graunted me."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Malcous had turned his &thorn;ou&yogh;t &verbar; to Jhesu Crist biheue:</L>
<L N="390">For &thorn;e miracle &thorn;at he sei&yogh;e &verbar; he turned to gode bileue.</L>
<L>And sori he was in hert &verbar; &thorn;at he schuld hir greue,</L>
<L>And &yogh;ete he smot of hir heued, &verbar; ar &thorn;at it was eue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Anon as he had ydon, &verbar; he kneled opon &thorn;e grounde</L>
<L>And bisou&yogh;t him merci &verbar; &thorn;at for ous &thorn;oled wounde.</L>
<L N="395">&THORN;e angels cam from heuen &verbar; wi&thorn;-in a litel stounde</L>
<L>And bar Mergrete soule, &verbar; &thorn;er al mir&thorn;e is founde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Teodosious, a kni&yogh;t &verbar; &thorn;at leued on godes lay,<MILESTONE N="21" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And &thorn;e norice of Asie &verbar; &thorn;at loked &thorn;at fair may,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai tok vp hir swete bodi, &verbar; slawe &thorn;er it lay,</L>
<L N="400">And bir(i)d it wi&thorn; miche anour &verbar; opon &thorn;at o&thorn;er day.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;o Mergrete was bir(i)d, &verbar; as be&thorn; o&thorn;er mo,</L>
<L>And Teodosious &thorn;e kni&yogh;t &verbar; was ywent hir fro:</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;at were seke, &verbar; &thorn;at &thorn;(i)der wald go,</L>
<L>Jhesu &thorn;urch his vertu &verbar; deliuerd hem of wo.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="405">Teodosious &thorn;e kni&yogh;t &verbar; he lete writen hir liif,</L>
<L>&THORN;at is now ouer al &thorn;e world &verbar; name-cou&thorn;e and riif:</L>
<L>Hou sche &thorn;oled hir passioun &verbar; stille wi&thorn;outen striif,</L>
<L>&THORN;at mir&thorn;e is of to here &verbar; to maiden and to wiif.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Jhesu, &thorn;at on &thorn;e rode was don &verbar; our soules forto borwe,</L>
<L N="410">Scheld ous fram &thorn;e pine of helle &verbar; and bring ous out of sorwe,</L>
<L>And grace forto &yogh;eme ous &verbar; out of dedli sinne,</L>
<L>And grant ous &thorn;e miche ioie &verbar; &thorn;er seynt Mergrete is inne!</L>
<TRAILER>Amen.</TRAILER>
<TRAILER>Explicit.
</TRAILER>

</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="appendix"><PB REF="00000374.tif" N="[236]">
<HEAD>Beilage. Mergarete, aus Ms. Ashm. 61, fol. 145.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Old &amp; &yogh;onge, &thorn;at here be,</L>
<L>Lystyns a whyle vnto me,</L>
<L>What I schall &yogh;ou sey:</L>
<L>How it befell vpone a dey</L>
<L N="5">Off a virgyn, feyre &amp; suete,</L>
<L>Whos name was Mergarete.</L>
<L>Hyr fadere was a nobull clerke</L>
<L>And a mane &thorn;at couth mych werke,</L>
<L>Also a prince of hy degre &mdash;</L>
<L N="10">There my&yogh;ht no-where a better be &mdash;</L>
<L>In Antyche. he had a wyffe:</L>
<L>Both wer heythen of &thorn;er lyffe.</L>
<L>He was a man offe grete powere:</L>
<L>Off all &thorn;e cuntre gouernere;</L>
<L N="15">False he was offe hys ley,</L>
<L>Both be ny&yogh;ht &amp; be dey.</L>
<L>Theodosyas was hys name,</L>
<L>A nobulle man of grete fame.</L>
<L>He hade vnderstondyng longe beforne</L>
<L N="20">He schuld haue a dou&yogh;ture borne,</L>
<L>As &thorn;e scryptoure hym tolde,</L>
<L>And when sche wex olde</L>
<L>That sche schuld crystyne be</L>
<L>And beleue of &thorn;e trinyte,<NOTE PLACE="foot">of st. on.</NOTE></L>
<L N="25">All-my&yogh;hty god &thorn;at vs dere bou&yogh;ht</L>
<L>And all &thorn;is werld made of nou&yogh;ht.</L>
<L>Hyre fader comandyd longe beforne</L>
<L>That, none as sche was borne,<NOTE PLACE="foot">none = anone.</NOTE></L>
<L>To &thorn;e deth sche schuld be brou&yogh;ht,</L>
<L N="30">In what wyse, he ne rou&yogh;ht.</L>
<L>Bot hyre modor, &thorn;at hyre bore,</L>
<L>Made fore hyre full grete care</L>
<L>And bethou&yogh;t hyre beforne,</L>
<L>That, a-none as sche was borne,</L>
<L N="35">In-to A&yogh;y sche hyre sente.</L>
<L>The messanger forth wente,</L>
<L>To a norys &thorn;at wonyd &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>Forto putte hyre to lere;</L>
<L>He toke with hym grete spendynge</L>
<L N="40">Forto kepe &thorn;at meyden &yogh;enge.</L>
<L>And sche (he)re kepte &thorn;er in dede<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. schere st. sche here.</NOTE></L>
<L>And norysschyd here in &thorn;at nede.</L>
<L>Sche was feyre &amp; comly off chere</L>
<L>And off hyre bewty feyre &amp; clere;</L>
<L N="45">All hyre louyd in &thorn;at cuntre,</L>
<L>Olde &amp; &yogh;onge, &thorn;at hyre my&yogh;ht se.</L>
<L>When sche wax more in age</L>
<L>And hade vnderstondynge &amp; knawelege,</L>
<L>Sche toke hyre to Crystys lore</L>
<L N="50">And beleuyd In hym euer-more.</L>
<L>The norys &thorn;at kepte hyre fro dispare,</L>
<L>Had VII chylder, &thorn;at wer fare,</L>
<L>And welle sche kepte &thorn;is chylder VII,</L>
<L>The VIII was Crystys meyden of heuyne.</L>
<L N="55">Both of heuen &amp; off helle</L>
<L>Full gode tayles sche cuthe telle,</L>
<L>And what &thorn;ei schuld haue to mede</L>
<L>As &thorn;ei deferuyd in dede,</L>
<L>And how &thorn;ei sofferd merterdome euyne</L>
<L N="60">Both seynte Laurance &amp; seynte Steuyne,</L>
<L>Off many o&thorn;er seyntys mo,</L>
<L>How &thorn;ei sufferd peyne &amp; wo</L>
<L>And how &thorn;ei merterdome gane take</L>
<L>All fore Jhesu Crystys sake;</L>
<L N="65">Off many seyntys sche told &thorn;e lyffe</L>
<L>Both to man &amp; to wyffe.</L>
<L>And when sche was XV &yogh;erys olde,</L>
<L>Sche was feyre woman &amp; bold.</L>
<L>Hyre norys sette hyre to kepe</L>
<L N="70">In &thorn;e feld to fede hyre schepe.</L>
<L>Hyre felowys gane hyre behold,</L>
<L>When sche hyre prayers make wold.</L>
<L>Than was in &thorn;at cuntre a kynge,</L>
<L>A nobull man of grete cunnynge,</L>
<L N="75">He was a kyng of grete my&yogh;ht:</L>
<L>Olybrius fore-soth he hy&yogh;ht;</L>
<L>All A&yogh;y, as I &yogh;ou telle,</L>
<L>Was hys awne, to gyff or selle.</L>
<L>Also he seruyd dey &amp; ny&yogh;ht</L>
<L N="80">Hys fals godys, I &yogh;ou behy&yogh;ht;</L>
<L>He seruyd euer &thorn;e deuyll of helle</L>
<L>And crystine pepull he dyde quelle.</L>
<L>Fro Antyoch to A&yogh;ye</L>
<L>Be myles mo &thorn;an fyfte.</L>
<L N="85">Euer to strew &thorn;e crysten mene,</L>
<L>He dyde hys powere euer then;</L>
<L>What with werre &amp; with stryffe</L>
<L>He left bote few pepull of lyue.</L>
<L>Tyll it befelle on a dey,</L>
<L N="90">As he rode by &thorn;e wey,</L>
<L>He saw &thorn;at louely meydene</L>
<L>Kepynge schepe vpon &thorn;e grene.</L>
<L>Anone he commandyd a kny&yogh;ht</L>
<L>To brynge hyre to hym anone ry&yogh;ht.
<PB REF="00000375.tif" N="237"></L>
<L N="95">The kny&yogh;ht wente anone hyre to</L>
<L>And seyd &thorn;at sche must with hym go.</L>
<L>The meydene, was so myld of chere,</L>
<L>Ansuerd hym, as &yogh;e schall here,</L>
<L>And seyd: sche hade no-thinge to do</L>
<L N="100">Oute of &thorn;at ground with hym to go;</L>
<L>Sche prayde hym off hys curtassye</L>
<L>To pase hys wey &amp; late hyre be.</L>
<L>And, schortly &thorn;is tale to telle,</L>
<L>He wente awey fro &thorn;at damselle</L>
<L N="105">And come to Olybryus, &thorn;e kynge,</L>
<L>And told hym all &thorn;at tydinge:</L>
<L>That sche wold fore no thinge,</L>
<L>Cum to hym sche ne wold,</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;ei with hyre stryue schuld.</L>
<L N="110">To Jhesu Cryst gane sche calle</L>
<L>That sofyrd deth fore vs alle,</L>
<L>That he wold hyre defend</L>
<L>That no sary&yogh;en schuld hyre schend,</L>
<L>And besou&yogh;t hym of hys grace</L>
<L N="115">Hyre to socore in euery place,</L>
<L>And seyd: "fore &thorn;i luffe, lord, wyll I dy&yogh;e</L>
<L>And foresake all werdly compenye".<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. fore soke.</NOTE></L>
<L>Than spake Olibryus,</L>
<L>To hys men he seyd &thorn;us:</L>
<L N="120">"Off all &thorn;e men &thorn;at I haue here</L>
<L>Cane none of hem brynge hyre nere?</L>
<L>And I had hyre to me brou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Full sone I schuld change hyre thou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Sche schall vpone my godys beleue,</L>
<L N="125">Or els sore I schall hyre greue"</L>
<L>They wente a&yogh;en vnto &thorn;at meyd</L>
<L>And onto hyre <I>&thorn;us &thorn;ei</I> seyd:</L>
<L>"Thou must cum one with vs</L>
<L>To oure kynge, <I>sir</I> Olibryus.</L>
<L N="130">Bot iff &thorn;ou come with-outyne stryffe,</L>
<L>Or we schall reffe &thorn;e thy lyffe".</L>
<L>With &thorn;em sche wente meke &amp; styll</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e kynge a&yogh;en hyre wyll,</L>
<L>And fulle feyre sche hym grete.</L>
<L N="135">He askyd hyre name. sche seyd: Mergrete.</L>
<L>He seyd: "iff &thorn;ou be borne fre,</L>
<L>Fore-soth my lemane schall &thorn;ou be;</L>
<L>I wyll haue &thorn;e to my wyfe,</L>
<L>To lyue in Joy all &thorn;i lyue.</L>
<L N="140">Gold &amp; ryches I wylle &thorn;e gyffe,</L>
<L>All &thorn;e whyll &thorn;at &thorn;ou dost lyue".</L>
<L>Sche seyd to hym anone &thorn;ane:</L>
<L>"I wyll haue none erthly mane.</L>
<L>Bot for &thorn;e loue of Cryst alone</L>
<L N="145">I wyll be baptyst at &thorn;e fonte-stone.</L>
<L>Fore-soth, I wyll hym neuer foresake</L>
<L>Fore none erthly mane to take".</L>
<L>Than anone to hyre he seyd:</L>
<L>"We dyde Jhesu Cryst to dede</L>
<L N="150">And dyde hym streyne vpon &thorn;e rode,</L>
<L>Tyll he suet water &amp; blode,</L>
<L>And crownyd with a croune of thorne.</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou leue on hym, &thorn;ou arte lorne".</L>
<L>To hym sche seyd anone ry&yogh;t:</L>
<L N="155">"He is a lord of mykyll my&yogh;ht</L>
<L>And dy&yogh;ed one &thorn;e crose fore all man-kynd,</L>
<L>Fore we schuld haue hym in mynde;</L>
<L>He ros fro deth &amp; to helle wente,</L>
<L>The fendys powere forto schente,</L>
<L N="160">And many saulys he fette oute &thorn;er</L>
<L>That in grete peyne wer".</L>
<L>To stryue with hyre he fond no bote,</L>
<L>Bot dyde hyre bynd hand &amp; fote</L>
<L>And cast hyre in-to prisone stronge,</L>
<L N="165">Fore-to ouercome hyr with wronge.</L>
<L>Meyd Mergarete all &thorn;at ny&yogh;ht</L>
<L>In prison ley with grete vnry&yogh;ht.</L>
<L>And on &thorn;e morow wen it was dey,</L>
<L>He sente fore hyre, &thorn;e soth to sey.</L>
<L N="170">They brou&yogh;t hyre to <I>sir</I> Olybryus.</L>
<L>Sone to hyre he seyd &thorn;us:</L>
<L>"Mergaret, beleue vpone my lore,</L>
<L>Or I schall greue &thorn;e full sore &mdash;</L>
<L>Thy god &thorn;at &thorn;ou doyst on beleue<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. &thorn;at that.</NOTE></L>
<L N="175">Schall not saue &thorn;e fro my greue.</L>
<L>And trow on me &amp; be my wyue</L>
<L>And lyue in Joy all &thorn;i lyue!</L>
<L>Antyoche &amp; all A&yogh;ye</L>
<L>After my deth I gyue to &thorn;e;</L>
<L N="180">Sylke &amp; gold &amp; purpull paule,</L>
<L>I wyll &thorn;e wede, were &thorn;ou schalle,</L>
<L>Welle furryd with ryche ermyne &mdash;</L>
<L>In all &thorn;is werld is none so fyne;</L>
<L>And with &thorn;e beste metys &thorn;at is in lond</L>
<L N="185">I schall &thorn;e fede, I vnderstond.</L>
<L>And Jhesu Criste pute oute off &thorn;i thou&yogh;t!"</L>
<L>"Nay, sche seyd, &thorn;at wyll I nou&yogh;ht.</L>
<L>Jhesu wyll I neuer foresake</L>
<L>Fore all &thorn;at is on erth to take".</L>
<L N="190">He seyd: "it schall be sene full sone</L>
<L>What &thorn;i god wyll fore &thorn;e done".</L>
<L>He bade hys sergeantys euerychon</L>
<L>Bynd hyre fote &amp; hond anone.</L>
<L>The sergeantys dyde as he heme bade,</L>
<L N="195">They turment hyre, as &thorn;ei wer made;</L>
<L>They bete hyre with scow(r)gys stronge</L>
<L>And turment hyre with grete wronge;</L>
<L>They bete hyre, both man &amp; wyffe,</L>
<L>And fast with hyre &thorn;ei gane stryffe:</L>
<L N="200">Tyll &thorn;e rede blod felle adounne</L>
<L>To hyre fete fro hyre crounne,</L>
<L>Tyll &thorn;ei wend sche hade be dede:</L>
<L>So fast on hyre &thorn;ei hade leyde.</L>
<L>Than seyd Olybryus, &thorn;er he stode:</L>
<L N="205">"Mergaret, thinkys <I>&thorn;ou &thorn;is</I> werkys gode?</L>
<L>Beleue onne my lord &amp; be my wyue,
<PB REF="00000376.tif" N="238"></L>
<L>And I wylle no more with &thorn;e stryue.</L>
<L>Haue mersy on &thorn;i feyre fleche</L>
<L>And onne &thorn;i skyne &thorn;at is so nessche!"</L>
<L N="210">To Jhesu Cryst sche cryed &thorn;ane</L>
<L>That dy&yogh;ed fore &thorn;e loue off mane</L>
<L>And off a virgyne was borne,</L>
<L>Fore man-kynd schuld not be lorne.</L>
<L>"Thys peynes &thorn;at I soffere &amp; synke (!)</L>
<L N="215">They be full suete, as me thinke;</L>
<L>All &thorn;e peynes &thorn;at I here dryue</L>
<L>Be sueter to me &thorn;an thynge off lyue".</L>
<L>Olybrius seyd to hys sergeantys &thorn;o:</L>
<L>"Sche felys no-thynge off alle &thorn;is wo.</L>
<L N="220">Fore all &thorn;e peynes we to hyre gyue</L>
<L>Sche wyll not on oure godys beleue".</L>
<L>He bad hys sergeantys euerychone</L>
<L>They schuld turment hyre anone.</L>
<L>The sergeantys dyde as he heme bade &mdash;</L>
<L N="225">Lytell mersy on hyre &thorn;ei hade:</L>
<L>With &thorn;er nayles &thorn;ei dude hyre flessch drawe</L>
<L>Lyke as hundys had hyre gnawe,</L>
<L>And hyre ey&yogh;en &thorn;at wer so bry&yogh;ht</L>
<L>They pute hem oute &amp; merede hyre sy&yogh;ht;</L>
<L N="230">They dud hyre both peyne &amp; wo</L>
<L>And rent hyre lyere fro &thorn;e flessch tho.</L>
<L>Mych off &thorn;e pepull &thorn;at wer &thorn;ere</L>
<L>In &thorn;er hertys wer full sore,</L>
<L>And sey(d) to hyre stondyng &thorn;ere,</L>
<L N="235">When &thorn;ei se hyre &thorn;us I-tore,</L>
<L>And seyd: "feyre meyden Mergarete,</L>
<L>Thou &thorn;at arte so feyre &amp; suete,</L>
<L>Turne to hym &amp; be hys wyue</L>
<L>And no more with hym stryue!</L>
<L N="240">Fore &thorn;e, Mergaret, we haue care</L>
<L>And wold &thorn;at &thorn;ou sauyd were".</L>
<L>"After &yogh;ou, sche seyd, I wyll not do,</L>
<L>Bot go &yogh;our wey, sche seyd, me fro!</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;at fore me repente</L>
<L N="245">And se me haue &thorn;is turment,</L>
<L>As &thorn;ei thinke both gode &amp; euylle,</L>
<L>They schall be quyte after &thorn;er wylle.</L>
<L>The angell of Cryst come me to,</L>
<L>Als fast as he may come &amp; go".</L>
<L N="250">Than be-seyd Olybryus</L>
<L>With wyked wordys seynge &thorn;us:</L>
<L>"Mergaret, I haue sych poste</L>
<L>That blynd I haue made the;</L>
<L>Fore before &thorn;ou had &thorn;i sy&yogh;ht,</L>
<L N="255">No hast &thorn;ou none thorow my my&yogh;ht.</L>
<L>Beleue on my god, &thorn;ou mayd!"</L>
<L>"Nay, fore-soth, <I>sir</I>, sche seyd,</L>
<L>Fore &thorn;i godys &thorn;at &thorn;ou beleuys onne</L>
<L>The are dome as any stone.</L>
<L N="260">My lord to me he is full kynd,</L>
<L>He schall neuer out of my mynd.</L>
<L>Iff &thorn;e hope wer of my flessche</L>
<L>To do &thorn;i wyll both herd &amp; nessche,</L>
<L>To-rente &thorn;e flessch fro &thorn;e bone!</L>
<L N="265">Powere of my saule getys &thorn;ou none".</L>
<L>To hyre anone &thorn;an he seyd:</L>
<L>"In depe prisone &thorn;ou schall be leyd,</L>
<L>In prison schall &thorn;i body lye,</L>
<L>Thy feyre flessch forto dystreye;</L>
<L N="270">Thou schall be bounde fote &amp; hond</L>
<L>With bondys off Iren gret &amp; stronge".</L>
<L>"Jhesu Crist, sche seyd (him) vn-tylle,</L>
<L>May delyuer me, when he wylle".</L>
<L>In prison fast &thorn;ei gane hyre done.</L>
<L N="275">The angell come to hyre full sone</L>
<L>With &thorn;e grace of god all-my&yogh;ht,</L>
<L>As &thorn;e sone schynes bry&yogh;ht;</L>
<L>With parte of &thorn;e crose, god was on done,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e virgyne he come full sone</L>
<L N="280">And seyd to hyre with myld steuyne:</L>
<L>"Blyssed &thorn;ou arte with all in heuyne.</L>
<L>Fader &amp; sone &amp; holy goste,</L>
<L>Lord &amp; kynge of my&yogh;tys moste,</L>
<L>Thys crosse to &thorn;e hath send,</L>
<L N="285">Thy enmys &thorn;er-with to defend".</L>
<L>Sche seyd: "lord, blyssed &thorn;ou be,</L>
<L>That &thorn;is &yogh;yffte hath send me!</L>
<L>All-my&yogh;ty god, I &thorn;e praye,</L>
<L>A bone grante me to-deye:</L>
<L N="290">That I may with sy&yogh;ht &thorn;em se</L>
<L>What &thorn;ei be, &thorn;at &thorn;us hath turment me".</L>
<L>The angell bade hyre doute nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>For to heuyne sche schuld be brou&yogh;t:</L>
<L>"There is no tonge &thorn;at telle my&yogh;t</L>
<L N="295">The Joy was made of &thorn;e &thorn;is ny&yogh;ht,</L>
<L>With all &thorn;e melody &thorn;at is in heuyne,</L>
<L>Meyd Mergaret, &thorn;e forto neuyne".</L>
<L>And be &thorn;e grace of god all-my&yogh;ht</L>
<L>There anone sche hade a sy&yogh;ht.</L>
<L N="300">Then &thorn;e holy angell wente hyre fro &mdash;</L>
<L>Of hym sche saw no more tho.</L>
<L>Sche lokyd a lytell be hyre syde:</L>
<L>And saw a dragone be hyre glyde</L>
<L>That was of colour as grasse grene,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Nach 304 hat das Ms. folg. Vers: Mergaret hyre forto neuin(!), offenbar eine Wiederholung von v. 297.</NOTE></L>
<L N="305">With fyre flawmyng, foule to fene,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. seme st. sene.</NOTE></L>
<L>Out off hys mouth, fyre brynning bry&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Sche was agrysed off &thorn;at sy&yogh;ht,</L>
<L>Sche fell done vnto &thorn;e grounde,</L>
<L>Fore fere sche tremblyd in &thorn;at stonde.</L>
<L N="310">He toke hyre in hys mowth anone,</L>
<L>He sualowyd vp hyre body &amp; bone.</L>
<L>And when he had so I-done,</L>
<L>Than he my&yogh;ht no fer&thorn;er gone,</L>
<L>Bot he byrst vpone &thorn;e ground:</L>
<L N="315">The mayden come forth saue and sound,</L>
<L>As it was Cristys wylle,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. And st. as.</NOTE></L>
<L>With-in hym sche had none ylle.</L>
<L>Bot vpone &thorn;e dragone sche stode
<PB REF="00000377.tif" N="239"></L>
<L>With glade herte &amp; mylde mode,</L>
<L N="320">And thankyde Jhesu off hys my&yogh;ht</L>
<L>That sche hade ouercome &thorn;at foule wy&yogh;ht,</L>
<L>And vnderstode welle &thorn;at it was</L>
<L>Thorow &thorn;e vertu of &thorn;e croysse</L>
<L>That foule dragone was sleyne &thorn;ere,</L>
<L N="325">Thorow godys my&yogh;t &amp; hyre prayere.</L>
<L>Anon sche wente &thorn;e dragone fro</L>
<L>And sey a fowlere come hyre to.</L>
<L>A grysly sy&yogh;ht fore-so&thorn;e was he,</L>
<L>A foulere best neuer mane se.</L>
<L N="330">To hym sche wente, I vnderstond,</L>
<L>With &thorn;e holy crosse in hyre hond,</L>
<L>And smote hym so vpone &thorn;e fynnes</L>
<L>That he my&yogh;ht not abyde hyre dynnes;</L>
<L>That staff &thorn;at was so longe,</L>
<L N="335">That thorow Criste my&yogh;t so stronge</L>
<L>Downe to &thorn;e grond sche hym caste,</L>
<L>And with hyre wy(m)ple bond hym faste,</L>
<L>In hys neke sche sette hyre fote &mdash;</L>
<L>To stryue with hyre it was no bote.</L>
<L N="340">To hym sche seyd: "I coniure &thorn;e,</L>
<L>What &thorn;ou arte &thorn;ou telle me!</L>
<L>Fore &thorn;ou arte so lothly a thynge,</L>
<L>What &thorn;ou arte I wyll haue knowynge;</L>
<L>Fore best saw I neuer nonne</L>
<L N="345">So lothly forto loke vpone."</L>
<L>He seyd: "fore my lordys sake</L>
<L>Fro my neke &thorn;i fote &thorn;ou take!</L>
<L>I haue gon wyde be water &amp; londe,</L>
<L>&YOGH;it was I neuer so sore I-bonde.</L>
<L N="350">My ry&yogh;ht name hy&yogh;ht Belgys &mdash;</L>
<L>To ly&yogh;e to &thorn;e none aveyll ys &mdash;</L>
<L>Geffron is my bro&thorn;er, &thorn;at thou slewe;</L>
<L>In &thorn;e werld we dyd sorow I-nowe.</L>
<L>Dede &amp; borston is my bro&thorn;er,</L>
<L N="355">And &thorn;ou hast ouercome me, I se non o&thorn;er.</L>
<L>When we wer bo&thorn;e togeder,</L>
<L>We made &thorn;e sone to sle &thorn;e fader,</L>
<L>We stroyd pepull dey &amp; nyht,</L>
<L>We dyd all &thorn;e sorow &thorn;at we my&yogh;ht.</L>
<L N="360">In dragons wyse we come to &thorn;e</L>
<L>To spyll &thorn;i wytte &amp; make &thorn;e wode to be;</L>
<L>The kynge sir Olybryus</L>
<L>In &thorn;is lyknes sent vs &thorn;us</L>
<L>Forto strey &thorn;i fare body,</L>
<L N="365">With hys craft &amp; nygramansy.</L>
<L>Thy hede peyne &thorn;at is so stronge,</L>
<L>I may not suffyre &thorn;is full longe.</L>
<L>My wey is not In erth: by &thorn;e wynd I fle;</L>
<L>All &thorn;at I se I wyll dystroye.</L>
<L N="370">Where I wyst a woman with chyld,</L>
<L>The&thorn;er I went wode &amp; wyld;</L>
<L>And yff &thorn;e child vn-crystynd wer,</L>
<L>Lege &amp; arme I made crokyd &thorn;er.</L>
<L>I wrou&yogh;t mykyll sorow &amp; wo:</L>
<L N="375">I made &thorn;e one neybour &thorn;e o&thorn;er slo,</L>
<L>I wente to &thorn;e feld vnto &thorn;e plou&yogh;e</L>
<L>And &thorn;e bestys all to-drew&yogh;e;</L>
<L>Where-euer I went, I dyde grete care &mdash;</L>
<L>There was my Joy aboute to fare.</L>
<L N="380">Whe(n) &thorn;at Salomon &thorn;e wyse was alyue,</L>
<L>In-to a tunne of bras he dyd vs dryue</L>
<L>He dyde vs bery in an hylle</L>
<L>Sone anone a&yogh;enst our wylle.</L>
<L>Men of Babylone come vs to,</L>
<L N="385">They dyged vs oute &amp; lete vs go;</L>
<L>When &thorn;ei mynede in &thorn;e gronde,</L>
<L>They wenyd gold &amp; syluer to hafe fonde.</L>
<L>There be in &thorn;e erth of vs fleynge</L>
<L>Mo &thorn;an XV M, in &thorn;e wynd beynge;</L>
<L N="390">Som are swyfter &thorn;an a do,</L>
<L>And some are suyfter &thorn;an a ro,</L>
<L>Som are suyfter &thorn;an a sualow,</L>
<L>And some are suyfter &thorn;an an arow.</L>
<L>And all &thorn;at on Cryst beleue,</L>
<L N="395">We dyde them vex &amp; sore greue.</L>
<L>Both in towne &amp; in feld</L>
<L>We streyd many wyff &amp; chyld,</L>
<L>We streyd fruyt on &thorn;e erth growynge,</L>
<L>And dronyd schypes in &thorn;e se seylinge.</L>
<L N="400">Thys was oure labour &amp; delyte,</L>
<L>To do crysten pepull dyspyte.</L>
<L>Now I pray &yogh;ou late me go!</L>
<L>I haue told &yogh;ou euery dele also."</L>
<L>Margaret seyd to &thorn;at foule wy&yogh;ht:</L>
<L N="405">"I coniure &thorn;e by Cristys my&yogh;ht</L>
<L>And in godys holy name</L>
<L>That &thorn;ou do neuer more schame,</L>
<L>Bot synke doune in-to helle</L>
<L>Fore euer-more &thorn;er to duelle.</L>
<L N="410">Synke doune, &thorn;ou foulle fend,</L>
<L>There-in to be with-outyne ende!"</L>
<L>He sanke adoune by godys my&yogh;t</L>
<L>Thorow &thorn;e prayere of &thorn;at virgyne bry&yogh;ht. &mdash;</L>
<L>All &thorn;is trobull had &thorn;is holy meyd</L>
<L N="415">In &thorn;e stronge castell where sche was leyd,</L>
<L>In a dey &amp; in a ny&yogh;ht</L>
<L>All &thorn;is hade &thorn;at meydene bry&yogh;ht,</L>
<L>And thankyd god of hys grace</L>
<L>That sche ouercome &thorn;em in &thorn;at place.</L>
<L N="420">The secund dey at &thorn;e after-none</L>
<L>Olybryus sente fore hyre full sone.</L>
<L>The sergeantys wer redy to go</L>
<L>And oute off prison fette hyre tho,</L>
<L>With &thorn;e holy crosse in hyre hond</L>
<L N="425">Wer-with sche dyde &thorn;e fendys schond.</L>
<L>He saw hyre come in als feyre case</L>
<L>Of flesch &amp; blode as euer sche was.</L>
<L>Than bespake sir Olybryus</L>
<L>And to &thorn;at meyd he seyd &thorn;us:</L>
<L N="430">"Meyd Mergaret, I pray &thorn;e</L>
<L>That &thorn;ou wyll turne vnto me."</L>
<L>Sche seyd: "cursyd mote &thorn;i godys be,
<PB REF="00000378.tif" N="240"></L>
<L>To beleue on &thorn;ou woldys haue me!</L>
<L>Fore &thorn;i godys &thorn;at thou beleuyst In,</L>
<L N="435">The be cursyd &amp; full of syne,</L>
<L>Fore &thorn;ei bene of Sathanas kynd;</L>
<L>I wyll neuer haue them in mynde.</L>
<L>When &thorn;ou thinkys best to thy lykyng,</L>
<L>On-to myscheff &thorn;ei wyll &thorn;e brynge.</L>
<L N="440">Therefore I rede &amp; counsyll &thorn;e:</L>
<L>Beleue on my lord &thorn;at is so fre,</L>
<L>That made &thorn;e &amp; me &amp; euery mane,</L>
<L>That most of wytte &amp; vertu cane!</L>
<L>Therefore beleue hym vpon</L>
<L N="445">A(nd) be baptyst at &thorn;e fonte-stone!"</L>
<L>He seyd to hyre in &thorn;at stound:</L>
<L>"A crounne of gold I wyll found:</L>
<L>My godys are trew &amp; thyne are lesse.</L>
<L>Therefore I byde &thorn;e hold &thorn;i pes."</L>
<L N="450">He seyd to hys seruantys thane.</L>
<L>"I charge &yogh;ou euery mane</L>
<L>That &yogh;e poure vpone hyre hede</L>
<L>Sethinge oyle &amp; boylinge lede;</L>
<L>Schald hyre fro &thorn;e hede vnto &thorn;e fote,</L>
<L N="455">To sche turne and ax bote."</L>
<L>The turmente hyre &thorn;an full sore</L>
<L>With oyle &amp; hote lede ouer-more,</L>
<L>Tyll sche suete, flessch &amp; fell,</L>
<L>As it wer water oute of a well.</L>
<L N="460">Than seyd &thorn;ei to &thorn;at holy meyd:</L>
<L>"Beleue vppon oure godys! "&thorn;ei seyd.</L>
<L>Sche seyd: "fro them I me defend</L>
<L>And beleue on Cryst with-outen end.</L>
<L>Cursyd be &thorn;ei &thorn;at on &thorn;i godys thinke</L>
<L N="465">Or on hem wryte with pauper &amp; ynke!"</L>
<L>They had no powere hyre to quelle:</L>
<L>The holy crosse kepte hyre welle.</L>
<L>He comandyd hyre anon tho</L>
<L>In a fate of water to be do,</L>
<L N="470">There anone to be sente,</L>
<L>All hyre hete to be queynte.</L>
<L>Anone as sche &thorn;e water gane se,</L>
<L>Sche thou&yogh;t &thorn;er-in crystynd to be</L>
<L>And seyd: "in Crystys holy name</L>
<L N="475">Here I take baptym &amp; defy &thorn;er blame."</L>
<L>Anon &thorn;e thonder began to berst &mdash;</L>
<L>The pepull fled awey full fast.</L>
<L>The angell toke hyre out of &thorn;e water than.</L>
<L>They my&yogh;ht it se euery mane,</L>
<L N="480">And turnyd anone to hyre beleue.</L>
<L>Many a M, or it wer eve,</L>
<L>Both old pepull &amp; &yogh;onge</L>
<L>Turnyd to hyre &amp; of hyre songe;</L>
<L>On Jhesu Cryst &thorn;ei dyde beleue</L>
<L N="485">Both meyd, chyld, &amp; wyue.</L>
<L>The kynge saw anone ry&yogh;ht</L>
<L>That herme to hyre do none he my&yogh;ht:</L>
<L>He callyd to Malcus, &thorn;at was</L>
<L>Hys man-quellere in euery place,</L>
<L N="490">And bad hym &thorn;at he schold</L>
<L>Take hyre fast into hys hold</L>
<L>And lede hyre with-oute &thorn;e towne than</L>
<L>And in a fyere he schuld hyre bryn</L>
<L>And brynge hyre oute of hyre lyue,</L>
<L N="495">That sche no-more with hym stryue.</L>
<L>And when sche come vnto &thorn;at sted</L>
<L>&THORN;er sche schuld be pute to dede,</L>
<L>Mych pepull folowyd hyre tho,</L>
<L>Also fast as sche my&yogh;ht go.</L>
<L N="500">Anon &thorn;e sone wexyd blake,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e thunder gane to crake.</L>
<L>The folke wer ferd in &thorn;at stound,</L>
<L>That fore fere &thorn;ei fell to grond;</L>
<L>They wer so afreyd tho,</L>
<L N="505">That &thorn;ei knew no&thorn;er wele ne wo.</L>
<L>Anon oure lord an angell sente</L>
<L>In-to &thorn;e place sche schuld be brente,</L>
<L>And seyd so hyre with myld steuen:</L>
<L>"Blyssed &thorn;ou arte to-dey in heuen:</L>
<L N="510">Thys dey in heuyn &thorn;ou schall crounned be</L>
<L>Before Crystys maieste."</L>
<L>Malcus herd &thorn;e wordys &thorn;at sche speke,</L>
<L>And thou&yogh;t he wold not do hyre wreke;</L>
<L>He knelyd doune vpon &thorn;e grounde</L>
<L N="515">And axyd mersy in &thorn;at stonde.</L>
<L>And &thorn;an he saw in &thorn;at place</L>
<L>Multytude of angellus &thorn;er sche was.</L>
<L>He leyd done hys suerd hym by</L>
<L>And seyd: "maden, I ax mersy."</L>
<L N="520">Than bespake &thorn;e vergyne bry&yogh;ht</L>
<L>And seyd to hym anone ry&yogh;ht:</L>
<L>"Broder, iff &thorn;i wyll it be,</L>
<L>A lytell whyle abyde &thorn;ou me</L>
<L>And late me make my prayere</L>
<L N="525">To Jhesu Cryst &thorn;at bou&yogh;t me dere.</L>
<L>And anon in &thorn;is tyde</L>
<L>Awey &thorn;ou schall me ryde.</L>
<L>"The fader &amp; son &amp; &thorn;e holy goste,</L>
<L>Lord &amp; kynge of my&yogh;tys moste,</L>
<L N="530">That all &thorn;is werld made of nou&yogh;t</L>
<L>And man-kynd &thorn;ou hast dere bou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Off a floure &thorn;ou wer forth brou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Fore we schuld not be lorne:</L>
<L>Jhesu Cryst, I beseche &thorn;e,</L>
<L N="535">Thys dey a bone &thorn;ou grante me</L>
<L>Thys pepull here beforne:</L>
<L>All &thorn;at in &thorn;e wyrschype of &thorn;e</L>
<L>And in mynde do honore me,</L>
<L>Thou late hem neuer in peynes be bound</L>
<L N="540">Ne in dedly synne be fond!</L>
<L>All &thorn;at my turmente here or rede</L>
<L>Or in my name do almus-dede,</L>
<L>Jhesu Cryst, &yogh;yff them to mede</L>
<L>The blyss of heuyn fore &thorn;er gode dede!</L>
<L N="545">Iff any woman be with chyld,</L>
<L>I praye to oure lady meke &amp; myld</L>
<L>Off hyre peynes &thorn;at sche be vnbond</L>
<L>And be lyuerd saue &amp; sond;
<PB REF="00000379.tif" N="241"></L>
<L>Jhesu Cryst, I besech &thorn;e</L>
<L N="550">That, when sche callys vpone &thorn;e,</L>
<L>That &thorn;ou wold be &thorn;er socure!</L>
<L>That &thorn;e crosse doth honore,</L>
<L>And all &thorn;at worschyp my dey</L>
<L>Or honore me as &thorn;ei may</L>
<L N="555">Or here my memory dey or ny&yogh;ht</L>
<L>With gode hert or candell-ly&yogh;ht,</L>
<L>I beseke &thorn;e fore &thorn;i glory</L>
<L>Late &thorn;em neuer in syne dy&yogh;e!</L>
<L>Where-some-euer &thorn;at body be,</L>
<L N="560">On &thorn;at saule haue mersye!</L>
<L>And &thorn;at &thorn;e fend do &thorn;em no skathe,</L>
<L>Ne&thorn;er late ne&thorn;er rathe,</L>
<L>That berythe on &thorn;em my lyffe,</L>
<L>No&thorn;er man, chyld, ne wyffe."</L>
<L N="565">Oure lord herde hyre prayere sone</L>
<L>And grantyd hyr all hyre bone.</L>
<L>Anone sche seyd &thorn;us</L>
<L>And spake onto Malcus,</L>
<L>Sche bad hym &thorn;at he schuld fullfylle</L>
<L N="570">And do all hys lordys wyll.</L>
<L>"That wyll I not, he seyd, fore all &thorn;e erth to wyne,</L>
<L>Fore I haue se &thorn;e lord &thorn;at thou beleuys In."</L>
<L>Sche seyd: "sir, do as I &thorn;e byde,</L>
<L>Take &amp; smyte off myne hede!</L>
<L N="575">Fore god hath foregyffe &thorn;e</L>
<L>That I byde &thorn;e do to me,</L>
<L>Fore it is a&yogh;enst &thorn;i wylle</L>
<L>Tha(t) commandment to fullfylle;</L>
<L>Into paradyse &thorn;ou schall wend,</L>
<L N="580">There-in to be with-outen ende."</L>
<L>Malcus herd hyre sey &thorn;is sawe:</L>
<L>And hys suerd he gane draw</L>
<L>And hyre hede he smote offe,</L>
<L>As &thorn;e law &thorn;er-to hym droffe.</L>
<L N="585">Michaell, Gabryell, &amp; Raphaell infere</L>
<L>Saw &thorn;is don all in sych manere,</L>
<L>With Joy &amp; blysse &amp; melody</L>
<L>The bare hyre saule to heuyne on hye;</L>
<L>Before oure lord &thorn;ei gane hyre bere:</L>
<L N="590">To hym sche was leffe and dere.</L>
<L>Thyopy, &thorn;e grete clerke,</L>
<L>Remembyrd all hyre lyff &amp; werke</L>
<L>And made hyre lyue in memory,</L>
<L>And (s)he hyre norysschyd in A&yogh;y,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. he st. sche.</NOTE></L>
<L N="595">In Antyoche &thorn;ei hyre brou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And in gode intente &thorn;er &thorn;en wrou&yogh;t</L>
<L>A chapell in hyre name.</L>
<L>And all &thorn;at wer seke &amp; lame,</L>
<L>The&thorn;er fast gane &thorn;ei gone:</L>
<L N="600">Hole &amp; so&umacr;nd home &thorn;ei come</L>
<L>Thorow grace off god all-my&yogh;t</L>
<L>And be prayere of &thorn;at meidyne bry&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Jhesu, gyfe vs grace, we may lyfe so:</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;i blyss we my&yogh;t come to.</L>
<L N="605">The lyue of &thorn;is vergyne I haue rede.</L>
<L>On a tewysdey sche was quyke &amp; dede. &mdash;</L>
<L>Jhesu Cryst, heuyn kynge,</L>
<L>Grant them all hys blyssinge</L>
<L>That &thorn;is story wyll haue in mynd</L>
<L N="610">With clene thou&yogh;ht &amp; hert kynd.</L>
<L>Thorow prayere of seynte Mergarete</L>
<L>That in heuen we may mete,</L>
<L>By &thorn;e prayere of &thorn;at meyden hend</L>
<L>To &thorn;e Joy &thorn;at we mey wend,</L>
<L N="615">There to duell &amp; se &thorn;i face,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. &thorn;e st. &thorn;i.</NOTE></L>
<L>Lord god &thorn;erto gyffe vs grace!</L>
<L>Pray we all, yt may so be,</L>
<L>Amen, amen, fore charyte!</L>
<TRAILER>Amen quod Rate.
</TRAILER>

</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="4" TYPE="legend"><PB REF="00000380.tif" N="[242]">
<HEAD>4. Seynt Katerine.</HEAD>
<DIV3 TYPE="version">
<HEAD>a) Ms. Auchinl. fol. 21.</HEAD>
<DIV4 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>He &thorn;at made heuen &amp; er&thorn;e</L>
<L>&amp; sonne &amp; mone for to schine,</L>
<L>Bring ous into his riche</L>
<L>&amp; scheld ous fram helle pine!</L>
<L N="5">Herken, &amp; y &yogh;ou wil telle</L>
<L>&THORN;e liif of an holy virgine,</L>
<L>&THORN;at treuli trowed in Jhesu Crist:</L>
<L>Hir name was hoten Katerine.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whilom it bitid so:</L>
<L N="10">In Grece it was an emperour;</L>
<L>He was king of mani palays,</L>
<L>Castels gret &amp; mani a tour.</L>
<L>&THORN;e riche men of &thorn;at lond</L>
<L>Serued him wi&thorn; gret honour.</L>
<L N="15">Maxens was his ri&yogh;t name,</L>
<L>Man he was of gret fauour.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Mahoun he held for his god:</L>
<L>He trowed in &thorn;at fals lay;</L>
<L>On Jhesu Crist no leued he nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="20">&THORN;at lord is &amp; god verray.</L>
<L>Sarra&yogh;in he was ful strong,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; cristendom he seyd nay,</L>
<L>For alle &thorn;at leued on Jhesu Crist</L>
<L>He stroyd hem bo&thorn;e ni&yogh;t &amp; day.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="25">When he hadde. XXXV. &amp; &thorn;ritti &yogh;er</L>
<L>(Ben) emperour &amp; born &thorn;e croun,</L>
<L>Ouer alle &thorn;e lond he sent his sond</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; messangers fram toun to toun;</L>
<L>To &thorn;e borwe of Alisander</L>
<L N="30">He bad &thorn;e folk schuld be boun,</L>
<L>Riche &amp; pouer, hei&yogh;e &amp; lowe,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; her offrend to seke Mahoun.
<PB REF="00000381.tif" N="243"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>He bad &thorn;at riche men schuld bring</L>
<L>Schepe &amp; nete to her offrinde,</L>
<L N="35">&THORN;e pouer men he bad come</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; quic foules on her honde;</L>
<L>&amp;, as &thorn;ai wald her liues haue,</L>
<L>For no &thorn;ing no schuld &thorn;ai wond.</L>
<L>It was &thorn;e kinges comandment</L>
<L N="40">&THORN;at he hadde comand in &thorn;at lond.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e folk com alle on &thorn;is maner &mdash;</L>
<L>To wret&thorn;e &thorn;e king &thorn;ai were fordred.</L>
<L>Bifor his godes himseluen he stode,</L>
<L>In riche clo&thorn;es was he cled.</L>
<L N="45">Glewemen were &thorn;er fele &amp; gode,</L>
<L>He bad hem be bli&thorn;e &amp; glad;</L>
<L>Noise &thorn;ai made swi&thorn;e miche,</L>
<L>So &thorn;emperour hem badde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ano&thorn;er king was in &thorn;at lond:</L>
<L N="50">Costus his name was told.</L>
<L>A douhter he had, &amp; no mo,</L>
<L>XV. winter was sche old:</L>
<L>Katerine was hir ri&yogh;t name,</L>
<L>Of witt &amp; wisdome was sche bold;</L>
<L N="55">Jhesu sche loued aldermest &mdash;</L>
<L>For his loue was hir liif sold.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>As sche stode in hir fader court,</L>
<L>Glewemen herd sche miri sing,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; pipes &amp; wi&thorn; trompes bo&thorn;e,</L>
<L N="60">Belles herd sche fast ring.</L>
<L>Sche axed at hir fader men</L>
<L>What was &thorn;at noise &amp; &thorn;at pipeing.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai told hir of &thorn;at riche offring</L>
<L>&THORN;at Maxens dede his men to bring.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="65">Sche heue vp hir holy hond</L>
<L>&amp; blisced hir ful witterly,</L>
<L>First hir brest &amp; se&thorn;&thorn;en hir tonge &mdash;</L>
<L>So seyt &thorn;e boke of hir stori.</L>
<L>Sche seyd sche wald &thorn;ider wende</L>
<L N="70">For to se &thorn;at melodye.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;outen fere &yogh;ede sche nou&yogh;t:</L>
<L>&THORN;ai &yogh;ede hir wi&thorn; &thorn;at stode hir bi.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>When sche com to &thorn;at palays,</L>
<L>Miche sche sey&yogh;e of gamen &amp; gle.
<PB REF="00000382.tif" N="244"></L>
<L N="75">&amp; al &thorn;at trowed on Jhesu Crist,</L>
<L>Wel sori men sche sei&yogh;e hem be:</L>
<L>Or &thorn;ai schuld make sacrifise</L>
<L>To his maumet, was maked of tre</L>
<L>&amp; of ston &amp; of bras,</L>
<L N="80">O&thorn;er elles schuld &thorn;ai marterd be.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Sche com bifor &thorn;at emperour,</L>
<L>&THORN;er he made his sacrifise,</L>
<L>&amp; gret him on &thorn;is maner,</L>
<L>Wordes had sche bold &amp; wise:</L>
<L N="85">"Jhesus Crist be wi&thorn; &thorn;e,</L>
<L>Ri&yogh;twise king &amp; heye Justise,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;oled ded opon &thorn;e tre</L>
<L>&amp; se&thorn;&thorn;en hadde pouwer forto rise.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Y speke of Jhesu, Marie sone,</L>
<L N="90">Of alle kinges he is flour;</L>
<L>&THORN;at suffred de&thorn; for al man kin,</L>
<L>He is our alder creatour.</L>
<L>Y hold &thorn;e ful wise of witt,</L>
<L>Sir Maxens, our emperour,</L>
<L N="95">&YOGH;if &thorn;ou makest alle &thorn;is folk</L>
<L>Him to seche wi&thorn; swiche honour.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot now me &thorn;enke &thorn;ou dost nou&yogh;t so,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou werchest on a wers wise:</L>
<L>&THORN;e folk, &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast hider brou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="100">&THORN;ou dost hem do &thorn;e fende seruise.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ai do more after &thorn;e,</L>
<L>Forso&thorn;e it is a cowardise;</L>
<L>For &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast ymaked here,</L>
<L>Fikel it is &amp; al feyntise."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="105">&THORN;is emperour forwonderd was</L>
<L>Of &thorn;at maidens fair vise,</L>
<L>&amp; of hir bold wordes also.</L>
<L>"Maiden, he seyd, &thorn;ou art vnwise.</L>
<L>Whi mispraises &thorn;ou our god</L>
<L N="110">&amp; holdest hem of so litel prise?</L>
<L>So no sestow ous nou&yogh;t do,</L>
<L>&THORN;at were&thorn; bo&thorn;e fowe &amp; grise.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou were lered on our lore</L>
<L>&amp; to our scole entendaunt,</L>
<L N="115">&THORN;ou wost say we dede ful wel,</L>
<L>&amp; wi&thorn; &thorn;i tonge &thorn;ou wost it graunt;</L>
<L>Jhesus Crist &thorn;ou wost forsake</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou drawest to &thorn;i waraunt,
<PB REF="00000383.tif" N="245"></L>
<L>&amp; our godes wostow seke,</L>
<L N="120">Bo&thorn;e Mahoun &amp; Teruagaunt.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot for we han bigonne here<NOTE PLACE="foot">Nach 121 sind 11 Verse mit der Initiale der R&uuml;ckseite ausgeschnitten.</NOTE></L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L N="125">. . . . .</L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L N="130">. . . . .</L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L>"&THORN;ise ben quic deuelen alle<MILESTONE N="22" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;is folk han here ysou&yogh;t;</L>
<L N="135">It is no god bot on y-wis,</L>
<L>&THORN;at me &amp; te &amp; alle ha&thorn; wrou&yogh;t".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;is emperour ful wiley was</L>
<L>&amp; &yogh;ete he cou&thorn;e ano&thorn;er croke:</L>
<L>Letters dede he swi&thorn;e make</L>
<L N="140">Priueli, so seyt &thorn;e boke,</L>
<L>How &thorn;at a maiden was &thorn;er com</L>
<L>"&THORN;at our godes al forsoke".</L>
<L>He seld it wi&thorn; his owen ring</L>
<L>&THORN;at he of his finger tok.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="145">He toke &thorn;e messanger &thorn;e letter</L>
<L>&THORN;at seled was wi&thorn; his ring,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e wisest men of &thorn;at lond</L>
<L>He bad hem go wi&thorn;outen duelleing.</L>
<L>He hi&yogh;t to don hem gret anour,</L>
<L N="150">As he was trewe kni&yogh;t &amp; king,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ai mi&yogh;t wi&thorn; her wisdom</L>
<L>Ouercom &thorn;at may, &thorn;at was so &yogh;ing.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e maiden was in prisoun don,</L>
<L>Son &thorn;e messangers were went.</L>
<L N="155">An angel com to hir ful sone</L>
<L>&THORN;at Jhesu Crist hir hadde ysent.</L>
<L>He seyd: "mi lord grete&thorn; &thorn;e wele</L>
<L>&THORN;at witt &amp; wisdom ha&thorn; &thorn;e lent,</L>
<L>&amp; biddes &thorn;e be of hert strong</L>
<L N="160">&amp; trow on him wi&thorn; gode entent.
<PB REF="00000384.tif" N="246"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Maxens ha&thorn; now sent his sond</L>
<L>Ouer-al into &thorn;is cuntre</L>
<L>After men &thorn;at ben ful wise,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;e to striue, astow schalt se.</L>
<L N="165">Bot bi &thorn;ai han &thorn;i wordes herd</L>
<L>As Jhesus Crist schal wisse &thorn;e,</L>
<L>Her trou&thorn;e wor&thorn; in god ful gode,</L>
<L>&amp; for his loue &thorn;ai schal marterd be".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ouer al &thorn;e lond, &thorn;at was so wide,</L>
<L N="170">His messanger(s) went ful &yogh;are.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. messangers mit auspunkt. s.</NOTE></L>
<L>Fifti men wi&thorn; hem &thorn;ai brou&yogh;t,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. him he corr. in hem &thorn;ai.</NOTE></L>
<L>Grete clerkes &amp; wise of lare.</L>
<L>Of al &thorn;e wisdom of &thorn;e lond</L>
<L>Men seyd &thorn;at &thorn;ai redi ware</L>
<L N="175">Forto despute wi&thorn; Katerine,</L>
<L>&THORN;at Maxens hadde in prisoun pare.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Among hem was &thorn;e maiden brou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Wro&thorn;ly &thorn;ai gun to hir bere,</L>
<L>Her resouns &thorn;ai seyden on &amp; on,</L>
<L N="180">Euerich on his best maner.</L>
<L>&THORN;is mayden, &thorn;at ich of told,</L>
<L>Stode euer wi&thorn; simple chere</L>
<L>&amp; herd her resouns euerichon&mdash;</L>
<L>Godes angel was hir fere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="185">When &thorn;ai hadde her ressouns seyd,</L>
<L>Euerichon more &amp; lesse,</L>
<L>Sche answerd hem at eueri point</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; ful michel mildenis,</L>
<L>&amp; se&thorn;&thorn;en seyd hir aviis</L>
<L N="190">Of god &thorn;at louerd was &amp; euer isse,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. loured, r ist &uuml;berschr.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at euer was &amp; ay schal be&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;e godspelle sche tok to witnisse.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Sche schewed hem wi&thorn; holy writ</L>
<L>Of Jhesus incarnacioun,</L>
<L N="195">Hou he was of a maiden born,</L>
<L>&amp; hou he suffred passioun,</L>
<L>&amp; hou he sent his apostles wide</L>
<L>For our alder sauacioun&mdash;</L>
<L>&amp; alle &thorn;e bileue of cristen man</L>
<L N="200">Sche schewed hem wi&thorn; gode resoun.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>When &thorn;e maiden hadde seyd</L>
<L>Hir resouns, &thorn;at wer gode,
<PB REF="00000385.tif" N="247"></L>
<L>Ful redi were &thorn;e maisters alle</L>
<L>Forto chaungen her mode.</L>
<L N="205">Bot, &thorn;er Maxens himseluen sat,</L>
<L>For wret&thorn;e he wax wel ney wode</L>
<L>&amp; asked &yogh;if &thorn;ai cou&thorn;e ou&yogh;t sain</L>
<L>O&yogh;ain &thorn;e maiden, &thorn;er sche stode.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;an spac a maister sone,</L>
<L N="210">Of hei&yogh;e kin he was born:</L>
<L>"Sir, he seyd, we han gon mis,</L>
<L>Sche ha&thorn; a resoun ous biforn.</L>
<L>We wil trowe on Jhesu Crist,</L>
<L>&THORN;at bar &thorn;e croun was made of &thorn;orn,</L>
<L N="215">&amp; do, so Katerine ha&thorn; ous told&mdash;</L>
<L>Lo&thorn; ous is to be forlorn".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Sone anon he axed hem</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ai wald her mode amend.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai seyd: "we trowe on Jhesu Crist,</L>
<L N="220">So Katerine ous ha&thorn; kende".</L>
<L>He bad make a gre(te) fer</L>
<L>&amp; bind hem fot &amp; hende,</L>
<L>&amp; swore amidward &thorn;e borwe</L>
<L>Ich a fot schuld &thorn;ai be brende.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="225">When men kest hem in fer,</L>
<L>Fair miracle men mi&yogh;t se:<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. mirache.</NOTE></L>
<L>Her flesche, her clo&thorn;es &amp; her here</L>
<L>Of wem were quite &amp; fre.</L>
<L>For him &thorn;ai suffred passioun</L>
<L N="230">&THORN;at for hem dyed on tre;</L>
<L>To heuen were her soules born,</L>
<L>In godes frari to be.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;an bad &thorn;emperour his men</L>
<L>Bring for&thorn; &thorn;at fair may.</L>
<L N="235">&amp; when sche was biforn him com,</L>
<L>He seyd: "welcom, parmafay!</L>
<L>Hastow &yogh;ete &thorn;i conseyl take</L>
<L>For to trowe opon mi lay?</L>
<L>Haue merci on &thorn;i feirhed!</L>
<L N="240">Y schal &thorn;e wor&thorn;schip ich day.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ou schalt be wor&thorn;schiped as &thorn;e quen,</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e in bour &amp; halle;</L>
<L>&amp; in &thorn;i name schal be wrou&yogh;t</L>
<L>An ymage fair wi&thorn;-alle,</L>
<L N="245">&amp; in &thorn;is borwe it schal be sett,</L>
<L>Hei&yogh;e &amp; lowe to louten alle.
<PB REF="00000386.tif" N="248"></L>
<L>Of alle &thorn;e nedes of &thorn;is lond</L>
<L>To &thorn;e we schal conseyl calle.<NOTE PLACE="foot">l. &thorn;e we schal to.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Hei&yogh;e &amp; lowe wor&thorn;schipe &thorn;e.<NOTE PLACE="foot">schal fehlt.</NOTE></L>
<L N="250">Katerine, do as y &thorn;e bede!</L>
<L>&amp; &yogh;ete we schal &thorn;e more do,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou wilt wirche after mi red:<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. &thorn;if.</NOTE></L>
<L>A temple in &thorn;i wor&thorn;schip make</L>
<L>Of marble ston, when &thorn;ou art ded;</L>
<L N="255">Among our godes &thorn;ou schalt be sett</L>
<L>In siluer &amp; in gold rede".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Be stille, fole! whi seystow so?</L>
<L>&THORN;ou redest me to do gret sinne.</L>
<L>What man wald ydampned be</L>
<L N="260">For ani maner warldes winne?</L>
<L>Ich haue me taken to Jhesus Crist,</L>
<L>Him to serue &amp; trowen inne;</L>
<L>Ich hope to com to his riche,</L>
<L>&THORN;er ioie &amp; blis schal neuer blinne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="265">Min hope is in him aldermost,</L>
<L>Lord abouen in trinite,</L>
<L>He is mi loue, he is mi spouse:</L>
<L>To swiche a leman take y me.</L>
<L>&amp; &yogh;if it were ani bot,</L>
<L N="270">At &thorn;at conseyl wald y be</L>
<L>&THORN;ine maumettes to breke &amp; brenne &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou made hem, &amp; &thorn;ai nou&yogh;t &thorn;e".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>When &thorn;at Katerine hadde yseyd,</L>
<L>Him &thorn;ou&yogh;t he schuld brest in fiue.</L>
<L N="275">Wi&thorn; ire &amp; wre&thorn;e he bad his men:</L>
<L>"Do as y &yogh;ou bid swi&thorn;e!</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; schourges swi&thorn;e gret &amp; scharp</L>
<L>Bete&thorn; hir al out oliue,</L>
<L>&amp; do&thorn; hir se&thorn;&thorn;en in prisoun strong!</L>
<L N="280">Wat bote is it al day to striue?"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ai made hir body blo &amp; blac,<NOTE PLACE="foot">blo steht auf der Rasur eines l&auml;ngeren Wortes, welches auf te endete.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at er was white so alpes bon.<NOTE PLACE="foot">alpes = elpes; elp &mdash; elephant.</NOTE></L>
<L>Se&thorn;&thorn;en seyd he to his men:</L>
<L>"Prisouns hir swi&thorn;e anon!</L>
<L N="285">Honger schal sche han ynou&yogh;,</L>
<L>Mete no drink gif hir non,
<PB REF="00000387.tif" N="249"></L>
<L>Litel no miche &mdash; &thorn;at loke wel! &mdash;</L>
<L>Til &thorn;is tvelue days be comen &amp; gon.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Y mot fare out of &thorn;is lond &mdash;</L>
<L N="290">Bot y no schal nou&yogh;t long duelle:</L>
<L>To hei&yogh;e men &amp; wise bo&thorn;e</L>
<L>Of &thorn;is auentour y schal hem telle;</L>
<L>Conseyl y schal haue ful gode</L>
<L>Hou y schal &thorn;at maiden quelle;</L>
<L N="295">Bot &yogh;iue sche take ano&thorn;er rede.</L>
<L>Sche mai be siker &amp; wo to welle".<NOTE PLACE="foot">Dieser Vers ist unten nachgetragen. &amp; = an = on.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>When &thorn;is emperour was went,</L>
<L>&THORN;e quen hir seyd to a kni&yogh;t &mdash;</L>
<L>Of alle kni&yogh;tes he was chef:</L>
<L N="300">Porfir seyt &thorn;e bok he hi&yogh;t:</L>
<L>"&THORN;ou do me speke wi&thorn; Katerine,</L>
<L>And, if &thorn;ou may, &thorn;is ich ni&yogh;t!</L>
<L>Longing haue y swi&thorn;e miche</L>
<L>To speke wi&thorn; hir, &yogh;if &thorn;at y mi&yogh;t".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="305">Wi&thorn;in ni&yogh;t for&yogh;at he nou&yogh;t</L>
<L>To do &thorn;e quenes comandment:</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e prisoun, as he hir hi&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Priueliche he wi&thorn; hir went.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai sei&yogh;e &thorn;erin so michel li&yogh;t,<MILESTONE N="23" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="310">&amp; god his angels &thorn;ider sent,</L>
<L>&THORN;at sete about &thorn;at swete wi&yogh;t</L>
<L>And anoint hir wi&thorn; oinement.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ei sei&yogh;en angels anoinen hir cors,</L>
<L>Ich wem &amp; ich a wounde,</L>
<L N="315">&amp; &thorn;urch &thorn;e mi&yogh;t of Jhesu Crist</L>
<L>&THORN;an &thorn;ai were bo&thorn;e hole &amp; sounde.</L>
<L>No hadde &thorn;ai stonden at &thorn;e prisoun</L>
<L>Bot a litel wi&yogh;tine(!) stounde,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;at li&yogh;t &thorn;ai weren adrad:</L>
<L N="320">Aswon &thorn;ai fel adoun to grounde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e maiden aros &amp; com to hem</L>
<L>&amp; spac to hem wi&thorn; mild mode:</L>
<L>"Arise&thorn; vp in godes name,</L>
<L>&amp; loke &yogh;e ben of confort gode!"</L>
<L N="325">Sche bad hem leue on Jhesu Crist,</L>
<L>&THORN;at for mankin schadde his blod.</L>
<L>And when &thorn;ai herd &thorn;at maiden speke,</L>
<L>Vp &thorn;ai risen &amp; bi hir stode.
<PB REF="00000388.tif" N="250"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;an seyd &thorn;e quen ful sone:</L>
<L N="330">"A, Keterine, wele is &thorn;e!</L>
<L>Miche &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t do wi&thorn; Jhesu Crist,</L>
<L>We han sen of &thorn;i priuete".</L>
<L>&THORN;an sche seyd: "&yogh;e; trowe on him</L>
<L>&THORN;at is lord of swiche pouste!</L>
<L N="335">His seriaunce no for&yogh;et he nou&yogh;t</L>
<L>&THORN;at him serue wi&thorn; hert fre.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Certes, dame, y rede &thorn;e wel:</L>
<L>Forsake Maxens &amp; al his mi&yogh;t</L>
<L>For &thorn;at ich kinges loue</L>
<L N="340">&THORN;at made &thorn;e day &amp; eke &thorn;e ni&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Heuen &amp; er&thorn;e, man &amp; best,</L>
<L>Sonne &amp; mone to schine bri&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&THORN;e ioie of heuen schaltow haue.</L>
<L>And al-so y say to &thorn;e, sir kni&yogh;t".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="345">&THORN;an spak &thorn;e kni&yogh;t to Katerine:</L>
<L>"What maner ioie may &thorn;is be?"</L>
<L>Katerine seyd also sone:</L>
<L>"Porfir, y wil telle &thorn;e:</L>
<L>&THORN;at is &thorn;e ioie wi&thorn;outen enden</L>
<L N="350">&THORN;at ere no may here, no ei&yogh;e se,</L>
<L>No tong speke, no hert &thorn;ink&mdash;</L>
<L>Lord it sende &yogh;ou &amp; me!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;er nis non in &thorn;at riche</L>
<L>&THORN;at honger ha&thorn;, cold no &thorn;rest;</L>
<L N="355">&THORN;er is liif wi&thorn;outen ende,</L>
<L>&THORN;er is stede of ro &amp; rest".</L>
<L>&THORN;urch &thorn;e wordes &thorn;at sche spac</L>
<L>Er midni&yogh;t &thorn;ai weren al prest</L>
<L>To suffre de&thorn; for godes loue;</L>
<L N="360">Her hope was in his merci best.<NOTE PLACE="foot">l. fest st. best?</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Sche bitau&yogh;t hem Jhesu Crist,</L>
<L>&amp; se&thorn;&thorn;en went bo&thorn;e oway.</L>
<L>To hundred kni&yogh;tes serued hir:</L>
<L>Sche told hem &thorn;at o&thorn;er day</L>
<L N="365">Hou godes angels sat abouten hir</L>
<L>In &thorn;e prisoun, &thorn;er sche lay.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai trowed on god, as sche hem radde,</L>
<L>&amp; forsoken al her fals lay.
<PB REF="00000389.tif" N="251"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e maiden no most haue mete no dri(n)k<NOTE PLACE="foot">369 ff.) Die Stropfe ist in Auch. verderbt.</NOTE></L>
<L N="370">&THORN;ourch comandment of &thorn;at king,</L>
<L>Tvelue days &thorn;urch &amp; &thorn;urch</L>
<L>Sche no most haue mete no dring.</L>
<L>Angels com fram heuen to er&thorn;e</L>
<L>Ich day to &thorn;at swete &thorn;ing,</L>
<L N="375">Mete &amp; drink ynou&yogh; plente</L>
<L>&THORN;ai brou&yogh;ten, of alle gode tiding.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; when &thorn;e tvelue dayes were gon,</L>
<L>&THORN;an com Jhesu, heuen king,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; angels &amp; maidens bo&thorn;e,</L>
<L N="380">For to speke wi&thorn; his derling.</L>
<L>He seyd: "&thorn;ou hast ben for me ladde</L>
<L>In miche striif &amp; gret fonding:<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. fonging.</NOTE></L>
<L>Loke, &thorn;ou hert &thorn;e ful wele!</L>
<L>Y &yogh;iue &thorn;e, douhter, mi bliscing.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="385">Oft ichaue &thorn;i praiers herd,</L>
<L>When &thorn;at &thorn;ou me bisou&yogh;t;</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore schal y &thorn;e nou&yogh;t fayl</L>
<L>When &thorn;ou art to iugement brou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Loke, &thorn;ou be stedefast &amp; trewe!</L>
<L N="390">Of al her paines &yogh;iue &thorn;ou nou&yogh;t!</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e blis &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t be siker</L>
<L>&THORN;at ichaue to min hondewerk wrou&yogh;t".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; when he hadde &thorn;is wordes seyd,</L>
<L>Out of prisoun he gan glide</L>
<L N="395">To heuen blis, &thorn;er he com fro,</L>
<L>&amp; angels on ich a side.&mdash;</L>
<L>When Maxens hadde his wil do,</L>
<L>Hom he com wi&thorn; michel prede,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; erles &amp; wi&thorn; kni&yogh;tes fele,</L>
<L N="400">And knaues ernand bi her side.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Opon &thorn;at o&thorn;er day ful sone</L>
<L>He asked after &thorn;e maidens astat:</L>
<L>"&YOGH;if sche be oliue &yogh;ete,</L>
<L>Sche is ful feble, wele y wat.</L>
<L N="405">Fet hir for&thorn;, mi jaioler!</L>
<L>For hunger &amp; &thorn;rost sche is wel mate".<NOTE PLACE="foot">V. 406 ist in 2 Zeilen geschr.</NOTE></L>
<L>He &yogh;ede anon &amp; brou&yogh;t hir for&thorn;</L>
<L>Bifor &thorn;e king, &thorn;er he sat.
<PB REF="00000390.tif" N="252"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>When sche was biforn him come,</L>
<L N="410">He seyd: "welcom, damisele!<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. urspr. Sche.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ou hast ben strongliche ygreued</L>
<L>In iren bounden &amp; in stiel;</L>
<L>Bot &yogh;ete me &thorn;enke&thorn; &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t liue&mdash;</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;at like&thorn; me ful wel.</L>
<L N="415">Jhesu, &thorn;at &thorn;ou of speke,</L>
<L>Him forsake &thorn;ou euerichadel!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For y nold nou&yogh;t &thorn;i liif spille,</L>
<L>To prisoun y dede &thorn;e do.</L>
<L>Bot, certes, &thorn;ou most now nede</L>
<L N="420">Chesen on of &thorn;is &thorn;inges tvo:</L>
<L>O&thorn;er trowe opon mi godes</L>
<L>&amp; cristendom &thorn;ou do &thorn;e fro,</L>
<L>O&thorn;er we schal ous bi&thorn;enke</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; strong paines &thorn;e to slo".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="425">&THORN;an spac &thorn;e maiden, &thorn;er sche stode</L>
<L>Among &thorn;e sarra&yogh;ins so blake&mdash;</L>
<L>Jhesus Crist hir ha&thorn; ytau&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Hir wordes were wi&thorn;outen lake:</L>
<L>"&THORN;ei ine may liue, wite &thorn;ou wel</L>
<L N="430">God schal y neuer forsake;</L>
<L>For his loue am y ful prest</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; wille mi de&thorn; for to take.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ei &thorn;at &yogh;e alle bi&thorn;enke &yogh;ou</L>
<L>Of pines hard &amp; sore,</L>
<L N="435">&THORN;erto icham now ful prest,</L>
<L>Hem to suffre icham al yare.</L>
<L>Neuer-more, while y liue,</L>
<L>Mi flesche no blod wil y spare</L>
<L>To spende for mi lordes loue&mdash;</L>
<L N="440">For me he suffred wele mare.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ble&thorn;eliche wil y martird be</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; gret pines &amp; wi&thorn; smale:</L>
<L>He ha&thorn; me to his frari cald,</L>
<L>&THORN;at schal be bot of mi bale".</L>
<L N="445">Sche stode euer wi&thorn; mild mode</L>
<L>Bifor Maxens, to telle hir tale.</L>
<L>Bot, &thorn;er he sete opon his des,</L>
<L>For tene he grent &amp; wex al pale.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>As he sat &amp; couped hir,</L>
<L N="450">&THORN;er com a Sarra&yogh;in gon:
<PB REF="00000391.tif" N="253"></L>
<L>Cursates, seyt &thorn;e boke, he hi&yogh;t.</L>
<L>"King, he seyd, icham &thorn;i man.</L>
<L>&YOGH;ete y can a turnament make:</L>
<L>Swiche no herdestow neuer nan;</L>
<L N="455">Bi &thorn;an it be wrou&yogh;t &amp; sche it se,</L>
<L>Ano&thorn;er &thorn;ou&yogh;t sche schal &thorn;enke on.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Four wheles schal y make,</L>
<L>&THORN;e to schal turn o&yogh;ain to,</L>
<L>Ful &thorn;icke &thorn;ai schal be driuen</L>
<L N="460">Wi&thorn; wi&thorn;erhokes mo &amp; mo.</L>
<L>Among &thorn;e four sche schal be don,</L>
<L>Hir bodi forto wirche wo:</L>
<L>To smale peces sche schal be rent,</L>
<L>On er&thorn;e schal sche neuer go".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="465">&THORN;an bad Maxens his iayoler</L>
<L>&THORN;at he schuld &thorn;at maiden take</L>
<L>Into prisoun forto lede,</L>
<L>&THORN;erwhile he schul &thorn;e wheles make.</L>
<L>&amp; er &thorn;e &thorn;ridde day at ende</L>
<L N="470">&THORN;ai were wrou&yogh;t for hir sake;</L>
<L>So grisely were &thorn;ai on to se:</L>
<L>Mani a man &thorn;ai maden quake.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>When &thorn;o wheles weren prest,</L>
<L>Amid &thorn;e borwe &thorn;ai were sett</L>
<L N="475">Wi&thorn; sarra&yogh;ins bifor &thorn;e king&mdash;</L>
<L>Hard was &thorn;e maiden &thorn;rett.</L>
<L>&THORN;an bad &thorn;emperour his men</L>
<L>&THORN;at sche were out of prisoun fett.</L>
<L>Wele he wend wi&thorn;outen faile</L>
<L N="480">&THORN;at his tene schuld be bett.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ai ladden hir to &thorn;at stede</L>
<L>&THORN;er sche schuld on hem be don.</L>
<L>Mani a moder child &thorn;er was,</L>
<L>For to loke &thorn;e maiden opon.<NOTE PLACE="foot">loke aus leke corr.</NOTE></L>
<L N="485">Sche sett hir doun opon hir knes,<MILESTONE N="24" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>To god of heuen sche bad a bon.</L>
<L>Bot herkne&thorn; now wat bitid!</L>
<L>Godes help &thorn;er com ful sone.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e wheles for to brese &amp; breke</L>
<L N="490">Our louerd bad an angel gon.</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e wicked sarra&yogh;ins</L>
<L>Veniaunce he tok anon.
<PB REF="00000392.tif" N="254"></L>
<L>Among &thorn;e folk &thorn;ai gun driue:</L>
<L N="495">Four &thorn;ousend &thorn;er wer slawe</L>
<L>Of he&thorn;en men &thorn;at &thorn;ider wer come &mdash;</L>
<L>Bot iuel had &thorn;at maiden non.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Cristenmen &thorn;at &thorn;er weren</L>
<L>For &thorn;is miracle were wel glad.</L>
<L N="500">&THORN;e king no wist wat he dede:</L>
<L>So sori he was &amp; so madde.</L>
<L>&THORN;e sarra&yogh;ins &thorn;at mi&yogh;t aschape</L>
<L>Wel sori &thorn;ai were &amp; adrad</L>
<L>For &thorn;e periil &thorn;at &thorn;ai sey&yogh;en;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. scheinbar periis.</NOTE></L>
<L N="505">Of sorwe were &thorn;ai neuer (so) sad.<NOTE PLACE="foot">im Ms. fehlt so.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>When &thorn;at alle &thorn;is folk was slawe,</L>
<L>To him seyd his wiif, &thorn;e quen:</L>
<L>"Waileway, &thorn;ou wreche man!</L>
<L>Wherof makestow &thorn;e so kene?</L>
<L N="510">He ki&thorn;es wele &thorn;at he is king,</L>
<L>&THORN;at born was of &thorn;e maiden schene.</L>
<L>Y sorsake &thorn;e to day</L>
<L>And &thorn;ine werkes al bidene.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>O&yogh;ein &thorn;e lord &thorn;at ous schope</L>
<L N="515">No helpe&thorn; &thorn;e nou&yogh;t to chide;</L>
<L>&THORN;at cristen men leue&thorn; on,</L>
<L>His mi&yogh;tes ha&thorn; he ful wide.</L>
<L>Do cri him merci of &thorn;i gilt!</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou wilt long abide,</L>
<L N="520">On of &thorn;is days when &thorn;ou art dede<NOTE PLACE="foot">507&mdash;520) Die Versanf&auml;nge sind verwischt.</NOTE></L>
<L>Helle pine schal &thorn;e bitide".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>He wex swi&thorn;e wro&thorn; &amp; wode,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e quen he seyd anon:</L>
<L>"Now y wot, &thorn;ou art desceyued</L>
<L N="525">&THORN;urch wichecraft of &thorn;at woman.</L>
<L>Y &thorn;e swere bi min godes</L>
<L>&amp; bi al &thorn;at y swere can:</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;ou ra&thorn;er wende &thorn;i mode,</L>
<L>To wicked ded &thorn;ou schalt be don.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="530">Bot &thorn;ou forsake Jhesu Crist,</L>
<L>&THORN;is schal be &thorn;i iugement:</L>
<L>First &thorn;ine pappes of &thorn;i brest</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; iren hokes schal be rent;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Die letzte Silbe von tates ist verwischt.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000393.tif" N="255"></L>
<L>Biheueded schaltow &thorn;an be,</L>
<L>&THORN;i bodi on &thorn;e feld ysent,</L>
<L N="535">Wi&thorn; houndes &amp; wi&thorn; foules to-drawe.</L>
<L>And &thorn;is schal be mi comandment".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>When &thorn;is emperour was war</L>
<L>&THORN;at sche nold wenden hir &thorn;ou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;an bad he on &thorn;is maner</L>
<L N="540">&THORN;at sche were out of toun ybrou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Sche loked opon Katerine,</L>
<L>&amp; mildeliche sche hir bisou&yogh;t</L>
<L>&THORN;at sche schuld hir erande bere</L>
<L>To Jhesu Crist, &thorn;at ous ha&thorn; bou&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="545">&THORN;an spac &thorn;e maiden, &thorn;er sche stode:</L>
<L>"Forso&thorn;e, dame, y telle it &thorn;e:</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e ioie wi&thorn;outen ende</L>
<L>Trust &amp; siker may &thorn;ou be.</L>
<L>In his name &thorn;ou take &thorn;e ded</L>
<L N="550">&THORN;at sprad his bodi on &thorn;e tre,</L>
<L>As his swete wille was,</L>
<L>For to maken ous alle fre".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Men drou&yogh; hir tates of hir brest</L>
<L>&amp; heueded hir, as y &yogh;ou told.</L>
<L N="555">&amp; se&thorn;&thorn;en hete &thorn;at emperour</L>
<L>&THORN;at noman schuld be so bold</L>
<L>Hir bodi to hilen in er&thorn;e:</L>
<L>Houndes schulc han it in wold.</L>
<L>&THORN;e soule com bifor Jhesu,</L>
<L N="560">Er &thorn;e bodi were cold.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>After &thorn;at he hadde hir slawe</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;is strong passioun,</L>
<L>&THORN;an com Porfir, &thorn;e gode kni&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;er sche lay, wi&thorn; wel gode deuocioun</L>
<L N="565">&amp; brou&yogh;t hir to cristen biriel,</L>
<L>&THORN;er sche lay wi&thorn;outen &thorn;e toun,</L>
<L>O&yogh;ain &thorn;e kinges comandment &mdash;</L>
<L>To suffre de&thorn; he was al boun.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Sone opon &thorn;at o&thorn;er day</L>
<L N="570">Men told &thorn;emperour ful &yogh;are</L>
<L>&THORN;at sche was to er&thorn;e brou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&THORN;an spac he wordes wra&thorn;e:</L>
<L>"Enquere now who ha&thorn; &thorn;is don</L>
<L>Of min men &thorn;at y fede &amp; clo&thorn;e!"
<PB REF="00000394.tif" N="256"></L>
<L N="575">Mani man wi&thorn;outen gilt</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore was slawe &amp; prisound bo&thorn;e.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bifor &thorn;is crowel emperour</L>
<L>Ful baldelich com sir Porfir</L>
<L>&amp; seyd to him, &thorn;er he sete</L>
<L N="580">Ful of felonie &amp; ire:</L>
<L>"Icham godes comfessour,</L>
<L>&amp; ich haue birid &thorn;at martir;</L>
<L>Y wil wele &thorn;at &thorn;ou it wite,</L>
<L>Se&thorn;&thorn;en &thorn;ou hast so gret desir.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="585">&THORN;ou were ful wode &amp; out of witt,</L>
<L>&amp; litel &thorn;ou&yogh;tes of &thorn;i dede,</L>
<L>When &thorn;at &thorn;ou haddest hir slawe</L>
<L>&THORN;e er&thorn;e when &thorn;ou hir forbede.</L>
<L>In helle pine be&thorn; &thorn;i play<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. &thorn;ine st. pine.</NOTE></L>
<L N="590">Wi&thorn;outen ende wi&thorn; &thorn;e quede.</L>
<L>Y take me to Jhesu Crist</L>
<L>&amp; do &thorn;e al out of mi rede."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;an he gan forto crie</L>
<L>&amp; cleped him-selue caitif,</L>
<L N="595">As &thorn;ei he hadde wounded be</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; swerd, wi&thorn; spere o&thorn;er kniif.</L>
<L>"Now ha&thorn; Porfir me forsake,</L>
<L>&THORN;at was wardain of al mi liif!"</L>
<L>Oft he seyd allas allas</L>
<L N="600">&THORN;at euer was he born o wiif!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>He ha&thorn; so michel care &amp; diole:</L>
<L>Men &thorn;ou&yogh;t &thorn;at he wald wede.</L>
<L>He seyd: "now ichaue forelorn</L>
<L>&THORN;e best kni&yogh;t of al mi &thorn;ede!</L>
<L N="605">He was min help &amp; mi rede,</L>
<L>Ouer-al at al mi nede.</L>
<L>&THORN;e wiche schal it abigge de(re)<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. abiggede.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;urch whom he ha&thorn; don &thorn;is dede!"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e king tok his kni&yogh;tes anon,</L>
<L N="610">To asken hem in priuete</L>
<L>&THORN;urch whom it was &amp; was conseyl</L>
<L>&THORN;at he wald cristned be.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai said sone at a voice:</L>
<L>"&THORN;urch godes mi&yogh;t. &amp; so be we:</L>
<L N="615">We take ous to cristendom,</L>
<L>For drede of de&thorn; wil we nou&yogh;t fle.
<PB REF="00000395.tif" N="257"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Oft he was wro&thorn; &amp; wode,</L>
<L>Bot neuer &yogh;ete as he was &thorn;o!</L>
<L>Her heuedes he dede of smite &mdash;</L>
<L N="620">&THORN;er-of &yogh;af he nou&yogh;t a slo.</L>
<L>&THORN;e bodis on &thorn;e feld wer cast,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; houndes &amp; wi&thorn; bestes also.</L>
<L>Her soules come sone &thorn;ider</L>
<L>&THORN;er ioie &amp; blis is euer &amp; oo.<NOTE PLACE="foot">oo = ever.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="625">&THORN;erafter on &thorn;at o&thorn;er day</L>
<L>&THORN;e king was sett in his chayer;</L>
<L>&THORN;e sarra&yogh;ins &thorn;at wi&thorn; him held</L>
<L>On ich half &thorn;ai sete him ner.</L>
<L>Katerine he hete for&thorn; bring.</L>
<L N="630">To fechen hir went his iayoler.</L>
<L>Bifor him com sche swi&thorn;e sone</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; bli&thorn;e mode &amp; glad chere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ful sternliche loked he hir on</L>
<L>And spac to hir wi&thorn; gret enuie:</L>
<L N="635">"Miche wo &thorn;ou hast ous wrou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou wiche ful of felonie,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou hast me don mi folk forlese.</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou schalt ful dere abie!</L>
<L>No schaltow neuer, &yogh;if y may,</L>
<L N="640">Bitray ous wi&thorn; &thorn;i sorcerye.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot &thorn;ou trowe on mi godes,</L>
<L>&THORN;at al &thorn;is warld schal wake &amp; weld,</L>
<L>And to hem make sacrifise,</L>
<L>Fram wicked de&thorn; &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t &thorn;e schilde;</L>
<L N="645">O&thorn;er men schal &thorn;ine heued of smite</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;outen toun in &thorn;e feld</L>
<L>&THORN;is ich day, ar euen com &mdash;</L>
<L>So men schal &thorn;i seruise &yogh;eld."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;is maiden no forbar him nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="650">Sche said: "&thorn;ou tirant, nay.</L>
<L>Schalt &thorn;ou neuer &thorn;e day abide</L>
<L>&THORN;at y schal leue opon &thorn;i lay.</L>
<L>Graced be &thorn;e king of heuen,</L>
<L>&THORN;at me ha&thorn; lent so stable fay!
<PB REF="00000396.tif" N="258"></L>
<L N="655">Ble&thorn;elich wil y for his loue</L>
<L>&THORN;oly de&thorn; &thorn;is ich day.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Do now for&thorn;, &thorn;ou fendes lim!</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e no am y nou&yogh;t agast.</L>
<L>For al &thorn;at &thorn;ou canst bi&thorn;inke,</L>
<L N="660">Y will suffre al in hast.</L>
<L>&mdash; &mdash; &mdash; &mdash; &mdash;</L>
<L>So weit Ms. Auchinl.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="section">
<HEAD>Ms. Caj. Coll. enth&auml;lt folgenden Schluss:</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="665">For Jhesu loue, my spouse gay,</L>
<L>&THORN;at born was off a maydyn chast.</L>
<L>My soule to hym beteche I ay,</L>
<L>For I haue louyd hym al&thorn;er-mast."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;anne &thorn;at sare&yogh;yn bad hys men</L>
<L N="670">&THORN;at &thorn;ey scholden lede &thorn;at maydyn gent</L>
<L>Out off &thorn;e burghe-&yogh;ates &thorn;en</L>
<L>And geuen here &thorn;ere here jugement.</L>
<L>Ful bly&thorn;e &amp; glad &thorn;at fayre may</L>
<L>Out off &thorn;e tounward sche went.</L>
<L N="675">Wi&thorn; many a man &thorn;at ylke day</L>
<L>In &thorn;e toun sche was be-ment.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whan sche was led to &thorn;e place for so&thorn;e</L>
<L>&THORN;ere sche scholde I-hedyd be,</L>
<L>Wyues fele &amp; maydenys bo&thorn;e</L>
<L N="680">Folewyd here off &thorn;at cyte,</L>
<L>Makyng sorewe &amp; wepynge harde</L>
<L>For &thorn;at maydyn ffayr &amp; ffree.</L>
<L>Sche turnyd anon vnto hem-warde</L>
<L>And sayde, as I schal telle &thorn;e:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="685">"I pray &yogh;ow alle &thorn;at &yogh;e gon hom,</L>
<L>&YOGH;e wyuys &amp; &yogh;e maydenys bry&yogh;t!</L>
<L>Dystourbles nou&yogh;t my martyrdom!</L>
<L>But bes fful glad: ffor he me hy&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;at lord &thorn;at is ouer alle &thorn;ynge,</L>
<L N="690">Soone afftyr when I martyryd be,</L>
<L>To heuene blysse he schal me brynge."</L>
<L>Sche knelyd doun &amp; vp gan see,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>To heueneward, &thorn;ere sche hadde ty&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Sche sayde: "Jhesu, my loue ffre,</L>
<L N="695">Off al &thorn;at I leue in &thorn;e ry&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Lord, &thorn;is day I &thorn;anke &thorn;e.
<PB REF="00000397.tif" N="259"></L>
<L>A voys fro heuene oure lord dede sende,</L>
<L N="730">&THORN;at alle it herde &thorn;at &thorn;er werej:</L>
<L>"My &yogh;atys ben open, my leue ffrende,</L>
<L>Come to me, my dou&yogh;tyr dere!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>To suffre &thorn;e de&thorn; in &thorn;e name off me,</L>
<L>Dou&yogh;tyr, drede &thorn;ou no-wy&yogh;t!</L>
<L N="735">Be-ffor me schalt &thorn;ou corownyd be:</L>
<L>For hedyr hast &thorn;ou longe I-ty&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&THORN;e cumpany off aungelys schene</L>
<L>Schal come agayn &thorn;y soule bry&yogh;t</L>
<L>And brynge &thorn;e to &thorn;is place clene,</L>
<L N="740">&THORN;er euere is day &amp; neuere ny&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Come, my dou&yogh;tyr! come now smerte!</L>
<L>For herd is now &thorn;yn orysoun.</L>
<L>For alle &thorn;at &thorn;e haue in here herte</L>
<L>And blely here &thorn;y passyoun,</L>
<L N="745">And alle &thorn;at on &thorn;e calle in nede</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; hertely deuocyoun,</L>
<L>Off here prayer schole &thorn;ey spede</L>
<L>And &thorn;er-to haue my benysoun."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Off &thorn;is answere, when it was herd,</L>
<L N="750">I-wundryd was many a man.</L>
<L>Sche stoupyd doun vndyr &thorn;e swerd &mdash;</L>
<L>Here swyre was whyt as ony swan.</L>
<L>Swy&thorn;e he smot here hed off &thorn;ere &mdash;</L>
<L>But for &thorn;e blood &thorn;e mylk out ran.</L>
<L N="755">Aboue here stood &thorn;at manquellere,</L>
<L>He was ful blak, he was ful wan.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Anon come aungelys from &thorn;e ayr</L>
<L>And flowe awey wi&thorn; here body,</L>
<L>And beryyd it, &thorn;at swy&thorn;e was fayr,</L>
<L N="760">In &thorn;e mount off Synay,</L>
<L>&THORN;ere gaff &thorn;e lawe god off heuene</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e prophete Moysy.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV4>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="version"><PB REF="00000398.tif" N="[260]">
<HEAD>b) Ms. Cajus Coll. 175, p. 107.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Incipit vita s. Katerine virginis.</HEAD>
<DIV4 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>He &thorn;at made bo&thorn;e sunne &amp; mone</L>
<L>In heuene &amp; er&thorn;e for to schyne,</L>
<L>Brynge vs to heuene, wi&thorn; hym to wone,</L>
<L>And schylde vs from helle pyne!</L>
<L N="5">Lystnys, &amp; I schal &yogh;ow telle</L>
<L>&THORN;e lyff off an holy virgyne,</L>
<L>&THORN;at trewely Jhesu louede wel:</L>
<L>Here name was callyd Katerine.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>I vndyrstonde, it be-tydde soo:</L>
<L N="10">In Grece &thorn;er was an emperour;</L>
<L>He was kyng off landes moo,</L>
<L>Off casteles grete &amp; many a tour.</L>
<L>&THORN;e ryche men off &thorn;at land</L>
<L>&THORN;ey seruyd hym wi&thorn; mekyl honour.</L>
<L N="15">Maxenceus was his name hotand,</L>
<L>A man he was ful sterne &amp; stour.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Mahoun heeld he for hys god:</L>
<L>He trowyd in &thorn;e false lay;</L>
<L>On Jhesu Cryst leuede he not,</L>
<L N="20">&THORN;at lord is &amp; god verray.</L>
<L>He was a sare&yogh;yn ful tryst,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; crystyndom he werrede ay,</L>
<L>For alle &thorn;at trowyd on Jhesu Cryst</L>
<L>He stroyyd bo&thorn;e be ny&yogh;t &amp; day.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="25">Whenne (he) hadde fyue &amp; fyffty &yogh;er</L>
<L>Ben emperour &amp; born &thorn;e corown,</L>
<L>&THORN;orw&yogh; al &thorn;e land hys messanger</L>
<L>He sente aboute, fro toun to toun;</L>
<L>To Alisaundyr, he sente hys sawe</L>
<L N="30">And bad, &thorn;o folk scholde come wel sone,</L>
<L>Ryche &amp; pore, hey&yogh;e &amp; lawe,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; here offryng to seke Mahone.
<PB REF="00000381.tif" N="243"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>He bad &thorn;e ryche men scholde brynge</L>
<L>Neet &amp; scheep to here offerande,</L>
<L N="35">And pore men vp alle &thorn;ynge</L>
<L>Quyke foulys in here hande;</L>
<L>And, as &thorn;ey wolde here lyuys hente,</L>
<L>For no&thorn;yng ne scholde &thorn;ey wonde.</L>
<L>&THORN;is was &thorn;e kyngys comaundement</L>
<L N="40">&THORN;at he sente &thorn;orw&yogh; al hys londe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e folk vp-on &thorn;is manere &yogh;ood &mdash;</L>
<L>To wra&thorn;&thorn;e &thorn;e kyng &thorn;ey weren adrad.</L>
<L>Beforn hys goddys hym-seluen stood,</L>
<L>In ryche clo&thorn;yng was he clad.</L>
<L N="45">Alle(!) men were &thorn;ere, bo&thorn;e false &amp; fykil,</L>
<L>He bad &thorn;at &thorn;ey scholde be ful glad;</L>
<L>Noyse &thorn;ey maden wundyr mekyl,</L>
<L>As here emperour hem bad.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ano&thorn;er kyng in &thorn;at lande was &thorn;oo:</L>
<L N="50">Costus was hys name calde.</L>
<L>A dou&yogh;tyr he hadde &mdash; chyldryn no moo &mdash;</L>
<L>Off XVIII<SUP>e</SUP> wyntyr was sche alde:</L>
<L>Kateryne was here ry&yogh;te name,</L>
<L>Off wyt &amp; wysdom was sche bolde;</L>
<L N="55">Sche louyd Jhesu, &thorn;ou&yogh; sche bar blame &mdash;</L>
<L>For hys loue was here lyff solde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>As sche stood in here fadyr coort,</L>
<L>Gle-men herde sche lowde synge,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; pypys &amp; trumpys &thorn;ey maden de|spo(rt),</L>
<L N="60">&amp; bellys herde sche lowde rynge.</L>
<L>Sche fraynyd of here fadir men</L>
<L>What was &thorn;at noyse &amp; &thorn;at pypyng.</L>
<L>&THORN;ey tolde here of &thorn;at offryng &thorn;en</L>
<L>&THORN;at Maxcens garte his folk to bryng.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="65">Sche hooff vp here hand, &thorn;at mayden &yogh;ungge,</L>
<L>&amp; blyssyd here fol wyttyrly,</L>
<L>Ferst here brest &amp; &thorn;anne here tungge &mdash;</L>
<L>So says &thorn;e book off here story.</L>
<L>&THORN;edyr, sche sayde, alone sche &thorn;ou&yogh;te,</L>
<L N="70">For to se &thorn;at melody.</L>
<L>But al alone wente sche nou&yogh;te:</L>
<L>&THORN;ey wente wi&thorn; here &thorn;at stood here by.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whenne sche com to hys palayse,</L>
<L>Sum sche saw&yogh; make game &amp; glee.
<PB REF="00000382.tif" N="244"></L>
<L N="75">&THORN;at leuyd on Jhesu, weren euele at ayse,</L>
<L>Sory men sche dede hem see:</L>
<L>For ey&thorn;ir &thorn;ey scholde don sacrefyse</L>
<L>To hys mawmettys I-maad off tree,</L>
<L>Off ston &amp; bras, on alle wyse,</L>
<L N="80">Ey&thorn;ir &thorn;ey scholde Imartyryd be.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Sche com before &thorn;e emperour &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>&THORN;ere as he made hys sacrefy&yogh;e,</L>
<L>And grette hym al on &thorn;is manere,</L>
<L>Wordys sche spak bo&thorn;e bolde &amp; wyse:</L>
<L N="85">"Jhesu Cryst be wi&thorn; &thorn;e &thorn;en,</L>
<L>Ry&yogh;twyse kyng &amp; hey&yogh;e iustyse,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;olyd de&thorn; ffor synful men</L>
<L>And hadde pousty for to ryse.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>I speke off Jhesu of heuene wi&thorn;-In;</L>
<L N="90">Off alle kyngys he is fflour;</L>
<L>&THORN;at suffryd de&thorn; for alle man kyn,</L>
<L>He is oure alle creatour.</L>
<L>Behold Jhesu, &thorn;e welle off wyt,</L>
<L>Sere Maxence, kyng &amp; emperour!</L>
<L N="95">&THORN;is sacrefyse to hym doo it</L>
<L>And seke hym wi&thorn; &thorn;us mekyl honour!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>But now me &thorn;ynki&thorn; doost &thorn;ou so nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou wyrkyst on a werse wyse:</L>
<L>&THORN;is folk, &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast hedyr brou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="100">&THORN;ou doost hem make &thorn;e deuyl seruyse.</L>
<L>Al &thorn;at &thorn;ey doo, wi&thorn;-outen were,</L>
<L>To &thorn;ese mawmettys vpon &thorn;is gyse,</L>
<L>A dysseyuaunce is to hem here,</L>
<L>Fykyl &amp; fals &amp; al fayntyse."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="105">&THORN;is emperour awondryd was</L>
<L>Off &thorn;is maydyn, fayr off vyse:</L>
<L>Here stedefastnesse in herte he has,</L>
<L>And sayde to here wurdys ful nyse:</L>
<L>"Why dyspraysyst &thorn;ou oure goddys so</L>
<L N="110">And holdyst hem off so lytyl pryse?</L>
<L>Iwis, so scholdyst &thorn;ou nou&yogh;t doo,</L>
<L>Me &thorn;ynki&thorn; &thorn;ou art no-&thorn;yng wyse.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yff &thorn;ou were leryd off oure lay lel</L>
<L>And to oure scoles were entendaunte,</L>
<L N="115">&THORN;ou woldyst saye we deden ful wel,</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; &thorn;y tungge &thorn;ou woldist it graunte.</L>
<L>To my&yogh;teful goddes &thorn;ou &thorn;e take,</L>
<L>Swylk as Mahoun &amp; Termagaunt,
<PB REF="00000383.tif" N="245"></L>
<L>And Jhesu Cryst look &thorn;ou forsake</L>
<L N="120">&THORN;e whylke &thorn;ou holdyst &thorn;y waraunt!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And for we haue now on hande</L>
<L>&THORN;is ryche feste, as &thorn;ou mayst see,</L>
<L>Come now for&thorn; wi&thorn; &thorn;yn offerande,</L>
<L>And holde it for no vanyte!</L>
<L N="125">For to oure goddes, so good at nede,</L>
<L>&YOGH;iff &thorn;at &thorn;ou wylt buxum be,</L>
<L>Ryche gyfftys schal be &thorn;y mede</L>
<L>And &thorn;at &thorn;ou sayde forgeue I &thorn;e."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;enne bespak here Kateryne &mdash;</L>
<L N="130">God off heuene forgat sche nou&yogh;t;</L>
<L>&THORN;at schoop here wymman &amp; virgyne,</L>
<L>Sente grace in-tyl here &thorn;ou&yogh;t &mdash;:</L>
<L>"&THORN;ese aren quyke deuelys to calle</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;is peple haue here sou&yogh;t;</L>
<L N="135">&THORN;er is no god but on off alle,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e &amp; me &amp; al ha&thorn; wrou&yogh;t."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;is emperour wi&thorn; woo gan wake,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou&yogh;te on wylys &amp; queynte crokes.</L>
<L>Lettres gart he swy&thorn;e make</L>
<L N="140">And preuyly, as sai&thorn; &thorn;e bookes,</L>
<L>Ou a maydyn was come ful &yogh;yng,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. On st. ou = hou.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at here goddys alle forsook.</L>
<L>He selyd hem wi&thorn; hys owne ryng</L>
<L>&THORN;at he off hys ffyngyr took.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="145">He took &thorn;e messanger in hande</L>
<L>&THORN;e lettrys selyd for gret tokenyng</L>
<L>To alle &thorn;e wyse men of hys lande,</L>
<L>And bad hem come wi&thorn;-outen dwellyng.</L>
<L>Ful gret honour he hy&yogh;te hem &yogh;yt,</L>
<L N="150">As he was trewe kny&yogh;t &amp; kyng,</L>
<L>&YOGH;yff (&thorn;ey) wi&thorn; here wysdam &amp; here wyt</L>
<L>My&yogh;ten ouyrcome &thorn;at maydyn &yogh;yng.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;at maydyn was in presoun done,</L>
<L>Soone as &thorn;e messanger was went.</L>
<L N="155">An aungyl com to here fol sone</L>
<L>&THORN;at Jhesu Cryst here hadde Isent.</L>
<L>He sayde: "my lord gretes &thorn;e weel</L>
<L>&THORN;at wyt &amp; wysdam has &thorn;e lent &mdash;</L>
<L>And &thorn;at &thorn;yn herte be strong as steel</L>
<L N="160">And &thorn;ynk on hym wi&thorn; good entent!
<PB REF="00000384.tif" N="246"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Maxence ha&thorn; Isent hys sonde</L>
<L>Ouyr-al aboute in &thorn;is cuntree</L>
<L>Afftyr men wysest in londe,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;e (to) stryue, as &thorn;ou schalt see.</L>
<L N="165">Be &thorn;at &thorn;y wurdys &thorn;ey haue herd tel</L>
<L>As Jhesu Cryst schal wysse &thorn;e,</L>
<L>Here trow&thorn;e schal ben in god ful wel,</L>
<L>And for hym schole &thorn;ey martyryd be."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ouer al &thorn;e world, &thorn;at was so wyde,</L>
<L N="170">Hys messanger wente ful &yogh;are.</L>
<L>Fyffty men he brou&yogh;te &thorn;at tyde,</L>
<L>Grettest clerkys &amp; wys of lare.</L>
<L>In al wysdom &amp; eke latyne</L>
<L>Men sayde &thorn;at &thorn;ey ry&yogh;t redy wore</L>
<L N="175">For to dysspute wi&thorn; Kateryne,</L>
<L>&THORN;at Maxcense hadde wi&thorn;-holden &thorn;ore.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Amonges hem was &thorn;at mayden anon.</L>
<L>&THORN;ey desputyd wi&thorn; here of many matere,</L>
<L>Here resouns sayde &thorn;ey on be on,</L>
<L N="180">Ylkon on hys beste manere.</L>
<L>&THORN;is maydyn, &thorn;at I haue off tolde,</L>
<L>Sche stood wi&thorn; a stedefast chere,</L>
<L>In herte here resouns gan beholde&mdash;</L>
<L>Goddys aungyl was here fere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="185">Whenne &thorn;ey hadden here resouns sayde,</L>
<L>Euerylkone bo&thorn;e more &amp; lesse,</L>
<L>To ylke a poynt wi&thorn;-Inne a brayde</L>
<L>Sche answerde wi&thorn; wol gret mekenesse;</L>
<L>Al here deuys &thorn;enne sayde sche</L>
<L N="190">Off god off heuene, &thorn;at oure lord ysse,</L>
<L>Is &amp; was &amp; euere schal be&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;e gospel took sche to wytnysse.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Of holy wryt sche tau&yogh;te hem &thorn;ore</L>
<L>And off Crystys Incarnacyoun,</L>
<L N="195">And off a maydyn hou he was bore,</L>
<L>And hou he suffrede passyoun,</L>
<L>And hou he sente hys postelys wyde</L>
<L>To brynge men to saluacyoun&mdash;</L>
<L>And crystene trow&thorn;e sche tolde &thorn;at tyde</L>
<L N="200">And preuyd it hem wi&thorn; pure resoun.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whenne &thorn;is mayden hadde Isayde</L>
<L>Alle here resouns, &thorn;at were so goode,
<PB REF="00000385.tif" N="247"></L>
<L>Fol weel were &thorn;ese maystrys payde</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;ey begunne to chaunge here moode.</L>
<L N="205">But, &thorn;ere Maxcence sat, in fay,</L>
<L>For yre off herte he wax ny&yogh; wood</L>
<L>&amp; askyd: or &thorn;ey cowde ou&yogh;t say</L>
<L>Agayn &thorn;at maydyn, &thorn;at &thorn;ere stood.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;enne bespak a maystyr anon,</L>
<L N="210">Off ryche kynrede was he bore:</L>
<L>"Sere kyng, I wene we haue mysgon,</L>
<L>O&thorn;ere resouns be&thorn; betere vs fore.</L>
<L>For we schole trowe on Jhesu Cryst</L>
<L>&THORN;at bar &thorn;e corowne maad off &thorn;orn,</L>
<L N="215">As Kateryne ha&thorn; Itold fol tryst&mdash;</L>
<L>Ful lo&thorn; vs were to be fore-lorn."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Alle to-gedere hem askyd he</L>
<L>Whe&thorn;er &thorn;ey wolde here &thorn;ou&yogh;t ou&yogh;t wende.</L>
<L>&THORN;ey sayden, on Jhesu &thorn;at deyde on tree</L>
<L N="220">&THORN;ey wolde beleue wi&thorn;outen ende.</L>
<L>He wax agreuyd, &thorn;at stoute syre,</L>
<L>He bad hem bynden feet &amp; hande;</L>
<L>He swoor he scholde quyte here hyre,</L>
<L>&THORN;ey scholde(be) brend as brennyng brande.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. brend.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="225">He garte hem caste al in gret feer.</L>
<L>Gret myracle men my&yogh;t &thorn;er see;</L>
<L>Here fax(!), here clo&thorn;is &amp; here her<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. fax od. fay? st. face.</NOTE></L>
<L>Off wem were &thorn;ey quyt &amp; ffree.</L>
<L>Martyrdom &thorn;ey suffryd &thorn;ore</L>
<L N="230">For hym &thorn;at deyde vpon &thorn;e tree;</L>
<L>To heuene were here soulys bore,</L>
<L>In goddys frayry forto be.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;oo bad &thorn;e emperour hys men:</L>
<L>"Bryngys for&thorn; &thorn;at fayre may!"</L>
<L N="235">And whanne sche com beforn hym &thorn;en,</L>
<L>"Welcome, he sayde, par ma fay!</L>
<L>Hast &thorn;ou &yogh;it &thorn;y counseyl tan</L>
<L>For to turne vpon my lay?</L>
<L>Haue mercy on &thorn;y fayre pan!</L>
<L N="240">Me longis nou&yogh;t don it away.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ou schalt be menskyd as a qwene,</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e in boure &amp; eke in halle;</L>
<L>And in &thorn;y name I schal do clene</L>
<L>An ymage make, ry&yogh;t fayr wi&thorn;-alle,</L>
<L N="245">And in &thorn;is burgh &thorn;enne schal it stande,</L>
<L>And hey&yogh;e &amp; lowe schole loute it alle.
<PB REF="00000386.tif" N="248"></L>
<L>Off alle &thorn;e nedys of &thorn;is land</L>
<L>We schole &thorn;e vn-to counseyl calle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Hey&yogh;e &amp; lowe schal serue &thorn;e soo.</L>
<L N="250">Kateryne, doo as I &thorn;e bede!</L>
<L>And &yogh;it (I) wole &thorn;e more doo,</L>
<L>&YOGH;yff &thorn;ou wylt doo afftyr my rede:</L>
<L>Off marbylston schal I do make</L>
<L>A ryche temple, whenne &thorn;ou art ded;</L>
<L N="255">Among oure goddys &thorn;ou schalt be take</L>
<L>And layde in syluyr &amp; gold so red."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Be stylle, &thorn;ou fool! I saye to &thorn;e,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou redes me to ful mekyl synne.</L>
<L>What man wolde I-dampnyd be</L>
<L N="260">In helle, for ony worldys wynne?</L>
<L>I haue to Ihesu Cryst my loue:</L>
<L>He is my spouse, bo&thorn;e oute &amp; Inne;</L>
<L>I hope to come to his heuene aboue,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Im Ms. steht hier doppelter Vers: In heuene he schal me wedde aboue, u.: I hope to come to his heuene aboue, u. a. R. steht Elige</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ere ioye &amp; blysse schal neuere blynne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="265">He is myn hope, my ioye mest,</L>
<L>My lord, my god in trynyte,</L>
<L>My leeff, my lyff, my loue best:<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. my my lyff.</NOTE></L>
<L>To swylke a lemman take I me.</L>
<L>And &yogh;yff me were boote to speke,</L>
<L N="270">Off &thorn;y(s) counseyl now wolde I be<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;y st. &thorn;ys.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;y goddys for to brenne &amp; breke&mdash;</L>
<L>For &thorn;ou madyst hem, &amp; &thorn;ey nou&yogh;t &thorn;e."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Be &thorn;at sche hadde here wurdys sayde,</L>
<L>Hym &thorn;ou&yogh;te hys herte scholde breke on fyue;</L>
<L N="275">For yre &amp; wra&thorn;&thorn;e he styrte &amp; brayde</L>
<L>And bad hys men hastely &amp; blyue:</L>
<L>"Wi&thorn; whyppys &amp; scourgys do&thorn; here sterte,</L>
<L>Byndi&thorn; &amp; beti&thorn;, whyl sche is on lyue!</L>
<L>And in presoun &thorn;en do&thorn; here smerte!</L>
<L N="280">What boote is &thorn;us-gate for to stryue?"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ey maden here body al red blood ren</L>
<L>&THORN;at fyrst was whyt as whales bon.</L>
<L>And afftyr sayde he to hys men:</L>
<L>"Prysouns here now swy&thorn;e anon!</L>
<L N="285">Hungyr schal sche hastely ffeel,</L>
<L>Mete ne drynk ne geui&thorn; here non,
<PB REF="00000387.tif" N="249"></L>
<L>Lytyl ne mekyl &mdash; now wete &thorn;ou weel &mdash;</L>
<L>Tyl twelue dayes be comen &amp; gon!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Out off &thorn;is land I wole forso&thorn;e &mdash;</L>
<L N="290">Me be-houes nou&yogh;t longe dwelle:</L>
<L>To grete men &amp; wyse bo&thorn;e</L>
<L>Off &thorn;ese auntrys forto telle;</L>
<L>Counseyl I haue wi&thorn;-outen dred</L>
<L>Hou I schal &thorn;is maydyn quelle;</L>
<L N="295">But sche take ano&thorn;er red,</L>
<L>Sche schal wete off woo ful welle."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whenne &thorn;e emperour was Iwent,</L>
<L>&THORN;e qwene sayde vntyl a kny&yogh;te &mdash;</L>
<L>Off kny&yogh;tys he was cheeff &amp; gent:</L>
<L N="300">Porphurye, seys &thorn;e book, he hy&yogh;te &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;e qwene sayde: "wi&thorn; Kateryne</L>
<L>Doo me speke, &yogh;yff &thorn;at &thorn;ou my&yogh;t!</L>
<L>Longyng I haue in herte myne</L>
<L>To speke wi&thorn; here &thorn;is ylke ny&yogh;t."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="305">&THORN;at ylke ny&yogh;t forgat he nou&yogh;t</L>
<L>To doo &thorn;e qwenys comaundemente:</L>
<L>Vnto presoun &thorn;o he here brou&yogh;t</L>
<L>And preuyly wi&thorn; here he wente.</L>
<L>&THORN;ey saw&yogh; &thorn;er-Inne ful mekyl ly&yogh;t:</L>
<L N="310">Goddys aungelys &thorn;edyr were sent,</L>
<L>&THORN;at seten aboute &thorn;at swete wy&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Anoyntyd here wi&thorn; oynement.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Aungelys &thorn;ey seen here cors anoynte,</L>
<L>Ylke a wem &amp; ylke a wounde,</L>
<L N="315">&THORN;orw&yogh; Jhesu my&yogh;t in euery ioynte</L>
<L>&THORN;ey maden here bo&thorn;e heyl &amp; sounde.</L>
<L>&THORN;ey hadde nou&yogh;t at &thorn;e presoun dore</L>
<L>Istonden but a lytyl stounde,</L>
<L>Off &thorn;e ly&yogh;t &thorn;ey were adred so sore:</L>
<L N="320">In swownyng fel &thorn;ey to &thorn;e grounde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e maydyn ros &amp; to hem came</L>
<L>And spak to hem wi&thorn; mylde mood:</L>
<L>"Rysys vp in goddys name,</L>
<L>And loke &yogh;e ben off counfort good!"</L>
<L N="325">On Jhesu Cryst sche bad hem leue,</L>
<L>&THORN;at for man-kynde schedde hys blood.</L>
<L>And whanne sche hadde &thorn;is counseyl geue,</L>
<L>Vp &thorn;ey resen &amp; by here stood.
<PB REF="00000388.tif" N="250"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;enne bespak &thorn;e qwene sone anon:</L>
<L N="330">"Kateryne, fol weel is &thorn;e!</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; Jhesu Cryst meche mayst &thorn;ou don,</L>
<L>We haue seen al &thorn;y preuyte."</L>
<L>"Looke &thorn;ou, sche sayde, vpon hym trowe</L>
<L>&THORN;at lord is off swylke pouste!</L>
<L N="335">He nele forgete, he wole hem knowe</L>
<L>&THORN;at serue hym wi&thorn; herte ffree.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>I rede &thorn;e, dame, for &thorn;y behoue,</L>
<L>Forsake Maxence &amp; al hys my&yogh;t</L>
<L>For &thorn;at ylke kyngys loue</L>
<L N="340">&THORN;at made bo&thorn;e day &amp; ny&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Heuene &amp; er&thorn;e, beste &amp; man,</L>
<L>Sunne &amp; mone &thorn;at schynys bry&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&THORN;e ioye off heuene schalt &thorn;ou han,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou al-soo, <I>I</I> say, sere kny&yogh;t!"<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ou u. I &uuml;berschr, I &thorn;e nach say aus|gestrichen.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="345">&THORN;enne spak &thorn;at kny&yogh;t to Kateryne:</L>
<L>"What-kyn ioye may &thorn;at be?"</L>
<L>Kateryne sayde weel &amp; fyne:</L>
<L>"Porphyrye, I wole telle it &thorn;e:</L>
<L>It is &thorn;e ioye wi&thorn;-outen ende</L>
<L N="350">&THORN;at eeren ne ey&yogh;en may here ne see,</L>
<L>No tungge off speke, herte &thorn;ynke in mende;</L>
<L>&THORN;at loui&thorn; god lel, &thorn;is ordeyni&thorn; he.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;er is non in &thorn;at ryche empere</L>
<L>&THORN;at hungyr has, cold ne &thorn;reste;</L>
<L N="355">Drede ne wra&thorn;&thorn;e is &thorn;er non &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>But loue &amp; lykyng, ioye &amp; reste."</L>
<L>&THORN;orw&yogh; &thorn;e wurdys &thorn;at sche spake</L>
<L>Or mydny&yogh;t &thorn;ey were ful preste</L>
<L>To suffre de&thorn; for goddys sake;</L>
<L N="360">&THORN;ey leuyd in Jhesu al-&thorn;er beste.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ey here betau&yogh;te Jhesu, oure lord,</L>
<L>And si&thorn;&thorn;en wenten bo&thorn;e away.</L>
<L>Two hundryd kny&yogh;tys seruyd hym at bord.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. hym st. here.</NOTE></L>
<L>Whan sche tolde hym &thorn;at o&thorn;ir day<NOTE PLACE="foot">hym plur.</NOTE></L>
<L N="365">Hou goddys aungelys here seruyd had</L>
<L>In presoun, &thorn;at fayre may,</L>
<L>&THORN;ey leuyd on Jhesu, as sche hem bad,</L>
<L>And forsoken here false lay.
<PB REF="00000389.tif" N="251"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For sche ne moste haue ney&thorn;er mete ne drynk</L>
<L N="370">&THORN;orw&yogh; comaundement of &thorn;e emperour,</L>
<L>Twelue dayes, neuere a pynk,</L>
<L>Sche hadde a betere vyaundour:</L>
<L>Cryst sente to here goostly foode</L>
<L>Fro heuene, &thorn;at is oure saueour,</L>
<L N="375">Aungelys, &thorn;at brou&yogh;ten here lyfflode</L>
<L>&THORN;er sche sat presounnyd in a tour.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And whenne &thorn;e twelue dayes were gon,</L>
<L>&THORN;enne com Jhesu, heuene kyng,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; aungelys &amp; maydenys manyon,</L>
<L N="380">For to speke wi&thorn; hys derelyng.</L>
<L>He sayde: "ffor me &thorn;ou hast ben led</L>
<L>In ful gret stryff &amp; gret fandyng:</L>
<L>Looke &thorn;at &thorn;ou be nou&yogh;t adred:</L>
<L>I geue &thorn;e, dou&yogh;tyr, my blessyng.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="385">Offten I haue &thorn;y prayers herde,</L>
<L>Whenne &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast me besou&yogh;t;</L>
<L>I schal nou&yogh;t fayle &thorn;e &mdash; be nou&yogh;t aferde&mdash;</L>
<L>To iugement whenne &thorn;ou art brou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Looke, &thorn;ou be stedefast, trewe &amp; sekyr!</L>
<L N="390">Off alle here peynys geue &thorn;ou nou&yogh;t!</L>
<L>For off &thorn;e blysse &thorn;ou may be sekyr</L>
<L>&THORN;at I haue to myn handwerk wrou&yogh;t."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whenne he hadde sayde &thorn;ese wurdis &thorn;oo,</L>
<L>Out off &thorn;e presoun gan he glyde</L>
<L N="395">To heuene blysse, &thorn;er he com froo,</L>
<L>Hys aungelys vpon ylke a syde.&mdash;</L>
<L>Whenne Maxcense hadde Idon his dede,</L>
<L>Hom he come wi&thorn; mekyl pryde;</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; dukes, eerlys &amp; kny&yogh;tys he &yogh;ede,</L>
<L N="400">And pagys rennyng be here syde,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Vpon &thorn;at o&thorn;er day ful sone</L>
<L>He askyd off &thorn;e maydenys staat,</L>
<L>&YOGH;iff &thorn;at sche were on lyue or none:</L>
<L>"Sche is ful feble, weel I waat.</L>
<L N="405">Fette here for&thorn; now, my gayler!</L>
<L>For hungyr &amp; &thorn;yrst sche is ful mate."</L>
<L>&THORN;e gayler brou&yogh;te here to hym &thorn;er,</L>
<L>&THORN;er as he sat in ryal sate.
<PB REF="00000390.tif" N="252"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whenne sche was before hym led,</L>
<L N="410">He sayde: "welcome, damyseel!</L>
<L>&THORN;ou hast ben ful harde Isted</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e in yryn &amp; in steel;</L>
<L>But &yogh;it me &thorn;ynki&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;ou leue may&mdash;</L>
<L>And &thorn;at me lyki&thorn; swy&thorn;e wel.</L>
<L N="415">Jhesu, &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast spoken off ay,</L>
<L>&THORN;e behoui&thorn; forsaken euery del.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For I wolde nou&yogh;t do &thorn;e to dede,</L>
<L>To my presoun I dede &thorn;e goo.</L>
<L>But sertys now &thorn;ou mostyst nede</L>
<L N="420">To chese &thorn;e on off &thorn;yngys twoo:</L>
<L>Oy&thorn;er vpon my goddys leue</L>
<L>And Cryst forsake for euere-moo,</L>
<L>Or we schal &thorn;ynke bo&thorn;e morwe &amp; eue</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; stronge paynys &thorn;e to sloo".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="425">&THORN;enne spak &thorn;e maydyn, &thorn;ere sche stood</L>
<L>Among &thorn;e sare&yogh;ynys so blak,</L>
<L>As Jhesu here tau&yogh;te, &thorn;at is so good,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; mylde wurdys wi&thorn;-outen lak:</L>
<L>"&THORN;ou&yogh; I schole deye, &thorn;ou may me trest</L>
<L N="430">Jhesu ne schal I neuere forsake;</L>
<L>For Jhesu loue I am ful prest</L>
<L>Gladly here my de&thorn; to take.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;at &thorn;ou be&thorn;ynke &thorn;e</L>
<L>Afftyr peynys grete &amp; sare</L>
<L N="435">And doo hem alle to pyne me,</L>
<L>To suffre hem I wil be &yogh;are.</L>
<L>Neuere in my lyff, be god aboue!</L>
<L>My flesch, my blood ne wole I spare</L>
<L>To spende hem for &thorn;at lordys loue&mdash;</L>
<L N="440">For me he suffryd mekyl mare.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Blely wole I martyryd be</L>
<L>For hym wi&thorn; peynys grete &amp; smale:</L>
<L>He has me callyd to hys ffrayre,</L>
<L>&THORN;at schal be boote off al my bale."</L>
<L N="445">Sche stood wi&thorn; a ful bly&thorn;e mood</L>
<L>Before Maxence, to tellen here tale.</L>
<L>But, &thorn;ere he sat, he wex ny&yogh; wood,</L>
<L>For tene &amp; angyr he was al pale.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>He skypte &amp; styrte &amp; sore gan grame.</L>
<L N="450">&THORN;er com a sare&yogh;yn for&thorn; anon:
<PB REF="00000391.tif" N="253"></L>
<L>Cursates, &thorn;e book sai&thorn;, was his name.</L>
<L>"Sere kyng, he sayde, I am &thorn;y mon.</L>
<L>&YOGH;it I can a turnement make:</L>
<L>Off swylke on herdyst &thorn;ou neuere er telle;</L>
<L N="455">Whanne sche it see&thorn;, I vndyrtake,<NOTE PLACE="foot">sche it see&thorn; &uuml;berschr, it is wrou&yogh;t auspunctirt.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ano&thorn;er lessoun sche wole spelle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Foure wheles make schal I,</L>
<L>&THORN;e twoo schole turne agayn &thorn;e twoo,</L>
<L>Ful &thorn;ykke I-dreuen by &amp; by</L>
<L N="460">Wi&thorn; wy&thorn;ir-hokes, here to sloo.</L>
<L>Among &thorn;e foure sche schal be went,</L>
<L>Here body schal haue meche woo:</L>
<L>In smale peses sche schal be rent,</L>
<L>On er&thorn;e schal sche neuere efft goo."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="465">&THORN;enne bad Maxcence hys gayler</L>
<L>&THORN;at he scholde &thorn;e mayden take</L>
<L>And leden here in-to presoun &thorn;er,</L>
<L>&THORN;e whyles he scholde &thorn;e wheles make.</L>
<L>And or &thorn;e &thorn;rydde day were gon,</L>
<L N="470">&THORN;ey weren Iwrou&yogh;t al for here sake;</L>
<L>So grym &thorn;ey were to loke vpon,</L>
<L>&THORN;at many a man &thorn;ey garte quake.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whenne &thorn;e wheles weren al &yogh;are,</L>
<L>In &thorn;e cyte were &thorn;ey set.</L>
<L N="475">Many sare&yogh;yn before hem ware,</L>
<L>&THORN;e maydyn was ful gretly &thorn;ret.</L>
<L>&THORN;anne bad &thorn;e emperour hys men</L>
<L>&THORN;at sche were out off presoun ffet.</L>
<L>To ben awreke weel wende he &thorn;en</L>
<L N="480">Off &thorn;at maydyn wi&thorn;-outen let.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ey ledde here to &thorn;at ylke stede</L>
<L>&THORN;ere sche scholde in hem gon.</L>
<L>Many a modyr chyld &thorn;er &yogh;ede</L>
<L>For to loken here vpon.</L>
<L N="485">Sche knelyd adoun &thorn;at place amydde,</L>
<L>To god off heuene sche bad here bone.</L>
<L>But lystnes now what hap betydde!</L>
<L>Goddys help here com ful sone.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e whelys for to breke asundyr,</L>
<L N="490">Aungelys were sent fro god anon.</L>
<L>On sare&yogh;ynys &thorn;at were &thorn;er vndyr</L>
<L>Veniaunse took he sone vpon.<NOTE PLACE="foot">skypte aus stypte corr.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000392.tif" N="254"></L>
<L>Among &thorn;e folk &thorn;ey gunne to dryue,</L>
<L N="495">Foure &thorn;ousand &thorn;ere dede &thorn;ey slon.</L>
<L>Off he&thorn;ene men were ded ful ryue &mdash;</L>
<L>But euyl hadde &thorn;e maydyn non.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e crystene men &thorn;at &thorn;ere were</L>
<L>Off &thorn;is myracle &thorn;ey were ful glad.</L>
<L N="500">&THORN;e kyng ne wyste what he dede &thorn;ere:</L>
<L>So sorweful was he &amp; so mad.</L>
<L>&THORN;e sare&yogh;ynys &thorn;at askape my&yogh;te</L>
<L>Hyyd hem faste &mdash; &thorn;ey weren adrad</L>
<L>For &thorn;at ylke perylous sy&yogh;te;</L>
<L N="505">Off sorewe were &thorn;ey neuere so sad.<NOTE PLACE="foot">we in sorewe &uuml;berschr.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Soone afftyr &thorn;is folk was flowe &thorn;an,</L>
<L>Vntyl hym sayde hys wyff, &thorn;e qwene:</L>
<L>"Weylaway, &thorn;ou wrehche man!</L>
<L>Wher-off makys &thorn;ou &thorn;e so kene?</L>
<L N="510">He ha&thorn; weel kyd &thorn;at god is he,</L>
<L>&THORN;at born was off &thorn;e maydyn schene.</L>
<L>I forsake alle &thorn;yne &amp; &thorn;ee</L>
<L>And al &thorn;y my&yogh;t for euere clene.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Agayn &thorn;e lord &thorn;at &thorn;ou woldyst greue</L>
<L N="515">&THORN;y stryuyng is nou&yogh;t wur&thorn; a schyde;</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ese crystene men on leue,</L>
<L>Hys my&yogh;tynesse it go&thorn; ful wyde.</L>
<L>Crye hym mercy off &thorn;y gylt!</L>
<L>For, &yogh;yff &thorn;at &thorn;ou to longe abyde,</L>
<L N="520">When &thorn;ou art ded, &thorn;ou schalt be pylt</L>
<L>In helle pyne for al &thorn;y pryde."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>He wex for wro&thorn; bo&thorn;e wood &amp; wylde</L>
<L>Ande to &thorn;e qwene he sayde &thorn;en:</L>
<L>"&THORN;ou art dysseyuyd &mdash; &thorn;e deuyl &thorn;e hylde &mdash;</L>
<L N="525">&THORN;orw&yogh; wyhche-crafft off crystene men.</L>
<L>I swere &thorn;e be my goddys goode</L>
<L>And be al &thorn;at I can sayn:</L>
<L>But &thorn;ou &thorn;e sunnere chaunge &thorn;y moode,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; wykkyd de&thorn; &thorn;ou schalt be slayn.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="530">But &thorn;ou forsake Jhesu ful prest,</L>
<L>&THORN;is schal be &thorn;y Iugement:</L>
<L>Fyrst &thorn;y pappys off &thorn;y brest</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; yrene hookes schole be rent;
<PB REF="00000393.tif" N="255"></L>
<L>And afftyrward wi&thorn;-Inne a &thorn;rawe</L>
<L>&THORN;ou schalt be heuedyd, ar euere I stent,</L>
<L N="535">Wi&thorn; houndys &amp; foules al to-drawe,</L>
<L>&THORN;orw&yogh; myn owne comaundement."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whenne &thorn;is emperour was war</L>
<L>&THORN;at sche nolde nou&yogh;t turne here &thorn;ou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>On alle maner &thorn;an bad he &thorn;ar</L>
<L N="540">&THORN;at sche schoolde out off towne be brou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&THORN;enne lokyd sche to Kateryne,</L>
<L>And myldely sche here besou&yogh;t</L>
<L>To don here erende in &thorn;at pyne</L>
<L>To god off heuene, &thorn;at al ha&thorn; wrou&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="545">&THORN;enne sayde Kateryne, here trewe ffrende:</L>
<L>"For so&thorn;e, dame, I telle it &thorn;e:</L>
<L>Off &thorn;e ioye wi&thorn;-outen ende</L>
<L>Trust &amp; sekyr may &thorn;ou be,</L>
<L>&YOGH;iff &thorn;ou &thorn;y de&thorn; in hys name has</L>
<L N="550">&THORN;at spredde hys body vpon &thorn;e tree,</L>
<L>As hys swete wylle was,</L>
<L>Forto maken oure soules ffree."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Men drowen here pappys off here brest</L>
<L>And hedyd here, as I haue told.</L>
<L N="555">&THORN;an bad &thorn;e emperour ful feste</L>
<L>&THORN;at noman scholde be so bold</L>
<L>For to beryyn here body &mdash;</L>
<L>For houndes scholde haue it at wolde.</L>
<L>&THORN;e soule com ful hastyly</L>
<L N="560">Before Jhesu, &thorn;at it fore was solde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;enne afftyrward, whenne it was ny&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Afftyr &thorn;ys stronge passyoun,</L>
<L>Com Purphurye, &thorn;e goode kny&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And ffond here lye wi&thorn;-outen &thorn;e toun;</L>
<L N="565">In crystene beryeles wi&thorn; good entent</L>
<L>He beryyd here wi&thorn; deuocyoun,</L>
<L>Agayn &thorn;e kyngys comaundement &mdash;</L>
<L>To suffre de&thorn; he was ful boun.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;enne afftyr on &thorn;at o&thorn;ir day</L>
<L N="570">Men tolden &thorn;e emperour ful ra&thorn;e</L>
<L>&THORN;at sche was beryyd, so&thorn; to say.</L>
<L>&THORN;an spak he wurdys grymme &amp; wra&thorn;e:</L>
<L>"Enserches faste who &thorn;is ha&thorn; don,</L>
<L>My seriauntys &thorn;at I clo&thorn;e &amp; fede!"
<PB REF="00000394.tif" N="256"></L>
<L N="575">Many a man &thorn;at gylt hadde non</L>
<L>Was flemyd &amp; prysounnyd for &thorn;at dede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Before &thorn;is cruel emperour</L>
<L>Ful boldely com sere Purphury</L>
<L>And seyde hym, &thorn;ere he sat ful sour,</L>
<L N="580">Ry&yogh;t ful off yre &amp; felony:</L>
<L>"I wole &thorn;e telle who dede &thorn;is dede,</L>
<L>Si&thorn;&thorn;e &thorn;ou hast so gret desyr:</L>
<L>I, goddys seruaunt, wi&thorn;-outen drede,</L>
<L>I haue beryyd hys martyr.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="585">&THORN;ou was ful wood, wytles, sertayn,</L>
<L>And lytyl &thorn;ou&yogh;tyst &thorn;ou on &thorn;y dede,</L>
<L>Afftyr &thorn;at &thorn;ou haddyst here slayn</L>
<L>&THORN;e er&thorn;e whan &thorn;ou here forbede.</L>
<L>In helle pyne schal be &thorn;y play</L>
<L N="590">Wi&thorn;-outen ende for &thorn;y qwed.</L>
<L>To Jhesu Cryst I take me ay</L>
<L>And I forsake &thorn;y false red."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;anne he began to crye &amp; rore</L>
<L>And offten he callyd hym-selff caytyff,</L>
<L N="595">As he hadde be woundyd &thorn;ore</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; swerd, wi&thorn; spere, or wi&thorn; knyff.</L>
<L>Offten he sayde: "allas, allas,</L>
<L>&THORN;at euere I was born off wyff!</L>
<L>Now Purphurye forsake me has</L>
<L N="600">Wardayn off myn owne lyff."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>He hadde sorwe &amp; care most,</L>
<L>Wundyr woo he was in wede.</L>
<L>He sayde: "now I haue hym Ilost,</L>
<L>&THORN;e beste kny&yogh;t off al my lede,</L>
<L N="605">My beste help bo&thorn;e fer &amp; nere:</L>
<L>Ouer-al he was at my moste nede.</L>
<L>&THORN;e wyhche schal it abye ful dere</L>
<L>&THORN;orw&yogh; whom he ha&thorn; don &thorn;is dede!"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Hys kny&yogh;tys drow&yogh; &thorn;e kny&yogh;t saunfayle</L>
<L N="610">To &amp; ffrom in preuyte:</L>
<L>&THORN;orw&yogh; whom it was &amp; whos counsayle</L>
<L>&THORN;at he wolde I-crystenyd be.</L>
<L>When &thorn;ey hadde counsayllyd to &amp; fram</L>
<L>&THORN;e kny&yogh;tys sayden: "now so wil we:</L>
<L N="615">We take vs vnto crystyndam,</L>
<L>For drede off de&thorn; wole we nou&yogh;t fle."
<PB REF="00000395.tif" N="257"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Offten he was in ful wro&thorn; plyte,</L>
<L>But neuere so wro&thorn; as he was &thorn;oo!</L>
<L>Here hedes he bad anon off smyte &mdash;</L>
<L N="620">But &thorn;er-off gaff &thorn;ey nou&yogh;t a sloo.</L>
<L>Here bodyys he bad in feeld be caste</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; houndys to gnawe &amp; bestys &thorn;oo.</L>
<L>Here soules come ful swy&thorn;e in haste</L>
<L>&THORN;ere ioye &amp; blysse is euere-moo. &mdash;</L>
<L N="625">Pray we now bo&thorn;e fyrst &amp; laste,</L>
<L>Lytyl &amp; mochyl, I rede &thorn;er-too,</L>
<L>&THORN;at, whanne &thorn;at we be hens I-paste,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. be be.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at oure soules mowe do soo. &mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;enne afftyr on &thorn;at o&thorn;ir day</L>
<L N="630">&THORN;e kyng was set in hys chayere;</L>
<L>Sare&yogh;ynys &thorn;at heelden here lay</L>
<L>On ylke a syde &thorn;ey sat hym nere.</L>
<L>Kateryne he bad for&thorn; brynge.</L>
<L>To fetten here wente hys iayler.</L>
<L N="635">Beforn hym com &thorn;at holy &thorn;ynge</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; bly&thorn;e mood &amp; gladful cheer.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Wro&thorn;ly on here &thorn;an lokyd he</L>
<L>And spak to here wi&thorn; gret enuye:</L>
<L>"Mekyl woo hast &thorn;ou do me,</L>
<L N="640">&THORN;ou wyhche ful off ffelounnye,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou hast maad my folk forlorne.</L>
<L>And &thorn;at &thorn;ou schalt ful dere abye!</L>
<L>Ne schalt &thorn;ou neuere efft me scorne,</L>
<L>Betraye me wi&thorn; &thorn;y sorserye.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="645">But &thorn;ou wylt leue on alle wyse</L>
<L>Vpon my goddys &thorn;at al may weelde,</L>
<L>And mekely don hem sacrefy&yogh;e,</L>
<L>Knele &amp; vp &thorn;yn handes helde,</L>
<L>&THORN;is ylke day, &amp; &thorn;at als tyte,</L>
<L N="650">Wi&thorn;-owten &thorn;e toun ry&yogh;t in &thorn;e ffelde</L>
<L>My men schole &thorn;ere &thorn;yn hed off-smyte,</L>
<L>And so schole we &thorn;y seruyse &yogh;elde."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;is mayde forbar hym nou&yogh;t &thorn;at tyde,</L>
<L>Sche sayde: "nay, &thorn;ou teraunt, nay!</L>
<L N="655">&THORN;at day ne schalt &thorn;ou neuere abyde</L>
<L>&THORN;at I schal leue vpon &thorn;y lay.</L>
<L>Blessyd be heuene kyng aboue,</L>
<L>He ha&thorn; me lent fful stable fay.
<PB REF="00000396.tif" N="258"></L>
<L>Blely wole I for hys loue</L>
<L N="660">&THORN;ole de&thorn; &thorn;is ylke day.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Doo ffor&thorn; faste as &thorn;ou began,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou fendes leme, &thorn;ou ffendes gaste!</L>
<L>For al &thorn;at euere &thorn;ou &thorn;ynke kan,</L>
<L>I wole hem(!) suffre al in haste,</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="section">
<HEAD>Ms. Caj. Coll. enth&auml;lt folgenden Schluss:</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>I &thorn;anke &thorn;e, lord, now, ful off my&yogh;t,</L>
<L>For &thorn;ou hast maad me on off &thorn;yne,</L>
<L>To wone among &thorn;y maydenys bry&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="700">In heuene &thorn;er neuere schal be no pyne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Heuene &amp; er&thorn;e, bo&thorn;e ly&yogh;t &amp; derk,</L>
<L>Watyr &amp; land, sunne &amp; mone,</L>
<L>And al &thorn;is world &thorn;is was &thorn;y werk</L>
<L>&THORN;at hey&yogh;e syttyst in holy trone.</L>
<L N="705">I beseke &thorn;e to-day</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou graunte me a bone,</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;is world ar I go away &mdash;</L>
<L>For &thorn;at I wot schal be ful soone:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Alle &thorn;at in &thorn;e name off my</L>
<L N="710">My passyoun wole here or rede</L>
<L>Or haue me in good memory,</L>
<L>In ony lond or ony lede:</L>
<L>Lord, &yogh;yff &thorn;ey praye in ry&yogh;tful case,</L>
<L>In poynt off de&thorn; or o&thorn;er nede,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. or or.</NOTE></L>
<L N="715">&THORN;ou graunte hem for &thorn;yn holy grace</L>
<L>Off here prayer weel to spede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>To suffre de&thorn; I am here, loo,</L>
<L>Ful prest, lord, for loue off &thorn;e;</L>
<L>&THORN;is mace-greff is here al-soo</L>
<L N="720">Wi&thorn; drawen swerd, to hede me &mdash;</L>
<L>My soule greue he ne may</L>
<L>For &thorn;er-off ha&thorn; he no pouste:</L>
<L>Tak it to &thorn;e now, I &thorn;e pray,</L>
<L>In-to &thorn;e blysse &thorn;at euere schal be!"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="725">Soone as sche hadde maad an ende</L>
<L>Off here orysoun &amp; here prayer</L>
<L>For alle &thorn;at here hadde in mende</L>
<L>And ffor here-self in &thorn;is maner,
<PB REF="00000397.tif" N="259"></L>
<L>&THORN;e soule com to Jhesu euene</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; moche merthe &amp; melody.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="765">&THORN;at day sche deyde &mdash; weti&thorn; weel it! &mdash;</L>
<L>Syxe aungelys deden here body lende</L>
<L>In-to &thorn;e mount, &thorn;ere it is &yogh;it</L>
<L>And schal be to &thorn;e worldes ende.</L>
<L>Off syke folk were &thorn;er neuere so fele:</L>
<L N="770">Alle &thorn;at euere wolde &thorn;edyr wende,</L>
<L>Oure lord sente hem boote &amp; hele,</L>
<L>&THORN;at alle bales may amende.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e toumbe &thorn;at sche was layd in &thorn;er,</L>
<L>It was al maade off marbyl-ston.</L>
<L N="775">A strem off oyle fayr &amp; cler</L>
<L>Sprong &thorn;er-off ry&yogh;t ful good won &mdash;</L>
<L>And so it ha&thorn; don se&thorn;&thorn;yn euere,</L>
<L>Euere si&thorn;&thorn;e &thorn;at sche was slawe.</L>
<L>Alle crystene folk &thorn;at &thorn;edyr keuere</L>
<L N="780">Here body wurschepi&thorn; wundyr fawe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Here day it falli&thorn; in Nouembre,</L>
<L>In world as sche was martyryd here,</L>
<L>On &thorn;e seuyn&thorn;e kalendes of Decembre,</L>
<L>As wreten is in kalendere.</L>
<L N="785">He &thorn;at wrot here lyff &thorn;us,</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;at it rede &amp; here,</L>
<L>&THORN;e ioye off heuene hem &yogh;eue Jhesus,</L>
<L>For Maryes loue, hys modyr dere!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e hey&yogh;e kyng off alle men kynne,</L>
<L N="790">&THORN;at spredde hys body vp-on tree,</L>
<L>Brynge vs out off dedly synne</L>
<L>And sende vs loue &amp; charyte,</L>
<L>&THORN;at we mowe to &thorn;at stede wynne,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;outen ende in ioye to be,</L>
<L N="795">&THORN;at seynt Kateryne is Inne,</L>
<L>Amen, amen, pur charyte!</L>
<TRAILER>Explicit.
</TRAILER>

</LG>
</DIV4>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="5" TYPE="legend"><PB REF="00000398.tif" N="[260]">
<HEAD>5. S. Kateryne, aus Ms. Cbr. Ff. II, 38, N. 24 (c. 1420).</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>Diese Leg. ist bereits abgedruckt in Halliwell's Contributions to early English Literature, London 1844 (for private circulation). Sie scheint aus einer &auml;lteren Ver|sion in sechszeil. Strophen aufgel&ouml;st.</P></HEADNOTE>
<HEAD>Here folowe&thorn; &thorn;e lyfe of seynt Kateryn.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>All tho that be crystenyd &amp; dere,</L>
<L>Lystenyth, and ye may here</L>
<L>The lyfe of a swete vyrgyne:</L>
<L>Hur name ys clepydde Kateryne,</L>
<L N="5">The kyngys doghtur of Costentyne,</L>
<L>Of Alysaundur, as seythe the latyne.</L>
<L>Yonge to Cryste sche can to fonge,</L>
<L>Wolde sche not dwelle to longe:</L>
<L>XVIII yere whan sche was oolde,</L>
<L N="10">Os hyt ys in boke tolde,</L>
<L>To Jhesu Cryste sche hur be-toke</L>
<L>And worldely blys sche for-soke.</L>
<L>In Alysaundur was a kynge,</L>
<L>Crystendome louydde he nothynge:</L>
<L N="15">Maxent was hys name;</L>
<L>He dud &thorn;em to de&thorn;e &amp; to schame<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;em u. of ist zu tilgen.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of all tho &thorn;at he wete myghte</L>
<L>That be-leuydde on owre lorde bry&yogh;t.</L>
<L>He made a ryghte grete feste</L>
<L N="20">And sende ouer all hys londe, at hys heste</L>
<L>That &thorn;ey schulde come in all wyse,</L>
<L>For to do ther sacryfyse;</L>
<L>And tho &thorn;at come ne wolde,</L>
<L>He bad &thorn;at men &thorn;em take schulde</L>
<L N="25">And be-fore hym bryng &thorn;em &yogh;are &mdash;</L>
<L>That noon schulde they spare.</L>
<L>The ryche come certeynleche</L>
<L>And broghte wyth &thorn;em ryches moche,</L>
<L>And the pore come also</L>
<L N="30">And aftur there ese broght tho.</L>
<L>In that londe was a mayde</L>
<L>That the sacryfyse wyth-sayde;</L>
<L>Sche wolde not come to hys seruyce</L>
<L>Nor to do hym sacryfyse.</L>
<L N="35">He badde, to hym schulde come &thorn;e mayde.</L>
<L>"On whom be-leuyste &thorn;ou? he sayde.</L>
<L>"But thou leue on lay myne,</L>
<L>On Tarmagaunt and Apolyne,</L>
<L>Thou schalt be schent anon ry&yogh;t".</L>
<L N="40">Than answeryd &thorn;e mayde bry&yogh;t:</L>
<L>"Kyng, sche sayde, &thorn;ou art on-ryghte.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. on-ryghte st. onlede.</NOTE></L>
<L>I woll not do be thy redde:</L>
<L>Thy goddys be doome and dethe;<NOTE PLACE="foot">dethe st. defe, wie 436.</NOTE></L>
<L>But on hym 'y be-leue</L>
<L N="45">That ys of heuyn &amp; er&thorn;e kynge</L>
<L>And of noghte made all thynge.</L>
<L>I drede me noght, wyth-owt blame,</L>
<L>Thowe &thorn;ou do me peyne &amp; schame:</L>
<L>Of my soule &thorn;ou haste power noon</L>
<L N="50">To dethe hyt for to doone.</L>
<L>I be-leue in hys name</L>
<L>That schall kepe my soule fro shame,</L>
<L>That ys Jhesu, heuyn kynge</L>
<L>And of noght made all thynge".</L>
<L N="55">Maxent was &thorn;an full woo,</L>
<L>Whan sche spake of Jhesu soo.</L>
<L>Hys turmentourys he clepyd anone</L>
<L>And bad in pryson sche schulde be done,</L>
<L>In-to the darkest place.</L>
<L N="60">But Cryste Jhesu sente hur grace &mdash;</L>
<L>Blessyd be hys swete myghte! &mdash;</L>
<L>He sente hur sone moche lyghte,</L>
<L>That all &thorn;e prysone &thorn;ere sche lay</L>
<L>Was bryghter &thorn;en &thorn;e somers day;</L>
<L N="65">Aungels come to hur adowne</L>
<L>And soche yoye made in prysone,</L>
<L>Bothe be day and be nyghte,</L>
<L>That all &thorn;e men y-borne ne my&yogh;t</L>
<L>That yoye telle nor that blys</L>
<L N="70">That was ther-yn, wyth-owt mys.</L>
<L>The aungell to hur seyde:</L>
<L>"Mayde, haue thou no drede!</L>
<L>I-made ys thy wonnyng</L>
<L>Before Jhesu, heuyne kynge".
<PB REF="00000399.tif" N="261"></L>
<L N="75">The kyng Maxent anone than</L>
<L>Dud assembull all hys mene</L>
<L>And can them aske os &yogh;erne:</L>
<L>How &thorn;ey myght the mayde turne</L>
<L>To make hur to leue on hys lay.</L>
<L N="80">Some conne to hym say:</L>
<L>And he anone sende hys sonde<NOTE PLACE="foot">and = if, od. es fehlen Verse.</NOTE></L>
<L>Aftur the wyseste of hys londe,</L>
<L>That moche cowde of clargy:</L>
<L>For they schulde &thorn;e mayde turne.</L>
<L N="85">The maysters were sone come</L>
<L>Before the kynge, all and some.</L>
<L>And the kynge tolde &thorn;em thoo</L>
<L>How he was in moche woo</L>
<L>And how he had angur &amp; payne</L>
<L N="90">Thorow the mayde Kateryne,</L>
<L>That he my&yogh;t not hur to hys lay brynge;</L>
<L>But yf they myght wyth ony thynge</L>
<L>Turne hur owt of eresye</L>
<L>And forsake the sone of Mary:</L>
<L N="95">"Gyftys y hur &yogh;yf wolde<NOTE PLACE="foot">l. &yogh;ou st. hur.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of syluyr &amp; of ryche golde".</L>
<L>The fyrste maystyr to hur sayde:</L>
<L>"On whom be-leuyste &thorn;ou, feyre mayde?</L>
<L>And why for-sakest thou owre lay?"</L>
<L N="100">Tho answeryd the feyre may:</L>
<L>"I be-leue on hym</L>
<L>That &yogh;af me lyfe and lyme,</L>
<L>Maryes sone, heuyn kynge,</L>
<L>That made of noghte all thynge</L>
<L N="105">And of seynt Mary was bore</L>
<L>Wyth-owt weme or ony sore.</L>
<L>On that lorde ys all my thoghte,</L>
<L>And noon odur kepe y noghte".</L>
<L>He seyde: "thou spekyst grete folye</L>
<L N="110">Of Jhesu, &thorn;at was &thorn;e sone of Mary,</L>
<L>That he was of a vyrgyne bore</L>
<L>Wyth-owt weme or ony sore.</L>
<L>That ys not so, wele y wete,</L>
<L>For in nature hyt ys wrete</L>
<L N="115">That no mayde chylde bere myghte</L>
<L>Ne forme noon be no ryghte</L>
<L>But sche wyste of mannys moone &mdash;</L>
<L>Soche sawe y neuyr noone.</L>
<L>Thou schewyst here a false resone;</L>
<L N="120">Woman wyth-owt corrupcyone</L>
<L>Neuyr &yogh;yt chylde ne bare.</L>
<L>Ryghte be-leue &thorn;ou faylest thare".</L>
<L>Sche sayde: "thou sayste not so&thorn;e of me,</L>
<L>For ryght be-leue faylyth the.</L>
<L N="125">The holy-goste in Mary lyghte</L>
<L>And flesche and blode toke of hur in hys my&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And became man, thorow hys dyinge</L>
<L>Owt of helle vs for to brynge,</L>
<L>Thorow hys dethe and hys payne.</L>
<L N="130">Thou lyest, wrecche, in resone thyne</L>
<L>That hyt were a&yogh;enste ryghte</L>
<L>A mayde a chylde bere myghte.</L>
<L>Cryste, that made all wyth oon thoghte,</L>
<L>All &thorn;at here ys, of ryghte noghte,</L>
<L N="135">And may all do, that heuyn kynge,</L>
<L>Myght he not do soche a thynge,</L>
<L>Whan he may all thynge doo?</L>
<L>Fals maystyr, answere ther-too!"</L>
<L>The fyrste maystyr fell a-downe.</L>
<L N="140">"I forsake, he seyde, Mahowne</L>
<L>And y be-leue on heuyn kynge,</L>
<L>That lorde ys ouyr all thynge".</L>
<L>The todur maystyrs ylke-oone</L>
<L>On kneys &thorn;ey felle downe anone</L>
<L N="145">And be-leuydde on Jhesu also.</L>
<L>Maxent hyght &thorn;em to be brent &thorn;o.</L>
<L>But Jhesu sende hys sonde &thorn;at day,</L>
<L>That none of &thorn;em, there they lay,</L>
<L>Wyth the fyre ne persydde was,</L>
<L N="150">Nor no herre in that place</L>
<L>Nor ther clo&thorn;ys neuyr-the-moo.</L>
<L>Aungels come fro heuyn &thorn;o<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. An aungel.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;er sowlys vp they bare;</L>
<L>Before god they wonne there.</L>
<L N="155">Tho seyde Maxent to Kateryne:</L>
<L>"Wolt &thorn;ou be-leue on goddys myne,</L>
<L>To wyfe y wole haue the.</L>
<L>In Alysaundyr, that feyre cete,</L>
<L>An ymage y wole do make of golde,</L>
<L N="160">The feyrest that ys on molde,</L>
<L>That schall be the lyche;</L>
<L>All that goon, pore and ryche,</L>
<L>All they schall alowt to thee,</L>
<L>Yf &thorn;ou wylt alowte to me".</L>
<L N="165">Anone Kateryn to hym sayde:</L>
<L>"I woll note do be thy rede,</L>
<L>I wole not for no erthely thynge
<PB REF="00000400.tif" N="262"></L>
<L>Leue Jhesu, heuyn kynge;</L>
<L>He ys my lorde, that syttythe in blys.</L>
<L N="170">I kepe none of thy ryches".</L>
<L>Maxent tho wyth grete boste</L>
<L>Made hur to be bownde to a poste,</L>
<L>And let &thorn;em wyth &yogh;erdys kene</L>
<L>Bete hur, tyll sche nye dedde (had) bene.</L>
<L N="175">The turmentours can hur smyte</L>
<L>Wyth scorges on hur body whyte,</L>
<L>That hur body, there sche stode,</L>
<L>Coueryd was wyth redde bloode,</L>
<L>And rane downe on hur lyche</L>
<L N="180">Os watur dothe on the dyche.</L>
<L>Tho sayde Maxent to Kateryne:</L>
<L>"Leue thy god and leue on myne!</L>
<L>Or ellys, sekyr, y telle the,</L>
<L>That thou schalt dedde bee".</L>
<L N="185">Sche seyde: "blessyd be heuyn kynge!</L>
<L>All my sorow &amp; my peynynge</L>
<L>Me thynkyth hyt softer &thorn;an ony sylke</L>
<L>And swettur than ony mylke".</L>
<L>To hys turmentours he can grete:</L>
<L N="190">"In-to prysone ye hur lede!</L>
<L>That mete nor drynke haue sche noone,</L>
<L>Tyll thys weke be all goone!"</L>
<L>Sche ne dranke nor sche ne &yogh;ete.</L>
<L>But Jhesu Cryste hur noght for-&yogh;ate:</L>
<L N="195">Hys aungels he sente a-downe,</L>
<L>And soche yoye made in presone,</L>
<L>Bothe be day and be nyghte,</L>
<L>That noman hyt telle myghte.</L>
<L>Of the lyght &amp; of the melody</L>
<L N="200">Full sone harde Parforye.</L>
<L>That he had harde in presone,</L>
<L>To the quene he went sone</L>
<L>And tolde hur ther-of anone.</L>
<L>Preuely thedur can &thorn;ey gone.</L>
<L N="205">The preson-hows was full lyghte,</L>
<L>And fayre was to see &thorn;at syghte;</L>
<L>Aungels song &thorn;ey harde than &mdash;</L>
<L>Ther my&yogh;t neuer on erthe man</L>
<L>Telle the yoye that &thorn;ere was,</L>
<L N="210">That they harde in that place.</L>
<L>They spokyn in that hows:</L>
<L>"Kateryn, they seyde, speke wyth vs</L>
<L>That be-leuyn on Jhesus</L>
<L>That dyedde for the loue of vs,</L>
<L N="215">And on hys swete pascione!</L>
<L>And we forsake false Mahowne</L>
<L>And Maxent &amp; hys felowe-rede".</L>
<L>"Worschyppyd be Jhesu! &thorn;e mayde seyde,</L>
<L>Be in beleue stedfaste,</L>
<L N="220">And be ye not agaste,</L>
<L>And wyth me ye schall martyrde bee</L>
<L>And aftur heuyne ye schall see".</L>
<L>Jhesu Cryste &thorn;ey thanked moche</L>
<L>And wente ageyne full stylleche.</L>
<L N="225">On morowe the mayde gente</L>
<L>Was broghte before Maxent.</L>
<L>In newe peyne he had hur doo.</L>
<L>The quene seyde Maxent vn-too:</L>
<L>"Thou false, cursyde sarasyne,</L>
<L N="230">Thou schalt haue an euyll synne.<NOTE PLACE="foot">synne st. fyne.</NOTE></L>
<L>Helle hounde, &thorn;ou fowle wyghte,</L>
<L>Thou peynyste &thorn;at mayde wyth onryghte</L>
<L>For sche beleueth on Jhesus</L>
<L>That became man for &thorn;e loue of vs.</L>
<L N="235">Mahounde and the y forsake,</L>
<L>And to Jhesu y me be-take</L>
<L>That swett for vs hys swete bloode".</L>
<L>Tho Maxent was nere woode</L>
<L>And bad anon hys turmentours:</L>
<L N="240">"Do hange hur be hur tresourys,<NOTE PLACE="foot">tresourys-tresses.</NOTE></L>
<L>And hur brestys drawe away!</L>
<L>For sche sakyth owre lay.<NOTE PLACE="foot">sakyth st. forsakyth.</NOTE></L>
<L>And when ye haue so seruydde hyr,</L>
<L>Ye schall hur owt of towne bere,</L>
<L N="245">And let no-man hur body berye</L>
<L>But let howndys hur wery!"</L>
<L>Whan Parfory harde that,</L>
<L>Hym thoght hys herte brake.</L>
<L>"Hounde, he seyde, god ys &thorn;e schame!<NOTE PLACE="foot">yf=&yogh;yf, giue, wie 322.</NOTE></L>
<L N="250">Why thretyst thou hur and mee(!)</L>
<L>That we may not in erthe be doo?"</L>
<L>Hys turmentours he clepydde thoo</L>
<L>And badde anone Parforye nyme</L>
<L>And do hym lose lyfe and lyme.</L>
<L N="255">Parfory a schylde and a spere nam</L>
<L>And sone a&yogh;enst them ranne:</L>
<L>Of IIII thousande of hys mene</L>
<L>He lefte alyue neuyr oone.</L>
<L>Maxent quakyd, there he stode,</L>
<L N="260">For drede he wexyd nere wode.</L>
<L>Kateryn can to Parfory grete:<NOTE PLACE="foot">grete st. grede, wie 189.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000401.tif" N="263"></L>
<L>"Parfory, let be &thorn;y fyghtyng! sche seyde,</L>
<L>Yf &thorn;ou wylt wyth me martyrd be,</L>
<L>Fyghtynge &thorn;ou muste leue, y telle the,</L>
<L N="265">And take lyghtly thy payne</L>
<L>For goddys loue, os y do myne".</L>
<L>He threwe the schylde owt of hys honde,</L>
<L>That all on pecys hyt wonde,</L>
<L>And besoght hur, to prey hur lord vnto</L>
<L N="270">To forgyf hym that he had mysdoo.</L>
<L>And on kneys he felle downe,</L>
<L>And there he forsoke Mahowne</L>
<L>And beleuyd on Crystys lawe.</L>
<L>Maxent comawndyd wyth horsys hym to drawe</L>
<L N="275">And hys quene also.</L>
<L>Aungels come fro heuyn thoo</L>
<L>And ther soulys to heuyn bere;</L>
<L>Before god tronyd they were.</L>
<L>Kateryn &thorn;erof was full blythe</L>
<L N="280">And thankyd god fele sythe.</L>
<L>&YOGH;yt seyde Maxent to Kateryne:</L>
<L>"Forsake thy god and leue on myne!</L>
<L>And yf thou wylt soo,</L>
<L>Of peynes schalt &thorn;ou haue no moo,</L>
<L N="285">But all y wyll foryeue thee</L>
<L>That thou haste seyde and do to mee".</L>
<L>Than answeryd Kateryne:</L>
<L>"No-thyng helpyth the nor thyne.</L>
<L>My maydenhode &amp; my loue</L>
<L N="290">I haue geuyn hyt to god aboue;</L>
<L>To forsake hym, hyt were grete schame,</L>
<L>For thy malys or for thy blame.</L>
<L>But yf thou wylt well doo,</L>
<L>In my god thou leue alsoo,</L>
<L N="295">And forsake thy mawmentys,</L>
<L>That fro &thorn;e blys of heuyn &thorn;e lettys!</L>
<L>And do, as y schall teche the:</L>
<L>Beleue vpon the trynyte,</L>
<L>Fadur and sone and holy goste,</L>
<L N="300">That ar of all myghtys moost</L>
<L>And made all thynge of noghte,</L>
<L>And wyth hys blode vs dere ha&thorn; boghte;</L>
<L>And beleue ryghte wyttyrly</L>
<L>That he toke flesche of Mary</L>
<L N="305">And on &thorn;e crosse loste hys brethe</L>
<L>And for vs suffurde dethe,</L>
<L>The &thorn;rydde day he rose fro de&thorn;e to lyfe</L>
<L>And aftur steyede to heuyn blyue,</L>
<L>And thens schall come a&yogh;eyne,</L>
<L N="310">The qwyck &amp; the dedde to deme.</L>
<L>And yf thou wylt beleue soo,</L>
<L>I telle the wyth-owt moo</L>
<L>We schall &yogh;ylde to god owre loue,</L>
<L>To Jhesu Cryste, &thorn;at syttyth aboue".</L>
<L N="315">Maxent sawe sone well</L>
<L>That sche wolde not chaunge neuer a delle</L>
<L>Neythur turne hur beleue,</L>
<L>For no&thorn;yng &thorn;at he my&yogh;t hur greue.</L>
<L>In hys court was a false traytoure,</L>
<L N="320">That was a grete yngynore:</L>
<L>Curfatys hys name was bowne &mdash;</L>
<L>Cryste yf hym hys malysone!</L>
<L>He seyde to the kynge than:</L>
<L>"An yngyne y make cane,<NOTE PLACE="foot">And st. An.</NOTE></L>
<L N="325">And whan sche ys lokkyd therone,</L>
<L>I trowe sche schall chaunge anone".</L>
<L>He made IIII whelys thoo,</L>
<L>Eche contrary fro odur can goo;</L>
<L>Hyt was made full weywarde</L>
<L N="330">Full of crokys of stele harde.</L>
<L>Therwyth &thorn;ey &thorn;oght &thorn;e mayde to sloo,</L>
<L>Betwene &thorn;e whelys &thorn;ey set hur thoo.</L>
<L>Sche lokyd vp to heuyn lyghte:</L>
<L>"Jhesu, sche seyde, full of myghte,</L>
<L N="335">Haue mercy on me,</L>
<L>For here y schall marturde bee!</L>
<L>For thys turnament ys so deuysyd:</L>
<L>I schall be in my blode baptysyd".</L>
<L>The cursyd folke, that there were,</L>
<L N="340">The whelys can &thorn;ey turne there.</L>
<L>But Jhesu Cryste, heuyn kynge,</L>
<L>That mayde forgate he nothynge:</L>
<L>Aungels downe to hur he sente,</L>
<L>And the whelys all to-rente;</L>
<L N="345">The pecys that abowte wonde</L>
<L>Smote the folke down to &thorn;e grownde:</L>
<L>XL thousande there were yslawe</L>
<L>That had thoght &thorn;e mayde to drawe.</L>
<L>The folke that the myracull sye</L>
<L N="350">Turnyd anone to Jhesu in hye. &mdash;</L>
<L>And were slayne be Maxent;</L>
<L>Hur soulys anon to heuyn wente.</L>
<L>Maxent anon was full woo</L>
<L>For hys men were slawe soo.
<PB REF="00000402.tif" N="264"></L>
<L N="355">&YOGH;yt he thoght wyth false tresone</L>
<L>How he myght hur brynge to dominacione.</L>
<L>"Wolt thou, my doghtyr Kateryne,</L>
<L>Forsake goddys thyne</L>
<L>And beleue on hym &thorn;at y beleue,</L>
<L N="360">And thy lyfe y wole the yeue;</L>
<L>For me thynkyth, be my lewte!</L>
<L>Hyt were grete rewthe to sle the.</L>
<L>And yf thou wylt not assent &thorn;erto,</L>
<L>Anon &thorn;ou schalt to dethe be doo".</L>
<L N="365">Than answeryd that blessyd mayde</L>
<L>And to Maxent sone sche sayde:</L>
<L>"Hyt greuyth me not of &thorn;y peyne</L>
<L>Nor to be dedde, certeyne,</L>
<L>For y am sekure, in haste</L>
<L N="370">To come to &thorn;e blys &thorn;at euer schall laste.</L>
<L>Y see that swete companye</L>
<L>That schall me brynge to heuyn in hye</L>
<L>Before my lorde, Jhesu Cryste.</L>
<L>All thy doynge ys but a myste".</L>
<L N="375">The teraunt to hys folke can say:</L>
<L>"Ye that me loue be ony way</L>
<L>How myghte y beste vengeaunce take</L>
<L>On thys deuyll, &thorn;at hath me forsake</L>
<L>And my goddys also?</L>
<L N="380">What ys me beste to do hur to?"</L>
<L>Than the cursyd pepull in hye</L>
<L>Wyth lowde voyce can to hym crye:</L>
<L>"Do hur owt of towne lede</L>
<L>And do smyte of hur hede!"</L>
<L N="385">The mayde was owt of &thorn;e towne ladde,</L>
<L>As the kynge them badde,</L>
<L>And anon can hur tryppe &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">tryppe = to trip.</NOTE></L>
<L>Many for hur there can wepe.</L>
<L>And oon of the caytyveys</L>
<L N="390">Drowe hys swerde blyuys</L>
<L>And badde hur stowpe adowne &mdash;</L>
<L>To smyte of hur hedde, he was bowne.</L>
<L>And as he wolde haue do &thorn;at dede,</L>
<L>"Abyde a lytyll whyle, sche sayde,</L>
<L N="395">Whyll y make a lytyll prayere</L>
<L>To Jhesus, that boght me dere!</L>
<L>"Hye kynge in trynyte,</L>
<L>Haue now mercy on mee!</L>
<L>And all &thorn;at haue in the creauns</L>
<L N="400">Thou haue &thorn;em fro &thorn;e fendys comberauns,<NOTE PLACE="foot">haue st. saue.</NOTE></L>
<L>And all that haue goode deuocyone</L>
<L>And rewyth on thy pascyone,</L>
<L>Fro the fende thou them were,</L>
<L>That no deuyll them ne dere!</L>
<L N="405">Also, lorde, y prey the eke:</L>
<L>Tho that my body seke</L>
<L>In thy name, lorde, so mylde,</L>
<L>Fro all euyll &thorn;ou &thorn;em schylde!</L>
<L>Also, lorde, y prey the dere:</L>
<L N="410">Of these caytyfys that be here,</L>
<L>That for thy loue &amp; for thy name</L>
<L>Haue do me peyne and schame:</L>
<L>For they wot not what &thorn;ey doone,</L>
<L>Lorde, forgyf them anone!</L>
<L N="415">And y forgeue them a&yogh;enste me.</L>
<L>In manus tuas, domine,</L>
<L>My soule to the y comawnde".<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. comawnde st. comende.</NOTE></L>
<L>Jhesu an aungell downe can sende,</L>
<L>And seyde: "Kateryne,</L>
<L N="420">Jhesus hath herde prayere thyne</L>
<L>And the hath grauntyd sekyrly</L>
<L>All that of hym &thorn;ou doyst asky.</L>
<L>Owt of peyne anone &thorn;ou hye &mdash;</L>
<L>Thy yoye ys dyght rychely".</L>
<L N="425">Kateryn, that swete flowre,</L>
<L>Clepyd anon the turmentoure</L>
<L>And bad hym hur hedde of to smyte</L>
<L>Wyth hys swerde, that wolde byte.</L>
<L>Hur hedde he smote to the grounde.</L>
<L N="430">Mylke there os blode owt wonde.</L>
<L>Aungels owt of heuyn ther come</L>
<L>And the sowle to heuyn &thorn;ey nome,</L>
<L>And aftur beryed hur body</L>
<L>In the mounte of Synay</L>
<L N="435">In a well feyre tombe.</L>
<L>There ys made hole dethe &amp; dombe.</L>
<L>Fowre stremys, sothe hyt ys,</L>
<L>Renne owt of the tombe, ywys,</L>
<L>Of oyle fro the maydenys breste.</L>
<L N="440">There hath be botyde moost and leste;</L>
<L>Many haue there kaght ther heele &mdash;</L>
<L>No tonge may telle how fele.</L>
<L>Cryste thorow preying of &thorn;at vyrgyne</L>
<L>Schylde vs fro helle pyne</L>
<L N="445">And brynge vs to that blys</L>
<L>There that mayde dwellyng ys! Amen.
</L>
</LG>

