<DIV2 N="6" TYPE="legend"><PB REF="00000403.tif" N="[265]">
<HEAD>6. De Erkenwalde. (S. Erkenwald tauft einen Leichnam). aus Ms. Harl. 2250, fol. 72b. (Westn&ouml;rdl. Dialect.)</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>In halt. Bald nach der Bekehrung der Sachsen durch S. Augustin wird beim Neubau des "S. Paul's M&uuml;nsters", des alten Heidentempels "Triapolitan", in London, dem "neuen Troja" der Heidenzeit, ein wundersch&ouml;nes steinernes Grab gefunden, mit seltsamen goldenen Zeichen geziert, die Niemand lesen kann. Auf die Kunde hiervon str&ouml;mt ganz London herbei. Der Maire befiehlt das Grab zu &ouml;ffnen: da findet man einen Leichnam, k&ouml;niglich geschm&uuml;ckt, in reichem goldums&auml;umten Gewande, mit Krone und Scepter, und, seltsam, alles unversehrt, den Leichnam noch rosig und frisch wie schlafend. Aber Niemand kennt ihn, der doch erst vor kurzem gestorben scheint. Der Fund wird dem Bischofe Londons, S. Erkenwald, der gerade zur Visi|tation einer Abtei in Essex weilt, gemeldet. Er eilt herbei, schliesst das Grab ab und verbringt die Nacht im Gebet zu Gott, das Geheimniss zu l&ouml;sen. Am andern Morgen singt er das Hochamt vor allem Volke und geht dann zum Grabe. Der Dechant berichtet wie man vergeblich 7 Tage lang die Todtenregister durchsucht, um &umacr;ber den Todten Auskunft zu finden; aber Erkenwald weist auf die Allmacht Gottes, der die R&auml;thsel l&ouml;sen k&ouml;nne, tritt dann an den Leichnam und heisst ihn in Christi Namen sagen, wer er sei. Dieser antwortet, dass er kein Kaiser oder K&ouml;nig, sondern ein Richter im "neuen Troja" gewesen, vor vielen vielen Jahren, 1033 Jahre vor Chr. G., 482 Jahre nach Brutus' Erbauung der Stadt, unter der Regierung des Bretonenk&ouml;nigs Belin. Auf die Frage, warum er denn Krone und Scepter trage, antwortet er: weil er ein gerechter Richter gewesen, der nicht nach dem Ansehen der Person, nicht um Lohn oder Lob gerichtet, darum habe ihn das "neue Troja" k&ouml;niglich geehrt, als den K&ouml;nig der Richter. Der Bischof fragt ihn dann, warum sein Gewand, seine Farbe so frisch und unversehrt geblieben; er erwiedert, der himmlische K&ouml;nig der Gerech|tigkeit habe ihn so auszeichnen wollen, weil er Gerechtigkeit ge&uuml;bt. "Aber wo ist deine Seele, wenn du so gerecht warst?" Da st&ouml;hnt der Todte und spricht zu Gott: "O m&auml;chtiger Sch&ouml;pfer, wie konntest du deine Gnade mir zuwenden, da ich ein Heide, unkundig deines Gesetzes? Ach, ich geh&ouml;rte nicht zur Schaar der Erl&ouml;sten, da du zur H&ouml;lle fuhrst und sie befreitest! Da wohne ich noch, im Dunkel des Todes, weil die Taufe und der Glaube mich nicht geheiligt. Ach, was helfen mir nun meine guten Werke?" Alle weinen, die das h&ouml;ren; der Bischof schluchzt lange, wortlos; endlich spricht er unter str&ouml;menden Thr&auml;nen: "Wollte Gott, dass du lebtest bis ich Wasser geholt und es auf dich aufgegossen mit den Worten: Ich taufe dich im Namen des Vaters, Sohnes und heil. Geistes!" W&auml;hrend er so spricht, siehe da tropfen die Thr&auml;nen auf das Grab und eine f&auml;llt auf des Todten Antlitz. "Nun preise ich Gott", so spricht er, "und danke dir, o Bischof, da die Worte, die du gesprochen, und die Thr&auml;ne, die du vergossen, meine Taufe geworden; ein himmlischer Lichtstrahl hat in den Abgrund geschienen und meine Seele emporgehoben, dass ich nun sitze am himmlischen Mahle". Und pl&ouml;tzlich verstummt er, der Leichnam verweste, das eitle sterbliche Theil zerfiel.
<PB REF="00000404.tif" N="266"></P><P>Diese Legende geh&ouml;rt zu der Gruppe der westn&ouml;rdlichen alliterirenden (grossen|theils ungereimten) Dichtungen der 2. H&auml;lfte des 14. Jhdts, wie Troy Book, Morte Arthur, Gawayne, Alliter. Poems ed. Morris, Susanne u. a., denen von anderer Seite schottischer Ursprung (als Werke des schottischen Dichters Huchowne) vindicirt wird. Skeat in seinem Verzeichniss der alliterirenden Dichtungen f&uuml;hrt diese Legende nicht auf und scheint sie also nicht gekannt zu haben; vgl. An Essay on Allit. Poetry, by W. Skeat. Der Stil hat den Character des Grossartigen und Erhabenen, in den Formen und im Geiste der angels&auml;chsischen Poesie, deren k&uuml;nstliche Wiederbelebung die sp&auml;tern alliterirenden Dichtungen erzeugt hat.</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>At Londone in Englonde, no&yogh;t fulle longe sythene</L>
<L>Sythene Crist suffride one crosse &amp; cristendome stablyde,</L>
<L>Ther was a byschop in &thorn;at burghe, blessyd &amp; sacryd:</L>
<L>Saynt Erkenwolde, as I hope, &thorn;at holy mon hatte.</L>
<L N="5">In his tyme in &thorn;at tone &thorn;e temple aldergrattyst<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. ton,</NOTE></L>
<L>Was drawene done, &thorn;at one dole to dedifie new,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. don mit Abbr. f&uuml;r e, = toun doun.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot">dole = dale part. dedifie = edifie, zur Allitter., wie v. 23 u. daungerde = angerde 320.</NOTE></L>
<L>For hit hethene had bene in Hengyst dawes,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e Saxones vnsa&yogh;t hadene sende hyder.<NOTE PLACE="foot">vnsa&yogh;t dissatisfied.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ai bete oute &thorn;e Bretons &amp; bro&yogh;t hom in-to Wales,</L>
<L N="10">&amp; peruertyd alle &thorn;e pepul &thorn;at in &thorn;at place dwellide.</L>
<L>&THORN;ene wos this reame renaide mony ronke &yogh;eres,</L>
<L>Til saynt Austyne in-to Sandewiche was sende fro &thorn;e pope:<NOTE PLACE="foot">renaide = renegade, disbelieving, so M. Arth. 2913, 3572, 3892.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;en prechyd he here &thorn;e pure faythe &amp; plantyd &thorn;e trouthe</L>
<L>&amp; conuertyd alle &thorn;e communnates to cristendame newe.</L>
<L N="15">He turnyd temples &thorn;at tyme &thorn;at temyd to &thorn;e deuelle,</L>
<L>&amp; clansyd hom in Cristes nome &amp; kyrkes home callid,</L>
<L>He hurlyd owt hor ydols &amp; hade hym in sayntes,<NOTE PLACE="foot">hym acc. pl. (sonst hom).</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; chaungit cheuely hor nomes &amp; chargit home better:</L>
<L>&THORN;at ere was of Appolyne, is now of saynt Petre,</L>
<L N="20">Mahone to saynt Margrete o&thorn;er to Maudelayne,</L>
<L>&THORN;e Synagoge of &thorn;e sonne was sett to oure lady,</L>
<L>Jubiter &amp; Jono to Jhesu o&thorn;er to James.</L>
<L>So he home dedifiet &amp; dyght alle to dere halowes,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ere wos sett of Sathanas in Saxones tyme.</L>
<L N="25">Now &thorn;at Londone is neuenyd, hatte "&thorn;e new Troie" &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;e metropol &amp; &thorn;e mayster-tone hit euermore has bene.</L>
<L>&THORN;e mecul mynster &thorn;erinne a maghty deuel aght,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;e title of &thorn;e temple bitan was his name,</L>
<L>For he was dryghtyne derrest of ydols praysid;</L>
<L N="30">And &thorn;e solempnest of his sacrifices in Saxone londes,</L>
<L>&THORN;e thrid temple hit wos tolde of Triapolitanes &mdash;</L>
<L>By alle Bretaynes bonkes were bot othire twayne. &mdash;</L>
<L>Now of &thorn;is Augustynes art is Erkenwolde bischop</L>
<L>At loue Londone tone, &amp; the laghe teches,<NOTE PLACE="foot">loue great, immense, vgl. lawe Troy B. 2441 (leue ib. 12555).</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000405.tif" N="267"></L>
<L N="35">Syttes semely in &thorn;e sege of saynt Paule mynster,</L>
<L>&THORN;at was &thorn;e temple Triapolitan, as I tolde are.</L>
<L>&THORN;ene was hit abatyd &amp; beten done, &amp; buggyd efte new,</L>
<L>A noble note for &thorn;e nones, &amp; new werke hit hatte.</L>
<L>Mony a mery masone was made &thorn;er to wyrke,</L>
<L N="40">Harde stones for to hewe w<SUP>t</SUP> eggit toles;</L>
<L>Mony grubber in grete &thorn;e grounde for to seche,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e fundement one fyrst shuld &thorn;e fote halde.</L>
<L>&amp; as &thorn;ai makkyde &amp; mynyde, a meruayle &thorn;ai foundene,</L>
<L>As &yogh;et in crafty cronecles is kydde &thorn;e memorie:</L>
<L N="45">For as &thorn;ai dy&yogh;t &amp; dalfe so depe in-to &thorn;e erthe,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai foundene fourmyt one a flore a ferly faire toumbe.</L>
<L>Hit was a throghe of thykke stone, thryuandly hewene,</L>
<L>W<SUP>t</SUP> gargeles garnysht aboute, alle of gray marbre;</L>
<L>Thre sperlis of &thorn;e spelunke &thorn;at spradde hit o lofte<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. sperlis od. spertis?</NOTE></L>
<L N="50">Was metely made of &thorn;e marbre &amp; menskefully planede;</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;e bordure enbelicit w<SUP>t</SUP> bry&yogh;t golde lettres &mdash;</L>
<L>Bot roynyshe were &thorn;e resones <I>&thorn;at &thorn;er</I> one row stodene.</L>
<L>Fulle verray were &thorn;e vigures. &thorn;er auisyde hom mony,</L>
<L>Bot alle muset hit to mouthe &amp; quat hit mene shulde.<NOTE PLACE="foot">to mouthe to speak.</NOTE></L>
<L N="55">Mony clerke in &thorn;at clos, w<SUP>t</SUP> crownes ful brode,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. clerkis?</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;er besiet hom aboute no&yogh;t, to brynge home in wordes.</L>
<L>Quen tithynges tokene to &thorn;e tone of &thorn;e toumbe-wonder,</L>
<L>Mony hundrid hende mene highide &thorn;ider sone.</L>
<L>Burgeys boghit &thorn;er-to, bedels ande othire,<NOTE PLACE="foot">boghit went v. bo&yogh;en.</NOTE></L>
<L N="60">&amp; mony a mesters mon of maners dyuerse;</L>
<L>Laddes laftene hor werke &amp; lepene &thorn;iderwardes,</L>
<L>Ronnen radly in route w<SUP>t</SUP> ryngande noyce.</L>
<L>&THORN;er commene &thorn;ider of alle kynnes so kenely mony,</L>
<L>&THORN;at as alle &thorn;e worlde were &thorn;ider walon w<SUP>t</SUP>-in a honde-quile.</L>
<L N="65">Quen &thorn;e maire w<SUP>t</SUP> his meynye &thorn;at meruaile aspied,</L>
<L>By assent of &thorn;e sextene &thorn;e sayntuare &thorn;ai keptene,</L>
<L>Bede vnlouke &thorn;e lidde &amp; lay hit byside:</L>
<L>&THORN;ai wolde loke one &thorn;at lome quat lengyd w<SUP>t</SUP>-Inne.</L>
<L>Wy&yogh;t werke-men w<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;at wenten &thorn;er-tille,</L>
<L N="70">Putten prises &thorn;er-to, pinchid one vnder,</L>
<L>Kaghtene by &thorn;e corners w<SUP>t</SUP> crowes of yrne,</L>
<L>And, were &thorn;e lydde neuer so large, &thorn;ai laide hit by sone.</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;en wos wonder to wale one wehes &thorn;at stodene<NOTE PLACE="foot">wehe,</NOTE></L>
<L>That my&yogh;t not come to to knowe a quontyse strange&mdash;</L>
<L N="75">So was &thorn;e glode w<SUP>t</SUP>-in gay, al w<SUP>t</SUP> golde payntyde.<NOTE PLACE="foot">glode = clyde plaister?</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; a blisfulle body opone &thorn;e bothum lyggid,</L>
<L>Araide one a riche wise in rialle wedes:</L>
<L>Al w<SUP>t</SUP> glisnande golde his gowne wos hemmyd,
<PB REF="00000406.tif" N="268"></L>
<L>W<SUP>t</SUP> mony a precious perle picchit &thorn;er-one;</L>
<L N="80">&amp; a gurdille of golde bigripide his mydelle;</L>
<L>A meche mantel one lofte w<SUP>t</SUP> menyuer furrit,</L>
<L>&THORN;e clothe of camelyne ful clene, w<SUP>t</SUP> cumly bordures;</L>
<L>&amp; one his coyfe wos kest a coroun ful riche,<NOTE PLACE="foot">coyfe hier = Kopf.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; a semely septure sett in his honde.</L>
<L N="85">Als wemles were his wedes w<SUP>t</SUP>-outen any teiche,<NOTE PLACE="foot">teiche, sranz. tache = fault, wie teche Allit. P. B 1230, teccheles Troy B. 917.</NOTE></L>
<L>O&thorn;er of moulynge o&thorn;er of motes o&thorn;ir moght fretene,</L>
<L>&amp; als bry&yogh;t of hor blee in blysnande hewes,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. h&ymacr; = hyn, in.</NOTE></L>
<L>As &thorn;ai hade &yogh;epely in &thorn;at &yogh;orde bene &yogh;isturday shapene;</L>
<L>&amp; als freshe hyn &thorn;e face &amp; the ffleshe nakyde &mdash;</L>
<L N="90">Bi his eres &amp; bi his hondes &thorn;at openly shewid,</L>
<L>W<SUP>t</SUP> ronke rode as &thorn;e rose, &amp; two rede lippes,<NOTE PLACE="foot">rode, rubor.</NOTE></L>
<L>As he in sounde sodanly were slippide opone slepe.<NOTE PLACE="foot">sounde, sanitas, so Gaw. 2488.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;er was spedeles space to spyr vsch one o&thorn;er<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. vschon st. vch on.</NOTE></L>
<L>Quat body hit my&yogh;t be &thorn;at buried wos ther;</L>
<L N="95">How longe had he &thorn;er layne, his lere so vnchaungit</L>
<L>&amp; al his wede vnwemmyd, &thorn;us ylka weghe askyd.<NOTE PLACE="foot">weghe, man, person (ags. wiga warrier).</NOTE></L>
<L>"Hit my&yogh;t not be bot suche a mone in myde stode longe;</L>
<L>He has bene kynge of &thorn;is kithe, as couthely hit semes.</L>
<L>He lyes doluene &thorn;us depe, hit is a derfe wonder."</L>
<L N="100">Bot summe segge couthe say &thorn;at he hym sene hade &mdash;</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;at ilke note wos noght, for nourne none couthe,</L>
<L>No&thorn;er by title ne tokene ne by tale no&thorn;er</L>
<L>&THORN;at euer wos breuyt in burghe ne in boke notyde,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. boko st. bokis?</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at euer mynnyd suche a mone, more ne lasse.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. more st. mone?</NOTE></L>
<L N="105">&THORN;e bodeworde to &thorn;e byschop was broght one a quile,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;at buriede body al &thorn;e bolde wonder.</L>
<L>&THORN;e primate w<SUP>t</SUP> his prelacie was partyd fro home:</L>
<L>In Esex was ser Erkenwolde, ane abbay to visite.</L>
<L>Tulkes toldene hyme &thorn;e tale w<SUP>t</SUP> troubulle in &thorn;e pepul,</L>
<L N="110">And suche a cry aboute a cors crakit euer more.</L>
<L>The bischop sende hit to blynne, by bedels &amp; lettres,</L>
<L>Ande buskyd &thorn;iderwarde by tyme one his blonke after.<NOTE PLACE="foot">blonke = (white)horse; dass. bez. meere 114.</NOTE></L>
<L>By &thorn;at he come to &thorn;e kyrke kydde of saynt Paule,</L>
<L>Mony hym mettene on &thorn;at meere, &thorn;e meruayle to telle.</L>
<L N="115">He passyd in-to his palais &amp; pes he comaundit,</L>
<L>&amp; deuoydit fro &thorn;e dede &amp; ditte &thorn;e durre after. &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;e derke ny&yogh;t one drofe &amp; day-belle ronge:</L>
<L>And ser Erkenwolde was vp in &thorn;e vghtene ere &thorn;ene,<NOTE PLACE="foot">vghten morning.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at welneghe al &thorn;e ny&yogh;t hade naityd his houres,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. nattyd st. naityd, isl. njota, to use, ply.</NOTE></L>
<L N="120">To biseche his souerayne of his swete grace
<PB REF="00000407.tif" N="269"></L>
<L>To vouche safe, to reuele hym hit by a vis(i)one or elles:</L>
<L>"&THORN;aghe I be vnworthi", al wepande he sayde,</L>
<L>Thurghe his deere debonerte, "digne hit, my lorde,</L>
<L>In confirmynge &thorn;i cristen faithe fulsene me to kenne<NOTE PLACE="foot">fulsene = filsyn fulsten to aid.</NOTE></L>
<L N="125">&THORN;e mysterie of &thorn;is meruaile &thorn;at mene opone wondres!"</L>
<L>&amp; so longe he grette after grace, &thorn;at he graunte hade:</L>
<L>Ane ansuare of &thorn;e holy goste. &amp; afterwarde hit dawid.</L>
<L>Mynster-dores were makyd opone, quene matens were songene:</L>
<L>&THORN;e byschop hym shope solemply to synge &thorn;e heghe-masse.</L>
<L N="130">&THORN;e prelate in pontificals was prestly atyride,</L>
<L>Manerly w<SUP>t</SUP> his ministres &thorn;e masse he begynnes</L>
<L>Of sp(iritu)s d(o)m(ini) for his spede one sutile wise,</L>
<L>W<SUP>t</SUP> queme questis of &thorn;e quere, w<SUP>t</SUP> ful quaynt notes.</L>
<L>Mony a gay grete lorde was gedrid to herkene hit,</L>
<L N="135">As &thorn;e rekenest of &thorn;e reame repairene &thorn;ider ofte.<NOTE PLACE="foot">reken noble, worthy.</NOTE></L>
<L>Tille cessyd was &thorn;e seruice &amp; sayde &thorn;e later ende:</L>
<L>&THORN;ene heldyt fro &thorn;e autere alle &thorn;e heghe gynge.<NOTE PLACE="foot">heldyt v. helden to bend to, to go. gyng company (so in Troy B., Allit. P.).</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e prelate passide one &thorn;e playne &mdash; &thorn;er plied to hym lordes &mdash;</L>
<L>As riche reuestid as he was, he rayked to &thorn;e toumbe.</L>
<L N="140">Mene vnclosid hym &thorn;e cloyster w<SUP>t</SUP> clustrede keies&mdash;</L>
<L>Bot pyne wos w<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;e grete prece &thorn;at passyd hyme after.</L>
<L>The byschop come to &thorn;e burynes, him barones besyde,</L>
<L>&THORN;e maire w<SUP>t</SUP> mony ma&yogh;ti mene &amp; macers before hyme.</L>
<L>&THORN;e dene of &thorn;e dere place deuysit al one fyrst</L>
<L N="145">&THORN;e fyndynge of &thorn;at ferly, w<SUP>t</SUP> fynger he mynte:</L>
<L>"Lo, lordes", qua&thorn; &thorn;at lede, "suche a lyche here is,</L>
<L>Has layne lokene here one loghe, how longe, is vnknawene,<NOTE PLACE="foot">loghe altnord. lagr = pit, deep, so All. P. B. 366.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; &yogh;et his colour &amp; his clothe has ca&yogh;t no defaute</L>
<L>Ne his lire, ne &thorn;e lome &thorn;at he is layde Inne.</L>
<L N="150">&THORN;er is no lede opone lyfe of so longe age</L>
<L>&THORN;at may mene in his mynde &thorn;at suche a mone regnyd,</L>
<L>Ne no&thorn;er his nome ne his note nourne of one speche;</L>
<L>Que&thorn;er mony porer in &thorn;is place is putte into graue<NOTE PLACE="foot">que&thorn;er tamen.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at merkid is in oure martilage his mynde for euer.</L>
<L N="155">&amp; we haue oure librarie laitid &thorn;es longe seuene dayes,</L>
<L>Bot one clucle of &thorn;is kynge cone we neuer fynde.<NOTE PLACE="foot">clucle = clutch (l. cluche?).</NOTE></L>
<L>He has non layne here so longe, to loke hit by kynde,</L>
<L>To malte so out of memorie, bot meruayle hit were."</L>
<L>"&THORN;ou says so&thorn;e", qua&thorn; &thorn;e segge &thorn;at sacrid was byschop;</L>
<L N="160">"Hit is meruaile to mene, &thorn;at mountes to litelle</L>
<L>Towarde &thorn;e prouidens of &thorn;e prince &thorn;at paradis weldes,</L>
<L>Quene hym luste to vnlouke &thorn;e lefte of his my&yogh;tes.</L>
<L>Bot quene matyd is monnes my&yogh;t &amp; his mynde passyde
<PB REF="00000408.tif" N="270"></L>
<L>And al his resons are to-rent &amp; redeles he stondes,</L>
<L N="165">&THORN;ene lettis hit hym ful litelle to louse wyt a fynger</L>
<L>&THORN;at alle &thorn;e hondes vnder heuen halde my&yogh;t neuer;</L>
<L>&THORN;ere as creatures crafte of counselle oute swarues,</L>
<L>&THORN;e comforthe of &thorn;e creatore byhoues &thorn;e cure take.</L>
<L>&amp; so do we now oure dede, deuyne we no fyrre &mdash;</L>
<L N="170">To seche &thorn;e sothe at oure-selfe, &yogh;ee se &thorn;er no bote &mdash;</L>
<L>Bot glow we alle opone godde &amp; his grace aske,<NOTE PLACE="foot">glow, T. B. glogh = to gaze, blicken.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at careles is of counselle &amp; comforthe to sende.</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;at in fastynge of &yogh;our faithe &amp; of fyne bileue</L>
<L>I shal auay &yogh;ow so verrayly of vertues his,<NOTE PLACE="foot">auaye frz. avoier, to show, so in All. P. B. 1311, 1358.</NOTE></L>
<L N="175">&THORN;at &yogh;e may leue vpone longe &thorn;at he is lord my&yogh;ty</L>
<L>&amp; fayne &yogh;our talent to fulfille, if &yogh;e hym frende leues".</L>
<L>Thene he turnes to &thorn;e toumbe &amp; talkes to &thorn;e corce,</L>
<L>Lyftande vp his eghe-lyddes he loused suche wordes:</L>
<L>"Now, lykhame, &thorn;at &thorn;ou lies layne &thorn;ou no lenger!</L>
<L N="180">Sythene Jhesus has iuggit to-day his ioy to be schewyde,</L>
<L>Be &thorn;ou bone to his bode, I bydde in his behalue;</L>
<L>As he was bende one a beme, quene he his blode schedde,</L>
<L>As &thorn;ou hit wost wyterly &amp; we hit wele leuene,</L>
<L>Ansuare here to my sawe, councele no trouthe!</L>
<L N="185">Sithene we wot not qwo &thorn;ou art, witere vs &thorn;i-selwene,</L>
<L>In worlde quat weghe &thorn;ou was &amp; quy &thorn;ow &thorn;us ligges,</L>
<L>How longe &thorn;ou has layne here &amp; quat laghe &thorn;ou vsyt,</L>
<L>Que&thorn;er art &thorn;ou ioyned to ioy o&thorn;er iuggid to pyne?"</L>
<L>Quene &thorn;e segge hade &thorn;us sayde &amp; syked &thorn;er-after,</L>
<L N="190">&THORN;e bry&yogh;t body in &thorn;e burynes brayed a litelle,</L>
<L>&amp; w<SUP>t</SUP> a drery dreme he dryues owte wordes</L>
<L>&THORN;urghe sum lant goste, lyfe of hyme &thorn;at al redes:<NOTE PLACE="foot">lant, auch 272, = lent, vgl. lante&yogh; All. P. B. 348.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Bisshop", qua&thorn; &thorn;is ilke body, "&thorn;i boode is me dere,</L>
<L>I may not bot boghe to &thorn;i bone for bothe myne eghene:</L>
<L N="195">To &thorn;e name &thorn;at &thorn;ou neuenyd has &amp; nournet me after</L>
<L>Al heuene &amp; helle heldes to &amp; erthe bitwene.</L>
<L>Fyrst to say the &thorn;e sothe quo my-selfe were:</L>
<L>One &thorn;e vnhapnest hathel &thorn;at euer one erthe &yogh;ode,<NOTE PLACE="foot">vnhapnest v. vnhappen unfortunate All. P. B. 573. hathel a noble, man.</NOTE></L>
<L>Neuer kynge ne cayser ne &yogh;et no kny&yogh;t nothyre,</L>
<L N="200">Bot a lede of &thorn;e laghe &thorn;at &thorn;ene &thorn;is londe vsit.<NOTE PLACE="foot">lede ags le&oacute;d = man, person.</NOTE></L>
<L>I was committid &amp; made a mayster-mone here</L>
<L>To sytte vpone sayd causes; &thorn;is cite I &yogh;emyd,</L>
<L>Vnder a prince of parage of paynymes laghe,</L>
<L>&amp; vche segge &thorn;at him sewide, &thorn;e same faythe trowid.</L>
<L N="205">&THORN;e lengthe of my lyuing here &thorn;at is a lewid date,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. n&omacr;mbre, wie 289.</NOTE></L>
<L>Hit (is) to meche to any mone to make of a noumbre:<NOTE PLACE="foot">is fehlt im Ms.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000409.tif" N="271"></L>
<L>After &thorn;at Brutus &thorn;is burghe had buggid one fyrste</L>
<L>No&yogh;t bot fife hundred &yogh;ere &thorn;er aghtene wontyd,</L>
<L>Before &thorn;at kynned &yogh;our Criste by cristene acounte</L>
<L N="210">A &thorn;ousande &yogh;ere &amp; &thorn;ritty mo &amp; &yogh;et threnene aght.<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;renene 3, vgl. &thorn;rynne All. P. B. 606, 1727.</NOTE></L>
<L>I was ane heire of anoye in &thorn;e new Troie<NOTE PLACE="foot">heire = here, a man, person T. B.; heire of anoye, ein gef&uuml;rchteter Herr; vgl. noye T. B. 3701.</NOTE></L>
<L>In &thorn;e regne of &thorn;e riche kynge &thorn;at rewlit vs &thorn;ene,</L>
<L>The bolde Bretone ser Belyne, ser Berynge was his brothire &mdash;</L>
<L>Mony one was &thorn;e busmare bodene home bitwene</L>
<L N="215">For hor wrakeful werre, quil hor wrathe lastyd.</L>
<L>&THORN;ene was I iuge here enioynyd in gentil lawe".</L>
<L>Quil he in spelunke &thorn;us spake, &thorn;er sprange in &thorn;e pepulle</L>
<L>In al &thorn;is worlde no worde, ne wakenyd no noice,</L>
<L>Bot al as stille as &thorn;e stone stodene &amp; listonde,</L>
<L N="220">With meche wonder forwrast, &amp; wepid ful mony.</L>
<L>The bisshop biddes &thorn;at body: "biknowe &thorn;e cause,</L>
<L>Sithene &thorn;ou was kidde for no kynge, quy &thorn;ou &thorn;e croun weres?</L>
<L>Quy haldes &thorn;ou so heghe in honde &thorn;e septre</L>
<L>&amp; hades no londe of lege men, ne life ne lyme aghtes?"</L>
<L N="225">"Dere ser", qua&thorn; &thorn;e dede body, "deuyse &thorn;e I thenke.<NOTE PLACE="foot">deuyse hier = describe, wie All. P. A. 99, 984.</NOTE></L>
<L>Al was hit neuer my wille &thorn;at wroght &thorn;us hit were.</L>
<L>I wos deputate &amp; domesmane vnder a duke noble,</L>
<L>&amp; in my power &thorn;is place was putte al-to-geder:</L>
<L>I iustifiet &thorn;is ioly toun one gentil wise</L>
<L N="230">&amp; euer in fourme of gode faithe, more &thorn;ene fourty wynter.</L>
<L>&THORN;e folke was felouse &amp; fals &amp; frowarde to reule &mdash;</L>
<L>I hent harmes ful ofte, to holde home to ri&yogh;t;</L>
<L>Bot for wothe ne wele ne wrathe ne drede</L>
<L>Ne for maystrie ne for mede ne for no monnes aghe</L>
<L N="235">I remewit neuer fro &thorn;e ri&yogh;t by resone myne awene</L>
<L>For to dresse a wrange dome, no day of my lyue,</L>
<L>Declynet neuer my consciens for couetise one erthe</L>
<L>In no gynful iugement no iapes to make;</L>
<L>Were a renke neuer so riche, for reuerens sake,</L>
<L N="240">Ne for no monnes manas ne meschefe ne routhe,</L>
<L>None gete me fro &thorn;e heghe gate to glent out of ry&yogh;t,<NOTE PLACE="foot">glent = glide, slip, fall, wie All. P. A. 631. sonst = gleam, glitter (Sk. glent glint).</NOTE></L>
<L>Als ferforthe as my faithe confourmyd myn hert.</L>
<L>&THORN;aghe had bene my fader bone, I bede hym no wranges,<NOTE PLACE="foot">bone = bane murderer.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ne fals fauour to my fader, &thorn;aghe felle hyme be hongyt.</L>
<L N="245">&amp; for I was ry&yogh;twis &amp; rekene &amp; redy of &thorn;e laghe:</L>
<L>Quene I deghed, for dul denyed alle Troye,<NOTE PLACE="foot">denyed = dinned resounded.</NOTE></L>
<L>Alle menyd my dethe, &thorn;e more &amp; the lasse.</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;us to bounty my body &thorn;ai buriet in golde,
<PB REF="00000410.tif" N="272"></L>
<L>Claddene me for &thorn;e curtest &thorn;at courte couthe &thorn;en holde,</L>
<L N="250">In mantel for &thorn;e mekest &amp; monlokest one benche,</L>
<L>Gurdene me for &thorn;e gouernour &amp; graythist of Troie,</L>
<L>Furrid me for &thorn;e fynest of faithe me w<SUP>t</SUP>-inne,</L>
<L>For &thorn;e honour of myne honeste of heghest enprise</L>
<L>&THORN;ai coronyd me &thorn;e kidde kynge of kene iustises</L>
<L N="255">&THORN;at euer wos tronyd in Troye o&thorn;er trowid euer shulde,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. &thorn;er st. &thorn;at.</NOTE></L>
<L>And for I rewardid euer ri&yogh;t, &thorn;ai raght me the septre".</L>
<L>&THORN;e bisshop baythes hym &yogh;et w<SUP>t</SUP> bale at his hert:<NOTE PLACE="foot">baythes = asks? Gaw. baythe = consent, grant 1404, 1840, 327.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;aghe men menskid him so, how hit my&yogh;t worthe</L>
<L>&THORN;at his clothes were so clene. "In cloutes, me thynkes,</L>
<L N="260">Hom burde haue rotid &amp; bene rent in rattis longe sythene.<NOTE PLACE="foot">rattes = rags.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;i body may be enbawmyd, hit bashis me noght,</L>
<L>&THORN;at hit thar ryue ne rote ne no ronke wormes(!);<NOTE PLACE="foot">ryue od. ryne? vor no fehlt fede?</NOTE></L>
<L>Bot &thorn;i coloure ne &thorn;i clothe I know in no wise</L>
<L>How hit my&yogh;t lye by monnes lore &amp; last so longe".</L>
<L N="265">"Nay, bisshop", qua&thorn; &thorn;at body, "enbawmyd wos I neuer,</L>
<L>Ne no monnes counselle my clothe has kepyd vnwemmyd,</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;e riche kynge of resone, &thorn;at ri&yogh;t euer alowes<NOTE PLACE="foot">alow reward.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; loues al &thorn;e lawes lely &thorn;at longene to trouthe,</L>
<L>&amp; more he menskes mene for mynnynge of ri&yogh;tes<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. moste st. more.</NOTE></L>
<L N="270">&THORN;en for al &thorn;e meritorie medes &thorn;at men one molde vsene.</L>
<L>&amp; if renkes for ri&yogh;t &thorn;us me arayed has,</L>
<L>He has lant me to last, &thorn;at loues ry&yogh;t best".</L>
<L>"&YOGH;ea, bot sayes &thorn;ou of &thorn;i saule", &thorn;en sayd &thorn;e bisshop,</L>
<L>"Quere is ho stablid &amp; stadde, if &thorn;ou so stre&yogh;t wroghtes?</L>
<L N="275">He &thorn;at rewardes vche a renke as he has ri&yogh;t seruyd</L>
<L>My&yogh;t euel forgo the to gyfe of his grace summe brawnche,</L>
<L>For as he says in his sothe psalmyde writtes:<NOTE PLACE="foot">skelton v. skelt = hasten run, so in Allit. P. B. 1554.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e skilfulle &amp; &thorn;e vnskathely skeltone ay to me.</L>
<L>For&thorn;i say me of &thorn;i soule, in sele quere ho wonnes,</L>
<L N="280">And of &thorn;e riche restorment &thorn;at ra&yogh;t hyr oure lorde".</L>
<L>&THORN;en hummyd he &thorn;at &thorn;er lay, &amp; his hedde waggyd,</L>
<L>&amp; gefe a gronynge ful grete, &amp; to godde sayde:</L>
<L>"Ma&yogh;ty maker of mene, thi myghtes are grete!</L>
<L>How my&yogh;t &thorn;i mercy to me amounte any tyme?</L>
<L N="285">Nas I a paynym vnpreste &thorn;at neuer thi plite knewe</L>
<L>Ne &thorn;i mesure of &thorn;i mercy ne &thorn;i mecul vertue?</L>
<L>Bot ay a freke faitheles &thorn;at faylid &thorn;i laghes,<NOTE PLACE="foot">freke man, ags. freca warrior.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at euer &thorn;ou, lord, wos louyd in? Allas, &thorn;e harde stoundes!</L>
<L>I was none of &thorn;e noumbre &thorn;at &thorn;ou w<SUP>t</SUP> noy boghtes,</L>
<L N="290">W<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;e blode of thi body vpone &thorn;e blo rode;</L>
<L>Quene &thorn;ou herghedes helle-hole &amp; hentes hom &thorn;er-oute,</L>
<L>&THORN;i loffynge, oute of limbo, &thorn;ou laftes me &thorn;er.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. ne st. me.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000411.tif" N="273"></L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;er sittes my soule &thorn;at se may no fyrre,</L>
<L>Dwynande in &thorn;e derke dethe, &thorn;at dy&yogh;t vs oure fader,</L>
<L N="295">Adam, oure alder, &thorn;at ete of &thorn;at appulle</L>
<L>&THORN;at mony a ply&yogh;tles pepul has poysned for euer.<NOTE PLACE="foot">ply&yogh;tles = faultles.</NOTE></L>
<L>&YOGH;e were entouchid w<SUP>t</SUP> his tethe &amp; take in &thorn;e glotte,<NOTE PLACE="foot">glotte st. glette?</NOTE></L>
<L>Bot, mendyd w<SUP>t</SUP> a medecyne, &yogh;e are made for to lyuye:</L>
<L>&THORN;at is fulloght in fonte, w<SUP>t</SUP> faitheful bileue,</L>
<L N="300">&amp; &thorn;at hane we myste alle merciles, myselfe &amp; my soule.</L>
<L>Quat wane we w<SUP>t</SUP> oure wele-dede, &thorn;at wroghtyne ay ri&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Quene we are dampnyd dulfully into &thorn;e depe lake</L>
<L>&amp; exilid fro &thorn;at soper so, &thorn;at solempne fest</L>
<L>&THORN;er richely hit arne refetyd &thorn;at after right hungride?</L>
<L N="305">My soule may sitte &thorn;er in sorow &amp; sike, ful colde,</L>
<L>Dymly in &thorn;at derke dethe, &thorn;er dawes neuer morowene,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. dynly st. dimly.</NOTE></L>
<L>Hungre in-w<SUP>t</SUP> helle-hole &amp; herkene after meeles,</L>
<L>Longe er ho &thorn;at soper se, o&thorn;er segge hyr to lathe".</L>
<L>&THORN;us dulfully &thorn;is dede body deuisyt hit sorowe,</L>
<L N="310">&THORN;at alle wepyd for woo, &thorn;e wordes &thorn;at herdene.</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;e bysshop balefully bere done his eghene,</L>
<L>&THORN;at hade no space to speke so spakly &mdash; he &yogh;oskyd.<NOTE PLACE="foot">spakly quickly.</NOTE></L>
<L>Til he toke hyme a tome &amp; to &thorn;e toumbe lokyd,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e liche &thorn;er hit lay w<SUP>t</SUP> lauande teres:<NOTE PLACE="foot">lauande pouring, flowing, so All. P. B. 366.</NOTE></L>
<L N="315">"Oure lord lene, qua&thorn; &thorn;at lede, &thorn;at &thorn;ou lyfe hades</L>
<L>By goddis leue, as longe as I my&yogh;t lacche water</L>
<L>&amp; cast vpone &thorn;i faire cors &amp; carpe &thorn;es wordes:</L>
<L>I folwe &thorn;e in &thorn;e fader nome &amp; his fre childes</L>
<L>&amp; of &thorn;e gracious holy goste &mdash; &amp; not one grue lenger.<NOTE PLACE="foot">grue? Ms. undeutlich. grue = gre? wie Gaw. 2251 I schal gruch &thorn;e no grwe.</NOTE></L>
<L N="320">&THORN;ene &thorn;of &thorn;ou droppyd doun dede, hit daungerde me lasse!"<NOTE PLACE="foot">daungerde = angerd.</NOTE></L>
<L>W<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;at worde &thorn;at he warpyd &thorn;e wete of eghene</L>
<L>&amp; teres trillyd adoun &amp; one &thorn;e toumbe lightene:</L>
<L>&amp; one felle one his face: &amp; &thorn;e freke syked.</L>
<L>&THORN;ene sayd he w<SUP>t</SUP> a sadde soun: "oure sauyoure be louyd!</L>
<L N="325">Now herid be &thorn;ou, heghe god, &amp; &thorn;i hende moder,</L>
<L>&amp; blissid be &thorn;at blisful houre &thorn;at ho the bere in!</L>
<L>&amp; also be &thorn;ou, bysshop, &thorn;e bote of my sorowe</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;e relefe of &thorn;e lodely lures &thorn;at my soule has leuyd in!</L>
<L>For &thorn;e wordes &thorn;at &thorn;ou werpe, &amp; &thorn;e water &thorn;at &thorn;ou sheddes,</L>
<L N="330">&THORN;e bry&yogh;t bourne of &thorn;in eghene, my bapteme is worthyne;</L>
<L>&THORN;e fyrst slent &thorn;at one me slode, slekkyd al my tene.<NOTE PLACE="foot">slent Sw. slinta to slip, Gaw. 1260 slenting = shooting, glansing.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ry&yogh;t now to soper my soule is sette at &thorn;e table,</L>
<L>For w<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;e wordes &amp; &thorn;e water &thorn;at weshe vs of payne</L>
<L>Li&yogh;tly lasshit &thorn;er a leme loghe in &thorn;e abyme,</L>
<L N="335">&THORN;at spakly sprent my spyrit w<SUP>t</SUP> vnsparid murthe
<PB REF="00000412.tif" N="274"></L>
<L>In-to &thorn;e cenacle, solemply &thorn;er soupene alle trew;</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;er a marcialle hyr mette w<SUP>t</SUP> menske alder-grattest<NOTE PLACE="foot">marciall = marshal.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; w<SUP>t</SUP> reuerence a rowme he ra&yogh;t hyr for euer.</L>
<L>I heere &thorn;erof my heghe god &amp; also &thorn;e, bysshop,</L>
<L N="340">Fro bale has bro&yogh;t vs to blis! blessid &thorn;ou worth!"</L>
<L>Wyt this cessyd his sowne, sayd he no more.</L>
<L>Bot sodenly his swete chere swyndid &amp; faylide</L>
<L>And alle the blee of his body wos blakke, as &thorn;e moldes,</L>
<L>As rotene as &thorn;e rottok &thorn;at rises in powdere.</L>
<L N="345">For assone as &thorn;e soule was sesyd in blisse,</L>
<L>Corrupt was &thorn;at o&thorn;er crafte &thorn;at couert &thorn;e bones &mdash;</L>
<L>For &thorn;e ay-lastande life, &thorn;at lethe shalle neuer,</L>
<L>Deuoydes vche a vayne glorie, &thorn;at vayles so litelle.<NOTE PLACE="foot">loves = hands, so K. Alexand. p. 71 u. Allit. P. B. 987 (Altnord. lofi).</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ene wos louynge oure lorde w<SUP>t</SUP> loves vp haldene,</L>
<L N="350">Meche mournynge &amp; myrthe was mellyd to-geder.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai passyd forthe in processione, &amp; alle &thorn;e pepulle folowid,</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;e belles in &thorn;e burghe beryd at ones.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="7" TYPE="legend"><PB REF="00000413.tif" N="[275]">
<HEAD>7. Legende vom h. Blute zu Hayles,
aus Ms. Royal 17, C XVII, pag. 147. (Dialect von Cornwallis?)</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>Diese Legende ist eine Lokallegende. Sie hat 2 Theile: 1) die Geschichte des h. Blutes nach einer Schrift des Pabstes Urban IV: Das h. Blut wird von einem Judcn (dessen Name, Joseph von Arimathia, ungenannt bleibt) in einer Sch&uuml;ssel (dem heil. Graal) aufgefangen; desshalb wird er von den Juden in einem eigens gebauten Hause gefangen gehalten, 42 Jahre lang, vom h. Blute wunderbar ern&auml;hrt; die Zerst&ouml;rer Jerusalems, Titus und Vespasian, finden ihn und nehmen ihm seinen Schatz, worauf er todt zusammenbricht; sie bringen das h. Blut nach Rom in den Tempel des Frie|dens; Carl der Grosse theilt es und f&uuml;hrt die H&auml;lfte nach Deutschland, nach "Castell Trivelense". v. 37&mdash;180. 2) Die Ueberf&uuml;hrung eines Theils des h. Blutes aus "Castell Trivelense" nach der Abtei Hailes durch Edmund, Sohn Richard's von Cornwallis, damaligen deutschen Kaisers, im J. 1276. v. 183&mdash;370. &mdash; Ueber die Sage von Joseph v. Arimathia vgl. W. Skeat "Joseph of Arimathie" (f&uuml;r die Early E. Text Soc. 1871) Preface p. XXVIII ff. Eine Lokallegende vom h. Joseph von Arimathia, der nach der Ueberlieferung von Glastonbury in Somerset (vgl. Johannis Glastoniensis Chronica ed. Hearne), vom Apostel Philipp ausgesandt in England das Christenthum einf&uuml;hrt und in Glastonbury die erste Kirche baut, ist The lyfe of Joseph of Arma|thia in achtzeiligen Strophen, 1520 von Pynson gedruckt, wieder abgedruckt bei Skeat l. c. p. 35 ff. Mehr romantischen Inhalts, durch den Einfluss der Graalssage, ist das alliter. Ged. des Ms. Vernon fol. 403, gedr. bei Skeat l. c. p. 1 ff. Ein pro|saisches "lyfe of Joseph of Armathy" druckte Wynkyn de Worde, nach Capgrave's Nova Legenda Angliae (bei Skeat l. c. p. 33 ff.). &mdash; Chaucer erw&auml;hnt das h. Blut von Hales in Pardoner's Tale: "And by the blood of Christ that is in Hayles"; vgl. die Note v. Tyrwhitt a. l. u. Skeat's Note zu Chaucer's Man of law's Tale (Clar. Pr.).</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>(S)en-tyme &thorn;at alle &thorn;is warlde was wroght,<NOTE PLACE="foot">am Rande steht: Fuit homo missus a deo cui nomen erat.</NOTE></L>
<L>Many marwylles &thorn;er af bene falle:<NOTE PLACE="foot">af = haf, von derselben Hand nebengeschr. [ist af bene falle in af befalle zu bessern (Ms. af bene falle) --Corrigenda.]</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e qwylk, if &thorn;ai were alle throgh-soght,<NOTE PLACE="foot">q ist vor wylk vorgeschr.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e pepulle wylde not lewe &thorn;am alle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="5">For mankynd es so to synne ensured:</L>
<L>Of stedfastenes he takes no trest;</L>
<L>And in harte so harde indurede:</L>
<L>He wylle not lewe bot qwatt hym lyst &mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And so says Salamon, &thorn;at wysse clark,</L>
<L N="10">&THORN;at in &thorn;e stretys of &thorn;e towne</L>
<L>Wyt alle &thorn;e pepulle in worde &amp; wark<NOTE PLACE="foot">a. R.: Veritas corruit inplateis. wyt = wyth.</NOTE></L>
<L>Sothefastnes es alle falne downe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot &thorn;at god of hys specyalte</L>
<L>Schewes on herthe emang vs here,<NOTE PLACE="foot">herthe, wie 31, = erthe.</NOTE></L>
<L N="15">We suld not dowte hyt in no degre</L>
<L>Bot lewe on it wyt stedfast chere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Qwy es it more agayns mans wytte</L>
<L>To lewe &thorn;at Crystis blode es in Hayle,</L>
<L>&THORN;an on &thorn;e circumsicione &thorn;at at Rome &yogh;ytte</L>
<L N="20">Blode &amp; water wyt-owtyn fayle,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;at ran owte of oure lorde syde,</L>
<L>Wen he hang opone &thorn;e tre?</L>
<L>Who-so wylle &thorn;edyre go or ryde,</L>
<L>&THORN;is day &thorn;er he may it se.
<PB REF="00000414.tif" N="276"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="25">Bot for mekylle of &thorn;e here ofte in dowte<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e = &thorn;o?</NOTE></L>
<L>Of &thorn;e precius blode &thorn;at in Hayles is,<NOTE PLACE="foot">is aus es corr.</NOTE></L>
<L>To knaw how it was broght abowte,</L>
<L>Take hede &amp; rede owre &thorn;is,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. hete st. hede. owre = over, wie 35.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;at owre holy fadyr, pope Vrbane &thorn;e ferth,</L>
<L N="30">Made &amp; ordan to af in mynde</L>
<L>For &thorn;is holy blode &thorn;at here es in herth &mdash;</L>
<L>How? &yogh;e salle &thorn;e trewthe &thorn;ere fynde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot for latyn endytyng cumburus is</L>
<L>For dyuerce pylgrymes &thorn;at may not dwelle,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Dieser Vers ist durchstrichen v. a. H.</NOTE></L>
<L N="35">Rede owre &thorn;at here in ynglys es,</L>
<L>For playnely &thorn;is &thorn;e trewthe wyll telle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Fyrst at &thorn;e pope I wylle be-gynne,</L>
<L>To schew hys story wyt-owtyn fayle,</L>
<L>And aftyre how Erylle Edmunde gunne it wynne</L>
<L N="40">And broght it to &thorn;e abbay of Hayle;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Prayyng alle &thorn;e reders for godys sake</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;is lettyre be not refusede,</L>
<L>And, if any worde be mys-take,</L>
<L>My reclenes &yogh;e af excusyde. &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">l. reclesnes.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="45">Here begyns &thorn;e popes story.</L>
<L>In &thorn;e tyme of Cristes passyon</L>
<L>Emong &thorn;e Iues &thorn;at were so sory</L>
<L>Was a Iue as of &thorn;er nacyone,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Dieser Jude ist Joseph v. Arimathia, dessen Namen der Dichter verschweigt</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot of &thorn;er perfyte he was not so,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. perfyte = perfidy od. st. perversite verschr.</NOTE></L>
<L N="50">Wylk &thorn;e dede can aftyr schew;</L>
<L>He was enspyred wyt god also,</L>
<L>And, thofe he spak bot wordys few,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Hys hart was on hym bothe day &amp; nyght:</L>
<L>And I sulde &thorn;e sothe telle,</L>
<L N="55">&THORN;at sawyd hym fra &thorn;at fowle wyght</L>
<L>&THORN;at men calles &thorn;e dewelle of helle &mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For as saynt Paule in hys boke can telle:</L>
<L>"Of all nacyons he &thorn;at werkys godys wylle,<NOTE PLACE="foot">a. R.: In omni gente quicunque fecerit voluntatem dei e. c.</NOTE></L>
<L>He es accepte wyt hym to dwelle</L>
<L N="60">In hewen &amp; &thorn;er to abyde stylle".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;is Iue, &thorn;at I spake of be-fore,</L>
<L>Wyls oure lorde hang opon &thorn;e cros,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e body he come rynnyg sore,</L>
<L>Bot wyt &thorn;e mowthe he made no noys;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="65">Sum of &thorn;at swete blode to af he toght,<NOTE PLACE="foot">toght = thoght.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ware-fore he myght af hym in mynde:</L>
<L>A wessyll &thorn;er-fore wyt hym he broght.</L>
<L>&THORN;er-in full fare he gane it wynde &mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>As Ysaie &thorn;e prophete says in hys spelle:</L>
<L N="70">How he sulde blode draw drope-mele<NOTE PLACE="foot">a. R.: Sanguinem sensim et guttatim hauriet de fontibus e. c.</NOTE></L>
<L>Rennyg owte of oure saueours welle,</L>
<L>&amp; kepe it for cristyn mennes hele.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Where-fore &thorn;e Iues of mys-beleue</L>
<L>Wyt-outen &thorn;e cete made a howse of stone;</L>
<L N="75">For he sulde &thorn;am no more grewe,</L>
<L>To preson &thorn;er &thorn;ai pute hym o-none,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;er to abyde perpetually,</L>
<L>And &thorn;is holy blode to be hys fode;</L>
<L>&THORN;e dore &thorn;ai stoppyd full sekyrly,</L>
<L N="80">And went away, as (&thorn;ai) were wode.<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ai fehlt im Ms.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;er-in he was two &amp; fowrty &yogh;ere</L>
<L>Aftyr oure lorde dyed opon &thorn;e tre,</L>
<L>Wyt &thorn;at blode fayre &amp; clere,</L>
<L>&THORN;at hym sustened wele in euere degre.<NOTE PLACE="foot">euere = euery (vgl. Herre 185).</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="85">To &thorn;e tyme &thorn;at god wyld wengement take</L>
<L>Opon &thorn;e Iues, &thorn;at were so proude:</L>
<L>Where-fore &thorn;e Emperours of Rome gan wake,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai seget Jehrusalem all-abowte:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whylke were called Tytus and Vaspa|siane,</L>
<L N="90">&THORN;at in &thorn;er tyme &thorn;ai gouernyd &thorn;e empyre.</L>
<L>In &thorn;at sege &thorn;ai slo many a mane</L>
<L>And stroyd &thorn;e cete wyt stre(n)gh &amp; yre &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. stregh.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>As god prophesyd in hys gospell:</L>
<L>"&THORN;i enmys sal a-bowte &thorn;e gone<NOTE PLACE="foot">a. R.: Circumdabunt te inimici tui vallo et coangustabunt te.</NOTE></L>
<L N="95">&amp; sal dystroy bothe flesche &amp; fell</L>
<L>&amp; leue no howse nor stone opo stone".<NOTE PLACE="foot">opo st. opon.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000415.tif" N="277"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And so &thorn;ai dyd, I telle &yogh;ow trewly:</L>
<L>Dystroyd &thorn;e cete wyt towres proude</L>
<L>&amp; solde XXX (thyrte) Iues for a peny</L>
<L N="100">And rode &thorn;e strete wyt-in &amp; wyt-oute.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And when &thorn;is emperours had &thorn;us do,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai turnyd hamwarde in &thorn;er way.</L>
<L>&THORN;an se &thorn;ai a howse a lytyll &thorn;am fro</L>
<L>Oure-growne wyt Iwen, &thorn;e sothe to say.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Iwen = iwin, ivy.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="105">Onone &thorn;ai askyde &thorn;e Ieues &thorn;er-fore</L>
<L>Why &thorn;at howse was ordande &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>And &thorn;ai answerde bothe lesse &amp; more</L>
<L>&THORN;ai wyld tell as &thorn;ai lerende wore,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. scheinbar berende.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And sayd: "in Cristys passyon tyme,</L>
<L N="110">For a Iue lewed on hys law,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai putte hym &thorn;er to preson-pyne;</L>
<L>And &thorn;is was oure eldyrs saw".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whe(n) &thorn;e emperours hard &thorn;is tale,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. whe.</NOTE></L>
<L>To &thorn;e howse &thorn;i heed &thorn;am onone<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;i = &thorn;ai. heed = hi&yogh;ed,</NOTE></L>
<L N="115">And brake &thorn;e stones grete &amp; smale,</L>
<L>&amp; so &thorn;ai lefte no hole stone.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;er &thorn;ai fond &thorn;is Iue wyt fres chere<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. freschere; l. fresch ere (= aire)?</NOTE></L>
<L>Haldyng &thorn;e blode in hys lappe all rede.</L>
<L>&THORN;an were &thorn;ai in dowte bothe in-fere,</L>
<L N="120">Wondyryng &thorn;at he was not dede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ai askyd hym wyt wordys bolde</L>
<L>Of hys lynage &amp; wat he was,</L>
<L>And wat thyng in hys lappe he dyd holde,</L>
<L>And wy &thorn;at he was putte in &thorn;at place.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. &thorn;is od. &thorn;at?</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="125">&THORN;e Iue &thorn;am tolde bothe worde &amp; ende</L>
<L>As it es declared a lytyll be-fore,</L>
<L>And prayd &thorn;am forthe forto wende</L>
<L>&amp; sofur hym to hawe hys tresore:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"My luf, my lyst, my lyfe here-on es,</L>
<L N="130">I tell &yogh;ow, syrs, wyt grete chere.</L>
<L>Me thyng bot few days, I-wys,<NOTE PLACE="foot">thyng = thynk.</NOTE></L>
<L>Sen &thorn;e tyme &thorn;at I af kepyd it here".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ai ansuerd &amp; sayd: "nay,</L>
<L>&THORN;is blode we wyll bere wyt vs</L>
<L N="135">And ordan nyt in a better aray,</L>
<L>For &thorn;e lufe of suete Jhesus".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>To &thorn;e Iue &thorn;ai gan forthe reche,</L>
<L>&THORN;e holy blode &thorn;ai tok fro hym onone.</L>
<L>&THORN;an lost he bothe syght &amp; speche</L>
<L N="140">&amp; fel downe to powdyre, dede as a stone,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>As he had bene dede a hundered &yogh;ere before &mdash;</L>
<L>No no&thorn;er thyng of hym left &thorn;er was.</L>
<L>&THORN;an dyd &thorn;is Emperours sygh reght sore,</L>
<L>For a grete merwell to &thorn;am it was,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="145">And so godys worde may not esterte<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. esterte = aetsterte etsterte.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at in hys gospell wrytyn is:</L>
<L>"Were es &thorn;i tresure, &thorn;er es &thorn;i harte".</L>
<L>And &thorn;at was prowyd &thorn;er, I-wys:<NOTE PLACE="foot">a. R.: Vbi thesaurus, ibi cor tuum erit.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For alle hys tresure was in &thorn;at holy blode allone</L>
<L N="150">&THORN;at he had kepyd for hys solace;</L>
<L>Nedys most hym dy, wen it was gone.</L>
<L>&amp; so god toke hym to a no&thorn;er place.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Thys blode &thorn;ai toke, &thorn;is Emperours,</L>
<L>Wyt &thorn;e vernakylle and o&thorn;er relykys &thorn;at in &thorn;e tempul were,</L>
<L N="155">And broght &thorn;am to Rome wyt gret honours</L>
<L>To &thorn;e tempull of pes, &amp; sette &thorn;am &thorn;ere &mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>As saynt Jerom wyttyns wele Iwys<NOTE PLACE="foot">wyttyns v. witnen, altisl. vitna, testify.</NOTE></L>
<L>In &thorn;e exposicione of &thorn;e prophete Johell &mdash;</L>
<L>And he &thorn;at will not trow on &thorn;is,</L>
<L N="160">Seke &thorn;e bok, &amp; &thorn;er he may fynd hym well.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. hym st. hyt.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;is holy blode, &thorn;e vernakylle &amp; &thorn;e cir|cumsicione</L>
<L>In &thorn;e tempul of pes were done at Rome,</L>
<L>And &thorn;er here haldyn wyt grete deuocione<NOTE PLACE="foot">here = ere.</NOTE></L>
<L>To Charls, &thorn;e grete Emperour, come.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="165">&THORN;is Charles partyd &thorn;is holy blode in|two:</L>
<L>To Almayne wyt hym a part he brogh</L>
<L>In-to &thorn;e castell Triuelence, he ordand it so,</L>
<L>In grete worchep, as hym gode thogh.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And &thorn;er it was many a &yogh;ere in &thorn;at castell,</L>
<L N="170">In grete worchep &amp; hee deuocione,
<PB REF="00000416.tif" N="278"></L>
<L>Wyt o&thorn;er relykys fayre &amp; well,</L>
<L>Tyll Frederyk &thorn;e Emperours dere sone.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Wylke onone aftyre hys coronacione</L>
<L>Wold not aftyre godys lawes wyrk,</L>
<L N="175">Bot wyt Romanes de-batyd vppe &amp; downe</L>
<L>And wered agane &thorn;e popes holy kyrk.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And so &thorn;e Empyre woyde stode</L>
<L>Many &yogh;eres, I say certayne.</L>
<L>To Rycherd, kyng Jone sone, of ryall blode,</L>
<L N="180">Was chosyn to be kynge of Almayne.&mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;us endys pope Vrbane story,</L>
<L>Wyt &thorn;at he made bothe fare &amp; gode.<NOTE PLACE="foot">made durch einen Fleck nicht leserlich. wyt ist zu tilgen?</NOTE></L>
<L>Now most vs hawe to memory</L>
<L>How kyng Rychere sone comme to &thorn;is holy blode.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="185">&THORN;is Ric(herd) &thorn;e thyrd, kyng Herres brothere he was<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. Ric<GAP>.</NOTE></L>
<L>And in hys tyme Eryll of Cornewayle,</L>
<L>&THORN;e abbay of Hayles he fownded in &thorn;at place,</L>
<L>And &thorn;er he es beryd wyt-outyn fayle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Edmunde, hys sone be ryght herethage,</L>
<L N="190">Wyt hys fadyre wyt-outyn fayle</L>
<L>In-to Almane he tok &thorn;e passage</L>
<L>And &thorn;edyre-warde faste gane he sayle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Now wen &thorn;is Rychard was crowned kyng<NOTE PLACE="foot">renyd = regnyd.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; renyd in Almane wyt ryalte,</L>
<L N="195">Edmunde was in &thorn;e castyll duellyng</L>
<L>And luffed wyt al men of euery degre,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And specyally wyt &thorn;e steuerd, syre Warynere,</L>
<L>&THORN;at lufed hym for hys amabully porte;</L>
<L>He sofurd hym in &thorn;e castell bothe fere &amp; nere</L>
<L N="200">To walke were he wolde for hys dysporte.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;is Warynere was keper of Tryuelence castelle,</L>
<L>Stwarde &amp; gouernour of &thorn;e Emperours fee.</L>
<L>He had a sone &thorn;at he luffed welle,</L>
<L>&THORN;at hyght Rodyger, &amp; suld hys ayre be.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="205">&THORN;e trew tale (I) telle &amp; none nothyre.<NOTE PLACE="foot">I fehlt im Ms.</NOTE></L>
<L>Rodeger luffed Edmunde so welle:</L>
<L>He had hym abowte ryght as hys brothere,</L>
<L>To se alle &thorn;at was in &thorn;at ryche castelle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;er he saw relykes &amp; Juels many one</L>
<L N="210">And &thorn;e Emperours apparell, &thorn;e sothe forto say.</L>
<L>Bot emang &thorn;am all &thorn;er was one,</L>
<L>Closyd wyt pure golde in ryche aray,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Wyt chenes of golde wone a-bowte,</L>
<L>Wyt lokys set on euere syde.</L>
<L N="215">Wat &thorn;at myght be, he hade gret doute,</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;at fro Rodiger he wold not hyde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; has &thorn;ay ware on a day walkynge,<NOTE PLACE="foot">wone = wound.</NOTE></L>
<L>Edmunde gan Rodiger besyly affrayn<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. affrayn, a. R. refrene(?) von ders. Hand als Correctur.</NOTE></L>
<L>To telle hym wate maner of thynge</L>
<L N="220">Was lokyd so fast wyt &thorn;e golde chene.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Syre, he sayd, a precious thyng it is,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. es in is corr.</NOTE></L>
<L>For it es all cristyn mens fode:</L>
<L>Of oure lorde Cristys blode it (es), iwys,<NOTE PLACE="foot">es fehlt.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at he chedde o-pone &thorn;e holy rode,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="225">&THORN;at was schedde on gode-frayday<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. frayday st. fryday.</NOTE></L>
<L>In saluacyon of all man-kynde;</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;er-for it passe all o&thorn;er in aray,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;us we af it in mynde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Wylk kyng Cherlys, &thorn;e grete con|querour,</L>
<L N="230">Ordand hedyre be grete maystry,</L>
<L>Wyles he was hee Emperour</L>
<L>And chewef cheftayne of chewalry.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And wen &thorn;e Emperour crowned is,</L>
<L>Aboute hys nek it sall be done,</L>
<L N="235">For it passe all o&thorn;er I-wys</L>
<L>&THORN;at bene wyt-in crystyndome.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And sen hys tyme here as it be<NOTE PLACE="foot">as = has.</NOTE></L>
<L>Alle tymes kepyd in grete honour.
<PB REF="00000417.tif" N="279"></L>
<L>And wen &yogh;e wyll, &yogh;e sall it se,</L>
<L N="240">For &thorn;e precyoust thyng wyt-in &thorn;is tourre."<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. toure nebst Abbrev. f&uuml;r ur.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;an was Edmunde full glad &amp; blythe,</L>
<L>Of hys purpos he hopyd to spede.</L>
<L>He thankyd hym full fele sythe</L>
<L>And sayd he wyld quyte hym is mede,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="245">Wyt &thorn;at he wolde to hys fadyre spek,</L>
<L>&amp; hys frende faythefully for to be,</L>
<L>A porcyon of it hym to gete,</L>
<L>If-all it were bot lytyll in quantyte.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Rodiger answered and sayd: "in fay,</L>
<L N="250">For &thorn;at &yogh;e be so gentyll &amp; fre,</L>
<L>At my fadyre sone I sall a-say;</L>
<L>I hope wyt hym to make &yogh;our gre."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;an wolde not Edmunde no langare abyde</L>
<L>And tendyrely prayd to &thorn;is knyght,</L>
<L N="255">And Rodeger also opon hys syde<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. als od. also? corr. aus all.</NOTE></L>
<L>Halpe wele aftyre, bothe day &amp; nyght.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>So at reuerance of hys fadyre, &thorn;e kyng,</L>
<L>&amp; for Eryll Edmunde was so gentylle &amp; gode,</L>
<L>&THORN;e knygh hym grawnte hys askyng</L>
<L N="260">And gafe hym a porcyon of &thorn;e holy blode.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;er-wyt he toke hym a story gode</L>
<L>&THORN;at pope Vrbane &thorn;e ferthe made</L>
<L>In worscepe of &thorn;at oly blode,</L>
<L>To make alle cristyn pepull glade &mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="265">Wylke story es be-fore tolde,</L>
<L>For &yogh;e suld not trowe a-mys.</L>
<L>Bot euere man in hart be bolde</L>
<L>&THORN;e trewthe to telle after &thorn;is.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Onone &thorn;an Edmunde in a wesyll honest,</L>
<L N="270">&THORN;at he had ordan rede &thorn;er-fore,<NOTE PLACE="foot">rede = redy.</NOTE></L>
<L>A-bowte hys necke before on hys brest</L>
<L>A-rayde it, in-to Yngland to be bore.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;an Edmunde hym thanked, as he wele cowthe,</L>
<L>For &thorn;at tresure &amp; &thorn;at ryches,</L>
<L N="275">Bothe wyt hart &amp; also wyt mowthe,</L>
<L>As he &thorn;at cowthe of Jentyllnes.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Of &thorn;e kyng, hys fadyre, hys lewe he toke,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e knyght and o&thorn;er lordes also,</L>
<L>As it es wrytyn in hys boke,</L>
<L N="280">And heed hym in-to Inglande for-to go.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Wen he was commen in-to Inglande fayre &amp; welle,</L>
<L>He heed hym blythe bothe day &amp; nyght</L>
<L>To he come to Wallyngford castelle,</L>
<L>Wylke was hys awne duellyng-place be ryght.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="285">&THORN;ere he kepyd hyt in grete honour,</L>
<L>To-tyme he had takyn hys a-wyce</L>
<L>Wedyre he myght gyf &thorn;at grete tresour</L>
<L>To grete encres of godys serwyce.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Of &thorn;e abbay of Hayles grete was hys thoght,</L>
<L N="290">Ware-of (hys) fadyre fownder was,</L>
<L>And &thorn;edyre hys body soulde be broght,</L>
<L>To be beryed in &thorn;at fayre place;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And dame Senche, &thorn;e quene so bryght,</L>
<L>&THORN;at was Edmundes modyre welle dere,</L>
<L N="295">Sulde be beryed &thorn;are be ryght,</L>
<L>Hys fadyre &amp; scho bothe in-fere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;edyre-warde he made hys ordynaunce,</L>
<L>Wyt hys men&yogh;e bothe more &amp; lasse:</L>
<L>&THORN;er-wyt he wylde &thorn;e abbay a-waunce,</L>
<L N="300">Are &thorn;at he wolde &thorn;enes passe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Wen he was nere &thorn;at abbay, so wele dyght,</L>
<L>In Wynchecombe abbay, &thorn;at was &thorn;er ney,</L>
<L>&THORN;are he logede hym all &thorn;at nyght,</L>
<L>As &thorn;e boke vs telles full truly.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="305">On &thorn;e morne &thorn;e abbot &amp; couent wyt|outyn drede</L>
<L>Oute of &thorn;e abbay wyt grete deuocyone</L>
<L>Wente wyt &thorn;e Eryle to Rowlay mede</L>
<L>Full honestly wyt &thorn;er processyone,
<PB REF="00000418.tif" N="280"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And &thorn;edyre come &thorn;e abbot &amp; &thorn;e couent of Hayle</L>
<L N="310">Wyt &thorn;are processyon ful honestly,</L>
<L>And &thorn;are resaywed hym wyt-outyn fayle</L>
<L>Full fayre &amp; also full worchefully.<NOTE PLACE="foot">worchefully st. worschepfully.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;are was onone a tente vppe-pyght,</L>
<L>In lordys maner, full ryall &amp; gay,</L>
<L N="315">And a fayre auter &thorn;er-wyt-in was dyght</L>
<L>Wyt clothes of golde &amp; o&thorn;er ryche aray.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Tythynges were sprong &thorn;e contre all a-bowte,</L>
<L>In-to dyuerse place, bothe fare &amp; wyde.</L>
<L>&THORN;edyre come pepull a full grete rowte,</L>
<L N="320">Rennyg forthe be euere syde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Onone a sermone was sayd &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>&THORN;at dyde &thorn;e pepull full mekyll gode:</L>
<L>&THORN;are he exponyde all &thorn;e matere</L>
<L>How Eryll Edmunde gate &thorn;is precyus blode.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="325">And &thorn;e pepull kneled all downe</L>
<L>And hally thankyd god all-myght.</L>
<L>Onone &thorn;e Erylle wyt grete dewocyone</L>
<L>Lete schew &thorn;e blode in all mens syght.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;are &thorn;ai myght se men bothe lagh &amp; wepe &mdash;</L>
<L N="330">&THORN;ai ware so ioyfull of &thorn;at syght;</L>
<L>Sum on &thorn;er knes &thorn;an gan crepe</L>
<L>To do it worchep, at it was ryght.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And wen all &thorn;is was &thorn;us-gate do,</L>
<L>Bothe abbotes &amp; couentes wyt-owtyn fayle,</L>
<L N="335">And &thorn;e blyssyd Erylle wyt &thorn;am also,</L>
<L>Went wyt processyon ewen forthe to Hayle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ay&thorn;er couent toke a syde of &thorn;e quere,</L>
<L>Wyt melody, Joy and syngyng.</L>
<L>&THORN;e abbottes went wyt Eryll to &thorn;e hee|autere:</L>
<L N="340">&THORN;at bare &thorn;at swete blode for hys offerryng.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>On holy-rode-day in herwest, &thorn;e sothe to say,</L>
<L>Was done all &thorn;is solempnyte.</L>
<L>&THORN;e abbot of Wynchecombe toke home hys way</L>
<L>And hys couent wyt hym, fayre fre.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="345">&THORN;e &yogh;ere of oure lordes in-carnacyone</L>
<L>A thowsant two hundered thre score &amp; tenne.</L>
<L>Bot aftyre &thorn;at Eryll Edmundes dewo|cyone</L>
<L>Was more to &thorn;e abbay of Hayles &thorn;enne:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For &thorn;e holy blode dyd slyke reuerance:</L>
<L N="350">He bygyd a chapelle &thorn;er fayre, wyt fywe auteres abowte;</L>
<L>Opon &thorn;am he spared no spence, &mdash;</L>
<L>For &thorn;ai be ryall enoght wyt-in &amp; wyt|owte.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A schryne he made also, a nobull &amp; a ryche,</L>
<L>Of golde &amp; syluur &amp; precyous stones &mdash;</L>
<L N="355">In Yngland &thorn;er were bot few hym lyche,</L>
<L>For it was ordand for &thorn;e nones.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And syr Godfray Gyfford, byschope of Wyrceterre,</L>
<L>At &thorn;at Eryll Instance and hys prayere</L>
<L>He heloed &thorn;at place, to be &thorn;e better,<NOTE PLACE="foot">heloed = hallowed.</NOTE></L>
<L N="360">And also gret (pardon) he grawnte &thorn;ere:<NOTE PLACE="foot">pardon? Das Wort ist absichtlich durchstrichen, wie pope u. Urban an and. Stellen.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e thursday aftere &thorn;e trinite, verament,</L>
<L>&THORN;at holy es &amp; haldyn fra &yogh;ere to &yogh;ere</L>
<L>At reuerance of &thorn;at holy sacramente</L>
<L>Wyt all cristyn pepull, bothe fere &amp; nere,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="365">&THORN;e &yogh;ere of oure lordes Incarnacyone</L>
<L>A thowsand tw(o) honderyd thre score &amp; sewentene.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. tw.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wylk day for oure saluacione</L>
<L>All cristyn pepull heloy(n), as I wene.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. heloy.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Wen god dos merakylles fro day to day
<PB REF="00000419.tif" N="281"></L>
<L N="370">Thro wertu of hys blode precyous &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">vor blode ist precyos auspunktirt.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;er may no-man &thorn;ere-of say nay,</L>
<L>For &thorn;ai bene all day so plentwous.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Dede bodys be &thorn;ere raysyd to lywe,</L>
<L>&THORN;e defe &thorn;are take &thorn;er heryng a-ryght,</L>
<L N="375">&THORN;e lame men go &thorn;ens full blythe,</L>
<L>&THORN;e blynd takyn &thorn;are &thorn;er hee-syght,<NOTE PLACE="foot">hee = eye.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; not onely syght of bodyly,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. body ly st. bodyly sc. eyes.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bot of &thorn;e saule also &thorn;at in synne.<NOTE PLACE="foot">es fehlt.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;er be few days, sartanly,</L>
<L N="380">Bot sum slyke folke af bote &thorn;er-inne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Saynt Paule says in hys sentence,</L>
<L>And in hys pystyll &yogh;e may it rede:</L>
<L>&THORN;at Cristes blode mas clene &thorn;e concyence<NOTE PLACE="foot">mas = makes.</NOTE></L>
<L>Fro all warkes &thorn;at here dede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="385">Here-of we af prowes fulle gode</L>
<L>&THORN;at ere prowyd all day be experyence:</L>
<L>For &thorn;er be many &thorn;at mow not se &thorn;at holy blode</L>
<L>To &thorn;ai af puryd &thorn;er concyance.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ware-for, all pyllgryms, I &yogh;ow rede</L>
<L N="390">Clene schrywyn &thorn;at &yogh;e be,</L>
<L>Off worde, of thoght, &amp; also of dede,</L>
<L>Or &yogh;e presume it for-to se.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And yf &yogh;e be grewyd wyt any doyng,</L>
<L>A penytancere es all-way redy &thorn;are.</L>
<L N="395">And &thorn;er-fore, spare &yogh;e for nothyng</L>
<L>To clens &yogh;owre sawle wyt gode chere!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;us endys &thorn;e story wyt-outyn fayle</L>
<L>Of Erylle Edmunde, &thorn;at knyght so gode,</L>
<L>How he broght to &thorn;e abbay of Hayle</L>
<L N="400">&THORN;e swete &amp; &thorn;e holy precyous blode.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="8" TYPE="legend"><PB REF="00000420.tif" N="[282]">
<HEAD>8. Vita S. Etheldredae Eliensis,
aus Ms. Cotton. Faustina B. III, fol. 260 (c. 1420). (Dialect von Wiltshire.)</HEAD> <HEADNOTE><P>Ms. Cotton. Faust. B. III, fol., perg., 280 foll., aus verschiedenen Mss. zusammen|gesetzt, enth&auml;lt in der letzten H&auml;lfte:</P><P>1) Cantariae et prioratus Wiltoniensis fundatio et incrimentum rithmis angli|canis, res ab Egberto Rege suo more conectit autor, sed demum in s. Edithae vitam et miracula se totum mutat (so der Titel im Index des Ms.), fol. 194&mdash;259. Es ist die Legende der h. Editha, deren erster Theil die Chronik von Wilton Priory, beginnend mit der Geschichte der wests&auml;chs. K&ouml;nige von Egbert ab, umfasst. Nach fol. 205 fehlen leider 12 foll., die die Geburt und Erziehung Editha's ent|hielten. Am Schlusse ist ein lat. Appendix angef&uuml;gt mit dem Namen der Funda|toren und Donatoren der k&ouml;niglichen Abtei in Wilton, der mit "Henricus (V) nobilissi|mus rex, filius Henrici IV", dem mit der Abfassung des Gedichtes gleichzeitigen K&ouml;nige schliesst; und eine lat. Liste der Quellen des Dichters. Diese Leg. ist edirt von H. Black u. d. T.: Chronicon Vilodunense sive de vita et miraculis s. Edi|thae, regis Edgari filiae, 1830.</P><P>2) Die hier zum ersten Male gedruckte Legende von S. Etheldreda Eliensis, fol. 260&mdash;280; der Schluss ist leider im Ms. ausgefallen. Auch diese Leg. beginnt der Dichter "suo more" mit einer geschichtlichen Einleitung. &mdash; Beide Legenden sind Werke desselben Dichters, in demselben Dialecte, in demselben Metrum und der|selben Strophenform geschrieben. Der Dichter war ohne Zweifel einer der Geist|lichen der Abtei von Wilton, der w&auml;hrend der Regierung Heinrich's V. lebte und schrieb (c. 1420). Der Dialect ist der wests&auml;chsische von Wiltshire, der die vollen Endungen des Angels&auml;chsischen (d. i. der wests&auml;chs. Schriftsprache) noch theilweise bewahrte. Das Ms. ist wahrscheinlich die Originalschrift des Dichters selber, der auch die nicht seltenen Correcturen zu verschiedenen Zeiten eingetragen zu haben scheint; in Etheldrede scheint jedoch auf dem letzten fol. mit v. 1111 eine andere Hand zu beginnen, die den Schluss sp&auml;ter nachgetragen. Seine Quelle f&uuml;gt der gelehrte Dichter am Rande bei; so steht neben v. 117 in S. Etheldrede die Notiz: Cron. ecclesiastic. sanct Bede libro li cap. 17, neben v. 161: Beda libro et capitulo predictis; in S. Editha sind die Quellen nicht allein am Rande angemerkt, sondern am Ende nochmals in einer Liste zusammengestellt u. d. T.: Ista autorum sunt nomina de quorum libris et autoritatibus exilis materia istius libelli est extracta &amp; compilata. &mdash; Beide Legenden sind h&ouml;chst wichtige Denkm&auml;ler des wests&auml;chs. Dialectes. Die lange Legende der Editha, die ich nochmals nach der Hs. copirt habe, werde ich an einem anderen Orte mittheilen, da der Raum nicht erlaubt, sie hier aufzunehmen.</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>(S)euene kyndamus with-inne &thorn;is lond somme-tyme &thorn;er were</L>
<L>And seuene kyngys with-inne hem &thorn;ere regnede also:</L>
<L>&THORN;e wheche strevyn &amp; werryde euer y-ffere,</L>
<L>Til &thorn;e sixe kyndamus to &thorn;e kyndam of Westsexe weron knytto.
<PB REF="00000421.tif" N="283"></L>
<L N="5">&THORN;e kyndam of Kent first conquered hit was</L>
<L>By Hengestis and Orsus, his brother dere;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Orsus v. ders. H. &uuml;berschr.</NOTE></L>
<L>And so of Kent none other kyng bot Hengestys &thorn;er nas</L>
<L>&THORN;e mountenesse of two and thretty full &yogh;ere.</L>
<L>And with-inne &thorn;at kyndam twey bisshoperiche &thorn;ere were,</L>
<L N="10">Who-so wolle in story rede or se hit:</L>
<L>&THORN;e archebisshoperyche of Canterbury &amp; Rouchestre y-fere &mdash;</L>
<L>And ry&yogh;t in &thorn;e same manere &thorn;ey ben &thorn;er &yogh;ytte.</L>
<L>After &thorn;e Incarnacyon forsothe hit was</L>
<L>Foure hondrethe &yogh;ere fyfty &amp; fyue weren went,</L>
<L N="15">Or duke Hengestys hadde my&yogh;t or grace</L>
<L>To ben made &thorn;e kyng of Kent.</L>
<L>&amp; thre hondreth &amp; ay&yogh;ty &amp; sixsty &yogh;ere</L>
<L>Hit stode euer stylle in his prosperite,</L>
<L>Till kyng Egbert of Westsex hadde wonnon hit with were:</L>
<L N="20">For bothe kyng of Kent &amp; Westsex &thorn;e first was he.</L>
<L>And fyftene kyngus regnede after &thorn;ere</L>
<L>From Hengestis to kyng Egberde, as ychaue redde,<NOTE PLACE="foot">kyng v. ders. H. &uuml;berschr.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e wheche kepton hit euer alle holle y-ffere,</L>
<L>Tille kyng Aldrede was by Egberde put ou&yogh;t &amp; dedde.</L>
<L N="25">Sowthesex &thorn;e secund kyndam hit was:</L>
<L>&THORN;e wheche dured bot a litylle while y-wys;</L>
<L>And Elle &thorn;e first kyng of Sowthesex was by grace</L>
<L>&amp; regnyd &thorn;ere, he &amp; his thre sonys.</L>
<L>&THORN;e threttythe &yogh;ere after &thorn;e comyng in of Hengestys</L>
<L N="30">&THORN;e kyndam of Sowthsex toke his bygynnynge, as ychaue redde,</L>
<L>And fyue kyngys &thorn;ere regnede after y-wys,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;e sexsth kyng was putte ou&yogh;t &amp; dedde.</L>
<L>&THORN;e kyngdam of Estsex &thorn;e thrydde was &thorn;o.</L>
<L>In &thorn;e whyche regnede ten kyngus y-wys,</L>
<L N="35">From &thorn;e first kyng &thorn;at regnede &thorn;ere, his name was Segeberto,</L>
<L>In-to &thorn;e commyng inne of &thorn;e Denmarkys.</L>
<L>Vpon &thorn;e est-syde &thorn;is kyndam hadde &thorn;e see,</L>
<L>Vpon &thorn;e west-syde &thorn;e contrey of London y-wys,</L>
<L>Vpon &thorn;e sowthe-syde &thorn;e water of Temse hadde he,</L>
<L N="40">Vpon &thorn;e northe-syde Sowthefolke, &thorn;e story saythe &thorn;is.</L>
<L>&THORN;e fourthe kyndam Westsexe was y-clepte &thorn;o.</L>
<L>&THORN;e whyche nas neuer &yogh;et y-wonne y-wys,</L>
<L>Till Willyham Conquerour &thorn;is lond come to;</L>
<L>And &yogh;et in gret asperite stondyng hit is.</L>
<L N="45">Vpon &thorn;e est-side Sowthesex he hadde y-wys,</L>
<L>And vpone &thorn;e northe-syde &thorn;e water of Temse hadde he,</L>
<L>Bot vpon &thorn;e sowthe-side &amp; &thorn;e west-syde, as hit y-writon ys,</L>
<L>Forsothe hit hadde &thorn;e grette sowthe-see.</L>
<L>In &thorn;e whyche kyndam first regnede kyng
<PB REF="00000422.tif" N="284"></L>
<L N="50">&THORN;e gode duke Cerdyke, as ychaue redde,</L>
<L>With his owne sone, syre Kynerynge:</L>
<L>&THORN;use tweyne kepton &thorn;at kyndam, tylle &thorn;ey were dedde.</L>
<L>In &thorn;e fyuethhondreth &amp; &thorn;e ay&yogh;tethe &yogh;ere after &thorn;at goddus sone was bore</L>
<L>&THORN;is kyndam of Westsex toke furst his bygynnynge,</L>
<L N="55">&amp; sey&yogh;th wonne &thorn;e to&thorn;er sexe kyndamus to hym with strong werre &amp; sore</L>
<L>By grace of &thorn;e kyngys &thorn;ere so welle gouernynge.</L>
<L>&THORN;e kyndam of &thorn;e Marche &thorn;e fyuethe was.</L>
<L>&THORN;e whiche was &thorn;e greste kyndam of hem alle y-fere,</L>
<L>&THORN;e greste kyndam of alle hit was in space.</L>
<L N="60">Kyng Penda was &thorn;e first kynge &thorn;at regnede &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>&THORN;e lymytys of &thorn;is kyndam &thorn;ey strey&yogh;then y-wys</L>
<L>From &thorn;e water of Dee on &thorn;e west-syde Cheyster, &thorn;at fayre cyte,</L>
<L>Douneby &thorn;e water of Seuerne, &thorn;e whiche by Shrewysbury rennyng is,</L>
<L>And euene to Brystowe in-to &thorn;e sowthe-see,</L>
<L N="65">And othe sowthe-syde euene by Temse to Londone rau&yogh;te he,</L>
<L>And on &thorn;e northe-syde by &thorn;e water of Humbre hit come with-ou&yogh;t fayle,</L>
<L>&amp; strey&yogh;th so forthe sowthewarde to &thorn;e water of Mercie</L>
<L>Euene in-to &thorn;e west-see, fast by Corunwayle.</L>
<L>In &thorn;e sixehundryd &yogh;ere &amp; sixe &amp; twenty forsothe hit was</L>
<L N="70">After &thorn;at Jhesu of his modur Marie was bore,</L>
<L>&THORN;at kyng Penda wonne &thorn;at kyndam to hym by case</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e Britones, &thorn;e wheche weron kyngus &thorn;er byfore.</L>
<L>Abou&yogh;t two hundreth &yogh;ere sixsty and thre</L>
<L>&THORN;at kyndam stode in grete prosperite, as ichaue redde,</L>
<L N="75">Vndere &thorn;e gouerneylle of ay&yogh;thetene kyngus fre,</L>
<L>In-to &thorn;e tyme &thorn;at kyng Colwolfe by &thorn;e Danys was put ou&yogh;t &amp; dedde.</L>
<L>Bot kyng Egbert wonne &thorn;at kyndam at &thorn;e last</L>
<L>And to his kyndam of Westsex he hit knytte</L>
<L>And ou&yogh;t of &thorn;at kyndam &thorn;e Danys ou&yogh;t thraste.<MILESTONE N="261" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="80">And so to &thorn;e kyndom of Westsex y-knytte hit is &yogh;ette.</L>
<L>&THORN;e kyndam of Northumbrelonde &thorn;e sixste kyndam was.</L>
<L>&THORN;e whiche vpon &thorn;e est-syde &amp; also vpon &thorn;e west-syde had &thorn;e sowthe-se,</L>
<L>&amp; vpon &thorn;e sowth-syde of Humbre hit last doune a gret space</L>
<L>By &thorn;e hendys of Derbyshyre &amp; Notynghamshyre to &thorn;e water of Mercye,</L>
<L N="85">&amp; vpon &thorn;e north-syde &thorn;e mere &thorn;er-of ystrey&yogh;t ys</L>
<L>Euene in-to &thorn;e scottysshe grete se.</L>
<L>&THORN;e prouynce of Deyre &amp; of Beruice with-inne &thorn;at kyndam &thorn;ey ben y-wys,</L>
<L>In &thorn;e whyche &thorn;e Pictis weron y-wonte to be.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Danys also dwelton &thorn;ere long, with-ou&yogh;te ony dou&yogh;te,</L>
<L N="90">Tylle kyng Athelstone, &thorn;at dou&yogh;ty kny&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Draffe all &thorn;e enmyus &thorn;at weron in &thorn;at contrey, ou&yogh;te,</L>
<L>With strong batelle &amp; with gret my&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;e seuethe kyndam of Estenglonde was y-wys,</L>
<L>&THORN;e whiche conteynede Northfolk &amp; Sowthefolke botwo.</L>
<L N="95">&THORN;e whiche hathe on &thorn;e est-syde &amp; on &thorn;e north-syde, as hit ywriton is,</L>
<L>&THORN;e see o compas euene, Cambrygeshire to,
<PB REF="00000423.tif" N="285"></L>
<L>&amp; on &thorn;e westsyde Edmundus-borwe forsothe hit is,</L>
<L>&amp; on &thorn;e sowthesyde Hertfordeshire &amp; Essex also.</L>
<L>&THORN;is was &thorn;e compas of &thorn;at litulle kyndam y-wys</L>
<L N="100">Inne &thorn;e tyme when Englonde was dypartyd so.</L>
<L>Ten englysshe kyngus regnedyne ychone after other in &thorn;at londe,</L>
<L>Bot euery kyng werred with other fulle fast.</L>
<L>Bot when &thorn;e Danys hadden y-slawe seynt Edmunde,</L>
<L>&THORN;ey dwelleden &thorn;er hem-self &thorn;o a-last.</L>
<L N="105">Tille Edwarde senior, &thorn;at worthy kny&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Draffe &thorn;e Denmarkys ou&yogh;t of &thorn;at londe</L>
<L>&amp; wonne hit to &thorn;e kyndam of Westsex with strenght &amp; my&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And alle his lyue-dayes hult hit in his honde.</L>
<L>Bot of &thorn;use seuene kyndamus now wolle y nomore &yogh;ow telle,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. kymdamus.</NOTE></L>
<L N="110">By-cause &thorn;at &thorn;e processe is of gret lenge&thorn;.</L>
<L>Bot of a kyng &thorn;at &thorn;erinne somme-tyme dude dwelle</L>
<L>Somme-what to &yogh;ow of hym to speke we thenge&thorn;. &mdash;</L>
<L>In &thorn;e sixsthe hondryde &amp; sixste &yogh;ere &thorn;at goddus sone was bore</L>
<L>A worthy childe was y-bore in Estenglonde &thorn;anne,</L>
<L N="115">&THORN;e whiche was kyng afterwarde euene &thorn;ore:</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;at childus name was y-clepte &thorn;o Anne.</L>
<L>Bot afterwarde when he was y-growe to monnus age,<NOTE PLACE="foot">a. R. steht Hic incipit vita s. Etheldrede. Cron. ecclesiast. sancti Bede l. li, cap. 17 (Quelle des Dichters).</NOTE></L>
<L>Of Estenglonde he was y-cronyd &thorn;ere kynge,</L>
<L>&amp; a wiff he weddede of hye lynage:</L>
<L N="120">A gode woman he was &amp; off gode leuynge.</L>
<L>And bi hurre he hadde &thorn;re deu&yogh;tre, &amp; nomo,</L>
<L>&THORN;e whiche weren wemmen after of gret honour:</L>
<L>Etheldrede men clepten &thorn;e ton of &thorn;o,</L>
<L>&THORN;e whiche was y-clepte afterwarde &thorn;e shynynge flour;</L>
<L N="125">Sexburga &thorn;e tothere men clepte also,</L>
<L>&THORN;e whiche quene of Kent afterwarde wase &mdash;</L>
<L>Bot blessude virgyns &thorn;ey weron in &yogh;outhe boto,</L>
<L>&amp; in hurre age fullyche forthe-fult &thorn;orow goddus grace;</L>
<L>Bot Adelburga &thorn;e thred was clepte &thorn;o y-wys:</L>
<L N="130">A full blessude virgyn he was also,</L>
<L>For ou&yogh;t ofe a blessude rote &thorn;is mayden y-sprongone ys:</L>
<L>For &thorn;is blessud mon kyng Anne was fadur off alle &thorn;o.</L>
<L>&THORN;e whiche kynge Pende, &thorn;at heretyke, slow with falsnesse,</L>
<L>&amp; so he slow his brother, Adelhere, with wrong also:</L>
<L N="135">&amp; so bothe &thorn;ey weron marters in &thorn;at case;</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;at holy mon, kyng Ine, sones &thorn;ey weren bothe to.</L>
<L>Bot Etheldrede, his dou&yogh;ter, he maryed, or he were dedde,</L>
<L>&amp; his dou&yogh;ter Sexburwe he maryede hym-self also;</L>
<L>Bot whethere his dou&yogh;ter Adelburwe were mariede, yna not redde,</L>
<L N="140">For y my&yogh;t not come hurre story in no plase to.
<PB REF="00000424.tif" N="286"></L>
<L>Bot anone after &thorn;at &thorn;is mayde Etheldrede was of age,</L>
<L>Hurre fadur and hurre modur gouernede hurre fulle wysly,</L>
<L>&amp; &yogh;euen herre anone after &thorn;at in-to a hey&yogh;e mariage</L>
<L>To a worthy prynce, &thorn;e whiche dwelt in &thorn;e contreuy ny&yogh;e hym by.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. contreny?</NOTE></L>
<L N="145">Men clepten &thorn;at prince Tonbert &thorn;o;</L>
<L>At &thorn;e toune of Peturborwe was his dwellynge,</L>
<L>&amp; of alle Gyrwy ys londe he was prince &thorn;o,</L>
<L>&THORN;at now is clepte &thorn;e valey of Petursborwe, with-ou&yogh;t lesynge.</L>
<L>&THORN;is prince Tonbert was a mone of gret honour,</L>
<L N="150">&amp; lord &amp; syre of mony a gret toune,</L>
<L>&amp; rychelyche endowyd with castelle &amp; toure,</L>
<L>&amp; a worshipfulle prince &amp; a lorde of gret renoune;</L>
<L>&amp; a fulle vertwys mon in leuyng forsothe he was,</L>
<L>Meke, trewe, and chast, &amp; no-thyng in hert prou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="155">&amp; a monfulle inou in tyme of nede in euery place:</L>
<L>For non enmy abou&yogh;t hym &thorn;at tyme durst rou&yogh;t.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Petur aus Petus corr.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;is mayde &thorn;at prince weddede in-to his wyff,</L>
<L>&amp; dwelt alyue with hurre ny&yogh;e &yogh;eres thre,</L>
<L>And louede hurre as durelyche as his owne lyff,</L>
<L N="160">And kepte fulle clene hurre virgynyte.<MILESTONE N="262" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Bot somme-what byfore &thorn;re &yogh;ere &thorn;is prince Tonbart,<NOTE PLACE="foot">a. R. Beda li. &amp; cap. predictis.</NOTE></L>
<L>As &thorn;e story dothe vs bothe wryte &amp; mene,</L>
<L>Dyede &amp; his soule from his body dude departe,</L>
<L>&amp; lafte his wyff alyue here, as he was bore, a mayde clene.</L>
<L N="165">&THORN;en was he wedow, &amp; also clene mayde y-wys,</L>
<L>&amp; long hadde be wyff also byfore &thorn;at.</L>
<L>Hurre fadur, &thorn;e kynge, fulle welle &thorn;o conseyuede &thorn;ys</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;o a nother gret mariage to hurre he gate:</L>
<L>For he &yogh;aff hurre sone after to a fulle worthy kynge,</L>
<L N="170">&THORN;e whiche to monfulnesse hadde fulle gret delyde.<NOTE PLACE="foot">dely de aus delite corr.</NOTE></L>
<L>He weddede &thorn;o &thorn;at mayde, &thorn;at semely thyng,</L>
<L>&amp; his name was clepte &thorn;o syre Egfryde.</L>
<L>He was bothe sone &amp; heyre to &thorn;is worthy kyng Oswy,</L>
<L>&amp; kyng of Northumbrelonde he was also;</L>
<L N="175">A fulle worthy kny&yogh;t he was, &amp; a fulle dou&yogh;ty,</L>
<L>&amp; a ful semely mon of persone he was &thorn;erto,</L>
<L>&amp; a fulle holi mon in leuynge also sothelyche he was</L>
<L>&amp; louede ry&yogh;t welle to serue his god, bothe day &amp; ny&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Bot with a fulle gode wylle &thorn;at mayde to his wyff he chas,</L>
<L N="180">&amp; louede hurre ry&yogh;t welle with alle his my&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&amp; so he dwelt with his wyff &yogh;erys XII.</L>
<L>Bot for alle &thorn;at he was euer a clene mayde.</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;erof he was witnesse hym-self,</L>
<L>For to seynt Wilfride &thorn;us he &thorn;o sayde:</L>
<L N="185">"Syre Wylfride, quad &thorn;e kyng, on thynge now hertly prey y &thorn;e &mdash;
<PB REF="00000425.tif" N="287"></L>
<L>For y knowe well &thorn;at &yogh;e mow do &thorn;at of ony mon best:</L>
<L>Conselle my wyff &thorn;at he wolde be here-after to me</L>
<L>Bothe meke &amp; myelde &amp; eke honeste!</L>
<L>For he hath ben XII &yogh;ere now with me</L>
<L N="190">A full clene mayden, as &yogh;e fulle welle done knowe;</L>
<L>Bot ry&yogh;t gret &yogh;yftus, Wylfride, ychulle &yogh;eue &thorn;e</L>
<L>To turne hurre hert otherweys, &yogh;if &thorn;at &yogh;e mowe.</L>
<L>For an heyre y cholde fayne haue bytwenes vs two,</L>
<L>To enheyrydde owre heye heritage,</L>
<L N="195">A childe or tweyn, &yogh;if god wolde &thorn;at hit shulde be so,</L>
<L>Now in owre bothe &yogh;onge freysshe age".</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;en seynt Wylfryde, &thorn;at worthy mon,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;use wordus he toke ry&yogh;t gode hede</L>
<L>&amp; full sone &thorn;o lokede &thorn;is holy mayde vpone.</L>
<L N="200">Forto speke &thorn;use wordus to hurre he hadde grette drede:</L>
<L>For he knew &thorn;at maydyns hert ry&yogh;t welle</L>
<L>And alle hurre purpose he knew welle also:</L>
<L>&THORN;at he nolde not abeye to suche werkus neuer a delle,<NOTE PLACE="foot">abeye = obey.</NOTE></L>
<L>For no conselle &thorn;at he couthe or my&yogh;t &yogh;eue herre to;</L>
<L N="205">For he knew ry&yogh;t welle &thorn;at &thorn;at holy blessede mayde</L>
<L>Was euer full stidfast both in hert &amp; &thorn;ou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;en anone to hem bothe he vnswerede &thorn;us &amp; to hem sayde:</L>
<L>"Syrus, se &yogh;e not ry&yogh;t welle &thorn;at &thorn;is worlde nys nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Bot euer fals and fyculle &amp; ry&yogh;t vnsadde</L>
<L N="210">To alle hem &thorn;e whiche trustone &thorn;erto?</L>
<L>Wherfore let vs here serue clene &thorn;at god &thorn;at vs hath made,</L>
<L>Styll in clannasse, as we herebyfore algatus han do,</L>
<L>And purchese we to owre soule &thorn;at hey&yogh;e heritage</L>
<L>&THORN;at we my&yogh;ten in heuene clene maydenus y-cronyd be &mdash;</L>
<L N="215">For, forsothe, &thorn;at is to vs most a-vantetage</L>
<L>To haue owre heritage in heuene with god in trinite.</L>
<L>Wherfore ordeyne we &thorn;er in heuene owre dwellyng,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;at owre soule may be &thorn;ere owre heyre</L>
<L>In &thorn;at blessud ioy &thorn;e whiche hath non endynge,</L>
<L N="220">And dwelle among &thorn;e angelis, &thorn;e whiche ben &thorn;ere so bry&yogh;te &amp; feyre;</L>
<L>And, gode syre, lette vs kepus here maydenus clene</L>
<L>&amp; serue here owre god euer in clannasse:</L>
<L>For mayden-hode is a ry&yogh;t gode mene</L>
<L>To bryng vs vp to &thorn;at blessude place.</L>
<L N="225">A full feyre abbay of maydenus, my lord so dere,</L>
<L>Is here-ny&yogh;e byside vs, as &yogh;e welle knowe,</L>
<L>And &yogh;our owne aunte, my lorde, is abbas &thorn;ere</L>
<L>And seruyd god bothe ny&yogh;t &amp; day with hert fulle lowe.</L>
<L>Bot wolde &yogh;e, my lorde, now &yogh;eue me leue</L>
<L N="230">To dwelle &thorn;ere in &thorn;at abbay &amp; serue god &thorn;er for aye,
<PB REF="00000426.tif" N="288"></L>
<L>My maydenhode, syre, y shulde nowe &yogh;eue</L>
<L>To hym &thorn;at made bothe ny&yogh;t &amp; eke day.<NOTE PLACE="foot">bothe &uuml;berschr.</NOTE></L>
<L>For he is welle &amp; founder of alle godenesse,</L>
<L>&amp; of mayden-hode &amp; of clene virginite,</L>
<L N="235">And euer with-ou&yogh;t bygynnyng with hym hit was</L>
<L>And with his blessud angels fayre and fre:</L>
<L>For of a mayde Jhesu for vs was y-bore</L>
<L>And toke monkynde in vrthe here alowe &mdash;</L>
<L>And ellus owre soules hade ben forlore.</L>
<L N="240">Wherfore to &yogh;eue hit to hym, hit were ry&yogh;t welle by-towe.</L>
<L>And for by-cause &thorn;at he louythe so well &thorn;ate order y-wys</L>
<L>Of clene mayden-hode, as y chaue &yogh;ow now y-sayde,</L>
<L>A feyrore lyf, forsothe, my lord, non &thorn;er nys:</L>
<L>Wherfore, gode sire,graunt me to don as ychan &yogh;ow sayde."</L>
<L N="245">&THORN;e kyng stode stylle &thorn;o &amp; spake ry&yogh;t nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Bot thonk god heylyche of his gret grace,</L>
<L>And conseyuede hit ry&yogh;t well &thorn;o in his &thorn;ou&yogh;t</L>
<L>And know hit ry&yogh;t welle also &thorn;at no better lyf &thorn;er nas,</L>
<L>Ny no-thyng more plesyngur to goddus wylle</L>
<L N="250">Non to kepe hem-self for goddus sake maydenus clene.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. non = nen 909 = than.</NOTE></L>
<L>And in his hert anone &thorn;o consendyd &thorn;ere-tylle</L>
<L>To &yogh;eue suche leue to Etheldrede, &thorn;e quene.</L>
<L>And anon to seynt Wylfride &thorn;is worthy kyng sayde &thorn;o:</L>
<L>"Take &thorn;ou my wyff, syre Wylfride, &thorn;is mayde clene,</L>
<L N="255">And professe hur to religiose: for I graunt ry&yogh;t welle &thorn;er-to,</L>
<L>Sey&yogh;th hit wolle by no wey non other weys bene."</L>
<L>And Wilfride was in his hert &thorn;o ry&yogh;t well a-payde</L>
<L>And &thorn;ongede god &thorn;er-of ofte &amp; fele sythe,</L>
<L>And professede he in-to &thorn;e abbay of Colndy &thorn;o &thorn;at holy mayde &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">he aus hurre corr.</NOTE></L>
<L N="260">Bot he &thorn;erof &thorn;o was full gladde &amp; eke fulle blythe.</L>
<L>And mynchyn he was made at Colndy &thorn;o anon y-wys &mdash;</L>
<L>Bot he dwelt &thorn;er litull more &thorn;en on &yogh;ere.</L>
<L>And he encressede euery day in so grete godenesse,</L>
<L>In gode leuyng, as &yogh;e shulle here-after well here. &mdash;</L>
<L N="265">A vertwys leuer he was euer byfore &thorn;at tyme y-wys</L>
<L>And gode werchus he wolde euer hurre-thongus werche,</L>
<L>And, as ferforthelyche as he couthe, he nolde neuer do amys,</L>
<L>Bot he louede euer ry&yogh;t welle god &amp; holy chirche;</L>
<L>Pore men he louede also euer ry&yogh;t welle</L>
<L N="270">And wolde fulle feyne hem bothe clothe &amp; fede,</L>
<L>And to alle gode werkus he was fulle swefte &amp; snelle,</L>
<L>And also seyntus lyues in boke he wolde fayne rede.<NOTE PLACE="foot">vor seyntus ist holy ausradirt.</NOTE></L>
<L>Fulle gladsom he was, &amp; neuer was he wrou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Among lordus in dalyans he was of fulle myelde chere;
<PB REF="00000427.tif" N="289"></L>
<L N="275">Bot, what mater &thorn;at he spake of, he nold swere non othe</L>
<L>And iche mon towarde godenesse he wolde fayne lere.</L>
<L>Ny in hurre aray he nas neuer prou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Bot clanliche in hurre clothyng, as a quene ou&yogh;t to be;</L>
<L>Ny of wordeliche dyseyse he nadde neuer dou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="280">Bot, what &thorn;at euer god hurre sende, mekeliche god &thorn;erof thonged he. &mdash;</L>
<L>Bot when he in &thorn;e abbay of Colndy mynchyn made was,</L>
<L>By &thorn;e gouerneylle of seynt Wilfride, as y sayde ere,</L>
<L>&THORN;ere as hurre sustre(!), dame Hebbe, was &thorn;o abbas &mdash;</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;ere he abode not lytull more &thorn;en on &yogh;ere &mdash;:</L>
<L N="285">Bot alle-bette &thorn;aw he had ben quene of &thorn;at lond a litille byfore,<NOTE PLACE="foot">alle-bette, auch 287, auch 287, = all-be-it.</NOTE></L>
<L>Folle mekeliche he wolde abyde in &thorn;e quere at euery tyde;</L>
<L>And alle-bette he were a kyngus dou&yogh;ter, of quene y-bore,</L>
<L>&YOGH;et hadde he neuer-&thorn;e-rathere no pore creature in dispitte;</L>
<L>As trewe he was euermore as ony stele,</L>
<L N="290">And meke &amp; myelde, with-ou&yogh;ten ony pride;</L>
<L>&THORN;e seruyse of almy&yogh;ty god he louede so welle</L>
<L>&THORN;at he wolde &thorn;er-inne euer hurre-thongus abyde.</L>
<L>He leuede &thorn;ere as clene as angell bry&yogh;t,</L>
<L>With ry&yogh;t gode louyng hert to euery mon;</L>
<L N="295">He sessede neuer, nowther day ny ny&yogh;t,</L>
<L>To serue well god &amp; to plese hurre sustren euerich-one.</L>
<L>Bot hurre godenesse encresede euery day:</L>
<L>Hurre gode leuyng was spoken of in londe full wyde.</L>
<L>&amp; for hurre vertwys leuyng, &thorn;at he vsede in &thorn;at abbay,</L>
<L N="300">Seynt Wilfride nolde not let hurre &thorn;er no lengur abyde.</L>
<L>Bot anone he was choson &amp; made abbas &thorn;o</L>
<L>In-to (&thorn;e) abbay of Hely &mdash; for in &thorn;at contrey he was ybore,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e fehlt.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;at abbay was made for hurre loue also.</L>
<L>&amp; seuene &yogh;ere after &thorn;at hit was bulte, he dwelte &thorn;ore,</L>
<L N="305">In muche worshippe and grete prosperite.</L>
<L>Bot after &thorn;at tyme &thorn;at he had vpon hurre take</L>
<L>&THORN;at worshippefull state of abbas dignite,</L>
<L>All wordelyche lustes full clene he dude forsake.</L>
<L>Bot after &thorn;at he was made abbas &thorn;ere</L>
<L N="310">Wyth-inne &thorn;e yle of Hely in &thorn;at fayre abbay,</L>
<L>Lynyn clothus werede he &thorn;ere neuer,<MILESTONE N="264" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Bot wollen clothus, both ny&yogh;t &amp; day;</L>
<L>Bot an here he werede euer hurre body nexst</L>
<L>Vndur hurre worshipfull clothus of herre honeste,</L>
<L N="315">With gret knottus of here hurre fleysshe was fexst,<NOTE PLACE="foot">fexst = vexed.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; thus he kepte hurre fleysshe so freyle from Jolyte.</L>
<L>Ny hote bathis, for-sothe, he nolde take none</L>
<L>In hote water, of fleysshelyche lustynasse &mdash;
<PB REF="00000428.tif" N="290"></L>
<L>Bot thre tymes in a &yogh;ere hit was hurre wone</L>
<L N="320">To wasshe hurre body &thorn;en for clannasse:</L>
<L>A&yogh;eyne &thorn;e hey&yogh;e worshipfull fest of Pasce</L>
<L>&amp; a&yogh;eyne &thorn;e fest of Pentecost &amp; of &thorn;e Epiphanye,</L>
<L>Euery &yogh;ere hurre wonne hit was</L>
<L>Thus to ben y-wasshe thrye,</L>
<L N="325">In presence of hurre sustren alle,</L>
<L>For euer to mekenesse he was prest;</L>
<L>Bot when hurre sustren hadden y-wasshede hem alle,</L>
<L>&THORN;en wolde he hurre-self be wasshe lest.</L>
<L>So meke and myelde forsothe he euere was,</L>
<L N="330">&amp; euer so clene, in worde and dede,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he &yogh;aff gode ensampull to more &amp; lasse</L>
<L>In gode leuyng hem-self euere to lede.</L>
<L>By full pore meytus he lyuede y-wys,</L>
<L>&amp; no day forsothe he neytte bot ene:</L>
<L N="335">Bredde &amp; ale &amp; fulle seylden feysshe;</L>
<L>And &thorn;us he kepte hurre body fulle lene.</L>
<L>And euery ny&yogh;t sothely in hurre owne stalle</L>
<L>First at mayteynys he wolde &thorn;ere be</L>
<L>And mekeliche clepe vp hurre sustren alle &mdash;</L>
<L N="340">&THORN;us meke &amp; &thorn;us myelde, forsothe, was he.</L>
<L>To bedde forsothe he nolde go after mayteynys nomore,</L>
<L>Bot in hurre preyours he wolde abyde &thorn;ere fulle stylle &mdash;</L>
<L>Bot &yogh;if gret heuynasse of sekenesse sore</L>
<L>Gretlyche constreynede hurre &thorn;er-tylle.</L>
<L N="345">And so in gret abstinaunce forsothe he leuede,</L>
<L>Off meyte and drynke and eke off clothynge;</L>
<L>For all hurre lust to god he &yogh;euede;</L>
<L>He seruede hym euer with all hurre my&yogh;t to his plesynge.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Dieser Vers ist unten nachgetragen, ohne Zeichen im Texte, und stand ausserdem nach 380, wo er durchstrichen.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bot as &thorn;is blessude virgyn satte thus in hurre preyours vpone a ny&yogh;t</L>
<L N="350">Alle hurre-self in hurre stalle full preuely &mdash;</L>
<L>And in a sconsce he hadde hurre candelle with hurre ly&yogh;t:</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;e cursede feynde come &thorn;edur &thorn;o &amp; blew hit ou&yogh;t sodenly.</L>
<L>And when hurre ly&yogh;t was &thorn;us sodenlylyche from hurre agone,</L>
<L>&YOGH;et satte he stylle ry&yogh;t &thorn;ere, ful sore afrey&yogh;t;</L>
<L N="355">Bot &thorn;en, to help hurre-self, he couthe non other won</L>
<L>Bot preyede to god, of his grace to send herre somme ley&yogh;t.</L>
<L>And anon as he hadde to god hurre preyours &thorn;us sayde,</L>
<L>To hurre &thorn;ere &thorn;o apparede fulle sodenliche an angelle bry&yogh;t</L>
<L>To help and comforde &thorn;er &thorn;o &thorn;at blessud mayde,</L>
<L N="360">And anon a&yogh;eynne hurre candelle dude he &thorn;o ly&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And sayde: "Maydyn, haue &yogh;e no drede of &thorn;is foule creature!</L>
<L>For god hathe ordeynede me, mayden, keper of the to be
<PB REF="00000429.tif" N="291"></L>
<L>And to be &thorn;y help, &thorn;y keper &amp; &thorn;i gouernoure:</L>
<L>Wherfore from alle his weketnesse ychulle, mayden, kepe &thorn;e."</L>
<L N="365">And when seynt Auudre had herd &thorn;is angelle &thorn;us speke &thorn;ore<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. A&umacr;dre.</NOTE></L>
<L>And also hadde y-seye with hurre ynon &thorn;at gret ly&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And hadde in &thorn;ou&yogh;t &thorn;e gret derkenesse &thorn;at he had y-seye byfore:</L>
<L>He thongud god &amp; &thorn;at angelle with alle hurre my&yogh;t: &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;en knew he in herre hert &thorn;o ry&yogh;t welle</L>
<L N="370">&THORN;at hit was a feynde &thorn;at blew so sodenlyche ou&yogh;t hurre ly&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And also &thorn;at &thorn;ere was y-sende from god a bry&yogh;t angelle</L>
<L>&THORN;at sone tende hurre candell a&yogh;eyne by goddus my&yogh;t;</L>
<L>He &thorn;ongede god &thorn;o mekeliche of his benigne grace</L>
<L>And hertlyche he blessede his powere &amp; eke his my&yogh;t.</L>
<L N="375">And euer after &thorn;e better wommon, forsothe, he was,</L>
<L>By-cause &thorn;at he hadde y-sey&yogh;e so &thorn;ere &thorn;at merueylle sy&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&amp; he louede god in hurre hert euer full welle</L>
<L>&amp; mekeliche seruede hym with gode werkus day &amp; ny&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And &yogh;aff to pore pepulle for his loue mony a meylle</L>
<L N="380">&amp; fulle warme clothynge also fulle oft for his loue hem dy&yogh;t.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. lond st. loue.</NOTE></L>
<L>Forsothe, so well belouyd was he with god</L>
<L>&THORN;at an angelle come to hurre vpone a ny&yogh;t, &thorn;er as he lay,</L>
<L>&amp; tolde hurre what tyme he shulde be dodde</L>
<L>And pas ou&yogh;t of &thorn;is worlde away.</L>
<L N="385">And afterwarde vpon a day fulle stille he stodde<MILESTONE N="265" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Among hurre sustren euerychone,</L>
<L>And wyth semely chere &amp; myelde mode</L>
<L>&THORN;us to hem &thorn;o he made hurre mone:</L>
<L>"My dure sustren," quad he &thorn;enne, "my deu&yogh;tren alle,</L>
<L N="390">To &yogh;owe &thorn;e sothe y telle now y-wys:</L>
<L>A pestelens, sustren, wolle hastely among vs falle</L>
<L>And take away he wolle a certeyn of vs:<NOTE PLACE="foot">part fehlt?</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;en shall y dye &amp; ou&yogh;t of &thorn;is worlde pas,</L>
<L>And mony a nother also shall passe forthe of &yogh;ow.</L>
<L N="395">And &yogh;e shalle haue after me to &yogh;our abbas</L>
<L>Sexburwe, my sustre, for &thorn;at ry&yogh;t welle y know.</L>
<L>And sixstene wynter my body shulle lye</L>
<L>In &thorn;e vrthe, &thorn;ere as &yogh;e shull leyge hit full stylle &mdash;</L>
<L>Bot what men wolle do &thorn;en &thorn;ere-by,</L>
<L N="400">Y nyll &yogh;ow no-thyng now &thorn;erof telle;</L>
<L>Bot Wylfryde shalle passe ou&yogh;t of &thorn;is worde sone after y-wys,</L>
<L>&amp; Sexburwe shalle lyue &yogh;et lengurre here;</L>
<L>Bot Wylfride soule shalle come vp to heuene blys</L>
<L>With-inne &thorn;e fourtythe day after &thorn;e sixstenethe &yogh;ere.</L>
<L N="405">Bot when syxstene &yogh;ere ben fullyche y-past, &amp; no lasse,</L>
<L>My body y-translatudde sone after &thorn;at shalle be,</L>
<L>&amp; Wylfride shalle sone after of &thorn;is worlde passe</L>
<L>&amp; come vp to heuene &thorn;en &amp; dwelle with me."<NOTE PLACE="foot">406&mdash;8 sind unten nachgetragen.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000430.tif" N="292"></L>
<L>And ry&yogh;t as he sayde, hit was afterwarde y-donne.</L>
<L N="410">&THORN;at tyme hyede &thorn;o sone after &thorn;at fulle fast,</L>
<L>And a moreyn come in-to &thorn;at abbay after &thorn;at welle sonne,</L>
<L>And sixe wekes forsothe hit &thorn;ere last.</L>
<L>And nyenne(!) maydenus &thorn;at tyme forthe past,</L>
<L>As &thorn;is blessude virgyn, seynt Awdre, hadde y-tolde hem byfore,</L>
<L N="415">&amp; of alle &thorn;e maydenus he hurre-self was &thorn;e last&mdash;</L>
<L>For after &thorn;at &thorn;at he was dedde, at &thorn;at tyme &thorn;ey dyeden nomore.</L>
<L>Bot byfore hurre deythe &thorn;e fyuethe day</L>
<L>He toke hurre leue at hurre sustren on this monere</L>
<L>And sayde: "my sustren, haue &yogh;e gode day!</L>
<L N="420">For ychall not leue longe after &thorn;is here."</L>
<L>In &thorn;e last ende of &thorn;e fyueth &amp; bygynnyng of &thorn;e syxte</L>
<L>Among hurre sustren full styll he stode</L>
<L>And sayde: "forsothe, y shalle be &thorn;e nexst</L>
<L>&THORN;at shalle now passe forthe to god,</L>
<L N="425">And at &thorn;is tyme shull dye nomo</L>
<L>Bot y my-selfen now at &thorn;is tyme, y-wys.</L>
<L>For god hym-self hathe grauntede me so</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ey shull come euene wyth me in-to his blysse:</L>
<L>For by &thorn;at tyme hurre penance shalle alle ben y-donne</L>
<L N="430">And clene ou&yogh;t of Purgatory &thorn;ey shulle be brou&yogh;t also,</L>
<L>And mete with me after my deyth &thorn;ey shulle anon</L>
<L>And vp to &thorn;e blysse &thorn;ey shulle with me &thorn;en alle go:&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;use bysilyche to god for hem preyede haue y</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ey my&yogh;tyn euene come vp to blys with me</L>
<L N="435">&amp; dwell with other coronyde maydenus in heuene an hy&yogh;e</L>
<L>In presence of &thorn;e blessude trinyte.</L>
<L>Bot on thyng, my dure sustren, y &yogh;ow prye:</L>
<L>&THORN;at &yogh;e wolde bury me ry&yogh;t as my ordre ys,</L>
<L>&amp; amonge my sustren let me lye&mdash;</L>
<L N="440">For trewliche so my hole wylle hit ys&mdash;</L>
<L>And let make a litulle chest of tre</L>
<L>And put &yogh;e my body &thorn;ere-with-inne:</L>
<L>And, dure sustren, so bury &yogh;e me</L>
<L>Among my sustren here a-reynne!</L>
<L N="445">And settuth no cost abou&yogh;t me for a tombe,</L>
<L>Bot gode preyours &amp; almys-dede&mdash;</L>
<L>Bot alle &thorn;at &yogh;e wolden spende abou&yogh;t my tombe,</L>
<L>Y prey &yogh;ow &thorn;at &yogh;e wolden pore men clothe &amp; fede".<NOTE PLACE="foot">vor clothe fehlt with.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;en in-to hurre chambre with &thorn;at he went,</L>
<L N="450">With myelde chere &amp; hert fulle meke.</L>
<L>&amp; after seynt Wilfride fulle sone he sent,</L>
<L>And after meyster Cynfrey he sende &thorn;o eke.</L>
<L>And when &thorn;e messengerus comen &amp; hurre hernede sayde,</L>
<L>&THORN;ey heyden hem fulle faste &amp; comen hurre to,
<PB REF="00000431.tif" N="293"></L>
<L N="455">And in hurre chambre &thorn;ey founde &thorn;at blessude mayde.</L>
<L>&THORN;e whyche with myelde chere welcomede hem &thorn;o</L>
<L>&amp; sayde: "syres, &yogh;e ben ry&yogh;t welcome to me!</L>
<L>For now my lyff, dure syres, is brou&yogh;t nye to anende:</L>
<L>For y shull leue no lengur bot dayes thre,</L>
<L N="460">And &thorn;en ou&yogh;t of &thorn;is wrochede worlde my soule shulle wende.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. wrochede.</NOTE></L>
<L>Cynfrey, a gret swellyng abou&yogh;t my throte &thorn;er is,</L>
<L>&THORN;e whiche dothe my body now at &thorn;is tyme grette wo;</L>
<L>Were hit ybroke &amp; &thorn;e mater ou&yogh;t y-renne, y-wys,</L>
<L>To my body, as me &thorn;engu&thorn;, myche eysse hit wolde do".</L>
<L N="465">&THORN;use wordus he spake forsothe to mayster Cinfrey, &thorn;e thridde day<MILESTONE N="266" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Byfore &thorn;at hurre soule ou&yogh;t of &thorn;is worldde passte.</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;o hurre leche, &thorn;e whyche was clept meister Cinfrey,</L>
<L>&THORN;en in his hert full sone after &thorn;at he hym cast</L>
<L>To aperce &thorn;e skynne &thorn;o with a launset</L>
<L N="470">And lette &thorn;at fole humour ou&yogh;t of hurre body passe,</L>
<L>In hope &thorn;at he shulde &thorn;en fare &thorn;e bet</L>
<L>And haue penaunce myche &thorn;e lasse.</L>
<L>And &thorn;en a wel grete yssu he made &thorn;er y-wys,</L>
<L>To let &thorn;e foule humour ou&yogh;t of hurre boyche renne&mdash;</L>
<L N="475">In hope &thorn;at he shulde a farede &thorn;e better, he dude &thorn;is,<NOTE PLACE="foot">de in farede ist nachtr&auml;glich hinzugeschr. a=haue.</NOTE></L>
<L>And made &thorn;at yssu gret &amp; hoge &thorn;ere &thorn;en.</L>
<L>And when &thorn;at humour was ou&yogh;t of hurre boiche ronne,</L>
<L>&THORN;o myche &thorn;e ley&yogh;t-somere, forsothe, was he.</L>
<L>Bot sone after &thorn;at in litulle slombryng of slepe he felle &thorn;enne.</L>
<L N="480">And a graciose sweuene mette &thorn;o &thorn;at mayde fre:</L>
<L>A semeliche mayde hurre semede &thorn;at he dude &thorn;ere se</L>
<L>Stondyng ry&yogh;t at hurre beddus fete,</L>
<L>&THORN;e whiche sayde: "Etheldrede, how is hit with &yogh;ou now? slepe &yogh;e?"</L>
<L>"Nay, sothely, ma dame, quad he, y nam not a-slepe &yogh;et".</L>
<L N="485">"Hedur now goddus sonne of heuene to &yogh;ow sende me</L>
<L>To tell &thorn;e &thorn;at &thorn;is swellyng, &thorn;e whiche is &thorn;y nek abou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>For penaunce of synne was now y-sende to &thorn;e,</L>
<L>For &thorn;e synne of &thorn;i &yogh;onge age when &thorn;ou were wylde &amp; prou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>For when &thorn;ou were a childe of &yogh;ong age,</L>
<L N="490">Forsothe, in &thorn;yne hert &thorn;ou were somdelle prou&yogh;t</L>
<L>Bothe of &thorn;y bewte and of &thorn;y worthy lynage,</L>
<L>And ryall colers of golde &thorn;ou wereduste &thorn;y nek abou&yogh;t&mdash;</L>
<L>For gaynes &amp; pryde, forsothe, hit was</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou weredust suche ryalle colers &thorn;o.</L>
<L N="495">Bot almy&yogh;ty god knowy&thorn; ry&yogh;t welle of &thorn;at cas,</L>
<L>&amp;, forto quenche &thorn;e synne of &thorn;at, &thorn;is penaunce he sende &thorn;e to;</L>
<L>For goddus sonne, &thorn;e whiche was of Mary y-bore,</L>
<L>Taku&thorn; now ry&yogh;t gode hede &thorn;erto</L>
<L>&amp; suche gret penance he sendy&thorn; &thorn;e &thorn;erfore,</L>
<L N="500">Hennus ou&yogh;t of &thorn;is worlde or &thorn;at &thorn;ou go,
<PB REF="00000432.tif" N="294"></L>
<L>For &thorn;ou shuldust byfore &thorn;y deyth ry&yogh;t so clene here be</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ow shuldust haue no nede to go &thorn;orwe &thorn;e fyre of Purgatory,</L>
<L>Bot come to heuene anon with &thorn;use maydenes ffre,</L>
<L>&THORN;e whiche shull come with &thorn;e vp to heuene an hey&yogh;e".</L>
<L N="505">And when &thorn;at mayde &thorn;us hadde sayde &thorn;o, sodenly he vanysshede a-way,</L>
<L>And &thorn;is blessud virgyn Awdre a-woke &thorn;o of hurre slepe.</L>
<L>And anon he tolde &thorn;is sweuene to Wylfride &amp; Cynfrey.</L>
<L>Bot when Wylfride hadde hit herde, for very Joy anon he wepe.</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;is blessude virgyn heyede to hurre deyth fulle fast,</L>
<L N="510">And Wylfride seruede hurre of hurre sacramentys alle.</L>
<L>And he anon &thorn;en hurre yenon vp caste</L>
<L>And by name he clepte forthe hurre sustren alle,</L>
<L>And toke hurre leue at hurre sustren &thorn;er euerychone,</L>
<L>And at seynt Wilfride &amp; at Cynfrey he toke hurre leue also.</L>
<L N="515">Bot all &thorn;ey full sore &thorn;en wepton &amp; made gret mone,</L>
<L>For mony a sorwefull hert was &thorn;er among hem &thorn;o.</L>
<L>Bot when &thorn;is blessude virgyn seynt Awdre dude dye</L>
<L>&amp; hurre soule past vp to &thorn;e blysse of heuene,</L>
<L>Abou&yogh;t hurre &thorn;en gret ley&yogh;t &thorn;er &thorn;ey sye,</L>
<L N="520">And angels &thorn;ey herde syng with mylde steuene;</L>
<L>A fulle sote flauour &thorn;ey feltone &thorn;ere &thorn;o,</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;at weren &thorn;er &thorn;o in &thorn;at place,</L>
<L>And a full gret ley&yogh;t &thorn;ey sey &thorn;ere &thorn;o also,</L>
<L>And gret melodye also of angels also(!) &thorn;er &thorn;o was.</L>
<L N="525">Bot when &thorn;is blessude virgyn was &thorn;us forth paste</L>
<L>Hurre blessude soule vp to god in trinite,</L>
<L>And in a trene chest &thorn;en was y-cast</L>
<L>Hurre semelyche body, so fayre &amp; so fre,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ey buryedone hurre in &thorn;at same place</L>
<L N="530">Ry&yogh;t as hurre owne wyll westo.</L>
<L>&amp; sixstene wynter &thorn;er-inne he was&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;e story of hurre spekuth of nomo.</L>
<L>Bot hurre soule from hurre body past furthe y-wys</L>
<L>&THORN;e thre and twenty day of &thorn;e moneth of Juny,</L>
<L N="535">And at Hely &thorn;e first abbas he forsothe was,</L>
<L>In &thorn;e &yogh;ere &thorn;at god was bore sixe hundryd &amp; sixty.</L>
<L>And after herre &thorn;at abbay stode stylle in grete prosperite,</L>
<L>And a gret noumbre of holy maydens dwelton &thorn;er-inne,</L>
<L>A hundryd &yogh;ere &amp; foure &amp; fyfty, as &yogh;e mow rede in store,</L>
<L N="540">Tyll &thorn;e Danys come hedur wyth gret host, &thorn;is lond to wynne.<MILESTONE N="267" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Bot &thorn;e Danys distreydone &thorn;at abbay full clene ywys</L>
<L>&amp; drevyn away &thorn;use maydenus &thorn;enne euerychon.</L>
<L>Tylle Edward seniour, kyng of Englonde, y-coronyd was:<NOTE PLACE="foot">Edward ist &uuml;ber einem and. Namen corr.</NOTE></L>
<L>For he reparede &thorn;at abbay a&yogh;eynne in his tyme euery stone,</L>
<L N="545">And chanonys he stallede in-to &thorn;at abbay &thorn;o.</L>
<L>&THORN;e whiche dwelton &thorn;ere, tylle kyng Edgar was bore:
<PB REF="00000433.tif" N="295"></L>
<L>Bot blake monkus he put in-to &thorn;at abbay &thorn;o,</L>
<L>&THORN;e whiche han dwelt &thorn;ere styll seythe euer-more.</L>
<L>And when &thorn;is blessude virgyn was thus forthe y-past</L>
<L N="550">Hurre soule to heuene blys, as y sayde &yogh;ow ere,</L>
<L>&THORN;en was hurre sustre Sexburwe y-made abbas in gret hast,</L>
<L>And thre and twenty &yogh;ere was &thorn;er gouernere.</L>
<L>&THORN;is Sexburwe was kyng Annys dou&yogh;ter, &thorn;at holy marter,</L>
<L>And kyng Herconbertys wyff he was also,</L>
<L N="555">&THORN;e whiche was kyng of Canterbury &amp; dwelt &thorn;o &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>And abbas of Hely he was made, when deythe had take Herconbertys hurre fro.</L>
<L>Bot twey deu&yogh;tren he hadde by kyng Herconbertys, ywys:</L>
<L>Ercongote &amp; Hermendylda &thorn;use maydenus weren yclepte &thorn;o.</L>
<L>Bot Ercongote with hurre modur to Hely ygon ys</L>
<L N="560">And after Sexburwe hurre modur nexst abbas he was also,</L>
<L>And thredtene &yogh;ere gouernede &thorn;at abbay in gode prosperite&mdash;</L>
<L>A holy blessud virgyn, forsothe, &thorn;is Ercongote was!</L>
<L>And &thorn;ere &yogh;et fulle worshipfullyche y-shrynyd &yogh;et ys he</L>
<L>Fast by hurre modur at Hely in &thorn;at holy plase.</L>
<L N="565">Bot Hermendilda, &thorn;e whiche Ercongotys sustre was,</L>
<L>To Wulfery, &thorn;e whiche was kyng of &thorn;e Merche, was mariede anone;</L>
<L>&THORN;e whiche was abbas nexst hurre sustre in &thorn;at same plase,</L>
<L>When Welfry, hurre hosebonde, was vp to heuene agone.</L>
<L>&THORN;is Wlfry was kynge Penda, &thorn;e heretykys, sone,</L>
<L N="570">And &thorn;e first criston kynge of &thorn;e Merche he was also,</L>
<L>And by Hermendilda, his wyff, he hadde twey deu&yogh;tren, &amp; a sonne:</L>
<L>Merburwe &amp; Milgnyde weren &thorn;e namys of &thorn;e madenus two.</L>
<L>Bot Merburwe nexst after hurre modur Hermendildde</L>
<L>In &thorn;e abbay of Hely was y-made abbas;</L>
<L N="575">Bot Hermendilda, hurre modur, byfore herre &thorn;ere dwellede</L>
<L>Sixstene wynter &amp; abbas was &thorn;ere in &thorn;at same plase.</L>
<L>Bot Merburwe nas not abbas &thorn;er bot litull space:</L>
<L>For at Chester somme cronyculle sayn &thorn;at he &yogh;et ys.</L>
<L>Bot hurre sustre Mylgnyde twenty wynter was &thorn;er abbas,</L>
<L N="580">And in &thorn;at plase hurre bones &yogh;et ben y-wys.</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;us foure ladyes ben y-shrynede &yogh;et forsothe &thorn;ere:</L>
<L>Etheldrede, &amp; hurre sustre Sexburwe, &amp; Ercongote, hurre sustre dou&yogh;ter, also,</L>
<L>And Hermendilde hurre sustre is y-schryned also &thorn;ere;&mdash;</L>
<L>And of seynt Albons relekes &thorn;er is a shryne &yogh;et mo.</L>
<L N="585">Now wolly stynt of Sexburwe here more to wryte or rede,</L>
<L>&amp; hey&yogh;e me to my mater y-touchyd here byfore:</L>
<L>Of &thorn;is blessude virgyn seynt Etheldrede;</L>
<L>And of Selburwe(!) as at &thorn;is tyme nylle y speke nomore.&mdash;</L>
<L>Abou&yogh;t &thorn;e tombe of seynt Awdre oftymes, forsothe, &thorn;er was</L>
<L N="590">Mony gret ley&yogh;tys ofte-tymes &thorn;er weren(!) y-seye,</L>
<L>And meche swetnesse of swete sauour was oft felde in &thorn;at plase,</L>
<L>To what mon &thorn;at to &thorn;at plase come, other by ny&yogh;t or by day.
<PB REF="00000434.tif" N="296"></L>
<L>Mony sekemen hadden &thorn;ere hurre hele</L>
<L>&amp; restorynge of hurre lemys &thorn;ey hadden &thorn;er also,</L>
<L N="595">And blynde men &amp; crokyd mony &amp; fele,</L>
<L>&THORN;e whiche &thorn;edur come, holle &amp; sounde &thorn;ey went &thorn;erfro.</L>
<L>And mony a meracle byforen hurre tombe &thorn;er weren y-donne,</L>
<L>And sekemen weron &thorn;er y-helyd monyonne;</L>
<L>Mony &thorn;at came &thorn;edur, bothe deyffe &amp; doume,</L>
<L N="600">Holle &amp; sounde &thorn;ey wenton home &thorn;onne.</L>
<L>What ry&yogh;twys bone, forsothe, &thorn;at ony mone badde</L>
<L>Of &thorn;at blessude virgyn Etheldrede:</L>
<L>His wille, forsothe, after anone he hadde,</L>
<L>Or of what-monere sekenesse &thorn;at he of hurre his hele bede.</L>
<L N="605">So mony meracles god &thorn;er &thorn;o wrou&yogh;t</L>
<L>By-cause of &thorn;is blessude virgyn seynt Awdre,</L>
<L>&THORN;at to seynt Wylfride &amp; to Sexburwe hit come in &thorn;ou&yogh;t</L>
<L>To make a tombe of ston, to ley in hurre body fre.</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;at contrey was lowe &amp; mersshy, watery londe,</L>
<L N="610">And with watrys &amp; marrys y-closot all-abou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And gret sca(r)senesse of stonys &thorn;er was, yche vnderstonde.</L>
<L>Wherfore, to seche a ston, in ferne contrey &thorn;ey senden men ou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;en when &thorn;use men hadden ry&yogh;t wyde y-gone,</L>
<L>&THORN;orow-ou&yogh;t alle &thorn;e contrey in yche syde,</L>
<L N="615">&YOGH;et my&yogh;t &thorn;ey not fynde non sufficiant stone,</L>
<L>Bot comen hom a&yogh;eyn &amp; tolden so seynt Wilfride.<MILESTONE N="272" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="foot">Die folg. Bl&auml;tter sind im Ms. unrichtig gebunden, die Fortsetzung folgt erst auf fol. 272.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bot seynt Wylfride bare hit still in his mynde</L>
<L>And preyede to god, somme grace of hym to wynne</L>
<L>Suche a ston in &thorn;at contrey sum-where to fynde,</L>
<L N="620">&THORN;is blessude body to leyge with-inne.</L>
<L>And anon after, as seynt Wylfride ley in his bed vpone a ny&yogh;t&mdash;</L>
<L>Bot he nas not fulliche &yogh;et a-slepe:</L>
<L>Hym &thorn;ou&yogh;t &thorn;at he sey an angel fulle bry&yogh;t</L>
<L>Stondynge at his beddus fete,</L>
<L N="625">And &thorn;at with hym come a ry&yogh;t gret ly&yogh;t.</L>
<L>And holy Sexburwe forsothe also he hurre-self sayde</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e same tyme he sawe &thorn;ylke same sy&yogh;t&mdash;</L>
<L>Bot Sexburwe thou&yogh;t hit was a semely mayde&mdash;</L>
<L>And also &thorn;at he come &thorn;edur with gret ley&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="foot">V. 629 ist zu tilgen.</NOTE></L>
<L N="630">Bot he spake on worde to hem bothe.</L>
<L>Bot Sexburwe, when he hit seye, was sore agast;</L>
<L>&amp; hurre &thorn;ou&yogh;t &thorn;at he sayde: "y nyll, Sexburwe, do &thorn;e no lothe.</L>
<L>Bot knowe &yogh;e welle &thorn;at sixstene &yogh;ere ben fully past,</L>
<L>And god wolde my body were vp of &thorn;e vrthe y-take</L>
<L N="635">And y-putte in-to gretter worshippe, y-wys.</L>
<L>And, also, Wylfride, &thorn;ou shalt hastely &thorn;e worde forsake</L>
<L>&amp; come vp to me in-to heuene blys.
<PB REF="00000435.tif" N="297"></L>
<L>Bot &yogh;if &yogh;e spare for &thorn;e defauu&yogh;t of a stone</L>
<L>To take vp my body, &thorn;at hathe ley in &thorn;e vrthe sixstene &yogh;ere,</L>
<L N="640">Y chulle tell &yogh;ow redily where &yogh;e shulle fynde one,</L>
<L>And also ychull help &yogh;ow &thorn;at hit were here:</L>
<L>For &thorn;er is a litulle toun in &thorn;is contrey ney&yogh;e here byside,</L>
<L>&THORN;e whiche somme-tyme a fulle fayre cite hit was,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e whiche &thorn;e walles ben broke, &thorn;e &yogh;atys ben wyde,</L>
<L N="645">Bot &thorn;e compas of &thorn;at toune is full gret space;</L>
<L>And byside &thorn;at wall &thorn;ere leyth a fulle fayre stone</L>
<L>Of gode marbull, &thorn;e whiche is why&yogh;t and clene,</L>
<L>Sufficiant y-now to reseyue my body, euery bone.</L>
<L>Ry&yogh;t &thorn;us hit is as y &yogh;ow say &mdash; &yogh;e witte welle what y mene."</L>
<L N="650">And with &thorn;at &thorn;is blessud lady fanysshede from seynt Sexburwe away,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e angel from seynt Wylfride wanyssede away also.</L>
<L>&THORN;ey reson vp &thorn;o anon after, for hit was &thorn;en ny&yogh;e day.</L>
<L>And Wylfride come to Sexburwe anon after &thorn;at &thorn;o</L>
<L>And tolde hurre his vision &thorn;o &thorn;ere euerydelle.</L>
<L N="655">How &thorn;er come &amp; spake with hym an angelle bry&yogh;t.</L>
<L>"Forsothe, quad Sexburwe, to me &thorn;er come a mayde, &amp; &thorn;e same wordus he dude me telle,</L>
<L>&amp; abou&yogh;t hurre in my chambre was gret ly&yogh;t."</L>
<L>"Forsothe, quad Wilfride, now y chotte welle and am ry&yogh;t sure</L>
<L>&THORN;at hit was seynt Awdre &thorn;e whiche come to &thorn;e:</L>
<L N="660">For he sayde, while he lyuede, &thorn;at anon after sixstene &yogh;ere</L>
<L>&THORN;at hurre Translacione sone after &thorn;en shulde be."</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;en seynt Wylfride send forth after &thorn;at ry&yogh;t anon</L>
<L>Meyster Cynfrey, &thorn;e whiche was seynt Awdre leche,</L>
<L>And prey&yogh;ede hym &thorn;at he shulde hym-self forthe gone</L>
<L N="665">&THORN;e litull toune &thorn;at &thorn;e mayde spake of, forto seche&mdash;</L>
<L>And &thorn;ey tolden meyster Cynfrey &thorn;o anone</L>
<L>&THORN;e vision &thorn;e whiche &thorn;e sey, ri&yogh;t as hit was,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e = &thorn;ey.</NOTE></L>
<L>And preyeden him &thorn;at he shulde fast gone<NOTE PLACE="foot">hem st. him.</NOTE></L>
<L>And seche &thorn;at toune tyll he hit hadde, from place to plase,<NOTE PLACE="foot">nach hadde fehlt founde?</NOTE></L>
<L N="670">And &yogh;erne walke abou&yogh;t &thorn;at litull space</L>
<L>Euermore tylle he hadde &thorn;at ston y-founde,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e whiche, &yogh;if god wolde &yogh;eue hym suche grace,</L>
<L>To make &thorn;erof to &thorn;at mayden a tombe.</L>
<L>Bot Cynfrey went forth &thorn;o anone vpone his way,</L>
<L N="675">And other thre wisemen with hym went mo.</L>
<L>Till hit was vpone &thorn;e secunde day:</L>
<L>&THORN;is litull toune &thorn;ey come &thorn;o by goddus grace to,</L>
<L>A litull byfore &thorn;e merke euenynge;</L>
<L>Wherfore &thorn;ey &thorn;ou&yogh;t &thorn;ey wolden dwell &thorn;er alle ny&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="680">&YOGH;yff &thorn;ey my&yogh;ten here &thorn;ere ony tithynge</L>
<L>Of &thorn;is ston, &thorn;orwe goddus grace &amp; my&yogh;t.
<PB REF="00000436.tif" N="298"></L>
<L>Bot on &thorn;e morwe, when hit was clere day,</L>
<L>&THORN;ey reson vp full smertlyche &thorn;o euerychon,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou&yogh;ten &thorn;at &thorn;ey wolden passe forth vpon hurre way</L>
<L N="685">Abou&yogh;t all &thorn;at contrey, to seche &thorn;at stone.</L>
<L>Bot Cynfrey past forthe &thorn;o by an olde walle,</L>
<L>And &yogh;erne he sou&yogh;t abou&yogh;t &thorn;ere in &thorn;at mortyde:</L>
<L>Bot at &thorn;e last he saye where a ston lay as whytte as whall,<MILESTONE N="273" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Leygynge &thorn;er a litull hem all bysyde.</L>
<L N="690">"A, brethren, quad Cynfrey &thorn;o, me thengu&thorn; y now &yogh;onde se<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. brothren in brethren corr.</NOTE></L>
<L>A fayre stone, y-shape ry&yogh;t welle &thorn;erfore.</L>
<L>Comethe hedur, y &yogh;ow prey, all now with me!</L>
<L>For &thorn;is ston was y-shewyd to me here byfore:</L>
<L>For, treweliche, by visione to-ny&yogh;t &thorn;er come to me</L>
<L N="695">A semely man, &thorn;e whiche was of gret age,</L>
<L>His berde was feyre &amp; whyte, his body was fre,</L>
<L>Forsothe he hadde a ry&yogh;t fayre vy&yogh;age;</L>
<L>A kyng me &thorn;ou&yogh;t hit hadde y-be,</L>
<L>Or ellus a mon of fulle hey&yogh;e parage;</L>
<L N="700">And &thorn;use wordus he sayde &thorn;o to me</L>
<L>Opynliche in oure owne langage:</L>
<L>"'Cynfrey, quad he, &thorn;ou hast ferre &amp; wyde y-gone</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;is contrey wyde all-a-bou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Forto seche a fayre marbull-stone:</L>
<L N="705">Lowe where a fulle fayre stone leythe with-ou&yogh;t dou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Loke vp, he sayde, &amp; se hit with &thorn;yn ynon ry&yogh;t welle:</L>
<L>For lowe where hit leythe by-side &thorn;e &yogh;ondere walle,</L>
<L>Kyndliche y-wrou&yogh;t for hurre euery-delle,</L>
<L>Redy, to resayue hurre clene body now alle'".</L>
<L N="710">And with &thorn;at worde anone he past forthe away</L>
<L>Clene ou&yogh;t of my sey&yogh;t &thorn;ethon anone.</L>
<L>&amp; y loked hym &thorn;o after: &amp; me &thorn;ou&yogh;t &thorn;o &thorn;at y seye</L>
<L>Leygynge ry&yogh;t here &thorn;is same stone".</L>
<L>And &thorn;ey kneledone a-doune &thorn;o &thorn;ere euerichon</L>
<L N="715">And thongude god &thorn;o with alle hurre my&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &yogh;aff hem grace to fynde suche a stone,</L>
<L>For hure body so mete &amp; so clene y-dy&yogh;t;</L>
<L>For &thorn;at ston was well ygraue euery geyntte</L>
<L>&THORN;at holy body to close alle holle with-inne,</L>
<L N="720">With ry&yogh;t curiose crafte eueryche a neynche;<NOTE PLACE="foot">a neynche = an inch.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;er my&yogh;t no fau&yogh;t be founden &thorn;er-inne.</L>
<L>&THORN;ey weron &thorn;o fulle gladde &amp; &thorn;ongeden god fulle fast</L>
<L>Of &thorn;at gret grace, &thorn;at hadde hem y-sende.</L>
<L>Bot of cariage &thorn;ey were &thorn;o full sore agast,</L>
<L N="725">And prayede to god with hert fulle hende</L>
<L>To &yogh;eue to hem bothe grace and my&yogh;t</L>
<L>&THORN;at ston to carie to Hely bothe sounde &amp; saue,
<PB REF="00000437.tif" N="299"></L>
<L>&THORN;at was so follych and so redy y-dy&yogh;t</L>
<L>To resayue &thorn;at body &thorn;at ley &thorn;ere in graue.</L>
<L N="730">Bot anone by grace &thorn;er come a mone</L>
<L>&THORN;at dwelt ney&yogh;e &thorn;er-byside in &thorn;at contrey,</L>
<L>And sayde: "sires, what do &yogh;e to &thorn;at fayre stone?</L>
<L>For hit motte to &thorn;e abbay of Hely.</L>
<L>For to me to-ny&yogh;t &thorn;er come a fayre semely lady in gode aray</L>
<L N="735">&amp; he hathe y-bou&yogh;t &thorn;is marbull-stone of me,</L>
<L>And ychaue y-seuryd hurre by my fay</L>
<L>To carie hit to &thorn;e fayre abbay of Hele".</L>
<L>Bot Cynfrey stode styll &thorn;o &amp; speke ry&yogh;t nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And in his hert he was bothe gladde &amp; blythe,</L>
<L N="740">And for &thorn;is meracle, &thorn;at was &thorn;er &thorn;us y-wrou&yogh;t,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. sithes mit durchstr. s.</NOTE></L>
<L>He &thorn;ongede god oft &amp; fele sithe;</L>
<L>And sayde: "sire, what lady was &thorn;at</L>
<L>&THORN;e whiche hathe y-bou&yogh;t &thorn;is fayre stone of &thorn;e?"</L>
<L>"Trewliche, sire, he sayde, y not.</L>
<L N="745">Bot a fulle semely lady, forsothe, was he,</L>
<L>A mantyll of sable &thorn;at lady werede vpone;</L>
<L>And a religiose womon, forsothe, me &thorn;ou&yogh;t, was he.</L>
<L>And with full gret ly&yogh;t he come to me &thorn;on,</L>
<L>And &thorn;use wordus forsothe he sayde to me</L>
<L N="750">And he askede me: wherre &thorn;at iche wolde sylle</L>
<L>&THORN;is marbull-stone so fayre &amp; so fre,</L>
<L>And sayde &thorn;at hurre sustre hadde gret nede &thorn;er-tylle,</L>
<L>&THORN;e whiche was, as he sayde, &thorn;e abbas of Hely.</L>
<L>And y sayde anon: " "&yogh;e, my lady so dure" " &mdash;</L>
<L N="755">For y durst not to hurre say nay:</L>
<L>So semely he was &amp; so gladde of chure.</L>
<L>And anon after to me thus dudde he say:</L>
<L>"'And also &thorn;ou most carie hit &thorn;edur now anone&mdash;</L>
<L>&amp; hye blyue &thorn;ou most, &thorn;at hit were y-do!</L>
<L N="760">And other thre men, &thorn;at han ferre y-gone,</L>
<L>Wollen come &thorn;edur &amp; help welle &thorn;erto.<MILESTONE N="268" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And haue here, he sayde, &thorn;y heyre &thorn;er-fore,</L>
<L>A ryng of golde, bothe riche and gay!'"</L>
<L>And of hurre seythe y saw nomore,</L>
<L N="765">Bot thus he past forth from me a-way".</L>
<L>"Now treweliche, felowys, quad mayster Cynfrey,</L>
<L>&THORN;is lady &thorn;at hath y-bou&yogh;t here &thorn;is stone</L>
<L>Hit was myn owne lady, seynt Awdrey&mdash;</L>
<L>For treweliche other womon was hit none.</L>
<L N="770">Bot heye &yogh;ow fast now &amp; haue y-donne,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;is fayre ston were caryede from &thorn;is plase away!</L>
<L>For iche wold be gladde, were hit fayre brou&yogh;t home &thorn;onne,</L>
<L>&THORN;at blessude fayre body &thorn;erinne to lay".
<PB REF="00000438.tif" N="300"></L>
<L>Bot &thorn;is mon vnswered &thorn;en anon with &thorn;at</L>
<L N="775">And sayde: "syre, hit shalle ry&yogh;t sone be &thorn;ere:</L>
<L>For my waynne shalle be heddurre anon y-fatte,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e abbay of Hely hit forto bere".</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;at stone was fulle hoge &amp; full heuy y-wys.</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;ey tokon hit vp ry&yogh;t ly&yogh;tliche by goddus grace &thorn;o,</L>
<L N="780">And in-to &thorn;e wayne full sone y-done hit is,</L>
<L>And fulle meriliche home &thorn;er-with &thorn;en dude &thorn;ey go.</L>
<L>&THORN;en went &thorn;ey hammarde a welle gode passe</L>
<L>With hurre wayne &amp; with hurre stone,</L>
<L>With gret gladnesse, mirthe &amp; grace.</L>
<L N="785">And by alle &thorn;e way lettyng nad &thorn;ey none.</L>
<L>And when &thorn;ey come home to &thorn;e abbay with &thorn;at ston</L>
<L>And hadden y-told Wylfride &amp; Sexburwe hurre gode spede,</L>
<L>&THORN;en were &thorn;ey gladde and blythe euerichon:</L>
<L>For of no masynry, to dey&yogh;t &thorn;at ston, &thorn;ey nadde no nede.</L>
<L N="790">Bot when Cynfrey hadde y-tolde Wilfride &amp; Sexburwe of &thorn;e rynge</L>
<L>&THORN;e wheche was y-&yogh;eue of &thorn;at lady to &thorn;e caryeng mone,</L>
<L>&THORN;en preyede &thorn;ey &thorn;e mone &thorn;at he wolde hit to hem bryng.</L>
<L>&THORN;e whiche thyng he grauntede hem anone to done &mdash;</L>
<L>For Sexburwe heyde hurre fulle fast</L>
<L N="795">&THORN;at he my&yogh;t by-tyme y-se &thorn;at holy thyng:</L>
<L>For in hurre hert anone forsothe he cast</L>
<L>&THORN;at hit was hurre professhennalle rynge</L>
<L>Bot when he hit sawe, he knew hit full well,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ongede god heyliche of his grace &amp; of his my&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="800">And anon hit he bou&yogh;t of &thorn;at mon fulle snelle.</L>
<L>And anon after to seynt Awdre is tombe &thorn;ey hem dy&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Seynt Wilfride come &thorn;o anone &thorn;at tombe to</L>
<L>With his ministris &amp; with his clerkus alle, &mdash;</L>
<L>And &thorn;is blessude abbas hyede hurre fulle fast also,</L>
<L N="805">And alle hurre couent also he dude forthe calle, &mdash;</L>
<L>With copus and teneclus of ry&yogh;t gode aray,</L>
<L>And torchus &amp; sencerus, mony &amp; fele.</L>
<L>&amp; other men vncloseden &thorn;e vrthe &thorn;er as he lay.<NOTE PLACE="foot">vor men ist C durchstr.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bot mony a seke mon hadde &thorn;o his hele:</L>
<L N="810">&THORN;e grace of almy&yogh;ty god was &thorn;er &thorn;o so prest;</L>
<L>&amp; also so sote sauerus weren &thorn;er alle-abou&yogh;t</L>
<L>&THORN;at euery creature hadde &thorn;er &thorn;o gretter left</L>
<L>To knele to &thorn;at vrthe fulle lowe &amp; to &thorn;at body lowete,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ongedone god with alle hurre hert &amp; hurre my&yogh;t</L>
<L N="815">Of his gret godenesse &amp; of his hey&yogh;e grace.</L>
<L>&THORN;en nyene bleynde men hadden &thorn;er hurre sy&yogh;t</L>
<L>Ry&yogh;t anon &thorn;o in &thorn;at blessude place,</L>
<L>And crokede maymot crepuls seuene</L>
<L>Hadden herre lemys restoryd to hem anon ry&yogh;t &thorn;ere,
<PB REF="00000439.tif" N="301"></L>
<L N="820">And cryeden &amp; sayden wyth heye steuene</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ey weren holle &amp; sounde &thorn;er &thorn;o ally-fere.</L>
<L>&THORN;ere was gret solace, murthe &amp; gret ioy,</L>
<L>&amp; mony a sekemon was made &thorn;er holle &amp; sounde;</L>
<L>And also bellus rongon &amp; maden gret noy</L>
<L N="825">With-ou&yogh;t ony touchyng of monnus honde.</L>
<L>And when &thorn;ey knewen &amp; herden &thorn;e bellus ryng &amp; knylle</L>
<L>So schryll with-ou&yogh;t ony touche of monnus honde,</L>
<L>Seynt Wilfride went anon &thorn;e tombe tylle,</L>
<L>And Sexburwe went anon &thorn;o doune in-to &thorn;e grounde.</L>
<L N="830">Bot when seynt Wilfride hadde y-seye alle this,</L>
<L>In his hert forsothe he was wondre gladde,</L>
<L>&amp; doune in-to &thorn;e tombe with Sexburwe y-gon he is,</L>
<L>And tweyn other bysshoppus with hym he ladde,</L>
<L>And touchede &thorn;e chest &thorn;o he dude with his honde</L>
<L N="835">And &thorn;erof he toke away &thorn;e lede &thorn;o after anone:</L>
<L>And hurre blessude body as hole &thorn;er lyg&ymacr;nge he fonde</L>
<L>As euer hit was with-inne &thorn;at chest y-done;<MILESTONE N="269" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>As whyte, as rody and as freysshe</L>
<L>Hurre fayre body was &thorn;er as hit &thorn;o lay,</L>
<L N="840">And with-ou&yogh;t ony corrupcione of hurre fleysshe,</L>
<L>Ry&yogh;t as &thorn;aw hit hadde ben leyde with-in &thorn;e chest &thorn;at same day;</L>
<L>Hurre lures weron white as ony lely floure,</L>
<L>Y-meynde with rod ry&yogh;t, as hit was best,</L>
<L>And hurre body was of &thorn;e same coloure,</L>
<L N="845">Ry&yogh;t semely and sote and eke full honest;</L>
<L>And &thorn;e grete suellyng &thorn;e whyche was her nekke abou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Was vanysshede a-way and nothyng seuene,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. seuene, wie sewen Genes. 1195, = sene.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;e wonde was clene holle, with-ou&yogh;t ony dou&yogh;t;</L>
<L>And alle hurre body lay &thorn;er bothe stre&yogh;t &amp; euene.</L>
<L N="850">Hurre body lay &thorn;er as semely in euerichemonnus sy&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Ry&yogh;t a-lyue as &thorn;aw hit &yogh;et were,</L>
<L>&THORN;orwe &thorn;e grace of goddus holy my&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Suche gret myraclus were done &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>Bot when Sexburwe, &thorn;at holy blessude abbas,</L>
<L N="855">Saw how semelyche &amp; how holle &thorn;at body ley &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>In hurre hert for-sothe fulle gladde he was,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ongede god mekeliche with gode chere</L>
<L>And sayde: "Jhesu, y-blessude mot &thorn;y nome be</L>
<L>Euer, lorde god, with-ou&yogh;ten ony hende,</L>
<L N="860">For &thorn;ou deydust for owre soule vpone &thorn;e tre</L>
<L>With fulle meke hert &amp; fulle hende."</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;ey tokon vp &thorn;is fayre body anone &thorn;o,</L>
<L>And with ry&yogh;t mery song &amp; melode,</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e hey&yogh;e auter &thorn;ere-with &thorn;ey duden go</L>
<L N="865">With fayre processione &amp; ry&yogh;t gret solemnite,
<PB REF="00000440.tif" N="302"></L>
<L>And vpone &thorn;e hey&yogh;e auter &thorn;ey leydone hit done<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. doune in done corr.</NOTE></L>
<L>Opynliche &thorn;ere in eueriche monnus sy&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;at euery mon my&yogh;t clereliche &amp; welle loke &thorn;er-vpone,</L>
<L>To merueylle vpone hurre colour so bry&yogh;t.</L>
<L N="870">And when eueryche mon hadde rediliche y-sey &thorn;at fayre body,</L>
<L>Ry&yogh;t at hurre owne plesauns &amp; at hurre owne wylle,</L>
<L>&THORN;ey token hit vpon herre armys fulle honestly</L>
<L>And beron hit forthe &thorn;e marbulstone &thorn;o tylle,</L>
<L>And leydone &thorn;at fayre body with-inne &thorn;e marbulle-stone</L>
<L N="875">&THORN;e whiche was so welle &amp; so heuene y-shape &thorn;er-fore</L>
<L>In &thorn;e toune of Grantechester byfore long a-gone &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">a. R. nomen uille in qua fuerat s. Etheldreda nata. Grantchester ist ein altbekanntes Dorf bei Cambridge, unweit Ely. Vgl. 302 u. 642.</NOTE></L>
<L>For &thorn;er was &thorn;at blessud mayde y-bore &mdash;</L>
<L>And &thorn;at ston was y-shape as mete for hurre body y-wys,</L>
<L>And bothe y-coruyn &amp; y-grauyd so sotelly,</L>
<L N="880">&THORN;at no geynte of hurre body lay &thorn;erinne amys,<NOTE PLACE="foot">geynte = joint.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bot euery lemme of hurre body ley &thorn;erinne bothe fayre &amp; honestly.</L>
<L>And byfore &thorn;e hey&yogh;e auter &thorn;ey satton &thorn;at tombe</L>
<L>And leydone hurre fayre body with-inne ry&yogh;t &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>And &thorn;edur come men &thorn;o bothe deff &amp; dombe</L>
<L N="885">And hadden herre hele &thorn;er byfore &thorn;e tombe alle-y-ffere;</L>
<L>Bothe leprus and men in &thorn;e frensy mony on</L>
<L>Hadden &thorn;ere hurre hele byfore &thorn;at tombe y-wys,</L>
<L>And men &thorn;at hadden &thorn;e hede-ache &amp; eke &thorn;e stone,</L>
<L>And mony men y-combryd with feyndis &amp; euell spiritys.</L>
<L N="890">Ny &thorn;er nas nomone &thorn;at touchede &thorn;at chest</L>
<L>&THORN;at hurre body byfore sexstene &yogh;ere hadde ley Inne,</L>
<L>Or touchud ony of hurre clothus, most or lest,</L>
<L>&THORN;at nas alle holle of his sekenesse, or he went &thorn;ynne. &mdash;</L>
<L>Forsothe, mony a pilgryme &thorn;edur dude come</L>
<L N="895">For diuerse sekenesse &thorn;at &thorn;ey &thorn;o hadden.</L>
<L>And a childe of &thorn;e whiche watere his lyff hadde bynome:</L>
<L>And &thorn;at dede child in a bere &thorn;edur &thorn;ey ladden</L>
<L>And setton hit a-doune byfore &thorn;at tombe</L>
<L>And prey&yogh;edone seynt Awdre of herre help &amp; of hurre grace:</L>
<L N="900">And &thorn;e childe rose vp &thorn;o anone, bothe hole &amp; sounde,</L>
<L>And stode byfore hem alle &thorn;er in &thorn;at place,</L>
<L>And to alle &thorn;e pepull, &thorn;at byfore hym stode, ry&yogh;t &thorn;us he sayde:</L>
<L>"Y prey &yogh;ow &thorn;at &yogh;e wolde knele adoune here euerychone,</L>
<L>And for me &thorn;onge&thorn; &thorn;is holy blessude mayde</L>
<L N="905">Of &thorn;e whyche &thorn;e body leyth y-closot here in &thorn;is stone!</L>
<L>For &thorn;orwe here preyere forsothe hit was</L>
<L>&THORN;at god hathe y-&yogh;eue to me my lyff a&yogh;eyne &mdash;</L>
<L>For, forsothe, murgure ny ley&yogh;ttur neuer y nas</L>
<L>Nen ycham here now, as &yogh;e mow welle seynne.
<PB REF="00000441.tif" N="303"></L>
<L N="910">For, forsothe, fulle of goddus grace he is,<MILESTONE N="270" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;is holy virgyne, y-blessude mot he be!</L>
<L>For full mery is he now in heuene blys</L>
<L>Among &thorn;e bry&yogh;t angelus &thorn;er so feyre and fre.</L>
<L>And &thorn;is worshipfull abbay by hurre ywys</L>
<L N="915">Here-after shalle haue ry&yogh;t gret prosperite,</L>
<L>And also hit shall haue hey&yogh;e encresse of honestnysse</L>
<L>By &thorn;e hey&yogh;e grace of god in trinite."</L>
<L>Bot when &thorn;is gret meracle was &thorn;us y-donne</L>
<L>And &thorn;is childe y-rerote &thorn;us from deythe to lyfe,</L>
<L N="920">&THORN;ey closedone vp &thorn;o &thorn;at marbull-stone</L>
<L>And set hit in &thorn;e same plase &thorn;ere as hit &yogh;et lythe.</L>
<L>And when Wylfryde &amp; Sexburwe hadden closote &thorn;at stone,</L>
<L>&THORN;ey paston forth &thorn;o vpon hurre way.</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;e pilgrymys abydde stille &thorn;er euerychone</L>
<L N="925">And &thorn;ongedone god mekelyche &amp; seynt Awdrey:</L>
<L>For mony a gret miracle &thorn;er was y-donne,</L>
<L>Bothe by ny&yogh;t &amp; also by day,</L>
<L>And mony an holle mon home dude gone</L>
<L>&THORN;e whiche come &thorn;edur fulle seke &amp; in fulle feble aray;</L>
<L N="930">For &thorn;er nas nomon &thorn;at &thorn;edur by-hette</L>
<L>For ony monere heuynasse &thorn;at he was Inne,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he his bote &thorn;er ne fette,</L>
<L>And gladde &amp; blythe he went home &thorn;ynne.</L>
<L>Thus was &thorn;is abbay encresset y-wys</L>
<L N="935">&THORN;orwe goddus grace &amp; &thorn;is blessude virgyn seynt Awdre, &mdash;</L>
<L>And &yogh;et continuallyche forsothe hit is</L>
<L>Stylle in gret worshippe vnto &thorn;is day;</L>
<L>Fulle gret grace &amp; godenesse is &yogh;et in &thorn;at abbay</L>
<L>By-causa of &thorn;at blessude virgyn &amp; mayden clene,</L>
<L N="940">And meraclus y-done &yogh;et &thorn;ere euery day,</L>
<L>For to euery nedefulle mon he is gode mene.</L>
<L>By-cause of hurre &thorn;at abbay &yogh;et hit is</L>
<L>In hi&yogh;e encresse and ry&yogh;t gode aray,</L>
<L>And "&thorn;e lanterne of Englonde" clepte hit is</L>
<L N="945">&YOGH;et inne-to &thorn;is same day.</L>
<L>And &thorn;er is &yogh;et &thorn;e trenyn cheste</L>
<L>In &thorn;e whiche seynt Awdre ys body lay inne,</L>
<L>And also alle hurre clothus bothe most &amp; lest,<NOTE PLACE="foot">lest aus last corr.</NOTE></L>
<L>Fulle clene y-kepte &thorn;ere with-ou&yogh;t wynne,</L>
<L N="950">And &thorn;e ryng of golde is &thorn;ere &yogh;et y-wys</L>
<L>&THORN;e whiche was hurre professhynalle ryng &mdash;</L>
<L>For vpone hurre shryne &thorn;at ryng &yogh;et hit is &mdash;</L>
<L>A full holy releke &amp; a full preciose thynge.</L>
<L>&THORN;use relekus ben &yogh;et ry&yogh;te folle of grace</L>
<L N="955">And &yogh;euen hele &amp; grace to mony a mone.
<PB REF="00000442.tif" N="304"></L>
<L>And gret pilgremage is &yogh;et to &thorn;at place,</L>
<L>In gret help and in grete hele to mony one,</L>
<L>&THORN;e whiche worshepen &amp; thongone &thorn;is blessude virgyn seynt Awdre</L>
<L>Of hurre grace and of herre gret my&yogh;t.</L>
<L N="960">For to all &thorn;e contrey ferre &amp; ney&yogh;e</L>
<L>Gret help and gret grace to hem &thorn;orow hurre ys dy&yogh;t,</L>
<L>I-grauntede of goddus sone of heuene</L>
<L>For &thorn;at blessude virgyn seynt Awdre</L>
<L>To alle hem &thorn;e whyche ascone with myelde steuene</L>
<L N="965">Of hurre ony help or ony hele hertlye;</L>
<L>&THORN;ay han hit y-grauntyde to hem ry&yogh;t anone</L>
<L>&THORN;orow grace and preyere of &thorn;at blessude virgyn seynt Awdrey,</L>
<L>&THORN;e whiche leythe &thorn;ere with-in &thorn;at marbulle-stone</L>
<L>In &thorn;at worshipfulle abbay of &thorn;e yle of Hely.</L>
<L N="970">Hurre body is &thorn;ere, bot hurre soule is in blys,</L>
<L>And euer shall be with-ou&yogh;t ony hende &mdash;</L>
<L>For so to hurre of god y-grauntyde hit is,</L>
<L>As to a blessude virgyn clene and hende.</L>
<L>And mony a feyre miracull for hurre god hathe &thorn;er wrou&yogh;t</L>
<L N="975">In Hely in &thorn;at worshipfull abbay.</L>
<L>Off &thorn;e whiche nowe on comethe in-to my &thorn;ou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;e whiche y chull to &yogh;ow now wryte and say.</L>
<L>&THORN;e whiche y founde in &thorn;e abbey of Godstow y-wys,</L>
<L>In hurre legent as y dude &thorn;ere &thorn;at tyme rede</L>
<L N="980">Howe &thorn;e abbay of Hely was distryed with &thorn;e Danys</L>
<L>&THORN;e sixstythe &yogh;ere after &thorn;at seynt Werburwe was dede,</L>
<L>And &thorn;use blessude virgynes weron clene put ou&yogh;t</L>
<L>And dweltone neuer sey&yogh;thon forsothe &thorn;ere:</L>
<L>For &thorn;us cursede Danys weron so stou&yogh;te &amp; prou&yogh;t</L>
<L N="985">&THORN;at &thorn;ey durst not dwelle &thorn;er for fere.</L>
<L>Bot in &thorn;e tyme of kyng Edwarde senioure<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. <ABBR>seniore</ABBR>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Seculere chanouns weren put &thorn;er y-wys &mdash;</L>
<L>Bot kyng Edgar &amp; seynt Dunstone, &thorn;at confessour,</L>
<L>Put &thorn;e chanouns ou&yogh;t &amp; set &thorn;ere blake monkys.</L>
<L N="990">Bot &thorn;at tyme &thorn;at &thorn;e chanons dweltone &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>As y sayde to &yogh;ow now ry&yogh;t here byfore,</L>
<L>Won of hem &thorn;ou&yogh;t &thorn;at he nolde not spare for no fere<NOTE PLACE="foot">won = one.</NOTE></L>
<L>To wete wherre &thorn;at maydenus body ley&yogh;e hole &yogh;et &thorn;ore:</L>
<L>And to &thorn;at tombe he went &thorn;o ry&yogh;t anone</L>
<L N="995">And with a chesell he made &thorn;ere a gret hole,</L>
<L>And a ley&yogh;t candelle brennyng he put in-to &thorn;at stone,</L>
<L>And totede in hym-self at a nother hole.<NOTE PLACE="foot">totede = looked.</NOTE></L>
<L>And with an hokude &yogh;erde he wolde han meuyd &thorn;e clothe away,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he my&yogh;t han sey&yogh;e ry&yogh;t at his owne wylle
<PB REF="00000443.tif" N="305"></L>
<L N="1000">&THORN;at blessude body veryliche ry&yogh;t as hit lay,</L>
<L>Wherre hit hadde yley&yogh;e &thorn;er &yogh;et alle hole stylle;</L>
<L>And he hadde put a strong hoke of hiron in &thorn;e &yogh;erde ende,</L>
<L>To han pulde &thorn;e clothe well from hurre body away;</L>
<L>And a gret candell he let &thorn;o tende,</L>
<L N="1005">&THORN;at he my&yogh;t han sey&yogh;e herre body nakede &thorn;er as hit lay.</L>
<L>And he put &thorn;e hoke of &thorn;e &yogh;erde &thorn;e clothes with-inne</L>
<L>And bygon to drawe at hem &thorn;o ry&yogh;t fast:</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;e &yogh;erde stekede styll &thorn;ere &amp; nolde not passe &thorn;ynne.</L>
<L>And &thorn;en was &thorn;is wreche full sore &thorn;erof agast</L>
<L N="1010">And drowe at &thorn;e &yogh;erde &thorn;o with alle his hole my&yogh;t;</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;at blessude virgyn nolde not let &thorn;e &yogh;erde go,</L>
<L>Bot hulte hit stylle ry&yogh;t &thorn;ere, as hit was py&yogh;t, &mdash;</L>
<L>And &thorn;e space of a noure hit stykkyd &thorn;er ry&yogh;t so.</L>
<L>And &thorn;e ley&yogh;t of &thorn;e candelle went ou&yogh;t also anone,</L>
<L N="1015">&THORN;at he hym-self sawe no-thyng y-wys.</L>
<L>&THORN;en stode he &thorn;ere as stylle as ony stone,</L>
<L>And in his hert knewe fulle well &thorn;at he hadde ydone amys.</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;enne fulle fayne he wolde han y-gone,</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf he hade hadde my&yogh;t or grace &thorn;erto:</L>
<L N="1020">Bot he was &thorn;o as blynde as ony stone,</L>
<L>And also he my&yogh;t not on fote &thorn;ennys go,</L>
<L>Bot stode styll &thorn;er with sorwefulle chere &amp; drery mode</L>
<L>And my&yogh;t not on fote &thorn;ennys passe;</L>
<L>Bot cryede fast, as &thorn;aw he were wode,</L>
<L N="1025">When he sye well &amp; veriliche &thorn;at he clene blynde was.</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;en come his felewys rennynge on euery syde</L>
<L>And sayden: "alas, syre Cerdyke, what eylluthe &thorn;e?"<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. Cerdyks od. Cerdyke?</NOTE></L>
<L>"I may not, quad he, gon henne, bot here y mot abyde,</L>
<L>For iche haue gretliche offendyde &thorn;is holy virgyn Awdre.</L>
<L N="1030">Ichaue offendyde, quad Cyrdyke, &thorn;is holy virgyn so</L>
<L>&THORN;at y hope after nomore hele of my body y-wys."</L>
<L>"Whey, sire Cerdyke, quad &thorn;e deyn, what han &yogh;e do</L>
<L>To &thorn;is virgyn so gretlyche amys?</L>
<L>Why may not hit be amendyde by no way?</L>
<L N="1135">Tell me alle-y-fere, ry&yogh;t as &thorn;ou duste,</L>
<L>&THORN;at we mow &thorn;at blessude virgyn for &thorn;e pray."</L>
<L>"To han y-sye hurre body, quad he, y chad gret luste &mdash;</L>
<L>For, treweliche, y tell &yogh;ow &thorn;e sothe alle-y-fere,</L>
<L>I nadde not fulle gret trust &thorn;erto</L>
<L N="1040">&THORN;at hurre body was alle holle now here,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou&yogh;t &thorn;at y shulde loke wherre hit were so:</L>
<L>And y come to &thorn;is tombe &thorn;o after anone,</L>
<L>And &thorn;is gret &yogh;erde in my honde y brou&yogh;t with me,</L>
<L>And made an hole with &thorn;is chesell in &thorn;e stone</L>
<L N="1045">And put in a candell brennyng, &thorn;e better &yogh;yff y my&yogh;t se,
<PB REF="00000444.tif" N="306"></L>
<L>And &thorn;is gret &yogh;erde y put also inne &thorn;ere-by</L>
<L>With a gret hyrone hoke, &thorn;at vpon &thorn;e hende ys,</L>
<L>To han y-drawe away &thorn;e clothus from hurre body,</L>
<L>&THORN;at y my&yogh;t well &thorn;e trewthe han seye how hurre body wys;<NOTE PLACE="foot">wys = was.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1050">And with &thorn;e hoke y cau&yogh;t in hurre clothus gode holde at &thorn;e last<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. clethus?</NOTE></L>
<L>And drow &thorn;e &yogh;erde to me with alle my maynne.</L>
<L>Bot seynt Awdry hulte &thorn;e &yogh;erde so fast</L>
<L>&THORN;at y my&yogh;t not drawe &thorn;e &yogh;erde to me a&yogh;aynne;</L>
<L>And &yogh;et &thorn;e &yogh;erde styketh ry&yogh;t &thorn;ere &mdash;</L>
<L N="1055">&YOGH;yff hit plese &yogh;ow, &yogh;e mow hit well se.</L>
<L>Loke &yogh;e wherre &yogh;e mow &thorn;at &yogh;erde ou&yogh;t tere,</L>
<L>And wherre he wolle fauere &yogh;ow more &thorn;en me!</L>
<L>For y drowe &thorn;e &yogh;erd so fast &thorn;at y doune felle</L>
<L>Euene vpone my bake here vpry&yogh;t;</L>
<L N="1060">And also y chaue y-lost my sy&yogh;t euery delle.</L>
<L>So vengauncelyche ycham now y-dy&yogh;t".</L>
<L>Bote &thorn;e deyn went to &thorn;e tombe anone &thorn;o</L>
<L>In sy&yogh;t of mony o&thorn;er grete men</L>
<L>And drowe at &thorn;e &yogh;erde, as Cerdyke hadde byfore ydo;</L>
<L N="1065">Bot alle &thorn;ey my&yogh;t not tere hit &yogh;et &thorn;en.</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;en &thorn;ey wentene o processione euerichone,</L>
<L>And deden offe hurre hosen &amp; hurre shone alle-y-ffere,</L>
<L>And kneledone doune afterwarde byfore &thorn;at stone</L>
<L>And mekeliche maden herre preyours &thorn;ere,</L>
<L N="1070">And mekelyche prey&yogh;eden seynt Awdry of hurre grace:</L>
<L>As he was wedow and mayden clene,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he wolde for&yogh;eue Cerdyke his gret trespace,</L>
<L>And also &thorn;at he my&yogh;t haue his sy&yogh;t a&yogh;ene.</L>
<L>Bot when &thorn;ay hadden &thorn;us hurre preyours y-made,</L>
<L N="1075">&THORN;ey reson hem vp &thorn;o from &thorn;e gronde euerichone.</L>
<L>And to &thorn;at &yogh;erde a&yogh;eyn &thorn;o anone he &yogh;ade:</L>
<L>And drowe hit &thorn;o ley&yogh;tliche ynowe ou&yogh;t of &thorn;e stone.</L>
<L>Bot when he hadde drowyn ou&yogh;t &thorn;at &yogh;erde,</L>
<L>And stopudde feyre &thorn;at hole alle holle a&yogh;eynne:</L>
<L N="1080">An angels voys forsothe &thorn;er &thorn;ey herde,</L>
<L>&THORN;e whiche sayde &thorn;at Cerdyke wrou&yogh;t all &thorn;at werke in veynne.</L>
<L>And gret ly&yogh;t &thorn;ey seye &thorn;ere &thorn;o also,</L>
<L>And full sote sauere &thorn;ey feltone &thorn;o in euery syde,</L>
<L>And also &thorn;ey herdyn &thorn;e voys eft-sone speke &thorn;o,</L>
<L N="1085">&THORN;e whyche sayde &thorn;at hurre body was as hole as hit was &thorn;erinne lyde;</L>
<L>"And, Cerdyke, he sayde, y warne &thorn;e now also</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou shalt neuer haue &thorn;y sy&yogh;t after &thorn;is,</L>
<L>Bot alle &thorn;i lyff blynde &thorn;ou shalt ry&yogh;t so go,</L>
<L>By-cause &thorn;at &thorn;ou by-leueduste of &thorn;is mayden amys".<NOTE PLACE="foot">by vor leueduste &uuml;berschr.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000445.tif" N="307"></L>
<L N="1090">Bot &thorn;o alle &thorn;ey weron fulle sore agast</L>
<L>&THORN;e whiche herden &thorn;at voys speke on &thorn;is manere.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. herdon od. herden?</NOTE></L>
<L>And when &thorn;ay hadde long yknelyde &thorn;o, at &thorn;e last</L>
<L>&THORN;o blynde Cerdyk &amp; alle &thorn;ey wenton forthe yffere.</L>
<L>And in gret worshepe euer after &thorn;ey hadden &thorn;at mayden y-wys,</L>
<L N="1095">And nomone durst blaspheme herre &thorn;er-after more,</L>
<L>Bot wyst ry&yogh;t well &thorn;at hurre soule was in heuene blys,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at hurre body was as hole as he was mayde y-bore,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at hurre body euer in vrthe in gret worship euer shall be</L>
<L>And ry&yogh;t so hurre blessude soule shall be in heuene blys</L>
<L N="1100">And in &thorn;e ioy &thorn;at euer shall last among &thorn;e coronede maydenus is he:<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. shalt.</NOTE></L>
<L>For amonge hem forsothe hurre dwellynge-plase y-ordenyde hit is.<NOTE PLACE="foot">1110 ff.) D&auml;s Folgende ist sp&auml;ter nach|getragen.</NOTE></L>
<L>And prey we now with alle owre my&yogh;t</L>
<L>To god, owre fader in trinite</L>
<L>&THORN;orow his gret mercy a place vs dy&yogh;t</L>
<L N="1105">To dwelle &thorn;ere, with &thorn;at blessude mayde fre,</L>
<L>And to haue herre euer in owre thou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>In &thorn;e ioy &thorn;at he is now inne,</L>
<L>&THORN;edur as god hathe vs so dure y-bou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>And &thorn;at hit be ry&yogh;t so, say we amen. &mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1110">A no&thorn;ur myracle y &thorn;enke here to pyte</L>
<L>Ry&yogh;te here yn &thorn;is same place,</L>
<L>&THORN;e whyche y say at Hely y-wrete,</L>
<L>Whenne y on pylgrymage laste &thorn;er was,</L>
<L>As y redde yn hure story boke</L>
<L N="1115">By helpe of &thorn;e sexteyne &thorn;at was &thorn;er &thorn;at day,</L>
<L>Whate sorwe kyng Egfryde yn hys herte toke</L>
<L>Whenne seynt Awdre was ago to hure abbay.</L>
<L>For whenne heo was gone fro hym, y-wys,</L>
<L>And yn &thorn;e abbay of Colndy mynchyn furste y-made,</L>
<L N="1120">&THORN;e kyng &thorn;ou&yogh;te he had y-done al amys,</L>
<L>&amp; yn hys herte grete angur he hade</L>
<L>&THORN;at he had y-&yogh;eue hure &thorn;us leue to gone hym fro,</L>
<L>Yn &thorn;e maner byfore wrete &amp; sayde,</L>
<L>And callyd hys cuncel ful ofte hym to</L>
<L N="1125">And dysyryd of hem to haue a&yogh;en &thorn;at mayde,</L>
<L>And ful ofte yn herte he purposyd hym al-so</L>
<L>&THORN;at mayde to fache with streng&thorn;e a&yogh;eyne.</L>
<L>But hys cuncelle nolde not consente &thorn;erto:</L>
<L>Wherefore hys labour was al yn-veyne.</L>
<L N="1130">But whenne he say hys cuncel wuld not consente</L>
<L>To fasche &thorn;at mayde a&yogh;eyne fro hure abbay,</L>
<L>. . . . . </L>
</LG>
<P>(Ende fehlt.)</P>
</DIV2>
