<DIV2 N="10" TYPE="legend"><PB REF="00000453.tif" N="[315]">
<HEAD>10. The Child of Bristowe, aus Ms. Harl. 2382, fol. 118b.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>Dasselbe Ms. enth&auml;lt im Anfang Lydgate's Marienleben, in 6 B&uuml;chern (das 5. de purificatione Mariae fol. 86b, und das 6. de assumptione Mariae fol. 74b&mdash;letzteres das bekannte, von Lumby in s. Ausg. des King Horn edirte Gedicht &mdash; sind willk&uuml;hr|lich angeh&auml;ngt), dann The testament of Lydgate, Chaucer's Prioresses tale und Cae|cilia, darauf Erasmus (ed. in der "Sammlung altengl. Leg." Heilbronn 1878 p. 199, ein and. Ms. ist Cbr. Dd 1, 1), Testamentum Christi, und The Child of Bristowe fol. 118b. Diese Legende, in 12 zeil. Stropfen, scheint in der 2. H&auml;lfte des 14. Jhdts., urspr&uuml;nglich in einem n&ouml;rdlicheren Dialecte, verfasst. Sie ist bereits gedruckt in der Retrosp. Review, New Series, Part VI (v. Thom. Wright), und in Hazlitt's Remains of the early pop. poetry of Engl. I, p. 111&mdash;131.</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>He that made bothe helle &amp; heuene,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. heuene &amp; helle st. helle &amp; heuene, vgl. 555.</NOTE></L>
<L>Man &amp; womman, in dayes VII,</L>
<L>And alle shal fede and fille,</L>
<L>He graunte vs alle his blessyng,<NOTE PLACE="foot">["<I>e</I> nach g in blessyng<I>e</I> V. 4 ... u.s.w. ist zu tilgen, da der Strich an g nicht der Abk&uuml;rzungsstrick ist" --Corrigenda]</NOTE></L>
<L N="5">More &amp; lasse, bothe olde &amp; yong,</L>
<L>That herkeneth &amp; hold hem stille.</L>
<L>The beste song that euer was made</L>
<L>Ys not worth a lekys blade,</L>
<L>But men wol tende &thorn;er-tille.</L>
<L N="10">Therfor y pray yow in &thorn;is place,</L>
<L>Of your talkynge &thorn;at ye be pes,</L>
<L>Yf it be youre wille.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>I found it writen in olde hand</L>
<L>That som-tyme dwellid in Englond</L>
<L N="15">A squyer mykel of myght;</L>
<L>He had castels, tounes &amp; toures,</L>
<L>Feyre forestis &amp; feldes with floures,</L>
<L>Beestis wilde and wight.</L>
<L>To lawe he went a gret while,</L>
<L N="20">Pore men he lerned to begile</L>
<L>Alle agayns the right;</L>
<L>Mykel good he gadred to-gedir</L>
<L>Alle with treson &amp; dedis lither;</L>
<L>He drad not god almyght.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="25">The good he gadred to-geder than,</L>
<L>He had it of many a pore man,</L>
<L>The most partye with wrong.</L>
<L>He had a sone; shuld be his heyre,</L>
<L>Of shap he was semely &amp; feyre,</L>
<L N="30">Of lymes large &amp; long.</L>
<L>So moche his mynde was on &thorn;at childe:</L>
<L>He rought not whom (he) begiled<NOTE PLACE="foot">he fehlt im Ms.</NOTE></L>
<L>Worly good to fong,<NOTE PLACE="foot">worly = worldly.</NOTE></L>
<L>And al to make his sone so riche</L>
<L N="35">That none other myght hym be liche&mdash;</L>
<L>So ment he euer among.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>When the child was XII yere &amp; more,</L>
<L>His fader put hym vnto lore,</L>
<L>To lerne to be a clerke.</L>
<L N="40">So longe he lernyd in clergie</L>
<L>Til he was wise and wittye,</L>
<L>And drad al dedis derke.</L>
<L>The fader seid to his sone dere:</L>
<L>"To lawe thu shalt go a yere,</L>
<L N="45">And coste me XX marke;</L>
<L>For euer the better thu shalt be:</L>
<L>Ther shal no-man begile the,</L>
<L>Neyther in word ne werke"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The child answerd with a softe sawe:</L>
<L N="50">"They fare ful wel &thorn;at lerne no lawe,</L>
<L>And so y hope to do;</L>
<L>That lyue wil y neuer lede</L>
<L>To put my soule in so gret drede</L>
<L>To make god my foo.
<PB REF="00000454.tif" N="316"></L>
<L N="55">To sle my soule, it were routhe.</L>
<L>Any science that is trouthe</L>
<L>Y shal amytte me ther-to;</L>
<L>For to forsake my soule helthe,</L>
<L>For any wynnyng of worldes welthe,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. wordldes.</NOTE></L>
<L N="60">That wille y neuer do.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Hit hath euer be myn avise</L>
<L>To lede my lyf by marchandise,</L>
<L>To lerne to bye and selle;</L>
<L>That good getyne by marchancye<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. marchantye.</NOTE></L>
<L N="65">It is trouthe, as thenketh me;</L>
<L>Ther-with wille y melle.</L>
<L>Here at Bristow dwellith on,</L>
<L>Is hold right a iuste, trew man,</L>
<L>As y here now telle:</L>
<L N="70">His prentys wille y be VII yere,</L>
<L>His science truly for to lere,</L>
<L>And with hym wille y dwelle."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The squyer vnto Bristow rode</L>
<L>And with the marchand cownant made</L>
<L N="75">VII yere to haue his sone;</L>
<L>He gaf hym gold gret plente,</L>
<L>The child his prentys shuld be</L>
<L>His science for to conne.</L>
<L>The child toke ful wel to lore;</L>
<L N="80">His loue was in god euer-more,</L>
<L>As it was his wone.</L>
<L>He wax so curteise &amp; bolde:</L>
<L>Al merrchaunt&yogh; loued hym, yong &amp; olde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at in &thorn;at contre gan wone. &mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="85">Leue we now that child thore,</L>
<L>And of his fader speke we more,</L>
<L>That was so stoute &amp; bolde.</L>
<L>He was avaunced so hye:</L>
<L>Ther was no-man in &thorn;at contre</L>
<L N="90">Durst done but as he wolde.</L>
<L>And euer he vsid vsery,</L>
<L>He wold not lene but he wyst why</L>
<L>Avauntage dobelle tolde;</L>
<L>Tethynges he liste neuer to pay;</L>
<L N="95">Yf parsones &amp; vicares wold oght say,</L>
<L>He newid hem cares colde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Alle thyng wol ende atte last.</L>
<L>God on hym soche sekenes cast:</L>
<L>He myght no lenger abide,</L>
<L N="100">But on his ded-bed he lay</L>
<L>And drow toward his endyng day,</L>
<L>For al his power &amp; pride.</L>
<L>Then he sent for knyghtes &amp; squyers,</L>
<L>Whiche were his comperys,</L>
<L N="105">In that contre besyde.</L>
<L>He seid emonges hem euerychon:</L>
<L>"Sires, my lyf is nere gone,</L>
<L>Hit may not be denyede."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ther was no-man in &thorn;at contre</L>
<L N="110">That his excutour wold be,</L>
<L>Nor for no good ne ille;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Der Reim ist verdorben.</NOTE></L>
<L>They seid his good was geten so:</L>
<L>They wold not haue &thorn;er-with to do,</L>
<L>For drede of god in heuen.</L>
<L N="115">He prayed hem, &amp; they seid nay.</L>
<L>Allas he seid and welaway,</L>
<L>With a rufulle stevyne.</L>
<L>After his sone son he sent</L>
<L>Evyn to Bristow verrament &mdash;</L>
<L N="120">Was thens but myles VII.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The child to chamber toke his way</L>
<L>There his fader on ded-bed lay,</L>
<L>And asked hym of his chere.</L>
<L>"Sone, he seid, wel-come to me!</L>
<L N="125">Y ly here now as &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> may se,</L>
<L>My endyng day negheth nere.</L>
<L>But, sone, thu most be myn heyre</L>
<L>Of al my londes, good &amp; faire,</L>
<L>And my lordships fere &amp; nere.</L>
<L N="130">Therfor, sone, now y pray the</L>
<L>Myn attourney that thu be,</L>
<L>When y am broght to bere."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The child answerd with wordes mylde:</L>
<L>"Ye se, fader, y am but a childe,</L>
<L N="135">Discrecion haue y none;</L>
<L>To take soche a charge on me,</L>
<L>By my faith! that shal not be,</L>
<L>Y can no skyle ther-on.</L>
<L>Here ben knyghtes &amp; squyers</L>
<L N="140">Whiche were your compers,</L>
<L>And many a worthy man;</L>
<L>Yf y shuld soche on me take<NOTE PLACE="foot">nach soche fehlt charge.</NOTE></L>
<L>That alle thes worthi men forsake,</L>
<L>A fole then were y one!"
<PB REF="00000455.tif" N="317"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="145">He seid: "y haue no sone but the,</L>
<L>And myn heire &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> most nedis be &mdash;</L>
<L>Ther may no-man sey nay.</L>
<L>Moche good haue I gadred to-geder</L>
<L>With extorcion &amp; dedis lither &mdash;</L>
<L N="150">Alas and welaway!</L>
<L>Alle this, sone, y gadred for the:</L>
<L>And thu so sone failest me</L>
<L>At my nedeful day!</L>
<L>Frendship, sone, is ylle to triste,</L>
<L N="155">Eche man be ware of "had y wiste",</L>
<L>God wote, so may y say.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Sone, he seid, thu scapest not so &mdash;</L>
<L>That shalt &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> weten, or thu go &mdash;</L>
<L>Hethen charge y the:</L>
<L N="160">To-fore god thu mothe answere,</L>
<L>And as thu wilt my blessyng bere,</L>
<L>Myn attourney that thu be."</L>
<L>"A, fader, ye bynde me with a charge,</L>
<L>And y shal bynde yow with as large</L>
<L N="165">As ye bynde now me:</L>
<L>The same day fortenyght &thorn;at ye passe</L>
<L>Y charge yow appere in this place,</L>
<L>Your spiret lat me se!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For ye haue bound me so sare,</L>
<L N="170">Now y most nedis, how-euer y fare,</L>
<L>Do youre commaundement.</L>
<L>Therfor y charge yow &thorn;at ye appere,</L>
<L>That y may se your soule here,</L>
<L>Whethir it be saued or shent, &mdash;</L>
<L N="175">And that ye do no scathe to me,</L>
<L>Ne none that shal come with the!"</L>
<L>"Sone, he seid, y assent.</L>
<L>But allas that y was borne,</L>
<L>&THORN;at man is soule shuld be lorne</L>
<L N="180">For my golde or rent."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Al thyng most ende atte last.</L>
<L>God soche sekenys on hym cast,</L>
<L>That he most nedis go.</L>
<L>The parishe prest vp was soght,</L>
<L N="185">The gloriose sacrament with hym he broght</L>
<L>That dyed for mannys woo;</L>
<L>There he shrow hym with hert sore,</L>
<L>And cryed god mercy euer-more,</L>
<L>As it was tyme to do.</L>
<L N="190">When god wold, he went his way.</L>
<L>His sones song was welaway,</L>
<L>Fo(r) hym his hert was wo.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>His sone sought fro toune to toune</L>
<L>For prestis &amp; men of religione,</L>
<L N="195">The dirige for to say.</L>
<L>An C prestis he had &amp; mo;</L>
<L>Gret yeftys he gaf hem tho,</L>
<L>Chargyng hem for his fader to pray.</L>
<L>Yonge children had gret hole<NOTE PLACE="foot">had st. mad.</NOTE></L>
<L N="200">And pore wymmen had gret dole &mdash;</L>
<L>That holpe hym not a day.</L>
<L>And sitthe broght hym in his pytt &mdash;</L>
<L>As al men muste, thei may not flyt,</L>
<L>Whethir thei be wel or nay.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="205">When thei had broght hym in his graue,</L>
<L>His sone, &thorn;at thoght his soule to saue</L>
<L>Yf god wold gef hym leue,</L>
<L>Al the catel his fader hade</L>
<L>He sold it vp &amp; money made,</L>
<L N="210">And labored morow &amp; eve:</L>
<L>He sought aboute in &thorn;at contre tho</L>
<L>Where any almes myght be do,</L>
<L>And largely he dud hem yeue,</L>
<L>Wayes &amp; brugges for to make,</L>
<L N="215">And pore men for goddis sake</L>
<L>He yeaf them gret releve.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Who-so axed oght, he made here pay,</L>
<L>And XXX<SUP>ti</SUP> trental of masses he let say</L>
<L>For his fadres sake.</L>
<L N="220">He let neuer til he had bewared</L>
<L>Alle the tresour his fader spared,</L>
<L>Aseth to god forto make.</L>
<L>By &thorn;at day fortenyghtis ende was come,</L>
<L>His gold was gone, alle &amp; some &mdash;</L>
<L N="225">Many one of hym spake;</L>
<L>And al thynges that were meuable</L>
<L>He gaf aboute with-outen fable</L>
<L>To pore men that wold take.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>By than &thorn;e fourtenyght was broght to ende,</L>
<L N="230">The child to the chamber gan wende</L>
<L>Where his fader dyed.
<PB REF="00000456.tif" N="318"></L>
<L>Adoune he knelid half a day,</L>
<L>Al the good prayers &thorn;at he couthe say (!)</L>
<L>His fader forto abide.</L>
<L N="235">Betwene mydday and vnder</L>
<L>&THORN;er cam a blast of lightnynge &amp; dunder</L>
<L>Thurgh the walles wide,</L>
<L>As al &thorn;e place on fire had be.</L>
<L>The child seid benedicite</L>
<L N="240">And fast on god he cryde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And as he sate on his prayere,</L>
<L>Sone before hym gan appere</L>
<L>Foule tydynges betwene:</L>
<L>His faders soule brennynge as glede,</L>
<L N="245">The deuel bi &thorn;e nekke gan hym lede</L>
<L>In a brennynge cheyne.</L>
<L>This child seid: "y coniure the,</L>
<L>What-so-euer &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> be, speke to me!"</L>
<L>That other answerd ageyne:</L>
<L N="250">"Y am thi fader that &thorn;e begate.</L>
<L>Now thu may se of myn astate:</L>
<L>Lo, how y dwelle in peyne."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The child seid: "ful woo is me</L>
<L>In this plite that (y) yow se;<NOTE PLACE="foot">y fehlt.</NOTE></L>
<L N="255">Hit persheth myn hert sore."</L>
<L>"Sone, he seid, thus am y led,</L>
<L>For be-cause of my falshed</L>
<L>That y vsed euer-more,</L>
<L>Mi good was getyn wrongfully.</L>
<L N="260">But it myght restored be</L>
<L>And aseth be made ther-fore,</L>
<L>An C yere thus shal y do.</L>
<L>Gef me my trouthe y were ago!</L>
<L>For til than my soule is lore."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="265">"Nay, fader, that shal not be,</L>
<L>In better plite y wol yow se,</L>
<L>Yf god wol gef me grace.</L>
<L>But ye shal me your trouthe plighte:</L>
<L>This same day fourtenyght</L>
<L N="270">Ye shal appere in this place.</L>
<L>And y shal laboure, yf y may,</L>
<L>To bryng your soule in better way,</L>
<L>Yf y haue lyf and space."</L>
<L>He graunted hym in gret hast.</L>
<L N="275">With that ther cam a donder-blast,</L>
<L>And bothe ther way gan passe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The child had neuer so gret sorwe.</L>
<L>He rose vp apone the morwe,</L>
<L>To Bristow gan he wende.</L>
<L N="280">To his mayster he gan say:</L>
<L>"Y haue serued yow many a day:</L>
<L>For goddis loue be my frend!</L>
<L>My fader out of this world is past.</L>
<L>Y am come to yow in hast,</L>
<L N="285">Y haue euer founde yow kynde:</L>
<L>Me nedith a litel somme of gold:</L>
<L>Myn heritage shal be sold,</L>
<L>Croppe, rote and rynde."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>His maister seid: "what nede were the</L>
<L N="290">To selle thi thrift so hastely?</L>
<L>It were not for thy prow.</L>
<L>Yf thu any bargeyn haue boght,</L>
<L>For gold ne siluer care &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> noght:</L>
<L>Y shal lene the right ynow.</L>
<L N="295">An C mark yf thu wilt haue,</L>
<L>This VII yere I wil none craue.</L>
<L>Wherfor avise the now!</L>
<L>For yf thu selle thyn heritage</L>
<L>That shuld &thorn;e helpe in thi yonge age,</L>
<L N="300">An vnwise man art thow."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Gramercy, he seid, maister hende,</L>
<L>This was a proffer of a frende.</L>
<L>But truly, it shal be sold.</L>
<L>Better chepe ye shal it haue</L>
<L N="305">Then any man, so god me saue!</L>
<L>For nedys y must haue gold."</L>
<L>He seid: "what is it worth by yere?"</L>
<L>"An C marke of money clere:<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. and st. an.</NOTE></L>
<L>The stuward this me tolde".</L>
<L N="310">"Then shal y gef the III C pound,</L>
<L>Euery peny hole and round".</L>
<L>The yonge seid: "y holde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Dere mayster, y yow pray,</L>
<L>Haue here dedis, fech me my pay!<NOTE PLACE="foot">sech st. fech,</NOTE></L>
<L N="315">For y most home agayne.<NOTE PLACE="foot">[home ist zweifelhaft, Ms. eher hone oder hene --Corrigenda]</NOTE></L>
<L>Y haue to do in soundre place,</L>
<L>Y pray yow of fourtenyght space,
<PB REF="00000457.tif" N="319"></L>
<L>Y shal yow quytte, certayne".</L>
<L>His mayster loued hym so welle:</L>
<L N="320">He fette hym gold euery delle.</L>
<L>Than was &thorn;e child ful fayne,</L>
<L>He toke his good &amp; gan to go &mdash;</L>
<L>&amp; for his fader his hert was woo</L>
<L>That bode in so mykel payne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="325">His sone lete crie alaboute</L>
<L>In churches &amp; markettis with-oute doute</L>
<L>Wher his fader dud wone,</L>
<L>Where his fader dud destritione</L>
<L>To man or womman in any toune,</L>
<L N="330">They shuld come to his sone,</L>
<L>"And he shal make aseth &thorn;er-fore</L>
<L>And his good ayen restore,</L>
<L>Eche man his porcione".</L>
<L>Euer as they come, he made here pay,</L>
<L N="335">And charged hem for his fader pray</L>
<L>In blisse that he myght wone.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>By that the fourtenyght was come,</L>
<L>His gold was gon, al &amp; some,</L>
<L>Then had he no more.</L>
<L N="340">In-to the chamber he went &thorn;at tide,</L>
<L>The same that his fader in dyde,</L>
<L>And knelid as he dud ore.</L>
<L>And as he sate in his prayere,</L>
<L>The spiret before hym gan appere,</L>
<L N="345">Right as he dud before,</L>
<L>Saue &thorn;e cheyn away was caught;</L>
<L>Blak he was, but he brent noght;</L>
<L>But yet he was in care.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Welcome, fader! seid the childe,</L>
<L N="350">Y pray yow with wordes mylde,</L>
<L>Tel me of youre astate!"</L>
<L>"Sone, he seid, the better for the.</L>
<L>Y-blessid mote the tyme be</L>
<L>That euer y the begate!</L>
<L N="355">Thou hast releuyd me of moche wo,</L>
<L>My bitter chayne is fal me fro</L>
<L>And the fire so hote.</L>
<L>But yet dwel y stille in peyn,</L>
<L>And euer must, in certeyne,</L>
<L N="360">Tyl y haue fulfilled my day".<NOTE PLACE="foot">Der Reim ist verdorben, st. day l. date.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Fader, he seid, y charge yow tel me:</L>
<L>What is moste ayens the</L>
<L>And doth yow most disese?"</L>
<L>"Tethynges &amp; offrynges, sone, he sayd,</L>
<L N="365">For y them neuer truly payd.</L>
<L>Wherfor my peynes may not cesse</L>
<L>But it be restored agayne</L>
<L>To as many churches, in certayne,</L>
<L>And also mykel encresse.</L>
<L N="370">Alle that for me thu dos pray,</L>
<L>Helpeth me not to the vttermost day</L>
<L>The valure of a pese.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Therfor, sone, y pray the,</L>
<L>Gef me my trouthe y left wit h the,</L>
<L N="375">And let me wynde my way!"</L>
<L>"Nay, fader, he seid, ye gete it noght.</L>
<L>Another craft ther shal be soght,</L>
<L>Yet efte y wille assay.</L>
<L>But your trouthe ye shal me plight:</L>
<L N="380">This same day a fourtenyght</L>
<L>Ye shal come ageyn to your day,</L>
<L>Ye shalle appere here in this place;</L>
<L>And y shal loke with goddis grace</L>
<L>To amende yow, yf y may".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="385">The spiret went forth in his way.</L>
<L>The childe rose vp that other day,</L>
<L>For no-thynge wold he lette,</L>
<L>Even to Bristow gan he wynde.</L>
<L>There he mette with his maister hynde,</L>
<L N="390">Wel goodly he hym grette.</L>
<L>"When y haue nede, y come to yow.</L>
<L>Mayster, but ye help me now,</L>
<L>In sorwe my herte is sette;</L>
<L>Me nedith a litel summe of gold,</L>
<L N="395">Another bargeyn make y wold"</L>
<L>And with that word he wepte.<NOTE PLACE="foot">l. grette st. wepte?</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Hys maister seid: "&thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> art a fole,</L>
<L>Thu has bene at som bad scole;</L>
<L>By my feith! y hold the mad.</L>
<L N="400">For thu has played atte dice</L>
<L>Or at som other games nyce</L>
<L>And loft vp sone &thorn;at thu had.</L>
<L>Thu hast right noght &thorn;at &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> may selle:
<PB REF="00000458.tif" N="320"></L>
<L>Alle is gone, as y here telle.</L>
<L N="405">Thi gouernaunce, sone, is bad".</L>
<L>Then he seid vntil his maister fre:</L>
<L>"Myn owne body y wil selle to the,</L>
<L>For euer to be thy lad.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bonde to the y wille me bynde,</L>
<L N="410">Me &amp; alle myne to &thorn;e worldis ende,</L>
<L>To helpe me in this nede".</L>
<L>He seid: "how mykel woldest &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> haue?"</L>
<L>"XL mark, and ye wold foche-saue,</L>
<L>For that shuld do my dede.</L>
<L N="415">I hope that shal my cares kele".</L>
<L>The burges louyd &thorn;e child so wele,</L>
<L>That to his chamber he yede;</L>
<L>XL pound he gan hym brynge:</L>
<L>"Sone, here is more than thyn askynge.</L>
<L N="420">Almyghti god the spede!"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Gramercy, sire! gan he say,</L>
<L>God yow quiytte, that best may!</L>
<L>And trewe ye shal me fynde.</L>
<L>Y haue to do a thynge or two,</L>
<L N="425">A fourtenyght gef me lef to go!</L>
<L>Y haue euer founde yow kynde".</L>
<L>He gaf hym leue. he went his way,</L>
<L>But on his fader he thoght ay &mdash;</L>
<L>He goth not out of mynde.</L>
<L N="430">He sought alle &thorn;e churches in &thorn;at contre</L>
<L>Where his fader had dwellid by,</L>
<L>He left not one behynde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>He made aseth with hem echon.</L>
<L>By &thorn;at tyme his gold was gone,</L>
<L N="435">They couthe aske hym no mare.</L>
<L>Saue as he went by &thorn;e strete,</L>
<L>With a pore man gan he mete,</L>
<L>Almost naked and bare.</L>
<L>"Your fader oweth me for a &yogh;eme of corn" &mdash;</L>
<L N="440">Doun he knelid hym beforne &mdash;</L>
<L>"And y hym drad ful sare.</L>
<L>For your fader soules sake,</L>
<L>Som amendes to me ye make,</L>
<L>For hym that Marie bare!"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="445">"Welaway, seid &thorn;e yonge man,</L>
<L>For my gold &amp; siluer is gan;</L>
<L>Y haue not for to pay".</L>
<L>Of his clothes he gan take</L>
<L>And put hem on &thorn;e poreman is bake,</L>
<L N="450">Chargynge for his fader to pray;</L>
<L>Hosen &amp; shon he gaue hym tho,</L>
<L>In sherte and breche he gan go,</L>
<L>He had no clothes gay.</L>
<L>In-to the chamber he went &thorn;at tide,</L>
<L N="455">The same &thorn;at his fader on dyde,</L>
<L>And knelid half a day.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>When he had knelid &amp; prayed longe,</L>
<L>Hym thoght he herd &thorn;e myriest songe</L>
<L>&THORN;at any erthely man myght here.</L>
<L N="460">After the song he saw a light,</L>
<L>As thow a thousant torches bright:</L>
<L>It shone so faire and clere.</L>
<L>In that light so faire lemand</L>
<L>A naked child in angelis hand</L>
<L N="465">Before hym dud appere</L>
<L>And seid: "sone, blessid thu be,</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;at euer shalle come of the,</L>
<L>That euer thu goten were!"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Fader, he seid, ful wel is me,</L>
<L N="470">In that plite that y yow se!</L>
<L>Y houe that ye be saue".<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. houe = howe oder st. hope.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Sone, he seid, y go to blisse.</L>
<L>God almyghti quyte the this</L>
<L>Thi good ageyn to haue.</L>
<L N="475">Thu has made the ful bare,</L>
<L>To aqueynche me of mykel care.</L>
<L>My trouthe, good sone, y craue".</L>
<L>"Haue your trouthe, he seid, fre,</L>
<L>And of thi blessynge y pray the,</L>
<L N="480">Yf that ye wold foche-saue".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"In that blessynge mote &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> wone</L>
<L>That oure lady gaf here sone,</L>
<L>And myn on the y lay".</L>
<L>Now that soule is gon to blisse,</L>
<L N="485">With moche ioye and angelis,</L>
<L>More then y can say.</L>
<L>This child thanked god almyght
<PB REF="00000459.tif" N="321"></L>
<L>And his moder, Marye bright,</L>
<L>When he sey that aray.</L>
<L N="490">Even to Bristow gan he gon,</L>
<L>In his sherte &amp; breche allone &mdash;</L>
<L>Had he no clothes gay.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>When &thorn;is burges &thorn;e child gan se,</L>
<L>He seid then "benedicite!</L>
<L N="495">Sone, what araye is this?"</L>
<L>"Truly, maister, seid &thorn;e childe,</L>
<L>Y am come me to yelde</L>
<L>As youre bonde-man".<NOTE PLACE="foot">Die Reime sind verdorben.</NOTE></L>
<L>The burges seid anone right:</L>
<L N="500">Me mervayleth mykel of &thorn;is sight.</L>
<L>Tel me now, how it ys?"<NOTE PLACE="foot">499&mdash;501 sind umzustellen.</NOTE></L>
<L>"What-som-euer ye put me to,</L>
<L>After my power it shal be do,</L>
<L>While my lyf wil laste".<NOTE PLACE="foot">502&mdash;4 sind umzustellen.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot">Die Reime sind verdorben.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="505">"For &thorn;e loue be-twene vs hath be,</L>
<L>Telle me, sone, how it stant with the,</L>
<L>Why thu gos in this aray?"</L>
<L>"Sir, al my good y haue sold, ywys,</L>
<L>To gete my fader to heuene blys,</L>
<L N="510">For-sothe, as y yow say.</L>
<L>For ther was no-man but y</L>
<L>That wold be his attourny</L>
<L>At his endynge day".</L>
<L>Tho he told hym furthere</L>
<L N="515">How ofte he dud his fader appere</L>
<L>And eke in what aray.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"And now his soule into blisse</L>
<L>Y sey hym led with angelis.</L>
<L>Al-myghti god the yelde!</L>
<L N="520">For thurf youre good he is saue.</L>
<L>And his dere blessyng y haue,</L>
<L>And al my cares be kelde".</L>
<L>"Sone, he seid, blessid mote &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> be</L>
<L>That so pore woldest make the,</L>
<L N="525">Thi faders soule to saue!<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. saue st. belde?</NOTE></L>
<L>To speke &thorn;e honour may almankynde:</L>
<L>Thu art a tristy, siker frende &mdash;</L>
<L>Soche fynde y but sildene.<NOTE PLACE="foot">sildene st. selde.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>But fewe sones ben of tho</L>
<L N="530">That wol serue here fader so,</L>
<L>When he is hens gone.</L>
<L>Sectours fynd y many on,</L>
<L>But none soche as &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> art on,</L>
<L>By my feith! y leve not on".<NOTE PLACE="foot">Nach 534 fehlt eine halbe Stropfe.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="535">Hys maister seid: "y shal &thorn;e telle:</L>
<L>Thu canst bothe bye &amp; selle:</L>
<L>Here now make y the</L>
<L>Myn owne felow in al wise</L>
<L>Of worldly good &amp; marchandise,</L>
<L N="540">For thy trouthe so fre.</L>
<L>Al-so, sone, y haue no childe,</L>
<L>Myn heritage for to wilde,</L>
<L>Goten of my body:</L>
<L>Here y make the now myn heyre</L>
<L N="545">Of alle my landes, good &amp; faire &mdash;</L>
<L>And myn attorney that &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> be"!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>His maister dud hym weddid be</L>
<L>To a worthy man is doghter of &thorn;at contre,</L>
<L>With ioye and grete solace.</L>
<L N="550">And when his mayster was ded,</L>
<L>In-to alle his good he entred,</L>
<L>Londes, catelle and place.</L>
<L>Thus hath &thorn;is yonge man keuered care,</L>
<L>First was riche &amp; sitthen bare,</L>
<L N="555">And sitthen riccher then euer he was.</L>
<L>Now he &thorn;at made bothe helle &amp; heuene</L>
<L>And alle the worlde in dayes seuene,</L>
<L>Graunte vs alle his grace! Amen.</L>
<TRAILER>Explicit the Tale of the Childe of Bristow.
</TRAILER>

</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="11" TYPE="legend"><PB REF="00000460.tif" N="[322]">
<HEAD>II. The Tale of the Smyth and his Dame. Aus einem alten Drucke in der Bodleiana zu Oxford (4<SUP>to</SUP>, Seld. C. 39).</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>Dieses Gedicht, in demselben Dialect und Strop?enbau und wol von demselben Dichter wie die Disputisoun bytwene a cristenemon and a Jew (Sir Water of Berewyk's wunderbarer Sieg &uuml;ber einen Juden) gedruckt in der "Sammlung altengl. Leg." Heilbronn 1878, p. 204 ff., ist wol schon c. 1360 gedichtet, leider aber nur in einem sp&auml;teren Druck des Will. Copland in Lothbury, ohne Angabe der Jahreszahl (Anfang des 16. Jhdts.) erhalten; das einzige Exemplar dieser Ausgabe ist in der Bodleiana zu Oxford, Seld. C 39, beschrieben in Dibdin's British Bibliographer 1810 I p. 61&mdash;5. Hieraus ist das Gedicht edirt von Halliwell in s. Contributions to early Engl. Litterature London 1849 (for private circulation). In dem Exemplar zu Oxford fehlt leider ein Blatt mit V. 114&mdash;180. Neuerdings hat sich im Cajus Coll. zu Cambridge ein Fragment in 2 Halbbl&auml;ttern aus einer anderen Ausg. dess. Gedichts, von Wynkyn de Worde London ab. 1505, gefunden, welches einen Theil des Fehlen|den erg&auml;nzt; von dem ersten Blatte ist die obere H&auml;lfte wit je 19 V. auf der Vorder|und R&uuml;ckseite, von dem zweiten die untere H&auml;lfte mit je 12 V. erhalten, mit den Vv. 105&mdash;123, 135&mdash;154, 184&mdash;195, 214&mdash;225. &mdash; Der urspr&uuml;ngliche, n&ouml;rdliche Dialect ist in der Ausg. zum Theil verderbt.</P><P>Here begynneth a plesaunt treatyse of the smyth that brent hys dame and after forged her agayne by the helpe of our blessed lorde.</P><P>Imprinted in London, Lothburi, over against Sainct Margarites Church, by Willyam Copland.</P></HEADNOTE>
<HEAD>Here begynneth a treatyse of the smyth whych that forged hym a new dame.</HEAD>
<DIV3 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>God that dyed on a tree,</L>
<L>He glad them al with his gle</L>
<L>That wyll herken unto me</L>
<L>And here what I wyll say:</L>
<L N="5">And ye shall here a marvel,</L>
<L>Of a tale I shall you tell,</L>
<L>How in Egypt it befell.</L>
<L>And in that same countraye</L>
<L>Some tyme ther dwelled a smyth,</L>
<L N="10">That hath bothe lande and lyth,</L>
<L>Many a plowman hym wyth,</L>
<L>By nyght and eke by day.</L>
<L>The smyth was a subtyll syer,</L>
<L>For well could he werke wyth the fyer</L>
<L N="15">What men of hym wolde desyer &mdash;</L>
<L>I tel you trouth, by my fay!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>He coude werke wyth a mall</L>
<L>Many maner of metall.</L>
<L>Hymselfe mayster dyd he call</L>
<L N="20">Wythouten any pere.</L>
<L>Moche boste gan he blowe</L>
<L>And sayd he had no felowe</L>
<L>That coud worke worth a strawe</L>
<L>To hym, ferre nor nere;</L>
<L N="25">He called hymselfe the kynge,</L>
<L>Wythout any leasynge,</L>
<L>Of all maner of cunnynge,</L>
<L>And of certes clere.<NOTE PLACE="foot">certes = desertes; od. l. artes?</NOTE></L>
<L>Tyll it befell upon a day</L>
<L N="30">Our lorde came thereaway</L>
<L>And thought the smyth to assay,</L>
<L>As ye shall after here.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For hys pompe and hys pryde</L>
<L>That he blewe in eche syde,</L>
<L N="35">Our lorde thought at that tyde</L>
<L>His pryde should be layed.
<PB REF="00000461.tif" N="323"></L>
<L>As the smyth stode workynge,</L>
<L>To hym came our heaven kynge,</L>
<L>"Now he that made all thynge,</L>
<L N="40">Spede the!" he sayde,</L>
<L>He sayd: "I have a thyng to make;</L>
<L>And thou wylt it undertake</L>
<L>And do for my sake,</L>
<L>Thou shalt be well payed."</L>
<L N="45">The smyth sayd: "So mote I the,</L>
<L>Tell on and let me se!</L>
<L>It shal be done full wyghtely</L>
<L>Wythin a lyttel brayed.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For I am mayster of all</L>
<L N="50">That smyteth wyth hamer or mall,</L>
<L>And so may thou me call,</L>
<L>I tell the for veray:</L>
<L>I sawe hym never wyth myne eye</L>
<L>That could werke lyke I,</L>
<L N="55">I tell the full truely,</L>
<L>By nyght ne by day."</L>
<L>"Can thou make a yerd&egrave; of stele,</L>
<L>To lede a blynde man wele" &mdash;</L>
<L>. . . . .<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Nach 59 fehlt ein Vers.</NOTE></L>
<L N="60">Our lorde gan to say,</L>
<L>"And make it so wyth thy mall,</L>
<L>That he shall never stomble ne fall?</L>
<L>Than a mayster I wyll the call,</L>
<L>Syr, by my fay!"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="65">The smyth than in a stody stode,</L>
<L>Sayde: "I trowe thou be wode,</L>
<L>Or els thou can but litle good,</L>
<L>To talke of suche a thynge!</L>
<L>And he be blynde, he must nede</L>
<L N="70">Have a felowe, hym to lede,</L>
<L>That may se well indede,</L>
<L>To kepe hym fro fallynge.</L>
<L>For, and two blynd men together go,</L>
<L>Full oft they fall bothe two &mdash;</L>
<L N="75">It must nedes be so:</L>
<L>They have no maner of seynge.</L>
<L>How should a blynde dotarde</L>
<L>Walke wyth a blynd yarde,</L>
<L>If it be stele never so harde?</L>
<L N="80">It is but a very leasynge.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>It were a(s) lytell maystry<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Copl. a st. as.</NOTE></L>
<L>To make a blynde man to se</L>
<L>As suche a yerde truely,</L>
<L>Wythouten any layne."</L>
<L N="85">"Yes, sayde oure lorde, that I can:</L>
<L>Make suche yerde, certayne,</L>
<L>Or he that is an olde man</L>
<L>To make hym yonge agayne."</L>
<L>The smyth sayd: "So mote I the,</L>
<L N="90">I have an olde quayne wyth me,</L>
<L>Myne olde beldame is she,</L>
<L>I tell the, wythout any layne;</L>
<L>It is forty wynter and mo</L>
<L>Syth on fote she dyd go;</L>
<L N="95">And thou coud make her yonge so,</L>
<L>Than wolde I be fayne."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Our lorde sayd: "Where is she?</L>
<L>Anone let me her se,</L>
<L>And thou shalt se a maystre</L>
<L N="100">More than thou can."</L>
<L>The smyth sayd: "So mote I the,</L>
<L>I shall her fetche unto the."</L>
<L>Anone than full wyghtely</L>
<L>After her the smyth ranne,</L>
<L N="105">And sayd: "Dame, slepest thou?<NOTE PLACE="foot2">sayde.</NOTE></L>
<L>I am come for the: thou mayest me trowe,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">com. mayste.</NOTE></L>
<L>Thou shalt be made nowe<NOTE PLACE="foot2">shalte.</NOTE></L>
<L>Agayne a yonge woman."</L>
<L>He hent her up than on hye:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">hyr vp.</NOTE></L>
<L N="10">Than set she forth a loude cry<NOTE PLACE="foot2">forthe. lowde crye.</NOTE></L>
<L>And sayd: "Stronge thefe, let me ly!<NOTE PLACE="foot2">sayde. lye.</NOTE></L>
<L>Thou art, I trowe, a madde man.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">arte. mad.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Lette me lye, thou unthryfty swayne!"<NOTE PLACE="foot2">vnthryfty.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<P><B>Hier fehlt ein Blatt.</B></P>
<P>Das Fragment des Druckes Worde's f&auml;hrt fort p. I: ["Nay, dame! withouten ony layne]</P>
<LG>
<L N="115">
<PB REF="00000462.tif" N="324">Thou shalte be made yonge agayne &mdash;</L>
<L>Thou arte a very olde trote."</L>
<L>To our lorde than he hyr bore</L>
<L>And sayde: "syr, loo, I haue broughte hyr here.</L>
<L>Thou maye se by hyr chere</L>
<L N="120">That she is chekmate."</L>
<L>Oure lorde sayde: "gode syre,</L>
<L>Hye the faste and make a fyre,</L>
<L>And blowe gladly for thy hyre!"<NOTE PLACE="foot2">V. 105&mdash;123 finden sich auf der I. Seite des Fragmentes des Druckes von Wyn|kyn de Worde, London ab. 1505, in Caj. Coll. Cbr. Varianten dieses Druckes sind:</NOTE></L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L>(11 V. fehlen. p. 2 enth&auml;lt V. 135&mdash;154.)</L>
<L N="135">Than began she to grone</L>
<L>And lowde out to crye,</L>
<L>Sayde: "I forfende you to-daye</L>
<L>Ony handes on me to ley.</L>
<L>What, wyll ye bren me?</L>
<L N="140">Fye on you, fye!</L>
<L>Out, theues! wyll ye me kyll?</L>
<L>Lete god on me worke his wyll!</L>
<L>Ye shall be hanged on a hyll.</L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L N="145">I am fyue-score yere olde,</L>
<L>Yet lyue lenger I wolde.</L>
<L>Howe dare ye be so bolde</L>
<L>With me thus for to fare?"</L>
<L>"Howe, quod our lorde to the smyth,</L>
<L N="150">Thou canste beste dele her with:</L>
<L>Lay hyr vpon the styth</L>
<L>Without ony more stryfe!"</L>
<L>The smyth toke hyr vp tyte.</L>
<L>Tho began she to byte]</L>
<L N="155">. . . . .</L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L N="180">"She shall be made at a brayd</L>
<L>Yonge now agayne."</L>
<L>The smyth blewe, as god bed,</L>
<L>Tyll she was reed as a gled;</L>
<L>Yet for all that dede</L>
<L>Felt she no maner of payne.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Felte.</NOTE></L>
<L N="185">The smith said: "Now is she shent:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">sayde. nowe. shente.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bothe her eyen are out brent;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">hyr iyen.</NOTE></L>
<L>They wyl never be ment,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">wylI. neuer. amende.</NOTE></L>
<L>Our workes are all in vayne.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">werkes.</NOTE></L>
<L>She hath had suche a hete:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">has. an.</NOTE></L>
<L N="190">She wyll never eat mete;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">That she. ete.</NOTE></L>
<L>I have blowen tyll I swete,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">haue.</NOTE></L>
<L>Withouten any layne."<NOTE PLACE="foot2">ony.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Our lorde sayd: "Let me alone!<NOTE PLACE="foot2">sayde. lete.</NOTE></L>
<L>Thou shalt se, and that anone,</L>
<L N="195">A full fayre woman<NOTE PLACE="foot2">V. 184&mdash;195 stehen auf der 3. Seite des Fragments. Varianten:</NOTE></L>
<L>Of thys olde wyght".</L>
<L>Our lord blessed her at a brayd</L>
<L>And on the styth he her layd,</L>
<L>"Take thy hamer, he sayd,</L>
<L N="200">And make her now ryght!</L>
<L>"Dame, I shall the wake".</L>
<L>Wyth a hamer he her strake,</L>
<L>No bone of her he brake:</L>
<L>She was a byrd bryght.</L>
<L N="205">"Stand up now, lette me se!"</L>
<L>Than at that worde rose she,</L>
<L>A fayre woman, truely,</L>
<L>And semely unto syght.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Our lord sayd to the smyth:</L>
<L N="210">"She is sounde of lymme and lyth,</L>
<L>Nowe I have made her on the styth<NOTE PLACE="foot1">nowe st. newe?</NOTE></L>
<L>Wyth hamer and wyth mall".</L>
<L>Than was she loveseme of chere,<NOTE PLACE="foot1">C. loveseme.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bright as blosome on brere &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">bryght. blosom.</NOTE></L>
<L N="215">None in Egypt her pere,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">egypte. hyr.</NOTE></L>
<L>So fayre and so tall;</L>
<L>Her colour was clere,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Hyr coloure was full clere.</NOTE></L>
<L>She semed but thyrty yere,</L>
<L>She was whiter of lere<NOTE PLACE="foot2">whyter.</NOTE></L>
<L N="220">Than bone is of whale.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">bones is.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000463.tif" N="325"></L>
<L>Than our lorde gan say:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">oure. saye.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Now is here a fayre may!<NOTE PLACE="foot2">nowe.</NOTE></L>
<L>Smyth, by night and by day<NOTE PLACE="foot2">nyght.</NOTE></L>
<L>Thy mayster thou me call!</L>
<L N="225">Now mayest thou se here in syght<NOTE PLACE="foot2">nowe mayste.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">V. 214&mdash;225 sind auf der 4. Seite des Fragments erhalten. Varianten:</NOTE></L>
<L>Hole and of lym lyght</L>
<L>That was before an olde wyght,</L>
<L>Both croked fote and hande".</L>
<L>"Gramercy, syr, sayd she,</L>
<L N="230">For thou hast wrought on me,</L>
<L>It was a full great maystry,</L>
<L>As I understande.</L>
<L>I was blynde, nowe may I se;</L>
<L>Croked I was truely,</L>
<L N="235">Now may I walke wyghtly;</L>
<L>My bales are unbande.</L>
<L>Suche a smyth as thou art one,</L>
<L>I dare say, here is none,</L>
<L>And a man shoulde gone</L>
<L N="240">Throughout thys land.</L>
<L>For I dare say that thou can,</L>
<L>Yf here were a dead man,<NOTE PLACE="foot1">C. wert.</NOTE></L>
<L>Make hym on lyve anone</L>
<L>With thy excelent maystry".</L>
<L N="245">Than the smyth gan say:</L>
<L>"Syr, what shall I to the pay,</L>
<L>Or thou wende thy way,</L>
<L>Thy craft to teche me?"</L>
<L>Our lord sayd than to him againe:</L>
<L N="250">"That thou desyrest, is all in vayne;</L>
<L>Thought &thorn;ou woldest never so faine,</L>
<L>Yet wyl it never be;</L>
<L>Thou shalt never, yf thou wolde,</L>
<L>Make an yonge man of an olde.</L>
<L N="255">Therfore be not to bolde,</L>
<L>Leest it do disceyve thee!</L>
<L>Yet thou toldest me longe ere</L>
<L>Thou were wysest man of leere</L>
<L>That was knowen any-where,</L>
<L N="260">Other farre or els nere!</L>
<L>Farewell now and have good day!</L>
<L>I must forthe wende on my jorney</L>
<L>Into another countrey</L>
<L>Amonge many craftes there.</L>
<L N="265">And leve thy bostes, I rede the!</L>
<L>For I tell the now treuely:</L>
<L>Is none so wyse ne to sle</L>
<L>But ever ye may somwhat lere". &mdash;</L>
<L>Now lysten, syrs, at asent,</L>
<L N="270">And ye wil nowe my tale tent,</L>
<L>How the smith hys dame brent</L>
<L>In the next fyt ye shall here.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="section">
<HEAD>The seconde fytte.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whan our lorde was gone,</L>
<L>The smyth rathely and anone</L>
<L N="275">Called on hys dame Jone</L>
<L>And bad her com on fast.</L>
<L>Anone she aunswered tho:</L>
<L>"Thou wotest I may not go,</L>
<L>Wherto cryest thou so?</L>
<L N="280">Is thy wytte past?</L>
<L>I am croked and also lame,</L>
<L>And now to go, it is no shame(!),<NOTE PLACE="foot1">now st. not?</NOTE></L>
<L>Age doth me muche grame,</L>
<L>Me thynketh my bones brast.</L>
<L N="285">Thou wotest well I may no(t) se,</L>
<L>Almost I am as blynde as a be;</L>
<L>And yf I bye me, truely,</L>
<L>To fall I am agast".</L>
<L>The smyth hande on her layd:</L>
<L N="290">"Come forth, dame! he sayd,</L>
<L>Thou shalt be made at a brayd</L>
<L>Younge and lusty agayne.</L>
<L>Thy dame is yonge agayne, i-wys,</L>
<L>She is mended of her mysse,</L>
<L N="295">Her rudde redder it is</L>
<L>Than the rose is in rayne".</L>
<L>"That is a lye, quod she,</L>
<L>I fayth, that wyl never be!</L>
<L>She is blynde of that one eye,</L>
<L N="300">Her bones are unbayne".</L>
<L>The smyth sayd: "Lo! she is here,</L>
<L>The swete dame that the bere:</L>
<L>She is lovesome of chere,</L>
<L>Wythouten any layne".</L>
<L N="305">"Art thou my mother?" sayd she.</L>
<L>"Ye", sayd she, "truely".
<PB REF="00000464.tif" N="326"></L>
<L>Than sayd she: "Benedicite!</L>
<L>Who hath made the thus?"</L>
<L>Anone to her gan she say:</L>
<L N="310">"I was made thus to-daye</L>
<L>Wyth one that came by the waye,</L>
<L>Men call hys name Jesus".</L>
<L>"Now truely, than, sayd she,</L>
<L>He hath amended well thy ble;</L>
<L N="315">For yesterday, so mote I the,</L>
<L>Thou were a foule sose".</L>
<L>"Dame, sayd the smyth tho,</L>
<L>I can make the yonge so,<NOTE PLACE="foot">C. yonde st. yonge.</NOTE></L>
<L>Had I a fyre brennynge blo.</L>
<L N="320">But now thou must helpe us".</L>
<L>Than the smyth at a brayed</L>
<L>A quarter of coles on he layed:</L>
<L>"Let us blowe nowe, he sayed,</L>
<L>Tyl all be on glede!</L>
<L N="325">And thou shalt se, dame, in hy</L>
<L>A crafte for the maystry;</L>
<L>Full fewe men can it but I,</L>
<L>I tel the trouthe, indede".</L>
<L>"Why, what wylt thou do with me?"</L>
<L N="330">"Dame, brenne the" sayd he.</L>
<L>"Nay, not so, sayd she,</L>
<L>Chryst it forbede!</L>
<L>To brenne me, were a shrewde game:</L>
<L>Wottest not thou, knave, whome I am?</L>
<L N="335">Thefe, I am thyne owne dame!</L>
<L>Evyll mote thou spede!</L>
<L>Traytour, and thou brenne me,</L>
<L>Thou shalt be hanged on a tree.</L>
<L>My malyson I gyve thee,</L>
<L N="340">Woldest thou me slo:</L>
<L>God let thee never eate brede,</L>
<L>Woldest thou have thy dam dede.</L>
<L>Touche me not, I thee rede,</L>
<L>For bothe thyne eyen two!</L>
<L N="345">The fyrst tyme I thee see,</L>
<L>I wolde I had throtled thee,</L>
<L>Now thou woldest brenne me</L>
<L>And werke me thys wo!</L>
<L>I tell thee, by sweete saynt John,</L>
<L N="350">Thou shalt have my malyson,</L>
<L>But thy hamer anone</L>
<L>Thou cast thee fro.</L>
<L>Moche wo hast thou wrought;</L>
<L>I kept the when thou were nought,</L>
<L N="355">Fostred and forth the brought,</L>
<L>Full oft dyd I wake".<NOTE PLACE="foot">C. make st. wake.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Dame, sayd the smyth, I trowe,</L>
<L>Olde shrewe, it is for thy prowe</L>
<L>That on thys wyse nowe</L>
<L N="360">Yonge I shall thee make.</L>
<L>Anone se that thou shall:</L>
<L>Had I my hamer and mi mall,</L>
<L>I wolde make the full tall</L>
<L>And yonge, I undertake".</L>
<L N="365">He layed hande on her tho.</L>
<L>Than she spurned at hym so</L>
<L>That hys shynnes bothe two</L>
<L>In-sonder she there brake.</L>
<L>Than the smyth began to stare</L>
<L N="370">And sayd: "Dame, God gyve the care!</L>
<L>What aylest thee thus to fare?<NOTE PLACE="foot">aylest st. ayles.</NOTE></L>
<L>I trowe thou art wode!</L>
<L>Yonge ful soone I can make thee,</L>
<L>And that anone thou shalt se;</L>
<L N="375">I am waxen now full crafty,</L>
<L>I tell thee, by the rode!</L>
<L>Thou spendest now and mai not pay,</L>
<L>Thou hast lyen full many a day</L>
<L>By the wall, for sothe I thee say,</L>
<L N="380">And can do no good".</L>
<L>Full fast the fyre gan he blow,</L>
<L>And sayd: "Be thou never so throw,</L>
<L>I shal amende the sonne, I trow,</L>
<L>Of bone and eke of bloud".</L>
<L N="385">She sayde: "Syr, by saynt Jhone,</L>
<L>Of thy mendyng kepe I none.</L>
<L>Therfore let me alone</L>
<L>And touche me no more!"</L>
<L>"Yes, sayde he, that I mote.</L>
<L N="390">Come forthe, olde dote!"</L>
<L>She catched hym by the throte,</L>
<L>That bloud out gan fare.</L>
<L>As he drew her nere,</L>
<L>She set her fote agaynst a spere,</L>
<L N="395">And sayd: "Thefe, wylt thou me dere?</L>
<L>God gyve the care!"</L>
<L>He cast her on the smythes stocke,</L>
<L>And than she hent hym by the locke
<PB REF="00000465.tif" N="327"></L>
<L>And gave hym many a great knocke,</L>
<L N="400">She spared not the bare.</L>
<L>Ever she sporned wyth her fote;</L>
<L>In hande a hamer she gate</L>
<L>And knocked hym above the pate:</L>
<L>The bloud gan out-brast.</L>
<L N="405">And she carped at hym then,</L>
<L>"Strong thefe, she sayd, I shall the ken</L>
<L>Thyne owne dame for to brenne!"</L>
<L>She bette upon him fast.</L>
<L>There she had welny</L>
<L N="410">Stryken out his one eye &mdash;</L>
<L>Though the smyth bygge be,</L>
<L>Of her he was abasshed.</L>
<L>Stefly on her fete she stode</L>
<L>And smote on him as she were wode;</L>
<L N="415">The smyth ranne on reed blode,</L>
<L>All to-rent and rasshed.</L>
<L>The smyth at a brayd</L>
<L>Wolde her in the fyre have layd.</L>
<L>"Nay, thefe, tho she sayd,</L>
<L N="420">Yet wyl I not come there.</L>
<L>"Helpe, some good man, sayd she,</L>
<L>Thys thefe wyl brenne me!"</L>
<L>Anone than full myghtely</L>
<L>She caught hym by the heer;</L>
<L N="425">Of his lockes gan she pull</L>
<L>Many great handfull,</L>
<L>Rent the skyn from the skull,</L>
<L>The pan gan appeare.</L>
<L>She sayd: "Thefe, lette me go!</L>
<L N="430">Wylt thou thy dame slo?"</L>
<L>Loude out cryed she tho,</L>
<L>That many a man myght here.</L>
<L>The smyth than in hast</L>
<L>Water on the coles cast,</L>
<L N="435">The fyre he blewe full fast</L>
<L>And made it brenne full bryght.</L>
<L>The smyth, angred wyth that,</L>
<L>Cast her in the fyre flat;</L>
<L>All-way fast gan she scrat</L>
<L N="440">At hym wyth all her myght.</L>
<L>Into the fyre he her thrast</L>
<L>And sayd: "I holde thy wytte past.</L>
<L>Olde shrowe, at the last</L>
<L>Thou shalt be newe dyght".</L>
<L N="445">Whan he had smored her in the smok,</L>
<L>Out of the fyre he her toke:</L>
<L>She had none eyen for to loke,</L>
<L>For lost was her syght.</L>
<L>He laide her on the stythe alonge</L>
<L N="450">And wyth an hamer he on throng,</L>
<L>That both her armes of spronge.</L>
<L>Than waxed he unfayne,</L>
<L>And sayd: "So ever eate I meate,</L>
<L>Thou shalt have a better heate".</L>
<L N="455">Mo coles gan he gete,</L>
<L>To blowe he was full fayne.</L>
<L>The fyre sparkeled and spronge,</L>
<L>He cast on water sometymes amonge,</L>
<L>And sayd: "Yet I hope to make the yonge,</L>
<L N="460">Wythout any layne".</L>
<L>Than he hent her up on hy</L>
<L>And layed her on the stethy</L>
<L>And hamered her strongely</L>
<L>With strokes that were ungayne.</L>
<L N="465">Fast on her he layed,</L>
<L>"Waxe yong, dame!" he sayd.</L>
<L>Than bothe her legges at a brayd</L>
<L>Fell sone her fro.</L>
<L>"What, evyll hayle! sayd he,</L>
<L N="470">Wylt not thou yonge be?</L>
<L>Speke now, let me se,</L>
<L>And say ones bo!"</L>
<L>Than he toke her by the heed</L>
<L>And sayd: "Dame, art thou deed?</L>
<L N="475">Speke now in thys steed</L>
<L>And say ye or els nay!</L>
<L>Though both thy legges be awai,</L>
<L>Yet speke, pardy, thou may.</L>
<L>Say on, dame, I the pray,</L>
<L N="480">Felest thou any wo?</L>
<L>Dame, I have lost on the</L>
<L>Moche labour truely;</L>
<L>Now and thou deed be,</L>
<L>So fayre must me befall".</L>
<L N="485">Loud on her he can cry</L>
<L>And sayde: "Dame, speke on hye,</L>
<L>Or by my trouth, truely</L>
<L>Brenne thee up I shall.</L>
<L>What? canst thou nothyng say?</L>
<L N="490">I holde thee deed by this day".
<PB REF="00000466.tif" N="328"></L>
<L>Her arme anone he thr&emacr;w away</L>
<L>Even agaynst the wall.</L>
<L>And lyghtly his way he went than,</L>
<L>After Jesu fast he ran,</L>
<L N="495">As he had ben a madde man,</L>
<L>And full fast kan hym call,</L>
<L>And sayd: "For saynt charyte,</L>
<L>Abyde nowe and speke wyth me!</L>
<L>But thou me helpe, truely,</L>
<L N="500">My cares are full colde.</L>
<L>My owne dame I have slayne,</L>
<L>I wolde have made her yonge agayne &mdash;</L>
<L>All my laboure was in vayne,</L>
<L>Her legges wolde not holde".</L>
<L N="505">Our lorde sayd verament:</L>
<L>"Hast thou thy dame brent?"</L>
<L>He sayd: "Lorde, she is shent,</L>
<L>But yf thou helpe wolde".</L>
<L>Our lorde sayd: "Go we full yare.</L>
<L N="510">Yet I bad the longe eare</L>
<L>Of suche craft to beware</L>
<L>And be not to bolde!"</L>
<L>"A, good lorde, sayd he,</L>
<L>I crye the hartely mercy;</L>
<L N="515">I wolde have wrought after the</L>
<L>And learned of thy lore".</L>
<L>Sayd our lorde: "Go thy way!</L>
<L>Now thou doest me pray,</L>
<L>I shall helpe that I maye</L>
<L N="520">Her for to restore".</L>
<L>Anone as he her se,</L>
<L>He blessed her full fayrely</L>
<L>And bad her stande upon hy:</L>
<L>Anone she rose up there.</L>
<L N="525">She semed younge and not olde,</L>
<L>Bryght as blossome her to beholde,</L>
<L>Fayrer by a thosand folde</L>
<L>Than she was before;</L>
<L>She was whyte as a bone of whale,</L>
<L N="530">Bryghter then berall.</L>
<L>Than to the earth gan she fall</L>
<L>And thanked god intere.</L>
<L>The smyth had good game</L>
<L>And fetched forth hys beldame.</L>
<L N="535">Than they all thre in-same</L>
<L>Kneled there in-fere</L>
<L>And helde up theyr hands on hy(ght)</L>
<L>And thanked god wyth all theyr mygh(t)</L>
<L>That he had them so dyght</L>
<L N="540">And mended theyr chere.</L>
<L>Our lorde sayd to the smyth tho:</L>
<L>"Loke, thou brenne never mo!</L>
<L>For this craft, I shal tel the,</L>
<L>Can thou never lere.</L>
<L N="545">But here a poynt I gyve the:</L>
<L>The mayster shalt thou yet be</L>
<L>Of all thy craft truely</L>
<L>Wythout any delay;</L>
<L>What man of craft soever be,</L>
<L N="550">And he have no helpe of the,</L>
<L>Thoughe he be never so sle,</L>
<L>Warke not he may".</L>
<L>Than our lorde forth went</L>
<L>And bad the smyth take good tent</L>
<L N="555">That he no mo folke brent,</L>
<L>By nyght nor yet by day.</L>
<L>Our lorde thus forth gan go</L>
<L>And left them togyther so,</L>
<L>And dyd many a mervayle mo</L>
<L N="560">In dyvers countreis.</L>
<L>He made many a croked ryght</L>
<L>And gave blynd men agayne theyr syght,</L>
<L>Dead men throughe hys myght</L>
<L>He raysed full sone agayne,</L>
<L N="565">Leprous made he clere,</L>
<L>Defe men for to here,</L>
<L>And other sycknesses in fere</L>
<L>He heled them certayne:</L>
<L>All sycke men that to hym sought</L>
<L N="570">And to hym that were brought,</L>
<L>And loved lely in theyr thought,<NOTE PLACE="foot">l. leved?</NOTE></L>
<L>And were losed of theyr payne.</L>
<L>Pray we all to hym thys</L>
<L>That suche a lordy is:</L>
<L N="575">That he brynge us to blys</L>
<L>That never shall mys. Amen.</L>
<L>Thus endeth the game</L>
<L>How the smyth brent hys dame</L>
<L>And after made her agayne</L>
<L N="580">By our blessed lord.</L>
<TRAILER>Finis.</TRAILER>
<TRAILER>Imprented at London in Lothburi, ouer agaynst Sainct Margarites church, by me Wyllyam Copland.</TRAILER>
</LG>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="12" TYPE="legend">

<PB REF="00000467.tif" N="[329]">
<HEAD>12. Marienlegende Vom guten Ritter und seinem eifers&uuml;chtigen Weibe. Aus Ms. Ashmol. 61, fol. 62.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>Die zwei folg. Legenden, im Katalog der Ashm. Mss. f&auml;lschlich als ein Gedicht aufgef&uuml;hrt, geh&ouml;ren demselben Dichter an und sind ohne Zweifel bedeutend &auml;lter als die Hs. Die erste ist nur im Ms. Ashm. 61 erhalten und ohne den Schluss, da nach fol. 65 ein Blatt absichtlich ausgerissen ist; die zweite findet sich ganz in Ms. Cbr. Ff V, 48 fol. 44, und theilweise, von v. 118 an, in Ms. Ashm. 61 fol. 66 (der Anfang ist mit dem vorhergehenden Blatte ausgerissen). &mdash; Die altenglischen Marienlegenden sind in sp&auml;terer "dunkler" Zeit absichtlich zerst&ouml;rt; von der Sammlung von 42 Marien|legenden des Ms. Vernon sind nur die ersten 9 erhalten (edirt in Herrig's Archiv Bd. LVI p. 221&mdash;236); die 66 Marienlegenden Barbour's, die derselbe im Eingange seiner Legendensammlung als sein Werk nennt, sind ganz verloren; 15 Marien|legenden in Prosa, kurz skizzirt, enth&auml;lt noch Ms. Lamb. 432 fol. 85 (edirt in der Anglia, 1880); ein Fragment einer Marienlegende Ms. Auchinl., ein anderes, Ms. Thornton. Altfranz&ouml;sische Sammlungen finden sich in Ms. Egert. 612 und Ms. Reg. 20 B XIV (beide ver|schieden).</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Lordyngys curtase &amp; hen(d)e,</L>
<L>Lystyns how &thorn;is tale schall ende</L>
<L>T(hat) I wyll &yogh;ow seyne!</L>
<L>And if &yogh;e wyll with gode wyll here,</L>
<L N="5">Gret gode &yogh;e may &thorn;er-in lere,</L>
<L>In hert iff &yogh;e (it) leyne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>I schall tell wyffe &amp; mane</L>
<L>How owre lady helpe cane</L>
<L>That to hyre clepe at nede;</L>
<L N="10">Thare schall no-man sykerly</L>
<L>Do nou&yogh;ht fore owre dere lady</L>
<L>Bot he schall haue his mede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Thys schall I preue thorow a skyll.</L>
<L>Herkyns, if it be &yogh;oure wyll</L>
<L N="15">Thys gest forto here,</L>
<L>A feyre merakyll of a kny&yogh;ht,</L>
<L>And of hys lady feyre &amp; bry&yogh;ht,</L>
<L>That was hym leffe &amp; dere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A kny&yogh;ht wonyd here-besyde,</L>
<L N="20">That had I-no&yogh;he of gret pride</L>
<L>Vnto hys lyffys ende.</L>
<L>A lady he had to hys wyffe,</L>
<L>That he louyd as hys lyffe,</L>
<L>Was come of nobulle kynde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="25">Syche a grace(!) god theme gafe,</L>
<L>That &thorn;ei my&yogh;ht no chyld haue</L>
<L>Off all a VII &yogh;ere.</L>
<L>Therefore &thorn;e kny&yogh;ht &amp; hys lady</L>
<L>Both &thorn;ei were full sory</L>
<L N="30">And changyd oft &thorn;er chere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Neuer-&thorn;e-les &thorn;e kny&yogh;ht &amp; hys wyffe</L>
<L>Both &thorn;ei were of gowd lyffe.</L>
<L>To god &thorn;ei made a bone:</L>
<L>That he schuld &thorn;em some chyld sende.</L>
<L N="35">Jhesu Cryst, &thorn;at is so hend,</L>
<L>God grantyd &thorn;em well sone.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>So longe to-ge&thorn;er &thorn;ei gane praye,</L>
<L>That he sent them childer tweye</L>
<L>Off &thorn;er awne blode.</L>
<L N="40">The knyght &amp; hys lady wer full blythe</L>
<L>And thankyd god many a sythe</L>
<L>Off hys sonde gode.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Thus &thorn;e knyght &amp; hys wyfe</L>
<L>Lyued mery in clene lyffe</L>
<L N="45">With Joy &amp; grete solas,</L>
<L>Tyll sche was with &thorn;e thyrd chylde;</L>
<L>Welle oft &thorn;ei thankyd Mary myld</L>
<L>That sente &thorn;em &thorn;at grace.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Than &thorn;ei wer both blyth &amp; glad,</L>
<L N="50">Iche to o&thorn;er grete Joy made,</L>
<L>Both erly &amp; late.</L>
<L>The deuell &thorn;er-of had envy
<PB REF="00000468.tif" N="330"></L>
<L>And went aboute as a spy</L>
<L>There trew lufe to abate.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="55">Thus dyde &thorn;e fende, &thorn;e fowle wyght:</L>
<L>He was about dey &amp; ny&yogh;ht</L>
<L>In bale to brynge theme bothe.</L>
<L>Bot he myght neuer be &thorn;e more</L>
<L>In all &thorn;e tyme &thorn;er-before,</L>
<L N="60">Ons to make them wrothe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Sych a maner had &thorn;e knyght</L>
<L>In serteyne vsage, euery ny&yogh;ht</L>
<L>Thorow &thorn;e longe &yogh;ere</L>
<L>In-to hys chapell forto wend,</L>
<L N="65">Before owre lady gode &amp; hend</L>
<L>To make hys prayere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Before oure lady suete &amp; dere</L>
<L>There he made hys prayere</L>
<L>With full gode wyll.</L>
<L N="70">Hys lady neuer ondername</L>
<L>When he &yogh;ede ne when he came,</L>
<L>Bot ley &amp; slepyd wyll stylle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The fend of helle fondyd fast</L>
<L>Iff &thorn;at he my&yogh;ht wordys cast</L>
<L N="75">Forto wrothe &thorn;em a-twyne.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. tywyne.</NOTE></L>
<L>And fore hys wycked intysment</L>
<L>Well ny&yogh;e &thorn;ei had both be schente:</L>
<L>Herkyns, I schall &yogh;ow seyne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Vpon a dey, as &yogh;e may here,</L>
<L N="80">The kny&yogh;ht &amp; his lady dere</L>
<L>Sate in solas,</L>
<L>And &thorn;er feyre chylder twey</L>
<L>Wente afore theme forto pley</L>
<L>In &thorn;at Iche place.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="85">The thyrd was in hyre wome I-wys.</L>
<L>The knyght &thorn;erof hade Joy &amp; blysse.</L>
<L>And hys lady &thorn;at stownd</L>
<L>"Leff syre, seyd sche,</L>
<L>Louyst &thorn;ou any-thinge beter &thorn;an me,</L>
<L N="90">That owhere may be fonde?"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Sertys, dame, he seyd, nay,</L>
<L>In no-thinge, me neuyne may,</L>
<L>Ine haue so grete lykynge, &mdash;</L>
<L>Bot of a woman &thorn;at I wote</L>
<L N="95">I loue wele more, god it wote,</L>
<L>Than any erthly thynge."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"&YOGH;e, &yogh;e, &thorn;an seyd sche,</L>
<L>Louyst &thorn;ou an o&thorn;er better &thorn;an me?"</L>
<L>And thought a lythere gyne</L>
<L N="100">And wend &thorn;at hyre lord thane</L>
<L>Had louyd some o&thorn;er womane</L>
<L>In &thorn;e maner of synne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Nay, be god! it was not so &mdash;</L>
<L>It was an o&thorn;er, worth &thorn;e two,</L>
<L N="105">That he louyd in lede:</L>
<L>It was owre lady &thorn;at he mente &mdash;</L>
<L>And els &thorn;ei had both be schente</L>
<L>At &thorn;er most nede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The deuyll of hell wyst wele &thorn;is</L>
<L N="110">That hyre herte wrethyd is,</L>
<L>And thou&yogh;ht it schulde be more;</L>
<L>To helle he wente with-outen feyle,</L>
<L>At &thorn;e fendys to take co&umacr;nseylle</L>
<L>What hym best do were.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. de st. do.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="115">Thorow co&umacr;nsyll of &thorn;e fendys felle</L>
<L>The most schrewe &thorn;at wer in helle</L>
<L>Went with-outen feylle,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. schrewys.</NOTE></L>
<L>To a wych in &thorn;e to&umacr;ne he wente,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. &thorn;ei st. he.</NOTE></L>
<L>That was out of &thorn;e ry&yogh;ht entente,</L>
<L N="120">And told hyre hys co&umacr;nsell.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Sey, woman, &thorn;an seyd he,</L>
<L>Wyll &thorn;ou wynne gold &amp; fe?</L>
<L>Hast &thorn;ou &thorn;er-to nede,</L>
<L>Inow&yogh;e I schall &thorn;e gyfe of tho,</L>
<L N="125">That &thorn;ou of myne erande go<NOTE PLACE="foot">of st. on.</NOTE></L>
<L>And do als I &thorn;e rede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>To a castyll I wyll &thorn;e send,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e lady gode &amp; hende,</L>
<L>Go &thorn;ou now forth rathe!</L>
<L N="130">Sche is a party of my kyne,</L>
<L>Wherefore I wolde with some gynne</L>
<L>Werne hyre of hyre skathe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Sche is led with grete vnryght:</L>
<L>Hyre lord aryseth euery nyght</L>
<L N="135">And fro hyre goth full stylle,</L>
<L>To an o&thorn;er woman wendys he,</L>
<L>That he louys more than suche thre,</L>
<L>And pleys with hyre hys fylle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>All cold he commys a&yogh;en hyre to.</L>
<L N="140">Go to hyre &amp; sey hyre so!
<PB REF="00000469.tif" N="331"></L>
<L>No word &thorn;ou schalt lye.</L>
<L>The next ny&yogh;ht &thorn;at schall come</L>
<L>He schall do &thorn;at he is wone:</L>
<L>Loke &thorn;at sche aspye!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="145">Sey hyre &thorn;at sche schew hym nou&yogh;ht &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">schew = sew 178 = sue.</NOTE></L>
<L>So myght sche sone to deth be brou&yogh;t;</L>
<L>Byd hyre lye full styll!</L>
<L>Iff &thorn;ou do as I &thorn;e rede,</L>
<L>Thow schalt haue rych mede,</L>
<L N="150">Of rede gold thy fylle."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"&YOGH;is, sche seyde, well glad am I</L>
<L>Forto go to my lady;</L>
<L>I schall be &thorn;er full rathe.</L>
<L>Sche hath do me full mykyll gode;</L>
<L N="155">I ame full Joyfull in my mode</L>
<L>To werne hyre of hyre skathe."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Thorow &thorn;e deuyllus intysmente</L>
<L>Te &thorn;e castell sche is wente,</L>
<L>And salewy&yogh;h &thorn;e lady &thorn;ere.</L>
<L N="160">"Leffe madam, seyd sche,</L>
<L>I wolde speke a word with &yogh;ow,</L>
<L>Iff it &yogh;oure wyll were.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Comly lady gente &amp; fre,</L>
<L>I wold &thorn;e tell a priuyte,</L>
<L N="165">Iff &thorn;ou me not bewrye.</L>
<L>Thow schall leue onne my lare;</L>
<L>Thynge &thorn;at thow ne wyst are,</L>
<L>Herkyns now, I schall &thorn;e sey.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Thy lord, &thorn;at thow louys so myche,</L>
<L N="170">He betrays &thorn;e sykerlych</L>
<L>And doyht &thorn;e vylony:</L>
<L>He gose fro &thorn;e Iche ny&yogh;ht ons</L>
<L>To a womane in hys wonys.</L>
<L>Luke &thorn;at thow aspye!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="175">The nex(t) nyght &thorn;at schall come</L>
<L>He schall do as he is wone,</L>
<L>By hyre forto lye.</L>
<L>Bot at &thorn;ou sew hym nou&yogh;ht:</L>
<L>So myght &thorn;ou sone to deth be bro&yogh;ht;</L>
<L N="180">Styll &thorn;at thow lye!"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The lady spake wordys no mo:</L>
<L>"Womane, sche seyd, if it be so,</L>
<L>Thow schall haue &thorn;i mede.</L>
<L>Crystys cursse on &thorn;er hedys thane,</L>
<L N="185">The wych &amp; hyre lorys-mane,</L>
<L>Fore &thorn;at ilke dede!"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The fyrst ny&yogh;ht &thorn;at after came</L>
<L>The knyght wente to bede anone,</L>
<L>And hys lady dere.</L>
<L N="190">Styll sche ley as sche slepe,</L>
<L>Fore &thorn;at sch(e) wolde take kepe</L>
<L>The soth how it were.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Hyre lorde wend sche hade slepe tho,</L>
<L>And ros vp &amp; gane to go,</L>
<L N="195">Als he was bowne;</L>
<L>Into his chapell he gane wende,</L>
<L>To pray to owre lady hende,</L>
<L>That bare godys sone.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>When the lady wyst &thorn;o</L>
<L N="200">That hyre lord was fro hyre go,</L>
<L>Sche seyd alas &thorn;at whyle:</L>
<L>"Now I wote &thorn;at it is,</L>
<L>The wydew seyd me I-wys<NOTE PLACE="foot">soth fehlt.</NOTE></L>
<L>My lord had do me gyle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="205">He louys an o&thorn;er better thane me.</L>
<L>Alas, alas! &thorn;an seyd sche,</L>
<L>Myne herte is full of care.</L>
<L>The werke &thorn;at he wyrkys now</L>
<L>It schall not fall fore hys prow,</L>
<L N="210">It schall hym rew full sore!"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Thus sche gane alone speke,</L>
<L>And thou&yogh;t how (sche) my&yogh;ht it wreke.</L>
<L>To schend hyre-selue &thorn;at tyde,</L>
<L>Sche drew a knyfe, soth to seyne,</L>
<L N="215">And slew hyre feyre chylder tweyne</L>
<L>That ley be hyre syde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>When sche had &thorn;is werke wro&yogh;ht,</L>
<L>Sche seyd alas! &amp; hyre bethou&yogh;ht,</L>
<L>"Myne herte is full of sorow!</L>
<L N="220">Wyte my lorde what I haue done,</L>
<L>He wyll me scle ry&yogh;ht sone,</L>
<L>That no-mane schall me borow.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ney, &thorn;at schall not be so,</L>
<L>Wers I schall my-selue do,</L>
<L N="225">What-euer &thorn;erof fall."</L>
<L>With a knyffe, was kene &amp; scherpe,</L>
<L>She smote hyre-selue to &thorn;e herte &mdash;</L>
<L>That was werst of all!
<PB REF="00000470.tif" N="332"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Now was &thorn;is a rewfull syght</L>
<L N="230">In &thorn;at chamber &thorn;at same ny&yogh;ht,</L>
<L>The mane &thorn;at my&yogh;ht beholde:</L>
<L>The lady &amp; hyre chylder twey,</L>
<L>In hyre wombe &thorn;e thyrd, I sey,</L>
<L>All &thorn;ei were wele colde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="235">The fend of hell was glad off &thorn;is,</L>
<L>Fore he wend wele I-wys</L>
<L>Off theme he schuld not feyle.</L>
<L>Bot &yogh;e schall here in a whyle</L>
<L>How &thorn;at he was begyle</L>
<L N="240">And left all hys traueyle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Fore &thorn;e kny&yogh;ht, as &yogh;e may here,</L>
<L>Ley welle fast in hys prayere</L>
<L>With full gode wylle.</L>
<L>When hys prayers were a(l) done,<NOTE PLACE="foot">a st. all.</NOTE></L>
<L N="245">To hys chamber he went sone</L>
<L>Hym-selue a-lone wele stylle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>To &thorn;e bede &thorn;e knyght gane go:</L>
<L>He fonde hys wyfe, hys chylder two,</L>
<L>Ded &thorn;ei ley there;</L>
<L N="250">The bede was spred with &thorn;er blode.</L>
<L>The kny&yogh;ht fore sorow wex ne wode</L>
<L>And wonderyd on &thorn;at fare.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Lady, mersy! seyd &thorn;e kny&yogh;ht,</L>
<L>Who has ben here &thorn;is nyght</L>
<L N="255">And done &thorn;is rewfull dede?</L>
<L>Lady, helpe, I ame forelorne,</L>
<L>Bot &yogh;e, &thorn;at I haue bene beforne,</L>
<L>Helpe me at &thorn;is nede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Thys womane hath hyre-selue schente</L>
<L N="260">Thorow &thorn;e fendys entysmente &mdash;</L>
<L>Lord, how may &thorn;is be?</L>
<L>Iff I be takyne in &thorn;is lede,</L>
<L>I schall be hangyd fore &thorn;is dede.</L>
<L>Whe&thorn;er may I fle?</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="265">Thys castell is so stronge with-alle:</L>
<L>I ne mey owte at &thorn;e walle</L>
<L>Nou-where a-boute</L>
<L>Tyll to-morne, &thorn;at it be dey.</L>
<L>Bot I may thane skape awey,</L>
<L N="270">Off my deth I doute."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Thus he wepyd &amp; made wo.</L>
<L>To owre lady he clepyd tho &mdash;</L>
<L>In herte hade he no gamme:</L>
<L>As he was gyltles of &thorn;at dede,</L>
<L N="275">He prayd here helpe hym in &thorn;at nede</L>
<L>And scheld hym fro schame.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>To &thorn;e chapell he went in haste</L>
<L>And prayd oure lady swyth faste</L>
<L>Send hym of hyre grace.</L>
<L N="280">What fore sorow &amp; fore wepe,</L>
<L>Sone he fell fast on sclepe</L>
<L>In &thorn;at same plas.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Owre lady foregate hym no-thinge,</L>
<L>Ne hyre sone, heuen kynge,</L>
<L N="285">To helpe at &thorn;at nede. &mdash;</L>
<L>There schall no-man sykerly<MILESTONE N="65" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. no no.</NOTE></L>
<L>Do nou&yogh;ht fore owre dere lady,</L>
<L>Bot he schall haue his mede. &mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Herkyns how &thorn;e fendys felle,</L>
<L N="290">How &thorn;at they wente oute of hell.</L>
<L>So lothe &thorn;ei were to tyne:</L>
<L>A thousand wente on a raw,</L>
<L>Fore &thorn;ei wend in a throw</L>
<L>The sawle haue to pyne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="295">Some were ragyd &amp; longe-tayled,</L>
<L>Scharpe clawyde &amp; longe nayled,</L>
<L>The fendys euery-Ichon,</L>
<L>Some had hornes grel &amp; longe,<NOTE PLACE="foot">grel gril = sharp, horrible.</NOTE></L>
<L>Oute of &thorn;er mouth &thorn;e fyre spronge &mdash;</L>
<L N="300">With-outene lake wer none.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Than &thorn;is was a grysly syght,</L>
<L>Who-so hade sene &thorn;em &thorn;at ny&yogh;ht</L>
<L>Come rakynge on a raw.</L>
<L>Lystyns now &amp; herkyns gamme,</L>
<L N="305">How all &thorn;er Joy was turned to schame</L>
<L>In a lytell throw,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Thorow &thorn;e my&yogh;ht of meyd Mary,</L>
<L>That sche come do&umacr;ne frome heuyne hy<NOTE PLACE="foot">sche ist zu tilgen.</NOTE></L>
<L>A&yogh;ene &thorn;e fendys felle.</L>
<L N="310">Sche seyd: "fendys, fle awey!</L>
<L>Fore here &yogh;e haue tyned &yogh;oure pray:</L>
<L>The saule schall with me duelle."
<PB REF="00000471.tif" N="333"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Ney, fore-soth, seyde Sathanas,</L>
<L>Hyte hath hyre happyd a foule cas,</L>
<L N="315">Thou feylest of &thorn;i arte:</L>
<L>Sche slew hyre-selue with ny&yogh;ht &amp; onde<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. my&yogh;ht st. ny&thorn;e.</NOTE></L>
<L>And hyre chylder with hyre honde.</L>
<L>Of them(!) &thorn;ou hast no parte."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The quene of heuen stude full styll</L>
<L N="320">And sofyrd &thorn;em to sey &thorn;er wyll;</L>
<L>There-of sche gane smyle:</L>
<L>"He &thorn;at ly&yogh;ht in my seruys,</L>
<L>It schall be at hys asyse:</L>
<L>He schall not tyne hys whyle."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="325">The fendys cryed as &thorn;ei wer wode:</L>
<L>"Go we hens with body &amp; blode!</L>
<L>No lenger wyll we duelle."</L>
<L>Fowre thousand fendys &amp; one<NOTE PLACE="foot">&amp; one st. anone.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wend to take hyre &amp; gone</L>
<L N="330">With-oute lettynge to helle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Late be, fendys, &yogh;oure feleny!</L>
<L>Wene &yogh;e fore-to haue mastry</L>
<L>At &yogh;oure awne wyll?</L>
<L>Fyrst we schall speke wordys mo,</L>
<L N="335">That schall &yogh;ow lyke non of tho</L>
<L>Bot make &yogh;oure hertys gryll.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>I congour &thorn;e, fend, &thorn;at thou me sey &mdash;</L>
<L>That &thorn;ou ne lete fore loue ne aye! &mdash;</L>
<L>How camme &thorn;is sorow in place?</L>
<L N="340">And in what maner it fyrst begane;</L>
<L>Where that it were thorow fend or wo|mane?</L>
<L>Tell me, or &thorn;ou passe!"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Fore-soth, lady, seyd he,</L>
<L>It come thorow a wych &amp; me &mdash;</L>
<L N="345">I may it not foresake;</L>
<L>Boldly I haue it wro&yogh;ht.</L>
<L>Therefore &thorn;ei schall to hell be brou&yogh;t,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. &thorn;u st. &thorn;ei.</NOTE></L>
<L>There pays forto make."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Ney, &thorn;er me thinke &thorn;ou doyst wronge,</L>
<L N="350">When &yogh;e hyre chermyd to &yogh;oure hond</L>
<L>That lyued in pese &amp; gry&yogh;ht.</L>
<L>Take &yogh;e, sche seyd, &thorn;at &yogh;e haue wrou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And leue &thorn;at my sone hath bou&yogh;ht</L>
<L>And delyth no-more &thorn;em wyth!<NOTE PLACE="foot">Nach 354 fehlt eine Stropfe.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="355">Nay, I &yogh;en-sey, sothly.</L>
<L>Whyll sche dyd &thorn;is foly,</L>
<L>Hyre lord was my seruaunte;</L>
<L>And thorow hyre lordys besekynge</L>
<L>They schall haue lyfe &amp; gode endynge</L>
<L N="360">Thorow my sones grante."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The fendys lowd &thorn;ei gane crye</L>
<L>And seyd: "late be &thorn;at, Mary!</L>
<L>Hens I rede &thorn;ou fle!</L>
<L>Sche dyd it thorow a mys-chans,</L>
<L N="365">With-out schryft &amp; repenta(n)s:</L>
<L>Oure sche schall be."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Than ansuerd &thorn;e quene Mary:</L>
<L>"Late be &thorn;is noys &amp; &thorn;is cry!</L>
<L>It helpe &yogh;ou ry&yogh;ht nou&yogh;ht.</L>
<L N="370">Hyre lord &amp; sche be of a blode,</L>
<L>And thorow his werkys trew &amp; gode</L>
<L>To lyfe &thorn;ei schall be brou&yogh;ht,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And ches &thorn;an at &thorn;er fre wyll,</L>
<L>After &thorn;at they thinke skyll,</L>
<L N="375">To whome &thorn;ei wyll &thorn;em holde:</L>
<L>With my sone sorto duell</L>
<L>Or with &yogh;ou, fendys of hell,</L>
<L>That makys &yogh;ou so bolde."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>When &thorn;e angellus begane to se</L>
<L N="380">The bodys schuld on lyue be</L>
<L>Thorow oure ladys saw,</L>
<L>Euery angell a deuyll hente</L>
<L>And thyrst &thorn;em, &thorn;at there rybbys bente<NOTE PLACE="foot">thyrst = thryst.</NOTE></L>
<L>Fore tene of &thorn;er plaw.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="385">The fendys saw &thorn;at they hade lorne:</L>
<L>Euery fend had o&thorn;er torne</L>
<L>With a mody chere.</L>
<L>Neuer &thorn;ei stynte ne blane</L>
<L>To &thorn;ei to &thorn;e wych came,</L>
<L N="390">And sette hyre house on fyre.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The fyre was blo as brymstone;</L>
<L>They brake &thorn;e wychys bake-bone:</L>
<L>Oneth on lyffe hyre lete.<NOTE PLACE="foot">oneth = vnne&thorn;e.</NOTE></L>
<L>Hyre ney&yogh;bors &thorn;er be-syde</L>
<L N="395">Dorste no lenger abyde,</L>
<L>Bot fled awey full sore.</L>
<L>. . . . .<NOTE PLACE="end">Ende fehlt.</NOTE>
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="13" TYPE="legend"><PB REF="00000472.tif" N="[334]">
<HEAD>13. A Tale of an incestuous doughter, aus Ms. Cbr. Ff V, 48, fol. 44 (und Ashm. 61, fol. 66).</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Herkyns now, bothe more and lasse:</L>
<L>I wille yow telle of a heuy casse,</L>
<L>Listyns, I wille yow telle.</L>
<L>If &yogh;e &thorn;is tale wille here,</L>
<L N="5">Sum gode &thorn;er-in &yogh;e mow lere,</L>
<L>At home if &yogh;e wille dwelle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ther was a man of myculle mayne</L>
<L>In &thorn;o bisshope-riche of Wyan,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. &thorn;o st. &thorn;e, wie 225.</NOTE></L>
<L>Riche of londe and ledis.</L>
<L N="10">He hade a wyfe gentille &amp; fre,</L>
<L>The best woman &thorn;at my&yogh;t be,</L>
<L>And fulle of almys-dedis.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A dou&yogh;tur they had betwen hem twoo,</L>
<L>The fayrest &thorn;at my&yogh;t on erthe goo,</L>
<L N="15">Made of flesshe and blode.</L>
<L>A fulle harde grace was hir lentte,</L>
<L>Er she owt of &thorn;is worde wentte;</L>
<L>And alle hit turned to gode.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Seche dedis hade she wrou&yogh;t:</L>
<L N="20">In dedly synne she was brou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>In wanhope with-out bote;</L>
<L>Suche a grace was hir lent:</L>
<L>&THORN;at she come to mendment &mdash;</L>
<L>God graunte &thorn;at we so mow&yogh;te!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="25">The fende of helle agayn skylle</L>
<L>Put in hir a harde wille</L>
<L>Hur fadur luf to wynne;</L>
<L>And also temped was &thorn;at man</L>
<L>His owne dou&yogh;tur for to tan,</L>
<L N="30">To do a dedly synne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e fende tempted hym on a day:</L>
<L>&THORN;e mayden came, &thorn;e sothe to say,</L>
<L>In a pryue stede;</L>
<L>Hur fadur prayed hir of luf derne,</L>
<L N="35">And she wolde hym not werne</L>
<L>Thorow &thorn;e fendis rede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The fadur with his dou&yogh;tur did his wille.</L>
<L>They &yogh;ede to-gedur priuely &amp; stille,</L>
<L>&THORN;ei were wondur wylde!</L>
<L N="40">In holy churche as clerkys fynde,</L>
<L>On his dou&yogh;tur agayne kynde</L>
<L>&THORN;er he gate a knave childe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;et &thorn;ei wolde not of &thorn;at blynne,</L>
<L>But lyved forthe in dedly synne,</L>
<L N="45">In romans as we rede.</L>
<L>Holy churche berys wytnesse sadde:</L>
<L>Thre knaue childur be hym she hadde,</L>
<L>And alle she putte to dede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>So priuely to-gedur &thorn;ei wrou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="50">&THORN;at noman perceyued hem nou&yogh;t</L>
<L>Wher-aboute &thorn;ei &yogh;ede.</L>
<L>Vpon a day hir modur con gon</L>
<L>Fulle priuely hir-self allon,</L>
<L>And fonde hem in &thorn;e dede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="55">"Alasse, she seid, &thorn;at &yogh;e were borne!</L>
<L>Fulle wele I wot &yogh;e ar forlorne,</L>
<L>&YOGH;e ar &thorn;e deuels of helle."<NOTE PLACE="foot">Nach V. 57 fehlen 3 V.</NOTE></L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L N="60">. . . . .</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Alasse, he seyde, now am I woo!</L>
<L>I wot she wille bewrye vs too",</L>
<L>Gret sorow con he make.</L>
<L>"Nay, seid his dou&yogh;tur, so mot I the,</L>
<L N="65">So shalle hit not be,</L>
<L>And I may hir ouretake."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Thorow &thorn;e deuels intisement</L>
<L>Aftur hir modur she went</L>
<L>Euen in-to &thorn;e halle,</L>
<L N="70">A knyfe in hir hande she hent ful smerte</L>
<L>And smote hir modur to &thorn;e herte,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ded down can she falle.
<PB REF="00000473.tif" N="335"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>When &thorn;at synfulle dede was done,</L>
<L>They toke &thorn;e body vp sone</L>
<L N="75">And leyde hit in a cheste,</L>
<L>And beryd &thorn;e cors with bo&thorn;e her rede,</L>
<L>As she sodenly hade be ded,</L>
<L>&THORN;at no-man odur wiste.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;et wolde &thorn;ei not lefe her foly,</L>
<L N="80">But lyued forthe in lechory,</L>
<L>Be day and eke be ny&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Alle on a day to churche he went<NOTE PLACE="foot1">alle st. tille?</NOTE></L>
<L>With goode wille and gode intent,</L>
<L>Thorow &thorn;e grace of god almy&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="85">He bethou&yogh;t hym &amp; vndurstode</L>
<L>In how synfulle life he &yogh;ede;</L>
<L>His synnes he wolde forsake,</L>
<L>And, if he my&yogh;t haue legeans,</L>
<L>For his synnes to do penans:</L>
<L N="90">Schrifte he thou&yogh;t to take.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>When folke out of &thorn;e kyrke wer gon,</L>
<L>&THORN;e man folowed &thorn;e preest anon</L>
<L>Stille with-owte strife;</L>
<L>He tolde &thorn;e preest his synnes ychon,</L>
<L N="95">How he and his dou&yogh;tur had don</L>
<L>And alle was holden her life.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e preest seid: "hast &thorn;ou gode wille</L>
<L>For &thorn;i synne, &thorn;ou has don ille,</L>
<L>Schrifte forto take:</L>
<L N="100">&THORN;ou shalt not be &thorn;i dou&yogh;tur lye</L>
<L>Nor touche hir with no vilany;</L>
<L>&THORN;i synnes &thorn;ou most forsake.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>If &thorn;ou &thorn;i penance wilt vndurstonde,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou most in-to &thorn;e holy londe</L>
<L N="105">Wher god was whik &amp; dede."<NOTE PLACE="foot1">whik st. quik.</NOTE></L>
<L>"&YOGH;is, forsothe, seid he,</L>
<L>If my life wille laste me,</L>
<L>I wille do aftur thy rede".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>When he was schryven of his synnes,</L>
<L N="110">He went hom in-to his Innes</L>
<L>Wher his dou&yogh;tur was.</L>
<L>His dou&yogh;tur hade his meyte made:<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Ms. meyle od. meyte?</NOTE></L>
<L>She bade hur fadur make hym glade,</L>
<L>And made hym fayre solace.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="115">"Do way, dou&yogh;tur, sich thynge!</L>
<L>I wille no-more of &thorn;i playnge,<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Nach 116 fehlen 2 V.</NOTE></L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L>. . . . .<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Bei V. 118 beginnt das Fragment dess. Gedichtes in Ms. Ashmol. 61, fol. 66 (bessere Hs.).</NOTE></L>
<L>At mete nor at no mele &mdash;</L>
<L N="120">My synnes I haue forsake."<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Varianten: 118&mdash;20) That I schall neuer with &thorn;e dele, At bede, at borde, mete ne mele; My synne I haue foresake.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>She seid: "fadur, wyckud man,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">A, sche seyd, &thorn;ou wyked mane,</NOTE></L>
<L>Haste &thorn;ou tolde &thorn;e prest oure synnes ychan,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Haste &thorn;ou here-abowte gone,</NOTE></L>
<L>Fulle ille &thorn;ou shalt hit like.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Euyll it schall &thorn;e lyke.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ou made me furst my thre childur to sloo</L>
<L N="125">And my dere modur also</L>
<L>To &thorn;e hert forto smyte.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">124&mdash;6) Thow hast me made my moder sle, And my chyldere all thre, And wold me &thorn;us beswyke?</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ou wotte welle &thorn;at hit is soo,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Now, sche seyd, seth it is so,</NOTE></L>
<L>And o&thorn;ur-gatis hit shalle goo<NOTE PLACE="foot2">O&thorn;er-weys it schall go,</NOTE></L>
<L>Er to-morne at prime;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Or to-morow prime.</NOTE></L>
<L N="130">&THORN;ou hast me brou&yogh;t in-to &thorn;is ille,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">brou&yogh;ht me in all &thorn;e gyle,</NOTE></L>
<L>And I shalle ful wele haue my wille,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">And euyll &thorn;ou schall haue &thorn;e whyle</NOTE></L>
<L>When I se my tyme."<NOTE PLACE="foot2">When &thorn;at.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>When it was tyme of &thorn;e ny&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;e godeman was to bed di&yogh;t,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">133&mdash;4) When &thorn;at &thorn;e ny&yogh;ht was Icome, The god mane gane to bede gone.</NOTE></L>
<L N="135">His rest forto take;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">reste.</NOTE></L>
<L>The gode man thou&yogh;t: when hit was day]</L>
<L>In pilgremage to wende his wey<NOTE PLACE="foot2">136&mdash;7) Fore erly he wold in &thorn;e dey On pylgrymage wend his wey.</NOTE></L>
<L>For his synnes sake.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Thorow &thorn;e fendis intisynge<NOTE PLACE="foot2">egynge.</NOTE></L>
<L N="140">&THORN;e dou&yogh;tur &thorn;ou&yogh;t anodur thynge:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Hys. ano&thorn;er.</NOTE></L>
<L>Hir fadur for to sloo.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Wers forto do.</NOTE></L>
<L>When hir fadur on slepe was,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">hyre fader.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000474.tif" N="336"></L>
<L>She hyed to hym a gret pas<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Hys dou&yogh;ter wente a wele gode pace.</NOTE></L>
<L>And karve his hart in-twoo.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">kerue hys throte.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="145">Whan she hade don, as I yow telle,</L>
<L>&THORN;er wolde she no longur dwelle</L>
<L>But busket hir son to gon;</L>
<L>She &yogh;ede in-to a fer cuntre,</L>
<L>&THORN;er no-man knew hir pryuete</L>
<L N="150">Nor fro what stid she come.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">145&mdash;150) fehlen.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>She toke tresur, as I yow swere,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">And toke hyre tresoure &thorn;er.</NOTE></L>
<L>Also myculle as she my&yogh;t bere,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">myche. sche my&yogh;ht.</NOTE></L>
<L>And o&thorn;er felawes thre.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">felos.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ei went out of &thorn;at towne<NOTE PLACE="foot2">They wente sone oute off &thorn;e t.</NOTE></L>
<L N="155">To a borow of gret renowne,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">syte of grete.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;er wonned in &thorn;at cuntre.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&thorn;er fehlt. wonyd. syte st. cuntre.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>They spendit &thorn;er fulle fast,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Off &thorn;at tresowre &thorn;ei spendyd faste,</NOTE></L>
<L>Whil &thorn;at her gode wold last,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Whyles &thorn;at it my&yogh;ht laste,</NOTE></L>
<L>In gret honoure and in pride.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">With grete bobans of pride.</NOTE></L>
<L N="160">Men of &thorn;at cuntre, as I yow say,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Gentyll men of &thorn;at contrey</NOTE></L>
<L>Comyn thidur, with hir to play,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Come fast with hyre to pley</NOTE></L>
<L>Aboute on ilke a side.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&YOGH;erne onne euery syde.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>She was faire woman in alle thynge,</L>
<L>Sche gaf to lechory hir likynge,</L>
<L N="165">And of hir life not to mende:</L>
<L>She hopid neuer heuen to wynne</L>
<L>For &thorn;e synne &thorn;at she was inne,</L>
<L>But helle with-owt ende.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">163&mdash;8) fehlen.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Alle wyckud men &thorn;at were folis<NOTE PLACE="foot1">men st. women.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot1">Ms. fals st. folis.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">All &thorn;e women &thorn;at wold be folys,</NOTE></L>
<L N="170">&THORN;ei came to hur scolis,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Fast &thorn;ei come vnto hyre scolys,</NOTE></L>
<L>She helde mony &amp; fell;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Fast many &amp; fele.</NOTE></L>
<L>She forsoke nou&thorn;er preest nor clerke<NOTE PLACE="foot2">ney&thorn;er preste ne.</NOTE></L>
<L>Nor non &thorn;at lechory wolde werke,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Ne none &thorn;at were(d) brech ne scherte,</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at wolde with hur dwelle.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">That with hyre wold dele.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="175">So befelle thorow goddis sonde:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Vpone a dey th(r)ou&yogh;t godys sond</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e bisshop &thorn;at was of &thorn;at londe<NOTE PLACE="foot2">An holy buschop of &thorn;at lond</NOTE></L>
<L>Prechid in &thorn;at cite.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Preched. a st. &thorn;at.</NOTE></L>
<L>Alle gode men of &thorn;at towne<NOTE PLACE="foot2">And all &thorn;e. of &thorn;e.</NOTE></L>
<L>Come to his predicacion,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Com forto here hys sermone,</NOTE></L>
<L N="180">Hym to herkyn and se.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Hym forto here &amp; se.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>But &thorn;at synfulle woman<NOTE PLACE="foot2">All bot &thorn;at woman alone,</NOTE></L>
<L>With hir felows euerychon<NOTE PLACE="foot2">And hyre feleys e.</NOTE></L>
<L>Lafte stille in &thorn;at strete.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Duellyd at &thorn;er In.</NOTE></L>
<L>Sory was she &thorn;at ilke day<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Wo was &thorn;em &thorn;at ylke dey,</NOTE></L>
<L N="185">&THORN;at noman with hir wold play:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">There come noman with &thorn;em to pley;</NOTE></L>
<L>Siluer my&yogh;t she non gete.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">No syluer they my&yogh;ht wynne.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Tille hur felowes she seide;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Sche seyd to hyre feleys anone,</NOTE></L>
<L>"To &thorn;e churche go we, I rede,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">I rede &thorn;at we to &thorn;e chyrche gone,</NOTE></L>
<L>As swythe as we may!<NOTE PLACE="foot2">And haste vs in &thorn;e wey.</NOTE></L>
<L N="190">&THORN;er may we sum &yogh;onge man fynde,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">we schall some.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at is both curtesse and hynde,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">both god and kynde</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at wille with vs play."<NOTE PLACE="foot2">And with vs wyll pley.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Thorow &thorn;e grace of god almy&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;at is mercifulle to euery wy&yogh;t,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">193&mdash;4) To &thorn;e chyrch &thorn;ei forth wente Thourght &thorn;e grace of god omnipotente.</NOTE></L>
<L N="195">And thru&yogh; his modur Mary,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">thru&yogh; fehlt. modor.</NOTE></L>
<L>The holy bisshop, <I>&thorn;at &thorn;er</I> stode,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&thorn;er he stode.</NOTE></L>
<L>Prechid wordis bothe fayre &amp; gode,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">He preched w. well gode.</NOTE></L>
<L>On hir he cast his ee.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">hyre. ey.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000475.tif" N="337"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Foure fendis se he als<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Fowre deuylles &thorn;at wer fals</NOTE></L>
<L N="200">Hongyng fast aboute hir hals,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">He se hange aboute hyre h.</NOTE></L>
<L>And with chenys hir ledde,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">by cheynes. lede.</NOTE></L>
<L>In-to &thorn;e kyrke con &thorn;ei gon.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Be euery cheyne lede hyre one.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e bisshope saw &thorn;o fendis ilkon &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">The holy man sey them euery chone</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;er-of wondur he hade.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Grete wonder &thorn;erof.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="205">About her nek a coler stronge,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Abowte hyre neke. spronge.</NOTE></L>
<L>Fendis led hir with arrable songe,<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Ms. arrable = horrible.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">The fendys lede &thorn;e cheynes longe.</NOTE></L>
<L>Behynde &amp; &yogh;eke before.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&yogh;eke fehlt.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e bisshop wist wel be &thorn;aim<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Wele &thorn;e byschop wyst thane</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at synfulle was &thorn;at woman &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">That sche was a synfull w.</NOTE></L>
<L N="210">For hir he siked sore.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">sy&yogh;ed.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>She putte to a squyer &amp; on hym looghe<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Sche pukyd a squyre. lew.</NOTE></L>
<L>And hym be &thorn;e slefe she drowghe,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">And be &thorn;e sleue sche hym drew,</NOTE></L>
<L>And o&thorn;er of his felaws also.<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Ms. hir st. his.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">And o&thorn;er &yogh;onge men mo.</NOTE></L>
<L>He bade hir go away:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">They b. h. leue &amp; go hyre wey,</NOTE></L>
<L N="215">Hit was apon a gode-friday,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Fore it was on god f.</NOTE></L>
<L>With hir &thorn;ei wolde not goo.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">wold. go.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e bisshop lokid and saw all this:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">When &thorn;e b. sey all &thorn;is,</NOTE></L>
<L>Sore in hert he was Iwys,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">In his hert was sory Iwys,</NOTE></L>
<L>When he lokid hur vntille.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">When he vpon hyre sey.</NOTE></L>
<L N="220">&THORN;e fende he thou&yogh;t to wreke:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Of &thorn;e fendys he wold be wreke.</NOTE></L>
<L>Off goddis mercy cowde he speke,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">he gan.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bothe lowde and stille.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Both lowd &amp; hy&yogh;e.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Thorow &thorn;e grace of god almy&yogh;t</L>
<L>A worde in-to hir body li&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="foot2">word in hyre herte.</NOTE></L>
<L N="225">&THORN;at &thorn;o bisshop speke.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&thorn;e. spake.</NOTE></L>
<L>Terys felle hir een froo,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">That a tere fell fro hyre eye,</NOTE></L>
<L>Down on hir brest cowthe &thorn;ei goo:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">And be hyre lares it gane done fle.</NOTE></L>
<L>Hur colars &thorn;ei alto-breke.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">And &thorn;e colere brake.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">Nach 228 hat A. eine Stropfe mehr: The fendys fley &amp; wer adrad. The byschop &thorn;erof was full glad And thankyd god full styll. The holy mane prechyd of godys lore: The woman sate &amp; sy&yogh;ede sore And wepyd all hyre fylle. Die folg. Str. lautet: So bytterly sche wepyd with-all: Be hyre lyres &thorn;e terys gone fall Fast on ylke a syde. The byschop &thorn;erof was full glad, The fendys fley &amp; wer adrad, No lenger &thorn;er durste byde.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Fyndes &thorn;at be &thorn;e armus hur ladde,</L>
<L N="230">The chenys breke(!), away &thorn;ei fledde,</L>
<L>They durst no longur abide.</L>
<L>She hade gret sorow with-alle,</L>
<L>Vpon hir brest terys cowth downe falle</L>
<L>Faste on ilke a side.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="235">She sette hir downe vpon hir kne<NOTE PLACE="foot2">sett hyre. onne.</NOTE></L>
<L>And prayed to god in trinite,</L>
<L>Grace she con hym craue.<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Ms. Such grace.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">236&mdash;7) To god sche besou&yogh;ht in trinyte, Mersy gane sche craue.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Bisshop, she seid, what may &thorn;is be?<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Sche seyd: syr bysschop, I ame sche.</NOTE></L>
<L>Alle day &thorn;ou hast spoken of me,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">All &thorn;is dey. spoke.</NOTE></L>
<L N="240">And here &thorn;ou may me haue.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">mayst.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>I haue done &thorn;e grettist synne<NOTE PLACE="foot2">all dedly synne</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at any woman may be inne<NOTE PLACE="foot2">That euer my&yogh;ht womane begynne,</NOTE></L>
<L>Agaynes god &amp; his seyntys ychon:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Ageyne godys law.</NOTE></L>
<L>With my fadur I haue done foly,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">By my fader I dyde f.</NOTE></L>
<L N="245">Thre childur I had hym by,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">knaue-chylder.</NOTE></L>
<L>And I haue hem alle sloon.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">And all I haue &thorn;em slaw.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>My modur I slow with a knyf also,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">I stykyd. knyffe. also fehlt.</NOTE></L>
<L>And karve my fadur hert in-twoo.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">My fader I reft hym hys lyffe,</NOTE></L>
<L>For sorow alasse I crye.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Bysschop, I &thorn;e sey.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000476.tif" N="338"></L>
<L N="250">Bisshop, she seid, if &thorn;i wil be,<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Ms. if wil be st. I pray &thorn;e.</NOTE></L>
<L>Howsil and schrifte for charite!<NOTE PLACE="foot">250&mdash;1) And now in &thorn;is sted fore charyte Swythe of schryft I pray the.</NOTE></L>
<L>For sorow now I dye."<NOTE PLACE="foot">or st. now. dy&yogh;e.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Te bisshop seyd anon ry&yogh;t:</L>
<L>"Abide, woman, in &thorn;at ti&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="foot">Woman, abyde a lytell wyght.</NOTE></L>
<L N="255">Tille my fermonde be done!"<NOTE PLACE="foot">sermone.</NOTE></L>
<L>She swonyd &amp; fel downe there;</L>
<L>So ful she was of sorow &amp; care:<NOTE PLACE="foot">256&mdash;7) Sche was so full of sorow &amp; care, She fell adoune before &thorn;em there.</NOTE></L>
<L>To berst hir hert began.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Hyre hert braste in-two.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e bisshop saw she likid ille:<NOTE PLACE="foot">When &thorn;e bysschop had seyd hys wyll.</NOTE></L>
<L N="260">He bade &thorn;e folke sitte stille<NOTE PLACE="foot">bad. sytte &amp; be styll.</NOTE></L>
<L>And sone tille hir he start.<NOTE PLACE="foot">And to hyre he lepe,</NOTE></L>
<L>Vpon hir fast con he calle &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">And gane on hyre to clepe &amp; call.</NOTE></L>
<L>And she was ded amonge hem alle.<NOTE PLACE="foot">He fonde hyre. &thorn;em all.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e bisshop was sory in hert.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Full sore fore hyre he wepe.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="265">He bade &thorn;e folke <I>&thorn;at &thorn;er</I> ware<NOTE PLACE="foot">there wer all.</NOTE></L>
<L>Falle on knees with-owten mare,<NOTE PLACE="foot">On &thorn;er kneys &thorn;ei schuld fall,</NOTE></L>
<L>A prayer forto make,<NOTE PLACE="foot">A bede forto seyne,</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at god graunte &thorn;e askynge of &thorn;is:<NOTE PLACE="foot">That god schuld &thorn;em wyte &amp; wys</NOTE></L>
<L>Whedur hir saule be in heuon blisse<NOTE PLACE="foot">Whe&thorn;er &thorn;e saule wer in blys,</NOTE></L>
<L N="270">Or to helle take.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Or in hell peyne.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>When &thorn;ei hade made &thorn;eire oryson,<NOTE PLACE="foot">had. &thorn;er.</NOTE></L>
<L>A voyce came fro heuon down,<NOTE PLACE="foot">come. heuyne done.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at alle men my&yogh;t here,<NOTE PLACE="foot">That &thorn;ei myght he(re).</NOTE></L>
<L>And seid: "&thorn;e saule of &thorn;is synfulle wy&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="foot">of &thorn;at.</NOTE></L>
<L N="275">Is wonnen in-to heuon bright,<NOTE PLACE="foot">wonnen fehlt. in heuyne.</NOTE></L>
<L>To Jhesu lefe and dere."<NOTE PLACE="foot">Before Jhesu full dere.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The voyce seid to &thorn;e bisshop right:</L>
<L>"Asoyle &thorn;e body with alle &thorn;i myght</L>
<L>And bery hit in a graue!</L>
<L N="280">Alle-if it did gret foly,</L>
<L>With rufulle hert hit cryed mercy;</L>
<L>God graunt &thorn;at hit shuld haue."<NOTE PLACE="foot">277&mdash;82) fehlen.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Gode men, I warne alle<NOTE PLACE="foot">Crystene men, I werne &yogh;ou all,</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at &yogh;e in no wanhope falle,<NOTE PLACE="foot">That none of &yogh;ou in wanhop fall,</NOTE></L>
<L N="285">&YOGH;if &yogh;e haue don gret synne.<NOTE PLACE="foot">They &yogh;e be in synne.</NOTE></L>
<L>Forthynk hit sore and crye mercy,</L>
<L>Were hit neuer so gret foly,</L>
<L>And &yogh;et shalle &yogh;e heuon wynne.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><P>286&mdash;8) Who-so wyll of a preste be schryfe, And do penans by his lyfe, Heuyne he may wynne. Darauf hat A. noch 3 Stropfen:</P><P>Thoff a mane hade done alone All &thorn;e synnes euery-chone That euer &yogh;it wer wrou&yogh;t: And he may in his last dey To a preste his lyue sey, God wyll foregete hym nought. And if a mane haue no preste, To a man &thorn;at sytte hym nexte &YOGH;erne to hym schryfe; And if he may do no more Bot fore hys synnes rew sore, God wyll hym foregyffe. Kynge &thorn;at is of my&yogh;htys moste, Fader &amp; sone &amp; holy goste, &YOGH;iff vs my&yogh;ht &amp; space: When we haue do oure ende, Vnto Joy &thorn;at we may wende, Lord, for &thorn;i holy grace.</P></NOTE></L>
<TRAILER>Finitur fabula.
</TRAILER>

</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="14" TYPE="legend"><PB REF="00000477.tif" N="[339]">
<HEAD>14. Legende vom Crucifix, aus Ms. Ashmol. 61, fol. 26b.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>By-twyx two knyghtys be-&yogh;ond &thorn;e se</L>
<L>Fell a gret conteke to be.</L>
<L>By-twyx &thorn;em felle syche wreth &amp; wo,</L>
<L>That &thorn;e one weyted &thorn;e o&thorn;er to slo.</L>
<L N="5">This sleyne knyght hade a chyld,</L>
<L>A dou&yogh;hty bachyler &amp; wylde.</L>
<L>This chyld toke hym to rede</L>
<L>Forto venge his fader dede.</L>
<L>He gerte hym grete powere (&amp;) myght,</L>
<L N="10">To besege &thorn;e o&thorn;er knyght.</L>
<L>The o&thorn;er knyght perseyued hym wele</L>
<L>And droff hym to his best castelle.<NOTE PLACE="foot">droff = drew.</NOTE></L>
<L>Than was he besegyd so streytly,</L>
<L>That he durste come oute on no party</L>
<L N="15">Off all &thorn;e XII moneth, with no deseyte:</L>
<L>So was he beseged streyte.</L>
<L>Messe ne matyns he ne herd</L>
<L>Ne neuer to &thorn;e chirche he ferde.</L>
<L>And it was in &thorn;e lentyne tyde,</L>
<L N="20">When men schuld leue wreth &amp; pride.</L>
<L>Than felle it on &thorn;e gode-frydey:</L>
<L>The knyght &thorn;at in &thorn;e castell ley</L>
<L>Lukyd out &amp; saw men go</L>
<L>To &thorn;e chyrche to &amp; fro;</L>
<L N="25">Barefote to &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> chyrch (&thorn;ei) &yogh;ede,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. he u. his st. &thorn;ei u. &thorn;er.</NOTE></L>
<L>To aske mersy fore (&thorn;er) mysdede.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. he u. his st. &thorn;ei u. &thorn;er.</NOTE></L>
<L>The knyght thou&yogh;ht: "it is longe gone</L>
<L>That messe at &thorn;e chirche I herd none.</L>
<L>What-so-euer god fore me wylle wyrche,</L>
<L N="30">I wylle ryse &amp; go to &thorn;e chyrche".</L>
<L>He drew on his hose &amp; schone,<MILESTONE N="27" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And dude &thorn;e &yogh;atys be vndone;</L>
<L>Barefote he &yogh;ede, as is &thorn;e gyse,</L>
<L>To chirche, to here godys seruys.</L>
<L N="35">And as he &thorn;e wey to &thorn;e chirche name,</L>
<L>His enmy sone a&yogh;ens hym came,</L>
<L>And seyd: "tratoure, now schall &thorn;ou dy&yogh;e</L>
<L>And my faderes deth full dere aby&yogh;e!</L>
<L>No werldys gode &thorn;e schalle saue,</L>
<L N="40">Bot thou &thorn;i deth of me schall haue".</L>
<L>The knyght saw none o&thorn;er bote,</L>
<L>Bot fell on kneys before his fote</L>
<L>And seyd: "offe me &thorn;ou haue mersy,</L>
<L>Fore hym &thorn;at ly&yogh;ht in &thorn;e virgyne Mary</L>
<L N="45">And sofryd deth on &thorn;e rode tre<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. sofeyd.</NOTE></L>
<L>This dey, to saue both &thorn;e &amp; me,</L>
<L>And foregaffe hym &thorn;at his blode spylte:</L>
<L>Right so &thorn;ou foregyff me &thorn;at gylte!</L>
<L>I ame as a presonere in &thorn;is place,</L>
<L N="50">I put me now all in &thorn;i grace,</L>
<L>That godys grace be on &thorn;e lente</L>
<L>At the dey of Jugemente".</L>
<L>This knyght &thorn;at was his enmy</L>
<L>Herd hym praye so reufolly,</L>
<L N="55">And seyd: "seth &thorn;ou haste me besou&yogh;ht</L>
<L>Fore Jhesu loue, &thorn;at dere vs bou&yogh;ht,</L>
<L>And fore his moder loue so dere,</L>
<L>Fore them I grante &thorn;e my powere".</L>
<L>This Iche chyld sone do&umacr;ne ly&yogh;ht</L>
<L N="60">And in gode loue kyssed &thorn;e kny&yogh;ht.</L>
<L>"We be now frendys, &thorn;at are wer wrothe.</L>
<L>Go we now to &thorn;e chyrche bothe</L>
<L>In gowd loue &amp; parfyte charyte</L>
<L>Fore his sake &thorn;at ordeynd &thorn;us to be!"</L>
<L N="65">The knyght was glade veraly,</L>
<L>And so wer all &thorn;at compeny,</L>
<L>That he foregyffe (hym) &thorn;is mysdede.<NOTE PLACE="foot">foregyffe = forgaffe. Ms. them st. him.</NOTE></L>
<L>And to &thorn;e chyrch than both &thorn;ei &yogh;ede.
<PB REF="00000478.tif" N="340"></L>
<L>Before &thorn;e cros &thorn;ei knelyd do&umacr;ne,</L>
<L N="70">In &thorn;e worschyppe off Jhesus passyoune</L>
<L>Forto kysse &thorn;e crosse &thorn;at dey,</L>
<L>As custome is in crysten ley.</L>
<L>The eldere knyght fore honour</L>
<L>&YOGH;ede fyrst &amp; kyst hys creatour.</L>
<L N="75">After &thorn;an &yogh;ede &thorn;e chyld,</L>
<L>That was becomme meke &amp; mylde;</L>
<L>With &thorn;e tokyne he ganne hym blysse</L>
<L>And knelyd downe &thorn;e crosse to kys.</L>
<L>The crusyfix, &thorn;at there was leyd,</L>
<L N="80">His arme fro &thorn;e crosse vppe breyd</L>
<L>And clyped &thorn;e chyld hym betwyx,</L>
<L>And sethe hym kyssed &thorn;e crusyfix.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. he st. hym,</NOTE></L>
<L>All &thorn;e parysch, bo&thorn;e olde &amp; &yogh;enge,</L>
<L>Perseyued &amp; saw &thorn;at clyppenge,</L>
<L N="85">And how &thorn;e crucyfyx hym kyste;</L>
<L>The saw it alle &amp; wele it wyste,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ei thankyd suete Jhesu</L>
<L>Off &thorn;at merakyll &amp; &thorn;at vertu.</L>
<L>Off &thorn;is chylde was grete selcouthe<NOTE PLACE="foot">Off st. to?</NOTE></L>
<L N="90">That &thorn;e crucyfix kyste his mouthe;</L>
<L>Neuer-&thorn;e-les &yogh;it Iwys</L>
<L>In his herte was myche blys,</L>
<L>And all &thorn;e folke &thorn;at saw &thorn;at thinge</L>
<L>Made to god grete thankynge.</L>
<L N="95">Of thes two knyghtys how it betyde</L>
<L>The merakylle spronge wele wyde,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. strong st. sprong,</NOTE></L>
<L>And euery mane &thorn;erof gane telle,</L>
<L>Prestys in prechingys &thorn;erof cane spell,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at euery man in &thorn;at contre</L>
<L N="100">Lyue(d) well &thorn;e more in charite<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. lyue.</NOTE></L>
<L>And all men &thorn;e sonere foregaue</L>
<L>There wreth <I>&thorn;at &thorn;ei</I> to o&thorn;er haue.</L>
<L>Sykyre &thorn;ou be he was ry&yogh;ht wele</L>
<L>That gode fore hym dude sych merakell!</L>
<L N="105">A syngne it was of grete loue,</L>
<L>That god all-my&yogh;hty of heuen aboue</L>
<L>Prefer(d) hym to kys so lawly,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. prefere.</NOTE></L>
<L>Fore he mekyd his herte so hye.</L>
<L>Now may &yogh;e se, god loues &thorn;em dere</L>
<L N="110">That foregyue &thorn;er wreth in &thorn;is werld here.</L>
<L>So schall his wreth on hym be sene<NOTE PLACE="foot">hym plur.?</NOTE></L>
<L>That here wylle not foregyffe &thorn;er tene.</L>
<L>Therefore prinsypally I hold it beste</L>
<L>Forto loue pece &amp; lyue in reste.</L>
<L N="115">And &thorn;at it myght so be,</L>
<L>Prey we all fore charite!</L>
<TRAILER>Amen quod Rate.
</TRAILER>

</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="15" TYPE="legend"><PB REF="00000479.tif" N="[341]">
<HEAD>15. Ipotis, aus Ms. Vernon fol. 296.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>Dieses Gedicht folgt hier in der &auml;ltesten erhaltenen Fassung, der des Ms. Vernon. Es findet sich, ausser in diesem und Ms. Addit. 22283 (einer w&ouml;rtlichen Copie des Ms. Vern.), in mehreren j&uuml;ngeren Hss., welche, unter sich verwandt, dem &auml;lteren Texte gegen&uuml;berstehen: Ms. Cotton. Calig. A II fol. 79b, Arundel 140 fol. 1, Ashmol. 750, Ashmol. 61, Douce 323 fol. 160 (bis V. 495, Schluss fehlt,) und Ms. Cotton. Tit. A XXVI fol. 163 (Anfang fehlt, es beg. mit V. 100, worauf wieder 101&mdash;114 fehlen). &mdash; Der Text des Ms. Vern. ist bereits vielfach verderbt; noch fehlerhafter sind die j&uuml;ngeren Hss., so dass die Herstellung des urspr. Textes kaum m&ouml;glich scheint.</P></HEADNOTE>
<HEAD>Her biginne&thorn; a tretys &thorn;at me clepe&thorn; Ypotys.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Alle &thorn;at wolle&thorn; of wisdom lere,</L>
<L>Lustne&thorn; nou, and &yogh;e may here</L>
<L>Of a tale of holy writ &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. Addit. 22283 l. in holy writ.</NOTE></L>
<L>Seint Jon &thorn;e Ewangelist witnesse&thorn; hit &mdash;</L>
<L N="5">Hou hit bifel in grete Rome,</L>
<L>&THORN;e cheef cite of cristendome.</L>
<L>A child was sent of mi&yogh;tes most</L>
<L>&THORN;orw vertue of &thorn;e holy gost.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Emperour of Rome &thorn;an</L>
<L N="10">His nome was hoten sire Adrian.</L>
<L>And whon &thorn;e child of gret honour</L>
<L>Was come bifore &thorn;e Emperour,</L>
<L>Vppon his kneos he him sette,</L>
<L>&THORN;e Emperour ful feire he grette.</L>
<L N="15">&THORN;e Emperour wi&thorn; mylde chere</L>
<L>Askede from whe&thorn;ene he come were.</L>
<L>&THORN;e child onswerde al a-pliht:</L>
<L>"From my mooder I com now riht</L>
<L>And from my fader, &thorn;e hei&yogh;e Justise,</L>
<L N="20">To techen men, &thorn;at be&thorn; not wyse</L>
<L>Ne folfulle&thorn; not godes lawe".</L>
<L>&THORN;enne seide &thorn;e Emperour in his sawe:</L>
<L>"&THORN;enne artou wys wisdam to teche?"<NOTE PLACE="foot">A. wisdom.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e child onswerde wi&thorn; mylde speche:</L>
<L N="25">"He is wys &thorn;at heuene may wynne</L>
<L>And kepe him out of dedly synne".</L>
<L>&THORN;e Emperour wi&thorn;-outen blame:</L>
<L>"Child, he seide, what is &thorn;i name?"</L>
<L>"My nome, he seide, is Ypotis,</L>
<L N="30">&THORN;at muche con tellen of heuene blis".<NOTE PLACE="foot">A. telle.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e Emperour seide: "what may heuene be?"</L>
<L>"Sire, he seide, godes priuete".</L>
<L>"What, he seide, is god almiht?"</L>
<L>&THORN;e child onswerde anon riht:</L>
<L N="35">"He is wi&thorn;-outen beginnyng</L>
<L>And schal be wi&thorn;-outen endyng".</L>
<L>&THORN;e Emperour seide: "&thorn;at is selcou&thorn;.</L>
<L>What com furst of godes mou&thorn;?"</L>
<L>&THORN;e child onswerde and seide anon:</L>
<L N="40">"&THORN;er-of speke&thorn; &thorn;e apostel seynt Jon</L>
<L>In his godspel al and sum:</L>
<L>In principio erat verbum.</L>
<L>&THORN;is was &thorn;e furste bigynnyng</L>
<L>&THORN;at spak vre heuene kyng;</L>
<L N="45">At &thorn;at word was he sone,</L>
<L>Fader &amp; &thorn;e holigost to-geder come,</L>
<L>&THORN;reo persones in trinite &mdash;</L>
<L>Neuer on may from o&thorn;er be".</L>
<L>&THORN;enne seide &thorn;e Emperour ful euene:</L>
<L N="50">"Leue child, hastou ben in heuene,</L>
<L>Hou feole heuenes ha&thorn; god almiht?"
<PB REF="00000480.tif" N="342"></L>
<L>"Seuene, seide &thorn;e child a-pliht;</L>
<L>&THORN;e hexte heuene &thorn;at may be,</L>
<L>&THORN;at is &thorn;e holy trinite:</L>
<L N="55">&THORN;er is &thorn;e fader and &thorn;e sone,</L>
<L>&THORN;e holygost to-gedere wone,<NOTE PLACE="foot">A. And &thorn;e h.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;reo persones in o godhede,</L>
<L>As clerkes in heore bokes rede.</L>
<L>&THORN;e o&thorn;er heuene nis not lowe;<NOTE PLACE="foot">A. is.</NOTE></L>
<L N="60">&THORN;e hexte &thorn;at eny mon of knowe</L>
<L>Is at a lowere degre,<NOTE PLACE="foot">A. lower,</NOTE></L>
<L>As &yogh;e nou mowen I-se;</L>
<L>&THORN;ulke Joye ne may telle no mon</L>
<L>Til domes-day, whon we gon hom.</L>
<L N="65">&THORN;e &thorn;ridde heuene seme&thorn; cristal,</L>
<L>Ful of Joye and swete smel;</L>
<L>To mon and wommon &thorn;at place is diht<NOTE PLACE="foot">Die and. Mss. l. For confessours.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at serue&thorn; god wi&thorn; al heore miht.</L>
<L>&THORN;e feor&thorn;e heuene is gold iliche,</L>
<L N="70">Ful of precious stones riche;</L>
<L>To Innocens &thorn;at place is diht;</L>
<L>&THORN;er is day, and neuer niht.</L>
<L>&THORN;e fyf&thorn;e heuene is long and brod:</L>
<L>&THORN;at is &thorn;e folfullynge of godes monhod.<NOTE PLACE="foot">A. folfillyng.</NOTE></L>
<L N="75">&YOGH;if &thorn;at godes monhod nere,</L>
<L>Al &thorn;is world forlore were;</L>
<L>&THORN;orw &thorn;e passion of godes monhede</L>
<L>Heuene blisse schal ben heore mede.</L>
<L>&THORN;e sixte heuene is holi chirche,</L>
<L N="80">Ful of angles, &thorn;er-inne worche;</L>
<L>Heo synge&thorn; of god bo&thorn;e day and niht,</L>
<L>Of his streng&thorn;e and of his miht.</L>
<L>&THORN;e seuen&thorn;e heuene, sei&thorn; &thorn;e storie,</L>
<L>Is paradys aftur purgatorie;</L>
<L N="85">Whon soules han don heore penaunce,</L>
<L>&THORN;er &thorn;ei schul resten, wi&thorn;-oute distaunce.</L>
<L>Heer be&thorn; seuen heuenes, sir Emperour, a-pliht".</L>
<L>"Hou feole ordres, seide &thorn;e Emperour, be&thorn; angles bri&yogh;t?"</L>
<L>&THORN;e child onswerde him a&yogh;en:</L>
<L N="90">"Ni&yogh;ene ordres, sire, &thorn;er ben:<NOTE PLACE="foot">A. &thorn;en st. &thorn;er.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e furste ordre is Cherubin,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at o&thorn;er Seraphin,</L>
<L>&THORN;e &thorn;ridde is cleped Trones,</L>
<L>&THORN;e feor&thorn;e Dominaciones,</L>
<L N="95">&THORN;e fyf&thorn;e is Principatus,</L>
<L>&THORN;e sixte is Potestates,</L>
<L>&THORN;e seuen&thorn;e Virtutes is,</L>
<L>&THORN;e eihte&thorn;e Angelica iwis,</L>
<L>&THORN;e ni&thorn;e ordre is Archangeli:</L>
<L N="100">Eueri prince ha&thorn; his parti,</L>
<L>Mony &thorn;ousend angles to heore baneere,</L>
<L>To serue god bo&thorn;e feor and neere.</L>
<L>&THORN;e ten&thorn;e ordre schal monkuynde ben,</L>
<L>Forto fulle &thorn;e place a&yogh;en<NOTE PLACE="foot">A. forte.</NOTE></L>
<L N="105">In heuene bi &thorn;at ilke syde</L>
<L>&THORN;at Lucifer lees for his pruyde;</L>
<L>&THORN;er schal &thorn;e monhede of god almiht</L>
<L>Ben vre prince, and &thorn;at is riht;</L>
<L>Abouen alle o&thorn;ure he schal be,<NOTE PLACE="foot">A. al.</NOTE></L>
<L N="110">Wi&thorn; his fader, in trinite.</L>
<L>Of muche Joye he may telle</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ere wi&thorn;-outen enden may dwelle,</L>
<L>&THORN;at his oune bro&thorn;er may se</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; his fader in maieste!"</L>
<L N="115">&THORN;en seide &thorn;e Emperour: "&thorn;is leue I wel</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;is is so&thorn;, eueridel.</L>
<L>But tel me, child, I &thorn;e pray,</L>
<L>What made god on &thorn;e furste day?"</L>
<L>"On &thorn;e monenday, verreyment,</L>
<L N="120">God made &thorn;e firmament,</L>
<L>Sonne and mone schyne brihte,</L>
<L>Mony sterres, &thorn;eron Idihte.</L>
<L>On &thorn;e tewesday, Ich vnderstonde,</L>
<L>God made &thorn;e see and &thorn;e londe,</L>
<L N="125">Welles feole and watres fresche,<NOTE PLACE="foot">A. fele, fresch.</NOTE></L>
<L>To tempre &thorn;e eor&thorn;e hard and nesche;<NOTE PLACE="foot">A. nesch.</NOTE></L>
<L>Herbes he made, treo and gras,</L>
<L>And o&thorn;er &thorn;ing, what his wille was.</L>
<L>Vppon &thorn;e wedenesday made god almiht<NOTE PLACE="foot">A. wednesday.</NOTE></L>
<L N="130">Fisch in flod and foul in fliht,</L>
<L>And bad hem aboute &thorn;e world wende,</L>
<L>Forto helpen al monkynde.<NOTE PLACE="foot">A. forte.</NOTE></L>
<L>On &thorn;e &thorn;oresday god made beestes fale,</L>
<L>Monye diuerse, bi doune and dale,</L>
<L N="135">And &yogh;af &thorn;e eor&thorn;e to heore foode,</L>
<L>And bad hem torne monkuynde to goode</L>
<L>On &thorn;e fryday god made Adame,
<PB REF="00000481.tif" N="343"></L>
<L>And after his schap he &yogh;af him name;</L>
<L>Si&thorn;en his o rib he gan take<NOTE PLACE="foot">A. gon.</NOTE></L>
<L N="140">And maade Eue to his make;</L>
<L>He maade him mon of mihtes most</L>
<L>And bleu&yogh; in him &thorn;e holigost,</L>
<L>And paradys he gan him take,<NOTE PLACE="foot">A. gon.</NOTE></L>
<L>And gret mayster he gon him make:</L>
<L N="145">He maade him maister of &thorn;at he hedde wrou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>On &thorn;e seterday, god for&yogh;at nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>On &thorn;e saterday god blessed wi&thorn; wille<NOTE PLACE="foot">A. seterday.</NOTE></L>
<L>Alle his werkes, bo&thorn;e loude &amp; stille,</L>
<L>And bad hem waxen and multiplye,</L>
<L N="150">Eueri beest on his partye.</L>
<L>On &thorn;e sonenday after god reste tok,</L>
<L>As we fynden in holy book;</L>
<L>He comaundede al monkuynde</L>
<L>&THORN;at day reste haue in muynde.</L>
<L N="155">On &thorn;at day scholde no-mon worche,<NOTE PLACE="foot">A. schal.</NOTE></L>
<L>But bidde his beodes and go to churche,</L>
<L>And kepe him out of dedly synne,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he ne falle not &thorn;er-inne.</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore I rede &thorn;at &yogh;e me lustne,</L>
<L N="160">And helpe&thorn; &thorn;at day oure euen-cristne".</L>
<L>&THORN;en seide &thorn;e Emperour: "&thorn;is leue I wel</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;is beo so&thorn;, eueridel.</L>
<L>But tel me, child, &yogh;if &thorn;at &thorn;ou can,</L>
<L>Os hou feole &thorn;inges god maade Adam?"</L>
<L N="165">&THORN;e child seide: "of &thorn;inges seuene.</L>
<L>Whuche hit be&thorn;, Ichul &thorn;e nempne:<NOTE PLACE="foot">A. ne nemene.</NOTE></L>
<L>Er&thorn;e-slym was on of &thorn;o,</L>
<L>Water of &thorn;e see he tok &thorn;erto,</L>
<L>And of &thorn;e sonne and of &thorn;e wynde,</L>
<L N="170">And of &thorn;e cloudes, as we Ifynde,</L>
<L>And of &thorn;e stones bi &thorn;e see-cost,</L>
<L>And also of &thorn;e holy gost.</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e eor&thorn;e he made his flesch,</L>
<L>And of &thorn;e water his blod so nesch,</L>
<L N="175">And of &thorn;e sonne his herte and his bowels,<NOTE PLACE="foot">A. boweles.</NOTE></L>
<L>His liknesse and his goode &thorn;ewes,<NOTE PLACE="foot">A. lihtnesse.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of &thorn;e wynt he made his bre&thorn;,</L>
<L>And of &thorn;e cloudes his wittes be&thorn;,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e ston he made his bon,</L>
<L N="180">And of &thorn;e holygost his soule anon.</L>
<L>Lo, Emperour, sire Adrian,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;us feole &thorn;inges god maade Adam. &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">A. fele.</NOTE></L>
<L>Eueri mon, &thorn;at nou lyue&thorn; heere,</L>
<L>Is mad of diuerse manere.</L>
<L N="185">Whose of &thorn;e er&thorn;e haue&thorn; most,<NOTE PLACE="foot">A. hose.</NOTE></L>
<L>He schal ben heuy, wel &thorn;ou wost,</L>
<L>Heuy in word and in dede</L>
<L>And o&thorn;er &thorn;ing, as I ow rede.</L>
<L>Whose of &thorn;e see ha&thorn; most plente,<NOTE PLACE="foot">A. hose.</NOTE></L>
<L N="190">Leof to trauayle schal him be,</L>
<L>Muche to coueyten, lond and leode,</L>
<L>And luyte may helpen him at neode:</L>
<L>Hit fare&thorn; bi &thorn;is worldes good</L>
<L>As bi an ebbe and bi a flood:</L>
<L N="195">Now hit is, and nou hit nis &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;enk no-mon &thorn;eron I-wis.</L>
<L>Whose of &thorn;e cloudes ha&thorn; most foysun,</L>
<L>He schal be wys, bi good reson,</L>
<L>Wys in word and in dede</L>
<L N="200">And o&thorn;er &thorn;ing, as I ow rede.</L>
<L>Whose of &thorn;e wynt ha&thorn; most miht,</L>
<L>Bi god reson he schal be liht,</L>
<L>Sauage in dede and in &thorn;ou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And speke muche &thorn;at helpe&thorn; nou&yogh;t.</L>
<L N="205">Whose of &thorn;e sonne ha&thorn; most plente,</L>
<L>Hot and hastyf he schal be,</L>
<L>Stalwor&thorn;e and of gret miht,</L>
<L>And bi good reson feir of siht.</L>
<L>Whose of &thorn;e ston is most I-wrou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="210">He schal beo studefast of &thorn;ou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>In his herte trusti and trewe,</L>
<L>And bi good reson pale of hewe.</L>
<L>Whose ha&thorn; of &thorn;e holigost,<NOTE PLACE="foot">A. hose.</NOTE></L>
<L>He schal haue fyn herte most,</L>
<L N="215">Good word, good &thorn;ou&yogh;t, and good dede,</L>
<L>And o&thorn;er &thorn;ing, as I ou rede,</L>
<L>Loue wel god and holy churche,</L>
<L>And o&thorn;er penaunce forto worche".<NOTE PLACE="foot">A. forte.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;en seide &thorn;e Emperour: "&thorn;is leue I wel</L>
<L N="220">&THORN;at &thorn;is beo so&thorn;, eueridel.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou speke &yogh;arwhile of &thorn;e see;</L>
<L>What &thorn;ing may &thorn;at be?"</L>
<L>&THORN;e child seide: "wi&thorn;-oute lesyng,</L>
<L>A wylde wey in wendyng.<NOTE PLACE="foot">A, weendyng.</NOTE></L>
<L N="225">Such wei a mon may wende wi&thorn;-inne
<PB REF="00000482.tif" N="344"></L>
<L>Schal he neuere lond I-winne".</L>
<L>&THORN;enne seyde &thorn;e Emperour: "&thorn;at is meruayle.</L>
<L>But tel me, child, wi&thorn;-outen fayle,</L>
<L>What tyme dude Adam &thorn;e dede amis</L>
<L N="230">&THORN;at he foreode paradis?"</L>
<L>&THORN;e child seide: "at midmorwe tyde,</L>
<L>And ar midday he les his pruyde;</L>
<L>An aungel him drof in-to decert</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; a briht brennynde swerd,<NOTE PLACE="foot">A. swert.</NOTE></L>
<L N="235">Him and his ofspring euermare</L>
<L>Heer to liuen in serwe and care".</L>
<L>"Allas, seide &thorn;e Emperour, for deol,<NOTE PLACE="foot">l. dol.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at Adam was so gret a fol!</L>
<L>Hou fele sunnes dude Adam,<NOTE PLACE="foot">) A. synnes.</NOTE></L>
<L N="240">&THORN;at god on him so wreche nam?"</L>
<L>&THORN;e child seide: "seuene, and mo.</L>
<L>Sacrilegie was on of &thorn;o,<NOTE PLACE="foot">A. is st. was.</NOTE></L>
<L>Fornicacion and envye,</L>
<L>Auarice and couetyse,</L>
<L N="245">Gula and superbia &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;us feole sunnes dude Adam &thorn;a.<NOTE PLACE="foot">A. synnes.</NOTE></L>
<L>In pride dude Adam sungen ille,</L>
<L>Whon he wrou&yogh;te aftur his oune wille</L>
<L>And held not after &thorn;e heste of gode,</L>
<L N="250">But al a&yogh;eynes his forbode.<NOTE PLACE="foot">V. forbede, A. forbode.</NOTE></L>
<L>In sacrilegye he sungede sore,<NOTE PLACE="foot">A. sacrilege, sunged.</NOTE></L>
<L>Whon he wrou&yogh;te after &thorn;e fendes lore</L>
<L>And folfulde his oune talent<NOTE PLACE="foot">A. fillede.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bi &thorn;e fendes comaundement.<NOTE PLACE="foot">A. entisement.</NOTE></L>
<L N="255">Lecherye he hedde in muynde,</L>
<L>Whon he wrou&yogh;te after &thorn;e fende</L>
<L>And held &thorn;at godes lore was fals.</L>
<L>In couetyse he sunged als,</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;at he coueytede more<NOTE PLACE="foot">A. coueyted.</NOTE></L>
<L N="260">&THORN;en he hedde neode fore;</L>
<L>He hedde paradys at his wille &mdash;</L>
<L>No wonder &thorn;ei god him liked ille.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if he hedde beo mon of goode,</L>
<L>He ne schulde ha stole &thorn;at him was forbode;</L>
<L N="265">Sikerliche, as I ow seye,</L>
<L>He was wor&thorn;i forto dye.<NOTE PLACE="foot">A. forte.</NOTE></L>
<L>Monsleere he was I-nouh,</L>
<L>Whon he is owne soule slouh;</L>
<L>Whon he was ded, to helle (he) nom,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. &thorn;o him to telle nom.</NOTE></L>
<L N="270">And alle &thorn;at euere of him com.</L>
<L>In glotenye he sunged vyle,<NOTE PLACE="foot">A. glotonye.</NOTE></L>
<L>Whon he him putte in &thorn;at perile</L>
<L>Of &thorn;at treo &thorn;e appel to take</L>
<L>&THORN;at god forbed him, and his make.</L>
<L N="275">In sleu&thorn;e he sunged worst of alle:</L>
<L>Whon he was in sunne I-falle,</L>
<L>He nedde no pouste forte aryse.</L>
<L>Whon god spac to him on &thorn;is wyse</L>
<L>And seide: "Adam, what dost &thorn;ou nou&thorn;e?"</L>
<L N="280">Adam onswerde him wi&thorn; mou&thorn;e:</L>
<L>"Lord, Ich here &thorn;e speke a-pliht,</L>
<L>But of &thorn;e haue I no siht". &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;en vr lord to Adam sede:</L>
<L>"Mon, whi dust &thorn;ou wikked dede?"<NOTE PLACE="foot">A. dustou.</NOTE></L>
<L N="285">Adam onswerde wordes ille:</L>
<L>"&THORN;e wommon, &thorn;at &thorn;ou toke me tille,</L>
<L>Made me forte don &thorn;at dede".</L>
<L>&THORN;enne vr lord to Eue sede:</L>
<L>"Wommon, whi wrou&yogh;testou wikked wile?"<NOTE PLACE="foot">A. wrouhtust &thorn;ou.</NOTE></L>
<L N="290">"&THORN;e neddre, lord, me dude begyle".</L>
<L>Vre lord to &thorn;e neddre seide &thorn;o:</L>
<L>"Fend, whi wrou&yogh;testou al &thorn;is wo?"</L>
<L>&THORN;e fend onswerde wi&thorn; maistrie:</L>
<L>"For to hem Ich hedde envye,</L>
<L N="295">&THORN;at &thorn;ei scholde wone in &thorn;at blis<NOTE PLACE="foot">A. schulde.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at I for pruide dude amis"(!).<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at st. &thorn;er?</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;enne vre lord seide to Adam:</L>
<L>"For &thorn;i gult, he seide, mon,<NOTE PLACE="foot">A. man.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ou schalt in eor&thorn;e swynke &amp; swete,<NOTE PLACE="foot">A. l. to helle he hom. on st. in.</NOTE></L>
<L N="300">Suffre penaunce in chele and hete".</L>
<L>To Eue seide vre heuene kyng:</L>
<L>"For &thorn;i wikked entysyng<NOTE PLACE="foot">A. wikkede.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ou schalt ben vnder monnes heste,</L>
<L>In muche drede, wo and cheste,</L>
<L N="305">Bere &thorn;i fruit in gronyng and care,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou and &thorn;in ofspring euer-mare".</L>
<L>&THORN;enne vre lord seide to Sathan:</L>
<L>"In fourme of worm &thorn;ou entysest man:
<PB REF="00000483.tif" N="345"></L>
<L>I comaunde &thorn;e, &thorn;at &thorn;ou on &thorn;y wombe glyde,</L>
<L N="310">And al &thorn;e harm bi &thorn;i syde;<NOTE PLACE="foot">A. be.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of &thorn;e schule men beo sore afert.<NOTE PLACE="foot">A. aferd.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;en schal &thorn;er come into middel-ert</L>
<L>A virgyne I-boren also blyue,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;i pouwer schal al to-dryue". &mdash;</L>
<L N="315">Adam wonede in eor&thorn;e heere<NOTE PLACE="foot">A. on st. in.</NOTE></L>
<L>Folle ni&yogh;ene hondred &yogh;ere<NOTE PLACE="foot">A. fulle.</NOTE></L>
<L>And two and &thorn;ritti, as I ow telle.</L>
<L>Whon he was ded, he wente to helle.</L>
<L>Foure &thorn;ousend winter &amp; seuen hondred &amp; more</L>
<L N="320">Adam was in helle &thorn;ore</L>
<L>&THORN;reo &yogh;eer and tydes seuene,</L>
<L>Til &thorn;e mihti kyng of heuene</L>
<L>Kud he was of mihtes most<NOTE PLACE="foot">V A And, al. Kyde.</NOTE></L>
<L>And sende adoun &thorn;e holygost,</L>
<L N="325">Was I-boren of &thorn;e virgyne Marie</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;-oute wem of hire bodye.<NOTE PLACE="foot">A. wi&thorn;outen.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ritti winter and &thorn;ridde half &yogh;eer</L>
<L>God wonede on eor&thorn;e heer.</L>
<L>Fourti dawes for vs he faste.</L>
<L N="330">&THORN;e Jewes token him atte laste<NOTE PLACE="foot">A. him token.</NOTE></L>
<L>And duden godes sone on &thorn;e rode;</L>
<L>&THORN;er he di&yogh;ede, for vre goode.</L>
<L>Whon he was ded, he wente to helle,</L>
<L>&THORN;e fendes pouste forto quelle,<NOTE PLACE="foot">A. forte.</NOTE></L>
<L N="335">And fette out Adam and Eue,</L>
<L>And o&thorn;er mo &thorn;at weren him leue:</L>
<L>Moyses, Dauid, and Abraham;</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e goode wi&thorn; him he nam</L>
<L>And ladde hem in-to paradis,</L>
<L N="340">&THORN;er Joye &amp; blisse euere is.</L>
<L>And si&thorn;en aftur his vp-rysing</L>
<L>He stei&yogh; to heuene, &thorn;er he is kyng;</L>
<L>On his fader ri&yogh;t hond he set him &thorn;on,</L>
<L>&THORN;er he is studefast god &amp; mon.</L>
<L N="345">&THORN;at ilke god omnipotent</L>
<L>Wol come to &thorn;e day of Jugement</L>
<L>And demen men after heore dede &mdash;</L>
<L>He is not wys &thorn;at hit nul drede &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;e goode to Joye, &thorn;e wikked to pyne.</L>
<L N="350">&THORN;e godnes of Joye may nomon fyne;</L>
<L>Joye &thorn;ei schulen han to heore seruyse<NOTE PLACE="foot">A. schul.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at seruen god in alle wyse."</L>
<L>&THORN;e Emperour seide: "bi heuene kyng!</L>
<L>Child, &thorn;is was a feir endyng.</L>
<L N="355">And also &thorn;is I leeue wel<NOTE PLACE="foot">A. leeue I.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;is is so&thorn;, eueridel.</L>
<L>But tel me, child, &yogh;if &thorn;at &thorn;ou con,</L>
<L>Wherwi&thorn; &thorn;e fend most tempte&thorn; mon,<NOTE PLACE="foot">A. a mon.</NOTE></L>
<L>And hou feole synnes, &thorn;ow me telle,</L>
<L N="360">Bringe&thorn; monnes soule to helle?"</L>
<L>&THORN;e child seide: "sunnes fyue<NOTE PLACE="foot">A. synnes.</NOTE></L>
<L>Beo&thorn; among monkuynde ful ryue:</L>
<L>Wikked &thorn;ou&yogh;t in monnes herte,</L>
<L>Whil &thorn;at he is hol and qwerte;</L>
<L N="365">Mon-slau&yogh;t is ano&thorn;er schame,</L>
<L>Bringe&thorn; monnes soule in wikked fame;</L>
<L>Pruide, forso&thorn;e, is ano&thorn;er;</L>
<L>Glotenye is &thorn;e &thorn;ridde bro&thorn;er;<NOTE PLACE="foot">A. glotonye.</NOTE></L>
<L>Lecherye is &thorn;e feor&thorn;e,</L>
<L N="370">On &thorn;e worste abouen eor&thorn;e.</L>
<L>Couetyse, as I ow telle,</L>
<L>Bringe&thorn; monnes soule to helle.</L>
<L>Seint Poul witnesse&thorn; in his storie:</L>
<L>Peyne for couetyse is purgatorie;</L>
<L N="375">Bi hem-seluen hit is diht</L>
<L>A welle of bras, brennynge bri&yogh;t,</L>
<L>As ful of hokes abouen and vnder:</L>
<L>Whon hit go&thorn;, hit rot as &thorn;onder;<NOTE PLACE="foot">A. rut.</NOTE></L>
<L>As ful of soules hit is hongynge</L>
<L N="380">As on may bi o&thorn;er hynge.</L>
<L>Couetyse ende&thorn; neuer a del,</L>
<L>For hit is liknet to a whel.<NOTE PLACE="foot">for st. for&thorn;i.</NOTE></L>
<L>&YOGH;it &thorn;e pruide, &thorn;at is so bold,<NOTE PLACE="foot">A. is st. &thorn;e, in 384 fehlt is.</NOTE></L>
<L>Is worse bi an hondred fold:</L>
<L N="385">For angles, &thorn;at weren in heuene liht,</L>
<L>&THORN;at weoren so feire and so briht,<NOTE PLACE="foot">A. feir.</NOTE></L>
<L>For pruide god wreche on hem dude take:</L>
<L>And summe bicome fendes blake</L>
<L>And fulle from heuene, as I ow telle,<NOTE PLACE="foot">A. fullen.</NOTE></L>
<L N="390">In-to &thorn;e neo&thorn;emaste put of helle.</L>
<L>Summe ben her among monkunne</L>
<L>And tyse men al day to sunne.<NOTE PLACE="foot">A. tyse&thorn; al day men.</NOTE></L>
<L>For&thorn;i, mon, schrif &thorn;e of &thorn;i pride!
<PB REF="00000484.tif" N="346"></L>
<L>Whon wormes han I-&yogh;ete &thorn;i syde</L>
<L N="395">And &thorn;i bodi lih&thorn; deope in grounde</L>
<L>And &thorn;i soule in wo I-bounde,</L>
<L>Sore schal &thorn;i soule smerte</L>
<L>&THORN;at euer &thorn;ou heddest pruide in herte.</L>
<L>Glotenye, I wol now skriue,</L>
<L N="400">Is among monkunne ful ryue;</L>
<L>&THORN;e fend take&thorn; of men wreches fale</L>
<L>Whon heo be&thorn; dronken of wyn and ale,<NOTE PLACE="foot">A. or st. and.</NOTE></L>
<L>Sweren &amp; cry&yogh;en, as &thorn;ei ben wode,</L>
<L>Bi Cristes herte, bi Cristes blode,</L>
<L N="405">And vpbreyde&thorn; his passioun.<NOTE PLACE="foot">A. vbbreyde&thorn;.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;erfore &thorn;ei han his malisoun;</L>
<L>But &thorn;ei schriuen hem of heore glotonye,</L>
<L>In helle schal ben heore baylye;</L>
<L>For heore fals o&thorn;es &thorn;at &thorn;ei maken,</L>
<L N="410">&THORN;e fend of helle schal hem taken.</L>
<L>Summe be slay&yogh;en in &thorn;e weye,<NOTE PLACE="foot">A. slayn.</NOTE></L>
<L>And summe in water &thorn;ei schulen dye.</L>
<L>Al &thorn;is betit of heore glotonye,</L>
<L>&THORN;orw false o&thorn;es and lecherie".<NOTE PLACE="foot">A. o&thorn;us.</NOTE></L>
<L N="415">&THORN;en seide &thorn;e Emperour: "&thorn;is leue i wel</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;is is so&thorn;, eueridel.</L>
<L>But tel me, child, &yogh;if &thorn;at &thorn;ou con,</L>
<L>On how fele de&thorn;es may dye mon?"</L>
<L>&THORN;e child onswerde: "de&thorn;es &thorn;re.</L>
<L N="420">Ichulle ow telle, whuche &thorn;ei be:</L>
<L>&THORN;at o de&thorn; is bodilich here:<NOTE PLACE="foot">A. bodi|liche.</NOTE></L>
<L>And a mon be strong in streng&thorn;e &amp; fere</L>
<L>In his bodi wi&thorn;-inne<NOTE PLACE="foot">A. here wi&thorn;inne.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ar lyf and soule may parte a-twynne.</L>
<L N="425">&THORN;at o&thorn;er de&thorn; is de&thorn; of schame,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if mon dye in dette or in wikked fame.</L>
<L>&THORN;e &thorn;ridde de&thorn;, as seyen &thorn;is clerkes,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if a mon dye wi&thorn;oute goode werkes".</L>
<L>&THORN;en seide &thorn;e Emperour:</L>
<L N="430">"Tel me, child, paramour,</L>
<L>Hou fele sunnes beo&thorn; vnschriuen</L>
<L>&THORN;at god of heuene nul not for&yogh;iuen?"</L>
<L>&THORN;e child onswerde: "sunnes two.<NOTE PLACE="foot">A. seide.</NOTE></L>
<L>Misbileeue is on of &thorn;o:</L>
<L N="435">&YOGH;if a mon for no resoun</L>
<L>Leeue&thorn; not on godes passioun,</L>
<L>&THORN;at god knelede on &thorn;e Mount of Olyuete,</L>
<L>For fere of de&thorn; blod gon he swete,</L>
<L>And was I-bounde to a piler,<NOTE PLACE="foot">A. Ibounden.</NOTE></L>
<L N="440">Beten wi&thorn; scourges stronge and ster,</L>
<L>And was I-crouned wi&thorn; &thorn;ornes kene&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;e woundes on his bodi wer ful sene,</L>
<L>Cristes bodi, &thorn;er hit stod,</L>
<L>I-femed al in his oune blod;<NOTE PLACE="foot">A. Iwrapped.</NOTE></L>
<L N="445">And si&thorn;en a duden him vppon &thorn;e tre.<NOTE PLACE="foot">a = &thorn;ei.</NOTE></L>
<L>But &yogh;if &thorn;ei leeue &thorn;at hit so be,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;if fehlt in A.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. &thorn;ou st. &thorn;ei.</NOTE></L>
<L>Sikerliche, as I ow telle,</L>
<L>For &thorn;at sunne heo gon to helle.<NOTE PLACE="foot">A. he ge&thorn;.</NOTE></L>
<L>Whonhope is &thorn;at o&thorn;er synne,<NOTE PLACE="foot">A. wonhope.</NOTE></L>
<L N="450">Regne&thorn; in londe and nul not blynne:</L>
<L>&YOGH;if a mon haue so muche misgult,</L>
<L>&THORN;e fend in wonhope him ha&thorn; I-pult<NOTE PLACE="foot">A. pult.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at he nul no merci craue,<MILESTONE N="297" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>For he wene&thorn; no merci haue;</L>
<L N="455">For &thorn;is sunne, as we fynde,</L>
<L>&THORN;ei gon to helle wi&thorn;-outen ende".</L>
<L>&THORN;en seide &thorn;e Emperour: "&thorn;is leue I wel</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;is beo so&thorn;, eueridel.</L>
<L>But tel me, child, &yogh;if &thorn;at &thorn;ow con,</L>
<L N="460">What dede paye&thorn; best god of mon?"</L>
<L>&THORN;e child onswerde him and sede:</L>
<L>"Good word, good &thorn;ou&yogh;t, and good dede.</L>
<L>A mon &thorn;at ha&thorn; feir speche,</L>
<L>And his fo wole on him take wreche,</L>
<L N="465">He may wi&thorn; his feir speche, ar he wende,<NOTE PLACE="foot">A. er.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of his fo maken his frende;</L>
<L>Feir speche is more of miht</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; god &thorn;at is in heuene liht.</L>
<L>A mon may wi&thorn; good word, god &thorn;ou&yogh;t, &amp; god dede</L>
<L N="470">Wynnen heuene blisse to his meede".</L>
<L>&THORN;en seide &thorn;e Emperour: "whon hit is so</L>
<L>&THORN;at synne worche&thorn; mon so wo,</L>
<L>Wher-wi&thorn; schal a mon him were</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e fend ne schal him dere?"</L>
<L N="475">&THORN;e child seide: "good deuocion,</L>
<L>&THORN;enken on Cristes passion.</L>
<L>&THORN;enk on his woundes smerte</L>
<L>And haue his passion in &thorn;in herte!</L>
<L>&THORN;erwi&thorn; schal a mon him were</L>
<L N="480">&THORN;at &thorn;e fend ne schal him dere".
<PB REF="00000485.tif" N="347"></L>
<L>&THORN;en seide &thorn;e Emperour: "&thorn;is leue I wel</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;is beo so&thorn;, eueridel.</L>
<L>But tel me, child, &yogh;if &thorn;at &thorn;ou con,</L>
<L>Hou fele dedes paye&thorn; best god of mon?"</L>
<L N="485">&THORN;e child seide: "deedes &thorn;re.</L>
<L>Ichulle ou telle, whuche &thorn;ei be.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if a mon liue&thorn; and ha&thorn; chaunce</L>
<L>To leden his lyf in rihtful penaunce</L>
<L>And kepen him from &thorn;e fendes fondynge</L>
<L N="490">And his herte out of wikked lykynge,</L>
<L>God is payed of &thorn;at enprise,<NOTE PLACE="foot">A. apa&yogh;ed.</NOTE></L>
<L>He schal han heuene for his seruise.<NOTE PLACE="foot">A. haue.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at o&thorn;ur pay&yogh;e&thorn; god muche in herte:</L>
<L>&YOGH;if a mon beo large in pouerte,</L>
<L N="495">&THORN;onken god wi&thorn; good wille</L>
<L>His pouerte, bo&thorn;e loud and stille,</L>
<L>Wolde bleo&thorn;elich helpen and keuere</L>
<L>His euen-cristne &thorn;at beo&thorn; pouere;</L>
<L>&YOGH;if he mowe do no more</L>
<L N="500">But in his herte rewen hem sore,</L>
<L>He schal han heuene for his goode wille<NOTE PLACE="foot">A. haue, god.</NOTE></L>
<L>At his endynge, and &thorn;at is skille.</L>
<L>&THORN;e &thorn;ridde paye&thorn; god ful muche:<NOTE PLACE="foot">A. miche.</NOTE></L>
<L>&YOGH;if a mon beo in eor&thorn;e riche</L>
<L N="505">And beo I-come of riche kunne,<NOTE PLACE="foot">A. kynne.</NOTE></L>
<L>Forsake&thorn; richesse and worldes winne</L>
<L>And take&thorn; his penaunce in pouerte:</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore in heuene he schal be".</L>
<L>&THORN;en seide &thorn;e Emperour: "&thorn;is I leeue.</L>
<L N="510">Leoue child, tak hit not a-greeue,</L>
<L>Whi faste&thorn; men friday so muche,</L>
<L>More &thorn;en eny o&thorn;er day in &thorn;e wike?"</L>
<L>&THORN;e child onswerde him a&yogh;eyn:</L>
<L>"For &thorn;rettene resons, &thorn;at I con seyn.</L>
<L N="515">&THORN;e furste reson, I ow telle con:</L>
<L>On a friday god made mon,</L>
<L>In &thorn;e vale of Ebron, &thorn;orw his grace,</L>
<L>And schop him aftur his oune face.</L>
<L>&THORN;at o&thorn;er is, woltou me leeue:</L>
<L N="520">Vppon a fridai god made Adam &amp; Eue,</L>
<L>And loren paradis, as I ow telle,</L>
<L>And si&thorn;en weore I-dampned to helle.</L>
<L>&THORN;e &thorn;ridde reson, I wol ou telle:</L>
<L>On a friday Caym slouh Abelle,</L>
<L N="525">&THORN;e furste martir, for-so&thorn;e I-wis,</L>
<L>&THORN;at euer dyede for Jhesus.<NOTE PLACE="foot">A. euere.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e feor&thorn;e reson is ful swete:</L>
<L>Hou Gabriel vr ladi gon grete</L>
<L>Vppon &thorn;e friday wi&thorn; milde mood;</L>
<L N="530">Godes sone tok in hire flesch and blood,</L>
<L>In &thorn;at ilke holy virgyne Marie,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;-outen wem of hire bodye.</L>
<L>&THORN;e fif&thorn;e reson, &thorn;at is bifore:</L>
<L>On a friday godes sone was bore.</L>
<L N="535">&THORN;e sixte reson is feir enprise:</L>
<L>How Jhesu Crist was circumcise.</L>
<L>&THORN;e seue&thorn;e reson, I telle con:<NOTE PLACE="foot">A. seuen&thorn;e.</NOTE></L>
<L>How seynt Steuene, godes mon,</L>
<L>&THORN;orw Heroudes and his false red</L>
<L N="540">On a friday he was stened to ded.</L>
<L>&THORN;e ei&yogh;te&thorn;e reson, I wol ou telle,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &yogh;e wollen a stounde dwelle:</L>
<L>Hou seynt Jon &thorn;e Baptist</L>
<L>Was martred for &thorn;e loue of Jhesu Crist</L>
<L N="545">In &thorn;e heruest after &thorn;e Assumpcion:</L>
<L>&THORN;at is I-cleped &thorn;e Decollacion.</L>
<L>&THORN;e ni&thorn;e reson is ful good:</L>
<L>Hou Jhesu Crist was don on rood</L>
<L>For &thorn;e gult of Adam and Eue;</L>
<L N="550">&THORN;e blod he bledde for vre bileue.</L>
<L>&THORN;enne is &thorn;e ten&thorn;e reson</L>
<L>Of vre ladi &thorn;e Assumpcion,</L>
<L>Vppon a friday &yogh;eld vp &thorn;e gost</L>
<L>To hire sone, &thorn;at heo louede most;</L>
<L N="555">&THORN;erfore in heuene &thorn;e virgyne is</L>
<L>Bodi and soule, forso&thorn;e I-wis;</L>
<L>Jhesu is kyng, and heo is qween&mdash;</L>
<L>I-blesset mote &thorn;e tyme ben!</L>
<L>&THORN;e elleue&thorn;e reson is ful trewe,</L>
<L N="560">Of &thorn;e apostel seint Andrewe,</L>
<L>Vppon a friday was don on crois</L>
<L>And seide, "Jhesu", wi&thorn; milde vois</L>
<L>And, "Jhesu", clepede, "In trinite,</L>
<L>&THORN;is passion I suffre for &thorn;e".</L>
<L N="565">&THORN;e twelf&thorn;e reson is ful good:</L>
<L>Hou seynt Eleyne fond &thorn;e rood</L>
<L>Vppon &thorn;e Mount of Caluarie&mdash;</L>
<L>Vppon &thorn;at crois Jhesu gon dye:</L>
<L>&THORN;er was &thorn;e holy crois I-founde,</L>
<L N="570">I-dolue deope vp of &thorn;e grounde.
<PB REF="00000486.tif" N="348"></L>
<L>&THORN;e &thorn;rettene&thorn;e reson, verreyment:</L>
<L>Vppon a friday god wol &yogh;iue Jugement</L>
<L>And deme men after heore dede &mdash;</L>
<L>He is not wys &thorn;at hit nul drede! &mdash;</L>
<L N="575">&THORN;e gode to Joye, &thorn;e wikked to pyne;</L>
<L>&THORN;e godnesse of Joye may no-mon fyne:</L>
<L>Heo schule haue Joye to heore seruise</L>
<L>&THORN;at seruen god in alle wyse.<NOTE PLACE="foot">573&mdash;8 = 347&mdash;52.</NOTE></L>
<L>For&thorn;i haue, mon, friday in mynde!</L>
<L N="580">&THORN;eos &thorn;rettene resons &thorn;erfore we fynde.</L>
<L>Friday is day of chaunce</L>
<L>Best to fasten and do penaunce.</L>
<L>&THORN;e seterday aftur, sikerly,</L>
<L>Is good to fasten for vre ladi:</L>
<L N="585">&THORN;orw hire we weoren al vnbounde<NOTE PLACE="foot">A. alle.</NOTE></L>
<L>And I-brou&yogh;t out of helle grounde;</L>
<L>Heo is ful of merci</L>
<L>To alle &thorn;at to hire wol clepen and cri,</L>
<L>To wasche and to make clene</L>
<L N="590">Alle &thorn;at euere in synne bene;</L>
<L>&THORN;e blessed ledere I-cleped heo is &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;e wey to heuene heo vs wis.</L>
<L>I-blesset mote &thorn;ei alle be<NOTE PLACE="foot">A. Iblessed.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at seruen hire wi&thorn; herte fre!"</L>
<L N="595">&THORN;e Emperour wi&thorn; wordes sterne</L>
<L>&THORN;us seide to &thorn;e child &yogh;erne:</L>
<L>"Child, he seide, I coniure &thorn;e</L>
<L>In &thorn;e nome of &thorn;e trinite,</L>
<L>&THORN;orw &thorn;e passion of Jhesu Crist,</L>
<L N="600">Of his de&thorn; and of his vprist,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou me &thorn;e so&thorn;e seye,</L>
<L>Ar &thorn;ou from me weende a-weye:</L>
<L>Whe&thorn;ur art &thorn;ou a wikked angel, or a good?"</L>
<L>&THORN;e child onswerde wi&thorn; milde mood:</L>
<L N="605">"I am he &thorn;at &thorn;e wrouhte,</L>
<L>And also &thorn;at &thorn;e deore abou&yogh;te".</L>
<L>&THORN;e child wente to heuene &thorn;o,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e stude &thorn;at he com fro.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Emperour kneled on &thorn;e grounde</L>
<L N="610">And &thorn;onked god &thorn;at blisful stounde.</L>
<L>He bicom good in alle wyse,</L>
<L>Lyuede &amp; di&yogh;ede in godes seruise. &mdash;</L>
<L>Seynt Jon &thorn;e Ewangelist,</L>
<L>Ede on eor&thorn;e wi&thorn; Jhesu Crist:</L>
<L N="615">&THORN;is tale he wrot in latin</L>
<L>In holi bok in parchemin,</L>
<L>Bad and heet almonkynde</L>
<L>Cristes passion hauen in mynde.<NOTE PLACE="foot">A. haue.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;us ende&thorn; &thorn;is spellyng</L>
<L N="620">Of Jhesu, vre heuene kyng.</L>
<L>God graunt vs alle his swete blessyng,</L>
<L>Schrift &amp; hosel, and good endyng!</L>
<TRAILER>Amen.
</TRAILER>

</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="16" TYPE="legend"><PB REF="00000487.tif" N="[349]">
<HEAD>16. De Principio Creationis mundi, eine Allegorie, von Grosthed. Aus Ms. Ashm. 61, fol. 78b.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>Der erste Theil des Gedichtes, &mdash; v. 222, handelt von der Sch&ouml;pfung und dem S&uuml;ndenfalle, definirt die S&uuml;nde und die Erl&ouml;sung; der zweite Theil, V. 223&mdash;440, ist eine Allegorie der Erl&ouml;sung: die 4 Cardinaltugenden Mercy, Sothnes, Rightfulnes und Pes, pl&auml;diren vor ihrem Vater, dem (himmlischen) K&ouml;nige, f&uuml;r und wider den s&uuml;ndigen Knecht (den Menschen), bis des K&ouml;nigs Sohn, Wisdom, die Schuld des|selben auf sich nimmt. Die lateinischen Anweisungen vor V. 295 und am Schluss, weisen auf einen Einfluss der dramatischen Moralit&auml;ten. Doch finden sich &auml;hnliche Allegorien schon weit fr&uuml;her; so enth&auml;lt die Homilie Sawles warde in Morris' Old Engl. Homilies of the twelfth and thirteenth cent. First series, Part II, London 1868, p. 245 eine &auml;hnliche Allegorie von den vier Cardinaltugenden in anderer Anwendung; eine &auml;hnliche Homilie de Initio Creature s. ib. p. 217. &mdash; Nach V. 11 ff. ist das Ge|dicht von Grosthed, dem bekannten Bischof von Lincoln, aus dem lateinischen ins franz&ouml;sische &uuml;bersetzt, dann in das englische &uuml;bertragen. Der franz. Text ist in Ms. Bodl. 4057 erhalten, u. d. T. Tractatus domini Roberti Grosete (in lingua) romana: de principio creationis mundi. Ms. Ashm. 61 ist eine sp&auml;tere Copie des englischen Textes, der aus keiner andern Hs. bekannt ist.</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Jhesu Cryst, heuyn kynge,</L>
<L>Be at my begyninge! &mdash;</L>
<L>There is no-man &thorn;at may &yogh;elpe,</L>
<L>Bot he hath nede of godys helpe.</L>
<L N="5">Fader &amp; sone and holy goste,</L>
<L>One god, of my&yogh;htys moste,</L>
<L>He helpe vs at oure nede &mdash;</L>
<L>Withoutene hym may we not spede. &mdash;</L>
<L>I sate and lokyd on a romance,</L>
<L N="10">Was made in &thorn;e lond of France:</L>
<L>Grostyd it made oute of dyuine</L>
<L>All in french out of latyne:</L>
<L>He saw all men hade not vertu</L>
<L>To know latyn, ebrew &amp; grew,</L>
<L N="15">The(re)fore in french he mad it &thorn;ere,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. thefore; diese Verschreibung begegnet &ouml;fter in Ms. Ashm.</NOTE></L>
<L>That men my&yogh;t wyte what it were.</L>
<L>&YOGH;it may not all men frenche vnderstond,</L>
<L>And namely men of Ingelond:</L>
<L>Therefore, soth as I &thorn;e tolde,</L>
<L N="20">Ryme on Inglych make he wolde,<NOTE PLACE="foot">l. I st. he?</NOTE></L>
<L>That men my&yogh;ht haue &thorn;er-of solace.</L>
<L>Now god &thorn;erto gyfe vs grace!</L>
</LG>
<P>De principio creacionis mundi.</P>
<LG>
<L>Now at &thorn;e fyrst begyninge</L>
<L>I schall tell of &thorn;e werlde makynge,</L>
<L N="25">And how it was fyrste gyuen to Adam</L>
<L>Of whome oure fyrst synne camme,</L>
<L>And also of paradys I-wys</L>
<L>That was full of werldys blys;</L>
<L>And of heuen &thorn;at is so hye,</L>
<L N="30">How it was lorne thorow folye,</L>
<L>How it come after to man-kynd,</L>
<L>As &yogh;e may afterwerd fynde.</L>
<L>With-in VI deys ry&yogh;ht</L>
<L>All &thorn;e werld we(s) I-dy&yogh;ht;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. we.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000488.tif" N="350"></L>
<L N="35">All-my&yogh;hty god &thorn;at is &thorn;e beste</L>
<L>The VII dey he gane reste.</L>
<L>There-of &yogh;e haue herd telle &mdash;</L>
<L>God kep vs fro &thorn;e peyne of helle! &mdash;</L>
<L>When god all-my&yogh;hty of nou&yogh;ht</L>
<L N="40">Heuyn and erth all hade wrought,</L>
<L>With all &thorn;e pourtynans small &amp; grete,</L>
<L>Lord, &thorn;at was feyre &amp; swete!</L>
<L>Now is &thorn;e sone clere &amp; ly&yogh;ht:</L>
<L>That tyme it was VII so bry&yogh;ht;</L>
<L N="45">The mone &thorn;at schynes no(w) by ny&yogh;ht,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. no st. now.</NOTE></L>
<L>Than it schone also bry&yogh;ht</L>
<L>As do &thorn;e sone now onne deye.<NOTE PLACE="foot">do st. dos.</NOTE></L>
<L>And sey there-of no-mane naye:</L>
<L>I tell &yogh;ow now sothlye,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. &yogh;ew st. &yogh;ow.</NOTE></L>
<L N="50">It witnes &thorn;e prophete Isaye,</L>
<L>And at hym I take wytnesse</L>
<L>That euery thynge more &amp; lesse</L>
<L>In erth, in ayere, water &amp; flode,</L>
<L>Seth Adam synned, was not so gode</L>
<L N="55">Als it was fyrste beforne,</L>
<L>Or Adam &amp; Eue wer forelorne.</L>
<L>Lorne was Adam &amp; all hys kynne</L>
<L>Fore &thorn;at ilke foule synne,</L>
<L>And all &thorn;er kynne, as I &yogh;ow telle,</L>
<L N="60">Euerychon &thorn;ei wente to helle.</L>
<L>Wronge was it not, bote skyll &mdash;</L>
<L>So euery man may (se) &thorn;at wyll.<NOTE PLACE="foot">se fehlt im Ms.</NOTE></L>
<L>Gode is to thinke <I>&thorn;er-on</I> ary&yogh;ht,</L>
<L>Forto loue god all-my&yogh;ht.</L>
<L></L>
</LG>
<P>De medio mundi et de fine.</P>
<LG>
<L N="65">When &thorn;at god &thorn;e werlde hade wrou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at there ne feyled nou&yogh;ht</L>
<L>Ne&thorn;er of more ne lesse,</L>
<L>Bestys &amp; treys, frute &amp; graffe,</L>
<L>Fowlys in &thorn;e eyere, fyffches in flode,</L>
<L N="70">Sterrys &amp; mone, sone, feyre &amp; gode:</L>
<L>At &thorn;e laste, after all thys,</L>
<L>Thane made he Adam I-wys</L>
<L>In &thorn;e veyll of Ebron of cley gente,</L>
<L>Lyke hym-selue veramente;</L>
<L N="75">After he holy trinyte</L>
<L>He made hys saule, I telle &thorn;e,</L>
<L>In &thorn;e body he dyde a lyuing goste,</L>
<L>Of all bestys powere gafe hym moste.</L>
<L>That was loue &amp; grete grace</L>
<L N="80">To make hym lyke hys awne face!</L>
<L>He made hym wytty &amp; wyse,</L>
<L>And led hym in-to paradyse.</L>
<L>Than thou&yogh;ht god all-my&yogh;hty &thorn;ere</L>
<L>He wold not he alone were.</L>
<L N="85">When &thorn;at god thus thou&yogh;t &amp; seyd,</L>
<L>Clepyd Adam, &thorn;er he was leyd,</L>
<L>Of hys lefte syde he toke a rybe-bone:</L>
<L>There-of he made Eue anone.</L>
<L>Eue before Adam he brou&yogh;ht,</L>
<L N="90">To wytte how he by hyre thou&yogh;ht.</L>
<L>Than seyd Adam, &amp; thou&yogh;t it gode:</L>
<L>"Thys is my flesch &amp; my blode".</L>
<L>In paradys in that stounde</L>
<L>There was wedloke fyrst I-fonde. &mdash;</L>
<L N="95">Fore &thorn;at skyll euery man of lyfe</L>
<L>Is holden to loue hys wyfe,</L>
<L>After &thorn;at sche is worthey;</L>
<L>That wyll god all-my&yogh;hty. &mdash;</L>
<L>God gaf &thorn;an Adam wytte &amp; skylle,</L>
<L N="100">Grete powere &amp; fre wylle:</L>
<L>Powere ouer all erthely thynge,</L>
<L>And gaff hym lyfe with-outen endynge;</L>
<L>Of paradys he made hym fre</L>
<L>Ouer all thynge, saue a tre.</L>
<L N="105">He gafe hym tyme to be &thorn;er-Ine,</L>
<L>Iff &thorn;at he hade done no synne,</L>
<L>With-outene hete, with-outen chele</L>
<L>There to a lyffyd in longe wele,<NOTE PLACE="foot">a = have,</NOTE></L>
<L>With-outene wo &amp; seknes,</L>
<L N="110">With mekyll Joy &amp; bry&yogh;htnes:</L>
<L>Seuyne so bry&yogh;ht he schuld hafe bene</L>
<L>As is &thorn;e sone &thorn;at now is sene;</L>
<L>Syche a blys god hade hym lente,</L>
<L>And at &thorn;e last to heuyne haue wente.</L>
<L N="115">Now was &thorn;er a feyre franches,</L>
<L>Was ordenyd to Adam &amp; all hys,</L>
<L>Sych an herytage euer-mo</L>
<L>To haue wonyd in with-outen wo! &mdash;</L>
<L>In paradys Adam had two lawys,</L>
<L N="120">As we telle in owre sawys:</L>
<L>He schulde haue kepyd in hys lyfe</L>
<L>The naturall &amp; &thorn;e posytyfe.
<PB REF="00000489.tif" N="351"></L>
<L>The naturall law was skyll &amp; ry&yogh;ht:</L>
<L>To be buxsome to god all-my&yogh;ht</L>
<L N="125">That dyde hym &thorn;at grete curtasy,</L>
<L>Of paradys gaue hym &thorn;e masterry.</L>
<L>A commandment onne hym he leyde</L>
<L>And off all hys frute, he seyde,</L>
<L>"Bot a tre I the forbyde.</L>
<L N="130">Ete &thorn;ou not &thorn;er-of, fore non nede!</L>
<L>Iff &thorn;ou ete &thorn;er-of, I &thorn;e sey,</L>
<L>Sone &thorn;er-after &thorn;ou schall dey.</L>
<L>Iff &thorn;ou my commaundment kepe, in pefe</L>
<L>Than &thorn;ou schall haue &thorn;at ilke grace:</L>
<L N="135">Paradyse &amp; bestys, water &amp; londe</L>
<L>Schall be obedyente to &thorn;i honde."</L>
<L>Off all &thorn;e blys of paradys</L>
<L>Adam hade seseyne I-wys.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. seseyne = seizin.</NOTE></L>
<L>Alas, sone it was ago</L>
<L N="140">All &thorn;e Joy &thorn;at he had tho!</L>
<L>Alas &thorn;erfore may we synge</L>
<L>And sore wepe &amp; handys wrynge!</L>
<L>Oure herytage we schuld haue,</L>
<L>And we hade not done &thorn;at skathe.</L>
<L N="145">The comandment we dyde nou&yogh;ht:</L>
<L>Therefore sore it was bou&yogh;ht,</L>
<L>And fore &thorn;at trespas &thorn;at was done</L>
<L>All we wer made thrall full sone.</L>
<L>The naturall &amp; &thorn;e posytyfe</L>
<L N="150">Adam breke fore lufe of hys wyfe;</L>
<L>Buxumere he was forto do</L>
<L>The dede &thorn;at hys wyfe bad hym do,</L>
<L>Than to god &thorn;at hym hade wrou&yogh;ht.</L>
<L>Alas, &thorn;erfore, what was hys thou&yogh;ht!</L>
<L N="155">Than was he oute &amp; hade lorne</L>
<L>The sesyn &thorn;at he hade beforne;</L>
<L>Hys herytage was hym benome,</L>
<L>And all theme &thorn;at after hym comme,</L>
<L>Oute of Joy in-to grete care</L>
<L N="160">Hys-felue &amp; hys kyne to fare;</L>
<L>With swynke &amp; suete was he bonde &mdash;</L>
<L>Where schall any hele be fonde?</L>
<L>Alas &thorn;at synne, it was so stronge!</L>
<L>Fore amonge all thinge it spronge:</L>
<L N="165">Both &thorn;e sterres, sone, &amp; mone</L>
<L>Off &thorn;at synne &thorn;ei hade to done;</L>
<L>Foulys in &thorn;e eyere, bestys in londe,</L>
<L>All &thorn;ei had &thorn;er-of a onde,</L>
<L>Fysschys, erbys, frute and tre,</L>
<L N="170">All &thorn;e wers forto be;</L>
<L>Euery thynge, both more &amp; les,</L>
<L>Fore &thorn;at synne lest there godnes. &mdash;</L>
<L>Adam fore hys defaute I-wys</L>
<L>Lost hys herytage, &amp; all hys;</L>
<L N="175">Fore synne(e) is non o&thorn;er thynge</L>
<L>Before defaute of wele doynge.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. Bo for st. before od. st. bot?</NOTE></L>
<L>Fore defaute he leste &thorn;e Joys suete,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at was skyll: so do mene &yogh;ete:</L>
<L>Fore defaute euery wyght</L>
<L N="180">Hys herytage may lese ry&yogh;ht;</L>
<L>At kyngys courte, in euery londe,</L>
<L>&YOGH;it men haue sych lawys fonde.</L>
<L>Fore defaute Adam les</L>
<L>That he my&yogh;ht haue leuyd in pes.</L>
<L N="185">Alas, &thorn;at was grete pyte!</L>
<L>Now be we thrall &thorn;at are wer fre. &mdash;</L>
<L>Thrall he is &thorn;at to hym longys</L>
<L>What seruys he vnderfongys.<NOTE PLACE="foot">l. whas st. what?</NOTE></L>
<L>He &thorn;at is so thrall become,</L>
<L N="190">Hys powere is hym benome.</L>
<L>When he seruys in seruage,</L>
<L>He hade no franches of herytage:<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. hade st. has.</NOTE></L>
<L>Than when he is all thrall become,</L>
<L>His fre herytage is hym benome.</L>
<L N="195">He may not pleyne in non wys</L>
<L>With whome he is in sych seruys:</L>
<L>He ne schuld no-thynge be herde,</L>
<L>His wordys be all in sperd(!).<NOTE PLACE="foot">l. misferd?</NOTE></L>
<L>His herytage if he wyll wynne,</L>
<L N="200">He behouys to do ano&thorn;er thynge:</L>
<L>He muste seke if he may fynd</L>
<L>A man &thorn;at borne is of fre kynd,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at he be of ry&yogh;ht lynage,</L>
<L>Forto clame his herytage,</L>
<L N="205">And &thorn;at he may well &amp; wele canne,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at he be a gode fre mane,</L>
<L>That he not of &thorn;at appull ete</L>
<L>That Adame thou&yogh;t fyrst so suete.</L>
<L>He behoueth to be with-outyne synne</L>
<L N="210">And all oure lawys hym with-Ine:<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. law ys.</NOTE></L>
<L>The II lawys of paradys sykerly,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at of &thorn;e mounte of Synay
<PB REF="00000490.tif" N="352"></L>
<L>That was gyuen to Moyses,</L>
<L>That he held neuer with-outene les</L>
<L N="215">In whom was se oure wekyd wrynke.</L>
<L>Off sych a mane who my&yogh;ht thinke</L>
<L>That my&yogh;ht be with-outen synne,</L>
<L>Hys herytage &thorn;us to wynne?<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. to st. my&yogh;ht he?</NOTE></L>
<L>He(r)on schall my mater duelle,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. he st. her.</NOTE></L>
<L N="220">Fore a tale I wyll &yogh;ou telle</L>
<L>That acordys to sych a mane.</L>
<L>Now wyll I tell &yogh;ou, if I canne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>IT was a kynge nobull &amp; riche,</L>
<L>That had a sone &thorn;at was hym lyche:</L>
<L N="225">Off wytte &amp; powere lyke hym he was,</L>
<L>Like &thorn;e fader, in all case.</L>
<L>That &thorn;e fader wyst, &thorn;e sone thou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>All thorow &thorn;e sone &thorn;e fader wrou&yogh;t:</L>
<L>What &thorn;e fader wold haue wrou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="230">The sone it dyde, fore he knew his thought;</L>
<L>In his kyndome all nedys</L>
<L>Wer fullfylled thorow hys dedys.</L>
<L>Foure dou&yogh;teres hade &thorn;e kynge,</L>
<L>And euerych of &thorn;em hade some-thynge</L>
<L N="235">Off hys wyte and hys powere,</L>
<L>Iche-one as &thorn;ei hade mystere;</L>
<L>And neuer-&thorn;e-les all was &thorn;e kyngys</L>
<L>The IIII dou&yogh;tures with all &thorn;er thyngys:</L>
<L>Fore with-outen &thorn;em euery dele</L>
<L N="240">My&yogh;ht he not reule hys kyngdome wele.</L>
<L>Feyre names &thorn;ei had euery-chone,</L>
<L>I schall &thorn;em telle ry&yogh;ht anone:</L>
<L>The fyrst dou&yogh;ter hyght Mersy &mdash;</L>
<L>That is a feyre name, sykerly!</L>
<L N="245">The secunde douter hyght Sothnes,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e thyrd Ryghtfullnes,</L>
<L>The IIII dou&yogh;ter hyght Pese &mdash;</L>
<L>Feyre names, with-outene lese!</L>
<L>With-oute &thorn;e foure &thorn;at I named</L>
<L N="250">May no-thinge ryght be demed. &mdash;</L>
<L>Thys ryche kynge hade a mane &mdash;</L>
<L>Thorow whome mych wreche begane, &mdash;</L>
<L>And hym louyd wele &thorn;e kynge</L>
<L>And made hym mayster of mych thynge.</L>
<L N="255">Bot a comandment he hym toke</L>
<L>And seyd: when he &thorn;at foresoke,</L>
<L>He schuld to turment, vnderstond &thorn;is,</L>
<L>Oute of hys courte, &amp; all hys.</L>
<L>Thys seruant &yogh;ede forth with &thorn;at,</L>
<L N="260">Hys commandment sone he brake.</L>
<L>Iugement on hym was leyd</L>
<L>After &thorn;at &thorn;e kynge hade seyd;</L>
<L>To IIII turmentowres he was take,</L>
<L>Hys Jugement on hym to make.</L>
<L N="265">The turmentowres, as bad &thorn;e kynge,</L>
<L>They schuld hym do an euyll dubynge:</L>
<L>The one schuld hym depriuene faste,</L>
<L>The o&thorn;er hym fle whyll hys lyfe laste,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. sle st. fle.</NOTE></L>
<L>The o&thorn;er hym strangyll ryght also,</L>
<L N="270">The o&thorn;er hym fetyre. so dyde &thorn;ei tho.</L>
<L>Mersy, &thorn;e dou&yogh;ter, all &thorn;is sey &amp; herd<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. ley st. sey.</NOTE></L>
<L>How he was in presone sperd.</L>
<L>To hyre fader sche come anone</L>
<L>And askyd hym &mdash; what forto done?</L>
<L N="275">"Thy dou&yogh;ter, fader, &thorn;ou wote I ame,</L>
<L>Mersy I hyght, of &thorn;e I camme,</L>
<L>Off &thorn;i &yogh;ifte I vnderstode</L>
<L>To haue mersy with myld mode.</L>
<L>Therefore, fader, I pray &thorn;e here</L>
<L N="280">That &thorn;ou herkyne my prayere:</L>
<L>Haue mersy of &thorn;at ilke wyght</L>
<L>That in presone is euyll dyght!</L>
<L>Hys enmyse dyd to hym trespas,</L>
<L>Fader, of hym haue mersy &amp; grace!</L>
<L N="285">Hys enmyse fore envye</L>
<L>They dyde hym &thorn;at trecherye.</L>
<L>Do now, fader, &thorn;at I craue,</L>
<L>&YOGH;iff &thorn;ou wyll me &thorn;i dou&yogh;ter haue!</L>
<L>Mersy I ame: yff &thorn;ou wyll me,</L>
<L N="290">Thou must haue mersy &amp; pyte.</L>
<L>With gode skyll he muste be sauyd,</L>
<L>Fore I, &thorn;e dou&yogh;ter, haue &thorn;e crauyd.<NOTE PLACE="foot">M. &thorn;e st. &thorn;i.</NOTE></L>
<L>Fore hym mersy schall be my crye,</L>
<L>Whyll &thorn;at I may fynde mersy." &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">whyll = till.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<P>Misericordia et veritas obuiauerunt sibi.</P>
<LG>
<L N="295">Sothnes, hyre syster, &thorn;is pleynt herd.</L>
<L>Sone sche come and ansuerd:</L>
<L>"Fader, what may &thorn;is pleynte be</L>
<L>That Mersy, my syster, makys to &thorn;e?
<PB REF="00000491.tif" N="353"></L>
<L>Wold sche fore hyre myld herte</L>
<L N="300">Brynge &thorn;is prisonere owte of smerte?</L>
<L>Sche wolde he wer fro peyne I-brou&yogh;ht,</L>
<L>Bot I, Sothnes, wyll it nou&yogh;ht.</L>
<L>A trew thynge, fader, I tell &thorn;e:</L>
<L>&YOGH;iff all thynge my&yogh;ht sauyd be</L>
<L N="305">Fore whome my syster wyll praye,</L>
<L>Schall none of &thorn;e stond aye.</L>
<L>I ame Sothnes, herkens to me!</L>
<L>And &thorn;at name I hade of &thorn;e;</L>
<L>Men callys me kynge in euery kythe;</L>
<L N="310">And &yogh;iff Sothnes wones &thorn;e wyth,</L>
<L>Mersy of hym may &thorn;ou haue none,</L>
<L>Bot I, Sothnes, fro &thorn;e gone.</L>
<L>Pyte off hym may none be wroght,</L>
<L>Fore hym-selue wyll it nou&yogh;ht.</L>
<L N="315">Kynge off Sothnes, do than ryght</L>
<L>And late avenge &thorn;e of &thorn;at wyght!"</L>
<L>The syster, Ryght, &thorn;eder gane gone,</L>
<L>Thys wordys sche herd euerychone.</L>
<L>When sche &thorn;e pleynte onderstode,</L>
<L N="320">Sche ansuerd with mylde mode:</L>
<L>"Fader, my name is callyd Ryght,</L>
<L>That name I hade of thy myght.</L>
<L>Seth I ame Ryght &amp; &thorn;ou hast me,</L>
<L>As Soth it seys, it muste be,</L>
<L N="325">Fore Ryght wyll in none wyse</L>
<L>That seruante were in vnyse.</L>
<L>That Soth hath seyd, I, Ry&yogh;ht, it wyll,</L>
<L>Fore it is resone &amp; skyll.</L>
<L>Late &thorn;ou hym in preso(n) be,</L>
<L N="330">Tyll &thorn;ou hym Juge before &thorn;e!</L>
<L>Fore Ryght wyll haue all onder honde,</L>
<L>That he Soth do onderstond;</L>
<L>Ryght gyffes Iche man be Sothe his rede,</L>
<L>Be it to gode, be it to quede.</L>
<L N="335">Whyll &thorn;at he thyne hest held,</L>
<L>We wer with hym with spere &amp; scheld,</L>
<L>Both Mersy, Soth, &amp; Ryght,</L>
<L>And Pese, my syster, with all oure my&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Vs all IIII he hath foresake:</L>
<L N="340">Right wyll &thorn;erfore vengeans take."</L>
<L>Non gode word was &thorn;er speke,</L>
<L>When &thorn;at Mersy was oute steke. &mdash;</L>
<L>Than was &thorn;at wrech with peynes schente,</L>
<L>Hys gode benome, hys clothes rente;</L>
<L N="345">In peyne was he many-folde,</L>
<L>As Soth &amp; Ryght bothe it wolde.</L>
<L>And also &thorn;at of hym come,</L>
<L>All &thorn;ei had &thorn;e same d&omacr;me.</L>
<L>Soth &amp; Ryght with-outen les</L>
<L N="350">Wente, with-oute Mersy and Pes,</L>
<L>And, be contre as &thorn;ei wend,</L>
<L>All &thorn;at wreches kynde &thorn;ei schent;</L>
<L>So fast &thorn;ei gane &thorn;em done dryue,</L>
<L>That &thorn;ei left neuer one of lyue.</L>
<L N="355">A flode ouer all dyde go,</L>
<L>VIII &thorn;at left of lyue &amp; nomo:<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. &thorn;at st. &thorn;er?</NOTE></L>
<L>That was Noe &amp; his thre sones &mdash;</L>
<L>There wer no mo left in no wonys &mdash;</L>
<L>In Noys schype with &thorn;er wyues,</L>
<L N="360">Where-in &thorn;ei sauyd &thorn;er lyues.</L>
<L>That was &thorn;an a reufull syght!</L>
<L>And &yogh;it it was bote soth &amp; ry&yogh;ht. &mdash;</L>
<L>The syster Pes my&yogh;ht no-where be,</L>
<L>Sche was sent oute contre,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. out st. out of.</NOTE></L>
<L N="365">Fore sche may fore no thynge</L>
<L>Be amonge wreth &amp; werrynge.</L>
<L>Than was Pes in mych care,</L>
<L>When sche saw &thorn;e werld &thorn;us fare.</L>
<L>To hyre fader hyre wey sche leyd</L>
<L N="370">And come to hym sone and seyd:</L>
<L>"Fader, I ame &thorn;i dou&yogh;ter Pes,</L>
<L>I au&yogh;ht be at thy dese;</L>
<L>Thou arte kynge of Pes so dere:</L>
<L>Me, fader, &thorn;an must &thorn;ou here.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. my st. me.</NOTE></L>
<L N="375">My two systeres, Soth &amp; Ryght,</L>
<L>With Pes &amp; Mersy &thorn;ei hold fyght,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. syght st. fyght, od. slyght?</NOTE></L>
<L>All with-out oure asente</L>
<L>They done all &thorn;er Jugemente.</L>
<L>I, Pese, &amp; my syster Mersy bothe</L>
<L N="380">We come no(t) heder consell to noye,</L>
<L>And we foure aw be all at one.</L>
<L>Thys thynge, fader, may not &thorn;us gone,</L>
<L>I, Pes, wyll abyde with the,</L>
<L>Tyll all pese amonge &thorn;em be.</L>
<L N="385">All godnes thorow pes to end is brou&yogh;t;</L>
<L>Who-so hath pes, he feylys nou&yogh;ht;</L>
<L>With-outen pes is wro&yogh;ht no thynge,</L>
<L>Be it neuer so grete doynge.
<PB REF="00000492.tif" N="354"></L>
<L>Who-so euer aboute wyll wende,</L>
<L N="390">Pese schall folow at &thorn;e ende.</L>
<L>Soth &amp; Ryght it is &thorn;er fe</L>
<L>Forto kepe &thorn;e name of me,</L>
<L>Fore &thorn;ei haue non o&thorn;er nede</L>
<L>Bot pes to kepe in euery lede.</L>
<L N="395">Why schall I thane be foresake,</L>
<L>When &thorn;ou pes fore me gane take?</L>
<L>Bot I haue Mersy, my syster, with me:</L>
<L>I may not els sauyd be.</L>
<L>Seth &thorn;ou arte kynge of Pes in lond,</L>
<L N="400">My word aw to be vnderstonde.</L>
<L>Off (vs) foure systeres a resyne clere<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. &thorn;is st. vs.</NOTE></L>
<L>Now ry&yogh;ht wyll I schew here:</L>
<L>Thorow vs IIII schall all be wrou&yogh;t</L>
<L>In vnyte, is all my thou&yogh;t;</L>
<L N="405">All we IIII verament</L>
<L>Schall make one Jugement.</L>
<L>Therefore Jugement au&yogh;ht be nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Tyll we IIII at one be brou&yogh;t;</L>
<L>All we behouyth to-geder take,</L>
<L N="410">Ryght Jugement forto make.</L>
<L>Thys seruant onne non wyse</L>
<L>May be leuyd in &thorn;at vnyse.</L>
<L>With-outene my syster Mersy &amp; me</L>
<L>Jugement may non gyuen be;</L>
<L N="415">Mersy, my syster, cryes euer-mo</L>
<L>Mersy fore hym &thorn;at is in wo:</L>
<L>Therefore I, Pes, at &thorn;e endes</L>
<L>Schall fond to make &thorn;em frendys." &mdash;</L>
<L>The kyngys sone, both wyse &amp; queynte,</L>
<L N="420">Herd &thorn;e IIII systeres pleynte.</L>
<L>With-outen hym on none wyse</L>
<L>Acord may not ry&yogh;ht aryse.</L>
<L>"Fader, he seyd, thyne I ame,</L>
<L>Off &thorn;e, fader, fyrst I come,</L>
<L N="425">Wysdome, fader, my name it is</L>
<L>Fore whom was made &thorn;is werldys blys;</L>
<L>Thou &amp; I, fader, all one we be</L>
<L>In wytte &amp; my&yogh;ht &amp; dygnyte.</L>
<L>Off &thorn;is contake, &thorn;at I here,</L>
<L N="430">Mersy hath told me resone clere:</L>
<L>Where-of, fader, I haue pyte</L>
<L>That seruant in peyne schall so be.</L>
<L>Thy seruante clothinge take I wyll,</L>
<L>Both with sothnes &amp; with skyll</L>
<L N="435">That Jugement I wyll onderfonge</L>
<L>And all &thorn;at euer to ry&yogh;ht wyll longe.</L>
<L>I schall cry pes with-outen mys</L>
<L>And Ry&yogh;ht &amp; Pese I schall do kys.</L>
<L>All contake leyd schall be,</L>
<L N="440">My wyll it is I schall saue &thorn;e."</L>
<L>Justicia &amp; pax osculate sunt.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="17" TYPE="legend"><PB REF="00000493.tif" N="[355]">
<HEAD>17. The stasyons of Jerusalem. (Wallfahrt nach Jerusalem). Aus Ms. Ashm. 61, fol. 128.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>Das Gedicht schildert eine jener Pilgerfahrten, welche im 14. u. 15. Jahrh. so h&auml;ufig von F&uuml;rsten, Edlen und reichen B&uuml;rgern, in gr&ouml;sseren oder kleineren Z&uuml;gen, nach dem h. Lande unternommen wurden. Die Seereise begann von Venedig aus, zu Ostern oder S. Johanni, auf grossen Galeeren unter Leitung eines venetianischen Patrons, der die Pilger auch im h. Lande selbst begleitete und ihre Verhandlungen mit den muhamedanischen Beh&ouml;rden f&uuml;hrte; sie ging die H&auml;fen Venedigs entlang: Corfu, Modon auf Morea, Candia, Rhodus, Cypern, und endete in Joppe, dem Hafen Jerusalems. Hier landete man unter feierlichem Gesange des Te deum, k&uuml;sste den h. Boden und schm&uuml;ckte sich mit den Strandmuscheln, dem Attribute des Pilgers. Von da ritt man, unter dem Geleit von Muhamedanern, auf Eseln nach Jerusalem, welches man in h&ouml;chster Andacht, mit einem Te deum betrat. Man herbergte hier in der Regel in dem ber&uuml;hmten Franziskanerkloster auf Sion<NOTE PLACE="foot">Andere stiegen im Johanniterhospiz, oder bei einem der venetianischen oder genuesischen Consuln ab.</NOTE>, dessen Guardian den Pilgern meist schon bis Rama entgegenkam. Diese M&ouml;nche waren die Wegweiser der Pilger an den h. St&auml;tten, in seit langer Zeit hergebrachter Ordnung; sie hatten die Pil|gerfahrten wieder in Fluss gebracht, die Sagen und Legenden gesammelt und lokalisirt, auch wohl in B&uuml;chlein verzeichnet, die sie den Pilgern mitgaben &mdash; so erkl&auml;rt sich die genaue Uebereinstimmung aller Reisebeschreibungen dieser Art. Man besuchte nun die h. St&auml;tten, soweit der Besuch von den Herren des Landes (seit 1382 den &auml;gyp|tischen Mameluken, seit 1517 den T&uuml;rken) gestattet wurde: die Grabeskirche (in unserm Ged. zuerst, in der Regel erst am Schlusse der Wanderung), wo man der Mitternachtsmesse beiwohnte; die h. St&auml;tten an der via dolorosa, dann rechtsherum im Thale Josaphat und Siloe (&ouml;stlich) und auf dem Sionsberge (s&uuml;dlich). An den folg. Tagen besuchte man Bethlehem (2 deutsche Meilen von Jerusalem), und auf einem Umwege zur&uuml;ckkehrend die h. St&auml;tten im Gebirge Juda; dann den Jordan, worin man, meist in voller Kleidung, badete an der Stelle der Taufe Christi, das todte Meer, und auf dem R&uuml;ckwege den Berg der 40 t&auml;gigen Fasten (Quarentana) und Bethanien. Selten besuchte man noch den Berg Sinai mit seinem ber&uuml;hmten Katharinenkloster. &mdash; Reisebeschreibungen dieser Art haben sich mehrere erhalten, meist genau &uuml;berein|stimmend in der Ordnung und Beschreibung der h. St&auml;tten, Legenden und Reliquien; so von deutschen die des Landgrafen Wilhelm des Tapfern von Th&uuml;ringen i. J. 1461, ed. von J. G. Kohl Bremen 1868, die der B&uuml;rger Hans Tucher von N&uuml;rnberg i. J. 1478 und Helfrich von Leipzig i. J. 1565, besonders des Dominikaners Felix Faber aus Ulm Evagatorium in terrae sanctae peregrinationem (aus d. J. 1480 u. 83) ed. von C. D. Hassler 1843 u. 49 (in d. Biblioth. des litter. Vereins von Stuttgart, vol. I, II, u. III), ferner das "Reissbuch des h. Landes" Frankfurt 1609. &mdash; Von neueren H&uuml;lfsmitteln vgl. Ersch u. Gruber's Encycl. s. v. Jerusalem, Robinson "Pal&auml;stina" Halle 1841, Tobler "Denkw&uuml;rdigkeiten aus Jerusalem" S. Gallen 1853, Tobler "Die Siloahquelle und der Oelberg" S. Gallen 1852, Geisheim "Die Hohenzollern am h. Grabe zu Jeru|salem" Berlin 1858, Sepp "Jerusalem und das h. Land" Schaffhausen 1863, Vogu&eacute; "le temple de J&eacute;rusalem" Paris 1864 u. a.</P><P>Die einzige Hs. des engl. Gedichts, Ashm. 61, ist vielfach verderbt und fehler|haft; insbesondere ist ein ganzer Passus, v. 809&mdash;840, mit dem Besuche Bethaniens und den Schlussworten des Dichters, vom Schreiber unrichtig hinter V. 736 (nach dem Besuche Bethlehems) versetzt &mdash; ich habe diese Stelle an dem richtigen Orte wieder eingef&uuml;gt. Auch sonst scheint der urspr&uuml;ngl. Text vielfach ver&auml;ndert; auff&auml;llig ist jedenfalls der Wechsel von Stropfen (im Anfange u. am Ende u. v. 271&mdash;4) und Reim|paaren. Das Alter des Gedichts ist schwer zu bestimmen. Ein &auml;hnliches Gedicht ist "the stacions of Rome" in Reimpaaren, aus Ms. Vernon fol. 314 (c. 1370) ed. v. Furnivall f&uuml;r die Early Engl. Text Soc. 1867, und aus Mss. Cott. Calig. A II u. Lamb. 306 ed. v. Furnivall in Political, religious and love poems pp. 113&mdash;44 f&uuml;r die E. E. T. S. 1866.</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<PB REF="00000494.tif" N="356">
<L>God that schupe both heuen &amp; helle,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e, lord, I make my mone,</L>
<L>And gyue me grace &thorn;e sothe to telle</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e pylgrymeage &thorn;at I haue gone!</L>
<L N="5">I toke my leue at Venys to&umacr;ne,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. take.</NOTE></L>
<L>And bade felous fore me praye, &mdash;</L>
<L>Fore it is a cyte of grete reno&umacr;ne.<NOTE PLACE="foot">ist interpolirt.</NOTE></L>
<L>And to Jerusaleme I toke &thorn;e wey.</L>
<L>Bot of all cytes &thorn;at I haue seyne,</L>
<L N="10">Forto rekyne euerychone,</L>
<L>Than may Venys be a (quene),<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. kyng st. quene.</NOTE></L>
<L>That stondys in &thorn;e greke se alone.</L>
<L>It is so rownd, ryche &amp; stoute:</L>
<L>Off enmys there them not drede.<NOTE PLACE="foot">there = &thorn;arf, &thorn;ar.</NOTE></L>
<L N="15">Fore seyntys lyes in &thorn;e towne aboute &mdash;</L>
<L>Who-so wyll seke &thorn;em, he schall haue mede.</L>
<L>Seynt Marke &amp; seynte Nycholas,</L>
<L>Thes two seyntys &thorn;ei lyne in sy&yogh;ht;</L>
<L>Seynte Elyne, &thorn;at fonde &thorn;e cros,</L>
<L N="20">And seynt Jeorge, oure lady kny&yogh;ht,</L>
<L>Amonge them berys grete voys</L>
<L>And lyes in gold &amp; syluer wele dy&yogh;ht.</L>
<L>Seynte Paule &thorn;e fyrst hermyte &thorn;at was,</L>
<L>And seynte Symeone Justus &thorn;at hy&yogh;ht,</L>
<L N="25">And &thorn;e fader of seynt Johne baptyst</L>
<L>Lyes thens a lytell &thorn;er-fro.</L>
<L>And seynt Lucy, &thorn;at vergyne blyste,</L>
<L>&THORN;at stedfast was in all here wo,</L>
<L>And a thousand Innocentys mene may se,</L>
<L N="30">Ly&yogh;et &thorn;er closyd in &thorn;at towne;</L>
<L>Seynte Cristofe lege &amp; hys the &mdash;</L>
<L>At ons I may not rekyne ne soune &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. sone = soune od. somne?</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot">Nach 32 scheint ein Verspaar zu fehlen.</NOTE></L>
<L>Fore &thorn;er is &thorn;e whyrlbone of hys kne</L>
<L>And his toth closyd in crystall to se.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Nach dem Reisebuche des Land|grafen Wilhem liegt Simeon in Zara, die Innocentes in Murano bei Venedig.</NOTE></L>
<L N="35">Twyse in &thorn;e &yogh;ere, who &thorn;edure come</L>
<L>To vyset &thorn;is corseyntys in &thorn;at plas,</L>
<L>He schall haue plene remyssyone,</L>
<L>Als wele as In &thorn;e &yogh;ere of grace.</L>
<L>Than passe(we) in-to &thorn;e Iles of &thorn;e se:<NOTE PLACE="foot">we fehlt.</NOTE></L>
<L N="40">Curfe, Modyne, &amp; Candy.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Modyne = Modon auf Morea (das alte Methone).</NOTE></L>
<L>Some of &thorn;e Iles, with-outene doute<NOTE PLACE="foot">Candia hat nach Landgr. Wilhelm 700 "welsche Meilen" im Umfang.</NOTE></L>
<L>Be VII C. myle abowte,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. abowte to sey; to sey ist zu tilgen.</NOTE></L>
<L>And all langys to Venys towne,</L>
<L>That is a cyte of grete renowne.</L>
<L N="45">In &thorn;e Ile of Rodys as we gan gone,</L>
<L>We founde relykes many one:</L>
<L>A crosse, made of &thorn;e basyne fuete</L>
<L>That oure lord wessch in hys postyllus fete;</L>
<L>And &thorn;er &thorn;e plate we se</L>
<L N="50">Where-in he made hys mande;</L>
<L>And a thorne of &thorn;e crowne</L>
<L>That styked in hys hede aboune,</L>
<L>That blomys euery godefrydey &mdash;</L>
<L>A feyr merakyll it is to sey!</L>
<L N="55">And &thorn;er is seynt Loy &amp; Blasy,</L>
<L>And o&thorn;er, mo &thorn;an twenty;</L>
<L>There is &thorn;e arme &amp; hond of seynt Ca|teryne,</L>
<L>That blyssyd holy vergyne,</L>
<L>And euer-more, who-so &thorn;eder come,
<PB REF="00000495.tif" N="357"></L>
<L N="60">A thousand &yogh;eres of pardone.</L>
<L>And in Sypres as we schuld go,</L>
<L>We fond relykys one or two:</L>
<L>The cros of &thorn;e gode thefe<NOTE PLACE="foot">Dieses Kreuz des Sch&auml;chers ist naeh d. Landgr. Wilh. in einem Kloster auf e&iuml;nem Berge unweit Paphos.</NOTE></L>
<L>That cryed mersy &amp; found gode preue.</L>
<L N="65">We saw a chapelle onne a hylle;</L>
<L>Bot we my&yogh;ht not come &thorn;ertylle.</L>
<L>Be&yogh;ond &thorn;at in a coste</L>
<L>A lytell besyde is Famagoste;</L>
<L>We fond a chapell beforne,</L>
<L N="70">Where seynte Kateryne was borne;</L>
<L>There is many &yogh;eres of pardone</L>
<L>Fore euery man &thorn;at &thorn;eder wyll come.</L>
<L>Thane came we to a-no&thorn;er place,</L>
<L>There &thorn;at &thorn;e whalle sualowyde Jonas</L>
<L N="75">And bare hym in-to Ninyue &mdash;</L>
<L>A feyre merakyll it ys to se!</L>
<L>Than come we to porte J&aacute;ffe &mdash;</L>
<L>I schall &yogh;ow telle who &thorn;at name &yogh;affe:</L>
<L>Japhet, &thorn;at was Noeys sone,</L>
<L N="80">Was &thorn;er fyrst, or &thorn;at was begonne;</L>
<L>And when he leyd &thorn;e fyrst stone,</L>
<L>He callyd it Jaffe after hys name.</L>
<L>This is &thorn;e breyd of &thorn;e grekys se:</L>
<L>Twenty hundreth myle &amp; thre. &mdash;</L>
<L N="85">Than passyd we to &thorn;at same stede</L>
<L>There seynte Johne was quyke &amp; dede.</L>
<L>The nexte thinge after, as I &yogh;ow telle,</L>
<L>Is &thorn;e graue of Samuelle,</L>
<L>That is besyde &thorn;e castell of Emaus</L>
<L N="90">Theere Jhesu spake to Cleophas.</L>
<L>Fyrst Joy after &thorn;at to vs come</L>
<L>When we sey &thorn;e wawle of Jerusaleme.</L>
<L>And &thorn;e fyrst fote &thorn;at we sette &thorn;er-Ine</L>
<L>We were deliuerde of all oure synne</L>
<L N="95">And reseyued indulgens "a pena &amp; culpa",</L>
<L>And at o&thorn;er many places mo also.</L>
<L>And after &thorn;is with gode intente</L>
<L>To &thorn;e hospytall sone we wente.<NOTE PLACE="foot">the hospitall ist das Franziskanerkloster auf Sion, die Herberge der Pilger.</NOTE></L>
<L>And onne &thorn;e morne, when it was dey,</L>
<L N="100">To &thorn;e temple we wente oure wey.<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e temple die Grabeskirche. Der Besuch ders. und die Anh&ouml;rung der Mitter|nachtsmesse bildete in der Regel den Schluss, nicht, wie hier, den Anfang der Wanderung.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;er lyes &thorn;e same stone</L>
<L>That oure lorde restyd hym onne;</L>
<L>The Jues dyde hym so mekyll wo:</L>
<L>The manhed my&yogh;ht no ferthere go.</L>
<L N="105">And after &thorn;is a &yogh;arysene come</L>
<L>And callyd vs In, be a treyne;</L>
<L>When he hade done, he wente hys weye</L>
<L>And lokyd &thorn;e dore with a keye.</L>
<L>Now schall &yogh;e here &thorn;e begyninge,</L>
<L N="110">How we worschypped oure heuen kynge.</L>
<L>The warden reysede a crosse full hye</L>
<L>And clerkys songe &thorn;e letany;</L>
<L>And lewde men &thorn;an &thorn;er ey&yogh;ene wepe,</L>
<L>That teres fell vndere &thorn;er fete,</L>
<L N="115">And thankyde god with all &thorn;er my&yogh;ht</L>
<L>That gaffe them grace to se &thorn;at syght.</L>
<L>Than askyd we a bo&umacr;ne with-all:</L>
<L>That we schuld neuer in synne falle.</L>
<L>And after &thorn;at with gode entente</L>
<L N="120">To &thorn;e sepulcour forth we wente;</L>
<L>When we hade offerd &amp; kyssed &thorn;e stone,</L>
<L>All oure feloys dyde &thorn;e same.</L>
<L>Be&yogh;ond &thorn;at we fond a pleyne</L>
<L>There Jhesu mette with Mary Maude|leyne,</L>
<L N="125">And &thorn;er sche wolde haue kyssed his fete,</L>
<L>When he bakwerd fro hyr &yogh;ede</L>
<L>And sche persyde onne hym so ofte,</L>
<L>And (he) seyd: "Mary, touche me nou&yogh;ht."</L>
<L>Behynd &thorn;at is a pylere</L>
<L N="130">Where-to was bond hys body bare;</L>
<L>That stondys in a chapell suete,</L>
<L>There oure lady stode &amp; wepe.</L>
<L>And &thorn;us we passyd bye</L>
<L>To &thorn;e mydys of &thorn;e mundye:<NOTE PLACE="foot">Die "Mitte der Welt" war durch einen Stein dargestellt; vgl. 385.</NOTE></L>
<L N="135">There he wrote with-outene doute</L>
<L>The mydys of &thorn;e werld ronde aboute.</L>
<L>Be&yogh;ond &thorn;at as we schuld gone,</L>
<L>We fond &thorn;e holys in &thorn;e stone</L>
<L>There-in &thorn;ei Joddyd hym onne &thorn;e gronde<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. Joddyd st. joggyd?</NOTE></L>
<L N="140">And gafe hym many a blody wonde.</L>
<L>And &thorn;er &thorn;ei spolyd hym of hys clothys</L>
<L>And swore hys deth with grete othes,
<PB REF="00000496.tif" N="358"></L>
<L>And &thorn;er at &thorn;e dyfe &thorn;ei gane pleye</L>
<L>Who schuld bere hys clothys aweye.</L>
<L N="145">And whene he sufferd all &thorn;is scorne,</L>
<L>On hys hede &thorn;ei sete a crone of thorne</L>
<L>And after askyd hym of &thorn;at thinge</L>
<L>Iff &thorn;at he were Jues kynge.</L>
<L>Behynd &thorn;at is a pylere also</L>
<L N="150">There &thorn;at he sufferd mekyll wo:</L>
<L>They bonde hys hondys &amp; his fete</L>
<L>And rollyd hys body in &thorn;e strete,</L>
<L>That erth &amp; grauell onne &thorn;e grounde</L>
<L>Hade fylled full ilke a wounde;</L>
<L N="155">And vnder an auter betwene &thorn;e stones</L>
<L>They made hym crepe all at-ones.</L>
<L>When he was so sore Ibonde,</L>
<L>With &thorn;er fete &thorn;ei spurned (him) as a hunde &mdash;</L>
<L>And he ley as a babe stylle</L>
<L N="160">And sufferd them to do &thorn;er wylle. &mdash;</L>
<L>All crysten kyngys, with one assente</L>
<L>Fore godys luffe gyffe &thorn;is Jugemente:</L>
<L>What cursyde Jue cum to &yogh;oure ground,</L>
<L>Spurne &yogh;e his body as a hounde,</L>
<L N="165">And, bote he wylle mersy crye,</L>
<L>Honge hym vp on galow-tre,</L>
<L>Fore-why &thorn;ei dyde hym all &thorn;is wo!</L>
<L>That schall I telle &yogh;ou or I go. &mdash;</L>
<L>The crosse was not ordeynde mete</L>
<L N="170">To nayle onne his body suete:</L>
<L>Than kepyd &thorn;ei hym in presone stylle,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e crosse was ordeynd at &thorn;er wylle.</L>
<L>That presone is hold a welle of grace</L>
<L>Fore all &thorn;at comys in &thorn;at place,</L>
<L N="175">And it is callyd off olde &amp; &yogh;enge</L>
<L>The prisone of oure heuen kynge.</L>
<L>Be&yogh;ond &thorn;at is a chapell sqware,</L>
<L>Forty gresys depe &amp; more.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Diese 40 Stufen f&uuml;hrten zu den V. 247&mdash;53 genannten St&auml;tten.</NOTE></L>
<L>Be hym &thorn;at schope both heuen &amp; helle!</L>
<L N="180">This tale is trew &thorn;at I schall telle:</L>
<L>There is in a orytory</L>
<L>Noys of &thorn;e peynes of purgatory &mdash;</L>
<L>And what man seys it is not so,</L>
<L>I schall fynd wytnes, or &thorn;at I go,</L>
<L N="185">Off prestys &thorn;at duellys &thorn;er ny&yogh;ht &amp; dey:</L>
<L>They schall bere wytnes (of) &thorn;at I sey.</L>
<L>And &thorn;er synge prestys of cytes thre</L>
<L>In worschype of &thorn;e trinyte:</L>
<L>The fyrste prestys are os Inde,<MILESTONE N="130" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="190">That preuyd &thorn;em-selue gode &amp; kynde,<NOTE PLACE="foot">189 ff.) Oefter werden 7 Secten mit besonderen Alt&auml;ren aufgef&uuml;hrt.</NOTE></L>
<L>Fore &thorn;ei care fore none o&thorn;er gode</L>
<L>Bot worschipe god &thorn;at dyed onne rode.</L>
<L>And &thorn;ei synge no&thorn;er more ne lesse</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;e pater noster at &thorn;er messe,</L>
<L N="195">Because oure lord bade &thorn;em so pray &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;em st. men?</NOTE></L>
<L>They wyll non o&thorn;er messe sey;</L>
<L>Off brede &amp; wyne hys body dere</L>
<L>They resayue it with mylde chere.</L>
<L>Bare-fote &thorn;ei gone &amp; in febulle aray,</L>
<L N="200">And duell in &thorn;e chyrche both ny&yogh;t &amp; dey;</L>
<L>Bred &amp; water is most &thorn;er fode &mdash;</L>
<L>I hold &thorn;em holy mene &amp; gode.</L>
<L>In &thorn;e north syde of &thorn;at mynstere</L>
<L>They worschype god onne &thorn;is manere. &mdash;</L>
<L N="205">The cyte of Grekys duelle fast by,</L>
<L>That syngys in &thorn;e mounte of Caluery;</L>
<L>Bot what &thorn;ei synge or what &thorn;ei seye,</L>
<L>Oure prestys wote not what &thorn;ei praye.</L>
<L>And when &thorn;ei reyse &thorn;e oste onne hye,</L>
<L N="210">The Grekys kastys vp a loude crye;</L>
<L>And when &thorn;ei breke &thorn;e oste in thre,</L>
<L>Iche man is housyld as wele as he(!):</L>
<L>With a spone with-outene doute</L>
<L>They fede &thorn;e pepulle all aboute;</L>
<L N="215">And a party of &thorn;at body dere</L>
<L>He reseyues on &thorn;is manere.</L>
<L>Also &thorn;e prestys hath no ly(u)inge</L>
<L>Bot what &thorn;e pylgrymus to &thorn;em brynge,</L>
<L>Fore faute of clothys &thorn;er sydys goth owte,</L>
<L N="220">And lyues in tribute &amp; in doute;<NOTE PLACE="foot">l. tribulacion.</NOTE></L>
<L>What lyue-lode &thorn;er is to &thorn;em leyd,</L>
<L>They gruch not, bote hold &thorn;em payd.</L>
<L>And in &thorn;at place with drery mode</L>
<L>They wepe fore hym &thorn;at dy&yogh;ed onne rode,</L>
<L N="225">And &thorn;ei aske non o&thorn;er thynge</L>
<L>Bot heuens blyss at &thorn;er endynge. &mdash;</L>
<L>The thyrd cyte are prestys off owre,
<PB REF="00000497.tif" N="359"></L>
<L>That syngys messe at &thorn;e sepulcoure:</L>
<L>On &thorn;e same graue &thorn;at oure lord in leye,</L>
<L N="230">Prestys synge in latyne euery deye.</L>
<L>Off oure maner is &thorn;er songe &mdash;</L>
<L>Saue &thorn;er berdys are wele longe:</L>
<L>That is &thorn;e vse of &thorn;at contre:</L>
<L>That haue longe berdys, are of degre;</L>
<L N="235">The ordour of &thorn;em are bare-fote frerys.</L>
<L>Off almus-dedys &thorn;ei haue no perys,</L>
<L>Fore &thorn;ei hold none o&thorn;er astate</L>
<L>Bot worschype god arly &amp; late,</L>
<L>Both with &thorn;e new law &amp; &thorn;e olde &mdash;</L>
<L N="240">They passe all cytes a M. folde.</L>
<L>When &thorn;ei make to god &thorn;er mone,</L>
<L>They pray fore all as wele as one.</L>
<L>Thys holy (prestys), &thorn;er duelle,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. saules st. prestys.</NOTE></L>
<L>Schall wytnes &thorn;at I &yogh;ou telle:</L>
<L N="245">Fore &thorn;ei haue spokyne in &thorn;er orytory</L>
<L>With sallys &thorn;at are in &thorn;e peynes of pur|gatory. &mdash;</L>
<L>Be&yogh;ond &thorn;er is an auter vnder an hylle</L>
<L>That seynte Elyne louyd full wele,</L>
<L>And an hole in &thorn;e gro&umacr;nde</L>
<L N="250">There &thorn;e holy crosse was fonde,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e two crossys of &thorn;e theuys all-so:</L>
<L>The beter was betwene &thorn;em two;</L>
<L>There is "a pena &amp; culpa" in &thorn;at place</L>
<L>Fore all men &thorn;at comys theder fore grace,</L>
<L N="255">And beforne as we schuld fare,</L>
<L>Many gode sy&yogh;htys as wele as &thorn;are.</L>
<L>Seynte Elyne, &thorn;e emperyse,</L>
<L>And Constantyne, hyre sone so wyse,</L>
<L>Ordeynd &thorn;at place fore grete delyte</L>
<L N="260">Fore euer-more it schuld be replyed(!);</L>
<L>Seynt Syluester, &thorn;at holy pope,</L>
<L>Confermyd it vnder hys holy cope,</L>
<L>And what sche wold haue &thorn;ertylle &mdash;</L>
<L>The pope was redy at hyre wylle.</L>
<L N="265">And &yogh;it it is more stronge &thorn;an so,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at schall I preue, or I go:<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. I schall I.</NOTE></L>
<L>The Jewys askyd Jhesu of &thorn;er wylle(!)</L>
<L>And bade hym ansuere to &thorn;at skylle;</L>
<L>He seyd in myddys of &thorn;e werld with skylle,</L>
<L N="270">Full hy&yogh;e brou&yogh;t vpone an hylle,<NOTE PLACE="foot">267&mdash;70 sind verderbt.</NOTE></L>
<L>And seyd: "who-so be in charyte</L>
<L>And fore my loue hydere wyll wende,</L>
<L>In Ioy &amp; blysse he schall me se</L>
<L>And with me duelle with-outen ende."</L>
<L N="275">Be&yogh;ond &thorn;at we may to a pylere go</L>
<L>Where &thorn;at he sufferd mekyll wo:</L>
<L>Bonde &amp; betyne &thorn;er he stode,</L>
<L>Tyll all hys body ranne onne blode;</L>
<L>So thyke &thorn;ei spyte on hym by rawe,</L>
<L N="280">That nomane my&yogh;ht hys vysage knowe. &mdash;</L>
<L>Than turned we vponne a grece in hye<NOTE PLACE="foot">Auf den Calvarienberg f&uuml;hrten 18 Stufen, er lag innerhalb der Grabeskirche.</NOTE></L>
<L>On-to &thorn;e mounte of Caluerye.</L>
<L>There was fond a fote of gro&umacr;nde,</L>
<L>There is none sych in &thorn;e werld ro&umacr;nde:</L>
<L N="285">Fore it was plantyd with &thorn;at tre</L>
<L>There Jhesu bou&yogh;ht vs &amp; made vs fre,</L>
<L>And it was halowyd with &thorn;at blode</L>
<L>That oute of hys body &yogh;ode,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at was payd in ransone</L>
<L N="290">Fore all &thorn;e synnes &thorn;at we hade done.</L>
<L>There turnyd all hys cruelte(!)</L>
<L>To grete mersy, as we may se,</L>
<L>When he foregaffe &thorn;e stronge theffe</L>
<L>That cryede mersy, as he was leffe,</L>
<L N="295">And pute hym in no lau&yogh;hynge ley(!)</L>
<L>Bot gaffe hym paradys &thorn;at same dey.</L>
<L>Crysten man, if &thorn;ou be wyse,</L>
<L>Hold <I>&thorn;ou &thorn;is</I> of mekyll price! &mdash;</L>
<L>And &yogh;it dyde he more, to feyne:</L>
<L N="300">He foregaue &thorn;em &thorn;at brast hys veyne,</L>
<L>And prayde hys fader hy&yogh;e on lofte</L>
<L>Foregyue &thorn;e soules &thorn;at he hade wrou&yogh;ht.</L>
<L>There he betau&yogh;t hys modere dere</L>
<L>To Johne, his cosyne, &thorn;at stode hym nere,</L>
<L N="305">And John betoke hys modure also;</L>
<L>And &thorn;ei forth to-geder gane go.</L>
<L>And &thorn;er he soferd grete pouerte,</L>
<L>Neuer man so mekyll as he &mdash;</L>
<L>A fox hath hole, a byrd hath neste,</L>
<L N="310">He had not where-onne hys hede to reste &mdash;</L>
<L>The drynke he askyd, was grete amours,</L>
<L>Was mans saule, &amp; non o&thorn;er lycours.
<PB REF="00000498.tif" N="360"></L>
<L>Than askyd he folke of yche degre</L>
<L>Who sufferd more peyne thane he,</L>
<L N="315">And he cast vppe a loud cry&yogh;e</L>
<L>And seyd lama &yogh;abatamye.</L>
<L>There is &thorn;e roche of stone &thorn;at cleft in|two,</L>
<L>When he sufferd al &thorn;is wo.</L>
<L>Euer-ilke planet was so kynd:</L>
<L N="320">They hade hym some-dele in &thorn;er mynd.</L>
<L>Fore-sothe &thorn;ei comme of Kaymes kyne,</L>
<L>They sette it fore no dedly synne<NOTE PLACE="foot">they st. that.</NOTE></L>
<L>To reyse &thorn;e crose betwene them alle<NOTE PLACE="foot">mortas, mortise.</NOTE></L>
<L>And in a mortas &thorn;ei lete (it) falle;</L>
<L N="325">And when it smote among &thorn;e stones,</L>
<L>His wondys brast all at-ones.</L>
<L>They turnyd hys fete donwerde to helle:</L>
<L>His blode on Adams hede gane felle.</L>
<L>He prayd vnto hys fader of blys,</L>
<L N="330">To saue &thorn;e pepull &thorn;at wolde be hys;</L>
<L>Hys one hond &yogh;ede est, &thorn;e o&thorn;er &yogh;ede weste;</L>
<L>As &thorn;e pylicane sytte on here neste</L>
<L>When sche prykes hyre herte blode<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. pryked st. prykes.</NOTE></L>
<L>To gyffe here byrdys fore &thorn;er fode:</L>
<L N="335">Thus was he strenyd on a tre,</L>
<L>That bou&yogh;ht vs all in &thorn;is degre:</L>
<L>In euery veyne &thorn;ei sou&yogh;ht hys blode &mdash;</L>
<L>Thus fulle dere he bou&yogh;t hys brode;</L>
<L>The cro&umacr;ne of thorne wente throu&yogh;t hys breyne &mdash;</L>
<L N="340">Hys penans passe &thorn;e pelycane;</L>
<L>A spere was pute thorow his rybbys</L>
<L>And with hys blode he fede his brydys,</L>
<L>So fre he was to vs Ichone:</L>
<L>He held oute water, whene blod was gone;</L>
<L N="345">The spere &thorn;at thyrled thorow his herte,</L>
<L>&YOGH;it god foregaffe hym all &thorn;at smerte.</L>
<L>What erthly man in synne is bounde,</L>
<L>And he aske mersy in &thorn;at gro&umacr;nde:</L>
<L>Haue he done neuer so meky(l) a mysse,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. meky.</NOTE></L>
<L N="350">He schall be saluyd of all synne &thorn;at is.</L>
<L>Bot why I neuen here no pardone,</L>
<L>That schall &yogh;e here, or &thorn;at I gone:</L>
<L>Be-cause my wytte may not expond</L>
<L>To knaw &thorn;e pardon of &thorn;at gro&umacr;nde:</L>
<L N="355">Fore &thorn;er is &thorn;e crope &amp; rote</L>
<L>And &thorn;er begane all oure bote;</L>
<L>Fore all &thorn;e pardone &thorn;at is in Rome</L>
<L>There is &thorn;e well, &amp; thens it come.</L>
<L>There is more pardone, I telle &thorn;e,</L>
<L N="360">Than is all &thorn;e water in &thorn;e se</L>
<L>Or gresse or grauell onne &thorn;e ground</L>
<L>Or sterrys be in &thorn;e sky so ro&umacr;nde</L>
<L>Or motys be in &thorn;e sone,</L>
<L>Sen &thorn;e werld was fyrst begone; &mdash;</L>
<L N="365">For euery contre here hath end of ry&yogh;ht,</L>
<L>And he is lord of en(d)les my&yogh;ht.</L>
<L>The pardon &thorn;at he gaff to hys frend,</L>
<L>Is &thorn;e blysse with-outen ende.</L>
<L>And all his grace &amp; mekyll more<NOTE PLACE="foot">his st. &thorn;is.</NOTE></L>
<L N="370">Was purchast in a fote of square:</L>
<L>It passyd not a fote in bred,</L>
<L>What mane wyll mete it with a threde.</L>
<L>I haue so mekyll more to telle:</L>
<L>On &thorn;e mo&umacr;nte I may no lenger duelle. &mdash;</L>
<L N="375">Than fonde we in Galgatha so:</L>
<L>Beryed worthyly &thorn;er lyggys two:</L>
<L>Godfrey of Boleyn &amp; Baudwyne, his bro&thorn;er &mdash;</L>
<L>Jhesu brynge the&thorn;er sych two o&thorn;er:</L>
<L>Than durst I sey, &thorn;at blyssed lond</L>
<L N="380">Schuld duell in crystyne mennys hond!</L>
<L>Be&yogh;ond &thorn;er is &thorn;e same stede</L>
<L>Where Jhesu wondys wer bobbyd rede. &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. babbyd st. bobbyd.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;us we woke all &thorn;e ny&yogh;ht,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;us st. &thorn;er? Ms. toke st. woke.</NOTE></L>
<L>Euery man with a candyll-ly&yogh;ht.</L>
<L N="385">And when we had gone &thorn;e serkyll aboute,</L>
<L>We prayd fore them &thorn;at wer in doute.</L>
<L>And at &thorn;e myd-ny&yogh;ht more &amp; les</L>
<L>Oure prestys disposyd them to messe,</L>
<L>Som at &thorn;e mounte of Caluerye</L>
<L N="390">And som at o&thorn;er plasys &thorn;er-bye,</L>
<L>And at &thorn;e sepulcour many one songe,</L>
<L>And housyld pepull euer amonge;</L>
<L>Fore ilke man ches hym a preste</L>
<L>And told hym &thorn;at ley on hys breste,</L>
<L N="395">And after resauyd hym in forme of bred</L>
<L>That &thorn;er fore vs was offerd quyke &amp; dede.
<PB REF="00000499.tif" N="361"></L>
<L>On &thorn;e morne, at vndrene of &thorn;e deye,</L>
<L>A sary&yogh;en bad vs gone oure weye.</L>
<L>And &thorn;an ranne we ferre &amp; nere</L>
<L N="400">As conys doth to &thorn;er couere,</L>
<L>Some to &thorn;e mounte of Caluerye,</L>
<L>And some to o&thorn;er placys &thorn;er-bye,</L>
<L>And some knelyd yn &thorn;at stede<MILESTONE N="132" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>That hys wondys wer anoyntyd rede.<NOTE PLACE="foot">that st. ther.</NOTE></L>
<L N="405">And sone a frere was to vs sente</L>
<L>And bade we schuld do hys command|mente;</L>
<L>Than durst we no more sey</L>
<L>Bot toke oure palmes &amp; wente awey,</L>
<L>And in-to &thorn;e hospytall we wente</L>
<L N="410">And ete &amp; dranke sych as god vs sente.</L>
<L>When we hade done, we to ke) &thorn;e wey<NOTE PLACE="foot">to st. toke.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot">Die n&auml;chsten St&auml;tten liegen an der via dolorosa; die des Thals Josaphat folgen v. 466.</NOTE></L>
<L>To &thorn;e veyle of Iosphey (!).</L>
<L>That passyd we be a cornere,</L>
<L>The(re) Jhesu (met) and hys modere dere,<NOTE PLACE="foot">met fehlt.</NOTE></L>
<L N="415">And &thorn;ei felle in a swonyng also,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e crosse betwene &thorn;em two;</L>
<L>And <I>&thorn;er &thorn;ei</I> constreyned Symone</L>
<L>To bere &thorn;e crosse, as he was wone, &mdash;</L>
<L>It was so heuy &amp; so square:<NOTE PLACE="foot">l. swere.</NOTE></L>
<L N="420">His manhede my&yogh;ht it no ferthere bere.</L>
<L>And &thorn;e womene of Jerusaleme</L>
<L>Wepyd on Cryst, when &thorn;at he come,</L>
<L>And he ansuerd on &thorn;is degre:</L>
<L>"Wepe onne &yogh;our-selue, &amp; not fore me!"</L>
<L N="425">Be&yogh;ond &thorn;at is a chapell smale,</L>
<L>There some-tyme was sette an halle:</L>
<L>There sche(!) brou&yogh;t forth hyre derlynge,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. sche statt Anna? es ist das Geburtshaus Mari&auml;?</NOTE></L>
<L>The modere of oure heuen kynge.</L>
<L>Be&yogh;ond &thorn;at sche was sette to scole,</L>
<L N="430">That euer was wyse &amp; neuer no fole.</L>
<L>Be&yogh;ond &thorn;at is &thorn;e same lake<NOTE PLACE="foot">es ist die Probatica piscina.</NOTE></L>
<L>That &thorn;e angell styred fore mens sake;</L>
<L>Some comme &thorn;eder with gode entente;</L>
<L>When &thorn;e angell was fro &thorn;ens wente,</L>
<L N="435">Thoff he (!) had neuer so mekyll care,</L>
<L>He schuld be couerde of all hys sore.</L>
<L>Than passyd we to &thorn;e duellynge</L>
<L>Off corsyd Herode, &thorn;e fals kynge:</L>
<L N="440">There oure lorde was clothyd in whyte,</L>
<L>They bette hym sore with grete delyte.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. better.</NOTE></L>
<L>Be&yogh;ond &thorn;at is an o&thorn;er stede,</L>
<L>There Pylate dampned oure lord to dede.</L>
<L>Besyde <I>&thorn;at &thorn;er</I> is ano&thorn;er place,</L>
<L N="445">There Mary Maudeleyne had feyre grace;</L>
<L>Men callyd it Symone leperus halle:</L>
<L>There Cryst foregaue hyre synne alle.</L>
<L>Be an o&thorn;er place we comme<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. wyues duelle st. wyles duelled, vor man ist toune ausgestr.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;er wyles duelle(d) in &thorn;at rych mane</L>
<L N="450">Qhych bette &thorn;e pore man with hys hond</L>
<L>And now lyes brynand in helle gro&umacr;nde.</L>
<L>At &thorn;e ende of &thorn;e toune as we schuld gone,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Salomonis Tempel, wie das Haus Pilati und das g&uuml;ldene Thor, war den Christen verschlossen.</NOTE></L>
<L>We fond &thorn;e temple of Salamone.</L>
<L>Be &thorn;e gyldyne &yogh;ates as we gon pas,</L>
<L N="455">There Jhesu rode vpone hys asse;</L>
<L>The Jues spred clothes vnder his fete,</L>
<L>When &thorn;ei mette hym in &thorn;e strete.</L>
<L>There seynte Anne mett with hyre fere,</L>
<L>When sche conseyued oure lady dere.</L>
<L N="460">With-outen &thorn;at &yogh;ate is &thorn;e sep(u)lkyre</L>
<L>Of many cursyd cr(e)atore:</L>
<L>Fore sary&yogh;yns of grete astate</L>
<L>Are beryed before &thorn;at &yogh;ate.</L>
<L>Be &thorn;at there is an odour stede,</L>
<L N="465">There seynt Steuyne was stonyd to dede.</L>
<L>To &thorn;e veyle of Josaphat with gode e(n)tente,</L>
<L>There oure lady (was) beryed, we wente.</L>
<L>And &thorn;er is a caue vnder &thorn;e erth by,</L>
<L>Wer-in was Cryst sykerly</L>
<L N="470">When he suete blode &amp; watere</L>
<L>And prayd vp to hys fadere:</L>
<L>"Fader, he seyd, if it may so be,</L>
<L>Late &thorn;is deth passe fro me!</L>
<L>And if &thorn;ou wyll not &thorn;at it so be,</L>
<L N="475">Fader, do thy wyll with me!"</L>
<L>There is a place, &thorn;er &thorn;e apostyllus slepe</L>
<L>When Jhesu knelyd onne Olyuete</L>
<L>And &thorn;e Jues sou&yogh;ht hym infere;</L>
<L>There Malcus lost hys ry&yogh;ht ere.
<PB REF="00000500.tif" N="362"></L>
<L>And &thorn;er is a stone &mdash; we kyssyd it alle &mdash;</L>
<L N="480">Wer oure lady lete hyre gyrdell falle</L>
<L>When sche was borne vp to hyre sone,</L>
<L>Euer in blys with hym to wone.</L>
<L>Be&yogh;ond &thorn;at as we schuld go,</L>
<L>Oure lord wepyd vpone &thorn;e cyte all-so.</L>
<L N="485">And an o&thorn;er place we sou&yogh;ht</L>
<L>There &thorn;e palme was to oure lady brou&yogh;ht.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ein Engel brachte Maria ein Palmenreis mit der Ank&uuml;ndigung ihres nahen Todes.</NOTE></L>
<L>Than passyd we to an o&thorn;er sty&yogh;e,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e mounte of Caluery&yogh;e(!):<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. Caluery&yogh;e st. Galile; die &ouml;rtliche Tradition verlegte das ferne Galil&auml;a an diese St&auml;tte.</NOTE></L>
<L>There Jhesu and hys apostyllus dere</L>
<L N="490">There &thorn;ei mete all-infere</L>
<L>After &thorn;e tyme &thorn;at he was dede:</L>
<L>He schewyd them hys wondys rede.</L>
<L>Than turnyd we to &thorn;at same strete</L>
<L>That goth to &thorn;e monte of Olyuete:</L>
<L N="495">There Jhesu sty&yogh;ed vp in &thorn;er syght</L>
<L>To hys fader full of my&yogh;ht.</L>
<L>And &thorn;er lyes &thorn;e stone &yogh;ite<NOTE PLACE="foot">Den Stein mit den Fussstapsen Christi erw&auml;hnt der Dichter nicht.</NOTE></L>
<L>Where-on he wrote &thorn;is holy bede:</L>
<L>The pater noster, as we calle;</L>
<L N="500">The stone lyes muryd in &thorn;e walle.</L>
<L>And &thorn;er &thorn;e apostellus made &thorn;e crede,</L>
<L>That help crysten&egrave; mene at nede.</L>
<L>Furthe we went to a stone,</L>
<L>There oure lady rest hyre vpone.</L>
<L N="505">There is a caue vnder a stone,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Diese Rast hielt Marie bei ihrem t&auml;glichen Besuch der h. St&auml;tten (sie war die erste Pilgerin) nach Christi Himmelfahrt, 14 J. bis zu ihrem Tode.</NOTE></L>
<L>There James wepyd &amp; made hys mone:</L>
<L>Fro &thorn;at tyme &thorn;at hys lord was dede,</L>
<L>He thou&yogh;t neuer to ete brede</L>
<L>Bot he had sene hym ryse ageyne,</L>
<L N="510">With hungour hym-selue he wold h(aue) sleyne;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. hym st. haue.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;er oure lord in &thorn;at place</L>
<L>Aperyd to James, when he vp rase,</L>
<L>And seyd: "I ame resyn now here:</L>
<L>Ete &thorn;i mete &amp; make god chere!" &mdash;</L>
<L N="515">This was James &thorn;e mynoure,</L>
<L>The apostyll of oure sauyoure.</L>
<L>And &thorn;er is &thorn;e graue of Absolone,<MILESTONE N="133" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Of kynge Josaphat &amp; of Ysayone;</L>
<L>All, saue &thorn;e graue of Absolone,</L>
<L N="520">Is transtorrentem Sedrone,</L>
<L>And vnder &thorn;at ley &thorn;e same tre</L>
<L>That &thorn;e crosse was made of, sykyrlye.</L>
<L>There is a welle a lytell thens,<NOTE PLACE="foot">im Thal Siloe.</NOTE></L>
<L>There oure lady gane oure lordys clothys clens.</L>
<L N="525">Be-syde &thorn;at a lytell &thorn;er-fro</L>
<L>Was Jsay &thorn;e prophet sawyne in-two.</L>
<L>And &thorn;er stondys a well alone<NOTE PLACE="foot">das natatorium Siloe.</NOTE></L>
<L>There god releuyd &thorn;e blynd mane. &mdash;</L>
<L>Now haue we bot a myle to gone</L>
<L N="530">Vnto &thorn;e mounte of Syone.</L>
<L>The fyrst thinge &thorn;at we &thorn;er fond,</L>
<L>Was &thorn;e roste of &thorn;e holy lambe &thorn;at stond;<NOTE PLACE="foot">der Rost f&uuml;r das Osterlamm wurde binter dem Chore des Sions-Klosters gezeigt. Ms. roste ost of.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;er the water stode to hete<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. &thorn;at the.</NOTE></L>
<L>That oure lord wessch with his postyllus fete.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Nach Landgr. Wilhelm waren es 2 Steine, der eine f&uuml;r Christus, der andere f&uuml;r die Apostel.</NOTE></L>
<L N="535">And &thorn;er ly&yogh;es &yogh;it XII stons,</L>
<L>That &thorn;e apostyllus sate on all at-ons</L>
<L>And oure lady amonge &thorn;em alle,</L>
<L>Whyll Jhesu prechyd onne a walle.</L>
<L>With-in a chyrch at an autere<NOTE PLACE="foot">es ist die Sionskirche, von S. Helena zuerst erbaut.</NOTE></L>
<L N="540">He fede hys postyllus all-infere:</L>
<L>Of bred &amp; wyne he made his fode</L>
<L>And callyd it hys flessch &amp; blode;</L>
<L>When &thorn;ei wer seruyd with &thorn;e lambe,</L>
<L>He bade &thorn;em ete &amp; drynke &amp; make &thorn;em stronge:</L>
<L N="545">"Fore &thorn;is &thorn;at I afore &yogh;ou ley,</L>
<L>Is my flessch &amp; blod, as I &yogh;ou sey.</L>
<L>What man so be in charyte,</L>
<L>(He) reseyue &thorn;is in &thorn;e mynd of me;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. and st. he.</NOTE></L>
<L>And what man &thorn;at be fals in thou&yogh;ht,</L>
<L N="550">I werne hym reseyue it nou&yogh;t".</L>
<L>On &thorn;e o&thorn;er syde he wessch &thorn;er fete</L>
<L>And dry&yogh;ed them with a towelle suete.</L>
<L>Be-nethe &thorn;er is a hous of stone,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Diese St&auml;tte war eine Kapelle im Kreuzgange.</NOTE></L>
<L>There &thorn;e apostyllus wer hyde euer-ychone
<PB REF="00000501.tif" N="363"></L>
<L N="555">When Jhesu come throu&yogh;e a walle</L>
<L>And bade: "pesse be to &yogh;ou alle!"</L>
<L>And than he askyd Thomas of Ynde</L>
<L>What skyll he hade to be vnkynde,</L>
<L>And schewyd hym hys wondys wyde</L>
<L N="560">And bad hym pute his hond in his ry&yogh;ht syde;</L>
<L>When Thomas hade rowyd in his wonde,</L>
<L>He wepe full sore &amp; fell to gro&umacr;nde</L>
<L>And lyft vp hys hondys on hy&yogh;ht</L>
<L>And cryed mersy with all hys my&yogh;ht.</L>
<L N="565">To any of &thorn;is IIII &thorn;at &yogh;e gone,</L>
<L>Is "a pena &amp; cu(l)pa", euerychone.</L>
<L>With-outen &thorn;e dore a place we sey,<NOTE PLACE="foot">An dieser St&auml;tte war ein "steinern M&auml;uerlein, wie ein Altar zusammengeleget" (so Landgr. Wilh.).</NOTE></L>
<L>There oure lady duellyd many a dey,</L>
<L>XIIII &yogh;ere after &thorn;at Cryst was dede,</L>
<L N="570">And prayd &thorn;er many a holy bede;</L>
<L>And &thorn;er seynt Johne &thorn;e ewangelyste</L>
<L>Songe messe to hyre, when sche lyste.</L>
<L>And &thorn;er was seynt Mathey</L>
<L>Chosyne in-to &thorn;e co(m)peney.</L>
<L N="575">Be&yogh;ond &thorn;at in &thorn;e same coste<NOTE PLACE="foot">Nach and. Berichten soll Maria in ihrem Wohnhause gestorben sein.</NOTE></L>
<L>Oure lady dy&yogh;ed &amp; &yogh;eld &thorn;e goste,</L>
<L>And sche toke Johne &thorn;er &thorn;e palme-tre</L>
<L>That was brou&yogh;(t) hyre in-to Galyle.</L>
<L>On &thorn;e o&thorn;er syde is Cayfas halle,</L>
<L N="580">And &thorn;eder wente we pylgryms alle;</L>
<L>And &thorn;er we fonde a pylere py&yogh;ht</L>
<L>That Jhesu was bound to in &thorn;e ny&yogh;ht;</L>
<L>And <I>&thorn;er &thorn;ei</I> sette hym on a stole</L>
<L>And blyndfeld hym as a fole,</L>
<L N="585">And when &thorn;ei bofsyd hym faste,</L>
<L>They askyd hym who smote hym laste;</L>
<L>Than Cayfas seyd in hys Jugemente:</L>
<L>"Bot he be dede, &thorn;e pepull is sohente".</L>
<L>There is a stone both longe &amp; brode,</L>
<L N="590">Mekyll more &thorn;an a carte lode,</L>
<L>That on &thorn;e sepulcour of oure lord ley</L>
<L>When Cryst rose &amp; wente hys wey;</L>
<L>And onne &thorn;at stone was blode rede,</L>
<L>That Cryst bled onne, sen he was dede.</L>
<L N="595">That ston &thorn;e Grekys hath in kepynge</L>
<L>In wy(r)schype of oure heuen kynge.</L>
<L>On &thorn;e o&thorn;er syde we fond a stone</L>
<L>That Dauyd made &thorn;e satere vpone,</L>
<L>And &thorn;er lyes beryd also,</L>
<L N="600">And o&thorn;er prelatys many mo.</L>
<L>Than wente we to &thorn;e "feld of blode",<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e feld of blood = Hakeldama, Begr&auml;bnissort der Fremdlinge, f&uuml;r des Judas 30 Silberlinge erkauft; es lag gegen&uuml;ber Sion an einem Berge am Rande des Tales Hinom. to = in der Richtung auf.</NOTE></L>
<L>There Peter to hys penans &yogh;ode</L>
<L>Be-cause he hade hys god foresake:</L>
<L>He toke on hys body mekyll wrake,</L>
<L N="605">He wronge hys hondys &amp; drew hys here</L>
<L>And cryed mersy, "lord, thy nore!"</L>
<L>And euer when-he askyd grace,</L>
<L>The water ranne doune by hys face.</L>
<L>Than wente we forth onne oure weye</L>
<L N="610">To &thorn;e well, &thorn;at oure lord dronke of euery deye;</L>
<L>Two herymetys &thorn;at there duelle</L>
<L>Calle it "oure lordys welle".</L>
<L>And &thorn;er &thorn;e apostylles all-infere</L>
<L>Bare oure lady on a bere,</L>
<L N="615">And when &thorn;e Jues come in gret deray</L>
<L>And wold haue drawyne &thorn;e body awey,</L>
<L>And fore &thorn;ei wold haue done here schame:</L>
<L>Some wex wode &amp; some wex lame;</L>
<L>Than couth &thorn;ei no more sey</L>
<L N="620">Bot cryed mersy &amp; welowey;</L>
<L>Than Peter held stylle &thorn;e bere</L>
<L>And ansuerd &thorn;em on &thorn;is manere:</L>
<L>He &thorn;at askys mersy with herte &amp; thou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>He schall haue foregyffnes (of) &thorn;at he has wro&yogh;ht.</L>
<L N="625">In godys name all-infere</L>
<L>Spyte no more on Jhesu moder dere!"</L>
<L>Fast-be (is) a tempulle feyre &amp; fre;<NOTE PLACE="foot">S. Jacob's Kirche, nahe beim Berge Sion.</NOTE></L>
<L>There mete Jhesu with meydens thre:</L>
<L>The(re) is a crosse made in a stone,</L>
<L N="630">There pylgrymes knelys &amp; kys Ichone.</L>
<L>Be&yogh;ond &thorn;at is ano&thorn;er stede,</L>
<L>There seynte Jame was quyke &amp; dede.</L>
<L>There is &thorn;e serkyll of &thorn;e to&umacr;ne aboute,</L>
<L>Sex myle with-outen doute. &mdash;<MILESTONE N="134" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="635">And sex myle we wente on &thorn;e morne<NOTE PLACE="foot">es sind 2 deutsche Meilen.</NOTE></L>
<L>To Bethlem, where oure lord was borne.
<PB REF="00000502.tif" N="364"></L>
<L>Bot &thorn;er-of we muste a whyll dwelle,</L>
<L>Iff I schall of &thorn;e wey telle.</L>
<L>As Jhesus by &thorn;e wey &yogh;ede,</L>
<L N="640">He fond a Jew sawynge hys sede;</L>
<L>He askyd "what sawys &thorn;ou onys?"</L>
<L>And he seyd "I saw stonys".</L>
<L>And Crist seyd "stone mot &thorn;ei be":</L>
<L>And truly &thorn;er lyes grete plente. &mdash;</L>
<L N="645">The nex(t) thinge after, &thorn;at I cane &yogh;ou telle,</L>
<L>There is &thorn;e graue of Rachelle,</L>
<L>And o&thorn;er prophetys graues, one or two,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Elias' und Abacucks Haus lag da.</NOTE></L>
<L>There ly&yogh;et in &thorn;e wey, as we schuld go.</L>
<L>Off Bedlem I wyll not ly&yogh;e,</L>
<L N="650">Bot &thorn;at I saw &thorn;er with myne eye.</L>
<L>Fore, <I>&thorn;er &thorn;at</I> the asse &amp; &thorn;e ox stode,</L>
<L>Is now a feyre chyrch &amp; gode;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Die Krippe lag 3 Stufen tiefer als die durch einen in Marmorpflaster in Grau und Roth ausgelegten, pr&auml;chtig geschm&uuml;ckten, Stein bezeichnete Geburtsst&auml;tte. chyrch bez. wol Kapelle od. Krypte.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;er owre lady in child-bede ley,</L>
<L>There (is) a feyre chyrch, I dere wele sey;</L>
<L N="655">Be&yogh;ond &thorn;at is &thorn;e same stone</L>
<L>That oure lord was cyrcumsy(se)d vpone,</L>
<L>And &thorn;er he blede hys fyrst blode</L>
<L>That euer he bled fore mannys fode.</L>
<L>Bot why he(!) layd hym in &thorn;e stalle,</L>
<L N="660">That schall I tell amonge &yogh;ou alle:</L>
<L>Fore &thorn;er was no thinge so redy</L>
<L>That schuld longe to sych a lady,</L>
<L>Feyre clothys &amp; werme fyre,</L>
<L>That women in trauell schuld desyre;</L>
<L N="665">Than chefe &thorn;ei &thorn;e wermyst place of all</L>
<L>And leyd hym in an asse-stalle.</L>
<L>The ox and &thorn;e asse dyde curtasly</L>
<L>And gaue hym place, onne to ly,</L>
<L>And euer-more with eyn gray</L>
<L N="670">Oure (lord) beheld how he ley.</L>
<L>And whe(n) &thorn;e bed was dy&yogh;ht aboute,</L>
<L>Sche prayd &thorn;at sche my&yogh;ht gyff hym souke.</L>
<L>And now &yogh;e schall here &thorn;e metynge</L>
<L>Betwyx oure lady &amp; hyre derlynge:<NOTE PLACE="foot">V. 673&mdash;4 sind im Ms. nach 688 nochmals wiederholt.</NOTE></L>
<L N="675">Sche sey(d): "welcome heuen kynge,</L>
<L>Welcum makere of all thynge,</L>
<L>Welcome prince in trinyte,</L>
<L>That is &amp; was &amp; euer schall be!</L>
<L>Welcum both god &amp; man,</L>
<L N="680">Welcum my lord, welcum my sone,</L>
<L>Welcum my Joy, welcum my blys,</L>
<L>With all my hert &thorn;at I may &thorn;e kys!</L>
<L>In heuen blyssed be &thorn;i name,</L>
<L>That wold chese me to be &thorn;i dame!</L>
<L N="685">So rych a emperour &amp; a kynge</L>
<L>To be borne of so vnworthy a thinge!"</L>
<L>And than sche praysyd hym all aboute</L>
<L>And with hyre pappys gaue hym sowke.</L>
<L>At Iche of <I>&thorn;is, &thorn;er</I> pylgryme be,<NOTE PLACE="foot">I. &thorn;is placys.</NOTE></L>
<L N="690">There is "a pena &amp; a culpa", at all thre.</L>
<L>Then passyd we in-to a valey,</L>
<L>The(re) C &amp; XLIIII M. ley</L>
<L>Of chylder &thorn;at dy&yogh;ed fore godys sake,</L>
<L>When cursyd Herod of hem toke wrake.</L>
<L N="695">And in &thorn;at place, with-outene doute,</L>
<L>Seynt Jerom wrote &thorn;e bybull aboute.</L>
<L>Then wente we arly onne &thorn;e morne<NOTE PLACE="foot">Die folg. St&auml;tten. liegen im Gebirge Judae, &uuml;ber welches die Pilger nach Jerusalem zur&uuml;ckkehrten.</NOTE></L>
<L>There seynt Johne baptyst was borne.<NOTE PLACE="foot">An dieser St&auml;tte war eine Kirche, vgl. 734.</NOTE></L>
<L>Than wente we in-to a grete valey</L>
<L N="700">There Adam duellyd many a dey,</L>
<L>And he is beryd a lytell &thorn;er-fro &mdash;</L>
<L>Bot no crystyne mane may come &thorn;er-to.</L>
<L>And &thorn;er is mekyll of &thorn;e story</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e hous of &YOGH;akary.</L>
<L N="705">There me(tte) two ladys feyre &amp; bry&yogh;ht&mdash;</L>
<L>Truly, it was a wele feyre syght!</L>
<L>The &omacr;ne was past chyld-byrth be kynd,</L>
<L>The o&thorn;er was vergyne feyre &amp; hend</L>
<L>And neuer dyde synne, in boure ne in halle,</L>
<L N="710">And bore &thorn;at chyld &thorn;at schall saue vs alle.</L>
<L>When Ely&yogh;abeth of Mary hade syght,</L>
<L>Sche prophesyd anone ry&yogh;ht</L>
<L>And askyd: "what may &thorn;is meruylle be</L>
<L>That godys modere commys to me?</L>
<L N="715">The chyld &thorn;at is in my wome so &yogh;onge,</L>
<L>Reiofet, Mary, at &yogh;oure comynge.</L>
<L>All &thorn;at I haue is at &yogh;oure wylle,
<PB REF="00000503.tif" N="365"></L>
<L>And I &yogh;oure feruant, loud &amp; stylle."</L>
<L>When Mary herd &thorn;is wordys dere,</L>
<L N="720">Sche ansuerde on &thorn;is manere:</L>
<L>All hyre herte to god sche hy&yogh;ht</L>
<L>And thankyd god off all hys my&yogh;ht;</L>
<L>Sche knely(d) after onne a stone,</L>
<L>Magnificat sche made anone.</L>
<L N="725">And when Ely&yogh;abeth with hyre e&yogh;ene graye</L>
<L>Had sene &thorn;e wysdome of &thorn;at maye</L>
<L>And &thorn;e feyrnes of hyre face,</L>
<L>Anon sche callyd hyre quene of grace;</L>
<L>Do&umacr;ne sone on hyre kneys sche felle</L>
<L N="730">And prayd &thorn;at sche my&yogh;ht with hyre duelle.</L>
<L>Before &thorn;e wey as we come</L>
<L>Fro seynte Johne in-to Jerusalem,</L>
<L>Standys &thorn;e compas of &thorn;e rote<NOTE PLACE="foot">Diese St&auml;tte, eine Kirche zum h. Kreuze, liegt &frac12; Stunde westlich von Jerusalem.</NOTE></L>
<L>Where-on grew &thorn;e tre of owre bote. &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Nach 734 folgt im Ms. in unrichtiger Ordnung zun&auml;chst der Besuch Bethaniens, 807&mdash;838, vor dem Besuch des Jordan. Bethanien aber wurde auf dem R&uuml;ckwege vom Jordan besucht. Offenbar hat der Schreiber diese Stelle versetzt, wie auch die den Besuch Bethaniens angeh&auml;ngten Schlussverse beweisen.</NOTE></L>
<L N="735">And at &thorn;e morne, when it was dey,</L>
<L>To flome Jordeyne we toke &thorn;e wey.</L>
<L>At Jeryco as we schuld gone,</L>
<L>We fond a hond of seynte Johne,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at is callyd &thorn;e Grekys law(!);</L>
<L N="740">The(re) we offerd, when we it saw.</L>
<L>And &thorn;er &YOGH;achee, &thorn;e lytell mane,</L>
<L>Abod oure lord, tylle &thorn;at he came,</L>
<L>And clame in-to &thorn;e tre on hy&yogh;ht,</L>
<L>That he my&yogh;ht wysly se &thorn;at sy&yogh;ht.</L>
<L N="745">And &thorn;er we saw &thorn;e same stonke<NOTE PLACE="foot">stonke, frz. &eacute;tang, stagnum; l. also stanke i. R. zu sanke.</NOTE></L>
<L>The(re) Sodome &amp; Gomore fore synne sonke;</L>
<L>Fyue cytys, as I wene,</L>
<L>Sanke to hell fore vnkyndly synne;</L>
<L>There passyd none awey with lyffe</L>
<L N="750">Bot Lothe &amp; hys childer &amp; wyfe:</L>
<L>An angelle come to Lothe halle</L>
<L>And told of &thorn;e sorow &thorn;at schuld falle,</L>
<L>He bade hym take hys folke &amp; go,</L>
<L>"Fore &yogh;e schall here of mykell wo;</L>
<L N="755">Spede &yogh;ou fast with all &yogh;oure mayne,</L>
<L>And fore no-thinge &yogh;e turne ageyne!"</L>
<L>The wyfe Lothe was freyll of thou&yogh;t</L>
<L>And sette &thorn;e angelle worde at nou&yogh;t</L>
<L>And sche brake hys comandment.</L>
<L N="760">Here now, &thorn;er-fore how sche was schente!</L>
<L>Hyre husbond bade hyre forth to gone,</L>
<L>And sche turnyd in-to a falte stone.</L>
<L>And who-so commys to Galile,</L>
<L>Where &thorn;at (stone) stondys, &yogh;e may se. &mdash;</L>
<L N="765">There growys no&thorn;er corne ne haye,</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;at &thorn;e wate berys awaye;</L>
<L>What fysch or foule commys &thorn;ere-Ine,</L>
<L>He schall neuer fle ne swyme,</L>
<L>Bot synkys done, as a plombe of lede;</L>
<L N="770">Tharefore it is callyd "&thorn;e see of dede."</L>
<L>It is XL myle longe, &amp; large of brede.</L>
<L>There dare no-mane touche it fore drede;</L>
<L>Fore &yogh;arysins &thorn;at &thorn;ere duelle<NOTE PLACE="foot">fore st. for&thorn;i.</NOTE></L>
<L>Seys &thorn;at it is &thorn;e pytte of helle.</L>
<L N="775">Than come we to flome Jordane,</L>
<L>There Jone baptyst both god &amp; man.</L>
<L>There we resauy(d) "a pena &amp; culpa"</L>
<L>And wesch vs in &thorn;e water also.</L>
<L>And after we toke a soppe in w&ymacr;ne,</L>
<L N="780">And turnyd vp to Qu(a)ryntyne,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Quarentana hiess der (schwer zu ersteigende) Berg der 4ot&auml;gigen Fasten und Versuchung Christi.</NOTE></L>
<L>There Jhesu fastyd XL deys,</L>
<L>When he began oure new lawys.</L>
<L>And &thorn;er lyes &thorn;e stones rede</L>
<L>That &thorn;e deuyll bade Cryst turne in-to brede;</L>
<L N="785">And when he wolde not wyrke hys wylle,</L>
<L>An o&thorn;er thinge betwen &thorn;em felle:</L>
<L>He bare oure lord in hys armys two</L>
<L>Fro Jerusalem to Jerico</L>
<L>And he sette hym on a pynn(a)cle hye,</L>
<L N="790">Als fere as men my&yogh;ht hym se(!),</L>
<L>And schewyd hym there haulys &amp; bourys,</L>
<L>Riche castellus &amp; many toures.</L>
<L>When he hade sch(e)wyd hym &thorn;e werld aboute,</L>
<L>He spake wordys &thorn;at wer in doute,</L>
<L N="795">He seyd: "all &thorn;is I schall gyfe &thorn;e,</L>
<L>And (&thorn;ou) falle do&umacr;ne &amp; wyrschyp me."</L>
<L>Off all &thorn;at he seyd beforne</L>
<L>Oure lorde toke it to lytell scorne
<PB REF="00000504.tif" N="366"></L>
<L>And ansuerd hym wyth a word:</L>
<L N="800">"Go forth, theff, &amp; tempe not &thorn;i lorde!"</L>
<L>Than roulyd &thorn;at thefe vpone a hepe</L>
<L>More tha(n) a M. fathome depe,</L>
<L>Fore it was XX<SUP>ti</SUP> oures &amp; mo</L>
<L>Or of &thorn;at mountan he my&yogh;ht go.</L>
<L N="805">Do&umacr;ne at &thorn;e fote of &thorn;at mountayne</L>
<L>We founde a garthyne of Abrahame. &mdash;</L>
<L>Than sou&yogh;ht we forth, bo&thorn;e mane &amp; wyfe,</L>
<L>The(re) La&yogh;are was reysed fro deth to lyue</L>
<L>And had ly&yogh;e stynkynge in &thorn;e grond,</L>
<L N="810">A hundreht parte wers &thorn;an a hunde.</L>
<L>Besyde &thorn;er in a feyre pleyne</L>
<L>Is Martha halle &amp; Mary Madeleyne,</L>
<L>There Jhesu at &thorn;e sopere sate</L>
<L>When Mary Maudeleyne kyssed his fete,</L>
<L N="815">And Martha prayd amonge &thorn;e(m) alle</L>
<L>That sche my&yogh;ht ryse &amp; serue in halle;</L>
<L>Than seyd oure lord fore Marye</L>
<L>That sche hade chosyne &thorn;e better partye.</L>
<L>All is befalle &thorn;at I des(criue)<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. be felle. desyre st. descryue.</NOTE></L>
<L N="820">In Betany &amp; in Betphage:</L>
<L>I(n) Betphage sate oure lord vpone a stone</L>
<L>And bode hys asse, to it wer come;</L>
<L>There be &thorn;e stepys of &thorn;e asse fete,</L>
<L>There Jhesu onne hys asse lepe.</L>
<L N="825">Thys wey is to comme &amp; go</L>
<L>Sexty myle &amp; X &amp; mo. &mdash;</L>
<L>Now haue we tolde all &thorn;at we haue sene,</L>
<L>So god me saue fro sorow &amp; tene!</L>
<L>And all &thorn;e cause &thorn;at I cane seye,</L>
<L N="830">Is, to teche a man &thorn;e weye.</L>
<L>What pylgryme &thorn;at the&thorn;er wylle go,</L>
<L>I praye god saue hym to &amp; fro</L>
<L>And gyfe &thorn;em grace so to do,</L>
<L>That heuens blys &thorn;ei may come to.</L>
<L N="835">Now, lord god all-my&yogh;tye,</L>
<L>Thou grante vs grace &thorn;at it so be,</L>
<L>That we be redy to come to &thorn;e</L>
<L>When &thorn;at oure saulys schall partyd be!</L>
<L>Jhesu, &thorn;at fore vs dy&yogh;ed on &thorn;e rode-tre,</L>
<L N="840">Saue vs all fore &thorn;i pyte!</L>
<L>Be &thorn;e vertu of &thorn;i holy crosse</L>
<L>Latte vs neuer in synne falle,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at we be redy thorow &thorn;i grace</L>
<L>To comme to &thorn;i Joys eternalle!</L>
<L N="845">When we schall out off &thorn;is werld wende,</L>
<L>God, grante vs fore &thorn;i holy grace</L>
<L>Off &thorn;e, lord, to haue in mynd(!),</L>
<L>Fore to behold &thorn;i blyssyd face!</L>
<TRAILER>Amen quod Rate.
</TRAILER>

</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="18" TYPE="legend"><PB REF="00000505.tif" N="[367]">

<PB REF="00000505.tif" N="[367]">
<HEAD>18. Zwei Geschichten aus der H&ouml;lle, aus Ms. Ashm. 61, fol. 139.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>Beide St&uuml;cke folgen im Ms. unmittelbar hintereinander ohne Titel und Unter|scheidung. Der Text ist v&ouml;llig verderbt.</P></HEADNOTE>
<DIV3 N="1" TYPE="section">
<HEAD>I. Klage der Seele des William Basterdfeld.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"All crysten men &thorn;at walke by me,</L>
<L>Behold &amp; se &thorn;is dulfull sy&yogh;ht!</L>
<L>It helpys not to calle ne cry,</L>
<L>Fore I ame dampned, a dollfole wy&yogh;ht.</L>
<L N="5">[Some-tyme in Ingland duellynge &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">sind interpolirt.</NOTE></L>
<L>Thys was trew with-outen lesynge &mdash;]<NOTE PLACE="foot">sind interpolirt.</NOTE></L>
<L>I was callyd sir Wylliam Basterdfeld kny&yogh;t.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. basterd feld.</NOTE></L>
<L>Be were be me, [both kynge &amp; kny&yogh;ht,<NOTE PLACE="foot">sind interpolirt.</NOTE></L>
<L>And amend &yogh;ou,] whyle &yogh;e haue space!</L>
<L N="10">Fore I haue lost euer-lastynge ly&yogh;ht</L>
<L>And &thorn;us of mercy cane I gete no grace.</L>
<L>When I was now as &yogh;e be,</L>
<L>I kepyd neuer o&thorn;er lyffe:</L>
<L>I spendyd my lyffe in vanyte,</L>
<L N="15">I(n) veynglory, bate &amp; stryffe;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. I st. In.</NOTE></L>
<L>Grete othes with me wer fulle ryffe,</L>
<L>I had no grace me to amend;</L>
<L>I sparyd no&thorn;er meyd ne wyffe,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at hath brou&yogh;t me to &thorn;is ende.</L>
<L N="20">I hade no hape, whyll I was here,</L>
<L>Forto aryse &amp; me repent,</L>
<L>Tyll &thorn;at I was brou&yogh;t on bere:</L>
<L>Than was to late, fore I was schente.</L>
<L>All-wey with &thorn;em(!) I ame aweyde,</L>
<L N="25">In fyre of hell I schall euer be brente.</L>
<L>Alas, &thorn;is werld hath me deseyuede,</L>
<L>Fore I hade no grace me to amende!</L>
<L>In lechery I lede my lyfe,</L>
<L>Fore I hade gode &amp; gold at wylle,</L>
<L N="30">I scleu&yogh;e my-selue with-outene knyffe,</L>
<L>And of glotony I hade my fylle;</L>
<L>In sleuth I ley &amp; slepyd stylle:</L>
<L>I was deseyued in a reyfte,<NOTE PLACE="foot">reyste = ryste, rest.</NOTE></L>
<L>A dolefulle deth &thorn;at dyde me kylle.</L>
<L N="35">Than was to late off "had I wyste".</L>
<L>Thus ame I lappyd all-aboute</L>
<L>With todys &amp; snakys, as &yogh;e may se,</L>
<L>I ame gnawyne my body aboute &mdash;</L>
<L>Alas, alas, full wo is me!</L>
<L N="40">It is to late, it will not be.</L>
<L>I knaw welle women more &amp; mynne:</L>
<L>Fore hym &thorn;at dy&yogh;ed fore &yogh;ou &amp; me,</L>
<L>Aryse &amp; rest not in &yogh;our synne!</L>
<L>Fore when I was in my flowres,</L>
<L N="45">Than was I ly&yogh;ht as byrd on brere.</L>
<L>Therefore I suffere scharpe schoures</L>
<L>And by &thorn;at bergayne wonder dere,</L>
<L>And byde in peynes many &amp; sere.</L>
<L>Therefore &thorn;us I make my mone.</L>
<L N="50">Now may helpe me no prayere,</L>
<L>I haue no gode, bot god alone.</L>
<L>Wo be &thorn;ei, who-so euer &thorn;ei be,</L>
<L>And haue &thorn;er V wyttys at wylle,</L>
<L>And wyll not be wer be me</L>
<L N="55">And knaw gode thinge fro &thorn;e ylle.</L>
<L>The pore fore faute late &thorn;em not spylle!</L>
<L>And &yogh;e do, &yogh;oure deth is dy&yogh;ht.</L>
<L>&YOGH;oure fals flessch &yogh;e not fullfylle</L>
<L>Loft with Lucyfere fro &thorn;e ly&yogh;ht.</L>
<L N="60">In delycate metys I sette my delyte</L>
<L>And my&yogh;hty wynes vnto my pay:
<PB REF="00000506.tif" N="368"></L>
<L>That make &thorn;is wormys on me to byte,</L>
<L>Therefore my songe is wellywey.</L>
<L>I my&yogh;ht not fast, I wold not praye,</L>
<L N="65">I thou&yogh;t to amend me in myn age,</L>
<L>I droffe euer forth fro dey to dey:</L>
<L>Therefore I byde here in &thorn;is cage.</L>
<L>Thys cage is euer-lastynge fyre,</L>
<L>I ame ordeynde &thorn;er-in to duelle;</L>
<L N="70">It is me gyuen fore myne hyre,</L>
<L>Euer to bryne in &thorn;e pytte of helle;</L>
<L>I ame feteryd with &thorn;e fendys felle,</L>
<L>There I abyde as best in stalle.</L>
<L>There is no tonge my care cane telle.</L>
<L N="75">Be were &yogh;e haue not sych a falle!</L>
<L>Alas, &thorn;at euer I borne was</L>
<L>Or modere me bore! why dyde sche so?</L>
<L>Fore I ame lost fore my trespas</L>
<L>And abyde in euer-lastynge wo.</L>
<L N="80">I haue no frend, bot many a fo.</L>
<L>Behold me, how &thorn;at I ame torne!</L>
<L>Fore I ame rente fro tope to to.</L>
<L>Alas, &thorn;at euer I was borne!</L>
<L>Gode bro&thorn;er, haue me in mynd</L>
<L N="85">And thinke how &thorn;ou schall dy&yogh;e, all-wey,</L>
<L>And to &thorn;i soule be not vnkynde &mdash;</L>
<L>Remembyre it bo&thorn;e ny&yogh;t &amp; dey!</L>
<L>Besyly loke &thorn;at &thorn;ou praye,</L>
<L>And beseke &thorn;ou heuen kynge</L>
<L N="90">To saue &thorn;e on &thorn;at dredfull dey</L>
<L>That euery man schall gyffe rekenynge!</L>
<L>Fore &thorn;er no lordys schall fore &thorn;e praye,</L>
<L>Ne Justys no&thorn;er no mane of lawe,</L>
<L>There charter helpys &thorn;e not &thorn;at dey,</L>
<L N="95">There pletyne is not worth an hawe.</L>
<L>God gyue &thorn;e grace, &thorn;i-selue to know,</L>
<L>And euery mane in hys degre.</L>
<L>Fare wele! I here an horne blow:</L>
<L>I may no lenger byde with &thorn;e."</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="2" TYPE="section">
<HEAD>II. Strafe des Ehebruchs.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Man, fro myscheff &thorn;ou &thorn;e amend</L>
<L>And to my talkynge &thorn;ou take god hede!</L>
<L>Fro synnes VII &thorn;ou &thorn;e defend,</L>
<L>The lest of all is forto drede.</L>
<L N="5">Fore of &thorn;e lest I wyll &yogh;ou speke,</L>
<L>And fro hell I wyll &yogh;ou tech.</L>
<L>Be wer, man! god wyll hym wreke</L>
<L>Off hym &thorn;at his techinge do breke.</L>
<L>The fyrst sacrement &thorn;at euer god made,</L>
<L N="10">That was wedloke, in gode fey.<MILESTONE N="137" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Beleue <I>&thorn;ou &thorn;at</I> with-outen drede,</L>
<L>Fore &thorn;at schall last to domes-dey &mdash;</L>
<L>Hys awne word if we wyll hold &mdash;</L>
<L>Tyll deth come &thorn;at all schall werke(!)</L>
<L N="15">And vs all in cley to fold.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Nach 15 fehIt ein Vers.</NOTE></L>
<L>The gretyst kynge in all &thorn;is werld</L>
<L>Be some cause hys cro&umacr;ne may fore|gone:</L>
<L>I take wytnes of kynge Rycherd</L>
<L>And kynge Fabere &amp; Absolone,</L>
<L N="20">And kynge Dauyd &thorn;at made &thorn;e sauter boke:</L>
<L>Fore synne &thorn;at he dyde with Bersabe,</L>
<L>Cryst fro hym hys cro&umacr;ne he toke:</L>
<L>Thus holy wryte tellys me.</L>
<L>The gretyst clerke &thorn;at euer &thorn;ou seyste,</L>
<L N="25">To take hym vnder heuen cope,</L>
<L>He may neuer take ordure of preste<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. ha st. he.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bot he haue leue of &thorn;e pope;</L>
<L>And he be getyne in vowtry</L>
<L>Or els a basterd he be borne,</L>
<L N="30">Thus I canne well telle to &thorn;e:</L>
<L>The ordyre of preste he hath forelorne.</L>
<L>And &thorn;e begger at &thorn;e to&umacr;nes ende</L>
<L>To hym wedloke is as fre</L>
<L>As &thorn;e ryall kynge of kynd,</L>
<L N="35">Fore all is bot a dyngnite.</L>
<L>Man, if &thorn;ou wyst what it were</L>
<L>To take ano&thorn;er than &thorn;i wyffe,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. it st. here.</NOTE></L>
<L>Thou woldyst ra&thorn;er sofere (here)
<PB REF="00000507.tif" N="369"></L>
<L>To be sleyne with a knyffe.</L>
<L>Fore if &thorn;ou take ano&thorn;er mans wyffe,</L>
<L N="40">A wronge eyere &thorn;ou muste nedvs gete,</L>
<L>And &thorn;us thou bryngys thre saulys in stryffe,</L>
<L>In hell fyre to ly &amp; hete.</L>
<L>Bot wreches thinke in &thorn;er herte</L>
<L>That fele <I>&thorn;em</I> gylty in &thorn;is case:</L>
<L N="45">With schryft of mo(u)th &amp; penans smerte</L>
<L>They wene &thorn;er blys forto vnbrace;<NOTE PLACE="foot">vnbrace st. enbrace?</NOTE></L>
<L>Bot and &thorn;ei dyed a sothen deth</L>
<L>With-outen schryft or repentans,</L>
<L>To hell &thorn;ei go with-outen lete,</L>
<L N="50">Fore &thorn;ei canne chefe non o&thorn;er chans.</L>
<L>A god sampull I wyll &yogh;ou telle,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ou st. &yogh;ou.</NOTE></L>
<L>To my tale if &yogh;e take hede.</L>
<L>In Felamownte &thorn;is case befelle</L>
<L>XXX<SUP>ti</SUP> wynter senne &thorn;e deth(!).<NOTE PLACE="foot">deth st. dede.</NOTE></L>
<L N="55">There duellyd two bre&thorn;er in &thorn;e to&umacr;ne,</L>
<L>As &thorn;e story tellys me beforne,</L>
<L>Be one fader &amp; modere getyne;</L>
<L>Squyres &thorn;ei wer of grete reno&umacr;ne.</L>
<L>The eldere bro&thorn;er had a wyffe,</L>
<L N="60">The feyrest woman in all &thorn;at londe,</L>
<L>And &yogh;it vsyde a cursyde lyffe</L>
<L>And brou&yogh;t hys saule in bytter bonde;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. hyre st. hys.</NOTE></L>
<L>He rou&yogh;ht not what woman he toke:</L>
<L>So lytell he set by hys wyffe.</L>
<L N="65">The devyll cau&yogh;ht hym in a croke</L>
<L>And merkyd hys mode with grete mys|cheffe.</L>
<L>The two bre&thorn;er vpone a dey</L>
<L>With enmys were sleyne in fy&yogh;ht.</L>
<L>The eldure to helle he toke &thorn;e wey,</L>
<L N="70">The &yogh;enger to paradys ry&yogh;ht.</L>
<L>And &thorn;is was kna&umacr;ne in sothnes:</L>
<L>Herkyns, sires, what I schall sey!</L>
<L>Take gode hede, both more &amp; les,</L>
<L>Fore godys loue bere &thorn;is tale awey!</L>
<L N="75">The eldure bro&thorn;er hade a sonne, a clerke,</L>
<L>Fully XV &yogh;ere of age;</L>
<L>He was ry&yogh;ht holy in hys werke,</L>
<L>Tho hym schuld fall &thorn;e herytage.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. tho st. to.</NOTE></L>
<L>Fore hys fadere he made grete mone,</L>
<L N="80">As fallys a gode sone of kynd;</L>
<L>Euery ny&yogh;t to hys fadure graue wold he gone,</L>
<L>Forto haue hys soule in mynde.</L>
<L>Thus he prayd both dey &amp; ny&yogh;ht</L>
<L>To god &amp; to hys modere dere:</L>
<L N="85">Of hys fadere to haue a sy&yogh;ht</L>
<L>In what place &thorn;at he in were.</L>
<L>The chyld &thorn;at was so nobull &amp; wyfe</L>
<L>Stod at hys fadere graue:</L>
<L>There come one in a whyte surples</L>
<L N="90">And preuely toke hym by &thorn;e sleue.</L>
<L>"Come onne, chyld, &amp; go with me,</L>
<L>Fore god hath herd &thorn;i prayere:</L>
<L>Chyld, &thorn;i fadere &thorn;ou schall se,</L>
<L>Wer he bryneth in helle fyre."</L>
<L N="95">He lede hym to a comly hylle:</L>
<L>The erth opynd, &amp; he in &yogh;ede.</L>
<L>Smoke &amp; fyere gane &thorn;er oute welle,</L>
<L>And many saules glowand in glede.</L>
<L>There he saw many a sore turmente,</L>
<L N="100">How soulys were pute in grete pyninge.</L>
<L>He saw hys fadere how he brente,</L>
<L>And be &thorn;e membyrs how he hynge;</L>
<L>Fendys bold with crowkys kene</L>
<L>Rente hys fader fro lyth to leme.</L>
<L N="105">"Chyld, &thorn;ou couetys &thorn;i fader to sene:</L>
<L>Loke vp now &amp; speke with hym!"</L>
<L>"Alas, fadere, how stand &thorn;is case</L>
<L>That &yogh;e be in &thorn;is peynes stronge?"</L>
<L>"Son, he seyd, I may sey alas</L>
<L N="110">That euer I dyde &thorn;i modure wronge!</L>
<L>Fore sche was both feyre &amp; gode</L>
<L>And also both trusty &amp; trew;</L>
<L>Alas, I was wers than wode,</L>
<L>Myn awne bale &thorn;er I dyde brew."</L>
<L N="115">"Whe&thorn;er is &thorn;er any seynt in heuyne</L>
<L>That &yogh;e wer wonte to haue in mynde,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. wente.</NOTE></L>
<L>That my&yogh;ht &yogh;ou lowse oute of prisone,</L>
<L>Oure lady Mary or some gode frende?"</L>
<L>"Sone, all &thorn;e seyntys &thorn;at be in heuen</L>
<L N="120">Ne all &thorn;e angellus vnder &thorn;e skye</L>
<L>One oure space oute of &thorn;is peyne</L>
<L>They haue no powere to lyst me.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. lyst = lese, wie &ouml;fter praet. lest in diesem Ms.</NOTE></L>
<L>Sone, if euery gras wer a preste
<PB REF="00000508.tif" N="370"></L>
<L>That growys vpone godys gro&umacr;nde,</L>
<L N="125">Off &thorn;is peyne &thorn;at thou me seyste</L>
<L>Canne neuer make me vnbonde.</L>
<L>Sonne, &thorn;ou be a preste, I wote wele,</L>
<L>Ons or &thorn;is dey VII &yogh;ere:</L>
<L>At messe, at matyns ne at mele</L>
<L N="130">Thou take me neuer in &thorn;i prayere!</L>
<L>Loke, sone, &thorn;ou do, as I &thorn;e sey,</L>
<L>The(re)fore I werne &thorn;e wele beforne:</L>
<L>Fore euer &thorn;e more &thorn;ou prayst fore me,</L>
<L>My peynes schall be more &amp; more.</L>
<L N="135">Fare wele, he seyd, my dere sone!</L>
<L>The fader of heuen betech I &thorn;e.</L>
<L>And werne euery mane, where so &thorn;ou come,</L>
<L>Off wedloke-brekynge wer to be!"</L>
<L>The angell begane &thorn;e chyld to lede</L>
<L N="140">Sone out off &thorn;at wrechyd wone,</L>
<L>In-to a forest, was longe in brede.</L>
<L>The sone was vppe &amp; bry&yogh;ht it schone.</L>
<L>He lede hym to a feyre arbour &mdash;</L>
<L>The pathys wer of clene crystalle &mdash;</L>
<L N="145">That to hys fy&yogh;ht was passynge feyre</L>
<L>And als bry&yogh;t as any ber(i)alle.</L>
<L>The wallys semyd of gold bry&yogh;ht,</L>
<L>With dores &amp; with tourys stronge.</L>
<L>They herd vpone &thorn;e &yogh;atys on hyht</L>
<L N="150">Mynstralsy with angellus songe,</L>
<L>The pylycane &amp; &thorn;e popyne-Jay,</L>
<L>The tymour &amp; &thorn;e turtell trewe,</L>
<L>A hondreht M. on a rewe,</L>
<L>The ny&yogh;htyngale with notys newe.</L>
<L N="155">On a grene hyll he saw a (tre),</L>
<L>The fauour of it was stronge &amp; ftore;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. fauour.</NOTE></L>
<L>Pale it was &amp; w&amacr;ne of ble,</L>
<L>Lost it had &thorn;e frute &amp; floure.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. hat.</NOTE></L>
<L>A reufull sy&yogh;ht &thorn;at chyld gane se,</L>
<L N="160">And of &thorn;at sy&yogh;h(t) he hade grete drede,</L>
<L>"A, god lady, how may &thorn;is be?</L>
<L>The blode of &thorn;is tre lokys so rede."</L>
<L>The angelle seyd: "&thorn;is is &thorn;e tre</L>
<L>That god Adam &thorn;e frute forbede,</L>
<L N="165">And &thorn;erfore dryuene oute was he</L>
<L>And in &thorn;e erth hys lyffe he lede.</L>
<L>Fore in &thorn;e place &thorn;er thou seys it spred,</L>
<L>Grow &thorn;e appull &thorn;at Adam bote,<NOTE PLACE="foot">grow st. grew.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;at was thourhe Evys rede</L>
<L N="170">And &thorn;e deuyll of hell it wote.</L>
<L>When any synfull come here-Ine,</L>
<L>As &thorn;ou seyst, chyld, with me,</L>
<L>Fore vengawnce of &thorn;at cursyd synne</L>
<L>The blode rynneth oute of &thorn;is tre."<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. an hylle st. a tre.</NOTE></L>
<L N="175">He lede hym forth vpone &thorn;e pleyne:</L>
<L>He was wer of a pynnakyll py&yogh;ht:</L>
<L>Syche one saw he neuer none,</L>
<L>Off clothes of gold &thorn;at burnest bry&yogh;ht.</L>
<L>There vnder sate a creatoure</L>
<L N="180">Als bry&yogh;ht as any sonne-beme.</L>
<L>The angell dyde hym grete honoure.</L>
<L>"Lo, son, he seyd, &thorn;is is &thorn;i neme:<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;i neme = &thorn;in eme.</NOTE></L>
<L>Thy (fader) bro&thorn;er &thorn;ou may sene,<NOTE PLACE="foot">feyre st. fader.</NOTE></L>
<L>In heuens blys with-outen ende.</L>
<L N="185">So my&yogh;ht &thorn;i fader wele a bene,<NOTE PLACE="foot">a = haue.</NOTE></L>
<L>And he to wedloke had be kynde.</L>
<L>Therefore he hath gete hym helle</L>
<L>Endles in &thorn;at depe dongeone,</L>
<L>There euer-more forto duelle,</L>
<L N="190">Fore in helle is no redempcione."</L>
<L>Man, fro myscheff the amend,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou may syte all saue fro care.</L>
<L>Fro dedly synne god &thorn;e defende,</L>
<L>And vnto blys &thorn;i saull schall fare.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="19" TYPE="legend"><PB REF="00000509.tif" N="[371]">
<HEAD>19. S. Giles, von Lydgate, aus Ms. Harl. 2255, fol. 95b.</HEAD>
<DIV3 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Off Agamenoun vndir the large empire,</L>
<L>Born in Athenys, of grekys roial lyne,</L>
<L>Blissid Giles, thy grace lat enspire</L>
<L>In-to my penne, the tratys tenlvmyne;</L>
<L N="5">Cast doun thy look, lat the streemys shyne</L>
<L>Of thy tweyn eyen, this processe to con|veye,</L>
<L>Bynfluence of grace, which is divyne,</L>
<L>Me to directe of that I wolde seye:</L>
<L>In thy worship compendiously to write,</L>
<L N="10">By a maneer breef compilacioun</L>
<L>To remembre, so as I can endite,</L>
<L>Thy glorious lyff, thy conversacioun,</L>
<L>Thoruh al the world in every regioun</L>
<L>Rad and rehersyd, bexaumplysful notable,</L>
<L N="15">Lyk a myrrour of contemplacioun</L>
<L>To folk that cast them in vertu to be stable.</L>
<L>A litil glene gadryd in the feeld</L>
<L>Tween large shokkys of parfit hoolynesse,</L>
<L>Mong grete shevys that I ther beheeld</L>
<L N="20">To gadryn vp eerys did my besynesse,</L>
<L>Greyn tryed out, celestial of swetnesse,</L>
<L>To fostre and feede folk contemplatyff,</L>
<L>Ful in purpoos breeffly to expresse</L>
<L>Sentenciously thy myraclys and thy lyff:</L>
<L N="25">Wherupon, my purpoos to fulfylle,</L>
<L>By goddys grace, fortvne or aventure</L>
<L>Ther was to me brouht a litil bille</L>
<L>Of gret devocioun by a creature,</L>
<L>Requeryng me to do my besy cure</L>
<L N="30">Afftir the tenour oonly for Giles sake</L>
<L>Out of latyn translate that scripture,</L>
<L>Folwyng the copee this labour vndirtake.</L>
<L>To whos requeste I lowly did obeye,</L>
<L>Breefly this stoory to put in remem|braunce,</L>
<L N="35">Long processe lefft, took the nexte weye &mdash;</L>
<L>For shorte meetrys don gladly gret ple|saunce,</L>
<L>By cleer repoort rehersyd the substaunce,</L>
<L>Prolixite forto sette a-syde;</L>
<L>Bood no lenger, but gan my penne avaunce,</L>
<L N="40">Trustyng seyn Gile forto be my guyde.</L>
<L>Compendiously was remembrid thus,</L>
<L>So as in ordre I shal rehersen heer.</L>
<L>Thy fadir was namyd Theodorus,</L>
<L>Callyd Pellagia was thy moodir deer,</L>
<L N="45">Of roial blood bothe born I-feer;</L>
<L>Thy youthe fostryd, bookys determyne,</L>
<L>With dilligence, vertu forto leer</L>
<L>And profite in vertuous disciplyne.</L>
<L>Thus disposyd in vertu to profite,</L>
<L N="50">Lyk thy maistris, which tauht the spelle &amp; reede,</L>
<L>Tendre of age gretly list delite,</L>
<L>As seith thy liff, in almesse-deede:</L>
<L>Of compassioun castist of thy weede,</L>
<L>Gaff it freely to oon that quook for cold:</L>
<L N="55">Which was maad hool, refresshyd in his neede &mdash;</L>
<L>First myracle in thy legende toold.</L>
<L>Fadir, moodir anoon as they were ded,</L>
<L>Thu dist reioisshe ther tresour and rich|esse,</L>
<L>Thy patrymonye for moost goodly speed</L>
<L N="60">Thu gaff to poore of merciful almesse.</L>
<L>Anothir poysowned, the venym dist re|presse;</L>
<L>To oon also, with a feend travayled,</L>
<L>Thy prayer and expert hoolynesse</L>
<L>To his recure hath souereynly avayled.</L>
<L N="65">Thy myraclys sprad in thy contre,</L>
<L>For teschewe veynglory and fals pryde</L>
<L>Of perfeccioun, fleddist ovir the se,
<PB REF="00000510.tif" N="372"></L>
<L>Preysyng of peeple forto sette asyde.</L>
<L>Vnto shipmen savacioun and guyde,</L>
<L N="70">Madist the tempest graciously asswage</L>
<L>And fro perisshyng dist so for them pro|vide,</L>
<L>From al pereil to fortune ther passage.</L>
<L>Sike and poore thu list also visite,</L>
<L>And alle that wern in tribulacioun.</L>
<L N="75">Of the wydewe, callid Theocrite,</L>
<L>To hir douhtir thu were sauacioun,</L>
<L>Of oold langoure hir consolacioun;</L>
<L>To al the contre pleynyng for skarsete,</L>
<L>By thy prayer and mediacioun</L>
<L N="80">They did habounde with gracious plente.</L>
<L>Whan the heremyte Veredemyus</L>
<L>Was ferre absent &mdash; thy stoory doth ex|presse &mdash;</L>
<L>Thoruh thy meryt notable and vertuous</L>
<L>Thu madyst a penaunt hool from al sik|nesse.</L>
<L N="85">Toward desert thy Journe thu dist dresse;</L>
<L>With coold watir and herbys rauh and greene</L>
<L>Complet thre yeer &mdash; thy stoory berith witnesse &mdash;</L>
<L>Laddist thy liff, of colour pale and leene.</L>
<L>God of his grace had vpon the mynde:</L>
<L N="90">Lyst ordeyne, for a restoratyff,</L>
<L>To thy repaast whit as snowh an hynde</L>
<L>With plentevous mylk, to fostre therby thy liff.</L>
<L>Myd sharpe breerys, thu were contem|platyff,</L>
<L>Thy body peyned with rigerous conty|nence,</L>
<L N="95">Ageyn Sathan of custom was thy striff.</L>
<L>Dauntyng thy flessh by vertuous ab|stinence,</L>
<L>Thy foode was nouthir on flessh nor fissh,</L>
<L>Sool by thy-silff in a desert place,</L>
<L>Othir deyntees cam noon in thy dissh</L>
<L N="100">But frute and rootis, which thu dist up race &mdash;</L>
<L>Beestys reioisshyng to looke vpon thy face;</L>
<L>Moong sharp busshys keptist thy hermy|tage;</L>
<L>As I toold erst, among by goddys grace</L>
<L>Soowk of an hynde which that was savage.</L>
<L N="105">Thus of custom the hynde kept hyr tyme</L>
<L>At certeyn houres duryng ful thre yeer:</L>
<L>Wente in pasture, gresyng fro the pryme;</L>
<L>Toward mydday she cam with ful glad cheer,</L>
<L>Of god provided to be thy vitaleer,</L>
<L N="110">With a repaast of(hyr) mylk moost soote;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. thy st. hir.</NOTE></L>
<L>She was thy cook, she was thy boteleer,</L>
<L>Ageyn the constreynt of hungir to do boote.</L>
<L>This myracle and this vnkouth thyng</L>
<L>Was at Tuskan, to Gascoigne adiacent,</L>
<L N="115">Vpon Burgoyne regnyng ther as kyng,</L>
<L>As I reede, his name was Fluent,</L>
<L>Which in huntyng set al his entent,</L>
<L>Curteys, gentyl in al his governaunce;</L>
<L>To conclude shortly in sentement,</L>
<L N="120">He was soget to the kyng of Fraunce.</L>
<L>At Mount-pilerys holdyng his soiour,</L>
<L>As thy stoory, Giles, makyth mynde,</L>
<L>Vpon a day the kyng with gret lobour,</L>
<L>Al his meyne, noon was lefft behynde,</L>
<L N="125">Houndys vncouplyd, to chasen at thyn hynde,</L>
<L>Royal lymerys, with alauntys huge.</L>
<L>Thy beeste swift lefft hem echoon behynde,</L>
<L>Ran to thy feet for socoure and refuge.</L>
<L>The kyng, the bisshop, thy stoory who list reede,</L>
<L N="130">Of that kyngdam, cam to thy presence:</L>
<L>Hurt with an arwe sauh thy wounde bleede,</L>
<L>Proferyd amendys and gold for ther offence.</L>
<L>The kyng in wyl thy wrong to recompence,</L>
<L>By the assigned of hool affeccioun</L>
<L N="135">To bylde of monkys in goddis reverence</L>
<L>A monasterye withynne his regioun:</L>
<L>At thy request the bisshop and the kyng</L>
<L>Condescendid, with a condicioun:</L>
<L>That thu woldist accomplissh ther askyng</L>
<L N="140">To been abbot of that religioun,</L>
<L>Sett a ground of hih perfeccioun</L>
<L>By good exaunple, take of thy persone,</L>
<L>And of desert leve thy mansioun</L>
<L>For comoun profit, and lyve nat so allone.</L>
<L N="145">At ther prayer with al hvmylite
<PB REF="00000511.tif" N="373"></L>
<L>In thyn avys thu were condescendid,</L>
<L>That the religioun myht encreesid be</L>
<L>By thy presence, and vertuously amen|did &mdash;</L>
<L>Circumstauncis breefly comprehendid:</L>
<L N="150">Thoruh oo persone, often hath be prevyd,</L>
<L>Al a religioun myhte been amendid,</L>
<L>By oo good man socouryd and relevid.</L>
<L>In this mateer it needith nat to tarye.</L>
<L>To daunte thy flessh &mdash; the trouthe was weel seene &mdash;</L>
<L N="155">Whan thu leftist to been solitarye,</L>
<L>Feedyng thy-silf with rootis rawh and greene,</L>
<L>Drank welle watir, of colour megre &amp; leene;</L>
<L>Thy wounde open, thy blood distillyng doun</L>
<L>As dewy droopys ageyn the sonne sheene,</L>
<L N="160">Ay to remembre on Cristis passioun:</L>
<L>Prayeng the lord duryng al thy liffe,</L>
<L>Bexperience as it was afftir founde,</L>
<L>In remembraunce of Cristis woundys five</L>
<L>That evir bleedyng shuld be thy wounde,</L>
<L N="165">That no leeche with salue shulde founde</L>
<L>Thy grevous hurt to staunche it or to bynde,</L>
<L>Cristis carectis, large, wyde and rounde</L>
<L>Eternally tenpreente hem in thy mynde.</L>
<L>The sayd abbey accomplisshid and I|wallyd,</L>
<L N="170">The kyng present in his roial estat</L>
<L>With the bisshop whan that thu were stallyd:</L>
<L>Meek of thy poort, nat pompous nor elat,</L>
<L>Lovyd and drad, with grace fortunat,</L>
<L>Launpe and lanterne of perfeccioun,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. launpe = laumpe.</NOTE></L>
<L N="175">Tauhtist thy sogettys eerly and eek lat</L>
<L>To profite in ther religioun;</L>
<L>Fastyng, wakyng, and liggyng hard a nyht,</L>
<L>To thy disciplis patroun and exaunplarye,</L>
<L>First at matynes settist vp the liht</L>
<L N="180">In eche party of the seyntuarye;</L>
<L>Kneelyng in chirche or in thy librarye</L>
<L>Evere in study or contemplacioun,</L>
<L>Pastor callid &mdash; nat a mercenarye;</L>
<L>With a bridil of castigacioun</L>
<L N="185">Madist thy flessh meekly to obeye</L>
<L>To the spirit, voyd of rebellioun.</L>
<L>Of alle thy werkys discrecioun bar the keye,</L>
<L>With hih prudence and no presumpcioun:</L>
<L>Tweyne of counsayl, equyte and resoun,</L>
<L N="190">Lyk a fadir peised rigour and clemence,</L>
<L>Tween thextremytees hate or affeccioun</L>
<L>Rewlyng thy covent vndir obedience,</L>
<L>Witt and discrecioun kept egal the ballaunce</L>
<L>Attwen cherisshyng and iust correcciouns;</L>
<L N="195">Thu bar the torche of prudent gover|naunce</L>
<L>Fro parcial drauht of fals dyuysiouns,</L>
<L>Resoun repressyd foreyn occasiouns,</L>
<L>With softe speeche and with woordys fayre</L>
<L>Wer sett a-syde alle rebelliouns &mdash;</L>
<L N="200">To thy precept was no soget contrayre.</L>
<L>Swifft of wynge, fliht of thy good fame</L>
<L>By cleer repoort cam to the audience</L>
<L>Of kyng Charlys, and of thy parfiht name.</L>
<L>Wherof supprysed, with spiritual fer|vence</L>
<L N="205">By auctoryte of royal excellence</L>
<L>Sent to the devoutly by massage,</L>
<L>Beyng thy-sylf at Aralatence.</L>
<L>Toward hym holdyng thy viage,</L>
<L>Mettist a man which in his entraile</L>
<L N="210">Was oppressyd by the feendys myht &mdash;</L>
<L>A wykkyd goost so did hym assayle,</L>
<L>Alle men feerful to comen in his siht.</L>
<L>But of compassioun and grace of Cristis myht</L>
<L>By thy prayer he was maad hool by grace.</L>
<L N="215">Afftir this myracle Charlys the noble knyht</L>
<L>In bothe his armys the meekly did enbrace.</L>
<L>The kyng lowly, with devout obeisaunce</L>
<L>Prayde, thu woldist in thyn orisouns</L>
<L>Haue hym dayly in thy remembraunce:</L>
<L N="220">Sith it stood so, for short conclusiouns,</L>
<L>He hadde offendid of froward mocioun</L>
<L>In a synne, terrible to descryve,
<PB REF="00000512.tif" N="374"></L>
<L>Nevere of purpoos in his oppynyoun</L>
<L>Therof to been confessyd in his lyve.</L>
<L N="225">Nat longe aftir, beyng at thy masse,</L>
<L>By gret avys praidest for the kyng</L>
<L>In thy Memento, list nat lihtly passe.</L>
<L>Tyl Crist Jhesu grauntyd thyn axing,</L>
<L>In a bille the trespas rehersyng</L>
<L N="230">With goldene lettris, cast on the auhteer,</L>
<L>Brouht by aungil from hevene descendyng,</L>
<L>Of al the caas declaryng the maneer.</L>
<L>To mor encrees of this vnkouth my|racle &mdash;</L>
<L>As the bille in ordre did expresse &mdash;</L>
<L N="235">To thy request was maad noon obstacle:</L>
<L>"Crist hath foryove of his gret goodnesse</L>
<L>The kyngis gilt thoruh thy parfitnesse".</L>
<L>Alle circumstauncys pleynly out declarid,</L>
<L>Attween you too as thu dist hym confesse,</L>
<L N="240">Trewly in ordre, ther was no poynt I|sparid.</L>
<L>This vnkouth bille by an angil brouht</L>
<L>Cast on the auhteer, briht as the sonne shoon &mdash;</L>
<L>What was writen noman kneuh riht nouht,</L>
<L>Woord nor sillable, but thy-silf alloon;</L>
<L N="245">They gaff a liht lik a charboncle-stoon</L>
<L>Thoruh the Chapel &mdash; the scrowe shoon so sheene &mdash;</L>
<L>Among hem alle sothly was nat oon</L>
<L>Except thy-silff, knew what they did, meene:</L>
<L>Grauntyd to the for a prerogatiff,</L>
<L N="250">In this bille with this addicioun:</L>
<L>"What synful man list amende his liff</L>
<L>Ful repentaunt with contricioun</L>
<L>And the sacrament with confessioun,</L>
<L>The lord above shal hem to mercy take</L>
<L N="255">Thoruh thy prayeer and hooly orisoun,</L>
<L>So that they list ther synne to forsake".</L>
<L>Charlys restoryd vnto goostly helthe</L>
<L>By thy notable informacioun,</L>
<L>To gret encrees of this wordly welthe</L>
<L N="260">And gret prosperite of al his regioun,</L>
<L>At thy departyng from his roial dongoun</L>
<L>To dissevere ye tweyne were so loth:</L>
<L>Of fervent love and trewe affeccioun &mdash;</L>
<L>Thy lyff remembrith, that ye wepte bothe.</L>
<L N="265">Repeyryng hom, by thy decert, ay morid</L>
<L>Bencrees in vertu &mdash; Crist Jhesu was thy speed &mdash;</L>
<L>A dukys sone was to liff restoryd</L>
<L>By thy prayeer, which lay affore the deed.</L>
<L>Among thy brethre with obeissaunce &amp; dreed,</L>
<L N="270">Comyng hom, brouht in with glad visage,</L>
<L>Abood nat longe, clad in a pilgrym weed</L>
<L>Toward Rome madist thy viage &mdash;</L>
<L>Cause of thy goyng in thy liff expressyd</L>
<L>Was of gret &yogh;el and gret affeccioun,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;el = zeal.</NOTE></L>
<L N="275">Ful weel expert, for grace hath so dressyd</L>
<L>Thy pilgrymage toward Rome toun,</L>
<L>And to expleite al thyn entencioun</L>
<L>Noon obstacle, as it is comprehendid.</L>
<L>To thy request and iust peticioun</L>
<L N="280">Graciously the Poope is condescendid.</L>
<L>Gret heed he took to thyn hoolynesse</L>
<L>And to thy famous gret hvmylite,</L>
<L>Sette thy chirche for evir in sikyrnesse</L>
<L>And thy religioun in tranquillite,</L>
<L N="285">By bulle asselyd, with many liberte,</L>
<L>Peynnes annexid by ful hard sentence</L>
<L>Ageyn alle tho that of iniquite</L>
<L>To thy covent did violence.</L>
<L>And by anothir favourable sygne,</L>
<L N="290">Of god enspired, the pope did his peyne,</L>
<L>Lyk a fadir gracious and benygne</L>
<L>Putte thy freedamys to stonden in cer|teyne:</L>
<L>Vnto thyn hous he gaff doorys tweyne</L>
<L>By crafft out-corve, wrouht by fressh entaille,</L>
<L N="295">Maugre alle tho that list at it disdeyne &mdash;</L>
<L>Thyn hous tenpugne they shal nat pre|vaylle.</L>
<L>Thes seid doorys corve out of cipresse,</L>
<L>Brouht to Tibre they fond noon obstacle,</L>
<L>Next to that stronde, thy stoory seith ex|presse,</L>
<L N="300">They fro Tibre conveid by myracle</L>
<L>To thy closet and litil tabernacle,</L>
<L>Brouht to londe with gret solennyte</L>
<L>Afore thy steepil with many fressh pynacle.</L>
<L>In which doorys, who lyst thy stoory se,
<PB REF="00000513.tif" N="375"></L>
<L N="305">Was hool complet lyff of the apostlys twelue</L>
<L>In fressh picture, with liffly quyk ymages &mdash;</L>
<L>Thouh Pygmaleon hadde be ther hym|selve,</L>
<L>He coude haue maad no goodliere visages &mdash;</L>
<L>Reised bentaile vpon smale stages,</L>
<L N="310">Garnysshed with gold, fret with stoonys ryche.</L>
<L>Blissid Giles, by thy pilgrymages</L>
<L>Thu gat thes lowkys, to which ther be noon liche:</L>
<L>Kept in thy chirche for a memorial,</L>
<L>Tokne of ful graunt and confirmacioun</L>
<L N="315">That thy mynstre in especial</L>
<L>Fraunchysed was, for pleyn conclusioun,</L>
<L>From al maneer Jurediccioun</L>
<L>Of foreyn poweer, by thyn hoolynesse,</L>
<L>Prelat nor prynce of no presumpcioun</L>
<L N="320">Thy libertees nor fraunchise to oppresse.</L>
<L>By a spirit oonly of profecye</L>
<L>Knewh beforn whan thu shuldist pace;</L>
<L>Thy brethren present, with many wepyng ye,</L>
<L>On a sonday kneelyng in the place</L>
<L N="325">Spreynt with teerys lookyng on thy face,</L>
<L>Whan that thu gaff, as I can remembre,</L>
<L>Thy goost to god, conveied vp by grace</L>
<L>With hooly angelis, moneth of Septembre.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="section">
<HEAD>Oratio ad scm Egidium.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>O gracious Gile, of poore folk cheef patroun,</L>
<L N="330">Medicyne to syk in ther distresse,</L>
<L>To alle needy sheeld and proteccioun,</L>
<L>Refut to wrechis, ther damagys to redresse,</L>
<L>Folk that were deed restoryng to quyk|nesse:</L>
<L>Sith thu of god wer choose to be so good,</L>
<L N="335">Pray for our synnes, pray for our wikkyd|nesse</L>
<L>To Crist Jhesu that bouht vs with his blood!</L>
<L>Cast vpon vs thy goodly pitous ye,</L>
<L>To our request thyn eerys doun enclyne,</L>
<L>For the love of Jhesu and Marie,</L>
<L N="340">Born in Bedleem, she a pure virgine;</L>
<L>And, as thu were triacle and medicyne</L>
<L>To kyng Charlys whan he in myscheef stood,</L>
<L>Teeche vs the weye by thy goostly doctryne</L>
<L>To love that lord that bouht vs with his blood!</L>
<L N="345">Geyn our enmyes which been in nombre thre:</L>
<L>The flessh, the world, the dreedful ful serpent,</L>
<L>Of thy grace and merciful pite</L>
<L>To thy servauntis that serve the of entent,</L>
<L>Ageyn al trouble be with hem present,</L>
<L N="350">Maugre the feend and his furyous mood;</L>
<L>Gracious Gile, be nevir from vs absent,</L>
<L>For love of Jhesu that bouht vs with his blood!</L>
<L>We put our trust and our affeccioun</L>
<L>In thy moost feithful prudent gover|naunce;</L>
<L N="355">Be thu our sheeld, our pavys and sheltroun,</L>
<L>That were so famous by myraclys in sub|staunce,</L>
<L>Wrouht by thy meryt, in Germanye and Fraunce,</L>
<L>Maugre Leviathan, mankyndis foo moost wood;</L>
<L>Ageyn whos werre have vs in remem|braunce</L>
<L N="360">To-fore that lord which bouht vs with his blood!</L>
<L>O myn a-vowe which callyd art seyn Gile,</L>
<L>Tween hoope and dreed moost meekly I requere:</L>
<L>Thynk on thy man, that labourid to compile</L>
<L>This litil ditee of hool herte and enteere!</L>
<L N="365">Haue mynde on alle that truste on thy prayeere,</L>
<L>For love of hym that starff vpon the rood!</L>
<L>Yiff thu be meene, we stonde no-thyng in weere</L>
<L>To have his mercy that bouht vs with his blood.</L>
<TRAILER><I>Explicit quod Lidgate.</I>
</TRAILER>

</LG>
</DIV3>
