<HEAD>Anhang.</HEAD>
<DIV2 N="1" TYPE="legend">
<HEAD>1) Meidan Maregrete,
aus Hickes Thes. I p. 224 (nach einem Ms. Trin. Coll. Cambr.).</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>Vgl. p. 211 ff. Der folgende Text der Margarete ist uns nur in dem Abdruck in Hickes' Thesaurus I p. 224 ff. erhalten, da die Hs. selbst, ein Ms. des Trin. Coll. Cbr., seit Hickes leider verloren gegangen ist; im Ganzen scheint der Hickes'sche Abdruck zuverl&auml;ssig zu sein; er ist wieder abgedruckt in O. Cockayne S. Marh. Dieser Text ist bedeutend &auml;lter als der des Ms. Auchinl. p. 212 ff. und reicht in die erste H&auml;lfte des 13. Jhdts. hinab. Dennoch ist er bereits sehr verderbt; das Original ist noch weit &auml;lter anzusetzen.</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Olde ant yonge, i preie ou . oure folies for to lete;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Hick, preit, Cock. prei. l. preie.</NOTE></L>
<L>&ETH;enchet on god &thorn;at yef ou wit . oure sunnes to bete!</L>
<L>Here i mai tellen ou . wid wordes feire ant swete</L>
<L>&ETH;e vie of one meidan, . was hoten Maregrete.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="5">Hire fader was a patria(r)c, . as ic ou tellen may,</L>
<L>In Auntioge wif e ches . i &eth;e false lay;<NOTE PLACE="foot">H eches = e (= he) ches; die Pronom. wurden in &auml;lteren Mss. gern mit dem Verb verbunden.</NOTE></L>
<L>Deve godes ant doumbe . he serued, nitt ant day, &mdash;</L>
<L>So deden mony o&thorn;ere, . &thorn;at singet weilaway.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Theodosius was is nome. . on Crist ne levede he noutt,</L>
<L N="10">He levede on &thorn;e false godes . &eth;at &THORN;eren wid honden wroutt.<NOTE PLACE="foot">weren mit Rune f&uuml;r w.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot">Nach v. 10 fehlen mehrere Verse,</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<P>. . . . .</P>
<LG>
<L>&ETH;o &thorn;at child sculde christine ben, . it com him well in &thorn;outt;<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;o st. &thorn;at?</NOTE></L>
<L>E bed: wen it were ibore, . to de&thorn;e it were ibroutt.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&ETH;e moder was an he&thorn;ene wif, . &thorn;at hire to wyman bere.</L>
<L>&ETH;o &thorn;at child ibore was, . nolde ho hit furfare;</L>
<L N="15">Ho sende it into Asye . wid messagers ful yare,</L>
<L>To a norice, &thorn;at hire wiste . ant sette hire to lore.
<PB REF="00000628.tif" N="490"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&ETH;e norice &thorn;at hire wiste, . children a heuede seuene &mdash;</L>
<L>&ETH;e eitte&thorn;e was Maregrete, . Cristes may of heuene;</L>
<L>Tales ho am tolde . ful feire ant ful euene,</L>
<L N="20">Wou ho &thorn;oleden martirdom, . sein Laurence ant seinte Steuene.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&ETH;e norice hire fedde . wid wel muchele wunne;</L>
<L>Alle loueden hire, . in &thorn;e toun &thorn;er ho was inne.</L>
<L>Ho toc hire to Jhesu Christ . ant leuede al hire cunne;</L>
<L>&ETH;o ho cou&thorn;e of wisdom, . ho hatede muche sunne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="25">Sone so &thorn;e maidan was . of &thorn;rettene winter elde,</L>
<L>Ho wiste hire norice scep . daies i &thorn;e felde.</L>
<L>Hir felawes &thorn;at hire biseten, . ful yerne hire bihulde<NOTE PLACE="foot">biseten surrounded.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wou ho makede ir bone . to Jhesu, &thorn;at al mai welde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Olibrius was louerd, . ase &thorn;e boc us telle,</L>
<L N="30">He haued Auntio&yogh;e, . to yeuen ant to selle;</L>
<L>He seruede nitt ant day . fendes in helle.</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;at leueden on Jhesu Christ . e heitt hem aquelle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>From Asie to Auntioge . bet miles tene ant fiue.</L>
<L>For to slen christene men . he hiede him biliue.</L>
<L N="35">E sei maiden Maregrete . scep biforen hire driue:</L>
<L>Sone wolde &thorn;e sarezin . habben hire to wiue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>He said to his serjauns: . "a maidan ic isee,</L>
<L>Faret somme of myne men . ant fatchet hire to me!</L>
<L>Bi my lay, yef ho is boren . of cunraden free,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H. cumraden, C. cunnraden.</NOTE></L>
<L N="40">Of all hire cunne . best scal hire bee.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ant for ir feirnesse, . &thorn;au ho bee comen of &thorn;relle,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H. &thorn;au, C. &thorn;an.</NOTE></L>
<L>Hire wedlac ne scal ho nout lesen all:</L>
<L>Ful wel ic scal ir clo&thorn;en . wid ciclatoun ant pelle,</L>
<L>Ho scal be my leuemon: . so me hire scal calle."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="45">&ETH;e sergaunz eden, ase he am bed, . to meidan Maregrete,</L>
<L>As a wist ir norice scep, . nout fer from &thorn;e strete.</L>
<L>Sone muchele a hire boden . ant more a hire bihete &mdash;</L>
<L>&ETH;e trou&thorn;e of hire herte . nolde ho nout furlete.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&ETH;e sergaunz deden ar ernde . feire ant fele si&thorn;e:</L>
<L N="50">"Meidan Maregrete, . nulle we nout mitte fike.<NOTE PLACE="foot">mitte = mit &thorn;e.</NOTE></L>
<L>Olibrius is louerd . of Auntio&yogh;e &thorn;e riche,</L>
<L>He wil het &thorn;e to wiue; . wel it may &thorn;e like."<NOTE PLACE="foot">H. wil het, wol. st. wilnet.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000629.tif" N="491"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Maidan Maregrete, . britt so eni leme,</L>
<L>Sone ham onswerede . wid wel milde steuene:</L>
<L N="55">"Ic abbe iyeuen my maidanhod . Jhesu Christ of heuene &mdash;</L>
<L>He me wite to-day . for is nomen seuene.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Jhesu Christ my louerd, . &eth;at deet &thorn;olede for us alle,</L>
<L>&ETH;e heie king of heuene, . to him wol ic calle.</L>
<L>Of mine stable herte . ne lete ir neuer at-falle,<NOTE PLACE="foot">ir st. me?</NOTE></L>
<L N="60">Ne lete neuere my bodi . to-dai in sunne falle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Jhesu Christ mi louerd, . to &thorn;e ic wile me yelde,<NOTE PLACE="foot">yelde st. rende.</NOTE></L>
<L>&ETH;ou neuedest bigunne . ne neuer neuedest ende;</L>
<L>Yef &thorn;i wille were, . &thorn;e holi gost &thorn;ou me sende,</L>
<L>&ETH;at from &thorn;e saresinz . i mitte me defende!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="65">Al my cun i fursake . to &thorn;e ni&thorn;e cne,</L>
<L>Jhesu Christ my louerd, . to &thorn;e i take me;</L>
<L>For &thorn;i loue here . martir woll i bee.</L>
<L>&ETH;es houndes habbet me biset, . ne mai ic henne fle."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&ETH;e sargaunz ayein eden . ant seiden here sawe:</L>
<L N="70">"Of alle &thorn;ine mitte . ne yeued ho word an hawe,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H. ati st. an. word = wor&thorn;.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of all &thorn;at we saiden . al ir &thorn;unchet plawe;</L>
<L>Ho leued on Jhesu Christ, . to waraunt ho him drawet."<NOTE PLACE="foot">H. leued, C. leuet.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&ETH;enne spec Olibrius &mdash; . awarie him sonne ant mone! &mdash;:</L>
<L>"Of alle mine sergauns . gode nabbi none.</L>
<L N="75">Bringet hire bifore me! . ic turne hir mod ful sone,</L>
<L>Ho scal leuen o mine godes, . er halfuey to none."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&ETH;e sergaunz ayein eden . ant cunnen hire imete,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H. cunnen, = gunnen; C. unrichtig cumen.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ho leiden honden hire upon . ant ledden ir to &thorn;e strete.</L>
<L>Ho com biforn Olibrius. . ant he hire con grete,</L>
<L N="80">He asked what ir nome was . . ho seide: Maregrete.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Meidan Maregret, . my leuemon &thorn;ou scal bee,</L>
<L>Ant habben (!) &thorn;e to wive, . yef &thorn;u art of cunne fre;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ant st. to? oder l. Ic habbe.</NOTE></L>
<L>Yef &thorn;ou art of &thorn;relles, . ic yeue &thorn;e gold ant fee.</L>
<L>&ETH;ou scalt be my leuemon, . so long so ic be."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="85">&ETH;e meidan him onswerede . swi&thorn;e feire anon:</L>
<L>"Christine wiman ic am . iheuen of &thorn;e fonston.</L>
<L>Jhesu Christ my louerd, . to him ic wille gon,</L>
<L>I nule leten is loue . for o&thorn;er neuer on."
<PB REF="00000630.tif" N="492"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Leuestou on Jhesu Christ? . men deden him o rode;</L>
<L N="90">Yef &thorn;ou leuest &thorn;at e leuet, . ic holde &thorn;e for wode.</L>
<L>Of is side orn adoun . &thorn;e water ant te blode,</L>
<L>&ETH;e croune was of &thorn;ornes . &thorn;at on is heued stode."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&ETH;e meidan him answerede, . ase &thorn;e an&yogh;el hire kende:</L>
<L>"Ye deden him on rode . al christine folc ta-mende.</L>
<L N="95">Ant se&thorn;en in-to helle . &thorn;e holi gost he sende,</L>
<L>To alesen christine men &mdash; . ant &thorn;ider &thorn;ou scalt wende."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&ETH;o isei &thorn;e saresin . &thorn;at him nes no bot<NOTE PLACE="foot">H. ues st. nes.</NOTE></L>
<L>To str(i)uen wid &thorn;at meidan &mdash; . ir herte was so god.<NOTE PLACE="foot">H. struen.</NOTE></L>
<L>He bed &thorn;at ho bounden hire . bo&thorn;en hond ant fot</L>
<L N="100">Ant depe into prisun don: . turnen e wolde ir mod.<NOTE PLACE="foot">H. med.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Meidan Maregret . one nitt in prisun lai.</L>
<L>Ho com biforn Olibrius . on &thorn;at o&thorn;er dai.</L>
<L>"Meidan Maregrete, . lef up-on my lay!</L>
<L>Ant Jhesu &thorn;at tou leuest on . &thorn;ou do him al awey!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="105">Lef on me ant be my wif! . ful wel &thorn;e mai spede:</L>
<L>Auntioge ant Asie . scaltou han to mede;</L>
<L>Ciclatoun ant purpel pal . scaltou haue to wede;</L>
<L>Wid alle &thorn;e metes of my lond . ful wel i scal &thorn;e fede."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Alle &thorn;ine redes . i do ut of my &thorn;outt<NOTE PLACE="foot">H. ido.</NOTE></L>
<L N="110">Ant take me to Jhesu Christ, . &thorn;at me haued iwrott;</L>
<L>For he all &thorn;is middelerd . makede of rett noutt,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H. rett st. ritt = ri&yogh;t.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ant se&thorn;en mid is swete flesc . of helle he us boutt."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&ETH;enne spec Olibrius: . "nou it scal ben sene</L>
<L>Upon wam &thorn;ou leuest . ant wi &thorn;ou art so kene.</L>
<L N="115">Honget ir up bi &thorn;e fet, . hire louerd to tene,</L>
<L>Wid scourges betet hire fleisc, . &thorn;at ho ir deet wene!"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&ETH;e sergaunz deden &thorn;at he bed, . on hire gunne striue,</L>
<L>Wid swopen ant wid scourges . bo&thorn;e ful riue.</L>
<L>&ETH;e blod ron of hire fleisc . wnder-liche swi&thorn;e;<NOTE PLACE="foot">H. wnder lich.</NOTE></L>
<L N="120">Alle ho wenden . &thorn;at broutt a were of liue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&ETH;o spec Olibrius, . bi hire &thorn;er he stod:</L>
<L>"Meidan Maregrete, . is &thorn;is pine god?</L>
<L>Lef nou on my godes, . ant sone wend ti mod!</L>
<L>Haue merci of &thorn;i fleisc! . me spillet &thorn;i blod."
<PB REF="00000631.tif" N="493"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="125">"Jhesu Christ my louerd . was born ine Bedlehem,</L>
<L>On &thorn;e holi meidan . he sende litt ant glem.</L>
<L>&ETH;ou dest ase techet . satanas, &thorn;in em.<NOTE PLACE="foot">C. schaltet &thorn;e ein vor techet.</NOTE></L>
<L>Me &thorn;enchet &thorn;es pine swete . so eni milc rem."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&ETH;o spec Olibrius: . "nauet ho none care?<NOTE PLACE="foot">care st. awe.</NOTE></L>
<L N="130">Of al &thorn;ilke pine . al ir &thorn;unchet plawe.</L>
<L>Wid oure scarp nailes . ir hude al to-drawe,</L>
<L>Ase clene from &thorn;e fleisc . so hound it hede ignawe!"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&ETH;e sergaunz deden so, . to hire gonnen go,</L>
<L>Al &thorn;et fel from &thorn;e fleisc . gunnen ho to flo;</L>
<L N="135">Al &thorn;et blod &thorn;at in hire was . out it ede &thorn;o.</L>
<L>Al &thorn;is ho &thorn;olede, . ant o&thorn;ere pinen mo.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Summe &thorn;at ter stoden, . ar herte was ful sore,</L>
<L>For hire wite fleisc . ant for ir yelewe here.</L>
<L>"Maidan Maregrete, . of &thorn;e we habbet care;</L>
<L N="140">Lef on him ant be his wif! . ne &thorn;oele &thorn;ou so nan-more!"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Awei, ye euele consilers! . wi said ye so?<NOTE PLACE="foot">H. &thorn;e st. ye, beide male.</NOTE></L>
<L>Mit swopes ant mit scorges . habbe ye me flo.</L>
<L>Jhesu Christes angles . comet me to ant fro.</L>
<L>Al &thorn;is is my ioie, . ne do ye me so wo."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="145">&ETH;enne spec Olibrius: . "&thorn;is is oure pouste;</L>
<L>Er hauedestou eyen, . nou maistou nout isee.</L>
<L>Lef on me ant be my wif! . ful wel i rede &thorn;e;</L>
<L>Yef &thorn;ou leuest o&thorn;er-weis, . sclawen scaltou bee."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"&ETH;e godes &thorn;at tou leuest on . are dede ase a ston;</L>
<L N="150">Of my louerdes ioie . ne mai tellen no mon.</L>
<L>Nou &thorn;ou hauest pouste . of my fleisce ant bon,</L>
<L>To deruen myne soule . pouste nauestou non."<NOTE PLACE="foot">deruen afflict, so Old Engl. Misc. 225, 85-</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Olibrius heist(!) . &thorn;at mai in prisun don.<NOTE PLACE="foot">H. heist; orig. wol heitt.</NOTE></L>
<L>&ETH;e holi gost from heuene . to hire com ful son,</L>
<L N="155">Ant &thorn;e rode in his hond . &thorn;at Christ was on idon,</L>
<L>Ant scon ase britt . so sonne abouten none.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Meidan Maregrete, . &middot;ne drede &thorn;ou nowid?<NOTE PLACE="foot">nowid st. nowitt = nowi&yogh;t.</NOTE></L>
<L>&ETH;i sege is maked in heuene . biforen Jhesu ful britt.</L>
<L>Nis no ton&yogh;e an er&thorn;e, . ne non eyen litt,</L>
<L N="160">&ETH;at mai telle &thorn;e ioie . &thorn;at was maket of &thorn;e to-nitt.
<PB REF="00000632.tif" N="494"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Meidan Maregrete, . britt so eny leme,</L>
<L>Iblesset wort &thorn;ou to-dai . of al &thorn;at i con neme.</L>
<L>&ETH;e heie king of heuene . ful wel hauet herde &thorn;i steuene:</L>
<L>He &thorn;e sende &thorn;is crois, . &thorn;ine fon to aferene."<NOTE PLACE="foot">H. fou st. fon.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="165">"Blessed be Jhesu Christ . &thorn;at me bote sende,</L>
<L>Ant is holi angel, . to me &thorn;at he wende!</L>
<L>Fader ant sone ant holi gost, . &thorn;at alle us mai amende,</L>
<L>Ne lete neuer to-dai . myne herte wende!"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Meidan Maregrete . lokede hire bi-side:.</L>
<L N="170">Ho sei a foul dragun . ine &thorn;e hurne glide,</L>
<L>Berninde ase fur, . ant goninde ful wide;</L>
<L>He wert ase grene . so gres ine someres tide.<NOTE PLACE="foot">H ho st. he.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&ETH;e fur flei of is mou&thorn;e . so leie of brenston.</L>
<L>Ho fel to &thorn;en er&thorn;e . ant quakede uich bon.</L>
<L N="175">He nom ir in is mou&thorn;e . ant swalen hire anon.<NOTE PLACE="foot">ant st. to?</NOTE></L>
<L>He barst a two peces, . felawe nauede he non.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Meidan Maregrete . upon &thorn;e dragun stod;</L>
<L>Bli&thorn;e was ir herte, . ioiful was ir mod:</L>
<L>Sclawen was &thorn;e dragun . &thorn;oru &thorn;e uertu of &thorn;e rod.</L>
<L N="180">"Blessed be Jhesu Christ! . is mitten is so god."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Meidan Maregret . &thorn;e dragun ede fro:</L>
<L>Ho sei ano&thorn;er deuel . &thorn;er-inne &thorn;o.</L>
<L>E heuede eien on is cleu . ant eken on is to&mdash;</L>
<L>Ne mitte foulore &thorn;in&yogh; . neuer (on) er&thorn;e go.<NOTE PLACE="foot">on fehlt vor er&thorn;e.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="185">Ho wende to &thorn;e lo&thorn;e &thorn;ing, . &thorn;e rode in hire hond,</L>
<L>&ETH;oru &thorn;e mitte of Jhesu Christ . wid her wempel ho hin bond,</L>
<L>Ho toc him bi &thorn;e toppe, . abouten ho him swong,</L>
<L>Sette ir fot in is necke . ant to &thorn;en er&thorn;e wrong.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Sai me nou&thorn;e wat tou art, . &thorn;ou foule lo&thorn;e &thorn;in&yogh;,</L>
<L N="190">Upon wam &thorn;ou bileuest . ant wo is &thorn;i kin&yogh;,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H. wo, C. wa.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ant wo &thorn;e hider sende . to maken stourbing;</L>
<L>Tel me nou swi&thorn;e, . ant into helle spring!"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Leuedi, for &thorn;e rode loue . &thorn;at is i &thorn;ine honde,</L>
<L>Hef up &thorn;i fot a littel . &thorn;at ine myn necke stond!</L>
<L N="195">Muchel ic habbe iwalken . bi water ant bi londe,</L>
<L>Nas ic neuer ibounden . in so harde bonde.
<PB REF="00000633.tif" N="495"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ruffin was my bro&thorn;er, . &thorn;at tou here sclowe;</L>
<L>&ETH;e wile e was aliue, . e cou&thorn;e sunnes inowe;</L>
<L>E dede men to sunne &mdash; . &thorn;ere-fore we loude lowe</L>
<L N="200">Ant yeld here seruise . ofte mid muchele wowe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>In a dragones liche . i sende him to &thorn;e,</L>
<L>To turne &thorn;ine herte . ant apaie me.</L>
<L>He is iborsten a-two, . ibounden hauestou me &mdash;</L>
<L>A maidain (!) hauet us ouercomen, . noutt nis oure pouste!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="205">Belsebug is my nome &mdash; . i ne may &thorn;e nout lie &mdash;</L>
<L>Ne mai ic longe &thorn;olien . &thorn;e pine &thorn;at i drie.</L>
<L>Al ic wolde biswike . &thorn;at i sen mitte mid eie &mdash;</L>
<L>Nab ic none mitte . &thorn;e nou to struye.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Wen ic wist a wif . sculde be bet of berne,</L>
<L N="210">Ic com &thorn;ider sone, . swift as an erne,</L>
<L>Ant, wen i &thorn;ider come, . to-croke fot o&thorn;er arme;<NOTE PLACE="foot">to st. it? od. l. i croked it.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ant te wif ir-selue . i fonde to furfarne."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Haue &thorn;i pais, &thorn;ou foule &thorn;ing! . &thorn;ou fli into helle &mdash;</L>
<L>Ne be &thorn;ou so hardi . lengore &thorn;at tou duelle!</L>
<L N="215">I bidde Jhesu Christ . &thorn;i mitte &thorn;at he felle.</L>
<L>&ETH;ou fal into helle, . so ston deet into welle!"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Upon &thorn;et o&thorn;er dai . a lute biforn non</L>
<L>Olibrius heitte &thorn;e mai . ut of prisun don.</L>
<L>&ETH;e sergaunz were snelle . ant broutten hire son,</L>
<L N="220">Wid &thorn;e rode on hire honde . &thorn;at Christ was on idon.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&ETH;o spec Olibrius &mdash; . i-wis, e was ful wroet &mdash;</L>
<L>Ant saide to is sergaunz: . "wonder, wou ho goet.</L>
<L>"Lef on me, Maregrete, . ant haue mete ant cloet!</L>
<L>Do after me ant be my wif, . ne be &thorn;e &thorn;i lif so loet!"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="225">"Awaried wor&thorn;e &thorn;ine godes . &thorn;at tou leuest inne &mdash;</L>
<L>Ho weren yare awaried, . ant al ful of sunne;</L>
<L>Ho beet al of helle, . of satanas cunne.</L>
<L>Wene &thorn;ou wenest best to liue, . to him a wollet &thorn;e winne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ac do nou wel ant lef on him . &thorn;at made &thorn;e to mon:</L>
<L N="230">Fader ant sone ant holi gost, . &thorn;at &thorn;is world bigon,</L>
<L>Ant let &thorn;e folewen . in holi fonston,</L>
<L>Ase Jhesu Christ was ymself . y &thorn;e flem Jurdan!"
<PB REF="00000634.tif" N="496"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&ETH;enne spec Olibrius: . "a pine ic chulle kenne.</L>
<L>Wellinde laumpes . letet on hire renne,</L>
<L N="235">From &thorn;e necke to &thorn;e to, . scalden ir as an henne!</L>
<L>Bote ho turne hire mod, . to de&thorn;e ye sculen ir brenne."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&ETH;e sergaunz deden al-so: . ely letten ho welle,</L>
<L>Heie upon ir heuede . wallinde letten ho felle.</L>
<L>It orn on hire wite fleisc, . so water det of welle.</L>
<L N="240">&ETH;e holi gost ir wist, . ne mitten ho hire aquelle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Alle (!) weren &thorn;e saresinz, . so boc is writen wid enke,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H. Alle st. eille.</NOTE></L>
<L>To bringen hire of liue . ho gunnen hem bi&thorn;enke.</L>
<L>In a fet ful of water . ho gunnen hire adrencke.</L>
<L>"Ant bote ho turne hire mod, . &thorn;er a scal adrencke."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="245">"Louerd, yef &thorn;i wille is: . a water ic isee:</L>
<L>&ETH;rin ic chulle deien . for &thorn;e loue of &thorn;e."<NOTE PLACE="foot">Anders Ms. Auch. 316: let me cristen &THORN;erinne.</NOTE></L>
<L>&ETH;et fet bigon to bersten &mdash; . &thorn;e folc bigon to fle;</L>
<L>&ETH;e engel ir nom of &thorn;e water, . &thorn;at alle it mitten isee.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&ETH;er bileueden on Jhesu Christ . a &thorn;ousend ant fiue,</L>
<L N="250">Al widouten children . ant widouten wiue.</L>
<L>To don ham to de&thorn;e . he hiede biliue;</L>
<L>For ho leueden on Jhesu Christ, . he broutte hem of liue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Wel sey &thorn;e sarezin . ne mitte hire dere;</L>
<L>E clepede ford Malcus, . is monquellere,</L>
<L N="255">He bed leden hire widoute toun, . o&thorn;er hire bere,</L>
<L>Ant bringen hire of liue, . wid sworde o&thorn;er wid spere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&ETH;o ho com widout &thorn;e toun . &thorn;er me ir sculde sclo,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Im Folg. ist der Text abweichend von Auch. v. 341 ff.</NOTE></L>
<L>Al siwede hire . &thorn;at euer mitte go.</L>
<L>&ETH;e wind bigun to blowen, . &thorn;e sonne wert al blo:</L>
<L N="260">&ETH;et folc fel to &thorn;en er&thorn;e, . ne wisten ho hire nout &thorn;o.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ure lord sende to hire . a ful feire steuene,</L>
<L>Ant gon hire greten . ful feire ant wel euene:</L>
<L>"Blessed be &thorn;ou (to)-dai . mid al &thorn;at ic con nemme:<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. dai st. to-dai.</NOTE></L>
<L>To-day &thorn;ou scalt ben icrounet . biforn &thorn;e king of heuene."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="265">Malcus herde &thorn;es wordes: . he sette him acne.<NOTE PLACE="foot">H. acue.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Meidan Maregrete, . &thorn;i louerd hat speke wid &thorn;e,</L>
<L>Ant a &thorn;ousent angles . aboute &thorn;e i see.</L>
<L>Spred &thorn;in hond ant nym my swerde, . ant haue merci of me!"
<PB REF="00000635.tif" N="497"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&ETH;o spec &thorn;at meidan, . seinte Maregrete:</L>
<L N="270">"Bro&thorn;er, yef &thorn;i wil is, . abid a lutel yet,</L>
<L>&ETH;e wile i make my bone . to him &thorn;at may bete!</L>
<L>Bidde wat tou euer wile, . ic it wole gete.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Alle &thorn;at my lif . wollet heren o&thorn;er rede,</L>
<L>O&thorn;er for me cirche sette, . mid almes-dede,</L>
<L N="275">Jhesu Christ my louerd . mit monscipe &thorn;ou am fede;</L>
<L>&ETH;e heie blisse of hiuene . habben ho to mede.<NOTE PLACE="foot">l. heuene.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Alle &thorn;at habbet me aday . ine memorie</L>
<L>O&thorn;er mid gode herte . iheret myne vie,</L>
<L>Jhesu Christ my louerd, . sone sainte Marie,</L>
<L N="280">Haue merci of &thorn;e soules, . leie were &thorn;e bones lye!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Jhesu Christ my louerd, . wen wiman bet scal be,</L>
<L>Iher hire bone, . yef ho clepet to me;</L>
<L>Deliure hir myd menske . for &thorn;e loue of &thorn;e tre</L>
<L>&ETH;at tou dedest &thorn;i bodi on . to maken us alle fre!"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="285">&ETH;o spec ure louerd, . seinte Marie sone:</L>
<L>"Bi heuene, bi er&thorn;e, . bi sonne, bi mone,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H. soune.</NOTE></L>
<L>Maidan Maregrete, . i cui&thorn;e &thorn;e &thorn;i bone.</L>
<L>Cum into &thorn;e ioie, . &thorn;er &thorn;ou scalt euer wone."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Maidan Maregrete . ir bone hauede &thorn;enne.</L>
<L N="290">"Malcus, smit of myne heued! . furyeuen is &thorn;e &thorn;e sunne."</L>
<L>"&ETH;at ne dude ic nout . for al &thorn;is worldes wune;</L>
<L>&ETH;i louerd haet igrete te . &thorn;at tou leuest inne."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Bote &thorn;ou do ase i bidde, . ne scalt tou neuer haue</L>
<L>&ETH;e ioie &thorn;at is in heuene, . ne lif boute care."</L>
<L N="295">Malcus &thorn;is iherde, . is swerde e gon out drawe,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H. iherdes, C. vermuthet iherdet; l. iherde.</NOTE></L>
<L>Smot of hire heued &mdash; . &thorn;at wes hore lawe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Michael ant Gabriel . ant Raffael, here fere,</L>
<L>Cherubin ant Serafin, . a &thorn;ousend &thorn;er were,</L>
<L>Mit tapres ant mit sensers . to heuene he ir bere,</L>
<L N="300">To hore louerdes blisse; . ho was ym lef ant dere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Theodosius &thorn;e clerc, &mdash; . he wrot hire vie &mdash;</L>
<L>Hire nource &thorn;at hir wist . i &thorn;e toun of Asie,</L>
<L>Ho ir &thorn;ider beren . mid gode memorie,</L>
<L>Ant makeden an chirche . ant &thorn;erine maden hire to lie.
<PB REF="00000636.tif" N="498"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="305">Alle &thorn;at seke weren . ant &thorn;ider wolde go,</L>
<L>Hore hele haueden, . are a heden ir fro.<NOTE PLACE="foot">H. aheden = a eden; C. ver&auml;ndert unrichtig in ahe(le)den.</NOTE></L>
<L>&ETH;e heie king of heuene . lef us to don so</L>
<L>&ETH;at we habben &thorn;e blisse . &thorn;at lest euer ant oo!<NOTE PLACE="foot">H. ouer st. euer.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Of &thorn;e swete meidan . &thorn;is is hire vie.</L>
<L N="310">&ETH;e twenteu&thorn;e dai is hire . i &thorn;e time of iulie.<NOTE PLACE="foot">C. liest of st. is, H. is.</NOTE></L>
<L>Jhesu Christ &thorn;at was born . of seinte Marie,</L>
<L>For seinte Maregrete loue, of us haue mercie!<NOTE PLACE="foot">H. Far st. for.</NOTE></L>
<TRAILER>Amen. Amen. checun die Amen.
</TRAILER>

</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="2" TYPE="legend"><PB REF="00000637.tif" N="[499]">
<HEAD>2) Marienlegenden, zwei Fragmente.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>Die folgenden zwei Bruchst&uuml;cke geh&ouml;ren, nebst den p. 220 u. 329 ff. gedruckten und den 9 von der Sammlung des Ms. Vernon erhaltenen Marienlegenden, zu den wenigen Ueberresten dieser von der Reformation sp&auml;ter absichtlich ausgetilgten Legendengattung; man riss die Bl&auml;tter aus den Mss., um diese Dichtungen zu ver|nichten, und liess h&ouml;chstens den Anfang oder das Ende einer solchen Legende stehen, wenn auf demselben Blatte ein anderartiges Gedicht, welches man erhalten wollte, endete oder anfing. Das erste, nur in der letzten H&auml;lfte erhaltene, Fragment des Ms. Auchinl., welches erz&auml;hlt, wie ein "clerk" den Leib der Mutter Gottes zu sehen ver|langt, obwohl daf&uuml;r mit dem Verluste seiner Augen bedroht, steht in den sprachlichen Formen der, nur aus Ms. Vernon bekannten, aber ohne Zweifel weit &auml;lteren, mittel|l&auml;ndischen Sammlung von Marienlegenden nahe (vgl. Formen wie kem = came v. 7 u. Vern. Mar. II, 137, corn = chosen, Infin. auf en u. i), und scheint dieser Sammlung angeh&ouml;rt zu haben, obwohl von den im Index des Ms. Vern. angef&uuml;hrten Titeln dieser Sammlung keiner auf unser Fragment anwendbar scheint. &mdash; Das zweite Fragment des Ms. Thornton ist nur im Anfang und Ende erhalten, da nach v. 97 ein Blatt aus dem Ms. ausgerissen ist; dadurch ist der eigentliche Kern der Geschichte (von einem s&uuml;ndhaften Ritter, der von einem "friar" durch ein Wunder der Mutter Gottes bekehrt wird), das miraculum selbst, unkennbar. Es ist in 12 zeiligen Strophen, nach Art des Child of Bristol p. 315 ff., abgefasst und erscheint in den n&ouml;rdl. Formen der &uuml;brigen Gedichte desselben Ms. &mdash; Abschrift des 1. Fragments danke ich Prof. K&ouml;lbing. Von fol. 37 des Ms. Auch. ist ein L&auml;ngsstreifen abgerissen, mit den Anf&auml;ngen der Verse, die ich erg&auml;nze.</P></HEADNOTE>
<DIV3 N="1" TYPE="fragment">
<HEAD>I. Aus Ms. Auchinl., fol. 37b (c.).</HEAD>

<P>(Anfang fehlt)</P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><MILESTONE N="37b" UNIT="folio"> . . . . .</L>
<L>(An an)gel sche sent to him anon.</L>
<L>(He) gret &thorn;e clerk wi&thorn; milde steuen.</L>
<L>(Into) &thorn;e chamber when he gan gon,</L>
<L>(He w)as bri&yogh;ter &thorn;an ani leuen.</L>
<L N="5">(Leuen)no no sonnes bem</L>
<L>(In so)mers day nas neuer so bri&yogh;t,</L>
<L>(&THORN;an) &thorn;at angel, when he doun kem</L>
<L>(Into) &thorn;at hous about midni&yogh;t.</L>
<L>(He &thorn;o)u&yogh;t his hert schuld to-spring,</L>
<L N="10">(&THORN;o h)e gan on &thorn;at angel sen.</L>
<L>"(Mi) clerk, drede &thorn;e no-&thorn;ing,</L>
<L>(Grace) of god be ous bitven!</L>
<L>(Tidan)des now y &thorn;e bring</L>
<L>(Fram M)arie, our heuen quen;</L>
<L N="15">(I &thorn;e) telle certain tiding:</L>
<L>(If &thorn;ou) wilt hir bodi sen,</L>
<L>(If sen) &thorn;ou wilt &thorn;at leuedi bri&yogh;t,</L>
<L>(&THORN;is p)enaunce &thorn;ou most chesen:</L>
<L>(&THORN;ou m)i&yogh;t be siker, &thorn;ine ei&yogh;e-si&yogh;t</L>
<L N="20">(O&thorn;er &thorn;)i liif &thorn;ou schalt forlesen."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>(&THORN;e cler)k anon gan him bi&thorn;ink:</L>
<L>"(&YOGH;et y) can ano&thorn;er croke:
<PB REF="00000638.tif" N="500"></L>
<L>(Wi&thorn;) mi no nei&yogh;e y schal wink,</L>
<L>(&amp; wi&thorn;) mi no&thorn;er y schal loke;</L>
<L>(Mi wa)risoun y schal biswink</L>
<L N="25">(Til y) may sen opon a boke,</L>
<L>(&amp; haue) anowe mete &amp; drink."</L>
<L>(Gode) comfort to him he tok.</L>
<L>(He tok) to him anon gode hede:</L>
<L>"(Iwis, m)i no nei&yogh;e may me seruen</L>
<L N="30">(&THORN;er to) do wi&thorn; al mi dede;</L>
<L>(It is) ynou&yogh; til y schal steruen."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>(&THORN;e cl)erk him fair answerd o&yogh;ain:<NOTE PLACE="foot">o&yogh;ain st. a&yogh;en.</NOTE></L>
<L>"(Ich) do me alle in her manay.</L>
<L>(Sch)eu now what y schal mene</L>
<L N="35">(To) Mari, as y &thorn;e say.</L>
<L>(Hir s)eriaunt ichaue long ben;</L>
<L>(Wi&thorn; a)ll loue now ichir pray</L>
<L>(&THORN;at) ich mot hir ones sen</L>
<L>(Aper)tliche, er &thorn;an y day.</L>
<L N="40">(Whe)n y dye, sche &yogh;iue me grace</L>
<L>(To come) to hir wi&thorn; gode entent,</L>
<L>(To sen) hir bodi &amp; hir face."</L>
<L>(&THORN;e an)gel o&yogh;ain to heuene is went.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Fram heuen into &thorn;e clerkes bour,<MILESTONE N="38" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="45">Ri&yogh;t doun biforn his beddes fet,</L>
<L>&THORN;e angel ali&yogh;t wi&thorn; gret honour,</L>
<L>&amp; wel fair he gan him gret.</L>
<L>"Mari, &thorn;at bar our saueour,</L>
<L>He seyd, &thorn;ou schalt sen as sket."</L>
<L N="50">Wi&thorn; him &thorn;er com a gret odour,</L>
<L>Nas neuer no smel half so swete.</L>
<L>So swete a smel nas neuer non,</L>
<L>Of rose no of no spicerie,</L>
<L>As com in-to &thorn;at leueli won<NOTE PLACE="foot">leueli = loueli.</NOTE></L>
<L N="55">Befor &thorn;at leueliche compeynie.<NOTE PLACE="foot">leueli = loueli.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Wi&thorn; angel song &amp; miri play</L>
<L>Our leuedi adoun sche li&yogh;t</L>
<L>Into &thorn;e chaumber &thorn;er he lay,</L>
<L>&amp; seyd: "clerk, drede &thorn;e no-wi&yogh;t!"&mdash;</L>
<L N="60">&THORN;ei a man bi&thorn;ou&yogh;t him ay,</L>
<L>No schuld he reden apoin (!) ari&yogh;t</L>
<L>Hennes vn-to domesday</L>
<L>Hou fair sche is, &thorn;at maiden bri&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Hou bri&yogh;t sche is, no tong may telle&mdash;</L>
<L N="65">Yblisced mot hye euer ben!</L>
<L>Of heuen, of er&thorn;e &amp; of helle</L>
<L>Sche is emperice &amp; quene.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A mantel our leuedy vnfeld,</L>
<L>Bri&yogh;ter &thorn;an sonne &thorn;at schine&thorn; schire.</L>
<L N="70">"Clerk, drede &thorn;e nou&yogh;t, but be nov beld,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. nob beld.</NOTE></L>
<L>For &thorn;ou schalt haue &thorn;i desire;</L>
<L>&THORN;er-whiles &thorn;ou hast &thorn;ine ei&yogh;en in weld,</L>
<L>Avise &thorn;e wele of min atire,</L>
<L>Apertliche &thorn;ou me biheld,</L>
<L N="75">Bodi &amp; face, brest &amp; swire!"</L>
<L>Swire &amp; al hir bodi he sei&yogh;e,</L>
<L>When sche hadde to him spoken:</L>
<L>He loked on hir wi&thorn; his onei&yogh;e&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at o&thorn;er he held stille yloken.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="80">O&yogh;ain to heuen our leuedi went</L>
<L>Wel stillelich out of &thorn;at clos.</L>
<L>&THORN;e clerk held him foulely schent,</L>
<L>Amorwe, when &thorn;at he aros.</L>
<L>His &yogh;alu here he ha&thorn; al to-rent,</L>
<L N="85">&amp; in his hert sore him agros;</L>
<L>Al &thorn;us he seyd, &amp; him bi-ment:</L>
<L>"&THORN;is ni&yogh;t y saued on of mi fos;</L>
<L>Mi fo y spard, allas &thorn;at while!<NOTE PLACE="foot">Der Feind ist das eine, gerettete Auge.</NOTE></L>
<L>Sori icham, &amp; wele ich owe:</L>
<L N="90">Minei&yogh;e do&thorn; mi soule gile,</L>
<L>&amp; often bringe&thorn; it ful lowe."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ri&yogh;t in his chaumber, &thorn;er he stode,</L>
<L>Him &thorn;ou&yogh;t his liif was him ful lo&thorn;,</L>
<L>He wepe sore wi&thorn; dreri mode,</L>
<L N="95">&amp; out of his chaumber he go&thorn;.</L>
<L>"&THORN;at me no deined, ich was wode,</L>
<L>To loke wi&thorn; min ei&yogh;en bo&thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. deined, vgl. Old Engl. Misc. 228, 168: &thorn;at hem deynet not of to ete.</NOTE></L>
<L>Opon &thorn;at leuedi fair &amp; gode;</L>
<L>Y wot &thorn;erfore &thorn;at sche is wro&thorn;.</L>
<L N="100">Wro&thorn; sche is, &amp; wele sche may,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; me, &thorn;at am sinful chaitif,</L>
<L>&THORN;at y schuld hir so bitraye,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ichaue loued in al mi liif.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Euer me may rewe &thorn;at ich while</L>
<L N="105">&THORN;at y schuld for ani drede</L>
<L>Do Marie &thorn;at gret gile.
<PB REF="00000639.tif" N="501"></L>
<L>Allas, what schal me to rede?</L>
<L>Mi soule y brou&yogh;t in gret periil.</L>
<L>A, leuedi, for &thorn;i maidenhed</L>
<L N="110">For&yogh;iue me mi sinnes vile,</L>
<L>&amp; help me in &thorn;is muchel nede!</L>
<L>In &thorn;is nede &thorn;ou me saue,</L>
<L>&THORN;at y no be neuer forlorn;</L>
<L>Graunt me &thorn;at y &thorn;e craue,</L>
<L N="115">For his loue &thorn;at of &thorn;e was born!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A, leuedi, to me &thorn;ou li&thorn;e,</L>
<L>For care min hert wil to-riue;</L>
<L>Michel loue ichil &thorn;e ki&thorn;e</L>
<L>&amp; wor&thorn;schip &thorn;ine ioies fiue.</L>
<L N="120">Lene me grace, ano&thorn;er si&thorn;e</L>
<L>To se &thorn;i bodi wi&thorn;outen striue!</L>
<L>Bi so, ichil be bli&thorn;e</L>
<L>To be blinde in al mi liue.</L>
<L>In al mi liue ichil be glad</L>
<L N="125">In swiche penaunce forto ben,</L>
<L>Bi so &thorn;ou graunt &thorn;at y &thorn;e bad:</L>
<L>Efsones y mot &thorn;e sen."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Alday he was in sorwe strong;</L>
<L>&amp; after-ward &thorn;at com &thorn;e ni&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="130">His white honden hard he wrong,</L>
<L>He ne may for wo slepe no-wi&yogh;t.</L>
<L>He herd &thorn;an a miri song</L>
<L>Of angels &thorn;at were so bri&yogh;t;</L>
<L>Our leuedi com hem among,</L>
<L N="135">&amp; seyd: "clerk, drede (&thorn;e) no-wi&yogh;t!"&mdash;</L>
<L>Sche spac &thorn;e clerk so fair vntille:<NOTE PLACE="foot">&THORN;e fehlt im Ms.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Ich for&yogh;iue &thorn;e al &thorn;i gilt;</L>
<L>&THORN;i praier y schal fulfille:<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. mi st. &thorn;i.</NOTE></L>
<L>Loke on me, &yogh;if &thorn;at &thorn;ou wilt!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="140">&THORN;er-whiles &thorn;at &thorn;ou art hayl &amp; quert,</L>
<L>Biheld me wele euerich a bon!</L>
<L>Bi&thorn;enche in &thorn;ine owhen hert</L>
<L>&THORN;at warisoun no hastow non;</L>
<L>&THORN;ine axing sore schal &thorn;e smert,</L>
<L N="145">&YOGH;if &thorn;ou be blinde as ani ston;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou most liue in gret pouert,</L>
<L>(W)hen &thorn;ou hast &thorn;ine ei&yogh;en forgon.</L>
<L>When &thorn;ou forgos &thorn;i warldes wele,</L>
<L>&amp; loue of frendes, fremed &amp; sibbe,</L>
<L N="150">Angwis &thorn;ou most suffri fele,</L>
<L>In alle time &thorn;at &thorn;ou schalt libbe."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e clerk answerd, &amp; lou&yogh;:</L>
<L>"Min hert is ful of gret solas;</L>
<L>Icham bli&thorn;er &thorn;an brid on bou&yogh;,</L>
<L N="155">&THORN;at ich haue seyn &thorn;ine holy face;</L>
<L>Of al ioie ichaue anou&yogh;,</L>
<L>Sende me now, leuedi, of &thorn;i grace!&mdash;</L>
<L>To suffren wo mi body is tou&yogh;,</L>
<L>Bi so ich mot hauen a place:</L>
<L N="160">A place graunt me, Marie,</L>
<L>&THORN;at mi soule mot wone,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; ioie &amp; wi&thorn; melodye,</L>
<L>In heuen bifor &thorn;i swet sone!"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Sche seyd: "mi clerk, no wepe &thorn;ou nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="165">No make no mornand chere!</L>
<L>&THORN;i bon, &thorn;ou hast me bisou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Ich graunt &thorn;e in al maner:</L>
<L>In-to &thorn;at ioie &thorn;ou schalt be brou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>When &thorn;ou hast laten &thorn;i liif here,</L>
<L N="170">&THORN;at mi swete sone ha&thorn; wrou&yogh;t</L>
<L>To hem &thorn;at ben him leue &amp; dere.</L>
<L>Dere &thorn;ou art to me, ywis.</L>
<L>O&yogh;ain to heuen now ich mot wende;</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;ou schalt com in-to &thorn;at blis,</L>
<L N="175">When &thorn;ou hast laten &thorn;i liues ende."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Vp into heuen anon sche stey&yogh;e,</L>
<L>&THORN;er sche is quen &amp; leuedi corn.</L>
<L>&THORN;e clerk his ei&yogh;en fast he wrei&yogh;e,</L>
<L>He wende his si&yogh;t were forlorn.</L>
<L N="180">When it was day, ful wele he sei&yogh;e</L>
<L>&THORN;is warldes pride al him biforn.</L>
<L>"Merci, leuedi! he crid on hei&yogh;e,</L>
<L>Wele be &thorn;e time &thorn;at &thorn;ou were born!</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou were born of o wiman,</L>
<L N="185">Blisced be euer &thorn;e day!</L>
<L>&THORN;er liue&thorn; nowi&yogh;t &thorn;at telle can</L>
<L>&THORN;e ioie &thorn;at of &thorn;e springe&thorn; ay.
<PB REF="00000640.tif" N="502"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Leuedi, flour &amp; frout of Jesse,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou art maiden, gode &amp; hende,</L>
<L N="190">Godes moder, mild &amp; fre;</L>
<L>Michel &thorn;ou helpest al man-kende:</L>
<L>On &thorn;i seruaunt haue pite,</L>
<L>&amp; saue ous, lord, fram &thorn;e fende</L>
<L>&amp; graunt ous, &yogh;if &thorn;i wille be:<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. lord st. leuedi.</NOTE></L>
<L N="195">When we schul of &thorn;is warld wende,</L>
<L>When we schul wend out of &thorn;is liue,</L>
<L>Here our prayer &amp; our steuen:</L>
<L>Bring ous, for &thorn;ine ioies fiue,</L>
<L N="200">Into &thorn;e swete blis of heuen. Amen. Explicit.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="2" TYPE="fragment"><PB REF="00000641.tif" N="[503]">
<HEAD>II. De miraculo be(ate) Marie. Aus Ms. Thornton fol. 147.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Jhesu, lorde in trinyte,</L>
<L>&THORN;at was &amp; es and aye schall be,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou brynge vs to thi blyffe;</L>
<L>&THORN;e same blyffe &thorn;ou bryng vs to,</L>
<L N="5">Thou late vs neuer so menly do</L>
<L>Thy mirthis &thorn;at we mysse!</L>
<L>&YOGH;e &thorn;at will a storye lere,</L>
<L>A better Ensample may no-mane here,</L>
<L>Trewly, &thorn;ane es this.</L>
<L N="10">And by a knyght it sall be talde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at was hardy wyghte &amp; balde</L>
<L>And wondir wykked I-wysse.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>He was bothe fers and felle &mdash;</L>
<L>A fellere deuyll was noghte in helle,</L>
<L N="15">Ne none so lefe to do ill;</L>
<L>Weddid wyffes wolde he ta,</L>
<L>Maydyns, maryage alfwa</L>
<L>Blethely wolde he spill,</L>
<L>And refe lele m(en) . . . .<NOTE PLACE="foot">Das Blatt ist unten beschnitten.</NOTE></L>
<L N="20">So wexe . . . . .</L>
<L>Durf . . . . .</L>
<L>And who so did oghte hym agayne,</L>
<L>Full sone he garte &thorn;am be slayne &mdash;</L>
<L>So wexe he wikkede of will.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="25">Messe ne matyns wolde he none here,</L>
<L>Ne &yogh;itt no prechynge of no frere &mdash;</L>
<L>Thare-to hym was full lathe;</L>
<L>Who so stode vpe &amp; oghte fold faye,</L>
<L>He bade &thorn;ame ga in &thorn;e deuyll waye,</L>
<L N="30">And glomede als he were wrathe.</L>
<L>Hym ware wele leuer ga by &thorn;e water</L>
<L>&THORN;an for to here a frere clater &mdash;</L>
<L>Sa wexe he bryme and brathe;</L>
<L>Thaym were wele better ga &thorn;aire gate</L>
<L N="35">&THORN;an for to come vnto his &yogh;ate</L>
<L>To aske hym corne or clathe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>In &thorn;e lande &thorn;at tyme &thorn;er welke a frere,</L>
<L>A better clerke thurt na-mane here</L>
<L>Ne nane wyth eghne see,</L>
<L N="40">To teche mene &thorn;e redy lare</L>
<L>How &thorn;at &thorn;ay solde till heuene fare</L>
<L>&amp; euer in blys to bee.</L>
<L>So many a mane had he conuert</L>
<L>And ploukked &thorn;e fend owt of &thorn;aire herte</L>
<L N="45">Als apills ere on the tre.</L>
<L>&THORN;is knyght &thorn;er-at had grete envy,</L>
<L>&amp; saide he techide bot heresy</L>
<L>&THORN;at euer &yogh;itt prechide hee.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Till on an tyme &thorn;e frere herd tell</L>
<L N="50">How nere-hand &thorn;e knyght gune duelle,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Nach v. 50 fehlt eine Stro he?</NOTE></L>
<L>Byfore &thorn;e n&omacr;ne in a kirke.</L>
<L>And firste he prechide gud latyne,</L>
<L>And sythyne Inglysche gud &amp; fyne,</L>
<L N="55">Wha sa after hym walde wyrke.</L>
<L>So &thorn;at many mene full sore wepide.</L>
<L>(&THORN;)e knyghte satt ay styll &amp; slepide,</L>
<L>. . . . in to the myrke.</L>
<L>. . . . .lowde to hym</L>
<L N="60">. . . . .</L>
<L>. . . . .Irke.
<PB REF="00000642.tif" N="504"></L>
<L>"It es me tolde in this contre</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou spekes mekill agaynes me</L>
<L>And sais I preche bot herefy;</L>
<L>To holy kirke wittnes I drawe</L>
<L N="65">I preche no thynge agaynes &thorn;e lawe,</L>
<L>&amp; I sall telle the why,</L>
<L>&THORN;e same ordir &thorn;at god gafe here</L>
<L>&THORN;e foure gosepells wretyne fere</L>
<L>On &thorn;e rode whene he gune dy;</L>
<L N="70">&THORN;at &thorn;ou arte bot an heretyke;</L>
<L>&THORN;e fende of helle &thorn;ou erte full lyke,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou lyffes noghte ryghtwyffly."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e knyghtes hert bygane to tene,</L>
<L>Bot he ne wold not hym to no-mane mene,</L>
<L N="75">Bot satt ay still als stane;</L>
<L>Had it noghte bene mare for manes sp(e)che,</L>
<L>&THORN;e frere had nedid none o&thorn;er leche</L>
<L>Bot sone he hade bene slayne; &mdash;</L>
<L>For &thorn;e awe of god ne lettyd he noghte,</L>
<L N="80">Bot for dishonour &thorn;at hym thoghte</L>
<L>&THORN;at he thare had tane.</L>
<L>&THORN;e frere tuke vp ano&thorn;(er) tale;</L>
<L>&THORN;e knyght satt still &amp; wexe alle pale,</L>
<L>Als his lyfe had bene gane.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="85">Whene &thorn;e frere had sayd what he walde,</L>
<L>Folke drew to hym thikk-falde,</L>
<L>To schryfe &thorn;ame of thaire synne.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Die Reime sind verderbt, oder nach v. 90 fehlt eine Strophe.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e knyghte, &thorn;at was &thorn;e fendys fere,</L>
<L>He styrte by-twix &thorn;ame &amp; &thorn;e frere:</L>
<L N="90">&THORN;ay myghte noghte to hym wynne.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Die Reime sind verderbt, oder nach v. 90 fehlt eine Strophe.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ilk a mane wend he wold do saa</L>
<L>Penance for his synns to taa:</L>
<L>So wende both mane &amp; wyfe;</L>
<L>He was abowte &thorn;e frere to tary,</L>
<L N="95">Bathe to fkorne god &amp; Mary</L>
<L>&amp; thayme to hethyng to dryfe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Of his commyng &thorn;e frere was fayne</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="inter"><B>(Hier ist grosse L&uuml;cke).</B></NOTE> . . . . .</L>
<L><MILESTONE N="148" UNIT="folio">"The thare noghte be so bayne."</L>
<L>Full preualy he helde hym still,</L>
<L N="100">And thanked Mary hir gud will,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. fewlis st. fowlis.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at helde hym fra &thorn;at trayne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e frere, &thorn;e fend vaneste awaye.</L>
<L>It was myrke &amp; ferre fra daye,</L>
<L>&THORN;e fewlis sange was still.</L>
<L N="105">&THORN;e foulle warlawes of helle</L>
<L>Vndir &thorn;e wallys fkrykked schille,</L>
<L>And sayd: Mary did wrange &amp; ill</L>
<L>&THORN;at scho solde with hir qwaynt fare</L>
<L>Reue &thorn;am &thorn;at &thorn;airs ware,</L>
<L N="110">Thay myght noghte come &thorn;er-till;</L>
<L>Mighte &thorn;ay hafe getyne hym on any wyse,</L>
<L>&THORN;ay wold hafe qwitt hym his seruyse.</L>
<L>For sorowe &thorn;ay cryed fchill.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Fra &thorn;at tym, to &thorn;e sone rase,</L>
<L N="115">Byfore oure lady kneland he was</L>
<L>And prayed hir &thorn;at scho walde gaa</L>
<L>And bere his erande to hir dere childe</L>
<L>To forgyffe hym his werkes wylde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he had bene so thraa.</L>
<L N="120">At forthe dayes &thorn;ane come his ownne frere</L>
<L>With a full mylde chere,</L>
<L>The better of thase twa.</L>
<L>And appone his knes he sett hym downne</L>
<L>And tuk hys absolucyone.</L>
<L N="125">The fend was flayed hym fra.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And &thorn;are he schrafe hym of his synne</L>
<L>&THORN;at he had lange lyuede Inne,</L>
<L>Wele ferly lange.</L>
<L>Ilk a mane agayne his gud he gaffe</L>
<L N="130">&THORN;at he had tane with ryfe &amp; raffe,</L>
<L>With falsehed &amp; with wrange.</L>
<L>And &thorn;us to &thorn;e blysse gune he wyne.</L>
<L>God late vs neuer byleue in syne</L>
<L>With hert &thorn;at es so strange.</L>
<L N="135">&THORN;e mane &thorn;at will ilk day do better &thorn;ane o&thorn;er,</L>
<L>He may be goddis ownne bro&thorn;er</L>
<L>And duelle angells amange.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;us Endis here our talkyng.</L>
<L>Jhesu till his blysse vs brynge,</L>
<L N="140">&THORN;at es euer-lastande. amen. par charite.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="3" TYPE="legend"><PB REF="00000643.tif" N="[505]">
<HEAD>3) Spr&uuml;che des h. Beda. Aus Ms. Digby 86, fol. 127b.</HEAD> 
<HEADNOTE><P>Vgl. p. 211. Das folgende Gedicht des Ms. Digby 86 (in der Regierungszeit Edward's I, 1272&mdash;1307, geschrieben) ist ein j&uuml;ngerer Text des aus Ms. Jesus Coll. Oxf. I, Arch. I, 29, fol. 248 (aus der Zeit Heinrich's III. c. 1250) in An Old English Mis|cellany ed. by Rich. Morris 1872 (f&uuml;r die E. E. T. S.) p. 72 unter d. T. Sinners Beware, abgedruckten Gedichtes. Wir verdanken dem Ms. Digby die Erhaltung des Titels, welcher in dem &auml;lteren Ms. fehlt; der Text selbst ist bereits sehr verderbt. Ein &auml;hnliches Gedicht sind die Spr&uuml;che des h. Bernard (Ms. Digby 86, Laud 108 u. a.).</P></HEADNOTE>
<HEAD>Her beginne&thorn; &thorn;e sawe of Seint Bede prest.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Holi gost, &thorn;i mi&yogh;tte</L>
<L>Ous wisse and rede and di&yogh;te</L>
<L>And helpe ous and teche</L>
<L>To witen ous wi&thorn; &thorn;e onwi&yogh;tte,</L>
<L N="5">&THORN;at bi day and bi ni&yogh;tte</L>
<L>&THORN;enche&thorn; ous bipeche,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Make&thorn; ous to don sunne,</L>
<L>And abben to monkunne</L>
<L>Swi&thorn;e muchel honde;</L>
<L N="10">He &thorn;enche&thorn; ous biwinne</L>
<L>And wonien ous wi&thorn;inne</L>
<L>And ouer ous habben honde.<NOTE PLACE="foot">habben mit nachtr&auml;glich vorgeschr. h. honde = onde.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ac bidde we Crist &yogh;erne</L>
<L>Nou &thorn;at he hem werne</L>
<L N="15">For his mildenesse; &mdash;</L>
<L>For hy &thorn;at to hem sulen turne,</L>
<L>In helle hy shulen forberne</L>
<L>In hewche &thorn;esternesse.<NOTE PLACE="foot">hewche st. eche eternal.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>We houten oure suppinde<NOTE PLACE="foot">suppinde, J. C. suppen = scippend, Sch&ouml;pfer.</NOTE></L>
<L N="20">Herien of alle &thorn;inge</L>
<L>And louien hine wel swi&thorn;e;</L>
<L>For he ous wille werien</L>
<L>&THORN;at fendes ous ne derien,</L>
<L>&THORN;at folle be&thorn; of ni&thorn;e.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="25">Ne be we nout here</L>
<L>Swi&thorn;e fele &yogh;ere.</L>
<L>Bote we, her we henne wende,<NOTE PLACE="foot">J. C. For&thorn;i . . Makie we.</NOTE></L>
<L>Makien ous clene and skere,</L>
<L>&THORN;at we in heuene englene fere</L>
<L N="30">Ben ho wi&thorn;-outen ende,<NOTE PLACE="foot">ho = o = ay.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>In heuene in &thorn;e blisse</L>
<L>&THORN;at muchel is, midiwisse,</L>
<L>And leste&thorn; euere-more;</L>
<L>&THORN;er-inne is reste and lisse.</L>
<L N="35">Ne may &thorn;er no-mon misse</L>
<L>&THORN;at louie&thorn; godes ore.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ac hit sai&thorn; in &thorn;e gospelle:</L>
<L>Ne may non tounge al telle</L>
<L>&THORN;e blisse &thorn;at &thorn;er is euere,</L>
<L N="40">Ne &thorn;e pine of helle &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;erto we be&thorn; wel swelle(!);<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. swelle st. snelle? bolde and swelle Octav. 1557. Jes. Col. liest snelle.</NOTE></L>
<L>Awey, hit ne hende&thorn; nevere.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Hier hat Ms. Jes. Col. eine Strophe mehr.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000644.tif" N="506"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;er-inne is chele and hete,</L>
<L>And hounger ounimete,</L>
<L N="45">And &thorn;urst alles to kene;</L>
<L>Pikede be&thorn; &thorn;e shete,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Morris corr. unrichtig pikede in wikede.</NOTE></L>
<L>And wormes &thorn;er be&thorn; kete,</L>
<L>To don &thorn;e soule tene;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;erinne is wop and woninge,<NOTE PLACE="foot">woninge v. w&acirc;nien ags. plorare.</NOTE></L>
<L N="50">And muchel bimeninge</L>
<L>&THORN;at hoe I-boren were;</L>
<L>Ac &thorn;er nis non hendinge</L>
<L>Ne non a&yogh;ein-cherhinge<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. cher hinge; cherren, ags cerran verti.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at enes come&thorn; &thorn;ere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="55">Wel we owen nimen gome &mdash;</L>
<L>He &thorn;at elles &thorn;ider come &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">he st. &thorn;e relat.</NOTE></L>
<L>And serven heuene kinge,</L>
<L>And bidden him I-lome</L>
<L>&THORN;at he ous at &thorn;e dome</L>
<L N="60">Of here pine bringe.<NOTE PLACE="foot">here aus &thorn;are &thorn;ere (Dativ des Art.) verderbt.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Oute we owre sunnen leten</L>
<L>And munien Crist and beten</L>
<L>Of alle oure misdede;</L>
<L>To doinde hoe be&thorn; swete:</L>
<L N="65">For-&thorn;y ous is helle &yogh;ete,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;ete granted (ags. geaten to grant); J. C. e&thorn;gete easy to get.</NOTE></L>
<L>Helle &thorn;at is ounlede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e seuene heued-sunne,</L>
<L>&THORN;at we be&thorn; ofte wi&thorn;inne,</L>
<L>&THORN;e soule wolle&thorn; amerre;</L>
<L N="70">Hoe be&thorn; of swikele kunne:</L>
<L>&THORN;ermide &thorn;e wi&thorn;erwinne</L>
<L>Ous alle &thorn;enche&thorn; to bicherre.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Modinesse and ouerfastnesse,<NOTE PLACE="foot">modinesse pride.</NOTE></L>
<L>Onde, wrathe, swikelnesse,</L>
<L N="75">Hordom and &yogh;evernesse:<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;evernesse v. ags. &yogh;ifre Geiz.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;is we houten alle ounderstonde</L>
<L>&THORN;at moni men in londe</L>
<L>Bringe&thorn; to sorinesse;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For &thorn;is be&thorn; &thorn;e seuene</L>
<L N="80">&THORN;at bringe&thorn; out of heuene</L>
<L>Swi&thorn;e fele monne;</L>
<L>&THORN;e weyes be&thorn; in hoere wene,<NOTE PLACE="foot">J. C. &thorn;e weyes beo&thorn; vneuene.</NOTE></L>
<L>Mid wepinde steuene</L>
<L>In-to helle hoe shulen &thorn;enne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="85">HOe wene&thorn;, monie of &thorn;ise riche,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he henglen ben I-liche</L>
<L>For hoere proude clo&thorn;e;</L>
<L>And &thorn;erfore hoe sulen scriken</L>
<L>And in helle siken</L>
<L N="90">And corien hit foul wro&thorn;e.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Hierauf hat Ms. Jes. Col. eine Strophe mehr.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>So wene&thorn; &thorn;is wreche</L>
<L>&THORN;at hoe ne weren riche,<NOTE PLACE="foot">J. C. &thorn;at he ne &thorn;urue recche.</NOTE></L>
<L>For-&thorn;i &thorn;at hoe haytte nabbe&thorn;;</L>
<L>Ac Satanas, &thorn;e wreche,<NOTE PLACE="foot">wrecche = frecche 318, fierce; vgl. 117 were st. fere.</NOTE></L>
<L N="95">&THORN;e soule wille drecche,</L>
<L>Wen hoe ani got(!) habbe&thorn;.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. go mit klein angesetztem t; J. C. hwanne he agult habbe&thorn;.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e riche midiwisse</L>
<L>Mi&yogh;tte comen to blisse,</L>
<L>If he hit wolde hernye.</L>
<L N="100">And &thorn;e wreche may wel misse,</L>
<L>Bote he his pouernesse</L>
<L>In mildenesse &thorn;olie.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;is monekes wene&thorn; soumme,</L>
<L>&THORN;at gedere&thorn; garisoumme,</L>
<L N="105">&THORN;at hoe hit shulen brouke;</L>
<L>Ac wene &thorn;e de&thorn; shal comen,</L>
<L>Hit shal hem ben binomen;</L>
<L>Bitaut hoe be&thorn; &thorn;e pouke.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e prest &thorn;at singe&thorn; masse</L>
<L N="110">&THORN;oru godes herienesse</L>
<L>And wot of tethinge,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. techinge.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;erof nul don almesse,</L>
<L>In euche sorinesse</L>
<L>His soule he may bringe.
<PB REF="00000645.tif" N="507"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="115">&THORN;es kni&yogh;ttes be&thorn; wel bolde,</L>
<L>For hy abbe&thorn; aquolde</L>
<L>Here ani cristine were;</L>
<L>For-&thorn;i satanas, &thorn;e holde,</L>
<L>&THORN;e soule wille atholde</L>
<L N="120">And makien hire ounifere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;es plaidours be&thorn; wel kene,</L>
<L>&THORN;at werie&thorn; red and grene,</L>
<L>And al &thorn;is ounri&yogh;t deme&thorn;;</L>
<L>Hy shulen wi&thorn;-houten wene</L>
<L N="125">To helle, &thorn;at is so kene,</L>
<L>&THORN;er &thorn;e fendes reme&thorn;.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;is chapmen monie bi strete</L>
<L>Hy be&thorn; swikele ounimete,</L>
<L>Hy ne recche&thorn; &thorn;au hy swerien,<NOTE PLACE="foot">l. &thorn;au oder &thorn;an? vgl. 263. 350.</NOTE></L>
<L N="130">For to abben here bi&yogh;ete;</L>
<L>For-&thorn;i satanas, &thorn;e kete,</L>
<L>Here soule wille derien.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Of alle men on londe</L>
<L>Mest swinke&thorn; &thorn;e bonde</L>
<L N="135">And mest bi&yogh;et mit ri&yogh;te;</L>
<L>If he cou&thorn;e ounderstonde</L>
<L>And te&thorn;ege ri&yogh;t ounder his honde,</L>
<L>To Crist he comen mi&yogh;tte;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ac for alle his biswinke,</L>
<L N="140">If he may comen to sottes drinke<NOTE PLACE="foot">J. C. In helle he may adrinke, If he stele &thorn;.</NOTE></L>
<L>And stelen Cristes teu&thorn;inge,</L>
<L>sstrong de&thorn; hit wile him &thorn;enke;</L>
<L>Depe in helle winke</L>
<L>His soule he may bringe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="145">&THORN;es proude leuedies,</L>
<L>&THORN;at louen driweries</L>
<L>And breken here spousinge</L>
<L>And do&thorn; to gabbie,</L>
<L>&THORN;at loveden simonie</L>
<L N="150">Of eni gode &thorn;inge;<NOTE PLACE="foot">148&mdash;150) J. C. For hoere lecherye, Nulle&thorn; here sermonye Of none gode &thorn;inge.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Hy drawe&thorn; here wede</L>
<L>Mid selkene &thorn;rede</L>
<L>I-frenget and I-bounde:</L>
<L>Swart and swi&thorn;e ounlede</L>
<L N="155">Remen hy shulen and grede</L>
<L>Depe in helle grounde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Monekes and eremites and nonnen</L>
<L>&THORN;at hem witen ne cunnen</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; swecche lecherie,</L>
<L N="160">Hy shulen to &thorn;ere ounwinne;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. to&thorn;ere.</NOTE></L>
<L>Alle here clo&thorn;es dounne<NOTE PLACE="foot">dounne dun fuscus.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ne shulen hem warauntie.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>So&thorn;liche, al betere hem were</L>
<L>&THORN;at hy I-boren nere,</L>
<L N="165">&THORN;at &thorn;ider shule wende!</L>
<L>Warni ich ou here;</L>
<L>For &yogh;e &thorn;at enes come&thorn; &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>&THORN;er &yogh;e be&thorn; ho, bouten hende.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ac hy wene&thorn; libbie<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. Aat st. Ac.</NOTE></L>
<L N="170">And longe sunegie,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ene at &thorn;en ende</L>
<L>Here sunnen al anendie<NOTE PLACE="foot">J. C. endye.</NOTE></L>
<L>And birewsie,</L>
<L>And se&thorn;&thorn;en to heuene wende.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="175">Ne ben &yogh;e nout so ownriste<NOTE PLACE="foot">ownriste st. &THORN;ryste J. C. verschr.</NOTE></L>
<L>Nou to Jhesu Criste,</L>
<L>&THORN;er-to ich ou lere;</L>
<L>For &thorn;er nes non &thorn;at weste,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;-houten Jhesu Criste,</L>
<L N="180">Wen his honday were.<NOTE PLACE="foot">honday st. henday, endeday.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For ous ne be&thorn; nout so e&thorn;e</L>
<L>To-&yogh;eines houre de&thorn;e,<NOTE PLACE="foot">181 ff.) Die n&auml;chsten 2 Strophen fehlen im Ms. Jes. Coll.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;atwe ous moowen so wel hede</L>
<L>Ne speken bote oun&thorn;ewe,</L>
<L N="185">For ous be&thorn; stronge and wre&thorn;e</L>
<L>To beten oure misdede.
<PB REF="00000646.tif" N="508"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Nout wi&thorn; Criste scolde</L>
<L>Leten ous &thorn;enne on londe</L>
<L>To habben houre ri&yogh;tte;</L>
<L N="190">Wen we him seruen nolde,</L>
<L>Ne laufoul ben ne holde</L>
<L>Her, we nou for&thorn;er ne mi&yogh;tte.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>So&thorn;liche, wen we be&thorn; dede,</L>
<L>Euerich sal fongen mede</L>
<L N="195">After his herihinge;</L>
<L>Bote we ous &thorn;e bet bihede,</L>
<L>&THORN;e soule hit shal I-frede</L>
<L>&THORN;at fare&thorn; to pininge.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e bali me binde&thorn;,</L>
<L N="200">In here me him &thorn;ringe&thorn;</L>
<L>And bringe&thorn; him hounder er&thorn;e;</L>
<L>Wormes him I-finde&thorn;,</L>
<L>To axnen hoe him grinde&thorn; &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;arto hy shulen wor&thorn;e.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="205">He li&thorn; and rote&thorn; lowe,</L>
<L>He ne haue&thorn; &thorn;at be his owe</L>
<L>Of aytte ne of londe,</L>
<L>Ne now&thorn;er mey ne mowe</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;er doren a &thorn;rowe</L>
<L N="210">Bi hem sitten ne stonde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ac wer be&thorn; &thorn;enne his haytte</L>
<L>&THORN;at he here raytte<NOTE PLACE="foot">211 ff.) Die folg. 2 Strophen fehlen im Ms. Jes. Coll.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot">he aus hy corr. 229, 233, 235 fehlen in Jes. Coll.</NOTE></L>
<L>And in &thorn;is lif wonne?</L>
<L>So&thorn;liche hy be&thorn; bi-pay&yogh;tte;</L>
<L N="215">Swecche o&thorn;ere hoe be&thorn; bitai&yogh;tte</L>
<L>&THORN;at him no &thorn;onk ne cunne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ac wer be&thorn; &thorn;enne his ringes</L>
<L>And his proude &thorn;inges</L>
<L>And his golt-peinte gloue!</L>
<L N="220">Wor al his proude &thorn;inges</L>
<L>Ne vaille&thorn; him no&thorn;inges</L>
<L>&THORN;enne to his bihoue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>So&thorn;liche, naked and bare,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; wop and wi&thorn; kare</L>
<L N="225">&THORN;ou come to &thorn;isse liue:</L>
<L>And so &yogh;e sulen eft-sones fare,</L>
<L>I saye &thorn;e so&thorn; wi&thorn;-oute sware.</L>
<L>Grey&thorn;e&thorn; ou biliue!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e salt (!) &thorn;e world forleten and lewe,</L>
<L N="230">&THORN;er-of &yogh;e shulden &thorn;enken eue</L>
<L>And oure sunne aquenche,</L>
<L>Mid beden and mid almesse,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;-outen idelnesse,</L>
<L>If &yogh;e mi&yogh;tten atblenche</L>
<L N="235">From &thorn;e sori Satanasse</L>
<L>And from his swikelnesse</L>
<L>And from his heuele wrenche.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>If &thorn;ou fallest in sunne,</L>
<L>Ne li&thorn;ou nout &thorn;er-inne,</L>
<L N="240">Hie&thorn;e, &thorn;e oup to arisen,</L>
<L>And shend &thorn;e wi&thorn;er-wine,</L>
<L>Satanas, mid his pine,</L>
<L>And do &thorn;e also &thorn;e wise!<NOTE PLACE="foot">J. C. do&thorn; we.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For mon nohute nout to abbe some,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Diese Strophe fehlt Jes. Coll. Ms. noute mit &uuml;bergeschr. h &uuml;ber o; l. nohute od. houte? some undeutlich im Ms. (scheinbar soule).</NOTE></L>
<L N="245">Wen his wrecche licome</L>
<L>In sunnen be I-falle,</L>
<L>Ac abbeyes houte dome (!)</L>
<L>And ounwren his sunnen I-lome,</L>
<L>And Crist in fuir pine&thorn; alle.<NOTE PLACE="foot">And st. or?</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="250">&THORN;e mon him let wel sriven</L>
<L>And &thorn;ene fend out driven,</L>
<L>Ne &thorn;arf him nout shomie;</L>
<L>For ne be&thorn; in &thorn;isse live</L>
<L>Wepmenne, wimmen fiue</L>
<L N="255">&THORN;at ofte ne svnegie&thorn;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ac &thorn;es modie gome</L>
<L>And leuedies and &thorn;e ounrome</L>
<L>Doute&thorn; hem also &thorn;e ounwise;<NOTE PLACE="foot">J. C. Heo dyhte&thorn; heom vnwreste.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;es &yogh;ounlinges somme,</L>
<L N="260">&THORN;ey &thorn;at hoe to srifte come,</L>
<L>Hoe be&thorn; sottes and shomefaste.
<PB REF="00000647.tif" N="509"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Hy nulle&thorn; so&thorn; tellen,</L>
<L>&THORN;au me shulde hem quellen,</L>
<L>Hy ounweren here misdede.<NOTE PLACE="foot">J. C. Ne vnwreo.</NOTE></L>
<L N="265">For-&thorn;i hoe shulen in helle</L>
<L>Euere gronen and swelle</L>
<L>And euere-mo ben &thorn;er-inne.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Hierauf hat Ms. Jes. Coll. eine Strophe mehr.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Wenne eni grome&thorn; sore,</L>
<L>&THORN;e grome &thorn;unche&thorn; more</L>
<L N="270">&THORN;en al hore o&thorn;er pine.</L>
<L>To &thorn;e(!) bi prestes lore</L>
<L>Nolden herien godes hore,</L>
<L>&THORN;enne hoe hit shulen biwine.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>At &thorn;e mounte of Olifete</L>
<L N="275">&THORN;er we ous shulen alle I-mete,</L>
<L>&THORN;e gode and &thorn;e ounwreste.</L>
<L>&THORN;e day wor&thorn; milde and sete,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. sete st. swete.</NOTE></L>
<L>And bitter unimete</L>
<L>To hem &thorn;at forlete</L>
<L N="280">To don godes heste.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;er come&thorn; god on his rode,<NOTE PLACE="foot">J. C. mid st. on.</NOTE></L>
<L>And his side his ablode,</L>
<L>And sewe&thorn; ou he ous boute.<NOTE PLACE="foot">sewe&thorn; = schewe&thorn;.</NOTE></L>
<L>Afered be&thorn; &thorn;enne &thorn;e gode,</L>
<L N="285">And wo is &thorn;enne &thorn;e ouermode</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;er-of ne route.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Loke&thorn;, sey&thorn; god nou&thorn;e,</L>
<L>Wat ich for ou ou&thorn;e,<NOTE PLACE="foot">ou&thorn;e praet. v. unnan to grant.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wat ich for ou gon &thorn;olie.</L>
<L N="290">Luitel &thorn;onk &yogh;e me cou&thorn;e,</L>
<L>Ne mid werke ne mid mou&thorn;e</L>
<L>Nolden &yogh;e me &thorn;onkie."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ac he sey&thorn; &thorn;enne to &thorn;e gode</L>
<L>And to his milde moder(!):<NOTE PLACE="foot">J. C. And spek myd milde mode.</NOTE></L>
<L N="295">"&YOGH;e duden gode dede,</L>
<L>&YOGH;e me fedden and srudden</L>
<L>And wel me bihedden,</L>
<L>&THORN;o ich among ou hede,</L>
<L>And leide me a softe bedde.</L>
<L N="300">&THORN;arfore ich ou wole aredde,</L>
<L>For nou &yogh;e habbe&thorn; nede."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e gode sege&thorn; &thorn;enne:</L>
<L>"Louerd, were and wenne</L>
<L>Duden we &thorn;e gode deden?"</L>
<L N="305">"&YOGH;use, he sei&thorn;, &thorn;e poure monne,</L>
<L>&THORN;o hoe help neden nen,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. nen, J. C. nenne.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bote as hoe for me beden.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ac &yogh;e, mine gode, midiwisse,</L>
<L>To heueriche blisse</L>
<L N="310">To-day &yogh;e shulen wende.</L>
<L>And &thorn;e acoursede to sorinesse</L>
<L>And to euche &thorn;esternesse,</L>
<L>And &thorn;er ben euere bouten ende."<NOTE PLACE="foot">308&mdash;313 folgen in J. C. erst nach 337.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>He sei&thorn; &thorn;enne to &thorn;e wrecche:</L>
<L N="315">"&YOGH;e nolden nout hof me recche;</L>
<L>For hounger ich aswal &thorn;route,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&THORN;route &thorn;eroute.</NOTE></L>
<L>&YOGH;e nolden me in fecche:</L>
<L>Ou-self &yogh;e weren so frecche,</L>
<L>So modi and so proude."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="320">Hoe grede&thorn; &thorn;enne on heye,</L>
<L>&THORN;e wrecches and &thorn;e ounweye<NOTE PLACE="foot">J. C. vnsleye; ounweye = oun-feye.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at loueden &thorn;e ounredes,</L>
<L>And sigge&thorn;: "louerd, wi&thorn; oure eye</L>
<L>We &thorn;e neuere ne seye,</L>
<L N="325">&THORN;er &thorn;ou nede heuedest."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>God sey&thorn;: "&yogh;use, mine</L>
<L>Povere, ounhole hine</L>
<L>&THORN;at to oure dore come&mdash;</L>
<L>For chele hoe heueden pine,</L>
<L N="330">Wor hounger hoe gonnen chine,<NOTE PLACE="foot">chine to split.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;erof ne nome &yogh;e gome,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;er-of &yogh;e nolden hede</L>
<L>Ne &yogh;euen hem of oure brede</L>
<L>Ne of drinke ne of clo&thorn;e.</L>
<L N="335">To-day &yogh;e sulen frede</L>
<L>And ounder-fongen mede,</L>
<L>For me &yogh;e be&thorn; wel lo&thorn;e."
<PB REF="00000648.tif" N="510"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Hoe &yogh;erre&thorn; &thorn;enne and grede&thorn;.</L>
<L>&THORN;e fendes hem for&thorn; lede&thorn;,</L>
<L N="340">Bo&thorn;e licome and soule,</L>
<L>Se&thorn;e&thorn; hem and grede&thorn;,</L>
<L>Stike&thorn; hem and brede&thorn;</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; pikes and wi&thorn; howeles.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Vor 343 fehlt eine Strophe, die Anklage des Leibes gegen die Seele.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e soule sey&thorn; to onsuare:</L>
<L N="345">"Licom, al &thorn;ou forfare,</L>
<L>So wrechede and so ounlede!</L>
<L>Wor &thorn;ou ous hauest I-wrout &thorn;is fare</L>
<L>And I-brout ous ewche kare</L>
<L>&THORN;at euere we shulen &thorn;olie."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="350">Ac &thorn;e gode and &thorn;e clene,</L>
<L>&THORN;an hoe I-seien ous &thorn;enne,</L>
<L>Al &thorn;at cun &thorn;at we of come,</L>
<L>Nulle hoe neuer ene</L>
<L>Bi-rewen ne bimene</L>
<L N="355">Ne &thorn;arto nimen gome.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Hem-self hoe be&thorn; so bli&thorn;e</L>
<L>&THORN;at hoe of wone li&thorn;e</L>
<L>Moten ane day wonie,</L>
<L>And &thorn;onke&thorn; god swi&thorn;e</L>
<L N="360">Ofte and monie si&thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">355&mdash;360 fehlen in J. C.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at hy hit mosten herie.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ac &yogh;if we ous wolden vel di&yogh;tte</L>
<L>And leden ous mid ri&yogh;tte,</L>
<L>&THORN;e wiles &thorn;at we her were,</L>
<L N="365">Ich ou sugge and pli&yogh;tte:<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. domes, l. domesday.</NOTE></L>
<L>At &thorn;e domes &yogh;e mi&yogh;tte</L>
<L>Ben englene fere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ac bidde we oure dri&yogh;tte,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms sop = schop, J. C. scop.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at dayes sop and ni&yogh;tte,</L>
<L N="370">&THORN;at do houre soule bote,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at we mi&yogh;tte</L>
<L>I-seiene ben at si&yogh;tte</L>
<L>Among &thorn;e hengles bri&yogh;te.</L>
<L>Amen, so hit be mote! Amen.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="4" TYPE="legend"><PB REF="00000649.tif" N="[511]">
<HEAD>4. Ypotys.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>Varianten der Mss. Arundel 140 fol. I (A), Ashm. 61 (B) und Cotton. Tit. A XXVI fol. 163 (T); in letzterem Ms. fehlt der Anfang, es beginnt erst mit V. 100.</P><P>Ms. Cott. Cal. A II, fol. 79 b. . Vgl. p. 341 ff. Ich lasse hier noch den Text der besten der j&uuml;ngeren Hss., Ms. Cott. Cal. A II, c. 1420, folgen, und gebe die Varianten der Mss. Arund. 140, Ashm. 61, Cott. Tit. A XXVI (Ashm. 750 und Douce 323 habe ich noch nicht ver|gleichen k&ouml;nnen). Alle diese Hss. sind gleich verderbt und gleich weit von Ms. Vernon entfernt; f&uuml;r die Kritik des Textes sind sie fast von gleichem Werthe.</P><P>Die Herstellung des urspr&uuml;nglichen Textes ist bei der Verderbniss der Hss. mit grossen Schwierigkeiten verbunden; ich halte es f&uuml;r gerathener, zuerst das hand|schriftliche Material zusammenzustellen.</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>He &thorn;at wyll of wysdome lere,<NOTE PLACE="foot">AB Alle. A wolle; of fehlt; wysdam; here.</NOTE></L>
<L>Herkeneth now, &amp; &yogh;e may here<NOTE PLACE="foot">A Herkenyth me now. B Lystyns to me &amp; ye schall lere.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of a tale of holy wryte &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">A writte.</NOTE></L>
<L>Seynt Jon &thorn;e euangelist wytnesseth hyt:<NOTE PLACE="foot">AB Johne. A &thorn;e euangelist fehlt. B &thorn;e apostyll. B wytnes. A itte, B ite.</NOTE></L>
<L N="5">How hyt befell yn grete Rome,<NOTE PLACE="foot">how fehlt in A. AB it. A byfelle. A gret.</NOTE></L>
<L>The chefe cyte of crystendome.<NOTE PLACE="foot">A chef. AB crystyndome.</NOTE></L>
<L>A chyld was sent of my&yogh;tes most<NOTE PLACE="foot">A sente, B send. A myghtys, B my&yogh;tys. AB moste.</NOTE></L>
<L>Thorow vertu of &thorn;e holy gost<NOTE PLACE="foot">A &thorn;orgh. B &thorn;e vertu. AB goste.</NOTE></L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e emperour of Rome,</L>
<L N="10">A nobull man &amp; wyse of dome;<NOTE PLACE="foot">9&mdash;10) fehlen in AB, wie in V.</NOTE></L>
<L>The emperour of Rome &thorn;an<NOTE PLACE="foot">B To &thorn;e. AB thane.</NOTE></L>
<L>Men called hym syr Adryan.<NOTE PLACE="foot">A Was Iclepyd Adryane. B Hys name was callyd sir A.</NOTE></L>
<L>When &thorn;at chyld of gret honour<NOTE PLACE="foot">AB the. B grete.</NOTE></L>
<L>Was comen before &thorn;e emperour,<NOTE PLACE="foot">A come, B brou&yogh;t. A byfor.</NOTE></L>
<L N="15">On hys kne he hym sette,<NOTE PLACE="foot">A Adoune on knes, set.</NOTE></L>
<L>Well fayre &thorn;e emperour &thorn;er he grette.<NOTE PLACE="foot">A &thorn;e Emperoure well faire he gret, B And feyre &thorn;e e. he grete.</NOTE></L>
<L>The emperour wyth mylde chere<NOTE PLACE="foot">A myld. B &thorn;e e. withouten les.</NOTE></L>
<L>Askede &thorn;e chylde of whens he were.<NOTE PLACE="foot">AB asked. in A fehlt &thorn;e chylde of. A wheynes, B of when. A come were, B he was.</NOTE></L>
<L>The chyld answered hym aply&yogh;t:<NOTE PLACE="foot">A answerd, B ansuerd. AB son st. hym. A aplyght.</NOTE></L>
<L N="20">"Fro my fadur y come now ry&yogh;t,<NOTE PLACE="foot">in A ist fadyr durchstrichen u. modyr &uuml;bschr. B fader. AB I. B now fehlt.</NOTE></L>
<L>And that ys fro &thorn;e hy&yogh; Justyse,<NOTE PLACE="foot">AB And (fehlt in B) fro my fadyr &thorn;e. A hye, B hy&yogh;e. A Justice, B Justys.</NOTE></L>
<L>To teche &thorn;em &thorn;at ben vnwyse<NOTE PLACE="foot">AB men st. &thorn;em. A beth, B be. AB nou&yogh;t (B not) wyce (B wyse).</NOTE></L>
<L>Ne now&yogh;t fulfylled of &thorn;e lawes."<NOTE PLACE="foot">A Ne full|fyllyd of goddys lawe.</NOTE></L>
<L>Then sayde &thorn;e emperour yn hys sawes:<NOTE PLACE="foot">23&mdash;4) fehlen in B.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot">A The e. sayd in his sawe.</NOTE></L>
<L N="25">"Then art &thorn;ou wyse wysdome to teche?"<NOTE PLACE="foot">AB Than. B arte &thorn;ou. A thow. B wys. A wysdam.</NOTE></L>
<L>The chylde answered wyth mylde spech:<NOTE PLACE="foot">AB child, myld.</NOTE></L>
<L>"He ys wyse &thorn;at heuen may wynne<NOTE PLACE="foot">AB is. B wyne.</NOTE></L>
<L>And kepe hym out of deedly synne."<NOTE PLACE="foot">A kep. B oute. A fro. AB dedly.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000650.tif" N="512"></L>
<L>The emperour sayde wythout blame:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">B. withoute.</NOTE></L>
<L N="30">"Chylde, tell me &thorn;y ry&yogh;t name!"<NOTE PLACE="foot2">A child.</NOTE></L>
<L>"My name, he sayde, ys Ypotyse,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">A Ipotyse.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at mych kon telle of heuen blysse."<NOTE PLACE="foot2">29&mdash;32) fehlen in B.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">A For I can. blyse.</NOTE></L>
<L>The emperour sayde: "what may heuen be?"<NOTE PLACE="foot2">B What he seyd may.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Syr, sayde &thorn;e chyld, goddys pryuyte."<NOTE PLACE="foot2">AB he sayde (B seyd). B godys. A priuate.</NOTE></L>
<L N="35">"What, he sayde, ys god allmy&yogh;t?"</L>
<L>The chylde answered anon ry&yogh;t:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">A answere.</NOTE></L>
<L>"He ys wythoute begynnynge<NOTE PLACE="foot2">B was withoutene.</NOTE></L>
<L>And shall be wythoute endynge."<NOTE PLACE="foot2">A eke st. shall be.</NOTE></L>
<L>The emperour sayde: "y haue gret selkow&thorn;.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">A that is couth, B I ame selcouthe.</NOTE></L>
<L N="40">What come fyrst of goddus mow&thorn;?"<NOTE PLACE="foot2">B mouthe.</NOTE></L>
<L>The chyld answered &amp; sayd anone:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">AB son st. &amp; sayd.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Therof speketh &thorn;e apostell Johne<NOTE PLACE="foot2">AB &thorn;ere of. A spekyth, B spekys. A postill Jone.</NOTE></L>
<L>In hys gospell all &amp; summe:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">A alle, B all. AB some.</NOTE></L>
<L>In principio erat verbum.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">A verbume (!).</NOTE></L>
<L N="45">Thys was &thorn;e fyrst bygynny(n)ge<NOTE PLACE="foot2">A It.</NOTE></L>
<L>That euer spake our heuen kyng;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">euer fehlt in A. A spak.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wyth &thorn;at word was &thorn;e fadur &amp; &thorn;e sone<NOTE PLACE="foot2">was fehlt in A. &thorn;e fehlt in B. A sonne.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;e holy gost to-gedur kome,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">A And fehlt, &thorn;e holy gost togyder wonne. B wone st. kome.</NOTE></L>
<L>Thre persones in trinite &mdash;</L>
<L N="50">Ther may none fro o&thorn;ur be."<NOTE PLACE="foot2">A non, othere.</NOTE></L>
<L>The emperour sayde full euenne:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">A well.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Chyld, &thorn;ou hast be yn heuenne,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">A ben at.</NOTE></L>
<L>How fele heuens hath god almy&yogh;t?"<NOTE PLACE="foot2">A many heuenys. A alle-my&yogh;t.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Seuen, sayde &thorn;e chylde aply&yogh;t;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">A child.</NOTE></L>
<L N="55">The hyeste heuen &thorn;at may be<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Ms. fyrste in hyeste corr.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">A hyest.</NOTE></L>
<L>That ys of &thorn;e holy trinite:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">of fehlt in A.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ther ys &thorn;e fadur wyth &thorn;e sone,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">A &thorn;ere; fadyr; son.</NOTE></L>
<L>The holy gost to-gedur &thorn;ey wone,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">A togydere wone.</NOTE></L>
<L>As &thorn;ese clerkes both syng &amp; rede,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">49)-59) fehlen in B.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">AB So (B Als) clerkys in bok (B bokys) rede.</NOTE></L>
<L N="60">Thre persones in on godhede;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">59&mdash;60) in AB umgestellt.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">A persons, o, B a.</NOTE></L>
<L>That Joye may no-man dyscryue,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">AB ioy.</NOTE></L>
<L>Lered ne lewed, &thorn;at ys on-lyue.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">(61&mdash;2 fehlen in Vernon).</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">B Lernyd. AB lewyd. A beth o.</NOTE></L>
<L>That o&thorn;ur heuen ys gostly wrow&yogh;t,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">B ouer st. o&thorn;er. A gostelyche fuyr (!).</NOTE></L>
<L>Of lower degre, but hy&yogh;er now&yogh;t(!);<NOTE PLACE="foot2">A Alle ho (!) were togydere, &thorn;ow my&yogh;t be suyr. B Withoutene Joy it is nou&yogh;t.</NOTE></L>
<L N="65">That Joye may no-man telle,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">A ne may.</NOTE></L>
<L>Thyll domus-day &thorn;ow&yogh; he wold spelle.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">A Tyl, B Tyll. A domys, B domes. A &thorn;owe he dispelle, B thofe he spelle.</NOTE></L>
<L>The &thorn;rydde heuen shyneth as cristall,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">A &thorn;irde, B thyrd. A schynyh, B schynes. A crystalle.</NOTE></L>
<L>Full of Joye &amp; swete smelle;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">A And is full. B joys grete &amp; small. A swet.</NOTE></L>
<L>For confessores &thorn;at place ys dy&yogh;t;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">A confessours, B confessorys.</NOTE></L>
<L N="70">Ther euur ys day &amp; neuur ny&yogh;t.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">AB &thorn;at seruyth (B serue) god fulle (B full) of myght.</NOTE></L>
<L>The fowr&thorn;e heuen ys gold lych,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">A ferth, B forth. A godelyche, B gostlyche.</NOTE></L>
<L>Full of precyows stones rych;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">A stonys. B And full of presyos stones.</NOTE></L>
<L>For Innocentes &thorn;at place ys sette,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">A For mannys soul. B For innocentys. AB dyght.</NOTE></L>
<L>And euur yn Joye wythowten lette.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">AB &thorn;ere euer is (is fehlt in B) day (B dey) and neuer nyght.</NOTE></L>
